<p><centered><point26>M.</point26></centered></p>

<p><ent>M</ent><br/
<hw>M</hw> <pr>(<ecr/m)</pr>. <sn>1.</sn> <def>M, the thirteenth letter of the English alphabet, is a vocal consonant, and from the manner of its formation, is called the <xex>labio-nasal</xex> consonant. See <xex>Guide to Pronunciation</xex>, <sect/<sect/ 178-180, 242.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>    The letter M came into English from the Greek, through the Latin, the form of the Greek letter being further derived from the Ph<oe/nician, and ultimately, it is believed, from the Egyptian. Etymologically M is related to <xex>n</xex>, in li<xex>me</xex>, li<xex>n</xex>den; <xex>emm</xex>et, a<it>n</it>t; also to <xex>b</xex>.<br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>    M is readily followed by <xex>b</xex> and <xex>p</xex>. the position of the lips in the formation of both letters being the same. The relation of <xex>b</xex> and <xex>m</xex> is the same as that of <xex>d</xex> and <xex>t</xex> to <xex>n</xex>. and that of <xex>g</xex> and <xex>k</xex> to <xex>ng</xex>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>As a numeral, M stands for one thousand, both in English and Latin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>M</ent><br/
<hw>M</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>A quadrat, the face or top of which is a perfect square; also, the size of such a square in any given size of type, used as the unit of measurement for that type: 500 m's of pica would be a piece of matter whose length and breadth in pica m's multiplied together produce that number.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>em</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(law)</fld> <def>A brand or stigma, having the shape of an M, formerly impressed on one convicted of manslaughter and admitted to the benefit of clergy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><col><b>M roof</b></col> <fld>(Arch.)</fld>, <cd>a kind of roof formed by the junction of two common roofs with a valley between them, so that the section resembles the letter M.</cd><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>M-1</ent><br/
<hw>M-1</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A semiautomatic rifle which was standard issue to infantrymen in the United States Army in the mid-20th century.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Garand rifle, Garand, M-1 rifle.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>M1</ent><br/
<hw>M1</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The narrowest measure of the money supply, comprising the currency in circulation plus demand deposits or checking account balances.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>M2</ent><br/
<hw>M2</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A measure of the money supply broader than M1 but narrower than M3, comprising M1 plus net time deposits (other than large certificates of deposit).</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>M3</ent><br/
<hw>M3</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A broad measure of the money supply, comprising M2 plus deposits at nonbanks such as savings and loan associations.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ma</ent><br/
<hw>Ma</hw> <pr>(m<aum/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Mamma</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A child's word for <sig>mother</sig>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[Hind.]</ety> <def>In Oriental countries, a respectful form of address given to a woman; mother.</def> <au>Balfour (Cyc. of India).</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ma</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma</hw>, <pos>conj.</pos> <ety>[It.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>But; -- used in cautionary phrases; <as>as, <ldquo/Vivace, <ex>ma</ex> non troppo presto<rdquo/ (i. e., lively, <xex>but</xex> not too quick)</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Moore (Encyc. of Music).</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maa</ent><br/
<hw>Maa</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>New</er> a gull.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The common European gull (<spn>Larus canus</spn>); -- called also <altname>mar</altname>. See <er>New</er>, a gull.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maad</ent><br/
<hw>Maad</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <mark>obs.</mark> <pos>p. p.</pos> <mord>of <er>Make</er>.</mord> <def>Made.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maalin</ent><br/
<hw>Maa"lin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The sparrow hawk.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The kestrel.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maalox</ent><br/
<hw>Maalox</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A trademark for an antacid.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ma'am</ent><br/
<hw>Ma'am</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Madam; my lady; -- a colloquial contraction of <xex>madam</xex> often used in direct address, and sometimes as an appellation.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> dame, madam, madame, lady, gentlewoman.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maara shell</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"a*ra shell`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A large, pearly, spiral, marine shell (<spn>Turbo margaritaceus</spn>), from the Pacific Islands. It is used as an ornament.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maasha</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*ash"a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An East Indian coin, of about one tenth of the weight of a rupee.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maat</ent><br/
<hw>Maat</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mate</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>Dejected; sorrowful; downcast.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/So piteous and so <xex>maat</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mab</ent><br/
<hw>Mab</hw> <pr>(m<acr/b)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. W. <ets>mad</ets> a male child, a boy.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A slattern.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <mark>[capitalized]</mark> <def>The name of a female fairy, esp. the queen of the fairies; and hence, sometimes, any fairy.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mabble</ent><br/
<hw>Mab"ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To wrap up.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mabby</ent><br/
<hw>Mab"by</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A spirituous liquor or drink distilled from potatoes; -- used in the Barbadoes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mabolo</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*bo"lo</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A kind of persimmon tree (<spn>Diospyros discolor</spn>) from the Philippine Islands, now introduced into the East and West Indies. It bears an edible fruit as large as a quince.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mac</ent><br/
<hw>Mac</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>Shortened form of <altname>Macintosh</altname>, a brand name for a personal computer; <as>as, the latest <ex>Mac</ex> has great new features</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mac</ent><br/
<hw>Mac</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[Gael., son.]</ety> <def>A prefix, in names of Scotch origin, signifying <sig>son</sig>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mac</ent><br/
<hw>mac</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Shortened form of <altname>mackintosh</altname>, a waterproof raincoat made of rubberized fabric.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mackintosh, mac, mack.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macabre</ent><br/
<hw>macabre</hw> <pr>(m<adot/*k<aum/"b<etil/r)</pr> <pos>adj.</pos>  <sn>1.</sn> <def>portraying human injury or death in a way so as to inspiring shock or horror; gruesome; ghastly; <as>as, <ex>macabre</ex> tortures conceived by madmen</as>.</def> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>macaber</asp>.]</altsp><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> ghastly, grisly, gruesome, lurid.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Pertaining to or portraying the grim aspects of death, or the allegorical <cref>dance of death</cref>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macaca</ent><br/
<hw>Macaca</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of macaques including the  rhesus monkey (<spn>Macaca mulatta</spn>), much used in laboratory biomedical research.  Formerly called <altname>Macacus</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Macaca</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macaca mulatta</ent><br/
<hw>Macaca mulatta</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The rhesus monkey of South Asia; used in medical research.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> rhesus, rhesus monkey.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macaca radiata</ent><br/
<hw>Macaca radiata</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>An Indian macaque with a bonnetlike tuft of hair.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> bonnet macaque, bonnet monkey, capped macaque, crown monkey.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macaca sylvana</ent><br/
<hw>Macaca sylvana</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The Barbary ape, a tailless macaque of rocky cliffs and forests of Northwest Africa and Gibralter.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macaco</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*ca"co</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Pg. <ets>macaco</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of several species of lemurs, as the ruffed lemur (<spn>Lemur macaco</spn>), and the ring-tailed lemur (<spn>Lemur catta</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macacus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*ca"cus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., a word of African origin.  Cf. <er>Macaco</er>, <er>Macaque</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of monkeys, found in Asia and the East Indies, now usually called <altname>Macaca</altname>.  They have short tails and prominent eyebrows.  See also <er>Macaca</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macadam</ent><br/
<hw>macadam</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The broken stone used in macadamized roadways.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A paved surface formed of compressed layers of broken rocks held together with tar.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> tartarmac, macadam.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macadamized</ent><br/
<ent>macadam</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>macadam</hw> <hw>macadamized</hw></mhw> <pos>adj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>  <def>paved with macadam{2}.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> asphalt, tarmac, tarmacadam.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macadamia</ent><br/
<hw>macadamia</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>any tree of the genus <gen>Macadamia</gen>, especially <spn>Macadamia ternifolia</spn>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> macadamia tree.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>A <er>macadamia nut</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macadamia nut</ent><br/
<hw>macadamia nut</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The hard-shelled nut of the <spn>Macadamia ternifolia</spn>, or the delicious edible nut without its shell; large quantities are produced in Hawaii and sold commercially.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macadamization</ent><br/
<hw>Mac*ad`am*i*za"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The process or act of macadamizing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macadamize</ent><br/
<hw>Mac*ad"am*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Macadamized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Macadamizing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From <person>John Loudon <etsep>McAdam</etsep></person>, who introduced the process into Great Britain in 1816.]</ety> <def>To cover, as a road, or street, parking lot, playground, or other flat area, with <er>macadam</er>, so as to form a smooth, hard, convex surface.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> tarmac.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macadam road</ent><br/
<hw>Mac*ad"am road`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[See <er>Macadamize</er>.]</ety> <def>A macadamized road.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macamba</ent><br/
<hw>macamba</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A tropical American feather palm (<spn>Acrocomia aculeata</spn>) having a swollen spiny trunk and edible nuts.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> grugru, gri gri, grugru palm, <spn>Acrocomia aculeata</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macao</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*ca"o</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A macaw.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macao</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*ca"o</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A territory in South China, on the Zhu Jiang river on the South China sea, formerly a territory of Portugal.  Also, the capital city of this territory.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macaque</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma`caque"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. See <er>Macacus</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of several species of short-tailed monkeys of the genus <gen>Macaca</gen> (formerly <gen>Macacus</gen>), found in rocky regions of Asia and Africa; <as>as, <spn>Macaca maurus</spn>, the moor <ex>macaque</ex> of the East Indies</as>.</def>  <note><spn>Macaca mulatta</spn> is the <stype>Rhesus monkey</stype>, much used in biomedical research, and namesake of the Rh factor used in blood typing (due to discovery of that factor in the <it>Rh</it>esus monkey).</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macaranga gum</ent><br/
<hw>Mac`a*ran"ga gum`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <def>A gum of a crimson color, obtained from a tree (<spn>Macaranga Indica</spn>) that grows in the East Indies.  It is used in taking impressions of coins, medallions, etc., and sometimes as a medicine.</def>  <rj><au>Balfour (Cyc. of India).</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macarena</ent><br/
<hw>macarena</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a dance performed by dancers in a line, or several lines, consisting mainly of hand and arm movements; also, the name of the song to which the dance is usually performed.  It became popular in 1996.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macarize</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"a*rize</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ to bless.]</ety> <def>To congratulate.</def> <mark>[Oxford Univ. Cant]</mark>  <rj><au>Whately.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macaroni</ent><br/
<hw>Mac`a*ro"ni</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Macaronis</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, or <plw>Macaronies</plw>.</plu> <ety>[Prov. It. <ets>macaroni</ets>, It. <ets>maccheroni</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/ happiness, later, a funeral feast, fr. <?/ blessed, happy. Prob. so called because eaten at such feasts in honor of the dead; cf. Gr. <?/ blessed, i. e., dead.  Cf. <er>Macaroon</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Long slender tubes made of a paste chiefly of a wheat flour such as semolina, and used as an article of food; a form of Italian <isa>pasta</isa>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ A paste similarly prepared is largely used as food in Persia, India, and China, but is not commonly made tubular like the Italian <xex>macaroni</xex>.</note>  <rj><au>Balfour (Cyc. of India).</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A medley; something droll or extravagant.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A sort of droll or fool.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A finical person; a fop; -- applied especially to English fops of about 1775, who affected the mannerisms and clothing of continental Europe.</def>  <rj><au>Goldsmith.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]<-- See lyrics of Yankee Doodle --></p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(U. S. Hist.)</fld> <def>The designation of a body of Maryland soldiers in the Revolutionary War, distinguished by a rich uniform.</def>  <rj><au>W. Irving.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macaronic</ent><br/
<ent>Macaronian</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mac`a*ro"ni*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mac`a*ron"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. It. <ets>maccheronico</ets>, F. <ets>macaronique</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Pertaining to, or like, macaroni (originally a dish of mixed food); hence, mixed; confused; jumbled.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the burlesque composition called macaronic; <as>as, <ex>macaronic</ex> poetry</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macaronic</ent><br/
<hw>Mac`a*ron"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A heap of things confusedly mixed together; a jumble.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A kind of burlesque composition, in which the vernacular words of one or more modern languages are intermixed with genuine Latin words, and with hybrid formed by adding Latin terminations to other roots.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macaroon</ent><br/
<hw>Mac`a*roon"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>macaron</ets>, It. <ets>maccherone</ets>. See <er>Macaroni</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A small cake, composed chiefly of the white of eggs, almonds or coconut, and sugar.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A finical fellow, or macaroni.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macartney</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*cart"ney</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From Lord <etsep>Macartney</etsep>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A fire-backed pheasant. See <er>Fireback</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macassar oil</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*cas`sar oil"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A kind of oil formerly used in dressing the hair; -- so called because originally obtained from <etsep>Macassar</etsep>, a district of the Island of Celebes. Also, an imitation of the same, of perfumed castor oil and olive oil.  Cf. <er>antimacassar</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macau</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*ca"u</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Macao</er>, the territory.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macauco</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*cau"co</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of several species of small lemurs, as <spn>Lemur murinus</spn>, which resembles a rat in size.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macavahu</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma`ca*va"hu</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A small Brazilian monkey (<spn>Callithrix torquatus</spn>), -- called also <altname>collared teetee</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macaw</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*caw"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From the native name in the Antilles.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any parrot of the genus <gen>Ara</gen>, <gen>Sittace</gen>, or <gen>Macrocercus</gen>.  About eighteen species are known, all of them found in Central and South America.  They are large and have a very long tail, a strong hooked bill, and a naked space around the eyes.  The voice is harsh, and the colors are brilliant and strongly contrasted; they are among the largest and showiest of parrots.  Different species names have been given to the same macaw, as for example the <stype>Hyacinthine macaw</stype>, which has been variously classified as <spn>Anodorhyncus hyacynthinus</spn>, <spn>Anodorhyncus maximiliani</spn>, and <spn>Macrocercus hyacynthinus</spn>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><-- e.g. Scarlet macaw -->
<-- Insert: Illustration of Blue and Yellow Macaw --><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Macaw bush</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a West Indian name for a prickly kind of nightshade (<spn>Solanum mammosum</spn>).</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Macaw palm</b></col>, <col><b>Macaw tree</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a tropical American palm (<spn>Acrocomia fusiformis</spn> and other species) having a prickly stem and pinnately divided leaves. Its nut yields a yellow butter, with the perfume of violets, which is used in making violet soap. Called also <altname>grugru palm</altname>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maccabean</ent><br/
<hw>Mac`ca*be"an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to <person>Judas Maccabeus</person> or to the Maccabees; <as>as, the <ex>Maccabean</ex> princes; <ex>Maccabean</ex> times.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maccabees</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"ca*bees</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The name given in later times to the Asmonaeans, a family of Jewish patriots, who headed a religious revolt in the reign of <person>Antiochus IV.</person>, 168-161 <sc>b. c.</sc>, which led to a period of freedom for Israel.</def>  <rj><au>Schaff-Herzog.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The name of two ancient historical books, which give accounts of Jewish affairs in or about the time of the Maccabean princes, and which are received as canonical books in the Roman Catholic Church, but are included in the Apocrypha by Protestants. Also applied to three books, two of which are found in some MSS. of the Septuagint.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 879 --></p>

<p><ent>Maccoboy</ent><br/
<ent>Maccaboy</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mac"ca*boy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mac"co*boy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From a district in the Island of Martinique where it is made: cf. F. <ets>macouba</ets>.]</ety> <def>A kind of snuff.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maccaroni wheat</ent><br/
<hw>maccaroni wheat</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A type of wheat (<spn>Triticum durum</spn>) with hard dark-colored kernels high in gluten and used for bread and pasta; grown especially in South Russia, North Africa, and North central North America.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> durum, durum wheat, hard wheat, <spn>Triticum durum</spn>, <spn>Triticum turgidum</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macco</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"co</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A gambling game in vogue in the eighteenth century.</def>  <rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mace</ent><br/
<hw>Mace</hw> <pr>(m<amac/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Jav. & Malay. <ets>m<amac/s</ets>, fr. Skr. <ets>m<amac/sha</ets> a bean.]</ety> <def>A money of account in China equal to one tenth of a tael; also, a weight of 57.98 grains.</def>  <rj><au>S. W. Williams.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mace</ent><br/
<hw>Mace</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>macis</ets>, L. <ets>macis</ets>, <ets>macir</ets>, Gr. <?/; cf. Skr. <ets>makar</ets>anda the nectar or honey of a flower, a fragrant mango.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A kind of spice; the aril which partly covers nutmegs. See <er>Nutmeg</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <stype>Red mace</stype> is the aril of <spn>Myristica tingens</spn>, and <stype>white mace</stype> that of <spn>Myristica Otoba</spn>, -- East Indian trees of the same genus with the nutmeg tree.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mace</ent><br/
<hw>Mace</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>mace</ets>, F. <ets>masse</ets>, from (assumed) L. <ets>matea</ets>, of which the dim.  <ets>mateola</ets> a kind of mallet or beetle, is found.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A heavy staff or club of metal; a spiked club; -- used as weapon in war before the general use of firearms, especially in the Middle Ages, for breaking metal armor.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Death with his <qex>mace</qex> petrific . . . smote.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>A staff borne by, or carried before, a magistrate as an ensign of his authority.</def> <ldquo/Swayed the royal <xex>mace</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Wordsworth.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An officer who carries a mace as an emblem of authority; a macebearer.</def>  <rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A knobbed mallet used by curriers in dressing leather to make it supple.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Billiards)</fld> <def>A rod for playing billiards, having one end suited to resting on the table and pushed with one hand.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mace</ent><br/
<hw>Mace</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[Trademark.]</ety> <def>A chemical preparation containing tear gas in a solvent, packaged in the form of a spray, and used to temporarily incapacitate people, such as rioters or criminals, by causing intense eye and skin irritation; also called <altname>chemical mace</altname>.  It is designed to be a non-lethal weapon for defending against violent people.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mace bearer</ent><br/
<ent>macebearer</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>macebearer</hw>, <hw>mace bearer</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>an official who carries the mace of office before persons in authority.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mace, macer.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macedoine</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma`c<eacute/`doine"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., apparently the same word as <ets>Mac<eacute/doine</ets> Macedonia.]</ety> <def>A kind of mixed dish, as of cooked vegetables with white sauce, sweet jelly with whole fruit, mixed diced fruits or vegetables etc.; served hot or cold;</def> <specif>Also,</specif> <mark>(fig.)</mark>, <def>a medley.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macedonia</ent><br/
<ent>Macedon</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Macedon</hw>, <hw>Macedonia</hw></mhw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The ancient kingdom of <person>Phillip II</person> and <person>Alexander the Great</person> in the Southeastern Balkans that is now part of Greece, Bulgaria and the independent republic of Macedonia that was part of the former Yugoslavia.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Macedonia.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The modern republic of Macedonia, population 2,033,964, which was formerly one of the constituent republics of <country>Yugoslavia</country>.  It became independent on November 17, 1991, after a referendum held on September 9, 1991.  Its capital city is <city>Skopje</city>.  The currency is the Denar. The ethnic composition is approximately 65% Macedonians, 21.73% Albanians, 3.79 Turks, 2.56% Romanians, 2.10% Serbs, and 0.38% Vlachs.  Its language is Macedonian, which  uses the Cyrillic alphabet.  Its second largest city is <city>Bitola</city> (pop. 84,002).<br/
    At independence in 1991 a new Constitution was adopted, which proclaimed the Republic of Macedonia a sovereign and independent state.   On april 8, 1993, the Republic of Macedonia became a member of the United Nations Organization. Due to the pressure of Greece, which was concerned about possible claims on part of its territory, it was admitted under the name of the <altname>Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia</altname>.<br/
    The Republic of Macedonia is situated in the center of the the Balkan Peninsula and has a unique strategic position at the junction of the main routes which have for millenia linked the West to the Orient. It covers an area of  25,713 square killometres and borders with Bulgaria to the east, Greece to the south, Albania to the west and Serbia to the north.  With the 1913 treaty of  Bucharest, the territory of Macedonia, mainly populated with macedonians, was divided between Greece, Serbia and Bulgaria.  Vardar Macedonia (the territory of today's Republic of Macedonia) became part of the newly established Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes - later known as the Kingdom of Yugoslavia - which existed until 1941. The larger part of Macedonia, geographically known as Aegean Macedonia, covering an area  of 34,356 sqare kilometres, was incorporated into Greece.  The territory of Pirin Macedonia (6,798 sqare kilometres) was assigned to Bulgaria.<br/
    In World War II Macedonians started to struggle against the fascist occupiers on October 11, 1941.  The First Session of ASNOM (The Anti-Fascist Assembly of the National Liberation of Macedonia) was held on August 2, 1944.  It finally crowned the process of the historical establishment of the Macedonian state and was the basis for its soveregnity, and integrity.  Macedonia (Socialistic Republic of Macedonia) became part of Tito's Yugoslavia and remained part until independence in 1991.</def> <au>Goce Vasilevski</au><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A region in northern Greece with its capital at Thessalonica.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macedonian</ent><br/
<hw>Mac`e*do"ni*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>Macedonius</ets>, Gr. <?/.]</ety> <fld>(Geog.)</fld> <def>Belonging, or relating, to Macedonia.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A native or inhabitant of Macedonia.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macedonian</ent><br/
<hw>Mac`e*do"ni*an</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>One of a certain religious sect, followers of <etsep>Macedonius</etsep>, Bishop of Constantinople, in the fourth century, who held that the <person>Holy Ghost</person> was a creature, like the angels, and a servant of the <persfn>Father</persfn> and the <persfn>Son</persfn>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macedonianism</ent><br/
<hw>Mac`e*do"ni*an*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The doctrines of <persfn>Macedonius</persfn>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macer</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"cer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>massier</ets>. See <er>Mace</er> staff.]</ety> <def>A mace bearer; an officer of a court.</def>  <rj><au>P. Plowman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macerate</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"er*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Macerated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Macerating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>maceratus</ets>, p. p.  of <ets>macerare</ets> to make soft, weaken, enervate; cf. Gr. <?/ to knead.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make lean; to cause to waste away.</def> <mark>[Obs. or R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Harvey.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To subdue the appetites of by poor and scanty diet; to mortify.</def>  <rj><au>Baker.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To soften by steeping in a liquid, with or without heat; to wear away or separate the parts of by steeping; <as>as, to <ex>macerate</ex> animal or vegetable fiber</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macerater</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"er*a`ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who, or that which, macerates; an apparatus for converting paper or fibrous matter into pulp.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maceration</ent><br/
<hw>Mac`er*a"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>maceratio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mac<eacute/ration</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act or process of macerating.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macerative</ent><br/
<hw>mac`er*a"tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Accompanied by or  characterized by maceration.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Machaeranthera</ent><br/
<hw>Machaeranthera</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A genus of wildflowers of Western North America.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Machaeranthera</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Machairodus</ent><br/
<ent>Machaerodus</ent><br/
<mhw>{ \'d8<hw>Ma*chae"ro*dus</hw> <pr>(m<adot/*k<emac/"r<osl/*d<ucr/s)</pr>, \'d8<hw>Ma*chai"ro*dus</hw> <pr>(m<adot/*k<imac/"r<osl/*d<ucr/s)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>ma`chaira</grk> dagger + <grk>'odoy`s</grk> tooth.]</ety> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>A genus of extinct mammals allied to the cats, and having in the upper jaw canine teeth of remarkable size and strength; -- hence called <altname>saber-toothed tigers</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Machete</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*che"te</hw> <pr>(m<adot/*sh<ecr/t"<esl/; <it>Sp.</it> m<adot/*ch<amac/"t<asl/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp.]</ety> <def>A large heavy knife resembling a broadsword, often two or three feet in length, -- used by the inhabitants of Spanish America as a hatchet to cut their way through thickets, and for various other purposes.</def>  <rj><au>J. Stevens.</au></rj><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> matchet.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Machiavellian</ent><br/
<ent>Machiavelian</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Mach`i*a*vel"ian</hw>, <hw>Mach`i*a*vel"lian</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <persfn><etsep>Machiavel</etsep></persfn> (also called <persfn>Machiavelli</persfn>), an Italian writer, secretary and historiographer to the republic of Florence.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to <persfn>Machiavelli</persfn>, or to his supposed principles for conduct of government, as enunciated in his tract <booki>The Prince</booki>; politically cunning; characterized by duplicity, political expediency, unscrupulous cunning, or bad faith; crafty.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Machiavellian</ent><br/
<ent>Machiavelian</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Mach`i*a*vel"ian</hw>, <hw>Mach`i*a*vel"lian</hw></mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who adopts the principles of <persfn>Machiavelli</persfn>; a cunning and unprincipled politician.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Machiavellianism</ent><br/
<ent>Machiavelism</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mach"i*a*vel*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mach`i*a*vel"lian*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>machiav<eacute/lisme</ets>; It. <ets>machiavellismo</ets>.]</ety> <def>The supposed principles of <persfn>Machiavelli</persfn>, or practice in conformity to them; political artifice, intended to favor arbitrary power.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Machicolated</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*chic"o*la`ted</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>machicolatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>machicolare</ets>, <ets>machicollare</ets>. See <er>Machicolation</er>.]</ety> <def>Having machicolations.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Machicolated</xex> turrets.<rdquo/  <rj><au>C. Kingsley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Machicolation</ent><br/
<hw>Mach`i*co*la"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. LL. <ets>machicolamentum</ets>, <ets>machacolladura</ets>, F. <ets>m<acir/chicolis</ets>, <ets>m<acir/checoulis</ets>; perh. fr. F. <ets>m<egrave/che</ets> match, combustible matter + OF. <ets>coulis</ets>, <ets>couleis</ets>, flowing, fr. OF. & F. <ets>couler</ets> to flow. Cf. <er>Match</er> for making fire, and <er>Cullis</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Mil. Arch.)</fld> <def>An opening between the corbels which support a projecting parapet, or in the floor of a gallery or the roof of a portal, for shooting or dropping missiles upon assailants attacking the base of the walls.  Also, the construction of such defenses, in general, when of this character. See <xex>Illusts</xex>. of <er>Battlement</er> and <er>Castle</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of discharging missiles or pouring burning or melted substances upon assailants through such apertures.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Machicoulis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma`chi`cou`lis"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<acir/chicoulis</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Mil. Arch.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Machicolation</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>machilid</ent><br/
<hw>mach"i*lid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A wingless insect living in dark moist places, as under tree trunks; they make erratic leaps when disturbed; called also <altname>jumping bristletail</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> jumping bristletail.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Machilidae</ent><br/
<hw>Machilidae</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of insects including the jumping bristletails.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Machinal</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*chin"al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>machinalis</ets>: cf. F. <ets>machinal</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to machines.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Machinate</ent><br/
<hw>Mach"i*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Machinated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Machinating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>machinatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>machinari</ets> to devise, plot. See <er>Machine</er>.]</ety> <def>To plan; to contrive; esp., to form a scheme with the purpose of doing harm; to contrive artfully; to plot.</def> <ldquo/How long will you <xex>machinate</xex>!<rdquo/  <rj><au>Sandys.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Machinate</ent><br/
<hw>Mach"i*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To contrive, as a plot; to plot; <as>as, to <ex>machinate</ex> evil</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Machination</ent><br/
<hw>Mach`i*na"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>machinatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>machination</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of machinating.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is devised; a device; a hostile or treacherous scheme; an artful design or plot.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Devilish <qex>machinations</qex> come to naught.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His ingenious <qex>machinations</qex> had failed.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Machinator</ent><br/
<hw>Mach"i*na`tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.]</ety> <def>One who machinates, or forms a scheme with evil designs; a plotter or artful schemer.</def>  <rj><au>Glanvill. Sir W. Scott.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Machine</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*chine"</hw> <pr>(m<adot/*sh<emac/n")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>machina</ets> machine, engine, device, trick, Gr. <grk>mhchanh`</grk>, from <grk>mh^chos</grk> means, expedient.  Cf. <er>Mechanic</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>In general, any combination of bodies so connected that their relative motions are constrained, and by means of which force and motion may be transmitted and modified, as a screw and its nut, or a lever arranged to turn about a fulcrum or a pulley about its pivot, etc.; especially, a construction, more or less complex, consisting of a combination of moving parts, or simple mechanical elements, as wheels, levers, cams, etc., with their supports and connecting framework, calculated to constitute a prime mover, or to receive force and motion from a prime mover or from another machine, and transmit, modify, and apply them to the production of some desired mechanical effect or work, as weaving by a loom, or the excitation of electricity by an electrical machine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The term <xex>machine</xex> is most commonly applied to such pieces of mechanism as are used in the industrial arts, for mechanically shaping, dressing, and combining materials for various purposes, as in the manufacture of cloth, etc.  Where the effect is chemical, or other than mechanical, the contrivance is usually denominated an <xex>apparatus</xex> or <xex>device</xex>, not a machine; as, a <xex>bleaching apparatus</xex>.  Many large, powerful, or specially important pieces of mechanism are called <xex>engines</xex>; as, a <xex>steam engine</xex>, <xex>fire engine</xex>, <xex>graduating engine</xex>, etc.  Although there is no well-settled distinction between the terms <xex>engine</xex> and machine among practical men, there is a tendency to restrict the application of the former to contrivances in which the operating part is not distinct from the motor.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any mechanical contrivance, as the wooden horse with which the Greeks entered Troy; a coach; a bicycle.</def>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au> <au>Southey.</au> <au>Thackeray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A person who acts mechanically or at the will of another.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A combination of persons acting together for a common purpose, with the agencies which they use; <as>as, the social <ex>machine</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The whole <qex>machine</qex> of government ought not to bear upon the people with a weight so heavy and oppressive.</q> <rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A political organization arranged and controlled by one or more leaders for selfish, private or partisan ends; the Tammany <ex>machine</ex>.</def> <mark>[Political Cant]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Supernatural agency in a poem, or a superhuman being introduced to perform some exploit.</def>  <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Elementary machine</b></col>, <cd>a name sometimes given to one of the simple mechanical powers. See under <er>Mechanical</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Infernal machine</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Infernal</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Machine gun</b></col>.<cd>See under <er>Gun.</er></cd> -- <col><b>Machine screw</b></col>, <cd>a screw or bolt adapted for screwing into metal, in distinction from one which is designed especially to be screwed into wood.</cd> -- <col><b>Machine shop</b></col>, <cd>a workshop where machines are made, or where metal is shaped by cutting, filing, turning, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Machine tool</b></col>, <cd>a machine for cutting or shaping wood, metal, etc., by means of a tool; especially, a machine, as a lathe, planer, drilling machine, etc., designed for a more or less general use in a machine shop, in distinction from a machine for producing a special article as in manufacturing.</cd> -- <col><b>Machine twist</b></col>, <cd>silken thread especially adapted for use in a sewing machine.</cd> -- <col><b>Machine work</b></col>, <cd>work done by a machine, in contradistinction to that done by hand labor.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Machine</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*chine"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Machined</conjf> <pr>(m<adot/*sh<emac/nd")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Machining</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To subject to the action of machinery; to make, cut, shape, or modify with a machine; to effect by aid of machinery; to print with a printing machine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>machine bolt</ent><br/
<hw>machine bolt</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A threaded hexagonal or square-headed bolt with a nut; it is tightened with a wrench and used to connect metal parts.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>machine code</ent><br/
<hw>machine code</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Computers) </fld> <def>Same as <er>machine language</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>machine-driven</ent><br/
<ent>machine-controlled</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>machine-controlled</hw> <hw>machine-driven</hw></mhw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>same as <er>automated</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> automated.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>machine gun</ent><br/
<hw>machine gun</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A fully automatic rapid-firing rifle, which continues to fire bullets repeatedly as long as the trigger is depressed; lighter versions may be carried in the hands, and heavier versions may be mounted on a tripod, vehicle, or other mount.  The lighweight versions are sometimes called a <stype>submachine gun</stype>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>machine gun</ent><br/
<ent>machine-gun</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>machine-gun</hw>, <hw>machine gun</hw></mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Occurring in rapid succession, like the firing of a <er>machine gun</er>; <as>as, Tom was a persuasive speaker, with a smooth deep voice, polysyllabic vocabulary, and a <ex>machine-gun</ex> articulation that overwhelmed listeners</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> rapid-fire.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>machine gunner</ent><br/
<hw>machine gunner</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A soldier who operates a machine gun.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>machine language</ent><br/
<hw>machine language</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Computers)</fld> <def>a set of instructions{3} in a binary form that can be executed directly by the CPU of a computer without translation by a computer program.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> machine code, binary code.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>machine-like</ent><br/
<ent>machinelike</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>machinelike</hw>, <hw>machine-like</hw></mhw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>behaving in an unthinking manner, like the functioning of a machine; <as>as, <ex>machine-like</ex> fools</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> automatic, automaton-like, automatonlike, machinelike, robotlike.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>machine-made</ent><br/
<hw>machine-made</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>made by a machine.  Contrasted with <ant>handmade</ant>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>machine-oriented language</ent><br/
<hw>machine-oriented language</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A programming language designed for use on a specific class of computers.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> computer language, computer-oriented language, machine language.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>machine pistol</ent><br/
<hw>machine pistol</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A fully automatic pistol; a small submachine gun.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Machiner</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*chin"er</hw> <pr>(m<adot/*sh<emac/n"<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who or operates a machine; a machinist{2}.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>machine-readable</ent><br/
<hw>ma*chin"e-read"a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Computers)</fld> <def>Readable by a machine;</def> <specif>especially,</specif> <def>available on a data-storage medium in a binary format that can be rapidly converted by standard input devices into data in a computer memory; <as>as, the CIDE dictionary is a <ex>machine-readable</ex> dictionary</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Machinery</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*chin"er*y</hw> <pr>(m<adot/*sh<emac/n"<etil/r*<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Machine</er>: cf. F. <ets>machinerie</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Machines, in general, or collectively.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The working parts of a machine, engine, or instrument; <as>as, the <ex>machinery</ex> of a watch</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The supernatural means by which the action of a poetic or fictitious work is carried on and brought to a catastrophe; in an extended sense, the contrivances by which the crises and conclusion of a fictitious narrative, in prose or verse, are effected.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>machinery</qex>, madam, is a term invented by the critics, to signify that part which the deities, angels, or demons, are made to act in a poem.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The means and appliances by which anything is kept in action or a desired result is obtained; a complex system of parts adapted to a purpose.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An indispensable part of the <qex>machinery</qex> of state.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The delicate inflexional <qex>machinery</qex> of the Aryan languages.</q> <rj><qau>I. Taylor (The Alphabet).</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>machine screw</ent><br/
<hw>machine screw</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A type of screw used either with a nut or with a tapped hole; it has a slotted head which can be driven by a screwdriver.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>machine shop</ent><br/
<hw>machine shop</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A small business or a room within a business establishment where metal is cut and shaped etc., by machine tools.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>machine tool</ent><br/
<hw>machine tool</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A power-driven machine for cutting or shaping or finishing metals or other materials.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>machine translation</ent><br/
<hw>ma*chine" trans*la"tion</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Computers)</fld> <def>The translation of human language from one language to another by a computer; -- a branch of <branchof>artificial intelligence</branchof>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> computer translation, automatic translation.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Machining</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*chin"ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the machinery of a poem; acting or used as a machine.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Machinist</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*chin"ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>machiniste</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A constructor of machines and engines; one versed in the principles of machines.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One skilled in the use of machine tools.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A person employed to shift scenery in a theater.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>machismo</ent><br/
<hw>machismo</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A strong, and by some considered exaggerated, sense of manly pride, associated with an attitude that the proper expression of masculinity includes virility, courage, and an entitlement to dominate, especially over women.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An exaggerated sense of power entitling one to dominate others; <as>as, the civilian authorities occasionally need to rein in the military's <ex>machismo</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>machmeter</ent><br/
<hw>machmeter</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>an instrument for measuring the speed of an aircraft relative to the speed of sound.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mach number</ent><br/
<hw>mach number</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(aeronautics)</fld> <def>The ratio of the speed of a moving body to the speed of sound.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macho</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"cho</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The striped mullet of California (<spn>Mugil cephalus</spn>, syn. <spn>Mugil Mexicanus</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macho</ent><br/
<hw>ma"cho</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Sp.]</ety> <def>Manly, especially with an assertive and domineering manner toward women.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>MACHO</ent><br/
<hw>MACHO</hw> <pr>(m<aum/"k<osl/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[acronym from <ets>M</ets>assive <ets>A</ets>strophysical <ets>C</ets>ompact <ets>H</ets>alo <ets>O</ets>bject.]</ety> <def>A form of <isa>dark matter</isa> in distant outer space unobservable except by its gravitational effect, and believed to be at least part of the <ldquo/missing matter<rdquo/ which is unobservable as ordinary stars, but helps keep galaxies from flying apart; MACHOS are massive but compact objects such as neutron stars or brown dwarfs, which can be detected (with difficulty) by their effect in bending light from distant light sources, such as other galaxies.  This can occur if by rare chance a MACHO passes in front of a more distant visible object, and the light from that object becomes temporarily amplified by the MACHO acting as a gravitational lens.  Some MACHOs have been discovered in the halo of dark matter that surrounds our milky way.  It is, however, questionable whether the amount of such matter is sufficient to explain the ability of galaxies to stay together in spite of rotation rates that would cause them to fly apart if the only matter present was that observable as visible stars.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macilency</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"i*len*cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Macilent</er>.]</ety> <def>Leanness.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sandys.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macilent</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"i*lent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>macilentus</ets>, fr. <ets>macies</ets> leanness, <ets>macere</ets> to be lean.]</ety> <def>Lean; thin.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bailey.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macintosh</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"in*tosh</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Same as <er>Mackintosh</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[Trademark.]</ety> <fld>(Computers)</fld> <def>A brand of personal computer featuring an integrated system in which the hardware and system-operating software were designed by or under the control of a single company, the <corpn>Apple Computer Corporation</corpn>; among personal computers, distinguished from the <contr>IBM-compatible</contr> or <contr>Intel-based</contr> series of computers.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mack</ent><br/
<hw>mack</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A <er>mackintosh</er>; -- a shortened form.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> macintosh, mackintosh, mac.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mackenzie</ent><br/
<hw>Mackenzie</hw> <pos>peop. n.</pos> <def>a Canadian river; flows into the Beaufort Sea.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Mackenzie River.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mackerel</ent><br/
<hw>Mack"er*el</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>maquerel</ets>, F. <ets>maquereau</ets>, fr. D. <ets>makelaar</ets> mediator, agent, fr. <ets>makelen</ets> to act as agent.]</ety> <def>A pimp; also, a bawd.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mackerel</ent><br/
<hw>Mack`er*el</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>maquerel</ets>, F. <ets>maquereau</ets> (LL. <ets>macarellus</ets>), prob. for <ets>maclereau</ets>, fr. L. <ets>macula</ets> a spot, in allusion to the markings on the fish.  See <er>Mail</er> armor.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any species of the genus <gen>Scomber</gen> of the family <fam>Scombridae</fam>, and of several related genera.  They are finely formed and very active oceanic fishes.  Most of them are highly prized for food.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The common mackerel (<spn>Scomber scombrus</spn>), which inhabits both sides of the North Atlantic, is one of the most important food fishes.  It is mottled with green and blue.  The Spanish mackerel (<spn>Scomberomorus maculatus</spn>), of the American coast, is covered with bright yellow circular spots.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Bull mackerel</b></col>, <col><b>Chub mackerel</b></col></mcol>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Chub</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Frigate mackerel</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Frigate</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Horse mackerel</b></col> . <cd>See under <er>Horse</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mackerel bird</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the wryneck; -- so called because it arrives in England at the time when mackerel are in season.</cd> -- <col><b>Mackerel cock</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the Manx shearwater; -- so called because it precedes the appearance of the mackerel on the east coast of Ireland.</cd> -- <col><b>Mackerel guide</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Garfish</er> <sd>(a)</sd>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mackerel gull</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>any one of several species of gull which feed upon or follow mackerel, as the kittiwake.</cd> -- <col><b>Mackerel midge</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a very small oceanic gadoid fish of the North Atlantic.  It is about an inch and a half long and has four barbels on the upper jaw.  It is now considered the young of the genus <gen>Onos</gen>, or <gen>Motella</gen>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mackerel plow</b></col>, <cd>an instrument for creasing the sides of lean mackerel to improve their appearance.</cd> <au>Knight.</au> -- <col><b>Mackerel shark</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the porbeagle.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Mackerel sky</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Mackerel-back sky</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a sky flecked with small white clouds; a cirro-cumulus. See <er>Cloud</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mackerel sky</qex> and mare's-tails<br/
Make tall ships carry low sails.</q> <rj><qau>Old Rhyme.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mackerel shad</ent><br/
<ent>mackerel scad</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mackerel scad</hw>, <hw>mackerel shad</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A small silvery fish (<spn>Decapterus macarellus</spn>) found from Nova Scotia to Brazil.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mackerel sky</ent><br/
<hw>mackerel sky</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A sky filled with rows of cirrocumulus or small altocumulus clouds.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mackinaw</ent><br/
<ent>Mackinaw blanket</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mack"i*naw blan"ket</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mack"i*naw</hw>. }</mhw><ety>[From <ets>Mackinac</ets>, the State of Michigan, where blankets and other stores were distributed to the Indians.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A thick blanket formerly in common use in the western part of the United States.</def> <wns>[wns=2]</wns><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>a heavy woolen cloth heavily napped and felted, often with a plaid design.</def> <wns>[wns=4]</wns><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mackinaw boat</ent><br/
<ent>Mackinaw</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Mack"i*naw</hw>, <hw>Mack"i*naw boat</hw></mhw>. <def>A flat-bottomed boat with a pointed prow and square stern, using oars or sails or both, used esp. on the upper Great Lakes and their tributaries.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mackinaw coat</ent><br/
<ent>Mackinaw</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Mack"i*naw</hw>, <hw>Mack"i*naw coat</hw></mhw>. <def>A short, heavy, double-breasted plaid coat, the design of which is large and striking.</def> <mark>[Local, U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mackinaw trout</ent><br/
<hw>Mackinaw trout</hw>. <def>The namaycush.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mackintosh</ent><br/
<hw>Mack"in*tosh</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A waterproof outer garment; -- so called from the name of the inventor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mackle</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"kle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Macle</er>.]</ety> <def>Same as <er>Macule</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mackle</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"kle</hw>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To blur, or be blurred, in printing, as if there were a double impression.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macle</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"cle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>macula</ets> a spot: cf. F. <ets>macle</ets>.  Cf. <er>Mackle</er>, <er>Mascle</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Chiastolite; -- so called from the tessellated appearance of a cross section. See <er>Chiastolite</er>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A crystal having a similar tessellated appearance.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>A twin crystal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macleaya</ent><br/
<hw>Macleaya</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of East Asian perennial herbs including the plume poppy.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macled</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"cled</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Marked like macle (chiastolite).</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Having a twin structure. See <er>Twin</er>, <pos>a.</pos></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>See <er>Mascled</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maclura</ent><br/
<hw>Maclura</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of plants including the yellowwood trees and shrubs.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maclurea</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*clu"re*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. Named from <person>William <etsep>Maclure</etsep></person>, the geologist.]</ety> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>A genus of spiral gastropod shells, often of large size, characteristic of the lower Silurian rocks.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maclurin</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*clu"rin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>See <er>Morintannic</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maconnais</ent><br/
<ent>macon</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>macon</hw>, <hw>maconnais</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A fine Burgundy wine usually white and dry, produced in the area around Macon, a city in France.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macoun</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*coun"</hw> <pr>(m<adot/*k<oomac/n")</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A juicy, late-ripening apple similar to a McIntosh.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macowanites</ent><br/
<hw>Macowanites</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A stout-stemmed genus of fungi belonging to the family <fam>Secotiaceae</fam> having fruiting bodies that never expand completely.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macowanites americanus</ent><br/
<hw>Macowanites americanus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A small fungus with a fragile cap that cracks to expose the white context and a white stalk that is practically enclosed by the cap.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrame</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"ra*me</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>the art of tying knots in patterns.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>a coarse lace, made by weaving and knotting cords; <er>macrame lace</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrame lace</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"ra*me lace"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <def>A coarse lace made of twine, used especially in decorating furniture.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrencephalous</ent><br/
<ent>Macrencephalic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mac`ren*ce*phal"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mac`ren*ceph"a*lous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Macro</ets> + <ets>encephalic</ets>, <ets>encephalous</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to macrencephaly; having a large brain.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macrencephaly</ent><br/
<hw>macrencephaly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The condition of having an abnormally large braincase.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macro</ent><br/
<hw>macro</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[shortened form of <ets>macroinstruction</ets>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>a single computer instruction which symbolizes, and is converted at the time of program execution or by a compiler into, a series of instructions in the same computer language.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A keystroke (or combination of keystrokes) which symbolizes and is replaced by a series of keystrokes; -- a convenient feature of some advanced programs, such as word processors or database programs, which allows a user to rapidly execute any series of operations which may be performed multiple times.  Such macros may typically be defined by the program user, without rewriting or recompiling the program.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macro</ent><br/
<hw>macro</hw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>very large in scale or scope or capability; <as>as, <ex>macro</ex>economics</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macro-</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"ro-</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> <pos>pref.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>makro`s</grk>, adj.]</ety> <def>A combining form signifying <sig>long</sig>, <sig>large</sig>, <sig>great</sig>; <as>as <ex>macro</ex>diagonal, <ex>macro</ex>spore, <ex>macro</ex>molecule, <ex>macro</ex>cosm</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrobiotic</ent><br/
<hw>Mac`ro*bi*ot"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ long-lived; <grk>makro`s</grk> long + <grk>bi`os</grk> life: cf. F. <ets>macrobiotique</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Long-lived.</def>  <rj><au> Dunglison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to macrobiotics.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to macrobiotic food; serving macrobiotic food.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macrobiotic diet</ent><br/
<hw>macrobiotic diet</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A diet consisting chiefly of beans and whole grains.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrobiotics</ent><br/
<hw>Mac`ro*bi*ot"ics</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>The art of prolonging life.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <def>A philosophy or attitude that health and long life are promoted by adhering to a diet consisting mostly of whole grains, with some vegetables, beans, fruit, and moderate amounts of seafood.  However, the absence of essential nutrients such as fat makes such a diet of questionable value if strictly adhered to.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macrocephalous</ent><br/
<ent>macrocephalic</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mac`ro*ce*phal"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>mac`ro*ceph"a*lous</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Macro</ets> + Gr. <grk>kefalh`</grk> the head.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to macrocephaly; having an unusually large head.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having the cotyledons of a dicotyledonous embryo confluent, and forming a large mass compared with the rest of the body.</def>  <rj><au>Henslow.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macrocephaly</ent><br/
<hw>macrocephaly</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>THe condition of having an unusually large head; it differs from <contr>hydrocephalus</contr> because there is no increase intracranial pressure and the overgrowth is symmetrical.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> megacephaly, megalocephaly.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrocheira</ent><br/
<hw>Macrocheira</hw> <pos>peop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of giant crabs of Japan.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Macrocheira</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macro-chemistry</ent><br/
<hw>Mac`ro-chem"is*try</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Macro-</ets> + <ets>chemistry</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>The science which treats of the chemical properties, actions or relations of substances in quantity; -- distinguished from <contr>micro-chemistry</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrochires</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mac`ro*chi"res</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>makro`s</grk> long + <?/ hand.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A division of birds including the swifts and humming birds. So called from the length of the distal part of the wing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macroclemys</ent><br/
<hw>Macroclemys</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A genus of alligator snapping turtles.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Macroclemys</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrocosm</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"ro*cosm</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Macro-</ets> + Gr. <?/ the world: cf. F. <ets>macrocosme</ets>.]</ety> <def>The great world; that part of the universe which is exterior to man; -- contrasted with <xex>microcosm</xex>, or man. See <er>Microcosm</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrocosmic</ent><br/
<hw>Mac`ro*cos"mic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the macrocosm.</def>  <rj><au>Tylor.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrocystis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mac`ro*cys"tis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Macro-</er>, and <er>Cyst</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>An immensely long blackish seaweed of the Pacific (<spn>Macrocystis pyrifera</spn>), having numerous almond-shaped air vessels.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macro lens</ent><br/
<hw>macro lens</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a camera lens designed to focus at short distances so as to achieve photographic magnifications of objects larger than with standard lenses.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macrocyte</ent><br/
<hw>macrocyte</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>An abnormally large red blood cell, associated with pernicious anemia.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macrocytosis</ent><br/
<hw>macrocytosis</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>An abnormal physiological condition characterized by the presence of macrocytes in the blood.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 880 --></p>

<p><ent>Macrodactyl</ent><br/
<hw>Mac`ro*dac"tyl</hw> <pr>(m<acr/k`r<osl/*d<acr/k"t<icr/l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>makroda`ktylos</grk> long-fingered; <grk>makro`s</grk> long + <grk>da`ktylos</grk> finger: cf. F. <ets>macrodactyle</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of a group of wading birds (<it>Macrodactyli</it>) having very long toes.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>macrodactyle</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrodactylous</ent><br/
<ent>Macrodactylic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mac`ro*dac*tyl"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mac`ro*dac"tyl*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having long toes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrodiagonal</ent><br/
<hw>Mac`ro*di*ag"o*nal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Macro-</ets> + <ets>diagonal</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Crystallog.)</fld> <def>The longer of two diagonals, as of a rhombic prism. See <er>Crystallization</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrodome</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"ro*dome</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Macro-</ets> + <ets>dome</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Crystallog.)</fld> <def>A dome parallel to the longer lateral axis of an orthorhombic crystal. See <er>Dome</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 4.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrodont</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"ro*dont</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Macro-</ets> + Gr. <grk>'odoy`s</grk>, <grk>'odo`ntos</grk>, a tooth.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having large teeth.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A macrodont animal.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrofarad</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"ro*far`ad</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Macro-</ets> + <ets>farad</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>See <er>Megafarad</er>.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macroglia</ent><br/
<hw>macroglia</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Tissue consisting of large stellate neuroglial cells.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> astroglia.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macroglossia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mac`ro*glos"si*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Macro-</er>, and <er>Glossa</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Enlargement or hypertrophy of the tongue.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrognathic</ent><br/
<hw>Mac`rog*nath"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Macro-</ets> + <ets>gnathic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anthropol.)</fld> <def>Long-jawed.</def>  <rj><au>Huxley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrograph</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"ro*graph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>  <ety>[<ets>Macro-</ets> + <ets>-graph</ets>.]</ety> <def>A picture of an object as seen by the naked eye (that is, unmagnified); <as>as, a <ex>macrograph</ex> of a metallic fracture</as>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrography</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*crog"ra*phy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Examination or study with the naked eye, as distinguished from <contr>micrography</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrology</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*crol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>macrologia</ets>, Gr. <?/; <?/ long + <grk>lo`gos</grk> discourse: cf. F. <ets>macrologie</ets>.]</ety> <def>Long and tedious talk without much substance; superfluity of words.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrometer</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*crom"e*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Macro-</ets> + <ets>-meter</ets>.]</ety> <def>An instrument for determining the size or distance of inaccessible objects by means of two reflectors on a common sextant.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macromolecule</ent><br/
<hw>mac`ro*mol"e*cule</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem., Biochem.)</fld> <def>A very large molecule, especially a polymer having from hundreds to many thousands of atoms, such as <stype>DNA</stype>, <stype>RNA</stype>, <stype>protein</stype>, <stype>polysaccharide</stype>, <stype>polyethylene</stype>, <stype>polycarbonate</stype>, etc.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macromolecular</ent><br/
<hw>mac`ro*mo*lec"u*lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Of, pertaining to, or consisting of macromolecules.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macron</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"cron</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ long.]</ety> <fld>(Pron.)</fld> <def>A short, straight, horizontal mark [-], placed over vowels to denote that they are to be pronounced with a long sound; as, <examp><amac/</examp>, in <examp>d<amac/me</examp>; <examp><emac/</examp>, in <examp>s<emac/am</examp>, etc.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> macrotone.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macropetalous</ent><br/
<hw>Mac`ro*pet"al*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Macro-</ets> + <ets>petal</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having long or large petals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macrophage</ent><br/
<hw>mac"ro*phage</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A large phagocyte.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrophyllous</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*croph"yl*lous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Macro-</ets> + Gr. <?/ a leaf.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having long or large leaves.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macropinacoid</ent><br/
<hw>Mac`ro*pin"a*coid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Macro-</ets> + <ets>pinacoid</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Crystallog.)</fld> <def>One of the two planes of an orthorhombic crystal which are parallel to the vertical and longer lateral (macrodiagonal) axes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macropod</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"ro*pod</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Macro-</ets> + <ets>-pod</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of a group of maioid crabs remarkable for the length of their legs; -- called also <altname>spider crab</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macropodal</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*crop"o*dal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having long or large feet, or a long stem.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macropodian</ent><br/
<hw>Mac`ro*po"di*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A macropod.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macropodous</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*crop"o*dous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having long legs or feet.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macroprism</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"ro*prism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Macro-</ets> + <ets>prism</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Crystallog.)</fld> <def>A prism of an orthorhombic crystal between the macropinacoid and the unit prism; the corresponding pyramids are called <xex>macropyramids</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macropteres</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*crop"te*res</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ long + <grk>ptero`n</grk> feather, wing.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A division of birds; the Longipennes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macropterous</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*crop"ter*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Macropteres</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having long wings or fins.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macropus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mac"ro*pus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Macropod</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of marsupials including the common kangaroo.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macropyramid</ent><br/
<hw>Mac`ro*pyr"a*mid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Macro-</ets> + <ets>pyramid</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Crystallog.)</fld> <def>See <er>Macroprism</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macroscopical</ent><br/
<ent>Macroscopic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mac`ro*scop"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mac`ro*scop"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Macro-</ets> + Gr. <?/ to view.]</ety> <def>Visible to the unassisted eye; -- as opposed to <ant>microscopic</ant>.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mac`ro*scop"ic*al*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrosporangium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mac`ro*spo*ran"gi*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Macro-</er>, and <er>Sporangium</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A sporangium or conceptacle containing only large spores; -- opposed to <contr>microsporangium</contr>.  Both are found in the genera <gen>Selaginella</gen>, <gen>Isoctes</gen>, and <gen>Marsilia</gen>, plants remotely allied to ferns.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrospore</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"ro*spore</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Macro-</ets> + <ets>spore</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>One of the specially large spores of certain flowerless plants, as <gen>Selaginella</gen>, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrosporic</ent><br/
<hw>Mac`ro*spor"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to macrospores.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrotone</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"ro*tone</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ stretched out. See <er>Macro-</er>, and <er>Tone</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Pron.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Macron</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrotous</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*cro"tous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Macro-</ets> + Gr. <grk>o"y^s</grk>, gen. <grk>'wto`s</grk>, the ear.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Large-eared.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macrotus</ent><br/
<hw>ma*cro"tus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A large-eared grayish bat (<spn>Macrotus californicus</spn>) of southern California and northwestern Mexico.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macroural</ent><br/
<ent>Macroura</ent><br/
<mhw>\'d8<hw>Ma*crou"ra</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos>, <hw>Ma*crou"ral</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>, etc.</mhw> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Macrura</er>, <er>Macrural</er>, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrouridae</ent><br/
<hw>Macrouridae</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos>, <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A natural family of fish including the grenadiers.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Macruridae.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.6</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrozoospore</ent><br/
<hw>Mac`ro*zo"o*spore</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Macro-</ets> + <ets>zoospore</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A large motile spore having four vibratile cilia; -- found in certain green algae.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrura</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*cru"ra</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ long + <?/ tail.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A subdivision of decapod Crustacea, having the abdomen largely developed. It includes the lobster, prawn, shrimp, and many similar forms.  Cf. <er>Decapoda</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrural</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*cru"ral</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Macrurous</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macruran</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*cru"ran</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the Macrura.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macruridae</ent><br/
<hw>Macruridae</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos>, <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Macrouridae</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Macrouridae.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.6</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macruroid</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*cru"roid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Macrura</ets> + <ets>-oid</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Like or pertaining to the Macrura.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macrurous</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*cru"rous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the Macrura; having a long tail.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mactation</ent><br/
<hw>Mac*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mactatio</ets>, fr. <ets>macture</ets> to slay, sacrifice.]</ety> <def>The act of killing a victim for sacrifice.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mactra</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mac"tra</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ kneading trough, fr. <?/ to knead.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any marine bivalve shell of the genus <gen>Mactra</gen>, and allied genera. Many species are known. Some of them are used as food, as <spn>Mactra stultorum</spn>, of Europe. See <cref>Surf clam</cref>, under <er>Surf</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macula</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mac"u*la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Maculae</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., spot, stain, blot. See <er>Mail</er> armor, and cf. <er>Mackle</er>, <er>Macule</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A spot, as on the skin, or on the surface of the sun or of some other luminous orb; called also <altname>macule</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A rather large spot or blotch of color.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macular area</ent><br/
<ent>macula lutea</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>macula lutea</hw>, <hw>macular area</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A yellowish central area of the retina that is rich in cones.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> macula, yellow spot.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maculate</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"u*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>maculatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>maculare</ets> to spot. See <er>Macula</er>, and cf. <er>Macule</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <def>To spot; to stain; to blur.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Maculate</qex> the honor of their people.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. Elyot.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maculate</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"u*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>maculatus</ets>, p. p.]</ety> <def>Marked with spots or maculae; blotched; hence, defiled; impure; <as>as, most <ex>maculate</ex> thoughts</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maculated</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"u*la`ted</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having spots or blotches; maculate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maculation</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"u*la"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>maculatio</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act of spotting; a spot; a blemish; a macula.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maculatory</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"u*la*to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Causing a spot or stain.</def>  <rj><au>T. Adams.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maculature</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"u*la*ture</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Blotting paper.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macule</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"ule</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>macule</ets>. See <er>Macula</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A spot.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>A blur, or an appearance of a double impression, as when the paper slips a little; a mackle.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Macule</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"ule</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>maculer</ets>. See <er>Maculate</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <def>To blur; especially <fld>(Print.)</fld>, to blur or double an impression from type. See <er>Mackle</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maculose</ent><br/
<hw>Mac"u*lose`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>maculosus</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to spots upon a surface; spotted; maculate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macumba</ent><br/
<hw>macumba</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>, <sn>1.</sn> <def>A popular dance music of Brazil, derived from the practices of the macumba religious cult.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.6</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>a Brazilian religious cult of African origin; combines voodoo elements with singing a chanting and dancing.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.6</source>]</p>

<p><ent>macumba</ent><br/
<hw>macumba</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>, <def>darling; -- an Irish term of address expressing affection.</def> <mark>[Irish]</mark> <br/
[<source>WordNet 1.6</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mad</ent><br/
<hw>Mad</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <mark>obs.</mark> <def><pos>p. p.</pos> of <er>Made</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mad</ent><br/
<hw>Mad</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Madder</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Maddest</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</amorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>gem<?/d</ets>, <ets>gem<amac/d</ets>, mad; akin to OS. <ets>gem<?/d</ets> foolish, OHG. <ets>gameit</ets>, Icel. <ets>mei<?/a</ets> to hurt, Goth. <ets>gam<aacute/ids</ets> weak, broken. <?/.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Disordered in intellect; crazy; insane.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have heard my grandsire say full oft,<br/
Extremity of griefs would make men <qex>mad</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Excited beyond self-control or the restraint of reason; inflamed by violent or uncontrollable desire, passion, or appetite; <as>as, to be <ex>mad</ex> with terror, lust, or hatred; <ex>mad</ex> against political reform.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is the land of graven images, and they are <qex>mad</qex> upon their idols.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. 1. 88.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And being exceedingly <qex>mad</qex> against them, I persecuted them even unto strange cities.</q> <rj><qau>Acts xxvi. 11.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Proceeding from, or indicating, madness; expressing distraction; prompted by infatuation, fury, or extreme rashness.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Mad</xex> demeanor.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mad</qex> wars destroy in one year the works of many years of peace.</q> <rj><qau>Franklin.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>mad</qex> promise of Cleon was fulfilled.</q> <rj><qau>Jowett (Thucyd.).</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Extravagant; immoderate.</def> <ldquo/Be <xex>mad</xex> and merry.<rdquo/ <au>Shak.</au> <ldquo/Fetching <xex>mad</xex> bounds.<rdquo/ <au>Shak.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Furious with rage, terror, or disease; -- said of the lower animals; <as>as, a <ex>mad</ex> bull</as>; esp., having hydrophobia; rabid; <as>as, a <ex>mad</ex> dog</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Angry; out of patience; vexed; <as>as, to get <ex>mad</ex> at a person</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Having impaired polarity; -- applied to a compass needle.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Like mad</b></col>, <cd>like a mad person; in a furious manner; <as>as, to run <ex>like mad</ex>. <au>L'Estrange</au></as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To run mad</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To become wild with excitement</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To run wildly about under the influence of hydrophobia; to become affected with hydrophobia.</cd> -- <col><b>To run mad after</b></col>, <cd>to pursue under the influence of infatuation or immoderate desire.</cd> <ldquo/The world is <xex>running mad after</xex> farce.<rdquo/ <au>Dryden.</au></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mad</ent><br/
<hw>Mad</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Madded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Madding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To make mad or furious; to madden.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Had I but seen thy picture in this plight,<br/
It would have <qex>madded</qex> me.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mad</ent><br/
<hw>Mad</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be mad; to go mad; to rave. See <er>Madding</er>.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Festus said with great voice, Paul thou <qex>maddest</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Wyclif (Acts).</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mad</ent><br/
<hw>Mad</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>ma<?/a</ets>; akin to D. & G. <ets>made</ets>, Goth. <ets>mapa</ets>, and prob. to E. <ets>moth</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An earthworm.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>made</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madagascan</ent><br/
<hw>Madagascan</hw> <pos>prop. a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to Madagascar; <as>as, <ex>Madagascan</ex> pepper</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>Of or pertaining to the inhabitants of Madagascar; <as>as, <ex>Madagascan</ex> soldiers</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Malagasy.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madagascan</ent><br/
<hw>Madagascan</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A native or inhabitant of Madagascar.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madagascar</ent><br/
<hw>Mad`a*gas"car</hw> <pr>(m<acr/d`<adot/*g<acr/s"k<etil/r)</pr> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>An island in the Indian Ocean, about 240 miles off the southeast coast of Africa, governed as a single country, the <country>Republic of Madagascar</country>.  It is the world's fourth-largest island, with a total area of 587,040 sq km, with 4,828 km of coastline.  Once a French colony, it gained independence from France in 1960.  The name of the government after independence was the <country>Malagasy Republic</country>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>   Formerly an independent kingdom, <country>Madagascar</country> became a French colony in 1886, but regained its independence in 1960. During 1992-93, free presidential and National Assembly elections were held, ending 17 years of single-party rule. In 1997 in the second presidential race, Didier RATSIRAKA, the leader during the 1970s and 1980s, was returned to the presidency.  The Population: is 15,982,563 (July 2001 est.)  The highest point is Maromokotro, at 2,876 m.   Natural resources are: graphite, chromite, coal, bauxite, salt, quartz, tar sands, semiprecious stones, mica, fish, and hydropower.</q> <qau>CIA World Factbook</qau><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>madagascar cat</ent><br/
<hw>madagascar cat</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A small lemur having its tail barred with black.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> ring-tailed lemur, <spn>Lemur catta</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>madagascar jasmine</ent><br/
<hw>madagascar jasmine</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A twining woody vine (<spn>Stephanotis floribunda</spn>) of Madagascar having thick dark waxy evergreen leaves and clusters of large fragrant waxy white flowers along the stems; widely cultivated in warm regions.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> waxflower, <spn>Stephanotis floribunda</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>madagascar pepper</ent><br/
<hw>madagascar pepper</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A climber (<spn>Piper nigrum</spn>) having dark red berries (peppercorns) when fully ripe; found in South India and <country>Sri Lanka</country>; naturalized in North Burma and Assam.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> pepper, common pepper, black pepper, white pepper, Madagascar pepper, <spn>Piper nigrum</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>madagascar periwinkle</ent><br/
<hw>madagascar periwinkle</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A commonly cultivated Old World woody herb (<spn>Vinca rosea</spn>) having large pinkish to red flowers.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> periwinkle, rose periwinkle, Madagascar periwinkle, old maid, Cape periwinkle, red periwinkle, cayenne jasmine, <spn>Catharanthus roseus</spn>, <spn>Vinca rosea</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>madagascar plum</ent><br/
<hw>madagascar plum</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A small shrubby tree (<spn>Flacourtia indica</spn>) of Madagascar cultivated in tropical regions as a hedge plant and for its deep red acid fruits resembling small plums.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> governor's plum, governor plum, Madagascar plum, ramontchi, batoko palm, <spn>Flacourtia indica</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>madake</ent><br/
<hw>madake</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>large bamboo having thick-walled culms; native of China and perhaps Japan; widely brown elsewhere.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> giant timber bamboo, ku-chiku, Phyllostachys bambusoides.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madam</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"am</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Madams</plw>, or <plw>Mesdames</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[See <er>Madame</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A gentlewoman; -- an appellation or courteous form of address given to a lady, especially an elderly or a married lady; -- much used in the address, at the beginning of a letter, to a woman. The corresponding word in addressing a man is <contr>Sir</contr>; often abbreviated <abbr>ma'am</abbr> when used as a term of address.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The woman who is in charge of a household.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The woman who is in charge of a brothel.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madame</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma`dame"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mesdames</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>ma</ets> my (L. <ets>mea</ets>) + <ets>dame</ets> dame. See <er>Dame</er>, and cf. <er>Madonna</er>.]</ety> <def>My lady; -- a French title formerly given to ladies of quality; now, in France, given to all married women.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mad apple</ent><br/
<ent>Mad-apple</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Mad"-ap`ple</hw>, <hw>Mad" ap`ple</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The eggplant bush (<spn>Solanum melongena</spn>).  See <er>Eggplant</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> eggplant, aubergine, brinjal, eggplant bush, garden egg, <spn>Solanum melongena</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The fruit of the eggplant bush, a large egg-shaped vegetable having a shiny skin typically dark purple but occasionally white or yellow.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> eggplant, aubergine.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madbrain</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"brain`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Hot-headed; rash.</def> <au>Shak.</au> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A rash or hot-headed person.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madbrained</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"brained`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Disordered in mind; hot-headed.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madcap</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"cap`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Inclined to wild sports; delighting in rash, absurd, or dangerous amusements.</def> <ldquo/The merry <xex>madcap</xex> lord.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Wild; reckless.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Madcap</xex> follies<rdquo/  <rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madcap</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"cap`</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A person of wild behavior; an excitable, rash, violent person.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madden</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"den</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Maddened</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Maddening</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make mad; to drive to madness; to drive to insanity; to craze.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make very angry; to enrage; to excite violently with passion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madden</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"den</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become mad; to act as if mad.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They rave, recite, and <qex>madden</qex> round the land.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maddened</ent><br/
<hw>maddened</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>filled with or indicating extreme anger.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> angered, enraged, furious, infuriated.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maddening</ent><br/
<hw>maddening</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>extremely annoying or displeasing.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> annoying, exasperating, infuriating, vexing.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madder</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"der</hw> <pr>(m<acr/d"d<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mader</ets>, AS. <ets>maedere</ets>; akin to Icel. <ets>ma<edh/ra</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A plant of the genus <gen>Rubia</gen> (<spn>Rubia tinctorum</spn>).  The root is much used in dyeing red, and formerly was used in medicine.  It is cultivated in France and Holland.  See <er>Rubiaceous</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Madder is sometimes used in forming pigments, as lakes, etc., which receive their names from their colors, such as <prod>madder yellow</prod>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Field madder</b></col>, <cd>an annual European weed (<spn>Sherardia arvensis</spn>) resembling madder.</cd> -- <col><b>Indian madder</b></col> , <cd>the East Indian <spn>Rubia cordifolia</spn>, used in the East for dyeing; -- called also <altname>munjeet</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Wild madder</b></col>, <cd><spn>Rubia peregrina</spn> of Europe; also the <spn>Galium Mollugo</spn>, a kind of bedstraw.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>madder family</ent><br/
<hw>madder family</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A widely distributed natural family of mostly tropical trees and shrubs and herbs including coffee; chinchona; gardenia; madder; bedstraws; nd partridgeberry.</def><br/
<syn>   Rubiaceae, family Rubiaceae, madder family --</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madderwort</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"der*wort`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A name proposed for any plant of the same natural order (<ord>Rubiaceae</ord>) as the madder.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madding</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"ding</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Affected with madness; raging; furious.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mad"ding*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> <mark>[Archaic]</mark></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Far from the <qex>madding</qex> crowd's ignoble strife.</q> <rj><qau>Gray.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>madding</qex> wheels<br/
Of brazen chariots raged.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maddish</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"dish</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Somewhat mad.</def>  <rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mad-dog weed</ent><br/
<ent>mad-dog skullcap</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mad-dog skullcap</hw>, <hw>mad-dog weed</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>An American mint (<spn>Scutellaria lateriflora</spn>) that yields a resinous exudate used esp. formerly as an antispasmodic.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> blue pimpernel, blue skullcap, <spn>Scutellaria lateriflora</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Made</ent><br/
<hw>Made</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Mad</er>, <pos>n.</pos></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Made</ent><br/
<hw>Made</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <def><pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> of <er>Make</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Made</ent><br/
<hw>Made</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Artificially produced; pieced together; formed by filling in; <as>as, <ex>made</ex> ground; a <ex>made</ex> mast, in distinction from one consisting of a single spar.</as></def> <wns>[wns=1]</wns><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>having the sheets and blankets set in order; -- of a bed; <as>as, is the bed <ex>made</ex>?</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>successful or assured of success; <as>as, a self-<ex>made</ex> man</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now I am a made man forever.</q> <rj><qau>Christopher Marlowe</qau></rj><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Made up</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>Complete; perfect</cd>. <ldquo/A <xex>made up</xex> villain.<rdquo/ <au>Shak.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Falsely devised; fabricated; <as>as, a <ex>made up</ex> story</as>.</cd> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>Artificial; <as>as, a <ex>made up</ex> figure or complexion</as>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madecassee</ent><br/
<ent>Madecass</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mad"e*cass</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mad`e*cas"see</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A native or inhabitant of Madagascar, or Madecassee. See <er>Malagasy</er></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The language of the natives of Madagascar.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madecassee</ent><br/
<hw>Mad`e*cas"see</hw>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to Madagascar or its inhabitants; now replaced by <altname>Madagascan</altname>.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark> <br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madefication</ent><br/
<ent>Madefaction</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mad`e*fac"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mad`e*fi*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>madefacere</ets> to make wet; <ets>madere</ets> to be wet + <ets>facere</ets> to make: cf. F. <ets>mad<eacute/faction</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act of madefying, or making wet; the state of that which is made wet.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madefy</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"e*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Madefied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Madefying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mad<eacute/fier</ets>, L. <ets>madefacere</ets>. See <er>Madefaction</er>.]</ety> <def>To make wet or moist.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madegassy</ent><br/
<hw>Mad`e*gas"sy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. & a.</pos> <def>See <er>Madecassee</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madeira</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*dei"ra</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pg., the Island Madeira, properly, wood, fr. L. <ets>materia</ets> stuff, wood. The island was so called because well wooded. See <er>Matter</er>.]</ety> <def>A rich wine made on the Island of Madeira.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A cup of <qex>Madeira</qex>, and a cold capon's leg.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Madeira nut</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the European walnut; the nut of the <spn>Juglans regia</spn>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madeira vine</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*dei"ra vine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A herbaceous climbing vine (<spn>Boussingaultia baselloides</spn>) very popular in cultivation, having shining entire leaves and racemes of small fragrant white flowers.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>madeira winter cherry</ent><br/
<hw>madeira winter cherry</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A small South American shrub (<spn>Solanum pseudocapsicum</spn>) cultivated as a houseplant for its abundant ornamental but poisonous red or yellow cherrylike fruit.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Jerusalem cherry, winter cherry, Madeira winter cherry, <spn>Solanum pseudocapsicum</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madeira wood</ent><br/
<hw>Madeira wood</hw>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The mahogany tree (<spn>Swietenia Mahogoni</spn>).</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A West Indian leguminous tree (<spn>Lysiloma Latisiliqua</spn>) the wood of which is used for boat trimming.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mademoiselle</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma`de*moi`selle"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mesdemoiselles</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>ma</ets> my, f. of <ets>mon</ets> + <ets>demoiselle</ets> young lady. See <er>Damsel</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A French title of courtesy given to a girl or an unmarried lady, equivalent to the English <sig>Miss</sig>.</def>  <rj><au>Goldsmith.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A marine food fish (<spn>Sciaena chrysura</spn>), of the Southern United States; -- called also <altname>yellowtail</altname>, and <altname>silver perch</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>made-to-order</ent><br/
<hw>made-to-order</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>made specially for a specific purpose; -- of articles of manufacture.  Contrasted with <er>mass-produced</er>, <er>standard</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> custom-made.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>made or tailored to fit a specific person; -- of clothing.  Contrasted with <er>off-the-rack</er>, <er>ready-to-wear</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> custom-made, custom-tailored.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>made-up</ent><br/
<hw>made-up</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>formed or conceived by the imagination; not true; <as>as, a <ex>made-up</ex> story</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> fabricated, fancied, fictional, fictitious, invented.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>having been paved.</def> <mark>[British]</mark><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>marked by the use of cosmetic makeup; <as>as, heavily <ex>made-up</ex> eyes</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>formed by fitting or joining components together.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> assembled, built(prenominal).</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madge</ent><br/
<hw>Madge</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. & Prov. F. <ets>machette</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The barn owl.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The magpie.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mad-headed</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"-head`ed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Wild; crack-brained.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madhouse</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"house`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An house or institution where insane persons are confined; an insane asylum; a bedlam; -- usually used in a deprecatory sense.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Bedlam, booby hatch, crazy house, cuckoo's nest, funny farm, funny house, insane asylum, loony bin, nuthouse, sanatorium.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <mark>(fig.)</mark> <def>A chaotic, raucus or highly disordered situation.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma"di*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Sp. <ets>madi</ets>, fr. Chilian <ets>madi</ets>, the native name.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of composite plants, of which one species (<spn>Madia sativa</spn>) is cultivated for the oil yielded from its seeds by pressure.  This oil is sometimes used instead of olive oil for the table.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> melosa, Chile tarweed, madia oil plant, <spn>Madia sativa</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>madia oil</ent><br/
<hw>madia oil</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The vegetable oil obtained from the <spn>Madia sativa</spn>.  See <er>Madia</er> and <er>madia oil plant</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>madia oil plant</ent><br/
<hw>madia oil plant</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The <spn>Madia sativa</spn>, a South American herb with sticky glandular foliage, the source of madia oil.  See <er>Madia</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madid</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"id</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>madidus</ets>, fr. <ets>madere</ets> to be wet.]</ety> <def>Wet; moist; <as>as, a <ex>madid</ex> eye</as>.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <au>Beaconsfield.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madisterium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mad`is*te"ri*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/.]</ety> <fld>(Surg.)</fld> <def>An instrument to extract hairs.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madjoun</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mad"joun</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Hind., fr. Ar. <ets>ma'j<umac/n</ets>.]</ety> <def>An intoxicating confection from the hemp plant; -- used by the Turks and Hindus.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>majoun</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madly</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mad</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>In a mad manner; without reason or understanding; wildly.</def> <wns>[wns=2]</wns><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> insanely, crazily, dementedly.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In a desperate manner; <as>as, she fought back <ex>madly</ex></as>.</def> <wns>[wns=1]</wns><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.6</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>intensely; <as>as, she was <ex>madly</ex> in love</as>.</def> <wns>[wns=3]</wns><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> insanely, deadly, deucedly, devilishly.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.6</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madman</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"man</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Madmen</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>A man who is mad; lunatic; a crazy person.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When a man mistakes his thoughts for person and things, he is mad. A <qex>madman</qex> is properly so defined.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madnep</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"nep</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The masterwort (<spn>Peucedanum Ostruthium</spn>), a tall and coarse European umbelliferous plant.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A biennial weed in Europe and America having large pinnate leaves and yellow flowers and a bitter and somewhat poisonous root; the ancestor of cultivated parsnip; called also <altname>wild parsnip</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madness</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mad</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The condition of being mad; insanity; lunacy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Frenzy; ungovernable rage.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Extreme folly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Insanity; distraction; derangement; craziness; lunacy; mania; frenzy; franticness; rage; aberration; alienation; monomania. See <er>Insanity</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madonna</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*don"na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It. <ets>madonna</ets> my lady. See <er>Dame</er>, <er>Donna</er>, and cf. <er>Madame</er>, <er>Monkey</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>My lady; -- a term of address in Italian formerly used as the equivalent of <xex>Madame</xex>, but for which <xex>Signora</xex> is now substituted. Sometimes introduced into English.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <plu>[<it>pl.</it> <er>Madonnas</er> <pr>(n<adot/z)</pr>.]</plu> <def>A picture of the Virgin Mary (usually with the babe).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Italian painters are noted for drawing the <qex>Madonnas</qex> by their own wives or mistresses.</q> <rj><qau>Rymer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>madonna lily</ent><br/
<hw>madonna lily</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A lily (<spn>Lilium candidum</spn>) of the Eastern Mediterranean and Balkans with broad funnel-shaped white flowers.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> white lily, Annunciation lily, Lent lily, <spn>Lilium candidum</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madoqua</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma"do*qua</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A small Abyssinian antelope (<spn>Neotragus Saltiana</spn>), about the size of a hare.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madrague</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma`drague"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[R.]</ety> <def>A large fish pound used for the capture of the tunny in the Mediterranean; also applied to the seines used for the same purpose.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>madras</ent><br/
<hw>ma*dras"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[So named after <etsep>Madras</etsep>, a city and presidency of India.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A large silk-and-cotton kerchief, usually of bright colors, such as those often used by negroes for turbans.</def></p>

<p><q>A black woman in blue cotton gown, red-and-yellow <qex>madras</qex> turban . . . crouched against the wall.</q>  <rj><qau>G. W. Cable.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A light patterned cotton fabric.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madreperl</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"dre*perl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It. <ets>madreperla</ets>.]</ety> <def>Mother-of-pearl.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 881 --></p>

<p><ent>Madrepora</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mad`re*po"ra</hw> <pr>(m<acr/d`r<esl/*p<omac/"r<adot/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Madrepore</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of reef corals abundant in tropical seas. It includes than one hundred and fifty species, most of which are elegantly branched.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mad`re*po"ral</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madreporaria</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mad`re*po*ra"ri*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Madrepore</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An extensive division of Anthozoa, including most of the species that produce stony corals. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Anthozoa</er>.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mad`re*po*ra"ri*an</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a. & n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madrepore</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"re*pore</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>madrepore</ets>, perh. fr.  <ets>madr<eacute/</ets> spotted, fr. OF. <ets>madre</ets>, <ets>mazre</ets>, a kind of knotty wood with brown spots, fr. OHG. <ets>masar</ets> a knot, grain, or vein in wood, a speck, G. <ets>maser + pore</ets> (see <er>Pore</er>); or perh. F. <ets>madr<eacute/pore</ets> is rather from It. <ets>madrepora</ets>, and this perh. fr. It. <ets>madre</ets> mother (see <er>Mother</er>) + Gr. <?/ a soft stone.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any coral of the genus <gen>Madrepora</gen>, a group of corals having calcareous skeletons aggregations of which form reefs and islands; formerly, often applied to any stony coral.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> stony coral, madriporian coral.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>madriporian coral</ent><br/
<hw>madriporian coral</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A madrepore .</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madreporic</ent><br/
<ent>Madreporian</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mad`re*po"ri*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mad`re*po"ric</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Resembling, or pertaining to, the genus <gen>Madrepora</gen>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Madreporic plate</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a perforated plate in echinoderms, through which water is admitted to the ambulacral tubes; -- called also <altname>madreporic tubercule</altname>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madreporiform</ent><br/
<hw>Mad`re*po"ri*form</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Madrepore</ets> + <ets>-form</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Resembling a madreporian coral in form or structure.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madreporite</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"re*po*rite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>madr<eacute/porite</ets>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>A fossil coral.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The madreporic plate of echinoderms.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madrier</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*drier"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., from Sp. <ets>madero</ets>, or Pg. <ets>madeiro</ets>, fr. Sp. <ets>madera</ets> wood for building, timber, Pg. <ets>madeira</ets>, L. <ets>materia</ets> stuff, materials, lumber. See <er>Matter</er>.]</ety> <def>A thick plank, used for several mechanical purposes</def>; <specif>especially:</specif> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A plank to receive the mouth of a petard, with which it is applied to anything intended to be broken down.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A plank or beam used for supporting the earth in mines or fortifications.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madrigal</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"ri*gal</hw> <pr>(m<acr/d"r<icr/*g<ait/l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It. <ets>madrigale</ets>, OIt. <ets>madriale</ets>, <ets>mandriale</ets> (cf. LL. <ets>matriale</ets>); of uncertain origin, possibly fr. It <ets>mandra</ets> flock, L. <ets>mandra</ets> stall, herd of cattle, Gr. <grk>ma`ndra</grk> fold, stable; hence, <ets>madrigal</ets>, originally, a pastoral song.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A little amorous poem, sometimes called a <altname>pastoral poem</altname>, containing some tender and delicate, though simple, thought.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whose artful strains have oft delayed<br/
 The huddling brook to hear his <qex>madrigal</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>An unaccompanied polyphonic song, in four, five, or more parts, set to secular words, but full of counterpoint and imitation, and adhering to the old church modes.  Unlike the freer glee, it is best sung with several voices on a part. See <er>Glee</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madrigaler</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"ri*gal*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A madrigalist.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madrigalist</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"ri*gal*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A composer of madrigals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madrilenian</ent><br/
<hw>Mad`ri*le"ni*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>Madrile<ntil/o</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to Madrid in Spain, or to its inhabitants.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A native or inhabitant of Madrid.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madrina</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*dri"na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp., prop., a godmother.]</ety> <def>An animal (usually an old mare), wearing a bell and acting as the leader of a troop of pack mules.</def> <mark>[S. America]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>madrono</ent><br/
<ent>madrona</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>ma*dro"na</hw>, <hw>ma*dro"<ntil/a</hw>, <hw>ma*dro"no</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>madro<ntil/o</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A small evergreen tree or shrub (<spn>Arbutus Menziesii</spn>), of Pacific North America, having a smooth bark, thick glossy leathery leaves, and edible orange-red berries, which are often called <prod>madro<ntil/a apples</prod>; the wood is used for furniture and the bark for tanning.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>madro<ntil/o</asp>.]</altsp><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> madrona, manzanita, <spn>Arbutus menziesii</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>madrilene</ent><br/
<hw>madrilene</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a tomato-flavored consomme, often served chilled.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.6</source>]</p>

<p><ent>madwoman</ent><br/
<hw>madwoman</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a woman lunatic.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madwort</ent><br/
<hw>Mad"wort`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of cruciferous plants (<gen>Alyssum</gen>) with white or yellow flowers and rounded pods. <spn>Alyssum maritimum</spn> is the commonly cultivated sweet alyssum, a fragrant white-flowered annual.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maeandra</ent><br/
<hw>Maeandra</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of brain corals.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Maeandra</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mae West</ent><br/
<hw>Mae West</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[after <etsep>Mae West</etsep> (1892-1980) an actress with a well-developed bosom.]</ety> <def>An inflatable life jacket, originally used as a personal flotation device by aviators downed at sea.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> air jacket.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.6</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magbote</ent><br/
<ent>Maegbote</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Maeg"bote`</hw>, <hw>Mag"bote`</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<aemac/g</ets> kinsman + <ets>b<omac/t</ets> compensation.]</ety> <fld>(Anglo-Saxon Law)</fld> <def>Compensation for the injury done by slaying a kinsman.</def>  <rj><au>Spelman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maelstrom</ent><br/
<hw>Mael"strom</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Norw., a whirlpool.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A celebrated whirlpool on the coast of Norway.</def>  <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>any large or powerful whirlpool.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> whirlpool, vortex.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Also</specif> <mark>(Fig.)</mark>  <def>An uncontrollable agitated or confusedly disordered state or situation; <as>as, a <ex>maelstrom</ex> of vice</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maenad</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mae"nad</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>Maenas</ets>, <ets>-adis</ets>, Gr. <?/, <?/, fr. <?/ to rave.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A Bacchante; a priestess or votary of Bacchus.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A frantic or frenzied woman.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maestoso</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma`es*to"so</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a. & adv.</pos> <ety>[It.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Majestic or majestically; -- a direction to perform a passage or piece of music in a dignified manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maestricht monitor</ent><br/
<hw>Maes"tricht mon"i*tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[So called from <ets>Maestricht</ets>, a town in Holland.]</ety> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>The <spn>Mosasaurus Hofmanni</spn>. See <er>Mosasaurus</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maestro</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*es"tro</hw> <pr>(m<imac/s"tr<osl/; <it>It</it>. m<aum/*<asl/s"tr<osl/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It., fr. L. <ets>magister</ets>. See <er>Master</er>.]</ety> <def>A master in any art, especially in music; a composer or orchestra conductor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mafa</ent><br/
<hw>Mafa</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> <pos>prop. n.</pos>.  <fld>(Linguistics)</fld> <def>A Chadic language spoken south of Lake Chad; called also <altname>Matakam</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.6</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mafia</ent><br/
<ent>Maffia</ent><br/
<mhw>{ \'d8<hw>Maf"fi*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, \'d8<hw>Ma"fi*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It. <ets>maffia</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A secret society which organized in Sicily as a political organization, but is now widespread among Italians, and is used to further or protect private interests, reputedly by illegal methods; called also the <altname>Sicilian Mafia</altname>.</def> <wns>[wns=2]</wns><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A group of loosely associated of criminal organizations in the United States, some having ties to the Sicilian Mafia, and organized in <ldquo/families<rdquo/; the term is applied to the entire group of organizations, or to any one local group.  Also, loosely, organized groups of criminals anywhere, as the Russian <ex>mafia</ex>.</def> <wns>[wns=1]</wns><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> syndicate, mob, Cosa Nostra, La Cosa Nostra, organized crime.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.6</source> + <source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Any tightly knit group of trusted associates having strong control or influence in some area; <as>as, Kennedy and his Irish <ex>Mafia</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[informal]</mark> <wns>[wns=3]</wns><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maffick</ent><br/
<hw>maffick</hw> <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>to celebrate publicly with boisterous rejoicing and hilarious and extravagant behavior.</def> <mark>[Chiefly Brit.]</mark> <br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mafioso</ent><br/
<ent>Maffioso</ent><br/
<mhw>{ \'d8<hw>Maf`fi*o"so</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, \'d8<hw>Ma`fi*o"so</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu>pl. <plw>-si</plw> <pr>(#)</pr></plu>. <ety>[It. <ets>maffioso</ets>.]</ety> <def>A member of the mafia.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maffle</ent><br/
<hw>Maf"fle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Akin to OD. <ets>maffelen</ets> to stammer.  Cf. <er>Muffle</er> to mumble.]</ety> <def>To stammer.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maffler</ent><br/
<hw>Maf"fler</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A stammerer.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mafioso</ent><br/
<ent>Mafia</ent><br/
<mhw>{ \'d8<hw>Maf"i*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, \'d8<hw>Ma`fi*o"so</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>see <er>maffia</er>, <er>maffioso</er>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mag</ent><br/
<hw>mag</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Shortened form of <altname>magazine</altname>, the periodic paperback publication.</def> <mark>[slang]</mark> <br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magadhan</ent><br/
<hw>Magadhan</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Linguistics)</fld> <def>A subfamily of Indic languages.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.6</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magazine</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`a*zine"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>magasin</ets>, It. <ets>magazzino</ets>, or Sp. <ets>magacen</ets>, <ets>almagacen</ets>; all fr. Ar. <ets>makhzan</ets>, <ets>almakhzan</ets>, a storehouse, granary, or cellar.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A receptacle in which anything is stored, especially military stores, as ammunition, arms, provisions, etc.</def> <ldquo/Armories and <xex>magazines</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The building or room in which the supply of powder is kept in a fortification or a ship.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A chamber in a gun for holding a number of cartridges to be fed automatically to the piece.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A pamphlet published periodically containing miscellaneous papers or compositions.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A country or district especially rich in natural products.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn>  <def>A city viewed as a marketing center.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn>  <def>A reservoir or supply chamber for a stove, battery, camera, typesetting machine, or other apparatus.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn>  <def>A store, or shop, where goods are kept for sale.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Magazine dress</b></col>, <cd>clothing made chiefly of woolen, without anything metallic about it, to be worn in a powder magazine.</cd> -- <col><b>Magazine gun</b></col>, <cd>a portable firearm, as a rifle, with a chamber carrying cartridges which are brought automatically into position for firing.</cd> -- <col><b>Magazine stove</b></col>, <cd>a stove having a chamber for holding fuel which is supplied to the fire by some self-feeding process, as in the common base-burner.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magazine</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`a*zine"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Magazined</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Magazining</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To store in, or as in, a magazine; to store up for use.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magazine camera</ent><br/
<hw>Magazine camera</hw>. <fld>(Photog.)</fld> <def>A camera in which a number of plates can be exposed without reloading.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magaziner</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`a*zin"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who edits or writes for a magazine.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Goldsmith.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magazine rack</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`a*zine" rack`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A rack or stand for displaying magazines{4}.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.6</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magazining</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`a*zin"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of editing, or writing for, a magazine.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>  <rj><au>Byron.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magazinist</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`a*zin"ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who edits or writes for a magazine.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magbote</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"bote`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Maegbote</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magdala</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"da*la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Designating an orange-red dyestuff obtained from naphthylamine, and called <xex>magdala red</xex>, <xex>naphthalene red</xex>, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magdalen</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"da*len</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From Mary <ets>Magdalene</ets>, traditionally reported to have been the repentant sinner forgiven by Christ. See <ets>Luke</ets> vii. 36.]</ety> <def>A reformed prostitute.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magdaleon</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*da"le*on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ crumb of bread, fr. <?/ to knead.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A medicine in the form of a roll, a esp. a roll of plaster.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magdeburg</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"de*burg</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A city of Saxony.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Magdeburg centuries</b></col>, <col><b>Magdeburg hemispheres</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See under <er>Century</er>, and <er>Hemisphere</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mage</ent><br/
<hw>Mage</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mage</ets>. See <er>Magi</er>.]</ety> <def>A magician.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser. Tennyson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magellanic</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`el*lan"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to, or named from, <person>Ferdinand <etsep>Magellan</etsep></person> (1480-1521), the navigator.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magellanic cloud</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`el*lan"ic cloud</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>Either of two conspicuous celestial nebulae near the south celestial pole, resembling thin white clouds, each of which is a <isa>galaxy</isa>{2} smaller than but separate from the Milky Way galaxy, and together they are the galactic formations nearest to our galaxy.  They are not visible from the northern hemisphere, and are named after <person>Ferdinand <etsep>Magellan</etsep></person>, who saw them in his expedition, which passed through the Strait of Magellan in South America, and one ship of which completed the first circumnavigation of the globe.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magen David</ent><br/
<hw>Magen David</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Hebrew, shield of David.]</ety> <def>A hexagram{1a}, when used as the symbol of Judaism; called also <altname>Mogen David</altname> and <altname>Star of David</altname>.  It is included on the flag of Israel</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Star of David, Mogen David.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magenta</ent><br/
<hw>ma*gen"ta</hw> <pr>(m<adot/*j<ecr/n"t<adot/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>An aniline dye obtained as an amorphous substance having a green bronze surface color, which dissolves to a shade of red; also, the color; -- so called from <etsep>Magenta</etsep>, in Italy, in allusion to the battle fought there about the time the dye was discovered. Called also <altname>fuchsin</altname>, <altname>fuchsine</altname>, <altname>roseine</altname>, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The purplish-red color of magenta.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magged</ent><br/
<hw>Magged</hw> <pr>(m<acr/gd)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>Worn; fretted; <as>as, a <ex>magged</ex> brace</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Ham. Nav. Encyc.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maggiore</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mag`gio"re</hw> <pr>(m<aum/d`j<omac/"r<asl/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[It., from L. <ets>major</ets>, compar. of <ets>magnus</ets> great. See <er>Major</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Greater, in respect to scales, intervals, etc., when used in opposition to <contr>minor</contr>; major.</def>  <rj><au>Moore (Encyc. of Music).</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maggot</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"got</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[W. <ets>macai</ets>, pl. <ets>maceiod</ets>, <ets>magiod</ets>, a worn or grub; cf. <ets>magu</ets> to bread.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The footless larva of any fly. See <er>Larval</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A whim; an odd fancy.</def>  <rj><au>Hudibras. Tennyson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maggotiness</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"got*i*ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>State of being maggoty.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maggotish</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"got*ish</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Full of whims or fancies; maggoty.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maggot-pie</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"got-pie`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A magpie.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maggoty</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"got*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Infested with maggots.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Full of whims; capricious.</def>  <rj><au>Norris.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magh</ent><br/
<hw>Magh</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The eleventh month of the Hindu calendar.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maghet</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"ghet</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Fl. <ets>maghet</ets> maid.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A name for daisies and camomiles of several kinds.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magi</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma"gi</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[L., pl. of <ets>Magus</ets>, Gr. <?/; of Per. origin.  Cf. <er>Mage</er>, <er>Magic</er>.]</ety> <def>A caste of priests, philosophers, and magicians, among the ancient Persians; hence, any holy men or sages of the East.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The inspired <qex>Magi</qex> from the Orient came.</q> <rj><qau>Sandys.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magian</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"gi*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the Magi.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magian</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"gi*an</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One of the Magi, or priests of the Zoroastrian religion in Persia; an adherent of the Zoroastrian religion.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Ma"gi*an*ism</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magic</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>magique</ets>, L. <ets>magice</ets>, Gr. <?/ (sc. <?/), fr. <?/. See <er>Magic</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and <er>Magi</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A comprehensive name for all of the pretended arts which claim to produce effects by the assistance of supernatural beings, or departed spirits, or by a mastery of secret forces in nature attained by a study of occult science, including enchantment, conjuration, witchcraft, sorcery, necromancy, incantation, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An appearance made by some <qex>magic</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The art of creating illusions which appear to the observer to be inexplicable except by some supernatural influence; it includes simple sleight of hand (legerdemain) as well as more elaborate stage magic, using special devices constructed to produce mystifying effects; <as>as, the <ex>magic</ex> of <person>David Copperfield</person></as>.  It is practised as an entertainment, by magicians who do not pretend to have supernatural powers.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Celestial magic</b></col>, <cd>a supposed supernatural power which gave to spirits a kind of dominion over the planets, and to the planets an influence over men.</cd> -- <col><b>Natural magic</b></col>, <cd>the art of employing the powers of nature to produce effects apparently supernatural.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Superstitious magic</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Geotic magic</b></col></mcol>, <cd>the invocation of devils or demons, involving the supposition of some tacit or express agreement between them and human beings.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Sorcery; witchcraft; necromancy; conjuration; enchantment.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magical</ent><br/
<ent>Magic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mag"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mag"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>magicus</ets>, Gr. <?/, fr. <?/: cf. F. <ets>magique</ets>. See <er>Magi</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Pertaining to the hidden wisdom supposed to be possessed by the Magi; relating to the occult powers of nature, and the producing of effects by their agency.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Performed by, or proceeding from, occult and superhuman agencies; done by, or seemingly done by, enchantment or sorcery; <as>as, a <ex>magical</ex> spell</as>.</def> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>Seemingly requiring more than human power; imposing or startling in performance; producing effects which seem supernatural or very extraordinary; having extraordinary properties; <as>as, a <ex>magic</ex> lantern; a <ex>magic</ex> square or circle.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The painter's <qex>magic</qex> skill.</q> <rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Although with certain words <xex>magic</xex> is used more than <xex>magical</xex>, -- as, <xex>magic</xex> circle, <xex>magic</xex> square, <xex>magic</xex> wand, -- we may in general say <xex>magic</xex> or <xex>magical</xex>; as, a <xex>magic</xex> or <xex>magical</xex> effect; a <xex>magic</xex> or <xex>magical</xex> influence, etc. But when the adjective is predicative, <xex>magical</xex>, and not <xex>magic</xex>, is used; as, the effect was <xex>magical</xex>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Magic circle</b></col>, <cd>a series of concentric circles containing the numbers 12 to 75 in eight radii, and having somewhat similar properties to the magic square.</cd> -- <col><b>Magic humming bird</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a Mexican humming bird (<spn>Iache magica</spn>) , having white downy thing tufts.</cd> -- <col><b>Magic lantern</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Lantern</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Magic square</b></col>, <cd>numbers so disposed in parallel and equal rows in the form of a square, that each row, taken vertically, horizontally, or diagonally, shall give the same sum, the same product, or an harmonical series, according as the numbers taken are in arithmetical, geometrical, or harmonical progression.</cd> -- <col><b>Magic wand</b></col>, <cd>a wand used by a magician in performing feats of magic.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magically</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"ic*al*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a magical manner; by magic, or as if by magic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magic bullet</ent><br/
<hw>magic bullet</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From the notion of a <ets>bullet</ets> that will kill only the bacterium or disease it is intended for.]</ety> <def>A drug or therapy or preventive that cures or prevents a disease, with only minimal side effects; <as>as, there is no <ex>magic bullet</ex> against cancer</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magician</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*gi"cian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>magicien</ets>. See <er>Magic</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One skilled in magic; one who practices the black art; an enchanter; a necromancer; a sorcerer or sorceress; a conjurer.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An entertainer who produces seemingly magical effects by clever illusions; most magicians admit that the craft is mere illusion, rather than a true supernatural art.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magic lantern</ent><br/
<hw>magic lantern</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>An early form of <isa>slide projector</isa>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magic spell</ent><br/
<hw>magic spell</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A verbal formula considered to have magical force.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> spell, incantation.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magic trick</ent><br/
<hw>magic trick</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>An feat of illusion performed by an illusionist, which appears magical to naive observers.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> conjuring trick, trick, magic, legerdemain, illusion, deception.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magilph</ent><br/
<ent>Magilp</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Ma*gilp"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Ma*gilph"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Paint.)</fld> <def>See <er>Megilp</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maginot line</ent><br/
<hw>Maginot line</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A line of fortifications built before World War II to protect France's eastern border.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magister</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*gis"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. See <er>Master</er>.]</ety> <def>Master; sir; -- a title of the Middle Ages, given to a person in authority, or to one having a license from a university to teach philosophy and the liberal arts.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magisterial</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`is*te"ri*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>magisterius</ets> magisterial. See <er>Master</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a master or magistrate, or one in authority; having the manner of a magister; official; commanding; authoritative. Hence: Overbearing; dictatorial; dogmatic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When <qex>magisterial</qex> duties from his home<br/
Her father called.</q> <rj><qau>Glover.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We are not <qex>magisterial</qex> in opinions, nor, dictator-like, obtrude our notions on any man.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. Browne.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Pretenses go a great way with men that take fair words and <qex>magisterial</qex> looks for current payment.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Alchem. & Old Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, produced by, or of the nature of, magistery. See <er>Magistery</er>, 2.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Authoritative; stately; august; pompous; dignified; lofty; commanding; imperious; lordly; proud; haughty; domineering; despotic; dogmatical; arrogant.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Magisterial</er>, <er>Dogmatical</er>, <er>Arrogant</er>. One who is <xex>magisterial</xex> assumes the air of a master toward his pupils; one who is <xex>dogmatical</xex> lays down his positions in a tone of authority or dictation; one who is <xex>arrogant</xex> insults others by an undue assumption of superiority.  Those who have long been teachers sometimes acquire, unconsciously, a manner which borders too much on the <xex>magisterial</xex>, and may be unjustly construed as <xex>dogmatical</xex>, or even <xex>arrogant</xex>.</usage><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magisteriality</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`is*te`ri*al"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Magisterialness; authoritativeness.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magisterially</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`is*te"ri*al*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a magisterial manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magisterialness</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`is*te"ri*al*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being magisterial.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magistery</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"is*ter*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>magisterium</ets> the office of a chief, president, director, tutor. See <er>Magistrate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Mastery; powerful medical influence; renowned efficacy; a sovereign remedy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Holland.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A magisterial injunction.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Brougham.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A precipitate; a fine substance deposited by precipitation; -- applied in old chemistry to certain white precipitates from metallic solutions; <as>as, <ex>magistery</ex> of bismuth</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Ure.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magistracy</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"is*tra*cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Magistracies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[From <er>Magistrate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The office or dignity of a magistrate.</def>  <rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The collective body of magistrates.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magistral</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"is*tral</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>magistralis</ets>: cf. F. <ets>magistral</ets>. See <er>Magistrate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Pertaining to a master; magisterial; authoritative; dogmatic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Commanded or prescribed by a magister, esp. by a doctor; hence, effectual; sovereign; <as>as, a <ex>magistral</ex> sirup</as>.</def> <ldquo/Some <xex>magistral</xex> opiate.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Pharmacy)</fld> <def>Formulated extemporaneously, or for a special case; -- opposed to <ant>officinal</ant>, and said of prescriptions and medicines.</def>  <rj><au>Dunglison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Magistral line</b></col> <fld>(Fort.)</fld>, <cd>the guiding line, or outline, by which the form of the work is determined. It is usually the crest line of the parapet in fieldworks, or the top line of the escarp in permanent fortifications.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magistral</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"is*tral</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A sovereign medicine or remedy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Burton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Fort.)</fld> <def>A magistral line.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Metal.)</fld> <def>Powdered copper pyrites used in the amalgamation of ores of silver, as at the Spanish mines of Mexico and South America.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magistrality</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`is*tral"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>-ties</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>Magisterialness; arbitrary dogmatism.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magistrally</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"is*tral*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a magistral manner.</def>  <rj><au>Abp. Bramhall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magistrate</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"is*trate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>magistratus</ets>, fr. <ets>magister</ets> master: cf. F. <ets>magistrat</ets>. See <er>Master</er>.]</ety> <def>A person clothed with power as a public civil officer; a public civil officer invested with the executive government, or some branch of it.</def> <ldquo/All Christian rulers and <xex>magistrates</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Book of Com. Prayer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of <qex>magistrates</qex> some also are supreme, in whom the sovereign power of the state resides; others are subordinate.</q> <rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magistratical</ent><br/
<ent>Magistratic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mag`is*trat"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mag`is*trat"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of, pertaining to, or proceeding from, a magistrate; having the authority of a magistrate.</def>  <rj><au>Jer. Taylor.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magistrature</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"is*tra`ture</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>magistrature</ets>.]</ety> <def>Magistracy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magma</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mag"ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ to squeeze, knead.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Any crude mixture of mineral or organic matters in the state of a thin paste.</def>  <rj><au>Ure.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A thick residuum obtained from certain substances after the fluid parts are expressed from them; the grounds which remain after treating a substance with any menstruum, as water or alcohol.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A salve or confection of thick consistency.</def>  <rj><au>Dunglison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 882 --></p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The molten matter within the earth, the source of the material of lava flows, dikes of eruptive rocks, etc.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The glassy base of an eruptive rock.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>The amorphous or homogenous matrix or ground mass, as distinguished from well-defined crystals; <as>as, the <ex>magma</ex> of porphyry</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magna Charta</ent><br/
<ent>Magna Carta</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Mag"na Car"ta</hw>, <hw>Mag"na Char"ta</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[L., great charter.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The great Charter, so called, obtained by the English barons from King John, <sc>A. D.</sc> 1215.  This name is also given to the charter granted to the people of England in the ninth year of <person>Henry III.</person>, and confirmed by <person>Edward I.</person></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, a fundamental constitution which guaranties rights and privileges.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnality</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*nal"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>magnalis</ets> mighty, fr. <ets>magnus</ets> great.]</ety> <def>A great act or event; a great attainment.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magna Mater</ent><br/
<hw>Magna Mater</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A great nature goddess of ancient Phrygia in Asia Minor; the counterpart of the Greek <altname>Rhea</altname> and the Roman <altname>Ops</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Cybele, Dindymene, Great Mother, Mater Turrita.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnanimity</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`na*nim"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>magnanimit<eacute/</ets>, L. <ets>magnanimitas</ets>.]</ety> <def>The quality of being magnanimous; greatness of mind; elevation or dignity of soul; that quality or combination of qualities, in character, which enables one to encounter danger and trouble with tranquility and firmness, to disdain injustice, meanness and revenge, and to act and sacrifice for noble objects.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnanimous</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*nan"i*mous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos><ety>[L. <ets>magnanimus</ets>; <ets>magnus</ets> great + <ets>animus</ets> mind. See <er>Magnate</er>, and <er>Animus</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Great of mind; elevated in soul or in sentiment; raised above what is low, mean, or ungenerous; of lofty and courageous spirit; <as>as, a <ex>magnanimous</ex> character; a <ex>magnanimous</ex> conqueror.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Be <qex>magnanimous</qex> in the enterprise.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To give a kingdom hath been thought<br/
Greater and nobler done, and to lay down<br/
Far more <qex>magnanimous</qex> than to assume.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Dictated by or exhibiting nobleness of soul; honorable; noble; not selfish.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Both strived for death; <qex>magnanimous</qex> debate.</q> <rj><qau>Stirling.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is an indissoluble union between a <qex>magnanimous</qex> policy and the solid rewards of public prosperity and felicity.</q> <rj><qau>Washington.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnanimously</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*nan"i*mous*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a magnanimous manner; with greatness of mind.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnase black</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"nase black`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Paint.)</fld> <def>A black pigment which dries rapidly when mixed with oil, and is of intense body.</def>  <rj><au>Fairholt.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnate</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <ety>[F. <ets>magnat</ets>, L. (pl.) <ets>magnates</ets>, <ets>magnati</ets>, fr. <ets>magnus</ets> great. See <er>Master</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A person of rank; a noble or grandee; a person of influence or distinction in any sphere; -- used mostly of prominent business executives; <as>as, an industrial <ex>magnate</ex></as>.</def>  <rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One of the nobility, or certain high officers of state belonging to the noble estate in the national representation of Hungary, and formerly of Poland.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnes</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"nes</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.]</ety> <def>Magnet.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnesia</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*ne"si*a</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>Magnesia</ets>, fem. of <ets>Magnesius</ets> of the country Magnesia, Gr. <grk>h` Magnhsi`a li`qos</grk> a magnet.  Cf. <er>Magnet</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A light earthy white substance, consisting of magnesium oxide (<chform>MgO</chform>), and obtained by heating magnesium hydrate or carbonate, or by burning magnesium.  It has a slightly alkaline reaction, and is used in medicine as a mild antacid laxative. See <er>Magnesium</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Magnesia alba</b></col> <ety>[L.]</ety> <fld>(Med. Chem.)</fld>, <cd>a bulky white amorphous substance, consisting of a hydrous basic carbonate of magnesium, and used as a mild cathartic.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnesian</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*ne"sian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to, characterized by, or containing, magnesia or magnesium.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Magnesian limestone</b></col>.  <fld>(Min.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Dolomite</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnesic</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*ne"sic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or containing, magnesium; <as>as, <ex>magnesic</ex> oxide</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnesite</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"ne*site</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>magn<eacute/site</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Native magnesium carbonate occurring in white compact or granular masses, and also in rhombohedral crystals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnesium</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*ne"si*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. & F. See <er>Magnesia</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A light silver-white metallic element of atomic number 12, malleable and ductile, quite permanent in dry air but tarnishing in moist air. It burns, forming (the oxide) magnesia, with the production of a blinding light (the so-called <xex>magnesium light</xex>) which is used in signaling, in pyrotechny, or in photography where a strong actinic illuminant is required. Its compounds occur abundantly, as in dolomite, talc, meerschaum, etc.  Symbol Mg.  Atomic weight, 24.305.  Specific gravity, 1.75.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Magnesium sulphate</b></col>. <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <cd>Same as <er>Epsom salts</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnesium hydroxide</ent><br/
<hw>magnesium hydroxide</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A slightly alkaline chemical substance, <chform>Mg(OH)2</chform>, the active principle in the antacid <partof>milk of magnesia</partof>, also used as a laxative.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnesium oxide</ent><br/
<hw>magnesium oxide</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Magnesia.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnet</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"net</hw> <pr>(m<acr/g"n<ecr/t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>magnete</ets>, OF. <ets>magnete</ets>, L. <ets>magnes</ets>, <ets>-etis</ets>, Gr. <grk>Magnh^tis li`qos</grk> a magnet, metal that looked like silver, prop., Magnesian stone, fr. Gr. <grk>Magnhsi`a</grk>, a country in Thessaly.  Cf. <er>Magnesia</er>, <er>Manganese</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The loadstone; a species of iron ore (the ferrosoferric or magnetic ore, <chform>Fe3O4</chform>) which has the property of attracting iron and some of its ores, and, when freely suspended, of pointing to the poles; -- called also <altname>natural magnet</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Dinocrates began to make the arched roof of the temple of Arsino<eum/ all of <qex>magnet</qex>, or this loadstone.</q> <rj><qau>Holland.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Two <qex>magnets</qex>, heaven and earth, allure to bliss,<br/
The larger loadstone that, the nearer this.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>A bar or mass of steel or iron to which the peculiar properties of the loadstone have been imparted; -- called, in distinction from the loadstone, an <altname>artificial magnet</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ An artificial magnet, produced by the action of an electrical current, is called an <stype>electro-magnet</stype>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Field magnet</b></col> <fld>(Physics & Elec.)</fld>, <cd>a magnet used for producing and maintaining a magnetic field; -- used especially of the stationary or exciting magnet of a dynamo or electromotor in distinction from that of the moving portion or armature.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnetical</ent><br/
<ent>Magnetic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mag*net"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mag*net"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>magneticus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>magn<eacute/tique</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Pertaining to the magnet; possessing the properties of the magnet, or corresponding properties; <as>as, a <ex>magnetic</ex> bar of iron; a <ex>magnetic</ex> needle.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to, or characterized by, the earth's magnetism; <as>as, the <ex>magnetic</ex> north; the <ex>magnetic</ex> meridian.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Capable of becoming a magnet; susceptible to magnetism; <as>as, the <ex>magnetic</ex> metals</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Endowed with extraordinary personal power to excite the feelings and to win the affections; attractive; inducing attachment.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She that had all <qex>magnetic</qex> force alone.</q> <rj><qau>Donne.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Having, susceptible to, or induced by, animal magnetism, so called; hypnotic; <as>as, a <ex>magnetic</ex> sleep</as>. See <er>Magnetism</er>.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark> <br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Magnetic amplitude</b></col>, <col><b>attraction</b></col>, <col><b>dip</b></col>, <col><b>induction</b></col></mcol>, <cd>etc. See under <er>Amplitude</er>, <er>Attraction</er>, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Magnetic battery</b></col>, <cd>a combination of bar or horseshoe magnets with the like poles adjacent, so as to act together with great power.</cd> -- <col><b>Magnetic compensator</b></col>, <cd>a contrivance connected with a ship's compass for compensating or neutralizing the effect of the iron of the ship upon the needle.</cd> -- <col><b>Magnetic curves</b></col>, <cd>curves indicating lines of magnetic force, as in the arrangement of iron filings between the poles of a powerful magnet.</cd> -- <col><b>Magnetic elements</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Chem. Physics)</fld> <cd>Those elements, as iron, nickel, cobalt, chromium, manganese, etc., which are capable or becoming magnetic.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <cd>In respect to terrestrial magnetism, the declination, inclination, and intensity</cd>. <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>See under <er>Element</er>.</cd>  -- <col><b>Magnetic fluid</b></col>, <cd>the hypothetical fluid whose existence was formerly assumed in the explanations of the phenomena of magnetism; -- no longer considered a meaningful concept.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Magnetic iron</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Magnetic iron ore</b></col></mcol>. <fld>(Min.)</fld> <cd>Same as <er>Magnetite</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Magnetic needle</b></col>, <cd>a slender bar of steel, magnetized and suspended at its center on a sharp-pointed pivot, or by a delicate fiber, so that it may take freely the direction of the magnetic meridian.  It constitutes the essential part of a compass, such as the mariner's and the surveyor's.</cd> -- <col><b>Magnetic poles</b></col>, <cd>the two points in the opposite polar regions of the earth at which the direction of the dipping needle is vertical.</cd> -- <col><b>Magnetic pyrites</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Pyrrhotite</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Magnetic storm</b></col> <fld>(Terrestrial Physics)</fld>, <cd>a disturbance of the earth's magnetic force characterized by great and sudden changes.</cd> -- <col><b>magnetic tape</b></col> <fld>(Electronics)</fld>, <cd>a ribbon of plastic material to which is affixed a thin layer of powder of a material which can be magnetized, such as ferrite.  Such tapes are used in various electronic devices to record fluctuating voltages, which can be used to represent sounds, images, or binary data.  Devices such as audio casette recorders, videocasette recorders, and computer data storage devices use <ex>magnetic tape</ex> as an inexpensive medium to store data.  Different magnetically susceptible materials are used in such tapes.</cd> -- <col><b>Magnetic telegraph</b></col>, <cd>a telegraph acting by means of a magnet. See <er>Telegraph</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnetic</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*net"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A magnet.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As the <qex>magnetic</qex> hardest iron draws.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any metal, as iron, nickel, cobalt, etc., which may receive, by any means, the properties of the loadstone, and which then, when suspended, fixes itself in the direction of a magnetic meridian.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnetically</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*net"ic*al*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>By or as by, magnetism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magneticalness</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*net"ic*al*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Quality of being magnetic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic bottle</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic bottle</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>Any configuration of magnetic fields used to contain a plasma during controlled thermonuclear reactions.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic compass</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic compass</hw> <pos>n.</pos>  <def>An device using a magnet (such as a magnetic needle) to indicate the direction of magnetic north.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic declination</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic declination</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The angle (at a particular location) between magnetic north and true north; called also <altname>magnetic variation</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic dip</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic dip</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The angle that a magnetic needle makes with the plane of the horizon.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> dip, angle of dip, magnetic inclination, inclination.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic dipole</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic dipole</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A dipole with opposing magnetic poles.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic dipole moment</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic dipole moment</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A physical quantity associated with the magnetic field of a dundamental particle; <as>as, An orbiting electron in an atom will have a <ex>magnetic dipole moment</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic disk</ent><br/
<ent>magnetic disc</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>magnetic disc</hw>, <hw>magnetic disk</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A ditical memory device consisting of a flat disk covered with a magnetic coating on which information is stored; a <stype>hard disk</stype>, <stype>floppy disk</stype>, and <stype>diskette</stype> are typically magnetic disks.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> disk, disc.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic equator</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic equator</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>An imaginary line paralleling the equator where a magnetic needle has no dip, the dipping needle being horizontal; called also <altname>aclinic line</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic field</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic field</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>The space around a magnet through which it exerts magnetic force; a field of force surrounding a permanent magnet, electrical current, or a moving charged particle; called also <altname>magnetic flux</altname> and <altname>field of magnetic force</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic field strength</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic field strength</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The amount of magnetic flux in a unit area perpendicular to the direction of magnetic flow.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> magnetic intensity, magnetic induction, magnetic flux density.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic flux</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic flux</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A measure of the strength of a magnetic field over a given area.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Same as <er>magnetic field</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic flux density</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic flux density</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The amount of magnetic flux in a unit area perpendicular to the direction of magnetic flow.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> magnetic field strength, magnetic intensity, magnetic induction.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic force</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic force</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The force caused by a magnetic field, a force which affects objects having a magnetic field and objects in which a magnetic field can be induced, such as ferromagnetic substances; a magnetic force manifests itself as an attraction for iron. It is associated with electric currents and moving charged paticles as well as permanent magnets.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> magnetism, magnetic attraction.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic head</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic head</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Electronics)</fld> <def>An electromagnet (as on a tape recorder) that converts electrical variations into magnetic variations that can be stored on a magnetizable surface and later retrieved.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnetician</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`ne*ti"cian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One versed in the science of magnetism; a magnetist.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic inclination</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic inclination</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>magnetic dip</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic induction</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic induction</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The process that makes a substance magnetic (temporarily or permanently).</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> magnetization, magnetisation.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Same as <er>magnetic field strength</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> magnetic intensity, magnetic flux density.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic intensity</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic intensity</hw> <fld>(Physics)</fld>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>magnetic field strength</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> magnetic flux density.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic iron-ore</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic iron-ore</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Magnetite.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic levitation</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic levitation</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The process of supporting an object, such as a vehicle, with a magnetic field so that it does not contact the object supporting it; it is a method used for eliminating friction in moving vehicles, and is used, e.g. in high-speed rail technology where a train is suspended on a magnetic cushion above a magnetized track and so travels free of friction.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic line of force</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic line of force</hw> <fld>(Physics)</fld>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A line of force in a magnetic field.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic meridian</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic meridian</hw> <fld>(Physics)</fld>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An imaginary line passing through both magnetic poles of the earth.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic mine</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic mine</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A marine mine that is detonated by a mechanism that detects the nearness of magnetic material (as the steel hull of a ship).  A <stype>magnetic counter mine</stype> may allow the passagw of several ships before detonating.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic moment</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic moment</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The torque exerted on a magnet or dipole when it is placed in a magnetic field.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> moment of a magnet.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic monopole</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic monopole</hw> <fld>(Physics)</fld>, <def>a hypothetical subatomic particle having only one type of magnetic charge, the magnetic analogue of an electrically charged particle; it has only one magnetic pole instead of the two observed in all common magnetic object; -- it was still not observed as of 1998.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic needle</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic needle</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A slender magnet suspended in a magnetic compass on a low-friction mounting; used to indicate the direction of the earth's magnetic pole.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic north</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic north</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The direction in which the north-pointing end of a compass needle points; at low latitudes it is close to geographic (true) north, but deviates substantially from true north as one nears the north pole.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> north, compass north.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magneticness</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*net"ic*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Magneticalness.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic pole</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic pole</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Either of two points where the lines of force of the earth's magnetic field are vertical.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One of the two ends of a magnet where the magnetic field is strongest.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic recorder</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic recorder</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A device for making records (of sound, data, etc.) on magnetic media such as magnetic tape or wire.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic resonance</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic resonance</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>A phenomenon resulting from quantization in the magnetic field of electrons or atoms or molecules or nuclei exposed to an external magnetic field, by which a narrow frequency band of radio waves may be absorbed and re-emitted by the object.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic resonance imaging</ent><br/
<hw>mag*net"ic res"on*ance im"ag*ing</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Medicine)</fld>  <def>a medical diagnostic procedure utilizing the phenomenon of <er>nuclear magnetic resonance</er> to generate images of internal parts of the body.  It depends on the differential absorption of electromagnetic radiation by different types of living tissue in a magnetic field.  It is complementary to X-ray imaging in that the softer tissue show more prominently in magnetic resonance images, rather than bone, as with X-rays.  It is a non-invasive procedure, allowing such images to be obtained without penetration of the tissue by objects.  It is abbreviated <altname>MRI</altname>.  As with <er>computerized tomography</er>, the results are usually presented as images of sequential planar sections of that part of the body of concern to the physician.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnetics</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*net"ics</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The science of magnetism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic storm</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic storm</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A sudden disturbance of the earth's magnetic field; caused by emission of particles from the sun.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic tape</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic tape</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A long thin plastic ribbon coated with iron oxide or other ferromagnetic material, used to record audio or video signals digital data in the form of small magnetized regions on the tape; it is a common <isa>digital data storage medium</isa> for computer information.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mag tape, tape.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetic variation</ent><br/
<hw>magnetic variation</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>magnetic declination</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnetiferous</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`net*if"er*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>magnes</ets>, <ets>-etis</ets> + <ets>-ferous</ets>.]</ety> <def>Producing or conducting magnetism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnetism</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"net*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>magn<eacute/tisme</ets>.]</ety> <def>The property, quality, or state, of being magnetic; the manifestation of the force in nature which is seen in a magnet.  At one time it was believed to be separate from the electrical force, but it is now known to be intimately associated with electricity, as part of the phenomenon of <er>electromagnetism</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The science which treats of magnetic phenomena.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Power of attraction; power to excite the feelings and to gain the affections.</def> <ldquo/By the <xex>magnetism</xex> of interest our affections are irresistibly attracted.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Glanvill.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Animal magnetism</b></col>, <cd>Same as <er>hypnotism</er>, at one time believe to be due to a force more or less analogous to magnetism, which, it was alleged, is produced in animal tissues, and passes from one body to another with or without actual contact.  The existence of such a force, and its potentiality for the cure of disease, were asserted by <persfn>Mesmer</persfn> in 1775.  His theories and methods were afterwards called <xex>mesmerism</xex>, a name which has been popularly applied to theories and claims not put forward by Mesmer himself. See <er>Mesmerism</er>, <er>Biology</er>, <er>Od</er>, <er>Hypnotism</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Terrestrial magnetism</b></col>, <cd>the magnetic force exerted by the earth, and recognized by its effect upon magnetized needles and bars.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnetist</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"net*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One versed in magnetism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnetite</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"net*ite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>An oxide of iron (<chform>Fe3O4</chform>) occurring in isometric crystals, also massive, of a black color and metallic luster.  It is readily attracted by a magnet and sometimes possesses polarity, being then called <stype>loadstone</stype>.  It is an important iron ore.  Called also <altname>magnetic iron</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnetizable</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"net*i`za*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Capable of being magnetized.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnetization</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`net*i*za"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of magnetizing, or the state of being magnetized.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnetize</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"net*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Magnetized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>prep. & adv.</pos> <conjf>Magnetizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>magn<eacute/tiser</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To communicate magnetic properties to; to make magnetic; <as>as, to <ex>magnetize</ex> a needle</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To attract as a magnet attracts, or like a magnet; to move; to influence.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fascinated, <qex>magnetized</qex>, as it were, by his character.</q> <rj><qau>Motley.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To bring under the influence of animal magnetism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnetizee</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`net*i*zee"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A person subjected to the influence of animal magnetism.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnetizer</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"net*i`zer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who, or that which, imparts magnetism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magneto</ent><br/
<hw>mag*ne"to</hw> <pr>(m<acr/g*n<emac/"t<osl/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>  <def>A small electric generator with an armature rotating in a magnetic field, having a secondary winding that generates a high voltage, such as one used to generate a voltage sufficient to cause a spark to jump between the poles of a spark plug in an internal-combustion engine.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magneto-</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"net*o-</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>pref.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Magnet</er>.]</ety> <def>A prefix meaning <xex>pertaining to</xex>, <xex>produced by</xex>, or in some way <xex>connected with</xex>, magnetism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magneto-electrical</ent><br/
<ent>Magneto-electric</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mag`net*o-e*lec"tric</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mag`net*o-e*lec"tric*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or characterized by, electricity by the action of magnets; <as>as, <ex>magneto-electric</ex> induction</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Magneto-electric machine</b></col>, <cd>a form of dynamo-electric machine in which the field is maintained by permanent steel magnets instead of electro-magnets.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magneto-electricity</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`net*o-e`lec*tric"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Electricity evolved by the action of magnets.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>That branch of science which treats of the development of electricity by the action of magnets; -- the counterpart of <xex>electro-magnetism</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnetograph</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*net"o*graph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Magneto-</ets> + <ets>-graph</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>An automatic instrument for registering, by photography or otherwise, the states and variations of any of the terrestrial magnetic elements.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetohydrodynamics</ent><br/
<hw>mag*net"o*hy`dro*dy*nam"ics</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The study of the interaction of magnetic fields with electrically conductive fluids, such as a plasma or a molten metal.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnetometer</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`net*om"e*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Magneto-</ets>  + <ets>-meter</ets>: cf. F. <ets>magn<eacute/tom<egrave/tre</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>An instrument for measuring the intensity of magnetic forces; also, less frequently, an instrument for determining any of the terrestrial magnetic elements, as the dip and declination.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnetometric</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`net*o*met"ric</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to, or employed in, the measurement of magnetic forces; obtained by means of a magnetometer; <as>as, <ex>magnetometric</ex> instruments; <ex>magnetometric</ex> measurements.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnetomotive</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`net*o*mo"tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>  <ety>[<ets>Magneto-</ets> + <ets>motive</ets>, a.]</ety> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or designating, a force producing magnetic flux, analogous to electromotive force, and equal to the magnetic flux multiplied by the magnetic reluctance.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetomotive force</ent><br/
<hw>magnetomotive force</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The force that produces magnetic flux.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnetomotor</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`net*o*mo"tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A voltaic series of two or more large plates, producing a great quantity of electricity of low tension, and hence adapted to the exhibition of electro-magnetic phenomena.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magneton</ent><br/
<hw>mag"net*on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A unit of magnetic moment for a subatomic particle, atom, or molecule.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetosphere</ent><br/
<hw>mag*net"o*sphere</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>the magnetic field of a planet; the volume around the planet in which charged particles are subject more to the planet's magnetic field than to the solar magnetic field.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.6</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnetotherapy</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`net*o*ther"a*py</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>The treatment of disease by the application of magnets to the surface of the body.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnetron</ent><br/
<hw>mag"ne*tron</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>a diode vacuum tube in which the flow of electrons from a central cathode to a cylindrical anode is controlled by crossed magnetic and electric fields; used mainly in microwave oscillators.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnifiable</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"ni*fi`a*ble</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Magnify</er>.]</ety> <def>Such as can be magnified, or extolled.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnifical</ent><br/
<ent>Magnific</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mag*nif"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mag*nif"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>magnificus</ets>; <ets>magnus</ets> great + <ets>facere</ets> to make: cf. F. <ets>magnifique</ets>. See <er>Magnitude</er>, <er>Fact</er>. and cf. <er>Magnificent</er>.]</ety> <def>Grand; splendid; illustrious; magnificent.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>1 Chron. xxii. 5.</au> <ldquo/Thy <xex>magnific</xex> deeds.<rdquo/ <au>Milton.</au> -- <wordforms><wf>Mag*nif"ic*al*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> <mark>[Obs.]</mark></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnificat</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mag*nif"i*cat</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., it magnifies.]</ety> <def>The song of the Virgin Mary, <au>Luke i. 46</au>; -- so called because it commences with this word in the Vulgate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnificate</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*nif"i*cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>magnificatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>magnificare</ets>.]</ety> <def>To magnify or extol.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Marston.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnification</ent><br/
<hw>Mag`ni*fi*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of magnifying; enlargement; exaggeration.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnificence</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*nif"i*cence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>magnificence</ets>, L. <ets>magnificentia</ets>. See <er>Magnific</er>.]</ety> <def>The act of doing what is magnificent; the state or quality of being magnificent.</def> <au>Acts xix. 27.</au> <ldquo/Then cometh <xex>magnificence</xex>.<rdquo/ <au>Chaucer.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And, for the heaven's wide circuit, let it speak<br/
The Maker's high <qex>magnificence</qex>, who built<br/
so spacious.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The noblest monuments of Roman <qex>magnificence.</qex></q> <rj><qau>Eustace.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnificent</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*nif"i*cent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Magnificence</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Doing grand things; admirable in action; displaying great power or opulence, especially in building, way of living, and munificence.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A prince is never so <qex>magnificent</qex><br/
As when he's sparing to enrich a few<br/
With the injuries of many.</q> <rj><qau>Massinger.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Grand in appearance; exhibiting grandeur or splendor; splendid; pompous.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When Rome's exalted beauties I descry<br/
<qex>Magnificent</qex> in piles of ruin lie.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Glorious; majestic; sublime. See <er>Grand</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnificently</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*nif"i*cent*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a Magnificent manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnifico</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*nif"i*co</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Magnificoes</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[It. See <er>Magnific</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A grandee or nobleman of Venice; -- so called in courtesy.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A rector of a German university.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnified</ent><br/
<hw>magnified</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>enlarged to an abnormal degree.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> exaggerated, enlarged.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnifier</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"ni*fi`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who, or that which, magnifies.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnify</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"ni*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Magnified</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Magnifying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>magnifien</ets>, F. <ets>magnifier</ets>, L. <ets>magnificare</ets>. See <er>Magnific</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make great, or greater; to increase the dimensions of; to amplify; to enlarge, either in fact or in appearance; <as>as, the microscope <ex>magnifies</ex> the object by a thousand diameters</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The least error in a small quantity . . . will in a great one . . . be proportionately <qex>magnified</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Grew.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To increase the importance of; to augment the esteem or respect in which one is held.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On that day the Lord <qex>magnified</qex> Joshua in the sight of all Israel.</q> <rj><qau>Joshua iv. 14.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To praise highly; to laud; to extol.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O, <qex>magnify</qex> the Lord with me, and let us exalt his name together.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. xxxiv. 3.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To exaggerate; <as>as, to <ex>magnify</ex> a loss or a difficulty</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To magnify one's self</b></col> <fld>(Script.)</fld>, <cd>to exhibit pride and haughtiness; to boast.</cd> -- <col><b>To magnify one's self against</b></col> <fld>(Script.)</fld>, <cd>to oppose with pride.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnify</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"ni*fy</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To have the power of causing objects to appear larger than they really are; to increase the apparent dimensions of objects; <as>as, some lenses <ex>magnify</ex> but little</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To have effect; to be of importance or significance.</def> <mark>[Cant & Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spectator.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnifying glass</ent><br/
<hw>magnifying glass</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A single convex lens which magnifies the apparent dimensions of objects seen through it, and is used to produce an enlarged image.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> hand glass.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magniloquence</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*nil"o*quence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>magniloquentia</ets>.]</ety> <def>The quality of being magniloquent; pompous discourse; grandiloquence.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magniloquent</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*nil"o*quent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>magnus</ets> great + <ets>loquens</ets>, <ets>-entis</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>loqui</ets> to speak. See <er>Magnitude</er>, <er>Loquacious</er>.]</ety> <def>Speaking pompously; using swelling discourse; bombastic; tumid in style; grandiloquent.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mag*nil"o*quent*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magniloquous</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*nil"o*quous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>magniloquus</ets>.]</ety> <def>Magniloquent.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnitude</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"ni*tude</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>magnitudo</ets>, from <ets>magnus</ets> great. See <er>Master</er>, and cf. <er>Maxim</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Extent of dimensions; size; -- applied to things that have length, breadth, and thickness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Conceive those particles of bodies to be so disposed amongst themselves, that the intervals of empty spaces between them may be equal in <qex>magnitude</qex> to them all.</q> <rj><qau>Sir I. Newton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>That which has one or more of the three dimensions, length, breadth, and thickness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Anything of which greater or less can be predicated, as time, weight, force, and the like.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 883 --></p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Greatness; grandeur.</def> <ldquo/With plain, heroic <xex>magnitude</xex> of mind.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Greatness, in reference to influence or effect; importance; <as>as, an affair of <ex>magnitude</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>magnitude</qex> of his designs.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Horsley.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>See <cref>magnitude of a star</cref>, below.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Apparent magnitude</b></col> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Opt.)</fld>, <cd>the angular breadth of an object viewed as measured by the angle which it subtends at the eye of the observer; -- called also <altname>apparent diameter</altname>.</cd> <sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <cd>Same as <cref>magnitude of a star</cref>, below.</cd> -- <col><b>Magnitude of a star</b></col> <fld>(Astron.)</fld>, <cd>the rank of a star with respect to brightness. About twenty very bright stars are said to be of first magnitude, the stars of the sixth magnitude being just visible to the naked eye; called also <altname>visual magnitude</altname>, <altname>apparent magnitude</altname>, and simply <altname>magnitude</altname>.  Stars observable only in the telescope are classified down to below the twelfth magnitude.  The difference in actual brightness between magnitudes is now specified as a factor of 2.512, i.e. the difference in brightness is 100 for stars differing by five magnitudes.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnolia</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*no"li*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. Named after Pierre <etsep>Magnol</etsep>, professor of botany at Montpellier, France, in the 17th century.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of American and Asiatic trees, with aromatic bark and large sweet-scented whitish or reddish flowers.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <spn>Magnolia grandiflora</spn> has coriaceous shining leaves and very fragrant blossoms. It is common from North Carolina to Florida and Texas, and is one of the most magnificent trees of the American forest. The sweet bay (<spn>Magnolia glauca</spn>)is a small tree found sparingly as far north as Cape Ann.  Other American species are <spn>Magnolia Umbrella</spn>, <spn>Magnolia macrophylla</spn>, <spn>Magnolia Fraseri</spn>, <spn>Magnolia acuminata</spn>, and <spn>Magnolia cordata</spn>.  <spn>Magnolia conspicua</spn> and <spn>Magnolia purpurea</spn> are cultivated shrubs or trees from Eastern Asia. <spn>Magnolia Campbellii</spn>, of India, has rose-colored or crimson flowers.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Magnolia warbler</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a beautiful North American wood warbler (<spn>Dendroica maculosa</spn>).  The rump and under parts are bright yellow; the breast and belly are spotted with black; the under tail coverts are white; the crown is ash.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnoliaceae</ent><br/
<hw>Magnoliaceae</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A natural family of plants, a subclass of the Magnoliidae; it includes the genera <gen>Liriodendron</gen>; <gen>Magnolia</gen>; <gen>Manglietia</gen>; and <gen>Michelia</gen>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Magnoliaceae</fam>, magnolia family.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnoliaceous</ent><br/
<hw>Mag*no`li*a"ceous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to a natural order (<ord>Magnoliaceae</ord>) of trees of which the magnolia, the tulip tree, and the star anise are examples.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnolia State</ent><br/
<hw>Magnolia State</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The state of Mississippi; -- a nickname.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnoliidae</ent><br/
<hw>Magnoliidae</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a group of families of trees and shrubs and herbs having well-developed perianths and apocarpous ovaries and generally regarded as the most primitive extant flowering plants; contains 36 families including <fam>Magnoliaceae</fam> and <fam>Ranunculaceae</fam>; sometimes classified as a superorder.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> subclass Magnoliidae, ranalian complex.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnoliophyta</ent><br/
<hw>Magnoliophyta</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A class of flowering plants that produce seeds enclosed in an ovary; in some systems considered a class (<class>Angiospermae</class>) and in others a division (Magnoliophyta or Anthophyta).</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Angiospermae, class <class>Angiospermae</class>, division Magnoliophyta, Anthophyta, division Anthophyta.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnoliopsid</ent><br/
<hw>magnoliopsid</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A flowering plant.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> dicot, dicotyledon.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnoliopsida</ent><br/
<hw>Magnoliopsida</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A class of seed plants that produce an embryo with two cotyledons and net-veined leaves; divided into six (not always well distinguished) subclasses (or superorders): Magnoliidae and Hamamelidae (considered primitive); Caryophyllidae (an early and distinctive offshoot); and three more or less advanced groups: Dilleniidae; Rosidae; Asteridae.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Dicotyledones, class Dicotyledones, Dicotyledonae, class Dicotyledonae, class Magnoliopsida.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnum</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"num</hw> <pr>(m<acr/g"n<ucr/m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Neut. sing. of L. <ets>magnus</ets> great.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A large wine bottle.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They passed the <qex>magnum</qex> to one another freely.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A bone of the carpus at the base of the third metacarpal bone.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A magnum pistol, or the cartridge such a pistol uses; <as>as, he always carried a .44 <ex>magnum</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnum</ent><br/
<hw>mag"num</hw> <pr>(m<acr/g"n<ucr/m)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Firearms)</fld> <def>Having a larger charge than usual for a cartridge of the same caliber; -- of cartridges for handgun; <as>as, a .44 <ex>magnum</ex> cartridge</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Firearms)</fld> <def>Designed to use a cartridge with a larger charge than usual for handguns of the same caliber; -- of handguns; <as>as, a .44 <ex>magnum</ex> pistol</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnum opus</ent><br/
<hw>mag"num o"pus</hw> <pr>(m<acr/g"n<ucr/m <omac/"p<ucr/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A great work of art or literature.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The greatest work or achievement of a particular artist, writer, or other individual.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>Inspired by this milieu, [Max Stirner] wrote his <qex>magnum opus</qex> <it>The Ego and Its Own</it>, which was published in November 1844.</q> <rj><qau>Svein Nyberg (The Small Max Stirner Web Page, 1988 [http://www.math.uio.no/~solan/stirner/stirner.html])</qau></rj><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magnus hitch</ent><br/
<hw>magnus hitch</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A rolling hitch similar to a clove hitch.</def><br/
<source>WordNet 1.5</source></p>

<p><ent>mag tape</ent><br/
<hw>mag tape</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>magnetic tape</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> magnetic tape, tape.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magot</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"ot</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The Barbary ape.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magot-pie</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"ot-pie`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A magpie.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magpie</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"pie</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. & Prov. E. <ets>magot pie</ets>, <ets>maggoty pie</ets>, fr. <ets>Mag</ets>, <ets>Maggot</ets>, equiv. to <ets>Margaret</ets>, and fr. F. <ets>Marquerite</ets>, and common name of the magpie. <ets>Marguerite</ets> is fr. L. <ets>margarita</ets> pearl, Gr. <?/, prob. of Eastern origin. See <er>Pie</er> magpie, and cf. the analogous names <er>Tomtit</er>, and <er>Jackdaw</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of numerous species of the genus <gen>Pica</gen> and related genera, allied to the jays, but having a long graduated tail.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any one of several black-and-white birds, such as <spn>Gymnorhina tibicen</spn>, not belonging to the genus <gen>Pica</gen>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The common European magpie (<spn>Pica pica</spn>, or <spn>Pica caudata</spn>) is a black and white noisy and mischievous bird. It can be taught to speak.  The American magpie (<spn>Pica Hudsonica</spn>) is very similar. The yellow-belled magpie (<spn>Pica Nuttalli</spn>) inhabits California.  The blue magpie (<spn>Cyanopolius Cooki</spn>) inhabits Spain. Other allied species are found in Asia.  The Tasmanian and Australian magpies are crow shrikes, as the white magpie (<spn>Gymnorhina organicum</spn>), the black magpie (<spn>Strepera fuliginosa</spn>), and the Australian magpie (<spn>Cracticus picatus</spn>).</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A talkative person; a chatterbox.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Magpie lark</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a common Australian bird (<spn>Grallina picata</spn>), conspicuously marked with black and white; -- called also <altname>little magpie</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Magpie moth</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a black and white European geometrid moth (<spn>Abraxas grossulariata</spn>); the harlequin moth. Its larva feeds on currant and gooseberry bushes.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maguari</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma`gua*ri"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From native name: cf. Pg. <ets>magoari</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A South American stork (<spn>Euxenara maguari</spn>), having a forked tail.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maguey</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"uey</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>maguey</ets>, Mexican <ets>maguei</ets> and <ets>metl</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Any of several species of <gen>Agave</gen>,  such as the <stype>century plant</stype> (<spn>Agave Americana</spn>), a plant requiring many years to come to maturity and blossoming only once before dying; and the <spn>Agave atrovirens</spn>, a Mexican plant used especially for making <prod>pulque</prod>, the source of the colorless Mexican liquor <prod>mescal</prod>; and the <stype>cantala</stype> (<spn>Agave cantala</spn>), a Philippine plant yielding a hard fibre used in making coarse twine.  See <er>Agave</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A hard fibre used in making coarse twine, derived from the Philippine Agave <prodby>cantala</prodby> (<spn>Agave cantala</spn>); also called <altname>cantala</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>magus</ent><br/
<hw>magus</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>a magician or sorcerer of ancient times.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>a member of the Zoroastrian priesthood of the ancient Persians.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magyar</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"yar</hw> <pr>(m<acr/g"y<aum/r; <it>Hung</it>. m<ocr/d"y<ocr/r)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[Hung.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>One of the dominant people of Hungary, allied to the Finns; a Hungarian.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The language of the Magyars.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magyar</ent><br/
<hw>Mag"yar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the Magyars or their language; Hungarian.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maha</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma"ha</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A kind of baboon; the wanderoo.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maha</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"ha</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>A member of the Siouan people formerly living in the Missouri river valley in Northeastern Nebraska; called also <altname>Omaha</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahabharatam</ent><br/
<ent>Mahabarata</ent><br/
<mhw>{ \'d8<hw>Ma*ha*ba"ra*ta</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, \'d8<hw>Ma*ha*bha"ra*tam</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Skr. <ets>mah<amac/bh<amac/rata</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Hinduism)</fld> <def>A celebrated sacred epic poem of the Hindus, written in Sanskrit.  It is of great length, and is chiefly devoted to a history, in many episodes, of a civil war between two dynasties of ancient India.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Mahabharatam, Mahabharatum.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahaled</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*ha"led</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos><ety>[Ar. <ets>mahled</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A cherry tree (<spn>Prunus Mahaleb</spn>) of Southern Europe.  The wood is prized by cabinetmakers, the twigs are used for pipe stems, the flowers and leaves yield a perfume, and from the fruit a violet dye and a fermented liquor (like kirschwasser) are prepared.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maharajah</ent><br/
<ent>maharaja</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>maharaja</hw>, <hw>ma*ha*ra"jah</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Skr. <ets>mah<amac/r<amac/ja</ets>; <ets>mahat</ets> great + <ets>r<amac/ja</ets> king.]</ety> <def>A sovereign prince in India; a Hindu prince or king in India ranking above a raja; -- a title given also to other persons of high rank.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maharani</ent><br/
<hw>maharani</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A great rani; a princess in India or the wife of a maharaja.</def> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>maharanee</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maharif</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma`ha*rif"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An African antelope (<spn>Hippotragus Bakeri</spn>). Its face is striped with black and white.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maharmah</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*har"mah</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A muslin wrapper for the head and the lower part of the face, worn by Turkish and Armenian women when they go abroad.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahatma</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*hat"ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Skr. <ets>mah<amac/tman</ets>, lit., great-souled, wise.]</ety> <fld>(Theosophy)</fld> <def>One of a class of sages, or <ldquo/adepts,<rdquo/ reputed to have knowledge and powers of a higher order than those of ordinary men.</def>

<note>The title was popularly applied to <person>Mohandas Karamchand Gandhi</person> in tribute to his wisdom, though not implying any supernatural powers; he is thus often referred to as <person>Mahatma Ghandi</person> or <person>The Mahatma</person>.  He was most noted for his advocacy of non-violence in resisting oppression, and played an important role in convincing Great Britain to grant independence to India and Pakistan.</note> -- <wordforms><wf>Ma*hat"ma*ism</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahatma Ghandi</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*hat"ma Ghandi</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>See the note under <er>mahatma</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahayana</ent><br/
<hw>Mahayana</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>a major school of Buddhism teaching social concern and universal salvation, found in China; Japan; Tibet; Nepal; Korea; and Mongolia.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>one of two great schools of Buddhist doctrine emphasizing a common search for universal salvation esp through faith alone; chiefly in China; Tibet; Japan.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahayanist</ent><br/
<hw>Mahayanist</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>an adherent of Mahayana Buddhism.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahdi</ent><br/
<hw>Mah"di</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Ar., guide, leader.]</ety> <def>Among Muslims, the last <xex>imam</xex> or leader of the faithful.  The Sunni, the largest sect of the Muslims, believe that he is yet to appear.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The title has been taken by several persons in countries where Islam prevails, -- notably by <person>Mohammad Ahmed</person>, who overran the Egyptian Sudan, and in 1885 captured Khartum, his soldiers killing <person>General Gordon</person>, an Englishman, who was then the Egyptian governor of the region.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahdiism</ent><br/
<hw>Mah"di*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mahdism</er>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahdism</ent><br/
<hw>Mah"dism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Belief in the coming of the Mahdi; fanatical devotion to the cause of the Mahdi or a pretender to that title.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mah"dist</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms></p>

<p><q><qex>Mahdism</qex> has proved the most shameful and terrible instrument of bloodshed and oppression which the modern world has ever witnessed.</q>  <rj><qau>E. N. Bennett.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahican</ent><br/
<hw>Mahican</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>Variant of <er>Mohican</er>.</def> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>Mohican</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mahimahi</ent><br/
<hw>mahimahi</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>either of two large slender food and game fish (<spn>Coryphaena equisetis</spn> or <spn>Coryphaena hippurus</spn>) of warm waters.  They are highly esteemed as food fish, especially in Hawaii.  See also <er>dolphin{2}</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> dolphin, dolphinfish.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>lean-fleshed fish of warm waters, esp. Hawaii.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> dolphinfish.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mah-Jongg</ent><br/
<ent>mahjong</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mahjong</hw>, <hw>Mah-Jongg</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A Chinese game played by 4 people with 144 tiles.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mahl-stick</ent><br/
<ent>mahlstick</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mahl"stick`</hw>, <hw>mahl"-stick`</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G. <ets>malerstock</ets>; <ets>maler</ets> a painter + <ets>stock</ets> stick.]</ety> <def>A long stick that a painter uses to support the hand holding the brush while painting.  Same as <er>Maul-stick</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahoe</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"hoe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A name given to several malvaceous trees (species of <gen>Hibiscus</gen>, <gen>Ochroma</gen>, etc.), and to their strong fibrous inner bark, which is used for strings and cordage.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahogany tree</ent><br/
<ent>Mahogany</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Ma*hog"a*ny</hw>, <hw>Ma*hog"a*ny tree`</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From the South American name.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A large tree of the genus <gen>Swietenia</gen> (<spn>Swietenia Mahogoni</spn>), found in tropical America.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Several other trees, with wood more or less like mahogany, are called by this name; as, African mahogany (<spn>Khaya Senegalensis</spn>), Australian mahogany (<spn>Eucalyptus marginatus</spn>), Bastard mahogany (<spn>Batonia apetala</spn> of the West Indies), Indian mahogany (<spn>Cedrela Toona</spn> of Bengal, and trees of the genera <gen>Soymida</gen> and <gen>Chukrassia</gen>), Madeira mahogany (<spn>Persea Indica</spn>), Mountain mahogany, the black or cherry birch (<spn>Betula lenta</spn>), also the several species of <gen>Cercocarpus</gen> of California and the Rocky Mountains.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The wood of the <spn>Swietenia Mahogoni</spn>. It is of a reddish brown color, beautifully veined, very hard, and susceptible of a fine polish. It is used in the manufacture of furniture.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A table made of mahogany wood.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To be under the mahogany</b></col>, <cd>to be so drunk as to have fallen under the table.</cd> <mark>[Eng.]</mark> -- <col><b>To put one's legs under some one's mahogany</b></col>, <cd>to dine with him.</cd> <mark>[Slang]</mark></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maholi</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*ho"li</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A South African lemur (<spn>Galago maholi</spn>), having very large ears.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>moholi</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahometan</ent><br/
<ent>Mahomedan</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Ma*hom"ed*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Ma*hom"et*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mohammedan</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahomet</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*hom"et</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Mohammed</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahometanism</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*hom"et*an*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mohammedanism</er> and <er>Islam</er>.</def>  <mark>[Archaic]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahometanize</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*hom"et*an*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mahometanized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mahometanizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To convert to Islam, the religion of Mohammed; to Mohammedanize.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahometism</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*hom"et*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mohammedanism</er> and <er>Islam</er>.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahometist</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*hom"et*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A Muslim.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahometry</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*hom"et*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Islam.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahone</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*hone"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A large Turkish ship.</def>  <rj><au>Crabb.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mahonia</ent><br/
<hw>ma*ho"ni*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Named after <person>Bernard Mc<etsep>Mahon</etsep></person>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The Oregon grape, a species of barberry (<spn>Berberis Aquifolium</spn>), often cultivated for its hollylike foliage.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahonia</ent><br/
<hw>Mahonia</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of evergreen shrubs and small trees of North and Central America and Asia.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mahon stock</ent><br/
<hw>ma*hon" stock`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>An annual cruciferous plant with reddish purple or white flowers (<spn>Malcolmia maritima</spn>).  It is called in England <altname>Virginia stock</altname>, but the plant comes from the Mediterranean.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahoohoo</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*hoo"hoo</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The African white two-horned rhinoceros (<spn>Atelodus simus</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahori</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"ho*ri</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Native name.  Cf. <er>Maori</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>One of the dark race inhabiting principally the islands of Eastern Polynesia. Also used adjectively.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahound</ent><br/
<hw>Ma`hound</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A contemptuous name for Mohammed; hence, an evil spirit; a devil.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who's this, my <qex>mahound</qex> cousin ?</q> <rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahout</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*hout"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Hind. <ets>mah<amac/wat</ets>, Skr. <ets>mah<amac/m<amac/tra</ets>; <ets>mahat</ets> great + <ets>m<amac/tr<amac/</ets> measure.]</ety> <def>The keeper and driver of an elephant.</def> <mark>[East Indies]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahovo</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*ho"vo</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>A device for saving power in stopping and starting a railroad car, by means of a heavy fly wheel.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahrati</ent><br/
<hw>Mah*rat"i</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The language of the Mahrattas; the language spoken in the Deccan and Concan.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>Marathi</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahratta</ent><br/
<hw>Mah*rat"ta</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Hind. <ets>Marhat<amac/</ets>, <ets>Marh<amac/tt<amac/</ets>, the name of a famous Hindoo race, from the old Skr. name <ets>Mah<amac/-r<amac/shtra</ets>.]</ety> <def>One of a numerous people inhabiting the southwestern part of India. Also, the language of the Mahrattas; Mahrati. It is closely allied to Sanskrit.</def> -- <def2><pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the Mahrattas.</def></def2> <altsp>[Written also <asp>Maratha</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahumetanism</ent><br/
<ent>Mahumetan</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Ma*hu"met*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Ma*hu"met*an*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> }</mhw> <def>See <er>Mohammedan</er>, <er>Muslim</er>, <er>Mohammedanism</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahwa tree</ent><br/
<hw>Mah"wa tree`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>An East Indian sapotaceous tree (<spn>Bassia latifolia</spn>, and also <spn>Bassia butyracea</spn>), whose timber is used for wagon wheels, and the flowers for food and in preparing an intoxicating drink. It is one of the butter trees. The oil, known as <xex>mahwa</xex> and <xex>yallah</xex>, is obtained from the kernels of the fruit.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma"i*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From L. <ets>Maia</ets>, a goddess.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A genus of spider crabs, including the common European species (<spn>Maia squinado</spn>).</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A beautiful American bombycid moth (<spn>Eucronia maia</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maian</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"ian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any spider crab of the genus Maia, or family <fam>Maiadae</fam>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maid</ent><br/
<hw>Maid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Shortened from <ets>maiden</ets>. <ets><?/</ets>. See <er>Maiden</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An unmarried woman; usually, a young unmarried woman; esp., a girl; a virgin; a maiden.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Would I had died a <qex>maid</qex>,<br/
And never seen thee, never borne thee son.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Can a <qex>maid</qex> forget her ornaments, or a bride her attire? Yet my people have forgotten me.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. ii. 32.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A man who has not had sexual intercourse.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Christ was a <qex>maid</qex> and shapen as a man.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A female servant.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Spinning amongst her <qex>maids</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Maid</xex> is used either adjectively or in composition, signifying <xex>female</xex>, as in <xex>maid</xex> child, <xex>maid</xex>servant.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The female of a ray or skate, esp. of the gray skate (<spn>Raia batis</spn>), and of the thornback (<spn>Raia clavata</spn>).</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fair maid</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Fair</er>, <pos>a.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>Maid of honor</b></col>, <cd>a female attendant of a queen or royal princess; -- usually of noble family, and having to perform only nominal or honorary duties.</cd> -- <col><b>Old maid</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Old</er>.</cd></cs>
<-- maid of honor. principal female attendant (if unmarried) of a bride at wedding. (If married, matron of honor.) --><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maidan</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mai*dan"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <altsp>[Written also <asp>midan</asp>, <asp>meidan</asp>, <asp>mydan</asp>, etc.]</altsp> <ety>[Hind. & Per. <ets>maid<amac/n</ets>, fr. Ar. <ets>maid<amac/n</ets>.]</ety> <def>In various  parts of Asia, an open space, as for military exercises, or for a market place; an open grassy tract; an esplanade.</def></p>

<p><q>A gallop on the green <qex>maidan</qex>.</q>  <rj><qau>M. Crawford.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maiden</ent><br/
<hw>Maid"en</hw> <pr>(m<amac/d"'n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>maiden</ets>, <ets>meiden</ets>, AS. <ets>maegden</ets>, dim. of AS. <ets>maeg<edh/</ets>, fr. <ets>mago</ets> son, servant; akin to G. <ets>magd</ets>, <ets>m<aum/dchen</ets>, maid, OHG. <ets>magad</ets>, Icel. <ets>m<oum/gr</ets> son, Goth.  <ets>magus</ets> boy, child, <ets>magaps</ets> virgin, and perh. to Zend. <ets>magu</ets> youth.  Cf. <er>Maid</er> a virgin.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An unmarried woman; a girl or woman who has not experienced sexual intercourse; a virgin; a maid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She employed the residue of her life to repairing of highways, building of bridges, and endowing of <qex>maidens</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Carew.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>maiden</qex> of our century, yet most meek.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A female servant.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An instrument resembling the guillotine, formerly used in Scotland for beheading criminals.</def>  <rj><au>Wharton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A machine for washing linen.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maiden</ent><br/
<hw>Maid"en</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a maiden, or to maidens; suitable to, or characteristic of, a virgin; <as>as, <ex>maiden</ex> innocence</as>.</def> <ldquo/Amid the <xex>maiden</xex> throng.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Have you no modesty, no <qex>maiden</qex> shame ?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Never having been married; not having had sexual intercourse; virgin; -- said usually of the woman, but sometimes of the man; <as>as, a <ex>maiden</ex> aunt</as>.</def> <ldquo/A surprising old <xex>maiden</xex> lady.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Fresh; innocent; unpolluted; pure; hitherto unused.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Maiden</xex> flowers.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Full bravely hast thou fleshed<br/
Thy <qex>maiden</qex> sword.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Used of a fortress, signifying that it has never been captured, or violated.</def>  <rj><au> T. Warton. Macaulay.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Maiden assize</b></col> <fld>(Eng. Law)</fld>, <cd>an assize which there is no criminal prosecution; an assize which is unpolluted with blood. It was usual, at such an assize, for the sheriff to present the judge with a pair of white gloves.</cd> <au>Smart.</au> -- <col><b>Maiden name</b></col>, <cd>the surname of a woman before her marriage.</cd> -- <col><b>Maiden pink</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Pink</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Maiden plum</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a West Indian tree (<spn>Comocladia integrifolia</spn>) with purplish drupes. The sap of the tree is glutinous, and gives a persistent black stain.</cd> -- <col><b>Maiden speech</b></col>, <cd>the first speech made by a person, esp. by a new member in a public body.</cd> -- <col><b>Maiden tower</b></col>, <cd>the tower most capable of resisting an enemy.</cd> -- <col><b>maiden voyage</b></col> <cd>the first regular service voyage of a ship.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maiden</ent><br/
<hw>Maid"en</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To act coyly like a maiden; -- with <xex>it</xex> as an indefinite object.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For had I <qex>maiden'd</qex> it, as many use.<br/
Loath for to grant, but loather to refuse.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Hall.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Maiden grass</b></col>, <cd>the smaller quaking grass.</cd> -- <col><b>Maiden tree</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Ginkgo</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maiden aunt</ent><br/
<hw>maiden aunt</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Literally, an aunt who has never been married.  Figuratively, it is a term used as the prototype of a person who is broadly naive and not wise in worldly ways; <as>as, he knows as much about programming as my <ex>maiden aunt</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maiden blue-eyed mary</ent><br/
<hw>maiden blue-eyed mary</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A small widely branching Western wildflower (<spn>Collinsia parviflora</spn>) with tiny blue-and-white flowers; found from British Columbia to Ontaria and south to California and Colorado.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maidenhair fern</ent><br/
<ent>maidenhair</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>maid"en*hair`</hw>, <hw>maidenhair fern</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Any of various small to large terrestrial ferns of the genus <gen>Adiantum</gen> having very slender graceful stalks and delicate palmately branched fronds, especially  (<spn>Adiantum pedatum</spn>).  It is common in the United States, and is sometimes used in medicine.  The name is also applied to other species of the same genus, as to the Venus-hair.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maidenhair berry</ent><br/
<hw>maidenhair berry</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A slow-growing procumbent evergreen shrublet (<spn>Gaultheria hispidula</spn>) of Northern North America and Japan having white flowers and numerous white fleshy rough-hairy seeds.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> creeping snowberry, moxie plum, <spn>Gaultheria hispidula</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maidenhair fern</ent><br/
<hw>maidenhair fern</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>maidenhair</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maidenhair spleenwort</ent><br/
<hw>maidenhair spleenwort</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A small rock-inhabiting fern (<spn>Asplenium trichomanes</spn>) of the North temperate zone and Hawaii, having pinnate fronds.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maidenhair tree</ent><br/
<hw>maidenhair tree</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A deciduous dioecious gymnospermous Chinese tree (<spn>Ginkgo biloba</spn>) having fan-shaped leaves and fleshy yellow seeds, also called the <altname>ginkgo</altname>; it exists almost exclusively in cultivation esp. as an ornamental street tree.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maidenhead</ent><br/
<hw>Maid"en*head</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Maidenhood</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The state of being a maiden; maidenhood; virginity.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state of being unused or uncontaminated; freshness; purity.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>maidenhead</qex> of their credit.</q> <rj><qau>Sir H. Wotton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The hymen, or virginal membrane.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maidenhood</ent><br/
<hw>Maid"en*hood</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>maegdenh<amac/d</ets>. See <er>Maid</er>, and <er>-hood</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The state of being a maid or a virgin; virginity.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Newness; freshness; uncontaminated state.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>maidenhood</qex><br/
Of thy fight.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maidenlike</ent><br/
<hw>Maid"en*like`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Like a maiden; modest; coy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maidenliness</ent><br/
<hw>Maid"en*li*ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality of being maidenly; the behavior that becomes a maid; modesty; gentleness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maidenly</ent><br/
<hw>Maid"en*ly</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Like a maid; suiting a maid; maiden-like; gentle, modest, reserved.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Must you be blushing ? . . . <br/
What a <qex>maidenly</qex> man-at-arms are you become !</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maidenly</ent><br/
<hw>Maid"en*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a maidenlike manner.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Maidenly</xex> demure.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Skelton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maiden over</ent><br/
<hw>maiden over</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(cricket)</fld> <def>An over in which no runs are scored.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maiden pink</ent><br/
<hw>maiden pink</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A low-growing loosely mat-forming Eurasian pink (<spn>Dianthus deltoides</spn>) with single crimson-eyed pale pink flowers.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maidenship</ent><br/
<hw>Maid"en*ship</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Maidenhood.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maidhood</ent><br/
<hw>Maid"hood</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>maeg<edh/h<amac/d</ets>. See <er>Maid</er>, and <er>-hood</er>.]</ety> <def>Maidenhood.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maidmarian</ent><br/
<hw>Maid`ma"ri*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Maid</ets> + <ets>Marian</ets>, relating to <ets>Mary</ets>, or the Virgin <ets>Mary</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The lady of the May games; one of the characters in a morris dance; a May queen. Afterward, a grotesque character personated in sports and buffoonery by a man in woman's clothes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A kind of dance.</def>  <rj><au>Sir W. Temple.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maidpale</ent><br/
<hw>Maid"pale`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pale, like a sick girl.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maidservant</ent><br/
<hw>Maid"serv`ant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A female servant.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maid's hair</ent><br/
<hw>Maid's" hair`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The yellow bedstraw (<spn>Galium verum</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maieutical</ent><br/
<ent>Maieutic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Ma*ieu"tic</hw> <pr>(m<asl/*<umac/"t<icr/k)</pr>, <hw>Ma*ieu"tic*al</hw> <pr>(m<asl/*<umac/"t<icr/*k<ait/l)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>maieytiko`s</grk>, fr. <grk>mai^a</grk> midwife.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Serving to assist childbirth.</def>  <rj><au>Cudworth.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <mark>[Fig.]</mark> <def>Aiding, or tending to, the definition and interpretation of thoughts or language.</def>  <rj><au>Payne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maieutic method</ent><br/
<hw>maieutic method</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A method of teaching by question and answer; it was used by <persfn>Socrates</persfn> to elicit truths from his students; -- called also the <altname>Socratic method</altname></def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maieutics</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*ieu"tics</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The art of giving birth (<it>i. e.</it>, clearness and conviction) to ideas, which are conceived as struggling for birth.</def>  <rj><au>Payne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maiger</ent><br/
<hw>Mai"ger</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The meagre.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maigre</ent><br/
<hw>Mai"gre</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. See <er>Meager</er>.]</ety> <def>Belonging to a fast day or fast; <as>as, a <ex>maigre</ex> day</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Walpole.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Maigre food</b></col> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld>, <cd>food allowed to be eaten on fast days.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 884 --></p>

<p><ent>Maihem</ent><br/
<hw>Mai"hem</hw> <pr>(m<amac/"h<ecr/m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Maim</er>, and <er>Mayhem</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maikel</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mai*kel"</hw> <pr>(m<aum/<icr/*k<asl/l")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A South American carnivore of the genus <gen>Conepatus</gen>, allied to the skunk, but larger, and having a longer snout. The tail is not bushy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maikong</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mai*kong"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A South American wild dog (<spn>Canis cancrivorus</spn>); the crab-eating dog.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mail</ent><br/
<hw>Mail</hw> <pr>(m<amac/l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A spot.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mail</ent><br/
<hw>Mail</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>maille</ets>, OF. also <ets>maaille</ets>, LL. <ets>medalia</ets>. See <er>Medal</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A small piece of money; especially, an English silver half-penny of the time of <person>Henry V.</person></def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <altsp>[Written also <asp>maile</asp>, and <asp>maille</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Rent; tribute.</def> <mark>[Obs., except in certain compounds and phrases, as blackmail, mails and duties, etc.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mail and duties</b></col> <fld>(Scots Law)</fld>, <cd>the rents of an estate, in whatever form paid.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mail</ent><br/
<hw>Mail</hw> <pr>(m<amac/l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>maile</ets>, <ets>maille</ets>, F. <ets>maille</ets> a ring of mail, mesh, network, a coat of mail, fr. L. <ets>macula</ets> spot, a mesh of a net.  Cf. <er>Macle</er>, <er>Macula</er>, <er>Mascle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A flexible fabric made of metal rings interlinked. It was used especially for defensive armor.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Chain mail</b></col>, <col><b>Coat of mail</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See under <er>Chain</er>, and <er>Coat</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence generally, armor, or any defensive covering.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A contrivance of interlinked rings, for rubbing off the loose hemp on lines and white cordage.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any hard protective covering of an animal, as the scales and plates of reptiles, shell of a lobster, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We . . . strip the lobster of his scarlet <qex>mail</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Gay.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mail</ent><br/
<hw>Mail</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To arm with mail.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To pinion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mail</ent><br/
<hw>Mail</hw> <pr>(m<amac/l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>male</ets> bag, OF. <ets>male</ets>, F. <ets>malle</ets> bag, trunk, mail, OHG. <ets>malaha</ets>, <ets>malha</ets>, wallet; akin to D. <ets>maal</ets>, <ets>male</ets>; cf. Gael. & Ir. <ets>mala</ets>, Gr. <grk>molgo`s</grk>  hide, skin.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A bag; a wallet.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The bag or bags with the letters, papers, or other matter contained therein, conveyed under public authority from one post office to another; the whole system of appliances used by government in the conveyance and delivery of mail matter.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is a <qex>mail</qex> come in to-day, with letters dated Hague.</q> <rj><qau>Tatler.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which comes in the mail; letters, etc., received through the post office.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A trunk, box, or bag, in which clothing, etc., may be carried.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir W. Scott.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mail catcher</b></col>, <cd>an iron rod, or other contrivance, attached to a railroad car for catching a mail bag while the train is in motion.</cd> -- <col><b>Mail guard</b></col>, <cd>an officer whose duty it is to guard the public mails.</cd> <mark>[Eng.]</mark> -- <col><b>Mail train</b></col>, <cd>a railroad train carrying the mail.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mail</ent><br/
<hw>Mail</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mailed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mailing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To deliver into the custody of the postoffice officials, or place in a government letter box, for transmission by mail; to post; <as>as, to <ex>mail</ex> a letter</as>.</def> <mark>[U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ In the United States <xex>to mail</xex> and <xex>to post</xex> are both in common use; as, to <xex>mail</xex> or <xex>post</xex> a letter. In England <xex>post</xex> is the commoner usage.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mailable</ent><br/
<hw>Mail"a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Admissible lawfully into the mail.  Opposed to <ant>non-mailable</ant>.  Dangerous items such as explosives, weapons, or corrosive chemicals are often classified by the postal authorities as non-mailable.</def> <mark>[U.S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mail bag</ent><br/
<ent>mailbag</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mail"bag`</hw>, <hw>mail bag</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A bag in which mailed matter is conveyed or shipped under public authority.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mail pouch.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A letter carrier's shoulder bag; <as>as, in England they call a <ex>mailbag</ex> a postbag</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> postbag.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mail boat</ent><br/
<ent>mailboat</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mail"boat`</hw>, <hw>mail" boat`</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>a boat that carries the mail.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mail boat, packet, packet boat.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mailbox</ent><br/
<hw>mail"box`</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A public box for deposit of mail, where it is later picked up by the postal authority for delivery.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> postbox, letter box.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A private box to recieve delivery of mail.  The term is used both for boxes receiving mail delivered by the public postal authority, or by a private services, such as for mail to employees in large corporations.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> letter box.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Computers)</fld> <def>A location within a computer storage device where electronic mail is held until it is retrieved by the addressee.  Creation and use of an electronic <ex>mailbox</ex> requires special software as well as a data storage device.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mail call</ent><br/
<hw>mail call</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A call of the names of those persons receiving mail for the purpose of transmitting mail to them; -- a technique used in the military services to deliver mail to enlisted personnel.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mail car</ent><br/
<hw>mail car</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A  railway car of special design used for the transportation and sorting of mail en route to its destination, and having employees of the post office inside to perform those functions.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mail carrier</ent><br/
<hw>mail carrier</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A person who delivers the mail; -- also called a <altname>letter carrier</altname>.  A male mail carrier is also called a <altname>mailman</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> postman, letter carrier, carrier, mailman.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mailclad</ent><br/
<hw>Mail"clad`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Protected by a coat of mail; clad in armor.</def>  <rj><au>Sir W. Scott.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mail clerk</ent><br/
<hw>mail clerk</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A clerk in a post office.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> postal clerk.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mailed</ent><br/
<hw>Mailed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Protected by an external coat, or covering, of scales or plates.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mailed</ent><br/
<hw>Mailed</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See 1st <er>Mail</er>.]</ety> <def>Spotted; speckled.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mail fraud</ent><br/
<hw>mail fraud</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The use of the mails to defraud someone.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mailing</ent><br/
<hw>Mail"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Scot., fr. <ets>mail</ets> tribute, rent. See 2d <er>Mail</er>.]</ety> <def>A farm.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir W. Scott.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mailing</ent><br/
<hw>mail"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or process of sending materials through the mail.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A quantity of mail, such as letters, magazines, advertising brochures, etc., sent at one time by one person or organization; <as>as, the ads with coupons will go out in our next <ex>mailing</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mailing address</ent><br/
<hw>mailing address</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The postal address where a maile can be addressed to a person or organization.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mailing list</ent><br/
<hw>mailing list</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A list of names and addresses to which advertising, solicitations of money, or other materials material sent in large quantities is mailed; -- it is usually used by comercial or charitable organizations.  Mailing lists are often sold by organizations to other organizations, and are frequently used for <ecol><b>targeted mailing</b></ecol>, i. e., mailing to groups of people who are more likely htan the general population to respond as desired to the message in the mail.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maillot</ent><br/
<hw>maillot</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A woman's one-piece bathing suit.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> tank suit.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>for dancers or gymnasts.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mailman</ent><br/
<hw>mail"man`</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A man who delivers the mail.  A male <er>mail carrier</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> postman, mail carrier, letter carrier, carrier.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mail-order</ent><br/
<ent>mail-order buying</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mail-order buying</hw>, <hw>mail-order</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The buying and selling of goods to be shipped from the vendor through the mail to the purchaser.  Information about to be purchased may be found in catalogs, advertisements, on the web, etc., and purchase orders transmitted to the vendor by mail, telephone, or internet connection.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mail pouch</ent><br/
<hw>mail pouch</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>mailbag</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mail-shell</ent><br/
<hw>Mail"-shell`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A chiton.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mail slot</ent><br/
<hw>mail slot</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A usually horizontal slot in a door through which mail can be delivered.  It often has a hinged cover to keep the opening cloised when not in use.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mailsorter</ent><br/
<hw>mailsorter</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A machine that sorts mail, according to the address.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mail train</ent><br/
<hw>mail train</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A railroad train that carries mail.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maim</ent><br/
<hw>Maim</hw> <pr>(m<amac/m)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Maimed</conjf> <pr>(m<amac/md)</pr>;<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Maiming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>maimen</ets>, OF. <ets>mahaignier</ets>, <ets>mehaignier</ets>, <ets>meshaignier</ets>, cf. It. <ets>magagnare</ets>, LL. <ets>mahemiare</ets>, <ets>mahennare</ets>; perh. of Celtic origin; cf. Armor. <ets>mac'ha<ntil/a</ets> to mutilate, <ets>m<amac/c'ha</ets> to crowd, press; or cf. OHG. <ets>mang<omac/n</ets> to lack, perh. akin to E. <ets>mangle</ets> to lacerate.  Cf.  <er>Mayhem</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To deprive of the use of a limb, so as to render a person in fighting less able either to defend himself or to annoy his adversary.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By the ancient law of England he that <qex>maimed</qex> any man whereby he lost any part of his body, was sentenced to lose the like part.</q> <rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To mutilate; to cripple; to injure; to disable; to impair.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My late <qex>maimed</qex> limbs lack wonted might.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You <qex>maimed</qex> the jurisdiction of all bishops.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To mutilate; mangle; cripple.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maim</ent><br/
<hw>Maim</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <altsp>[Written in law language <asp>maihem</asp>, and <asp>mayhem</asp>.]</altsp> <ety>[OF. <ets>mehaing</ets>. See <er>Maim</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The privation of the use of a limb or member of the body, by which one is rendered less able to defend himself or to annoy his adversary.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The privation of any necessary part; a crippling; mutilation; injury; deprivation of something essential. See <er>Mayhem</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Surely there is more cause to fear lest the want there of be a <qex>maim</qex> than the use of it a blemish.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A noble author esteems it to be a <qex>maim</qex> in history that the acts of Parliament should not be recited.</q> <rj><qau>Hayward.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maimedly</ent><br/
<hw>Maim"ed*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a maimed manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maimedness</ent><br/
<hw>maim"ed*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>State of being maimed.</def>  <rj><au>Bolton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>main</ent><br/
<hw>main</hw> <pr>(m<amac/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>main</ets> hand, L. <ets>manus</ets>. See <er>Manual</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A hand or match at dice.</def>  <rj><au>Prior.</au> <au>Thackeray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A stake played for at dice.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The largest throw in a match at dice; a throw at dice within given limits, as in the game of hazard.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A match at cockfighting.</def> <ldquo/My lord would ride twenty miles . . . to see a <xex>main</xex> fought.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A main-hamper.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Ainsworth.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Main</ent><br/
<hw>Main</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<ae/gen</ets> strength, power, force; akin to OHG. <ets>magan</ets>, Icel. <ets>megin</ets>, and to E. <ets>may</ets>, v.  <root/103.  See <er>May</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Strength; force; might; violent effort.</def> <mark>[Obs., except in certain phrases.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There were in this battle of most might and <qex>main</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>R. of Gl.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He 'gan advance,<br/
With huge force, and with importable <qex>main</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The chief or principal part; the main or most important thing.</def> <mark>[Obs., except in special uses.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Resolved to rest upon the title of Lancaster as the <qex>main</qex>, and to use the other two . . . but as supporters.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The great sea, as distinguished from an arm, bay, etc. ; the high sea; the ocean.</def> <ldquo/Struggling in the <xex>main</xex>.<rdquo/ <au>Dryden.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The continent, as distinguished from an island; the mainland.</def> <ldquo/Invaded the <xex>main</xex> of Spain.<rdquo/ <au>Bacon.</au> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>principal duct or pipe, as distinguished from lesser ones; esp. <fld>(Engin.)</fld>, a principal pipe leading to or from a reservoir; <as>as, a fire <ex>main</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Forcing main</b></col>, <cd>the delivery pipe of a pump.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>For the main</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>In the main</b></col></mcol>, <cd>for the most part; in the greatest part.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>With might and main</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>With all one's might and main</b></col></mcol>, <cd>with all one's strength; with violent effort.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>With might and main</qex> they chased the murderous fox.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Main</ent><br/
<hw>Main</hw> <pr>(m<amac/n)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Main</er> strength, possibly influenced by OF.  <ets>maine</ets>, <ets>magne</ets>, great, L. <ets>magnus</ets>.  Cf. <er>Magnate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Very or extremely strong.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That current with <qex>main</qex> fury ran.</q> <rj><qau>Daniel.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Vast; huge.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/The <xex>main</xex> abyss.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Unqualified; absolute; entire; sheer.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/It's a <xex>man</xex> untruth.<rdquo/ <au>Sir W. Scott.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Principal; chief; first in size, rank, importance, etc.; <as>as, the <ex>main</ex> reason to go; the <ex>main</ex> proponent</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our <qex>main</qex> interest is to be happy as we can.</q> <rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Important; necessary.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That which thou aright<br/
Believest so <qex>main</qex> to our success, I bring.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>By main force</b></col>, <cd>by mere force or sheer force; by violent effort; <as>as, to subdue insurrection <ex>by main force</ex></as>.</cd><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That Maine which <qex>by main force</qex> Warwick did win.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <col><b>By main strength</b></col>, <cd>by sheer strength; <as>as, to lift a heavy weight <ex>by main strength</ex></as>.</cd> -- <col><b>Main beam</b></col> <fld>(Steam Engine)</fld>, <cd>working beam.</cd> -- <col><b>Main boom</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>the boom which extends the foot of the mainsail in a fore and aft vessel.</cd> -- <col><b>Main brace</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <cd>The brace which resists the chief strain.  Cf. <er>Counter brace</er>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>The brace attached to the main yard.</cd> -- <col><b>Main center</b></col> <fld>(Steam Engine)</fld>, <cd>a shaft upon which a working beam or side lever swings.</cd> -- <col><b>Main chance</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Chance</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Main couple</b></col> <fld>(Arch.)</fld>, <cd>the principal truss in a roof.</cd> -- <col><b>Main deck</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>the deck next below the spar deck; the principal deck.</cd> -- <col><b>Main keel</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>the principal or true keel of a vessel, as distinguished from the false keel.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Principal; chief; leading; cardinal; capital.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Main</ent><br/
<hw>Main</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Main</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>Very; extremely; <as>as, <ex>main</ex> heavy</as>.</def> <ldquo/I'm <xex>main</xex> dry.<rdquo/ <au>Foote.</au> <mark>[Obs. or Low]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>main course</ent><br/
<hw>main course</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The principal part of a meal.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> entree.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Nautical)</fld> <def>A square mainsail.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>main deck</ent><br/
<hw>main deck</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The uppermost sheltered deck that runs the entire length of a large vessel.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> second deck.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maine</ent><br/
<hw>Maine</hw> <pr>(m<amac/n)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>One of the New England States.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Maine law</b></col>, <cd>any law prohibiting the manufacture and sale of intoxicating beverages, esp. one resembling that enacted in the State of Maine.  At present, the state of Maine sells such beverages in its own stores.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maine lobster</ent><br/
<hw>maine lobster</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Any of several cold-water lobsters with large tender claws, caught from Maine to the Carolinas.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> American lobster, Northern lobster.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A lobster (<spn>Homarus americanus</spn>) found off the Atlantic coast of North America.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> American lobster, Northern lobster, <spn>Homarus americanus</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>main entry word</ent><br/
<hw>main entry word</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The form of a word that heads a lexical entry and is alphabetized in a dictionary; also called <altname>entry word</altname>, <altname>headword</altname>, and <altname>lemma</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> citation form, entry word, headword, lemma.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/  In different languages, different wordforms, such as cases for verbs, may be taken as the main entry word.  In English dictionaries, it is the infinitive form, but in latin dictionaries it is usually the first person singular present.</note><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>main file</ent><br/
<hw>main file</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(computers)</fld> <def>A file that is used as the authority in a given job and that is relatively permanent.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> master file.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mainframe</ent><br/
<hw>main"frame`</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Computers)</fld> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A large digital computer serving 100-400 users and occupying a special air-conditioned room.  At any given point in development of computer technology, the <ex>mainframe</ex> will be faster, have large main memeory, and be more capable than a <contr>minicomputer</contr>, which will in turn be faster and more capable than a <contr>personal computer</contr>.  The typical personal computer in 1999 is faster than a <ex>mainframe</ex> was in 1970.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mainframe computer.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The board holding the CPU and the memory forming the central part of a computer to which the peripherals are attached.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Main-gauche</ent><br/
<hw>Main`-gauche"</hw> <pr>(m<acr/N`g<omac/sh")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., the left hand.]</ety> <fld>(Ancient Armor)</fld> <def>The dagger held in the left hand, while the rapier is held in the right; -- used to parry thrusts of the adversary's rapier.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Main-hamper</ent><br/
<hw>Main"-ham`per</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.  <ets>main</ets> hand (see <er>Main</er> a hand at dice) + E. <ets>hamper</ets>.]</ety> <def>A hamper to be carried in the hand; a hand basket used in carrying grapes to the press.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mainland</ent><br/
<hw>Main"land`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The continent; the principal land; -- opposed to <contr>island</contr>, or <contr>peninsula</contr>.</def>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>After the two wayfarers had crossed from the peninsula to the <qex>mainland</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mainland China</ent><br/
<hw>mainland China</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The People's Republic of China, also called <altname>Communist China</altname>, in distinction from <contr>Nationalist China</contr>, the government located on the island of Taiwan.  Both governments claim to represent the entire people of China, but the People's republic is recognized as China by the United Nationss and most of its member states.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Red China, PRC, Beijing.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>main line</ent><br/
<hw>main line</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Ahe principal route of a transportation system, such as a railroad or bus line.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mainline</ent><br/
<hw>main"line`</hw> <pr>(m<amac/n"l<imac/n`)</pr> <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>to inject (illegal drugs) into the vein; <as>as, he preferred to <ex>mainline</ex> heroin rather than sniff coke</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mainly</ent><br/
<hw>Main"ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[From <ets>main</ets> strong. See <er>Main</er> strength.]</ety> <def>Very strongly; mightily; to a great degree.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bacon. Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mainly</ent><br/
<hw>Main"ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[From <ets>main</ets> principal, chief.]</ety> <def>Principally; chiefly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mainmast</ent><br/
<hw>Main"mast`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The principal mast in a ship or other vessel.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>main office</ent><br/
<hw>main office</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The office that serves as the administrative center of an enterprise,</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> headquarters, central office, home office.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>main memory</ent><br/
<hw>main memory</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Computers)</fld> <def>The memory in a computer that holds programs and data for rapid access during execution of a program; it usually hold the largest quantity of rapid-access storage in a computer; -- also called <altname>RAM</altname> (<altname>random access memory</altname>.  It is contrasted to <contr>ROM</contr>, <contr>disk data storage</contr>, <contr>cache</contr>, <contr>registers</contr> and other forms of data storage.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mainor</ent><br/
<hw>Main"or</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Anglo-Norm. <ets>meinoure</ets>, OF. <ets>manuevre</ets>. See <er>Maneuver</er>.]</ety> <fld>(O. Eng. Law)</fld> <def>A thing stolen found on the person of the thief.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ A thief was said to be <ldquo/taken with the <xex>mainor</xex>,<rdquo/ when he was taken with the thing stolen upon him, that is, <xex>in his hands</xex>.</note>  <rj><au>Wharton.</au>  <au>Bouvier.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mainpernable</ent><br/
<hw>Main"per*na*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>main</ets> hand + <ets>pernable</ets>, for <ets>prenable</ets>, that may be taken, pregnable. See <er>Mainpernor</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Capable of being admitted to give surety by mainpernors; able to be mainprised.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mainpernor</ent><br/
<hw>Main"per*nor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>main</ets> hand + <ets>pernor</ets>, for <ets>preneor</ets>, a taker, F. <ets>preneur</ets>, fr. <ets>prendre</ets> to take.]</ety> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A surety, under the old writ of mainprise, for a prisoner's appearance in court at a day.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Mainpernors</xex> differ from <xex>bail</xex> in that a man's <xex>bail</xex> may imprison or surrender him before the stipulated day of appearance; <xex>mainpernors</xex> can do neither; they are bound to produce him to answer all charges whatsoever.</note>  <rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mainpin</ent><br/
<hw>Main"pin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Vehicles)</fld> <def>A kingbolt.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mainprise</ent><br/
<hw>Main"prise</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>main</ets> hand + <ets>prise</ets> a taking, fr. <ets>prendre</ets>, p. p. <ets>pris</ets> to take, fr. L. <ets>prehendere</ets>, <ets>prehensum</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A writ directed to the sheriff, commanding him to take sureties, called <xex>mainpernors</xex>, for the prisoner's appearance, and to let him go at large. This writ is now obsolete.</def> <au>Wharton.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Deliverance of a prisoner on security for his appearance at a day.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mainprise</ent><br/
<hw>Main"prise</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mainprised</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr.  & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mainprising</conjf>.]</vmorph> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To suffer to go at large, on his finding sureties, or mainpernors, for his appearance at a day; -- said of a prisoner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>main road</ent><br/
<hw>main road</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A major road for any form of motor transport.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> highway.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>main rotor</ent><br/
<hw>main rotor</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Aviation)</fld> <def>The assembly of large rotating airfoils (blades) on a helicopter that produce the lift to support the helicopter in the air.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mains</ent><br/
<hw>mains</hw> <pr>(m<amac/nz)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Scot. See <er>Manse</er>.]</ety> <def>The farm attached to a mansion house; a manse.</def> <mark>[Scot. or Brit. dial.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mains</ent><br/
<hw>mains</hw> <pr>(m<amac/nz)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Electricity)</fld> <def>The source of electrical power in a building; the wiring system of a building.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mainsail</ent><br/
<hw>Main"sail`</hw> <pr>(m<amac/n"s<amac/l`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The principal sail in a ship or other vessel.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[They] hoised up the <qex>mainsail</qex> to the wind.</q> <rj><qau> Acts xxvii. 40.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The <xex>mainsail</xex> of a ship is extended upon a yard attached to the mainmast, and that of a sloop or schooner upon the boom.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>main sequence</ent><br/
<hw>main" se`quence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Astronomy)</fld> <def>That region on a two-dimensional graph of luminosity versus temperature for stars (the <ecol><b>Herzsprung-Russel diagram</b></ecol>), which runs from high temperature and high luminosity to low temperature and low luminosity, in which most of the stars (plotted as points on the diagram) are found.  A normal star such as the earth's sun will spend most of its time over billions of years within this region of temperature and luminosity, as it progressively converts more of its original hydrogen into heavier elements.  After the hydrogen is consumed, a star may become a <er>red giant</er> or evolve into other types of star not within the <ex>main sequence</ex> region.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mainsheet</ent><br/
<hw>main"sheet`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>One of the ropes by which the mainsail is hauled aft and trimmed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mainspring</ent><br/
<hw>main"spring`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The principal or most important spring in a piece of mechanism, especially the moving spring of a watch or clock or the spring in a gunlock which impels the hammer.</def> <specif>Hence:</specif> <mark>(Fig.)</mark> <def>The chief or most powerful motive; the efficient cause of action; <as>as, the <ex>mainspring</ex> of action</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mainstay</ent><br/
<hw>Main"stay`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The stay extending from the foot of the foremast to the maintop.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Main support; principal dependence.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The great <qex>mainstay</qex> of the Church.</q> <rj><qau>Buckle.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mainstream</ent><br/
<hw>main"stream`</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The prevailing opinion or practise; <as>as, the doctor avoided using therapies outside the <ex>mainstream</ex> of modern medical practice</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mainstream</ent><br/
<hw>main"stream`</hw> <pos>v. t.</pos> <fld>(Education)</fld> <def>TO place (a student) in regular school classes; -- used especially of mentally or physically handicapped children.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mainstreamed</ent><br/
<hw>main"streamed`</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <fld>(Education)</fld> <def>Placed in regular school classes; -- of the handicapped.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>main street</ent><br/
<hw>main street</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A main thoroughfare, usually one in a small town having the largest concentration of retail businesses.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <mark>(Fig.)</mark> <def>The attitudes, environment, or life style of a small town; -- usually capitalized, and often used attributively; <as>as, <ex>Main Street</ex> attitudes toward Washington</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mainswear</ent><br/
<hw>Main"swear`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<amac/nswerian</ets> to forswear; <ets>m<amac/n</ets> sin, crime + <ets>swerian</ets> to swear.]</ety> <def>To swear falsely.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Blount.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maintain</ent><br/
<hw>Main*tain</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Maintained</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Maintaining</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>maintenen</ets>, F. <ets>maintenir</ets>, properly, to hold by the hand; <ets>main</ets> hand (L. <ets>manus</ets>) + F. <ets>tenir</ets> to hold (L. <ets>tenere</ets>). See <er>Manual</er>, and Tenable.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To hold or keep in any particular state or condition; to support; to sustain; to uphold; to keep up; not to suffer to fail or decline; <as>as, to <ex>maintain</ex> a certain degree of heat in a furnace; to <ex>maintain</ex> a fence or a railroad; to <ex>maintain</ex> the digestive process or powers of the stomach; to <ex>maintain</ex> the fertility of soil; to <ex>maintain</ex> present reputation.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To keep possession of; to hold and defend; not to surrender or relinquish.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God values . . . every one as he <qex>maintains</qex> his post.</q> <rj><qau>Grew.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To continue; not to suffer to cease or fail.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Maintain</qex> talk with the duke.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To bear the expense of; to support; to keep up; to supply with what is needed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Glad, by his labor, to <qex>maintain</qex> his life.</q> <rj><qau>Stirling.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What <qex>maintains</qex> one vice would bring up two children.</q> <rj><qau>Franklin.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To affirm; to support or defend by argument.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is hard to <qex>maintain</qex> the truth, but much harder to be maintained by it.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To assert; vindicate; allege. See <er>Assert</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maintainable</ent><br/
<hw>Main*tain"a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>That may be maintained.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maintainer</ent><br/
<hw>Main*tain"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who maintains.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maintainor</ent><br/
<hw>Main*tain"or</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>mainteneor</ets>, F. <ets>mainteneur</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Crim. Law)</fld> <def>One who, not being interested, maintains a cause depending between others, by furnishing money, etc., to either party.</def>  <rj><au>Bouvier.</au>  <au>Wharton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maintenance</ent><br/
<hw>Main"te*nance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>maintenance</ets>. See <er>Maintain</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of maintaining; sustenance; support; defense; vindication.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whatsoever is granted to the church for God's honor and the <qex>maintenance</qex> of his service, is granted to God.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which maintains or supports; means of sustenance; supply of necessaries and conveniences.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those of better fortune not making learning their <qex>maintenance</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Crim. Law)</fld> <def>An officious or unlawful intermeddling in a cause depending between others, by assisting either party with money or means to carry it on. See <er>Champerty</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Wharton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Those actions required for the care of machinery, a building, etc., to keep it clean and in proper functioning condition, and to prevent or forestall damage due to normal use.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Payments, such as child support or alimony, to a dependent child not living with one or to a divorced wife.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Cap of maintenance</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Cap</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maintenance man</ent><br/
<hw>maintenance man</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A worker, usually in an enterprise or apartment building, whose job is to repair damaged parts of a building or its fixtures, and sometimes to make improvements or other changes to the building.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maintenance staff</ent><br/
<hw>maintenance staff</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Those persons in a business responsible for maintaining the physical plant in good condition.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> service staff, maintenance crew.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maintop</ent><br/
<hw>main"top`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The platform about the head of the mainmast in square-rigged vessels.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>main-topmast</ent><br/
<hw>main-topmast</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the mast next above the mainmast.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>main-topsail</ent><br/
<hw>main-topsail</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a topsail set on the mainmast.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Main yard</ent><br/
<hw>Main" yard`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The yard on which the mainsail is extended, supported by the mainmast.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maioid</ent><br/
<hw>Mai"oid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Maia</ets> + <ets>-oid</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the genus <gen>Maia</gen>, or family <fam>Maiadeae</fam>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maister</ent><br/
<hw>Mais"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Master.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer. Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maister</ent><br/
<hw>Mais"ter</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Principal; chief.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maistry</ent><br/
<ent>Maistrie</ent><br/
<ent>Maistre</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mais"tre</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mais"trie</hw>, <hw>Mais"try</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mastery; superiority; art. See <er>Mastery</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maistress</ent><br/
<hw>Mais"tress</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mistress.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maithes</ent><br/
<hw>Mai"thes</hw> <pr>(m<amac/"th<ecr/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Maghet</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maitre d'hotel</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mai`tre d'ho*tel"</hw>, <hw>ma<icir/`tre d'h<ocir/*tel`</hw></mhw> <pr>(m<amac/"t<etil/r d<omac/*t<ecr/l" or m<amac/"tr<ucr/ d<omac/*t<ecr/l")</pr>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>maitres d'hotel</plw></plu>. <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A headwaiter.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> captain, head waiter.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The manager or owner of a hotel.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maize</ent><br/
<hw>maize</hw> <pr>(m<amac/z)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>maiz</ets>. fr. <ets>mahiz</ets> or <ets>mahis</ets>, is the language of the Island of Haiti.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A large species of American grass of the genus <gen>Zea</gen> (<spn>Zea Mays</spn>), widely cultivated as a forage and food plant; Indian corn, commonly called <altname>corn</altname>.  Also, its seed, growing on cobs, and used as food for men and animals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Maize eater</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a South American bird of the genus <gen>Pseudoleistes</gen>, allied to the troupials.</cd> -- <col><b>Maize yellow</b></col>, <cd>a delicate pale yellow.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>majagua</ent><br/
<hw>majagua</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A shrubby tree (<spn>Hibiscus tiliaceus</spn>) widely distributed along tropical shores, which yields a light tough wood used for canoe outriggers and a fiber used for cordage and caulk; it is often cultivated for ornament.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mahoe, mahagua, balibago, purau, <spn>Hibiscus tiliaceus</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An erect forest tree (<spn>Hibiscus elatus</spn>) of Cuba and Jamaica having variably hairy leaves and orange-yellow or orange-red flowers; it yields a moderately dense timber for cabinetwork and gunstocks.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Cuban bast, blue mahoe, mahoe, mahagua, <spn>Hibiscus elatus</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maja squinado</ent><br/
<hw>maja squinado</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[species name.]</ety> <def>A large European spider crab.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> European spider crab, king crab, <spn>Maja squinado</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Majestatal</ent><br/
<ent>Majestatic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Maj`es*tat"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Maj`es*tat"*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Majestic.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>E. Pocock.</au>  <au>Dr. J. Scott.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Majestic</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*jes"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Majesty</er>.]</ety> <def>Possessing or exhibiting majesty; of august dignity, stateliness, or imposing grandeur; lofty; noble; grand.</def> <ldquo/The <xex>majestic</xex> world.<rdquo/ <au>Shak.</au> <ldquo/Tethys' grave <xex>majestic</xex> pace.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The least portions must be of the epic kind; all must be grave, <qex>majestic</qex>, and sublime.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- August; splendid; grand; sublime; magnificent; imperial; regal; pompous; stately; lofty; dignified; elevated.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 885 --></p>

<p><ent>Majestical</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*jes"tic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Majestic.</def>  <rj><au>Cowley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An older architecture, greater, cunninger, more <qex>majestical</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>M. Arnold.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Ma*jes"tic*al*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Ma*jes"tic*al*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Majesticness</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*jes"tic*ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being majestic.</def>  <rj><au>Oldenburg.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Majesty</ent><br/
<hw>Maj"es*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Majesties</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>magestee</ets>, F. <ets>majest<eacute/</ets>, L. <ets>majestas</ets>, fr. an old compar. of <ets>magnus</ets> great. See <er>Major</er>, <er>Master</er>.]</ety> <def>The dignity and authority of sovereign power; quality or state which inspires awe or reverence; grandeur; exalted dignity, whether proceeding from rank, character, or bearing; imposing loftiness; stateliness; -- usually applied to the rank and dignity of sovereigns.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Lord reigneth; he is clothed with <qex>majesty</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. xciii. 1.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No sovereign has ever represented the <qex>majesty</qex> of a great state with more dignity and grace.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, used with the possessive pronoun, the title of an emperor, king or queen; -- in this sense taking a plural; <as>as, their <ex>majesties</ex> attended the concert</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In all the public writs which he [Emperor Charles V.] now issued as King of Spain, he assumed the title of <qex>Majesty</qex>, and required it from his subjects as a mark of respect. Before that time all the monarchs of Europe were satisfied with the appellation of <qex>Highness</qex> or <qex>Grace</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Robertson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Dignity; elevation of manner or style.</def>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Majidae</ent><br/
<hw>Majidae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family comprising the spider crabs.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Majidae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Majolica</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*jol"i*ca</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It.]</ety> <def>A kind of pottery, with opaque glazing and showy decoration, which reached its greatest perfection in Italy in the 16th century.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The term is said to be derived from Majorca, which was an early seat of this manufacture.</note>  <rj><au>Heyse.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Major</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"jor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <ety>[L. <ets>major</ets>, compar. of magnus great: cf. F. <ets>majeur</ets>.  Cf. <er>Master</er>, <er>Mayor</er>, <er>Magnitude</er>, <er>More</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Greater in number, quantity, or extent; <as>as, the <ex>major</ex> part of the assembly; the <ex>major</ex> part of the revenue; the <ex>major</ex> part of the territory.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of greater dignity; more important.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Of full legal age; adult.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Greater by a semitone, either in interval or in difference of pitch from another tone.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Major key</b></col> <fld>(Mus.)</fld>, <cd>a key in which one and two, two and three, four and five, five and six and seven, make major seconds, and three and four, and seven and eight, make minor seconds.</cd> -- <col><b>Major offense</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>an offense of a greater degree which contains a lesser offense, as murder and robbery include assault.</cd> -- <col><b>Major scale</b></col> <fld>(Mus.)</fld>, <cd>the natural diatonic scale, which has semitones between the third and fourth, and seventh and fourth, and seventh and eighth degrees; the scale of the major mode, of which the third is major. See <er>Scale</er>, and <er>Diatonic</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Major second</b></col> <fld>(Mus.)</fld>, <cd>a second between whose tones is a difference in pitch of a step.</cd> -- <col><b>Major sixth</b></col> <fld>(Mus.)</fld>, <cd>a sixth of four steps and a half step. In major keys the third and sixth from the key tone are major. Major keys and intervals, as distinguished from minors, are more cheerful.</cd> -- <col><b>Major third</b></col> <fld>(Mus.)</fld>, <cd>a third of two steps.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Major</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"jor</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>major</ets>. See <er>Major</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>An officer next in rank above a captain and next below a lieutenant colonel; the lowest field officer.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A person of full age.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Logic)</fld> <def>That premise which contains the major term. It its the first proposition of a regular syllogism; as: No unholy person is qualified for happiness in heaven [the major]. Every man in his natural state is unholy [minor]. Therefore, no man in his natural state is qualified for happiness in heaven [conclusion or inference].</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ In hypothetical syllogisms, the hypothetical premise is called the <xex>major</xex>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <ety>[LL. See <er>Major</er>.]</ety> <def>A mayor.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Majorana</ent><br/
<hw>Majorana</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A small genus of herbs usually included in the genus <gen>Origanum</gen>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Majorana</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Majorat</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma`jo`rat"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>majorat</ets>, LL. <ets>majoratus</ets>. See <er>Major</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and cf. <er>Majorate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The right of succession to property according to age; -- so termed in some of the countries of continental Europe.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(French Law)</fld> <def>Property, landed or funded, so attached to a title of honor as to descend with it.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Majorate</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"jor*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The office or rank of a major.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Majorate</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"jor*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>majorare</ets> to augment. See <er>Major</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>To augment; to increase.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Howell.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Majoration</ent><br/
<hw>Ma`jor*a"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Increase; enlargement.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>major axis</ent><br/
<hw>major axis</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Geom.)</fld>, <def>The greater axis of a geometrical figure.</def> <specif>Especially</specif>: <def>the longest axis of an ellipse or ellipsoid, which passes through the two foci. See <er>Focus</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 2.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Majorcan</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*jor"can</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to Majorca.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A native or inhabitant of Majorca.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>major diatonic scale</ent><br/
<hw>major diatonic scale</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Mus.)</fld>, <def>The natural diatonic scale, which has semitones between the third and fourth, and seventh and eighth notes, and whole tones between the other notes;  the scale of the major mode, of which the third is major; also called <altname>major scale</altname>.   See <er>Scale</er>, and <er>Diatonic</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Major-domo</ent><br/
<hw>Ma`jor-do"mo</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>mayordomo</ets>, or It. <ets>maggiordomo</ets>; both fr. LL. <ets>majordomus</ets>; L. <ets>major</ets> greater + <ets>domus</ets> house.]</ety> <def>A man who has authority to act, within certain limits, as master of the house; a steward; also, a chief minister or officer.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>major form class</ent><br/
<hw>major form class</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Grammar)</fld> <def>Any of the <er>parts of speech</er> of traditional grammar.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Major general</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"jor gen"er*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <def>An officer of the army holding a rank next above that of brigadier general and next below that of lieutenant general, and who usually commands a division or a corps.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Majority</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*jor"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Majorities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F. <ets>majorit<eacute/</ets>. See <er>Major</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality or condition of being major or greater; superiority.</def> Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The military rank of a major.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The condition of being of full age, or authorized by law to manage one's own affairs.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The greater number; more than half; <as>as, a <ex>majority</ex> of mankind; a <ex>majority</ex> of the votes cast.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <ety>[Cf. L. <ets>majores</ets>.]</ety> <def>Ancestors; ancestry.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The amount or number by which one aggregate exceeds all other aggregates with which it is contrasted; especially, the number by which the votes for a successful candidate exceed those for all other candidates; <as>as, he is elected by a <ex>majority</ex> of five hundred votes</as>. See <er>Plurality</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To go over to the majority</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To join the majority</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to die.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>majority leader</ent><br/
<hw>majority leader</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Politics)</fld> <def>The leader of the majority party in a legislature.  Compare <contr>minority leader</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>majority rule</ent><br/
<hw>majority rule</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The rule or doctrine that the numerical majority{2} of an organized group can make decisions binding on the whole group; <as>as, our club makes decisions by <ex>majority rule</ex>.</as>.  Contrasted with <contr>unanimous consent</contr>, or decision by a <contr>decree</contr> of a single person or small committee forming part of an organization.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>major league</ent><br/
<hw>major league</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Sports)</fld> <def>The most important league{2} in any sport (especially baseball); contrasted with <contr>minor league</contr>.  Its teams are more competent, its members are paid more, and its games attract more interest and publicity, than those of a minor league.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p> 

<p><ent>major league</ent><br/
<ent>major-league</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>major-league</hw>, <hw>major league</hw></mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a <er>major league</er>; <as>as, <ex>major-league</ex> football rules</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Among the best or most important of its class; <as>as, a <ex>major-league</ex> computer manufacturer</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>major-league team</ent><br/
<ent>major-league club</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>major-league club</hw>, <hw>major-league team</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A sports team that plays in a major league.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>major leaguer</ent><br/
<hw>major leaguer</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A member of a major-league baseball team.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>major power</ent><br/
<hw>major power</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A nation powerful enough to influence events throughout the world.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> world power, great power, power.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>major premise</ent><br/
<hw>major premise</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Logic)</fld>, <def>That premise of a syllogism that contains the major term (which is the predicate of the conclusion).  Contrasted to <contr>minor premise</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Majorship</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"jor*ship</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The office of major.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>majors</ent><br/
<hw>majors</hw> <pos>n. pl.</pos> <def>The teams in the major leagues.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> major leagues, big leagues.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>major suit</ent><br/
<hw>major suit</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bridge)</fld> <def>A suit of playing cards which has higher scoring value; specifically, either spades or hearts.  Contrasted with a <contr>minor suit</contr>, being either diamonds or clubs.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>major term</ent><br/
<hw>major term</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Logic)</fld>, <def>That term of a syllogism which forms the predicate of the conclusion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Majoun</ent><br/
<hw>Maj"oun</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Madjoun</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Majusculae</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*jus"cu*lae</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[L., fem. pl. fr. <ets>majusculus</ets> somewhat greater or great, dim. of <ets>major</ets>, <ets>majus</ets>. See <er>Major</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Palaeography)</fld> <def>Capital letters, as found in manuscripts of the sixth century and earlier.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Majuscule</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*jus"cule</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>majuscule</ets>. See <er>Majusculae</er>.]</ety> <def>A capital letter; especially, one used in ancient manuscripts. See <er>Majusculae</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Majuscule writing</b></col>, <cd>writing composed wholly of capital letters, especially the style which prevailed in Europe from the third to the sixth century.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>makable</ent><br/
<hw>mak"a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Capable of being made.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Makalu</ent><br/
<hw>Makalu</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A mountain in Nepal and Tibet, 27,824 feet high.</def> <comm>According to WordNet, it is 27,790 feet high.</comm><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Makalu I.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>makaron</ent><br/
<hw>mak"a*ron</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Macaroon</er>, 2.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>make</ent><br/
<hw>make</hw> <pr>(m<amac/k)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>maca</ets>, <ets>gemaca</ets>. See <er>Match</er>.]</ety> <def>A companion; a mate; often, a husband or a wife.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For in this world no woman is<br/
Worthy to be my <qex>make</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>make</ent><br/
<hw>make</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>made</conjf> <pr>(m<amac/d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>making</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>maken</ets>, <ets>makien</ets>, AS. <ets>macian</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>mak<?/n</ets>, OFries. <ets>makia</ets>, D. <ets>maken</ets>, G. <ets>machen</ets>, OHG. <ets>mahh<?/n</ets> to join, fit, prepare, make, Dan. <ets>mage</ets>.  Cf. <er>Match</er> an equal.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to exist; to bring into being; to form; to produce; to frame; to fashion; to create.</def> Hence, in various specific uses or applications: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To form of materials; to cause to exist in a certain form; to construct; to fabricate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He . . . fashioned it with a graving tool, after he had <qex>made</qex> it a molten calf.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xxxii. 4.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>To produce, as something artificial, unnatural, or false; -- often with <xex>up</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>make</ex> up a story</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And Art, with her contending, doth aspire<br/
To excel the natural with <qex>made</qex> delights.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>To bring about; to bring forward; to be the cause or agent of; to effect, do, perform, or execute; -- often used with a noun to form a phrase equivalent to the simple verb that corresponds to such noun; as, to <xex>make</xex> complaint, for to complain; to <xex>make</xex> record of, for to record; to <xex>make</xex> abode, for to abide, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Call for Samson, that he may <qex>make</qex> us sport.</q> <rj><qau>Judg. xvi. 25.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wealth <qex>maketh</qex> many friends.</q> <rj><qau>Prov. xix. 4.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will neither plead my age nor sickness in excuse of the faults which I have <qex>made</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <def>To execute with the requisite formalities; as, to <xex>make</xex> a bill, note, will, deed, etc.</def> <sd>(e)</sd> <def>To gain, as the result of one's efforts; to get, as profit; to make acquisition of; to have accrue or happen to one; <as>as, to <ex>make</ex> a large profit; to <ex>make</ex> an error; to <ex>make</ex> a loss; to <ex>make</ex> money</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He accuseth Neptune unjustly who <qex>makes</qex> shipwreck a second time.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(f)</sd> <def>To find, as the result of calculation or computation; to ascertain by enumeration; to find the number or amount of, by reckoning, weighing, measurement, and the like; as, he <xex>made</xex> the distance of; to travel over; <as>as, the ship <ex>makes</ex> ten knots an hour; he <ex>made</ex> the distance in one day</as>.</def> <sd>(h)</sd> <def>To put in a desired or desirable condition; to cause to thrive.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who <qex>makes</qex> or ruins with a smile or frown.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause to be or become; to put into a given state verb, or adjective; to constitute; <as>as, to <ex>make</ex> known; to <ex>make</ex> public; to <ex>make</ex> fast.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who <qex>made</qex> thee a prince and a judge over us?</q> <rj><qau>Ex. ii. 14.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>See, I have <qex>made</qex> thee a god to Pharaoh.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. vii. 1.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ When used reflexively with an adjective, the reflexive pronoun is often omitted; as, to <xex>make</xex> merry; to <xex>make</xex> bold; to <xex>make</xex> free, etc.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to appear to be; to constitute subjectively; to esteem, suppose, or represent.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He is not that goose and ass that Valla would <qex>make</qex> him.</q> <rj><qau>Baker.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To require; to constrain; to compel; to force; to cause; to occasion; -- followed by a noun or pronoun and infinitive.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ In the active voice the <xex>to</xex> of the infinitive is usually omitted.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will <qex>make</qex> them hear my words.</q> <rj><qau>Deut. iv. 10.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They should be <qex>made</qex> to rise at their early hour.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To become; to be, or to be capable of being, changed or fashioned into; to do the part or office of; to furnish the material for; <as>as, he will <ex>make</ex> a good musician; sweet cider <ex>makes</ex> sour vinegar; wool <ex>makes</ex> warm clothing.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And old cloak <qex>makes</qex> a new jerkin.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To compose, as parts, ingredients, or materials; to constitute; to form; to amount to; <as>as, a pound of ham <ex>makes</ex> a hearty meal</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The heaven, the air, the earth, and boundless sea,<br/
<qex>Make</qex> but one temple for the Deity.</q> <rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To be engaged or concerned in.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Gomez, what <qex>makest</qex> thou here, with a whole brotherhood of city bailiffs?</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To reach; to attain; to arrive at or in sight of.</def> <ldquo/And <xex>make</xex> the Libyan shores.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They that sail in the middle can <qex>make</qex> no land of either side.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. Browne.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To make a bed</b></col>, <cd>to prepare a bed for being slept on, or to put it in order.</cd> -- <col><b>To make a card</b></col> <fld>(Card Playing)</fld>, <cd>to take a trick with it.</cd> -- <col><b>To make account</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Account</er>, <pos>n.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>To make account of</b></col>, <cd>to esteem; to regard.</cd> -- <col><b>To make away</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To put out of the way; to kill; to destroy.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If a child were crooked or deformed in body or mind, they <qex>made</qex> him <qex>away</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Burton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To alienate; to transfer; to make over.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Waller.</au> -- <col><b>To make believe</b></col>, <cd>to pretend; to feign; to simulate.</cd> -- <col><b>To make bold</b></col>, <cd>to take the liberty; to venture.</cd> -- <col><b>To make the cards</b></col> <fld>(Card Playing)</fld>, <cd>to shuffle the pack.</cd> -- <col><b>To make choice of</b></col>, <cd>to take by way of preference; to choose.</cd> -- <col><b>To make danger</b></col>, <cd>to make experiment.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Beau. & Fl.</au> -- <col><b>To make default</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>to fail to appear or answer.</cd> -- <col><b>To make the doors</b></col>, <cd>to shut the door.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Make the doors</qex> upon a woman's wit, and it will out at the casement.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>- <col><b>To make free with</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Free</er>, <pos>a.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>To make good</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Good</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To make head</b></col>, <cd>to make headway.</cd> -- <col><b>To make light of</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Light</er>, <pos>a.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>To make little of</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To belittle.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To accomplish easily.</cd> -- <col><b>To make love to</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Love</er>, <pos>n.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>To make meat</b></col>, <cd>to cure meat in the open air.</cd> <mark>[Colloq. Western U. S.]</mark> -- <col><b>To make merry</b></col>, <cd>to feast; to be joyful or jovial.</cd> -- <col><b>To make much of</b></col>, <cd>to treat with much consideration,, attention, or fondness; to value highly.</cd> -- <col><b>To make no bones</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Bone</er>, <pos>n.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>To make no difference</b></col>, <cd>to have no weight or influence; to be a matter of indifference.</cd> -- <col><b>To make no doubt</b></col>, <cd>to have no doubt.</cd> -- <col><b>To make no matter</b></col>, <cd>to have no weight or importance; to make no difference.</cd> -- <col><b>To make oath</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>to swear, as to the truth of something, in a prescribed form of law.</cd> -- <col><b>To make of</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To understand or think concerning; <as>as, not to know what <ex>to make of</ex> the news</as>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To pay attention to; to cherish; to esteem; to account.</cd> <ldquo/<xex>Makes</xex> she no more <xex>of</xex> me than <xex>of</xex> a slave.<rdquo/ <au>Dryden.</au> -- <col><b>To make one's law</b></col> <fld>(Old Law)</fld>, <cd>to adduce proof to clear one's self of a charge.</cd> -- <col><b>To make out</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To find out; to discover; to decipher; <as>as, <ex>to make out</ex> the meaning of a letter</as>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>to gain sight of; to recognize; to discern; to descry; <as>as, as they approached the city, he could <ex>make out</ex> the tower of the Chrysler Building</as>.</cd>  <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To prove; to establish; <as>as, the plaintiff was unable <ex>to make</ex> out his case</as></cd>. <sd>(d)</sd> <cd>To make complete or exact; <as>as, he was not able <ex>to make out</ex> the money</as>.</cd> <sd>(d)</sd> <cd>to write out; to write down; -- used especially of a bank check or bill; <as>as, he <ex>made out</ex> a check for the cost of the dinner; the workman <ex>made out</ex> a bill and handed it to him</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To make over</b></col>, <cd>to transfer the title of; to convey; to alienate; <as>as, he <ex>made over</ex> his estate in trust or in fee</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To make sail</b></col>. <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To increase the quantity of sail already extended</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To set sail.</cd> -- <col><b>To make shift</b></col>, <cd>to manage by expedients; <as>as, they <ex>made shift</ex> to do without it</as>.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>. -- <col><b>To make sternway</b></col>, <cd>to move with the stern foremost; to go or drift backward.</cd> -- <col><b>To make strange</b></col>, <cd>to act in an unfriendly manner or as if surprised; to treat as strange; <as>as, <ex>to make strange</ex> of a request or suggestion</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To make suit to</b></col>, <cd>to endeavor to gain the favor of; to court.</cd> -- <col><b>To make sure</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Sure</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To make up</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To collect into a sum or mass; <as>as, <ex>to make up</ex> the amount of rent; <ex>to make up</ex> a bundle or package</as>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To reconcile; to compose; <as>as, <ex>to make up</ex> a difference or quarrel</as>.</cd> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To supply what is wanting in; to complete; <as>as, a dollar is wanted <ex>to make up</ex> the stipulated sum</as></cd>. <sd>(d)</sd> <cd>To compose, as from ingredients or parts; to shape, prepare, or fabricate; <as>as, <ex>to make up</ex> a mass into pills; <ex>to make up</ex> a story</as>.</cd><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was all <qex>made up</qex> of love and charms!</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(e)</sd> <cd>To compensate; to make good; <as>as, <ex>to make up</ex> a loss</as>.</cd> <sd>(f)</sd> <cd>To adjust, or to arrange for settlement; <as>as, <ex>to make up</ex> accounts</as></cd>. <sd>(g)</sd> <cd>To dress and paint for a part, as an actor; <as>as, he was well <ex>made up</ex></as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To make up a face</b></col>, <cd>to distort the face as an expression of pain or derision.</cd> -- <col><b>To make up one's mind</b></col>, <cd>to reach a mental determination; to resolve.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>To make way</b></col>, <it>or</it>  <col><b>To make one's way</b></col></mcol>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To make progress; to advance.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To open a passage; to clear the way</cd>. -- <col><b>To make words</b></col>, <cd>to multiply words.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Make</ent><br/
<hw>Make</hw> <pr>(m<amac/k)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To act in a certain manner; to have to do; to manage; to interfere; to be active; -- often in the phrase <xex>to meddle or make</xex>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A scurvy, jack-a-nape priest to meddle or <qex>make</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To proceed; to tend; to move; to go; <as>as, he <ex>made toward home</ex>; <ex>the tiger made</ex> at the sportsmen.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Formerly, authors used <xex>to make on</xex>, <xex>to make forth</xex>, <xex>to make about</xex>; but these phrases are obsolete. We now say, <xex>to make at</xex>, <xex>to make away</xex>, <xex>to make for</xex>, <xex>to make off</xex>, <xex>to make toward</xex>, etc.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To tend; to contribute; to have effect; -- with <xex>for</xex> or <xex>against</xex>; <as>as, it <ex>makes</ex> for his advantage</as>.</def>  <rj><au>M. Arnold.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Follow after the things which <qex>make</qex> for peace.</q> <rj><qau>Rom. xiv. 19.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Considerations infinite<br/
Do <qex>make</qex> against it.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To increase; to augment; to accrue.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To compose verses; to write poetry; to versify.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer. Tennyson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To solace him some time, as I do when I <qex>make</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>P. Plowman.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To make as if</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>To make as though</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to pretend that; to make show that; to make believe (see under <er>Make</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>).</cd><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Joshua and all Israel <qex>made as if</qex> they were beaten before them, and fled.</q> <rj><qau>Josh. viii. 15.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My lord of London <qex>maketh as though</qex> he were greatly displeased with me.</q> <rj><qau>Latimer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <col><b>To make at</b></col>, <cd>to go toward hastily, or in a hostile manner; to attack.</cd> -- <col><b>To make away with</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To carry off.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To transfer or alienate; hence, to spend; to dissipate</cd>. <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To kill; to destroy.</cd> -- <col><b>To make off</b></col>, <cd>to go away suddenly.</cd> -- <col><b>To make out</b></col>, <cd>to succeed; to manage oneself; to be able at last; to make shift; <as>as, he <ex>made out</ex> to reconcile the contending parties; after the earthquake they <ex>made out</ex> all right</as>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>to engage in fond caresses; to hug and kiss; to neck; -- of courting couples or individuals (for individuals, used with <ptcl>with</ptcl>); <as>as, they <ex>made out</ex> on a bench in the park; he was <ex>making out</ex> with the waitress in the kitchen</as></cd> <mark>[informal]</mark> -- <col><b>To make up</b></col>, <cd>to become reconciled or friendly.</cd> -- <col><b>To make up for</b></col>, <cd>to compensate for; to supply an equivalent for.</cd> -- <col><b>To make up to</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To approach; <as>as, a suspicious boat <ex>made up to</ex> us</as>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To pay addresses to; to make love to.</cd> -- <col><b>To make up with</b></col>, <cd>to become reconciled to.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> -- <col><b>To make with</b></col>, <cd>to concur or agree with.</cd> <au>Hooker.</au></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Make</ent><br/
<hw>Make</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Structure, texture, constitution of parts; construction; shape; form.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It our perfection of so frail a <qex>make</qex><br/
As every plot can undermine and shake?</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>On the make</b></col>, <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>bent upon making great profits; greedy of gain.</cd> <mark>[Low, U. S.]</mark></cs>  <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>seeking higher social status or a higher employment position.</cd> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>seeking a sexual partner; looking for sexual adventure.</cd> <br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Make and break</ent><br/
<hw>Make and break</hw>. <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>Any apparatus for making and breaking an electric circuit; a circuit breaker.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Makebate</ent><br/
<hw>Make"bate`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Make</ets>, v. + <ets>bate</ets> a quarrel.]</ety> <def>One who excites contentions and quarrels.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>make-belief</ent><br/
<hw>make"-be*lief`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A feigning to believe; make believe.</def>  <rj><au>J. H. Newman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>make believe</ent><br/
<hw>make" be*lieve`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To pretend; -- often used with <ptcl>that</ptcl>, but often having the that omitted; <as>as, he <ex>made believe</ex> he didn't hear her; or he <ex>made believe</ex> that he didn't hear her</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>make-believe</ent><br/
<hw>make"-be*lieve`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A feigning to believe, as in the play of children; a mere pretense; a fiction; an invention.</def> <ldquo/Childlike <xex>make-believe</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Tylor.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To forswear self-delusion and <qex>make-believe</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>M. Arnold.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Make-believe</ent><br/
<hw>Make"-be*lieve`</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Feigned; insincere.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Make-believe</xex> reverence.<rdquo/ <rj><au>G. Eliot.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Imaginary; <as>as, the child had a <ex>make-believe</ex> friend to whom he often talked</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maked</ent><br/
<hw>Mak"ed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <mark>obs.</mark> <mord><pos>p. p.</pos> of <er>Make</er></mord>. <def>Made.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Make-game</ent><br/
<hw>Make"-game`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An object of ridicule; a butt.</def>  <rj><au>Godwin.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>make known</ent><br/
<hw>make known</hw> <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To reveal; to disclose; <as>as, the congressman <ex>made known</ex> his interest in the company only after he voted on the bill</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Makeless</ent><br/
<hw>Make"less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See 1st <er>Make</er>, and cf. <er>Matchless</er>, <er>Mateless</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Matchless.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Without a mate.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Make-peace</ent><br/
<hw>Make"-peace`</hw> <pr>(-p<emac/s`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A peacemaker.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maker</ent><br/
<hw>Mak"er</hw> <pr>(m<amac/k"<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who makes, forms, or molds; a manufacturer; specifically, the Creator.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The universal <qex>Maker</qex> we may praise.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The person who makes a promissory note.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One who writes verses; a poet.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <ldquo/The Greeks named the poet <grk>poihth`s</grk>, which name, as the most excellent, hath gone through other languages.  It cometh of this word <grk>poiei^n</grk>, <xex>make</xex>; wherein, I know not whether by luck or wisdom, we Englishmen have met well the Greeks in calling him a <xex>maker</xex>.<rdquo/</note>  <rj><au>Sir P. Sidney.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To meet one's maker</b></col>, <cd>to die.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>makeready</ent><br/
<hw>makeready</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The final preparation and adjustments.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 886 --></p>

<p><ent>makeshift</ent><br/
<hw>make"shift`</hw> <pr>(m<amac/k"sh<icr/ft`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>That with which one makes shift; a temporary expedient, with implication of inferiority to the more usual object or means.</def>  <rj><au>James Mill.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am not a model clergyman, only a decent <qex>makeshift</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>G. Eliot.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>make-up</ent><br/
<ent>makeup</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>make"up`</hw>, <hw>make"-up`</hw></mhw> <pr>(m<amac/k"<ucr/p`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>  <sn>1.</sn> <def>The way in which the parts of anything are put together.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The unthinking masses are necessarily teleological in their mental <qex>make-up</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>L. F. Ward.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The constituent parts of anything; <as>as, the <ex>makeup</ex> of the new congress was predominantly conservative</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Cosmetics applied to the face, such as <stype>lipstick</stype>, <stype>facial power</stype>, or <stype>eye shadow</stype>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The aggregate of cosmetics and costume worn by an actor.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The effect or appearance of the wearing of makeup (in senses 3 or 4); often, the way in which an actor is dressed, painted, etc., in personating a character; <as>as, her <ex>makeup</ex> was very realistic</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>An action that is taken to fulfill a requirement not accomplished at the expected time, such as a make-up examination; <as>as, the student took his <ex>make-up</ex> on Saturday</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Printing)</fld> <def>The appearance of a page of a publication, specifically the type style of the text and the spatial arrangement of the text, illustrations, advertising material etc., on the page.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Printing)</fld> <def>The art or process of arranging the portions of a printed publication on the pages for esthetic reasons or for optimal effect on the reader.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>make water</ent><br/
<hw>make water</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To leak.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To urinate; -- a euphemism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Makeweight</ent><br/
<hw>Make"weight`</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>That which is thrown into a scale to make weight; something of little account added to supply a deficiency or fill a gap.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>make-work</ent><br/
<hw>make-work</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Active work of litle value, such as assignments given by teachers to students to keep them busy while the teacher performs other tasks, or chores performed to while away time; also called <altname>busywork</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> busywork.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maki</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma"ki</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., from native name.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A lemur. See <er>Lemur</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Making</ent><br/
<hw>Mak"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of one who makes; workmanship; fabrication; construction; <as>as, this is cloth of your own <ex>making</ex>; the <ex>making</ex> of peace or war was in his power.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Composition, or structure.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>a poem.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir J. Davies.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That which establishes or places in a desirable state or condition; the material of which something may be made; <as>as, early misfortune was the <ex>making</ex> of him</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>External appearance; from.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Making-iron</ent><br/
<hw>Mak"ing-i`ron</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A tool somewhat like a chisel with a groove in it, used by calkers of ships to finish the seams after the oakum has been driven in.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Making-up</ent><br/
<hw>Mak"ing-up`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of bringing spirits to a certain degree of strength, called <xex>proof</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of becoming reconciled or friendly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mako</ent><br/
<hw>mako</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>mako shark</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>makomako</ent><br/
<hw>makomako</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A graceful deciduous shrub or small tree (<spn>Aristotelia serrata</spn>) having attractive foliage and small red berries that turn black at maturity and are used for making wine.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> New Zealand wine berry, wineberry, <spn>Aristotelia serrata</spn>, <spn>Aristotelia racemosa</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mako shark</ent><br/
<hw>mako shark</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A powerful and fierce mackerel shark of the Atlantic and Pacific, of the family <fam>Lamidae</fam>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maksutov telescope</ent><br/
<hw>Maksutov telescope</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A type of reflecting telescope in which the aberration of the concave mirror is reduced by a meniscus lens.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mal-</ent><br/
<hw>Mal-</hw> <pr>(m<acr/l-)</pr>. <def>A prefix in composition denoting <sig>ill</sig>, or <sig>evil</sig>, F. <ets>male</ets>, adv., fr. <ets>malus</ets>, bad, ill.  In some words it has the form <altname>male-</altname>, as in <ex>male</ex>diction, <ex>male</ex>volent. See <er>Malice</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The form <xex>male-</xex> is chiefly used in cases where the <eit/, either alone or with other letters, is pronounced as a separate syllable, as in <xex>male</xex>diction, <xex>male</xex>factor, <xex>male</xex>ficent, etc. Where this is not the case, as in <xex>mal</xex>feasance or <xex>male</xex>-feasance, <xex>mal</xex>formation or <xex>male</xex>-formation, etc., as also where the word to which it is prefixed commences with a vowel, as in <xex>mal</xex>administration, etc., the form <ex>mal</ex> is to be preferred, and is the one commonly employed.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mala</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma"la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos>; <sing>pl. of <singw>Malum</singw>.</sing> <ety>[L.]</ety> <def>Evils; wrongs; offenses against right and law.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mala in se</b></col> <ety>[L.]</ety> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>offenses which are such from their own nature, at common law, irrespective of statute.</cd> -- <col><b>Mala prohibita</b></col> <ety>[L.]</ety> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>offenses prohibited by statute, as distinguished from <contr>mala in se</contr>, which are offenses at common law.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malabar</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"a*bar`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A region in the western part of the Peninsula of India, between the mountains and the sea.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Malabar nut</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the seed of an East Indian acanthaceous shrub, the <spn>Adhatoda Vasica</spn>, sometimes used medicinally.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malabar kino</ent><br/
<hw>malabar kino</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The reddish or black juice or resin from certain trees of the genus <gen>Pterocarpus</gen>, used in medicine and tanning etc.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> East India kino, kino gum.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacanthidae</ent><br/
<hw>Malacanthidae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of short-headed marine fishes which are often brightly colored.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Malacanthidae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacatune</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`a*ca*tune"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Melocoton</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacca</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*lac"ca</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A town and district upon the seacoast of the Malay Peninsula.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malacca cane</ent><br/
<hw>malacca cane</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <def>A walking cane made from the stem of a species of palm of the genus <gen>Calamus</gen> (<spn>Calamus Scipionum</spn>), and of a brown color, often mottled. The plant is a native of Cochin China, Sumatra, and Malays.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malachite</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"a*chite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Fr. Gr. <grk>mala`chh</grk> a mallow, from its resembling the green color of the leaf of mallows: cf. F. <ets>malachite</ets>.  Cf. <er>Mallow</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Native hydrous carbonate of copper, usually occurring in green mammillary masses with concentric fibrous structure.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Green malachite</xex>, or malachite proper, admits of a high polish, and is sometimes used for ornamental work. <xex>Blue malachite</xex>, or azurite, is a related species of a deep blue color.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Malachite green</b></col>. <cd>See <cref>Emerald green</cref>, under <er>Green</er>, <pos>n.</pos></cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacissant</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`a*cis"sant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Malacissation</er>.]</ety> <def>Softening; relaxing.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacissation</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`a*cis*sa"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>malacissare</ets> to make soft, Gr. <grk>malaki`zein</grk>.]</ety> <def>The act of making soft or supple.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacobdella</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mal`a*cob*del"la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>malako`s</grk> soft + <?/ a leech.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of nemertean worms, parasitic in the gill cavity of clams and other bivalves. They have a large posterior sucker, like that of a leech. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Bdellomorpha</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacoderm</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"a*co*derm</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>malako`s</grk> soft  + <?/ skin.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of a tribe of beetles (<spn>Malacodermata</spn>), with a soft and flexible body, as the fireflies.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacolite</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"a*co*lite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>malako`s</grk> soft + <ets>-lite</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A variety of pyroxene.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacologist</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`a*col"o*gist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One versed in the science of malacology.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacology</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`a*col"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>malako`s</grk> soft + <ets>-logy</ets>: cf. F. <ets>malacologie</ets>.]</ety> <def>The science which relates to the structure and habits of mollusks.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacopoda</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mal`a*cop"o*da</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>malako`s</grk> soft + <ets>-poda</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A class of air-breathing <phylum>Arthropoda</phylum>; -- called also <altname><class>Protracheata</class></altname>, and <altname><class>Onychophora</class></altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ They somewhat resemble myriapods, and have from seventeen to thirty-three pairs of short, imperfectly jointed legs, two pairs of simple jaws, and a pair of antennae. The trancheae are connected with numerous spiracles scattered over the surface of the body. <gen>Peripatus</gen> is the only known genus. See <er>Peripatus</er>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacopterygian</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`a*cop`ter*yg"i*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>malacopt<eacute/rygien</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the <ord>Malacopterygii</ord>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacopterygii</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mal`a*cop`te*ryg"i*i</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>malako`s</grk> soft + <grk>pte`ryx</grk> wing, fin, fr. <grk>ptero`n</grk> feather.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An order of fishes in which the fin rays, except the anterior ray of the pectoral and dorsal fins, are closely jointed, and not spiny.  It includes the carp, pike, salmon, shad, etc. Called also <ord>Malacopteri</ord>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacopterygious</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`a*cop`ter*yg"i*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Belonging to the <ord>Malacopterygii</ord>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacosteon</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`a*cos"te*on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., Gr. fr. <grk>malako`s</grk> soft + <grk>'oste`on</grk> bone.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A peculiar disease of the bones, in consequence of which they become softened and capable of being bent without breaking.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacostomous</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`a*cos"to*mous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>malako`s</grk> soft + <?/ mouth.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having soft jaws without teeth, as certain fishes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacostraca</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mal`a*cos"tra*ca</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., from Gr. <grk>malako`s</grk> soft + <?/ shell of a testacean.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A subclass of Crustacea, including Arthrostraca and Thoracostraca, or all those higher than the Entomostraca.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacostracan</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`a*cos"tra*can</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the <subclass>Malacostraca</subclass>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacostracology</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`a*cos`tra*col"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Malacostrac</ets>an + <ets>-logy</ets>.]</ety> <def>That branch of Zoological science which relates to the crustaceans; -- called also <altname>carcinology</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacostracous</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`a*cos"tra*cous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Belonging to the Malacostraca.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacotoon</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`a*co*toon"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>See <er>Melocoton</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacozoa</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mal`a*co*zo"a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>malako`s</grk> soft + <grk>zw^,on</grk> an animal.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An extensive group of Invertebrata, including the <phylum>Mollusca</phylum>, Brachiopoda, and Bryozoa. Called also <altname>Malacozoaria</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malacozoic</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`a*co*zo"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the Malacozoa.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maladdress</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`ad*dress"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mal-</ets> + <ets>address</ets>.]</ety> <def>Bad address; an awkward, tactless, or offensive way of accosting one or talking with one.</def>  <rj><au>W. D. Howells.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maladjustment</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`ad*just"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mal-</ets> + <ets>adjustment</ets>.]</ety> <def>A bad adjustment.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maladministration</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`ad*min`is*tra"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mal-</ets> + <ets>administration</ets>.]</ety> <def>Bad administration; bad management of any business, especially of public affairs.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>maleadministration</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maladroit</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`a*droit"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. See <er>Malice</er>, and <er>Adroit</er>.]</ety> <def>Of a quality opposed to adroitness; clumsy; awkward; unskillful.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mal"a*droit`ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mal`a*droit"ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malady</ent><br/
<hw>mal"a*dy</hw> <pr>(m<acr/l"<adot/*d<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Maladies</plw> <pr>(m<acr/l"<adot/*d<icr/z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F. <ets>maladie</ets>, fr. <ets>malade</ets> ill, sick, OF. also, <ets>malabde</ets>, fr. L. <ets>male habitus</ets>, i. e., ill-kept, not in good condition. See <er>Malice</er>, and <er>Habit</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Any disease of the human body; a distemper, disorder, or indisposition, proceeding from impaired, defective, or morbid organic functions; especially, a lingering or deep-seated disorder.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>maladies</qex> of the body may prove medicines to the mind.</q> <rj><qau>Buckminster.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A moral or mental defect or disorder.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Love's a <qex>malady</qex> without a cure.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Disorder; distemper; sickness; ailment; disease; illness. See <er>Disease</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malaga</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"a*ga</hw> <pr>(m<acr/l"<adot/*g<adot/ Sp. m<aum/"l<adot/*g<adot/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A city and a province of <city>Spain</city>, on the Mediterranean.   Hence, <ex>Malaga</ex> grapes, <ex>Malaga</ex> raisins, <ex>Malaga</ex> wines.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malagash</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mal`a*gash"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Malagasy</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malagasy</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`a*gas"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. sing. & pl.</pos> <def>A native or natives of Madagascar; also (<singf>sing</singf>.), the language.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malagasy Republic</ent><br/
<hw>Malagasy Republic</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>Former name of the Republic of Madagascar, a nation in Africa occupying the island of Madagascar in the Indian Ocean east of Mozambique.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malaise</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma`laise"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>mal</ets> ill + <ets>aise</ets> ease.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>An indefinite feeling of uneasiness, or of being sick or ill at ease.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malamate</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*lam"ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of malamic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malambo</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*lam"bo</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pg.]</ety> <def>A yellowish aromatic bark, used in medicine and perfumery, said to be from the South American shrub <spn>Croton Malambo</spn>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malamethane</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`am*eth"ane</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Malamic</ets> + <ets>ethane</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A white crystalline substance forming the ethyl salt of malamic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malamic</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*lam"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mal</ets>ic + <ets>amic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Of or designating an acid intermediate between malic acid and malamide, and known only by its salts.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malamide</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*lam"ide</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Malic</ets> + <ets>amide</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>The acid amide derived from malic acid, as a white crystalline substance metameric with asparagine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malanders</ent><br/
<hw>mal"an*ders</hw> <pr>(m<acr/l"<ait/n*d<etil/rz)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>malandres</ets>, fr. L. <ets>malandria</ets> blisters or pustules on the neck, especially in horses.]</ety> <fld>(Far.)</fld> <def>A scurfy eruption in the bend of the knee of the fore leg of a horse. See <er>Sallenders</er>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mallenders</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malapert</ent><br/
<hw>mal"a*pert</hw> <pr>(m<acr/l"<adot/*p<etil/rt)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>malapert</ets> unskillful, ill-taught, ill-bred; <ets>mal</ets> ill + <ets>apert</ets> open, adroit, intelligent, L. <ets>apertus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>aperire</ets> to open. See <er>Malice</er>, and <er>Aperient</er>.]</ety> <def>Bold; forward; impudent; saucy; pert.</def> <au>Shak.</au> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A malapert person.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Are you growing <qex>malapert</qex>! <qex>Will you force me to make use of my authority</qex> ?</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Mal"a*pert`ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>mal"a*pert`ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malapropism</ent><br/
<hw>mal"a*prop*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <person>Mrs. <etsep>Malaprop</etsep></person>, a character in <persfn>Sheridan's</persfn> drama, <ldquo/ The Rivals,<rdquo/ who makes amusing blunders in her use of words. See <er>Malapropos</er>.]</ety> <def>A grotesque misuse of a word; a word so used.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malapropos</ent><br/
<hw>mal*ap"ro*pos`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a. & adv.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mal <agrave/ propos</ets>; <ets>mal</ets> evil + <ets><agrave/ propos</ets> to the purpose.]</ety> <def>Unseasonable or unseasonably; unsuitable or unsuitably.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malapterurus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mal*ap`te*ru"rus</hw> <pr>(m<acr/l*<acr/p`t<esl/*r<udd/"r<ucr/s)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[NL., from Gr. <grk>malako`s</grk> soft + <grk>ptero`n</grk> wing + <grk>o'yra`</grk> tail.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of African siluroid fishes, including the electric catfishes. See <cref>Electric cat</cref>, under <er>Electric</er>.</def> <altsp>[Sometimes spelled <asp>Malopterurus</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malapterurus electricus</ent><br/
<hw>Malapterurus electricus</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The species name of the <altname>electric catfish</altname>, a freshwater catfish of the Nile and tropical central Africa having an electric organ.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malar</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mala</ets> the cheek: cf. F. <ets>malaire</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the region of the cheek bone, or to the malar bone; jugal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malar</ent><br/
<hw>ma"lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The cheek bone, which forms a part of the lower edge of the orbit; that arch of bone beneath the eye that forms the prominence of the cheek; also called the <altname>malar bone</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> cheekbone, zygomatic bone, malar bone, jugal bone, os zygomaticum.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malar bone</ent><br/
<hw>malar bone</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>malar</er>, <pos>n.</pos></def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malaria</ent><br/
<hw>ma*la"ri*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It., contr. fr. <ets>malaaria</ets> bad air. See <er>Malice</er>, and Air.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Air infected with some noxious substance capable of engendering disease; esp., an unhealthy exhalation from certain soils, as marshy or wet lands, producing fevers; miasma.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The morbific agent in malaria is supposed by some to be a vegetable microbe or its spores, and by others to be a very minute animal blood parasite (an <xex>infusorian</xex>).</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A human disease caused by infection of red blood cells by a protozoan of the genus <gen>Plasmodium</gen>, giving rise to fever and chills and many other symptoms, characterized by their tendency to recur at definite and usually uniform intervals.  The protozoal infection is usually transmitted from another infected individual by the bite of an <gen>Anopheles</gen> mosquito.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malarious</ent><br/
<ent>Malarian</ent><br/
<ent>Malarial</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Ma*la"ri*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Ma*la"ri*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Ma*la"ri*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining, to or infected by, malaria.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Malarial fever</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>a fever produced by malaria, and characterized by the occurrence of chills, fever, and sweating in distinct paroxysms, At intervals of definite and often uniform duration, in which these symptoms are wholly absent (<xex>intermittent fever</xex>), or only partially so (<xex>remittent fever</xex>); fever and ague; chills and fever.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malarial mosquito</ent><br/
<ent>malaria mosquito</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>malaria mosquito</hw>, <hw>malarial mosquito</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mosquito that transmits the malaria parasite; it is most commonly the <gen>Anopheles</gen> mosquito.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malaria parasite</ent><br/
<hw>Malaria parasite</hw>. <def>Any of several minute protozoans of the genus <gen>Plasmodium</gen> (syn. <gen>Haematozoon</gen>) which in their adult condition live in the tissues of mosquitoes of the genus <gen>Anopheles</gen> (which see) and when transferred to the blood of man, by the bite of the mosquito, produce malaria.</def>  <note>The young parasites, or <b>sporozoites</b>, enter the red blood corpuscles, growing at their expense, undergoing sporulation, and finally destroying the corpuscles, thus liberating in the blood plasma an immense number of small spores called <b>merozoites</b>.  An indefinite but not ultimated number of such generations may follow, but if meanwhile the host is bitten by a mosquito, the parasites develop into gametes in the stomach of the insect. These conjugate, the zygote thus produced divides, forming spores, and eventually sporozoites, which, penetrating to the salivary glands of the mosquito, may be introduced into a new host. The attacks of the disease coincide with the dissolution of the corpuscles and liberation of the spores and products of growth of the parasites into the blood plasma. Several species of the parasite are distinguished, as <spn>Plasmodium vivax</spn>, producing tertian malaria; <spn>Plasmodium malariae</spn>, quartan malaria; and <spn>Plasmodium (<plain>subgenus</plain> Laverania) falciferum</spn>, the malarial fever of summer and autumn common in the tropics.</note><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malashaganay</ent><br/
<hw>Ma`la*sha"ga*nay</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Indian name.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The fresh-water drumfish (<spn>Haploidonotus grunniens</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malassimilation</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`as*sim`i*la"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mal-</ets> + <ets>assimilation</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Imperfect digestion of the several leading constituents of the food.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>An imperfect elaboration by the tissues of the materials brought to them by the blood.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malate</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>malum</ets> apple: cf. F. <ets>malate</ets>. See <er>Malic</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of malic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malawi kwacha</ent><br/
<hw>malawi kwacha</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The kwacha, the monetary unit of Malawi.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malaxate</ent><br/
<ent>Malax</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Ma"lax</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Ma*lax"ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>malaxare</ets>, <ets>malaxatum</ets>, cf. Gr. <?/, fr. <grk>malako`s</grk> soft: cf. F. <ets>malaxer</ets>.]</ety> <def>To soften by kneading or stirring with some thinner substance.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malaxation</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`ax*a"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>malaxatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>malaxation</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act of softening by mixing with a thinner substance; the formation of ingredients into a mass for pills or plasters.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malaxator</ent><br/
<hw>mal"ax*a`tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who, or that which, malaxates; esp., a machine for grinding, kneading, or stirring into a pasty or doughy mass.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malaxis</ent><br/
<hw>Malaxis</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A large genus of largely terrestrial orchids with one or a few plicate leaves and slender spikes or tiny mostly green flowers; it is cosmopolitan.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Malaxis</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malaxis-unifolia</ent><br/
<hw>Malaxis-unifolia</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A North American orchid having a solitary leaf and flowers with threadlike petals.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> green adder's mouth, <spn>Malaxis ophioglossoides</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malay</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*lay"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>One of a race of a brown or copper complexion in the Malay Peninsula and the western islands of the Indian Archipelago.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malayan</ent><br/
<ent>Malay</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Ma*lay"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Ma*lay"an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>prop. a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the Malays or their country.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>The Malay language.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Malay apple</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a myrtaceous tree (<spn>Eugenia Malaccensis</spn>) common in India; also, its applelike fruit.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malaya</ent><br/
<hw>Malaya</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>Formerly, an Asian country on Borneo and the Malay Peninsula, now part of <partof>Malaysia</partof>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malayalam</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"la*ya"lam</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The name given to one the cultivated Dravidian languages, closely related to the Tamil.</def>  <rj><au>Yule.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malayan tapir</ent><br/
<hw>Malayan tapir</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A large inoffensive chiefly nocturnal ungulate (<spn>Tapirus indicus</spn>) of tropical America and Southeast Asia having a heavy body and fleshy snout.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Indian tapir, <spn>Tapirus indicus</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malay Archipelago</ent><br/
<hw>Malay Archipelago</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A group of islands in the Indian and Pacific Oceans between Asia and Australia.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malayo-Polynesian</ent><br/
<hw>Malayo-Polynesian</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>of or pertaining to Malayo-Polynesia.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malay Peninsula</ent><br/
<hw>Malay Peninsula</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>a peninsula in Southeastern Asia occupied by parts of Malaysia and Thailand and Burma.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malaysia</ent><br/
<hw>Malaysia</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A country in Southeast Asia including the former nation of <part>Malaya</part> on the Malay Peninsula, and part of Borneo; sometimes still referred to as <altname>Malaya</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malaysian</ent><br/
<hw>Malaysian</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to or characteristic of Malaysia or its people or their culture; <as>as, <ex>Malaysian</ex> police cracked down hard on drug smugglers; <ex>Malaysian</ex> poetry</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malbrouck</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mal"brouck</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A West African arboreal monkey (<spn>Cercopithecus cynosurus</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malcolmia</ent><br/
<hw>Malcolmia</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of plants usually found in coastal habitats; native from the Mediterranean to Afghanistan.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Malcolmia</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malcolm Little</ent><br/
<hw>Malcolm Little</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A militant American black nationalist leader, also called <altname>Malcolm X</altname>; (1925-1965).</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malcolm stock</ent><br/
<hw>Malcolm stock</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Any of various ornamental flowering plants of the genus <gen>Malcolmia</gen>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malcolm X</ent><br/
<hw>Malcolm X</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>See <er>Malcolm Little</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malconformation</ent><br/
<hw>mal*con`for*ma"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mal-</ets> + <ets>conformation</ets>.]</ety> <def>Imperfect, disproportionate, or abnormal formation; ill form; disproportion of parts.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malcontent</ent><br/
<hw>mal"con*tent`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>mal</ets> ill + <ets>content</ets>. See <er>Malice</er>, <er>Content</er>.]</ety> <def>discontented; uneasy; dissatisfied; especially, dissatisfied with the government.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>malecontent</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The famous <qex>malcontent</qex> earl of Leicester.</q> <rj><qau>Milner.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malcontent</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"con*tent`</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>malcontent</ets>.]</ety> <def>One who discontented; especially, a discontented subject of a government; one who expresses his discontent by words or overt acts.</def>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au>  <au>Berkeley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malcontented</ent><br/
<hw>mal`con*tent"ed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Malcontent.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mal`con*tent"ed*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mal`con*tent"ed*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maldanian</ent><br/
<hw>mal*da"ni*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any species of marine annelids of the genus <gen>Maldane</gen>, or family <fam>Maldanidae</fam>.  They have a slender, round body, and make tubes in the sand or mud.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mal de mer</ent><br/
<hw>mal de mer</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Motion sickness experienced while traveling on water; seasickness.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> seasickness, naupathia.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maldive Islands</ent><br/
<hw>Maldive Islands</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A group of about 2000 islands in the Indian ocean; also known as the <altname>Maldives</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maldivian</ent><br/
<hw>Maldivian</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A native or inhabitant of Maldives.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Maldivan.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maldon</ent><br/
<hw>Maldon</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A battle in which the Danes defeated the East Saxons in 991; it is celebrated in an old English poem.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> battle of Maldon.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Male-</ent><br/
<hw>Male-</hw> <pr>(m<acr/l- <it>or</it>  m<acr/l<esl/-)</pr>. <def>See <er>Mal-</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Male</ent><br/
<hw>Male</hw> <pr>(m<amac/l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>malus</ets>. See <er>Malice</er>.]</ety> <def>Evil; wicked; bad.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Marston.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Male</ent><br/
<hw>Male</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Mail</er>, a bag.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Male</ent><br/
<hw>Male</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<acir/le</ets>, OF. <ets>masle</ets>, <ets>mascle</ets>, fr. L. <ets>masculus</ets> male, masculine, dim. of <ets>mas</ets> a male; possibly akin to E. <ets>man</ets>.  Cf. <er>Masculine</er>, <er>Marry</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the sex that begets or procreates young, or (in a wider sense) to the sex that produces spermatozoa, by which the ova are fertilized; not female; <as>as, <ex>male</ex> organs</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Capable of producing fertilization, but not of bearing fruit; -- said of stamens and antheridia, and of the plants, or parts of plants, which bear them.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Suitable to the male sex; characteristic or suggestive of a male; masculine; <as>as, <ex>male</ex> courage</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Consisting of males; <as>as, a <ex>male</ex> choir</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>Adapted for entering another corresponding piece (the <xex>female</xex> piece) which is hollow and which it fits; <as>as, a <ex>male</ex> gauge, for gauging the size or shape of a hole; a <ex>male</ex> screw, etc.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Male fern</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a fern of the genus <gen>Aspidium</gen> (<spn>Aspidium Filixmas</spn>), used in medicine as an anthelmintic, esp. against the tapeworm. <spn>Aspidium marginale</spn> in America, and <spn>Aspidium athamanticum</spn> in South Africa, are used as good substitutes for the male fern in medical practice. See <cref>Female fern</cref>, under <er>Female</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Male rhyme</b></col>, <cd>a rhyme in which only the last syllables agree, as <xex>laid</xex>, <xex>afraid</xex>, <xex>dismayed</xex>. See <cref>Female rhyme</cref>, under <er>Female</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Male screw</b></col> <fld>(Mech.)</fld>, <cd>a screw having threads upon its exterior which enter the grooves upon the inside of a corresponding nut or female screw.</cd> -- <col><b>Male thread</b></col>, <cd>the thread of a male screw.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Male</ent><br/
<hw>Male</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An animal of the male sex.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A plant bearing only staminate flowers.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maleadministration</ent><br/
<hw>Male`ad*min`is*tra"tion</hw> <pr>(m<acr/l`<acr/d*m<icr/n`<icr/s*tr<amac/"sh<ucr/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Maladministration.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maleate</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*le"ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A salt of maleic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>male berry</ent><br/
<ent>maleberry</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>male"ber`ry</hw>, <hw>male" ber`ry</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A deciduous much-branched shrub (<spn>Lyonia ligustrina</spn>) with dense downy panicles of small bell-shaped white flowers; also called <altname>swamp andromeda</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> privet andromeda, he-huckleberry, <spn>Lyonia ligustrina</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A kind of coffee. See <er>Pea berry</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>male body</ent><br/
<hw>male body</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The body of an adult human male; -- a term used especially in art; <as>as, <person>Da Vinci</person> was unexcelled in painting the <ex>male body</ex></as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> adult male body, man's body.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malebranchism</ent><br/
<hw>Male*branch"ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The philosophical system of <persfn><etsep>Malebranche</etsep></persfn>, an eminent French metaphysician.  The fundamental doctrine of his system is that the mind can not have knowledge of anything external to itself except in its relation to God.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>male chauvinism</ent><br/
<hw>male chauvinism</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Disparaging, patronizing, discriminatory or abusive speech or behavior by males toward females stemming from a belief that males are superior to females and females therefore worthy of less respect and inferior treatment.  A form of <isa>sexism</isa>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>male chauvinist</ent><br/
<hw>male chauvinist</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A man with a belief in the inferiority of women; one who believes in or practises male chavinism.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> sexist.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 887 --></p>

<p><ent>Maleconformation</ent><br/
<hw>Male*con`for*ma"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Malconformation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malecontent</ent><br/
<hw>Male"con*tent`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Malcontent.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maledicency</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`e*di"cen*cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>maledicentia</ets>. See <er>Maledicent</er>.]</ety> <def>Evil speaking.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Atterbury.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maledicent</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`e*di"cent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>maledicens</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>maledicere</ets> to speak ill; <ets>male</ets> ill + <ets>dicere</ets> to say, speak. See <er>Malice</er>, and <er>Diction</er>.]</ety> <def>Speaking reproachfully; slanderous.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir E. Sandys.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maledict</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"e*dict</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>maledictus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>maledicere</ets>.]</ety> <def>Accursed; abominable.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malediction</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`e*dic"tion</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>maledictio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mal<eacute/diction</ets>. See <er>Maledicent</er>.]</ety> <def>A proclaiming of evil against some one; a cursing; imprecation; a curse or execration; -- opposed to <ant>benediction</ant>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No <qex>malediction</qex> falls from his tongue.</q> <rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Cursing; curse; execration; imprecation; denunciation; anathema.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Malediction</er>, <er>Curse</er>, <er>Imprecation</er>, <er>Execration</er>. <xex>Malediction</xex> is the most general term, denoting bitter reproach, or wishes and predictions of evil.  <xex>Curse</xex> implies the desire or threat of evil, declared upon oath or in the most solemn manner.  <xex>Imprecation</xex> is literally the praying down of evil upon a person. <xex>Execration</xex> is literally a putting under the ban of excommunication, a curse which excludes from the kingdom of God.  In ordinary usage, the last three words describe profane swearing, <xex>execration</xex> being the strongest.</usage><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malefaction</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`e*fac"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Malefactor</er>.]</ety> <def>A crime; an offense; an evil deed.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malefactor</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`e*fac"tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. <ets>malefacere</ets> to do evil; <ets>male</ets> ill, evil + <ets>facere</ets> to do. See <er>Malice</er>, and <er>Fact</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An evil doer; one who commits a crime; one subject to public prosecution and punishment; a criminal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who does wrong by injuring another, although not a criminal.  Opposite of <ant>benefactor</ant>.</def> <rj><au>H. Brooke.</au>  <au>Fuller.</au></rj><br/ <ldquo/Malefactors of great wealth.<rdquo/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Evil doer; criminal; culprit; felon; convict.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malefactress</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`e*fac"tress</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A female malefactor.</def>  <rj><au>Hawthorne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malefeasance</ent><br/
<hw>Male*fea"sance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Malfeasance</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>male fern</ent><br/
<hw>male fern</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A fern of North America and Europe (<spn>Dryopteris filix-mas</spn>) whose rhizomes and stalks yield an oleoresin used to expel tapeworms.  It is a member of the <isa>woodfern</isa> genus.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malefic</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*lef"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>maleficus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mal<eacute/fique</ets>. See <er>Malefaction</er>.]</ety> <def>Doing mischief; causing harm or evil; nefarious; hurtful.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malefice</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"e*fice</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>maleficium</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mal<eacute/fice</ets>. See <er>Malefactor</er>.]</ety> <def>An evil deed; artifice; enchantment.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maleficence</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*lef"i*cence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>maleficentia</ets>.  Cf. <er>Malfeasance</er>.]</ety> <def>Evil doing, esp. to others.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maleficent</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*lef"i*cent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Malefic</er>.]</ety> <def>Doing evil to others; harmful; mischievous.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maleficial</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`e*fi"cial</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Injurious.</def>  <rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maleficiate</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`e*fi"ci*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>maleficiatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>maleficiare</ets> to bewitch, fr. L. <ets>maleficium</ets>. See <er>Malefice</er>.]</ety> <def>To bewitch; to harm.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Burton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maleficiation</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`e*fi`ci*a"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A bewitching.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maleficience</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`e*fi"cience</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Maleficence</er>.]</ety> <def>The doing of evil, harm, or mischief.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maleficient</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`e*fi"cient</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Maleficent</er>.]</ety> <def>Doing evil, harm, or mischief.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maleformation</ent><br/
<hw>Male`for*ma"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Malformation</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maleic</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*le"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mal<eacute/ique</ets>. See <er>Malic</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or designating, an acid of the ethylene series (maleic acid), metameric with fumaric acid and obtained by heating malic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maleic acid</ent><br/
<hw>maleic acid</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>An unsaturated dicarboxylic acid (<chform>HO.CO.CH=CH.CO.OH</chform>) of <it>cis</it> conformation, having various uses in the manufacture of artificial resins, the dyeing and finishing of wool, silk, and cotton, and also combined with certain drugs to make salts more soluble than the basic forms.  The corresponding isomer having <it>trans</it> conformation, is identical in chemical formula, is called <contr>fumaric acid</contr>.</def> <au>MI11</au><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malengine</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*len"gine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>malengin</ets>; L. <ets>malus</ets> bad, evil + <ets>ingenium</ets> natural capacity. See <er>Engine</er>.]</ety> <def>Evil machination; guile; deceit.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Gower.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maleo</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"le*o</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From its native name.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A bird of Celebes (<spn>megacephalon maleo</spn>), allied to the brush turkey. It makes mounds in which to lay its eggs.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Male-odor</ent><br/
<hw>Male-o"dor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Malodor</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>male orchis</ent><br/
<hw>male orchis</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A Eurasian orchid (<spn>Orchis mascula</spn>) with showy pink or purple flowers in a loose spike.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> early purple orchid, <spn>Orchis mascula</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>male orgasm</ent><br/
<hw>male orgasm</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>An orgasm in a male animal accompanied by the ejaculation of semen.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>male plug</ent><br/
<hw>male plug</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Electricity)</fld> <def>The connecting end of the cord on an electrical device, having two or three pins, that is inserted into a matching socket to make an electrical connection.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> plug.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malepractice</ent><br/
<hw>Male*prac"tice</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Malpractice</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Male-spirited</ent><br/
<hw>Male"-spir`it*ed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having the spirit of a male; vigorous; courageous.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malet</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"et</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mallette</ets>, dim. of <ets>malle</ets>. See <er>Mail</er> a bag.]</ety> <def>A little bag or budget.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shelton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maletreat</ent><br/
<hw>Male*treat"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>See <er>Maltreat</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malevolence</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*lev"o*lence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>malevolentia</ets>. See <er>Malevolent</er>.]</ety> <def>The quality or state of being malevolent; evil disposition toward another; inclination to injure others; ill will. See Synonym of <er>Malice</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malevolent</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*lev"o*lent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>malevolens</ets>, <ets>-entis</ets>; <ets>male</ets> ill + <ets>volens</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>velle</ets> to be willing or disposed, to wish. See <er>Malice</er>, and <er>Voluntary</er>.]</ety> <def>Wishing evil; disposed to injure others; rejoicing in another's misfortune.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Ill-disposed; envious; mischievous; evil-minded; spiteful; malicious; malignant; rancorous.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malevolently</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*lev"o*lent*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a malevolent manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malevolous</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*lev"o*lous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>malevolus</ets>; fr. <ets>male</ets> ill + <ets>velle</ets> to be disposed.]</ety> <def>Malevolent.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bp. Warburton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malexecution</ent><br/
<hw>Mal*ex`e*cu"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mal-</ets> + <ets>execution</ets>.]</ety> <def>Bad execution.</def>  <rj><au>D. Webster.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maleyl</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*le"yl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Maleic</ets> + <ets>-yl</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A hypothetical radical derived from maleic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malfeasance</ent><br/
<hw>Mal*fea"sance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>malfaisance</ets>, fr. <ets>malfaisant</ets> injurious, doing ill; <ets>mal</ets> ill, evil + <ets>faisant</ets> doing, p. pr. of <ets>faire</ets> to do. See <er>Malice</er>, <er>Feasible</er>, and cf. <er>Maleficence</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The doing of an act which a person ought not to do; evil conduct; an illegal deed.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>malefeasance</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malfeasant</ent><br/
<hw>malfeasant</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>One guilty of malfeasance.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malformation</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`for*ma"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mal-</ets> + <ets>formation</ets>.]</ety> <def>Ill formation; irregular or anomalous formation; abnormal or wrong conformation or structure; -- often used of body parts such as limbs which do not develop properly during fetal maturation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malgracious</ent><br/
<hw>Mal*gra"cious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>malgracieux</ets>.]</ety> <def>Not graceful; displeasing.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Gower.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malgre</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"gre</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prep.</pos> <def>See <er>Mauger</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malheur wire lettuce</ent><br/
<hw>malheur wire lettuce</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A small mustardlike plant (<spn>Stephanomeria malheurensis</spn>) of Oregon, belonging to the family <fam>Cruciferae</fam>; it is a threatened species.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malian</ent><br/
<hw>Malian</hw> <pos>prop. a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to Mali; <as>as, <ex>Malian</ex> deserts</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>of or pertaining to the inhabitants of Mali; <as>as, <ex>Malian</ex> nomads</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malian</ent><br/
<hw>Malian</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A native or inhabitant of Mali.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mali franc</ent><br/
<hw>Mali franc</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The standard monetary unit in Mali and some other countries.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malic</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"lic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>malum</ets> an apple: cf. F. <ets>malique</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or obtained from, apples; <as>as, <ex>malic</ex> acid</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Malic acid</b></col>, <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <cd>a hydroxy acid (<chform>HO.CO.CH2.CH(OH).CO.OH</chform>) obtained from unripe fruit (such as <prodby>green apples</prodby>, <prodby>currants</prodby>, <prodby>tomatoes</prodby> or <prodby>cherries</prodby>) as a substance which is sirupy or crystallized with difficulty, and has a strong but pleasant sour taste.  It is levorotatory or dextrorotatory according to the temperature and concentration; the natural form is of L- conformation.  A synthetic variety is a derivative of succinic acid, but as with most simple synthetic compounds, is a racemic mixture of isomers and thus has no rotatory action on polarized light.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malice</ent><br/
<hw>mal"ice</hw> <pr>(m<acr/l"<icr/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>malice</ets>, fr. L. <ets>malitia</ets>, from <ets>malus</ets> bad, ill, evil, prob. orig., dirty, black; cf. Gr. <grk>me`las</grk> black, Skr. <ets>mala</ets> dirt.  Cf. <er>Mauger</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Enmity of heart; malevolence; ill will; a spirit delighting in harm or misfortune to another; a disposition to injure another; a malignant design of evil.</def> <ldquo/Nor set down aught in <xex>malice</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Envy, hatred, and <qex>malice</qex> are three distinct passions of the mind.</q> <rj><qau>Ld. Holt.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Any wicked or mischievous intention of the mind; a depraved inclination to mischief; an intention to vex, annoy, or injure another person, or to do a wrongful act without just cause or cause or excuse; a wanton disregard of the rights or safety of others; willfulness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Malice aforethought</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Malice prepense</b></col></mcol>, <cd>malice previously and deliberately entertained.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Spite; ill will; malevolence; grudge; pique; bitterness; animosity; malignity; maliciousness; rancor; virulence.</syn> <usage> See <er>Spite</er>. -- <er>Malevolence</er>, <er>Malignity</er>, <er>Malignancy</er>. <xex>Malice</xex> is a stronger word than <xex>malevolence</xex>, which may imply only a desire that evil may befall another, while <xex>malice</xex> desires, and perhaps intends, to bring it about. <xex>Malignity</xex> is intense and deepseated <xex>malice</xex>. It implies a natural delight in hating and wronging others. One who is <xex>malignant</xex> must be both <xex>malevolent</xex> and <xex>malicious</xex>; but a man may be <xex>malicious</xex> without being <xex>malignant</xex>.</usage><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Proud tyrants who <qex>maliciously</qex> destroy<br/
And ride o'er ruins with <qex>malignant</qex> joy.</q> <rj><qau>Somerville.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>in some connections, <qex>malignity</qex> seems rather more pertinently applied to a radical depravity of nature, and <qex>malignancy</qex> to indications of this depravity, in temper and conduct in particular instances.</q> <rj><qau>Cogan.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malice</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"ice</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To regard with extreme ill will.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malicho</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"i*cho</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>malhecho</ets>; <ets>mal</ets> bad + <ets>hecho</ets> deed, L. <ets>factum</ets>. See <er>Fact</er>.]</ety> <def>Mischief.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malicious</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*li"cious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Of. <ets>malicius</ets>, F. <ets>malicieux</ets>, fr. L. <ets>malitiosus</ets>. See <er>Malice</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Indulging or exercising malice; harboring ill will or enmity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I grant him bloody, . . . <br/
Sudden, <qex>malicious</qex>, smacking of every sin<br/
That has a name.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Proceeding from hatred or ill will; dictated by malice; <as>as, a <ex>malicious</ex> report; <ex>malicious</ex> mischief.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>With wicked or mischievous intentions or motives; wrongful and done intentionally without just cause or excuse; <as>as, a <ex>malicious</ex> act</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Malicious abandonment</b></col>, <cd>the desertion of a wife or husband without just cause.</cd> <au>Burrill.</au> -- <mcol><col><b>Malicious prosecution</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Malicious arrest</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>a wanton prosecution or arrest, by regular process in a civil or criminal proceeding, without probable cause.</cd> <au>Bouvier.</au></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Ill-disposed; evil-minded; mischievous; envious; malevolent; invidious; spiteful; bitter; malignant; rancorous; malign.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Ma*li"cious*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Ma*li"cious*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malicious mischief</ent><br/
<hw>malicious mischief</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <def>Malicious and willful destructionof or injury to the property of others; -- it is an offense at common law.</def> <au>Wharton.</au><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> vandalism, hooliganism.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p> 

<p><ent>malign</ent><br/
<hw>ma*lign"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>malignus</ets>, for <ets>maligenus</ets>, i. e., of a bad kind or nature; <ets>malus</ets> bad + the root of <ets>genus</ets> birth, race, kind: cf. F. <ets>malin</ets>, masc., <ets>maligne</ets>, fem. See <er>Malice</er>, <er>Gender</er>, and cf. <er>Benign</er>, <er>Malignant</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having an evil disposition toward others; harboring violent enmity; malevolent; malicious; spiteful; -- opposed to <ant>benign</ant>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Witchcraft may be by operation of <qex>malign</qex> spirits.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Unfavorable; unpropitious; pernicious; tending to injure; <as>as, a <ex>malign</ex> aspect of planets</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Malignant; <as>as, a <ex>malign</ex> ulcer</as>.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malign</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*lign"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Maligned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Maligning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. L. <ets>malignare</ets>. See <er>Malign</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>To treat with malice; to show hatred toward; to abuse; to wrong; to injure.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The people practice what mischiefs and villainies they will against private men, whom they <qex>malign</qex> by stealing their goods, or murdering them.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To speak great evil of; to traduce; to defame; to slander; to vilify; to asperse.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To be envied and shot at; to be <qex>maligned</qex> standing, and to be despised falling.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malign</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*lign"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To entertain malice.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malignancy</ent><br/
<ent>Malignance</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Ma*lig"nance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Ma*lig"nan*cy</hw> , }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Malignant</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The state or quality of being malignant; extreme malevolence; bitter enmity; malice; disposition toward evil; intense ill will; <as>as, <ex>malignancy</ex> of heart</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Unfavorableness; evil nature.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>malignancy</qex> of my fate might perhaps distemner yours.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Virulence; tendency to a fatal issue; <as>as, the <ex>malignancy</ex> of an ulcer or of a fever</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A cancerous tumor that is spreading beyond the point of origin.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> malignant tumor, malignant neoplasm, metastatic tumor.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The state of being a malignant.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malignant</ent><br/
<hw>ma*lig"nant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>malignans</ets>, <ets>-antis</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>malignare</ets>, <ets>malignari</ets>, to do or make maliciously. See <er>Malign</er>, and cf. <er>Benignant</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Disposed to do harm, inflict suffering, or cause distress; actuated by extreme malevolence or enmity; virulently inimical; bent on evil; malicious.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>malignant</qex> and a turbaned Turk.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Characterized or caused by evil intentions; pernicious.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Malignant</xex> care.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some <qex>malignant</qex> power upon my life.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Something deleterious and <qex>malignant</qex> as his touch.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Tending to produce death; threatening a fatal issue; virulent; <as>as, <ex>malignant</ex> diphtheria</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Malignant pustule</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>a very contagious disease produced by infection of subcutaneous tissues with the bacterium <spn>Bacillus anthracis</spn>.  It is transmitted to man from animals and is characterized by the formation, at the point of reception of the infection, of a vesicle or pustule which first enlarges and then breaks down into an unhealthy ulcer.  It is marked by profound exhaustion and often fatal.  The disease in animals is called <altname>charbon</altname>; in man it is called <altname>cutaneous anthrax</altname>, and formerly was sometimes called simply <altname>anthrax</altname>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malignant</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*lig"nant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A man of extreme enmity or evil intentions.</def>  <rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Eng. Hist.)</fld> <def>One of the adherents of <person>Charles I.</person> or <person>Charles II.</person>; -- so called by the opposite party.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malignant anemia</ent><br/
<hw>malignant anemia</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A chronic progressive anemia of older adults, thought to result from a lack of intrinsic factor (a substance secreted by the stomach that is responsible for the absorption of vitamin B-12); also called <altname>pernicious anemia</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malignant melanoma</ent><br/
<hw>malignant melanoma</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <def>Any of several malignant neoplasms (usually of the skin) consisting of melanocytes; called also <altname>melanoma</altname>.  It is classed as a type of <isa>skin cancer</isa>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malignant neoplasm</ent><br/
<hw>malignant neoplasm</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <def>Same as malignancy{4}.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> malignancy, malignance, malignant tumor, metastatic tumor.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malignant tumor</ent><br/
<hw>malignant tumor</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <def>Same as malignancy{4}.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> malignancy, malignance, malignant tumor, metastatic tumor.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malignantly</ent><br/
<hw>ma*lig"nant*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a malignant manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maligned</ent><br/
<hw>maligned</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Assailed with contemptuous language.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> reviled.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maligner</ent><br/
<hw>ma*lign"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who maligns.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malignify</ent><br/
<hw>ma*lig"ni*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Malignified</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Malignifying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>malignus</ets> malign + <ets>-fy</ets>.]</ety> <def>To make malign or malignant.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <ldquo/A strong faith <xex>malignified</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Southey.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malignity</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*lig"ni*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>malignit<eacute/</ets>, L. <ets>malignitas</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The state or quality of being malignant; disposition to do evil; virulent enmity; malignancy; malice; spite.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Virulence; deadly quality.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His physicians discerned an invincible <qex>malignity</qex> in his disease.</q> <rj><qau>Hayward.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Extreme evilness of nature or influence; perniciousness; heinousness; <as>as, the <ex>malignity</ex> of fraud</as>.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Malice</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malignly</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*lign"ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a malign manner; with malignity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malinger</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*lin"ger</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>MAlingered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Malingering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To act the part of a malingerer; to feign illness or inability.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malingerer</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*lin"ger*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>malingre</ets> sickly, weakly, prob. from <ets>mal</ets> ill + OF. <ets>heingre</ets>, <ets>haingre</ets>, thin, lean, infirm, fr. L. <ets>aeger</ets>.]</ety> <def>In the army, a soldier who feigns himself sick, or who induces or protracts an illness, in order to avoid doing his duty; hence, in general, one who shirks his duty by pretending illness or inability.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malingery</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*lin"ger*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The spirit or practices of a malingerer; malingering.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malison</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"i*son</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>maleicon</ets>, L. <ets>maledictio</ets>. See <er>Malediction</er>, and cf. <er>Benison</er>.]</ety> <def>Malediction; curse; execration.</def> <mark>[Poetic]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God's <qex>malison</qex> on his head who this gainsays.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malkin</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"kin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Dim. of <ets>Maud</ets>, the proper name.  Cf. <er>Grimalkin</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also <asp>maukin</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Originally, a kitchenmaid; a slattern.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A mop made of clouts, used by the kitchen servant.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A scarecrow.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A mop or sponge attached to a jointed staff for swabbing out a cannon.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mall</ent><br/
<hw>Mall</hw> <pr>(m<add/l; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <altsp>[Written also <asp>maul</asp>.]</altsp> <ety>[OE. <ets>malle</ets>, F. <ets>mail</ets>, L. <ets>malleus</ets>.  Cf. <er>Malleus</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A large heavy wooden beetle; a mallet for driving anything with force; a maul.</def>  <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A heavy blow.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An old game played with <xex>malls</xex> or mallets and balls. See <er>Pall-mall</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Cotton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A place where the game of <xex>mall</xex> was played. Hence: A public walk; a level shaded walk.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Part of the area was laid out in gravel walks, and planted with elms; and these convenient and frequented walks obtained the name of the City <qex>Mall</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Southey.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mall</ent><br/
<hw>Mall</hw> <pr>(m<add/l)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Malled</conjf> <pr>(m<add/ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Malling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>mailler</ets>. See <er>Mall</er> beetle, and cf. <er>Malleate</er>.]</ety> <def>To beat with a mall; to beat with something heavy; to bruise; to maul.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mall</ent><br/
<hw>Mall</hw> <pr>(m<acr/l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>mallum</ets> a public assembly; cf. OHG. <ets>mahal</ets> assembly, transaction; akin to AS. <ets>m<ae/<edh/el</ets>, <ets>me<edh/el</ets>, assembly, <ets>m<aemac/lan</ets> to speak, Goth. <ets>ma<thorn/l</ets> market place.]</ety> <def>Formerly, among Teutonic nations, a meeting of the notables of a state for the transaction of public business, such meeting being a modification of the ancient popular assembly.</def> Hence: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A court of justice.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A place where justice is administered.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>A place where public meetings are held.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Councils, which had been as frequent as diets or <qex>malls</qex>, ceased.</q> <rj><qau>Milman.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mall</ent><br/
<hw>Mall</hw> <pr>(m<add/l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A public access area containing a promenade for pedestrians; <as>as, to gather near the Washington monument on the <ex>mall</ex> in Washington</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The paved or grassy strip between two roadways.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A shopping area with multiple shops and a concourse for predominantly or exclusively pedestrian use; in cities the concourse is usually a city street which may be temporarily or permamently closed to motor vehicles; in suburban areas, a mall is often located on a convenient highway, may be large, contained in one building or in multiple buildings connected by (usually covered) walkways.  Also called <altname>shopping mall</altname></def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mallard</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"lard</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>malari</ets>,fr. <ets>m<acir/le</ets> male + <ets>-art</ets> = <ets>-ard</ets>. See <er>Male</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and <er>-ard</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A drake; the male of <spn>Anas boschas</spn>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A large wild duck (<spn>Anas boschas</spn>) inhabiting both America and Europe.  The domestic duck has descended from this species.  Called also <altname>greenhead</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malleability</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"le*a*bil"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[CF. F.  <ets>mall<eacute/abilit<eacute/</ets>.]</ety> <def>The quality or state of being malleable; -- opposed to <contr>friability</contr> and <contr>brittleness</contr>.</def>  <rj><au>Locke.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malleable</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"le*a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mall<eacute/able</ets>, fr. LL. <ets>malleare</ets> to hammer. See <er>Malleate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Capable of being extended or shaped by beating with a hammer, or by the pressure of rollers; -- applied to metals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Capable of being influenced to behave as desired; tractable; -- used mostly of children.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Malleable iron</b></col>, <cd>iron that is capable of extension or of being shaped under the hammer; decarbonized cast iron. See under <er>Iron</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Malleable iron castings</b></col>, <cd>articles cast from pig iron and made malleable by heating then for several days in the presence of some substance, as hematite, which deprives the cast iron of some of its carbon.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malleableize</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"le*a*ble*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make malleable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malleableness</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"le*a*ble*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Quality of being malleable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malleal</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"le*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to the malleus.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malleate</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"le*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Malleated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Malleating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>malleatus</ets> hammered, fr. <ets>malleus</ets> a hammer. See <er>Mall</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <def>To hammer; to beat into a plate or leaf.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malleation</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`le*a"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>malleatio</ets>: cf. OF. <ets>mall<eacute/ation</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act or process of beating into a plate, sheet, or leaf, as a metal; extension by beating.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 888 --></p>

<p><ent>mallecho</ent><br/
<hw>mal"le*cho</hw> <pr>(m<acr/l"l<esl/*ch<omac/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Malicho</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mallee</ent><br/
<hw>mal"lee</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Native name.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A dwarf Australian eucalypt with a number of thin stems springing from a thickened stock.  The most common species are <spn>Eucalyptus dumosa</spn> and <spn>Eucalyptus Gracilis</spn>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>Scrub or thicket formed by the mallee.</def> <mark>[Australia]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mallee bird</ent><br/
<hw>mal*lee" bird`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <ety>[From native name.]</ety> <def>The leipoa, or Australian moundbird; it incubates eggs naturally in sandy mounds.  See <er>Leipoa</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mallee fowl, mallee-fowl, leipoa, lowan, <spn>Leipoa ocellata</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mallee fowl</ent><br/
<hw>mallee fowl</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <def>Same as <er>mallee bird</er> (<spn>Leipoa ocellata</spn>).  See also <er>Leipoa</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mallee hen</ent><br/
<hw>mallee hen</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <def>The adult female of the mallee fowl (<spn>Leipoa ocellata</spn>).  See <er>Leipoa</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mallemoke</ent><br/
<ent>Mallemock</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mal"le*mock</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mal"le*moke</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Mollemoke</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mallenders</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"len*ders</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <fld>(Far.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Malanders</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malleolar</ent><br/
<hw>Mal*le"o*lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Malleolus</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the malleolus; in the region of the malleoli of the ankle joint.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malleolus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mal*le"*o*lus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Malleoli</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., dim. of <ets>malleus</ets> hammer.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A projection at the distal end of each bone of the leg at the ankle joint. The malleolus of the tibia is the internal projection, that of the fibula the external.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def><ldquo/ A layer, <rdquo/ a shoot partly buried in the ground, and there cut halfway through.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mallet</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"let</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>maillet</ets>, dim. of <ets>mail</ets>. See <er>Mall</er> a beetle.]</ety> <def>A small maul with a short handle, -- used esp. for driving a tool, as a chisel or the like; also, a light beetle with a long handle, -- used in playing croquet.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malleus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mal"le*us</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mallei</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., hammer. See <er>Mall</er> a beetle.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The outermost of the three small auditory bones, ossicles; the hammer. It is attached to the tympanic membrane by a long process, the handle or manubrium. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Far</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the hard lateral pieces of the mastax of Rotifera. See <er>Mastax</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of bivalve shells; the hammer shell.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mallophaga</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mal*loph"a*ga</hw> <pr>(m<acr/l*l<ocr/f"<adot/*g<adot/)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mallo`s</grk> a lock of wool + <grk>fagei^n</grk> to eat.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An extensive group of insects which are parasitic on birds and mammals, and feed on the feathers and hair; -- called also <altname>bird lice</altname>. See <cref>Bird louse</cref>, under <er>Bird</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mallotus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mal*lo"tus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr Gr. <?/ fleecy.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of small Arctic fishes. One American species, the capelin (<spn>Mallotus villosus</spn>), is extensively used as bait for cod.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mallows</ent><br/
<ent>Mallow</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mal"low</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mal"lows</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>malwe</ets>, AS. <ets>mealwe</ets>, fr. L. <ets>malva</ets>, akin to Gr. <grk>mala`chh</grk>; cf. <grk>mala`ssein</grk> to soften, <grk>malako`s</grk> soft. Named either from its softening or relaxing properties, or from its soft downy leaves.  Cf. <er>Mauve</er>, <er>Malachite</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of plants (<gen>Malva</gen>) having mucilaginous qualities. See <er>Malvaceous</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The flowers of the common mallow (<spn>Malva sylvestris</spn>) are used in medicine. The dwarf mallow (<spn>Malva rotundifolia</spn>) is a common weed, and its flattened, dick-shaped fruits are called <xex>cheeses</xex> by children.  Tree mallow (<spn>Malva Mauritiana</spn> and <spn>Lavatera arborea</spn>), musk mallow (<spn>Malva moschata</spn>), rose mallow or hollyhock, and curled mallow (<spn>Malva crispa</spn>), are less commonly seen.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Indian mallow</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Abutilon</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Jew's mallow</b></col>, <cd>a plant (<spn>Corchorus olitorius</spn>) used as a pot herb by the Jews of Egypt and Syria.</cd> -- <col><b>Marsh mallow</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Marsh</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mallow family</ent><br/
<hw>mallow family</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The natural family <fam>Malvaceae</fam>, a <isa>dilleniid dicot family</isa> consisting of herbs and shrubs and some trees, and including the mallows, cotton, and okra.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mallowwort</ent><br/
<hw>mal"low*wort`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Any plant of the order <ord>Malvaceae</ord>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malmbrick</ent><br/
<ent>Malm</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Malm</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Malm"brick`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. AS. <ets>mealm</ets> sand.]</ety> <def>A kind of brick of a light brown or yellowish color, made of sand, clay, and chalk.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malma</ent><br/
<hw>mal"ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A spotted trout (<spn>Salvelinus malma</spn>), inhabiting Northern America, west of the Rocky Mountains; -- called also <altname>Dolly Varden trout</altname>, <altname>bull trout</altname>, <altname>red-spotted trout</altname>, and <altname>golet</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- Insert: Illustr. of Malma (Salvelinus malma) --><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malmag</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mal"mag</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., from native name in Madagascar.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The tarsius, or spectral lemur.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malmsey</ent><br/
<hw>Malm"sey</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>malvesie</ets>, F. <ets>malvoisie</ets>, It. <ets>malvasia</ets>, <ets>malavagia</ets>, fr. <ets>Malvasia</ets>, or Napoli di <ets>Malvasia</ets>, in the Morea.]</ety> <def>A kind of sweet wine from Crete, the Canary Islands, etc.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malnourished</ent><br/
<hw>malnourished</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Not getting adequate food; suffering from malnutrition; underfed.</def> [Narrower terms: <stype>starved, starving</stype>; <stype>unfed</stype>; <stype>foodless</stype>]<br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malnutrition</ent><br/
<hw>mal`nu*tri"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mal-</ets> + <ets>nutrition</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>Faulty or imperfect nutrition; inadequate or unbalanced food intake.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malobservation</ent><br/
<hw>Mal*ob`ser*va"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mal-</ets> + <ets>observation</ets>.]</ety> <def>Erroneous observation.</def>  <rj><au>J. S Mill.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malodor</ent><br/
<hw>mal*o"dor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An offensive odor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malodorous</ent><br/
<hw>mal*o"dor*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Offensive to the sense of smell; ill-smelling.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>mal*o"dor*ous*ness</wf>. <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>  <rj><au>Carlyle.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malodorousness</ent><br/
<hw>mal*o"dor*ous*ness</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The attribute of having a strong offensive smell.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> stinkiness, foulness, rankness.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malonate</ent><br/
<hw>mal"o*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of malonic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malonic</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*lon"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or designating, a dicarboxylic acid produced artifically as a white crystalline substance, <chform>CH2.(CO2H)2</chform>, and so called because obtained by the oxidation of <xex>malic</xex> acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malonyl</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"o*nyl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Malonic</ets> + <ets>-yl</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A divalent diacyl radical, <chform>CH2.(CO)2</chform>, from malonic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malonylurea</ent><br/
<hw>malonylurea</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A white crystalline acid derived from pyrimidine; it is used in preparing barbiturate drugs.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> barbituric acid.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malope</ent><br/
<hw>malope</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A Western Mediterranean annual (<spn>Malope trifida</spn>) having deep purple-red flowers subtended by three large cordate bracts.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> <spn>Malope trifida</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malopterurus</ent><br/
<hw>Malopterurus</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[NL., from Gr. <grk>malako`s</grk> soft + <grk>ptero`n</grk> wing + <grk>o'yra`</grk> tail.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A variant spelling of <er>Malapterurus</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malopterurus electricus</ent><br/
<hw>Malopterurus electricus</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Malopterurus electricus</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malosma</ent><br/
<hw>Malosma</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus having only one species; often included in the genus <gen>Rhus</gen>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Malosma</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malpais</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"pais`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Sp. <ets>mal</ets>, <ets>malo</ets>, bad, and <ets>pa<iacute/s</ets> country.]</ety> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>The rough surface of a congealed lava stream.</def> <mark>[Southwestern U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malpighia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mal*pi"ghi*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Malpighian</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of tropical American shrubs with opposite leaves and small white or reddish flowers. The drupes of <spn>Malpighia glabra</spn> (formerly <spn>Malpighia urens</spn>) are eaten under the name of <prod>Barbadoes cherries</prod>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malpighiaceous</ent><br/
<hw>Mal*pi`ghi*a"ceous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or resembling, a natural order of tropical trees and shrubs (<ord>Malpighiaceae</ord>), some of them climbing plants, and their stems forming many of the curious lianes of South American forests.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malpighia glabra</ent><br/
<hw>Malpighia glabra</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>THe species name of the acerola, also called <altname>barbados cherry</altname>, a tropical American shrub bearing edible cherrylike acid red fruit.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> barbados cherry, acerola, Surinam cherry, West Indian cherry.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malpighian</ent><br/
<hw>Mal*pi"ghi*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or discovered by, <person>Marcello <etsep>Malpighi</etsep></person>, an Italian anatomist of the 17th century.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Malpighian capsules</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Malpighian corpuscles</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Anatomy)</fld>, <cd>the globular dilatations, containing the glomeruli or Malpighian tufts, at the extremities of the urinary tubules of the kidney.</cd> -- <col><b>Malpighian corpuscles of the spleen</b></col>, <cd>masses of adenoid tissue connected with branches of the splenic artery.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malpighian body</ent><br/
<hw>malpighian body</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Anatomy)</fld>, <def>The capsule that contains a glomerulus at the expanded end of a nephron; also called <altname>malpighian corpuscle</altname> and <altname>Malpighian capsule</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p> 

<p><ent>malpighian corpuscle</ent><br/
<hw>malpighian corpuscle</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Anatomy)</fld>, <def>See malpighian body.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> malpighian body,  Malpighian capsule.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malpighian layer</ent><br/
<hw>malpighian layer</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Anatomy)</fld>, <def>The innermost layer of the epidermis.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> stratum germinativum, rete Malpighii.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malposed tooth</ent><br/
<hw>malposed tooth</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A tooth that has grown in a faulty position.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malposition</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`po*si"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mal-</ets> + <ets>position</ets>.]</ety> <def>A wrong position.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malpractice</ent><br/
<hw>Mal*prac"tice</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mal-</ets> + <ets>practice</ets>.]</ety> <def>Evil practice; illegal or immoral conduct; practice contrary to established rules; specifically, the treatment of a case by a surgeon or physician in a manner which is contrary to accepted rules and productive of unfavorable results.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>malepractice</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malt</ent><br/
<hw>Malt</hw> <pr>(m<add/lt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>mealt</ets>; akin to D. <ets>mout</ets>, G. <ets>malz</ets>, Icel., Sw., & Dan. <ets>malt</ets>, and E. <ets>melt</ets>. <root/108. See <er>Melt</er>.]</ety> <def>Barley or other grain, steeped in water and dried in a kiln, thus forcing germination until the saccharine principle has been evolved. It is used in brewing and in the distillation of whisky.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malt</ent><br/
<hw>Malt</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Relating to, containing, or made with, malt.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Malt liquor</b></col>, <cd>an alcoholic liquor, as beer, ale, porter, etc., prepared by fermenting an infusion of malt.</cd> -- <col><b>Malt dust</b></col>, <cd>fine particles of malt, or of the grain used in making malt; -- used as a fertilizer.</cd> <ldquo/ <xex>Malt dust</xex> consists chiefly of the infant radicle separated from the grain.<rdquo/ <au>Sir H. Davy.</au> -- <col><b>Malt floor</b></col>, <cd>a floor for drying malt.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Malt house</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Malthouse</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a house in which malt is made.</cd> -- <col><b>Malt kiln</b></col>, <cd>a heated chamber for drying malt.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malt</ent><br/
<hw>Malt</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Malted</conjf>: <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Malting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To make into malt; <as>as, to <ex>malt</ex> barley</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malt</ent><br/
<hw>Malt</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become malt; also, to make grain into malt.</def>  <rj><au>Mortimer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malta</ent><br/
<hw>Malta</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A country on the island of Malta.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An island south of Sicily in the Mediterranean Sea.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malta fever</ent><br/
<hw>malta fever</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>An infectious disease contracted from meat or milk products from infected domestic animals; called also <altname>brucellosis</altname> and <altname>undulant fever</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maltalent</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"ta*lent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. See <er>Malice</er>, and <er>Talent</er>.]</ety> <def>Ill will; malice.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Rom. of R.</au>  <au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maltase</ent><br/
<hw>malt"ase</hw> <pr>(m<add/lt"<amac/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Biochem.)</fld> <def>An enzyme, <alpha/-D-glucosidase, which hydrolyzes maltose with production of glucose, and also hydrolyzes certain other <alpha/-D-glucosides.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malted</ent><br/
<hw>malt"ed</hw> <pr>(m<add/lt"<ecr/d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Same as <er>malted milk</er>{1}.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malted milk</ent><br/
<hw>malted milk</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A milkshake made with malt powder; also called simply a <altname>malted</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A powder made of dried milk and malted cereals.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maltese</ent><br/
<hw>Mal*tese"</hw> <pr>(m<add/l*t<emac/s" or m<add/l*t<emac/z")</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to <etsep>Malta</etsep> or to its inhabitants.</def> -- <def2><pos>n. sing. & pl.</pos> <def>A native or inhabitant of Malta; the people of Malta.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Maltese cross</b></col>. <cd>See <xex>Illust.</xex> 5, of <er>Cross</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Maltese dog</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a breed of small terriers, having long silky white hair. The breed originated in Malta.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maltese cat</ent><br/
<hw>maltese cat</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <def>A short-haired bluish-gray breed of the domestic cat.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maltese cross</ent><br/
<hw>maltese cross</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A Eurasian garden perennial (<spn>Lychins chalcedonica</spn>) having scarlet flowers in dense terminal heads.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> scarlet lychnis, <spn>Lychins chalcedonica</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A cross with triangular or arrow-shaped arms and the points toward the center. See illustration under <er>cross</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maltese dog</ent><br/
<hw>Maltese dog</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A breed of <isa>toy dog</isa> having a long straight silky white coat; also called a <altname>Maltese</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maltese pound</ent><br/
<hw>maltese pound</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The monetary unit of Malta.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maltha</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mal"tha</hw> <pr>(m<acr/l"th<adot/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <grk>ma`lqa</grk>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A variety of bitumen, viscid and tenacious, like pitch, unctuous to the touch, and exhaling a bituminous odor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Mortar.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Holland.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malthus</ent><br/
<hw>Malthus</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>Thomas Robert Malthus, an English economist who argued that increases in population would outgrow increases in the means of subsistence (1766-1834).</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Thomas Malthus, Thomas Robert Malthus.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malthusian</ent><br/
<hw>Mal*thu"sian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the political economist, the <person>Rev. T. R. <etsep>Malthus</etsep></person>, or conforming to his views; <as>as, <ex>Malthusian</ex> theories</as>.  See <er>Malthus</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Malthus held that population tends to increase faster than its means of subsistence can be made to do, and hence that the lower classes must necessarily suffer more or less from lack of food, unless an increase of population be checked by prudential restraint or otherwise.  The steadily increasing capacity of world economic systems and food production has proven this theory to be at least premature, since economic production has increased notably faster than population since the time of Malthus.  The general notion that there is an ultimate limit on the ability of mankind to continue increasing food and goods in proportion to population is still held by many people, especially environmentalists, some of whom who feel that the chief limiting factor will be the inability to dispose of the waste products of industry, leading to a steady degradation of the environment in the absence of population limitation.  However, even those that believe this differ widely in their estimates of when this limit will be reached.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malthusian</ent><br/
<hw>Mal*thu"sian</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A follower of Malthus.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malthusianism</ent><br/
<hw>Mal*thu"sian*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The system of Malthusian doctrines relating to population.  See <er>Malthusian</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malthusian theory</ent><br/
<hw>malthusian theory</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Malthus' theory that population increase would outpace increases in the means of subsistence; Malthusianism.  See <er>Malthusian</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maltine</ent><br/
<ent>Maltin</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Malt"in</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Malt"ine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Physiol. Chem.)</fld> <def>The fermentative principle of malt; malt diastase; also, a name given to various medicinal preparations made from or containing malt.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malting</ent><br/
<hw>Malt"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The process of making, or of becoming malt.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malt liquor</ent><br/
<hw>malt liquor</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>An alcoholic drink made with malt.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maltman</ent><br/
<hw>Malt"man</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Maltmen</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>A man whose occupation is to make malt.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maltobiose</ent><br/
<hw>mal"to*bi"ose</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Maltose; <altname>malt sugar</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maltonic</ent><br/
<hw>Mal*ton"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or derived from, maltose; specif., designating an acid called also <altname>gluconic</altname> or <altname>dextronic</altname> acid. See <er>Gluconic</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maltose</ent><br/
<hw>Malt"ose`</hw> <pr>(m<add/lt"<omac/s`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Malt</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Biochem.)</fld> <def>A crystalline disaccharide (<chform>C12H22O11</chform>) formed from starch by the action of diastase of malt, and the amylolytic ferment of saliva and pancreatic juice; called also <altname>maltobiose</altname> and <altname>malt sugar</altname>.  Chemically it is <chname>4-O-<alpha/-D-glucopyranosyl-D-glucose</chname>.  It rotates the plane of polarized light further to the right than does dextrose and possesses a lower cupric oxide reducing power.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maltreat</ent><br/
<hw>mal*treat"</hw> <pr>(m<acr/l*tr<emac/t")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Maltreated</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Maltreating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[<ets>Mal-</ets> + <ets>treat</ets>: cf. F. <ets>maltraiter</ets>.]</ety> <def>To treat ill; to abuse; to treat roughly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maltreatment</ent><br/
<hw>mal*treat"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>maltraitement</ets>.]</ety> <def>Cruel or inhumane treatment; ill usage; abuse.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> ill-treatment.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maltster</ent><br/
<hw>Malt"ster</hw> <pr>(m<add/lt"st<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A maltman.</def>  <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malt sugar</ent><br/
<hw>malt sugar</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>maltose</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malt whisky</ent><br/
<ent>malt whiskey</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>malt whiskey</hw>, <hw>malt whisky</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A whiskey distilled in Scotland (esp. whiskey made from malted barley in a pot still); Scotch whisky.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Scotch, Scotch-whiskey, Scotch whisky.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maltworm</ent><br/
<hw>malt"worm`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A tippler.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malty</ent><br/
<hw>malt"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Containing, or like, malt.</def>  <rj><au>Dickens.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malum</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma"lum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mala</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L.]</ety> <def>An evil. See <er>Mala</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malva</ent><br/
<hw>Malva</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of herbs and subshrubs including the mallows.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Malva</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malvaceae</ent><br/
<hw>Malvaceae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of herbs and shrubs and some trees, including the mallows, cotton, and okra; the <altname>mallow family</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Malvaceae</fam>, mallow family.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malvaceous</ent><br/
<hw>Mal*va"ceous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>malvaceus</ets>, from <ets>malva</ets> mallows. See <er>Mallow</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or resembling, a natural family of plants (<fam>Malvaceae</fam>), of which the mallow is the type.  The cotton plant, hollyhock, and abutilon are of this family.  It was formerly classified as an order, and included the baobab and the silk-cotton trees.  The baobab and silk-cotton trees are now placed in the family <fam>Bombacaceae</fam>, which is included with the <fam>Malvaceae</fam> in the order <ord>Malvales</ord>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malvales</ent><br/
<hw>Malvales</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A natural order of plants including the families <fam>Malvaceae</fam>, <fam>Bombacaceae</fam>, <fam>Elaeocarpaceae</fam>, <fam>Sterculiaceae</fam>, and <fam>Tiliaceae</fam>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> order <ord>Malvales</ord>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malva neglecta</ent><br/
<hw>Malva neglecta</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The species name of the common mallow, an annual Old World plant with clusters of pink or white flowers; naturalized in U.S..</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malvasia</ent><br/
<hw>malvasia</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A sweet grape used to make malmsey wine.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malvastrum</ent><br/
<hw>Malvastrum</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A genus of mallows characterized by red and yellow flowers often placed in other genera.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Malvastrum</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malva sylvestris</ent><br/
<hw>Malva sylvestris</hw><pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The species name of the tall mallow, an erect or decumbent Old World perennial with axillary clusters of rosy-purple flowers; introduced into the U. S.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> tall mallow, high mallow, cheese, cheeseflower.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malvaviscus</ent><br/
<hw>Malvaviscus</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A small genus of shrubs of Central and South America: wax mallows.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Malvaviscus</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malversation</ent><br/
<hw>Mal`ver*sa"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>malverser</ets> to be corrupt in office, fr. L. <ets>male</ets> ill + <ets>versari</ets> to move about, to occupy one's self, <ets>vertere</ets> to turn. See <er>Malice</er>, and <er>Verse</er>.]</ety> <def>Evil conduct; fraudulent practices; misbehavior, corruption, or extortion in office.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malvesie</ent><br/
<hw>Mal"ve*sie</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Malmsey wine. See <er>Malmsey</er>.</def> <ldquo/ A jub of <xex>malvesye</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mam</ent><br/
<hw>Mam</hw> <pr>(m<acr/m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Abbrev. fr. <ets>mamma</ets>.]</ety> <def>Mamma.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mama</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*ma"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mamma</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mamaluke</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"a*luke</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Mameluke</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mama's boy</ent><br/
<hw>mama's boy</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>mamma's boy</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mamelon</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mam"e*lon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>A rounded hillock; a rounded elevation or protuberance.</def>  <rj><au>Westmin. Rev.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mameluco</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mam`e*lu"co</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pg.]</ety> <def>A child born of a white father and Indian mother.</def> <mark>[S. Amer.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mameluke</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"e*luke</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mamelouk</ets>, cf. Sp. <ets>mameluco</ets>, It. <ets>mammalucco</ets>; all fr. Ar. <ets>maml<umac/k</ets> a purchased slave or captive; lit., possessed or in one's power, p. p. of <ets>malaka</ets> to possesses.]</ety> <def>One of a body of mounted soldiers recruited from slaves converted to Muslimism, who, during several centuries, had more or less control of the government of Egypt, until exterminated or dispersed by <person>Mehemet Ali</person> in 1811.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mamillated</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"il*la`ted</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>See <er>Mammillated</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mamma</ent><br/
<hw>Mam*ma"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Reduplicated from the infantine word <ets>ma</ets>, influenced in spelling by L. <ets>mamma</ets>.]</ety> <def>Mother; -- word of tenderness and familiarity.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mama</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tell tales papa and <qex>mamma</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mamma</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mammae</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>mamma</ets> breast.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A glandular organ for secreting milk, characteristic of all mammals, but usually rudimentary in the male; a mammary gland; a breast; udder; bag.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammal</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"mal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mammals</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>mammalis</ets> belonging to the breast, fr. <ets>mamma</ets> the breast or pap: cf. F. <ets>mammal</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the Mammalia.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Age of mammals</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Age</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 8.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammalia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mam*ma"li*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., from L. <ets>mammalis</ets>. See <er>Mammal</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The highest class of Vertebrata.  The young are nourished for a time by milk, or an analogous fluid, secreted by the mammary glands of the mother.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Mammalia are divided into three subclasses; --<br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>I. <stype>Placentalia</stype>. This subclass embraces all the higher orders, including man. In these the fetus is attached to the uterus by a placenta.<br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>II. <stype>Marsupialia</stype>. In these no placenta is formed, and the young, which are born at an early state of development, are carried for a time attached to the teats, and usually protected by a marsupial pouch. The opossum, kangaroo, wombat, and koala are examples.<br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>III. <stype>Monotremata</stype>. In this group, which includes the genera <gen>Echidna</gen> and <gen>Ornithorhynchus</gen>, the female lays large eggs resembling those of a bird or lizard, and the young, which are hatched like those of birds, are nourished by a watery secretion from the imperfectly developed mammae.
</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammalian</ent><br/
<hw>Mam*ma"li*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the Mammalia or mammals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammaliferous</ent><br/
<hw>Mam`ma*lif"er*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mammal</ets> + <ets>-ferous</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>Containing mammalian remains; -- said of certain strata.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammalogical</ent><br/
<hw>Mam`ma*log"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to mammalogy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammalogist</ent><br/
<hw>Mam*mal"o*gist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mammalogiste</ets>.]</ety> <def>One versed in mammalogy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammalogy</ent><br/
<hw>Mam*mal"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mamma</ets> breast + <ets>-logy</ets>: cf. f. <ets>mammalogie</ets>.]</ety> <def>The science which relates to mammals or the <class>Mammalia</class>. See <er>Mammalia</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammary</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"ma*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mammaire</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the mammae or breasts; <as>as, the <ex>mammary</ex> arteries and veins</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mammary gland</ent><br/
<hw>mammary gland</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The milk-secreting organ of female mammals.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mamma.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mama's boy</ent><br/
<hw>mama's boy</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A boy excessively attached to his mother; a boy lacking the usual masculine interests; also spelled <asp>mamma's boy</asp>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mother's boy.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammea</ent><br/
<hw>Mammea</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A genus of American and Asiatic trees having edible one-seeded fruit.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Mammea</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammea americana</ent><br/
<hw>Mammea americana</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The speciaes name for the mammee tree.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammee tree</ent><br/
<ent>Mammee</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Mam*mee"</hw>, <hw>Mam*mee" tree`</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Haitian <ets>mamey</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A fruit tree of tropical America, belonging to the genus <gen>Mammea</gen> (<spn>Mammea Americana</spn>); also, its fruit, called the <prod>mammee apple</prod>.  The latter is large, covered with a thick, tough ring, and contains a bright yellow pulp of a pleasant taste and fragrant scent.  It is often called <altname>mammee apple</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mammee apple, mammee, mamey, <spn>Mammea americana</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mammee apple</ent><br/
<hw>mammee apple</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A tropical American tree (<spn>Mammea americana</spn>) having edible fruit (the <prod>mammee apple</prod>) with a leathery rind.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mammee, mamey, mammee tree, <spn>Mammea americana</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The globular or ovoid tropical fruit of the mammee tree (<spn>Mammea americana</spn>), having a thick russet leathery rind and juicy yellow or reddish flesh.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammer</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"mer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. G. <ets>memme</ets> coward, poltroon.]</ety> <def>To hesitate; to mutter doubtfully.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammet</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"met</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mawmet</er>.]</ety> <def>An idol; a puppet; a doll.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Selden.</au>  <au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammetry</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"met*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mawmetry</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammifer</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"mi*fer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Mammiferous</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A mammal. See <er>Mammalia</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammiferous</ent><br/
<hw>Mam*mif"er*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mamma</ets> breast + <ets>-ferous</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mammif<egrave/re</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having breasts; of, pertaining to, or derived from, the Mammalia.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammiform</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"mi*form</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mamma</ets> breast + <ets>-form</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mammiforme</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having the form of a mamma (breast) or mammae.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammilla</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mam*mil"la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mammilae</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., dim. of <ets>mamma</ets> a breast.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The nipple.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammillary</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"mil*la*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mammilaire</ets>. See <er>Mammilla</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the mammilla, or nipple, or to the breast; resembling a mammilla; mammilloid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Composed of convex convex concretions, somewhat resembling the breasts in form; studded with small mammiform protuberances.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammillated</ent><br/
<ent>Mammillate</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mam"mil*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mam"mil*la`ted</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mammilla</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having small nipples, or small protuberances like nipples or mammae.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Bounded like a nipple; -- said of the apex of some shells.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammilliform</ent><br/
<hw>Mam*mil"li*form</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mammilla</ets> + <ets>-form</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having the form of a mammilla.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammilloid</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"mil*loid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mammilla</ets> + <ets>-oid</ets>.]</ety> <def>Like a mammilla or nipple; mammilliform.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammock</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"mock</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Ir. & Gael. <ets>mam</ets> a round hill + <ets>-ock</ets>.]</ety> <def>A shapeless piece; a fragment.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammock</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"mock</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To tear to pieces.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammodis</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"mo*dis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mamoudis</ets>, fr. Hind. <ets>mahm<umac/d<imac/</ets> a muslin.]</ety> <def>Coarse plain India muslins.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammology</ent><br/
<hw>Mam*mol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mamma</ets> + <ets>-logy</ets>.]</ety> <def>Mastology. See <er>Mammalogy</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammon</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"mon</hw> <pr>(m<acr/m"m<ucr/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mammona</ets>, Gr. <grk>mammwna^s</grk> riches, Syr. <ets>mam<omac/n<amac/</ets>; cf. Heb. <ets>matm<omac/n</ets> a hiding place, subterranean storehouse, treasury, fr. <ets>t<amac/man</ets> to hide.]</ety> <def>Riches; wealth; the god of riches; riches, personified.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye can not serve God and <qex>Mammon</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. vi. 24.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammonish</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"mon*ish</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Actuated or prompted by a devotion to money getting or the service of Mammon.</def>  <rj><au>Carlyle.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammonism</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"mon*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Devotion to the pursuit of wealth; worldliness.</def>  <rj><au>Carlyle.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammonist</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"mon*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mammonite.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammonite</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"mon*ite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One devoted to the acquisition of wealth or the service of Mammon.</def>  <rj><au>C. Kingsley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammonization</ent><br/
<hw>Mam`mon*i*za"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The process of making mammonish; the state of being under the influence of mammonism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammonize</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"mon*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make mammonish.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammose</ent><br/
<hw>Mam*mose"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mammosus</ets> having large breasts, <ets>mamma</ets> breast.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having the form of the breast; breast-shaped.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 889 --></p>

<p><ent>Mammoth</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"moth</hw> <pr>(m<acr/m"m<ocr/th)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Russ. <ets>m<acir/mont</ets>, <ets>m<aacute/mant</ets>, fr. Tartar <ets>mamma</ets> the earth.  Certain Tartar races, the Tungooses and Yakoots, believed that the mammoth worked its way in the earth like a mole.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An extinct, hairy, maned elephant (<spn>Mammuthus primigenius</spn> formerly <spn>Elephas primigenius</spn>), of enormous size, remains of which are found in the northern parts of both continents.  The last of the race, in Europe, were coeval with prehistoric man.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Several specimens have been found in Siberia preserved entire, with the flesh and hair remaining.  They were imbedded in the ice cliffs at a remote period, and became exposed by the melting of the ice.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammoth</ent><br/
<hw>Mam"moth</hw> <pr>(m<acr/m"m<ocr/th)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Resembling the mammoth in size; very large; gigantic; <as>as, a <ex>mammoth</ex> ox</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mammothrept</ent><br/
<hw>mam"mo*thrept</hw> <pr>(m<acr/m"m<osl/*thr<ecr/pt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mammo`qreptos</grk>; <grk>ma`mma</grk> grandmother + <grk>tre`pein</grk> to nourish.]</ety> <def>A child brought up by its grandmother; a spoiled child.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O, you are a more <qex>mammothrept</qex> in judgment.</q> <rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammuthus</ent><br/
<hw>Mammuthus</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>An extinct genus comprising the mammoths.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Mammuthus</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammuthus primigenius</ent><br/
<hw>Mammuthus primigenius</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The species name for the woolly mammoth, a very hairy mammoth common in colder portions of the Northern hemisphere.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> woolly mammoth, northern mammoth.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mammutidae</ent><br/
<hw>Mammutidae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>An extinct natural family of mammals, comprising the mastodons.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Mammutidae</fam>, family <fam>Mastodontidae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mammy</ent><br/
<hw>mam"my</hw> <pr>(m<acr/m"m<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>mammies</plw> <pr>(m<acr/m"m<icr/z)</pr>.</plu> <def>A child's name for <sig>mamma</sig>, mother.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mamoncillo</ent><br/
<hw>mamoncillo</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A tropical American tree (<spn>Melicocca bijuga</spn>, or <spn>Melicocca bijugatus</spn>) bearing a small edible fruit with green leathery skin and sweet juicy translucent pulp.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Spanish lime, Spanish lime tree, honey berry, genip, ginep, <spn>Melicocca bijuga</spn>, <spn>Melicocca bijugatus</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mamzer</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mam"zer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Heb. <ets>m<aacute/mz<emac/r</ets>.]</ety> <def>A person born of relations between whom marriage was forbidden by the Mosaic law; a bastard.</def> <au>Deut. xxiii. 2 (Douay version).</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Man</ent><br/
<hw>Man</hw> <pr>(m<acr/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Men</plw> <pr>(m<ecr/n)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[AS. <ets>mann</ets>, <ets>man</ets>, <ets>monn</ets>, <ets>mon</ets>; akin to OS., D., & OHG. <ets>man</ets>, G. <ets>mann</ets>, Icel. <ets>ma<edh/r</ets>, for <ets>mannr</ets>, Dan. <ets>Mand</ets>, Sw. <ets>man</ets>, Goth. <ets>manna</ets>, Skr. <ets>manu</ets>, <ets>manus</ets>, and perh. to Skr. <ets>man</ets> to think, and E. <ets>mind</ets>.  <root/104.  Cf. <er>Minx</er> a pert girl.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A human being; -- opposed to <contr>beast</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These <qex>men</qex> went about wide, and <qex>man</qex> found they none,<br/
But fair country, and wild beast many [a] one.</q> <rj><qau>R. of Glouc.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The king is but a <qex>man</qex>, as I am; the violet smells to him as it doth to me.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>'Tain't a fit night out for <qex>man</qex> nor beast!</q> <rj><qau>W. C. Fields</qau></rj><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Especially:</specif> <def>An adult male person; a grown-up male person, as distinguished from a woman or a child.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When I became a <qex>man</qex>, I put away childish things.</q> <rj><qau>I Cor. xiii. 11.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ceneus, a woman once, and once a <qex>man</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The human race; mankind.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And God said, Let us make <qex>man</qex> in our image, after our likeness, and let them have dominion.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. i. 26.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The proper study of mankind is <qex>man</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The male portion of the human race.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Woman has, in general, much stronger propensity than <qex>man</qex> to the discharge of parental duties.</q> <rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>One possessing in a high degree the distinctive qualities of manhood; one having manly excellence of any kind.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This was the noblest Roman of them all . . . the elements<br/
So mixed in him that Nature might stand up<br/
And say to all the world <ldquo/This was a <qex>man</qex>!<rdquo/</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>An adult male servant; also, a vassal; a subject.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like master, like <qex>man</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Old Proverb.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The vassal, or tenant, kneeling, ungirt, uncovered, and holding up his hands between those of his lord, professed that he did become his <qex>man</qex> from that day forth, of life, limb, and earthly honor.</q> <rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A term of familiar address at one time implying on the part of the speaker some degree of authority, impatience, or haste; <as>as, Come, <ex>man</ex>, we 've no time to lose!</as>  In the latter half of the 20th century it became used in a broader sense as simply a familiar and informal form of address, but is not used in business or formal situations; <as>as, hey, <ex>man</ex>!  You want to go to a movie tonight?</as>.</def> <mark>[Informal]</mark> <br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A married man; a husband; -- correlative to <inv>wife</inv>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I pronounce that they are <qex>man</qex> and wife.</q> <rj><qau>Book of Com. Prayer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>every wife ought to answer for her <qex>man</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>One, or any one, indefinitely; -- a modified survival of the Saxon use of <xex>man</xex>, or <xex>mon</xex>, as an indefinite pronoun.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>man</qex> can not make him laugh.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>man</qex> would expect to find some antiquities; but all they have to show of this nature is an old rostrum of a Roman ship.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>One of the piece with which certain games, as chess or draughts, are played.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <ex>Man</ex> is often used as a prefix in composition, or as a separate adjective, its sense being usually self-explaining; as, <ex>man</ex> child, <ex>man</ex> eater or <ex>man</ex>eater, <ex>man-</ex>eating, <ex>man</ex> hater or <ex>man</ex>hater, <ex>man-</ex>hating, <ex>man</ex>hunter, <ex>man-</ex>hunting, <ex>man</ex>killer, <ex>man-</ex>killing, <ex>man</ex> midwife, <ex>man</ex> pleaser, <ex>man</ex> servant, <ex>man-</ex>shaped, <ex>man</ex>slayer, <ex>man</ex>stealer, <ex>man-stealing</ex>, <ex>man</ex>thief, <ex>man</ex> worship, etc.<br/
<br/
<ex>Man</ex> is also used as a suffix to denote a person of the male sex having a business which pertains to the thing spoken of in the qualifying part of the compound; ash<ex>man</ex>, butter<ex>man</ex>, laundry<ex>man</ex>, lumber<ex>man</ex>, milk<ex>man</ex>, fire<ex>man</ex>, repair<ex>man</ex>, show<ex>man</ex>, water<ex>man</ex>, wood<ex>man</ex>.  Where the combination is not familiar, or where some specific meaning of the compound is to be avoided, <ex>man</ex> is used as a separate substantive in the foregoing sense; as, apple <ex>man</ex>, cloth <ex>man</ex>, coal <ex>man</ex>, hardware <ex>man</ex>, wood <ex>man</ex> (as distinguished from wood<ex>man</ex>).</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Man ape</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a anthropoid ape, as the gorilla.</cd> -- <col><b>Man at arms</b></col>, <cd>a designation of the fourteenth and fifteenth centuries for a soldier fully armed.</cd> -- <col><b>Man engine</b></col>, <cd>a mechanical lift for raising or lowering people through considerable distances;</cd> <specif>specifically</specif> <fld>(Mining)</fld>, <cd>a contrivance by which miners ascend or descend in a shaft.  It consists of a series of landings in the shaft and an equal number of shelves on a vertical rod which has an up and down motion equal to the distance between the successive landings.  A man steps from a landing to a shelf and is lifted or lowered to the next landing, upon which he them steps, and so on, traveling by successive stages.</cd> -- <col><b>Man Friday</b></col>, <cd>a person wholly subservient to the will of another, like Robinson Crusoe's servant Friday.</cd> -- <col><b>Man of straw</b></col>, <cd>a puppet; one who is controlled by others; also, one who is not responsible pecuniarily.</cd> -- <col><b>Man-of-the earth</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a twining plant (<spn>Ipomoea pandurata</spn>) with leaves and flowers much like those of the morning-glory, but having an immense tuberous farinaceous root.</cd> -- <col><b>Man of sin</b></col> <fld>(Script.)</fld>, <cd>one who is the embodiment of evil, whose coming is represented (<au>2 Thess. ii. 3</au>) as preceding the second coming of Christ.</cd> <mark>[A Hebraistic expression]</mark> -- <col><b>Man of war</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A warrior; a soldier</cd>. <au>Shak.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>See in the Vocabulary.</cd> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>See <cref>Portuguese man-of-war</cref> under <er>man-of-war</er> and also see <er>Physalia</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Man-stopping bullet</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>a bullet which will produce a sufficient shock to stop a soldier advancing in a charge; specif., a small-caliber bullet so modified as to expand when striking the human body, producing a severe wound which is also difficult to treat medically.  Types of bullets called <stype>hollow-nosed bullets</stype>, <stype>soft-nosed bullets</stype> and <stype>hollow-point bullets</stype> are classed as man-stopping.  The <stype>dumdum bullet</stype> or <stype>dumdum</stype> is another well-known variety.  Such bullets were originally designed for wars with savage tribes.</cd> -- <col><b>great man</b></col>, <cd>a man{2} who has become prominent due to substantial and widely admired contributions to social or intellectual endeavors; <as>as, Einstein was one of the <ex>great men</ex> of the twentieth century</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To be one's own man</b></col>, <cd>to have command of one's self; not to be subject to another.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Man</ent><br/
<hw>Man</hw> <pr>(m<acr/n)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Manned</conjf> <pr>(m<acr/nd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Manning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To supply with men; to furnish with a sufficient force or complement of men, as for management, service, defense, or the like; to guard; <as>as, to <ex>man</ex> a ship, boat, or fort</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>See how the surly Warwick <qex>mans</qex> the wall !</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>man</qex> their boats, and all their young men arm.</q> <rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To furnish with strength for action; to prepare for efficiency; to fortify.</def> <ldquo/Theodosius having <xex>manned</xex> his soul with proper reflections.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To tame, as a hawk.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To furnish with a servant or servants.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To wait on as a manservant.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ In <ldquo/Othello,<rdquo/ V. ii. 270, the meaning is uncertain, being, perhaps: To point, to aim, or to manage.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To man a yard</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to send men upon a yard, as for furling or reefing a sail.</cd> -- <col><b>To man the yards</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to station men on the yards as a salute or mark of respect.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manable</ent><br/
<hw>Man"a*ble</hw> <pr>(m<acr/n"<adot/*b'l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Marriageable.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manace</ent><br/
<hw>Man"ace</hw> <pr>(m<acr/n"<asl/s)</pr>, <pos>n. & v.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Menace</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manacle</ent><br/
<hw>Man"a*cle</hw> <pr>(m<acr/n"<adot/*k'l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>manicle</ets>, OF. <ets>manicle</ets>, F. <ets>manicle</ets> sort glove, manacle, L. <ets>manicula</ets> a little hand, dim. of <ets>manus</ets> hand; cf. L. <ets>manica</ets> sleeve, manacle, fr. <ets>manus</ets>. See <er>Manual</er>.]</ety> <def>A handcuff; a shackle for the hand or wrist; -- usually in the plural.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Doctrine unto fools is as fetters on the feet, and like <qex>manacles</qex> on the right hand.</q> <rj><qau>Ecclus. xxi. 19.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manacle</ent><br/
<hw>Man"a*cle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Manacled</conjf> <pr>(m<acr/n"<adot/*k'ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Manacling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To put handcuffs or other fastening upon, for confining the hands; to shackle; to confine; to restrain from the use of the limbs or natural powers.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Is it thus you use this monarch, to <qex>manacle</qex> and shackle him hand and foot ?</q> <rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manage</ent><br/
<hw>Man"age</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>man<egrave/ge</ets>, It.  <ets>maneggio</ets>, fr. <ets>maneggiare</ets> to manage, fr. L. <ets>manus</ets>hand. Perhaps somewhat influenced by F.  <ets>m<eacute/nage</ets> housekeeping, OF. <ets>mesnage</ets>, akin to E. <ets>mansion</ets>. See <er>Manual</er>, and cf. <er>Manege</er>.]</ety> <def>The handling or government of anything, but esp. of a horse; management; administration. See <er>Manege</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Young men, in the conduct and <qex>manage</qex> of actions, embrace more than they can hold.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Down, down I come; like glistering Phaethon<br/
Wanting the <qex>manage</qex> of unruly jades.</q>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The unlucky <qex>manage</qex> of this fatal brawl.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ This word, in its limited sense of management of a horse, has been displaced by <xex>manege</xex>; in its more general meaning, by <xex>management</xex>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manage</ent><br/
<hw>Man"age</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Managed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Managing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From <er>Manage</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To have under control and direction; to conduct; to guide; to administer; to treat; to handle.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Long tubes are cumbersome, and scarce to be easily <qex>managed</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir I. Newton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What wars I<qex>manage</qex>, and what wreaths I gain.</q> <rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence, Esp.:</specif> <def>to guide by careful or delicate treatment; to wield with address; to make subservient by artful conduct; to bring around cunningly to one's plans.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was so much his interest to <qex>manage</qex> his Protestant subjects.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was not her humor to <qex>manage</qex> those over whom she had gained an ascendant.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Hurd.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To train in the manege, as a horse; to exercise in graceful or artful action.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To treat with care; to husband.</def>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To bring about; to contrive.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To direct; govern; control; wield; order; contrive; concert; conduct; transact.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manage</ent><br/
<hw>Man"age</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To direct affairs; to carry on business or affairs; to administer.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Leave them to <qex>manage</qex> for thee.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manageability</ent><br/
<hw>Man`age*a*bil"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state or quality of being manageable; manageableness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manageable</ent><br/
<hw>Man"age*a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Such as can be managed or used; suffering control; governable; tractable; subservient; <as>as, a <ex>manageable</ex> horse</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Governable; tractable; controllable; docile.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Man"age*a*ble*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos> -- <wf>Man"age*a*bly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>managed economy</ent><br/
<hw>managed economy</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A non-market economy in which government intervention is important in allocating goods and resources and determining prices.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manageless</ent><br/
<hw>Man"age*less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Unmanageable.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Management</ent><br/
<hw>Man"age*ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Manage</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or art of managing; the manner of treating, directing, carrying on, or using, for a purpose; conduct; administration; guidance; control; <as>as, the <ex>management</ex> of a family or of a farm; the <ex>management</ex> of a business enterprise; the <ex>management</ex> of state affairs.</as></def> <ldquo/The <xex>management</xex> of the voice.<rdquo/  <rj><au>E. Porter.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Business dealing; negotiation; arrangement.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He had great <qex>managements</qex> with ecclesiastics.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Judicious use of means to accomplish an end; conduct directed by art or address; skillful treatment; cunning practice; -- often in a bad sense.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mark with what <qex>management</qex> their tribes divide<br/
Some stick to you, and some to t'other side.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The collective body of those who manage or direct any enterprise or interest; the board of managers.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Conduct; administration; government; direction; guidance; care; charge; contrivance; intrigue.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>management consultant</ent><br/
<hw>management consultant</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>An adviser to business about efficient management practices.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>management personnel</ent><br/
<hw>management personnel</hw> <pos>n. pl.</pos> <def>Personnel having ovrall planning and direction responsibilities.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manager</ent><br/
<hw>Man"a*ger</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who manages; a conductor or director; <as>as, the <ex>manager</ex> of a theater</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A skillful <qex>manager</qex> of the rabble.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A person who conducts business or household affairs with economy and frugality; a good economist.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A prince of great aspiring thoughts; in the main, a <qex>manager</qex> of his treasure.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Temple.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A contriver; an intriguer.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manageress</ent><br/
<hw>manageress</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A woman manager.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Managerial</ent><br/
<hw>Man`a*ge"ri*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to management or a manager; <as>as, <ex>managerial</ex> qualities</as>.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Managerial</xex> responsibility.<rdquo/  <rj><au>C. Bront<eacute/.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Managership</ent><br/
<hw>Man"a*ger*ship</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The office or position of a manager.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Managery</ent><br/
<hw>Man"age*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>menagerie</ets>, <ets>mesnagerie</ets>. See <er>Manage</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, and cf. <er>Menagerie</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Management; manner of using; conduct; direction.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Husbandry; economy; frugality.</def>  <rj><au>Bp. Burnet.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>managing director</ent><br/
<hw>managing director</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A person who manages a busness though not the owner or chief executive.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> director, manager.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>managing editor</ent><br/
<hw>managing editor</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The editor in charge of all editorial activities of a newspaper or magazine.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manakin</ent><br/
<hw>Man"a*kin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.  & G. <ets>manakin</ets>; prob. the native name.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of numerous small birds belonging to <gen>Pipra</gen>, <gen>Manacus</gen>, and other genera of the family <fam>Pipridae</fam>.  They are mostly natives of Central and South America.  Some are bright-colored, and others have the wings and tail curiously ornamented.  The name is sometimes applied to related birds of other families.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manakin</ent><br/
<hw>Man"a*kin</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A dwarf. See <er>Manikin</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manannan</ent><br/
<hw>Manannan</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Irish mythology)</fld>  <def>The Irish god of the sea; son of <persfn>Ler</persfn>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>man and wife</ent><br/
<hw>man and wife</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A man and woman who are married to each other; a married couple.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>man-at-arms</ent><br/
<hw>man-at-arms</hw> <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>men-at-arms</plw> <pr>(?)</pr></plu>. <def>A heavily armed and sometimes mounted soldier in medieval times.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manatee</ent><br/
<hw>man`a*tee"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>manat<iacute/</ets>, from the native name in Haiti.  Cf. <er>Lamantin</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any species of <gen>Trichechus</gen>, a genus of sirenians; -- called also <altname>sea cow</altname>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>manaty</asp>, <asp>manati</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ One species (<spn>Trichechus Senegalensis</spn>) inhabits the west coast of Africa; another (<spn>Trichechus Americanus</spn>) inhabits the east coast of South America, and the West-Indies. The Florida manatee (<spn>Trichechus latirostris</spn>) is by some considered a distinct species, by others it is thought to be a variety of <spn>Trichechus Americanus</spn>. It sometimes becomes fifteen feet or more in length, and lives both in fresh and salt water. It was hunted for its oil and flesh, and every species is now an <isa>endangered species</isa>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manation</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*na"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos><ety>[L. <ets>manatio</ets>, fr. <ets>manare</ets> to flow.]</ety> <def>The act of issuing or flowing out.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manbird</ent><br/
<hw>Man"bird`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An aviator.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manbote</ent><br/
<hw>Man"bote`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>man</ets> man, vassal +  <ets>b<omac/t</ets> recompense.]</ety> <fld>(Anglo-Saxon Law)</fld> <def>A sum paid to a lord as a pecuniary compensation for killing his man (that is, his vassal, servant, or tenant).</def>  <rj><au>Spelman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manca</ent><br/
<hw>Man"ca</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.]</ety> <def>See <er>Mancus</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manche</ent><br/
<hw>Manche</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <altsp>[Also <asp>maunch</asp>.]</altsp> <ety>[F. <ets>manche</ets>, fr. L. <ets>manica</ets>. See <er>Manacle</er>.]</ety> <def>A sleeve.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manchester terrier</ent><br/
<hw>Manchester terrier</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A breed of short-haired black-and-tan terrier developed in Manchester England.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> black-and-tan terrier.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manchet</ent><br/
<hw>Man"chet</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Fine white bread; a loaf of fine bread.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>  <rj><au>Bacon. Tennyson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manchineel</ent><br/
<hw>Man`chi*neel"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp.  <ets>manzanillo</ets>, fr.  <ets>manzana</ets> an apple, fr. L.  <ets>malum Matianum</ets> a kind of apple. So called from its apple-like fruit.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A euphorbiaceous tree (<spn>Hippomane Mancinella</spn>) of tropical America, having a poisonous and blistering milky juice, and poisonous acrid fruit somewhat resembling an apple.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Bastard manchineel</b></col>, <cd>a tree (<spn>Cameraria latifolia</spn>) of the East Indies, having similar poisonous properties.</cd> <au>Lindley.</au></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manchu</ent><br/
<hw>Man*chu"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Written also <ets>Manchoo</ets>, <ets>Mantchoo</ets>, etc.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to Manchuria or its inhabitants.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A native or inhabitant of Manchuria; also, the language spoken by the Manchus.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mancipate</ent><br/
<hw>Man"ci*pate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mancipatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>mancipare</ets> to sell.  Cf. <er>Emancipate</er>.]</ety> <def>To enslave; to bind; to restrict.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir M. Hale.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mancipation</ent><br/
<hw>Man`ci*pa"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mancipatio</ets> a transfer.]</ety> <def>Slavery; involuntary servitude.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manciple</ent><br/
<hw>Man"ci*ple</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From OF. <ets>mancipe</ets> slave, servant (with <ets>l</ets> inserted, as in <ets>participle</ets>), fr. L.  <ets>mancipium</ets>. See <er>Mancipate</er>.]</ety> <def>A steward; a purveyor, particularly of a college or Inn of Court.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mancona bark</ent><br/
<hw>Man*co"na bark`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <def>See <er>Sassy bark</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mancus</ent><br/
<hw>Man"cus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.]</ety> <def>An old Anglo Saxon coin both of gold and silver, and of variously estimated values.  The silver <ex>mancus</ex> was equal to about one shilling of modern English money.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>-mancy</ent><br/
<hw>-man`cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[Gr. <?/ divination: cf. F. <ets>-mancie</ets>.]</ety> <def>A combining form denoting <xex>divination</xex>; <as>as, aleuro<ex>mancy</ex>, chiro<ex>mancy</ex>, necro<ex>mancy</ex>, etc.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mand</ent><br/
<hw>Mand</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A demand.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <see>See <er>Demand</er>.</see><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandamus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Man*da"mus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., we command, fr. <ets>mandare</ets> to command.]</ety> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A writ issued by a superior court and directed to some inferior tribunal, or to some corporation or person exercising authority, commanding the performance of some specified duty.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandarin</ent><br/
<hw>Man`da*rin"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pg. <ets>mandarim</ets>, from Malay <ets>mantr<imac/</ets> minister of state, prop. a Hind. word, fr. Skr. <ets>mantrin</ets> a counselor, <ets>manira</ets> a counsel, <ets>man</ets> to think.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A Chinese public officer or nobleman; a civil or military official in China and Annam.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>A powerful government official or bureaucrat, especially one who is pedantic and has a strong sense of his own importance and privelege.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>A member of an influential, powerful or elite group, espcially within artistic or intellectual circles; -- used especially of elder members who are traditionalist or conservative about their specialties.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The form of the Chinese language spoken by members of the Chinese Imperial Court an officials of the empire.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Any of several closely related dialects of the Chinese language spoken by a mojority of the population of China, the standard variety of which is spoken in the region around Beijing.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A small flattish reddish-orange loose-skinned orange, with an easily separable rind. It is thought to be of Chinese origin, and is counted a distinct species (<spn>Citrus reticulata</spn> formerly <spn>Citrus nobilis</spn>); called also <altname>mandarin orange</altname> and <altname>tangerine</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mandarin language</b></col>, <cd>the spoken or colloquial language of educated people in China.</cd> -- <col><b>Mandarin yellow</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>an artificial aniline dyestuff used for coloring silk and wool, and regarded as a complex derivative of quinoline.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandarinate</ent><br/
<hw>Man`da*rin"ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The collective body of officials or persons of rank in China.</def>  <rj><au>S. W. Williams.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mandarin duck</ent><br/
<hw>mandarin duck</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A showy crested Asiatic duck (<spn>Aix galericulata</spn>, formerly <spn>Dendronessa galericulata</spn>), often domesticated, and regarded by the Chinese as an emblem of conjugal affection.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 890 --></p>

<p><ent>Mandarinic</ent><br/
<hw>Man`da*rin"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Appropriate or peculiar to a mandarin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandarining</ent><br/
<hw>Man`da*rin"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Dyeing)</fld> <def>The process of giving an orange color to goods formed of animal tissue, as silk or wool, not by coloring matter, but by producing a certain change in the fiber by the action of dilute nitric acid.</def>  <rj><au>Tomlinson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandarinism</ent><br/
<hw>Man`da*rin"ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A government by mandarins (senses 1 or 2); character or spirit of the mandarins{2}.</def>  <rj><au>F. Lieder.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mandarin orange</ent><br/
<hw>man`da*rin" or"ange</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A shrub or small tree (<spn>Citrus reticulata</spn>) having flattened globose fruit with very sweet aromatic pulp and thin yellow-orange to flame-orange rind that is loose and easily removed; native to Southeast Asia.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mandarin orange tree.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Same as <er>mandarin</er>{7}.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandatary</ent><br/
<hw>Man"da*ta*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. mandatarius, fr. <ets>mandatum</ets> a charge, commission, order: cf. F. <ets>mandataire</ets>. See <er>Mandate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One to whom a command or charge is given; hence, specifically, a person to whom the pope has, by his prerogative, given a mandate or order for his benefice.</def>  <rj><au>Ayliffe.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>One who undertakes to discharge a specific business commission; a mandatory.</def>  <rj><au>Wharton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandate</ent><br/
<hw>Man"date</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mandatum</ets>, fr. <ets>mandare</ets> to commit to one's charge, order, orig., to put into one's hand; <ets>manus</ets> hand + <ets>dare</ets> to give: cf. F. <ets>mandat</ets>. See <er>Manual</er>, <er>Date</er> a time, and cf. <er>Commend</er>, <er>Maundy Thursday</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An official or authoritative command, order, or authorization from a superior official to a subordinate; an order or injunction; a commission; a judicial precept.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This dream all-powerful Juno; I bear<br/
Her mighty <qex>mandates</qex>, and her words you hear.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <fld>(Politics)</fld> <def>An authorization to carry out a specific public policy, given by the electorate to their representatives; -- it is considered to be implied by the election of a candidate by a significant margin after that candidate has campaigned with that policy as a prominent element of the campaign platform.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>Authorization by a multinational body to a nation to administer the government and affairs of a territory, usually a former colony; <as>as, termination of the British <ex>mandate</ex> in Palestine</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Canon Law)</fld> <def>A rescript of the pope, commanding an ordinary collator to put the person therein named in possession of the first vacant benefice in his collation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Scots Law)</fld> <def>A contract by which one employs another to manage any business for him.  By the Roman law, it must have been gratuitous.</def>  <rj><au>Erskine.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandator</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Man*da"tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A director; one who gives a mandate or order.</def>  <rj><au>Ayliffe.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Rom. Law)</fld> <def>The person who employs another to perform a mandate.</def>  <rj><au>Bouvier.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandatory</ent><br/
<hw>Man"da*to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mandatorius</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Containing a command; preceptive; directory.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Obligatory; compulsory; required by authority.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Not optional; not able to be modified or disregarded; <as>as, seven <ex>mandatory</ex> clauses in the contract</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandatory</ent><br/
<hw>Man"da*to*ry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Mandatary</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandelate</ent><br/
<hw>Man"del*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of mandelic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandelic</ent><br/
<hw>Man*del"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[G. <ets>mandel</ets> almond.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to an acid first obtained from benzoic aldehyde (oil of better almonds), as a white crystalline substance; -- called also <xex>phenyl glycolic acid</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mander</ent><br/
<hw>Man"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>See <er>Maunder</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manderil</ent><br/
<hw>Man"der*il</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mandrel.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandible</ent><br/
<hw>Man"di*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mandibula</ets>, <ets>mandibulum</ets>, fr. <ets>mandere</ets> to chew.  Cf. <er>Manger</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The bone, or principal bone, of the lower jaw; the inferior maxilla; -- also applied to either the upper or the lower jaw in the beak of birds.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The anterior pair of mouth organs of insects, crustaceaus, and related animals, whether adapted for biting or not. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Diptera</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandibular</ent><br/
<hw>Man*dib"u*lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mandibulaire</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to a mandible; like a mandible.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>The principal mandibular bone; the mandible.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mandibular arch</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>the most anterior visceral arch, -- that in which the mandible is developed.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mandibular joint</ent><br/
<hw>mandibular joint</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(anatomy)</fld> <def>The joint between the head of the lower jawbone and the temporal bone.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> temporomandibular joint, articulatio temporomandibularis.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandibulated</ent><br/
<ent>Mandibulate</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Man*dib"u*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Man*dib"u*la`ted</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Provided with mandibles adapted for biting, as many insects.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandibulate</ent><br/
<hw>Man*dib"u*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An insect having mandibles.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandibuliform</ent><br/
<hw>Man`di*bu"li*form</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having the form of a mandible; -- said especially of the maxillae of an insect when hard and adapted for biting.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandibulohyoid</ent><br/
<hw>Man*dib`u*lo*hy"oid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Pertaining both to the mandibular and the hyoid arch, or situated between them.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mandil</ent><br/
<hw>man"dil</hw> <pr>(m<acr/n"d<icr/l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>mandil</ets>; cf. Sp. & Pg. <ets>mandil</ets> a coarse apron, a haircloth; all from Ar. <ets>mandil</ets> tablecloth, handkerchief, mantle, fr. LGr. <grk>mandh`lion</grk>, fr. L. <ets>mantile</ets>, <ets>mantele</ets>. See <er>Mantle</er>.]</ety> <def>A loose outer garment worn the 16th and 17th centuries.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandilion</ent><br/
<hw>Man*dil"ion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mandil</er>.</def> <au>Chapman.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandingos</ent><br/
<hw>Man*din"gos</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos>; <sing><it>sing.</it> <singw>Mandingo</singw></sing>. <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>An extensive and powerful tribe of West African negroes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandioca</ent><br/
<ent>Mandioc</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Man"di*oc</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, \'d8<hw>Man`di*o"ca</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>See <er>Manioc</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandlestone</ent><br/
<hw>Man"dle*stone`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G. <ets>mandelstein</ets> almond stone.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Amygdaloid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandment</ent><br/
<hw>Mand"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Commandment.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandola</ent><br/
<hw>Man*do"la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It. See <er>Mandolin</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>An instrument closely resembling the mandolin, but of larger size and tuned lower.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandoline</ent><br/
<ent>Mandolin</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Man"do*lin</hw>, <hw>Man"do*line</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mandoline</ets>, It. <ets>mandolino</ets>, dim. of <ets>mandola</ets>, fr. L. <ets>pandura</ets>. See <er>Bandore</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A small and beautifully shaped instrument resembling the lute.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandore</ent><br/
<hw>Man"dore</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mandolin</er>, and <er>Bandore</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A kind of four-stringed lute.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandragora</ent><br/
<hw>Man*drag"o*ra</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., <ets>mandragoras</ets> the mandrake.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of plants; the mandrake. See <er>Mandrake</er>, 1.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandragorite</ent><br/
<hw>Man*drag"o*rite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who habitually intoxicates himself with a narcotic obtained from mandrake.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mandrake</ent><br/
<hw>man"drake</hw> <pr>(m<acr/n"dr<amac/k)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>mandragora</ets>, L. <ets>mandragoras</ets>, fr. Gr. <grk>mandrago`ras</grk>: cf. F. <ets>mandragore</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A low plant (<spn>Mandragora officinarum</spn>) of the Nightshade family, having a fleshy root, often forked, and supposed to resemble a man.  It was therefore supposed to have animal life, and to cry out when pulled up.  All parts of the plant are strongly narcotic.  It is found in the Mediterranean region.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And shrieks like <qex>mandrakes</qex>, torn out of the earth,<br/
That living mortals, hearing them, run mad.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The mandrake of Scripture was perhaps the same plant, but proof is wanting.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The May apple (<spn>Podophyllum peltatum</spn>). See <cref>May apple</cref> under <er>May</er>, and <er>Podophyllum</er>.</def> <mark>[U.S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mandrake root</ent><br/
<hw>mandrake root</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The root of the mandrake plant; used medicinally or as a narcotic; as a substance it is also called <altname>mandrake</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mandrel</ent><br/
<hw>Man"drel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mandrin</ets>, prob. through (assumed) LL. <ets>mamphurinum</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mamphur</ets> a bow drill.]</ety> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A bar of metal inserted in the work to shape it, or to hold it, as in a lathe, during the process of manufacture; an arbor.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The live spindle of a turning lathe; the revolving arbor of a circular saw. It is usually driven by a pulley.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>manderil</asp> and <asp>mandril</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mandrel lathe</b></col>, <cd>a lathe with a stout spindle, adapted esp. for chucking, as for forming hollow articles by turning or spinning.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mandril</ent><br/
<hw>mandril</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>any of various shafts that rotate or serve as axes for larger rotating parts.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>manderil</asp> and <asp>mandrel</asp>.]</altsp><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> spindle, mandrel, arbor.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mandrill</ent><br/
<hw>man"drill</hw> <pr>(m<acr/n"dr<icr/l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mandrille</ets>, Sp. <ets>mandril</ets>, It. <ets>mandrillo</ets>; prob. the native name in Africa.  Cf. <er>Drill</er> an ape.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A large West African baboon (<spn>Papio sphinx</spn> syn. <spn>Mandrillus sphinx</spn>, formerly <spn>Cynocephalus mormon</spn> syn. <spn>Papio mormon</spn>).  The adult male has, on the sides of the nose, large, naked, grooved swellings, conspicuously striped with blue and red.  It is an <isa>endangered species</isa>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manduca</ent><br/
<hw>Manduca</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of moths whose larvae are hornworms.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Manduca</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manducable</ent><br/
<hw>Man"du*ca*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>manducable</ets>. See <er>Manducate</er>.]</ety> <def>Such as can be chewed; fit to be eaten.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Any <qex>manducable</qex> creature.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. Herbert.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manducate</ent><br/
<hw>Man"du*cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Manducated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Manducating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>manducatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>manducare</ets> to chew. See <er>Manger</er>.]</ety> <def>To masticate; to chew; to eat.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Jer. Taylor.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manducation</ent><br/
<hw>Man`du*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>manducatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>manducation</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act of chewing.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Jer. Taylor.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manducatory</ent><br/
<hw>Man"du*ca*to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to, or employed in, chewing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manducus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Man*du"cus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. <ets>manducare</ets> to chew.]</ety> <fld>(Gr. & Rom. Antiq.)</fld> <def>A grotesque mask, representing a person chewing or grimacing, worn in processions and by comic actors on the stage.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mane</ent><br/
<hw>Mane</hw> <pr>(m<amac/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>manu</ets>; akin to OD. <ets>mane</ets>, D. <ets>maan</ets>, G. <ets>m<aum/hne</ets>, OHG. <ets>mana</ets>, Icel. <ets>m<oum/n</ets>, Dan. & Sw. <ets>man</ets>, AS. <ets>mene</ets> necklace, Icel. <ets>men</ets>, L. <ets>monile</ets>, Gr. <?/, <?/, Skr. <ets>many<amac/</ets> neck muscles. <root/275.]</ety> <def>The long and heavy hair growing on the upper side of, or about, the neck of some quadrupedal animals, as the horse, the lion, etc. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Horse</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maned sheep</ent><br/
<hw>maned sheep</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A type of wild sheep (<spn>Ammotragus lervia</spn>) of northern Africa; called also <altname>Barbary sheep</altname> and <altname>aoudad</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> aoudad, arui, audad, Barbary sheep, <spn>Ammotragus lervia</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maned wolf</ent><br/
<hw>maned wolf</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A reddish-gray wolf (<spn>Canis rufus</spn> or <spn>Canis niger</spn>) of Southwestern North America.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> red wolf, <spn>Canis rufus</spn>, <spn>Canis niger</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Man-eater</ent><br/
<hw>Man"-eat`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One who, or that which, has an appetite for human flesh; specifically, one of certain large sharks (esp. <spn>Carcharodon carcharias</spn> syn. <spn>Carcharodon Rondeleti</spn>); also, a lion or a tiger which has acquired the habit of feeding upon human flesh.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>man-eating shark</ent><br/
<hw>man-eating shark</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A term applied to sharks that attack humans, especially the great white shark (<spn>Carcharodon carcharias</spn>), a large aggressive shark widespread in warm seas.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> great white shark, white shark, man-eater, <spn>Carcharodon carcharias</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maned</ent><br/
<hw>Maned</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having a mane.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Maned seal</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the sea lion.</cd> -- <col><b>Maned sheep</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the aoudad.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manege</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*nege"</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>man<egrave/ge</ets>. See <er>Manage</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The art of horsemanship, or of training horses.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A school for teaching horsemanship, and for training horses.</def>  <rj><au>Chesterfield.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maneh</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma"neh</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Heb. <ets>m<amac/neh</ets>.]</ety> <def>A Hebrew weight for gold or silver, being one hundred shekels of gold and sixty shekels of silver.</def>  <rj><au>Ezek. xlv. 12.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maneless</ent><br/
<hw>Mane"less</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having no mane.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Maneless lion</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a variety of the lion having a short, inconspicuous mane.  It inhabits Arabia and adjacent countries.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manequin</ent><br/
<hw>Man"e*quin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Manikin</er>.]</ety> <def>An artist's model of wood or other material.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manerial</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*ne"ri*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>See <er>Manorial</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manes</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma"nes</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[L.]</ety> <fld>(Rom. Antiq.)</fld> <def>The benevolent spirits of the dead, especially of dead ancestors, regarded as family deities and protectors.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hail, O ye holy <qex>manes</qex>!</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manesheet</ent><br/
<hw>Mane"sheet`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A covering placed over the upper part of a horse's head.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manoeuvre</ent><br/
<ent>Maneuver</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Ma*neu"ver</hw>, <hw>Ma*noeu"vre</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>manoeuvre</ets>, OF. <ets>manuevre</ets>, LL. <ets>manopera</ets>, lit., hand work, manual labor; L. <ets>manus</ets> hand + <ets>opera</ets>, fr. <ets>opus</ets> work. See <er>Manual</er>, <er>Operate</er>, and cf. <er>Mainor</er>, <er>Manure</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Management; dexterous movement; specif., a military or naval evolution, movement, or change of position.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Management with address or artful design; adroit proceeding; stratagem.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manoeuvre</ent><br/
<ent>Maneuver</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Ma*neu"ver</hw>, <hw>Ma*noeu"vre</hw>, }</mhw> <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Maneuvered</conjf> <pr>(#)</pr> or <conjf>Manoeuvred</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Maneuvering</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, or <conjf>Manoeuvring</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>manoeuvrer</ets>. See <er>Maneuver</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To perform a movement or movements in military or naval tactics; to make changes in position with the intention of getting an advantage in attack or defense.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>To make changes in one's approach to solving a problem, so as to achieve maximum advantage in a changing situation; -- used especially in competitive situations, as in politics, diplomacy, or sports.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To manage with address or art; to scheme.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manoeuvre</ent><br/
<ent>Maneuver</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Ma*neu"ver</hw>, <hw>Ma*noeu"vre</hw>, }</mhw> <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To change the positions of, as of troops of ships.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manoeuvrer</ent><br/
<ent>Maneuverer</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Ma*neu"ver*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Ma*noeu"vrer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who maneuvers.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This charming widow Beaumont is a <qex>nanoeuvrer</qex>. We can't well make an English word of it.</q> <rj><qau>Miss Edgeworth.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>man Friday</ent><br/
<hw>man Friday</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[From <etsep>Friday</etsep>, the name of a character in the novel <booki>Robinson Crusoe</booki> (1719) by DeFoe.]</ety> <def>A person who contributes to the fulfillment of a need or furtherance of an effort or purpose; a devoted assistant.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> right-hand man, chief assistant.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manful</ent><br/
<hw>Man"ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Showing manliness, or manly spirit; hence, brave, courageous, resolute, noble.</def> <ldquo/ <xex>Manful</xex> hardiness.<rdquo/ <au>Chaucer.</au> -- <wordforms><wf>Man"ful*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Man"ful*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mangabey</ent><br/
<hw>Man"ga*bey</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[So called by <person>Buffon</person> from <etsep>Mangaby</etsep>, in Madagascar, where he erroneously supposed them be native.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of several African monkeys of the genus <gen>Cercocebus</gen>, as the sooty mangabey (<spn>Cercocebus fuliginosus</spn>), which is sooty black.</def> <altsp>[Also written <asp>mangaby</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mangan</ent><br/
<hw>Man"gan</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mangonel</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manganate</ent><br/
<hw>Man"ga*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>manganate</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of manganic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The manganates are usually green, and are well-known compounds, though derived from a hypothetical acid.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manganesate</ent><br/
<hw>Man`ga*ne"sate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A manganate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manganese</ent><br/
<hw>Man`ga*nese"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mangan<egrave/se</ets>, It. <ets>manganese</ets>, sasso <ets>magnesio</ets>; prob. corrupted from L. <ets>magnes</ets>, because of its resemblance to the magnet. See <er>Magnet</er>, and cf. <er>Magnesia</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>An element obtained by reduction of its oxide, as a hard, grayish white metal, fusible with difficulty (melting point 1244<deg/ C), but easily oxidized.  Its ores occur abundantly in nature as the minerals pyrolusite, manganite, etc.  Symbol <it>Mn.</it>  Atomic number 25; Atomic weight 54.938 [C=12.011].</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ An alloy of manganese with iron (called <xex>ferromanganese</xex>) is used to increase the density and hardness of steel.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Black oxide of manganese</b></col>, <col><b>Manganese dioxide</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Manganese peroxide</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Black manganese</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>a heavy black powder <chform>MnO2</chform>, occurring native as the mineral pyrolusite, and valuable as a strong oxidizer; -- called also familiarly <altname>manganese</altname>. It colors glass violet, and is used as a decolorizer to remove the green tint of impure glass.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manganese bronze</ent><br/
<hw>manganese bronze</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A brass alloy having from 1 to 4 percent of manganese added to harden it; made by adding manganese to the copper and zinc used in brass.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> high-strength brass.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manganese steel</ent><br/
<hw>Man`ga*nese" steel</hw>. <def>Cast steel containing a considerable percentage (10-14) of manganese, which makes it very hard and tough and highly resistant to wear. See <er>Alloy steel</er>, above.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manganesian</ent><br/
<hw>Man`ga*ne"sian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mangan<eacute/sien</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Manganic.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manganesic</ent><br/
<hw>Man`ga*ne"sic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mangan<eacute/sique</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Manganic.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manganesious</ent><br/
<hw>Man`ga*ne"sious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Manganous.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manganesium</ent><br/
<hw>Man`ga*ne"si*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL.]</ety> <def>Manganese.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manganesous</ent><br/
<hw>Man`ga*ne"sous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Manganous.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manganic</ent><br/
<hw>Man`gan"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>manganique</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to resembling, or containing, manganese; specif., designating compounds in which manganese has a higher valence as contrasted with <contr>manganous</contr> compounds.  Cf. <er>Manganous</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manganic acid</ent><br/
<hw>manganic acid</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A dibasic acid <chform>H2MnO4</chform>, formed from manganese, analogous to sulphuric acid; it is found only in solution and in manganate salts.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manganiferous</ent><br/
<hw>Man`ga*nif"er*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Manganese</ets> + <ets>-ferous</ets>.]</ety> <def>Containing manganese.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manganite</ent><br/
<hw>Man"ga*nite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>One of the oxides of manganese; -- called also <altname>gray manganese ore</altname>.  It occurs in brilliant steel-gray or iron-black crystals, also massive.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A compound of manganese dioxide with a metallic oxide; so called as though derived from the hypothetical <xex>manganous</xex> acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manganium</ent><br/
<hw>Man*ga"ni*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL.]</ety> <def>Manganese.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manganous</ent><br/
<hw>Man"ga*nous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, designating, those compounds of manganese in which the element has a lower valence as contrasted with <contr>manganic</contr> compounds; <as>as, <ex>manganous</ex> oxide</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Manganous acid</b></col>, <cd>a hypothetical compound analogous to sulphurous acid, and forming the so-called <xex>manganites</xex>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mangcorn</ent><br/
<hw>Mang"corn`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mengen</ets> to mix. See <er>Mingle</er>, and <er>Corn</er>.]</ety> <def>A mixture of wheat and rye, or other species of grain.</def> <mark>[Prov Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mange</ent><br/
<hw>Mange</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mangy</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Vet.)</fld> <def>The scab or itch in cattle, dogs, and other beasts.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mange insect</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one of several species of small parasitic mites, which burrow in the skin of cattle. horses, dogs, and other animals, causing the mange.  The mange insect of the horse (<spn>Psoroptes equi</spn> or <spn>Dermatodectes equi</spn>), and that of cattle (<spn>Symbiotes bovis</spn>  or <spn>Dermatophagys bovis</spn>) are the most important species.  See <er>Acarina</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mangel-wurzel</ent><br/
<hw>Man"gel-wur`zel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G., corrupted fr. <ets>mangoldwurzel</ets>; <ets>mangold</ets> beet  + <ets>wurzel</ets> root.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A kind of large field beet (<spn>Beta macrorhiza</spn>), used as food for cattle, -- by some considered a mere variety of the ordinary beet. See <er>Beet</er>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mangold-wurzel</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- Insert: Illustr. of Mangel-Wurzel --><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manger</ent><br/
<hw>man"ger</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mangeoire</ets>, fr. <ets>manger</ets> to eat, fr. L. <ets>manducare</ets>, fr. <ets>mandere</ets> to chew.  Cf. <er>Mandible</er>, <er>Manducate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A trough or open box in which fodder is placed for horses or cattle to eat.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And she brought forth her firstborn son, and wrapped him in swaddling clothes, and laid him in a <qex>manger</qex>; because there was no room for them in the inn.</q>  <rj><qau>Luke 2: 7</qau></rj><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The fore part of the deck, having a bulkhead athwart ships high enough to prevent water which enters the hawse holes from running over it.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mangey</ent><br/
<hw>mangey</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>Same as <er>mangy</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mangy, threadbare; worn-out, seedy, squalid.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mangifera</ent><br/
<hw>Mangifera</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def> genus of tropical trees native to Asia bearing fleshy fruit.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Mangifera</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mangily</ent><br/
<hw>man"gi*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a mangy manner; scabbily.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manginess</ent><br/
<hw>man"gi*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mangy</er>.]</ety> <def>The condition or quality of being mangy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mangle</ent><br/
<hw>Man"gle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mangled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mangling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[A frequentative fr. OE. <ets>manken</ets> to main, AS. <ets>mancian</ets>, in <ets>bemancian</ets> to mutilate, fr. L. <ets>mancus</ets> maimed; perh. akin to G. <ets>mangeln</ets> to be wanting.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cut or bruise with repeated blows or strokes, making a ragged or torn wound, or covering with wounds; to tear in cutting; to cut in a bungling manner; to lacerate; to mutilate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mangled</qex> with ghastly wounds through plate and mail.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To mutilate or injure, in making, doing, or performing; <as>as, to <ex>mangle</ex> a piece of music or a recitation</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>mangle</qex> a play or a novel.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mangle</ent><br/
<hw>man"gle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[D. <ets>mangel</ets>, fr. OE. <ets>mangonel</ets> a machine for throwing stones, LL. <ets>manganum</ets>, Gr. <?/ a machine for defending fortifications, axis of a pulley.  Cf. <er>Mangonel</er>.]</ety> <def>A machine for smoothing linen or cotton cloth, as sheets, tablecloths, napkins, and clothing, by roller pressure, often with heated rollers.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mangle rack</b></col> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>a contrivance for converting continuous circular motion into reciprocating rectilinear motion, by means of a rack and pinion, as in the mangle. The pinion is held to the rack by a groove in such a manner that it passes alternately from one side of the rack to the other, and thus gives motion to it in opposite directions, according to the side in which its teeth are engaged.</cd> -- <col><b>Mangle wheel</b></col>, <cd>a wheel in which the teeth, or pins, on its face, are interrupted on one side, and the pinion, working in them, passes from inside to outside of the teeth alternately, thus converting the continuous circular motion of the pinion into a reciprocating circular motion of the wheel.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 891 --></p>

<p><ent>Mangle</ent><br/
<hw>Man"gle</hw> <pr>(m<acr/<nsm/"g'l)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf. D. <ets>mangelen</ets>. See <er>Mangle</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To smooth with a mangle, as damp linen or cloth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mangler</ent><br/
<hw>Man"gler</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See 1st <er>Mangle</er>.]</ety> <def>One who mangles or tears in cutting; one who mutilates any work in doing it.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mangler</ent><br/
<hw>Man"gler</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See 3d <er>Mangle</er>.]</ety> <def>One who smooths with a mangle.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mango</ent><br/
<hw>Man"go</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mangoes</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Pg. <ets>manga</ets>, fr. Tamil <ets>m<amac/nk<amac/y</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The fruit of the mango tree. It is rather larger than an apple, and of an ovoid shape. Some varieties are fleshy and luscious, and others tough and tasting of turpentine. The green fruit is pickled for market.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A green muskmelon stuffed and pickled.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mango bird</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>an oriole (<spn>Oriolus kundoo</spn>), native of India.</cd> -- <col><b>Mango fish</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a fish of the Ganges (<spn>Polynemus risua</spn>), highly esteemed for food.  It has several long, slender filaments below the pectoral fins.  It appears about the same time with the mango fruit, in April and May, whence the name.</cd> -- <col><b>Mango tree</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>an .</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mango tree</ent><br/
<hw>mango tree</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>An East Indian tree of the genus <gen>Mangifera</gen> (<spn>Mangifera Indica</spn>), related to the cashew and the sumac.  It grows to a large size, and produces a large oval smooth-skinned fruit which is the <prod>mango</prod> of commerce.  It is now cultivated in tropical America.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mangoldwurzel</ent><br/
<hw>Man"gold*wur`zel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>See <er>Mangel-wurzel</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mangonel</ent><br/
<hw>Man"go*nel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>mangonel</ets>, LL. <ets>manganellus</ets>, <ets>manganum</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/ See <er>Mangle</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>A military engine formerly used for throwing stones and javelins.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mangonism</ent><br/
<hw>Man"go*nism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The art of mangonizing, or setting off to advantage.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mangonist</ent><br/
<hw>Man"go*nist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who mangonizes.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A slave dealer; also, a strumpet.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mangonize</ent><br/
<hw>Man"go*nize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mangonizare</ets>, fr. <ets>mango</ets> a dealer in slaves or wares, to which he tries to give an appearance of greater value by decking them out or furbishing them up.]</ety> <def>To furbish up for sale; to set off to advantage.</def> <mark>[Obs. or R.]</mark>  <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mangosteen tree</ent><br/
<ent>Mangostan</ent><br/
<ent>Mangosteen</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Man"go*steen</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Man"go*stan</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>mangosteen tree</hw> }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Malay <ets>mangusta</ets>, <ets>mangis</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A tree of the East Indies of the genus <gen>Garcinia</gen> (<spn>Garcinia Mangostana</spn>) with thick leathery leaves.  The tree grows to the height of eighteen feet, and bears fruit also called <prod>mangosteen</prod>, of the size of a small apple, the pulp of which is very delicious food.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mangrove</ent><br/
<hw>Man"grove</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Malay <ets>manggi-manggi</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The name of one or two trees of the genus <gen>Rhizophora</gen> (<spn>Rhizophora Mangle</spn>, and <spn>Rhizophora mucronata</spn>, the last doubtfully distinct) inhabiting muddy shores of tropical regions, where they spread by emitting aerial roots, which fasten in the saline mire and eventually become new stems. The seeds also send down a strong root while yet attached to the parent plant.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The fruit has a ruddy brown shell, and a delicate white pulp which is sweet and eatable.  The bark is astringent, and is used for tanning leather.  The black and the white mangrove (<spn>Avicennia nitida</spn> and <spn>Avicennia tomentosa</spn>) have much the same habit.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The mango fish.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mangrove family</ent><br/
<hw>mangrove family</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A natural family (<fam>Rhizophoraceae</fam>) of trees and shrubs that usually form dense jungles along tropical seacoasts.  It includes the mangrove <member><spn>Rhizophora Mangle</spn></member>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mangrove snapper</ent><br/
<hw>mangrove snapper</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A fish (<spn>Lutjanus griseus</spn>) found in shallow waters off the coast of Florida; called also <altname>gray snapper</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mangue</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mangue</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The kusimanse.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mangy</ent><br/
<hw>man"gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>mangier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>mangiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[F. <ets>mang<eacute/</ets>, p. p. of <ets>manger</ets> to eat. See <er>Manger</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Infected with the mange; scabby.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Shabby; worn-out; seedy; run-down; squalid; <as>as, a <ex>mangy</ex> old coat; a <ex>mangy</ex> tavern</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manhaden</ent><br/
<hw>Man*ha"den</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Menhaden</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manhandle</ent><br/
<hw>Man*han"dle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>  <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>-handled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>-handling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To move, or manage, by human force without mechanical aid; <as>as, to <ex>manhandle</ex> a cannon</as>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>To handle roughly; <as>as, the captive was <ex>manhandled</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manhattan Project</ent><br/
<hw>Manhattan Project</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(U. S. History)</fld> <def>A former US agency that was responsible for developing atomic bombs during World War II.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manhead</ent><br/
<hw>Man"head</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Manhood.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manhes process</ent><br/
<hw>Man`h<egrave/s" proc"ess</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Copper Metal.)</fld> <def>A process by which copper matte is treated by passing through it a blast of air, to oxidize and remove sulphur. It is analogous in apparatus to the Bessemer process for decarbonizing cast iron. So called from <person>Pierre <etsep>Manh<egrave/s</etsep></person>, a French metallurgist, who invented it.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manhole</ent><br/
<hw>Man"hole`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A hole through which a man may descend or creep into a drain, sewer, steam boiler, parts of machinery, etc., for cleaning or repairing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manhood</ent><br/
<hw>Man"hood</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Man-</ets> + <ets>-hood</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The state of being man as a human being, or man as distinguished from a child or a woman.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Manly quality; virility; courage; bravery; resolution.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am ashamed<br/
That thou hast power to shake my <qex>manhood</qex> thus.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The genitalia of a male human.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The condition of being a human being.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>man-hour</ent><br/
<ent>man hour</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>man hour</hw>, <hw>man-hour</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quantity of work which one person can perform in one hour; -- often an estimate made for the purpose of deciding whether to undertake a project, and sometimes used in accounting; <as>as, it will take a hundred <ex>man-hours</ex> to write the program</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manhunt</ent><br/
<hw>man"hunt`</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <pr>(m<acr/n"h<ucr/nt)</pr> <def>An organized search (by police) for a person (charged with a crime).</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mania</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"ni*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mania</ets>, Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ to rage; cf. OE. <ets>manie</ets>, F. <ets>manie</ets>.  Cf. <er>Mind</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, <ets>Necromancy</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Violent derangement of mind; madness; insanity.  Cf. <er>Delirium</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Excessive or unreasonable desire; insane passion affecting one or many people; <as>as, the tulip <ex>mania</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mania a potu</b></col> <ety>[L.]</ety>, <cd>madness from drinking; delirium tremens.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Insanity; derangement; madness; lunacy; alienation; aberration; delirium; frenzy. See <er>Insanity</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maniable</ent><br/
<hw>Man"i*a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>manier</ets> to manage, fr. L. <ets>manus</ets> hand.]</ety> <def>Manageable.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maniac</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"ni*ac</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>maniaque</ets>. See <er>Mania</er>.]</ety> <def>Raving with madness; raging with disordered intellect; affected with mania; mad.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maniac</ent><br/
<hw>ma"ni*ac</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A raving lunatic; a madman.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maniacal</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*ni"a*cal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Affected with, or characterized by, madness; maniac.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Ma*ni"a*cal*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manic</ent><br/
<hw>Man"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>maniko`s</grk> mad, frenzied.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Of or pert. to, or characterized by, mania, or excitement; frenzied; <as>as, with <ex>manic</ex> energy</as>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manicate</ent><br/
<hw>Man"i*cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>manicatus</ets> sleeved, fr. <ets>manica</ets> a sleeve.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Covered with hairs or pubescence so platted together and interwoven as to form a mass easily removed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manic-depressive</ent><br/
<hw>manic-depressive</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <def>A person suffering from <er>manic-depressive psychosis</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manic-depressive psychosis</ent><br/
<hw>manic-depressive psychosis</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <def>A mental disorder characterized by alternating episodes of mania and depression.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> bipolar disorder, manic depression, manic depressive illness.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manic disorder</ent><br/
<hw>manic disorder</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <def>An affective disorder in which the victim tends to respond excessively and sometimes violently.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mania.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manichee</ent><br/
<ent>Manichean</ent><br/
<ent>Manichaean</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Man`i*chae"an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Man`i*che"an</hw>, <hw>Man"i*chee</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>Manichaeus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>manich<eacute/en</ets>.]</ety> <def>A believer in the doctrines of <persfn>Manes</persfn>, a Persian of the third century A. D., who taught a dualism in which Light is regarded as the source of Good, and Darkness as the source of Evil.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>Manichaeans</qex> stand as representatives of dualism pushed to its utmost development.</q> <rj><qau>Tylor.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manichean</ent><br/
<ent>Manichaean</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Man`i*chae"an</hw>, <hw>Man`i*che"an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the Manichaeans.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manicheism</ent><br/
<ent>Manichaeism</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Man"i*chae*ism</hw>, <hw>Man"i*che*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>manich<eacute/isme</ets>.]</ety> <def>The doctrines taught, or system of principles maintained, by the Manichaeans.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manicheist</ent><br/
<hw>Man"i*che*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>manich<eacute/iste</ets>.]</ety> <def>Manichaean.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manichordon</ent><br/
<ent>Manichord</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Man"i*chord</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Man`i*chor"don</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <ety>[L. <ets>monochordon</ets>, Gr. <?/; -- so called because it orig. had only one string. See <er>Monochord</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>The clavichord or clarichord; -- called also <altname>dumb spinet</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maniclike</ent><br/
<hw>maniclike</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>Resembling the mania of manic-depressive illness.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> manic.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manicotti</ent><br/
<hw>manicotti</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Tubular large noodles that are usually stuffed with mild cheese and baked in tomato sauce; -- a type of Italian <isa>pasta</isa>; also a dish of such noodles thus prepared.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manicure</ent><br/
<hw>Man"i*cure</hw>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos>  <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Manicured</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Manicuring</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To care for (the hands and nails); to care for the hands and nails of; to do manicure work.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>to trim carefully and meticulously; <as>as, to <ex>manicure</ex> a lawn</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manicure</ent><br/
<hw>man"i*cure</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The care of the hands and nails, especially a thorough cosmetic treatment of the hands, especially the trimming and polishing of the fingernails, and removing of cuticles, performed by a manicurist.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manicure</ent><br/
<hw>man"i*cure</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>manus</ets> hand + <ets>curare</ets> to cure.]</ety> <def>A person who makes a business of taking care of people's hands, especially their nails; -- an older term for a <altname>manicurist</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Men] who had taken good care of their hands by wearing gloves and availing themselves of the services of a <qex>manicure</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Pop. Sci. Monthly.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manicurist</ent><br/
<hw>man"i*cur`ist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>manus</ets> hand + <ets>curare</ets> to cure.]</ety> <def>A person who makes a business of taking care of people's hands, especially their fingernails; -- formerly called a <altname>manicure</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manid</ent><br/
<hw>ma"nid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any species of the genus <gen>Manis</gen>, or family <fam>Manidae</fam>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manie</ent><br/
<hw>ma`nie"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. See <er>Mania</er>.]</ety> <def>Mania; insanity.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manifest</ent><br/
<hw>Man"i*fest</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>manifeste</ets>, L. <ets>manifestus</ets>, lit., struck by the hand, hence, palpable; <ets>manus</ets> hand +  <ets>fendere</ets> (in comp.) to strike. See <er>Manual</er>, and <er>Defend</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Evident to the senses, esp. to the sight; apparent; distinctly perceived; hence, obvious to the understanding; apparent to the mind; easily apprehensible; plain; not obscure or hidden.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Neither is there any creature that is not <qex>manifest</qex> in his sight.</q> <rj><qau> Heb. iv. 13.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That which may be known of God is <qex>manifest</qex> in them.</q> <rj><qau>Rom. i. 19.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus <qex>manifest</qex> to sight the god appeared.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Detected; convicted; -- with <ptcl>of</ptcl>.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Calistho there stood <qex>manifest</qex> of shame.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Open; clear; apparent; evident; visible; conspicuous; plain; obvious.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Manifest</er>, <er>Clear</er>, <er>Plain</er>, <er>Obvious</er>, <er>Evident</er>. What is <xex>clear</xex> can be seen readily; what is <xex>obvious</xex> lies directly in our way, and necessarily arrests our attention; what is <xex>evident</xex> is seen so clearly as to remove doubt; what is <ex>manifest</ex> is very distinctly evident.</usage><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So <qex>clear</qex>, so shining, and so <qex>evident</qex>,<br/
That it will glimmer through a blind man's eye.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Entertained with solitude,<br/
Where <qex>obvious</qex> duty erewhile appeared unsought.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I saw, I saw him <qex>manifest</qex> in view,<br/
His voice, his figure, and his gesture knew.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manifest</ent><br/
<hw>Man"i*fest</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Manifests</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>manifeste</ets>. See <er>Manifest</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and cf. <er>Manifesto</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A public declaration; an open statement; a manifesto. See <er>Manifesto</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A list or invoice of a ship's cargo, containing a description by marks, numbers, etc., of each package of goods, to be exhibited at the customhouse; <as>as, to inspect the ship's <ex>manifest</ex></as>.</def>  <rj><au>Bouvier.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manifest</ent><br/
<hw>Man"i*fest</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Manifested</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Manifesting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To show plainly; to make to appear distinctly, -- usually to the mind; to put beyond question or doubt; to display; to exhibit.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is nothing hid which shall not be <qex>manifested</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Mark iv. 22.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy life did <qex>manifest</qex> thou lovedst me not.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To exhibit the manifests or prepared invoices of; to declare at the customhouse.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To reveal; declare; evince; make known; disclose; discover; display.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manifestable</ent><br/
<hw>Man"i*fest`a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Such as can be manifested.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manifestation</ent><br/
<hw>Man`i*fes*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>manifestatio</ets>: cf. F.  <ets>manifestation</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of manifesting or disclosing, or the state of being manifested; discovery to the eye or to the understanding.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which manifests; a phenomenon which gives evidence of something hidden; exhibition; display; revelation; <as>as, the <ex>manifestation</ex> of God's power in creation</as>; the delayed <ex>manifestation</ex> of a disease.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>The secret manner in which acts of mercy ought to be performed, requires this public <qex>manifestation</qex> of them at the great day.</q> <rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The materialization or apparition of a spirit; -- a phenomenon claimed to be seen by spiritualists.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manifest destiny</ent><br/
<hw>manifest destiny</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A policy of imperialism rationalized as inevitable (as if granted by God).</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manifestible</ent><br/
<hw>Man"i*fest`i*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Manifestable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manifestly</ent><br/
<hw>Man"i*fest*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a manifest manner; obviously; evidently; clearly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manifestness</ent><br/
<hw>Man"i*fest*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being manifest; obviousness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manifesto</ent><br/
<hw>Man`i*fes"to</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Manifestoes</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[It. <ets>manifesto</ets>. See <er>Manifest</er>, <pos>n. & a.</pos>]</ety> <def>A public declaration, usually of a prince, sovereign, or other person claiming large powers, showing his intentions, or proclaiming his opinions and motives in reference to some act done or contemplated by him; <as>as, a <ex>manifesto</ex> declaring the purpose of a prince to begin war, and explaining his motives</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Bouvier.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>it was proposed to draw up a <qex>manifesto</qex>, setting forth the grounds and motives of our taking arms.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Frederick, in a public <qex>manifesto</qex>, appealed to the Empire against the insolent pretensions of the pope.</q> <rj><qau>Milman.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manifold</ent><br/
<hw>Man"i*fold</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>manigfeald</ets>. See <er>Many</er>, and <er>Fold</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Various in kind or quality; many in number; numerous; multiplied; complicated.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O Lord, how <qex>manifold</qex> are thy works!</q> <rj><qau>Ps. civ. 24.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I know your <qex>manifold</qex> transgressions.</q> <rj><qau>Amos v. 12.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Exhibited at divers times or in various ways; -- used to qualify nouns in the singular number.</def> <ldquo/The <xex>manifold</xex> wisdom of God.<rdquo/ <au>Eph. iii. 10.</au> <ldquo/The <xex>manifold</xex> grace of God.<rdquo/ <au>1 Pet. iv. 10.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Manifold writing</b></col>, <cd>a process or method by which several copies, as of a letter, are simultaneously made, sheets of coloring paper being infolded with thin sheets of plain paper upon which the marks made by a stylus or a type-writer are transferred; writing several copies of a document at once by use of carbon paper or the like.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manifold</ent><br/
<hw>Man"i*fold</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A copy of a writing made by the manifold process.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>A cylindrical pipe fitting, having a number of lateral outlets, for connecting one pipe with several others; <as>as, the exhaust <ex>manifold</ex> of an automobile engine</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>The third stomach of a ruminant animal.</def> <mark>[Local, U.S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manifold</ent><br/
<hw>Man"i*fold</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Manifolded</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Manifolding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To take copies of by the process of manifold writing; <as>as, to <ex>manifold</ex> a letter</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manifolded</ent><br/
<hw>Man"i*fold`ed</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having many folds, layers, or plates; <as>as, a <ex>manifolded</ex> shield</as>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manifoldly</ent><br/
<hw>Man"i*fold`ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a manifold manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manifoldness</ent><br/
<hw>Man"i*fold`ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Multiplicity.</def>  <rj><au>Sherwood.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>A generalized concept of magnitude.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maniform</ent><br/
<hw>Man"i*form</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>manus</ets> hand + <ets>-form</ets>.]</ety> <def>Shaped like the hand.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maniglion</ent><br/
<hw>ma*ni"glion</hw> <pr>(m<adot/*n<icr/l"y<ucr/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It. <ets>maniglio</ets>, <ets>maniglia</ets>, bracelet, handle.  Cf. <er>Manilio</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Gun.)</fld> <def>Either one of two handles on the back of a piece of ordnance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manihot</ent><br/
<ent>Manihoc</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Man"i*hoc</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Man"i*hot</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Manioc</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manikin</ent><br/
<hw>Man"i*kin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>mannikin</asp>.]</altsp> <ety>[OD. <ets>manneken</ets>, dim. of <ets>man</ets> man. See <er>Man</er>, and <er>-kin</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A little man; a dwarf; a pygmy; a manakin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A model of the human body, made of papier-mache or other material, commonly in detachable pieces, for exhibiting the different parts and organs, their relative position, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A mannequin.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manilla</ent><br/
<ent>Manila</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Ma*nil"a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Ma*nil"la</hw>  }</mhw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to Manila or Manilla, the capital of the Philippine Islands; made in, or exported from, that city.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def><cref>Manila paper</cref> or the color of <cref>manila paper</cref>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Manila cheroot</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Manila cigar</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a cheroot or cigar made of tobacco grown in the Philippine Islands.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manila bay</ent><br/
<hw>manila bay</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The name of a naval battle in the Spanish-American War (1898), in which the American fleet under <person>Admiral Dewey</person> defeated the Spanish fleet off the shore of Manila in the Phillipines.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manila bean</ent><br/
<hw>manila bean</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A tuberous-rooted twining annual vine (<spn>Psophocarpus tetragonolobus</spn>) bearing clusters of purplish flowers and pods with four jagged wings; Old World tropics.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> winged bean, winged pea, goa bean, goa bean vine, <spn>Psophocarpus tetragonolobus</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manila grass</ent><br/
<hw>manila grass</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A lawn grass (<spn>Zoysia matrella</spn>) common in the Philippines; grown also in US.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Japanese carpet grass.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manila hemp</ent><br/
<hw>Manila hemp</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A fibrous material obtained from the abaca plant (<spn>Musa textilis</spn>), a plant allied to the banana, growing in the Philippine and other East India islands; -- called also by the native name <altname>abaca</altname>. From it matting, canvas, ropes, and cables are made.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Manilla hemp, abaca.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A Philippine plant (<spn>Musa textilis</spn>) having leafstalks that yield Manila hemp used for rope and paper etc.; called also the <altname>abaca</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manila maguey</ent><br/
<hw>manila maguey</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A hard fiber used in making coarse twine; from Philippine agave plants.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> cantala, Cebu maguey.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manila paper</ent><br/
<hw>manila paper</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A durable brown or buff paper or thin cardboard with a smooth light brown finish, made of Manila hemp, and used as a wrapping paper, or as a cheap printing and writing paper. The name is also given to inferior papers, made of other fiber.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> manila, manila paper, manilla, manilla paper.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manila tamarind</ent><br/
<hw>manila tamarind</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A common thorny tropical American tree (<spn>Pithecellobium dulce</spn>) having terminal racemes of yellow flowers followed by sickle-shaped or circinate edible pods and yielding good timber and a yellow dye and mucilaginous gum.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> camachile, huamachil, wild tamarind, <spn>Pithecellobium dulce</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manilio</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*nil"io</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Manilla</er>, 1.</def>  <rj><au>Sir T. Herbert.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manilla paper</ent><br/
<ent>manilla hemp</ent><br/
<ent>manilla</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>manilla</hw>, <hw>manilla hemp</hw>, <hw>manilla paper</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>manila</er>, <er>manila hemp</er>, <er>manila paper</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manilkara</ent><br/
<hw>Manilkara</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of large evergreen trees with milky latex; pantropical.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Manilkara</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manilla</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*nil"la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>manilla</ets>; cf. It. <ets>maniglio</ets>, <ets>maniglia</ets>; F.  <ets>manille</ets>; Pg. <ets>manilha</ets>; all fr. L. <ets>manus</ets> hand, and formed after the analogy of L. <ets>monile</ets>, pl. <ets>monilia</ets>, necklace: cf. F. <ets>manille</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A ring worn upon the arm or leg as an ornament, especially among the tribes of Africa.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A piece of copper of the shape of a horseshoe, used as money by certain tribes of the west coast of Africa.</def>  <rj><au>Simmonds.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manilla</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*nil"la</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Manila</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manille</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*nille"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>See 1st <er>Manilla</er>, 1.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>man in the street</ent><br/
<hw>man in the street</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>An average person; <as>as, the views of the <ex>man in the street</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manioc</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"ni*oc</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pg. <ets>mandioca</ets>, fr. Braz.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The tropical plants (<spn>Manihot utilissima</spn>, and <spn>Manihot Aipi</spn>), from which cassava and tapioca are prepared; also, cassava.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mandioc</asp>, <asp>manihoc</asp>, <asp>manihot</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maniple</ent><br/
<hw>Man"i*ple</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>manipulus</ets>, <ets>maniplus</ets>, a handful, a certain number of soldiers; <ets>manus</ets> hand + root of <ets>plere</ets> to fill, <ets>plenus</ets> full: cf. F. <ets>maniple</ets>. See <er>Manual</er>, and <er>Full</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A handful.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A division of the Roman army numbering sixty men exclusive of officers; any small body of soldiers; a company.</def>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Originally, a napkin; later, an ornamental band or scarf worn upon the left arm as a part of the vestments of a priest in the Roman Catholic Church. It is sometimes worn in the English Church service.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manipular</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*nip"u*lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>manipularis</ets>: cf. F. <ets>manipulaire</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the maniple, or company.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Manipulatory; <as>as, <ex>manipular</ex> operations</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manipulate</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*nip"u*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Manipulated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Manipulating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[LL. <ets>manipulatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>manipulare</ets> to lead by the hand, fr. L. <ets>manipulus</ets>. See <er>Maniple</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To treat, work, or operate with the hands, especially when knowledge and dexterity are required; to manage in hand work; to handle; <as>as, to <ex>manipulate</ex> scientific apparatus</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To control the action of, by management; <as>as, to <ex>manipulate</ex> a convention of delegates;</as> also, to manage artfully or fraudulently; <as>as, to <ex>manipulate</ex> accounts, or election returns; to <ex>manipulate</ex> the stock market</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manipulate</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*nip"u*late</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To use the hands in dexterous operations; to do hand work;</def> <specif>specifically,</specif> <def>to manage the apparatus or instruments used in scientific work, or in artistic or mechanical processes; also, specifically, to use the hand in mesmeric operations.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manipulation</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*nip`u*la"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>manipulation</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or process of manipulating, or the state of being manipulated; the act of handling work by hand; use of the hands, in an artistic or skillful manner, in science or art.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Manipulation</qex> is to the chemist like the external senses to the mind.</q>  <rj><au>Whewell.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The use of the hands in mesmeric operations.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Artful management; <as>as, the <ex>manipulation</ex> of political bodies</as>; sometimes, a management or treatment for purposes of deception or fraud.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manipulative</ent><br/
<hw>ma*nip"u*la*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to manipulation; performed by manipulation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Prone to attempt to influence others by devious or subtle psychological means, in order to induce them to do what one wants.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manipulative</ent><br/
<hw>ma*nip"u*la*tive</hw> <pr>(m<adot/*n<icr/p"<usl/*l<adot/*t<icr/v)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Education)</fld> <def>Any object given to children to encourage them to learn by manipulating physical objects; applied especially to solid objects of varying geometrical shape that can be fit together to form larger aggregates.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manipulator</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*nip"u*la`tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who manipulates, sometimes in an underhanded or fraudulent manner; <as>as, a stock market <ex>manipulator</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 892 --></p>

<p><ent>Manipulatory</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*nip"u*la*to*ry</hw> <pr>(m<adot/*n<icr/p"<usl/*l<adot/*t<osl/*r<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to manipulation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma"nis</hw> <pr>(m<amac/"n<icr/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. L. <ets>manes</ets> the ghosts or shades of the dead. So called from its dismal appearance, and because it seeks for its food by night.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of edentates, covered with large, hard, triangular scales, with sharp edges that overlap each other like tiles on a roof.  They inhabit the warmest parts of Asia and Africa, and feed on ants. Called also <altname>Scaly anteater</altname>. See <er>Pangolin</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manitu</ent><br/
<ent>Manitou</ent><br/
<ent>Manito</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Man"i*to</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Man"i*tou</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Man"i*tu</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A name given by tribes of American Indians to a great spirit, whether good or evil, or to any object of worship.</def>  <rj><au>Tylor.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Gitche <qex>Manito</qex> the mighty,<br/
The Great Spirit, the creator,<br/
Smiled upon his helpless children!</q> <rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mitche <qex>Manito</qex> the mighty,<br/
He the dreadful Spirit of Evil,<br/
As a serpent was depicted.</q> <rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manitrunk</ent><br/
<hw>Man"i*trunk</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>manus</ets> hand + E. <ets>trunk</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The anterior segment of the thorax in insects. See <er>Insect</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>man jack</ent><br/
<hw>man jack</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A single individual person; <as>as, every <ex>man jack</ex> of them</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mankind</ent><br/
<hw>man`kind"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>mancynn</ets>. See <er>Kin</er> kindred, <er>Kind</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The human race; man, taken collectively.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The proper study of <qex>mankind</qex> is man.</q> <rj><qau>Pore.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Men, as distinguished from women; the male portion of human race.</def>  <rj><au>Lev. xviii. 22.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Human feelings; humanity.</def> <mark>[Obs]</mark>  <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mankind</ent><br/
<hw>Man"kind`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Manlike; not womanly; masculine; bold; cruel.</def> <mark>[Obs]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Are women grown so <qex>mankind</qex>? Must they be wooing?</q> <rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Be not too <qex>mankind</qex> against your wife.</q> <rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manks</ent><br/
<hw>Manks</hw> <pr>(m<acr/<nsm/ks)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the language or people of the Isle of Man.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>The language spoken in the Isle of Man. See <er>Manx</er>.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manless</ent><br/
<hw>Man"less</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Destitute of men.</def>  <rj><au>Bakon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Unmanly; inhuman.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chapman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manlessly</ent><br/
<hw>Man"less*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Inhumanly.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manlike</ent><br/
<hw>Man"like`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Man</ets> + <ets>like.</ets> Cf. <er>Manly</er>.]</ety> <def>Like man, or like a man, in form or nature; having the qualities of a man, esp. the nobler qualities; manly.</def> <ldquo/ Gentle, <xex>manlike</xex> speech.<rdquo/ <au>Testament of Love.</au> <ldquo/ A right <xex>manlike</xex> man.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Sir P. Sidney.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In glaring Chloe's <qex>manlike</qex> taste and mien.</q> <rj><qau>Shenstone.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manliness</ent><br/
<hw>Man"li*ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being manly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manling</ent><br/
<hw>Man"ling</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A little man.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au> B. Jonson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manly</ent><br/
<hw>Man"ly</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Manlier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Manliest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[<ets>Man</ets> + <ets>-ly</ets>.  Cf. <er>Manlike</er>.]</ety> <def>Having qualities becoming to a man; not childish or womanish; manlike, esp. brave, courageous, resolute, noble.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let's briefly put on <qex>manly</qex> readiness.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Serene and <qex>manly</qex>, hardened to sustain<br/
The load of life.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Bold; daring; brave; courageous; firm; undaunted; hardy; dignified; stately.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manly</ent><br/
<hw>Man"ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a manly manner; with the courage and fortitude of a manly man; <as>as, to act <ex>manly</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>man-made</ent><br/
<hw>man-made</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>Not of natural origin; prepared or made by humans; artificial; of substances, made by chemical reaction rather than extracted from a natural source; <as>as, <ex>man-made</ex> fibers; <ex>man-made</ex> gems</as>.  Opposed to <ant>natural</ant>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> semisynthetic, synthetic.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>man-made fiber</ent><br/
<hw>man-made fiber</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A fiber created from natural materials or by chemical processes.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> synthetic fiber.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manna</ent><br/
<hw>Man"na</hw> <pr>(m<acr/n"n<adot/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <grk>ma`nna</grk>, Heb. <ets>m<amac/n</ets>; cf. Ar. <ets>mann</ets>, properly, gift (of heaven).]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Script.)</fld> <def>The food supplied to the Israelites in their journey through the wilderness of Arabia; hence, divinely supplied food.</def>  <rj><au>Ex. xvi. 15.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A name given to lichens of the genus <gen>Lecanora</gen>, sometimes blown into heaps in the deserts of Arabia and Africa, and gathered and used as food; called also <altname>manna lichen</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Bot. & Med.)</fld> <def>A sweetish exudation in the form of pale yellow friable flakes, coming from several trees and shrubs and used in medicine as a gentle laxative, as the secretion of <spn>Fraxinus Ornus</spn>, and <spn>Fraxinus rotundifolia</spn>, the manna ashes of Southern Europe.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <stype>Persian manna</stype> is the secretion of the camel's thorn (see <cref>Camel's thorn</cref>, under <er>Camel</er>); <stype>Tamarisk manna</stype>, that of the <spn>Tamarisk mannifera</spn>, a shrub of Western Asia; <stype>Australian, manna</stype>, that of certain species of eucalyptus; <stype>Brian<cced/on manna</stype>, that of the European larch.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Manna insect</b></col> <fld>(Zool)</fld>, <cd>a scale insect (<spn>Gossyparia mannipara</spn>), which causes the exudation of manna from the Tamarix tree in Arabia.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manna ash</ent><br/
<hw>manna ash</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <def>A South Mediterranean ash (<spn>Fraxinus ornus</spn>) having fragrant white flowers in dense panicles and yielding manna.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> flowering ash, <spn>Fraxinus ornus</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manna croup</ent><br/
<hw>Man"na croup`</hw> <pr>(m<acr/n"n<adot/ kr<oomac/p`)</pr>. <ety>[<ets>Manna</ets> + Russ. & Pol. <ets>krupa</ets> groats, grits.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The portions of hard wheat kernels not ground into flour by the millstones: a kind of semolina prepared in Russia and used for puddings, soups, etc. -- called also <altname>manna groats</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The husked grains of manna grass.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manna grass</ent><br/
<hw>manna grass</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <def>Any of several tall slender grasses of the genus <gen>Glyceria</gen>.  They have long loose panicles, have a sweet flavor or odor, and grow in moist places.  <stype>Nerved manna grass</stype> is <spn>Glyceria nervata</spn>, and <stype>Floating manna grass</stype> is <spn>Glyceria fluitans</spn>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manna gum</ent><br/
<hw>manna gum</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <def>A tall tree (<spn>Eucalyptus viminalis</spn>) yielding a false manna.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manna lichen</ent><br/
<hw>manna lichen</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Any of several Old World semicrustaceous or shrubby lecanoras that roll up and are blown about over African and Arabian deserts and used as food by people and animals; same as <er>manna</er>{2}.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manned</ent><br/
<hw>manned</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having a crew; -- of vehicles; <as>as, a <ex>manned</ex> earth satellite was considered a necessary research step; to minimize casualties, the military used cruise missiles rather than <ex>manned</ex> aircraft for the bombardment</as>.  Opposite of <ant>unmanned</ant>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mannequin</ent><br/
<hw>mannequin</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>a woman who wears clothes to display fashions; a fashion model.</def> <wns>[wns=1]</wns><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> fashion model, model.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A three-dimensional model of a person, used to display clothes, especially in retail stores and in window displays; a dummy.</def> <wns>[wns=2]</wns><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> manikin, mannikin, manakin.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A model of a human form used by tailors to help make clothing of the proper shape.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manner</ent><br/
<hw>Man"ner</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>manere</ets>, F. <ets>mani<egrave/re</ets>, from OF. <ets>manier</ets>, adj., manual, skillful, handy, fr. (assumed) LL. <ets>manarius</ets>, for L. <ets>manuarius</ets> belonging to the hand, fr. <ets>manus</ets> the hand. See <er>Manual</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Mode of action; way of performing or effecting anything; method; style; form; fashion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The nations which thou hast removed, and placed in the cities of Samaria, know not the <qex>manner</qex> of the God of the land.</q> <rj><qau>2 Kings xvii. 26.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The temptations of prosperity insinuate themselves after a gentle, but very powerful, <qex>manner</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Characteristic mode of acting, conducting, carrying one's self, or the like; bearing; habitual style.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Customary method of acting; habit.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Paul, as his <qex>manner</qex> was, went in unto them.</q> <rj><qau>Acts xvii. 2.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Air and <qex>manner</qex> are more expressive than words.</q> <rj><qau>Richardson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Carriage; behavior; deportment; also, becoming behavior; well-bred carriage and address; <as>as, mind your <ex>manners</ex>!</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Good <qex>manners</qex> are made up of petty sacrifices.</q> <rj><qau>Emerson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>The style of writing or thought of an author; characteristic peculiarity of an artist.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Certain degree or measure; <as>as, it is in a <ex>manner</ex> done already</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The bread is in <qex>a manner</qex> common.</q> <rj><qau>1 Sam. xxi.5.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Sort; kind; style; -- in this application sometimes having the sense of a plural, sorts or kinds; <as>as, all <ex>manners</ex> of people came to the rally</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>And they being afraid wondered, saying to one another, What <qex>manner</qex> of man is this! for he commandeth even the winds and the water, and they obey him.</q> <rj><qau>Luke 8: 25.</qau></rj></p>

<p><q>Ye tithe mint, and rue, and all <qex>manner</qex> of herbs.</q> <rj><qau>Luke xi. 42.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I bid thee say,<br/
What <qex>manner</qex> of man art thou?</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ In old usage, <ptcl>of</ptcl> was often omitted after <xex>manner</xex>, when employed in this sense. <ldquo/A <xex>manner</xex> Latin corrupt was her speech.<rdquo/</note>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>By any manner of means</b></col>, <cd>in any way possible; by any sort of means.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>To be taken in the manner</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To be taken with the manner</b></col></mcol>. <ety>[A corruption of <ets>to be taken in the mainor</ets>. See <er>Mainor</er>.]</ety> <cd>To be taken in the very act.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <see>See <er>Mainor</er>.</see> -- <col><b>To make one's manners</b></col>, <cd>to make a bow or courtesy; to offer salutation.</cd> -- <col><b>Manners bit</b></col>, <cd>a portion left in a dish for the sake of good manners.</cd> <au>Hallwell.</au></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Method; mode; custom; habit; fashion; air; look; mien; aspect; appearance. See <er>Method</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maennerchor</ent><br/
<ent>Mannerchor</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>M<aum/n"ner*chor`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>G. pl.</it> <plw>M<aum/nnerch<oum/re</plw> <pr>(#)</pr></plu>. <ety>[G.; <ets>m<aum/nner</ets>, pl. of <ets>mann</ets> man + <ets>chor</ets> chorus.]</ety> <def>A German men's chorus or singing club.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mannered</ent><br/
<hw>Man"nered</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having a certain way, esp. a polite way, of carrying and conducting one's self; <as>as, a well-<ex>mannered</ex> child</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Give her princely training, that she may be<br/
<qex>Mannered</qex> as she is born.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Affected with mannerism; marked by excess of some characteristic peculiarity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His style is in some degree <qex>mannered</qex> and confined.</q> <rj><qau>Hazlitt.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mannerism</ent><br/
<hw>Man"ner*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mani<eacute/risme</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Adherence to a peculiar style or manner; a characteristic mode of action, bearing, behavior, or treatment of others.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Adherence to a peculiar style or manner carried to excess, especially in literature or art.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mannerism</qex> is pardonable,and is sometimes even agreeable, when the manner, though vicious, is natural . . . . But a <qex>mannerism</qex> which does not sit easy on the mannerist, which has been adopted on principle, and which can be sustained only by constant effort, is always offensive.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mannerist</ent><br/
<hw>Man"ner*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mani<eacute/riste</ets>.]</ety> <def>One addicted to mannerism; a person who, in action, bearing, or treatment, carries characteristic peculiarities to excess. See citation under <er>Mannerism</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mannerliness</ent><br/
<hw>Man"ner*li*ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being mannerly; civility; complaisance.</def>  <rj><au>Sir M. Hale.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mannerly</ent><br/
<hw>Man"ner*ly</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Showing good manners; civil; respectful; complaisant.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What thou thinkest meet, and is most <qex>mannerly</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mannerly</ent><br/
<hw>Man"ner*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>With good manners.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manner name</ent><br/
<hw>manner name</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(linguistics)</fld> <def>A word that denotes a manner of doing something; a troponym; as, "march" is a <ex>manner name</ex> for "walk".</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manner of speaking</ent><br/
<hw>manner of speaking</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The characteristic style or manner that a person uses to express himself orally.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> delivery.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mannheim gold</ent><br/
<hw>Mann"heim gold"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[From <ets>Mannheim</ets> in Germany, where much of it was made.]</ety> <def>A kind of brass made in imitation of gold.  It contains eighty per cent of copper and twenty of zinc.</def>  <rj><au>Ure.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mannide</ent><br/
<hw>Man"nide</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mann</ets>ite + anhydr<ets>ide</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A white amorphous or crystalline substance, obtained by dehydration of mannite, and distinct from, but convertible into, mannitan.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mannish</ent><br/
<hw>Man"nish</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Man</ets> + <ets>-ish</ets>: cf. AS. <ets>mennisc</ets>, <ets>menisc</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Resembling a human being in form or nature; human.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But yet it was a figure<br/
Most like to <qex>mannish</qex> creature.</q> <rj><qau>Gower.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Resembling, suitable to, or characteristic of, a man, manlike, masculine.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A woman impudent and <qex>mannish</qex> grown.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Fond of men; -- said of a woman.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Man"nish*ly</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>,<pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Man"nish*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mannitan</ent><br/
<hw>Man"ni*tan</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mannite</ets> + <ets>an</ets>hydrite.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A white amorphous or crystalline substance obtained by the partial dehydration of mannite.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mannitate</ent><br/
<hw>Man"ni*tate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of mannitic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mannite</ent><br/
<hw>Man"nite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Same as <er>mannitol</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A sweet white efflorescence from dried fronds of kelp, especially from those of the <spn>Laminaria saccharina</spn>, or devil's apron.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mannitic</ent><br/
<hw>Man*nit"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, resembling, or derived from, mannitol.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mannitic acid</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>a white amorphous substance, intermediate between saccharic acid and mannitol, and obtained by the partial oxidation of the latter.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mannitol</ent><br/
<hw>man"ni*tol</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mannite</ets> + <ets>-ol</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A white crystalline hexose (<chform>HO.CH2.(CHOH)4.CH2.OH</chform>) of a sweet taste obtained from a so-called <xex>manna</xex>, the dried sap of the flowering ash (<prodby><spn>Fraxinus ornus</spn></prodby>); -- called also <altname>mannite</altname>, and <altname>hydroxy hexane</altname>.  Cf. <er>Dulcite</er>.  It is used in pharmacy as excipient and diluent for solids and liquids.  It is also used as a food additive for anti-caking properties, or as a sweetener, and, illegally, to "cut" (dilute) illegal drugs such as cocaine or heroin.</def>
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> D-mannitol; manna sugar; cordycepic acid; Diosmol; Mannicol; Mannidex; Osmiktrol; Osmosal.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mannitose</ent><br/
<hw>Man"ni*tose`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A variety of sugar obtained by the partial oxidation of mannite, and closely resembling levulose.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mano</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma"no</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp., lit., hand.]</ety> <def>The muller, or crushing and grinding stone, used in grinding corn on a metate.</def> <mark>[Mexico & Local U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manoeuvre</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*noeu"vre</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. & v.</pos> <def>See <er>Maneuver</er>.</def> <mark>[Chiefly Brit.]</mark> <br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>man of action</ent><br/
<hw>man of action</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A person who prefers to act rather than contemplate and gets things accomplished quickly an efficiently.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> man of deeds.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>man of affairs</ent><br/
<hw>man of affairs</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A person engaged in commercial or industrial business (especially an owner or executive).</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> businessman.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>man of deeds</ent><br/
<hw>man of deeds</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>man of action</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>man of letters</ent><br/
<hw>man of letters</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A writer, especially one who writes for a living.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A learned person; a scholar.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>man of means</ent><br/
<hw>man of means</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A wealthy person.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> rich man, wealthy man.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>man of science</ent><br/
<hw>man of science</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A scientist.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>man-of-the-earth</ent><br/
<hw>man-of-the-earth</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A long-rooted morning glory (<spn>Ipomoea leptophylla</spn>) of Western U. S.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> man of the earth, <spn>Ipomoea leptophylla</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A tropical American prostrate or climbing herbaceous perennial (<spn>Ipomoea panurata</spn> or <spn>Ipomoea fastigiata</spn>) having an enormous starchy root; sometimes held to be source of the sweet potato.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> wild potato vine, wild sweet potato vine, man of the earth, manroot, scammonyroot, <spn>Ipomoea panurata</spn>, <spn>Ipomoea fastigiata</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>man of the world</ent><br/
<hw>man of the world</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A worldly-wise person; a sophisticate.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Man-of-war</ent><br/
<hw>Man`-of-war"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Men-of-war</plw>.</plu> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A government vessel employed for the purposes of war, esp. one of large size; a ship of war.</def> <wns>[wns=1]</wns><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> ship of the line.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The <cref>Portuguese man-of-war</cref>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> , jellyfish.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Man-of-war hawk</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the frigate bird.</cd> -- <col><b>Man-of-war's man</b></col>, <cd>a sailor serving in a ship of war.</cd> -- <col><b>Portuguese man-of-war</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any species of the genus <gen>Physalia</gen>; it is a hydrozoan having both medusa and polyp stages present in a single colony.  It floats on the surface of the sea by a buoyant bladderlike structure, from which dangle multiple long tentacles with stinging cells.  Its can cause severe rashes when it comes in contact with humans swimming in the area.  See <er>Physalia</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>man-of-war bird</ent><br/
<hw>man-of-war bird</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <def>The frigate bird, a long-billed warm-water seabird with wide wingspan and forked tail; also applied to the skua gulls, and to the wandering albatross.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manograph</ent><br/
<hw>Man"o*graph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ thin, rare + <ets>-graph</ets>: cf. F. <ets>manographe</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Engin.)</fld> <def>An optical device for making an indicator diagram for high-speed engines. It consists of a light-tight box or camera having at one end a small convex mirror which reflects a beam of light on to the ground glass or photographic plate at the other end. The mirror is pivoted so that it can be moved in one direction by a small plunger operated by an elastic metal diaphragm which closes a tube connected with the engine cylinder. It is also moved at right angles to this direction by a reducing motion, called a <xex>reproducer</xex>, so as to copy accurately on a smaller scale the motion of the engine piston. The resultant of these two movements imparts to the reflected beam of light a motion similar to that of the pencil of the ordinary indicator, and this can be traced on the sheet of ground glass, or photographed.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manometer</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*nom"e*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ thin, rare + <ets>-meter</ets>: cf. F. <ets>manom<egrave/tre</ets>.]</ety> <def>An instrument for measuring the tension or elastic force of gases, steam, etc., constructed usually on the principle of allowing the gas to exert its elastic force in raising a column of mercury in an open tube, or in compressing a portion of air or other gas in a closed tube with mercury or other liquid intervening, or in bending a metallic or other spring so as to set in motion an index; a pressure gauge. See <er>Pressure</er>, and <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Air pump</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manometrical</ent><br/
<ent>Manometric</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Man`o*met"ric</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Man`o*met"ric*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>manom<eacute/trique</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to the manometer; made by the manometer.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manor</ent><br/
<hw>Man"or</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>maner</ets>, OF. <ets>maneir</ets> habitation, village, F. <ets>manoir</ets> manor, prop. the OF. inf. <ets>maneir</ets> to stay, remain, dwell, L. <ets>manere</ets>, and so called because it was the permanent residence of the lord and of his tenants. See <er>Mansion</er>, and cf. <er>Remain</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Eng. Law)</fld> <def>The land belonging to a lord or nobleman, or so much land as a lord or great personage kept in his own hands, for the use and subsistence of his family.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My <qex>manors</qex>, rents, revenues, l forego.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ In these days, a <xex>manor</xex> rather signifies the jurisdiction and royalty incorporeal, than the land or site, for a man may have a manor in gross, as the law terms it, that is, the right and interest of a court-baron, with the perquisites thereto belonging.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(American Law)</fld> <def>A tract of land occupied by tenants who pay a free-farm rent to the proprietor, sometimes in kind, and sometimes by performing certain stipulated services.</def>  <rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Manor house</b></col>, or <col><b>Manor seat</b></col></mcol>, <cd>the house belonging to a manor; the house of the lord of the manor; a manse.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manor hall</ent><br/
<hw>manor hall</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The large room of a manor or castle.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manorial</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*no"ri*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to a manor.</def> <ldquo/ <xex>Manorial</xex> claims.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Paley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manoscope</ent><br/
<hw>Man"o*scope</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ thin, rare + <ets>-scope</ets>.]</ety> <def>Same as <er>Manometer</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manoscopy</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*nos"co*py</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The science of the determination of the density of vapors and gases.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manovery</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*no"ver*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Maneuver</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Eng. Law)</fld> <def>A contrivance or maneuvering to catch game illegally.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manqueller</ent><br/
<hw>Man"quell`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A killer of men; a manslayer.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Carew.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manrent</ent><br/
<ent>Manred</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Man"red</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Man"rent`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Homage or service rendered to a superior, as to a lord; vassalage.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Scots Law]</mark>  <rj><au>Jamieson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manrope</ent><br/
<hw>Man"rope`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>One of the side ropes to the gangway of a ship.</def>  <rj><au>Totten.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mansard roof</ent><br/
<hw>Man"sard roof"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[So called from its inventor, <person>Fran<cced/ois <ets>Mansard</ets></person>, or <ets>Mansart</ets>, a distinguished French architect, who died in 1666.]</ety> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A hipped curb roof; that is, a roof having on all sides two slopes, the lower one being steeper than the upper one.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manse</ent><br/
<hw>Manse</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>mansa</ets>, <ets>mansus</ets>, <ets>mansum</ets>, a farm, fr. L. <ets>manere</ets>, <ets>mansum</ets>, to stay, dwell. See <er>Mansion</er>, <er>Manor</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A dwelling house, generally with land attached.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The parsonage; a clergyman's house.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Capital manse</b></col>, <cd>the manor house, or lord's court.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manservant</ent><br/
<hw>Man"serv`ant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A male servant.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mansion</ent><br/
<hw>Man"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>mansion</ets>, F. <ets>maison</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mansio</ets> a staying, remaining, a dwelling, habitation, fr. <ets>manere</ets>, <ets>mansum</ets>, to stay, dwell; akin to Gr. <?/.  Cf. <er>Manse</er>, <er>Manor</er>, <er>Menagerie</er>, <er>Menial</er>, <er>Permanent</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A dwelling place, -- whether a part or whole of a house or other shelter.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In my Father's house are many <qex>mansions</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>John xiv. 2.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These poets near our princes sleep,<br/
And in one grave their <qex>mansions</qex> keep.</q> <rj><qau>Den<?/am.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The house of the lord of a manor; a manor house; hence: Any house of considerable size or pretension.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Astrol.)</fld> <def>A twelfth part of the heavens; a house. See 1st <er>House</er>, 8.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The place in the heavens occupied each day by the moon in its monthly revolution.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The eight and twenty <qex>mansions</qex><br/
<qex>That longen to the moon</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mansion house</b></col>, <cd>the house in which one resides; specifically, in London and some other cities, the official residence of the Lord Mayor.</cd>  <rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mansion</ent><br/
<hw>Man"sion</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To dwell; to reside.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Mede.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mansionary</ent><br/
<hw>Man"sion*a*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Resident; residentiary; <as>as, <ex>mansionary</ex> canons</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mansion house</ent><br/
<hw>mansion house</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A large and imposing house.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mansion, manse, hall, residence.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mansionry</ent><br/
<hw>Man"sion*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state of dwelling or residing; occupancy as a dwelling place.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>man-sized</ent><br/
<hw>man-sized</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Calling for manly attributes; <as>as, a <ex>man-sized</ex> job</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Large enough to satisfy a man; <as>as, a <ex>man-sized</ex> piece of cake</as>.</def> <mark>[informal]</mark><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manslaughter</ent><br/
<hw>Man"slaugh`ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The slaying of a human being; destruction of men.</def>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The unlawful killing of a man, either in negligence or incidentally to the commission of some unlawful act, but without specific malice, or upon a sudden excitement of anger.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manslayer</ent><br/
<hw>Man"slay`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who kills a human being; one who commits manslaughter.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manstealer</ent><br/
<hw>Man"steal`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A person who steals or kidnaps a human being or beings.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manstealing</ent><br/
<hw>Man"steal`ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act or business of stealing or kidnaping human beings, especially with a view to e<?/slave them.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mansuete</ent><br/
<hw>Man"suete</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mansuetus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>mansuescere</ets> to tame; <ets>manus</ets> hand + <ets>suescere</ets> to accustom: cf. F. <ets>mansuet</ets>.]</ety> <def>Tame; gentle; kind.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Ray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mansuetude</ent><br/
<hw>Man"sue*tude</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mansuetudo</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mansu<eacute/tude</ets>.]</ety> <def>Tameness; gentleness; mildness.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manswear</ent><br/
<hw>Man"swear`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To swear falsely. Same as <er>Mainswear</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manta</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Man"ta</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From the native name.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The <er>manta ray</er>.  See also <er>Cephaloptera</er> and <er>Sea devil</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manta ray</ent><br/
<hw>manta ray</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>An extremely large pelagic tropical ray of the family <fam>Mobulidae</fam>, that feeds on plankton and small fishes.  It is usually harmless but its size (up to 20 feet across and up to a ton in weight) make it dangerous if harpooned.  Called also <altname>manta</altname>, <altname>sea devil</altname> and <altname>devilfish</altname>.  See also <er>Cephaloptera</er> and <er>Sea devil</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantchoo</ent><br/
<hw>Mant*choo"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a. & n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Manchu</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manteau</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Man`teau"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> F. <plw>Manteaux</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, E. <plw>Manteaus</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F. See <er>Mantle</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A woman's cloak or mantle.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A gown worn by women.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manteidae</ent><br/
<hw>Manteidae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of insects including the mantises.  Also spelled <altname><fam>Mantidae</fam></altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> <fam>Mantidae</fam>, family <fam>Mantidae</fam>, family Manteidae.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantel</ent><br/
<hw>Man"tel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[The same word as <ets>mantle</ets> a garment; cf. F. <ets>manteau de chemin<eacute/e</ets>. See <er>Mantle</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>The finish around a fireplace, covering the chimney-breast in front and sometimes on both sides; especially, a shelf above the fireplace, and its supports.  The shelf is called also a <altname>mantelpiece</altname> or <altname>mantlepiece</altname>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mantle</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantelet</ent><br/
<hw>Man"tel*et</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., dim. of <ets>manteau</ets>, OF. <ets>mantel</ets>. See <er>Mantle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A short cloak formerly worn by knights.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A short cloak or mantle worn by women.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>mantelet</qex> upon his shoulders hanging.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Fort.)</fld> <def>A musket-proof shield of rope, wood, or metal, which is sometimes used for the protection of sappers or riflemen while attacking a fortress, or of gunners at embrasures; -- now commonly written <asp>mantlet</asp>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 893 --></p>

<p><ent>Mantelletta</ent><br/
<hw>Man`tel*let"ta</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It. <ets>mantelletta</ets>. See <er>Mantelet</er>.]</ety> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld> <def>A silk or woolen vestment without sleeves worn by cardinals, bishops, abbots, and the prelates of the Roman court. It has a low collar, is fastened in front, and reaches almost to the knees.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantelpiece</ent><br/
<hw>Man"tel*piece`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Mantel</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantelshelf</ent><br/
<hw>Man"tel*shelf`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The shelf of a mantel.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manteltree</ent><br/
<hw>Man"tel*tree`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>The lintel of a fireplace when of wood, as frequently in early houses.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantic</ent><br/
<hw>Man"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ prophetic.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to divination, or to the condition of one inspired, or supposed to be inspired, by a deity; prophetic.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <ldquo/<xex>Mantic</xex> fury.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Trench.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manticore</ent><br/
<ent>manticora</ent><br/
<ent>mantichora</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mantichora</hw>, <hw>manticora</hw>, <hw>manticore</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mythical monster having the head of man (with horns) and the body of a lion and the tail of a scorpion.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> manticore, mantichora, mantiger.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mantid</ent><br/
<hw>mantid</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A <er>mantis</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mantis.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantidae</ent><br/
<hw>Mantidae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The natural family conmprising the mantises.  Same as <fam>Manteidae</fam>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family Mantidae, <fam>Manteidae</fam>, family Manteidae.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mantiger</ent><br/
<hw>mantiger</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The <er>manticore</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> manticore, mantichora, manticora.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantilla</ent><br/
<hw>Man*til"la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. See <er>Mantle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A lady's light cloak of cape of silk, velvet, lace, or the like.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A kind of veil, covering the head and falling down upon the shoulders; -- worn in Spain, Mexico, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantineia</ent><br/
<ent>Mantinea</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Mantinea</hw>, <hw>Mantineia</hw></mhw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The site of three famous battles among Greek city-states: in 418 BC and 362 BC and 207 BC.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Mantineia.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Man"tis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ a prophet.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of numerous species of voracious orthopterous insects of the genus <gen>Mantis</gen>, and allied genera. They are  predacious long-bodied large-eyed insects of warm regions, are remarkable for their slender grotesque forms, and for holding their stout anterior legs in a manner suggesting hands folded in prayer. The common American species is <spn>Mantis Carolina</spn>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mantis shrimp</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>The <er>Squilla</er>, a tropical marine burrowing crustacean with large grasping appendages.  Also called <altname>mantis crab</altname> and <altname>mantis prawn</altname>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mantis crab</ent><br/
<hw>mantis crab</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Squilla</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Mantis shrimp.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mantis prawn</ent><br/
<hw>mantis prawn</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Squilla</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Mantis shrimp.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mantispid</ent><br/
<hw>man*tis"pid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any neuropterous insect of the genus <gen>Mantispa</gen>, and allied genera.  The larvae feed on plant lice.  Also used adjectively. See <xex>Illust.</xex> under <er>Neuroptera</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantispidae</ent><br/
<hw>Mantispidae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The natural family comprising the mantispids.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Mantispidae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mantissa</ent><br/
<hw>man*tis*sa</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., an addition, makeweight; of Tuscan origin.]</ety> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>The decimal part of a <partof>logarithm</partof>, as distinguished from the integral part, or <contr>characteristic</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mantle</ent><br/
<hw>man"tle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mantel</ets>, OF. <ets>mantel</ets>, F. <ets>manteau</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mantellum</ets>, <ets>mantelum</ets>, a cloth, napkin, cloak, mantle (cf. <ets>mantele</ets>, <ets>mantile</ets>, towel, napkin); prob. from <ets>manus</ets> hand + the root of <ets>tela</ets> cloth. See <er>Manual</er>, <er>Textile</er>, and cf. <er>Mandil</er>, <er>Mantel</er>, <er>Mantilla</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A loose garment to be worn over other garments; an enveloping robe; a cloak.</def>  <specif>Hence,</specif> figuratively, <def>a covering or concealing envelope.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[The] children are clothed with <qex>mantles</qex> of satin.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The green <qex>mantle</qex> of the standing pool.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now Nature hangs her <qex>mantle</qex> green<br/
On every blooming tree.</q> <rj><qau>Burns.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Mantling</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The external fold, or folds, of the soft, exterior membrane of the body of a mollusk.  It usually forms a cavity inclosing the gills.  See <xex>Illusts.</xex> of <er>Buccinum</er>, and <er>Byssus</er>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Any free, outer membrane.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The back of a bird together with the folded wings.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A mantel. See <er>Mantel</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The outer wall and casing of a blast furnace, above the hearth.</def>  <rj><au>Raymond.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Hydraulic Engin.)</fld> <def>A penstock for a water wheel.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>The highly viscous shell of hot semisolid rock, about 1800 miles thick, lying under the crust of the Earth and above the core.  Also, by analogy, a similar shell on any other planet.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantle</ent><br/
<hw>Man"tle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mantled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mantling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To cover or envelop, as with a mantle; to cloak; to hide; to disguise.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantle</ent><br/
<hw>Man"tle</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To unfold and spread out the wings, like a mantle; -- said of hawks. Also used figuratively.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ne is there hawk which <qex>mantleth</qex> on her perch.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Or tend his sparhawk <qex>mantling</qex> in her mew.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Hall.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My frail fancy fed with full delight.<br/
Doth bathe in bliss, and <qex>mantleth</qex> most at ease.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To spread out; -- said of wings.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The swan, with arched neck<br/
Between her white wings <qex>mantling</qex> proudly, rows.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To spread over the surface as a covering; to overspread; <as>as, the scum <ex>mantled</ex> on the pool</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though <qex>mantled</qex> in her cheek the blood.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To gather, assume, or take on, a covering, as froth, scum, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is a sort of men whose visages<br/
Do cream and <qex>mantle</qex> like a standing pond.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor bowl of wassail <qex>mantle</qex> warm.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mantled</ent><br/
<hw>man"tled</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>Covered with or as if with clothes or a wrap or cloak.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> cloaked, clothed, draped, wrapped.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mantled ground squirrel</ent><br/
<hw>mantled ground squirrel</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A common black-striped reddish-brown ground squirrel (<spn>Citellus lateralis</spn>) of western North America, resembling a large chipmunk.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mantlepiece</ent><br/
<hw>man"tle*piece</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A shelf that projects from the wall above a fireplace; a mantel; <as>as, in England they call a <ex>mantelpiece</ex> a chimneypiece</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mantel, mantelpiece, mantle, chimneypiece.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantlet</ent><br/
<hw>Man"tlet</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mantelet</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantling</ent><br/
<hw>Man"tling</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>The representation of a mantle, or the drapery behind and around a coat of arms: -- called also <altname>lambrequin</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manto</ent><br/
<hw>Man"to</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It. or Sp. <ets>manto</ets>, abbrev., from L. <ets>mantelum</ets>. See <er>Mantle</er>.]</ety> <def>See <er>Manteau</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bailey.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantologist</ent><br/
<hw>Man*tol"o*gist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who is skilled in mantology; a diviner.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantology</ent><br/
<hw>Man*tol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ prophet + <ets>-logy</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act or art of divination.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantoux test</ent><br/
<hw>Mantoux test</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A skin test for hypersensitivity to tuberculin.  It determines whether there is or has been any infection with tubercle bacilli.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantra</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Man"tra</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Skr.]</ety> <def>A prayer; an invocation; a religious formula; a charm.</def> <mark>[India]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Among the Hindoos each caste and tribe has a <xex>mantra</xex> peculiar to itself; as, the <xex>mantra</xex> of the Brahmans.</note>  <rj><au>Balfour (Cyc. of India).</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantrap</ent><br/
<hw>Man"trap`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A trap for catching trespassers.</def> <mark>[Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A dangerous place, as an open hatch, into which one may fall.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantua</ent><br/
<hw>Man"tu*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A superior kind of rich silk formerly exported from Mantua in Italy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Beck (Draper's Dict.).</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A woman's cloak or mantle; also, a woman's gown.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantuamaker</ent><br/
<hw>Man"tu*a*mak`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who makes dresses, cloaks, etc., for women; a dressmaker.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mantuan</ent><br/
<hw>Man"tu*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to Mantua.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A native or inhabitant of Mantua.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manu</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma"nu</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Skr.]</ety> <fld>(Hind. Myth.)</fld> <def>One of a series of progenitors of human beings, and authors of human wisdom.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manual</ent><br/
<hw>Man"u*al</hw> <pr>(m<acr/n"<usl/*<ait/l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>manuel</ets>, F. <ets>manuel</ets>, L. <ets>manualis</ets>, fr. <ets>manus</ets> hand; prob. akin to AS. <ets>mund</ets> hand, protection, OHG. <ets>munt</ets>, G. <ets>m<uum/nd</ets>el a ward, vor<ets>mund</ets> guardian, Icel. <ets>mund</ets> hand.  Cf. <er>Emancipate</er>, <er>Legerdemain</er>, <er>Maintain</er>, <er>Manage</er>, <er>Manner</er>, <er>Manure</er>, <er>Mound</er> a hill.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the hand.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Performed by a person using physical as contrasted with <contr>mental</contr> effort; <as>as, <ex>manual</ex> labor</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Done or made by the hand.  In some contexts, contrasted with <contr>automatic</contr> or <contr>mechanical</contr>.</def>  <ldquo/<xex>Manual</xex> and ocular examination.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Tatham.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Manual exercise</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <cd>the exercise by which soldiers are taught the use of their muskets and other arms.</cd> -- <col><b>Seal manual</b></col>, <cd>the impression of a seal worn on the hand as a ring.</cd> -- <col><b>Sign manual</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Sign</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manual</ent><br/
<hw>Man"u*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>manuel</ets>, LL. <ets>manuale</ets>. See <er>Manual</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A small book, such as may be carried in the hand, or conveniently handled; a handbook; specifically, the service book of the Roman Catholic Church.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>manual</qex> of laws, styled the Confessor's Laws.</q> <rj><qau>Sir M. Hale.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A keyboard of an organ or harmonium for the fingers, as distinguished from the pedals; a clavier, or set of keys.</def>  <rj><au>Moore (Encyc. of Music).</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A prescribed exercise in the systematic handing of a weapon; <as>as, the <ex>manual</ex> of arms; the <ex>manual</ex> of the sword; the <ex>manual</ex> of the piece (cannon, mortar, etc.).</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manual alphabet</ent><br/
<hw>manual alphabet</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>An alphabet of signs made by movement of the hands, used by the deaf; in it letters are represented by finger positions.  See <er>Dactylology</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> finger alphabet.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manual dexterity</ent><br/
<hw>manual dexterity</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Adroitness in using the hands.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manualist</ent><br/
<hw>Man"u*al*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who works with the hands; an artificer.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manual labour</ent><br/
<ent>manual labor</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>manual labor</hw>, <hw>manual labour</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Labor done with the hands.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manual laborer</ent><br/
<hw>manual laborer</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A person who works with the hands, rather than with the mind.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> laborer, labourer.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manually</ent><br/
<hw>man"u*al*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>By hand.  In some contexts, contrasted with <contr>automatically</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manuary</ent><br/
<hw>Man"u*a*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>manuarius</ets>, fr. <ets>manus</ets> hand.]</ety> <def>Manual.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>An artificer.</def></def2> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manubial</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*nu"bi*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>manubialis</ets>, fr. <ets>manubiae</ets> money obtained from the sale of booty, booty.]</ety> <def>Belonging to spoils; taken in war.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bailey.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manubrial</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*nu"bri*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to a manubrium; shaped like a manubrium; handlelike.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manubrium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*nu"bri*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> L. <plw>Manubria</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, E. <plw>Manubriums</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., handle, fr. <ets>manus</ets> hand.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A handlelike process or part; esp., the anterior segment of the sternum, or presternum, and the handlelike process of the malleus.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The proboscis of a jellyfish; -- called also <altname>hypostoma</altname>. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Hydromedusa</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manucode</ent><br/
<hw>Man"u*code</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Javanese <ets>manukdewata</ets> the bird of the gods: cf. F. <ets>manucode</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any bird of the genus <gen>Manucodia</gen>, of Australia and New Guinea.  They are related to the bird of paradise.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manuducent</ent><br/
<hw>Man`u*du"cent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who leads by the hand; a manuductor.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manuduction</ent><br/
<hw>Man`u*duc"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>manus</ets> hand + <ets>ductio</ets> a leading, <ets>ducere</ets> to lead: cf. F. <ets>manuduction</ets>.]</ety> <def>Guidance by the hand.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Glanvill.</au>  <au>South.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manuductor</ent><br/
<hw>Man`u*duc"tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>manus</ets> the hand + <ets>ductor</ets> a leader, <ets>ducere</ets> to lead: cf. F. <ets>manuducteur</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A conductor; an officer in the ancient church who gave the signal for the choir to sing, and who beat time with the hand, and regulated the music.</def>  <rj><au>Moore (Encyc. of Music.)</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manufactory</ent><br/
<hw>Man`u*fac"to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>-ries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Cf. L. <ets>factorium</ets> an oil press, properly, place where something is made. See <er>Manufacture</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Manufacture.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A building or place where anything is manufactured; a factory.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manufactory</ent><br/
<hw>Man`u*fac"to*ry</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to manufacturing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manufactural</ent><br/
<hw>Man`u*fac"tur*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to manufactures.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manufacture</ent><br/
<hw>Man`u*fac"ture</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>manus</ets> the hand + <ets>factura</ets> a making, fr. <ets>facere</ets> to make: cf. F. <ets>manufacture</ets>. See <er>Manual</er>, and <er>Fact</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The operation of making wares or any products by hand, by machinery, or by other agency.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything made from raw materials by the hand, by machinery, or by art, as cloths, iron utensils, shoes, machinery, saddlery, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manufacture</ent><br/
<hw>Man`u*fac"ture</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Manufactured</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Manufacturing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>manufacturer</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make (wares or other products) by hand, by machinery, or by other agency; <as>as, to <ex>manufacture</ex> cloth, nails, glass, etc.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To work, as raw or partly wrought materials, into suitable forms for use; <as>as, to <ex>manufacture</ex> wool, cotton, silk, or iron</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manufacture</ent><br/
<hw>Man`u*fac"ture</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be employed in manufacturing something.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manufactured</ent><br/
<hw>manufactured</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Produced in a large-scale industrial operation.  Contrasted with <contr>hand-made</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manufacturer</ent><br/
<hw>Man`u*fac"tur*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who manufactures.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manufacturing</ent><br/
<hw>Man`u*fac"tur*ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Employed, or chiefly employed, in manufacture; <as>as, a <ex>manufacturing</ex> community; a <ex>manufacturing</ex> town.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Pertaining to manufacture; <as>as, <ex>manufacturing</ex> projects</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manufacturing business</ent><br/
<hw>manufacturing business</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A business engaged in manufacturing some product.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> manufacturer, maker.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manufacturing plant</ent><br/
<hw>manufacturing plant</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A factory.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mill, manufacturing plant, manufactory.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manul</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>ma"nul</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A wild cat (<spn>Felis manul</spn>), having long, soft, light-colored fur.  It is found in the mountains of Central Asia, and dwells among rocks.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manumise</ent><br/
<hw>Man"u*mise`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Manumit</er>.]</ety> <def>To manumit.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manumission</ent><br/
<hw>Man`u*mis"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>manumissio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>manumission</ets>. See <er>Manumit</er>.]</ety> <def>The act of manumitting, or of liberating a slave from bondage.</def> <ldquo/Given to slaves at their <xex>manumission</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Arbuthnot.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manumit</ent><br/
<hw>Man`u*mit"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Manumitted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Manumitting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>manumittere</ets>, <ets>manumissum</ets>; <ets>manus</ets> the hand + <ets>mittere</ets> to send, to send off. See <er>Manual</er>, and <er>Missile</er>.]</ety> <def>To release from slavery; to liberate from personal bondage or servitude; to free, as a slave.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Manumitted</xex> slaves.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Hume.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manumotive</ent><br/
<hw>Man"u*mo`tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>manus</ets> the hand + E. <ets>motive</ets>.]</ety> <def>Movable by hand.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manumotor</ent><br/
<hw>Man"u*mo`tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>manus</ets> the hand + E. <ets>motor</ets>.]</ety> <def>A small wheel carriage, so constructed that a person sitting in it may move it.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manurable</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*nur"a*ble</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Capable of cultivation.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir M. Hale.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Capable of receiving a fertilizing substance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manurage</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*nur"age</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Cultivation.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Warner.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manurance</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*nur"ance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Cultivation.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manure</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*nure"</hw> <pr>(m<adot/*n<umac/r")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Manured</conjf> <pr>(m<adot/*n<umac/rd")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Manuring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Contr, from OF. <ets>manuvrer</ets>, <ets>manovrer</ets>, to work with the hand, to cultivate by manual labor, F. <ets>man<oe/uvrer</ets>. See <er>Manual</er>, <er>Ure</er>, <er>Opera</er>, and cf. <er>Inure</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cultivate by manual labor; to till; hence, to develop by culture.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To whom we gave the strand for to <qex>manure</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Surrey.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Manure</qex> thyself then; to thyself be improved;<br/
And with vain, outward things be no more moved.</q> <rj><qau>Donne.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To apply manure to; to enrich, as land, by the application of a fertilizing substance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The blood of English shall <qex>manure</qex> the ground.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manure</ent><br/
<hw>ma*nure"</hw> <pr>(m<adot/*n<umac/r")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Any matter which makes land productive; a fertilizing substance.</def> <specif>Especially,</specif>, <def>dung, the contents of stables and barnyards, decaying animal or vegetable substances, etc.</def>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manurement</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*nure"ment</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>manouvrement</ets>.]</ety> <def>Cultivation.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>W. Wotton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manurer</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*nur"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who manures land.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manurial</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*nu"ri*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Relating to manures.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manuring</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*nur"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of process of applying manure; also, the manure applied.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma"nus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Manus</plw>.</plu> <ety>[L., the hand.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The distal segment of the fore limb, including the carpus and fore foot or hand.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manuscript</ent><br/
<hw>Man"u*script</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>manu scriptus</ets>. See <er>Manual</er>, and <er>Scribe</er>.]</ety> <def>Written with or by the hand; not printed; <as>as, a <ex>manuscript</ex> volume</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manuscript</ent><br/
<hw>Man"u*script</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>manuscriptum</ets>, lit., something written with the hand. See <er>Manuscript</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An original literary or musical composition written by the author, formerly with the hand, now usually by typewriter or word processor.  It is contrasted with a printed copy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Writing, as opposed to print; <as>as, the book exists only in <ex>manuscript</ex></as>.</def>  <rj><au>Craik.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The word is often abbreviated to <abbr>MS.</abbr>, plural <abbr>MSS.</abbr></note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manuscriptal</ent><br/
<hw>Man"u*script`al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Manuscript.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manutenency</ent><br/
<hw>Man`u*ten"en*cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>manus</ets> hand + <ets>tenere</ets> to hold.]</ety> <def>Maintenance.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Abp. Sancroft.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manway</ent><br/
<hw>Man"way`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A small passageway, as in a mine, that a man may pass through.</def>  <rj><au>Raymond.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manx</ent><br/
<hw>Manx</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the Isle of Man, or its inhabitants; <as>as, the <ex>Manx</ex> language</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Manx shearwater</b></col> <cd>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manx cat</ent><br/
<hw>Manx cat</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <def>A breed of domestic cats having a rudimentary tail, containing only about three vertebrae.  It is believed to have originated on the Isle of Man.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manx shearwater</ent><br/
<hw>Manx shearwater</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <def>A small black-and-white oceanic bird (<spn>Puffinus puffinus</spn>, or <spn>Puffinus anglorum</spn>), common in the Eastern North Atlantic.  Called also <altname>Manx petrel</altname>, <altname>Manx puffin</altname>.  It is avariety of <er>shearwater</er>.  It was formerly abundant in the Isle of Man.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manx</ent><br/
<hw>Manx</hw>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The language of the inhabitants of the Isle of Man, a dialect of the Celtic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Many</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"ny</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Meine</er>, <er>Mansion</er>.]</ety> <def>A retinue of servants; a household.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Many</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"ny</hw>, <pos>a. & pron.</pos> <note>[It has no variation to express degrees of comparison; <xex>more</xex> and <xex>most</xex>, which are used for the comparative and superlative degrees, are from a different root.]</note> <ety>[OE. <ets>mani</ets>, <ets>moni</ets>, AS. <ets>manig</ets>, <ets>m<ae/nig</ets>, <ets>monig</ets>; akin to D. <ets>menig</ets>, OS. & OHG. <ets>manag</ets>, G. <ets>manch</ets>, Dan. <ets>mange</ets>, Sw. <ets>m<aring/nge</ets>, Goth. <ets>manags</ets>, OSlav. <ets>mnog'</ets>, Russ. <ets>mnogii</ets>; cf. Icel. <ets>margr</ets>, Prov. E. <ets>mort</ets>. <root/103.]</ety> <def>Consisting of a great number; numerous; not few.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou shalt be a father of <qex>many</qex> nations.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. xvii. 4.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not <qex>many</qex> wise men after the flesh, not <qex>many</qex> mighty, not <qex>many</qex> noble, are called.</q> <rj><qau>1 Cor. i. 26.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Many</xex> is freely prefixed to participles, forming compounds which need no special explanation; as, <xex>many-</xex>angled, <xex>many-</xex>celled, <xex>many-</xex>eyed, <xex>many-</xex>footed, <xex>many-</xex>handed, <xex>many-</xex>leaved, <xex>many-</xex>lettered, <xex>many-</xex>named, <xex>many-</xex>peopled, <xex>many-</xex>petaled, <xex>many-</xex>seeded, <xex>many-</xex>syllabled (polysyllabic), <xex>many-</xex>tongued, <xex>many-</xex>voiced, <xex>many-</xex>wived, and the like.  In such usage it is equivalent to <altname>multi</altname>.
    Comparison is often expressed by <xex>many</xex> with <xex>as</xex> or <xex>so</xex>. <ldquo/As <xex>many</xex> as were willing hearted . . . brought bracelets.<rdquo/ <au>Exod. xxxv. 22.</au> <ldquo/So <xex>many</xex> laws argue so <xex>many</xex> sins.<rdquo/ <au>Milton.</au>
    <xex>Many</xex> stands with a singular substantive with <xex>a</xex> or <xex>an</xex>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Many a</b></col>, <cd>a large number taken distributively; each one of many.</cd> <ldquo/For thy sake have I shed <xex>many a</xex> tear.<rdquo/ <au>Shak.</au> <ldquo/Full <xex>many a</xex> gem of purest ray serene.<rdquo/ <au>Gray.</au> -- <col><b>Many one</b></col>, <cd>many a one; many persons.</cd> <au>Bk. of Com. Prayer.</au> -- <col><b>The many</b></col>, <cd>the majority; -- opposed to <contr>the few</contr>. See <er>Many</er>, <pos>n.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>Too many</b></col>, <cd>too numerous; hence, too powerful; <as>as, they are <ex>too many</ex> for us</as>.</cd>  <rj><au>L'Estrange.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Numerous; multiplied; frequent; manifold; various; divers; sundry.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Many</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"ny</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>menigeo</ets>, <ets>menigo</ets>, <ets>menio</ets>, multitude; akin to G. <ets>menge</ets>, OHG. <ets>manag<imac/</ets>, <ets>menig<imac/</ets>, Goth. <ets>managei</ets>. See <er>Many</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The populace; the common people; the majority of people, or of a community.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>After him the rascal <qex>many</qex> ran.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A large or considerable number.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>many</qex> of our bodies shall no doubt<br/
Find native graves.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Seeing a great <qex>many</qex> in rich gowns.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It will be concluded by <qex>many</qex> that he lived like an honest man.</q> <rj><qau>Fielding.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ In this sense, <xex>many</xex> is connected immediately with another substantive (without <xex>of</xex>) to show of what the <xex>many</xex> consists; as, a good <xex>many</xex> [of] people think so.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He is liable to a great <qex>many</qex> inconveniences.</q> <rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Many-minded</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"ny-mind`ed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having many faculties; versatile; many-sided.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manyplies</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"ny*plies</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Many</ets>, adj. + <ets>plies</ets>, pl. of <ets>ply</ets> a fold.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The third division, or that between the reticulum, or honeycomb stomach, and the abomasum, or rennet stomach, in the stomach of ruminants; the omasum; the psalterium.  So called from the numerous folds in its mucous membrane. See <xex>Illust</xex> of <er>Ruminant</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Many-sided</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"ny-sid`ed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having many sides; -- said of figures. Hence, presenting many questions or subjects for consideration; <as>as, a <ex>many-sided</ex> topic</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Interested in, and having an aptitude for, many unlike pursuits or objects of attention; versatile.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Ma"ny-sid`ed*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 894 --></p>

<p><ent>manywise</ent><br/
<ent>manyways</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>ma"ny*ways`</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/n"<ycr/*w<amac/z`)</pr>, <hw>ma"ny*wise`</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/n"<ycr/*w<imac/z`)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In many different ways; variously.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manzanilla</ent><br/
<hw>man`za*nil"la</hw> <pr>(m<acr/n`z<adot/*n<icr/l"l<adot/; <it>Sp.</it> m<aum/n`th<aum/*n<emac/l"y<aum/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Olive Trade)</fld> <def>A kind of small roundish olive with a small freestone pit, a fine skin, and a peculiar bitterish flavor. Manzanillas are commonly pitted and stuffed with Spanish pimientos.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>A very dry pale sherry from Spain.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manzanita</ent><br/
<hw>man`za*ni"ta</hw> <pr>(m<acr/n`z<adot/*n<emac/"t<adot/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp., dim. of <ets>manzana</ets> an apple.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A name given to several species of <spn>Arctostaphylos</spn>, but mostly to <spn>Arctostaphylos glauca</spn> and <spn>Arctostaphylos pungens</spn>, shrubs of California, Oregon, etc., with reddish smooth bark, ovate or oval coriaceous evergreen leaves, and bearing clusters of red berries, which are said to be a favorite food of the grizzly bear.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mao</ent><br/
<hw>Mao</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mao Tsetung</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maoism</ent><br/
<hw>Maoism</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A form of communism developed in China by Mao Zedong.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maoist</ent><br/
<hw>Maoist</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>An advocate of Maoism.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maori</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"o*ri</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Maoris</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>One of the aboriginal inhabitants of New Zealand; also, the original language of New Zealand.</def> -- <def2><pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the Maoris or to their language.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maori hen</ent><br/
<hw>maori hen</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A flightless New Zealand rail of thievish disposition having short wings each with a spur used in fighting.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> weka, wood hen.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mao Zedong</ent><br/
<ent>Mao Tsetung</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Mao Tsetung</hw>, <hw>Mao Zedong</hw></mhw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The leader of the Chinese communist party and later of the People's Republic of China; b. 1893, d. 1976.  Also referred to a simply <altname>Mao</altname>.</def> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>Mao Tse-Tung</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Map</ent><br/
<hw>Map</hw> <pr>(m<acr/p)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From F. <ets>mappe</ets>, in <ets>mappemonde</ets> map of the world, fr. L. <ets>mappa</ets> napkin, signal cloth; -- a Punic word.  Cf. <er>Apron</er>, <er>Napkin</er>, <er>Nappe</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A representation of the surface of the earth, or of some portion of it, showing the relative position of the parts represented; -- usually on a flat surface.  Also, such a representation of the celestial sphere, or of some part of it.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ There are five principal kinds of projection used in making maps: the <xex>orthographic</xex>, the <xex>stereographic</xex>, the <xex>globuar</xex>, the <xex>conical</xex>, and the <xex>cylindrical</xex>, or <xex>Mercator's projection</xex>. See <er>Projection</er>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A graphical representation of anything showing the relative arrangement of its parts in a maplike form.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Anything which represents graphically a succession of events, states, or acts; <as>as, an historical <ex>map</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus is his cheek the <qex>map</qex> of days outworn.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mathematics)</fld>  <def>A relation between two sets in which an element of one set is associated with each element of the other set.  Also called a <asp>mapping</asp>, <asp>transformation</asp>, or <asp>correspondence</asp>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Map lichen</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a lichen (<spn>Lecidea geographica</spn>.) growing on stones in curious maplike figures.</cd>  <rj><au>Dr. Prior.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Map</ent><br/
<hw>Map</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mapped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mapping</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To represent by a map; -- often with <xex>out</xex>; <as>as, to survey and <ex>map</ex>, or <ex>map out</ex>, a <ex>county</ex></as>. Hence, figuratively: To represent or indicate systematically and clearly; to sketch; to plan; <as>as, to <ex>map</ex>, or <ex>map out</ex>, a journey; to <ex>map out</ex> business.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am near to the place where they should meet, if Pisanio have <qex>mapped</qex> it truly.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mathematics)</fld>  <def>To create a mapping between two sets; see <er>map</er>{4}, <pos>n.</pos>.  Also, to create any list of corresponding elements of two sets of things; <as>as, to <ex>map</ex> the symbols of an ancient language into a modern phonetic alphabet</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mapach</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*pach"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Mexican.]</ety> <def>The raccoon.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mapinguari</ent><br/
<hw>mapinguari</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A supposed human-sized slothlike creature reported sighted by Indians in the Amazon rain forest.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maple</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"ple</hw> <pr>(m<amac/"p'l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>mapolder</ets>, <ets>mapulder</ets>, <ets>mapol</ets>; akin to Icel. <ets>m<oum/purr</ets>; cf. OHG. <ets>mazzaltra</ets>, <ets>mazzoltra</ets>, G. <ets>massholder</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A tree of the genus <gen>Acer</gen>, including about fifty species. <spn>Acer saccharinum</spn> is the <stype>rock maple</stype>, or <stype>sugar maple</stype>, from the sap of which sugar is made, in the United States, in great quantities, by evaporation; the <stype>red maple</stype> or <stype>swamp maple</stype> is <spn>Acer rubrum</spn>; the <stype>silver maple</stype>, <spn>Acer dasycarpum</spn>, having fruit wooly when young; the <stype>striped maple</stype>, <spn>Acer Pennsylvanium</spn>, called also <stype>moosewood</stype>.  The common maple of Europe is <spn>Acer campestre</spn>, the <stype>sycamore maple</stype> is <spn>Acer Pseudo-platanus</spn>, and the <stype>Norway maple</stype> is <spn>Acer platanoides</spn>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Maple</xex> is much used adjectively, or as the first part of a compound; as, <xex>maple</xex> tree, <xex>maple</xex> leaf, etc.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Bird's-eye maple</b></col>, <col><b>Curled maple</b></col></mcol>, <cd>varieties of the wood of the rock maple, in which a beautiful lustrous grain is produced by the sinuous course of the fibers.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Maple honey</b></col>, <col><b>Maple molasses</b></col>, <col><b>Maple syrup</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Maple sirup</b></col></mcol>, <cd>maple sap boiled to the consistency of molasses.</cd> -- <col><b>Maple sugar</b></col>, <cd>sugar obtained from the sap of the sugar maple by evaporation.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maple-leaf begonia</ent><br/
<hw>maple-leaf begonia</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A tuberous or semi-tuberous South African begonia (<spn>Begonia dregei</spn>) having shallowly lobed ovate leaves and small white flowers.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> grape-leaf begonia.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maple-leaved bayur</ent><br/
<hw>maple-leaved bayur</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>An Indian tree (<spn>Pterospermum acerifolium</spn>) having fragrant nocturnal white flowers and yielding a reddish wood used for planking; often grown as an ornamental or shade tree.  Called also <altname>mayeng</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maple family</ent><br/
<hw>maple family</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The natural family of trees <fam>Aceraceae</fam>, including the maples.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maplike</ent><br/
<hw>Map"like`</hw> <pr>(m<acr/p"l<imac/k`)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having or consisting of lines resembling a map; <as>as, the <ex>maplike</ex> figures in which certain lichens grow</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mapmaker</ent><br/
<ent>map maker</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>map" mak*er</hw>, <hw>map"mak*er</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A person who makes maps; a cartographer.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mapmaking</ent><br/
<hw>map"mak*ing</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The making of maps and charts; cartography.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> cartography.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mappery</ent><br/
<hw>map"per*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From Map.]</ety> <def>The making, or study, of maps.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mapping</ent><br/
<hw>map"ping</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>A function such that for every element of one set there is a unique element of another set.  Same as <er>map</er>{4}.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> map, correspondence.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maqui</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"qui</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A Chilian shrub (<spn>Aristotelia Maqui</spn>). Its bark furnishes strings for musical instruments, and a medicinal wine is made from its berries.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maquis</ent><br/
<hw>Maquis</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A guerrilla fighter in the French underground in World War II.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The French underground that fought against the German occupation in World War II.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mar</ent><br/
<hw>Mar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A small lake. See <er>Mere</er>.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mar</ent><br/
<hw>Mar</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Marred</conjf> <pr>(m<aum/rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Marring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>marren</ets>, <ets>merren</ets>, AS. <ets>merran</ets>, <ets>myrran</ets> (in comp.), to obstruct, impede, dissipate; akin to OS. <ets>merrian</ets>, OHG. <ets>marrjan</ets>, <ets>merran</ets>; cf. D. <ets>marren</ets>, <ets>meeren</ets>, to moor a ship, Icel. <ets>merja</ets> to bruise, crush, and Goth. <ets>marzjan</ets> to offend.  Cf. <er>Moor</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make defective; to do injury to, esp. by cutting off or defacing a part; to impair; to disfigure; to deface.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I pray you <qex>mar</qex> no more trees with wiring love songs in their barks.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But mirth is <qex>marred</qex>, and the good cheer is lost.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ire, envy, and despair<br/
Which <qex>marred</qex> all his borrowed visage.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To spoil; to ruin.</def> <ldquo/It makes us, or it <xex>mars</xex> us.<rdquo/ <ldquo/Striving to mend, to <xex>mar</xex> the subject.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mar</ent><br/
<hw>Mar</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mark or blemish made by bruising, scratching, or the like; a disfigurement.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mara</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma"ra</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Skr. <ets>m<amac/ra</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Hind. Myth.)</fld> <def>The principal or ruling evil spirit.</def>  <rj><au>E. Arnold.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mara</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma"ra</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Icel. <ets>mara</ets> nightmare, an ogress. See <er>Nightmare</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Norse Myth.)</fld> <def>A female demon who torments people in sleep by crouching on their chests or stomachs, or by causing terrifying visions.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mara</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma"ra</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The Patagonian cavy, a hare-like rodent (<spn>Dolichotis patagonum</spn> or <spn>Dolichotis Patagonicus</spn>) of the pampas of Argentina.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marabou</ent><br/
<hw>Mar`a*bou"</hw> <pr>(m<acr/r"<adot/b<oomac/")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A large black-and-white carrion-eating stork of the genus <gen>Leptoptilos</gen> (formerly <spn>Ciconia</spn>), esp. the African species (<spn>Leptoptilus crumeniferus</spn> syn. <spn>Leptoptilos crumenifer</spn>), whose downy under-wing feathers are used to trim garments; called also <altname>marabout</altname>.  The Asiatic species (<spn>Leptoptilos dubius</spn>, or <spn>Leptoptilos argala</spn>) is the adjutant. See <er>Adjutant</er>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>marabu</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One having five eighths negro blood; the offspring of a mulatto and a griffe.</def> <mark>[Louisiana]</mark>  <rj><au>Bartlett.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A kind of thrown raw silk, nearly white naturally, but capable of being dyed without scouring; also, a thin fabric made from it, as for scarfs, which resembles the feathers of the marabou in delicacy, -- whence the name.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marabout</ent><br/
<hw>Marabout"</hw> <pr>(m<acr/r"<adot/b<oomac/t")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., from Pg. <ets>marabuto</ets>, Ar. <ets>mor<amac/bit</ets>.  Cf. <er>Maravedi</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A Muslim saint; especially, one who claims to work cures supernaturally.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The <er>marabou</er>{1}.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maracan</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"a*can</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Braz. <ets>maracan<aacute/</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A macaw.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marai</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*rai"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A sacred inclosure or temple; -- so called by the islanders of the Pacific Ocean.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maranatha</ent><br/
<hw>Mar`a*nath"a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Aramaic <ets>m<amac/ran ath<amac/</ets>.]</ety> <def><ldquo/Our Lord cometh;<rdquo/ -- an expression used by St. Paul at the conclusion of his first Epistle to the Corinthians (xvi. 22). This word has been used in anathematizing persons for great crimes; as much as to say, <ldquo/May the Lord come quickly to take vengeance of thy crimes.<rdquo/ See <cref>Anathema maranatha</cref>, under <er>Anathema</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marang tree</ent><br/
<hw>marang tree</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A Philippine tree (<spn>Artocarpus odoratissima</spn>) similar to the breadfruit tree bearing edible fruit.  Called also <altname>marang</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maranta</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*ran"ta</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[NL.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of endogenous plants found in tropical America, and some species also in India.  They have tuberous roots containing a large amount of starch, and from one species (<spn>Maranta arundinacea</spn>, the <member>American arrowroot</member> or <member>obedience plant</member>) <prod>arrowroot</prod> (<prod>arrowroot starch</prod>) is obtained.  Many kinds are cultivated for ornament.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marantaceae</ent><br/
<hw>Marantaceae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of tropical perennial herbs with usually starchy rhizomes, including the arrowroot; the arrowroot family.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Marantaceae</fam>, arrowroot family.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marasca</ent><br/
<hw>marasca</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The small bitter fruit of the <prodby>marasca cherry</prodby> tree from whose juice maraschino liqueur is made.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The <er>marasca cherry</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> marasca cherry, maraschino cherry, Prunus cerasus marasca.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marasca cherry</ent><br/
<hw>marasca cherry</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A Dalmation bitter wild cherry tree (<spn>Prunus cerasus</spn> <varn>marasca</varn>) bearing fruit whose juice is made into maraschino liqueur.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> marasca, maraschino cherry.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maraschino</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma`ra*schi"no</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It., fr. <ets>marasca</ets>, <ets>amarasca</ets>, a sour cherry, L. <ets>amarus</ets> bitter.]</ety> <def>A liqueur distilled from fermented cherry juice, and flavored with the pit of a variety of cherry which grows in Dalmatia.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maraschino cherry</ent><br/
<hw>ma`ra*schi"no cher"ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A cherry which is colored a deep red and sweetened by cooking in colored syrup, and flavored with maraschino.  It is used as a garnish in deserts and cocktails.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The <er>marasca cherry</er> tree.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marasmius</ent><br/
<hw>Marasmius</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of chiefly small white-spored mushrooms, including the <styp><spn>Marasmius oreades</spn></styp>, the mushroon that grow in a <er>fairy ring</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Marasmius</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marasmus</ent><br/
<hw>ma*ras"mus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ , fr. <?/, to quench, as fire; pass., to die away.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A wasting of flesh without fever or apparent disease; a kind of consumption; atrophy; phthisis.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Pining atrophy,<br/
<qex>Marasmus</qex>, and wide-wasting pestilence.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Marasmus senilis</b></col> <ety>[L.]</ety>, <cd>progressive atrophy of the aged.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mahratta</ent><br/
<ent>Marathi</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Ma*ra"thi</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mah*rat"ta</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A Sanskritic language of western India, prob. descended from the Maharastri Prakrit, spoken by the Marathas and neighboring peoples.  It has an abundant literature dating from the 13th century.  It has a book alphabet nearly the same as Devanagari and a cursive script translation between the Devanagari and the Gujarati.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marathon</ent><br/
<hw>marathon</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A footrace of 26 miles 385 yards.</def> <wns>[wns=2]</wns><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>Any long and arduous undertaking, straining the endurance of the participants.</def> <wns>[wns=1]</wns><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> endurance contest.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <mark>(Capitalized)</mark><def>a battle in 490 BC in which the Athenians and their allies defeated the Persians.</def> <wns>[wns=3]</wns><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> battle of Marathon.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marattia</ent><br/
<hw>Marattia</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The type genus of the <fam>Marattiaceae</fam>, consisting of ferns having the sporangia fused together in two rows.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Marattia</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marattiaceae</ent><br/
<hw>Marattiaceae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The natural family of ferns coextensive with the order <ord>Marattiales</ord>, consisting of chiefly tropical eusporantiate ferns with gigantic fronds.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Marattiaceae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marattiales</ent><br/
<hw>Marattiales</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>An order of lower ferns coextensive with the family <fam>Marattiaceae</fam>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> order <ord>Marattiales</ord>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maraud</ent><br/
<hw>ma*raud"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Marauded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Marauding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>marauder</ets>, fr. <ets>maraud</ets> vagabond, OF. <ets>marault</ets>; of uncertain origin, perh. for <ets>malault</ets>, fr. (assumed) LL. <ets>malaldus</ets>; fr. L. <ets>malus</ets> bad, ill + a suffix of German origin (cf. <er>Herald</er>).  Cf. <er>Malice</er>.]</ety> <def>To rove in quest of plunder; to make an excursion for booty; to plunder.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Marauding</xex> hosts.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Milman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maraud</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*raud"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An excursion for plundering.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marauder</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*raud`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Maraud</er>, <pos>v.</pos>: cf. F. <ets>maraudeur</ets>.]</ety> <def>A rover in quest of booty or plunder; a plunderer; one who pillages.</def>  <rj><au>De Quincey.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maravedi</ent><br/
<hw>Mar`a*ve"di</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>maraved<iacute/</ets>; -- so called from the <ets>Mor<amac/bit<imac/n</ets> (lit., the steadfast), an Arabian dynasty which reigned in Africa and Spain.  Cf. <er>Marabout</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Numis.)</fld> <def>A small copper coin of Spain, equal to three mils American money, less than a farthing sterling.  Also, an ancient Spanish gold coin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maravilla</ent><br/
<hw>maravilla</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A wildflower (<spn>Mirabilis multiflora</spn>) having vibrant deep pink tubular evening-blooming flowers; found in sandy and desert areas from Southern California to Southern Colorado and into Mexico.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> desert four o'clock, Colorado four o'clock, <spn>Mirabilis multiflora</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A leafy wildflower (<spn>Mirabilis longiflora</spn>) having fragrant slender white or pale pink trumpet-shaped flowers; found in the Southwestern US and Northern Mexico.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> sweet four o'clock, <spn>Mirabilis longiflora</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marble</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ble</hw> <pr>(m<aum/r"b'l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>marbel</ets>, <ets>marbre</ets>, F. <ets>marbre</ets>, L. <ets>marmor</ets>, fr. Gr. <grk>ma`rmaros</grk>, fr. <grk>marmai`rein</grk> to sparkle, flash.  Cf. <er>Marmoreal</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A massive, compact limestone; a variety of calcite, capable of being polished and used for architectural and ornamental purposes. The color varies from white to black, being sometimes yellow, red, and green, and frequently beautifully veined or clouded. The name is also given to other rocks of like use and appearance, as serpentine or verd antique marble, and less properly to polished porphyry, granite, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <col><b>Breccia marble</b></col> consists of limestone fragments cemented together. -- <col><b>Ruin marble</b></col>, when polished, shows forms resembling ruins, due to disseminated iron oxide. -- <col><b>Shell marble</b></col> contains fossil shells. -- <col><b>Statuary marble</b></col> is a pure, white, fine-grained kind, including <xex>Parian</xex> (from Paros) and <xex>Carrara</xex> marble. If coarsely granular it is called <xex>saccharoidal</xex>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A thing made of, or resembling, marble, as a work of art, or record, in marble; or, in the plural, a collection of such works; <as>as, the Arundel or Arundelian <ex>marbles</ex>; the Elgin <ex>marbles</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A little ball of glass, marble, porcelain, or of some other hard substance, used as a plaything by children; or, in the plural, a child's game played with marbles.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Marble</xex> is also much used in self-explaining compounds; when used figuratively in compounds it commonly means, hard, cold, destitute of compassion or feeling; as, <xex>marble-</xex>breasted, <xex>marble-</xex>faced, <xex>marble-</xex>hearted.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marble</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ble</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Made of, or resembling, marble; <as>as, a <ex>marble</ex> mantel; <ex>marble</ex> paper.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Cold; hard; unfeeling; <as>as, a <ex>marble</ex> breast or heart</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marble</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ble</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Marbled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Marbling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>marbrer</ets>. See <er>Marble</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To stain or vein like marble; to variegate in color; <as>as, to <ex>marble</ex> the edges of a book, or the surface of paper</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marbled</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"bled</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Made of, or faced with, marble.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/The <er>marbled</er> mansion.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Made to resemble marble; veined or spotted like marble.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Marbled</xex> paper.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Boyle.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Varied with irregular markings, or witch a confused blending of irregular spots and streaks.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Having small flecks of fat interspered with the muscle; -- of cuts of meat, especially beef; <as>as, a well-<ex>marbled</ex> steak</as>.  Such marbling improves the flavor of beef for most people.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marble cake</ent><br/
<hw>marble cake</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A made of light and dark batter very lightly blended, so as to produce a variegated appearance resembling that of marble.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marble-edged</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ble-edged`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having the edge veined or spotted with different colors like marble, as a book.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marbleize</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ble*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Marbleized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Marbleizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To stain or grain in imitation of marble; to cover with a surface resembling marble; <as>as, to <ex>marbleize</ex> slate, wood, or iron</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marbleizing</ent><br/
<hw>marbleizing</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A texture like that of marble.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marbler</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"bler</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who works upon marble or other stone.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who colors or stains in imitation of marble.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marbles</ent><br/
<hw>marbles</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A children's game played with marbles{3}, little balls made of a hard substance (as glass).</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marblewood</ent><br/
<hw>marblewood</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A hard marbled wood.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A large Asiatic tree (<spn>Diospyros kurzii</spn>) having hard marbled zebrawood.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Andaman marble, Andaman marble, <spn>Diospyros kurzii</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marbling</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"bling</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The art or practice of variegating in color, in imitation of marble.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An intermixture of fat and lean in meat, giving it a marbled appearance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Distinct markings resembling the variegations of marble, as on birds and insects.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marbly</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"bly</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Containing, or resembling, marble.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marbrinus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mar*bri"nus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL., fr. OF. & F. <ets>marble</ets> marble. See <er>Marble</er>.]</ety> <def>A cloth woven so as to imitate the appearance of marble; -- much used in the 15th and 16th centuries.</def>  <rj><au>Beck (Draper's Dict.).</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marc</ent><br/
<hw>Marc</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>The refuse matter which remains after the pressure of fruit, particularly of grapes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marc</ent><br/
<hw>Marc</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>marc</ets>; akin to G. <ets>mark</ets>, Icel. <ets>m<oum/rk</ets>, perh. akin to E. <ets>mark</ets> a sign. <root/106, 273.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mark</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A weight of various commodities, esp. of gold and silver, used in different European countries. In France and Holland it was equal to eight ounces.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A coin formerly current in England and Scotland, equal to thirteen shillings and four pence.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A German coin and money of account. See <er>Mark</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marcantant</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"can*tant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It. <ets>mercatante</ets>. See <er>Merchant</er>.]</ety> <def>A merchant.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marcasite</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ca*site</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>marcassite</ets>; cf. It. <ets>marcassita</ets>, Sp. <ets>marquesita</ets>, Pg. <ets>marquezita</ets>; all fr. Ar. <ets>marqash<imac/tha</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A sulphide of iron resembling pyrite or common iron pyrites in composition, but differing in form; white iron pyrites.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Golden marcasite</b></col>, <cd>tin.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marcasitical</ent><br/
<ent>Marcasitic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mar`ca*sit"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mar`ca*sit"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Containing, or having the nature of, marcasite.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marcassin</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*cas"sin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>A young wild boar.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marcato</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mar*ca"to</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[It.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>In a marked emphatic manner; -- used adverbially as a direction.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marceline</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"cel*ine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>marcidus</ets> withered, fr. <ets>marcere</ets> to wither, shrivel.]</ety> <def>A thin silk fabric used for linings, etc., in ladies' dresses.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marcel Proust</ent><br/
<hw>Marcel Proust</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A French novelist (1871-1922).</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marcescent</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*ces"cent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>marcescens</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>marcescere</ets> to wither, decay, fr. <ets>marcere</ets> to wither, droop: cf. F. <ets>marcescent</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Withering without falling off; fading; decaying.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marcescible</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*ces"ci*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>marcescible</ets>.]</ety> <def>Liable to wither or decay.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>March</ent><br/
<hw>March</hw> <pr>(m<aum/rch)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>Martius mensis</ets> Mars'month fr. <ets>Martius</ets> belonging to <ets>Mars</ets>, the god of war: cf. F. <ets>mars</ets>.  Cf. <er>Martial</er>.]</ety> <def>The third month of the year, containing thirty-one days.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The stormy <qex>March</qex> is come at last,<br/
With wind, and cloud, and changing skies.</q> <rj><qau>Bryant.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>As mad as a March Hare</b></col>, <cd>an old English Saying derived from the fact that March is the rutting time of hares, when they are excitable and violent.</cd>  <rj><au>Wright.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>March</ent><br/
<hw>March</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>marche</ets>, F. <ets>marche</ets>; of German origin; cf. OHG. <ets>marcha</ets>, G. <ets>mark</ets>, akin to OS. <ets>marka</ets>, AS. <ets>mearc</ets>, Goth. <ets>marka</ets>, L. <ets>margo</ets> edge, border, margin, and possibly to E. <ets>mark</ets> a sign. <root/106.  Cf. <er>Margin</er>, <er>Margrave</er>, <er>Marque</er>, <er>Marquis</er>.]</ety> <def>A territorial border or frontier; a region adjacent to a boundary line; a confine; -- used chiefly in the plural, and in English history applied especially to the border land on the frontiers between England and Scotland, and England and Wales.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Geneva is situated in the <qex>marches</qex> of several dominions -- France, Savoy, and Switzerland.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lords of waste <qex>marches</qex>, kings of desolate isles.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>March</ent><br/
<hw>March</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>marchir</ets>. See 2d <er>March</er>.]</ety> <def>To border; to be contiguous; to lie side by side.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That was in a strange land<br/
Which <qex>marcheth</qex> upon Chimerie.</q> <rj><qau>Gower.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To march with</b></col>, <cd>to have the same boundary for a greater or less distance; -- said of an estate.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>March</ent><br/
<hw>March</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Marched</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Marching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>marcher</ets>, in OF. also, to tread, prob. fr. L. <ets>marcus</ets> hammer.  Cf. <er>Mortar</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To move with regular steps, as a soldier; to walk in a grave, deliberate, or stately manner; to advance steadily.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To proceed by walking in a body or in military order; <as>as, the German army <er>marched</er> into France</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>March</ent><br/
<hw>March</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cause to move with regular steps in the manner of a soldier; to cause to move in military array, or in a body, as troops; to cause to advance in a steady, regular, or stately manner; to cause to go by peremptory command, or by force.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>March</qex> them again in fair array.</q> <rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>March</ent><br/
<hw>March</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>marche</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of marching; a movement of soldiers from one stopping place to another; military progress; advance of troops.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These troops came to the army harassed with a long and wearisome <qex>march</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence: Measured and regular advance or movement, like that of soldiers moving in order; stately or deliberate walk; steady onward movement; <as>as, the <ex>march</ex> of time</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With solemn <qex>march</qex><br/
Goes slow and stately by them.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This happens merely because men will not bide their time, but will insist on precipitating the <qex>march</qex> of affairs.</q> <rj><qau>Buckle.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The distance passed over in marching; <as>as, an hour's <ex>march</ex>; a <ex>march</ex> of twenty miles.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A piece of music designed or fitted to accompany and guide the movement of troops; a piece of music in the march form.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The drums presently striking up a <qex>march</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Knolles.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To make a march</b></col>, <fld>(Card Playing)</fld>, <cd>to take all the tricks of a hand, in the game of euchre.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marchand de vin</ent><br/
<hw>marchand de vin</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Cookery)</fld> <def>A sauce consisting of brown sauce with mushrooms and red wine or madeira.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mushroom wine sauce.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marchantia</ent><br/
<hw>Marchantia</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The type genus of <fam>Marchantiaceae</fam>; liverworts that reproduce asexually by gemmae and have stalked antheridiophores.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Marchantia</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marchantiaceae</ent><br/
<hw>Marchantiaceae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of liverworts with prostrate and usually dichotomously branched thalli.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Marchantiaceae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marchantiales</ent><br/
<hw>Marchantiales</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>An oder of liverworts with gametophyte differentiated internally.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> order <ord>Marchantiales</ord>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>march equinox</ent><br/
<hw>march equinox</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The <er>vernal equinox</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marcher</ent><br/
<hw>March"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who marches.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marcher</ent><br/
<hw>March"er</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See 2d <er>March</er>.]</ety> <def>The lord or officer who defended the marches or borders of a territory.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merchet</ent><br/
<ent>Marchet</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mar"chet</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mer"chet</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>marcheta</ets>; of uncertain origin.]</ety> <def>In old English and in Scots law, a fine paid to the lord of the soil by a tenant upon the marriage of one the tenant's daughters.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marching</ent><br/
<hw>March"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <def><pos>a. & n.</pos>, fr. <er>March</er>, <pos>v.</pos></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Marching money</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>the additional pay of officer or soldier when his regiment is marching.</cd> -- <col><b>In marching order</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>equipped for a march.</cd> -- <col><b>Marching regiment</b></col>. <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A regiment in active service</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>In England, a regiment liable to be ordered into other quarters, at home or abroad; a regiment of the line.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marchioness</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"chion*ess</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>marchionissa</ets>, fr. <ets>marchio</ets> a marquis. See <ets>Marquis</ets>.]</ety> <def>The wife or the widow of a marquis; a woman who has the rank and dignity of a marquis.</def>  <rj><au>Spelman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>March-mad</ent><br/
<hw>March"-mad`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Extremely rash; foolhardy. See under <er>March</er>, the month.</def>  <rj><au>Sir W. Scott.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marchman</ent><br/
<hw>March"man</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A person living in the marches between England and Scotland or Wales.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marchpane</ent><br/
<hw>March"pane`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. It. <ets>marzapane</ets>,Sp. <ets>pan</ets>,. <ets>massepain</ets>, prob. fr. L. <ets>maza</ets> frumenty (Gr. <grk>ma^za</grk>) + L. <ets>panis</ets> bread; but perh. the first part of the word is from the name of the inventor.]</ety> <def>A kind of sweet bread or biscuit; a cake of pounded almonds and sugar.  Called also <altname>marzipan</altname>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>March-ward</ent><br/
<hw>March"-ward`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A warden of the marches; a marcher.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marcian</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"cian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Under the influence of Mars; courageous; bold.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marcid</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"cid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>marcidus</ets>, fr. <ets>marcere</ets> to wither, pine.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Pining; lean; withered.</def>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Characterized by emaciation, as a fever.</def>  <rj><au>Harvey.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marcidity</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*cid"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>marciditas</ets>.]</ety> <def>The state or quality of being withered or lean.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 895 --></p>

<p><ent>Marcionite</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"cion*ite</hw> <pr>(m<aum/r"sh<ucr/n*<imac/t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Eccl. Hist)</fld> <def>A follower of <persfn>Marcion</persfn>, a Gnostic of the second century, who adopted the Oriental notion of the two conflicting principles, and imagined that between them there existed a third power, neither wholly good nor evil, the Creator of the world and of man, and the God of the Jewish dispensation.</def>  <rj><au>Brande & C.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marcobrunner</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mar`co*brun"ner</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G. <ets>Marcobrunner</ets>.]</ety> <def>A celebrated Rhine wine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marconi</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*co"ni</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <ety>[After <person>Guglielmo <ets>Marconi</ets></person> (b. 1874), Italian inventor.]</ety> <def>Designating, or pert. to, Marconi's system of wireless telegraphy; <as>as, <ex>Marconi</ex> aerial, coherer, station, system, etc.</as> <mark>[archaic]</mark> </def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marconigram</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*co"ni*gram</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>  <ety>[<etsep>Marconi</etsep> + <ets>-gram</ets>.]</ety> <def>same as <er>radiogram</er>; a wireless message.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marconigraph</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*co"ni*graph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>  <ety>[<ets>Marconi</ets> + <ets>-graph</ets>.]</ety> <def>The apparatus used in Marconi wireless telegraphy.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marconi rig</ent><br/
<hw>marconi rig</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A rig of triangular sails for a yacht.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Bermuda rig, Bermudan rig, Bermudian rig.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marconi's law</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*co"ni's law</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Wireless Teleg.)</fld> <def>The law that the maximum good signaling distance varies directly as the square of the height of the transmitting antenna.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marconism</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*co"nism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The theory or practice of Marconi's wireless telegraph system.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark> <br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marconi system</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*co"ni system</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>A system or wireless telegraphy developed by <person>G. <etsep>Marconi</etsep></person>, an Italian physicist, in which Hertzian waves are used in transmission and a coherer is used as the receiving instrument.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marco polo's sheep</ent><br/
<ent>marco polo sheep</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>marco polo sheep</hw>, <hw>marco polo's sheep</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>An Asiatic wild sheep (<spn>Ovis poli</spn>) with exceptionally large horns; sometimes considered a variety of the argali: <spn>Ovis ammon</spn> <varn>poli</varn>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marcor</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mar"cor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. <ets>marcere</ets> to wither.]</ety> <def>A wasting away of flesh; decay.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marcosian</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*co"sian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>One of a Gnostic sect of the second century, so called from <xex>Marcus</xex>, an Egyptian, who was reputed to be a margician.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mardi gras</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mar"di` gras"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., literally, fat Tuesday.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The last day of Carnival; the Tuesday before Ash Wednesday (the beginning of Lent and fasting); Shrove Tuesday; -- in some cities a great day of carnival and merrymaking; in the United States it is especially associated with <city>New Orleans</city>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> pancake day.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The series of festival events celebrated on <er>Mardi Gras</er>{1}.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mare</ent><br/
<hw>Mare</hw> <pr>(m<acir/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mere</ets>, AS.  <ets>mere</ets>, <ets>myre</ets>, fem of AS. <ets>mearh</ets> horse, akin to D. <ets>merrie</ets> mare, G. <ets>m<aum/hre</ets>, OHG. <ets>marah</ets> horse, <ets>meriha</ets> mare, Icel. <ets>marr</ets> horse, OCelt. <ets>marka</ets> (Pausan. 19, 19,4), Ir. <ets>marc</ets>, W. <ets>march</ets>.  Cf. <er>Marshal</er>.]</ety> <def>The female of the horse and other equine quadrupeds.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mare</ent><br/
<hw>Mare</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>mara</ets> incubus; akin to OHG. & Icel. <ets>mara</ets>; cf. Pol. <ets>mora</ets>, Bohem. <ets>m<uring/ra</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Sighing, suffocative panting, intercepted utterance, with a sense of pressure across the chest, occurring during sleep; the incubus; -- obsolete, except in the compound <xex>nightmare</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will ride thee o' nights like the <qex>mare</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marechal Niel</ent><br/
<hw>Mare"chal Niel"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>A kind of large yellow rose.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>Marshal Niel</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mare clausum</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma"re clau"sum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[L.]</ety> <fld>(Internat. Law)</fld> <def>Lit., closed sea; hence, a body of water within the separate jurisdiction of the nation; -- opposed to <contr>open sea</contr> (<contr>mare liberum</contr>), the water open to all nations and over which no single nation has special control.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mareis</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"eis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A Marsh.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mare liberum</ent><br/
<hw>mare liberum</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., free sea.]</ety> <def>A navigable body of water to which all nations have equal access; the opposite of <contr>mare clausum</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marena</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*re"na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. <ets>Salmo maraena</ets>, G. <ets>mar<aum/ne</ets>, <ets>mor<aum/ne</ets>; -- so called from Lake <etsep>Morin</etsep>, in the March of Brandenburg, in Prussia.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A European whitefish of the genus <gen>Coregonus</gen>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mare nostrum</ent><br/
<hw>mare nostrum</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. our sea.]</ety> <def>The term used by the ancient Romans to refer to the <sig>Mediterranean Sea</sig>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mareschal</ent><br/
<hw>Mare"schal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>mareschal</ets>, F. <ets>mar<eacute/chal</ets>. See <er>Marshal</er>.]</ety> <def>A military officer of high rank; a marshal.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mare's-nest</ent><br/
<hw>mare's"-nest`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A supposed discovery which turns out to be a hoax; something grossly absurd.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A confused multitude of things.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> clutter, jumble, muddle, welter, smother.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mare's-tail</ent><br/
<hw>Mare's"-tail`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A long streaky cloud, spreading out like a horse's tail, and believed to indicate rain; a cirrus cloud. See <er>Cloud</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mackerel sky and <qex>mare's-tails</qex><br/
Make tall ships carry low sails.</q> <rj><qau>Old Rhyme.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>An aquatic plant of the genus <gen>Hippuris</gen> (<spn>Hippuris vulgaris</spn>), having narrow leaves in whorls.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margarate</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ga*rate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>margarate</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol. Chem.)</fld> <def>A compound of the so-called margaric acid with a base.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margaric</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*gar"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>margarique</ets>. See <er>Margarite</er>.]</ety> <def>Pertaining to, or resembling, pearl; pearly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Margaric acid</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Physiol. Chem.)</fld> <cd>A fatty body, crystallizing in pearly scales, and obtained by digesting saponified fats (soaps) with an acid. It was formerly supposed to be an individual fatty acid, but is now known to be simply an intimate mixture of stearic and palmitic acids.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <cd>A white, crystalline substance, <chform>C17H34O2</chform> of the <isa>fatty acid</isa> series, intermediate between palmitic and stearic acids, and obtained from the wax of certain lichens, from cetyl cyanide, and other sources.  Called also <altname>heptadecanoic acid</altname>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margarin</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ga*rin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>margarine</ets>. See <er>Margarite</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol. Chem.)</fld> <def>A fatty substance, extracted from animal fats and certain vegetable oils, formerly supposed to be a definite compound of glycerin and margaric acid, but now known to be simply a mixture or combination of tristearin and tripalmitin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margarine</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ga*rine</hw> <pr>(m<aum/r"j<ucr/*r<icr/n; m<aum/r`j<ucr/*r<emac/n")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.; see <er>margarin</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A processed food product used as an inexpensive substitute for butter, made primarily from refined vegetable oils, sometimes including animal fats, and churned with skim milk to form a semisolid emulsion; also called <altname>oleomargarine</altname>; artificial butter.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>The word <qex>margarine</qex> shall mean all substances, whether compounds or otherwise, prepared in imitation of butter, and whether mixed with butter or not.</q>  <rj><qau>Margarine Act, 1887 (50 & 51 Vict. c. 29).</qau></rj><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>Margarin.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margaritaceous</ent><br/
<hw>Mar`ga*ri*ta"ceous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to, or resembling, pearl; pearly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margarite</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ga*rite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>margarita</ets>, Gr. <?/ a pearl; cf. F. <ets>marguerite</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A pearl.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Peacham.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A mineral related to the micas, but low in silica and yielding brittle folia with pearly luster.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margaritic</ent><br/
<hw>Mar`ga*rit"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>margaritique</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol. Chem.)</fld> <def>Margaric.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margaritiferous</ent><br/
<hw>Mar`ga*ri*tif"er*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>margaritifer</ets>; <ets>margarita</ets> pearl + <ets>ferre</ets> to bear: cf. F. <ets>margaritif<egrave/re</ets>.]</ety> <def>Producing pearls.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margarodite</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*gar"o*dite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ pearl-like.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A hidrous potash mica related to muscovite.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margarone</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ga*rone</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Margar</ets>ic + <ets>-one</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>The ketone of margaric acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margarous</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ga*rous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Margaric; -- formerly designating a supposed acid.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margary's fluid</ent><br/
<ent>Margaryize</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ga*ry*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>  <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>-ized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>-izing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[(J. J. Lloyd) <etsep>Margary</etsep>, inventor of the process + <ets>-ize</ets>.]</ety> <def>To impregnate (wood) with a preservative solution of copper sulphate (often called <hw>Mar"ga*ry's flu"id</hw> <pr>(-r<icr/z)</pr>).</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margate fish</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"gate fish"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A sparoid fish (<spn>Diabasis aurolineatus</spn>) of the Gulf of Mexico, esteemed as a food fish; -- called also <altname>red-mouth grunt</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>margay cat</ent><br/
<ent>Margay</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Mar"gay</hw>, <hw>margay cat</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A small American wild cat (<spn>Felis wiedi</spn> syn. <spn>Felis tigrina</spn>), ranging from Mexico to Brazil.  It is spotted with black.  Called also <altname>long-tailed cat</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marge</ent><br/
<hw>Marge</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>marge</ets>. See <er>Margin</er>.]</ety> <def>Border; margin; edge; verge.</def> <mark>[Poetic]</mark>  <rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Along the river's stony <qex>marge</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margent</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"gent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. See <er>Margin</er>.]</ety> <def>A margin; border; brink; edge.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The beached <qex>margent</qex> of the sea.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margent</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"gent</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To enter or note down upon the margin of a page; to margin.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Mir. for Mag.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margin</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"gin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>margine</ets>, <ets>margent</ets>, L. <ets>margo</ets>, <ets>ginis</ets>.  Cf. <er>March</er> a border, <er>Marge</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A border; edge; brink; verge; <as>as, the <ex>margin</ex> of a river or lake</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Specifically: The part of a page at the edge left uncovered in writing or printing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Com.)</fld> <def>The difference between the cost and the selling price of an article.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Something allowed, or reserved, for that which can not be foreseen or known with certainty.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Brokerage)</fld> <def>Collateral security deposited with a broker to secure him from loss on contracts entered into by him on behalf of his principial, as in the speculative buying and selling of stocks, wheat, etc.  It is usually less than the full value of the security purchased, in which case it may be qualified by the portion of the full value required to be deposited; <as>as, to buy stocks on 50% <ex>margin</ex></as>.</def>  <rj><au>N. Biddle.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Margin draft</b></col> <fld>(Masonry)</fld>, <cd>a smooth cut margin on the face of hammer-dressed ashlar, adjacent to the joints.</cd> -- <col><b>Margin of a course</b></col> <fld>(Arch.)</fld>, <cd>that part of a course, as of slates or shingles, which is not covered by the course immediately above it. See 2d <er>Gauge</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Border; brink; verge; brim; rim.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margin</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"gin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Margined</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Marginging</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To furnish with a margin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To enter in the margin of a page.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>margin account</ent><br/
<hw>margin account</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Finance)</fld> <def>An account with a securities brokerage in which the broker extends credit.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marginal</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"gin*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>marginal</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a margin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Written or printed in the margin; <as>as, a <ex>marginal</ex> note or gloss</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>At the lower limit; barely sufficient; <as>as, of <ex>marginal</ex> utility</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marginal cost of production</ent><br/
<ent>marginal cost</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>marginal cost</hw>, <hw>marginal cost of production</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Economics)</fld> <def>The increase in total cost of production as a result of producing one more unit of output; since certain ovrhead costs are fixed, the <ex>marginal cost</ex> is almost aways less than the total per-unit cost of production averaged over all units produced.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> incremental cost, differential cost.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marginalia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mar`gi*na"li*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL.]</ety> <def>Marginal notes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marginality</ent><br/
<hw>marginality</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the property of being marginal or on the fringes.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marginally</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"gin*al*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>In the margin of a book.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In a <er>marginal</er>{3} manner; barely sufficiently; almost not; <as>as, <ex>marginally</ex> useful</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marginate</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"gin*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>marginatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>marginare</ets> to margin. See <er>Margin</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>Having a margin distinct in appearance or structure.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marginate</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"gin*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To furnish with a distinct margin; to margin.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Cockeram.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marginated</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"gin*a`ted</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Marginate</er>, <pos>a.</pos></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margined</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"gined</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having a margin.</def>  <rj><au>Hawthorne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Bordered with a distinct line of color.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>margin call</ent><br/
<hw>margin call</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Stock market)</fld> <def>A demand by a broker that a customer deposit enough to bring his margin up to the minimum requirement; -- caused by the decline in market prices of  a security or commodity purchased on margin{5}.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> call.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marginella</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mar`gi*nel"la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[NL., dim. of L. <ets>margo</ets>, <ets>marginis</ets>, a margin.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of small, polished, marine univalve shells, native of all warm seas.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marginicidal</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"gin*i*ci`dal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>margo</ets>, <ets>-ginis</ets>, margin + <ets>caedere</ets> to cut.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Dehiscent by the separation of united carpels; -- said of fruits.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margosa</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*go"sa</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pg. <ets>amargoso</ets> bitter.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A large tree of the genus <gen>Melia</gen> (<spn>Melia Azadirachta</spn>) found in India.  Its bark is bitter, and used as a tonic.  A valuable oil is expressed from its seeds, and a tenacious gum exudes from its trunk.  The <spn>Melia Azedarach</spn> is a much more showy tree, and is cultivated in the Southern United States, where it is known as <stype>Pride of India</stype>, <stype>Pride of China</stype>, or <stype>bead tree</stype>.  Various parts of the tree are considered anthelmintic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>margosa</qex> oil . . . is a most valuable balsam for wounds, having a peculiar smell which prevents the attacks of flies.</q> <rj><qau>Sir S. Baker.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margraviate</ent><br/
<ent>Margravate</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mar"gra*vate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mar*gra"vi*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>margraviat</ets>.]</ety> <def>The territory or jurisdiction of a margrave.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margrave</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"grave</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G. <ets>markgraf</ets>, prop., lord chief justice of the march; <ets>mark</ets> bound, border, march + <ets>graf</ets> earl, count, lord chief justice; cf. Goth. <ets>gagr<eum/fts</ets> decree: cf. D. <ets>markgraaf</ets>, F. <ets>margrave</ets>. See <er>March</er> border, and cf. <er>Landgrave</er>, <er>Graff</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Originally, a lord or keeper of the borders or marches in Germany.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The English equivalent of the German title of nobility, <xex>markgraf</xex>; a marquis.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Margravine</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"gra*vine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G. <ets>markgr<aum/fin</ets>: cf. F. <ets>margrafine</ets>.]</ety> <def>The wife of a margrave.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marguerite</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"gue*rite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., a pearl, a daisy. See <er>Margarite</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The daisy (<spn>Bellis perennis</spn>). The name is often applied also to the ox-eye daisy and to the China aster.</def>  <rj><au>Longfellow.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maria</ent><br/
<hw>maria</hw> <pos>n. pl.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>Plural form of <altname>mare</altname>, a dark region of considerable extent on the surface of the moon.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A valuable timber tree of Panama.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Calophyllum longifolium.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marian</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"ri*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to the <person>Virgin Mary</person>, or sometimes to <person>Mary, Queen of England</person>, daughter of <person>Henry VIII</person>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of all the <qex>Marian</qex> martyrs, Mr. Philpot was the best-born gentleman.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Maid Marian</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>See <er>Maidmarian</er> in the Vocabulary.</cd> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A prominent character in the legend of Robin Hood.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marie</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ie</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>interj.</pos> <def>Marry.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mariet</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"i*et</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mariette</ets>, prop. dim. of <ets>Marie</ets> Mary.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A kind of bellflower, <spn>Companula Trachelium</spn>, once called <spn>Viola Mariana</spn>; but it is not a violet.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marigenous</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*rig"e*nous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mare</ets> the sea + <ets>-genous</ets>.]</ety> <def>Produced in or by the sea.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marigold</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"i*gold</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mary</ets> + <ets>gold</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A name for several plants with golden yellow blossoms, especially the <spn>Calendula officinalis</spn> (see <er>Calendula</er>), and the cultivated species of <gen>Tagetes</gen>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ There are several yellow-flowered plants of different genera bearing this name; as, the <stype>African marigold</stype> <it>or</it> <stype>French marigold</stype> of the genus <gen>Tagetes</gen>, of which several species and many varieties are found in gardens. They are mostly strong-smelling herbs from South America and Mexico: <stype>bur marigold</stype>, of the genus <gen>Bidens</gen>; <stype>corn marigold</stype>, of the genus <gen>Chrysanthemum</gen> (<spn>Chrysanthemum segetum</spn>, a pest in the cornfields of Italy); <stype>fig marigold</stype>, of the genus <gen>Mesembryanthemum</gen>; <stype>marsh marigold</stype>, of the genus <gen>Caltha</gen> (<spn>Caltha palustris</spn>), commonly known in America as the <stype>cowslip</stype>. See <er>Marsh Marigold</er>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Marigold window</b></col>. <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <cd>See <cref>Rose window</cref>, under <er>Rose</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marijuana</ent><br/
<hw>marijuana</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A strong-smelling Asian plant (<spn>Cannabis sativa</spn>), also called <altname>hemp</altname>, from which a number of euphorogenic and halucinogenic drugs are prepared.  The euphoric effect is predominently due to <prod>tetrahydrocannabinol</prod> (<prod>THC</prod>).</def> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>marihuana</asp>.]</altsp><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> cannabis, ganja, pot, grass, marihuana, <spn>Cannabis sativa</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The dried leaves or the female flowers of the hemp plant, which is smoked or chewed to obtain a euphoric effect.  The flowers usually have a higher concentration of the active ingredient, tetrahydrocannabinol.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> cannabis, ganja, pot, grass, marihuana, dope, weed, gage, sess, sens, smoke, skunk, Mary Jane.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marikina</ent><br/
<hw>Mar`i*ki"na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From the native name: cf. Pg. <ets>mariquinha</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool)</fld> <def>A small marmoset (<spn>Midas rosalia</spn>); the silky tamarin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marimba</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*rim"ba</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pg.]</ety> <def>A musical istrument of percussion, consisting of bars yielding musical tones when struck.</def>  <rj><au>Knight.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marimonda</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mar`i*mon"da</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A spider monkey (<spn>Ateles belzebuth</spn>) of Central and South America.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marinade</ent><br/
<hw>Mar`i*nade"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.: cf. It. <ets>marinato</ets> marinade, F. <ets>mariner</ets> to preserve food for use at sea. See <er>Marinate</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Cookery)</fld> <def>A brine or pickle containing wine or vinegar, with opil, herbs, and spices, for enriching the flavor of meat and fish, which are steeped in it prior to cooking.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marinara</ent><br/
<hw>marinara</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>An Italian sauce containing tomatoes, garlic,  herbs, and spices.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marinara</ent><br/
<hw>marinara</hw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Served in marinara sauce; -- used postpositionally, as veal <ex>marinara</ex>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marinate</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"i*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Marine</er>, and cf. <er>Marinade</er>.]</ety> <def>To salt or pickle, as fish, and then preserve in oil or vinegar; to prepare (food) by the use of marinade.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marine</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*rine"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>marinus</ets>, fr. <ets>mare</ets> the sea: cf. F. <ets>marin</ets>. See <er>Mere</er> a pool.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the sea; having to do with the ocean, or with navigation or naval affairs; nautical; <as>as, <ex>marine</ex> productions or bodies; <ex>marine</ex> shells; a <ex>marine</ex> engine.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>Formed by the action of the currents or waves of the sea; <as>as, <ex>marine</ex> deposits</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Marine acid</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>hydrochloric acid.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> -- <col><b>Marine barometer</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Barometer</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Marine corps</b></col>, <cd>a corps formed of the officers, noncommissioned officers, privates, and musicants of marines.</cd><-- officially part of the navy, but now considered one of the four branches of the armed forces in the US --> -- <col><b>Marine engine</b></col> <fld>(Mech.)</fld>, <cd>a steam engine for propelling a vessel.</cd> -- <col><b>Marine glue</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Glue</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Marine insurance</b></col>, <cd>insurance against the perils of the sea, including also risks of fire, piracy, and barratry.</cd> -- <col><b>Marine interest</b></col>, <cd>interest at any rate agreed on for money lent upon respondentia and bottomry bonds.</cd> -- <col><b>Marine law</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Law</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Marine league</b></col>, <cd>three geographical miles.</cd> -- <col><b>Marine metal</b></col>, <cd>an alloy of lead, antimony, and mercury, made for sheathing ships.</cd> <au>Mc Elrath.</au> -- <col><b>Marine soap</b></col>, <cd>cocoanut oil soap; -- so called because, being quite soluble in salt water, it is much used on shipboard.</cd> -- <col><b>Marine store</b></col>, <cd>a store where old canvas, ropes, etc., are bought and sold; a junk shop.</cd> <mark>[Eng.]</mark></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marine</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*rine"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>marin</ets> a sea solider, <ets>marine</ets> naval economy, a marine picture, fr. L. <ets>marinus</ets>. See <er>Marine</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A solider serving on shipboard; a sea soldier; one of a body of troops trained to do duty in the navy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <def>A member of the United States Marine Corps, or a similar foreign military force.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The sum of naval affairs; naval economy; the department of navigation and sea forces; the collective shipping of a country; <as>as, the mercantile <ex>marine</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A picture representing some marine subject.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Tell that to the marines</b></col>, <cd>an expression of <sig>disbelief</sig>, the <xex>marines</xex> being regarded by sailors as credulous.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marined</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*rined"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>marin<eacute/</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>Having the lower part of the body like a fish.</def>  <rj><au>Crabb.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marine mine</ent><br/
<hw>ma*rine" mine`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A military explosive device designed to be placed on or under the surface of a body of water, and to explode when ships pass nearby or come in contact with it.  Its function is to destroy enemy ships or deny hostile naval forces access to certain areas of the sea, usually near the shoreline.  Also called <altname>underwater mine</altname> and <altname>floating mine</altname>, and previously referred to as a <altname>torpedo</altname> (See <er>torpedo</er>{2} <sd>(a)</sd>).</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mariner</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"i*ner</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>marinier</ets>, LL. <ets>marinarius</ets>. See <er>Marine</er>.]</ety> <def>One whose occupation is to assist in navigating ships; a seaman or sailor.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mariner's compass</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Compass</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marinership</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"i*ner*ship</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Seamanship.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Udalt.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marinism</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*ri"nism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A bombastic literary style marked by the use of metaphors and antitheses characteristic of the Italian poet <person>Giambattista Marini</person> (1569-1625).</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Ma*ri"nist</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marinorama</ent><br/
<hw>Mar`i*no*ra"ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., from L. <ets>marinus</ets> marine + Gr. <?/ view.]</ety> <def>A representation of a sea view.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mariolater</ent><br/
<hw>Ma`ri*ol"a*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mariolatry</er>.]</ety> <def>One who worships the Virgin Mary.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mariolatry</ent><br/
<hw>Ma`ri*ol"a*try</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ Mary + <?/ worship.]</ety> <def>The worship of the Virgin Mary.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marionette</ent><br/
<hw>Mar`i*o*nette"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>marionette</ets>, prop. a dim. of <ets>Marie</ets> Mary.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A puppet moved by strings, as in a puppet show.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The buffel duck.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mariotte's law</ent><br/
<hw>Ma`ri*otte's law`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Physics.)</fld> <def>See <cref>Boyle's law</cref>, under <er>Law</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mariposa lily</ent><br/
<hw>Ma`ri*po"sa lil`y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[Sp. <ets>mariposa</ets> a butterfly + E. <ets>lily</ets>. So called from the gay appearance of the blossoms.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>One of a genus (<gen>Calochortus</gen>) of tuliplike bulbous herbs with large, and often gaycolored, blossoms.  Called also <altname>butterfly lily</altname>.  Most of them are natives of California.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mariput</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"i*put</hw> <pr>(m<acr/r"<icr/*p<ucr/t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A species of civet; the zoril.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marish</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ish</hw> <pr>(m<acr/r"<icr/sh)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>marais</ets>, LL. <ets>marascus</ets>. See <er>Marsh</er>.]</ety> <def>Low, wet ground; a marsh; a fen; a bog; a moor.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>  <rj><au>Milton.</au>  <au>Tennyson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marish</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ish</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Moory; fenny; boggy.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Growing in marshes.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Marish</xex> flowers.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marital</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"i*tal</hw> <pr>(m<acr/r"<icr/*t<ait/l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>maritalis</ets>, fr. <ets>maritus</ets> belonging to marriage, <pos>n.</pos>, a husband. See <er>Marry</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a husband; <as>as, <ex>marital</ex> rights, duties, authority</as>.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark>  <ldquo/<xex>Marital</xex> affection.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Ayliffe.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to marriage; matrimonial.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maritated</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"i*ta`ted</hw> <pr>(m<acr/r"<icr/*t<amac/`t<ecr/d)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>maritatus</ets> married.]</ety> <def>Having a husband; married.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maritimale</ent><br/
<ent>Maritimal</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Ma*rit"i*mal</hw>, <hw>Ma*rit"i*male</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(m<adot/*r<icr/t"<icr/*m<ait/l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>See <er>Maritime</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maritime</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"i*time</hw> <pr>(m<acr/r"<icr/*t<imac/m, <it>formerly</it> m<acr/r"<icr/*t<icr/m; 277)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>maritimus</ets>, fr. <ets>mare</ets> the sea: cf. F. <ets>maritime</ets>. See <er>Mere</er> a pool.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Bordering on, or situated near, the ocean; connected with the sea by site, interest, or power; having shipping and commerce or a navy; <as>as, <ex>maritime</ex> states</as>.</def> <ldquo/A <xex>maritime</xex> town.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the ocean; marine; pertaining to navigation and naval affairs, or to shipping and commerce by sea.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Maritime</xex> service.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Sir H. Wotton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Maritime law</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Law</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Maritime loan</b></col>, <cd>a loan secured by bottomry or respodentia bonds.</cd> -- <col><b>Martime nations</b></col>, <cd>nations having seaports, and using the sea more or less for war or commerce.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maritimes</ent><br/
<ent>Maritime provinces</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Maritime provinces</hw>, <hw>Maritimes</hw></mhw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The Canadian provinces of New Brunswick and Nova Scotia and Prince Edward Island.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Maritime Provinces.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marjoram</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"jo*ram</hw> <pr>(m<aum/r"j<osl/*r<ait/m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>majoran</ets>, F. <ets>marjolaine</ets>, LL. <ets>marjoraca</ets>, fr. L. <ets>amaracus</ets>, <ets>amaracum</ets>, Gr. <grk>'ama`rakos</grk>, <grk>'ama`rakon</grk>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of mintlike plants (<gen>Origanum</gen>) comprising about twenty-five species.  The sweet marjoram (<spn>Origanum Majorana</spn>) is pecularly aromatic and fragrant, and much used in cookery.  The wild marjoram of Europe and America is <spn>Origanum vulgare</spn>, far less fragrant than the other.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mark</ent><br/
<hw>Mark</hw> <pr>(m<aum/rk)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A license of reprisals. See <er>Marque</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mark</ent><br/
<hw>Mark</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See 2d <er>Marc</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An old weight and coin. See <er>Marc</er>.</def> <ldquo/Lend me a <xex>mark</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The unit of monetary account of the German Empire, equal to 23.8 cents of United States money (1913); the equivalent of one hundred pfennigs.  Also, a silver coin of this value.  The unit was retained by subsequent German states up to the time of the Federal Republic of Germany.  In 1995, the value was approximately 65 cents American.  In 1999 it began to be superseded by the Euro as a unit of currency in Germany and throughout much of the European union.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mark</ent><br/
<hw>Mark</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>marke</ets>, <ets>merke</ets>, AS. <ets>mearc</ets>; akin to D. <ets>merk</ets>, MHG. <ets>marc</ets>, G. <ets>marke</ets>, Icel. <ets>mark</ets>, Dan. <ets>m<ae/rke</ets>; cf. Lith. <ets>margas</ets> party-colored. <root/106, 273.  Cf. <er>Remark</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A visible sign or impression made or left upon anything; esp., a line, point, stamp, figure, or the like, drawn or impressed, so as to attract the attention and convey some information or intimation; a token; a trace.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Lord set a <qex>mark</qex> upon Cain, lest any finding him should kill him.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. iv. 15.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 896 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A character or device put on an article of merchandise by the maker to show by whom it was made; a trade-mark.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A character (usually a cross) made as a substitute for a signature by one who can not write.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>mark</qex> of the artisan is found upon the most ancient fabrics that have come to light.</q> <rj><qau>Knight.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A fixed object serving for guidance, as of a ship, a traveler, a surveyor, etc.; <as>as, a sea<ex>mark</ex>, a land<ex>mark</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A trace, dot, line, imprint, or discoloration, although not regarded as a token or sign; a scratch, scar, stain, etc.; <as>as, this pencil makes a fine <ex>mark</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have some <qex>marks</qex> of yours upon my pate.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>An evidence of presence, agency, or influence; a significative token; a symptom; a trace; specifically, a permanent impression of one's activity or character.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The confusion of tongues was a <qex>mark</qex> of separation.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>That toward which a missile is directed; a thing aimed at; what one seeks to hit or reach.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>France was a fairer <qex>mark</qex> to shoot at than Ireland.</q> <rj><qau>Davies.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whate'er the motive, pleasure is the <qex>mark</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Attention, regard, or respect.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As much in mock as <qex>mark</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Limit or standard of action or fact; <as>as, to be within the <ex>mark</ex>; to come up to the <ex>mark</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Badge or sign of honor, rank, or official station.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the official <qex>marks</qex> invested, you<br/
Anon do meet the Senate.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>Preeminence; high position; <as>as, patricians of <ex>mark</ex>; a fellow of no <ex>mark</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <fld>(Logic)</fld> <def>A characteristic or essential attribute; a differential.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>A number or other character used in registering; <as>as, examination <ex>marks</ex>; a <ex>mark</ex> for tardiness.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <def>Image; likeness; hence, those formed in one's image; children; descendants.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/All the <xex>mark</xex> of Adam.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>One of the bits of leather or colored bunting which are placed upon a sounding line at intervals of from two to five fathoms. The unmarked fathoms are called <ldquo/deeps.<rdquo/</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>A man of mark</b></col>, <cd>a conspicuous or eminent man.</cd> -- <col><b>To make one's mark</b></col>. <fld>(a)</fld> <cd>To sign, as a letter or other writing, by making a cross or other mark.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To make a distinct or lasting impression on the public mind, or on affairs; to gain distinction.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Impress; impression; stamp; print; trace; vestige; track; characteristic; evidence; proof; token; badge; indication; symptom.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mark</ent><br/
<hw>Mark</hw> <pr>(m<aum/rk)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Marked</conjf> <pr>(m<aum/rkt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Marking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>marken</ets>, <ets>merken</ets>, AS. <ets>mearcian</ets>, from <ets>mearc</ets>. See <er>Mark</er> the sign.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To put a mark upon; to affix a significant mark to; to make recognizable by a mark; <as>as, to <ex>mark</ex> a box or bale of merchandise; to <ex>mark</ex> clothing.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be a mark upon; to designate; to indicate; -- used literally and figuratively; <as>as, this monument <ex>marks</ex> the spot where Wolfe died; his courage and energy <ex>marked</ex> him for a leader.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To leave a trace, scratch, scar, or other mark, upon, or any evidence of action; <as>as, a pencil <ex>marks</ex> paper; his hobnails <ex>marked</ex> the floor.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To keep account of; to enumerate and register; <as>as, to <ex>mark</ex> the points in a game of billiards or cards</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To notice or observe; to give attention to; to take note of; to remark; to heed; to regard; <as>as, <ex>mark</ex> my words</as>.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Mark</xex> the perfect man.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Ps. xxxvii. 37.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To mark out</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To designate, as by a mark; to select; as, the ringleaders were <xex>marked out</xex> for punishment</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To obliterate or cancel with a mark; as, to <xex>mark out</xex> an item in an account.</cd> -- <col><b>To mark time</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>to keep the time of a marching step by moving the legs alternately without advancing.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To note; remark; notice; observe; regard; heed; show; evince; indicate; point out; betoken; denote; characterize; stamp; imprint; impress; brand.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mark</ent><br/
<hw>Mark</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To take particular notice; to observe critically; to note; to remark.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mark</qex>, I pray you, and see how this man seeketh mischief.</q> <rj><qau>1 Kings xx. 7.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Markable</ent><br/
<hw>Mark"a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Remarkable.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sandys.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marked</ent><br/
<hw>Marked</hw> <pr>(m<aum/rkt)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Designated or distinguished by, or as by, a mark; hence; noticeable; conspicuous; <as>as, a <ex>marked</ex> card; a <ex>marked</ex> coin; a <ex>marked</ex> instance.</as></def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mark"ed*ly</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <au>J. S. Mill.</au></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>A marked man</b></col>, <cd>a man who is noted by a community, or by a part of it, as, for excellence or depravity; -- usually with an unfavorable suggestion.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Markee</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*kee"</hw> <pr>(m<aum/r*k<emac/")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Marquee</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marker</ent><br/
<hw>Mark"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who or that which marks.</def> Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>One who keeps account of a game played, as of billiards.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A counter used in card playing and other games.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>The soldier who forms the pilot of a wheeling column, or marks the direction of an alignment.</def> <sd>(d)</sd> <def>An attachment to a sewing machine for marking a line on the fabric by creasing it.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Market</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ket</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Akin to D. <ets>markt</ets>, OHG. <ets>mark<amac/t</ets>, <ets>merk<amac/t</ets>, G. <ets>markt</ets>; all fr.L. <ets>mercatus</ets> trade, market place, fr. <ets>mercari</ets>, p. p. <ets>mercatus</ets>, to trade, traffic, <ets>merx</ets>, <ets>mercis</ets>, ware, merchandise, prob. akin to <ets>merere</ets> to deserve, gain, acquire: cf. F. <ets>march<eacute/</ets>. See <er>Merit</er>, and cf. <er>Merchant</er>, <er>Mart</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A meeting together of people, at a stated time and place, for the purpose of buying and selling (as cattle, provisions, wares, etc.) by private purchase and sale, and not by auction; <as>as, a <ex>market</ex> is held in the town every week; a farmers' <ex>market</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He is wit's peddler; and retails his wares<br/
At wakes, and wassails, meetings, <qex>markets</qex>, fairs.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Three women and a goose make a <qex>market</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Old Saying.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A public place (as an open space in a town) or a large building, where a market is held; a market place or market house; esp., a place where provisions are sold.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is at Jerusalem by the sheep <qex>market</qex> a pool.</q> <rj><qau>John v. 2.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An opportunity for selling or buying anything; demand, as shown by price offered or obtainable; <as>as, to find a <ex>market</ex> for one's wares; there is no <ex>market</ex> for woolen cloths in that region; India is a <ex>market</ex> for English goods; there are none for sale on the <ex>market</ex>; the best price on the <ex>market</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is a third thing to be considered: how a <qex>market</qex> can be created for produce, or how production can be limited to the capacities of the <qex>market</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>J. S. Mill.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Exchange, or purchase and sale; traffic; <as>as, a dull <ex>market</ex>; a slow <ex>market</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The price for which a thing is sold in a market; market price. Hence: Value; worth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What is a man<br/
If his chief good and <qex>market</qex> of his time<br/
Be but to sleep and feed?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Eng. Law)</fld> <def>The privelege granted to a town of having a public market.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A specified group of potential buyers, or a region in which goods may be sold; a town, region, or country, where the demand exists; <as>as, the under-30 <ex>market</ex>; the New Jersey <ex>market</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Market</xex> is often used adjectively, or in forming compounds of obvious meaning; as, <xex>market</xex> basket, <xex>market</xex> day, <xex>market</xex> folk, <xex>market</xex> house, <xex>market</xex>man, <xex>market</xex> place, <xex>market</xex> price, <xex>market</xex> rate, <xex>market</xex> wagon, <xex>market</xex> woman, and the like.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Market beater</b></col>, <cd>a swaggering bully; a noisy braggart.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Chaucer.</au> -- <col><b>Market bell</b></col>, <cd>a bell rung to give notice that buying and selling in a market may begin.</cd> <mark>[Eng.]</mark> <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>Market cross</b></col>, <cd>a cross set up where a market is held.</cd> <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>Market garden</b></col>, <cd>a garden in which vegetables are raised for market.</cd> -- <col><b>Market gardening</b></col>, <cd>the raising of vegetables for market.</cd> -- <col><b>Market place</b></col>, <cd>an open square or place in a town where markets or public sales are held.</cd> -- <col><b>Market town</b></col>, <cd>a town that has the privilege of a stated public market.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Market</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ket</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Marketed</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Marketing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To deal in a market; to buy or sell; to make bargains for provisions or goods.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Market</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ket</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To expose for sale in a market; to traffic in; to sell in a market, and in an extended sense, to sell in any manner; <as>as, most of the farmes have <ex>marketed</ex> their crops</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Industrious merchants meet, and <qex>market</qex> there<br/
The world's collected wealth.</q> <rj><qau>Southey.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marketable</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ket*a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Fit to be offered for sale in a market; such as may be justly and lawfully sold; <as>as, dacayed provisions are not <ex>marketable</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Current in market; <as>as, <ex>marketable</ex> value</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Wanted by purchasers; salable; <as>as, furs are not <ex>marketable</ex> in that country</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marketableness</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ket*a*ble*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Quality of being marketable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marketer</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ket*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who attends a market to buy or sell; one who carries goods to market.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marketplace</ent><br/
<hw>marketplace</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>an area in a town where a public market is set up; a <cref>market place</cref>; a <er>market</er>{2}.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mart.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The commercial activity whereby good and services are exchanged; <as>as, without competition there would be no <ex>market</ex></as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> market.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The mechanism by which one finds a person to whom to sell or from whom to buy goods; the opportunity to buy and sell; a <er>market</er>{3}; <as>as, to put one's goods on the <ex>market</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marketing</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ket*ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of selling or of purchasing in, or as in, a market.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Articles in, or from, a market; supplies.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The activities required by a producer to sell his products, including advertising, storing, taking orders, and distribution to vendors or individuals.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marketstead</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ket*stead</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Market</ets> + <ets>stead</ets> a place.]</ety> <def>A market place.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Drayton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>markhor</ent><br/
<ent>Markhoor</ent><br/
<mhw>\'d8<hw>Mark"hoor`</hw>, <hw>mark"hor`</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Per. <ets>m<amac/r-kh<omac/r</ets> snake eater.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A large wild goat (<spn>Capra falconeri</spn> syn. <spn>Capra megaceros</spn>), having huge flattened spiral horns.  It inhabits the mountains of Northern India and Cashmere.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marking</ent><br/
<hw>Mark"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of one who, or that which, marks; the mark or marks made; arrangement or disposition of marks or coloring; <as>as, the <ex>marking</ex> of a bird's plumage</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Marking ink</b></col>, <cd>indelible ink, because used in marking linen.</cd> -- <col><b>Marking nut</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the nut of the <spn>Semecarpus Anacardium</spn>, an East Indian tree. The shell of the nut yields a blackish resinous juice used for marking cotton cloth, and an oil prepared from it is used for rheumatism.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Markis</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"kis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A marquis.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Markisesse</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"kis*esse</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A marchioness.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Markman</ent><br/
<hw>Mark"man</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A marksman.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Markov chain</ent><br/
<hw>Mark"ov chain</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[after <person>A. A. <etsep>Markov</etsep></person>, Russian mathematician, b. 1856, d. 1922.]</ety> <fld>(Statistics)</fld> <def>A random process (<isa>Markov process</isa>) in which the probabilities of discrete states in a series depend only on the properties of the immediately preceding state or the next preceeding state, independent of the path by which the preceding state was reached.  It differs from the more general Markov process in that the states of a <ex>Markov chain</ex> are discrete rather than continuous. Certain physical processes, such as diffusion of a molecule in a fluid, are modelled as a <ex>Markov chain</ex>.  See also <styp><er>random walk</er></styp>.</def> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>Markoff chain</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Markov process</ent><br/
<hw>Mark"ov pro`cess</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[after <person>A. A. <etsep>Markov</etsep></person>, Russian mathematician, b. 1856, d. 1922.]</ety> <fld>(Statistics)</fld> <def>a random process in which the probabilities of states in a series depend only on the properties of the immediately preceding state or the next preceeding state, independent of the path by which the preceding state was reached.  It is distinguished from a <contr>Markov chain</contr> in that the states of a <ex>Markov process</ex> may be continuous as well as discrete.</def> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>Markoff process</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marksman</ent><br/
<hw>Marks"man</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Marksmen</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Earlier <ets>markman</ets>; <ets>mark</ets> + <ets>man</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One skillful to hit a mark with a missile; one who shoots well. especially with a pistol or rifle.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>One who makes his mark, instead of writing his name, in signing documents.</def>  <rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marksmanship</ent><br/
<hw>Marks"man*ship</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Skill of a marksman.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>markup</ent><br/
<hw>markup</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Commerce)</fld> <def>The amount added to the cost to determine the asking price.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(printing)</fld> <def>Instructions for the typesetter that are written on the copy (e.g. underlining words that are to be set in italics).</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Legislation)</fld> <def>Changes in proposed legislation drafted in conference, as contrasted with changes resulting from the amendment process.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>markweed</ent><br/
<hw>markweed</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A climbing plant (<spn>Toxicodendron radicans</spn>) common in eastern and central U. S. with ternate leaves and greenish flowers followed by white berries.  It yields an irritating oil that causes a rash on contact; commonly called <altname>poison ivy</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> poison ivy, poison mercury, poison oak, <spn>Toxicodendron radicans</spn>, <spn>Rhus radicans</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marl</ent><br/
<hw>Marl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Marline</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To cover, as part of a rope, with marline, marking a pecular hitch at each turn to prevent unwinding.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Marling spike</b></col>. <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Marline</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marl</ent><br/
<hw>Marl</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>marle</ets>, F. <ets>marne</ets>, LL. <ets>margila</ets>, dim. of L. <ets>marga</ets> marl. Originally a Celtic word, according to Pliny, xvii. 7: <ldquo/Quod genus terrae Galli et Britanni <ets>margam</ets> vocant.<rdquo/ <root/274.]</ety> <def>A mixed earthy substance, consisting of carbonate of lime, clay, and sand, in very variable proportions, and accordingly designated as calcareous, clayey, or sandy. See <er>Greensand</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marl</ent><br/
<hw>Marl</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Marled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Marling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>marner</ets>. See <er>Marl</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To overspread or manure with marl; <as>as, to <ex>marl</ex> a field</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marlaceous</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*la"ceous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Resembling marl; partaking of the qualities of marl.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marlin</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"lin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The American great marbled godwit (<spn>Limosa fedoa</spn>). Applied also to the red-breasted godwit (<spn>Limosa haematica</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[from <ets>marlin</ets> spike, the shape of its bill.]</ety> <def> Any of several marine billfishes of the genera <gen>Makaira</gen> and <gen>Tetrapturus</gen>, popular as game in sport fishing.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hook-billed marlin</b></col>, <cd>a curlew.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marline</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"line</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LG. <ets>marlien</ets>, <ets>marling</ets>, or D. <ets>marling</ets>, <ets>marlijn</ets>, fr. D. <ets>marren</ets> to tie, prob. akin to E. <ets>moor</ets>, v., and <ets>lijn</ets> line: cf.F. <ets>merlin</ets>. See <er>Moor</er>, <pos>v.</pos>, <er>Line</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A small line composed of two strands a little twisted, used for winding around ropes and cables, to prevent their being weakened by fretting.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Marline spike</b></col>, <col><b>Marling spike</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>an iron tool tapering to a point, used to separate the strands of a rope in splicing and in marling. It has an eye in the thick end to which a lanyard is attached. See <er>Fid</er>.</cd> <altsp>[Written also <asp>marlin spike</asp>]</altsp> -- <col><b>Marline-spike bird</b></col>. <ety>[The name alludes to the long middle tail feathers.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A tropic bird.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A jager, or skua gull.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marline</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"line</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>merliner</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To wind marline around; <as>as, to <ex>marline</ex> a rope</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marlite</ent><br/
<hw>Marl"ite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>marlite</ets>. See <er>Marl</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A variety of marl.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marlitic</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*lit"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Partaking of the qualites of marlite.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marlpit</ent><br/
<hw>Marl"pit`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Apit where marl is dug.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marlstone</ent><br/
<hw>Marl"stone`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>A sandy calcareous straum, containing, or impregnated with, iron, and lying between the upper and lower Lias of England.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marly</ent><br/
<hw>Marl"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Marlier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Marliest</adjf>.]</amorph> <def>Consisting or partaking of marl; resembling marl; abounding with marl.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marmalade</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ma*lade</hw> <pr>(m<aum/r"m<adot/*l<amac/d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>marmelade</ets>, Pg. <ets>marmelada</ets>, fr. <ets>marm<eacute/lo</ets> a quince, fr. L. <ets>melimelum</ets> honey apple, Gr. <grk>meli`mhlon</grk> a sweet apple, an apple grafted on a quince; <grk>me`li</grk> honey + <grk>mh^lon</grk> apple.  Cf. <er>Mellifluous</er>, <er>Melon</er>.]</ety> <def>A preserve or confection made of the pulp of fruit, as the quince, pear, apple, orange, etc., boiled with sugar, and brought to a jamlike consistency.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Marmalade tree</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a sapotaceous tree (<spn>Lucuma mammosa</spn>) of the West Indies and Tropical America. It has large obovate leaves and an egg-shaped fruit from three to five inches long, containing a pleasant-flavored pulp and a single large seed.  The fruit is called <prod>marmalade</prod>, or <xex>natural marmalade</xex>, from its consistency and flavor.</cd></cs>
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marmalet</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ma*let`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Marmalade</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marmatite</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ma*tite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>marmatite</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A ferruginous variety of shalerite or zinc blende, nearly black in color.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marmolite</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"mo*lite</hw> <pr>(m<aum/r"m<osl/*l<imac/t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>maramai`rein</grk> to sparkle + <ets>-lite</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A thin, laminated variety of serpentine, usually of a pale green color.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marmoraceous</ent><br/
<hw>Mar`mo*ra"ceous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>marmor</ets> marble. See <er>Marble</er>.]</ety> <def>Pertaining to, or like, marble.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marmorated</ent><br/
<ent>Marmorate</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mar"mo*rate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mar"mo*ra`ted</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>marmoratus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>marmorate</ets> to overlay with marble, fr. <ets>marmor</ets> marble.]</ety> <def>Variegated like marble; covered or overlaid with marble.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marmoration</ent><br/
<hw>Mar`mo*ra"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>marmoratio</ets>.]</ety> <def>A covering or incrusting with marble; a casing of marble; a variegating so as to resemble marble.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marmoratum opus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mar`mo*ra`tum o"pus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[L. See <er>Marmorate</er>, and <er>Opus</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A kind of hard finish for plasterwork, made of plaster of Paris and marble dust, and capable of taking a high polish.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marmorean</ent><br/
<ent>Marmoreal</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mar*mo"re*al</hw> <pr>(m<aum/r*m<omac/"r<esl/*<ait/l)</pr>, <hw>Mar*mo"re*an</hw> <pr>(m<aum/r*m<omac/"r<esl/*<ait/n)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>marmoreus</ets>, fr. <ets>marmor</ets> marble: cf. F. <ets>marmor<eacute/en</ets>. See <er>Marble</er>.]</ety> <def>Pertaining to, or resembling, marble; made of marble.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marmorosis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mar`mo*ro"sis</hw> <pr>(m<aum/r`m<osl/*r<omac/"s<icr/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL.]</ety> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>The metamorphism of limestone, that is, its conversion into marble.</def>  <rj><au>Geikie.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marmose</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"mose`</hw> <pr>(m<aum/r"m<omac/s`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A species of small opossum (<spn>Didelphys murina</spn>) ranging from Mexico to Brazil.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marmoset</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"mo*set`</hw> <pr>(m<aum/r"m<osl/*z<ecr/t`; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>marmouset</ets> a grotesque figure, an ugly little boy, prob. fr. LL. <ets>marmoretum</ets>, fr. L. <ets>marmor</ets> marble. Perhaps confused with <ets>marmot</ets>. See <er>Marble</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of numerous species of small South American monkeys of the genera <gen>Hapale</gen> and <gen>Midas</gen>, family <fam>Hapalidae</fam>.  They have long soft fur, and a hairy, nonprehensile tail.  They are often kept as pets.  Called also <altname>squirrel monkey</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marmot</ent><br/
<hw>mar"mot</hw> <pr>(m<aum/r"m<ocr/t; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It. <ets>marmotta</ets>, <ets>marmotto</ets>, prob. fr. L. <ets>mus montanus</ets>, or <ets>mus montis</ets>, lit., mountain mouse or rat. See <er>Mountain</er>, and <er>Mouse</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any rodent of the genus <gen>Marmota</gen> (formerly <gen>Arctomys</gen>) of the subfamily <subfam>Sciurinae</subfam>.  The common European marmot (<spn>Marmota marmotta</spn>) is about the size of a rabbit, and inhabits the higher regions of the Alps and Pyrenees. The <stype>bobac</stype> is another European species.  The common American species (<spn>Marmota monax</spn>) is the <stype>woodchuck</stype> (also called <stype>groundhog</stype>), but the name <ex>marmot</ex> is usually used only for the western variety.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any one of several species of ground squirrels or gophers of the genus <gen>Spermophilus</gen>; also, the prairie dog.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Marmot squirrel</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a ground squirrel or spermophile.</cd> -- <col><b>Prairie marmot</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Prairie dog</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marmottes oil</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"mottes oil`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <def>A fine oil obtained from the kernel of <spn>Prunus brigantiaca</spn>. It is used instead of olive or almond oil.</def>  <rj><au>De Colange.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marmozet</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"mo*zet`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Marmoset</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maroc</ent><br/
<hw>Maroc</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>Morocco, a country in Northwestern Africa.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Morocco, Marruecos.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maroc</ent><br/
<hw>Maroc</hw> <pos>prop. a.</pos>  <def>Of or pertaining to Morocco; <as>as, <ex>Maroc</ex> mosques cannot be entered by women without a head covering</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Moroccan.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marocain</ent><br/
<hw>marocain</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A dress crepe; similar to Canton crepe.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> crepe marocain.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marone</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*rone"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Maroon</er>, the color.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maronite</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"o*nite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Maronites</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>One of a body of nominal Christians, who speak the Arabic language, and reside on Mount Lebanon and in different parts of Syria.  They take their name from one <persfn><etsep>Maron</etsep></persfn> of the 6th century.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maroon</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*roon"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <altsp>[Written also <asp>marroon</asp>.]</altsp> <ety>[F. <ets>marron</ets>, abbrev. fr. Sp. <ets>cimarron</ets> wild, unruly, from <ets>cima</ets> the summit of a mountain; hence, <ets>negro cimarron</ets> a runaway negro that lives in the mountains.]</ety> <def>In the West Indies and Guiana, a fugitive slave, or a free negro, living in the mountains.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maroon</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*roon"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Marooned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Marooning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Maroon</er> a fugitive slave.]</ety> <def>To put (a person) ashore on a desolate island or coast and leave him to his fate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Marooning party</b></col>, <cd>a social excursion party that sojourns several days on the shore or in some retired place; a prolonged picnic.</cd> <mark>[Southern U. S.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bartlett.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 897 --></p>

<p><ent>Maroon</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*roon"</hw> <pr>(m<adot/*r<oomac/n")</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>marron</ets> chestnut-colored, fr. <ets>marron</ets> a large French chestnut, It. <ets>marrone</ets>; cf. LGr. <grk>ma`raon</grk>.  Cf. <er>Marron</er>.]</ety> <def>Having the color called maroon. See 4th <er>Maroon</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Maroon lake</b></col>, <cd>lake prepared from madder, and distinguished for its transparency and the depth and durability of its color.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maroon</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*roon"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A brownish or dull red of any description, esp. of a scarlet cast rather than approaching crimson or purple.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An explosive shell. See <er>Marron</er>, 3.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marplot</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"plot`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who, by his officious interference, mars or frustrates a design or plot.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marque</ent><br/
<hw>Marque</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>marque</ets>, in <ets>lettre de marque</ets> letter of marque, a commission with which the commandant of every armed vessel was obliged to be provided, under penalty of being considered a pirate or corsair; <ets>marque</ets> here prob. meaning, border, boundary (the letter of marque being a permission to go beyond the border), and of German origin. See <er>March</er> border.]</ety> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A license to pass the limits of a jurisdiction, or boundary of a country, for the purpose of making reprisals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Letters of marque</b></col>, <col><b>Letters of marque and reprisal</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a license or extraordinary commission granted by a government to a private person to fit out a privateer or armed ship to cruise at sea and make prize of the enemy's ships and merchandise. The ship so commissioned is sometimes called a <xex>letter of marque</xex>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marquee</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*quee"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>marquise</ets>, misunderstood as a plural; prob. orig., tent of the marchioness. See <er>Marquis</er>.]</ety> <def>A large field tent; esp., one adapted to the use of an officer of high rank.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>markee</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marquess</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"quess</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Sp. <ets>marques</ets>. See <er>Marquis</er>.]</ety> <def>A marquis.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Lady marquess</b></col>, <cd>a marchioness.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marquetry</ent><br/
<ent>marqueterie</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mar"que*te*rie</hw>, <hw>mar"quet*ry</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>marqueterie</ets>, from <ets>marqueter</ets> to checker, inlay, fr. <ets>marque</ets> mark, sign; of German origin. See <er>Mark</er> a sign.]</ety> <def>Inlaid work; work inlaid with pieces of wood, shells, ivory, veneer, and the like, of several colors, fitted together to form a design or picture that is then used to ornament furniture.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marquis</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"quis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>marquis</ets>, OF. <ets>markis</ets>, <ets>marchis</ets>, LL. <ets>marchensis</ets>; of German origin; cf. G. <ets>mark</ets> bound, border, march, OHG. <ets>marcha</ets>. See <er>March</er> border, and cf. <er>Marchioness</er>, <er>Marquee</er>, <er>Marquess</er>.]</ety> <def>A nobleman in England, France, and Germany, of a rank next below that of duke.  Originally, the marquis was an officer whose duty was to guard the marches or frontiers of the kingdom.  The office has ceased, and the name is now a mere title conferred by patent.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marquisate</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"quis*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>marquisat</ets>.]</ety> <def>The seigniory, dignity, or lordship of a marquis; the territory governed by a marquis.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marquisdom</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"quis*dom</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A marquisate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/Nobles of the <xex>marquisdom</xex> of Saluce.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Holinshed.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marquise</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mar`quise"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. See <er>Marquis</er>, and cf. <er>Marquee</er>.]</ety> <def>The wife of a marquis; a marchioness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marquisship</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"quis*ship</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A marquisate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marram</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ram</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A coarse grass found on sandy beaches (<spn>Ammophila arundinacea</spn>). See <cref>Beach grass</cref>, under <er>Beach</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marrer</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"rer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who mars or injures.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marriable</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ri*a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mariable</ets>.]</ety> <def>Marriageable.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Coleridge.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marriage</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"riage</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mariage</ets>, F. <ets>mariage</ets>. See <er>Marry</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of marrying, or the state of being married; legal union of a man and a woman for life, as husband and wife; wedlock; matrimony.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Marriage</qex> is honorable in all.</q> <rj><qau>Heb. xiii. 4.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The marriage vow or contract.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A feast made on the occasion of a marriage.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The kingdom of heaven is like unto a certain king which made a <qex>marriage</qex> for his son.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. xxii. 2.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Any intimate or close union.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>In pinochle, b<eacute/zique, and similar games at cards, the combination of a king and queen of the same suit. If of the trump suit, it is called a <stype>royal marriage</stype>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Marriage brokage</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The business of bringing about marriages</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>The payment made or demanded for the procurement of a marriage.</cd> -- <col><b>Marriage favors</b></col>, <cd>knots of white ribbons, or bunches of white flowers, worn at weddings.</cd> -- <col><b>Marriage settlement</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>a settlement of property in view, and in consideration, of marriage.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Matrimony; wedlock; wedding; nuptials.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Marriage</er>, <er>Matrimony</er>, <er>Wedlock</er>. <xex>Marriage</xex> is properly the <xex>act</xex> which unites the two parties, and <xex>matrimony</xex> the <xex>state</xex> into which they enter. <xex>Marriage</xex> is, however, often used for the state as well as the act. <xex>Wedlock</xex> is the old Anglo-Saxon term for <xex>matrimony</xex>.</usage><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marriageability</ent><br/
<hw>Mar`riage*a*bil"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being marriageable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marriageable</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"riage*a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Fit for, or capable of, marriage; of an age at which marriage is allowable.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mar"riage*a*ble*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Married</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ried</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Being in the state of matrimony; having a spouse; wedded; <as>as, a <ex>married</ex> man or woman</as>; -- of one person.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to marriage; connubial; <as>as, the <ex>married</ex> state; one's <ex>married</ex> name</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Wedded to each other; <as>as, a <ex>married</ex> couple; John and Joan are no longer <ex>married</ex></as>; -- of two people.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <mark>[fig.]</mark> <def>Joined to form one object; united.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marrier</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ri*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who marries.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marron</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*ron"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Maroon</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A large chestnut.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Holland.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A chestnut color; maroon.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Pyrotechny & Mil.)</fld> <def>A paper or pasteboard box or shell, wound about with strong twine, filled with an explosive, and ignited with a fuse, -- used to make a noise like a cannon.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>maroon</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marroon</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*roon"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. & a.</pos> <def>Same as 1st <er>Maroon</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marrot</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"rot</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The razor-billed auk. See <er>Auk</er>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The common guillemot.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The puffin.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> <altsp>[Written also <asp>marrott</asp>, and <asp>morrot</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marrow</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"row</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>marou</ets>, <ets>mary</ets>, <ets>maruh</ets>, AS. <ets>mearg</ets>, <ets>mearh</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>marg</ets>, D. <ets>merg</ets>, G. <ets>Mark</ets>, OHG. <ets>marg</ets>, <ets>marag</ets>, Icel. <ets>mergr</ets>, Sw. <ets>merg</ets>, Dan. <ets>marv</ets>, Skr. <ets>majjan</ets>; cf. Skr. <ets>majj</ets> to sink, L. <ets>mergere</ets>. <root/274 Cf. <er>Merge</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The tissue which fills the cavities of most bones; the medulla.  In the larger cavities it is commonly very fatty, but in the smaller cavities it is much less fatty, and red or reddish in color.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The essence; the best part.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It takes from our achievements . . .<br/
The pith and <qex>marrow</qex> of our attribute.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <ety>[OE. <ets>maru</ets>, <ets>maro</ets>; -- perh. a different word; cf. Gael. <ets>maraon</ets> together.]</ety> <def>One of a pair; a match; a companion; an intimate associate.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Chopping and changing I can not commend,<br/
With thief or his <qex>marrow</qex>, for fear of ill end.</q> <rj><qau>Tusser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Marrow squash</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a name given to several varieties of squash, esp. to the <altname>Boston marrow</altname>, an ovoid fruit, pointed at both ends, and with reddish yellow flesh, and to the <altname>vegetable marrow</altname>, a variety of an ovoid form, and having a soft texture and fine grain resembling marrow.</cd> -- <col><b>Spinal marrow</b></col>. <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <cd>See <cref>Spinal cord</cref>, under <er>Spinal</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marrow</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"row</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Marrowed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Marrowing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To fill with, or as with, marrow or fat; to glut.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marrowbone</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"row*bone`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A bone containing marrow;</def> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>ludicrously, knee bones or knees; <as>as, to get down on one's <ex>marrowbones</ex>, <it>i. e.</it>, to kneel</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marrowfat</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"row*fat</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A rich but late variety of pea.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marrowish</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"row*ish</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of the nature of, or like, marrow.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marrowless</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"row*less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Destitute of marrow.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marrowy</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"row*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Full of marrow; pithy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marrubium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mar*ru"bi*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of bitter aromatic plants, sometimes used in medicine; hoarhound.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marruecos</ent><br/
<hw>Marruecos</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>Morocco, a country in Northwestern Africa.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Morocco, Maroc.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marry</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Married</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Marrying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>marien</ets>, F. <ets>marier</ets>, L. <ets>maritare</ets>, fr. <ets>maritus</ets> husband, fr. <ets>mas</ets>, <ets>maris</ets>, a male. See <er>Male</er>, and cf. <er>Maritral</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To unite in wedlock or matrimony; to perform the ceremony of joining, as a man and a woman, for life; to constitute (a man and a woman) husband and wife according to the laws or customs of the place.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tell him that he shall <qex>marry</qex> the couple himself.</q> <rj><qau>Gay.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To join according to law, (a man) to a woman as his wife, or (a woman) to a man as her husband. See the Note to def. 4.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A woman who had been <qex>married</qex> to her twenty-fifth husband, and being now a widow, was prohibited to marry.</q> <rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To dispose of in wedlock; to give away as wife.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Maecenas took the liberty to tell him [Augustus] that he must either <qex>marry</qex> his daughter [Julia] to Agrippa, or take away his life.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To take for husband or wife. See the Note below.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ We say, a man is <xex>married to</xex> or <xex>marries</xex> a woman; or, a woman is <xex>married to</xex> or <xex>marries</xex> a man.  Both of these uses are equally well authorized; but <xex>given in marriage</xex> is said only of the woman.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They got him [the Duke of Monmouth] . . . to declare in writing, that the last king [Charles II.] told him he was never <qex>married</qex> to his mother.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Lloyd.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Figuratively, to unite in the closest and most endearing relation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Turn, O backsliding children, saith the Lord; for I am <qex>married</qex> unto you.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. iii. 14.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To marry ropes</b></col>. <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To place two ropes along side of each other so that they may be grasped and hauled on at the same time</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To join two ropes end to end so that both will pass through a block.</cd>  <rj><au>Ham. Nav. Encyc.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marry</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ry</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To enter into the conjugal or connubial state; to take a husband or a wife.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will, therefore, that the younger women <qex>marry</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>1 Tim. v. 14.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Marrying man</b></col>, <cd>a man disposed to marry.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marry</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ry</hw>, <pos>interj.</pos> <def>Indeed! in truth! -- a term of asseveration said to have been derived from the practice of swearing by the Virgin Mary.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mars</ent><br/
<hw>Mars</hw> <pr>(m<aum/rz)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>Mars</ets>, gen. <ets>Martis</ets>, archaic <ets>Mavors</ets>, gen. <ets>Mavortis</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Rom. Myth.)</fld> <def>The god of war and husbandry.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>One of the planets of the solar system, the fourth in order from the sun, or the next beyond the earth, having a diameter of about 4,200 miles, a period of 687 days, and a mean distance of 141,000,000 miles. It is conspicuous for the redness of its light.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Alchemy)</fld> <def>The metallic element iron, the symbol of which <Male/ was the same as that of the planet Mars.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mars brown</b></col>, <cd>a bright, somewhat yellowish, brown.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marsala</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*sa"la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It., fr. <ets>Marsala</ets>, in Sicyly.]</ety> <def>A kind of wine exported from Marsala in Sicily.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marsdenia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mars*de"ni*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[NL. From W. <ets>Marsden</ets>, an English author.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of plants of the Milkweed family, mostly woody climbers with fragrant flowers, several species of which furnish valuable fiber, and one species (<spn>Marsdenia tinctoria</spn>) affords indigo.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marseillaise</ent><br/
<ent>Marseillais</ent><br/
<mhw>{ \'d8<hw>Mar`sei`llais"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a. m.</pos> \'d8<hw>Mar`sei`llaise"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a. f.</pos> }</mhw><ety>[F.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to Marseilles, in France, or to its inhabitants.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Marseillaise hymn</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>The Marseillaise</b></col></mcol>, <cd>the national anthem of France, popularly so called.  It was composed in 1792, by Rouget de l'Isle, an officer then stationed at Strasburg.  In Paris it was sung for the first time by the band of men who came from Marseilles to aid in the revolution of August 10, 1792; whence the name.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marseillaise</ent><br/
<ent>Marseillais</ent><br/
<mhw>{ \'d8<hw>Mar`sei`llais"</hw>, <pos>n. m.</pos> \'d8<hw>Mar`sei`llaise"</hw>, <pos>n. f.</pos> }</mhw><ety>[F.]</ety> <def>A native or inhabitant of Marseilles.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marseilles</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*seilles"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A general term for certain kinds of fabrics, which are formed of two series of threads interlacing each other, thus forming double cloth, quilted in the loom; -- so named because first made in <city>Marseilles</city>, France.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marsh</ent><br/
<hw>Marsh</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mersch</ets>, AS. <ets>mersc</ets>, fr. <ets>mere</ets> lake. See <er>Mere</er> pool, and cf. <er>Marish</er>, <er>Morass</er>.]</ety> <def>A tract of soft wet land, commonly covered partially or wholly with water; a fen; a swamp; a morass.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>marish</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Marsh asphodel</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a plant (<spn>Nartheeium ossifragum</spn>) with linear equitant leaves, and a raceme of small white flowers; -- called also <altname>bog asphodel</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Marsh cinquefoil</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a plant (<spn>Potentilla palustris</spn>) having purple flowers, and found growing in marshy places; marsh five-finger.</cd> -- <col><b>Marsh elder</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The guelder-rose or cranberry tree (<spn>Viburnum Opulus</spn>)</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>In the United States, a composite shrub growing in salt marshes (<spn>Iva frutescens</spn>).</cd> -- <col><b>Marsh five-finger</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>See <cref>Marsh cinquefoil</cref> (above).</cd> -- <col><b>Marsh gas</b></col>. <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Gas</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Marsh grass</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a genus (<gen>Spartina</gen>) of coarse grasses growing in marshes; -- called also <altname>cord grass</altname>.  The tall <spn>Spartina cynosuroides</spn> is not good for hay unless cut very young. The low <spn>Spartina juncea</spn> is a common component of salt hay.</cd> -- <col><b>Marsh harrier</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a European hawk or harrier (<spn>Circus aeruginosus</spn>); -- called also <altname>marsh hawk</altname>, <altname>moor hawk</altname>, <altname>moor buzzard</altname>, <altname>puttock</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Marsh hawk</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A hawk or harrier (<spn>Circus cyaneus</spn>), native of both America and Europe. The adults are bluish slate above, with a white rump. Called also <altname>hen harrier</altname>, and <altname>mouse hawk</altname>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>The marsh harrier.</cd> -- <col><b>Marsh hen</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a rail; esp., <spn>Rallus elegans</spn> of fresh-water marshes, and <spn>Rallus longirostris</spn> of salt-water marshes.</cd> -- <col><b>Marsh mallow</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a plant of the genus <gen>Althaea</gen> ( <spn>Althaea officinalis</spn>) common in marshes near the seashore, and whose root is much used in medicine as a demulcent.</cd> -- <col><b>Marsh marigold</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>See in the Vocabulary.</cd> -- <col><b>Marsh pennywort</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>any plant of the umbelliferous genus <gen>Hydrocotyle</gen>; low herbs with roundish leaves, growing in wet places; -- called also <altname>water pennywort</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Marsh quail</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the meadow lark.</cd> -- <col><b>Marsh rosemary</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a plant of the genus <gen>Statice</gen> (<spn>Statice Limonium</spn>), common in salt marshes. Its root is powerfully astringent, and is sometimes used in medicine. Called also <altname>sea lavender</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Marsh samphire</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a plant (<spn>Salicornia herbacea</spn>) found along seacoasts. See <er>Glasswort</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Marsh St. John's-wort</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>an American herb (<spn>Elodes Virginica</spn>) with small opposite leaves and flesh-colored flowers.</cd> -- <col><b>Marsh tea</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld>. <cd>Same as <er>Labrador tea</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Marsh trefoil</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>Same as <er>Buckbean</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Marsh wren</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any species of small American wrens of the genus <gen>Cistothorus</gen>, and allied genera.  They chiefly inhabit salt marshes.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marshal</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"shal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mareschal</ets>, OF. <ets>mareschal</ets>, F. <ets>mar<eacute/chal</ets>, LL. <ets>mariscalcus</ets>, from OHG. <ets>marah-scalc</ets> (G. <ets>marschall</ets>); <ets>marah</ets> horse + <ets>scalc</ets> servant (akin to AS. <ets>scealc</ets>, Goth. <ets>skalks</ets>). F. <ets>mar<eacute/chal</ets> signifies, a marshal, and a farrier. See <er>Mare</er> horse, and cf. <er>Seneschal</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Originally, an officer who had the care of horses; a groom.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An officer of high rank, charged with the arrangement of ceremonies, the conduct of operations, or the like</def>; <specif>as, specifically:</specif> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>One who goes before a prince to declare his coming and provide entertainment; a harbinger; a pursuivant.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>One who regulates rank and order at a feast or any other assembly, directs the order of procession, and the like.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The chief officer of arms, whose duty it was, in ancient times, to regulate combats in the lists.</def> <au>Johnson.</au> <sd>(d)</sd> <fld>(France)</fld> <def>The highest military officer.</def> In other countries of Europe a marshal is a military officer of high rank, and called <altname>field marshal</altname>. <sd>(e)</sd> <fld>(Am. Law)</fld> <def>A ministerial officer, appointed for each judicial district of the United States, to execute the process of the courts of the United States, and perform various duties, similar to those of a sheriff.  The name is also sometimes applied to certain police officers of a city.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Earl marshal of England</b></col>, <cd>the eighth officer of state; an honorary title, and personal, until made hereditary in the family of the Duke of Norfolk. During a vacancy in the office of high constable, the earl marshal has jurisdiction in the court of chivalry.</cd> <au>Brande & C.</au> -- <col><b>Earl marshal of Scotland</b></col>, <cd>an officer who had command of the cavalry under the constable. This office was held by the family of Keith, but forfeited by rebellion in 1715.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Knight marshal</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Marshal of the King's house</b></col></mcol>, <cd>formerly, in England, the marshal of the king's house, who was authorized to hear and determine all pleas of the Crown, to punish faults committed within the verge, etc. His court was called the Court of Marshalsea.</cd> -- <col><b>Marshal of the Queen's Bench</b></col>, <cd>formerly the title of the officer who had the custody of the Queen's bench prison in Southwark.</cd> <au>Mozley & W.</au></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marshal</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"shal</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Marshaled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or <conjf>Marshalled</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Marshaling</conjf> or <conjf>Marshalling</conjf>.]</vmorph><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To dispose in order; to arrange in a suitable manner; <as>as, to <ex>marshal</ex> troops or an army</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>marshaling</qex> the heroes of his name<br/
As, in their order, next to light they came.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To direct, guide, or lead.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou <qex>marshalest</qex> me the way that I was going.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>To dispose in due order, as the different quarterings on an escutcheon, or the different crests when several belong to an achievement.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marshaler</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"shal*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Written also <ets>marshaller</ets>.]</ety> <def>One who marshals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marshaling</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"shal*ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Written also <ets>marshalling</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of arranging in due order.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>The arrangement of an escutcheon to exhibit the alliances of the owner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Marshaling of assets</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>the arranging or ranking of assets in due order of administration.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marshalsea</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"shal*sea</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Marshal</ets> + OE. <ets>se</ets> a seat. See <er>See</er> a seat.]</ety> <def>The court or seat of a marshal; hence, the prison in Southwark, belonging to the marshal of the king's household.</def> <mark>[Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Court of Marshalsea</b></col>, <cd>a court formerly held before the steward and marshal of the king's house to administer justice between the king's domestic servants.</cd>  <rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marshalship</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"shal*ship</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The office of a marshal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marsebanker</ent><br/
<ent>Marshbanker</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Marsh"bank`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Marse"bank`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The menhaden.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 898 --></p>

<p><ent>marshiness</ent><br/
<hw>marsh"i*ness</hw> <pr>(m<aum/rsh"<icr/*n<ecr/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state or condition of being marshy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marsh marigold</ent><br/
<hw>marsh mar"i*gold</hw> <pr>(m<aum/rsh m<acr/r"<icr/*g<osl/ld)</pr>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A perennial plant of the genus <gen>Caltha</gen> (<spn>Caltha palustris</spn>), growing in wet places and bearing bright yellow flowers.  In the United States it is used as a pot herb under the name of <altname>cowslip</altname>. See <er>Cowslip</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marshy</ent><br/
<hw>marsh"y</hw> <pr>(m<aum/rsh"<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[E. <er>Marsh</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Resembling a marsh; wet; boggy; fenny.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Pertaining to, or produced in, marshes; <as>as, a <ex>marshy</ex> weed</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marsileaceae</ent><br/
<hw>Marsileaceae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of clover ferns.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Marsileaceae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marsipobranch</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"si*po*branch`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the <class>Marsipobranchia</class>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marsipobranchia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mar"si*po*bran"chi*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ a pouch + <?/ a gill.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A class of <subphylum>Vertebrata</subphylum>, lower than fishes, characterized by their purselike gill cavities, cartilaginous skeletons, absence of limbs, and a suckerlike mouth destitute of jaws.  It includes the lampreys and hagfishes. See <er>Cyclostoma</er>, and <er>Lamprey</er>. Called also <altname>Marsipobranchiata</altname>, and <altname>Marsipobranchii</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marsupial</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*su"pi*al</hw> <pr>(m<aum/r*s<umac/"p<icr/*<ait/l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>marsupial</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having a pouch for carrying the immature young; of or pertaining to the Marsupialia.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Anat. & Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to a marsupium; <as>as, the <ex>marsupial</ex> bones</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Marsupial frog</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Nototrema</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marsupial</ent><br/
<hw>mar*su"pi*al</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the <subclass>Marsupialia</subclass>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marsupialia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mar*su`pi*a"li*a</hw> <pr>(m<aum/r*s<umac/`p<icr/*<amac/"l<icr/*<adot/)</pr>, <pos>prop. n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. L. <ets>marsupium</ets> a pouch, bag, purse, Gr. <grk>marsy`pion</grk>, dim. of <grk>ma`rsypos</grk>, <grk>ma`rsipos</grk>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A subclass of <class>Mammalia</class>, including nearly all the mammals of Australia and the adjacent islands, together with the opossums of America.  They differ from ordinary mammals in having the corpus callosum very small, in being implacental, and in having their young born while very immature.  The female generally carries the young for some time after birth in an external pouch, or marsupium.  Called also <altname>Marsupiata</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marsupian</ent><br/
<ent>marsupialian</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>mar*su`pi*a"li*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>mar*su"pi*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the <subclass>Marsupialia</subclass>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marsupiate</ent><br/
<hw>mar*su"pi*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Related to or resembling the marsupials; furnished with a pouch for the young, as the marsupials, and also some fishes and Crustacea.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marsupion</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>mar*su"pi*on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL.]</ety> <def>Same as <er>Marsupium</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marsupite</ent><br/
<hw>mar"su*pite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>marsupial</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>A fossil crinoid of the genus <gen>Marsupites</gen>, resembling a purse in form.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marsupium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>mar*su"pi*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>marsupia</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., a pouch]</ety>, <fld>(Anat. & Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The pouch, formed by a fold of the skin of the abdomen, in which marsupials carry their young; also, a pouch for similar use in other animals, as certain Crustacea.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The pecten in the eye of birds and reptiles. See <er>Pecten</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mart</ent><br/
<hw>Mart</hw> <pr>(m<aum/rt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Contr. fr. <ets>market</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A market.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where has commerce such a <qex>mart</qex> . . . as London?</q> <rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A bargain.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mart</ent><br/
<hw>Mart</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To buy or sell in, or as in, a mart.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To sell and <qex>mart</qex> your officer for gold<br/
To undeservers.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mart</ent><br/
<hw>Mart</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To traffic.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mart</ent><br/
<hw>Mart</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mars</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The god Mars.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Battle; contest.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Fairfax.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>martagon</ent><br/
<hw>mar"ta*gon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. & Sp. <ets>martagon</ets>, It. <ets>martagone</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A lily (<spn>Lilium Martagon</spn>) with purplish red flowers, found in Europe and Asia.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>martel</ent><br/
<hw>mar"tel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>marteler</ets>, fr. <ets>martel</ets>, <ets>marteau</ets>, hammer, a dim. fr. L. <ets>martulus</ets>, <ets>marculus</ets>, dim. of <ets>marcus</ets> hammer.  Cf. <er>March</er> to step.]</ety> <def>To make a blow with, or as with, a hammer.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>martel de fer</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>mar`tel` de fer"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[OF., hammer of iron.]</ety> <def>A weapon resembling a hammer, often having one side of the head pointed; -- used by horsemen in the Middle Ages to break armor.</def>  <rj><au>Fairholt.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marteline</ent><br/
<hw>mar"te*line</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>A small hammer used by marble workers and sculptors.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martello tower</ent><br/
<hw>Mar*tel"lo tow`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[It. <ets>martello</ets> hammer.  The name was orig. given to towers erected on the coasts of Sicily and Sardinia for protection against the pirates in the time of Charles the Fifth, which prob. orig. contained an alarm bell to be struck with a hammer. See <er>Martel</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Fort.)</fld> <def>A building of masonry, generally circular, usually erected on the seacoast, with a gun on the summit mounted on a traversing platform, so as to be fired in any direction.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The English borrowed the name of the tower from Corsica in 1794.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marten</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ten</hw> <pr>(m<aum/r"t<ecr/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A bird. See <er>Martin</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marten</ent><br/
<hw>mar"ten</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From older <ets>martern</ets>, <ets>marter</ets>, <ets>martre</ets>, F. <ets>martre</ets>, <ets>marte</ets>, LL. <ets>martures</ets> (pl.), fr. L. <ets>martes</ets>; akin to AS. <ets>mear<edh/</ets>, <ets>meard</ets>, G. <ets>marder</ets>, OHG. <ets>mardar</ets>, Icel. <ets>m<oum/r<edh/r</ets>.  Cf. <er>Foumart</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of several fur-bearing carnivores of the genus <gen>Martes</gen> (formerly <gen>Mustela</gen>), closely allied to the sable.  Among the more important species are the European <stype>beech marten</stype> or <stype>stone marten</stype> (<spn>Martes foina</spn>); the <stype>pine marten</stype> (<spn>Martes martes</spn>); and the <stype>American marten</stype>, or <stype>sable</stype> (<spn>Martes Americana</spn>), which some Zoologists consider only a variety of the Russian sable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The fur of the marten, used for hats, muffs, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>martern</ent><br/
<hw>mar"tern</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Marten</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mar-text</ent><br/
<hw>mar"-text`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A blundering preacher.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martes</ent><br/
<hw>Martes</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The genus of mammals including the martens.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus Martes.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martial</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"tial</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>martialis</ets> of or belonging to <ets>Mars</ets>, the god of war.  Cf. <er>March</er> the month.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Of, pertaining to, or suited for, war; military; <as>as, <ex>martial</ex> music; a <ex>martial</ex> appearance.</as></def> <ldquo/<xex>Martial</xex> equipage.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Practiced in, or inclined to, war; warlike; brave.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But peaceful kings, o'er <qex>martial</qex> people set,<br/
Each other's poise and counterbalance are.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Belonging to war, or to an army and navy; -- opposed to <contr>civil</contr>; <as>as, <ex>martial</ex> law; a court<ex>-martial</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Pertaining to, or resembling, the god, or the planet, Mars.</def>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Old Chem. & Old Med.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or containing, iron; chalybeate; <as>as, <ex>martial</ex> preparations</as>.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Martial flowers</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>a reddish crystalline salt of iron; the ammonio-chloride of iron.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> -- <col><b>Martial law</b></col>, <cd>the law administered by the military power of a government when it has superseded the civil authority in time of war, or when the civil authorities are unable to enforce the laws. It is distinguished from <xex>military law</xex>, the latter being the code of rules for the regulation of the army and navy alone, either in peace or in war.</cd></cs><-- ???add air force --><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Martial</er>, <er>Warlike</er>.</syn> <usage> <xex>Martial</xex> refers more to war in <xex>action</xex>, its array, its attendants, etc.; as, <xex>martial</xex> music, a <xex>martial</xex> appearance, a <xex>martial</xex> array, courts<xex>-martial</xex>, etc. <xex>Warlike</xex> describes the feeling or temper which leads to war, and the adjuncts of war; as, a <xex>warlike</xex> nation, <xex>warlike</xex> indication, etc. The two words are often used without discrimination.</usage><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martialism</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"tial*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality of being warlike; exercises suitable for war.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martialist</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"tial*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A warrior.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martialize</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"tial*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Martialized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Martializing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To render warlike; <as>as, to <ex>martialize</ex> a people</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martially</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"tial*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a martial manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martialness</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"tial*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality of being martial.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martian</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"tian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>Martius</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to Mars, the Roman god of war, or to the planet bearing his name; martial.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martian</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"tian</hw>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>An inhabitant of the planet Mars; -- fictional or hypothetical.</def> <rj><au>Du Maurier.</au></rj><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/  In science fiction, it has often been postulated that there are intelligent creatures living on Mars, but no strong evidence of any form of life on Mars has been observed up to the end of 1998.</note></p>

<p><ent>Martin</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"tin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Stone Working)</fld> <ety>[Etymol. uncertain.]</ety> <def>A perforated stone-faced runner for grinding.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martin</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"tin</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>martin</ets>, from the proper name <ets>Martin</ets>.  Cf. <er>Martlet</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of several species of swallows, usually having the tail less deeply forked than the tail of the common swallows.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>marten</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The American <stype>purple martin</stype>, or <stype>bee martin</stype> (<spn>Progne subis</spn> or <spn>Progne purpurea</spn>), and the European <stype>house martin</stype>, or <stype>window martin</stype> (<spn>Hirundo urbica</spn> or <spn>Chelidon urbica</spn>), are the best known species.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Bank martin</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The bank swallow</cd>. See under <er>Bank</er>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>The fairy martin. See under <er>Fairy</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Bee martin</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The purple martin</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>The kingbird.</cd> -- <col><b>Sand martin</b></col>, <cd>the bank swallow.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martinet</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ti*net`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[So called from an officer of that name in the French army under <person>Louis XIV.</person>   Cf. <er>Martin</er> the bird, <er>Martlet</er>.]</ety> <def>In military language, a strict disciplinarian; in general, one who lays stress on a rigid adherence to the details of discipline, or to forms and fixed methods.</def> <mark>[Hence, the word is commonly employed in a depreciatory sense.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martinet</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ti*net`</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The martin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martineta</ent><br/
<hw>Mar`ti*ne"ta</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Sp. <ets>martinete</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A species of tinamou (<spn>Calopezus elegans</spn>), having a long slender crest.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martinetism</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ti*net`ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The principles or practices of a martinet; rigid adherence to discipline, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martingal</ent><br/
<ent>Martingale</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mar"tin*gale</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mar"tin*gal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>martingale</ets>; cf. It. <ets>martingala</ets> a sort of hose, martingale, Sp. <ets>martingala</ets> a greave, cuish, martingale, Sp. <ets>alm<aacute/rtaga</ets> a kind of bridle.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A strap fastened to a horse's girth, passing between his fore legs, and fastened to the bit, or now more commonly ending in two rings, through which the reins pass.  It is intended to hold down the head of the horse, and prevent him from rearing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A lower stay of rope or chain for the jib boom or flying jib boom, fastened to, or reeved through, the dolphin striker. Also, the dolphin striker itself.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Gambling)</fld> <def>The act of doubling, at each stake, that which has been lost on the preceding stake; also, the sum so risked; -- metaphorically derived from the bifurcation of the <xex>martingale</xex> of a harness.  Called also <altname>Martingale strategy</altname>.  Such a betting strategy does not change the overall likelihood of winning, but in a short run it increases the probability of winning a small sum, balancing it against an increased probability of losing a large sum.</def> <mark>[Cant]</mark>  <rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martinmas</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"tin*mas</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[St. <ets>Martin + mass</ets> religious service.]</ety> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>The feast of <person>St. Martin</person>, the eleventh of November; -- often called <altname>martlemans</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Martinmas summer</b></col>, <cd>a period of calm, warm weather often experienced about the time of Martinmas; Indian summer.</cd>  <rj><au>Percy Smith.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martite</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"tite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>Mars</ets>, <ets>Martis</ets>, the god Mars, the alchemical name of iron.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Iron sesquioxide in isometric form, probably a pseudomorph after magnetite.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martlemas</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"tle*mas</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Martinmas</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martlet</ent><br/
<hw>Mart"let</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.  <ets>martinet</ets>. See <er>Martin</er> the bird, and cf. <er>Martinet</er> a disciplinarian.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The European house martin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>merlette</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>A bird without beak or feet; -- generally assumed to represent a <sig>martin</sig>.  As a mark of cadency it denotes the fourth son.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martyniaceae</ent><br/
<hw>Martyniaceae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family in most classifications not considered a separate family but included in the <fam>Pedaliaceae</fam>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Martyniaceae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martyr</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"tyr</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS., from L. <ets>martyr</ets>, Gr. <grk>ma`rtyr</grk>, <grk>ma`rtys</grk>, prop., a witness; cf. Skr. <ets>sm<rsdot/</ets> to remember, E. <ets>memory</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>One who, by his death, bears witness to the truth of the gospel; one who is put to death for his religion; <as>as, <persfn>Stephen</persfn> was the first Christian <ex>martyr</ex></as>.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To be a <qex>martyr</qex>, signifies only to witness the truth of Christ; but the witnessing of the truth was then so generally attended with persecution, that martyrdom now signifies not only to witness, but to witness by death.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, one who sacrifices his life, his station, or what is of great value to him, for the sake of principle, or to sustain a cause.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then if thou fall'st, O Cromwell,<br/
Thou fall'st a blessed <qex>martyr</qex> !</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martyr</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"tyr</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Martyred</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Martyring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To put to death for adhering to some belief, esp. Christianity; to sacrifice on account of faith or profession.</def>  <rj><au>Bp. Pearson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To persecute; to torment; to torture.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The lovely Amoret, whose gentle heart<br/
Thou <qex>martyrest</qex> with sorrow and with smart.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Racked with sciatics, <qex>martyred</qex> with the stone.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martyrdom</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"tyr*dom</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Martyr</ets> + <ets>-dom</ets>.]</ety>  <sn>1.</sn> <def>The condition of a martyr; the death of a martyr; the suffering of death on account of adherence to the Christian faith, or to any cause.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I came from <qex>martyrdom</qex> unto this peace.</q> <rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Affliction; torment; torture.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martyrization</ent><br/
<hw>Mar`tyr*i*za"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Act of martyrizing, or state of being martyrized; torture.</def>  <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martyrize</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"tyr*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>martyriser</ets>, LL. <ets>martyrizare</ets>.]</ety> <def>To make a martyr of.</def>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martyrly</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"tyr*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In the manner of a martyr.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martyrologe</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"tyr*o*loge</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>martyrologium</ets>: cf. F. <ets>martyrologe</ets>.]</ety> <def>A martyrology.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martyrological</ent><br/
<ent>Martyrologic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mar`tyr*o*log"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mar`tyr*o*log"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to martyrology or martyrs; registering, or registered in, a catalogue of martyrs.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martyrologist</ent><br/
<hw>Mar`tyr*ol"o*gist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>martyrologiste</ets>.]</ety> <def>A writer of martyrology; an historian of martyrs.</def>  <rj><au>T. Warton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martyrology</ent><br/
<hw>Mar`tyr*ol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>-gies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[<ets>Martyr</ets> + <ets>-logy</ets>.]</ety> <def>A history or account of martyrs; a register of martyrs.</def>  <rj><au>Bp. Stillingfleet.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martyrship</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"tyr*ship</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Martyrdom.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marvel</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"vel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mervaile</ets>, F. <ets>merveille</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mirabilia</ets> wonderful things, pl., fr. <ets>mirabilis</ets> wonderful, fr. <ets>mirari</ets> to wonder or marvel at. See <er>Admire</er>, <er>Smile</er>, and cf. <er>Miracle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which causes wonder; a prodigy; a miracle.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will do <qex>marvels</qex> such as have not been done.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xxxiv. 10.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nature's sweet <qex>marvel</qex> undefiled.</q> <rj><qau>Emerson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Wonder.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <ldquo/Use lessens <xex>marvel</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Sir W. Scott.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marvel-of-Peru</ent><br/
<ent>marvel of Peru</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>marvel of Peru</hw>, <hw>marvel-of-Peru</hw></mhw>. <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A common garden plant (<spn>Mirabilis jalapa</spn> or <spn>Mirabilis uniflora</spn>) of North America having fragrant red or purple or yellow or white flowers that open in late afternoon; called also <altname>four-o'clock</altname>.  See <er>four-o'clock</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> common four-o'clock, marvel of Peru, <spn>Mirabilis jalapa</spn>, <spn>Mirabilis uniflora</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marvel</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"vel</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Marveled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or <conjf>Marvelled</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Marveling</conjf> or <conjf>Marvelling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>merveilen</ets>, OF. <ets>merveillier</ets>.]</ety> <def>To be struck with surprise, astonishment, or wonder; to wonder.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Marvel</qex> not, my brethren, if the world hate you.</q> <rj><qau>1 john iii. 13.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marvel</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"vel</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To marvel at.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Wyclif.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause to marvel, or be surprised; -- used impersonally.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But much now me <qex>marveleth</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Rich. the Redeless.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marvellous</ent><br/
<hw>marvellous</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>Marvelous.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> improbable, marvelous, tall(prenominal).</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marvelous</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"vel*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>merveillous</ets>, OF. <ets>merveillos</ets>, F. <ets>Merveilleux</ets>. See <er>Marvel</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <altsp>[Written also <asp>marvellous</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Exciting wonder or surprise; astonishing; wonderful.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This is the Lord's doing; it is <qex>marvelous</qex> in our eyes.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. cxiii. 23.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Partaking of the character of miracle, or supernatural power; incredible; so improbable as to defy belief.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>marvelous</qex> fable includes whatever is supernatural, and especially the machines of the gods.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The marvelous</b></col>, <cd>that which exceeds natural power, or is preternatural; that which is wonderful; -- opposed to <ant>the probable</ant>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Wonderful; astonishing; surprising; strange; improbable; incredible.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Marvelous</er>, <er>Wonderful</er>. We speak of a thing as <xex>wonderful</xex> when it awakens our surprise and admiration; as <xex>marvelous</xex> when it is so much out of the ordinary course of things as to seem nearly or quite incredible.</usage><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marvelously</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"vel*ous*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a marvelous manner; wonderfully; strangely.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marvelousness</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"vel*ous*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being marvelous; wonderfulness; strangeness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marver</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"ver</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. corrupt. fr. OE. or F. <ets>marbre</ets> marble.]</ety> <fld>(Glass Marking)</fld> <def>A stone, or cast-iron plate, or former, on which hot glass is rolled to give it shape.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marxism</ent><br/
<hw>Marx"ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A system of economic and political thought, originated by <person>Karl Marx</person>, and elaborated by others.  It holds that the state has been the a device for suppression of the masses, allowing exploitation by a dominant (capitalistic) class; that historical change occurs through class struggle; and that the capitalist system will inevitably wither away to be superseded by a classless society.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marxism-Leninism</ent><br/
<hw>Marx"ism-Len"in*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>Marxism, as interpreted by <person>V. I. Lenin</person>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marxist</ent><br/
<hw>Marx"ist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>One who believes in the theories of <person>Karl Marx</person>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marxist</ent><br/
<hw>Marx"ist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to <persfn>Marx</persfn> or Marxism.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marxist-Leninist</ent><br/
<hw>Marxist-Leninist</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>of or pertaining to Marxism-Leninism.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mary</ent><br/
<hw>Mar"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Marrow.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mary</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>interj.</pos> <def>See <er>Marry</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mary-bud</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"ry-bud`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The marigold; a blossom of the marigold.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maryolatry</ent><br/
<hw>Ma`ry*ol"a*try</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mariolatry.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marysole</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"ry*sole</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mary</ets>, the proper name + <ets>sole</ets> the fish.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A large British fluke, or flounder (<spn>Rhombus megastoma</spn>); -- called also <altname>carter</altname>, and <altname>whiff</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>marzipan</ent><br/
<hw>mar"zi*pan`</hw> <pr>(m<aum/r"z<icr/*p<acr/n`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A confection made of almonds and sugar mixed into a paste and molded into shapes.  Same as <er>marchpane.</er></def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masai</ent><br/
<hw>Masai</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A Nilotic language.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An African tribe inhabiting parts of Kenya and Tanzania.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note>Picture of <b>Masai women and children</b> standing by the roadside.<br/
 (Photographed in Kenya 1983 by PJC)<br/
<img src="images\masaiwom.jpg"></img><br/<br/
</note><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mascagnite</ent><br/
<ent>Mascagnin</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mas*ca"gnin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mas*ca"gnite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mascagnin</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Native sulphate of ammonia, found in volcanic districts; -- so named from <etsep>Mascagni</etsep>, who discovered it.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mascara</ent><br/
<hw>mascara</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A cosmetic used to darken and thicken the eye lashes, usually applied with a small brush.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mascle</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"cle</hw> <pr>(m<acr/s"k'l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>mascle</ets>, F. <ets>macle</ets>, L. <ets>macula</ets> spot, mesh of a net, LL. <ets>macula</ets>, <ets>macla</ets>, <ets>mascla</ets> a scale of a coat of mail. See <er>Mail</er> armor.]</ety> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>A lozenge voided.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mascled</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"cled</hw> <pr>(-k'ld)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Composed of, or covered with, lozenge-shaped scales; having lozenge-shaped divisions.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mascled armor</b></col>, <cd>armor composed of small lozenge-shaped scales of metal fastened on a foundation of leather or quilted cloth.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mascotte</ent><br/
<ent>Mascot</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mas"cot</hw>, <hw>Mas"cotte</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Through French fr. Pr. <ets>mascot</ets> a little sorcerer or magician, <ets>mascotto</ets> witchcraft, sorcery.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A person who is supposed to bring good luck to the household to which he or she belongs.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>Anything that brings good luck; especially, an animal kept by a group, as a sports team, to serve as a symbol and to bring luck.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masculate</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"cu*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>masculus</ets> male, masculine.]</ety> <def>To make strong.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Cockeram.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 899 --></p>

<p><ent>masculine</ent><br/
<hw>mas"cu*line</hw> <pr>(m<acr/s"k<usl/*l<icr/n)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>masculinus</ets>, fr. <ets>masculus</ets> male, manly, dim. of <ets>mas</ets> a male: cf. F. <ets>masculin</ets>. See <er>Male</er> masculine.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of the male sex; not female.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy <qex>masculine</qex> children, that is to say, thy sons.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Having the qualities of a man; suitable to, or characteristic of, a man; virile; not feminine or effeminate; strong; robust.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That lady, after her husband's death, held the reins with a <qex>masculine</qex> energy.</q> <rj><qau>Hallam.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Belonging to males; appropriated to, or used by, males.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <ldquo/A <xex>masculine</xex> church.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>Having the inflections of, or construed with, words pertaining especially to male beings, as distinguished from <contr>feminine</contr> and <contr>neuter</contr>. See <er>Gender</er>.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mas"cu*line*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mas"cu*line*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masculinity</ent><br/
<hw>Mas`cu*lin"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state or quality of being masculine; masculineness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mase</ent><br/
<hw>Mase</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. & v.</pos> <def>See <er>Maze</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maselyn</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"e*lyn</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A drinking cup. See 1st <er>Maslin</er>, 2.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mase</ent><br/
<hw>mase</hw> <pr>(m<amac/z)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[by back-formation from <er>maser</er>{2}.]</ety> <def>To emit coherent microwave radiation, as in a maser{2}.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maser</ent><br/
<hw>ma"ser</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Same as <er>Mazer</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <ety>[from <ets>M</ets>icrowave <ets>A</ets>mplification by <ets>S</ets>timulated <ets>E</ets>mission of <ets>R</ets>adiation.]</ety> <def>An electronic device producing coherent monochromatic microwave radiation; it produces less noise than other forms of <isa>microwave oscillator</isa>.</def> <mark>[acronym]</mark> <br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>MASH</ent><br/
<ent>MASH</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>MASH</hw>, <hw>M*A*S*H</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>An abbreviation for <altname>Mobile Army Surgical Hospital</altname>, consisting of the equipment and personnel required to perform emergency operations on injured soldiers, located in tents near the front lines of combat; <as>as, he worked in the 25th <ex>MASH</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mash</ent><br/
<hw>Mash</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mesh.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mash</ent><br/
<hw>Mash</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Akin to G. <ets>meisch</ets>, <ets>maisch</ets>, <ets>meische</ets>, <ets>maische</ets>, mash, wash, and prob. to AS. <ets>miscian</ets> to mix. See <er>Mix</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A mass of mixed ingredients reduced to a soft pulpy state by beating or pressure; a mass of anything in a soft pulpy state. Specifically <fld>(Brewing)</fld>, ground or bruised malt, or meal of rye, wheat, corn, or other grain (or a mixture of malt and meal) steeped and stirred in hot water for making the wort.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A mixture of meal or bran and water fed to animals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A mess; trouble.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mash tun</b></col>, <cd>a large tub used in making mash and wort.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mash</ent><br/
<hw>Mash</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mashed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mashing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Akin to G. <ets>meischen</ets>, <ets>maischen</ets>, to mash, mix, and prob. to <ets>mischen</ets>, E. <ets>mix</ets>. See 2d <er>Mash</er>.]</ety> <def>To convert into a mash; to reduce to a soft pulpy state by beating or pressure; to bruise; to crush; <as>as, to <ex>mash</ex> apples in a mill, or potatoes with a pestle</as>.</def> <specif>Specifically</specif> <fld>(Brewing)</fld>, <def>to convert, as malt, or malt and meal, into the mash which makes wort.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mashing tub</b></col>, <cd>a tub for making the mash in breweries and distilleries; -- called also <altname>mash tun</altname>, and <altname>mash vat</altname>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mashed potato</ent><br/
<hw>mashed potato</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>the name of a dance, briefly popular in the 1960's.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mashed potatoes</ent><br/
<hw>mashed potatoes</hw>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <def>Potatoes which have been boiled and mashed to a pulpy consistency, usu. with sparing addition of milk, salt, butter, or other flavoring.  It is a popular accompaniment to a meat course [U.S., 1900's], providing bulk and calories to a meal.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masher</ent><br/
<hw>Mash"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, mashes; also <fld>(Brewing)</fld>, a machine for making mash.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A charmer of women.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark>  <rj><au>London Punch.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mashy</ent><br/
<ent>Mashie</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mash"ie</hw>, <hw>Mash"y</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu>pl. <plw>Mashies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr></plu>. <ety>[Etym. uncert.]</ety> <def>A golf club like the iron, but with a shorter head, slightly more lofted, used chiefly for short approaches.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mashlin</ent><br/
<hw>Mash"lin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Maslin</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mashy</ent><br/
<hw>Mash"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Produced by crushing or bruising; resembling, or consisting of, a mash.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>masjid</ent><br/
<hw>masjid</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Arabic.]</ety> <def>A Muslim place of worship; a mosque.</def> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>musjid</asp>.]</altsp><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mosque.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mask</ent><br/
<hw>Mask</hw> <pr>(m<adot/sk)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>masque</ets>, LL. <ets>masca</ets>, <ets>mascha</ets>, <ets>mascus</ets>; cf. Sp. & Pg. <ets>m<aacute/scara</ets>, It. <ets>maschera</ets>; all fr. Ar. <ets>maskharat</ets> buffoon, fool, pleasantry, anything ridiculous or mirthful, fr. <ets>sakhira</ets> to ridicule, to laugh at.  Cf. <er>Masque</er>, <er>Masquerade</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A cover, or partial cover, for the face, used for disguise or protection; <as>as, a dancer's <ex>mask</ex>; a fencer's <ex>mask</ex>; a ball player's <ex>mask</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which disguises; a pretext or subterfuge.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A festive entertainment of dancing or other diversions, where all wear masks; a masquerade; hence, a revel; a frolic; a delusive show.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This thought might lead me through the world's vain <qex>mask</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A dramatic performance, formerly in vogue, in which the actors wore masks and represented mythical or allegorical characters.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A grotesque head or face, used to adorn keystones and other prominent parts, to spout water in fountains, and the like; -- called also <altname>mascaron</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Fort.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>In a permanent fortification, a redoubt which protects the caponiere.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A screen for a battery.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The lower lip of the larva of a dragon fly, modified so as to form a prehensile organ.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A person wearing a mask; a masker.</def></p>

<p><q>The <qex>mask</qex> that has the arm of the Indian queen.</q>  <rj><qau>G. W. Cable.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn>  <fld>(Sporting)</fld> <def>The head or face of a fox.</def></p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mask house</b></col>, <cd>a house for masquerades.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark></cs> -- <col><b>Death mask</b></col>, <cd>a cast of the face of a dead person.</cd><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mask</ent><br/
<hw>Mask</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Masked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Masking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cover, as the face, by way of concealment or defense against injury; to conceal with a mask or visor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They must all be <qex>masked</qex> and vizarded.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To disguise; to cover; to hide.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Masking</qex> the business from the common eye.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To conceal; also, to intervene in the line of.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>To cover or keep in check; <as>as, to <ex>mask</ex> a body of troops or a fortress by a superior force, while some hostile evolution is being carried out</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mask</ent><br/
<hw>Mask</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To take part as a masker in a masquerade.</def>  <rj><au>Cavendish.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To wear a mask; to be disguised in any way.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masked</ent><br/
<hw>Masked</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Wearing a mask or masks; characterized by masks; concealed; hidden.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Personate</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having the anterior part of the head differing decidedly in color from the rest of the plumage; -- said of birds.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Masked ball</b></col>, <cd>a ball in which the dancers wear masks.</cd> -- <col><b>Masked battery</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>a battery so placed as not to be seen by an enemy until it opens fire.</cd> <au>H. L. Scott.</au> -- <col><b>Masked crab</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a European crab (<spn>Corystes cassivelaunus</spn>) with markings on the carapace somewhat resembling a human face.</cd> -- <col><b>Masked pig</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a Japanese domestic hog (<spn>Sus pliciceps</spn>). Its face is deeply furrowed.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masker</ent><br/
<hw>Mask"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who wears a mask; one who appears in disguise at a masquerade.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masker</ent><br/
<hw>Mask"er</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To confuse; to stupefy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Holland.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maskery</ent><br/
<hw>Mask"er*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The dress or disguise of a masker; masquerade.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Marston.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maskinonge</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ki*nonge</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The muskellunge.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mask shell</ent><br/
<hw>Mask" shell`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any spiral marine shell of the genus <gen>Persona</gen>, having a curiously twisted aperture.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maslach</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"lach</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Ar. <ets>maslaq</ets>: cf. F. <ets>masloc</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>An excitant containing opium, much used by the Turks.</def>  <rj><au>Dunglison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maslin</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"lin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>missellane</ets>, <ets>misceline</ets>, <ets>miscelin</ets>, <ets>meslin</ets>, fr. <ets>miscellane</ets>. See <er>Miscellane</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A mixture composed of different materials</def>; especially: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A mixture of metals resembling brass.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A mixture of different sorts of grain, as wheat and rye.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>meslin</asp>, <asp>mislin</asp>, <asp>maselyn</asp>, <asp>mastlin</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A vessel made of maslin, 1 <sd>(a)</sd>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mead eke in a <qex>maselyn</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maslin</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"lin</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Composed of different sorts; <as>as, <ex>maslin</ex> bread, which is made of rye mixed with a little wheat</as>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>meslin</asp>, <asp>mislin</asp>, etc.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mason</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"son</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>ma<cced/on</ets>, LL. <ets>macio</ets>, <ets>machio</ets>, <ets>mattio</ets>, <ets>mactio</ets>, <ets>marcio</ets>, <ets>macerio</ets>; of uncertain origin.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>One whose occupation is to build with stone or brick; also, one who prepares stone for building purposes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A member of the fraternity of Freemasons. See <er>Freemason</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mason bee</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one of numerous species of solitary bees of the genus <gen>Osmia</gen>. They construct curious nests of hardened mud and sand.</cd> -- <col><b>Mason moth</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any moth whose larva constructs an earthen cocoon under the soil.</cd> -- <col><b>Mason shell</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a marine univalve shell of the genus <gen>Phorus</gen>; -- so called because it cements other shells and pebbles upon its own shell; a carrier shell.</cd> -- <col><b>Mason wasp</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any wasp that constructs its nest, or brood cells, of hardened mud. The female fills the cells with insects or spiders, paralyzed by a sting, and thus provides food for its larvae</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mason</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"son</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To build stonework or brickwork about, under, in, over, etc.; to construct by masons; -- with a prepositional suffix; <as>as, to <ex>mason</ex> up a well or terrace; to <ex>mason</ex> in a kettle or boiler.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masonic</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*son"ic</hw> <pr>(m<adot/*s<ocr/n"<icr/k)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to Freemasons or to their craft or mysteries.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masonite</ent><br/
<hw>Masonite</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[trademark.]</ety> <def>A type of fiberboard.</def> <mark>[trademark]</mark> <br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masonry</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"son*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>ma<cced/onnerie</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The art or occupation of a mason.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The work or performance of a mason; <as>as, good or bad <ex>masonry</ex>; skillful <ex>masonry</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is built by a mason; anything constructed of the materials used by masons, such as stone, brick, tiles, or the like. <stype>Dry masonry</stype> is applied to structures made without mortar.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The craft, institution, or mysteries of Freemasons; freemasonry.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masoola boat</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*soo"la boat`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <def>A kind of boat used on the coast of Madras, India. The planks are sewed together with strands of coir which cross over a wadding of the same material, so that the shock on taking the beach through surf is much reduced.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>masula</asp>, <asp>masulah</asp>, etc.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masora</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*so"ra</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NHeb. <ets>m<amac/s<omac/r<amac/h</ets> tradition.]</ety> <def>A Jewish critical work on the text of the Hebrew Scriptures, composed by several learned rabbis of the school of Tiberias, in the eighth and ninth centuries.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>Masorah</asp>, <asp>Massora</asp>, and <asp>Massorah</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masoret</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"o*ret</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A Masorite.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>Masorete</asp>, and <asp>Massorete</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masoretical</ent><br/
<ent>Masoretic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mas`o*ret"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mas`o*ret"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>massor<eacute/tique</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or relating to the Masora, or to its authors.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Masoretic points and accents</b></col>, <cd>the vowel points and accents of the Hebrew text of the Bible, of which the first mention is in the Masora.  See <er>vowel point</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masorite</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"o*rite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One of the writers of the Masora.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masque</ent><br/
<hw>Masque</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mask; a masquerade.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masquerade</ent><br/
<hw>Mas`quer*ade"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mascarade</ets>, fr. Sp. <ets>mascarada</ets>, or It. <ets>mascherata</ets>. See <er>Mask</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>An assembly of persons wearing masks, and amusing themselves with dancing, conversation, or other diversions.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In courtly balls and midnight <qex>masquerades</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A dramatic performance by actors in masks; a mask. See 1st <er>Mask</er>, 4.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Acting or living under false pretenses; concealment of something by a false or unreal show; pretentious show; disguise.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That <qex>masquerade</qex> of misrepresentation which invariably accompanied the political eloquence of Rome.</q> <rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A Spanish diversion on horseback.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masquerade</ent><br/
<hw>Mas`quer*ade"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Masqueraded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Masquerading</conjf>.]</vmorph><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To assemble in masks; to take part in a masquerade.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To frolic or disport in disquise; to make a pretentious show of being what one is not.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A freak took an ass in the head, and he goes into the woods, <qex>masquerading</qex> up and down in a lion's skin.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masquerade</ent><br/
<hw>Mas`quer*ade"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To conceal with masks; to disguise.</def> <ldquo/To <xex>masquerade</xex> vice.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Killingbeck.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masquerader</ent><br/
<hw>Mas`quer*ad"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who masquerades; a person wearing a mask; one disguised.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mass</ent><br/
<hw>Mass</hw> <pr>(m<adot/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>masse</ets>, <ets>messe</ets>, AS. <ets>maesse</ets>. LL. <ets>missa</ets>, from L. <ets>mittere</ets>, <ets>missum</ets>, to send, dismiss: cf. F. <ets>messe</ets>.  In the ancient churches, the public services at which the catechumens were permitted to be present were called <ets>missa catechumenorum</ets>, ending with the reading of the Gospel.  Then they were <ets>dismissed</ets> with these words : <ldquo/Ite, missa est<rdquo/ [<it>sc</it>. ecclesia], the congregation is dismissed.  After that the sacrifice proper began.  At its close the same words were said to those who remained.  So the word gave the name of <xex>Mass</xex> to the sacrifice in the Catholic Church. See <er>Missile</er>, and cf. <er>Christmas</er>, <er>Lammas</er>, <er>Mess</er> a dish, <er>Missal</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld> <def>The sacrifice in the sacrament of the Eucharist, or the consecration and oblation of the host.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>The portions of the Mass usually set to music, considered as a musical composition; -- namely, the <part>Kyrie</part>, the <part>Gloria</part>, the <part>Credo</part>, the <part>Sanctus</part>, and the <part>Agnus Dei</part>, besides sometimes an <part>Offertory</part> and the <part>Benedictus</part>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Canon of the Mass</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Canon</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>High Mass</b></col>, <cd>Mass with incense, music, the assistance of a deacon, subdeacon, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Low Mass</b></col>, <cd>Mass which is said by the priest throughout, without music.</cd> -- <col><b>Mass bell</b></col>, <cd>the sanctus bell. See <er>Sanctus</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mass book</b></col>, <cd>the missal or Roman Catholic service book.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mass</ent><br/
<hw>Mass</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Massed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Massing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To celebrate Mass.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mass</ent><br/
<hw>Mass</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>masse</ets>, F. <ets>masse</ets>, L. <ets>massa</ets>; akin to Gr. <?/ a barley cake, fr. <?/ to knead.  Cf. <er>Macerate</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A quantity of matter cohering together so as to make one body, or an aggregation of particles or things which collectively make one body or quantity, usually of considerable size; <as>as, a <ex>mass</ex> of ore, metal, sand, or water</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If it were not for these principles, the bodies of the earth, planets, comets, sun, and all things in them, would grow cold and freeze, and become inactive <qex>masses</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir I. Newton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A deep <qex>mass</qex> of continual sea is slower stirred<br/
To rage.</q> <rj><qau>Savile.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Phar.)</fld> <def>A medicinal substance made into a cohesive, homogeneous lump, of consistency suitable for making pills; <as>as, blue <ex>mass</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A large quantity; a sum.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the <qex>mass</qex> of gold that comes into Spain.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Raleigh.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He had spent a huge <qex>mass</qex> of treasure.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J. Davies.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Bulk; magnitude; body; size.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This army of such <qex>mass</qex> and charge.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The principal part; the main body.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Night closed upon the pursuit, and aided the <qex>mass</qex> of the fugitives in their escape.</q> <rj><qau>Jowett (Thucyd.).</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>The quantity of matter which a body contains, irrespective of its bulk or volume.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Mass</xex> and <xex>weight</xex> are often used, in a general way, as interchangeable terms, since the <xex>weight</xex> of a body is proportional to its <xex>mass</xex> (under the same or equal gravitative forces), and the <xex>mass</xex> is usually ascertained from the <xex>weight</xex>. Yet the two ideas, <xex>mass</xex> and <xex>weight</xex>, are quite distinct. <xex>Mass</xex> is the quantity of matter in a body; <xex>weight</xex> is the comparative force with which it tends towards the center of the earth. A <xex>mass</xex> of sugar and a <xex>mass</xex> of lead are assumed to be equal when they show an equal <xex>weight</xex> by balancing each other in the scales.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Blue mass</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Blue</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mass center</b></col> <fld>(Geom.)</fld>, <cd>the center of gravity of a triangle.</cd> -- <col><b>Mass copper</b></col>, <cd>native copper in a large mass.</cd> -- <col><b>Mass meeting</b></col>, <cd>a large or general assembly of people, usually a meeting having some relation to politics.</cd> -- <col><b>The masses</b></col>, <cd>the great body of the people, as contrasted with the higher classes; the populace.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mass</ent><br/
<hw>Mass</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To form or collect into a mass; to form into a collective body; to bring together into masses; to assemble.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But <qex>mass</qex> them together and they are terrible indeed.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Massacre</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"sa*cre</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. LL. <ets>mazacrium</ets>; cf. Prov. G. <ets>metzgern</ets>, <ets>metzgen</ets>, to kill cattle, G. <ets>metzger</ets> a butcher, and LG. <ets>matsken</ets> to cut, hew, OHG. <ets>meizan</ets> to cut, Goth. <ets>m<aacute/itan</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The killing of a considerable number of human beings under circumstances of atrocity or cruelty, or contrary to the usages of civilized people; <as>as, the <ex>massacre</ex> on St. Bartholomew's Day; the St. Valentine's Day <ex>massacre</ex>; the Amritsar <ex>massacre</ex>; the Wounded Knee <ex>massacre</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Murder.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Massacre</er>, <er>Butchery</er>, <er>Carnage</er>.</syn> <usage> <xex>Massacre</xex> denotes the promiscuous slaughter of <xex>many</xex> who can not make resistance, or much resistance. <xex>Butchery</xex> refers to cold-blooded cruelty in the killing of men as if they were brute beasts. <xex>Carnage</xex> points to slaughter as producing the heaped-up bodies of the slain.</usage><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I'll find a day to <qex>massacre</qex> them all,<br/
And raze their faction and their family.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If thou delight to view thy heinous deeds,<br/
Brhold this pattern of thy <qex>butcheries</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such a scent I draw<br/
Of <qex>carnage</qex>, prey innumerable!</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Massacre</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"sa*cre</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Massacred</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Massacring</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>massacrer</ets>. See <er>Massacre</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To kill in considerable numbers where much resistance can not be made; to kill with indiscriminate violence, without necessity, and contrary to the usages of nations; to butcher; to slaughter; -- limited to the killing of human beings.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If James should be pleased to <qex>massacre</qex> them all, as Maximian had <qex>massacred</qex> the Theban legion.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Massacrer</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"sa*crer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who massacres.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Massage</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"sage</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>A rubbing or kneading of the body, especially when performed as a hygienic or remedial measure.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Massage</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"sage</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>To treat by means of massage; to rub or knead; <as>as, to <ex>massage</ex> a patient with ointment</as>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Massagist</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"sag*ist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who practices massage; a masseur or masseuse.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Massasauga</ent><br/
<hw>Mas`sa*sau"ga</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The black rattlesnake (<spn>Crotalus tergemina</spn>, or <spn>Caudisona tergemina</spn>), found in the Mississippi Valley.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masse</ent><br/
<ent>Masse shot</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mass<eacute/</hw>, <it>or</it> <hw>Mass<eacute/ shot</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Billiards)</fld> <def>A stroke made with the cue held vertically.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masser</ent><br/
<hw>Mass"er</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A priest who celebrates Mass.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bale.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masseter</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"se*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ a chewer, <?/ a muscle of the lower jaw used in chewing, from <?/ to chew: cf. F. <ets>mass<eacute/ter</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The large muscle which raises the under jaw, and assists in mastication.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masseteric</ent><br/
<hw>Mas`se*ter"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the masseter.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masseterine</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"se*ter`ine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Masseteric.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masseur</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mas`seur"</hw> <pr>(m<adot/*s<ucir/r")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu>pl. <plw>Masseurs</plw> <pr>(m<adot/*s<ucir/rz"; <it>F.</it> m<adot/*s<ucir/r")</pr></plu>. <ety>[F. See <er>Massage</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A man who practices massage.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>An instrument used in the performance of massage.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masseuse</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mas`seuse"</hw> <pr>(m<adot/*s<ucir/z")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu>pl. <plw>Masseuses</plw> <pr>(<it>F.</it> m<adot/*s<ucir/z")</pr></plu>. <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>A woman who practices massage.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>massicot</ent><br/
<hw>mas"si*cot</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>massicot</ets>; E. <ets>masticot</ets> is a corruption.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Lead monoxide (also called <altname>Lead protoxide</altname>), <chform>PbO</chform>, obtained as a yellow amorphous powder, the fused and crystalline form of which is called <altname>litharge</altname>; lead ocher. It is used as a pigment.  It is also called <altname>lead oxide yellow</altname>, as opposed to <contr>red lead</contr>, which is lead tetroxide <chform>Pb3O4</chform>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Massicot</xex> is sometimes used by painters, and also as a drier in the composition of ointments and plasters.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>massif</ent><br/
<hw>massif</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>A block of the earth's crust bounded by faults and shifted to form peaks of a mountain range.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>massiness</ent><br/
<hw>mass"i*ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Massy</er>.]</ety> <def>The state or quality of being massy; ponderousness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 900 --></p>

<p><ent>massive</ent><br/
<hw>mass"ive</hw> <pr>(m<adot/s"<icr/v)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>massif</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Forming, or consisting of, a large mass; compacted; weighty; heavy; massy.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Massive</xex> armor.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Dr. H. More.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>In mass; not necessarily without a crystalline structure, but having no regular form; <as>as, a mineral occurs <ex>massive</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Massive rock</b></col> <fld>(Geol.)</fld>, <cd>a compact crystalline rock not distinctly schistose, as granite; also, with some authors, an eruptive rock.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Massively</ent><br/
<hw>Mass"ive*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a heavy mass.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Massiveness</ent><br/
<hw>Mass"ive*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state or quality of being massive; massiness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Massoola boat</ent><br/
<hw>Mas*soo"la boat`</hw>. <def>See <er>Masoola boat</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Massora</ent><br/
<hw>Mas*so"ra</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Masora</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Massoret</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"so*ret</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Masorite</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mass-produce</ent><br/
<hw>mass-produce</hw> <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To produce on a large scale.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mass-produced</ent><br/
<hw>mass-produced</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Produced in large quantity, often by automated or assembly-line techniques.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mass spectrometer</ent><br/
<hw>mass spectrometer</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Physics, Chemistry)</fld> <def>An analytical instrument which determines the mass of molecules of a substance or fragments of its molecules.  It functions by injecting ionized moecules or molecular gragments into a vacuum chamber subjected to a strong magnetic field, in which charged particles move in a curved trajectory.</def> <note>The mass is determined by observing the path of the molecule after being charged and accelerated in a magnetic field.  The path of the ionic fragment depends on the charge, velocity, and mass.  Several techniques of charging and detection are employed.  The mass information is usually used to infer structure or chemical composition of the substance analyzed.  Variants of mass spectrometer called <stype>high-resolution mass spectrometer</stype> permit determination of the mass of a molecule or molecular fragment with sufficient precision to unambiguously determine the atomic composition.</note><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mass-spectrometric</ent><br/
<hw>mass-spectrometric</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>of or pertaining to <er>mass spectrometry</er>; determined by <er>mass spectrometry</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mass spectroscopy</ent><br/
<ent>mass spectrometry</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mass spectrometry</hw> <hw>mass spectroscopy</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Physics, Chemistry)</fld> <def>A method for identifying chemical composition of substances by use of a <er>mass spectrometer</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Massy</ent><br/
<hw>Mass"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Massier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Massiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <def>Compacted into, or consisting of, a mass; having bulk and weight or substance; ponderous; bulky and heavy; weighty; heavy; <as>as, a <ex>massy</ex> shield; a <ex>massy</ex> rock.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your swords are now too <qex>massy</qex> for your strengths,<br/
And will not be uplifted.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yawning rocks in <qex>massy</qex> fragments fly.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mast</ent><br/
<hw>Mast</hw> <pr>(m<adot/st)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>maest</ets>, fem.; akin to G. <ets>mast</ets>, and E. <ets>meat</ets>. See <er>Meat</er>.]</ety> <def>The fruit of the oak and beech, or other forest trees; nuts; acorns.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Oak <qex>mast</qex>, and beech, . . . they eat.</q> <rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Swine under an oak filling themselves with the <qex>mast</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mast</ent><br/
<hw>Mast</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>maest</ets>, masc.; akin to D., G., Dan., & Sw. <ets>mast</ets>, Icel. <ets>mastr</ets>, and perh. to L. <ets>malus</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A pole, or long, strong, round piece of timber, or spar, set upright in a boat or vessel, to sustain the sails, yards, rigging, etc.  A mast may also consist of several pieces of timber united by iron bands, or of a hollow pillar of iron or steel.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The tallest pine<br/
Hewn on Norwegian hills, to be the <qex>mast</qex><br/
Of some great ammiral.<--sic--></q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The most common general names of <ex>masts</ex> are <stype>foremast</stype>, <stype>mainmast</stype>, and <stype>mizzenmast</stype>, each of which may be made of separate spars.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>The vertical post of a derrick or crane.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Aeronautics)</fld> <def>A spar or strut to which tie wires or guys are attached for stiffening purposes.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Afore the mast</b></col>, <col><b>Before the mast</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See under <er>Afore</er>, and <er>Before</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mast coat</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Coat</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mast hoop</b></col>, <cd>one of a number of hoops attached to the fore edge of a boom sail, which slip on the mast as the sail is raised or lowered; also, one of the iron hoops used in making a made mast. See <er>Made</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mast</ent><br/
<hw>Mast</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Masted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Masting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To furnish with a mast or masts; to put the masts of in position; <as>as, to <ex>mast</ex> a ship</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastabah</ent><br/
<ent>Mastaba</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mas"ta*ba</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> Also <hw>Mas"ta*bah</hw>  }</mhw>. <ety>[Ar. <ets>ma<cced/tabah</ets> a large stone bench.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>In Muslim countries, a fixed seat, common in dwellings and in public places.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <fld>(Egyptology)</fld> <def>A type of tomb, of the time of the Memphite dynasties, comprising an oblong structure with sloping sides (sometimes containing a decorated chamber, sometimes of solid masonry), and connected with a mummy chamber in the rock beneath.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastax</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mas"tax</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ mouth, jaws.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The pharynx of a rotifer. It usually contains four horny pieces. The two central ones form the incus, against which the mallei, or lateral ones, work so as to crush the food.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The lore of a bird.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masted</ent><br/
<hw>Mast"ed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Furnished with a mast or masts; -- chiefly in composition; <as>as, a three-<ex>masted</ex> schooner</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Master</ent><br/
<hw>Mast"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A vessel having (so many) masts; -- used only in compounds; <as>as, a two-<ex>master</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Master</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ter</hw> <pr>(m<adot/s"t<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>maistre</ets>, <ets>maister</ets>, OF. <ets>maistre</ets>, <ets>mestre</ets>, F. <ets>ma<icir/tre</ets>, fr. L. <ets>magister</ets>, orig. a double comparative from the root of <ets>magnus</ets> great, akin to Gr. <grk>me`gas</grk>.  Cf. <er>Maestro</er>, <er>Magister</er>, <er>Magistrate</er>, <er>Magnitude</er>, <er>Major</er>, <er>Mister</er>, <er>Mistress</er>, <er>Mickle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A male person having another living being so far subject to his will, that he can, in the main, control his or its actions; -- formerly used with much more extensive application than now.</def> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The employer of a servant.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The owner of a slave.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The person to whom an apprentice is articled.</def> <sd>(d)</sd> <def>A sovereign, prince, or feudal noble; a chief, or one exercising similar authority.</def> <sd>(e)</sd> <def>The head of a household.</def> <sd>(f)</sd> <def>The male head of a school or college.</def> <sd>(g)</sd> <def>A male teacher.</def> <sd>(h)</sd> <def>The director of a number of persons performing a ceremony or sharing a feast.</def> <sd>(i)</sd> <def>The owner of a docile brute, -- especially a dog or horse.</def> <sd>(j)</sd> <def>The controller of a familiar spirit or other supernatural being.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who uses, or controls at will, anything inanimate; <as>as, to be <ex>master</ex> of one's time</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Master</qex> of a hundred thousand drachms.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We are <qex>masters</qex> of the sea.</q> <rj><qau>Jowett (Thucyd.).</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One who has attained great skill in the use or application of anything; <as>as, a <ex>master</ex> of oratorical art</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Great <qex>masters</qex> of ridicule.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No care is taken to improve young men in their own language, that they may thoroughly understand and be <qex>masters</qex> of it.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A title given by courtesy, now commonly pronounced <pr><it>m<icr/ster</it></pr>, except when given to boys; -- sometimes written <asp>Mister</asp>, but usually abbreviated to <abbr>Mr.</abbr></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A young gentleman; a lad, or small boy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where there are little <qex>masters</qex> and misses in a house, they are impediments to the diversions of the servants.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The commander of a merchant vessel; -- usually called <altname>captain</altname>.  Also, a commissioned officer in the navy ranking next above ensign and below lieutenant; formerly, an officer on a man-of-war who had immediate charge, under the commander, of sailing the vessel.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A person holding an office of authority among the Freemasons, esp. the presiding officer; also, a person holding a similar office in other civic societies.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Little masters</b></col>, <cd>certain German engravers of the 16th century, so called from the extreme smallness of their prints.</cd> -- <col><b>Master in chancery</b></col>, <cd>an officer of courts of equity, who acts as an assistant to the chancellor or judge, by inquiring into various matters referred to him, and reporting thereon to the court.</cd> -- <col><b>Master of arts</b></col>, <cd>one who takes the second degree at a university; also, the degree or title itself, indicated by the abbreviation M. A., or A. M.</cd> -- <col><b>Master of the horse</b></col>, <cd>the third great officer in the British court, having the management of the royal stables, etc.  In ceremonial cavalcades he rides next to the sovereign.</cd> -- <col><b>Master of the rolls</b></col>, <cd>in England, an officer who has charge of the rolls and patents that pass the great seal, and of the records of the chancery, and acts as assistant judge of the court.</cd> <au>Bouvier.</au> <au>Wharton.</au> -- <col><b>Past master</b></col>, <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>one who has held the office of <xex>master</xex> in a lodge of Freemasons or in a society similarly organized.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>a person who is unusually expert, skilled, or experienced in some art, technique, or profession; -- usually used with <ptcl>at</ptcl> or <ptcl>of</ptcl>.</cd> -- <col><b>The old masters</b></col>, <cd>distinguished painters who preceded modern painters; especially, the celebrated painters of the 16th and 17th centuries.</cd> -- <col><b>To be master of one's self</b></col>, <cd>to have entire self-control; not to be governed by passion.</cd> -- <col><b>To be one's own master</b></col>, <cd>to be at liberty to act as one chooses without dictation from anybody.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Master</xex>, signifying <xex>chief</xex>, <xex>principal</xex>, <xex>masterly</xex>, <xex>superior</xex>, <xex>thoroughly skilled</xex>, etc., is often used adjectively or in compounds; as, <xex>master</xex> builder or <xex>master</xex>-builder, <xex>master</xex> chord or <xex>master</xex>-chord, <xex>master</xex> mason or <xex>master</xex>-mason, <xex>master</xex> workman or <xex>master</xex>-workman, <xex>master</xex> mechanic, <xex>master</xex> mind, <xex>master</xex> spirit, <xex>master</xex> passion, etc.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Throughout the city by the <qex>master</qex> gate.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Master joint</b></col> <fld>(Geol.)</fld>, <cd>a quarryman's term for the more prominent and extended joints traversing a rock mass.</cd> -- <col><b>Master key</b></col>, <cd>a key adapted to open several locks differing somewhat from each other; figuratively, a rule or principle of general application in solving difficulties.</cd> -- <col><b>Master lode</b></col> <fld>(Mining)</fld>, <cd>the principal vein of ore.</cd> -- <col><b>Master mariner</b></col>, <cd>an experienced and skilled seaman who is certified to be competent to command a merchant vessel.</cd> -- <col><b>Master sinew</b></col> <fld>(Far.)</fld>, <cd>a large sinew that surrounds the hough of a horse, and divides it from the bone by a hollow place, where the windgalls are usually seated.</cd> -- <col><b>Master singer</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Mastersinger</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Master stroke</b></col>, <cd>a capital performance; a masterly achievement; a consummate action; <as>as, a <ex>master stroke</ex> of policy</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>Master tap</b></col> <fld>(Mech.)</fld>, <cd>a tap for forming the thread in a screw cutting die.</cd> -- <col><b>Master touch</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The touch or skill of a master</cd>. <au>Pope.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Some part of a performance which exhibits very skillful work or treatment.</cd> <ldquo/Some <xex>master touches</xex> of this admirable piece.<rdquo/ <au>Tatler.</au> -- <col><b>Master work</b></col>, <cd>the most important work accomplished by a skilled person, as in architecture, literature, etc.; also, a work which shows the skill of a master; a masterpiece.</cd> -- <col><b>Master workman</b></col>, <cd>a man specially skilled in any art, handicraft, or trade, or who is an overseer, foreman, or employer.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Master</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mastered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mastering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become the master of; to subject to one's will, control, or authority; to conquer; to overpower; to subdue.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Obstinacy and willful neglects must be <qex>mastered</qex>, even though it cost blows.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To gain the command of, so as to understand or apply; to become an adept in; <as>as, to <ex>master</ex> a science</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To own; to posses.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wealth<br/
That the world <qex>masters</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Master</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ter</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be skillful; to excel.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>master-at-arms</ent><br/
<hw>master-at-arms</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The senior petty officer of a ship, responsible for discipline aboard the ship.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masterdom</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ter*dom</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Master</ets> + <ets>-dom</ets>.]</ety> <def>Dominion; rule; command.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mastered</ent><br/
<hw>mastered</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Learned thoroughly.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> down, down pat(predicate).</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masterful</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ter*ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Inclined to play the master; domineering; imperious; arbitrary.</def>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Having the skill or power of a master; indicating or expressing power or mastery.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His <qex>masterful</qex>, pale face.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs. Browning.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masterfully</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ter*ful*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a masterful manner; imperiously.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A lawless and rebellious man who held lands <qex>masterfully</qex> and in high contempt of the royal authority.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masterhood</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ter*hood</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state of being a master; hence, disposition to command or hector.</def>  <rj><au>C. Bront<eacute/.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masterless</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ter*less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Destitute of a master or owner; ungoverned or ungovernable.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mas"ter*less*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masterliness</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ter*li*ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being masterly; ability to control wisely or skillfully.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masterly</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ter*ly</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Suitable to, or characteristic of, a master; indicating thorough knowledge or superior skill and power; showing a master's hand; <as>as, a <ex>masterly</ex> design; a <ex>masterly</ex> performance; a <ex>masterly</ex> policy.</as></def> <ldquo/A wise and <xex>masterly</xex> inactivity.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Sir J. Mackintosh.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Imperious; domineering; arbitrary.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masterly</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ter*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>With the skill of a master.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou dost speak <qex>masterly</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masterous</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ter*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Masterly.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masterpiece</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ter*piece`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Anything done or made with extraordinary skill; a capital performance; a chef-d'oeuvre; a supreme achievement.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The top and <qex>masterpiece</qex> of art.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Dissimulation was his <qex>masterpiece</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Claredon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastership</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ter*ship</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The state or office of a master.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Mastery; dominion; superior skill; superiority.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where noble youths for <qex>mastership</qex> should strive.</q> <rj><qau>Driden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Chief work; masterpiece.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An ironical title of respect.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How now, seignior Launce! what news with your <qex>mastership</qex>?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastersinger</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ter*sing`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[A translation of G. <ets>meisters<aum/nger</ets>.]</ety> <def>One of a class of poets which flourished in Nuremberg and some other cities of Germany in the 15th and 16th centuries.  They bound themselves to observe certain arbitrary laws of rhythm.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Master vibrator</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ter vi"bra*tor</hw>. <def>In an internal-combustion engine with two or more cylinders, an induction coil and vibrator placed in the circuit between the battery or magneto and the coils for the different cylinders, which are used without vibrators of their own.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masterwort</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ter*wort`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A tall and coarse European umbelliferous plant (<spn>Peucedanum Ostruthium</spn>, formerly <spn>Imperatoria</spn>).</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The <spn>Astrantia major</spn>, a European umbelliferous plant with a showy colored involucre.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>Improperly, the <altname>cow parsnip</altname> (<spn>Heracleum lanatum</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastery</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ter*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Masteries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OF. <ets>maistrie</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The position or authority of a master; dominion; command; supremacy; superiority.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If divided by mountains, they will fight for the <qex>mastery</qex> of the passages of the tops.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Raleigh.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Superiority in war or competition; victory; triumph; preeminence.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The voice of them that shout for <qex>mastery</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xxxii. 18.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every man that striveth for the <qex>mastery</qex> is temperate in all things.</q> <rj><qau>1 Cor. ix. 25.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O, but to have gulled him<br/
Had been a <qex>mastery</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Contest for superiority.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Holland.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A masterly operation; a feat.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will do a <qex>maistrie</qex> ere I go.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <specif>Specifically,</specif> <def>the philosopher's stone.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>The act process of mastering; the state of having mastered.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He could attain to a <qex>mastery</qex> in all languages.</q> <rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The learning and <qex>mastery</qex> of a tongue, being unpleasant in itself, should not be cumbered with other difficulties.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastful</ent><br/
<hw>Mast"ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See 1st <er>Mast</er>.]</ety> <def>Abounding in mast; producing mast in abundance; <as>as, the <ex>mastful</ex> forest; a <ex>mastful</ex> chestnut.</as></def>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masthead</ent><br/
<hw>Mast"head`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The top or head of a mast; the part of a mast above the hounds.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masthead</ent><br/
<hw>Mast"head"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To cause to go to the masthead as a punishment.</def>  <rj><au>Marryat.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masthouse</ent><br/
<hw>Mast"house`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A building in which vessels' masts are shaped, fitted, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastic</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>mastiche</ets>, <ets>mastichum</ets>, Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ to chew, because of its being used in the East for chewing.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mastich</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A low shrubby tree of the genus <gen>Pistacia</gen> (<spn>Pistacia Lentiscus</spn>), growing upon the islands and coasts of the Mediterranean, and producing a valuable resin; -- called also, <altname>mastic tree</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A resin exuding from the mastic tree, and obtained by incision.  The best is in yellowish white, semitransparent tears, of a faint smell, and is used as an astringent and an aromatic, also as an ingredient in varnishes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A kind of cement composed of burnt clay, litharge, and linseed oil, used for plastering walls, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Barbary mastic</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the <spn>Pistachia Atlantica</spn>.</cd> -- <col><b>Peruvian mastic tree</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a small tree (<spn>Schinus Molle</spn>) with peppery red berries; -- called also <altname>pepper tree</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>West Indian mastic</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a lofty tree (<spn>Bursera gummifera</spn>) full of gum resin in every part.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masticable</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ti*ca*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Capable of being masticated.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masticador</ent><br/
<hw>Mas`ti*ca"dor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Sp. <ets>mastigador</ets>. See <er>Masticate</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Man.)</fld> <def>A part of a bridle, the slavering bit.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mastigador</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masticate</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ti*cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Masticated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Masticating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>masticatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>masticare</ets> to chew, prob. fr. <ets>mastiche</ets> mastic. See <er>Mastic</er>.]</ety> <def>To grind or crush with, or as with, the teeth and prepare for swallowing and digestion; to chew; <as>as, to <ex>masticate</ex> food</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masticater</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ti*ca`ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who masticates.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastication</ent><br/
<hw>Mas`ti*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>masticatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mastication</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act or operation of masticating; chewing, as of food.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mastication</qex> is a necessary preparation of solid aliment, without which there can be no good digestion.</q> <rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masticator</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ti*ca`tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who masticates.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A machine for cutting meat into fine pieces for toothless people; also, a machine for cutting leather, India rubber, or similar tough substances, into fine pieces, in some processes of manufacture.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masticatory</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ti*ca*to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>masticatoire</ets>.]</ety> <def>Chewing; adapted to perform the office of chewing food.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masticatory</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ti*ca*to*ry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>-ries</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A substance to be chewed to increase the saliva.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastich</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"tich</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mastic</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masticin</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ti*cin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A white, amorphous, tenacious substance resembling caoutchouc, and obtained as an insoluble residue of mastic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masticot</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ti*cot</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Massicot.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastiff</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"tiff</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mastiffs</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>. [<plw>Mastives</plw> is irregular and unusual.]</plu> <ety>[Prob. fr. Prov. E. <ets>masty</ets>, adj., large, n., a great dog, prob. fr. <ets>mast</ets> fruit, and hence, lit., fattened with mast.  There is perh. confusion with OF. <ets>mestif</ets> mongrel; cf. also F. <ets>m<acir/tin</ets> mastiff, OF. <ets>mastin</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A breed of large dogs noted for strength and courage.  There are various strains, differing in form and color, and characteristic of different countries.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mastiff bat</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>, any bat of the genus <gen>Molossus</gen>; so called because the face somewhat resembles that of a mastiff.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastigophora</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ti*go*phor`a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>ma`stix</grk>, <grk>ma`stigos</grk>, a whip + <grk>fe`rein</grk> to bear.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A phylum of protozoans the kingdom <kingdom>Protista</kingdom>, consisting mainly of free-living flagellated unicellular organisms, lacking photosynthetic capability.  Some members are pathogenic in man.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mastigopod</ent><br/
<hw>mas"ti*go*pod</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the Mastigopoda.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastigopoda</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mas`ti*gop"o*da</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>ma`stix</grk>, <grk>ma`stigos</grk>, a whip + <grk>poy`s</grk>, <grk>podo`s</grk>, foot.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Formerly considered identical to the Infusoria, now distinguished from that group, which has been reordered.  See <er>Mastigophora</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastigure</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"ti*gure</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>ma`stix</grk>, <grk>ma`stigos</grk>, a scourge + <?/ tail.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of several large spiny-tailed lizards of the genus <gen>Uromastix</gen>.  They inhabit Southern Asia and North Africa.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masting</ent><br/
<hw>Mast"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The act or process of putting a mast or masts into a vessel; also, the scientific principles which determine the position of masts, and the mechanical methods of placing them.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Masting house</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a large building, with suitable mechanism overhanging the water, used for stepping and unstepping the masts of vessels.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastitis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mas*ti"tis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>masto`s</grk> breast + <ets>-itis</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Inflammation of the breast.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastless</ent><br/
<hw>Mast"less</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See 1st <er>Mast</er>.]</ety> <def>Bearing no mast; <as>as, a <ex>mastless</ex> oak or beech</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastless</ent><br/
<hw>Mast"less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See 2d <er>Mast</er>.]</ety> <def>Having no mast; <as>as, a <ex>mastless</ex> vessel</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 901 --></p>

<p><ent>Mastlin</ent><br/
<hw>Mast"lin</hw> <pr>(m<acr/st"l<icr/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Maslin</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastodon</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"to*don</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>masto`s</grk> the breast + <grk>'odoy`s</grk>, <grk>'odo`ntos</grk>, a tooth. So called from the conical projections upon its molar teeth.]</ety> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>An extinct genus of mammals closely allied to the elephant, but having less complex molar teeth, and often a pair of lower, as well as upper, tusks, which are incisor teeth.  The species were mostly larger than elephants, and their remains occur in nearly all parts of the world in deposits ranging from Miocene to late Quaternary time.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastodonsaurus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mas`to*don*sau"rus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. E. <ets>Mastodon</ets> + Gr. <grk>say^ros</grk> a lizard.]</ety> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>A large extinct genus of labyrinthodonts, found in the European Triassic rocks.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastodontic</ent><br/
<hw>Mas`to*don"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to, or resembling, a mastodon; <as>as, <ex>mastodontic</ex> dimensions</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Everett.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastodyny</ent><br/
<ent>Mastodynia</ent><br/
<mhw>\'d8<hw>Mas`to*dyn"i*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mas*tod"y*ny</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr></mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. <ets>mastodynia</ets>, fr. Gr. <grk>masto`s</grk> the breast + <?/ pain.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Pain occuring in the mamma or female breast, -- a form of neuralgia.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastoid</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"toid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/; <grk>masto`s</grk> the breast + <grk>e'i^dos</grk> form: cf. F. <ets>masto<ium/de</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Resembling the nipple or the breast; -- applied specifically to a process of the temporal bone behind the ear.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Pertaining to, or in the region of, the mastoid process; mastoidal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastoidal</ent><br/
<hw>Mas*toid"al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Mastoid</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastoiditis</ent><br/
<hw>Mas`toid*i*tis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Mastoid</er>, and <er>-itis</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Inflammation in the mastoid process of the temporal bone.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastology</ent><br/
<hw>Mas*tol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>masto`s</grk> the breast + <ets>-logy</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mastologie</ets>.]</ety> <def>The natural history of Mammalia.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastotermes</ent><br/
<hw>Mastotermes</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A primitive genus of termites, mostly extinct; sometimes considered the most primitive isopterans.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Mastotermes</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastotermitidae</ent><br/
<hw>Mastotermitidae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family comprising primitive termites.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Mastotermitidae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mastress</ent><br/
<hw>Mas"tress</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mistress.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>masturbate</ent><br/
<hw>masturbate</hw> <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>masturbated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>masturbating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To achieve sexual gratification by stimulating one's own sexual organs, without the aid of a partner; -- typically to the point of orgasm.</def>  -- <wordforms><wf>masturbator</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> wank, she-bop, jack off, jerk off, whack off, beat the meat.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>masturbation</ent><br/
<hw>mas`tur*ba"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>masturbatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>masturbari</ets> to practice onanism: cf. F. <ets>masturbation</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act of masturbating; sexual self-gratification; onanism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masty</ent><br/
<hw>Mast"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See 1st <er>Mast</er>.]</ety> <def>Full of mast; abounding in acorns, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Masula boat</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*su"la boat`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <def>Same as <er>Masoola boat</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mat</ent><br/
<hw>Mat</hw> <pr>(m<acr/t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Matte</er>.]</ety> <def>A name given by coppersmiths to an alloy of copper, tin, iron, etc., usually called <xex>white metal</xex>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>matt</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mat</ent><br/
<hw>Mat</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OF. See 4th <er>Mate</er>.]</ety> <def>Cast down; dejected; overthrown; slain.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When he saw them so piteous and so <qex>maat</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mat</ent><br/
<hw>Mat</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>matt</ets>, <ets>meatt</ets>, fr. L. <ets>matta</ets> a mat made of rushes.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A thick flat fabric of sedge, rushes, flags, husks, straw, hemp, or similar material, placed on the floor and used for wiping and cleaning shoes at the door, for covering the floor of a hall or room to protect its surface, and for other purposes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any similar flat object made of fabric or other material, such as rubber or plastic, placed flat on a surface for various uses, as for covering plant houses, putting beneath dishes or lamps on a table, securing rigging from friction, and the like.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Anything growing thickly, or closely interwoven, so as to resemble a mat in form or texture; <as>as, a <ex>mat</ex> of weeds; a <ex>mat</ex> of hair.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An ornamental border made of paper, pasterboard, metal, etc., put under the glass which covers a framed picture; <as>as, the <ex>mat</ex> of a daguerreotype</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mat grass</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A low, tufted, European grass (<spn>Nardus stricta</spn>)</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Same as <er>Matweed</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mat rush</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a kind of rush (<spn>Scirpus lacustris</spn>) used in England for making mats.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mat</ent><br/
<hw>Mat</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Matted</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Matting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cover or lay with mats.</def>  <rj><au>Evelyn.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To twist, twine, or felt together; to interweave into, or like, a mat; to entangle.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And o'er his eyebrows hung his <qex>matted</qex> hair.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mat</ent><br/
<hw>Mat</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To grow thick together; to become interwoven or felted together like a mat, as hair when wetted with a sticky substance; <as>as, a long-haired cat whose fur is <ex>matted</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matabeles</ent><br/
<ent>Matabele</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mat`a*be"le</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <it>or</it> <hw>Mat`a*be"les</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>prop. n. pl.</pos>, <sing><it>sing.</it> <singw>Matabele</singw>.</sing> <altsp>[Written also <asp>Matabili</asp>.]</altsp> <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>A warlike South African Kaffir tribe.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matachin</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma`ta*chin"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp.]</ety> <def>An old dance with swords and bucklers; a sword dance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mataco</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"a*co</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The three-banded armadillo (<spn>Tolypeutis tricinctus</spn>). See <xex>Illust.</xex> under <er>Loricata</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matadore</ent><br/
<ent>Matador</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mat"a*dor</hw>, <hw>Mat"a*dore</hw>}</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>matador</ets>, prop., a killer, fr. <ets>matar</ets> to kill, L. <ets>mactare</ets> to sacrifice, kill.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The killer; the man appointed to kill the bull in bullfights; a bullfighter; a toreador.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Card Playing)</fld> <def>In the game of quadrille or omber, the three principal trumps, the ace of spades being the first, the ace of clubs the third, and the second being the deuce of a black trump or the seven of a red one.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When Lady Tricksey played a four,<br/
You took it with a <qex>matadore</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>[Skat]</fld> <def>The jack of clubs, or any other trump held in sequence with it, whether by the player or by his adversaries.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn>  <def>A certain game of dominoes in which four dominoes (the 4-3, 5-2, 6-1, and double blank), called <xex>matadors</xex>, may be played at any time in any way.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matagasse</ent><br/
<hw>Mat`a*gasse"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A shrike or butcher bird; -- called also <altname>mattages</altname>.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matajuelo</ent><br/
<hw>Ma`ta*jue"lo</hw> <pr>(m<aum/`t<adot/*hw<amac/"l<omac/; 239)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Sp. <ets>matajud<iacute/o</ets> a kind of fish.]</ety> <def>A large squirrel fish (<spn>Holocentrus ascensionis</spn>) of Florida and the West Indies.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matajuelo blanco</ent><br/
<hw>Ma`ta*jue"lo blan"co</hw> <pr>(m<aum/`t<adot/*hw<amac/"l<omac/ bl<aum/<nsm/"k<omac/)</pr>. <ety>[Sp. <ets>blanco</ets> white.]</ety> <def>A West Indian food fish (<spn>Malacanthus plumieri</spn>) related to the tilefish.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matamata</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma`ta*ma"ta</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pg.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The bearded tortoise (<spn>Chelys fimbriata</spn>) of South American rivers.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matanza</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*tan"za</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp., slaughter, fr. <ets>matar</ets> to kill.]</ety> <def>A place where animals are slaughtered for their hides and tallow.</def> <mark>[Western U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Match</ent><br/
<hw>Match</hw> <pr>(m<acr/ch)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>macche</ets>, F. <ets>m<egrave/che</ets>, F. <ets>m<egrave/che</ets>, fr. L. <ets>myxa</ets> a lamp nozzle, Gr. <grk>my`xa</grk> mucus, nostril, a lamp nozzle.  Cf. <er>Mucus</er>.]</ety> <def>Anything used for catching and retaining or communicating fire, made of some substance which takes fire readily, or remains burning some time; esp., a small strip or splint of wood or cardboard dipped at one end in a substance which can be easily ignited by friction, as a preparation of phosphorus or chlorate of potassium.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Match tub</b></col>, <cd>a tub with a perforated cover for holding slow matches for firing cannon, esp. on board ship.  The tub contains a little water in the bottom, for extinguishing sparks from the lighted matches.</cd> -- <col><b>Quick match</b></col>, <cd>threads of cotton or cotton wick soaked in a solution of gunpowder mixed with gum arabic and boiling water and afterwards strewed over with mealed powder. It burns at the rate of one yard in thirteen seconds, and is used as priming for heavy mortars, fireworks, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Slow match</b></col>, <cd>slightly twisted hempen rope soaked in a solution of limewater and saltpeter or washed in a lye of water and wood ashes. It burns at the rate of four or five inches an hour, and is used for firing cannon, fireworks, etc.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Match</ent><br/
<hw>Match</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>macche</ets>, AS. <ets>gemaecca</ets>; akin to <ets>gemaca</ets>, and to OS. <ets>gimako</ets>, OHG. <ets>gimah</ets> fitting, suitable, convenient, Icel. <ets>mark</ets> suitable, <ets>maki</ets> mate, Sw. <ets>make</ets>, Dan. <ets>mage</ets>; all from the root of E. <ets>make</ets>, v. See <er>Make</er> mate, and <er>Make</er>, <pos>v.</pos>, and cf. <er>Mate</er> an associate.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A person or thing equal or similar to another; one able to mate or cope with another; an equal; a mate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Government . . . makes an innocent man, though of the lowest rank, a <qex>match</qex> for the mightiest of his fellow subjects.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A bringing together of two parties suited to one another, as for a union, a trial of skill or force, a contest, or the like</def>; <specif>specifically:</specif> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A contest to try strength or skill, or to determine superiority; a sporting contest; an emulous struggle.</def> <ldquo/Many a warlike <xex>match</xex>.<rdquo/  <au>Drayton.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A solemn <qex>match</qex> was made; he lost the prize.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>A matrimonial union; a marriage.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An agreement, compact, etc.</def> <ldquo/Thy hand upon that <xex>match</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Love doth seldom suffer itself to be confined by other <qex>matches</qex> than those of its own making.</q> <rj><qau>Boyle.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A candidate for matrimony; one to be gained in marriage.</def> <ldquo/She . . . was looked upon as the richest <xex>match</xex> of the West.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Clarendon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Equality of conditions in contest or competition, or one who provides equal competition to another in a contest; <as>as, he had no <ex>match</ex> as a swordsman within the city</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It were no <qex>match</qex>, your nail against his horn.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Suitable combination or bringing together; that which corresponds or harmonizes with something else; <as>as, the carpet and curtains are a <ex>match</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Founding)</fld> <def>A perforated board, block of plaster, hardened sand, etc., in which a pattern is partly imbedded when a mold is made, for giving shape to the surfaces of separation between the parts of the mold.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Match boarding</b></col> <fld>(Carp.)</fld>, <cd>boards fitted together with tongue and groove, or prepared to be so fitted; a surface composed of match boarding.  See <er>matchboard</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Match game</b></col>, <cd>a game arranged as a test of superiority.</cd> -- <col><b>Match plane</b></col> <fld>(Carp.)</fld>, <cd>either of the two planes used to shape the edges of boards which are joined by grooving and tonguing.</cd> -- <col><b>Match plate</b></col> <fld>(Founding)</fld>, <cd>a board or plate on the opposite sides of which the halves of a pattern are fastened, to facilitate molding.</cd> <au>Knight.</au> -- <col><b>Match wheel</b></col> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>a cogwheel of suitable pitch to work with another wheel; specifically, one of a pair of cogwheels of equal size.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Match</ent><br/
<hw>Match</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Matched</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Matching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be a mate or match for; to be able to complete with; to rival successfully; to equal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No settled senses of the world can <qex>match</qex><br/
The pleasure of that madness.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To furnish with its match; to bring a match, or equal, against; to show an equal competitor to; to set something in competition with, or in opposition to, as equal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No history or antiquity can <qex>match</qex>is policies and his conduct.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To oppose as equal; to contend successfully against.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Eternal might<br/
To <qex>match</qex> with their inventions they presumed<br/
So easy, and of his thunder made a scorn.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To make or procure the equal of, or that which is exactly similar to, or corresponds with; <as>as, to <ex>match</ex> a vase or a horse; to <ex>match</ex> cloth.</as></def> <ldquo/<xex>Matching</xex> of patterns and colors.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To make equal, proportionate, or suitable; to adapt, fit, or suit (one thing <xex>to</xex> another).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let poets <qex>match</qex> their subject to their strength.</q> <rj><qau>Roscommon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To marry; to give in marriage.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A senator of Rome survived,<br/
Would not have <qex>matched</qex> his daughter with a king.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To fit together, or make suitable for fitting together; specifically, to furnish with a tongue and a groove, at the edges; <as>as, to <ex>match</ex> boards</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Matching machine</b></col>, <cd>a planing machine for forming a tongue or a groove on the edge of a board.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Match</ent><br/
<hw>Match</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be united in marriage; to mate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I hold it a sin to <qex>match</qex> in my kindred.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let tigers <qex>match</qex> with hinds, and wolves with sheep.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be of equal, or similar, size, figure, color, or quality; to tally; to suit; to correspond; <as>as, these vases <ex>match</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matchable</ent><br/
<hw>Match"a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Capable of being matched; comparable on equal conditions; adapted to being joined together; correspondent.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Match"a*ble*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sir Walter Raleigh . . . is <qex>matchable</qex> with the best of the ancients.</q> <rj><qau>Hakewill.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>matchboard</ent><br/
<hw>matchboard</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A board that has a groove cut into one edge and a tongue cut into the other so they fit tightly together (as in a floor); see <cref>match boarding</cref>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>matchbook</ent><br/
<hw>matchbook</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A small folder of paper safety matches.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> match book.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>match box</ent><br/
<ent>matchbox</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>match"box`</hw>, <hw>match" box`</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a box for holding matches.  See first <er>match</er>, <pos>n.</pos></def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>matchbush</ent><br/
<hw>match"bush`</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>any of several plants of the genus <gen>Gutierrezia</gen> having tiny matchlike flowerheads.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> matchweed.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Match-cloth</ent><br/
<hw>Match"-cloth`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A coarse cloth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Match-coat</ent><br/
<hw>Match"-coat`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A coat made of match-cloth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matcher</ent><br/
<hw>Match"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who, or that which, matches; a matching machine. See under 3d <er>Match</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Match game</ent><br/
<hw>Match game</hw>. <def>A game arranged as a test of superiority; also, one of a series of such games.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>matchet</ent><br/
<hw>matchet</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a large heavy knife used in Central and South America as a weapon or for cutting vegetation; usually called <altname>machete</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> machete, panga.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>matching</ent><br/
<hw>matching</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>  <def>having identical or closely similar appearance or properties; <as>as, a pair of <ex>matching</ex> candlesticks</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> duplicate, twin(prenominal), twinned.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>Harmonious and pleasing in appearance when used together; <as>as, a <ex>matching</ex> skirt and blouse</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> coordinated; color-coordinated.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matchless</ent><br/
<hw>Match"less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Mateless</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Having no equal; unequaled.</def> <ldquo/A <xex>matchless</xex> queen.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Waller.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Unlike each other; unequal; unsuited.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/<xex>Matchless</xex> ears.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Match"less*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Match"less*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matchlock</ent><br/
<hw>Match"lock`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An old form of gunlock containing a match for firing the priming; hence, a musket fired by means of a match.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matchmaker</ent><br/
<hw>Match"mak`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who makes matches for burning or kinding.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who tries to bring about marriages.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matchmaking</ent><br/
<hw>Match"mak`ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or process of making matches for kindling or burning.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act or process of trying to bring about a marriage for others.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matchmaking</ent><br/
<hw>Match"mak`ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Busy in making or contriving marriages; <as>as, a <ex>matchmaking</ex> woman</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Match play</ent><br/
<hw>Match play</hw>. <fld>(Golf)</fld> <def>Play in which the score is reckoned by counting the holes won or lost by each side; -- distinguished from <contr>medal play</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>matchwood</ent><br/
<hw>matchwood</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>wood in small pieces or splinters; <as>as, the vessel was beaten to <ex>matchwood</ex> on the rocks</as>.</def> <wns>[wns=1 & 3]</wns><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> splinters.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Wood suitable for making matchsticks.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mate</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma"te</hw> <pr>(m<aum/"t<asl/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp.]</ety> <def>The Paraguay tea, being the dried leaf of the Brazilian holly (<spn>Ilex Paraguensis</spn>).  The infusion has a pleasant odor, with an agreeable bitter taste, and is much used for tea in South America.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mate</ent><br/
<hw>Mate</hw> <pr>(m<amac/t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mat</ets>, abbrev. fr. <eacute/chec et <ets>mat</ets>. See <er>Checkmate</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Chess)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Checkmate</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mate</ent><br/
<hw>Mate</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>See 2d <er>Mat</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mate</ent><br/
<hw>Mate</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mater</ets> to fatigue, enfeeble, humiliate, checkmate. See <er>Mate</er> checkmate.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To confuse; to confound.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To checkmate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mate</ent><br/
<hw>Mate</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Perhaps for older <ets>make</ets> a companion; cf. also OD. <ets>maet</ets> companion, mate, D. <ets>maat</ets>.  Cf. <er>Make</er> a companion, <er>Match</er> a mate.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who customarily associates with another; a companion; an associate; any object which is associated or combined with a similar object.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, specifically, a husband or wife; and among the lower animals, one of a pair associated for propagation and the care of their young.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A suitable companion; a match; an equal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye knew me once no <qex>mate</qex><br/
For you; there sitting where you durst not soar.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>An officer in a merchant vessel ranking next below the captain.  If there are more than one bearing the title, they are called, respectively, <xex>first mate</xex>, <xex>second mate</xex>, <xex>third mate</xex>, etc.  In the navy, a subordinate officer or assistant; <as>as, master's <ex>mate</ex>; surgeon's <ex>mate</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mate</ent><br/
<hw>Mate</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mated</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To match; to marry.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If she be <qex>mated</qex> with an equal husband.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To match one's self against; to oppose as equal; to compete with.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is no passion in the mind of man so weak but it <qex>mates</qex> and masters the fear of death.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I, . . . in the way of loyalty and truth, . . .<br/
Dare <qex>mate</qex> a sounder man than Surrey can be.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To breed; to bring (animals) together for the purpose of breeding; <as>as, she <ex>mated</ex> a doberman with a German shepherd</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To join together; to fit together; to connect; to link; <as>as, he <ex>mated</ex> a saw blade to a broom handle to cut inaccessible branches.</as></def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mate</ent><br/
<hw>Mate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be or become a mate or mates, especially in sexual companionship; <as>as, some birds <ex>mate</ex> for life; this bird will not <ex>mate</ex> with that one.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mated</ent><br/
<hw>mated</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Brought together for sexual activity; bred; -- of animals.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Sorted into pairs of identical size, color, or other properties; -- used of gloves, socks, etc.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> paired.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Same as <er>married</er>.  Opposite of <ant>unmarried</ant>; <as>as, they were a devoted couple, <ex>mated</ex> for life</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matelasse</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mate`las`s<eacute/"</hw> <pr>(m<adot/`l<adot/`s<asl/")</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F., p.p. of <ets>matelasser</ets> to cushion, to cover as with a mattress, fr. <ets>matelas</ets> mattress. See <er>Mattress</er>.]</ety> <def>Ornamented by means of an imitation or suggestion of quilting, the surface being marked by depressed lines which form squares or lozenges in relief; <as>as, <ex>matelass<eacute/</ex> silks</as>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matelasse</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mate`las`s<eacute/"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A quilted ornamented dress fabric of silk or silk and wool.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mateless</ent><br/
<hw>Mate"less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Matchless</er>.]</ety> <def>Having no mate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matelotte</ent><br/
<ent>Matelote</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mat"e*lote</hw> <pr>(m<acr/t"<esl/*l<omac/t)</pr>, <hw>Mat"e*lotte</hw> <pr>(m<acr/t"<esl/*l<ocr/t)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>matelote</ets>, fr. <ets>matelot</ets> a sailor; properly, a dish such as a sailors prepare.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A stew, commonly of fish, flavored with wine, and served with a wine sauce containing onions, mushrooms, etc.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>An old dance of sailors, in double time, and somewhat like a hornpipe.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mateology</ent><br/
<hw>Ma`te*ol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(m<amac/`t<esl/*<ocr/l"<osl/*j<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mataiologi`a</grk>; <grk>ma`taios</grk> useless, vain + <grk>lo`gos</grk> discourse: cf. F. <ets>mat<eacute/ologie</ets>.]</ety> <def>A vain, unprofitable discourse or inquiry.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mateotechny</ent><br/
<hw>Ma`te*o*tech"ny</hw> <pr>(m<amac/`t<esl/*<osl/*t<ecr/k"n<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mataiotechni`a</grk>; <grk>ma`taios</grk> vain + <grk>te`chnh</grk> art, science.]</ety> <def>Any unprofitable science.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mater</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., mother. See <er>Mother</er>.]</ety> <def>See <er>Alma mater</er>, <er>Dura mater</er>, and <er>Pia mater</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Material</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*te"ri*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>materialis</ets>, fr. <ets>materia</ets> stuff, matter: cf. F. <ets>mat<eacute/riel</ets>. See <er>Matter</er>, and cf. <er>Mat<eacute/riel</er>.]</ety> <br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Consisting of matter; not spiritual; corporeal; physical; <as>as, <ex>material</ex> substance or bodies</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>material</qex> elements of the universe.</q> <rj><qau>Whewell.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>Pertaining to, or affecting, the physical nature of man, as distinguished from the <contr>mental</contr> or <contr>moral</contr> nature; relating to the bodily wants, interests, and comforts; <as>as, <ex>material</ex> well-being; <ex>material</ex> comforts</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Of solid or weighty character; not insubstantial; of consequence; not be dispensed with; important; significant.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Discourse, which was always <qex>material</qex>, never trifling.</q> <rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I shall, in the account of simple ideas, set down only such as are most <qex>material</qex> to our present purpose.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Logic.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to the matter, as opposed to the form, of a thing. See <er>Matter</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Material cause</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Cause</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Material evidence</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>evidence which conduces to the proof or disproof of a relevant hypothesis.</cd> <au>Wharton.</au></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Corporeal; bodily; important; weighty; momentous; essential.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Material</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*te"ri*al</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The substance or matter of which anything is made or may be made.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Raw material</b></col>, <cd>any crude, unfinished, or elementary materials that are adapted to use only by processes of skilled labor.  <as>Cotton, wool, ore, logs, etc., are <ex>raw material</ex></as>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Material</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*te"ri*al</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To form from matter; to materialize.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Materialism</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*te"ri*al*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mat<eacute/rialisme</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The doctrine of materialists; materialistic views and tenets; called also <altname>philosophical materialism</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The irregular fears of a future state had been supplanted by the <qex>materialism</qex> of Epicurus.</q> <rj><qau>Buckminster.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The tendency to give undue importance to material interests as contrasted with spiritual concerns; devotion to the material nature and its wants.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Material substances in the aggregate; matter.</def> <mark>[R. & Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>A. Chalmers.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>philosophical materialism</b></col> <cd>The theory that matter and energy are the only objects existing within the universe, and that mental and spiritual phenomena are explainable as functions of the nervous system of people.  Same as <er>materialism</er>{1}.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 902 --></p>

<p><ent>Materialist</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*te"ri*al*ist</hw> <pr>(m<adot/*t<emac/"r<icr/*<ait/l*<icr/st)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mat<eacute/rialiste</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who denies the existence of spiritual substances or agents, and maintains that spiritual phenomena, so called, are the result of some peculiar organization of matter.  A believer in <cref>philosophical materialism</cref>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who holds to the existence of matter, as distinguished from the idealist, who denies it.</def>  <rj><au>Berkeley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Materialistical</ent><br/
<ent>Materialistic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Ma*te`ri*al*is"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Ma*te`ri*al*is"tic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to materialism or materialists; of the nature of materialism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But to me his very spiritualism seemed more <qex>materialistic</qex> than his physics.</q> <rj><qau>C. Kingsley.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Primarily concerned with material objects and worldly activities, as contrasted with spiritual, moral or philosophical concerns; especially, concerned primarily with gaining money and the things that money can buy.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Materiality</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*te`ri*al"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mat<eacute/rialit<eacute/</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality or state of being material; material existence; corporeity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Importance; <as>as, the <ex>materiality</ex> of facts</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Materialization</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*te`ri*al*i*za"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of materializing, or the state of being materialized.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Materialize</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*te"ri*al*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Materialized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Materializing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mat<eacute/rialiser</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To invest with material characteristics; to make perceptible to the senses; hence, to present to the mind through the medium of material objects.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Having with wonderful art and beauty <qex>materialized</qex>, if I may so call it, a scheme of abstracted notions, and clothed the most nice, refined conceptions of philosophy in sensible images.</q> <rj><qau>Tatler.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To regard as matter; to consider or explain by the laws or principles which are appropriate to matter.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to assume a character appropriate to material things; to occupy with material interests; <as>as, to <ex>materialize</ex> thought</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Spiritualism)</fld> <def>To make visable in, or as in, a material form; -- said of spirits.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A female spirit form temporarily <qex>materialized</qex>, and not distinguishable from a human being.</q> <rj><qau>Epes Sargent.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Materialize</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*te"ri*al*ize</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To appear as a material form; to take substantial shape.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To come into existence; <as>as, the promised donations never <ex>materialized</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Materially</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*te"ri*al*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>In the state of matter.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I do not mean that anything is separable from a body by fire that was not <qex>materially</qex> preexistent in it.</q> <rj><qau>Boyle.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In its essence; substantially.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An ill intention is certainly sufficient to spoil . . . an act in itself <qex>materially</qex> good.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>In an important manner or degree; essentially; <as>as, it <ex>materially</ex> concerns us to know the real motives of our actions</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Materialness</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*te"ri*al*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state of being material.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Materia medica</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*te"ri*a med"i*ca</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[L. See <er>Matter</er>, and <er>Medical</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Material or substance used in the composition of remedies; -- a general term for all substances used as curative agents in medicine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That branch of medical science which treats of the sources, nature and properties of all the substances that are employed for the cure of diseases, primarily with natural preparations, rather than pure or synthetic medicines; pharmacognosy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Materiarian</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*te`ri*a"ri*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>materiarius</ets>.]</ety> <def>See <er>Materialist</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Materiated</ent><br/
<ent>Materiate</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Ma*te"ri*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Ma*te"ri*a`ted</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>materiatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>materiare</ets> to build of wood.]</ety> <def>Consisting of matter.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Materiation</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*te`ri*a"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>materiatio</ets> woodwork.]</ety> <def>Act of forming matter.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Materiel</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma`t<eacute/`ri`el"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. See <er>Material</er>.]</ety> <def>Those objects in a complex system which constitute the <xex>materials</xex>, or instruments employed, in distinction from the <xex>personnel</xex>, or men; for example, the buildings, libraries, and apparatus of a college, in distinction from its officers; -- used in a collective sense.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <fld>(Military)</fld> <def>The arms, munitions, baggage, equipment, provisions, etc., of an army.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Materious</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*te"ri*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>See <er>Material</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maternal</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*ter"nal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>maternel</ets>, L. <ets>maternus</ets>, fr. <ets>mater</ets> mother. See <er>Mother</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to a mother; becoming to a mother; motherly; <as>as, <ex>maternal</ex> love; <ex>maternal</ex> tenderness.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Motherly</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maternalistic</ent><br/
<hw>maternalistic</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>showing maternal instincts; behaving as a mother should; motherly.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maternally</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*ter"nal*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a motherly manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maternity</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*ter"ni*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>maternit<eacute/</ets>, LL. <ets>maternitas</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The state of being a mother; motherhood.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The character of a mother; maternal quality; motherliness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The maternity ward; the maternity department of a hospital.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maternity</ent><br/
<hw>ma*ter"ni*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to childbirth or the period during which a woman is pregnant; <as>as, <ex>maternity</ex> care; a <ex>maternity</ex> hospital</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>For use during pregnancy; <as>as, a <ex>maternity</ex> outfit</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maternity ward</ent><br/
<hw>ma*ter"ni*ty ward`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The section of a hospital devoted to assisting women during childbirth and caring for them and their newborn infants until they are released to go home.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>matey</ent><br/
<hw>matey</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>having the relationship of friends or pals.</def> <mark>[colloquial]</mark><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> chummy, pally, palsy-walsy.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matfelon</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"fel*on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[W. <ets>madfelen</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The knapweed (<spn>Centaurea nigra</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Math</ent><br/
<hw>Math</hw> <pr>(m<acr/th)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<aemac/<edh/</ets>; akin to <ets>m<amac/wan</ets> to mow, G. <ets>mahd</ets> math. See <er>Mow</er> to cut (grass).]</ety> <def>A mowing, or that which is gathered by mowing; -- chiefly used in composition; <as>as, an after<ex>math</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The first mowing thereof, for the king's use, is wont to be sooner than the common <qex>math</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Hall.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mathematic</ent><br/
<hw>Math`e*mat"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>math<eacute/matique</ets>, L. <ets>mathematicus</ets>, Gr. <?/ disposed to learn, belonging to learning or the sciences, especially to mathematics, fr. <?/ that which is learned, learning, pl. <?/ things learned, learning, science, especially mathematical science, fr. <?/, <?/, to learn; akin to E. <ets>mind</ets>. See <er>Mind</er>.]</ety> <def>See <er>Mathematical</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mathematical</ent><br/
<hw>Math`e*mat"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mathematic</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to mathematics; according to mathematics; hence, theoretically precise; accurate; <as>as, <ex>mathematical</ex> geography; <ex>mathematical</ex> instruments; <ex>mathematical</ex> exactness.</as></def> -- <wordforms><wf>Math`e*mat"ic*al*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mathematician</ent><br/
<hw>Math`e*ma*ti"cian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>math<eacute/maticien</ets>.]</ety> <def>One versed in mathematics.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mathematics</ent><br/
<hw>Math`e*mat"ics</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>math<eacute/matiques</ets>, pl., L. <ets>mathematica</ets>, sing., Gr. <?/ (sc. <?/) science. See <er>Mathematic</er>, and <er>-ics</er>.]</ety> <def>That science, or class of sciences, which treats of the exact relations existing between quantities or magnitudes, and of the methods by which, in accordance with these relations, quantities sought are deducible from other quantities known or supposed; the science of spatial and quantitative relations.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Mathematics</xex> embraces three departments, namely: <bold>1.</bold> <stype>Arithmetic</stype>. <bold>2.</bold> <stype>Geometry</stype>, including <stype>Trigonometry</stype> and <stype>Conic Sections</stype>. <bold>3.</bold> <stype>Analysis</stype>, in which letters are used, including <stype>Algebra</stype>, <stype>Analytical Geometry</stype>, and <stype>Calculus</stype>. Each of these divisions is divided into <xex>pure</xex> or <xex>abstract</xex>, which considers magnitude or quantity abstractly, without relation to matter; and <xex>mixed</xex> or <xex>applied</xex>, which treats of magnitude as subsisting in material bodies, and is consequently interwoven with physical considerations.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mather</ent><br/
<hw>Math"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Madder</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mathes</ent><br/
<hw>Math"es</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Perh. corrupted fr. L. <ets>anthemis</ets> camomile, Gr. <?/ .]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The mayweed.  Cf. <er>Maghet</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mathesis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma*the"sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/, from <?/, <?/, to learn.]</ety> <def>Learning; especially, mathematics.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mathurin</ent><br/
<hw>Math"u*rin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld> <def>See <er>Trinitarian</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matico</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*ti"co</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A Peruvian plant (<spn>Piperelongatum</spn> or <spn>Artanthe elongatum</spn>), allied to the pepper, the leaves of which are used as a styptic and astringent.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matie</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"ie</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A fat herring with undeveloped roe.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>matty</asp>.]</altsp> <mark>[Eng. & Scot.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matin</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>M<acir/`tin"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<acir/tin</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A French mastiff.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matin</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"in</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. fr. L. <ets>matutinum</ets> the morning, <ets>matutinus</ets> of the morning, <ets>Matuta</ets> the goddess of the morning. See <er>Matutinal</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Morning.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <ety>[F. <ets>matines</ets>. See Etymol. above.]</ety> <def>Morning worship or service; morning prayers or songs.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The winged choristers began<br/
To chirp their <qex>matins</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Cleveland.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Time of morning service; the first canonical hour in the Roman Catholic Church.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>matin</ent><br/
<hw>mat"in</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the morning, or to matins; used in the morning; matutinal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>matinal</ent><br/
<hw>mat"in*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Relating to the morning, or to matins; matutinal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>matinee</ent><br/
<hw>mat`i*n<eacute/e"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., from <ets>matin</ets>. See <er>Matin</er>.]</ety> <def>A reception, or a musical or dramatic entertainment, held in the daytime. See <er>Soir<eacute/e</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>matrass</ent><br/
<hw>ma*trass"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>matras</ets>; perh. so called from its long narrow neck; cf. OF. <ets>matras</ets> large arrow, L. <ets>materis</ets>, <ets>mataris</ets>, <ets>matara</ets>, a Celtic javelin, pike; of Celtic origin.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A round-bottomed glass flask having a long neck; a bolthead.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matress</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"ress</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Matress</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>matriarch</ent><br/
<hw>ma"tri*arch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mater</ets> mother + <ets>-arch</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The mother and ruler of a family or of her descendants; a ruler by maternal right.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A woman who dominates or is the most important member of a group or organization; in businesses, often the founder or owner of the largest interest.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A venerated old woman.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>matriarchal</ent><br/
<hw>ma`tri*ar"chal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to a matriarch; governed by a matriarch or matriarchs; <as>as, a <ex>matriarchal</ex> society</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matriarchate</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"tri*ar"chate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The office or jurisdiction of a matriarch; a matriarchal form of government.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>matric</ent><br/
<hw>matric</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Shortened from <ets>matriculation</ets>.]</ety> <def>admission to a group (especially a college or university).</def> <mark>[slang]</mark> <br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> matriculation.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matricaria</ent><br/
<hw>Matricaria</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of chiefly Old World strong-smelling weedy herbs; it comprises plants sometimes included in other genera, such as <gen>Tanacetum</gen> and  <gen>Tripleurospermum</gen>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Matricaria</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matrice</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"trice</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>matrice</ets>. See <er>Matrix</er>.]</ety> <def>See <er>Matrix</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>matricentric</ent><br/
<hw>matricentric</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>centered upon the mother.</def> [Narrower terms: <stype>matriarchal (vs. patriarchal)</stype>]<br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matricidal</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"ri*ci`dal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to matricide.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matricide</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"ri*cide</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>matricidium</ets>; <ets>mater</ets> mother + <ets>coedere</ets> to kill, slay: cf. F. <ets>matricide</ets>. See <er>Mother</er>, and cf. <er>Homicide</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The murder of a mother by her son or daughter.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[L. <ets>matricida</ets>: cf. F. <ets>matricide</ets>.]</ety> <def>One who murders one's own mother.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matriculate</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*tric"u*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Matriculated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Matriculating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>matricula</ets> a public roll or register, dim. of <ets>matrix</ets> a mother, in respect to propagation, also, a public register. See <er>Matrix</er>.]</ety> <def>To enroll; to enter in a register;</def> <specif>specifically,</specif> <def>to enter or admit to membership in a body or society, particularly in a college or university, by enrolling the name in a register.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In discovering and <qex>matriculating</qex> the arms of commissaries from North America.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matriculate</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*tric"u*late</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To go though the process of admission to membership, as by examination and enrollment, in a society or college.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matriculate</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*tric"u*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Matriculated.</def> <au>Skelton.</au> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>One who is matriculated.</def></def2>  <rj><au>Arbuthnot.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matriculation</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*tric`u*la"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act or process of matriculating; the state of being matriculated.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>matrilineage</ent><br/
<hw>matrilineage</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The line of descent traced through the maternal side of the family; the mother's line of descent.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> enation, cognation.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>matrilineal</ent><br/
<hw>matrilineal</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>tracing descent through the female line.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matrimoine</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"ri*moine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Matrimony.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matrimonial</ent><br/
<hw>Mat`ri*mo"ni*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>matrimonialis</ets>: cf. F. <ets>matrimonial</ets>. See <er>Matrimony</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to marriage; derived from marriage; connubial; nuptial; hymeneal; <as>as, <ex>matrimonial</ex> rights or duties</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If he relied upon that title, he could be but a king at courtesy, and have rather a <qex>matrimonial</qex> than a regal power.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Connubial; conjugal; sponsal; spousal; nuptial; hymeneal.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matrimonially</ent><br/
<hw>Mat`ri*mo"ni*al*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a matrimonial manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matrimonious</ent><br/
<hw>Mat`ri*mo"ni*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Matrimonial.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matrimony</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"ri*mo*ny</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>matrimoine</ets>, through Old French, fr. L. <ets>matrimonium</ets>, fr. <ets>mater</ets> mother. See <er>Mother</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The union of man and woman as husband and wife; the nuptial state; marriage; wedlock.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If either of you know any impediment, why ye may not be lawfully joined together in <qex>matrimony</qex>, ye do now confess it.</q> <rj><qau>Book of Com. Prayer (Eng. Ed.)</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A kind of game at cards played by several persons.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Matrimony vine</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a climbing thorny vine (<spn>Lycium barbarum</spn>) of the Potato family.</cd>  <rj><au>Gray.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Marriage; wedlock. See <er>Marriage</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>matrisib</ent><br/
<hw>matrisib</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>One related on the mother's side.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> enate, matrikin, matrilineal kin, matrilineal sib.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>matrix</ent><br/
<hw>ma"trix</hw> <pr>(m<amac/"tr<icr/ks)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Matrices</plw> <pr>(m<acr/t"r<icr/*s<emac/z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., fr. <ets>mater</ets> mother. See <er>Mother</er>, and cf. <er>Matrice</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The womb.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All that openeth the <qex>matrix</qex> is mine.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xxxiv. 19.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>That which gives form or origin to anything</def>; as: <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>The cavity in which anything is formed, and which gives it shape; a die; a mold, as for the face of a type.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>The earthy or stony substance in which metallic ores or crystallized minerals are found; the gangue.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Dyeing)</fld> <def>The five simple colors, black, white, blue, red, and yellow, of which all the rest are composed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The lifeless portion of tissue, either animal or vegetable, situated between the cells; the intercellular substance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>A rectangular arrangement of symbols in rows and columns.  The symbols may express quantities or operations.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matron</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"tron</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>matrone</ets>, L. <ets>matrona</ets>, fr. <ets>mater</ets> mother. See <er>Mother</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A wife or a widow, especially, one who has borne children; a woman of staid or motherly manners.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your wives, your daughters,<br/
Your <qex>matrons</qex>, and your maids.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Grave from her cradle, insomuch that she was a <qex>matron</qex> before she was a mother.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A housekeeper; esp., a woman who manages the domestic economy of a public instution; a head nurse in a hospital; <as>as, the <ex>matron</ex> of a school or hospital</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Jury of matrons</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>a jury of experienced women called to determine the question of pregnancy when set up in bar of execution, and for other cognate purposes.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matronage</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"ron*age</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The state of a matron.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The collective body of matrons.</def>  <rj><au>Burke.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Can a politician slight the feelings and convictions of the whole <qex>matronage</qex> of his country?</q> <rj><qau>Hare.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matronal</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"ron*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>matronalis</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to a matron; suitable to an elderly lady or to a married woman; grave; motherly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matronhood</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"tron*hood</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state of being a matron.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matronize</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"ron*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Matronized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Matronizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make a matron of; to make matronlike.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Childbed <qex>matronizes</qex> the giddiest spirits.</q> <rj><qau>Richardson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To act the part of a matron toward; to superintend; to chaperone; <as>as, to <ex>matronize</ex> an assembly</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matronlike</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"tron*like`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Like a matron; sedate; grave; matronly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matronly</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"tron*ly</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Advanced in years; elderly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Like, or befitting, a matron; grave; sedate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matronymic</ent><br/
<hw>Mat`ro*nym"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mater</ets> mother + <ets>-nymic</ets>, as in <ets>patronimic</ets>.]</ety> <def>See <er>Metronymic</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matross</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*tross"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[D. <ets>matroos</ets>, fr. F. <ets>matelot</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>Formerly, in the British service, a gunner or a gunner's mate; one of the soldiers in a train of artillery, who assisted the gunners in loading, firing, and sponging the guns.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matt</ent><br/
<hw>Matt</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Matte</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Knight.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mattages</ent><br/
<hw>Mat`ta*ges"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A shrike or butcher bird; -- written also <altname>matagasse</altname>.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mattamore</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"ta*more`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>matamore</ets>, from Ar. <ets>ma<tsdot/m<omac/ra</ets>.]</ety> <def>A subterranean repository for wheat.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matte</ent><br/
<hw>Matte</hw> <pr>(m<acr/t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>matte</ets>; cf. F. <ets>mat</ets>, masc., <ets>matte</ets>, fem., faint, dull, dim; -- said of metals. See <er>Mate</er> checkmate.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Metallurgy)</fld> <def>A partly reduced copper sulphide, obtained by alternately roasting and melting copper ore in separating the metal from associated iron ores, and called <altname>coarse metal</altname>, <altname>fine metal</altname>, etc., according to the grade of fineness.  On the exterior it is dark brown or black, but on a fresh surface is yellow or bronzy in color.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A dead or dull finish, as in gilding where the gold leaf is not burnished, or in painting where the surface is purposely deprived of gloss.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>matte</ent><br/
<hw>matte</hw> <pr>(m<acr/t)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having a dull, lusterless surface finish; opposed to <ant>glossy</ant> or <ex>polished</ex>; <as>as, a <ex>matte</ex> photograph; a proof coin with <ex>matte</ex> figures on a polished field</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matted</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"ted</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Matte</er>.]</ety> <def>Having a dull surface; lusterless; unburnished; same as <er>matte</er>; <as>as, <ex>matted</ex> gold leaf or gilding</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Matted glass</b></col>, <cd>glass ornamented with figures on a dull ground.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matted</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"ted</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See 3d <er>Mat</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Covered with a mat or mats; <as>as, a <ex>matted</ex> floor</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Tangled closely together; having its parts adhering closely together; <as>as, <ex>matted</ex> hair</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matter</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>matere</ets>, F. <ets>mati<egrave/re</ets>, fr. L. <ets>materia</ets>; perh. akin to L. <ets>mater</ets> mother.  Cf. <er>Mother</er>, <er>Madeira</er>, <er>Material</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That of which anything is composed; constituent substance; material; the material or substantial part of anything; the constituent elements of conception; that into which a notion may be analyzed; the essence; the pith; the embodiment.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He is the <qex>matter</qex> of virtue.</q> <rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That of which the sensible universe and all existent bodies are composed; anything which has extension, occupies space, or is perceptible by the senses; body; substance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Matter</xex> is usually divided by philosophical writers into three kinds or classes: <xex>solid</xex>, <xex>liquid</xex>, and <xex>gaseous</xex>. <xex>Solid</xex> substances are those whose parts firmly cohere and resist impression, as wood or stone. <xex>Liquids</xex> have free motion among their parts, and easily yield to impression, as water and wine. <xex>Gaseous</xex> substances are elastic fluids, called <xex>vapors</xex> and <xex>gases</xex>, as air and oxygen gas.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That with regard to, or about which, anything takes place or is done; the thing aimed at, treated of, or treated; subject of action, discussion, consideration, feeling, complaint, legal action, or the like; theme.</def> <ldquo/If the <xex>matter</xex> should be tried by duel.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Son of God, Savior of men!  Thy name<br/
Shall be the copious <qex>matter</qex> of my song.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every great <qex>matter</qex> they shall bring unto thee, but every small <qex>matter</qex> they shall judge.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xviii. 22.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That which one has to treat, or with which one has to do; concern; affair; business.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To help the <qex>matter</qex>, the alchemists call in many vanities out of astrology.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some young female seems to have carried <qex>matters</qex> so far, that she is ripe for asking advice.</q> <rj><qau>Spectator.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Affair worthy of account; thing of consequence; importance; significance; moment; -- chiefly in the phrases <xex>what matter</xex>? <xex>no matter</xex>, and the like.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A prophet some, and some a poet, cry;<br/
No <qex>matter</qex> which, so neither of them lie.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Inducing cause or occasion, especially of anything disagreeable or distressing; difficulty; trouble.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And this is the <qex>matter</qex> why interpreters upon that passage in Hosea will not consent it to be a true story, that the prophet took a harlot to wife.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 903 --></p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Amount; quantity; portion; space; -- often indefinite.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Away he goes, . . . a <qex>matter</qex> of seven miles.</q> <rj><qau>L' Estrange.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have thoughts to tarry a small <qex>matter</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Congreve.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No small <qex>matter</qex> of British forces were commanded over sea the year before.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Substance excreted from living animal bodies; that which is thrown out or discharged in a tumor, boil, or abscess; pus; purulent substance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Metaph.)</fld> <def>That which is permanent, or is supposed to be given, and in or upon which changes are effected by psychological or physical processes and relations; -- opposed to <contr>form</contr>.</def>  <rj><au>Mansel.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>Written manuscript, or anything to be set in type; copy; also, type set up and ready to be used, or which has been used, in printing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Dead matter</b></col> <fld>(Print.)</fld>, <cd>type which has been used, or which is not to be used, in printing, and is ready for distribution.</cd> -- <col><b>Live matter</b></col> <fld>(Print.)</fld>, <cd>type set up, but not yet printed from.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Matter in bar</b></col>, <col><b>Matter of fact</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See under <er>Bar</er>, and <er>Fact</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Matter of record</b></col>, <cd>anything recorded.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Upon the matter</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Upon the whole matter</b></col></mcol>, <cd>considering the whole; taking all things into view; all things considered.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Waller, with Sir William Balfour, exceeded in horse, but were, <qex>upon the whole matter</qex>, equal in foot.</q> <rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matter</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mattered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mattering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be of importance; to import; to signify.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It <qex>matters</qex> not how they were called.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To form pus or matter, as an abscess; to maturate.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <ldquo/Each slight sore <xex>mattereth</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Sir P. Sidney.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matter</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"ter</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To regard as important; to take account of; to care for.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He did not <qex>matter</qex> cold nor hunger.</q> <rj><qau>H. Brooke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matterhorn</ent><br/
<hw>Matterhorn</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A mountain in Italy and Switzerland, 14,690 feet high.</def>  <note>According to WordNet, 14,780 feet high</note><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matterless</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"ter*less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Not being, or having, matter; <as>as, <ex>matterless</ex> spirits</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Davies (Wit's Pilgr.).</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Unimportant; immaterial.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matter-of-fact</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"ter-of-fact"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Adhering to facts; not turning aside from absolute realities; not fanciful or imaginative; commonplace; dry.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mattery</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"ter*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Generating or containing pus; purulent.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Full of substance or matter; important.</def>  <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matteuccia</ent><br/
<hw>Matteuccia</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A small genus sometimes included in genus <gen>Onoclea</gen>; in some classifications both genera are placed in <gen>Polypodiaceae</gen>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Matteuccia</gen>, Pteretis, genus <gen>Pteretis</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matthew</ent><br/
<hw>Matthew</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def><person>Saint Matthew</person>, a disciple of Jesus; author of the first Gospel.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Saint Matthew, St. Matthew, Saint Matthew the Apostle, Levi.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matthiola</ent><br/
<hw>Matthiola</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of Old World plants grown as ornamentals.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Matthiola</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matting</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"ting</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mat</er>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of interweaving or tangling together so as to make a mat; the process of becoming matted.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Mats, in general, or collectively; mat work; a matlike fabric, for use in covering floors, packing articles, and the like; a kind of carpeting made of straw, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Materials for mats.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An ornamental border. See 3d <er>Mat</er>, 4.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matting</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"ting</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Matte</er>.]</ety> <def>A dull, lusterless surface in certain of the arts, as gilding, metal work, glassmaking, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mattock</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"tock</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>mattuc</ets>; cf. W. <ets>matog</ets>.]</ety> <def>An implement for digging and grubbing.  The head has two long steel blades, one like an adz and the other like a narrow ax or the point of a pickax.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>'T is you must dig with <qex>mattock</qex> and with spade.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mattoid</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"toid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It. <ets>matto</ets> mad (cf. L. <ets>mattus</ets>, <ets>matus</ets>, drunk) + <ets>-oid</ets>.]</ety> <def>A person of congenitally abnormal mind bordering on insanity or degeneracy.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mattoir</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mat*toir"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>matoir</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Engraving)</fld> <def>A kind of coarse punch with a rasplike face, used for making a rough surface on etching ground, or on the naked copper, the effect after biting being very similar to stippled lines.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mattowacca</ent><br/
<hw>Mat`to*wac"ca</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Indian name.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An American clupeoid fish (<spn>Clupea mediocris</spn>), similar to the shad in habits and appearance, but smaller and less esteemed for food; -- called also <altname>hickory shad</altname>, <altname>tailor shad</altname>, <altname>fall herring</altname>, and <altname>shad herring</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mattress</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"tress</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>materas</ets>, F. <ets>matelas</ets>, LL. <ets>matratium</ets>; cf. Sp. & Pg. al<ets>madraque</ets>, Pr. al<ets>matrac</ets>; all from Ar. <ets>ma<tsdot/rah</ets> a place where anything is thrown, what is thrown under something, fr. <ets><tsdot/araha</ets> to throw.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A large pad stuffed with hair, moss, or other suitable soft material, and quilted or otherwise fastened, used as or in a bed, to support the human body while lying down.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>matress</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Hydraulic Engin.)</fld> <def>A mass of interwoven brush, poles, etc., to protect a bank from being worn away by currents or waves.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>innerspring mattress</b></col>  <cd>A variety of mattress{1} having springs inside to provide a flexible support; it is considered more comfortable than a stuffed mattress.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maturant</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"u*rant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>maturans</ets>, p. pr. See <er>Maturate</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A medicine, or application, which promotes suppuration.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maturate</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"u*rate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Maturated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Maturating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>maturatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>maturare</ets> to make ripe, fr. <ets>maturus</ets> ripe, mature. See <er>Mature</er>, <pos>v.</pos> & <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To bring to ripeness or maturity; to ripen.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A tree may be <qex>maturated</qex> artificially.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To promote the perfect suppuration of (an abscess).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maturate</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"u*rate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To ripen; to become mature; specifically, to suppurate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maturation</ent><br/
<hw>Mat`u*ra"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>maturatio</ets> a hastening: cf. F. <ets>maturation</ets>.]</ety> <def>The process of bringing, or of coming, to maturity; hence, specifically, the process of suppurating perfectly; the formation of pus or matter.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maturative</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"u*ra*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>maturatif</ets>.]</ety> <def>Conducing to ripeness or maturity; hence, conducing to suppuration.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maturative</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"u*ra*tive</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A remedy promoting maturation; a maturant.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mature</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*ture"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Maturer</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Maturest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[L. <ets>maturus</ets>; prob. akin to E. <ets>matin</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Brought by natural process to completeness of growth and development; fitted by growth and development for any function, action, or state, appropriate to its kind; full-grown; ripe.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now is love <qex>mature</qex> in ear.</q> <rj><qau>Tennison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How shall I meet, or how accost, the sage,<br/
Unskilled in speech, nor yet <qex>mature</qex> of age?</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Completely worked out; fully digested or prepared; ready for action; made ready for destined application or use; perfected; <as>as, a <ex>mature</ex> plan</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This lies glowing, . . . and is almost <qex>mature</qex> for the violent breaking out.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a condition of full development; <as>as, a man of <ex>mature</ex> years</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Come to, or in a state of, completed suppuration.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Ripe; perfect; completed; prepared; digested; ready.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Mature</er>, <er>Ripe</er>. Both words describe <xex>fullness</xex> of growth. <xex>Mature</xex> brings to view the progressiveness of the process; <xex>ripe</xex> indicates the result. We speak of a thing as <xex>mature</xex> when thinking of the successive <xex>stayes</xex> through which it has passed; as <xex>ripe</xex>, when our attention is directed merely to its state. A <xex>mature</xex> judgment; <xex>mature</xex> consideration; <xex>ripe</xex> fruit; a <xex>ripe</xex> scholar.</usage><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mature</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*ture"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Matured</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Maturing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Maturate</er>, <er>Mature</er>.]</ety> <def>To bring or hasten to maturity; to promote ripeness in; to ripen; to complete; <as>as, to <ex>mature</ex> one's plans</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mature</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*ture"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To advance toward maturity; to become ripe; <as>as, wine <ex>matures</ex> by age; the judgment <ex>matures</ex> by age and experience.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, to become due, as a note.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>matured</ent><br/
<hw>matured</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>Fully grown.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> full-blown.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maturely</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*ture"ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>In a mature manner; with ripeness; completely.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>With caution; deliberately.</def>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Early; soon.</def> <mark>[A Latinism, little used]</mark>  <rj><au>Bentley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maturement</ent><br/
<hw>maturement</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The process of maturing; coming to full development; becoming mature; maturation.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> maturation, maturing, ripening.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matureness</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*ture"ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state or quality of being mature; maturity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maturer</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*tur"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who brings to maturity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maturescent</ent><br/
<hw>Mat`u*res"cent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>maturescens</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>maturescere</ets> to become ripe, v. incho. from <ets>maturus</ets>. See <er>Mature</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>Approaching maturity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maturing</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*tur"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Approaching maturity; <as>as, <ex>maturing</ex> fruits; <ex>maturing</ex> notes of hand.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maturity</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*tu"ri*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>maturitas</ets>: cf. F. <ets>maturit<eacute/</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The state or quality of being mature; ripeness; full development; <as>as, the <ex>maturity</ex> of corn or of grass; <ex>maturity</ex> of judgment; the <ex>maturity</ex> of a plan.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Arrival of the time fixed for payment; a becoming due; termination of the period a note, etc., has to run.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matutinal</ent><br/
<hw>Mat`u*ti"nal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>matutinalis</ets>, <ets>matutinus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>matutinal</ets>. See <er>Matin</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to the morning; early.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matutinary</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*tu"ti*na*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Matutinal.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matutine</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"u*tine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Matutinal.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matweed</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"weed`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A name of several maritime grasses, as the sea sand-reed (<spn>Ammophila arundinacea</spn>) which is used in Holland to bind the sand of the seacoast dikes (see <cref>Beach grass</cref>, under <er>Beach</er>); also, the <spn>Lygeum Spartum</spn>, a Mediterranean grass of similar habit.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maty</ent><br/
<hw>Mat"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Etymology uncertain.]</ety> <def>A native house servant in India.</def>  <rj><au>Balfour (Cyc. of India).</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>matzoh</ent><br/
<ent>matzo</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>matz"o</hw>, <hw>matz"oh</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> E. <plw>matzos</plw> or <plw>matzohs</plw>; Hebr. <plw>matzoth</plw> <pr>(#)</pr></plu> <ety>[Heb. <ets>matsts<omac/th</ets>, pl. of <ets>matsts<amac/h</ets> unleavened.]</ety> <def>A cake of unleavened bread eaten by the Jews at the feast of the Passover.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maucaco</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mau*ca"co</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From the native name.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A lemur; -- applied to several species, as the White-fronted, the ruffed, and the ring-tailed lemurs.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maud</ent><br/
<hw>Maud</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A gray plaid; -- used by shepherds in Scotland.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maudle</ent><br/
<hw>Mau"dle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To throw onto confusion or disorder; to render maudlin.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maudlin</ent><br/
<hw>Maud"lin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <ets>Maudlin</ets>, a contr. of <ets>Magdalen</ets>, OE. <ets>Maudeleyne</ets>, who is drawn by painters with eyes swelled and red with weeping.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Tearful; easily moved to tears; exciting to tears; excessively sentimental; weak and silly.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Maudlin</xex> eyes.<rdquo/ <au>Dryden.</au> <ldquo/<xex>Maudlin</xex> eloquence.<rdquo/ <au>Roscommon.</au> <ldquo/A <xex>maudlin</xex> poetess.<rdquo/ <au>Pope.</au> <ldquo/<xex>Maudlin</xex> crowd.<rdquo/ <au>Southey.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Drunk, or somewhat drunk; fuddled; given to drunkenness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Maudlin</qex> Clarence in his malmsey butt.</q> <rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maudeline</ent><br/
<ent>Maudlin</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Maud"lin</hw>, <hw>Maude"line</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>An aromatic composite herb, the costmary; also, the South European <spn>Achillea Ageratum</spn>, a kind of yarrow.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maudlinism</ent><br/
<hw>Maud"lin*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A maudlin state.</def>  <rj><au>Dickens.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maudlinwort</ent><br/
<hw>Maud"lin*wort`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The oxeye daisy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maugre</ent><br/
<ent>Mauger</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mau"ger</hw>, <hw>Mau"gre</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(m<add/"g<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>prep.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>maugr<eacute/</ets>, <ets>malgr<eacute/</ets>, F. <ets>malgr<eacute/</ets>. See <er>Mal-</er>, <er>Malice</er>, and <er>Agree</er>.]</ety> <def>In spite of; in opposition to; notwithstanding.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark> <br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A man must needs love <qex>maugre</qex> his heed.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>mauger</qex> all the world will I keep safe.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maugre</ent><br/
<hw>Mau"gre</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To defy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>J. Webster.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maukin</ent><br/
<hw>Mau"kin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>See <er>Malkin</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A hare.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maul</ent><br/
<hw>Maul</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mall</er> a hammer.]</ety> <def>A heavy wooden hammer or beetle.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mall</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maul</ent><br/
<hw>Maul</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mauled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mauling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To beat and bruise with a heavy stick or cudgel; to wound in a coarse manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Meek modern faith to murder, hack, and <qex>maul</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To injure greatly; to do much harm to.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It <qex>mauls</qex> not only the person misrepreseted, but him also to whom he is misrepresented.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maule</ent><br/
<hw>Maule</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The common mallow.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mauling</ent><br/
<hw>Maul"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A severe beating with a stick, cudgel, or the fist.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maul-stick</ent><br/
<ent>maulstick</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>maul"stick`</hw>, <hw>maul"-stick`</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G. <ets>malerstock</ets>; <ets>maler</ets> a painter + <ets>stock</ets> stick.]</ety> <def>A stick used by painters as a rest for the hand while working.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mahl-stick</asp> and <asp>mahlstick</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maumet</ent><br/
<hw>Mau"met</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mawmet</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maunch</ent><br/
<hw>Maunch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To munch.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maunch</ent><br/
<hw>Maunch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Manche</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maund</ent><br/
<hw>Maund</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>mand</ets>, <ets>mond</ets>.]</ety> <def>A hand basket.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Herrick.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maund</ent><br/
<hw>Maund</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Hind, & Per. <ets>man</ets>.]</ety> <def>An East Indian weight, varying in different localities from 25 to about 82 pounds avoirdupois.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maunder</ent><br/
<ent>Maund</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Maund</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Maund"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mendier</ets> to beg, E. <ets>mendicant</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To beg.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>B. Jonson. Beau. & Fl.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To mutter; to mumble; to grumble; to speak indistinctly or disconnectedly; to talk incoherently.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was ever <qex>maundering</qex> by the how that he met a party of scarlet devils.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maunder</ent><br/
<hw>Maund"er</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To utter in a grumbling manner; to mutter.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maunder</ent><br/
<hw>Maund"er</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A beggar.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maunderer</ent><br/
<hw>Maund"er*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who maunders.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maundril</ent><br/
<hw>Maun"dril</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Mandrel</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Coal Mining)</fld> <def>A pick with two prongs, to pry with.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maundy</ent><br/
<hw>Maun"dy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Maundy Thursday</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The sacrament of the Lord's Supper.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>The ceremony of washing the feet of the poor on Maundy Thursday.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn>  <def>The alms distributed in connection with this ceremony or on Maundy Thursday.</def></p>

<p><note><hand/ In England, the foot washing is obsolete, but the <ldquo/royal maundy<rdquo/ is distributed annually on behalf of the sovereign.  Since 1890 this distribution has been made from Westminster Abbey.</note><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maundy money</ent><br/
<ent>Maundy coins</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Maundy coins</hw> <it>or</it> <hw>Maundy money</hw>  }</mhw>. <def>Silver coins or money of the nominal value of 1<it>d.</it>, 2<it>d.</it>, 3<it>d.</it>, and 4<it>d.</it>, struck annually for the Maundy alms.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maundy Thursday</ent><br/
<hw>Maun"dy Thurs"day</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[OE. <ets>maunde</ets> a command, OF. <ets>mand<eacute/</ets>, L. <ets>mandatum</ets>, from <ets>mandare</ets> to command. See called from the ancient custom of washing the feet of the poor on this day, which was taken to be the fulfillment of the <ldquo/new commandment,<rdquo/ <au>John xiii. 5, 34.</au>]</ety> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>The Thursday in Passion week, or next before Good Friday.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maungy</ent><br/
<hw>Maun"gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Mangy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Skelton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mauresque</ent><br/
<hw>Mau*resque"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a. & n.</pos> <def>See <er>Moresque</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maurist</ent><br/
<hw>Maur"ist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <ets>Maurus</ets>, the favorite disciple of <person>St. Benedict</person>.]</ety> <def>A member of the <org>Congregation of Saint Maur</org>, an offshoot of the <org>Benedictines</org>, originating in France in the early part of the seventeenth century.  The <ex>Maurists</ex> have been distinguished for their interest in literature.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mauritius</ent><br/
<hw>Mauritius</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A country on the island of Mauritius.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An island in the Indian Ocean.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Ile de France.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mausolean</ent><br/
<hw>Mau`so*le"an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>Mausoleus</ets>. See <er>Mausoleum</er>.]</ety> <def>Pertaining to a mausoleum; monumental.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mausoleum</ent><br/
<hw>Mau`so*le"um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> E. <plw>Mausoleums</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, L. <plw>-lea</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>mausoleum</ets>, Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ <persfn>Mausolus</persfn>, king of Caria, to whom <persfn>Artemisia</persfn>, his widow, erected a stately monument, one of the wonders of the ancient world.]</ety> <def>A magnificent tomb, or stately sepulchral monument.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mauther</ent><br/
<hw>Mau"ther</hw> <pr>(m<add/"<th/<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. AS. <ets>maeg<thorn/</ets> a maid.]</ety> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>mawther</asp>, <asp>mother</asp>.]</altsp> <def>A girl; esp., a great, awkward girl; a wench.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mauvaniline</ent><br/
<hw>Mauv`an"i*line</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>See <cref>Mauve aniline</cref>, under <er>Mauve</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mauve</ent><br/
<hw>Mauve</hw> <pr>(m<omac/v)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., mallow, L. <ets>malva</ets>.  So named from the similarity of the color to that of the petals of common mallow, <spn>Malva sylvestris</spn>. See <er>Mallow</er>.]</ety> <def>A color of a delicate purple, violet, or lilac.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mauve aniline</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>a dyestuff produced artificially by the oxidation of commercial aniline, and the first discovered of the so-called <xex>coal-tar</xex>, or <xex>aniline</xex>, <xex>dyes</xex>.  It consists of the sulphate of mauve<ium/ne, and is a dark brown or bronze amorphous powder, which dissolves to a beatiful purple color.  Called also <altname>aniline purple</altname>, <altname>violine</altname>, <altname>Perkin's mauve</altname>, etc.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mauveine</ent><br/
<hw>mauve"<ium/ne</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>An artificial organic base, obtained by oxidizing a mixture of aniline and toluidine, and valuable for the dyestuffs it forms.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mauvine</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mauvine</ent><br/
<hw>Mauv"ine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Mauve-colored.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maverick</ent><br/
<hw>Mav"er*ick</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>In the southwestern part of the united States, a bullock or heifer that has not been branded, and is unclaimed or wild; -- said to be from <etsep>Maverick</etsep>, the name of a cattle owner in Texas who neglected to brand his cattle.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maverick</ent><br/
<hw>Mav"er*ick</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To take a maverick.</def> <mark>[Western U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maverick brand</ent><br/
<hw>Maverick brand</hw>. <def>A brand originated by a dishonest cattleman, who, without owning any stock, gradually accumulates a herd by finding mavericks.</def> <mark>[Western U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mavis</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"vis</hw> <pr>(m<amac/"v<icr/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mauvis</ets>, Arm. <ets>milvid</ets>, <ets>milfid</ets>, <ets>milc'hhouid</ets>, Corn. <ets>melhuez</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The European throstle or song thrush (<spn>Turdus musicus</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mavourneen</ent><br/
<ent>Mavournin</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Ma*vour"nin</hw>, <hw>Ma*vour"neen</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(m<adot/*v<oomac/r"n<emac/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Ir. <ets>mo mhuirnin</ets> my darling; <ets>mo</ets> my + <ets>mhuirnin</ets> darling.]</ety> <def>My darling; -- an Irish term of endearment for a girl or woman.</def> <ldquo/Erin <xex>mavournin</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Campbell.</au></rj><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maw</ent><br/
<hw>Maw</hw> <pr>(m<add/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mew</er> a gull.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A gull.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maw</ent><br/
<hw>Maw</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mawe</ets>, AS. <ets>maga</ets> stomach; akin to D. <ets>maag</ets>, OHG. <ets>mago</ets>, G. <ets>magen</ets>, Icel. <ets>magi</ets>, Sw. <ets>mage</ets>, Dan. <ets>mave</ets>. <root/103.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A stomach; the receptacle into which food is taken by swallowing; in birds, the craw; -- now used only of the lower animals, exept humorously or in contempt.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bellies and <qex>maws</qex> of living creatures.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Appetite; inclination.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Unless you had more <qex>maw</qex> to do me good.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fish maw</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Fish</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maw</ent><br/
<hw>Maw</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An old game at cards.</def>  <rj><au>Sir A. Weldon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mawk</ent><br/
<hw>Mawk</hw> <pr>(m<add/k)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mauk</ets>, <ets>ma<edh/ek</ets>, Icel. <ets>ma<edh/kr</ets>; akin to Dan. <ets>maddik</ets>, and E. <ets>mad</ets> an earthworm. See <er>Mad</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A maggot.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A slattern; a mawks.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mawkin</ent><br/
<hw>Maw"kin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Malkin</er>, and <er>Maukin</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mawkingly</ent><br/
<hw>Mawk"ing*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Slatternly.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mawkish</ent><br/
<hw>Mawk"ish</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Orig., maggoty. See <er>Mawk</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Apt to cause satiety or loathing; nauseous; slightly nauseating; disgusting.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So sweetly <qex>mawkish'</qex>, and so smoothly dull.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Easily disgusted; squeamish; sentimentally fastidious.</def>  <rj><au>J. H. Newman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Weakly sentimental; maudlin.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mawkishly</ent><br/
<hw>Mawk"ish*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a mawkish way.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mawkishness</ent><br/
<hw>Mawk"ish*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being mawkish.</def>  <rj><au>J. H. Newman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mawks</ent><br/
<hw>Mawks</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A slattern; a mawk.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mawky</ent><br/
<hw>Mawk"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Maggoty.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mawmet</ent><br/
<hw>Maw"met</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Contr. fr. <ets>Mahomet</ets>.]</ety> <def>A puppet; a doll; originally, an idol, because in the Middle Ages it was generally but falsely believed that the Muslims worshiped images representing <persfn>Mohammed</persfn>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Wyclif. Beau. & Fl.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mawmetry</ent><br/
<hw>Maw"met*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The religion of <persfn>Mohammed</persfn>; also, idolatry. See <er>Mawmet</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mawmish</ent><br/
<hw>Maw"mish</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Prov. E. <ets>mau</ets>m soft, mellow, rotten; cf. OD. <ets>molm</ets> rotten wood, G. <ets>mulm</ets>.]</ety> <def>Nauseous.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>L' Estrange.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mawseed</ent><br/
<hw>Maw"seed`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. G. <ets>magsamen</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The seed of the opium poppy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mawworm</ent><br/
<hw>Maw"worm`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Maw</ets> the belly + <ets>worm</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Any intestinal worm found in the stomach, esp. the common round worm (<spn>Ascaris lumbricoides</spn>), and allied species.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>One of the larvae of botflies of horses; a bot.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maxilla</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Max*il"la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Maxillae</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., dim. of <ets>mala</ets> jaw, jawbone.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The bone of either the upper or the under jaw.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The bone, or principal bone, of the upper jaw, the bone of the lower jaw being the <xex>mandible</xex>.</def> <mark>[Now commonly used in this restricted sense.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the lower or outer jaws of arthropods.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ There are usually two pairs in Crustacea and one pair in insects. In certain insects they are not used as jaws, but may form suctorial organs. See <xex>Illust.</xex> under <er>Lepidoptera</er>, and <er>Diptera</er>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 904 --></p>

<p><ent>Maxillary</ent><br/
<ent>Maxillar</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Max"il*lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Max"il*la*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>maxillaris</ets>, fr. <ets>maxilla</ets> jawbone, jaw: cf. F. <ets>maxillaire</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to either the upper or the lower jaw, but now usually applied to the upper jaw only.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>The principal maxillary bone; the maxilla.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to a maxilla.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maxilliform</ent><br/
<hw>Max*il"li*form</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Maxilla</ets> + <ets>-form</ets>: cf. F. <ets>maxilliforme</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having the form, or structure, of a maxilla.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maxilliped</ent><br/
<hw>Max*il"li*ped</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Maxilla</ets> + L. <ets>pes</ets>, <ets>pedis</ets>, foot.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the mouth appendages of Crustacea, situated next behind the maxillae.  Crabs have three pairs, but many of the lower Crustacea have but one pair of them.  Called also <altname>jawfoot</altname>, and <altname>foot jaw</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maxillo-mandibular</ent><br/
<hw>Max*il`lo-man*dib"u*lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Maxilla</ets> +  <ets>mandibular</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to the maxilla and mandible; <as>as, the <ex>maxillo-mandibular</ex> nerve</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maxillo-palatine</ent><br/
<hw>Max*il`lo-pal"a*tine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Maxilla</ets> + <ets>palatine</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to the maxillary and palatine regions of the skull; <as>as, the <ex>maxillo-palatine</ex> process of the maxilla</as>. Also used as <pos>n.</pos></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maxilloturbinal</ent><br/
<hw>Max*il`lo*tur`bi*nal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Maxilla</ets> + <ets>turbinal</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to the maxillary and turbinal regions of the skull.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>The maxillo-turbinal, or inferior turbinate, bone.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maxim</ent><br/
<hw>Max"im</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>maxime</ets>, L. <ets>maxima</ets> (sc. <ets>sententia</ets>), the greatest sentence, proposition, or axiom, i. e., of the greatest weight or authority, fem. fr. <ets>maximus</ets> greatest, superl. of <ets>magnus</ets> great. See <er>Magnitude</er>, and cf. <er>Maximum</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>An established principle or proposition; a condensed proposition of important practical truth; an axiom of practical wisdom; an adage; a proverb; an aphorism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>'T is their <qex>maxim</qex>, Love is love's reward.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>The longest note formerly used, equal to two longs, or four breves; a large.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Axiom; aphorism; apothegm; adage; proverb; saying. See <er>Axiom</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maxim gun</ent><br/
<hw>Max"im gun`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <def>A kind of machine gun; -- named after its inventor, <person>Hiram S. <etsep>Maxim</etsep></person>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maximilian</ent><br/
<hw>Max`i*mil"ian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From the proper name.]</ety> <def>A gold coin of Bavaria, of the value of about 13s. 6d. sterling, or about three dollars and a quarter.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maximisation</ent><br/
<hw>maximisation</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Maximization.</def> <mark>[Chiefly Brit.]</mark> <br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maximization</ent><br/
<hw>Max`i*mi*za"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act or process of increasing to the highest degree.</def>  <rj><au>Bentham.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maximize</ent><br/
<hw>Max"i*mize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>maximus</ets> greatest.]</ety> <def>To increase to the highest degree.</def>  <rj><au>Bentham.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maximizing</ent><br/
<hw>maximizing</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Making as great as possible; increasing tothe highest degree.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maximum</ent><br/
<hw>Max"i*mum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Maxima</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., neut. from <ets>maximus</ets> the greatest. See <er>Maxim</er>.]</ety> <def>The greatest quantity or value attainable in a given case; or, the greatest value attained by a quantity which first increases and then begins to decrease; the highest point or degree; -- opposed to <ant>minimum</ant>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Good legislation is the art of conducting a nation to the <qex>maximum</qex> of happiness, and the minimum of misery.</q> <rj><qau>P. Colquhoun.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Maximum thermometer</b></col>, <cd>a thermometer that registers the highest degree of temperature attained in a given time, or since its last adjustment.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maximum</ent><br/
<hw>Max"i*mum</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Greatest in quantity or highest in degree attainable or attained; <as>as, a <ex>maximum</ex> consumption of fuel; <ex>maximum</ex> pressure; <ex>maximum</ex> heat.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maxwell</ent><br/
<hw>maxwell</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A cgs unit of magnetic flux, abbreviated <abbr>Mx</abbr>; it is equal to the magnetic flux passing through one sqaure centimeter which is normal to a magnetic field of one gauss.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Mx.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>May</ent><br/
<hw>May</hw> <pr>(m<amac/)</pr>, <pos>v.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Might</conjf> <pr>(m<imac/t)</pr>]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. pres. <ets>maeg</ets> I am able, pret. <ets>meahte</ets>, <ets>mihte</ets>; akin to D. <ets>mogen</ets>, G. <ets>m<oum/gen</ets>, OHG. <ets>mugan</ets>, <ets>magan</ets>, Icel. <ets>mega</ets>, Goth. <ets>magan</ets>, Russ. <ets>moche</ets>. <root/103.  Cf. <er>Dismay</er>, <er>Main</er> strength, <er>Might</er>. The old imp. <ets>mought</ets> is obsolete, except as a provincial word.]</ety> <def>An auxiliary verb qualifying the meaning of another verb,</def> <specif>by expressing:</specif> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Ability, competency, or possibility; -- now oftener expressed by <altname>can</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How <qex>may</qex> a man, said he, with idle speech,<br/
Be won to spoil the castle of his health!</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For what he [the king] <qex>may</qex> do is of two kinds; what he <qex>may</qex> do as just, and what he <qex>may</qex> do as possible.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For of all sad words of tongue or pen<br/
The saddest are these: <ldquo/It <qex>might</qex> have been.<rdquo/</q> <rj><qau>Whittier.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>Liberty; permission; allowance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou <qex>mayst</qex> be no longer steward.</q> <rj><qau>Luke xvi. 2.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>Contingency or liability; possibility or probability.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though what he learns he speaks, and <qex>may</qex> advance<br/
Some general maxims, or be right by chance.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <def>Modesty, courtesy, or concession, or a desire to soften a question or remark.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How old <qex>may</qex> Phillis be, you ask.</q> <rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(e)</sd> <def>Desire or wish, as in prayer, imprecation, benediction, and the like.</def> <ldquo/<xex>May</xex> you live happily.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>May be</b></col>, <and/ <col><b>It may be</b></col></mcol>, <cd>are used as equivalent to <altname>possibly</altname>, <altname>perhaps</altname>, <altname>maybe</altname>, <altname>by chance</altname>, <altname>peradventure</altname>. See 1st <er>Maybe</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>May</ent><br/
<hw>May</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Icel. <ets>maer</ets>, Goth. <ets>mawi</ets>; akin to E. <ets>maiden</ets>. <root/103.]</ety> <def>A maiden.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>May</ent><br/
<hw>May</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>Mai</ets>, L. <ets>Maius</ets>; so named in honor of the goddess <ets>Maia</ets> (Gr. <grk>Mai^a</grk>), daughter of Atlas and mother of Mercury by Jupiter.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The fifth month of the year, containing thirty-one days.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The early part or springtime of life.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His <qex>May</qex> of youth, and bloom of lustihood.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The flowers of the hawthorn; -- so called from their time of blossoming; also, the hawthorn.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The palm and <qex>may</qex> make country houses gay.</q> <rj><qau>Nash.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Plumes that mocked the <qex>may</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The merrymaking of May Day.</def>  <rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Italian may</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a shrubby species of <gen>Spiraea</gen> (<spn>Spiraea hypericifolia</spn>) with many clusters of small white flowers along the slender branches.</cd> -- <col><b>May apple</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the fruit of an American plant (<spn>Podophyllum peltatum</spn>). Also, the plant itself (popularly called <altname>mandrake</altname>), which has two lobed leaves, and bears a single egg-shaped fruit at the forking. The root and leaves, used in medicine, are powerfully drastic.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>May beetle</b></col>, <col><b>May bug</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one of numerous species of large lamellicorn beetles that appear in the winged state in May.  They belong to <gen>Melolontha</gen>, and allied genera.  Called also <altname>June beetle</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>May Day</b></col>, <cd>the first day of May; -- celebrated in the rustic parts of England by the crowning of a May queen with a garland, and by dancing about a May pole.</cd> -- <col><b>May dew</b></col>, <cd>the morning dew of the first day of May, to which magical properties were attributed.</cd> -- <col><b>May flower</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a plant that flowers in May; also, its blossom. See <er>Mayflower</er>, in the vocabulary.</cd> -- <col><b>May fly</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any species of <spn>Ephemera</spn>, and allied genera; -- so called because the mature flies of many species appear in May. See <cref>Ephemeral fly</cref>, under <er>Ephemeral</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>May game</b></col>, <cd>any May-day sport.</cd> -- <col><b>May lady</b></col>, <cd>the queen or lady of May, in old May games.</cd> -- <col><b>May lily</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the lily of the valley (<spn>Convallaria majalis</spn>).</cd> -- <col><b>May pole</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Maypole</er> in the Vocabulary.</cd> -- <col><b>May queen</b></col>, <cd>a girl or young woman crowned queen in the sports of May Day.</cd> -- <col><b>May thorn</b></col>, <cd>the hawthorn.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maya</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Ma"ya</hw> <pr>(m<aum/"y<aum/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Hindu Philos.)</fld> <def>The name (in Vedantic philosphy) for the doctrine of the unreality of matter, called, in English, <altname>idealism</altname>; hence, nothingness; vanity; illusion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Hindu Philos.)</fld> <def>the Hindu goddess personifying the power that creates phenomena.</def> <au>[RHUD]</au><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Hindu Philos.)</fld> <def>the power to produce illusions.</def> <au>[RHUD]</au><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maya</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"ya</hw> <pr>(m<aum/"y<adot/)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Maya</plw> or <plw>Mayas</plw>.</plu> <sn>1.</sn> <def>the Indian people occupying the area of Veracruz, Chiapas, Tabasco, Campeche, and Yucatan, together with a part of Guatemala and a part of Salvador.  The Maya peoples are dark, short, and brachycephalic, and at the time of the discovery had attained a higher grade of culture than any other American people.  They cultivated a variety of crops, were expert in the manufacture and dyeing of cotton fabrics, used cacao as a medium of exchange, and were workers of gold, silver, and copper.  Their architecture comprised elaborately carved temples and palaces, and they possessed a superior calendar, and a developed system of hieroglyphic writing, with records said to go back to about 700 <sc>a. d</sc>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>the language of the Mayas.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mayaca</ent><br/
<hw>Mayaca</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A small genus of delicate mossy bog plants having white or violet flowers.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Mayaca</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mayan</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"yan</hw> <pr>(m<aum/"y<ait/n)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Designating, or pertaining to, an American Indian linguistic stock occupying the Mexican States of Veracruz, Chiapas, Tabasco, Campeche, and Yucatan, together with a part of Guatemala and a part of El Salvador. See 2nd <er>Maya</er>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>Of or pertaining to the Mayas.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maya arch</ent><br/
<ent>Mayan arch</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mayan arch</hw>, <it></it> <hw>Maya arch</hw>  }</mhw>. <def>A form of corbel arch employing regular small corbels.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>may apple</ent><br/
<ent>mayapple</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mayapple</hw>, <hw>may apple</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>North American herb (<spn>Podophyllum peltatum</spn>) with poisonous root stock and an edible though insipid egg-shaped yellowish fruit; called also <altname>wild mandrake</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> May apple, wild mandrake, <spn>Podophyllum peltatum</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The fruit of the mayapple{1}.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maybe</ent><br/
<hw>May"be</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[For <ets>it may be</ets>.]</ety> <def>Perhaps; possibly; peradventure.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Maybe</qex> the amorous count solicits her.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In a liberal and, <qex>maybe</qex>, somewhat reckless way.</q> <rj><qau>Tylor.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maybe</ent><br/
<hw>May"be</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Possible; probable, but not sure.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then add those <qex>maybe</qex> years thou hast to live.</q> <rj><qau>Driden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maybe</ent><br/
<hw>May"be</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Possibility; uncertainty.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What they offer is mere <qex>maybe</qex> and shift.</q> <rj><qau>Creech.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maybird</ent><br/
<hw>May"bird`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The whimbrel; -- called also <altname>May fowl</altname>, <altname>May curlew</altname>, and <altname>May whaap</altname>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The knot.</def> <mark>[Southern U. S.]</mark> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The bobolink.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maybloom</ent><br/
<hw>May"bloom`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The hawthorn.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maybush</ent><br/
<hw>May"bush`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The hawthorn.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mayduke</ent><br/
<hw>May"duke`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Corrupt. of <etsep>M<eacute/doc</etsep>, a province in France, where it is supposed to have originated.]</ety> <def>A large dark-red cherry of excellent quality.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mayfish</ent><br/
<hw>May"fish`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A common American minnow (<spn>Fundulus majalis</spn>). See <er>Minnow</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mayflower</ent><br/
<hw>May"flow`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>In England, the hawthorn; in New England, the trailing arbutus (see <er>Arbutus</er>); also, the blossom of these plants.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mayhap</ent><br/
<hw>May"hap</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Perhaps; peradventure.</def> <mark>[Prov. or Dialectic]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mayhaw</ent><br/
<hw>mayhaw</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The hawthorn tree (<spn>Crataegus aestivalis</spn>) of the Southern U. S. bearing a juicy acid scarlet fruit often used in jellies or preserves.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> summer haw, <spn>Crataegus aestivalis</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mayhem</ent><br/
<hw>may"hem</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[The same as <ets>maim</ets>. See <er>Maim</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The maiming of a person by depriving him of the use of any of his members which are necessary for defense or protection. See <er>Maim</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Violent disorder, especially such as causes serious harm to persons or damage to property.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maying</ent><br/
<hw>May"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The celebrating of May Day.</def> <ldquo/He met her once a-<xex>Maying</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>May laws</ent><br/
<hw>May laws</hw>. <sn>1.</sn> <def>See <er>Kulturkampf</er>, above.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>In Russia, severe oppressive laws against Jews, which have given occasion for great persecution; -- so called because they received the assent of the czar in May, 1882, and because likened to the Prussian May laws (see <er>Kulturkampf</er>).</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mayonnaise</ent><br/
<hw>ma`yon`naise"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>A thick white sauce compounded of raw yolks of eggs beaten up with olive oil to the consistency near to that of a gel, and seasoned with vinegar, pepper, salt, etc.; -- used in dressing salads, fish, etc.  Also, a dish dressed with this sauce.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mayor</ent><br/
<hw>may"or</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>maire</ets>, F. <ets>maire</ets>, fr. L. <ets>major</ets> greater, higher, nobler, compar. of <ets>magnus</ets> great; cf. Sp. <ets>mayor</ets>. See <er>Major</er>, and cf. <er>Merino</er>.]</ety> <def>The chief magistrate of a city or borough; the chief administrative officer of a municipal corporation.  In some American cities there is a city court of which the major is chief judge.  The post is usually elective, its holder chosen by the electorate of the entire city.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mayoral</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>May"or*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp., fr. <ets>mayor</ets> greater, L. <ets>major</ets>.]</ety> <def>The conductor of a mule team; also, a head shepherd.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mayoral</ent><br/
<hw>may"or*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to a mayor; <as>as, the <ex>mayoral</ex> limousine</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mayoralty</ent><br/
<hw>May"or*al*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The office, or the term of office, of a mayor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mayoress</ent><br/
<hw>May"or*ess</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The wife of a mayor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A woman who is mayor.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mayorship</ent><br/
<hw>May"or*ship</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The office of a mayor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maypole</ent><br/
<hw>May"pole`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A tall pole erected in an open place and wreathed with flowers, about which the rustic May-day sports were had.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maypop</ent><br/
<hw>May"pop</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Perh. corrupt. fr. <ets>maracock</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The edible fruit of a passion flower, especially that of the North American <spn>Passiflora incarnata</spn>, an oval yellowish berry as large as a small apple.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mayweed</ent><br/
<hw>May"weed`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A composite plant (<spn>Anthemis Cotula</spn>), having a strong odor; dog's fennel.  It is a native of Europe, now common by the roadsides in the United States.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The feverfew.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mazame</ent><br/
<ent>Mazama</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Ma*za"ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Ma*za"me</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A goatlike antelope (<spn>Haplocerus montanus</spn>) which inhabits the Rocky Mountains, frequenting the highest parts; -- called also <altname>mountain goat</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mazard</ent><br/
<hw>Maz"ard</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>merise</ets> a wild cherry.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A kind of small black cherry.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mazard</ent><br/
<hw>Maz"ard</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. fr. <ets>mazer</ets>, the head being compared to a large goblet.]</ety> <def>The jaw; the head or skull.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mazard</ent><br/
<hw>Maz"ard</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, <def>To knock on the head.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mazarine</ent><br/
<hw>Maz`a*rine"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to Cardinal <xex>Mazarin</xex>, prime minister of France, 1643-1661.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mazarine Bible</b></col>, <cd>the first Bible, and perhaps the first complete book, printed with movable metal types; -- printed by Gutenberg at Mentz, 1450-55; -- so called because a copy was found in the Mazarine Library, at Paris, about 1760.</cd> -- <col><b>Mazarine blue</b></col>, <cd>a deep blue color, named in honor of Cardinal Mazarin.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mazarine</ent><br/
<hw>Maz`a*rine"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mazarine blue.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mazarine</ent><br/
<hw>Maz`a*rine"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Cookery)</fld> <def>A forcemeat entr<eacute/e.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mazdean</ent><br/
<hw>Maz"de*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to <persfn>Ahura-<xex>Mazda</xex></persfn>, or <persfn>Ormuzd</persfn>, the beneficent deity in the Zoroastrian dualistic system; hence, Zoroastrian.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mazdeism</ent><br/
<hw>Maz"de*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The Zoroastrian religion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maze</ent><br/
<hw>Maze</hw> <pr>(m<amac/z)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mase</ets>; cf. OE. <ets>masen</ets> to confuse, puzzle, Norweg. <ets>masast</ets> to fall into a slumber, <ets>masa</ets> to be continually busy, prate, chatter, Icel. <ets>masa</ets> to chatter, dial. Sw. <ets>masa</ets> to bask, be slow, work slowly and lazily, <ets>mas</ets> slow, lazy.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A wild fancy; a confused notion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Confusion of thought; perplexity; uncertainty; state of bewilderment.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A confusing and baffling network, as of paths or passages; an intricacy; a labyrinth.</def> <ldquo/Quaint <xex>mazes</xex> on the wanton green.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Or down the tempting <qex>maze</qex> of Shawford brook.</q> <rj><qau>Wordaworth.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The ways of Heaven are dark and intricate,<br/
Puzzled with <qex>mazes</qex>, and perplexed with error.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A complex and confusing system or set of rules that causes bwilderment; <as>as, a <ex>maze</ex> of environemntal regulations</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Labyrinth; intricacy. See <er>Labyrinth</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maze</ent><br/
<hw>Maze</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mazed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mazing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To perplex greatly; to bewilder; to astonish and confuse; to amaze.</def>  <rj><au>South.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maze</ent><br/
<hw>Maze</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be bewildered.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mazedness</ent><br/
<hw>Maz"ed*ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The condition of being mazed; confusion; astonishment.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mazeful</ent><br/
<hw>Maze"ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Mazy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir P. Sidney.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mazer</ent><br/
<hw>Maz"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>maser</ets>, akin to OD. <ets>maser</ets> an excrescence on a maple tree, OHG. <ets>masar</ets>, G. <ets>maser</ets> spot, Icel. <ets>m<oum/surr</ets> maple.]</ety> <def>A large drinking bowl; -- originally made of maple.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their brimful <qex>mazers</qex> to the feasting bring.</q> <rj><qau>Drayton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mazily</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"zi*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a mazy manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maziness</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"zi*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state or quality of being mazy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mazological</ent><br/
<hw>Maz`o*log"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to mazology.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mazologist</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*zol"o*gist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One versed in mazology or mastology.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mazology</ent><br/
<hw>Ma*zol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mazo`s</grk> the breast + <ets>-logy</ets>.]</ety> <def>Same as <er>Mastology</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mazurka</ent><br/
<ent>Mazourka</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Ma*zour"ka</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Ma*zur"ka</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A Polish dance, or the music which accompanies it, usually in 3-4 or 3-8 measure, with a strong accent on the second beat.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mazy</ent><br/
<hw>Ma"zy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Maze</er>.]</ety> <def>Perplexed with turns and windings; winding; intricate; confusing; perplexing; embarrassing; <as>as, <ex>mazy</ex> error</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To range amid the <qex>mazy</qex> thicket.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To run the ring, and trace the <qex>mazy</qex> round.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>McCarthyism</ent><br/
<hw>McCarthyism</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[from <person>Senator Joseph <etsep>McCarthy</etsep></person>, who repeatedly asserted without evidence that numerous communists were present in the United States government.]</ety> <def>Unscrupulously accusing people of disloyalty (as by saying they were Communists).</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>McKinley</ent><br/
<hw>McKinley</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>Mount McKinley, the highest peak in North America; 20,300 feet high; also called by the native name <altname>Denali</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Mt. McKinley, Denali.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>MDMA</ent><br/
<hw>MDMA</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Methylenedioxymethamphetamine, a drug designed to have the effects of amphetamines but originally synthesized to avoid the drug laws; it is now a controlled substance.  It is informally called <altname>ecstasy</altname>.  It is used by some abusively and illegally without a prescription.</def> <mark>[acronym]</mark><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> methylenedioxymethamphetamine, Adam, ecstasy.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Me</ent><br/
<hw>Me</hw> <pr>(m<esl/)</pr>, <pos>pron.</pos> <def>One. See <er>Men</er>, <pos>pron.</pos></def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Me</ent><br/
<hw>Me</hw> <pr>(m<emac/)</pr>, <pos>pers. pron.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<emac/</ets>, dat. & acc., <ets>mec</ets>, acc. only ; akin to D. <ets>mij</ets>, G. <ets>mich</ets>, Icel. & Goth. <ets>mik</ets>, L. <ets>me</ets>, Gr. <grk>me`</grk>, <grk>'eme`</grk>, Skr. <ets>m<amac/</ets>, <ets>m<amac/m</ets>. <root/187.  Cf. 2d <er>Mine</er>.]</ety> <def>The person speaking, regarded as an object; myself; a pronoun of the first person used as the objective and dative case of the pronoum I; <as>as, he struck <ex>me</ex>; he gave <ex>me</ex> the money, or he gave the money to <ex>me</ex>; he got <ex>me</ex> a hat, or he got a hat for <ex>me</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ In <xex>methinks</xex>, <xex>me</xex> is properly in the dative case, and the verb is impersonal, the construction being, <xex>it appears to me</xex>.  In early use <xex>me</xex> was often placed before forms of the verb <xex>to be</xex> with an adjective; as, <xex>me</xex> were lief.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Me</qex> rather had my heart might frrl your love<br/
Than my unpleased eye see your courtesy.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meach</ent><br/
<hw>Meach</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To skulk; to cower. See <er>Mich</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meacock</ent><br/
<hw>Mea"cock</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. fr. <ets>meek</ets> + <ets>cock</ets>.]</ety> <def>An uxorious, effeminate, or spiritless man.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mead</ent><br/
<hw>Mead</hw> <pr>(m<emac/d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mede</ets>, AS. <ets>meodo</ets>; akin to D. <ets>mede</ets>, G. <ets>met</ets>, <ets>meth</ets>, OHG. <ets>metu</ets>, <ets>mitu</ets>, Icel. <ets>mj<oum/<edh/r</ets>, Dan. <ets>mi<oum/d</ets>, Sw. <ets>mj<oum/d</ets>, Russ. <ets>med'</ets>, Lith. <ets>midus</ets>, W. <ets>medd</ets>, Gr. <grk>me`qy</grk> wine, Skr. <ets>madhu</ets> honey, a sweet drink, as adj., sweet.  <root/270.  Cf. <er>Metheglin</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A fermented drink made of water and honey with malt, yeast, etc.; metheglin; hydromel.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A drink composed of sirup of sarsaparilla or other flavoring extract, and water.  It is sometimes charged with carbonic acid gas.</def> <mark>[U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mead</ent><br/
<hw>Mead</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<aemac/d</ets>. See <er>Meadow</er>.]</ety> <def>A meadow.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>mede</qex><br/
All full of freshe flowers, white and reede.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To fertile vales and dewy <qex>meads</qex><br/
My weary, wandering steps he leads.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meadow</ent><br/
<hw>Mead"ow</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>meady</ets>; akin to <ets>m<aemac/d</ets>, and to G. <ets>matte</ets>; prob. also to E. <ets>mow</ets>. See <er>Mow</er> to cut (grass), and cf. 2d <er>Mead</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A tract of low or level land producing grass which is mown for hay; any field on which grass is grown for hay.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Low land covered with coarse grass or rank herbage near rives and in marshy places by the sea; <as>as, the salt <ex>meadows</ex> near Newark Bay</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meadow</ent><br/
<hw>Mead"ow</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to a meadow; of the nature of a meadow; produced, growing, or living in, a meadow.</def> <ldquo/Fat <xex>meadow</xex> ground.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ For many names of plants compounded with <xex>meadow</xex>, see the particular word in the Vocabulary.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Meadow beauty</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>Same as <er>Deergrass</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Meadow foxtail</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a valuable pasture grass (<spn>Alopecurus pratensis</spn>) resembling timothy, but with softer spikes.</cd> -- <col><b>Meadow hay</b></col>, <cd>a coarse grass, or true sedge, growing in uncultivated swamp or river meadow; -- used as fodder or bedding for cattle, packing for ice, etc.</cd> <mark>[Local, U. S.]</mark> -- <col><b>Meadow hen</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The American bittern</cd>. See <er>Stake-driver</er>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>The American coot (<gen>Fulica</gen>).</cd> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>The clapper rail.</cd> -- <col><b>Meadow mouse</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any mouse of the genus <gen>Arvicola</gen>, as the common American species <spn>Arvicola riparia</spn>; -- called also <altname>field mouse</altname>, and <altname>field vole</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Meadow mussel</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>an American ribbed mussel (<spn>Modiola plicatula</spn>), very abundant in salt marshes.</cd> -- <col><b>Meadow ore</b></col> <fld>(Min.)</fld>, <cd>bog-iron ore , a kind of limonite.</cd> -- <col><b>Meadow parsnip</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Parsnip</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Meadow pink</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Pink</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Meadow pipit</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a small singing bird of the genus <gen>Anthus</gen>, as <spn>Anthus pratensis</spn>, of Europe.</cd> -- <col><b>Meadow rue</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a delicate early plant, of the genus <gen>Thalictrum</gen>, having compound leaves and numerous white flowers. There are many species.</cd> -- <col><b>Meadow saffron</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Saffron</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Meadow sage</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Sage</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Meadow saxifrage</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>an umbelliferous plant of Europe (<spn>Silaus pratensis</spn>), somewhat resembling fennel.</cd> -- <col><b>Meadow snipe</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the common or jack snipe.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>meadow grass</ent><br/
<ent>meadowgrass</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>meadowgrass</hw>, <hw>meadow grass</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Any of various grasses that thrive in the presence of abundant moisture, especially those of the genus <gen>Poa</gen>, common in meadows, and of great value for hay and for pasture. See <er>Grass</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>meadow lark</ent><br/
<ent>meadowlark</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>meadowlark</hw>, <hw>meadow lark</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos>  <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <def>Any species of <gen>Sturnella</gen>, a genus of North American songbirds allied to the starlings.  The common species (<spn>Sturnella magna</spn>) has a yellow breast with a black crescent.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> lark.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 905 --></p>

<p><ent>Meadowwort</ent><br/
<ent>Meadowsweet</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mead"ow*sweet`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mead"ow*wort`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The name of several plants of the genus <gen>Spiraea</gen>, especially the white- or pink-flowered <spn>Spiraea salicifolia</spn>, a low European and American shrub, and the herbaceous <spn>Spiraea Ulmaria</spn>, which has fragrant white flowers in compound cymes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meadowy</ent><br/
<hw>Mead"ow*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to meadows; resembling, or consisting of, meadow.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meagre</ent><br/
<ent>Meager</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mea"ger</hw>, <hw>Mea"gre</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>merge</ets>, F. <ets>maigre</ets>, L. <ets>macer</ets>; akin to D. & G. <ets>mager</ets>, Icel. <ets>magr</ets>, and prob. to Gr. <grk>makro`s</grk> long.  Cf. <er>Emaciate</er>, <er>Maigre</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Destitue of, or having little, flesh; lean.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Meager</qex> were his looks;<br/
Sharp misery had worn him to the bones.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Destitute of richness, fertility, strength, or the like; defective in quantity, or poor in quality; poor; barren; scanty in ideas; wanting strength of diction or affluence of imagery; <as>as, <ex>meager</ex> resources; <ex>meager</ex> fare</as>.  Opposite of <ant>ample</ant>.</def> <wns>[wns=1]</wns> [Narrower terms: <stype>exiguous</stype>] [Narrower terms: <stype>hardscrabble, marginal</stype>] [Narrower terms: <stype>measly, miserable, paltry</stype>]  <ldquo/<xex>Meager</xex> soil.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> meagre, meagerly, scanty.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of secular habits and <qex>meager</qex> religious belief.</q> <rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His education had been but <qex>meager</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Motley.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Dry and harsh to the touch, as chalk.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>less than a desirable amount; -- of items distributed from a larger supply.</def> <wns>[wns=2]</wns><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> scrimpy, skimpy, skimping.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Thin; lean; lank; gaunt; starved; hungry; poor; emaciated; scanty; barren.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meagre</ent><br/
<ent>Meager</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mea"ger</hw>, <hw>Mea"gre</hw>  }</mhw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make lean.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>meagerly</ent><br/
<hw>meagerly</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>same as <er>meager</er>, 2.  Opposite of <ant>ample</ant>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> meager, meagre.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meagrely</ent><br/
<ent>Meagerly</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mea"ger*ly</hw>, <hw>Mea"gre*ly</hw>  }</mhw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Poorly; thinly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meagreness</ent><br/
<ent>Meagerness</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mea"ger*ness</hw>, <hw>Mea"gre*ness</hw>  }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state or quality of being meager; leanness; scantiness; barrenness.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> meagreness, poorness, scantiness, scantness, exiguity.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meagre</ent><br/
<hw>Mea"gre</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>maigre</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A large European sciaenoid fish (<spn>Sciaena umbra</spn> or <spn>Sciaena aquila</spn>), having white bloodless flesh.  It is valued as a food fish.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>maigre</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meak</ent><br/
<hw>Meak</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. AS. <ets>m<emac/ce</ets> sword, OS. <ets>m<amac/ki</ets>, Icel. <ets>maekir</ets>.]</ety> <def>A hook with a long handle.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Tusser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meaking</ent><br/
<hw>Meak"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Meak</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The process of picking out the oakum from the seams of a vessel which is to be recalked.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Meaking iron</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>the tool with which old oakum is picked out of a vessel's seams.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meal</ent><br/
<hw>Meal</hw> <pr>(m<emac/l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mele</ets>, AS. <ets>m<aemac/l</ets> part, portion, portion of time; akin to E. <ets>meal</ets> a repast.  Cf. <er>Piecemeal</er>.]</ety> <def>A part; a fragment; a portion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meal</ent><br/
<hw>Meal</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mel</ets>; akin to E. <ets>meal</ets> a part, and to D. <ets>maal</ets> time, meal, G. <ets>mal</ets> time, <ets>mahl</ets> meal, Icel. <ets>m<amac/l</ets> measure, time, meal, Goth. <ets>m<emac/l</ets> time, and to E. <ets>measure</ets>. See <er>Measure</er>.]</ety> <def>The portion of food taken at a particular time for the satisfaction of appetite; the quantity usually taken at one time with the purpose of satisfying hunger; a repast; the act or time of eating a meal; <as>as, the traveler has not eaten a good <ex>meal</ex> for a week; there was silence during the <ex>meal</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What strange fish<br/
Hath made his <qex>meal</qex> on thee?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meal</ent><br/
<hw>Meal</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mele</ets>, AS. <ets>melu</ets>, <ets>melo</ets>; akin to D. <ets>meel</ets>, G. <ets>mehl</ets>, OHG. <ets>melo</ets>, Icel. <ets>mj<oum/l</ets>, SW. <ets>mj<oum/l</ets>, Dan. <ets>meel</ets>, also to D. <ets>malen</ets> to grind, G. <ets>mahlen</ets>, OHG., OS., & Goth. <ets>malan</ets>, Icel. <ets>mala</ets>, W. <ets>malu</ets>, L. <ets>molere</ets>, Gr. <grk>my`lh</grk> mill, and E. <ets>mill</ets>. <root/108.  Cf. <er>Mill</er>, <er>Mold</er> soil, <er>Mole</er> an animal, <er>Immolate</er>, <er>Molar</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Grain (esp. maize, rye, or oats) that is coarsely ground and unbolted; also, a kind of flour made from beans, pease, etc.; sometimes, any flour, esp. if coarse.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any substance that is coarsely pulverized like meal, but not granulated.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Meal beetle</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the adult of the meal worm. See <cref>Meal worm</cref>, below.</cd> -- <col><b>Meal moth</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a lepidopterous insect (<spn>Asopia farinalis</spn>), the larvae of which feed upon meal, flour, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Meal worm</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the larva of a beetle (<spn>Tenebrio molitor</spn>) which infests granaries, bakehouses, etc., and is very injurious to flour and meal.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meal</ent><br/
<hw>Meal</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To sprinkle with, or as with, meal.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To pulverize; <as>as, <ex>mealed</ex> powder</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mealies</ent><br/
<hw>Meal"ies</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mealy</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Maize or Indian corn; -- the common name in South Africa.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mealiness</ent><br/
<hw>Meal"i*ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being mealy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meal-mouthed</ent><br/
<hw>Meal"-mouthed`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>See <er>Mealy-mouthed</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>meals-on-wheels</ent><br/
<ent>meals on wheels</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>meals on wheels</hw>, <hw>meals-on-wheels</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A program that delivers hot meals to persons, such as the elderly or disabled, who are confined to their homes and unable to cook for themselves; also, the meals thus delivered.  Such programs are usually conducted by governmental or charitable organizations.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mealtime</ent><br/
<hw>Meal"time`</hw> <pr>(m<emac/l"t<imac/m`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The usual time of eating a meal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mealy</ent><br/
<hw>Meal"y</hw> <pr>(m<emac/l"<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Mealier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Mealiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having the qualities of meal; resembling meal; soft, dry, and friable; easily reduced to a condition resembling meal; <as>as, a <ex>mealy</ex> potato</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Overspread with something that resembles meal; <as>as, the <ex>mealy</ex> wings of an insect</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mealy bug</ent><br/
<ent>mealybug</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>meal"y*bug`</hw>, <hw>mealy bug</hw></mhw>  <pr>(m<emac/l"<ycr/*b<ucr/g`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <def>Any of several homopteran scale insects (as, <spn>Coccus adonidum</spn>, and related species of the families <fam>Pseudococcidae</fam> and <fam>Eriococcidae</fam>), that cover themselves with a white powderlike or cottony wax secretion.  They are common plant-eating pests in hothouses and are also destructive of fruit trees.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mealy-mouthed</ent><br/
<hw>Meal"y-mouthed`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Using soft words; not straightforward; plausible; affectedly or timidly delicate of speech; speaking deviously; unwilling to tell the truth in plain language.  Opposite of <ant>frank</ant> or <ant>blunt</ant>.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Mealy-mouthed</xex> philanthropies.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She was a fool to be <qex>mealy-mouthed</qex> where nature speaks so plain.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Meal"y-mouth`ness</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mean</ent><br/
<hw>Mean</hw> <pr>(m<emac/n)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Meant</conjf> <pr>(m<ecr/nt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Meaning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>menen</ets>, AS. <ets>m<aemac/nan</ets> to recite, tell, intend, wish; akin to OS. <ets>m<emac/nian</ets> to have in mind, mean, D. <ets>meenen</ets>, G. <ets>meinen</ets>, OHG. <ets>meinan</ets>, Icel. <ets>meina</ets>, Sw. <ets>mena</ets>, Dan. <ets>mene</ets>, and to E. <ets>mind</ets>.  <root/104.  See <er>Mind</er>, and cf. <er>Moan</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To have in the mind, as a purpose, intention, etc.; to intend; to purpose; to design; <as>as, what do you <ex>mean</ex> to do?</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What <qex>mean</qex> ye by this service ?</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xii. 26.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye thought evil against me; but God <qex>meant</qex> it unto good.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. 1. 20.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am not a Spaniard<br/
To say that it is yours and not to <qex>mean</qex> it.</q> <rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To signify; to indicate; to import; to denote.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What <qex>mean</qex> these seven ewe lambs ?</q> <rj><qau>Gen. xxi. 29.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Go ye, and learn what that <qex>meaneth</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. ix. 13.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mean</ent><br/
<hw>Mean</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To have a purpose or intention.</def> <mark>[Rare, except in the phrase to mean well, or ill.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mean</ent><br/
<hw>Mean</hw> <pr>(m<emac/n)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Meaner</adjf> <pr>(m<emac/n"<etil/r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Meanest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>mene</ets>, AS. <ets>m<aemac/ne</ets> wicked; akin to <ets>m<amac/n</ets>, a., wicked, n., wickedness, OS. <ets>m<emac/n</ets> wickedness, OHG. <ets>mein</ets>, G. <ets>meineid</ets> perjury, Icel. <ets>mein</ets> harm, hurt, and perh. to AS. <ets>gem<aemac/ne</ets> common, general, D. <ets>gemeen</ets>, G. <ets>gemein</ets>, Goth. <ets>gam<aacute/ins</ets>, and L. <ets>communis</ets>. The AS. <ets>gem<aemac/ne</ets> prob. influenced the meaning.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Destitute of distinction or eminence; common; low; vulgar; humble.</def> <ldquo/Of <xex>mean</xex> parentage.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Sir P. Sidney.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>mean</qex> man boweth down, and the great man humbleth himself.</q> <rj><qau>Is. ii. 9.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Wanting dignity of mind; low-minded; base; destitute of honor; spiritless; <as>as, a <ex>mean</ex> motive</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Can you imagine I so <qex>mean</qex> could prove,<br/
To save my life by changing of my love ?</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Of little value or account; worthy of little or no regard; contemptible; despicable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Roman legions and great Caesar found<br/
Our fathers no <qex>mean</qex> foes.</q> <rj><qau>J. Philips.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Of poor quality; <as>as, <ex>mean</ex> fare</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Penurious; stingy; close-fisted; illiberal; <as>as, <ex>mean</ex> hospitality</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Mean</xex> is sometimes used in the formation of compounds, the sense of which is obvious without explanation; as, <xex>mean</xex>born, <xex>mean</xex>-looking, etc.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Base; ignoble; abject; beggarly; wretched; degraded; degenerate; vulgar; vile; servile; menial; spiritless; groveling; slavish; dishonorable; disgraceful; shameful; despicable; contemptible; paltry; sordid. See <er>Base</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mean</ent><br/
<hw>Mean</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mene</ets>, OF. <ets>meiien</ets>, F. <ets>moyen</ets>, fr. L. <ets>medianus</ets> that is in the middle, fr. <ets>medius</ets>; akin to E. <ets>mid</ets>. See <er>Mid</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Occupying a middle position; middle; being about midway between extremes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Being of middle age and a <qex>mean</qex> stature.</q> <rj><qau>Sir. P. Sidney.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Intermediate in excellence of any kind.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>According to the fittest style of lofty, <qex>mean</qex>, or lowly.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>Average; having an intermediate value between two extremes, or between the several successive values of a variable quantity during one cycle of variation; <as>as, <ex>mean</ex> distance; <ex>mean</ex> motion; <ex>mean</ex> solar day.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mean distance</b></col> (of a planet from the sun) <fld>(Astron.)</fld>, <cd>the average of the distances throughout one revolution of the planet, equivalent to the semi-major axis of the orbit.</cd> -- <col><b>Mean error</b></col> <fld>(Math. Phys.)</fld>, <cd>the average error of a number of observations found by taking the mean value of the positive and negative errors without regard to sign.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Mean-square error</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Error of the mean square</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Math. Phys.)</fld>, <cd>the error the square of which is the mean of the squares of all the errors; -- called also, <altname>mean square deviation</altname>, <altname>mean error</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mean line</b></col>. <fld>(Crystallog.)</fld> <cd>Same as <er>Bisectrix</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mean noon</b></col>, <cd>noon as determined by mean time.</cd> -- <col><b>Mean proportional</b></col> (between two numbers) <fld>(Math.)</fld>, <cd>the square root of their product.</cd> -- <col><b>Mean sun</b></col>, <cd>a fictitious sun supposed to move uniformly in the equator so as to be on the meridian each day at mean noon.</cd> -- <col><b>Mean time</b></col>, <cd>time as measured by an equable motion, as of a perfect clock, or as reckoned on the supposition that all the days of the year are of a mean or uniform length, in contradistinction from <xex>apparent</xex> time, or that actually indicated by the sun, and from <xex>sidereal</xex> time, or that measured by the stars.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mean</ent><br/
<hw>Mean</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is mean, or intermediate, between two extremes of place, time, or number; the middle point or place; middle rate or degree; mediocrity; medium; absence of extremes or excess; moderation; measure.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But to speak in a <qex>mean</qex>, the virtue of prosperity is temperance; the virtue of adversity is fortitude.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is a <qex>mean</qex> in all things.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The extremes we have mentioned, between which the wellinstracted Christian holds the <qex>mean</qex>, are correlatives.</q> <rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>A quantity having an intermediate value between several others, from which it is derived, and of which it expresses the resultant value; usually, unless otherwise specified, it is the simple average, formed by adding the quantities together and dividing by their number, which is called an <stype>arithmetical mean</stype>.  A <stype>geometrical mean</stype> is the <it>n</it>th root of the product of the <it>n</it> quantities being averaged.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That through which, or by the help of which, an end is attained; something tending to an object desired; intermediate agency or measure; necessary condition or coagent; instrument.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their virtuous conversation was a <qex>mean</qex> to work the conversion of the heathen to Christ.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You may be able, by this <qex>mean</qex>, to review your own scientific acquirements.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Philosophical doubt is not an end, but a <qex>mean</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Hamilton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ In this sense the word is usually employed in the plural form <xex>means</xex>, and often with a singular attribute or predicate, as if a singular noun.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By <qex>this means</qex> he had them more at vantage.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What other <qex>means is</qex> left unto us.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>Resources; property, revenue, or the like, considered as the condition of easy livelihood, or an instrumentality at command for effecting any purpose; disposable force or substance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your <qex>means</qex> are very slender, and your waste is great.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A part, whether alto or tenor, intermediate between the soprano and base; a middle part.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>mean</qex> is drowned with your unruly base.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Meantime; meanwhile.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A mediator; a go-between.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Piers Plowman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He wooeth her by <qex>means</qex> and by brokage.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>By all means</b></col>, <cd>certainly; without fail; <as>as, go, <ex>by all means</ex></as>.</cd> -- <col><b>By any means</b></col>, <cd>in any way; possibly; at all.</cd><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If <qex>by any means</qex> I might attain to the resurrection of the dead.</q> <rj><qau>Phil. iii. ll.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <mcol><col><b>By no means</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>By no manner of means</b></col></mcol>, <cd>not at all; certainly not; not in any degree.</cd><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wine on this side of the lake is <qex>by no means</qex> so good as that on the other.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meander</ent><br/
<hw>Me*an"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>Maeander</ets>, orig., a river in Phrygia, proverbial for its many windings, Gr. <?/: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/andre</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A winding, crooked, or involved course; <as>as, the <ex>meanders</ex> of the veins and arteries</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Sir M. Hale.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>While lingering rivers in <qex>meanders</qex> glide.</q> <rj><qau>Sir R. Blackmore.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A tortuous or intricate movement.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>Fretwork. See <er>Fret</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meander</ent><br/
<hw>Me*an"der</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To wind, turn, or twist; to make flexuous.</def>
 <rj><qau>Dryton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meander</ent><br/
<hw>Me*an"der</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Meandered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Meandering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To wind or turn in a course or passage; to be intricate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Five miles <qex>meandering</qex> with a mazy motion<br/
Through wood and dale the sacred river ran.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meandrian</ent><br/
<hw>Me*an"dri*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>Maeandrius</ets>: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/andrien</ets>.]</ety> <def>Winding; having many turns.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meandrina</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me`an*dri"na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL.: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/andrine</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of corals with meandering grooves and ridges, including the brain corals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meandry</ent><br/
<ent>Meandrous</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Me*an"drous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Me*an"dry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Winding; flexuous.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meaning</ent><br/
<hw>Mean"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is meant or intended; intent; purpose; aim; object; <as>as, a mischievous <ex>meaning</ex> was apparent</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If there be any good <qex>meaning</qex> towards you.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is signified, whether by act lanquage; signification; sense; import; <as>as, the <ex>meaning</ex> of a hint</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Sense; power of thinking.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Mean"ing*less</wf>, <pos>a.</pos> -- <wf>Mean"ing*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>meaningful</ent><br/
<hw>meaningful</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Having a meaning or purpose; having significance; <as>as, a <ex>meaningful</ex> explanation; a <ex>meaningful</ex> discussion; a <ex>meaningful</ex> pause; to live a <ex>meaningful</ex> life</as>.  Opposite of <ant>meaningless</ant>.</def>  [Narrower terms: <stype>comprehensible, understandable</stype>; <stype>indicative, significative, suggestive </stype>; <stype>meaty, substantive </stype>; <stype>purposeful</stype>] <see>Also See: <er>purposeful</er>, <er>significant</er>, <er>important</er>.</see><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>meaningfulness</ent><br/
<hw>meaningfulness</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the quality of having great meaning or value.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>meaningless</ent><br/
<hw>meaningless</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>having no meaning; of no value; <as>as, a <ex>meaningless</ex> endeavor; a <ex>meaningless</ex> life; a <ex>meaningless</ex> explanation</as>.  Opposite of <ant>meaningful</ant>.</def> [Narrower terms: <stype>insignificant </stype>; <stype>mindless, unmeaning </stype>; <stype>nonsense(prenominal), nonsensical </stype>; <stype>pointless, purposeless </stype>] <see>Also See: <er>insignificant</er>, <er>unimportant</er>, <er>purposeless</er>, <er>unimportant</er>.</see><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meanly</ent><br/
<hw>Mean"ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[<er>Mean</er> middle.]</ety> <def>Moderately.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A man <qex>meanly</qex> learned himself, but not <qex>meanly</qex> affectioned to set forward learning in others.</q> <rj><qau>Ascham.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meanly</ent><br/
<hw>Mean"ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mean</er> low.]</ety> <def>In a mean manner; unworthily; basely; poorly; ungenerously.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>While the heaven-born child<br/
All <qex>meanly</qex> wrapt in the rude manger lies.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Would you <qex>meanly</qex> thus rely<br/
On power you know I must obey ?</q> <rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We can not bear to have others think <qex>meanly</qex> of them [our kindred].</q> <rj><qau>I. Watts.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meanness</ent><br/
<hw>Mean"ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The condition, or quality, of being mean; want of excellence; poorness; lowness; baseness; sordidness; stinginess.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This figure is of a later date, by the <qex>meanness</qex> of the workmanship.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A mean act; <as>as, to be guilty of <ex>meanness</ex></as>.</def>  <rj><au>Goldsmith.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mean-spirited</ent><br/
<ent>meanspirited</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mean"spir`it*ed</hw>, <hw>mean"-spir`it*ed</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of a mean spirit; petty; small-minded; base; groveling; -- of people.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mean"-spir`it*ed*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Done for malevolent reasons; -- of deeds and actions.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> base, contemptible, currish, mean, meanspirited, scurvy.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meant</ent><br/
<hw>Meant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <def><pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> of <er>Mean</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meanwhile</ent><br/
<ent>Meantime</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mean"time`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mean"while`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The intervening time; <as>as, in the <ex>meantime</ex> (or <ex>mean time</ex>)</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meanwhile</ent><br/
<ent>Meantime</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mean"time`</hw>, <hw>Mean"while`</hw>, }</mhw> <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In the intervening time; during the interval.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mear</ent><br/
<hw>Mear</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A boundary. See <er>Mere</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mease</ent><br/
<hw>Mease</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. G. <ets>mass</ets> measure.]</ety> <def>Five hundred; <as>as, a <ex>mease</ex> of herrings</as>.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Measelry</ent><br/
<hw>Mea"sel*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>meselrie</ets>, OF. <ets>mesellerie</ets>. See 1st <er>Measle</er>.]</ety> <def>Leprosy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>R. of Brunne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Measle</ent><br/
<hw>Mea"sle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mesel</ets>, OF. <ets>mesel</ets>, LL. <ets>misellus</ets>, L. <ets>misellus</ets> unfortunate, dim. of <ets>miser</ets>. See <er>Miser</er>.]</ety> <def>A leper.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <altsp>[Written also <asp>meazel</asp>, and <asp>mesel</asp>.]</altsp>  <rj><au>Wyclif (Matt. x. 8. ).</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Measle</ent><br/
<hw>Mea"sle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A tapeworm larva. See 2d <er>Measles</er>, 4.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Measled</ent><br/
<hw>Mea"sled</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See 2d <er>Measles</er>.]</ety> <def>Infected or spotted with measles, as pork.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mea"sled*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Measles</ent><br/
<hw>Mea"sles</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From 1st <er>Measle</er>.]</ety> <def>Leprosy; also, a leper.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Measles</ent><br/
<hw>Mea"sles</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> in form, but used as <xex>singular</xex> in senses 1, 2, & 3.</plu> <ety>[D. <ets>mazelen</ets>; akin to G. <ets>masern</ets>, pl., and E. <ets>mazer</ets>, and orig. meaning, little spots. See <er>Mazer</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A contagious viral febrile disorder commencing with catarrhal symptoms, and marked by the appearance on the third day of an eruption of distinct red circular spots, which coalesce in a crescentic form, are slightly raised above the surface, and after the fourth day of the eruption gradually decline; rubeola.  It is a common childhood disease.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Measles</qex> commences with the ordinary symptoms of fever.</q> <rj><qau>Am. Cyc.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 906 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Veter. Med.)</fld> <def>A disease of cattle and swine in which the flesh is filled with the embryos of different varieties of the tapeworm.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A disease of trees.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The larvae of any tapeworm (<gen>Taenia</gen>) in the cysticerus stage, when contained in meat.  Called also <altname>bladder worms</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>German measles</b></col> <cd>A mild contagious viral disease, which may cause birth defects if contracted by a pregnant woman during early pregnancy; also called <altname>rubella</altname>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>measly</ent><br/
<hw>mea"sly</hw> <pr>(m<emac/"zly)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Infected with measles.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Containing larval tapeworms; -- said of pork and beef.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Contemptibly small in quantity; meager; absurdly insufficient or bad; <as>as, a <ex>measly</ex> few dollars for all that work</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>measurability</ent><br/
<hw>measurability</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the quality of being measurable.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> quantifiability.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Measurable</ent><br/
<hw>Meas"ur*a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mesurable</ets>, L. <ets>mensurabilis</ets>. See <er>Measure</er>, and cf. <er>Mensurable</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Capable of being measured; susceptible of mensuration or computation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Moderate; temperate; not excessive.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of his diet <qex>measurable</qex> was he.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Meas"ur*a*ble*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos> -- <wf>Meas"ur*a*bly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yet do it <qex>measurably</qex>, as it becometh Christians.</q> <rj><qau>Latimer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>measure</ent><br/
<hw>meas"ure</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/zh"<usl/r; 135)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mesure</ets>, F. <ets>mesure</ets>, L. <ets>mensura</ets>, fr. <ets>metiri</ets>, <ets>mensus</ets>, to measure; akin to <ets>metrum</ets> poetical measure, Gr. <grk>me`tron</grk>, E. <ets>meter</ets>.  Cf. <er>Immense</er>, <er>Mensuration</er>, <er>Mete</er> to measure.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A standard of dimension; a fixed unit of quantity or extent; an extent or quantity in the fractions or multiples of which anything is estimated and stated; hence, a rule by which anything is adjusted or judged.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An instrument by means of which size or quantity is measured, as a graduated line, rod, vessel, or the like.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>False ells and <qex>measures</qex> be brought all clean adown.</q> <rj><qau>R. of Gloucester.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The dimensions or capacity of anything, reckoned according to some standard; size or extent, determined and stated; estimated extent; <as>as, to take one's <ex>measure</ex> for a coat</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>measure</qex> thereof is longer than the earth, and broader than the sea.</q> <rj><qau>Job xi. 9.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The contents of a vessel by which quantity is measured; a quantity determined by a standard; a stated or limited quantity or amount.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is like leaven which a woman took and hid in three <qex>measures</qex> of meal.</q> <rj><qau>Luke xiii. 21.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Extent or degree not excessive or beyong bounds; moderation; due restraint; esp. in the phrases, <xex>in measure</xex>; <xex>with measure</xex>; <xex>without</xex> or <xex>beyond measure</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hell hath enlarged herself, and opened her mouth without <qex>measure</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Is. v. 14.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Determined extent, not to be exceeded; limit; allotted share, as of action, influence, ability, or the like; due proportion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lord, make me to know mine end, and the <qex>measure</qex> of my days.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. xxxix. 4.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>The quantity determined by measuring, especially in buying and selling; <as>as, to give good or full <ex>measure</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Undefined quantity; extent; degree.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is a great <qex>measure</qex> of discretion to be used in the performance of confession.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Regulated division of movement</def>: <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Dancing)</fld> <def>A regulated movement corresponding to the time in which the accompanying music is performed; but, especially, a slow and stately dance, like the minuet.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> (1) <def>The group or grouping of beats, caused by the regular recurrence of accented beats.</def> (2) <def>The space between two bars.</def> See <er>Beat</er>, <er>Triple</er>, <er>Quadruple</er>, <er>Sextuple</er>, <cref>Compound time</cref>, under <er>Compound</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and <er>Figure</er>. <sd>(c)</sd> <fld>(Poetry)</fld> <def>The manner of ordering and combining the quantities, or long and short syllables; meter; rhythm; hence, a foot; <as>as, a poem in iambic <ex>measure</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Arith.)</fld> <def>A number which is contained in a given number a number of times without a remainder; as in the phrases, the <xex>common measure</xex>, the <xex>greatest common measure</xex>, etc., of two or more numbers; a denominator.  See <cref>common denominator</cref> under <er>denominator</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>A step or definite part of a progressive course or policy; a means to an end; an act designed for the accomplishment of an object; <as>as, political <ex>measures</ex>; prudent <ex>measures</ex>; an inefficient <ex>measure</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His majesty found what wrong <qex>measures</qex> he had taken in the conferring that trust, and lamented his error.</q> <rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>The act of measuring; measurement.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>Beds or strata; <as>as, coal <ex>measures</ex>; lead <ex>measures</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>linear measure</b></col>, <col><b>lineal measure</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>long measure</b></col></mcol>, <cd>measure of length; the measure of lines or distances.</cd> -- <col><b>Liquid measure</b></col>, <cd>the measure of liquids.</cd> -- <col><b>Square measure</b></col>, <cd>the measure of superficial area of surfaces in square units, as inches, feet, miles, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>To have hard measure</b></col>, <cd>to have harsh treatment meted out to one; to be harshly or oppressively dealt with.</cd> -- <col><b>To take measures</b></col>, <cd>to make preparations; to provide means.</cd> -- <col><b>To take one's measure</b></col>, <cd>to measure one, as for a garment; hence, to form an opinion of one's disposition, character, ability, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>To tread a measure</b></col>, <cd>to dance in the style so called. See 9 <sd>(a)</sd>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Say to her, we have measured many miles<br/
<qex>To tread a measure</qex> with her on this grass.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Measure</ent><br/
<hw>Meas"ure</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Measured</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Measuring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>mesurer</ets>, L. <ets>mensurare</ets>. See <er>Measure</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To ascertain by use of a measuring instrument; to compute or ascertain the extent, quantity, dimensions, or capacity of, by a certain rule or standard; to take the dimensions of; hence, to estimate; to judge of; to value; to appraise.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Great are thy works, Jehovah, infinite<br/
Thy power! what thought can <qex>measure</qex> thee?</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To serve as the measure of; <as>as, the thermometer <ex>measures</ex> changes of temperature</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To pass throught or over in journeying, as if laying off and determining the distance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A true devoted pilgrim is not weary<br/
To <qex>measure</qex> kingdoms with his feeble steps.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To adjust by a rule or standard.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To secure a contented spirit, <qex>measure</qex> your desires by your fortunes, not your fortunes by your desires.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To allot or distribute by measure; to set off or apart by measure; -- often with <xex>out</xex> or <xex>off</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With what measure ye mete, it shall be <qex>measured</qex> to you again.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. vii. 2.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That portion of eternity which is called time, <qex>measured</qex> out by the sun.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To measure swords with one</b></col>, <cd>to try another's skill in the use of the sword; hence, figuratively, to match one's abilities against an antagonist's.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Measure</ent><br/
<hw>Meas"ure</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make a measurement or measurements.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To result, or turn out, on measuring; <as>as, the grain <ex>measures</ex> well; the pieces <ex>measure</ex> unequally.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be of a certain size or quantity, or to have a certain length, breadth, or thickness, or a certain capacity according to a standard measure; <as>as, cloth <ex>measures</ex> three fourths of a yard; a tree <ex>measures</ex> three feet in diameter.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Measured</ent><br/
<hw>Meas"ured</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Regulated or determined by a standard; hence, equal; uniform; graduated; limited; moderated; <as>as, he walked with <ex>measured</ex> steps; he expressed himself in no <ex>measured</ex> terms.</as></def> -- <wordforms><wf>Meas"ured*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Measureless</ent><br/
<hw>Meas"ure*less</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Without measure; unlimited; immeasurable.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Meas"ure*less*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where Alf, the sacred river ran,<br/
Through canyons <qex>measureless</qex> to man,<br/
Down to a hidden sea.</q>  <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Boundless; limitless; endless; unbounded; unlimited; vast; immense; infinite; immeasurable.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Measurement</ent><br/
<hw>Meas"ure*ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or result of measuring; mensuration; <as>as, <ex>measurement</ex> is required</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The extent, size, capacity, amount. or quantity ascertained by measuring; <as>as, its <ex>measurement</ex> is five acres</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Measurer</ent><br/
<hw>Meas"ur*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who measures; one whose occupation or duty is to measure commondities in market.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Measuring</ent><br/
<hw>Meas"ur*ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Used in, or adapted for, ascertaining measurements, or dividing by measure.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Measuring faucet</b></col>, <cd>a faucet which permits only a given quantity of liquid to pass each time it is opened, or one by means of which the liquid which passes can be measured.</cd> -- <col><b>Measuring worm</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the larva of any geometrid moth.  They are so called because they move by a process in which they first pull the rear legs forward toward their front legs, forming a loop which resembles the process of measuring with a tape measure.  The motion is completed by subsequently moving the front legs forward to an advanced position. See <er>Geometrid</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meat</ent><br/
<hw>Meat</hw> <pr>(m<emac/t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mete</ets>, AS. <ets>mete</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>mat</ets>, <ets>meti</ets>, D. <ets>met</ets> hashed meat, G. <ets>mett</ets>wurst sausage, OHG. <ets>maz</ets> food, Icel. <ets>matr</ets>, Sw. <ets>mat</ets>, Dan. <ets>mad</ets>, Goth. <ets>mats</ets>.  Cf. <er>Mast</er> fruit, <er>Mush</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Food, in general; anything eaten for nourishment, either by man or beast.  Hence, the edible part of anything; <as>as, the <ex>meat</ex> of a lobster, a nut, or an egg</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And God said, Behold, I have given you every herb bearing seed, . . . to you it shall be for <qex>meat</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. i. 29.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every moving thing that liveth shall be <qex>meat</qex> for you.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. ix. 3.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The flesh of animals used as food; esp., animal muscle; <as>as, a breakfast of bread and fruit without <ex>meat</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <def>Dinner; the chief meal.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Meat biscuit</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Biscuit</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Meat earth</b></col> <fld>(Mining)</fld>, <cd>vegetable mold.</cd> <au>Raymond.</au> -- <col><b>Meat fly</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See <cref>Flesh fly</cref>, under <er>Flesh</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Meat offering</b></col> <fld>(Script.)</fld>, <cd>an offering of food, esp. of a cake made of flour with salt and oil.</cd> -- <col><b>To go to meat</b></col>, <cd>to go to a meal.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> -- <col><b>To sit at meat</b></col>, <cd>to sit at the table in taking food.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meat</ent><br/
<hw>Meat</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To supply with food.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Tusser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His shield well lined, his horses <qex>meated</qex> well.</q> <rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meatal</ent><br/
<hw>Me*a"tal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to a meatus; resembling a meatus.</def>  <rj><au>Owen.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meated</ent><br/
<hw>Meat"ed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Fed; fattened.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Tusser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Having (such) meat; -- used chiefly in composition; <as>as, thick-<ex>meated</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meathe</ent><br/
<ent>Meath</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Meath</hw>, <hw>Meathe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mead</er>.]</ety> <def>A sweet liquor; mead.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer. Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meatiness</ent><br/
<hw>Meat"i*ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Quality of being meaty.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meatless</ent><br/
<hw>Meat"less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having no meat; without food.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><ldquo/Leave these beggars <qex>meatless</qex>.<rdquo/</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. More.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meatoscope</ent><br/
<hw>Me*at"o*scope</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meatus</ets> + <ets>-scope</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A speculum for examining a natural passage, as the urethra.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meatotome</ent><br/
<hw>Me*at"o*tome</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meatus</ets> + Gr. <?/ to cut.]</ety> <fld>(Surg.)</fld> <def>An instrument for cutting into the urethra so as to enlarge its orifice.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meatus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*a"tus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. sing. & pl.</pos>; <plu>E. <it>pl.</it> <plw>Meatuses</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., a going, passage, fr. <ets>meare</ets> to go.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A natural passage or canal; <as>as, the external auditory <ex>meatus</ex></as>. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Ear</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meaty</ent><br/
<hw>Meat"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Abounding in meat.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meaw</ent><br/
<hw>Meaw</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The sea mew.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meaw</ent><br/
<hw>Meaw</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>See <er>Mew</er>, to cry as a cat.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meawl</ent><br/
<hw>Meawl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>See <er>Mewl</er>, and <er>Miaul</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meazel</ent><br/
<hw>Mea"zel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See 1st <er>Measle</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meazling</ent><br/
<hw>Meaz"ling</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Falling in small drops; mistling; mizzing.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Arbuthnot.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mebles</ent><br/
<hw>Me"bles</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <def>See <er>Moebles</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mecate</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*ca"te</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp.]</ety> <def>A rope of hair or of maguey fiber, for tying horses, etc.</def> <mark>[Southwestern U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meccawee</ent><br/
<hw>Mec`ca*wee"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to Mecca, in Arabia.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A native or inhabitant of Mecca.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mechanic</ent><br/
<hw>Me*chan"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/canique</ets> mechanics. See <er>Mechanic</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The art of the application of the laws of motion or force to construction.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A mechanician; an artisan; an artificer; one who practices any mechanic art; one skilled or employed in shaping and uniting materials, as wood, metal, etc., into any kind of structure, machine, or other object, requiring the use of tools, or instruments.  Also, a technician who maintains or repairs machinery; <as>as, an auto <ex>mechanic</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>An art quite lost with our <qex>mechanics</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. Browne.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mechanic</ent><br/
<hw>Me*chan"ic</hw> <pr>(m<esl/*k<acr/n"<icr/k)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/canique</ets>, L. <ets>mechanicus</ets>, Gr. <grk>mhchaniko`s</grk>, fr. <grk>mhchanh`</grk> a machine. See <er>Machine</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having to do with the application of the laws of motion in the art of constructing or making things; of or pertaining to mechanics; mechanical; <as>as, the <ex>mechanic</ex> arts</as>.</def> <ldquo/These <xex>mechanic</xex> philosophers.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Ray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mechanic</qex> slaves,<br/
With greasy aprons, rules, and hammers.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a mechanic or artificer, or to the class of artisans; hence, rude; common; vulgar.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To make a god, a hero, or a king<br/
Descend to a <qex>mechanic</qex> dialect.</q> <rj><qau>Roscommon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sometimes he ply'd the strong, <qex>mechanic</qex> tool.</q> <rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Base.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Whitlock.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mechanical</ent><br/
<hw>Me*chan"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mechanic</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Pertaining to, governed by, or in accordance with, mechanics, or the laws of motion; pertaining to the quantitative relations of force and matter on a macroscopic scale, as distinguished from <contr>mental</contr>, <contr>vital</contr>, <contr>chemical</contr>, <contr>electrical</contr>, <contr>electronic</contr>, <contr>atomic</contr> etc.; <as>as, <ex>mechanical</ex> principles; a <ex>mechanical</ex> theory</as>;</def> <specif>especially,</specif> <def>using only the interactions of solid parts against each other; <as>as <ex>mechanical</ex> brakes, in contrast to <contr>hydraulic</contr> brakes.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a machine or to machinery or tools; made or formed by a machine or with tools; <as>as, <ex>mechanical</ex> precision; <ex>mechanical</ex> products.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We have also divers <qex>mechanical</qex> arts.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Done as if by a machine; uninfluenced by will or emotion; proceeding automatically, or by habit, without special intention or reflection; <as>as, <ex>mechanical</ex> singing; <ex>mechanical</ex> verses; <ex>mechanical</ex> service.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Made and operated by interaction of forces without a directing intelligence; <as>as, a <ex>mechanical</ex> universe</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Obtained by trial, by measurements, etc.; approximate; empirical. See the 2d Note under <er>Geometric</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mechanical effect</b></col>, <cd>effective power; useful work exerted, as by a machine, in a definite time.</cd> -- <col><b>Mechanical engineering</b></col>. <cd>See the Note under <er>Engineering</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mechanical maneuvers</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>the application of mechanical appliances to the mounting, dismounting, and moving of artillery.</cd> <au>Farrow.</au> -- <col><b>Mechanical philosophy</b></col>, <cd>the principles of mechanics applied to the investigation of physical phenomena.</cd> -- <col><b>Mechanical powers</b></col>, <cd>certain simple instruments, such as the lever and its modifications (the wheel and axle and the pulley), the inclined plane with its modifications (the screw and the wedge), which convert a small force acting through a great space into a great force acting through a small space, or <it>vice versa</it>, and are used separately or in combination.</cd> -- <col><b>Mechanical solution</b></col> <fld>(Math.)</fld>, <cd>a solution of a problem by any art or contrivance not strictly geometrical, as by means of the ruler and compasses, or other instruments.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mechanical</ent><br/
<hw>Me*chan"ic*al</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mechanic.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mechanicalize</ent><br/
<hw>Me*chan"ic*al*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cause to become mechanical.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mechanically</ent><br/
<hw>Me*chan"ic*al*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a mechanical manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mechanicalness</ent><br/
<hw>Me*chan"ic*al*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state or quality of being mechanical.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mechanician</ent><br/
<hw>Mech`a*ni"cian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/canicien</ets>. See <er>Mechanic</er>.]</ety> <def>One skilled in the theory or construction of machines; a machinist.</def>  <rj><au>Boyle.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mechanico-chemical</ent><br/
<hw>Me*chan`i*co-chem"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to, connected with, or dependent upon, both mechanics and chemistry; -- said especially of those sciences which treat of such phenomena as seem to depend on the laws both of mechanics and chemistry, as electricity and magnetism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mechanics</ent><br/
<hw>Me*chan"ics</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/canique</ets>.]</ety> <def>That science, or branch of applied mathematics, which treats of the action of forces on bodies.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ That part of <xex>mechanics</xex> which considers the action of forces in producing rest or equilibrium is called <stype>statics</stype>; that which relates to such action in producing motion is called <stype>dynamics</stype>. The term <xex>mechanics</xex> includes the action of forces on all bodies, whether solid, liquid, or gaseous. It is sometimes, however, and formerly was often, used distinctively of <xex>solid</xex> bodies only: The mechanics of <xex>liquid</xex> bodies is called also <stype>hydrostatics</stype>, or <stype>hydrodynamics</stype>, according as the laws of rest or of motion are considered. The mechanics of <xex>gaseous bodies</xex> is called also <stype>pneumatics</stype>. The mechanics of fluids in motion, with special reference to the methods of obtaining from them useful results, constitutes <stype>hydraulics</stype>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Animal mechanics</b></col> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld>, <cd>that portion of physiology which has for its object the investigation of the laws of equilibrium and motion in the animal body. The most important mechanical principle is that of the lever, the bones forming the arms of the levers, the contractile muscles the power, the joints the fulcra or points of support, while the weight of the body or of the individual limbs constitutes the weight or resistance.</cd> -- <col><b>Applied mechanics</b></col>, <cd>the principles of abstract mechanics applied to human art; also, the practical application of the laws of matter and motion to the construction of machines and structures of all kinds.</cd> -- <col><b>orbital mechanics</b></col>, <cd>the principles governing the motion of bodies in orbit around other bodies under gravitational influence, such as artificial Earth satellites.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mechanisation</ent><br/
<hw>mechanisation</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mechanization.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> automation, mechanization, high technology, high-tech.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mechanism</ent><br/
<hw>Mech"an*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/canisme</ets>, L. <ets>mechanisma</ets>. See <er>Mechanic</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The arrangement or relation of the parts of a machine; the parts of a machine, taken collectively; the arrangement or relation of the parts of anything as adapted to produce an effect; <as>as, the <ex>mechanism</ex> of a watch; the <ex>mechanism</ex> of a sewing machine; the <ex>mechanism</ex> of a seed pod.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The series of causal relations that operate to produce an effect in any system; <as>as, the <ex>mechanism</ex> of a chemical reaction</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Mechanical operation or action.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He acknowledges nothing besides matter and motion; so that all must be performed either by <qex>mechanism</qex> or accident.</q> <rj><qau>Bentley.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Kinematics)</fld> <def>An ideal machine; a combination of movable bodies constituting a machine, but considered only with regard to relative movements.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mechanism of action</ent><br/
<hw>mech"an*ism of ac"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Medicine, Biochemistry)</fld> <def>The mechanism{2} by which a pharmacologically active substance produces an effect on a living organism or in a biochemical system; <as>as, the <ex>mechanism of action</ex> of actinomycin involves its binding to DNA</as>.  The mechanism of action is usually considered to include an identification of the specific molecular targets to which a pharmacologically active substance binds or whose biochemical action it influences; a general recognition of the broad biochemical pathways (such as DNA synthesis, protein synthesis, cholesterol synthesis) which are inhibited or affected by a substance is termed its <contr>mode of action</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mechanist</ent><br/
<hw>Mech"an*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A maker of machines; one skilled in mechanics.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who regards the phenomena of nature as the effects of forces merely mechanical.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mechanization</ent><br/
<hw>mechanization</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or process of mechanizing.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Causing to be performed by machines, especially by a highly technical implementation, usually involving electronic hardware; <as>as, the <ex>mechanization</ex> of a manufacturing process</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> automation, mechanisation, high technology, high-tech.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mechanize</ent><br/
<hw>Mech"an*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mechanized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mechanizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/chaniser</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to be mechanical.</def>  <rj><au>Shelley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To introduce machinery into (a process) in order to reduce human effort or improve uniformity or quality of the result;</def> <specif>especially,</specif> <def>To cause to be accomplished by a mechanical means which requires little or no human supervision; to automate.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>To equip (an armed force) with tanks or other vehicles.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mechanograph</ent><br/
<hw>Mech"an*o*graph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mhchanh`</grk> machine + <ets>-graph</ets>.]</ety> <def>One of a number of copies of anything multiplied mechanically.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 907 --></p>

<p><ent>Mechanographic</ent><br/
<hw>Mech`an*o*graph`ic</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/k`<ait/n*<osl/*gr<acr/f"<icr/k)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Treating of mechanics.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Written, copied, or recorded by machinery; produced by mechanography; <as>as, a <ex>mechanographic</ex> record of changes of temperature; <ex>mechanographic</ex> prints.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mechanographist</ent><br/
<hw>Mech`an*og"ra*phist</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/k`<ait/n*<ocr/g"r<adot/*f<icr/st)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An artist who, by mechanical means, multiplies copies of works of art.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mechanography</ent><br/
<hw>Mech`an*og"ra*phy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The art of mechanically multiplying copies of a writing, or any work of art.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mechanurgy</ent><br/
<hw>Mech"an*ur`gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mhchanh`</grk> machine + the root of <?/ work.]</ety> <def>That branch of science which treats of moving machines.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mechitarist</ent><br/
<hw>Mech"i*tar*ist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <ets>Mechitar</ets>, an Armenian., who founded the congregation in the early part of the eighteenth century.]</ety> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>One of a religious congregation of the <org>Roman Catholic Church</org> devoted to the improvement of Armenians.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mechlin</ent><br/
<hw>Mech"lin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A kind of lace made at, or originating in, <etsep>Mechlin</etsep>, in Belgium.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mechoacan</ent><br/
<hw>Me*cho"a*can</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A species of jalap, of very feeble properties, said to be obtained from the root of a species of <gen>Convolvulus</gen> (<spn>Convolvulus Mechoacan</spn>); -- so called from <etsep>Michoacan</etsep>, in Mexico, whence it is obtained.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meckelian</ent><br/
<hw>Meck*e"li*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or discovered by, J. F. <xex>Meckel</xex>, a German anatomist.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Meckelian cartilage</b></col>, <cd>the cartilaginous rod which forms the axis of the mandible; -- called also <altname>Meckel's cartilage</altname>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meconate</ent><br/
<hw>Mec"o*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/conate</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of meconic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meconic</ent><br/
<hw>Me*con"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ belonging to the poppy, fr. <?/ the poppy: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/conique</ets>.]</ety> <def>Pertaining to, or obtained from, the poppy or opium; specif. <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, designating an acid related to aconitic acid, found in opium and extracted as a white crystalline substance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meconidine</ent><br/
<hw>Me*con"i*dine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem)</fld> <def>An alkaloid found in opium, and extracted as a yellow amorphous substance which is easily decomposed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meconidium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mec`o*nid"i*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., dim. of Gr. <?/ a poppy. So called in allusion to the shape of the seed capsules of the poppy.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A kind of gonophore produced by hydroids of the genus <gen>Gonothyraea</gen>.  It has tentacles, and otherwise resembles a free medusa, but remains attached by a pedicel.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meconin</ent><br/
<hw>Mec"o*nin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/conine</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A substance regarded as an anhydride of meconinic acid, existing in opium and extracted as a white crystalline substance.  Also erroneously called <altname>meconina</altname>, <altname>meconia</altname>, etc., as though it were an alkaloid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meconinic</ent><br/
<hw>Mec`o*nin"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or designating, an acid which occurs in opium, and which may be obtained by oxidizing narcotine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meconium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*co"ni*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ poppy.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Opium.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The contents of the fetal intestine; hence, first excrement.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medal</ent><br/
<hw>Med"al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/daille</ets>, It. <ets>medaglia</ets>, fr. L. <ets>metallum</ets> metal, through (assumed) LL. <ets>metalleus</ets> made of metal. See <er>Metal</er>, and cf. <er>Mail</er> a piece of money.]</ety> <def>A piece of metal in the form of a coin, struck with a device, and intended to preserve the remembrance of a notable event or an illustrious person, or to serve as a reward.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medal</ent><br/
<hw>Med"al</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Medaled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>, or <conjf>Medalled</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Medaling</conjf> or <conjf>Medalling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To honor or reward with a medal.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Medaled</xex> by the king.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medalet</ent><br/
<hw>Med"al*et</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A small medal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medalist</ent><br/
<hw>Med"al*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/dailliste</ets>, It. <ets>medaglista</ets>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also <asp>medallist</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A person that is skilled or curious in medals; a collector of medals.</def>  <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A designer of medals.</def>  <rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One who has gained a medal as the reward of merit; <as>as, the gold <ex>medalist</ex> in downhill skiing</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medallic</ent><br/
<hw>Me*dal"lic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to a medal, or to medals.</def> <ldquo/Our <xex>medallic</xex> history.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Walpole.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medallion</ent><br/
<hw>Me*dal"lion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/daillion</ets>, It. <ets>medaglione</ets>, augm. of <ets>medaglia</ets>. See <er>Medal</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A large medal or memorial coin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A circular or oval (or, sometimes, square) tablet bearing a figure or figures represented in relief.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medal play</ent><br/
<hw>Med"al play`</hw>. <fld>(Golf)</fld> <def>Play in which the score is reckoned by counting the number of strokes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medalurgy</ent><br/
<hw>Med"al*ur`gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Medal</ets> + the root of Gr. <?/ work.]</ety> <def>The art of making and striking medals and coins.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>medallurgy</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meddle</ent><br/
<hw>Med"dle`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Meddled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Meddling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>medlen</ets> to mix, OF. <ets>medler</ets>, <ets>mesler</ets>, F. <ets>m<ecir/ler</ets>, LL. <ets>misculare</ets>, a dim. fr. L. <ets>miscere</ets> to mix.  <root/271.  See <er>Mix</er>, and cf. <er>Medley</er>, <er>Mellay</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To mix; to mingle.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>More to know<br/
Did never <qex>meddle</qex> with my thoughts.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To interest or engage one's self; to have to do; -- in a good sense.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Barrow.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Study to be quiet, and to <qex>meddle</qex> with your own business.</q> <rj><qau>Tyndale.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To interest or engage one's self unnecessarily or impertinently, to interfere or busy one's self improperly with another's affairs; specifically, to handle or distrub another's property without permission; -- often followed by <ptcl>with</ptcl> or <ptcl>in</ptcl>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Why shouldst thou <qex>meddle</qex> to thy hurt?</q> <rj><qau>2 Kings xiv. 10.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The civil lawyers . . . have <qex>meddled</qex> in a matter that belongs not to them.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To meddle and make</b></col>, <cd>to intrude one's self into another person's concerns.</cd> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To interpose; interfere; intermeddle.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meddle</ent><br/
<hw>Med"dle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To mix; to mingle.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><ldquo/Wine <qex>meddled</qex> with gall.<rdquo/</q> <rj><qau>Wyclif (Matt. xxvii. 34).</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meddler</ent><br/
<hw>Med"dler</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who meddles; one who interferes or busies himself with things in which he has no concern; an officious person; a busybody.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meddlesome</ent><br/
<hw>Med"dle*some</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Given to meddling; apt to interpose in the affairs of others; officiously intrusive.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Med"dle*some*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meddling</ent><br/
<hw>Med"dling</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Meddlesome.</def>  <rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meddlingly</ent><br/
<hw>Med"dling*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a meddling manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mede</ent><br/
<hw>Mede</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A native or inhabitant of Media in Asia.</def>  <ldquo/according to the law of the <xex>Medes</xex> and Persians, which altereth not<rdquo/ <au>Daniel 6: 8.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mede</ent><br/
<hw>Mede</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See 1st & 2d <er>Mead</er>, and <er>Meed</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>medfly</ent><br/
<hw>med"fly</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/d"fl<imac/)</pr>, <altsp>[Often cap.]</altsp> <def>Same as <er>Mediterranean fruit fly</er>; -- a shortened form.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>media</ent><br/
<hw>me"di*a</hw> <pr>(m<emac/"d<icr/*<adot/)</pr>, <pos>n. sing. & pl.</pos>, <sn>1.</sn> <def>The latinic plural form of <er>medium</er>, sometimes used as a singular noun with the same meaning as <sig>medium</sig>; <as>as, <fld>(Computers)</fld> place your installation <ex>media</ex> into the device which will read it; <fld>(Microbiology)</fld> the tuberculosis bacterium will only grow in a special <ex>media</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The public institutions that report the news, such as newspapers, magazines, radio, and television, collectively; the news media; <as>as, the <ex>media</ex> were obsessed with Monica Lewinsky for months</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Media</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me"di*a</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mediae</plw> <pr>(-<emac/)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL., fr. L. <ets>medius</ets> middle.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Phonetics)</fld> <def>One of the sonant mutes <beta/, <delta/, <gamma/ (<it>b</it>, <it>d</it>, <it>g</it>), in Greek, or of their equivalents in other languages, so named as intermediate between the <xex>tenues</xex>, <pi/, <tau/, <kappa/ (<it>p</it>, <it>t</it>, <it>k</it>), and the <it>aspiratae</it>  (aspirates) <phi/, <theta/, <chi/ (<it>ph</it> or <it>f</it>, <it>th</it>, <it>ch</it>). Also called <altname>middle mute</altname>, or <altname>medial</altname>, and sometimes <altname>soft mute</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediacy</ent><br/
<hw>Me"di*a*cy</hw> <pr>(m<emac/"d<icr/*<adot/*s<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state or quality of being mediate.</def>  <rj><au>Sir W. Hamilton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediaeval</ent><br/
<hw>Me`di*ae"val</hw> <pr>(m<emac/`d<icr/*<emac/"v<ait/l; 277)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>medius</ets> middle + <ets>aevum</ets> age. See <er>Middle</er>, and <er>Age</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or relating to the Middle Ages; <as>as, <ex>mediaeval</ex> architecture</as>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>medieval</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediaevalism</ent><br/
<hw>Me`di*ae"val*ism</hw> <pr>(m<emac/`d<icr/*<emac/"v<ait/l*<icr/z'm)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The method or spirit of the Middle Ages; devotion to the institutions and practices of the Middle Ages; a survival from the Middle Ages.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>medievalism</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediaevalist</ent><br/
<hw>Me`di*ae"val*ist</hw> <pr>(m<emac/`d<icr/*<emac/"v<ait/l*<icr/st)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who has a taste for, or is versed in, the history of the Middle Ages; one in sympathy with the spirit or forms of the Middle Ages.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>medievalist</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediaevally</ent><br/
<hw>Me`di*ae"val*ly</hw> <pr>(m<emac/`d<icr/*<emac/"v<ait/l*l<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In the manner of the Middle Ages; in accordance with mediaevalism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediaevals</ent><br/
<hw>Me`di*ae"vals</hw> <pr>(m<emac/`d<icr/*<emac/"v<ait/lz)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <def>The people who lived in the Middle Ages.</def>  <rj><au>Ruskin.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medial</ent><br/
<hw>Me"di*al</hw> <pr>(m<emac/"d<icr/*<ait/l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>medialis</ets>, fr. <ets>medius</ets> middle: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/dial</ets>. See <er>Middle</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to a mean or average; mean; <as>as, <ex>medial</ex> alligation</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medial</ent><br/
<hw>Me"di*al</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Phonetics)</fld> <def>See 2d <er>Media</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medialuna</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me"di*a*lu"na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>media luna</ets> half-moon.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Half-moon</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Median</ent><br/
<hw>Me"di*an</hw> <pr>(m<emac/"d<icr/*<ait/n)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>medianus</ets>, fr. <ets>medius</ets> middle. See <er>Medial</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Being in the middle; running through the middle; <as>as, a <ex>median</ex> groove</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Situated in the middle; lying in a plane dividing a bilateral animal into right and left halves; -- said of unpaired organs and parts; <as>as, <ex>median</ex> coverts</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Median line</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <cd>Any line in the mesial plane; specif., either of the lines in which the mesial plane meets the surface of the body.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <cd>The line drawn from an angle of a triangle to the middle of the opposite side; any line having the nature of a diameter.</cd> -- <col><b>Median plane</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>the mesial plane.</cd> -- <col><b>Median point</b></col> <fld>(Geom.)</fld>, <cd>the point where the three median lines of a triangle mutually intersect.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Median</ent><br/
<hw>Me"di*an</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>A median line or point.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediant</ent><br/
<hw>Me"di*ant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>medians</ets>, p. p. of <ets>mediare</ets> to halve: cf. It. <ets>mediante</ets>, F. <ets>m<eacute/diante</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>The third above the keynote; -- so called because it divides the interval between the tonic and dominant into two thirds.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediastinal</ent><br/
<hw>Me`di*as*ti"nal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to a mediastinum.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediastinum</ent><br/
<ent>Mediastine</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Me`di*as"tine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, \'d8<hw>Me`di*as*ti"num</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. <ets>mediastinum</ets>, fr. L. <ets>medius</ets> middle; cf. <ets>mediastinus</ets> helper, a menial servant, LL. <ets>mediastinus</ets> equiv. to <ets>medius</ets>: cf F. <ets>m<eacute/diastin</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A partition; a septum; specifically, the folds of the pleura (and the space included between them) which divide the thorax into a right and left cavity. The space included between these folds of the pleura, called the <xex>mediastinal space</xex>, contains the heart and gives passage to the esophagus and great blood vessels.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediate</ent><br/
<hw>Me"di*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mediatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>mediare</ets>, v. t., to halve, v. i., to be in the middle. See <er>Mid</er>, and cf. <er>Moiety</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Being between the two extremes; middle; interposed; intervening; intermediate.</def>  <rj><au>Prior.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Acting by means, or by an intervening cause or instrument; not direct or immediate; acting or suffering through an intervening agent or condition.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Gained or effected by a medium or condition.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An act of <qex>mediate</qex> knowledge is complex.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Hamilton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediate</ent><br/
<hw>Me"di*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mediated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mediating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[LL. <ets>mediatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>mediare</ets> to mediate. See <er>Mediate</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To be in the middle, or between two; to intervene.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To interpose between parties, as the equal friend of each, esp. for the purpose of effecting a reconciliation or agreement; <as>as, to <ex>mediate</ex> between nations</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediate</ent><br/
<hw>Me"di*ate</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To effect by mediation or interposition; to bring about as a mediator, instrument, or means; <as>as, to <ex>mediate</ex> a peace</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To divide into two equal parts.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Holder.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediately</ent><br/
<hw>Me"di*ate*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a mediate manner; by a secondary cause or agent; not directly or primarily; by means; -- opposed to <ant>immediately</ant>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God worketh all things amongst us <qex>mediately</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Raleigh.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The king grants a manor to A, and A grants a portion of it to B. In this case.  B holds his lands immediately of A, but <qex>mediately</qex> of the king.</q> <rj><qau>Blakstone.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediateness</ent><br/
<hw>Me"di*ate*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state of being mediate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediation</ent><br/
<hw>Me`di*a"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mediacioun</ets>, F. <ets>m<eacute/diation</ets>. See <er>Mediate</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of mediating; action or relation of anything interposed; action as a necessary condition, means, or instrument; interposition; intervention.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The soul [acts] by the <qex>mediation</qex> of these passions.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, specifically, agency between parties at variance, with a view to reconcile them; entreaty for another; intercession.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediative</ent><br/
<hw>Me"di*a*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to mediation; used in mediation; <as>as, <ex>mediative</ex> efforts</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Beaconsfield.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediatization</ent><br/
<hw>Me`di*at`i*za"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/diatisation</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act of mediatizing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediatize</ent><br/
<hw>Me"di*a*tize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mediatized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mediatizing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/diatiser</ets>.]</ety> <def>To cause to act through an agent or to hold a subordinate position; to annex; -- specifically applied to the annexation during the former German empire of a smaller German state to a larger, while allowing it a nominal sovereignty, and its prince his rank.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The misfortune of being a <qex>mediatized</qex> prince.</q> <rj><qau>Beaconsfield.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediator</ent><br/
<hw>Me"di*a`tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mediator</ets>: cf. E. <ets>m<eacute/diateur</ets>.]</ety> <def>One who mediates; especially, one who interposes between parties at variance for the purpose of reconciling them; hence, an intercessor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For there is one God, and one <qex>mediator</qex> between God and men, the man Christ Jesus.</q> <rj><qau>1 Tim. ii. 5.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediatorial</ent><br/
<hw>Me`di*a*to"ri*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to a mediator, or to mediation; mediatory; <as>as, a <ex>mediatorial</ex> office</as>.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Me`di*a*to"ri*al*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My measures were . . . healing and <qex>mediatorial</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediatorship</ent><br/
<hw>Me"di*a`tor*ship</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The office or character of a mediator.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediatory</ent><br/
<hw>Me"di*a*to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Mediatorial.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediatrix</ent><br/
<ent>Mediatress</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Me`di*a"tress</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Me`di*a*"trix</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mediatrix</ets>, f. of <ets>mediator</ets>: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/diatrice</ets>.]</ety> <def>A female mediator.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medic</ent><br/
<hw>Med"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>medica</ets>, Gr. <?/ (sc. <?/) a kind of clover introduced from <ets>Media</ets>, from <?/ Median.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A leguminous plant of the genus <gen>Medicago</gen>.  The black medic is the <spn>Medicago lupulina</spn>; the purple medic, or lucern, is <spn>Medicago sativa</spn>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medic</ent><br/
<hw>Med"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A person who serves to provide medical care.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A member of the medical corps in the military.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A medical doctor.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A medical student.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medic</ent><br/
<hw>Med"ic</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>medicus</ets>.]</ety> <def>Medical.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medicable</ent><br/
<hw>Med"i*ca*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>medicabilis</ets>, from <ets>medicare</ets>, <ets>medicari</ets>, to heal, fr. <ets>medicus</ets> physician. See <er>Medical</er>.]</ety> <def>Capable of being medicated; admitting of being cured or healed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>medicaid</ent><br/
<hw>medicaid</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A program controlled by the United States government to provide health care for the needy.  It is funded by contributions from the salaries of workers, and is therefore a form of health insurance.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medical</ent><br/
<hw>Med"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>medicalis</ets>, L. <ets>medicus</ets> belonging to healing, fr. <ets>mederi</ets> to heal; cf. Zend <ets>madha</ets> medical science, wisdom, Gr. <?/ to learn, E. <ets>mind</ets>: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/dical</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Of, pertaining to, or having to do with, the art of healing disease, or the science of medicine; <as>as, the <ex>medical</ex> profession; <ex>medical</ex> services; a <ex>medical</ex> dictionary; <ex>medical</ex> jurisprudence.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Containing medicine; used in medicine; medicinal; <as>as, the <ex>medical</ex> properties of a plant</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medically</ent><br/
<hw>Med"ic*al*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a medical manner; with reference to healing, or to the principles of the healing art.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medicament</ent><br/
<hw>Med"i*ca*ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>medicamentum</ets>, fr. <ets>medicare</ets>, <ets>medicari</ets>, to heal: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/dicament</ets>. See <er>Medicable</er>.]</ety> <def>Anything used for healing diseases or wounds, especially a medicine; a medication; a healing application.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medicamental</ent><br/
<hw>Med`ica*men"tal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to medicaments or healing applications; having the qualities of medicaments.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Med`ica*men"tal*ly</wf>, adv.</wordforms>
<-- pref. = medicinal --><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medicaster</ent><br/
<hw>Med"i*cas`ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/dicastre</ets>. See <er>Medical</er>.]</ety> <def>A quack.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Whitlock.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medicate</ent><br/
<hw>Med"i*cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Medicated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Medicating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>medicatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>medicare</ets>, <ets>medicari</ets>. See <er>Medicable</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To tincture or impregnate with anything medicinal; to drug.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Medicated</xex> waters.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Arbuthnot.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To treat with medicine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medication</ent><br/
<hw>Med`i*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <ety>[L. <ets>medicatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/dication</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act or process of medicating.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medicative</ent><br/
<hw>Med"i*ca*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Medicinal; acting like a medicine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medicean</ent><br/
<hw>Med`i*ce"an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <def>Of or relating to the <persfn>Medici</persfn>, a noted Italian family; <as>as, the <ex>Medicean</ex> Venus</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Medicean planets</b></col> <fld>(Astron.)</fld>, <cd>a name given by <persfn>Galileo</persfn> to the satellites of Jupiter.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medicinable</ent><br/
<hw>Me*dic"i*na*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Medicinal; having the power of healing.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medicinal</ent><br/
<hw>Me*dic"i*nal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>medicinalis</ets>: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/dicinal</ets>. See <er>Medicine</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having curative or palliative properties; used for the cure or alleviation of bodily disorders; <as>as, <ex>medicinal</ex> tinctures, plants, or springs</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Drop tears as fast as the Arabian trees<br/
Their <qex>medicinal</qex> gum.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to medicine; medical.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medicinally</ent><br/
<hw>Me*dic"i*nal*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a medicinal manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medicine</ent><br/
<hw>Med"i*cine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>medicina</ets> (sc. <ets>ars</ets>), fr. <ets>medicinus</ets> medical, fr. <ets>medicus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/decine</ets>. See <er>Medical</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The science which relates to the prevention, cure, or alleviation of disease.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any substance administered in the treatment of disease; a remedial agent; a medication; a drug; a pharmaceutical; a medicament; a remedy; physic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By <qex>medicine</qex>, life may be prolonged.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A philter or love potion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/decin</ets>.]</ety> <def>A physician.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Among the North American Indians, any object supposed to give control over natural or magical forces, to act as a protective charm, or to cause healing; also, magical power itself; the potency which a charm, token, or rite is supposed to exert.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><q>The North American Indian boy usually took as his <qex>medicine</qex> the first animal of which he dreamed during the long and solitary fast that he observed at puberty.</q>  <rj><qau>F. H. Giddings.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>Hence, a similar object or agency among other savages.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn>  <def>Short for <er>Medicine man</er>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn>  <def>Intoxicating liquor; drink.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Medicine bag</b></col>, <cd>a charm; -- so called among the North American Indians, or in works relating to them.</cd> -- <col><b>Medicine man</b></col> (among the North American Indians), <cd>a person who professes to cure sickness, drive away evil spirits, and regulate the weather by the arts of magic; a shaman.</cd> -- <col><b>Medicine seal</b></col>, <cd>a small gem or paste engraved with reversed characters, to serve as a seal. Such seals were used by Roman physicians to stamp the names of their medicines.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medicine</ent><br/
<hw>Med"i*cine</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To give medicine to; to affect as a medicine does; to remedy; to cure.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Medicine</xex> thee to that sweet sleep.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>medick</ent><br/
<hw>medick</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Any of several Old World herbs of the genus <gen>Medicago</gen> having small flowers and trifoliate compound leaves.</def>  <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>medic</asp>.]</altsp><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> trefoil.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>medico</ent><br/
<hw>medico</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>a student in medical school.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> medical student.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A licensed medical practitioner.</def> <mark>[slang]</mark> <br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> doctor, doc, physician, MD, Dr.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medico-legal</ent><br/
<hw>Med`i*co-le"gal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to law as affected by medical facts.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medicommissure</ent><br/
<hw>Med`i*com"mis*sure</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>medius</ets> middle + E. <ets>commissure</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A large transverse commissure in the third ventricle of the brain; the middle or soft commissure.</def>  <rj><au>B. G. Wildex.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medicornu</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Med`i*cor"nu</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Medicornua</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL., fr. L. <ets>medius</ets> middle + <ets>cornu</ets> horn.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The middle or inferior horn of each lateral ventricle of the brain.</def>  <rj><au>B. G. Wilder.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medics</ent><br/
<hw>Med"ics</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Science of medicine.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediety</ent><br/
<hw>Me*di"e*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>medietas</ets>.]</ety> <def>The middle part; half; moiety.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medievalist</ent><br/
<ent>Medievalism</ent><br/
<ent>Medieval</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Me`di*e"val</hw>, <hw>Me`di*e"val*ism</hw>, <hw>Me`di*e"val*ist</hw>  }</mhw>. <def>Same as <er>Mediaeval</er>, <er>Mediaevalism</er>, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medina epoch</ent><br/
<hw>Me*di"na ep"och</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[From <etsep>Medina</etsep> in New York.]</ety> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>A subdivision of the Niagara period in the American upper Silurian, characterized by the formations known as the Oneida conglomerate, and the Medina sandstone. See the <xex>Chart</xex> of <er>Geology</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medinilla</ent><br/
<hw>Medinilla</hw> <pos>peop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of tropical Old World ornamental evergreen shrubs having fleshy leaves and large panicles of white pink flowers.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Medinilla</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 908 --></p>

<p><ent>Medino</ent><br/
<hw>Me*di"no</hw> <pr>(m<esl/*d<emac/"n<osl/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Para</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediocral</ent><br/
<hw>Me"di*o`cral</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Mediocre.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mediocre</ent><br/
<hw>me`di*o"cre</hw> <pr>(m<emac/`d<icr/*<omac/"k<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/diocre</ets>, L. <ets>mediocris</ets>, fr. <ets>medius</ets> middle. See <er>Mid</er>.]</ety> <def>Of a middle quality; of but a moderate or low degree of excellence; indifferent; ordinary.</def> <ldquo/ A very <xex>mediocre</xex> poet.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediocre</ent><br/
<hw>Me"di*o`cre</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A mediocre person; a mediocrity.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A young monk who was excused from performing a portion of a monk's duties.</def>  <rj><au>Shipley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediocrist</ent><br/
<hw>Me"di*o`crist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mediocre person.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediocrity</ent><br/
<hw>Me`di*oc"ri*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/diocrit<eacute/</ets>, L. <ets>mediocritas</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality of being mediocre; a middle state or degree; a moderate degree or rate.</def> <ldquo/A <xex>mediocrity</xex> of success.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Moderation; temperance.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A mediocre person; -- used disparagingly.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediostapedial</ent><br/
<hw>Me`di*o*sta*pe"di*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>medius</ets> middle + E. <ets>stapedial</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to that part of the columella of the ear which, in some animals, connects the stapes with the other parts of the columella.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>The mediostapedial part of the columella.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medioxumous</ent><br/
<hw>Me`di*ox"u*mous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>medioxumus</ets> middlemost.]</ety> <def>Intermediate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Dr. H. More.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meditance</ent><br/
<hw>Med"i*tance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Meditation.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meditate</ent><br/
<hw>Med"i*tate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Meditated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Meditating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>meditatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>meditari</ets> to meditate; cf. Gr. <?/ to learn, E. <ets>mind</ets>.]</ety> <def>To keep the mind in a state of contemplation; to dwell on anything in thought; to think seriously; to muse; to cogitate; to reflect.</def>  <rj><au>Jer. Taylor.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In his law doth he <qex>meditate</qex> day and night.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. i. 2.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meditate</ent><br/
<hw>Med"i*tate</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To contemplate; to keep the mind fixed upon; to study.</def> <ldquo/Blessed is the man that doth <xex>meditate</xex> good things.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Ecclus. xiv. 20.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To purpose; to intend; to design; to plan by revolving in the mind; <as>as, to <ex>meditate</ex> a war</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>meditate</qex> to pass the remainder of life in a state of undisturbed repose.</q> <rj><qau>Washington.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To consider; ponder; weigh; revolve; study.</syn> <usage> -- To <er>Meditate</er>, <er>Contemplate</er>, <er>Intend</er>. We <xex>meditate</xex> a design when we are looking out or waiting for the means of its accomplishment; we <xex>contemplate</xex> it when the means are at hand, and our decision is nearly or quite made.  To <xex>intend</xex> is stronger, implying that we have decided to act when an opportunity may offer.  A general <xex>meditates</xex> an attack upon the enemy; he <xex>contemplates</xex> or <xex>intends</xex> undertaking it at the earliest convenient season.</usage><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meditation</ent><br/
<hw>Med`i*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>meditacioun</ets>, F. <ets>m<eacute/ditation</ets>, fr. L. <ets>meditatio</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of meditating; close or continued thought; the turning or revolving of a subject in the mind; serious contemplation; reflection; musing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let the words of my mouth and the <qex>meditation</qex> of my heart be acceptable in thy sight.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. xix. 14.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Thought; -- without regard to kind.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With wings as swift<br/
As <qex>meditation</qex> or the thoughts of love.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meditatist</ent><br/
<hw>Med"i*ta`tist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who is given to meditation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meditative</ent><br/
<hw>Med"i*ta*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>meditativus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/ditatif</ets>.]</ety> <def>Disposed to meditate, or to meditation; <as>as, a <ex>meditative</ex> man; a <ex>meditative</ex> mood.</as></def> -- <wordforms><wf>Med"i*ta*tive*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Med"i*ta*tive*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediterranean</ent><br/
<hw>Med`i*ter*ra"ne*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mediterraneus</ets>; <ets>medius</ets> middle + <ets>terra</ets> land. See <er>Mid</er>, and <er>Terrace</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Inclosed, or nearly inclosed, with land; <as>as, the <ex>Mediterranean</ex> Sea, between Europe and Africa</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Inland; remote from the ocean.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cities, as well <qex>mediterranean</qex> as maritime.</q> <rj><qau>Holland.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Of, pertaining to, or located in the Mediterranean Sea or on the adjacent lands; <as>as, <ex>Mediterranean</ex> trade; a <ex>Mediterranean</ex> voyage; a <ex>Mediterranean</ex> plant.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediterranean fruit fly</ent><br/
<hw>Med`i*ter*ra"ne*an fruit" fly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A small two-winged fly (<spn>Ceratitis capitata</spn>), a native of the Mediterranean countries but now widely distributed in warm regions, which can cause great damage to citrus and other succulent fruit crops when present in large numbers.  It is black and white and irregularly banded. It lays eggs in ripening oranges, peaches, and other fruits; when the eggs hatch into larvae (maggots) inside the fruit, they cause the fruit to decay and fall, and make the fruit unsaleable.  It is also popularly called the <altname>medfly</altname>.</def> <note>The possibility of infestation by this and other crop pests has caused some states such as California, where fruit is a major export, to ban the importation of fruit from other regions.  Outbreaks of infestation with the medfly have caused California to mobilize major eradication campaigns and have been the subject of political faultfinding.  The eradication tactic, of releasing sterile males to break the reproductive cycle, has been used to deal with outbreaks of the medfly.</note><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mediterraneous</ent><br/
<hw>Med`i*ter*ra"ne*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Inland.</def>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medium</ent><br/
<hw>Me"di*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> L. <plw>Media</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, <plw>E</plw>. <plw>Mediums</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>medium</ets> the middle, fr. <ets>medius</ets> middle. See <er>Mid</er>, and cf. <er>Medius</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which lies in the middle, or between other things; intervening body or quantity.</def> <specif>Hence, specifically:</specif> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Middle place or degree; mean.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The just <qex>medium</qex> . . . lies between pride and abjection.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>See <er>Mean</er>.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <fld>(Logic)</fld> <def>The mean or middle term of a syllogism; that by which the extremes are brought into connection.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A substance through which an effect is transmitted from one thing to another; <as>as, air is the common <ex>medium</ex> of sound</as>.</def> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>The condition upon which any event or action occurs; necessary means of motion or action; that through or by which anything is accomplished, conveyed, or carried on;</def> <specif>specifically,</specif> <def>in animal magnetism, spiritualism, etc., a person through whom the action of another being is said to be manifested and transmitted.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whether any other liquors, being made <qex>mediums</qex>, cause a diversity of sound from water, it may be tried.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I must bring together<br/
All these extremes; and must remove all <qex>mediums</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An average.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>medium</qex> of six years of war, and six years of peace.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A trade name for printing and writing paper of certain sizes. See <er>Paper</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Paint.)</fld> <def>The liquid vehicle with which dry colors are ground and prepared for application.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Microbiology)</fld> <def>A source of nutrients in which a microorganism is placed to permit its growth, cause it to produce substances, or observe its activity under defined conditions; also called <altname>culture medium</altname> or <altname>growth medium</altname>.  The <ex>medium</ex> is usually a solution of nutrients in water, or a similar solution solidified with gelatin or agar.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A means of transmission of news, advertising, or other messages from an information source to the public, also called a <altname>news medium</altname>, such as a newspaper or radio; used mostly in the plural form, i. e. <altname>news media</altname> or <altname>media</altname>.  See 1st <er>media</er>{2}.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Circulating medium</b></col>, <cd>a current medium of exchange, whether coin, bank notes, or government notes.</cd> -- <col><b>Ethereal medium</b></col> <fld>(Physics)</fld>, <cd>the ether.</cd> -- <col><b>Medium of exchange</b></col>, <cd>that which is used for effecting an exchange of commodities -- money or current representatives of money.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medium</ent><br/
<hw>Me"di*um</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having a middle position or degree; mean; intermediate; medial; <as>as, a horse of <ex>medium</ex> size; a decoction of <ex>medium</ex> strength.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medium-sized</ent><br/
<hw>Me"di*um-sized`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having a medium size; <as>as, a <ex>medium-sized</ex> man</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medius</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me"di*us</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Medii</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL., fr. L. <ets>medius</ets> middle. See <er>Medium</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The third or middle finger; the third digit, or that which corresponds to it.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medjidieh</ent><br/
<ent>Medjidie</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Me*dji"di*e</hw>, <hw>Me*dji"di*eh</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Turk. <ets>maj<imac/dieh</ets> (prop. fem. a., fr. Ar. <ets>mej<imac/d</ets> glorious); -- so called after the sultan Abdul <etsep>Mejid</etsep>, lit., <ldquo/servant of the Glorious One,<rdquo/ i.e., of God.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A silver coin of Turkey formerly rated at twenty, but since 1880 at nineteen, piasters (about 83 cents).</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A gold coin of Turkey equal (in 1913) to one hundred piastres ($4.396 or 18s. <frac34/d.); a lira, or Turkish pound.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>A Turkish honorary order established in 1851 by <persfn>Abdul-Mejid</persfn>, having as its badge a medallion surrounded by seven silver rays and crescents. It is often conferred on foreigners.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medlar</ent><br/
<hw>Med"lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>medler</ets> medlar tree, OF. <ets>meslier</ets>, F. <ets>n<eacute/flier</ets>, L. <ets>mespilum</ets>, <ets>mespilus</ets>, Gr. <?/, <?/.  Cf. <er>Naseberry</er>.]</ety> <def>A tree of the genus <gen>Mespilus</gen> (<spn>Mespilus Germanica</spn>); also, the fruit of the tree.  The fruit is something like a small apple, but has a bony endocarp.  When first gathered the flesh is hard and austere, and it is not eaten until it has begun to decay.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Japan medlar</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the loquat. See <er>Loquat</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Neapolitan medlar</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a kind of thorn tree (<spn>Crataegus Azarolus</spn>); also, its fruit.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medle</ent><br/
<hw>Med"le</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Meddle</er>.]</ety> <def>To mix; to mingle; to meddle.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>medly</asp>.]</altsp> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medley</ent><br/
<hw>Med"ley</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Medleys</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>medlee</ets>, OF. <ets>mesl<eacute/e</ets>, <ets>medl<eacute/e</ets>, <ets>mell<eacute/e</ets>, F. <ets>m<ecir/l<eacute/e</ets>. See <er>Meddle</er>, and cf. <er>Mel<eacute/e</er>, <er>Mellay</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A mixture; a mingled and confused mass of ingredients, usually inharmonious; a jumble; a hodgepodge; -- often used contemptuously.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>medley</qex> of philosophy and war.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Love is a <qex>medley</qex> of endearments, jars,<br/
Suspicions, reconcilements, wars.</q> <rj><qau>W. Walsh.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The confusion of a hand to hand battle; a brisk, hand to hand engagement; a m<ecir/l<eacute/e.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Holland.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A composition of passages detached from several different compositions; a potpourri.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Medley</xex> is usually applied to vocal, <contr>potpourri</contr> to instrumental, compositions.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A cloth of mixed colors.</def>  <rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medley</ent><br/
<hw>Med"ley</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Mixed; of mixed material or color.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/A <xex>medl<eacute/ coat</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Mingled; confused.</def>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medly</ent><br/
<hw>Med"ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>See <er>Medle</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medoc</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>M<eacute/`doc"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Mayduke</er>.]</ety> <def>A class of claret wines, including several varieties, from the district of M<eacute/doc in the department of Gironde.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medregal</ent><br/
<hw>Med"re*gal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Bonito</er>, 3.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medrick</ent><br/
<hw>Med"rick</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Etymol. uncertain.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A species of gull or tern.</def> <mark>[Prov.]</mark>  <rj><au>Lowell.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medulla</ent><br/
<hw>Me*dul"la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Marrow; pith; hence, essence.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The marrow of bones; the deep or inner portion of an organ or part; <as>as, the <ex>medulla</ex>, or medullary substance, of the kidney</as>; specifically, the medula oblongata.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A soft tissue, occupying the center of the stem or branch of a plant; pith.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>See <cref>medulla oblongata</cref>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Medulla oblongata</b></col>. <ety>[L., oblong medulla]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>the posterior part of the brain connected with the spinal cord.  It includes all the hindbrain except the cerebellum and pons, and from it a large part of the cranial nerves arise. It controls very largely respiration, circulation, swallowing, and other functions, and is the most vital part of the brain; -- called also <altname>bulb of the spinal cord</altname>. See <er>Brain</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medullar</ent><br/
<hw>Me*dul"lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>See <er>Medullary</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medullary</ent><br/
<hw>Med"ul*la*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>medullaris</ets>, fr. <ets>medulla</ets> marrow: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/dullaire</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Pertaining to, consisting of, or resembling, marrow or medulla.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Pertaining to the medula oblongata.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Filled with spongy pith; pithy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Medullary groove</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>a groove, in the epiblast of the vertebrate blastoderm, the edges of which unite, making a tube (the medullary canal) from which the brain and spinal cord are developed.</cd> -- <col><b>Medullary rays</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the rays of cellular tissue seen in a transverse section of exogenous wood, which pass from the pith to the bark.</cd> -- <col><b>Medullary sheath</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>the layer of white semifluid substance (myelin), between the primitive sheath and axis cylinder of a medullated nerve fiber.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medullated</ent><br/
<hw>Me*dul"la*ted</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Furnished with a medulla or marrow, or with a medullary sheath; <as>as, a <ex>medullated</ex> nerve fiber</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medullin</ent><br/
<hw>Me*dul"lin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/dulline</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot. Chem.)</fld> <def>A variety of lignin or cellulose found in the medulla, or pith, of certain plants.  Cf. <er>Lignin</er>, and <er>Cellulose</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medusa</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*du"sa</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Class. Myth.)</fld> <def>The Gorgon; or one of the Gorgons whose hair was changed into serpents, after which all who looked upon her were turned into stone.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <plu>[<it>pl.</it> <plw>Medusae</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.]</plu> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any free swimming acaleph; a jellyfish.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The larger <xex>medusae</xex> belong to the Discophora, and are sometimes called <stype>covered-eyed medusae</stype>; others, known as <stype>naked-eyed medusae</stype>, belong to the Hydroidea, and are usually developed by budding from hydroids. See <er>Discophora</er>, <er>Hydroidea</er>, and <er>Hydromedusa</er>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Medusa bud</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>one of the buds of a hydroid, destined to develop into a gonophore or medusa. See <er>Athecata</er>, and <er>Gonotheca</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Medusa's head</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>An astrophyton</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <cd>A cluster of stars in the constellation Perseus.  It contains the bright star Algol.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medusian</ent><br/
<hw>Me*du"si*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A medusa.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medusiform</ent><br/
<hw>Me*du"si*form</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Medusa</ets> + <ets>-form</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Resembling a medusa in shape or structure.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medusoid</ent><br/
<hw>Me*du"soid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Medusa</ets> + <ets>-oid</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Like a medusa; having the fundamental structure of a medusa, but without a locomotive disk; -- said of the sessile gonophores of hydroids.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A sessile gonophore. See <xex>Illust.</xex> under <er>Gonosome</er>.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meech</ent><br/
<hw>Meech</hw> <pr>(m<emac/ch)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>See <er>Mich</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Colloq.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meed</ent><br/
<hw>Meed</hw> <pr>(m<emac/d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mede</ets>, AS. <ets>m<emac/d</ets>, <ets>meord</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>m<emac/da</ets>, OHG. <ets>miata</ets>, <ets>mieta</ets>, G. <ets>miethe</ets> hire, Goth. <ets>mizd<omac/</ets> reward, Bohem. & Russ. <ets>mzda</ets>, Gr. <grk>misqo`s</grk>, Skr. <ets>m<imac/dha</ets>. <root/276.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is bestowed or rendered in consideration of merit; reward; recompense.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A rosy garland was the victor's <qex>meed</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Merit or desert; worth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My <qex>meed</qex> hath got me fame.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A gift; also, a bride.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meed</ent><br/
<hw>Meed</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To reward; to repay.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Waytt.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To deserve; to merit.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Heywood.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meedful</ent><br/
<hw>Meed"ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Worthy of meed, reward, or recompense; meritorious.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Meedful</xex> works.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Wiclif.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meedfully</ent><br/
<hw>Meed"ful*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>According to merit; suitably.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meek</ent><br/
<hw>Meek</hw> <pr>(m<emac/k)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Meeker</adjf> <pr>(m<emac/k"<etil/r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Meekest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>mek</ets>, <ets>meoc</ets>; akin to Icel. <ets>mj<umac/kr</ets> mild, soft, Sw. <ets>mjuk</ets>, Dan. <ets>myg</ets>, D. <ets>muik</ets>, Goth. <ets>muka</ets>m<omac/dei gentleness.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Mild of temper; not easily provoked or orritated; patient under injuries; not vain, or haughty, or resentful; forbearing; submissive.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now the man Moses was very <qex>meek</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Num. xii. 3.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Evincing mildness of temper, or patience; characterized by mildness or patience; <as>as, a <ex>meek</ex> answer; a <ex>meek</ex> face.</as></def> <ldquo/Her <xex>meek</xex> prayer.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Gentle; mild; soft; yielding; pacific; unassuming; humble. See <er>Gentle</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meeken</ent><br/
<ent>Meek</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Meek</hw>, <hw>Meek"en</hw> <pr>(-'n)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make meek; to nurture in gentleness and humility.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meekly</ent><br/
<hw>Meek"ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a meek manner.</def>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meekness</ent><br/
<hw>Meek"ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being meek.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meer</ent><br/
<hw>Meer</hw> <pr>(m<emac/r)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Simple; unmixed. See <er>Mere</er>, <pos>a.</pos></def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meer</ent><br/
<hw>Meer</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mere</er>, a lake.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meer</ent><br/
<hw>Meer</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A boundary. See <er>Mere</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meerkat</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Meer"kat</hw> <pr>(m<emac/r"k<acr/t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[D.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A South African carnivore (<spn>Suricata suricata</spn>, formerly <spn>Cynictis penicillata</spn>), allied to the ichneumons, having a lemurlike face and only four toes; called also <altname>yellow mongoose</altname> and <altname>suricate</altname>.</def> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>mierkat</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>While his compatrioits scuffle about in the sand for delicious scorpions or fat, tasty mice, one <qex>meerkat</qex> stands alone, bolt upright on an exposed perch, scanning for hawks with dark eyes wide, ready to call out at the first sign of danger.  Like other such guards in the animal kingdom, these endearingly vulnerable <qex>meerkat</qex> sentinels have long impressed biologists as true altruists -- creatures willing to forgo food and brave danger to protect others.<br/
    Now a study in the current <publ>Science</publ> suggests that these beasts may not be such adorable heroes after all.  Researchers have discovered that <qex>meerkats</qex> abandon their hunting to act as guards only when their bellies are good and full.  And they appear to do so, not as an act of noble daring, but because by being the first to see a predator, they can be sure of being the first down a hole and out of harm's way.  Standing guard, researchers concluded, may be the safest thing to do once a <qex>meerkat</qex> has had enough to eat.<br/
   . . .<br/
   Even the adorable <qex>meerkat</qex> may yet redeem itself as a bit of an altruist.  Although being a sentinel may itself not entail great risk, it is hard to imagine a selfish reason for their giving a shout of warning before dashing for cover.  . . .</q> <rj><qau>Carol Kaesuk Yoon (N. Y. Times, June 8, 1999 p. F3)</qau></rj><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meerschaum</ent><br/
<hw>Meer"schaum</hw> <pr>(m<emac/r"sh<add/m; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G., lit., sea foam; <ets>meer</ets> sea + <ets>schaum</ets> foam; but it perh. is a corruption of the Tartaric name <ets>myrsen</ets>.  Cf. <er>Mere</er> a lake, and <er>Scum</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A fine white claylike mineral, soft, and light enough when in dry masses to float in water.  It is a hydrous silicate of magnesia, and is obtained chiefly in Asia Minor.  It is manufacturd into tobacco pipes, cigar holders, etc. Also called <altname>sepiolite</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A tobacco pipe made of this mineral; a <ecol><b>meerschaum pipe</b></ecol>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meet</ent><br/
<hw>Meet</hw> <pr>(m<emac/t)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Met</conjf> <pr>(m<ecr/t)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Meeting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>meten</ets>, AS. <ets>m<emac/tan</ets>, fr. <ets>m<omac/t</ets>, <ets>gem<omac/t</ets>, a meeting; akin to OS. <ets>m<omac/tian</ets> to meet, Icel. <ets>maeta</ets>, Goth. <ets>gam<omac/tjan</ets>. See <er>Moot</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To join, or come in contact with; esp., to come in contact with by approach from an opposite direction; to come upon or against, front to front, as distinguished from contact by following and overtaking.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To come in collision with; to confront in conflict; to encounter hostilely; <as>as, they <ex>met</ex> the enemy and defeated them; the ship <ex>met</ex> opposing winds and currents.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To come into the presence of without contact; to come close to; to intercept; to come within the perception, influence, or recognition of; <as>as, to <ex>meet</ex> a train at a junction; to <ex>meet</ex> carriages or persons in the street; to <ex>meet</ex> friends at a party; sweet sounds <ex>met</ex> the ear.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His daughter came out to <qex>meet</qex> him.</q> <rj><qau>Judg. xi. 34.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To perceive; to come to a knowledge of; to have personal acquaintance with; to experience; to suffer; <as>as, the eye <ex>met</ex> a horrid sight; he <ex>met</ex> his fate.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of vice or virtue, whether blest or curst,<br/
Which <qex>meets</qex> contempt, or which compassion first.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To come up to; to be even with; to equal; to match; to satisfy; to ansver; <as>as, to <ex>meet</ex> one's expectations; the supply <ex>meets</ex> the demand.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To meet half way</b></col>, <cd>literally, to go half the distance between in order to meet (one); hence, figuratively, to yield or concede half of the difference in order to effect a compromise or reconciliation with.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meet</ent><br/
<hw>Meet</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To come together by mutual approach; esp., to come in contact, or into proximity, by approach from opposite directions; to join; to come face to face; to come in close relationship; <as>as, we <ex>met</ex> in the street; two lines <ex>meet</ex> so as to form an angle.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O, when <qex>meet</qex> now<br/
Such pairs in love and mutual honor joined !</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To come together with hostile purpose; to have an encounter or conflict.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Weapons more violent, when next we <qex>meet</qex>,<br/
May serve to better us and worse our foes.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To assemble together; to congregate; <as>as, Congress <ex>meets</ex> on the first Monday of December</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They . . . appointed a day to <qex>meet</qex> together.</q> <rj><qau>2. Macc. xiv. 21.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To come together by mutual concessions; hence, to agree; to harmonize; to unite.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To meet with</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To light upon; to find; to come to; -- often with the sense of unexpectedness.</cd><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We <qex>met with</qex> many things worthy of observation.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To join; to unite in company.</cd> <au>Shak.</au> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To suffer unexpectedly; <as>as, to <ex>meet with</ex> a fall; to <ex>meet with</ex> a loss</as>.</cd> <sd>(d)</sd> <cd>To encounter; to be subjected to.</cd><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Prepare <qex>to meet with</qex> more than brutal fury<br/
From the fierce prince.</q> <rj><qau>Rowe.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(e)</sd> <cd>To obviate.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meet</ent><br/
<hw>Meet</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An assembling together; esp., the assembling of huntsmen for the hunt; also, the persons who so assemble, and the place of meeting.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meet</ent><br/
<hw>Meet</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mete</ets> fitting, moderate, scanty, AS. <ets>m<aemac/te</ets> moderate; akin to <ets>gemet</ets> fit, meet, <ets>metan</ets> to mete, and G. <ets>m<aum/ssig</ets> moderate, <ets>gem<aum/ss</ets> fitting. See <er>Mete</er>.]</ety> <def>Suitable; fit; proper; appropriate; qualified; convenient.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was <qex>meet</qex> that we should make merry.</q> <rj><qau>Luke xv. 32.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To be meet with</b></col>, <cd>to be even with; to be equal to.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 909 --></p>

<p><ent>Meet</ent><br/
<hw>Meet</hw> <pr>(m<emac/t)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Meetly.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meeten</ent><br/
<hw>Meet"en</hw> <pr>(m<emac/t'n)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To render fit.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meeter</ent><br/
<hw>Meet"er</hw> <pr>(m<emac/t"<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who meets.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meeth</ent><br/
<hw>Meeth</hw> <pr>(m<emac/th)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mead. See <er>Meathe</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meeting</ent><br/
<hw>Meet"ing</hw> <pr>(m<emac/t"<icr/ng)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A coming together; an assembling; <as>as, the <ex>meeting</ex> of Congress</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A junction, crossing, or union; <as>as, the <ex>meeting</ex> of the roads or of two rivers</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A congregation; a collection of people; a convention; <as>as, a large <ex>meeting</ex>; an harmonious <ex>meeting</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An assembly for worship; <as>as, to attend <ex>meeting</ex> on Sunday</as>; -- in England, applied distinctively and disparagingly to the worshiping assemblies of Dissenters.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Conference; assembly; company; convention; congregation; junction; confluence; union.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meetinghouse</ent><br/
<hw>Meet"ing*house`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A house used as a place of worship; a church; -- in England, applied only to a house so used by Dissenters.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meetly</ent><br/
<hw>Meet"ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Fitly; suitably; properly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meetness</ent><br/
<hw>Meet"ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Fitness; suitableness; propriety.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megalo-</ent><br/
<ent>Mega</ent><br/
<ent>Meg-</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Meg-</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/g-)</pr>, <hw>Meg"a</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/g"<adot/-)</pr>, <hw>Meg"a*lo-</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/g"<adot/*l<osl/-)</pr> }</mhw>. <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`gas</grk>, gen. <grk>mega`loy</grk>, great.]</ety> <def>Combining forms signifying: <sd>(a)</sd> <sig>Great</sig>, <sig>extended</sig>, <sig>powerful</sig>; <as>as, <ex>mega</ex>scope, <ex>mega</ex>cosm</as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Metric System, Elec., Mech., etc.)</fld> <def><sig>A million times</sig>, <sig>a million of</sig>; <as>as, <ex>mega</ex>byte, a million butes; <ex>mega</ex>watt, a million watts; <ex>mega</ex>meter, a million meters; <ex>mega</ex>farad, a million farads; <ex>meg</ex>ohm, a million ohms</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megacephalous</ent><br/
<ent>Megacephalic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Meg`a*ce*phal"ic</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/g`<adot/*s<esl/*f<acr/l"<icr/k)</pr>, <hw>Meg`a*ceph"a*lous</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/g`<adot/*s<ecr/f"<adot/*l<ucr/s)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mega-</ets> + Gr. <grk>kefalh`</grk> head.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Large headed; -- applied to animals, and to plants when they have large flower heads.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megaceros</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*gac"e*ros</hw> <pr>(m<esl/*g<acr/s"<esl/*r<ocr/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`gas</grk> great + <grk>ke`ras</grk> horn.]</ety> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>The Irish elk.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megachile</ent><br/
<hw>Meg"a*chile</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mega-</ets> + Gr. <?/ lip.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A leaf-cutting bee of the genus <gen>Megachilus</gen>. See <cref>Leaf cutter</cref>, under <er>Leaf</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megacosm</ent><br/
<hw>Meg"a*cosm</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mega-</ets> + Gr. <?/ world.]</ety> <def>See <er>Macrocosm</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Croft.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megacoulomb</ent><br/
<hw>Meg`a*cou`lomb"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mega-</ets> + <ets>coulomb</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>A million coulombs.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megaderm</ent><br/
<hw>Meg"a*derm</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mega-</ets> + Gr. <?/ skin.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of several species of Old World blood-sucking bats of the genus <gen>Megaderma</gen>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megadyne</ent><br/
<hw>Meg"a*dyne</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mega-</ets> + <ets>dyne</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>One of the larger measures of force, amounting to one million dynes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megafarad</ent><br/
<hw>Meg"a*far`ad</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mega-</ets> + <ets>farad</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>One of the larger measures of electrical capacitance, amounting to one million farads; a macrofarad.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>megakaryocyte</ent><br/
<hw>meg`a*kar"y*o*cyte</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/g`<adot/*k<acr/r"<icr/*<osl/*s<imac/t)</pr> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A large bone marrow cell not usually found in the circulating blood; it is regarded as the precursors of blood platelets; it is up to 100 <mu/m in diameter, with a polyploid nucleus.  Also referred to as <altname>megacaryocyte</altname>, <altname>megalokaryocyte</altname>, and <altname>thromboblast</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>megakaryocytic</ent><br/
<hw>megakaryocytic</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to a megakaryocyte.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megalerg</ent><br/
<hw>Meg"a*lerg</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Megalo-</ets> + <ets>erg</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>A million ergs; a megerg.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megalesian</ent><br/
<hw>Meg`a*le"sian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>Megalesius</ets>, fr. Gr. <grk>Mega`lh</grk> the Great, a surname of Cybele, the Magna Mater.]</ety> <def>Pertaining to, or in honor of, Cybele; <as>as, the <ex>Megalesian</ex> games at Rome</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megalethoscope</ent><br/
<hw>Meg`a*leth"o*scope</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mega-</ets> + <ets>alethoscope</ets>.]</ety> <def>An optical apparatus in which pictures are viewed through a large lens with stereoptical effects.  It is often combined with the stereoscope.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megalith</ent><br/
<hw>Meg"a*lith</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mega-</ets> + <ets>-lith</ets>; cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/galithe</ets>.]</ety> <def>A large stone; especially, a large stone used in constructing ancient monuments.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Meg`a*lith"ic</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>megalithic</ent><br/
<hw>megalithic</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to megaliths or the period during which they were erected; <as>as, <ex>megalithic</ex> monuments like Stonehenge</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megalo-</ent><br/
<hw>Meg"a*lo-</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <def>See <er>Meg-</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megalobatrachus</ent><br/
<hw>Megalobatrachus</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of giant salamanders; in some classifications included in the genus <gen>Cryptobranchus</gen>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Megalobatrachus</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megalocephaly</ent><br/
<ent>Megalocephalia</ent><br/
<mhw>{ \'d8<hw>Meg`a*lo*ce*pha"li*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Meg`a*lo*ceph"a*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. <ets>megalocephalia</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/ having a large head.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>The condition of having an abnormally large head; called also <altname>megacephaly</altname>.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Meg`a*lo*ce*phal"ic</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megalocyte</ent><br/
<hw>Meg"a*lo*cyte</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Megalo-</ets> + Gr. <?/ a hollow vessel.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>A large, flattened red blood cell corpuscle having no nucleus, twice the diameter of the ordinary red corpuscle, found in considerable numbers in the blood in profound anaemia.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megalomania</ent><br/
<hw>Meg`a*lo*ma"ni*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. <ets>megalo-</ets> + <ets>mania</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Pathol.)</fld> <def>A form of mental alienation in which the patient has grandiose delusions.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>megalomanic</ent><br/
<ent>megalomaniacal</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>megalomaniacal</hw>, <hw>megalomanic</hw></mhw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Suffering from megalomania.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megalonychidae</ent><br/
<hw>Megalonychidae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family consisting of the two-toed sloths.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Megalonychidae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megalonyx</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Meg`a*lon"yx</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., from Gr. <grk>me`gas</grk>, <grk>mega`lh</grk>, great + <grk>'o`nyx</grk> claw.]</ety> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>An extinct quaternary mammal, of great size, allied to the sloth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megalophonous</ent><br/
<hw>Meg`a*loph"o*nous</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/g`<adot/*l<ocr/f"<osl/*n<ucr/s)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Megalo-</ets> + Gr. <grk>fwnh`</grk> voice.]</ety> <def>Having a loud voice.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megalopolis</ent><br/
<ent>Megapolis</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Meg`a*lop"o*lis</hw>, <hw>Meg`a"po*lis</hw></mhw> <pr>(m<ecr/g`<adot/*l<ocr/p"<osl/*l<icr/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>megalo`polis</grk>; <grk>me`gas</grk>, <grk>mega`lh</grk>, great + <grk>po`lis</grk> city.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A chief city; a very large cuity; a metropolis.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A region in which the suburbs of several large cities merge to form one large predominantly urbanized area.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megalops</ent><br/
<hw>Meg"a*lops</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/g"<adot/*l<ocr/ps)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`gas</grk>, <grk>-a`loy</grk>, large + <grk>'w`ps</grk> eye.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A larva, in a stage following the zoea, in the development of most crabs. In this stage the legs and abdominal appendages have appeared, the abdomen is relatively long, and the eyes are large. Also used adjectively.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A large fish; the tarpum.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>megalopsychy</ent><br/
<hw>meg`a*lop"sy*chy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Megalo-</ets> + Gr. <grk>psychh`</grk> soul, mind.]</ety> <def>Greatness of soul.</def> <mark>[Obs. & R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megalosaurus</ent><br/
<ent>Megalosaur</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Meg"a*lo*saur`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, \'d8<hw>Meg`a*lo*sau"rus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. <ets>megalosaurus</ets>, fr. Gr. <grk>me`gas</grk>, <grk>mega`lh</grk>, great + <grk>say^ros</grk> lizard: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/galosaure</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>A gigantic carnivorous dinosaur, whose fossil remains have been found in England and elsewhere.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megameter</ent><br/
<hw>Me*gam"e*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mega-</ets> + <ets>-meter</ets>: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/gam<egrave/tre</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An instrument for determining longitude by observation of the stars.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A micrometer.</def> <mark>[R. & Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Knight.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megametre</ent><br/
<ent>Megameter</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Meg"a*me`ter</hw>, <hw>Meg"a*me`tre</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mega-</ets> + <ets>meter</ets>, <ets>metre</ets>, n., 2.]</ety> <def>In the metric system, one million meters, or one thousand kilometers.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megampere</ent><br/
<hw>Meg`am`p<egrave/re"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mega-</ets> + <ets>amp<egrave/re</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>A million amp<egrave/res.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megaphone</ent><br/
<hw>Meg"a*phone</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mega-</ets> + Gr. <grk>fwnh`</grk> voice.]</ety> <def>A device to magnify sound, or direct it in a given direction in a greater volume, as a very large funnel used as an ear trumpet or as a speaking trumpet.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megaphyton</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*gaph"y*ton</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., from Gr. <grk>me`gas</grk> great + <grk>fyto`n</grk> plant.]</ety> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>An extinct genus of tree ferns with large, two-ranked leaves, or fronds.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megapode</ent><br/
<hw>Meg"a*pode</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/g"<adot/*p<omac/d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mega-</ets> + Gr. <grk>poy`s</grk>, <grk>podo`s</grk>, foot.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of several species of large-footed, gallinaceous birds of the genera <gen>Megapodius</gen> and <gen>Leipoa</gen>, inhabiting Australia and other Pacific islands.  Called also <altname>mound builder</altname>, <altname>scrub fowl</altname>, <altname>moundbird</altname>, and <altname>brush turkey</altname>.  See <cref>Jungle fowl</cref> <sd>(b)</sd> under <er>Jungle</er>, and <er>Leipoa</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megapolis</ent><br/
<hw>Me*gap"o*lis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`gas</grk> great + <grk>po`lis</grk> city.]</ety> <def>A metropolis.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir T. Herbert.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megaric</ent><br/
<ent>Megarian</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Me*ga"ri*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Me*gar"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Belonging, or pertaining, to Megara, a city of ancient Greece.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Megarian school</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Megaric school</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a school of philosophy established at <city>Megara</city>, after the death of Socrates, by his disciples, and remarkable for its logical subtlety.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megascope</ent><br/
<hw>Meg"a*scope</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mega-</ets> + <ets>-scope</ets>: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/gascope</ets>.]</ety> <def>A modification of the magic lantern (projector), used esp. for throwing a magnified image of an opaque object on a screen, solar or artificial light being used.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megascopical</ent><br/
<ent>Megascopic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Meg`a*scop"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Meg`a*scop"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the megascope or the projection upon a screen of images of opaque objects.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Enlarged or magnified; -- said of images or of photographic pictures, etc.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>Large enough to be seen; -- said of the larger structural features and components of rocks which do not require the use of the microscope to be perceived. Opposed to <ant>microscopic</ant>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megaseme</ent><br/
<hw>Meg"a*seme</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mega-</ets> + Gr. <?/ sing, mark: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/gas<egrave/me</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Having the orbital index relatively large; having the orbits narrow transversely; -- opposed to <contr>microseme</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megasse</ent><br/
<ent>Megass</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Me"gass"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Me*gasse"</hw>  }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Bagasse</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megasthene</ent><br/
<hw>Meg"as*thene</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`gas</grk> great + <grk>sqe`nos</grk> strength.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of a group which includes the higher orders of mammals, having a large size as a typical characteristic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megasthenic</ent><br/
<hw>Meg`as*then"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having a typically large size; belonging to the megasthenes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megastome</ent><br/
<hw>Meg"a*stome</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`gas</grk> great + <grk>sto`ma</grk> mouth.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of a group of univalve shells, having a large aperture or mouth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megatherium</ent><br/
<ent>Megathere</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Meg"a*there</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, \'d8<hw>Meg`a*the"ri*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. <ets>megatherium</ets>, fr. Gr. <grk>me`gas</grk> great + <grk>qhri`on</grk> beast.]</ety> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>An extinct gigantic quaternary mammal, allied to the ant-eaters and sloths. Its remains are found in South America.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megatheroid</ent><br/
<hw>Meg`a*the"roid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Megatherium</ets> + <ets>-oid</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>One of a family of extinct edentates found in America. The family includes the megatherium, the megalonyx, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megavolt</ent><br/
<hw>Meg`a*volt"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mega-</ets> + <ets>volt</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>One of the larger measures of electro-motive force, amounting to one million volts.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megaweber</ent><br/
<hw>Meg`a*we"ber</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mega-</ets> + <ets>weber</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>A million webers.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megerg</ent><br/
<hw>Meg"erg`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mega-</ets> + <ets>erg</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>One of the larger measures of work, amounting to one million ergs; -- called also <altname>megalerg</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megilph</ent><br/
<ent>Megilp</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Me*gilp"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Me*gilph"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Paint.)</fld> <def>A gelatinous compound of linseed oil and mastic varnish, used by artists as a vehicle for colors.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>magilp</asp>, and <asp>magilph</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>MEGO</ent><br/
<hw>MEGO</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>M</ets>y <ets>e</ets>yes <ets>g</ets>laze <ets>o</ets>ver.]</ety> <def>A very dull article, speech, or book, which causes the reader or listener to rapidly lose interest; -- often used of involved discussions of a technical nature, especially in newspapers.</def> <mark>[Acronym, Slang]</mark> <br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megohm</ent><br/
<hw>Meg"ohm"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mega-</ets> + <ets>ohm</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>One of the larger measures of electrical resistance, amounting to one million ohms.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megrim</ent><br/
<hw>Me"grim</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>migrim</ets>, <ets>migrene</ets>, F. <ets>migraine</ets>, LL. <ets>hemigrania</ets>, L. <ets>hemicrania</ets>, <ets>hemicranium</ets>, Gr. <?/; <?/- half + <?/ skull.  See <er>Hemi-</er> and <er>Cranium</er>, and cf. <er>Hemicrania</er>, <er>Migraine</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A kind of sick or nervous headache, usually periodical and confined to one side of the head; now more commonly called <altname>migraine headache</altname> or <altname>migraine</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A fancy; a whim; a freak; a humor; esp., in the plural, lowness of spirits.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These are his <qex>megrims</qex>, firks, and melancholies.</q> <rj><qau>Ford.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Far.)</fld> <def>A sudden vertigo in a horse, succeeded sometimes by unconsciousness, produced by an excess of blood in the brain; a mild form of apoplexy.</def>  <rj><au>Youatt.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megrim</ent><br/
<hw>Me"grim</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Etymol. uncertain.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The British smooth sole, or scaldfish (<spn>Psetta arnoglossa</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meibomian</ent><br/
<hw>Mei*bo"mi*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or discovered by, <persfn><etsep>Meibomius</etsep></persfn>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Meibomian glands</b></col>, <cd>the slender sebaceous glands of the eyelids, which discharge, through minute orifices in the edges of the lids, a fatty secretion serving to lubricate the adjacent parts.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meine</ent><br/
<hw>Meine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>See <er>Menge</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meiny</ent><br/
<ent>Meine</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mein"e</hw>, <hw>Mein"y</hw>, <pr>(<?/)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>maisni<eacute/e</ets>, <ets>maisnie</ets>. See <er>Menial</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A family, including servants, etc.; household; retinue; train.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer. Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Company; band; army.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meiocene</ent><br/
<hw>Mei"o*cene</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>See <er>Miocene</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meionite</ent><br/
<hw>Mei"o*nite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mei`wn</grk> smaller. So called in a allusion to the low pyramids of the crystals.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A member of the scapolite group, occuring in glassy crystals on Monte Somma, near Naples.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meiosis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mei*o"sis</hw> <pr>(m<isl/*<omac/"s<icr/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mei`wsis</grk>, fr. <grk>meioy^n</grk> to make smaller, from <grk>mei`wn</grk>. See <er>Meionite</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Rhet.)</fld> <def>Diminution; a species of hyperbole, representing a thing as being less than it really is; understatement; see also <stype>litotes</stype>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Cell Biology)</fld> <def>The cellular process by which a diploid progenitor cell forms haploid gametes, including a division of one diploid cell into two cells, each with one of the homologous sets of chromosomes.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meiostemonous</ent><br/
<hw>Mei`o*stem"o*nous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mei`wn</grk> smaller + <?/ warp, thread.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having fever stamens than the parts of the corolla.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>meiotic</ent><br/
<hw>mei*ot"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>meiosis</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Cell Biology)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to <er>meiosis</er>; <as>as, <ex>meiotic</ex> division</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>-meister</ent><br/
<hw>-meister</hw> <pos>suff.</pos> <ety>[G., master]</ety> <def>A suffix denoting <sig>master</sig> or <sig>professional practitioner</sig>, as in spin<ex>meister</ex> or hype<ex>meister</ex>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meistersinger</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Meis"ter*sing`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G.]</ety> <def>See <er>Mastersinger</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mekhitarist</ent><br/
<hw>Mekh"i*tar*ist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>See <er>Mechitarist</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melaconite</ent><br/
<hw>Me*lac"o*nite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`las</grk> black + <?/ dust.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>An earthy black oxide of copper, arising from the decomposition of other ores.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melado</ent><br/
<ent>Melada</ent><br/
<mhw>{ \'d8<hw>Me*la"da</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, \'d8<hw>Me*la"do</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp., prop. p. p. of <ets>melar</ets> to sugar, candy, fr. L. <ets>mel</ets> honey. See <er>Molasses</er>.]</ety> <def>A mixture of sugar and molasses; crude sugar as it comes from the pans without being drained.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melaena</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*lae"na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`las</grk>, m., <grk>me`laina</grk>, f., black.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A discharge from the bowels of black matter, consisting of altered blood.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melain</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"ain</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Melaena</er>.]</ety> <def>The dark coloring matter of the liquid of the cuttlefish.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melainotype</ent><br/
<hw>Me*lai"no*type</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Melanotype</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melam</ent><br/
<hw>Me"lam</hw> <pr>(m<emac/"l<acr/m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/lam</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A white or buff-colored granular powder, <chform>C6H9N11</chform>, obtained by heating ammonium sulphocyanate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>melamine</ent><br/
<hw>mel"a*mine</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/l"<adot/*m<emac/n)</pr> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A nitrogenous strongly basic chemical substance (<chform>C3H6N6</chform>), structurally <chname>2,4,6-triamino-1,3,5-triazine</chname>, produced from several cyanogen compounds, and obtained as a white crystalline substance; -- formerly supposed to be produced by the decomposition of <etsep>melam</etsep>.  Called also <altname>cyanuramide</altname>.  It is used as one of the starting components (together with formaldehyde) in the preparation of melamine resins, including the commercially marketed <er>Formica</er> (TM).  It is solid at room temperature, and sublimes at temperatures approaching 250<deg/ C, decomposing at 345<deg/ C.  Density 1.573.</def> <au>HCP61</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>melamine-fromaldehyde methanal resin</ent><br/
<ent>melamine resin</ent><br/
<hw>melamine resin</hw> <hw>melamine-fromaldehyde methanal resin</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A thermosetting plastic formed by the reaction of melamine and formaldehyde.  It is used for molding and for preparing laminated sheets used to surface counter tops, walls, and furniture.  The commercially marketed <styp><er>Formica</er></styp> (TM) is one type of melamine resin.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melampode</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"am*pode</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>melampo`dion</grk>; of uncertain origin.]</ety> <def>The black hellebore.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melampsoraceae</ent><br/
<hw>Melampsoraceae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of rust fungi.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Melampsoraceae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melampyrite</ent><br/
<ent>Melampyrin</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mel`am*py"rin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mel`am*py"rite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. <ets>Melampyrum</ets> cowwheat; Gr. <grk>me`las</grk> black + <grk>pyro`s</grk> wheat.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>The saccharine substance dulcite; -- so called because found in the leaves of cowwheat (<gen>Melampyrum</gen>). See <er>Dulcite</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanaemia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mel`a*nae"mi*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`las</grk>, <grk>me`lanos</grk>, black + <grk>a"i^ma</grk> blood.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A morbid condition in which the blood contains black pigment either floating freely or imbedded in the white blood corpuscles.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanagogue</ent><br/
<hw>Me*lan"a*gogue</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`las</grk>, <grk>me`lanos</grk>, black + <?/ leading, driving, <?/ to lead.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A medicine supposed to expel black bile or choler.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melancholia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mel`an*cho"li*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. See <er>Melancholy</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A kind of mental unsoundness characterized by extreme depression of spirits, ill-grounded fears, delusions, and brooding over one particular subject or train of ideas.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melancholian</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`an*cho"li*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A person affected with melancholy; a melancholic.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Dr. J. Scott.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melancholic</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"an*chol`ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>melancholicus</ets>, Gr. <?/: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/lancholique</ets>.]</ety> <def>Given to melancholy; depressed; melancholy; dejected; unhappy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Just as the <qex>melancholic</qex> eye<br/
Sees fleets and armies in the sky.</q> <rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melancholic</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"an*chol`ic</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One affected with a gloomy state of mind.</def>  <rj><au>J. Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A gloomy state of mind; melancholy.</def>  <rj><au>Clarendon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melancholily</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"an*chol`i*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a melancholy manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melancholiness</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"an*chol`i*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state or quality of being melancholy.</def>  <rj><au>Hallywell.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melancholious</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`an*cho"li*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>melancholieux</ets>.]</ety> <def>Melancholy.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melancholist</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"an*chol*ist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One affected with melancholy or dejection.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Glanvill.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melancholize</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"an*cho*lize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become gloomy or dejected in mind.</def>  <rj><au>Barrow.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melancholize</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"an*cho*lize</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make melancholy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melancholy</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"an*chol*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>melancolie</ets>, F. <ets>m<eacute/lancolie</ets>, L. <ets>melancholia</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/; <grk>me`las</grk>, <grk>me`lanos</grk>, black + <?/ gall, bile. See <er>Malice</er>, and 1st <er>Gall</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Depression of spirits; a gloomy state continuing a considerable time; deep dejection; gloominess.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Great and continued depression of spirits, amounting to mental unsoundness; melancholia.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Pensive maditation; serious thoughtfulness.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/Hail, divinest <xex>Melancholy</xex> !<rdquo/  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Ill nature.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melancholy</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"an*chol*y</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Depressed in spirits; dejected; gloomy dismal.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Producing great evil and grief; causing dejection; calamitous; afflictive; <as>as, a <ex>melancholy</ex> event</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Somewhat deranged in mind; having the jugment impaired.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bp. Reynolds.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Favorable to meditation; somber.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A pretty, <qex>melancholy</qex> seat, well wooded and watered.</q> <rj><qau>Evelin.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Gloomy; sad; dispirited; low-spirited; downhearted; unhappy; hypochondriac; disconsolate; heavy, doleful; dismal; calamitous; afflictive.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanconiaceae</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`an*co`ni*a"ce*ae</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A family of fungi constituting the order <ord>Melanconiales</ord>.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mel`an*co`ni*a"ceous</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanconiales</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`an*co`ni*a"les</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. <ets>Melanconium</ets>, name of the typical genus, fr. Gr. <grk>me`las</grk> black + <?/ dust, in allusion to the dark spores.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The smallest of the three orders of Fungi Imperfecti, including those with no asci nor pycnidia, but as a rule having the spores in cavities without special walls.  They cause many of the plant diseases known as <causes>anthracnose</causes>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanesian</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`a*ne"sian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`las</grk>, <grk>me`lanos</grk>, black + <?/ island. <ets>Melanesia</ets> was so called from the dark complexion of the natives.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to Melanesia.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melange</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>M<eacute/`lange"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. See <er>Mell</er>, <er>Meddle</er>.]</ety> <def>A mixture; a medley.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanian</ent><br/
<hw>Me*la"ni*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of a family of fresh-water pectinibranchiate mollusks, having a turret-shaped shell.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanic</ent><br/
<hw>Me*lan"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`las</grk>, <grk>-anos</grk>, black.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Melanotic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the black-haired races.</def>  <rj><au>Prichard.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melaniline</ent><br/
<hw>Me*lan"i*line</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A complex nitrogenous hydrocarbon obtained artificially (as by the action of cyanogen chloride on aniline) as a white, crystalline substance; -- called also <altname>diphenyl guanidin</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanin</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"a*nin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`las</grk>, <grk>me`lanos</grk>, black.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>A black pigment found in the pigment-bearing cells of the skin (particularly in the skin of the negro), in the epithelial cells of the external layer of the retina (then called <altname>fuscin</altname>), in the outer layer of the choroid, and elsewhere. It is supposed to be derived from the decomposition of hemoglobin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 910 --></p>

<p><ent>Melanism</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"a*nism</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/l"<adot/*n<icr/z'm)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`las</grk>, <grk>-anos</grk>, black.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>An undue development of dark-colored pigment in the skin or its appendages; -- the opposite of <contr>albinism</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A disease; black jaundice. See <er>Melaena</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanism</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"a*nism</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/l"<adot/*n<icr/z'm)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>The character of having a high degree of pigmentation, as shown in dark skin, eyes, and hair.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanistic</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`a*nis"tic</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/l`<adot/*n<icr/s"t<icr/k)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Affected with melanism; of the nature of melanism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanite</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"a*nite</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/l"<adot/*n<imac/t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`las</grk>, <grk>me`lanos</grk>, black: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/lanite</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A black variety of garnet.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanochroi</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mel`a*noch"ro*i</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Melanochroic</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>A group of the human race, including the dark whites.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanochroic</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`a*no*chro"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>melana`chroos</grk>; <grk>me`las</grk>, <grk>-anos</grk>, black + <grk>chroa`</grk> color.]</ety> <def>Having a dark complexion; of or pertaining to the Melanochroi.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanochroite</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`a*no*chro"ite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Melanochroic</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A mineral of a red, or brownish or yellowish red color.  It is a chromate of lead; -- called also <altname>phoenicocroite</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanocomous</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`a*noc"o*mous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`las</grk>, <grk>me`lanos</grk>, black + <?/ hair.]</ety> <def>Having very dark or black hair; black-haired.</def>  <rj><au>Prichard.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanoma</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mel`a*no"ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu>L. pl. <plw>-nomata</plw> <pr>(#)</pr></plu>. <ety>[NL.; Gr. <?/, <?/, black + <ets>-oma</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A tumor containing dark pigment.  Such tumors are usually malignant and often fatal.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Development of dark-pigmented tumors.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanorrhoea</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mel`a*nor*rhoe"a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`las</grk>, <grk>me`lanos</grk>, black + <?/ to flow.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>An East Indian genus of large trees. <spn>Melanorrh<oe/a usitatissima</spn> is the lignum-vitae of Pegu (in Burma), and yields a valuable black varnish.</def><-- #"Pegu" is part of Burma (now Myanmar) --><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanoscope</ent><br/
<hw>Me*lan"o*scope</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`las</grk>, <grk>me`lanos</grk>, black + <ets>-scope</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Opt.)</fld> <def>An instrument containing a combination of colored glasses such that they transmit only red light, so that objects of other colors, as green leaves, appear black when seen through it.  It is used for viewing colored flames, to detect the presence of potassium, lithium, etc., by the red light which they emit.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanosis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mel`a*no"sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ a growing black, fr. <grk>me`las</grk>, <grk>me`lanos</grk>, black.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>The morbid deposition of black matter, often of a malignant character, causing pigmented tumors.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanosperm</ent><br/
<hw>Me*lan"o*sperm</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`las</grk>, <grk>me`lanos</grk>, black + <grk>spe`rma</grk> seed.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>An alga of any kind that produces blackish spores, or seed dust.  The melanosperms include the rockweeds and all kinds of kelp.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mel`a*no*sper"mous</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanotic</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`a*not"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Melanistic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanotype</ent><br/
<hw>Me*lan"o*type</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`las</grk>, <grk>me`lanos</grk>, black + <ets>-type</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Photog.)</fld> <def>A positive picture produced with sensitized collodion on a smooth surface of black varnish, coating a thin plate of iron; also, the process of making such a picture.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>melainotype</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanterite</ent><br/
<hw>Me*lan"ter*ite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A hydrous sulphate of iron of a green color and vitreous luster; iron vitriol.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanure</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"a*nure</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. <ets>melanurus</ets>, fr. Gr. <grk>me`las</grk>, <grk>me`lanos</grk>, black + <grk>'oura`</grk> tail.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A small fish of the Mediterranean; a gilthead. See <er>Gilthead</er> <sd>(a)</sd>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melanuric</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`a*nu"ric</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Melam</ets> + <ets>urea</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or designating, a complex nitrogenous acid obtained by decomposition of melam, or of urea, as a white crystalline powder; -- called also <altname>melanurenic acid</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melaphyre</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"a*phyre</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. Gr. <grk>me`las</grk>, <grk>me`lanos</grk>, black + por<ets>phyre</ets> porphyry.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Any one of several dark-colored augitic, eruptive rocks allied to basalt.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melasma</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*las"ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ black spot.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A dark discoloration of the skin, usually local; <as>as, Addison's <ex>melasma</ex>, or Addison's disease</as>.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Me*las"mic</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melasses</ent><br/
<hw>Me*las"ses</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Molasses</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melassic</ent><br/
<hw>Me*las"sic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Molasses</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or designating, an acid obtained from molasses or glucose, and probably identical with <altname>saccharic</altname> acid (also called <altname>D-glucaric</altname> acid or <altname>tetrahydroxyadipic</altname> acid). See <er>Saccharic</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melastoma</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*las"to*ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`las</grk> black + <grk>sto`ma</grk> mouth.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of evergreen tropical shrubs; -- so called from the black berries of some species, which stain the mouth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melastomaceous</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`a*sto*ma"ceous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Belonging to the order of which <gen>Melastoma</gen> is the type.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>melatonin</ent><br/
<hw>mel`a*tonin</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Physiology)</fld> <def>A hormone secreted by the pineal gland.  Chemically it is <chname>N-acety-5-methoxytryptamine</chname>.  Research has indicated that there are daily rhythms in secretion of melatonin, in particular due to the depressing effect on melatonin production by light received by the retina.  Conversely it appears that melatonin may influence the circadian rhythms of animals.  There is some experimental evidence that administration of melatonin may increase the amount of sleep in people with sleep disorders.  However, the evidence is not convincing and the effect is not profound.  Nevertheless, the deregulation of melatonin and its availability over-the-counter has led to many people taking melatonin to help sleep, without consulting a physician.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>A role for melatonin in sleep facilitation has been inferred from its effect on electroencephalogram patterns, but it has not been possible to demonstrate that wakefulness sleep cycles are driven by periodic accumulation, depletion, or regeneration of melatonin.</q> <rj><qau>Uwe Ackermann, Essentials of Human Physiology, 1992</qau></rj></p>

<p><ent>Melchite</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"chite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Heb. <ets>melek</ets> king.]</ety> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>One of a sect, chiefly in Syria and Egypt, which acknowledges the authority of the pope, but adheres to the liturgy and ceremonies of the Eastern Church.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meld</ent><br/
<hw>Meld</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos>  <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Melded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Melding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[G. <ets>melden</ets> to announce.]</ety> <fld>(Card Playing)</fld> <def>In the game of pinochle, to declare or announce for a score; <as>as, to <ex>meld</ex> a sequence</as>.</def> <wns>[wns=1]</wns><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>to mix together so that the components are indistinguishable.</def> <wns>[wns=2]</wns><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> blend, mix, conflate, commingle, immix, fuse, coalesce, combine, merge.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>meld</ent><br/
<hw>meld</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Card Playing)</fld> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Any combination or score which may be declared, or melded, in pinochle.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A form of <isa>rummy</isa> using two decks and four jokers; jokers and dueces are wild; the object is to meld groups of seven of the same rank.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> canasta, basket rummy.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meleagrididae</ent><br/
<hw>Meleagrididae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of fowls including the turkeys and some extinct forms.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Meleagrididae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meleagrine</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`e*a"grine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the genus <gen>Meleagris</gen>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meleagris</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mel`e*a"gris</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[L., the Guinea fowl.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of American gallinaceous birds, including the <member>common turkey</member> and the <members>wild turkeys</members>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melee</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>M<ecir/`l<eacute/e"</hw> <pr>(m<asl/`l<asl/")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>m<ecir/ler</ets> to mix. See <er>Meddle</er>, <er>Mell</er>, and cf. <er>Mellay</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A fight in which the combatants are mingled in one confused mass; a hand to hand conflict; an affray.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A cavalry exercise in which two groups of riders try to cut paper plumes off the helmets of their opponents, the contest continuing until no member of one group retains his plume; -- sometimes called <altname>Balaklava m<ecir/l<eacute/e</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melena</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*le"na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>See <er>Melaena</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melene</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"ene</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mel</ets>issic + ethyl<ets>ene</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>An unsaturated hydrocarbon, <chform>C30H60</chform>, of the ethylene series, obtained from beeswax as a white, scaly, crystalline wax; -- called also <altname>melissene</altname>, and <altname>melissylene</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melenite</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"e*nite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`li</grk> honey.]</ety> <def>An explosive of great destructive power; -- so called from its color, which resembles honey.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meletin</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"e*tin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>See <er>Quercitin</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melezitose</ent><br/
<hw>Me*lez"i*tose`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/l<egrave/ze</ets> the larch + mel<ets>itose</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A variety of sugar, isomeric with sucrose, extracted from the manna of the larch (<gen>Larix</gen>).</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>melicitose</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meliaceous</ent><br/
<hw>Me`li*a"ceous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to a natural order (<ord>Meliacae</ord>) of plants of which the genus <gen>Melia</gen> is the type. It includes the mahogany and the Spanish cedar.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meliboean</ent><br/
<ent>Melibean</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mel`i*be"an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mel`i*b<oe/"an</hw>  }</mhw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From L. <ets>Meliboeus</ets>, one of the interlocutors in <persfn>Virgil's</persfn> first Eclogue.]</ety> <fld>(Rhet.)</fld> <def>Alternately responsive, as verses.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melic</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <ety>[Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ song.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to song; lyric; tuneful.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melicerous</ent><br/
<hw>Me*lic"er*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>meliceris</ets> a kind of tumor, fr. Gr. <?/; <grk>me`li</grk> honey + <?/ wax.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Consisting of or containing matter like honey; -- said of certain encysted tumors.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melic grass</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"ic grass`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of grasses (<gen>Melica</gen>) of little agricultural importance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melicotoon</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`i*co*toon"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>See <er>Melocoton</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melicratory</ent><br/
<hw>Me*lic"ra*to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>meli`kraton</grk>.]</ety> <def>A meadlike drink.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melilite</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"i*lite</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/l"<icr/*l<imac/t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`li</grk> honey + <ets>-lite</ets>; cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/lilithe</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A mineral occurring in small yellow crystals, found in the lavas (<it>melilite basalt</it>) of Vesuvius, and elsewhere.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mellilite</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melilot</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"i*lot</hw> <pr>(-l<ocr/t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/lilot</ets>, L. <ets>melilotus</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/, <?/, a kind of clover containing honey; <grk>me`li</grk> honey + <?/ lotus.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Any species of <gen>Melilotus</gen>, a genus of leguminous herbs having a vanillalike odor; sweet clover; hart's clover. The blue melilot (<spn>Melilotus caerulea</spn>) is used in Switzerland to give color and flavor to sapsago cheese.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melilotic</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`i*lot"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or obtained from, sweet clover or melilot; specifically, designating an acid of the aromatic series, obtained from melilot as a white crystalline substance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melinae</ent><br/
<hw>Melinae</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A subdivision of mammals not used in some classifications; it includes the badgers.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> subfamily <subfam>Melinae</subfam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melinite</ent><br/
<hw>M<eacute/"lin*ite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A high explosive similar to lyddite, consisting principally of picric acid, used in the French military service.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meliorate</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"io*rate</hw> <pr>(m<emac/l"y<osl/*r<amac/t)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Meliorated</conjf> <pr>(m<emac/l"y<osl/*r<amac/`t<ecr/d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Meliorating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>melioratus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>meliorare</ets> to meliorate, fr. <ets>melior</ets> better; akin to Gr. <grk>ma^llon</grk> rather, <grk>ma`la</grk> very.  Cf. <er>Ameliorate</er>.]</ety> <def>To make better; to improve; to ameliorate; to soften; to make more tolerable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nature by art we nobly <qex>meliorate</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The pure and benign light of revelation has had a <qex>meliorating</qex> influence on mankind.</q> <rj><qau>Washington.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meliorate</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"io*rate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To grow better.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meliorater</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"io*ra`ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Meliorator</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melioration</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`io*ra"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>melioratio</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act or operation of meliorating, or the state of being meliorated; improvement.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meliorator</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"io*ra`tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who meliorates.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meliorism</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"io*rism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From L. <ets>melior</ets> better.]</ety> <def>The doctrine that there is a tendency throughout nature toward improvement.</def>  <rj><au>J. Sully.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meliority</ent><br/
<hw>Mel*ior"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>melioritas</ets>, fr. L. <ets>melior</ets>. See <er>Meliorate</er>.]</ety> <def>The state or quality of being better; melioration.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meliphagan</ent><br/
<hw>Me*liph"a*gan</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`li</grk> honey + <?/ to eat.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Belonging to the genus <gen>Meliphaga</gen>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meliphagan</ent><br/
<hw>Me*liph"a*gan</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any bird of the genus <gen>Meliphaga</gen> and allied genera; a honey eater; -- called also <altname>meliphagidan</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meliphagous</ent><br/
<hw>Me*liph"a*gous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Meliphagan</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Eating, or feeding upon, honey.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melisma</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*lis"ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Melismata</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`lisma</grk> a song.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A piece of melody; a song or tune, -- as opposed to <contr>recitative</contr> or musical declamation.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A grace or embellishment.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melissa</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*lis"sa</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`lissa</grk> a bee, honey.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of labiate herbs, including the balm, or bee balm (<spn>Melissa officinalis</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melissic</ent><br/
<hw>Me*lis"sic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`lissa</grk> a bee, honey.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or derived from, beeswax; specif., denoting an acid obtained by oxidation of myricin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melissyl</ent><br/
<hw>Me*lis"syl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meliss</ets>ic +<ets>yl</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>See <er>Myricyl</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melissylene</ent><br/
<hw>Me*lis"sy*lene</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meliss</ets>ic + <ets>-yl</ets> + <ets>-ene</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>See <er>Melene</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melitose</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"i*tose`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`li</grk> honey.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A variety of sugar isomeric with sucrose, extracted from cotton seeds and from the so-called Australian manna (a secretion of certain species of Eucalyptus).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mell</ent><br/
<hw>Mell</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i. & t.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<ecir/ler</ets>, OF. <ets>meller</ets>, <ets>mester</ets>. See <er>Meddle</er>.]</ety> <def>To mix; to meddle.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mell</ent><br/
<hw>Mell</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mellifluous</er>.]</ety> <def>Honey.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Warner.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mell</ent><br/
<hw>Mell</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mill.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mellate</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mel</ets>, <ets>mellis</ets>, honey.  Cf. <er>Mellitate</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A mellitate.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mellay</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"lay</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A m<ecir/l<eacute/e; a conflict.</def>  <rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mellic</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"lic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>See <er>Mellitic</er>.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melliferous</ent><br/
<hw>Mel*lif"er*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mellifer</ets>; <ets>mel</ets>, <ets>mellis</ets>, honey + <ets>ferre</ets> to bear.]</ety> <def>Producing honey.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mellific</ent><br/
<hw>Mel*lif"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mel</ets>, <ets>mellis</ets>, honey + <ets>-ficare</ets> (in comp.) to make. See <er>-fy</er>.]</ety> <def>Producing honey.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mellification</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`li*fi*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mellificare</ets> to make honey: cf. F. <ets>mellification</ets>. See <er>Mellific</er>.]</ety> <def>The making or production of honey.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mellifluence</ent><br/
<hw>Mel*lif"lu*ence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A flow of sweetness, or a sweet, smooth flow.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mellifluent</ent><br/
<hw>Mel*lif"lu*ent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mellifluens</ets>. See <er>Mellifluous</er>.]</ety> <def>Flowing as with honey; smooth; mellifluous.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mellifluently</ent><br/
<hw>Mel*lif"lu*ent*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a mellifluent manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mellifluous</ent><br/
<hw>Mel*lif"lu*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mellifluus</ets>; <ets>mel</ets>, <ets>mellis</ets>, honey (akin to Gr. <?/, Goth. <ets>milip</ets>) + <ets>fluere</ets> to flow. See <er>Mildew</er>, <er>Fluent</er>, and cf. <er>Marmalade</er>.]</ety> <def>Flowing as with honey; smooth; flowing sweetly or smoothly; <as>as, a <ex>mellifluous</ex> voice</as>.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mel*lif"lu*ous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melligenous</ent><br/
<hw>Mel*lig"e*nous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mel</ets>, <ets>mellis</ets> + <ets>-genous</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having the qualities of honey.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melligo</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mel*li"go</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.]</ety> <def>Honeydew.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melliloquent</ent><br/
<hw>Mel*lil"o*quent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mel</ets>, <ets>mellis</ets> honey + <ets>loquens</ets> speaking, p. pr. of <ets>loqui</ets> to speak.]</ety> <def>Speaking sweetly or harmoniously.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melliphagan</ent><br/
<hw>Mel*liph"a*gan</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Meliphagan</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melliphagous</ent><br/
<hw>Mel*liph"a*gous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>See <er>Meliphagous</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mellitate</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"li*tate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mellitate</ets>. See <er>Mellitic</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of mellitic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mellite</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"lite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mel</ets>, <ets>mellis</ets>, honey: cf. F. <ets>mellite</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A mineral of a honey color, found in brown coal, and partly the result of vegetable decomposition; honeystone.  It is a mellitate of alumina.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mellitic</ent><br/
<hw>Mel*lit"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mellitique</ets>. See <er>Mellite</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Containing saccharine matter; marked by saccharine secretions; <as>as, <ex>mellitic</ex> diabetes</as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Pertaining to, or derived from, the mineral mellite.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mellitic acid</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>a white, crystalline, organic substance, <chform>C6(CO2H)6</chform>, occurring naturally in combination with aluminium in the mineral mellite, and produced artificially by the oxidation of coal, graphite, etc., and hence called also <altname>graphitic acid</altname>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mellone</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"lone</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A yellow powder, <chform>C6H3N9</chform>, obtained from certain sulphocyanates.  It has acid properties and forms compounds called <xex>mellonides</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mellonide</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"lon*ide</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mellone</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mellow</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"low</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Mellower</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Mellowest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>melwe</ets>; cf. AS. <ets>mearu</ets> soft, D. <ets>murw</ets>, Prov. G. <ets>mollig</ets> soft, D. <ets>malsch</ets>, and E. <ets>meal</ets> flour.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Soft or tender by reason of ripeness; having a tender pulp; <as>as, a <ex>mellow</ex> apple</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> Hence: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Easily worked or penetrated; not hard or rigid; <as>as, a <ex>mellow</ex> soil</as>.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Mellow</xex> glebe.<rdquo/ <au>Drayton</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Not coarse, rough, or harsh; subdued; soft; rich; delicate; -- said of sound, color, flavor, style, etc.</def> <ldquo/The <xex>mellow</xex> horn.<rdquo/ <au>Wordsworth.</au> <ldquo/The <xex>mellow</xex>-tasted Burgundy.<rdquo/ <au>Thomson.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The tender flush whose <qex>mellow</qex> stain imbues<br/
Heaven with all freaks of light.</q> <rj><qau>Percival.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Well matured; softened by years; genial; jovial.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>May health return to <qex>mellow</qex> age.</q> <rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As merry and <qex>mellow</qex> an old bachelor as ever followed a hound.</q> <rj><qau>W. Irving.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Warmed by liquor; slightly intoxicated.</def>  <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mellow</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"low</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mellowed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mellowing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To make mellow.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If the Weather prove frosty to <qex>mellow</qex> it [the ground], they do not plow it again till April.</q> <rj><qau>Mortimer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The fervor of early feeling is tempered and <qex>mellowed</qex> by the ripeness of age.</q> <rj><qau>J. C. Shairp.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mellow</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"low</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become mellow; <as>as, ripe fruit soon <ex>mellows</ex></as>.</def> <ldquo/Prosperity begins to <xex>mellow</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mellowed</ent><br/
<hw>mellowed</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>  <def>having a mild and pleasing flavor through proper aging.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mellow.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>having attained to kindliness or gentleness through age and experience; -- of people.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> gentle, mellow.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mellowing</ent><br/
<hw>mellowing</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def><pos>pr. p.</pos> of <er>mellow</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mellowing</ent><br/
<hw>mellowing</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act or process of acquiring desirable qualities by being left undisturbed for some time.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> ripening, aging, ageing.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mellowly</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"low*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a mellow manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mellowness</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"low*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Quality or state of being mellow.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mellowy</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"low*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Soft; unctuous.</def>  <rj><au>Drayton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melluco</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mel*lu"co</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A climbing plant (<spn>Ullucus officinalis</spn>) of the Andes, having tuberous roots which are used as a substitute for potatoes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melne</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"ne</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mill.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melocotoon</ent><br/
<ent>Melocoton</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mel`o*co*ton"</hw>, <hw>Mel`o*co*toon"</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>melocoton</ets> a kind of peach tree and its fruit, L. <ets>malum cotonium</ets>, or <ets>cotonea</ets>, or <ets>Cydonia</ets>, a quince, or quince tree, lit., apple of <ets>Cydonia</ets>, Gr. <?/ <?/. See <er>Quince</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A quince.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A kind of peach having one side deep red, and the flesh yellow.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>malacatoon</asp>, <asp>malacotune</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melodeon</ent><br/
<hw>Me*lo"de*on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ musical. See <er>Melody</er>, and cf. <er>Odeon</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A kind of small reed organ; -- a portable form of the seraphine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A music hall.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melodic</ent><br/
<hw>Me*lod"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>melodicus</ets>, Gr. <?/: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/lodique</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of the nature of melody; relating to, containing, or made up of, melody; melodious.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melodics</ent><br/
<hw>Me*lod"ics</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The branch of musical science which treats of the pitch of tones, and of the laws of melody.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melodiograph</ent><br/
<hw>Me*lo"di*o*graph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Melody</ets> + <ets>-graph</ets>.]</ety> <def>A contrivance for preserving a record of music, by recording the action of the keys of a musical instrument when played upon.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melodious</ent><br/
<hw>Me*lo"di*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/lodieux</ets>. See <er>Melody</er>.]</ety> <def>Containing, or producing, melody; musical; agreeable to the ear by a sweet succession of sounds; <as>as, a <ex>melodious</ex> voice</as>.</def> <ldquo/A <xex>melodious</xex> voice.<rdquo/ <ldquo/A <xex>melodious</xex> undertone.<rdquo/ <au>Longfellow.</au> -- <wordforms><wf>Me*lo"di*ous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Me*lo"di*ous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melodist</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"o*dist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/lodiste</ets>.]</ety> <def>A composer or singer of melodies.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melodize</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"o*dize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Melodized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Melodizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To make melodious; to form into, or set to, melody.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melodize</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"o*dize</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make melody; to compose melodies; to harmonize.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melodrama</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`o*dra"ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/lodrame</ets>, fr. Gr. <grk>me`los</grk> song + <grk>dra^ma</grk> drama.]</ety> <def>Formerly, a kind of drama having a musical accompaniment to intensify the effect of certain scenes.  Now, a drama abounding in romantic sentiment and agonizing situations, with a musical accompaniment only in parts which are especially thrilling or pathetic.  In opera, a passage in which the orchestra plays a somewhat descriptive accompaniment, while the actor speaks; <as>as, the <ex>melodrama</ex> in the gravedigging scene of Beethoven's <ldquo/Fidelio<rdquo/</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melodramatic</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`o*dra*mat"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/lodramatique</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to melodrama; like or suitable to a melodrama; unnatural in situation or action.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mel`o*dra*mat"ic*al*ly</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melodramatist</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`o*dram"a*tist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who acts in, or writes, melodramas.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melodrame</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"o*drame</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>Melodrama.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melody</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"o*dy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Melodies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>melodie</ets>, F. <ets>m<eacute/lodie</ets>, L. <ets>melodia</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/ a singing, choral song, fr. <?/ musical, melodious; <grk>me`los</grk> song, tune + <?/ song. See <er>Ode</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A sweet or agreeable succession of sounds.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lulled with sound of sweetest <qex>melody</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A rhythmical succession of single tones, ranging for the most part within a given key, and so related together as to form a musical whole, having the unity of what is technically called a musical thought, at once pleasing to the ear and characteristic in expression.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Melody</xex> consists in a succession of single tones; <xex>harmony</xex> is a consonance or agreement of tones, also a succession of consonant musical combinations or chords.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The air or tune of a musical piece.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Harmony</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meloe</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mel"o*e</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <ety>[ NL., fr. Gr. <?/ to probe a wound.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of beetles without wings, but having short oval elytra; the oil beetles.  These beetles are sometimes used instead of cantharides for raising blisters. See <cref>Oil beetle</cref>, under <er>Oil</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 911 --></p>

<p><ent>Melograph</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"o*graph</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/l"<osl/*gr<adot/f)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`los</grk> a song + <ets>-graph</ets> : cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/lographe</ets>.]</ety> <def>Same as <er>Melodiograph</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>meloid</ent><br/
<hw>meloid</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A beetle belongoing to the family <fam>Meloidae</fam>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meloidae</ent><br/
<hw>Meloidae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of insects comprising the blister beetles.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Meloidae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melolonthidae</ent><br/
<hw>Melolonthidae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural subfamily of beetles, considered a separate family in some classification systems.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> subfamily <fam>Melolonthidae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melolonthidian</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`o*lon*thid"i*an</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/l`<osl/*l<ocr/n*th<icr/d"<icr/*<ait/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mhlolo`nqh</grk> the cockchafer.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A beetle of the genus <gen>Melolontha</gen>, and allied genera.  See <cref>May beetle</cref>, under <er>May</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melon</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"on</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/l"<ucr/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>melo</ets>, for <ets>melopepo</ets> an apple-shaped melon, Gr. <grk>mhlope`pwn</grk> ; <grk>mh^lon</grk> apple + <grk>pe`pwn</grk> a species of large melon; cf. L. <ets>malum</ets> apple.  Cf. <er>Marmalade</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The juicy fruit of certain cucurbitaceous plants, as the muskmelon, watermelon, and citron melon; also, the plant that produces the fruit.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A large, ornamental, marine, univalve shell of the genus <gen>Melo</gen>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Melon beetle</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a small leaf beetle (<spn>Diabrotiea vittata</spn>), which damages the leaves of melon vines.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Melon cactus</b></col>, <col><b>Melon thistle</b></col></mcol>. <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>A genus of cactaceous plants (<gen>Melocactus</gen>) having a fleshy and usually globose stem with the surface divided into spiny longitudinal ridges, and bearing at the top a prickly and woolly crown in which the small pink flowers are half concealed</cd>.  <spn>Melocactus communis</spn>, from the West Indies, is often cultivated, and sometimes called <stype>Turk's cap</stype>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>The related genus <gen>Mamillaria</gen>, in which the stem is tubercled rather than ribbed, and the flowers sometimes large. See <xex>Illust.</xex> under <er>Cactus</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melopiano</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`o*pi*a"no</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`los</grk> song + E. <ets>piano</ets>.]</ety> <def>A piano having a mechanical attachment which enables the player to prolong the notes at will.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meloplastic</ent><br/
<hw>Mel`o*plas"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to meloplasty, or the artificial formation of a new cheek.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meloplasty</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"o*plas`ty</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/l"<osl/*pl<acr/s`t<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mh^lon</grk> an apple, a cheek + <ets>-plasty</ets>: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/loplastie</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Surg.)</fld> <def>The process of restoring a cheek which has been destroyed wholly or in part.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melopoeia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mel`o*p<oe/"ia</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/; <grk>me`los</grk> song + <grk>poiei^n</grk> to make.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>The art of forming melody; melody; -- now often used for a melodic passage, rather than a complete melody.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>melosa</ent><br/
<hw>melosa</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A South American herb (<spn>Madia sativa</spn>) with sticky glandular foliage; it is a source of <prod>madia oil</prod>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Chile tarweed, madia oil plant, <spn>Madia sativa</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melospiza</ent><br/
<hw>Melospiza</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of American song sparrows and swamp sparrows.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Melospiza</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melotype</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"o*type</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Photog.)</fld> <def>A picture produced by a process in which development after exposure may be deferred indefinitely, so as to permit transportation of exposed plates; also, the process itself.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark> <br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melpomene</ent><br/
<hw>Mel*pom"e*ne</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/, lit., the songstress, fr. <?/, <?/, to sing.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Class. Myth.)</fld> <def>The Muse of tragedy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>The eighteenth asteroid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melrose</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"rose</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Honey of roses.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melt</ent><br/
<hw>Melt</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/lt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See 2d <er>Milt</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melt</ent><br/
<hw>Melt</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Melted</conjf> <mark>(obs.)</mark> <pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Molten</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Melting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>meltan</ets>; akin to Gr. <grk>me`ldein</grk>, E. <ets>malt</ets>, and prob. to E. <ets>smelt</ets>, v. <root/108.  Cf. <er>Smelt</er>, <pos>v.</pos>, <er>Malt</er>, <er>Milt</er> the spleen.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To reduce from a solid to a liquid state, as by heat; to liquefy; <as>as, to <ex>melt</ex> wax, tallow, or lead; to <ex>melt</ex> ice or snow.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>To soften, as by a warming or kindly influence; to relax; to render gentle or susceptible to mild influences; sometimes, in a bad sense, to take away the firmness of; to weaken.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou would'st have . . . <qex>melted</qex> down thy youth.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For pity <qex>melts</qex> the mind to love.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To liquefy; fuse; thaw; mollify; soften.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melt</ent><br/
<hw>Melt</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be changed from a solid to a liquid state under the influence of heat; <as>as, butter and wax <ex>melt</ex> at moderate temperatures</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To dissolve; <as>as, sugar <ex>melts</ex> in the mouth</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>To be softened; to become tender, mild, or gentle; also, to be weakened or subdued, as by fear.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My soul <qex>melteth</qex> for heaviness.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. cxix. 28.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Melting</qex> with tenderness and kind compassion.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To lose distinct form or outline; to blend.  See <er>fondue</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The soft, green, rounded hills, with their flowing outlines, overlapping and <qex>melting</qex> into each other.</q> <rj><qau>J. C. Shairp.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To disappear by being dispersed or dissipated; <as>as, the fog <ex>melts</ex> away</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meltable</ent><br/
<hw>Melt"a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Capable of being melted.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melter</ent><br/
<hw>Melt"er</hw> <pr>(-<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who, or that which, melts.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melting</ent><br/
<hw>Melt"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Liquefaction; the act of causing (something) to melt, or the process of becoming melted.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Melting point</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>the degree of temperature at which a solid substance melts or fuses; <as>as, the <ex>melting point</ex> of ice is 0<deg/ Centigrade or 32<deg/ Fahr., that of urea is 132<deg/ Centigrade</as>.  Pressure affects the melting point somewhat, and if not specified the melting point is usually taken to be at atmospheric pressure.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melting</ent><br/
<hw>Melt"ing</hw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Causing to melt; becoming melted; -- used literally or figuratively; <as>as, a <ex>melting</ex> heat; a <ex>melting</ex> appeal; a <ex>melting</ex> mood</as>.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Melt"ing*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melting pot</ent><br/
<hw>Melt"ing pot</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A vessel in which anything is melted; a crucible.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Sociology)</fld> <mark>(fig.)</mark> <def>A place where people of different backgrounds become similar in culture.  The United States has often been referred to as a <ex>melting pot</ex>, though the differences in cultures of recently arrived immigrants persists beyond the generation of immigrants.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melton</ent><br/
<hw>Mel"ton</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Etymol. uncertain.]</ety> <def>A kind of stout woolen cloth with unfinished face and without raised nap. A commoner variety has a cotton warp.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melungeon</ent><br/
<hw>Me*lun"geon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/langer</ets> to mix, <ets>m<eacute/lange</ets> a mixture.]</ety> <def>One of a mixed white and Indian people living in parts of Tennessee and the Carolinas.  They are descendants of early intermixtures of white settlers with natives.  In North Carolina the <col><b>Croatan Indians</b></col>, regarded as descended from <person>Raleigh's</person> lost colony of Croatan, formerly classed with negroes, are now legally recognized as distinct.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melursus</ent><br/
<hw>Melursus</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of mammals including the sloth bears; in some classifications not a separate genus from <gen>Ursus</gen>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Melursus</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Melville</ent><br/
<hw>Melville</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>Herman Melville, American novelist, author of <booki>Moby Dick</booki>; b. 1819, d. 1891.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Herman Melville.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mem</ent><br/
<hw>mem</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the 13th letter of the Hebrew alphabet.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Member</ent><br/
<hw>Mem"ber</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Remember</er>.]</ety> <def>To remember; to cause to remember; to mention.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Member</ent><br/
<hw>Mem"ber</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>membre</ets>, F. <ets>membre</ets>, fr. L. <ets>membrum</ets>; cf. Goth. <ets>mimz</ets> flesh, Skr. <ets>mamsa</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A part of an animal capable of performing a distinct office; an organ; a limb.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We have many <qex>members</qex> in one body, and all <qex>members</qex> have not the same office.</q> <rj><qau>Rom. xii. 4.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>A part of a whole; an independent constituent of a body</def>; as: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A part of a discourse or of a period or sentence; a clause; a part of a verse.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>Either of the two parts of an algebraic equation, connected by the sign of equality.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <fld>(Engin.)</fld> <def>Any essential part, as a post, tie rod, strut, etc., of a framed structure, as a bridge truss.</def> <sd>(d)</sd> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>Any part of a building, whether constructional, as a pier, column, lintel, or the like, or decorative, as a molding, or group of moldings.</def> <sd>(e)</sd> <def>One of the persons composing a society, community, or the like; an individual forming part of an association; <as>as, a <ex>member</ex> of the society of Friends</as>.</def> <sd>(f)</sd> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>one of the elements which, taken together, comprise a set.</def> <sd>(g)</sd> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>one of the individual objects which comprise a group or class.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Compression member</b></col>, <col><b>Tension member</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Engin.)</fld>, <cd>a member, as a rod, brace, etc., which is subjected to compression or tension, respectively.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Membered</ent><br/
<hw>Mem"bered</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having limbs; -- chiefly used in composition.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>Having legs of a different tincture from that of the body; -- said of a bird in heraldic representations.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Membership</ent><br/
<hw>Mem"ber*ship</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The state of being a member.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The collective body of members, as of a society.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Membral</ent><br/
<hw>Mem"bral</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Relating to a member.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Membranaceous</ent><br/
<hw>Mem`bra*na"ceous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>membranaceus</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Same as <er>Membranous</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Arbuthnot.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Thin and rather soft or pliable, as the leaves of the rose, peach tree, and aspen poplar.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Membrane</ent><br/
<hw>Mem"brane</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>membrana</ets> the skin that covers the separate members of the body, fr. L. <ets>membrum</ets>. See <er>Member</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A thin layer or fold of tissue, usually supported by a fibrous network, serving to cover or line some part or organ, and often secreting or absorbing certain fluids.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The term is also often applied to the thin, expanded parts, of various texture, both in animals and vegetables.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Adventitious membrane</b></col>, <cd>a membrane connecting parts not usually connected, or of a different texture from the ordinary connection; as, the membrane of a cicatrix.</cd> -- <col><b>Jacob's membrane</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Retina</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mucous membranes</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>the membranes lining passages and cavities which communicate with the exterior, as well as ducts and receptacles of secretion, and habitually secreting mucus.</cd> -- <col><b>Schneiderian membrane</b></col>. <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Schneiderian</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Serous membranes</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <cd>, the membranes, like the peritoneum and pleura, which line, or lie in, cavities having no obvious outlet, and secrete a serous fluid.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Membraneous</ent><br/
<hw>Mem*bra"ne*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>membraneus</ets> of parchment.]</ety> <def>See <er>Membranous</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Membraniferous</ent><br/
<hw>Mem`bra*nif"er*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Membrane</ets> + <ets>-ferous</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having or producing membranes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Membraniform</ent><br/
<hw>Mem*bra"ni*form</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Membrane</ets> + <ets>-form</ets>: cf. F. <ets>membraniforme</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having the form of a membrane or of parchment.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Membranology</ent><br/
<hw>Mem`bra*nol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Membrane</ets> + <ets>-logy</ets>.]</ety> <def>The science which treats of membranes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Membranous</ent><br/
<hw>Mem"bra*nous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>membraneux</ets>.]</ety>  <sn>1.</sn> <def>Pertaining to, consisting of, or resembling, membrane; <as>as, a <ex>membranous</ex> covering or lining</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Membranaceous.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Membranous croup</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>true croup. See <er>Croup</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memento</ent><br/
<hw>Me*men"to</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mementos</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., remember, be mindful, imper. of <ets>meminisse</ets> to remember. See <er>Mention</er>.]</ety> <def>A hint, suggestion, token, or memorial, to awaken memory; that which reminds or recalls to memory; a souvenir.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Seasonable <qex>mementos</qex> may be useful.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memento mori</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*men"to mo"ri</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[L.]</ety> <def>Lit., remember to die, i.e., that you must die; a warning to be prepared for death; an object, as a death's-head or a personal ornament, usually emblematic, used as a reminder of death.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meminna</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*min"na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A small deerlet, or chevrotain, of India.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memnon</ent><br/
<hw>Mem"non</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., from Gr. <?/, lit., the Steadfast, Resolute, the son of <persfn>Tithonus</persfn> and <persfn>Aurora</persfn>, and king of the Ethiopians, killed by <persfn>Achilles</persfn>.]</ety> <fld>(Antiq.)</fld> <def>A celebrated Egyptian statue near Thebes, said to have the property of emitting a harplike sound at sunrise.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memoirs</ent><br/
<ent>Memoir</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mem"oir</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, or <pluf>pl.</pluf> <hw>Mem"oirs</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/moire</ets>, m., memorandum, fr. <ets>m<eacute/moire</ets>, f., memory, L. <ets>memoria</ets>. See <er>Memory</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A memorial account; a history composed from personal experience and memory; an account of transactions or events (usually written in familiar style) as they are remembered by the writer. See <er>History</er>, 2.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A memorial of any individual; a biography; often, a biography written without special regard to method and completeness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An account of something deemed noteworthy; an essay; a record of investigations of any subject; the journals and proceedings of a society.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memoirist</ent><br/
<hw>Mem"oir*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A writer of memoirs.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>memorabilia</ent><br/
<hw>mem`o*ra*bil"i*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. <ets>memorabilis</ets> memorable. See <er>Memorable</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Things remarkable and worthy of remembrance or record; also, the record of them.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Mementos of past events; souvenirs.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memorability</ent><br/
<hw>Mem`o*ra*bil"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being memorable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memorable</ent><br/
<hw>Mem"o*ra*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>memorabilis</ets>, fr. <ets>memorare</ets> to bring to remembrance, fr. <ets>memor</ets> mindful, remembering. See <er>Memory</er>, and cf. <er>Memorabilia</er>.]</ety> <def>Worthy to be remembered; very important or remarkable.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mem"o*ra*ble*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos> -- <wf>Mem"o*ra*bly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Surviving fame to gain,<br/
Buy tombs, by books, by <qex>memorable</qex> deeds.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J. Davies.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memorandum</ent><br/
<hw>Mem`o*ran"dum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> E. <plw>Memorandums</plw>, L. <plw>Memoranda</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., something to be remembered, neut. of <ets>memorandus</ets>, fut. pass. p. of <ets>memorare</ets>. See <er>Memorable</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A record of something which it is desired to remember; a note to help the memory.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I . . . entered a <qex>memorandum</qex> in my pocketbook.</q> <rj><qau>Guardian.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I wish you would, as opportunity offers, make <qex>memorandums</qex> of the regulations of the academies.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J. Reynolds.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A brief or informal note in writing of some transaction, or an outline of an intended instrument; an instrument drawn up in a brief and compendious form.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Memorandum check</b></col>, <cd>a check given as an acknowledgment of indebtedness, but with the understanding that it will not be presented at bank unless the maker fails to take it up on the day the debt becomes due.  It usually has <xex>Mem.</xex> written on its face.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memorate</ent><br/
<hw>Mem"o*rate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>memoratus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>memorare</ets>. See <er>Memorable</er>.]</ety> <def>To commemorate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memorative</ent><br/
<hw>Mem"o*ra*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/moratif</ets>.]</ety> <def>Commemorative.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Hammond.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memoria</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*mo"ri*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.]</ety> <def>Memory.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Memoria technica</b></col>, <cd>technical memory; a contrivance for aiding the memory.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memorial</ent><br/
<hw>Me*mo"ri*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/morial</ets>, L. <ets>memorialis</ets>, fr. <ets>memoria</ets>. See <er>Memory</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Serving to preserve remembrance; commemorative; <as>as, a <ex>memorial</ex> building</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There high in air, <qex>memorial</qex> of my name,<br/
Fix the smooth oar, and bid me live to fame.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Contained in memory; <as>as, a <ex>memorial</ex> possession</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Mnemonic; assisting the memory.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This succession of Aspirate, Soft, and Hard, may be expressed by the <qex>memorial</qex> word ASH.</q> <rj><qau>Skeat.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Memorial Day</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Memorial Day</er> in the vocabulary.  Also called <altname><er>Decoration Day</er></altname>.</cd> <mark>[U.S.]</mark></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memorial</ent><br/
<hw>Me*mo"ri*al</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/morial</ets>.]</ety>  <sn>1.</sn> <def>Anything intended to preserve the memory of a person or event; something which serves to keep something else in remembrance; a monument.</def>  <rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Churches have names; some as <qex>memorials</qex> of peace, some of wisdom, some in memory of the Trinity itself.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A memorandum; a record.</def> <mark>[Obs. or R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Hayward.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A written representation of facts, addressed to the government, or to some branch of it, or to a society, etc., -- often accompanied with a petition.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Memory; remembrance.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Precious is the <qex>memorial</qex> of the just.</q> <rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Diplomacy)</fld> <def>A species of informal state paper, much used in negotiation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memorial Day</ent><br/
<hw>Me*mo"ri*al Day</hw>. <sn>1.</sn> <def>A day, originally May 30, appointed for commemorating, by decorating their graves with flowers, by patriotic exercises, etc., the dead soldiers and sailors who served the Civil War (1861-65) in the United States; Also called <altname>Decoration Day</altname>. It is a legal holiday in most of the States. In the Southern States, the Confederate Memorial Day is: May 30 in Virginia; April 26 in Alabama, Florida, Georgia, and Mississippi; May 10 in North Carolina and South Carolina; the second Friday in May in Tennessee; June 3 in Louisiana.</def> <mark>[U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A day designated for commemoration of all of the war dead of the United States, clebrated on the last Monday in May in most states.  It supersedes the original <ex>Memorial Day</ex> celebrated May 30th.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>memorialise</ent><br/
<hw>me*mo"ri*al*ise</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>Same as memorialize.</def> <mark>[Chiefly Brit.]</mark><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memorialist</ent><br/
<hw>Me*mo"ri*al*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/morialiste</ets>.]</ety> <def>One who writes or signs a memorial.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memorialize</ent><br/
<hw>Me*mo"ri*al*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Memorialized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Memorializing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To address or petition by a memorial; to present a memorial to; <as>as, to <ex>memorialize</ex> the legislature</as>.</def>  <rj><au>T. Hook.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memorializer</ent><br/
<hw>Me*mo"ri*al*i`zer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who petitions by a memorial.</def>  <rj><au>T. Hook.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memorial rose</ent><br/
<hw>Memorial rose</hw>. <def>A Japanese evergreen rose (<spn>Rosa wichuraiana</spn>) with creeping branches, shining leaves, and single white flowers. It is often planted in cemeteries.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memorist</ent><br/
<hw>Mem"o*rist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Memorize</er>.]</ety> <def>One who, or that which, causes to be remembered.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memoriter</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*mor"i*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. <ets>memor</ets> mindful. See <er>Memorable</er>.]</ety> <def>By, or from, memory.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memorize</ent><br/
<hw>Mem"o*rize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Memorized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Memorizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Memory</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to be remembered ; hence, to record.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They neglect to <qex>memorize</qex> their conquest.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They meant to . . . <qex>memorize</qex> another Golgotha.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To commit to memory; to learn by heart.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>memorizer</ent><br/
<hw>memorizer</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A person who learns by rote.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memory</ent><br/
<hw>Mem"o*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Memories</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>memorie</ets>, OF. <ets>memoire</ets>, <ets>memorie</ets>, F. <ets>m<eacute/moire</ets>, L. <ets>memoria</ets>, fr. <ets>memor</ets> mindful; cf. <ets>mora</ets> delay.  Cf. <er>Demur</er>, <er>Martyr</er>, <er>Memoir</er>, <er>Remember</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The faculty of the mind by which it retains the knowledge of previous thoughts, impressions, or events.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Memory</qex> is the purveyor of reason.</q> <rj><qau>Rambler.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The reach and positiveness with which a person can remember; the strength and trustworthiness of one's power to reach and represent or to recall the past; <as>as, his <ex>memory</ex> was never wrong</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The actual and distinct retention and recognition of past ideas in the mind; remembrance; <as>as, in <ex>memory</ex> of youth; <ex>memories</ex> of foreign lands.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The time within which past events can be or are remembered; <as>as, within the <ex>memory</ex> of man</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And what, before thy <qex>memory</qex>, was done<br/
From the begining.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Something, or an aggregate of things, remembered; hence, character, conduct, etc., as preserved in remembrance, history, or tradition; posthumous fame; <as>as, the war became only a <ex>memory</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>memory</qex> of the just is blessed.</q> <rj><qau>Prov. x. 7.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That ever-living man of <qex>memory</qex>, Henry the Fifth.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Nonconformists . . . have, as a body, always venerated her [Elizabeth's] <qex>memory</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A memorial.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These weeds are <qex>memories</qex> of those worser hours.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Memory</er>, <er>Remembrance</er>, <er>Recollection</er>, <er>Reminiscence</er>.</syn> <usage> <xex>Memory</xex> is the generic term, denoting the power by which we reproduce past impressions. <xex>Remembrance</xex> is an exercise of that power when things occur <xex>spontaneously</xex> to our thoughts. In <xex>recollection</xex> we make a distinct effort to <xex>collect again</xex>, or call back, what we know has been formerly in the mind. <xex>Reminiscence</xex> is intermediate between <xex>remembrance</xex> and <xex>recollection</xex>, being a conscious process of recalling past occurrences, but without that full and varied reference to particular things which characterizes <xex>recollection</xex>. <ldquo/When an idea again recurs without the operation of the like object on the external sensory, it is <xex>remembrance</xex>; if it be sought after by the mind, and with pain and endeavor found, and brought again into view, it is <xex>recollection</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Locke.</au></rj>
</usage><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To draw to memory</b></col>, <cd>to put on record; to record. </cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer. Gower.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memphian</ent><br/
<hw>Mem"phi*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the ancient city of <city>Memphis</city> in Egypt; hence, Egyptian; <as>as, <ex>Memphian</ex> darkness</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the city of <city>Memphis</city> in Tennessee.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Memphian</ent><br/
<hw>Mem"phi*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A native or resident of the city of <city>Memphis</city> in Tennessee.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mem-sahib</ent><br/
<ent>memsahib</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mem"sa`hib</hw>, <hw>mem"-sa`hib</hw></mhw> <pr>(m<ecr/m"s<aum/`<icr/b)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Hind. <ets>mem-s<amac/hib</ets>; <ets>mem</ets> (fr. E. <ets>ma'am</ets>) + Ar. <ets><cced/<amac/hib</ets> master. See <er>Sahib</er>.]</ety> <def>Lady; mistress; -- used by Hindustani-speaking natives in India in addressing European women.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Men</ent><br/
<hw>Men</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>, <def><pos>pl.</pos> of <er>Man</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Men</ent><br/
<hw>Men</hw>, <pos>pron.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>me</ets>, <ets>men</ets>. <ldquo/Not the plural of <ets>man</ets>, but a weakened form of the word <ets>man</ets> itself.<rdquo/ <ets>Skeat</ets>.]</ety> <def>A man; one; -- used with a verb in the singular, and corresponding to the present indefinite <xex>one</xex> or <xex>they</xex>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Piers Plowman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Men</qex> moot give silver to the poure friars.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A privy thief, <qex>men</qex> clepeth death.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menaccanite</ent><br/
<hw>Me*nac"can*ite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <etsep>Menaccan</etsep>, in Cornwall, where it was first found.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>An iron-black or steel-gray mineral, consisting chiefly of the oxides of iron and titanium. It is commonly massive, but occurs also in rhombohedral crystals.  Called also <altname>titanic iron ore</altname>, and <altname>ilmenite</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menace</ent><br/
<hw>Men"ace</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/n"<asl/s; 48)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>minaciae</ets> threats, menaces, fr. <ets>minax</ets>, <ets>-acis</ets>, projecting, threatening, <ets>minae</ets> projecting points or pinnacles, threats.  Cf. <er>Amenable</er>, <er>Demean</er>, <er>Imminent</er>, <er>Minatory</er>.]</ety> <def>The show of an intention to inflict evil; a threat or threatening; indication of a probable evil or catastrophe to come.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His (the pope's) commands, his rebukes, his <qex>menaces</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milman.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The dark <qex>menace</qex> of the distant war.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 912 --></p>

<p><ent>Menace</ent><br/
<hw>Men"ace</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/n"<asl/s; 48)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Menaced</conjf> <pr>(<amac/st)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Menacing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF. <ets>menacier</ets>, F. <ets>menacer</ets>. See <er>Menace</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To express or show an intention to inflict, or to hold out a prospect of inflicting, evil or injury upon; to threaten; -- usually followed by <xex>with</xex> before the harm threatened; <as>as, to <ex>menace</ex> a country with war</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My master . . . did <qex>menace</qex> me with death.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To threaten, as an evil to be inflicted.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By oath he <qex>menaced</qex><br/
Revenge upon the cardinal.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menace</ent><br/
<hw>Men"ace</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To act in threatening manner; to wear a threatening aspect.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who ever knew the heavens <qex>menace</qex> so?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menacer</ent><br/
<hw>Men"a*cer</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/n"<asl/*s<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who menaces.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menacingly</ent><br/
<hw>Men"a*cing*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a threatening manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>menage</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>m<eacute/`nage"</hw> <pr>(m<asl/`n<adot/zh")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>manege</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>menage</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>m<eacute/`nage"</hw> <pr>(m<asl/`n<adot/zh")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Menagerie</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A collection of animals; a menagerie.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A social group living together; a household.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family, household, house.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A <er>menage a trois</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>menage a trois</ent><br/
<ent>menage-a-trois</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>m<eacute/`nage <agrave/` trois"</hw> <pr>(m<asl/`n<adot/zh" <adot/ trw<adot/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., household for three]</ety>  <sn>1.</sn> <def>A relationship involving three people, especially one in which three people live together and have sexual relations, such as a married couple and a lover of one of the pair.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A single sexual encounter in which three people participate.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <mark>[figurative]</mark>  <def>An unlikely situation in which a group of three people not normally associated with each other participate in an activity together.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>  For the first time in World Championships history, two racers shared the first-place gold medal.  <persfn>Maier</persfn> and <persfn>Kjus</persfn> arm-in-arm on the podium, with Austrian <person>Hans Knauss</person> just .01 seconds back from making it a <qex>menage-a-trois</qex>.</q><br/
<qau>Andrew Hood, in (http://classic.mountainzone.com/ski/worldcup/99/worldchamps/superg-m.html)</qau><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menagerie</ent><br/
<hw>Men*ag"er*ie</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/nagerie</ets>, fr. <ets>m<eacute/nager</ets> to keep house, <ets>m<eacute/nage</ets> household. See <er>Menial</er>, <er>Mansion</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A place where animals are kept and trained.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A collection of wild or exotic animals, kept for exhibition.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menagogue</ent><br/
<hw>Men"a*gogue</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/nagogue</ets>, fr. Gr. <grk>mh`n</grk> month + <?/ leading.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Emmenagogue.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menaion</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*na"ion</hw> <pr>(m<esl/*n<amac/"y<ocr/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Menaia</plw> <pr>(-y<adot/)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL., from Gr. <grk>mhnai^os</grk> monthly.]</ety> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>A work of twelve volumes, each containing the offices in the Greek Church for a month; also, each volume of the same.</def>  <rj><au>Shipley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menald</ent><br/
<ent>Menild</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Men"ald</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/n"<acr/ld)</pr>, <hw>Men"ild</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/n"<icr/ld)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Covered with spots; speckled; variegated.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mend</ent><br/
<hw>Mend</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/nd)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mended</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mending</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Abbrev. fr. <ets>amend</ets>. See <er>Amend</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To repair, as anything that is torn, broken, defaced, decayed, or the like; to restore from partial decay, injury, or defacement; to patch up; to put in shape or order again; to re-create; <as>as, to <ex>mend</ex> a garment or a machine</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To alter for the better; to set right; to reform; hence, to quicken; <as>as, to <ex>mend</ex> one's manners or pace</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The best service they could do the state was to <qex>mend</qex> the lives of the persons who composed it.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Temple.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To help, to advance, to further; to add to.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though in some lands the grass is but short, yet it <qex>mends</qex> garden herbs and fruit.</q> <rj><qau>Mortimer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You <qex>mend</qex> the jewel by the wearing it.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To improve; help; better; emend; amend; correct; rectify; reform.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mend</ent><br/
<hw>Mend</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To grow better; to advance to a better state; to become improved; to recover; to heal.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>on the mend</b></col> <pos>pred. a.</pos> <cd>recovering from an illness or injury.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mendable</ent><br/
<hw>Mend"a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Capable of being mended.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mendacious</ent><br/
<hw>Men*da"cious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mendax</ets>, <ets>-acis</ets>, lying, cf. <ets>mentiri</ets> to lie.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Given to deception or falsehood; lying; <as>as, a <ex>mendacious</ex> person</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>False; counterfeit; containing falsehood; <as>as, a <ex>mendacious</ex> statement</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Men*da"cious*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Men*da"cious*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mendacity</ent><br/
<hw>Men*dac"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mendacities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>mendacitas</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality or state of being mendacious; a habit of lying.</def>  <rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A falsehood; a lie.</def>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Lying; deceit; untruth; falsehood.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mendel</ent><br/
<hw>Mendel</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def><person>Gregor Johann Mendel</person>, founder of the science of genetics (1822-1884); <person>Gregor Mendel</person>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> <person>Gregor Mendel</person>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mendelevium</ent><br/
<hw>men*de*le"vi*um</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/n*d<ecr/*l<emac/"v<emac/*<ucr//m)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <person>Dmitri <etsep>Mendeleyev</etsep></person>, discoverer of the periodic law.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>an unstable radioactive element discovered in 1955 and produced artificially only in very small quantities; symbol Md (also Mv).  It is a <isa>transuranic element</isa> with atomic number 101.  Isotopes 255, 256, 257, and 258 have been prepared.  Md<sup>258</sup>, the longest-lived, has a half-life of two months.</def>  <au>HCP61</au><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mendelian</ent><br/
<hw>Men*de"li*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mendel's law</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Pert. to <persfn>Mendel</persfn>, or to Mendel's law; <as>as, <ex>Mendelian</ex> inheritance</as>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Behaving or being in accordance with Mendel's laws of inheritance; -- said of the distribution of inherited characteristics and of traits thus distributed.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Men*de"li*an*ism</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <wf>Men*del"ism</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mendelian character</ent><br/
<hw>Mendelian character</hw>. <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>A character which obeys Mendel's law in regard to its hereditary transmission.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mendel's law</ent><br/
<hw>Men"del's law</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <def>A principle governing the inheritance of many characters in animals and plants, discovered by <person>Gregor J. Mendel</person> (Austrian Augustinian abbot, 1822-84) in breeding experiments with peas.  He showed that the height, color, and other characters depend on the presence of determinating factors behaving as units.  In any given germ cell each of these is either present or absent.</def> <note>The following example (using letters as symbols of the determining factors and hence also of the individuals possessing them) shows the operation of the law: Tallness being due to a factor <xex>T</xex>, a tall plant, arising by the union in fertilization of two germ cells both bearing this factor, is <xex>TT</xex>; a dwarf, being without <xex>T</xex>, is <xex>tt</xex>. Crossing these, crossbreeds, <xex>Tt</xex>, result (called generation <it>F</it><subs>1</subs>). In the formation of the germ cells of these crossbreeds a process of segregation occurs such that germ cells, whether male or female, are produced of two kinds, <xex>T</xex> and <xex>t</xex>, in equal numbers. The <xex>T</xex> cells bear the factor <ldquo/tallness,<rdquo/ the <xex>t</xex> cells are devoid of it.  The offspring, generation <it>F</it><subs>2</subs>, which arise from the chance union of these germ cells in pairs, according to the law of probability, are therefore on an average in the following proportions:</p>

<p>1 <xex>TT</xex> : 2 <xex>Tt</xex> : 1 <xex>tt</xex>;</p>

<p>and thus plants pure in tallness (<xex>TT</xex>) and dwarfness (<xex>tt</xex>), as well as crossbreeds (<xex>Tt</xex>), are formed by the interbreeding of crossbreeds. Frequently, as in this example, owning to what is called the <xex>dominance</xex> of a factor, the operation of Mendel's law may be complicated by the fact that when a <xex>dominant</xex> factor (as <xex>T</xex>) occurs with its allelomorph (as <xex>t</xex>), called <xex>recessive</xex>, in the crossbreed <xex>Tt</xex>, the individual <xex>Tt</xex> is itself indistinguishable from the pure form <xex>TT</xex>. Generation <it>F</it><subs>1</subs>, containing only the <xex>Tt</xex> form, consists entirely of dominants (tall plants) and generation <it>F</it><subs>2</subs> consists of three dominants (2 <xex>Tt</xex>, 1 <xex>TT</xex>) to one dwarf (<xex>tt</xex>), which, displaying the feature suppressed in <it>F</it><subs>1</subs>, is called <xex>recessive</xex>.  Such qualitative and numerical regularity has been proved to exist in regard to very diverse qualities or characters which compose living things, both wild and domesticated, such as colors of flowers, of hair or eyes, patterns, structure, chemical composition, and power of resisting certain diseases.  The diversity of forms produced in crossbreeding by horticulturists and fanciers generally results from a process of analytical variation or recombination of the factors composing the parental types.  Purity of type consequently acquires a specific meaning.  An individual is pure in respect of a given character when it results from the union of two sexual cells both bearing that character, or both without it.</note><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mender</ent><br/
<hw>Mend"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who mends or repairs.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mendiant</ent><br/
<hw>Men"di*ant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mendinant</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mendicancy</ent><br/
<hw>Men"di*can*cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The condition of being mendicant; beggary; begging.</def>  <rj><au>Burke.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mendicant</ent><br/
<hw>Men"di*cant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mendicans</ets>, <ets>-antis</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>mendicare</ets> to beg, fr. <ets>mendicus</ets> beggar, indigent.]</ety> <def>Practicing beggary; begging; living on alms; <as>as, <ex>mendicant</ex> friars</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mendicant orders</b></col> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld>, <cd>certain monastic orders which are forbidden to acquire landed property and are required to be supported by alms, esp. the Franciscans, the Dominicans, the Carmelites, and the Augustinians.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mendicant</ent><br/
<hw>Men"di*cant</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A beggar; esp., one who makes a business of begging; specifically, a begging friar.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mendicate</ent><br/
<hw>Men"di*cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mendicatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>mendicare</ets> to beg.]</ety> <def>To beg.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mendication</ent><br/
<hw>Men`di*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act or practice of begging; beggary; mendicancy.</def>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mendicity</ent><br/
<hw>Men*dic"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mendicitas</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mendicit<eacute/</ets>. See <er>Mendicant</er>.]</ety> <def>The practice of begging; the life of a beggar; mendicancy.</def>  <rj><au>Rom. of R.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mendinant</ent><br/
<hw>Men"di*nant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mendicant or begging friar.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mendment</ent><br/
<hw>Mend"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Amendment.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mendole</ent><br/
<hw>Men"dole</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/n"d<omac/l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mendol</ets>, <ets>mendole</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The cackerel.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mendregal</ent><br/
<hw>Men"dre*gal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Medregal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mends</ent><br/
<hw>Mends</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/ndz)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Amends</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menge</ent><br/
<hw>Menge</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/nj)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Mente</conjf>, <conjf>Meinte</conjf>; <pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Ment</conjf>, <conjf>Meint</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Mingle</er>.]</ety> <def>To mix.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>menhaden</ent><br/
<hw>men*ha"den</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An American marine fish (<spn>Brevoortia tyrannus</spn>) of the <membof>Herring family</membof> (<fam>Clupeidae</fam>), chiefly valuable for its oil and as a component of fertilizers; -- called also <altname>mossbunker</altname>, <altname>bony fish</altname>, <altname>chebog</altname>, <altname>pogy</altname>, <altname>hardhead</altname>, <altname>whitefish</altname>, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menhir</ent><br/
<hw>Men"hir</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. Armor. <ets>men</ets> stone + <ets>hir</ets> high.]</ety> <def>A large stone set upright in olden times as a memorial or monument.  Many, of unknown date, are found in Brittany and throughout Northern Europe.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menial</ent><br/
<hw>Men"ial</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>meneal</ets>, fr. <ets>meine</ets>, <ets>maine</ets>, household, OF. <ets>maisni<eacute/e</ets>, <ets>maisnie</ets>, LL. <ets>mansionaticum</ets>. See <er>Mansion</er>, and cf. <er>Meine</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, <er>Meiny</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Belonging to a retinue or train of servants; performing servile office; serving.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Two <qex>menial</qex> dogs before their master pressed.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Pertaining to servants, esp. domestic servants; servile; low; mean; <as>as, <ex>menial</ex> tasks</as>.</def> <ldquo/ <xex>Menial</xex> offices.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menial</ent><br/
<hw>Men"ial</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A domestic servant or retainer, esp. one of humble rank; one employed in low or servile offices.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A person of a servile character or disposition.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meniere's disease</ent><br/
<hw>M<eacute/`ni<egrave/re's" dis*ease"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A disease characterized by deafness and vertigo, resulting in incoordination of movement.  It is supposed to depend upon a morbid condition of the semicircular canals of the internal ear.  Named after <persfn><etsep>M<eacute/ni<egrave/re</etsep></persfn>, a French physician.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menilite</ent><br/
<hw>Men"i*lite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/nilite</ets>; -- so called because it is found at <ets>M<eacute/nil</ets>montant, near Paris.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>See <er>Opal</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>meningeal</ent><br/
<hw>me*nin"ge*al</hw> <pr>(m<esl/*n<icr/n"j<esl/*<ait/l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the meninges.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meninges</ent><br/
<hw>Me*nin"ges</hw> <pr>(m<esl/*n<icr/n"j<emac/z)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos>; <sing>sing. <singw>Meninx</singw> <pr>(m<esl/*n<icr/<nsm/ks")</pr></sing>. <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mh^nigx</grk>, <grk>mh^niggos</grk>, a membrane.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The three membranes that envelop the brain and spinal cord; the pia mater, dura mater, and arachnoid membrane.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meningitis</ent><br/
<hw>Men`in*gi"tis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Meninges</er>, and <er>-itis</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Inflammation of the membranes of the brain or spinal cord.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Cerebro-spinal meningitis</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Cerebro-spinal</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meniscal</ent><br/
<hw>Me*nis"cal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to, or having the form of, a meniscus.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meniscoid</ent><br/
<hw>Me*nis"coid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meniscus</ets> + <ets>-oid</ets>.]</ety> <def>Concavo-convex, like a meniscus.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meniscus</ent><br/
<hw>Me*nis"cus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> L. <plw>Menisci</plw> <pr>(-s<imac/)</pr>, E. <plw>Meniscuses</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL., from Gr. <grk>mhni`skos</grk>, dim. of <grk>mh`nh</grk> the moon.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A crescent.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Opt.)</fld> <def>A lens convex on one side and concave on the other.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>An interarticular synovial cartilage or membrane; esp., one of the intervertebral synovial disks in some parts of the vertebral column of birds.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Converging meniscus</b></col>, <col><b>Diverging meniscus</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See <er>Lens</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menispermaceous</ent><br/
<hw>Men`i*sper*ma"ceous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mh`nh</grk> the moon + <grk>spe`rma</grk> seed.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to a natural order (<ord>Menispermaceae</ord>) of climbing plants of which moonseed (<gen>Menispermum</gen>) is the type.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menispermic</ent><br/
<hw>Men`i*sper"mic</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to, or obtained from, moonseed (<gen>Menispermum</gen>), or other plants of the same family, as the <spn>Anamirta Cocculus</spn>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menispermine</ent><br/
<hw>Men`i*sper"mine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/nispermine</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>An alkaloid distinct from picrotoxin and obtained from the cocculus indicus (the fruit of <spn>Anamirta Cocculus</spn>, formerly <spn>Menispermum Cocculus</spn>) as a white, crystalline, tasteless powder; -- called also <altname>menispermina</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meniver</ent><br/
<hw>Men"i*ver</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>menuver</ets>, <ets>menuveir</ets>, <ets>menuvair</ets>, a grayish fur; <ets>menu</ets> small + <ets>vair</ets> a kind of fur. See <er>Minute</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and <er>Vair</er>.]</ety> <def>Same as <er>Miniver</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mennonite</ent><br/
<ent>Mennonist</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Men"non*ist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Men"non*ite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>One of a small denomination of Christians, so called from <person><etsep>Menno</etsep> Simons</person> of Friesland, their founder.  They believe that the New Testament is the only rule of faith, that there is no original sin, that infants should not be baptized, and that Christians ought not to take oath, hold office, or render military service.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menobranchus</ent><br/
<ent>menobranch</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>men"o*branch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, \'d8<hw>Men`o*bran"chus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. <ets>menobranchus</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/ to remain + <?/ a gill.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A large aquatic American salamander of the genus <gen>Necturus</gen>, having permanent external gills.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menology</ent><br/
<ent>Menologium</ent><br/
<mhw>{ \'d8<hw>Men`o*lo"gi*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Me*nol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> L. <plw>Menologia</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, E. <plw>Menologies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL. <ets>menologium</ets>, fr. Gr. <grk>mh`n</grk> month + <grk>lo`gos</grk> discourse : cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/nologe</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A register of months.</def>  <rj><au>Bp. Stillingfleet.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Gr. Church)</fld> <def>A brief calendar of the lives of the saints for each day in the year, or a simple remembrance of those whose lives are not written.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menopause</ent><br/
<hw>Men"o*pause</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mh`n</grk> month + <?/ to cause to cease. See <er>Menses</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>The period of natural cessation of menstruation. See <cref>Change of life</cref>, under <er>Change</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menopome</ent><br/
<ent>Menopoma</ent><br/
<mhw>{ \'d8<hw>Men`o*po"ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Men"o*pome</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. <ets>menopoma</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/ to remain + <?/ lid.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The hellbender.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menorrhagia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Men`or*rha"gi*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mh`n</grk> month + <?/ to break.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Profuse menstruation.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Any profuse bleeding from the uterus; Metrorrhagia.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menostasis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*nos"ta*sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mh`n</grk> month + <grk>'ista`nai</grk> to stop.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Stoppage of the menses.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menostation</ent><br/
<hw>Men`os*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Menostasis</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menow</ent><br/
<hw>Men"ow</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A minnow.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Men-pleaser</ent><br/
<hw>Men"-pleas`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One whose motive is to please men or the world, rather than God.</def>  <rj><au>Eph. vi. 6.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mensal</ent><br/
<hw>Men"sal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mensalis</ets>, fr. <ets>mensa</ets> table.]</ety> <def>Belonging to the table; transacted at table; <as>as, <ex>mensal</ex> conversation</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mensal</ent><br/
<hw>Men"sal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mensis</ets> month.]</ety> <def>Occurring once in a month; monthly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mense</ent><br/
<hw>Mense</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>menske</ets>, AS. <ets>mennisc</ets> human, man. See <er>Man</er>.]</ety> <def>Manliness; dignity; comeliness; civility.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng. & Scot.]</mark> -- <wordforms><wf>Mense"ful</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> -- <wf>Mense"less</wf>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mense</ent><br/
<hw>Mense</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To grace.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng. & Scot.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menses</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Men"ses</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mensis</ets> month, pl. <ets>menses</ets> months, and the monthly courses of women.  Cf. <er>Month</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>The catamenial or menstrual discharge, a periodic flow of blood or bloody fluid from the uterus or female generative organs.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menstrual</ent><br/
<hw>Men"stru*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>menstrualis</ets>: cf. F. <ets>menstruel</ets>. See <er>Menstruous</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Recurring once a month; monthly; gone through in a month; <as>as, the <ex>menstrual</ex> revolution of the moon</as>; pertaining to monthly changes; <as>as, the <ex>menstrual</ex> equation of the sun's place</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the menses; <as>as, <ex>menstrual</ex> discharges; the <ex>menstrual</ex> period.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a menstruum.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menstruant</ent><br/
<hw>Men"stru*ant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>menstruans</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>menstruare</ets> to have a monthly term, fr. <ets>menstruus</ets>. See <er>Menstruous</er>.]</ety> <def>Subject to monthly flowing or menses.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menstruate</ent><br/
<hw>Men"stru*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Menstruous.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menstruate</ent><br/
<hw>Men"stru*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Menstruated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Menstruating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To discharge the menses; to have the catamenial flow.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>menstruating</ent><br/
<hw>menstruating</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>discharging menstrual fluid; -- of women during their menstrual period.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> unwell.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menstruation</ent><br/
<hw>Men`stru*a"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The discharge of the menses; also, the state or the period of menstruating.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menstrue</ent><br/
<hw>Men"strue</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>menstrues</ets>. See <er>Menstruous</er>.]</ety> <def>The menstrual flux; menses.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menstruous</ent><br/
<hw>Men"stru*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>menstruus</ets>, fr. <ets>mensis</ets> month.  Cf. <er>Menstruum</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having the monthly flow or discharge; menstruating.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the monthly flow; catamenial.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menstruum</ent><br/
<hw>Men"stru*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> E. <plw>Menstruums</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, L. <plw>Menstrua</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>menstruus</ets>. See <er>Menstruous</er>.]</ety> <def>Any substance which dissolves a solid body; a solvent.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The proper <qex>menstruum</qex> to dissolve metal.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All liquors are called <xex>menstruums</xex> which are used as dissolvents, or to extract the virtues of ingredients by infusion or decoction.</q> <rj><qau>Quincy.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The use is supposed to have originated in some notion of the old chemists about the influence of the moon in the preparation of dissolvents.</note>  <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mensurability</ent><br/
<hw>Men`su*ra*bil"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mensurabilit<eacute/</ets>.]</ety> <def>The quality of being mensurable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mensurable</ent><br/
<hw>Men"su*ra*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mensurabilis</ets>, fr. <ets>mensurare</ets> to measure, fr. <ets>mensura</ets> measure: cf. F. <ets>mensurable</ets>. See <er>Measurable</er>, <er>Measure</er>.]</ety> <def>Capable of being measured; measurable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mensurableness</ent><br/
<hw>Men"su*ra*ble*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being mensurable; measurableness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mensural</ent><br/
<hw>Men"su*ral</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mensuralis</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to measure.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mensurate</ent><br/
<hw>Men"su*rate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mensuratus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>mensurare</ets>. See <er>Measure</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <def>To measure.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mensuration</ent><br/
<hw>Men`su*ra"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mensuratio</ets> : cf. F. <ets>mensuration</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act, process, or art, of measuring.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That branch of applied geometry which gives rules for finding the length of lines, the areas of surfaces, or the volumes of solids, from certain simple data of lines and angles.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>-ment</ent><br/
<hw>-ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <ety>[F. <ets>-ment</ets>, L. <ets>-mentum</ets>.]</ety> <def>A suffix denoting <sig>that which does</sig> a thing; <sig>an act</sig> or <sig>process</sig>; <sig>the result of an act</sig> or <sig>process</sig>; <sig>state</sig> or <sig>condition</sig>; <as>as, ali<ex>ment</ex>, that which nourishes, orna<ex>ment</ex>, incre<ex>ment</ex>; frag<ex>ment</ex>, piece broken, seg<ex>ment</ex>; abridg<ex>ment</ex>, act of abridging, imprison<ex>ment</ex>, move<ex>ment</ex>, adjourn<ex>ment</ex>; amaze<ex>ment</ex>, state of being amazed, astonish<ex>ment</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ment</ent><br/
<hw>Ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <def><pos>p. p.</pos> of <er>Menge</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mentagra</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Men"ta*gra</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. L. <ets>mentum</ets> chin + Gr. <?/ a catching.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Sycosis.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mental</ent><br/
<hw>Men"tal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mentum</ets> the chin.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the chin; genian; <as>as, the <ex>mental</ex> nerve; the <ex>mental</ex> region.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mental</ent><br/
<hw>Men"tal</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A plate or scale covering the mentum or chin of a fish or reptile.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mental</ent><br/
<hw>Men"tal</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>mentalis</ets>, fr. <ets>mens</ets>, <ets>mentis</ets>, the mind; akin to E. <ets>mind</ets>. See <er>Mind</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to the mind; intellectual; <as>as, <ex>mental</ex> faculties; <ex>mental</ex> operations, conditions, or exercise.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What a <qex>mental</qex> power<br/
This eye shoots forth!</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mental alienation</b></col>, <cd>insanity.</cd> -- <col><b>Mental arithmetic</b></col>, <cd>the art or practice of solving arithmetical problems by mental processes, unassisted by written figures.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mentalism</ent><br/
<hw>mentalism</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>a doctrine that mind is the only true reality and that objects exist only as aspects of the mind's awareness.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any theory of psychology that accepts introspective data about the functioning of the mind as a valid object of study; contrasted to <contr>behaviorism</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mentalistic</ent><br/
<hw>men`tal*is"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertainig to mentalism.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mentality</ent><br/
<hw>Men*tal"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Quality or state of mind.</def> <ldquo/The same hard <xex>mentality</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Emerson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mentally</ent><br/
<hw>Men"tal*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In the mind; in thought or meditation; intellectually; in idea.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mentation</ent><br/
<hw>men*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/n*t<amac/"sh<ucr/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>the process of thinking (especially thinking carefully); mental activity.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> thinking, thought, cerebration, intellection.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mentha</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Men"tha</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. See <er>Mint</er> the plant.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A widely distributed genus of fragrant herbs, including the peppermint, spearmint, etc. The plants have small flowers, usually arranged in dense axillary clusters.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menthene</ent><br/
<hw>Men"thene</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Menth</ets>ol + terp<ets>ene</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A colorless liquid hydrocarbon resembling oil of turpentine, obtained by dehydrating menthol. It has an agreeable odor and a cooling taste.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>menthol</ent><br/
<hw>men"thol</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mentha</ets> + <ets>-ol</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A white, crystalline, aromatic substance (<chform>C10H20O</chform>) resembling camphor, extracted from oil of peppermint (<gen>Mentha</gen>); -- called also <altname>mint camphor</altname> or <altname>peppermint camphor</altname>.  It has the peculiar effect on skin and membranes of making them feel cool, and is used in liqueurs, confections, cigarettes, cough drops and perfumes, among other things.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menthyl</ent><br/
<hw>Men"thyl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mentha</ets> + <ets>-yl</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A compound radical forming the base of menthol.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menticirrhus</ent><br/
<hw>Menticirrhus</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of kingfishes, including the whiting.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Menticirrhus</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menticultural</ent><br/
<hw>Men`ti*cul"tur*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to mental culture; serving to improve or strengthen the mind.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mention</ent><br/
<hw>Men"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mencioun</ets>, F. <ets>mention</ets>, L. <ets>mentio</ets>, from the root of <ets>meminisse</ets> to remember. See <er>Mind</er>.]</ety> <def>A speaking or notice of anything, -- usually in a brief or cursory manner. Used especially in the phrase <xex>to make mention of</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will make <qex>mention</qex> of thy righteousness.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. lxxi. 16.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And sleep in dull, cold marble, where no <qex>mention</qex><br/
Of me more must be heard of.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 913 --></p>

<p><ent>Mention</ent><br/
<hw>Men"tion</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/n"sh<ucr/n)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mentioned</conjf> <pr>(m<ecr/n"sh<ucr/nd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mentioning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mentionner</ets>.]</ety> <def>To make mention of; to speak briefly of; to name.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will <qex>mention</qex> the loving-kindnesses of the Lord.</q> <rj><qau>Is. lxiii. 7.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mentionable</ent><br/
<hw>Men"tion*a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Fit to be mentioned.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mentomeckelian</ent><br/
<hw>Men`to*meck*e"li*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[1st <ets>ment</ets>al + <ets>Meckelian</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the chin and lower jaw.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>The bone or cartilage forming the anterior extremity of the lower jaw in some adult animals and the young of others.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mentor</ent><br/
<hw>Men"tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <etsep>Mentor</etsep>, the counselor of <persfn>Telemachus</persfn>, Gr. <grk>Me`ntwr</grk>, prop., counselor.  Cf. <er>Monitor</er>.]</ety> <def>A wise and faithful counselor or monitor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mentorial</ent><br/
<hw>Men*to"ri*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mentor</er>.]</ety> <def>Containing advice or admonition.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mentum</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>men"tum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., chin.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The front median plate of the labium in insects. See <er>Labium</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mentzelia</ent><br/
<hw>Mentzelia</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of bristly herbs or subshrubs of Western America lacking stinging hairs.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Mentzelia</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>menu</ent><br/
<hw>men"u</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/n"y<oomac/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., slender, thin, minute. See 4th <er>Minute</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The details of a banquet; a list of the dishes served at a meal, whether or not one has a choice.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any list of objects, activities, etc. from which to choose; a selection of alternatives.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif><def>A list of dishes form which to choose at a restaurant; a bill of fare.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <fld>(Computers)</fld> <def>A list displayed on the computer screen, by which a program provides the user with different options for processing by the program.  It usually includes a mechanism, such as pointing by a mouse or selection by arrow keys, to select the desired option from those on the list.  Depending on how the menu is displayed, it may be a <stype>pop-up menu</stype> or <stype>pull-down menu</stype>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>
	
<p><ent>Menurae</ent><br/
<hw>Menurae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A suborder of birds including lyrebirds and scrubbirds.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> suborder <subord>Menurae</subord>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menuridae</ent><br/
<hw>Menuridae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of birds including the lyrebirds.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Menuridae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menuse</ent><br/
<hw>Me"nuse</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>See <er>Amenuse</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menyanthes</ent><br/
<hw>Menyanthes</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The type genus of the <fam>Menyanthaceae</fam>, having only one species: the bogbeans.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Menyanthes</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menziesia</ent><br/
<hw>Menziesia</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of deciduous shrubs of North America and eastern Asia.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Menziesia</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meow</ent><br/
<hw>Me*ow"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i. & n.</pos> <def>See 6th and 7th <er>Mew</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mepacrine</ent><br/
<hw>mepacrine</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Quinacrine, a drug once used to treat malaria; <altname>Atabrine</altname> is a trademark.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> quinacrine, Atabrine.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>meperidine</ent><br/
<hw>meperidine</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A synthetic narcotic drug used as a sedative; <altname>Demerol</altname> is the trademark of a brand of meperidine.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> meperidine hydrochloride, Demerol.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mephistophelian</ent><br/
<ent>Mephistophelean</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Meph`is*to*phe"le*an</hw>, <hw>Meph`is*to*phe"li*an</hw></mhw> <pr>(? <or/ ?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to, or resembling, the devil <persfn>Mephistopheles</persfn>, <ldquo/a crafty, scoffing, relentless fiend;<rdquo/ devilish in character or aspect; crafty; showing cunning or ingenuity or wickedness; <as>as, a <ex>mephistophelean</ex> glint in his eye</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> devilish, diabolic, diabolical, mephistophelean.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mephistopheles</ent><br/
<hw>Meph*is*toph"e*les</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/f*<icr/s*tof"<esl/*l<emac/z)</pr>  <ety>[Written Mephostophilus in Shakespeare, Fletcher etc., Mephostophilis in Marlowe, but now generally Mephistopheles, as in Goethe: a made-up name, like most of the names of the medieval devils, but supposed by some to be formed (irregularly) from Gr. <grk>mh`</grk>, not, <grk>fw^s</grk> (<grk>fwt-</grk>), light, and <grk>fi`los</grk>, loving.]</ety>  <def>A familiar spirit mentioned in the old legend of <person>Sir John Faustus</person>, and a principal agent in Marlowe's play <publ><it>Dr. Faustus</it></publ> and in Goethe's <publ><it>Faust</it></publ>.  In medieval demonology, he was one of the seven chief devils.</def><br/
[<source>Century Dictionary 1906</source>]</p>

<p><q>    He is frequently referred to as <ldquo/the Devil,<rdquo/ but it was well understood that he was only a devil.  Goethe took only the name and a few circumstances connected with the first appearance of Mephistopheles from the legend: the character, from first to last, is his own creation; and, in his own words, <ldquo/on account of the irony and knowledge of the world it displays, is not easily comprehended.<rdquo/  Although he sometimes slyly used it (though less frequently than Faust) as a mask through which to speak with his own voice, he evidently drew the germ of some characteristics from his early associate, <persfn>Merck</persfn>.  . . .  The original form of this name was Mephostophiles.  There has been much discussion in regard to its meaning, but <persfn>D<uum/ntzen's</persfn> conjecture is probably correct, -- that it was imperfectly formed by some one who knew little Greek, and was intended to signify <ldquo/not loving the light.<rdquo/</q> <rj><qau>B. Taylor, Notes to Faust.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>Century Dictionary 1906</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mephitical</ent><br/
<ent>Mephitic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Me*phit"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Me*phit"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mephiticus</ets>, fr. <ets>mephitis</ets> mephitis: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/phitique</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Tending to destroy life; poisonous; noxious; <as>as, <ex>mephitic</ex> exhalations; <ex>mephitic</ex> regions.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Offensive to the smell; <as>as, <ex>mephitic</ex> odors</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mephitic air</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>carbon dioxide; -- so called because of its deadly suffocating power. See <cref>Carbonic acid</cref>, under <er>Carbonic</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mephitinae</ent><br/
<hw>Mephitinae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A subfamily of mammals including the skunks; it is a subdivision not used in some classifications.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> subfamily <subfam>Mephitinae</subfam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mephitis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*phi"tis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mephitis</ets> : cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/phitis</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Noxious, pestilential, or foul exhalations from decomposing substances, filth, or other source.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of mammals, including the skunks.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mephitism</ent><br/
<hw>Meph"i*tism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Mephitis</er>, 1.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meracious</ent><br/
<hw>Me*ra"cious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>meracus</ets>, fr. <ets>merus</ets> pure, inmixed.]</ety> <def>Being without mixture or adulteration; hence, strong; racy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercable</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ca*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mercabilis</ets>, fr. <ets>mercari</ets> to trade, traffic, buy. See <er>Merchant</er>.]</ety> <def>Capable of being bought or sold.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>merbromine</ent><br/
<hw>merbromine</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mercurial compound applied topically as an antiseptic; <altname>Mercurochrome</altname> is the trademark.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Mercurochrome.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercantile</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"can*tile</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mercantile</ets>, It. <ets>mercantile</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mercans</ets>, <ets>-antis</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>mercari</ets> to traffic. See <er>Merchant</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to merchants, or the business of merchants; having to do with trade, or the buying and selling of commodities; commercial.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The expedition of the Argonauts was partly <qex>mercantile</qex>, partly military.</q> <rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mercantile agency</b></col>, <cd>an agency for procuring information of the standing and credit of merchants in different parts of the country, for the use of dealers who sell to them.</cd> -- <col><b>Mercantile marine</b></col>, <cd>the persons and vessels employed in commerce, taken collectively.</cd> -- <col><b>Mercantile paper</b></col>, <cd>the notes or acceptances given by merchants for goods bought, or received on consignment; drafts on merchants for goods sold or consigned.</cd>  <rj><au>McElrath.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Mercantile</er>, <er>Commercial</er>.</syn> <usage> <xex>Commercial</xex> is the wider term, being sometimes used to embrace <xex>mercantile</xex>. In their stricter use, <xex>commercial</xex> relates to the shipping, freighting, forwarding, and other business connected with the <xex>commerce</xex> of a country (whether external or internal), that is, the exchange of commodities; while <xex>mercantile</xex> applies to the sale of merchandise and goods when brought to market. As the two employments are to some extent intermingled, the two words are often interchanged.</usage><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercaptal</ent><br/
<hw>Mer*cap"tal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mercapt</ets>an + <ets>al</ets>dehyde.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Any one of a series of compounds of mercaptans with aldehydes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercaptan</ent><br/
<hw>Mer*cap"tan</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. NL. <ets>mercurius</ets> mercury + L. <ets>captans</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>captare</ets> to seize, v. intens. fr. <ets>capere</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Any one of series of compounds having an <chform>-SH</chform> radical attached to a carbon atom, also considered as hydrosulphides of alcohol radicals, in composition resembling the alcohols, but containing sulphur in place of oxygen, and hence called also the <altname>sulphur alcohols</altname>.  In general, they are colorless liquids having a strong, repulsive, garlic odor.  The name is specifically applied to ethyl mercaptan, <chform>C2H5SH</chform>.  So called from its avidity for <xex>mercury</xex>, and other metals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercaptide</ent><br/
<hw>Mer*cap"tide</hw> <pr>(? <or/ ?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A compound of mercaptan formed by replacing its sulphur hydrogen by a metal; <as>as, potassium <ex>mercaptide</ex>, <chform>C2H5SK</chform></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercat</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"cat</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mercatus</ets> : cf. It. <ets>mercato</ets>. See <er>Market</er>.]</ety> <def>Market; trade.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bp. Sprat.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercatante</ent><br/
<hw>Mer`ca*tan"te</hw> <pr>(?; It. ?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It. See <er>Merchant</er>.]</ety> <def>A foreign trader.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercator's chart</ent><br/
<hw>Mer*ca"tor's chart"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <def>See under <er>Chart</er>, and see <cref>Mercator's projection</cref>, under <er>Projection</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercature</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ca*ture</hw> <pr>(?; 135)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mercatura</ets> commerce.]</ety> <def>Commerce; traffic; trade.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merce</ent><br/
<hw>Merce</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Amerce</er>.]</ety> <def>To subject to fine or amercement; to mulct; to amerce.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercenaria</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mer`ce*na"ri*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Mercenary</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The <er>quahog</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercenarian</ent><br/
<hw>Mer`ce*na"ri*an</hw> <pr>(-<it>a</it>n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mercenary.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercenarily</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ce*na`ri*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a mercenary manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercenariness</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ce*na*ri*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being mercenary; venality.</def>  <rj><au>Boyle.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercenary</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ce*na*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mercenarie</ets>, F. <ets>mercenaire</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mercenarius</ets>, fr. <ets>merces</ets> wages, reward. See <er>Mercy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Acting for reward; serving for pay; paid; hired; hireling; venal; <as>as, <ex>mercenary</ex> soldiers</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>Moved primarily by considerations of pay or profit; greedy of gain; sordid; selfish.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For God forbid I should my papers blot<br/
With <qex>mercenary</qex> lines, with servile pen.</q> <rj><qau>Daniel.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Venal</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercenary</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ce*na*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mercenaries</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>One who is hired; a hireling; especially, a soldier hired into foreign service.</def>  <rj><au>Milman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercer</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"cer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mercier</ets>, fr. L. <ets>merx</ets>, <ets>mercis</ets>, wares, merchandise. See <er>Merchant</er>.]</ety> <def>Originally, a dealer in any kind of goods or wares; now restricted to a dealer in textile fabrics, as silks or woolens.</def> <mark>[Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercerize</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"cer*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>  <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>-ized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>-izing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From (John) <etsep>Mercer</etsep> (1791-1866), an English calico printer who introduced the process + <ets>-ize</ets>.]</ety> <def>To treat (cotton fiber or fabrics) with a solution of caustic alkali.  Such treatment causes the fiber to shrink in length and become stronger and more receptive of dyes. If the yarn or cloth is kept under tension during the process, it assumes a silky luster.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mer`cer*i*za"tion</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercership</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"cer*ship</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The business of a mercer.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercery</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"cer*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mercerie</ets>.]</ety> <def>The trade of mercers; the goods in which a mercer deals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merchand</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"chand</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>marchander</ets>. See <er>Merchant</er>.]</ety> <def>To traffic.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merchandisable</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"chan*di`sa*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Such as can be used or transferred as merchandise.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merchandise</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"chan*dise</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>marchandise</ets>, OF. <ets>marcheandise</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The objects of commerce; whatever is usually bought or sold in trade, or market, or by merchants; wares; goods; commodities.</def>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act or business of trading; trade; traffic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merchandise</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"chan*dise</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Merchandised</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Merchandising</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To trade; to carry on commerce.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merchandise</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"chan*dise</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make merchandise of; to buy and sell.</def> <ldquo/Love is <xex>merchandised</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merchandiser</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"chan*di`ser</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A trader.</def>  <rj><au>Bunyan.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>merchandising</ent><br/
<hw>mer"chan*dis`ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Commerce)</fld> <def>The activities associated with selling products, such as identification of the market{7}, advertising at the right time in the right media{7}, and creating attractive packaging and displays; also, the study of the best methods to accomplish such goals.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merchandry</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"chand*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Merchant</er>.]</ety> <def>Trade; commerce.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bp. Sanderson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merchant</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"chant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>marchant</ets>, OF. <ets>marcheant</ets>, F. <ets>marchand</ets>, fr. LL. <ets>mercatans</ets>, <ets>-antis</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>mercatare</ets> to negotiate, L. <ets>mercari</ets> to traffic, fr. <ets>merx</ets>, <ets>mercis</ets>, wares. See <er>Market</er>, <er>Merit</er>, and cf. <er>Commerce</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who traffics on a large scale, especially with foreign countries; a trafficker; a trader.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Others, like <qex>merchants</qex>, venture trade abroad.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A trading vessel; a merchantman.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One who keeps a store or shop for the sale of goods; a shopkeeper.</def> <mark>[U. S. & Scot.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merchant</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"chant</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of, pertaining to, or employed in, trade or merchandise; <as>as, the <ex>merchant</ex> service</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Merchant bar</b></col>, <col><b>Merchant iron</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Merchant steel</b></col></mcol>, <cd>certain common sizes of wrought iron and steel bars.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Merchant service</b> <it>or</it> <b>Merchant marine</b></col></mcol>, <cd>the mercantile marine of a country.</cd> <au>Am. Cyc.</au> -- <col><b>Merchant ship</b></col>, <cd>a ship employed in commerce.</cd> -- <col><b>Merchant tailor</b></col>, <cd>a tailor who keeps and sells materials for the garments which he makes.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merchant</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"chant</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be a merchant; to trade.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merchantable</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"chant*a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Fit for market; such as is usually sold in market, or such as will bring the ordinary price; <as>as, <ex>merchantable</ex> wheat</as>; sometimes, a technical designation for a particular kind or class.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merchantly</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"chant*ly</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Merchantlike; suitable to the character or business of a merchant.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Gauden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merchantman</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"chant*man</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Merchantmen</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A merchant.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Matt. xiii. 45.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A trading vessel; a ship employed in the transportation of goods, <as>as, distinguished from a man-of-war</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>merchant marine</ent><br/
<hw>mer"chant ma*rine"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The ships owned by nationals of a particular country that are engaged in civilian commerce; also, the personnel operating those vessels.  Distinguished from the <contr>navy</contr>, which contains the vessels of war.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>merchantry</ent><br/
<hw>mer"chant*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The body of merchants taken collectively; <as>as, the <ex>merchantry</ex> of a country</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The business of a merchant; merchandise.</def>  <rj><au>Walpole.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merciable</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ci*a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OF.]</ety> <def>Merciful.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merciful</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ci*ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mercy</ets> + <ets>-ful</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Full of mercy; having or exercising mercy; disposed to pity and spare offenders; unwilling to punish.  Opposite of <ant>merciless</ant>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Lord, the Lord God, <qex>merciful</qex> and gracious.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xxxiv. 6.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Be <qex>merciful</qex>, great duke, to men of mold.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Unwilling to give pain; compassionate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>merciful</qex> man will be <qex>merciful</qex> to his beast.</q> <rj><qau>Old Proverb.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Compassionate; tender; humane; gracious; kind; mild; clement; benignant.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Mer"ci*ful*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mer"ci*ful*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercify</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ci*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To pity.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merciless</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ci*less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Destitute of mercy; cruel; unsparing; -- said of animate beings, and also, figuratively, of things; <as>as, a <ex>merciless</ex> tyrant; <ex>merciless</ex> waves.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The foe is <qex>merciless</qex>, and will not pity.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Cruel; unmerciful; remorseless; ruthless; pitiless; barbarous; savage.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Mer"ci*less*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mer"ci*less*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercurammonium</ent><br/
<hw>Mer`cur*am*mo"ni*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mercur</ets>ic + <ets>ammonium</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A radical regarded as derived from ammonium by the substitution of mercury for a portion of the hydrogen.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercurial</ent><br/
<hw>Mer*cu"ri*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mercurialis</ets>, fr. <ets>Mercurius</ets> Mercury: cf. F. <ets>mercuriel</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having the qualities fabled to belong to the god <persfn>Mercury</persfn>; swift; active; sprightly; fickle; volatile; changeable; <as>as, a <ex>mercurial</ex> youth; a <ex>mercurial</ex> temperament.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>mercurial</qex> man<br/
Who fluttered over all things like a fan.</q> <rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Having the form or image of <persfn>Mercury</persfn>; -- applied to ancient guideposts.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chillingworth.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to <persfn>Mercury</persfn> as the god of trade; hence, money-making; crafty.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>mercurial</qex> wand of commerce.</q> <rj><qau>J. Q. Adams.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to, or containing, mercury; <as>as, <ex>mercurial</ex> preparations, barometer</as>. See <er>Mercury</er>, 2.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Caused by the use of mercury; <as>as, <ex>mercurial</ex> sore mouth</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercurial</ent><br/
<hw>Mer*cu"ri*al</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A person having mercurial qualities.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A preparation containing mercury.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mercurialism</ent><br/
<hw>mer*cu"ri*al*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>  <ety>[<ets>Mercurial</ets> + <ets>-ism</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>The syndrome produced by poisoning due to exposure to mercury, it fumes, or its compounds; <altname>mercury poisoning</altname>.  Such exposure may occur in mining or smelting, or in using mercurial compounds.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercurialist</ent><br/
<hw>Mer*cu"ri*al*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One under the influence of Mercury; one resembling Mercury in character.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A physician who uses much mercury, in any of its forms, in his practice.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercurialize</ent><br/
<hw>Mer*cu"ri*al*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mercurialized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mercurializing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>To affect with mercury.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Photography)</fld> <def>To treat with mercury; to expose to the vapor of mercury.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercurialize</ent><br/
<hw>Mer*cu"ri*al*ize</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be sprightly, fantastic, or capricious.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercurially</ent><br/
<hw>Mer*cu"ri*al*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a mercurial manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercuric</ent><br/
<hw>Mer*cu"ric</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or derived from, mercury; containing mercury; -- said of those compounds of mercury into which this element enters in its lowest proportion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mercuric chloride</b></col>, <cd>corrosive sublimate. See <er>mercury bichloride</er> and <er>Corrosive</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercurification</ent><br/
<hw>Mer*cu`ri*fi*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mercurification</ets>. See <er>Mercurify</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Metal.)</fld> <def>The process or operation of obtaining the mercury, in its fluid form, from mercuric minerals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>The act or process of compounding, or the state of being compounded, with mercury.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercurify</ent><br/
<hw>Mer*cu"ri*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mercurified</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mercurifying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[<ets>Mercury</ets> + <ets>-fy</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To obtain mercury from, as mercuric minerals, which may be done by any application of intense heat that expels the mercury in fumes, which are afterward condensed.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To combine or mingle mercury with; to impregnate with mercury; to mercurialize.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercurism</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"cu*rism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A communication of news; an announcement.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercurous</ent><br/
<hw>Mer*cu"rous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or derived from, mercury; containing mercury; -- said of those compounds of mercury in which it is present in its highest proportion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mercurous chloride</b></col>. <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Calomel</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercury</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"cu*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>Mercurius</ets>; akin to <ets>merx</ets> wares.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Rom. Myth.)</fld> <def>A Latin god of commerce and gain; -- treated by the poets as identical with the Greek <persfn>Hermes</persfn>, messenger of the gods, conductor of souls to the lower world, and god of eloquence.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A metallic element mostly obtained by reduction from cinnabar, one of its ores.  It is a heavy, opaque, glistening liquid (commonly called <altname>quicksilver</altname>), and is used in barometers, thermometers, etc.  Specific gravity 13.6.  Symbol Hg (<it>Hydrargyrum</it>).  Atomic weight 199.8.  Mercury has a molecule which consists of only one atom.  It was named by the alchemists after the god Mercury, and designated by his symbol, <Mercury/.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Mercury forms alloys, called <xex>amalgams</xex>, with many metals, and is thus used in applying tin foil to the backs of mirrors, and in extracting gold and silver from their ores.  It is poisonous, and is used in medicine in the free state as in blue pill, and in its compounds as calomel, corrosive sublimate, etc.  It is the only metal which is liquid at ordinary temperatures, and it solidifies at about -39<deg/ Centigrade to a soft, malleable, ductile metal.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>One of the planets of the solar system, being the one nearest the sun, from which its mean distance is about 36,000,000 miles. Its period is 88 days, and its diameter 3,000 miles.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A carrier of tidings; a newsboy; a messenger; hence, also, a newspaper.</def> <au>Sir J. Stephen.</au> <ldquo/The monthly <xex>Mercuries</xex>.<rdquo/ <au>Macaulay.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Sprightly or mercurial quality; spirit; mutability; fickleness.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was so full of <qex>mercury</qex> that he could not fix long in any friendship, or to any design.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Burnet.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A plant (<spn>Mercurialis annua</spn>), of the Spurge family, the leaves of which are sometimes used for spinach, in Europe.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The name is also applied, in the United States, to certain climbing plants, some of which are poisonous to the skin, esp. to the <spn>Rhus Toxicodendron</spn>, or poison ivy.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Dog's mercury</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd><spn>Mercurialis perennis</spn>, a perennial plant differing from <spn>Mercurialis annua</spn> by having the leaves sessile.</cd> -- <col><b>English mercury</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a kind of goosefoot formerly used as a pot herb; -- called <altname>Good King Henry</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Horn mercury</b></col> <fld>(Min.)</fld>, <cd>a mineral chloride of mercury, having a semitranslucent, hornlike appearance.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercury</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"cu*ry</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To wash with a preparation of mercury.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mercury bichloride</ent><br/
<hw>mercury bichloride</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the compound (<chform>HgCl2</chform>) consisting of two atoms of chlorine united with one atom of mercury.   Also called <altname>bichloride of mercury</altname>, <altname>mercuric chloride</altname>, <altname>corrosive sublimate</altname>, and <altname>mercury perchloride</altname>.  It is used as <ldquo/a topical antiseptic and disinfectant for inanimate objects<rdquo/.</def> <au>Stedman's 25th</au><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mercury fulminate</ent><br/
<hw>mer"cu*ry ful"mi*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>The mercury salt of fulminic acid (<chform>Hg(CNO)2</chform>), called also <altname>fulminate of mercury</altname>.  It is an explosive compound prepared as gray crystals, and is used primarily in detonators for detonating high explosives, such as dynamite or TNT.  It is sensitive to shock and may be detonated by a blow.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mercy</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"cy</hw> <pr>(m<etil/r"s<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mercies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>merci</ets>, F. <ets>merci</ets>, L. <ets>merces</ets>, <ets>mercedis</ets>, hire, pay, reward, LL., equiv. to <ets>misericordia</ets> pity, mercy. L. <ets>merces</ets> is probably akin to <ets>merere</ets> to deserve, acquire. See <er>Merit</er>, and cf. <er>Amerce</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Forbearance to inflict harm under circumstances of provocation, when one has the power to inflict it; compassionate treatment of an offender or adversary; clemency.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Examples of justice must be made for terror to some; examples of <qex>mercy</qex> for comfort to others.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Compassionate treatment of the unfortunate and helpless; sometimes, favor, beneficence.</def>  <rj><au>Luke x. 37.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Disposition to exercise compassion or favor; pity; compassion; willingness to spare or to help.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In whom <qex>mercy</qex> lacketh and is not founden.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. Elyot.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A blessing regarded as a manifestation of compassion or favor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Father of <qex>mercies</qex> and the God of all comfort.</q> <rj><qau>2 Cor. i. 3.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mercy seat</b></col> <fld>(Bib.)</fld>, <cd>the golden cover or lid of the Ark of the Covenant. See <er>Ark</er>, 2.</cd> -- <col><b>Sisters of Mercy</b></col> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld>,<cd>a religious order founded in Dublin in the year 1827.  Communities of the same name have since been established in various American cities.  The duties of those belonging to the order are, to attend lying-in hospitals, to superintend the education of girls, and protect decent women out of employment, to visit prisoners and the sick, and to attend persons condemned to death.</cd> -- <col><b>To be at the mercy of</b></col>, <cd>to be wholly in the power of.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Grace</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merd</ent><br/
<hw>Merd</hw> <pr>(m<etil/rd)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>merde</ets>, L. <ets>merda</ets>.]</ety> <def>Ordure; dung.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Burton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>-mere</ent><br/
<hw>-mere</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[Gr. <?/ part.]</ety> <def>A combining form meaning <xex>part</xex>, <xex>portion</xex>; <as>as, blasto<ex>mere</ex>, epi<ex>mere</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mere</ent><br/
<hw>Mere</hw> <pr>(m<emac/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Written also <ets>mar</ets>.]</ety> <ety>[OE. <ets>mere</ets>, AS. <ets>mere</ets> mere, sea; akin to D. <ets>meer</ets> lake, OS. <ets>meri</ets> sea, OHG. <ets>meri</ets>, <ets>mari</ets>, G. <ets>meer</ets>, Icel. <ets>marr</ets>, Goth. <ets>marei</ets>, Russ. <ets>more</ets>, W. <ets>mor</ets>, Ir. & Gael. <ets>muir</ets>, L. <ets>mare</ets>, and perh. to L. <ets>mori</ets> to die, and meaning originally, that which is dead, a waste.  Cf. <er>Mortal</er>, <er>Marine</er>, <er>Marsh</er>, <er>Mermaid</er>, <er>Moor</er>.]</ety> <def>A pool or lake.</def>  <rj><au>Drayton.</au>  <au>Tennyson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mere</ent><br/
<hw>Mere</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Written also <ets>meer</ets> and <ets>mear</ets>.]</ety> <ety>[AS. <ets>gem<aemac/re</ets>. <root/269.]</ety> <def>A boundary.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 914 --></p>

<p><ent>Mere</ent><br/
<hw>Mere</hw> <pr>(m<emac/r)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To divide, limit, or bound.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Which <qex>meared</qex> her rule with Africa.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mere</ent><br/
<hw>Mere</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mare.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mere</ent><br/
<hw>Mere</hw> <pr>(m<emac/r)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Superl.</pos> <adjf>Merest</adjf>. The comparative is rarely or never used.]</amorph> <ety>[L. <ets>merus</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Unmixed; pure; entire; absolute; unqualified.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then entered they the <qex>mere</qex>, main sea.</q> <rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sorrows of this world would be <qex>mere</qex> and unmixed.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Only this, and nothing else; such, and no more; simple; bare; <as>as, a <ex>mere</ex> boy; a <ex>mere</ex> form.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From <qex>mere</qex> success nothing can be concluded in favor of any nation.</q> <rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merely</ent><br/
<hw>Mere"ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Purely; unmixedly; absolutely.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ulysses was to force forth his access,<br/
Though <qex>merely</qex> naked.</q> <rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Not otherwise than; simply; barely; only.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Prize not your life for other ends<br/
Than <qex>merely</qex> to oblige your friends.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Solely; simply; purely; barely; scarcely.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merenchyma</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*ren"chy*ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ a part + <ets>-enchyma</ets>, as in <ets>parenchyma</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Tissue composed of spheroidal cells.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meresman</ent><br/
<hw>Meres"man</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An officer who ascertains meres or boundaries.</def> <mark>[Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merestead</ent><br/
<hw>Mere"stead</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mere</ets> boundary + <ets>stead</ets> place.]</ety> <def>The land within the boundaries of a farm; a farmstead or farm.</def> <mark>[Archaic.]</mark>  <rj><au>Longfellow.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merestone</ent><br/
<hw>Mere"stone`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A stone designating a limit or boundary; a landmark.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meretricious</ent><br/
<hw>Mer`e*tri"cious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>meretricius</ets>, from <ets>meretrix</ets>, <ets>-icis</ets>, a prostitute, lit., one who earns money, <it>i. e.</it>, by prostitution, fr. <ets>merere</ets> to earn, gain. See <er>Merit</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to prostitutes; having to do with harlots; lustful; <as>as, <ex>meretricious</ex> traffic</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Resembling the arts of a harlot; alluring by false show; gaudily and deceitfully ornamental; tawdry; <as>as, <ex>meretricious</ex> dress or ornaments</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Deceptive or based on deception; seeming plausible, but based on pretense or insincerity; deceptive; misleading; insincere; specious; <as>as, <ex>meretricious</ex> arguments</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Mer`e*tri"cious*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mer`e*tri"cious*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>meretriciousness</ent><br/
<hw>mer`e*tri"cious*ness</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>an appearance of truth that is false or deceptive; seeming plausibility.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> speciousness.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>tasteless showiness.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> flashiness, garishness, gaudiness, loudness, tawdriness, glitz.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merganser</ent><br/
<hw>Mer*gan"ser</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>merg<aacute/nsar</ets>, fr. <ets>mergo</ets> a diver (L. <ets>mergus</ets>, fr. <ets>mergere</ets> to dip, dive) + <ets><aacute/nsar</ets> goose, L. <ets>anser</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any bird of the genus <gen>Mergus</gen> (<gen>Merganser</gen>), and allied genera of the subfamily <subfam>Merginae</subfam>.  They are allied to the ducks, but have a sharply serrated bill, eat fish, and dive for food.  Also called <altname>fish duck</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The red-breasted merganser (<spn>Merganser serrator</spn>) inhabits both hemispheres. It is called also <altname>sawbill</altname>, <altname>harle</altname>, and <altname>sheldrake</altname>.  The American merganser (<spn>Merganser Americanus</spn>.) and the hooded merganser (<spn>Lophodytes cucullatus</spn>) are well-known species.</note> -- <cs><col><b>White merganser</b></col>, <cd>the smew or white nun.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>merge</ent><br/
<hw>merge</hw> <pr>(m<etil/rj)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Merged</conjf> <pr>(m<etil/rjd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Merging</conjf> <pr>(m<etil/r"j<icr/ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>mergere</ets>, <ets>mersum</ets>.  Cf. <er>Emerge</er>, <er>Immerse</er>, <er>Marrow</er>.]</ety> <def>To cause to be swallowed up; to immerse; to sink; to absorb.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>merge</qex> all natural . . . sentiment in inordinate vanity.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whig and Tory were <qex>merged</qex> and swallowed up in the transcendent duties of patriots.</q> <rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merge</ent><br/
<hw>Merge</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be sunk, swallowed up, or lost.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Native irresolution had <qex>merged</qex> in stronger motives.</q> <rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>merged</ent><br/
<hw>merged</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>formed or united into a whole; -- of formerly separate objects, groups, etc.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> incorporate, incorporated, integrated, unified.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merger</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ger</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, merges.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>An absorption of one estate, or one contract, in another, or of a minor offense in a greater.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The combining of two groups into a unified single group under a single leadership, with voluntary participation by the leaders or management of both groups.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <fld>(Business, Finance)</fld> <def>The combining of two commercial enterprises into a unified single enterprise under a single management, with voluntary participation by both parties; <as>as, the <ex>merger</ex> of <corpn>Daimler-Benz</corpn> and <corpn>Chrysler</corpn> into <corpn>Daimler-Chrysler</corpn> created a powerful competitor in the automobile manufacturing industry</as>.  Compare <contr>acquisition</contr> and <contr>takeover</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>merging</ent><br/
<hw>merging</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>  <def>combining or mixing.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> blending, mingling.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>flowing together.</def> <mark>[prenominal]</mark><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> confluent.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>merging</ent><br/
<hw>merging</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or process of joining together into one entity.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> meeting, coming together.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>a flowing together (as of rivers).</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> confluence, conflux.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mergus</ent><br/
<hw>Mergus</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of ducks consisting of mergansers.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Mergus</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mericarp</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"i*carp</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`ros</grk> a part + <grk>karpo`s</grk> fruit.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>One carpel of an umbelliferous fruit. See <er>Cremocarp</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meride</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ide</hw> <pr>(? <or/ ?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ a part.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>A permanent colony of cells or plastids which may remain isolated, like Rotifer, or may multiply by gemmation to form higher aggregates, termed <xex>zoides</xex>.</def>  <rj><au>Perrier.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meridian</ent><br/
<hw>Me*rid"i*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/ridien</ets>, L. <ets>meridianus</ets> pertaining to noon, fr. <ets>meridies</ets> noon, midday, for older <ets>medidies</ets>; <ets>medius</ets> mid, middle + <ets>dies</ets> day. See <er>Mid</er>, and <er>Diurnal</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Being at, or pertaining to, midday; belonging to, or passing through, the highest point attained by the sun in his diurnal course.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Meridian</xex> hour.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tables . . . to find the altitude <qex>meridian</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Pertaining to the highest point or culmination; <as>as, <ex>meridian</ex> splendor</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meridian</ent><br/
<hw>Me*rid"i*an</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/ridien</ets>. See <er>Meridian</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Midday; noon.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence: The highest point, as of success, prosperity, or the like; culmination.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have touched the highest point of all my greatness,<br/
And from that full <qex>meridian</qex> of my glory<br/
I haste now to my setting.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>A great circle of the sphere passing through the poles of the heavens and the zenith of a given place. It is crossed by the sun at midday.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Geog.)</fld> <def>A great circle on the surface of the earth, passing through the poles and any given place; also, the half of such a circle included between the poles.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The planes of the geographical and astronomical meridians coincide. Meridians, on a map or globe, are lines drawn at certain intervals due north and south, or in the direction of the poles.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Calculated for the meridian of</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>fitted to the meridian of</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>adapted to the meridian of</b></col></mcol>, <cd>suited to the local circumstances, capabilities, or special requirements of.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All other knowledge merely serves the concerns of this life, and is <qex>fitted to the meridian</qex> there<qex>of</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir M. Hale.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <cs><mcol><col><b>First meridian</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>prime meridian</b></col></mcol>, <cd>the meridian from which longitudes are reckoned.   The meridian of Greenwich is the one commonly employed in calculations of longitude by geographers, and in actual practice, although in various countries other and different meridians, chiefly those which pass through the capitals of the countries, are occasionally used; as, in France, the meridian of Paris; in the United States, the meridian of Washington, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Guide meridian</b></col> <fld>(Public Land Survey)</fld>, <cd>a line, marked by monuments, running North and South through a section of country between other more carefully established meridians called <xex>principal meridians</xex>, used for reference in surveying.</cd> <mark>[U.S.]</mark> -- <col><b>Magnetic meridian</b></col>, <cd>a great circle, passing through the zenith and coinciding in direction with the magnetic needle, or a line on the earth's surface having the same direction.</cd> -- <col><b>Meridian circle</b></col> <fld>(Astron.)</fld>, <cd>an instrument consisting of a telescope attached to a large graduated circle and so mounted that the telescope revolves like the transit instrument in a meridian plane. By it the right ascension and the declination of a star may be measured in a single observation.</cd> -- <col><b>Meridian instrument</b></col> <fld>(Astron.)</fld>, <cd>any astronomical instrument having a telescope that rotates in a meridian plane.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Meridian of a globe</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Brass meridian</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a graduated circular ring of brass, in which the artificial globe is suspended and revolves.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meridional</ent><br/
<hw>Me*rid"i*o*nal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/ridional</ets>, L. <ets>meridionalis</ets>, fr. <ets>meridies</ets> midday. See <er>Meridian</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the meridian.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Having a southern aspect; southern; southerly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Offices that require heat . . . should be <qex>meridional</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir H. Wotton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Meridional distance</b></col>, <cd>the distance or departure from the meridian; the easting or westing.</cd> -- <col><b>Meridional parts</b></col>, <cd>parts of the meridian in Mercator's projection, corresponding to each minute of latitude from the equator up to 70 or 80 degrees; tabulated numbers representing these parts used in projecting charts, and in solving cases in Mercator's sailing.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meridionality</ent><br/
<hw>Me*rid`i*o*nal"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The state of being in the meridian.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Position in the south; aspect toward the south.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meridionally</ent><br/
<hw>Me*rid"i*o*nal*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In the direction of the meridian.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merils</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ils</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/relle</ets>, <ets>marelle</ets>, <ets>marelles</ets>, LL. <ets>marella</ets>, <ets>marrella</ets>.  Cf. <er>Morris</er> the game.]</ety> <def>A boy's play, called also <altname>fivepenny morris</altname>. See <er>Morris</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meringue</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me`ringue"</hw> <pr>(F. m<etil/`r<acr/N"g'; E. m<ecr/*r<acr/ng")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>A delicate pastry made of powdered sugar and the whites of eggs whipped up, -- with jam or cream added.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merino</ent><br/
<hw>Me*ri"no</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>merino</ets> moving from pasture to pasture, fr. <ets>merino</ets> a royal judge and superintendent or inspector of sheep walks, LL. <ets>merinus</ets>, fr. <ets>majorinus</ets>, i. e., major vill<?/, fr. L. <ets>major</ets> greater. See <er>Major</er>. Merino sheep are driven at certain seasons from one part of Spain to another, in large flocks, for pasturage.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a variety of sheep with very fine wool, originally bred in Spain.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Made of the wool of the merino sheep.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merino</ent><br/
<hw>Me*ri"no</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Merinos</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Sp.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A breed of sheep originally from Spain, noted for the fineness of its wool.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A fine fabric of merino wool.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merismatic</ent><br/
<hw>Mer`is*mat"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ division, fr. <?/ part.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Dividing into cells or segments; characterized by separation into two or more parts or sections by the formation of internal partitions; <as>as, <ex>merismatic</ex> growth, where one cell divides into many</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meristem</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"i*stem</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ divisible.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A tissue of growing cells, or cells capable of further division.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merit</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"it</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/rite</ets>, L. <ets>meritum</ets>, fr. <ets>merere</ets>, <ets>mereri</ets>, to deserve, merit; prob. originally, to get a share; akin to Gr. <?/ part, <?/ fate, doom, <?/ to receive as one's portion.  Cf. <er>Market</er>, <er>Merchant</er>, <er>Mercer</er>, <er>Mercy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality or state of deserving well or ill; desert.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here may men see how sin hath his <qex>merit</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Be it known, that we, the greatest, are misthought<br/
For things that others do; and when we fall,<br/
We answer other's <qex>merits</qex> in our name.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Esp. in a good sense:</specif> <def>The quality or state of deserving well; worth; excellence.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Reputation is . . . oft got without <qex>merit</qex>, and lost without deserving.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To him the wit of Greece and Rome was known,<br/
And every author's <qex>merit</qex>, but his own.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Reward deserved; any mark or token of excellence or approbation; <as>as, his teacher gave him ten <ex>merits</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those laurel groves, the <qex>merits</qex> of thy youth.</q> <rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merit</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"it</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Merited</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Meriting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/riter</ets>, L. <ets>meritare</ets>, v. intens. fr. <ets>merere</ets>. See <er>Merit</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To earn by service or performance; to have a right to claim as reward; to deserve; sometimes, to deserve in a bad sense; <as>as, to <ex>merit</ex> punishment</as>.</def> <ldquo/This kindness <xex>merits</xex> thanks.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To reward.</def> <mark>[R. & Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chapman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merit</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"it</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To acquire desert; to gain value; to receive benefit; to profit.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meritable</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"it*a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Deserving of reward.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meritedly</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"it*ed*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>By merit; deservedly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merithallus</ent><br/
<ent>Merithal</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mer"i*thal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, \'d8<hw>Mer`i*thal"lus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. <ets>merithallus</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/, <ets>or</ets> <?/, a part + <?/ a young shoot.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Internode</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meritmonger</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"it*mon`ger</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who depends on merit for salvation.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Milner.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>meritocracy</ent><br/
<hw>meritocracy</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A form of social system in which power goes to those with superior intellects.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The belief that rulers should be chosen for their superior abilities and not because of their wealth or birth.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>meritocratic</ent><br/
<hw>meritocratic</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>Of or pertaining to meritocracy; <as>as, <ex>meritocratic</ex> society</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meritorious</ent><br/
<hw>Mer`i*to"ri*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>meritorius</ets> that brings in money.]</ety> <def>Possessing merit; deserving of reward or honor; worthy of recompense; valuable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>meritorious</qex> shall that hand be called,<br/
Canonized, and worshiped as a saint.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Mer`i*to"ri*ous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mer`i*to"ri*ous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meritory</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"i*to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Meritorious.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meritot</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"i*tot</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A play of children, in swinging on ropes, or the like, till they are dizzy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merk</ent><br/
<hw>Merk</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Marc</er>.]</ety> <def>An old Scotch silver coin; a mark or marc.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merk</ent><br/
<hw>Merk</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mark; a sign.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merke</ent><br/
<hw>Merke</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Murky.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Piers Plowman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>merkin</ent><br/
<hw>mer"kin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Originally, a wig; afterwards, a mop for cleaning cannon.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A patch of false hair, or something resembling hair, worn on a string over the female pudenda; -- used by stripteasers.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The hair on the female pubic area.</def> <mark>[slang]</mark> <br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merle</ent><br/
<ent>Merl</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Merl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Merle</hw>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>merle</ets>, L. <ets>merula</ets>, <ets>merulus</ets>.  Cf. <er>Ousel</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The European blackbird. See <er>Blackbird</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Drayton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merlin</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"lin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>merlion</ets>, F. <ets><eacute/merillon</ets> ; cf. OHG. <ets>smirl</ets>, G. <ets>schmerl</ets> ; prob. fr. L. <ets>merula</ets> blackbird.  Cf. <er>Merle</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A small European falcon (<spn>Falco columbarius</spn>, syn. <spn>Falco lithofalco</spn>, or <spn>Falco aesalon</spn>).  In North America called also <altname>pigeon hawk</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>  <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merling</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ling</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The European whiting.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merlon</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"lon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., perh. fr. L. <ets>moerus</ets>, for <ets>murus</ets> a wall, through (assumed) dim. <ets>moerulus</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Fort.)</fld> <def>One of the solid parts of a battlemented parapet; a battlement. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Battlement</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merluce</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"luce</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>merluche</ets>, <ets>merlus</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The European hake; -- called also <altname>herring hake</altname> and <altname>sea pike</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mermaid</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"maid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>mere</ets> lake, sea. See <er>Mere</er> lake, and <er>maid</er>.]</ety> <def>A fabled marine creature, typically represented as having the upper part like that of a woman, and the lower like a fish; a sea nymph, sea woman, or woman fish.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Chaucer uses this word as equivalent to the <xex>siren</xex> of the ancients.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mermaid fish</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>the angel fish (<gen>Squatina</gen>).</cd> -- <col><b>Mermaid's glove</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a British branched sponge somewhat resembling a glove.</cd> -- <col><b>Mermaid's head</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a European spatangoid sea urchin (<spn>Echinocardium cordatum</spn>) having some resemblance to a skull.</cd> -- <col><b>Mermaid weed</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>an aquatic herb with dentate or pectinate leaves (<spn>Proserpinaca palustris</spn> and <spn>Proserpinaca pectinacea</spn>).</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merman</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"man</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mermen</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>The male corresponding to <contr>mermaid</contr>; a sea man, or man fish.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mero cabrolla</ent><br/
<ent>Mero de lo alto</ent><br/
<ent>Mero</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me"ro</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp.; cf. Pg. <ets>mero</ets>.]</ety> <def>Any of several large groupers of warm seas, esp. the guasa (<spn>Epinephelus guaza</spn>), the red grouper (<spn>Epinephelus morio</spn>), the black grouper (<spn>Epinephelus nigritas</spn>), distinguished as <styp><hw>Me"ro de lo al"to</hw></styp> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, and a species called also <stype>rock hind</stype>, distinguished as <styp><hw>Me"ro ca*brol"la</hw></styp> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meroblast</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"o*blast</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`ros</grk> part + <ets>-blast</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>An ovum, as that of a mammal, only partially composed of germinal matter, that is, consisting of both a germinal portion and an albuminous or nutritive one; -- opposed to <contr>holoblast</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meroblastic</ent><br/
<hw>Mer`o*blas"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Consisting only in part of germinal matter; characterized by partial segmentation only; <as>as, <ex>meroblastic</ex> ova, in which a portion of the yolk only undergoes fission; <ex>meroblastic</ex> segmentation; -- opposed to <ex>holoblastic</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merocele</ent><br/
<hw>Me"ro*cele</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mhro`s</grk> thigh + <?/ tumor.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Hernia in the thigh; femoral hernia .</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meroistic</ent><br/
<hw>Mer`o*is"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`ros</grk> part + <?/ an egg.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Applied to the ovaries of insects when they secrete vitelligenous cells, as well as ova.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meropidan</ent><br/
<hw>Me*rop"i*dan</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>merops</ets> a bee-eating bird, Gr. <grk>me`rops</grk>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of a family of birds (<fam>Meropidae</fam>), including the bee-eaters.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meropodite</ent><br/
<hw>Me*rop"o*dite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`ros</grk> thigh + <grk>poy`s</grk>, <grk>podo`s</grk>, foot.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The fourth joint of a typical appendage of Crustacea.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merorganization</ent><br/
<hw>Mer*or`gan*i*za"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`ros</grk> part + E. <ets>organization</ets>.]</ety> <def>Organization in part.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meros</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me"ros</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., from Gr. <grk>me`ros</grk> part.]</ety> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>The plain surface between the channels of a triglyph.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>merus</asp>.]</altsp>  <rj><au>Weale.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meros</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me"ros</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`ros</grk> the thigh.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The proximal segment of the hind limb; the thigh.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merosome</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"o*some</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`ros</grk> part + <ets>-some</ets> body.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the serial segments, or metameres, of which the bodies of vertebrate and articulate animals are composed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merostomata</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mer`o*stom"a*ta</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`ros</grk> thigh + <?/, -<?/, mouth.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A class of <phylum>Arthropoda</phylum>, allied to the <class>Crustacea</class>.  It includes the trilobites, <ord>Eurypteroidea</ord>, and <ord>Limuloidea</ord>.  All are extinct except the horseshoe crabs (<gen>Limulus</gen>) of the last group. See <er>Limulus</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merou</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>M<eacute/`rou"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Jack</er>, 8 <sd>(c)</sd>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merovingian</ent><br/
<hw>Mer`o*vin"gi*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <persfn><etsep>Merovaeus</etsep></persfn>, the Latin name of a king of the Franks.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to the first Frankish dynasty in Gaul or France.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>One of the kings of this dynasty.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merozoite</ent><br/
<hw>Mer`o*zo"ite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`ros</grk> part + Sporo<ets>zoa</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A form of spore, usually elongate or falciform, and somewhat amoeboid, produced by segmentation of the schizonts of certain Sporozoa, as the malaria parasite.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merrily</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ri*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Merry</er>.]</ety> <def>In a merry manner; with mirth; with gayety and laughter; jovially. See <er>Mirth</er>, and <er>Merry</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Merrily</qex> sing, and sport, and play.</q> <rj><qau>Granville.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merrimake</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ri*make`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Merrymake</er>, <pos>n.</pos></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merrimake</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ri*make`</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>See <er>Merrymake</er>, <pos>v.</pos></def>  <rj><au>Gay.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merriment</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ri*ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Gayety, with laughter; mirth; frolic.</def> <ldquo/Follies and light <xex>merriment</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Methought it was the sound<br/
Of riot and ill-managed <qex>merriment</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merriness</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ri*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being merry; merriment; mirth; gayety, with laughter.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merry</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Merrier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Merriest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>merie</ets>, <ets>mirie</ets>, <ets>murie</ets>, merry, pleasant, AS. <ets>merge</ets>, <ets>myrige</ets>, pleasant; cf. <ets>murge</ets>, adv.; prob. akin to OHG. <ets>murg</ets>, short, Goth. <ets>gama<uacute/rgjan</ets> to shorten; cf. L. <ets>murcus</ets> a coward, who cuts off his thumb to escape military service; the Anglo-Saxon and English meanings coming from the idea of making the time seem short.  Cf. <er>Mirth</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Laughingly gay; overflowing with good humor and good spirits; jovial; inclined to laughter or play; sportive.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They drank, and were <qex>merry</qex> with him.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. xliii. 34.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am never <qex>merry</qex> when I hear sweet music.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 915 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Cheerful; joyous; not sad; happy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Is any <qex>merry</qex>? let him sing psalms.</q> <rj><qau>Jas. v. 13.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Causing laughter, mirth, gladness, or delight; <as>as, a <ex>merry</ex> jest</as>.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Merry</xex> wind and weather.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Merry dancers</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Dancer</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Merry men</b></col>, <cd>followers; retainers.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His <qex>merie men</qex> commanded he<br/
To make him bothe game and glee.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <col><b>To make merry</b></col>, <cd>to be jovial; to indulge in hilarity; to feast with mirth.</cd> <au>Judg. ix. 27.</au></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Cheerful; blithe; lively; sprightly; vivacious; gleeful; joyous; mirthful; jocund; sportive; hilarious.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merry</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ry</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/r"r<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A kind of wild red cherry.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merry-andrew</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ry-an"drew</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/r"r<ycr/-<acr/n"dr<udd/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One whose business is to make sport for others; a buffoon; a zany; especially, one who attends a mountebank or quack doctor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ This term is said to have originated from one <person>Andrew Borde</person>, an English physician of the 16th century, who gained patients by facetious speeches to the multitude.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merry-go-round</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ry-go`-round"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Any revolving contrivance for affording amusement; esp., a group of seats in the shape of hobbyhorses or other fanciful animals, arranged in a circle on a platform that is rotated by a mechanical drive, often to the accompaniment of music; the seats often move up and down in synchrony with the rotation; -- called also <altname>carousel</altname>.  It is employed primarily for the amusement of children, and is typically found at an amusement park.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merrymake</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ry*make`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mirth; frolic; a meeting for mirth; a festival.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>merrimake</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merrymake</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ry*make`</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make merry; to be jolly; to feast.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>merrimake</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merrymaker</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ry*mak`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who makes merriment or indulges in conviviality; a jovial comrade.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merrymaking</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ry*mak`ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Making or producing mirth; convivial; jolly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merrymaking</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ry*mak`ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of making merry; conviviality; merriment; jollity.</def>  <rj><au>Wordsworth.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merrymeeting</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ry*meet`ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A meeting for mirth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merrythought</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"ry*thought`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The forked bone of a fowl's breast; -- called also <altname>wishbone</altname>. See <er>Furculum</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ It is a sportive custom for two persons to break this bone by pulling the ends apart to see who will get the longer piece, the securing of which is regarded as a lucky omen, signifying that the person holding it will obtain the gratification of some secret wish.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mersion</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mersio</ets>. See <er>Merge</er>.]</ety> <def>Immersion.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Barrow.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merulidan</ent><br/
<hw>Me*ru"li*dan</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>merula</ets>, <ets>merulus</ets>, blackbird. See <er>Merle</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A bird of the Thrush family.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me"rus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL.]</ety> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>See <er>Meros</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mervaille</ent><br/
<hw>Mer"vaille`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Marvel.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mes-</ent><br/
<hw>Mes-</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/s-)</pr>. <def>See <er>Meso-</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mesa</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>me"sa</hw> <pr>(m<asl/"s<adot/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp.]</ety> <def>A high tableland; a plateau on a hill.</def> <mark>[Southwestern U.S.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bartlett.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesaconate</ent><br/
<hw>Mes*ac"o*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of mesaconic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesaconic</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`a*con"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mes-</ets> + <ets>-aconic</ets>, as in <ets>citraconic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or designating, one of several isomeric acids obtained from citric acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mesad</ent><br/
<hw>mes"ad</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/s"<acr/d)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Same as <er>mesiad</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mesal</ent><br/
<hw>mes"al</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/s"<ait/l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Mesial</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesalliance</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>M<eacute/`sal`li`ance"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>A marriage with a person of inferior social position; a misalliance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mesally</ent><br/
<hw>mes"al*ly</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/s"<ait/l*l<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Mesially</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesamoeboid</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`a*m<oe/"boid</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/s`<adot/*m<emac/"boid)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mes-</ets> + <ets>am<oe/boid</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>One of a class of independent, isolated cells found in the mesoderm, while the germ layers are undergoing differentiation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesaraic</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`a*ra"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mesa`raion</grk> mesentery; <grk>me`sos</grk> middle + <grk>'araia`</grk> flank.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Mesenteric.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesaticephalic</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`a*ti*ce*phal"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <ets><?/</ets> midmost + E. <ets>cephalic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Having the ratio of the length to the breadth of the cranium a medium one; neither brachycephalic nor dolichocephalic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesaticephalous</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`a*ti*ceph"a*lous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Mesaticephalic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mescal</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes*cal"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp.]</ety> <def>A distilled liquor prepared in Mexico from a species of agave. See <er>Agave</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesdames</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`dames"</hw> <pr>(F. ?, E. ?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>, <def><pos>pl.</pos> of <er>Madame</er> and <er>Madam</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meseems</ent><br/
<hw>Me*seems"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. impers.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Meseemed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>It seems to me.</def> <mark>[Poetic]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesel</ent><br/
<hw>Me"sel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Measle</er>.]</ety> <def>A leper.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meselry</ent><br/
<hw>Me"sel*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Leprosy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesembryanthemum</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*sem`bry*an"the*mum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>meshmbri`a</grk> midday + <grk>'a`nqos</grk> flower.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of herbaceous or suffruticose plants, chiefly natives of South Africa.  The leaves are opposite, thick, and fleshy.  The flowers usually open about midday, whence the name.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesencephalic</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`en*ce*phal"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the mesencephalon or midbrain.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesencephalon</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`en*ceph"a*lon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Meso-</er> and <er>Encephalon</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The middle segment of the brain; the midbrain.  Sometimes abbreviated to <altname>mesen</altname>. See <er>Brain</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesenchyma</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes*en"chy*ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`sos</grk> middle + <ets>-enchyma</ets>, as in E. <ets>parenchyma</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The part of the mesoblast which gives rise to the connective tissues and blood.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesenteric</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`en*ter"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/sent<eacute/rique</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to a mesentery; mesaraic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesenteron</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes*en"te*ron</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Meso-</er>, and <er>Enteron</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>All that part of the alimentary canal which is developed from the primitive enteron and is lined with hypoblast. It is distinguished from the <xex>stomodaeum</xex>, a part at the anterior end of the canal, including the cavity of the mouth, and the <xex>proctodaeum</xex>, a part at the posterior end, which are formed by invagination and are lined with epiblast.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesentery</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"en*ter*y</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mesente`rion</grk>, <grk>me`sos</grk> + <grk>'e`nteron</grk> intestine: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/sent<egrave/re</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The membranes, or one of the membranes (consisting of a fold of the peritoneum and inclosed tissues), which connect the intestines and their appendages with the dorsal wall of the abdominal cavity. The mesentery proper is connected with the jejunum and ilium, the other mesenteries being called <xex>mesocaecum</xex>, <xex>mesocolon</xex>, <xex>mesorectum</xex>, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the vertical muscular radiating partitions which divide the body cavity of Anthozoa into chambers.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meseraic</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`e*ra"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Mesaraic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesethmoid</ent><br/
<hw>Mes*eth"moid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mes-</ets> + <ets>ethmoid</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the middle of the ethmoid region or ethmoid bone.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The median vertical plate, or median element, of the ethmoid bone.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesh</ent><br/
<hw>Mesh</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/sh)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>masc</ets>, <ets>max</ets>, <ets>m<ae/scre</ets>; akin to D. <ets>maas</ets>, <ets>masche</ets>, OHG. <ets>masca</ets>, Icel. <ets>m<oum/skvi</ets>; cf. Lith. <ets>mazgas</ets> a knot, <ets>megsti</ets> to weave nets, to knot.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The opening or space inclosed by the threads of a net between knot and knot, or the threads inclosing such a space; network; a net.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A golden <qex>mesh</qex> to entrap the hearts of men.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Gearing)</fld> <def>The engagement of the teeth of wheels, or of a wheel and rack.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mesh stick</b></col>, <cd>a stick on which the mesh is formed in netting.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesh</ent><br/
<hw>Mesh</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Meshed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Meshing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To catch in a mesh.</def>  <rj><au>Surrey.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesh</ent><br/
<hw>Mesh</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <fld>(Gearing)</fld> <def>To engage with each other, as the teeth of wheels.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meshed</ent><br/
<hw>Meshed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Mashed; brewed.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meshy</ent><br/
<hw>Mesh"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Formed with meshes; netted.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesiad</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"i*ad</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`sos</grk> middle + L. <ets>ad</ets> to.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Toward, or on the side toward, the mesial plane; mesially; -- opposed to <contr>laterad</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesial</ent><br/
<hw>Me"sial</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`sos</grk> middle.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Middle; median; in, or in the region of, the mesial plane; internal; -- opposed to <contr>lateral</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mesial plane</b></col>. <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Meson</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesially</ent><br/
<hw>Me"sial*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>In, near, or toward, the mesial plane; mesiad.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesityl</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"i*tyl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A hypothetical radical formerly supposed to exist in mesityl oxide.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mesityl oxide</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>a volatile liquid having the odor of peppermint, obtained by certain dehydrating agents from acetone; -- formerly called also <altname>dumasin</altname>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesitylenate</ent><br/
<hw>Me*sit"y*le*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of mesitylenic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesitylene</ent><br/
<hw>Me*sit"y*lene</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A colorless, fragrant liquid, <chform>C6H3(CH3)3</chform>, of the benzene series of hydrocarbons, obtained by distilling acetone with sulphuric acid.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Me*sit`y*len"ic</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesitylol</ent><br/
<hw>Me*sit"y*lol</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mesityl</ets>ene + <ets>-ol</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A crystalline substance obtained from mesitylene.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meslin</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"lin</hw> <pr>(? <or/ ?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Maslin</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesmeree</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`mer*ee"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A person subjected to mesmeric influence; one who is mesmerized.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesmerical</ent><br/
<ent>Mesmeric</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mes*mer"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mes*mer"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mesm<eacute/rique</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of, pertaining to, or induced by, mesmerism; <as>as, <ex>mesmeric</ex> sleep</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesmerism</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"mer*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <persfn><etsep>Mesmer</etsep></persfn>, who first brought it into notice at Vienna, about 1775: cf. F. <ets>mesm<eacute/risme</ets>.]</ety> <def>An earlier name for <altname>hypnosis</altname> or <altname>hypnotism</altname>, the art of inducing an extraordinary or abnormal state of the nervous system, in which the actor claims to control the actions, and communicate directly with the mind, of the recipient.  It is believed to be a state between sleep and wakefulness, in which a person is more susceptible to suggestion than when awake.  See <cref>Animal magnetism</cref>, under <er>Magnetism</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesmerist</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"mer*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who practices, or believes in, mesmerism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesmerization</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`mer*i*za"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of mesmerizing; the state of being mesmerized.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesmerize</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"mer*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mesmerized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mesmerizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>mesmerise</asp>.]</altsp><sn>1.</sn> <def>To bring into a state of mesmeric sleep; to hypnotize.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To produce an intense fascination in; to spellbind.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesmerizer</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"mer*i`zer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who mesmerizes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesne</ent><br/
<hw>Mesne</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Mean</er> intermediate.]</ety> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Middle; intervening; <as>as, a <ex>mesne</ex> lord, that is, a lord who holds land of a superior, but grants a part of it to another person, in which case he is a <ex>tenant</ex> to the superior, but <ex>lord</ex> or superior to the second grantee, and hence is called the <ex>mesne</ex> lord</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mesne process</b></col>, <cd>intermediate process; process intervening between the beginning and end of a suit, sometimes understood to be the whole process preceding the execution.</cd> <au>Blackstone.</au>  <au>Burrill.</au> -- <col><b>Mesne profits</b></col>, profits of premises during the time the owner has been wrongfully kept out of the possession of his estate.  <rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mes-</ent><br/
<ent>Meso-</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mes"o-</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mes-</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>. <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`sos</grk> in the middle.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A combining form denoting <sig>in the middle</sig>, <sig>intermediate</sig>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>specif.</specif> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <def>Denoting <xex>a type of hydrocarbons</xex> which are regarded as <xex>methenyl derivatives</xex>. Also used adjectively.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Optically inactive due to compensating optical activity at two or more asymmetric centers, often due to a plane of symmetry within the molecular structure; <as>as, <ex>meso-</ex>tartaric acid</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Attached to a carbon atom located between two hereoatoms in a heterocyclic ring.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesoarium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*a"ri*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., from Gr. <grk>me`sos</grk> middle + <grk>'w,a`rion</grk>, dim. of <grk>'w,o`n</grk> an egg.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The fold of peritoneum which suspends the ovary from the dorsal wall of the body cavity; the <altname>mesovarium</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesoblast</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"o*blast</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + <ets>-blast</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The mesoderm.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The cell nucleus; mesoplast.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesoblastic</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*blas"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Relating to the mesoblast; <as>as, the <ex>mesoblastic</ex> layer</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesobranchial</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*bran"chi*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + <ets>branchial</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to a region of the carapace of a crab covering the middle branchial region.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesobronchium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*bron"chi*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mesobronchia</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL. See <er>Meso-</er>, and <er>Bronchia</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The main bronchus of each lung.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesocaecum</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*cae"cum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <ety>[NL. See <er>Meso-</er>, and <er>Caecum</er>.]</ety> <def>The fold of peritoneum attached to the caecum.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mes`o*cae"cal</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesocarp</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"o*carp</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + Gr. <grk>karpo`s</grk> fruit.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The middle layer of a pericarp which consists of three distinct or dissimilar layers.</def>  <rj><au>Gray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesocephalic</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*ce*phal"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + <ets>cephalic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Of or pertaining to, or in the region of, the middle of the head; <as>as, the <ex>mesocephalic</ex> flexure</as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Having the cranial cavity of medium capacity; neither megacephalic nor microcephalic.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>Having the ratio of the length to the breadth of the cranium a medium one; mesaticephalic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesocephalon</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*ceph"a*lon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Meso-</er>, and <er>Cephalon</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The pons Varolii.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesocephalous</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*ceph"a*lous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Mesocephalic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesocoelia</ent><br/
<ent>Mesocoele</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mes`o*coe"le</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, \'d8<hw>Mes`o*coe"li*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. <ets>mesocoelia</ets>. See <er>Meso-</er>, and <er>Coelia</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The cavity of the mesencephalon; the iter.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesocolon</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*co"lon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>meso`kwlon</grk>; <grk>me`sos</grk> middle + <grk>kw^lon</grk> the colon: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/soc<ocir/lon</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The fold of peritoneum, or mesentery, attached to the colon.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mes`o*col"ic</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesocoracoid</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*cor"a*coid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + <ets>coracoid</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A process from the middle of the coracoid in some animals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesocuniform</ent><br/
<ent>Mesocuneiform</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mes`o*cu*ne"i*form</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mes`o*cu"ni*form</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + <ets>cuneiform</ets>, <ets>cuniform</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>One of the bones of the tarsus. See 2d <er>Cuneiform</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesoderm</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"o*derm</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + Gr. <grk>de`rma</grk> skin.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The layer of the blastoderm, between the ectoderm and endoderm; mesoblast. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Blastoderm</er> and <er>Ectoderm</er>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The middle body layer in some invertebrates.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The middle layer of tissue in some vegetable structures.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesodermal</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*der"mal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or derived from, the mesoderm; <as>as, <ex>mesodermal</ex> tissues</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesodermic</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*der"mic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Mesodermal</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesodont</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"o*dont</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + Gr. <grk>'odoy`s</grk>, <grk>'odo`ntos</grk>, a tooth.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Having teeth of moderate size.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesogaster</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*gas"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`sos</grk> middle + <?/ belly.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The fold of peritoneum connecting the stomach with the dorsal wall of the abdominal cavity; the mesogastrium.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesogastric</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*gas"tric</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + <ets>gastric</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Of or pertaining to the middle region of the abdomen, or of the stomach.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Of or pertaining to the mesogaster.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the middle gastric lobe of the carapace of a crab.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesogastrium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*gas"tri*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Mesogaster</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The umbilical region.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The mesogaster.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesogloea</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*gl<oe/"a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`sos</grk> middle + <?/ a glutinous substance.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A thin gelatinous tissue separating the ectoderm and endoderm in certain coelenterates.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mes`o*gl<oe/"al</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesognathous</ent><br/
<hw>Me*sog"na*thous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + Gr. <grk>gna`qos</grk> jaw.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Having the jaws slightly projecting; between prognathous and orthognathous. See <cref>Gnathic index</cref>, under <er>Gnathic</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesohepar</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*he"par</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Meso-</er>, and <er>Hepar</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A fold of the peritoneum connecting the liver with the dorsal wall of the abdominal cavity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesohippus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*hip"pus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`sos</grk> middle + <?/ a horse.]</ety> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>An extinct mammal of the Horse family, but not larger than a sheep, and having three toes on each foot.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesolabe</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"o*labe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mesolabium</ets>, Gr. <?/; <grk>me`sos</grk> middle + <?/ to take.]</ety> <def>An instrument of the ancients for finding two mean proportionals between two given lines, required in solving the problem of the duplication of the cube.</def>  <rj><au>Brande & C.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesole</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"ole</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>me`sos</grk> middle.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Thomsonite</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesolite</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"o*lite</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + <ets>-lite</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A zeolitic mineral, grayish white or yellowish, occuring in delicate groups of crystals, also fibrous massive. It is a hydrous silicate of alumina, lime, and soda.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesologarithm</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*log"a*rithm</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + <ets>logarithm</ets> : cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/sologarithme</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>A logarithm of the cosine or cotangent.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Kepler. Hutton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesometrium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*me"tri*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Meso-</er>, and <er>Metrium</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The fold of the peritoneum supporting the oviduct.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesomycetes</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*my*ce"tes</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL.; <ets>meso-</ets> + <ets>mycetes</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>One of the three classes into which the fungi are divided in <persfn>Brefeld's</persfn> classification.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mes`o*my*ce"tous</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesomyodian</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*my*o"di*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A bird having a mesomyodous larynx.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesomyodous</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*my"o*dous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + Gr. <?/, <?/, a muscle.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having the intrinsic muscles of the larynx attached to the middle of the semirings.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meson</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes"on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`son</grk> middle, neut. of <grk>me`sos</grk>, a., middle.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The mesial plane dividing the body of an animal into similar right and left halves. The line in which it meets the dorsal surface has been called the <part>dorsimeson</part>, and the corresponding ventral edge the <part>ventrimeson</part>.</def>  <rj><au>B. G. Wilder.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>An <isa>elementary particle</isa> made up of two quarks; a hadron having a baryon number of zero; any hadron other than a baryon.  Mesons are bosons with integral values of spin, having a mass intermediate between those of the electron and a nucleon; they may have positive or negative charges, or may be neutral.  Mesons are of three types: the <stype>pion</stype> (<pi/-meson), <stype>kaon</stype> (K-mesons), and <stype><eta/-mesons</stype>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>mu meson</b></col> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <cd>the former name for the <altname>muon</altname>, a particle which is not a true meson{2}.  The term is no longer used in technical literature, except historically.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mesonic</ent><br/
<hw>me*son"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to a meson.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesonasal</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*na"sal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + <ets>nasal</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the middle portion of the nasal region.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesonephric</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*neph"ric</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the mesonephros; <as>as, the <ex>mesonephric</ex>, or Wolffian, duct</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesonephros</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*neph"ros</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`sos</grk> middle + <grk>nefro`s</grk> kidney.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The middle one of the three pairs of embryonic renal organs developed in most vertebrates; the Wolffian body.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesonotum</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*no"tum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`sos</grk> middle + <grk>nw^ton</grk> the back.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The dorsal portion of the mesothorax of insects.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesophloeum</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*phl<oe/"um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`sos</grk> middle + <grk>floio`s</grk> bark.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The middle bark of a tree; the green layer of bark, usually soon covered by the outer or corky layer, and obliterated.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesophryon</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*soph"ry*on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., from Gr. <grk>meso`fryon</grk>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>See <er>Glabella</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesophyllum</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*phyl"lum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`sos</grk> middle + <grk>fy`llon</grk> leaf.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The parenchyma of a leaf between the skin of the two surfaces.</def>  <rj><au>Gray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesoplast</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"o*plast</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + <ets>-plast</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The nucleus of a cell; mesoblast.</def>  <rj><au>Agassiz.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 916 --></p>

<p><ent>Mesopodial</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*po"di*al</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/s`<osl/*p<omac/"d<icr/*<ait/l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the mesopodialia or to the parts of the limbs to which they belong.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesopodiale</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*po`di*a"le</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mesopodialia</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`sos</grk> middle + <?/, dim. of <grk>poy`s</grk>, <grk>podo`s</grk>, foot.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>One of the bones of either the carpus or tarsus.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesopodium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*po"di*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Mesopodiale</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The middle portion of the foot in the Gastropoda and Pteropoda.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesopterygium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*sop`te*ryg"i*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`sos</grk> middle + <?/ a fin.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The middle one of the three principal basal cartilages in the fins of fishes.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Me*sop`ter*yg"i*al</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesorchium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*sor"chi*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`sos</grk> middle + <?/ a testicle.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The fold of peritoneum which attaches the testis to the dorsal wall of the body cavity or scrotal sac.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesorectum</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*rec"tum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + <ets>rectum</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The fold of peritoneum, or mesentery, attached to the rectum.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mes`o*rec"tal</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesorhine</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"o*rhine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + Gr. <?/, <?/, the nose.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Having the nose of medium width; between leptorhine and platyrhine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesosauria</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*sau"ri*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Mosasauria</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesoscapula</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*scap"u*la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + <ets>scapula</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A process from the middle of the scapula in some animals; the spine of the scapula.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesoscapular</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*scap"u*lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the mesoscapula.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesoscutum</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*scu"tum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + <ets>scutum</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The scutum or dorsal plate of the middle thoracic segment of an insect. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Butterfly</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesoseme</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"o*seme</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + Gr. <?/ sign, mark; cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/sos<egrave/me</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Having a medium orbital index; having orbits neither broad nor narrow; between megaseme and microseme.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesosiderite</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*sid"er*ite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + <ets>siderite</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>See the Note under <er>Meteorite</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesosperm</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"o*sperm</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + Gr. <?/ seed: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/sosperme</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A membrane of a seed. See <er>Secundine</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesostate</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"o*state</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + Gr. <?/ to make to stand.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>A product of metabolic action.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Every <xex>mesostate</xex> is either an <xex>anastate</xex> or <xex>katastate</xex>, according as it is formed by an anabolic or katabolic process. See <er>Metabolism</er>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesosternal</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*ster"nal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the mesosternum.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesosternum</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*ster"num</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + <ets>sternum</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The middle portion, or body, of the sternum.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The ventral piece of the middle segment of the thorax in insects.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mesotartaric</ent><br/
<hw>mes`o*tar*tar"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + <ets>tartaric</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or designating, an acid called also <altname>inactive tartaric acid</altname>.  It is an optically inactive stereoisomer of <isa>tartaric acid</isa> due to internal compensation of the rotatory activity of the two asymmetric centers; it has a plane of symmetry in the molecule.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesotheca</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*the"ca</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`sos</grk> middle + <?/ box.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The middle layer of the gonophore in the Hydrozoa.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesothelium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*the"li*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`sos</grk> middle + E. epi<ets>thelium</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Epithelial mesoderm; a layer of cuboidal epithelium cells, formed from a portion of the mesoderm during the differetiation of the germ layers. It constitutes the boundary of the c<oe/lum.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesothoracic</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*tho*rac"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the mesothorax.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesothorax</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*tho"rax</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + <ets>thorax</ets>: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/sothorax</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The middle segment of the thorax in insects. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Coleoptera</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesothorium</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*tho"ri*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL.; <ets>meso-</ets> + <ets>thorium</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>a radioactive isotope of radium (radium-228) with a half-life of 5.8 years.  Also called <altname>mesothorium-1</altname> or <altname>mesothorium I</altname> to distinguish it from a subsequent decay product, mesothorium II (actinium-228).  It was discovered in 1907 by Otto Hahn as a decay product of thorium (produced by decay of thorium-232).  Mesothorium-1 (radium-228) in turn produces actinium-228 (mesothorium-2) as the first product of its radioactive decay, and the actinium-228 in turn decays quickly (half-life of 6 hours) to thorium-228 (which is also called <er>radiothorium</er>; the thorium-228 has a half-life of 1.91 years, shorter than that of the radium-228).  It was discovered and named before full recognition of the nature of isotopes of the elements, and was distinguished from other variants of radium by its half-life and mode of production and decay.  It was also cheaper to prepare than other short-lived radium isotopes, and was thus sold commercially, for use, e.g. in making watch dials readable in the dark by painting the hands and hour marks with a self-luminous paint containing the radioactive substance; it is therefore often referred to (e.g. in regulatory legislation) as though distinct from radium.  It was one of the isotopes believed responsible for radiation-induced diseases observed in industrial workers who painted radium on watch dials in the late 1950's and early 1960's.  The primary isotope of radium (radium-226) has a half-life of 1620 years, and these isotopes with shorter half-lives proved difficult to isolate and study for the purpose of finding the cause of such diseases.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesotrochal</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"o*tro`chal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + Gr. <?/ anything round, a hoop.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having the middle of the body surrounded by bands of cilia; -- said of the larvae of certain marine annelids.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesotype</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"o*type</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + <ets>-type</ets>: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/sotype</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>An old term covering natrolite or <xex>soda mesolite</xex>, scolecite or <xex>lime mesotype</xex>, and mesolite or <xex>lime-soda mesotype</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesovarium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*va"ri*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Meso-</er>, and <er>Ovary</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The fold of peritoneum connecting the ovary with the wall of the abdominal cavity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesoxalate</ent><br/
<hw>Mes*ox"a*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of mesoxalic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesoxalic</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`ox*al"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mes-</ets> + <ets>oxalic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or designating, an acid, <chform>CH2O2(CO2H)2</chform>, obtained from amido malonic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesozoa</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`o*zo"a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Mesozoic</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A group of very lowly organized, wormlike parasites, including the Dicyemata.  They are found in cephalopods. See <er>Dicyemata</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesozoic</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*zo"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meso-</ets> + Gr. <?/ life, fr. <?/ to live.]</ety> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>Belonging, or relating, to the secondary or reptilian age, or the era between the Paleozoic and Cenozoic. See <xex>Chart</xex> of <er>Geology</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesozoic</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`o*zo"ic</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The Mesozoic age or formation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesprise</ent><br/
<hw>Mes*prise"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>mespris</ets>, F. <ets>m<eacute/pris</ets>. See <er>Misprize</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Contempt; scorn.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[Perh. for F. <ets>m<eacute/prise</ets> mistake.  Cf. <er>Misprision</er>.]</ety> <def>Misadventure; ill-success.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesquit</ent><br/
<ent>Mesquite</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mes*qui"te</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/s*k<emac/"t<asl/)</pr>, <hw>Mes*quit"</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/s*k<emac/t")</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>mezquite</ets>; said to be a Mexican Indian word.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Aany of several small spiny trees or shrubs of the southwestern part of North America belonging to the genus <gen>Prosopis</gen> having small flowers in axillary cylindrical spikes followed by large sugar-rich pods, especially the <stype>honey mesquite</stype>, and <stype>screw-pod mesquite</stype>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Honey mesquite</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Algaroba</er> <sd>(b)</sd>.</cd> -- <col><b>Screw-pod mesquite</b></col>, <cd>a smaller tree (<spn>Prosopis pubescens</spn>), having spiral pods used as fodder and sometimes as food by the Indians.</cd> -- <col><b>Mesquite grass</b></col>, <cd>a rich native grass in Western Texas (<spn>Bouteloua oligostachya</spn>, and other species); -- so called from its growing in company with the mesquite tree; -- called also <altname>muskit grass</altname>, <altname>grama grass</altname>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesquite bean</ent><br/
<hw>Mes*qui"te bean</hw>. <def>The pod or seed of the mesquite.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mess</ent><br/
<hw>Mess</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mass; church service.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mess</ent><br/
<hw>Mess</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mes</ets>, OF. <ets>mets</ets>, LL. <ets>missum</ets>, p. p. of <ets>mittere</ets> to put, place (<it>e. g.</it>, on the table), L. <ets>mittere</ets> to send. See <er>Mission</er>, and cf. <er>Mass</er> religious service.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A quantity of food set on a table at one time; provision of food for a person or party for one meal; <as>as, a <ex>mess</ex> of pottage</as>; also, the food given to a beast at one time.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At their savory dinner set<br/
Of herbs and other country <qex>messes</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A number of persons who eat together, and for whom food is prepared in common; especially, persons in the military or naval service who eat at the same table; <as>as, the wardroom <ex>mess</ex></as>.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A set of four; -- from the old practice of dividing companies into sets of four at dinner.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Latimer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The milk given by a cow at one milking.</def> <mark>[U.S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <ety>[Perh. corrupt. fr. OE. <ets>mesh</ets> for <ets>mash</ets>: cf. <ets>muss</ets>.]</ety> <def>A disagreeable mixture or confusion of things; hence, a situation resulting from blundering or from misunderstanding; <as>as, he made a <ex>mess</ex> of it</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mess</ent><br/
<hw>Mess</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Messed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Messing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To take meals with a mess; to belong to a mess; to eat (with others); <as>as, I <ex>mess</ex> with the wardroom officers</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Marryat.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mess</ent><br/
<hw>Mess</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To supply with a mess.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make a mess{5} of; to disorder or muddle; to muss; to jumble; to disturb; to mess up.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was n't right either to be <qex>messing</qex> another man's sleep.</q>  <rj><qau>Scribner's Mag.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Message</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"sage</hw> <pr>(?; 48)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. LL. <ets>missaticum</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mittere</ets>, <ets>missum</ets>, to send. See <er>Mission</er>, and cf. <er>Messenger</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Any notice, word, or communication, written or verbal, sent from one person to another.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ehud said, I have a <qex>message</qex> from God unto thee.</q> <rj><qau>Judg. iii. 20.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, specifically, an official communication, not made in person, but delivered by a messenger; <as>as, the President's <ex>message</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Message shell</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Shell</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Message</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"sage</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To bear as a message.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Message</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"sage</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE., fr. OF. <ets>message</ets>, fr. LL. <ets>missaticus</ets>. See 1st <er>Message</er>.]</ety> <def>A messenger.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Messager</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"sa*ger</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.]</ety> <def>A messenger.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Message stick</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"sage stick</hw>. <def>A stick, carved with lines and dots, used, esp. by Australian aborigines, to convey information.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mess beef</ent><br/
<hw>Mess beef</hw>. <def>Barreled salt beef, packed with about 80 pounds chuck and rump, two flanks, and the rest plates.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Messenger</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"sen*ger</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>messager</ets>, OF. <ets>messagier</ets>, F. <ets>messager</ets>. See <er>Message</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who bears a message; the bearer of a verbal or written communication, notice, or invitation, from one person to another, or to a public body; specifically, an office servant who bears messages.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, foreshows, or foretells.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yon gray lines<br/
That fret the clouds are <qex>messengers</qex> of day.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A hawser passed round the capstan, and having its two ends lashed together to form an endless rope or chain; -- formerly used for heaving in the cable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A person appointed to perform certain ministerial duties under bankrupt and insolvent laws, such as to take charge of the estate of the bankrupt or insolvent.</def>  <rj><au>Bouvier. Tomlins.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Carrier; intelligencer; courier; harbinger; forerunner; precursor; herald.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Messenger bird</b></col>, <cd>the secretary bird, from its swiftness.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Messet</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"set</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A dog.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Messiad</ent><br/
<hw>Mes*si"ad</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A German epic poem on the Messiah, by Klopstock.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Messiah</ent><br/
<hw>Mes*si"ah</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Heb. <ets>m<amac/sh<imac/akh</ets> anointed, fr. <ets>m<amac/shakh</ets> to anoint.  Cf. <er>Messias</er>.]</ety> <def>The expected king and deliverer of the Hebrews; the Savior; Christ.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And told them the <qex>Messiah</qex> now was born.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Messiahship</ent><br/
<hw>Mes*si"ah*ship</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state or office of the Messiah.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Messianic</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`si*an"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or relating to the Messiah; <as>as, the <ex>Messianic</ex> office or character</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Messias</ent><br/
<hw>Mes*si"as</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL., fr. Gr. <?/. See <er>Messiah</er>.]</ety> <def>The Messiah.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I know that <qex>Messias</qex> cometh, which is called Christ.</q> <rj><qau>John iv. 25.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Messidor</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mes`si`dor"</hw> <pr>(F. ?; E. ?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>messis</ets> harvest.]</ety> <def>The tenth month of the French republican calendar dating from September 22, 1792.  It began June 19, and ended July 18.  See <er>Vend<eacute/miaire</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Messieurs</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"sieurs</hw> <pr>(?; F. ?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[F.; pl. of <ets>monsieur</ets>.]</ety> <def>Sirs; gentlemen; -- abbreviated to <abbr>Messrs.</abbr>, which is used as the plural of <it>Mr.</it></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Messinese</ent><br/
<hw>Mes`si*nese"</hw> <pr>(? <or/ ?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to <city>Messina</city>, or its inhabitans.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Messmate</ent><br/
<hw>Mess"mate`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An associate in a mess.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Messuage</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"suage</hw> <pr>(?; 48)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>mesuage</ets>, <ets>masnage</ets>, LL. <ets>messuagium</ets>, <ets>mansionaticum</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mansio</ets>, <ets>-onis</ets>, a staying, remaining, dwelling, fr. <ets>manere</ets>, <ets>mansum</ets>, to stay, remain, E. <ets>mansion</ets>, <ets>manse</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A dwelling house, with the adjacent buildings and curtilage, and the adjoining lands appropriated to the use of the household.</def>  <rj><au>Cowell. Bouvier.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They wedded her to sixty thousand pounds,<br/
To lands in Kent, and <qex>messuages</qex> in York.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mess up</ent><br/
<hw>mess up</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make a mess{5} of; to confuse, disorder, or muddle; to muss; to jumble; to disturb.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To botch{3}; to bungle.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mess-up</ent><br/
<hw>mess-up</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Something badly botched or muddled.</def> <mark>[British]</mark> <br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> ballup, balls-up, cockup.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mest</ent><br/
<hw>Mest</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Most.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mestee</ent><br/
<hw>Mes*tee"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mestizo</er>.]</ety> <def>The offspring of a white person and a quadroon; -- so called in the West Indies.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mustee</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mester</ent><br/
<hw>Mes"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <def>See <er>Mister</er>, a trade.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mestino</ent><br/
<hw>Mes*ti"no</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mestinos</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>See <er>Mestizo</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mestizo</ent><br/
<hw>Mes*ti"zo</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mestizos</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Sp. <ets>mestizo</ets>; akin to OF. <ets>mestis</ets>, F. <ets>m<eacute/tis</ets>; all fr. (assumed) LL. <ets>mixtitius</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mixtus</ets> mixed, p. p. of <ets>miscere</ets> to mix. See <er>Mix</er>, and cf. <er>Mestee</er>, <er>M<eacute/tif</er>, <er>M<eacute/tis</er>, <er>Mustee</er>.]</ety> <def>The offspring of an Indian or a negro and a European or person of European stock.</def> <mark>[Spanish America]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mestizo wool</b></col>, <cd>wool imported from South America, and produced by mixed breeds of sheep.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mestling</ent><br/
<hw>Mest"ling</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A kind of brass. See <er>Maslin</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mesymnicum</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*sym"ni*cum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>me`sos</grk> middle + <?/ a festive song. See <er>Hymn</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Anc. Poetry)</fld> <def>A repetition at the end of a stanza.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Met</ent><br/
<hw>Met</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <def><pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> of <er>Meet</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Met</ent><br/
<hw>Met</hw>, <mark>obs.</mark> <def><pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> of <er>Mete</er>, to measure.</def>  <rj><au>Chapman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Met</ent><br/
<hw>Met</hw>, <mark>obs.</mark> <def><pos>p. p.</pos> of <er>Mete</er>, to dream.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Met-</ent><br/
<ent>Meta-</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Met"a-</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Met-</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>. <ety>[Gr. <grk>meta`</grk> between, with, after; akin to AS. <ets>mid</ets> with, G. <ets>mit</ets>, Goth. <ets>mi<thorn/</ets>, E. <ets>mid</ets>, in <ets>midwife</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A prefix meaning <sig>between</sig>, <sig>with</sig>, <sig>after</sig>, <sig>behind</sig>, <sig>over</sig>, <sig>about</sig>, <sig>reversely</sig>; <as>as, <ex>meta</ex>chronism, the error of placing after the correct time; <ex>meta</ex>phor, lit., a carrying over; <ex>meta</ex>thesis, a placing reversely.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> A prefix denoting: <sd>(a)</sd> <def><sig>Other</sig>; <sig>duplicate</sig>, <sig>corresponding to</sig>; <sig>resembling</sig>; hence, <sig>metameric</sig>; <as>as, <ex>meta</ex>-arabinic, <ex>met</ex>aldehyde</as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Organic Chem.)</fld> <def>That two replacing radicals, in the benzene nucleus, occupy the <xex>relative positions</xex> of 1 and 3, 2 and 4, 3 and 5, 4 and 6, 5 and 1, or 6 and 2; <as>as, <ex>meta</ex>cresol, etc.</as>  See <er>Ortho-</er>, and <er>Para-</er>.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <fld>(Inorganic Chem.)</fld> <def>Having <sig>less than the highest number</sig> of hydroxyl groups; -- said of acids; <as>as, <ex>meta</ex>phosphoric acid</as>. Also used adjectively.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A prefix meaning <sig>at a level above</sig>, as in <ex>meta</ex>physics, <ex>meta</ex>language.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metabasis</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tab"a*sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Metabases</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ to pass over; <?/ beyond, over + <?/ to go.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Rhet.)</fld> <def>A transition from one subject to another.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Metabola</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metabole</ent><br/
<ent>Metabola</ent><br/
<mhw>{ \'d8<hw>Me*tab"o*la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, \'d8<hw>Me*tab"o*le</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., from Gr. <?/ change; <?/ beyond + <?/ to throw.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A change or mutation; a change of disease, symptoms, or treatment.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metabolia</ent><br/
<ent>Metabola</ent><br/
<mhw>{ \'d8<hw>Me*tab"o*la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, \'d8<hw>Met`a*bo"li*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL. See 1st <er>Metabola</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A comprehensive group of insects, including those that undegro a metamorphosis.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metabolian</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*bo"li*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Metabola</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An insect which undergoes a metamorphosis.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metabolic</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*bol"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/. See <er>Metabola</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to metamorphosis; pertaining to, or involving, change.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to metabolism; <as>as, <ex>metabolic</ex> activity; <ex>metabolic</ex> force.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metabolisis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Met`a*bol"i*sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL.]</ety> <def>Metabolism.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metabolism</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tab"o*lism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or process, by which living tissues or cells take up and convert into their own proper substance the nutritive material brought to them by the blood, or by which they transform their cell protoplasm into simpler substances, which are fitted either for excretion or for some special purpose, as in the manufacture of the digestive enzymes.  Hence, metabolism may be either constructive (<stype>anabolism</stype>), or destructive (<stype>catabolism</stype>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The series of chemical changes which take place in an organism, by means of which food is manufactured and utilized and waste materials are eliminated.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metabolite</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tab"o*lite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Physiol Chem.)</fld> <def>A product of metabolism; a substance produced by metabolic action, as urea.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metabolize</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tab"o*lize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>To change by a metabolic process. See <er>Metabolism</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metabranchial</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*bran"chi*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meta-</ets> + <ets>branchial</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the lobe of the carapace of crabs covering the posterior branchiae.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metacarpal</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*car"pal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the metacarpus.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A metacarpal bone.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metacarpus</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*car"pus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/; <?/ beyond, between + <?/ the wrist.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>That part of the skeleton of the hand or forefoot between the carpus and phalanges. In man it consists of five bones. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Artiodactyla</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metacentre</ent><br/
<ent>Metacenter</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Met`a*cen"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> <it>or</it> <hw>Met`a*cen"tre</hw> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>meta-</ets> + <ets>center</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Hydrostatics)</fld> <def>The point of intersection of a vertical line through the center of gravity of the fluid displaced by a floating body which is tipped through a small angle from its position of equilibrium, and the inclined line which was vertical through the center of gravity of the body when in equilibrium.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ When the metacenter is above the center of gravity, the position of the body is stable; when below it, unstable.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metacetone</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tac"e*tone</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>met-</ets> + <ets>acetone</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A colorless liquid of an agreeable odor, <chform>C6H10O</chform>, obtained by distilling a mixture of sugar and lime; -- so called because formerly regarded as a polymeric modification of acetone.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metachloral</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*chlo"ral</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>meta-</ets> + <ets>chloral</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A white, amorphous, insoluble substance regarded as a polymeric variety of chloral.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metachronism</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tach"ro*nism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/, <?/, after the time, happening afterward; <?/ beyond + <?/ time: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/tachronisme</ets>.]</ety> <def>An error committed in chronology by placing an event after its real time.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metachrosis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Met`a*chro"sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., from Gr. <?/ beyond + <?/ a coloring.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The power of changing color at will by the expansion of special pigment cells, under nerve influence, as seen in many reptiles, fishes, etc.</def>  <rj><au>Cope.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metacinnabarite</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*cin"na*bar*ite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>meta-</ets> + <ets>cinnabar</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Sulphide of mercury in isometric form and black in color.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metacism</ent><br/
<hw>Met"a*cism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>metacismus</ets>, Gr. <?/ fondness for the letter <mu/.]</ety> <def>A defect in pronouncing the letter <xex>m</xex>, or a too frequent use of it.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metacrolein</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*cro"le*in</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>met-</ets> + <ets>acrolein</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A polymeric modification of acrolein obtained by heating it with caustic potash.  It is a crystalline substance having an aromatic odor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metacromion</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Met`a*cro"mi*on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A process projecting backward and downward from the acromion of the scapula of some mammals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metadiscoidal</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*dis*coid"al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meta-</ets> + <ets>discoidal</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Discoidal by derivation; -- applied especially to the placenta of man and apes, because it is supposed to have been derived from a diffused placenta.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metagastric</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*gas"tric</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>meta-</ets> + <ets>gastric</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the two posterior gastric lobes of the carapace of crabs.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metage</ent><br/
<hw>Met"age</hw> <pr>(?; 48)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mete</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Measurement, especially of coal.</def>  <rj><au>De Foe.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Charge for, or price of, measuring.</def>  <rj><au>Simmonds.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metagenesis</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*gen"e*sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>meta-</ets> + <ets>genesis</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The change of form which one animal species undergoes in a series of successively produced individuals, extending from the one developed from the ovum to the final perfected individual.  Hence, metagenesis involves the production of sexual individuals by nonsexual means, either directly or through intervening sexless generations.  Opposed to <contr>monogenesis</contr>. See <cref>Alternate generation</cref>, under <er>Generation</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Alternation of sexual and asexual or gemmiparous generations; -- in distinction from <contr>heterogamy</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 917 --></p>

<p><ent>Metagenetic</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*ge*net"ic</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/t`<adot/*j<esl/*n<ecr/t"<icr/k)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to metagenesis.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metagenic</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*gen"ic</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/t`<adot/*j<esl/n"<icr/k)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Metagenetic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metagnathous</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tag"na*thous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>meta-</ets> + Gr. <grk>gna`qos</grk> the jaw.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Cross-billed; -- said of certain birds, as the crossbill.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metagrammatism</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*gram"ma*tism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Anagrammatism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metagraphic</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*graph"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>By or pertaining to metagraphy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metagraphy</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tag"ra*phy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>meta-</ets> + <ets>-graphy</ets>.]</ety> <def>The art or act of rendering the letters of the alphabet of one language into the possible equivalents of another; transliteration.</def>  <rj><au>Stormonth.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metal</ent><br/
<hw>Met"al</hw> <pr>(? <or/ ?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/tal</ets>, L. <ets>metallum</ets> metal, mine, Gr. <?/ mine; cf. Gr. <?/ to search after.  Cf. <er>Mettle</er>, <er>Medal</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>An elementary substance, as sodium, calcium, or copper, whose oxide or hydroxide has basic rather than acid properties, as contrasted with the nonmetals, or metalloids.  No sharp line can be drawn between the metals and nonmetals, and certain elements partake of both acid and basic qualities, as chromium, manganese, bismuth, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Popularly, the name is applied to certain hard, fusible metals, as gold, silver, copper, iron, tin, lead, zinc, nickel, etc., and also to the mixed metals, or metallic alloys, as brass, bronze, steel, bell metal, etc.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Ore from which a metal is derived; -- so called by miners.</def>  <rj><au>Raymond.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A mine from which ores are taken.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Slaves . . . and persons condemned to <qex>metals</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The substance of which anything is made; material; hence, constitutional disposition; character; temper.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not till God make men of some other <qex>metal</qex> than earth.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Courage; spirit; mettle. See <er>Mettle</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The allusion is to the temper of the metal of a sword blade.</note>  <rj><au>Skeat.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>The broken stone used in macadamizing roads and ballasting railroads.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>The effective power or caliber of guns carried by a vessel of war.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Glass in a state of fusion.</def>  <rj><au>Knight.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>The rails of a railroad.</def> <mark>[Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Base metal</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>any one of the metals, as iron, lead, etc., which are readily tarnished or oxidized, in contrast with the noble metals.  In general, a metal of small value, as compared with gold or silver.</cd> -- <col><b>Fusible metal</b></col> <fld>(Metal.)</fld>, <cd>a very fusible alloy, usually consisting of bismuth with lead, tin, or cadmium.</cd> -- <col><b>Heavy metals</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>the metallic elements not included in the groups of the alkalies, alkaline earths, or the earths; specifically, the heavy metals, as gold, mercury, platinum, lead, silver, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Light metals</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>the metallic elements of the alkali and alkaline earth groups, as sodium, lithium, calcium, magnesium, etc.; also, sometimes, the metals of the earths, as aluminium.</cd> -- <col><b>Muntz metal</b></col>, <cd>an alloy for sheathing and other purposes, consisting of about sixty per cent of copper, and forty of zinc.  Sometimes a little lead is added.  It is named from the inventor.</cd> -- <col><b>Prince's metal</b></col> <fld>(Old Chem.)</fld>, <cd>an alloy resembling brass, consisting of three parts of copper to one of zinc; -- also called <altname>Prince Rupert's metal</altname>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metal</ent><br/
<hw>Met"al</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Metaled</conjf> <pr>(? <or/ ?)</pr> or <conjf>Metalled</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Metaling</conjf> or <conjf>Metalling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To cover with metal; <as>as, to <ex>metal</ex> a ship's bottom; to <ex>metal</ex> a road.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metalammonium</ent><br/
<hw>Met`al*am*mo"ni*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Metal</ets> + <ets>ammonium</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A hypothetical radical derived from ammonium by the substitution of metallic atoms in place of hydrogen.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>metalanguage</ent><br/
<hw>metalanguage</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Any language that can be used to describe another language or system of symbols.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metalbumin</ent><br/
<hw>Met`al*bu"min</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>met-</ets> + <ets>albumin</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol. Chem.)</fld> <def>A form of albumin found in ascitic and certain serous fluids.  It is sometimes regarded as a mixture of albumin and mucin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metaldehyde</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tal"de*hyde</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>met-</ets> + <ets>aldehyde</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A white crystalline substance isomeric with, and obtained from, acetic aldehyde by polymerization, and reconvertible into the same.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metalepsis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Met`a*lep"sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Metalepses</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/ participation, alteration, fr. <?/ to partake, to take in exchange; <?/ beyond + <?/ to take.]</ety> <fld>(Rhet.)</fld> <def>The continuation of a trope in one word through a succession of significations, or the union of two or more tropes of a different kind in one word.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metalepsy</ent><br/
<hw>Met"a*lep`sy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Exchange; replacement; substitution; metathesis.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metaleptic</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*lep"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a metalepsis.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Transverse; <as>as, the <ex>metaleptic</ex> motion of a muscle</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, concerned in, or occurring by, metalepsy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metaleptical</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*lep"tic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Metaleptic.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Met`a*lep"tic*al*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metallic</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tal"lic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>metallicus</ets>, fr. <ets>metallum</ets>: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/tallique</ets>. See <er>Metal</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a metal; of the nature of metal; resembling metal; <as>as, a <ex>metallic</ex> appearance; a <ex>metallic</ex> alloy.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or characterized by, the essential and implied properties of a metal, as contrasted with a nonmetal or metalloid; conductive of electricity; basic; forming positive ions in solution; antacid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Metallic iron</b></col>, <cd>iron in the state of the metal, as distinquished from its ores, as magnetic iron.</cd> -- <col><b>Metallic paper</b></col>, <cd>paper covered with a thin solution of lime, whiting, and size.  When written upon with a pewter or brass pencil, the lines can hardly be effaced.</cd> -- <col><b>Metallic tinking</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>a sound heard in the chest, when a cavity communicating with the air passages contains both air and liquid.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metallical</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tal"lic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>See <er>Metallic</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metallicly</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tal"lic*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a metallic manner; by metallic means.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metallifacture</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tal`li*fac"ture</hw> <pr>(?; 135)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>metallum</ets> metal + <ets>facere</ets>, <ets>factum</ets>, to make.]</ety> <def>The production and working or manufacture of metals.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>R. Park.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metalliferous</ent><br/
<hw>Met`al*lif"er*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>metallifer</ets>; <ets>metallum</ets> metal + <ets>ferre</ets> to bear: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/tallif<egrave/re</ets>.]</ety> <def>Producing metals; yielding metals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metalliform</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tal"li*form</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>metallum</ets> metal + <ets>-form</ets>: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/talliforme</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having the form or structure of a metal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metalline</ent><br/
<hw>Met"al*line</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/tallin</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Pertaining to, or resembling, a metal; metallic; <as>as, <ex>metalline</ex> properties</as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Impregnated with metallic salts; chalybeate; <as>as, <ex>metalline</ex> water</as>.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metalline</ent><br/
<hw>Met"al*line</hw> <pr>(? <or/ ?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A substance of variable composition, but resembling a soft, dark-colored metal, used in the bearings of machines for obviating friction, and as a substitute for lubricants.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metallist</ent><br/
<hw>Met"al*list</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A worker in metals, or one skilled in metals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metallization</ent><br/
<hw>Met`al*li*za"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/tallisation</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act or process of metallizing.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metallize</ent><br/
<hw>Met"al*lize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Metallized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Metallizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/talliser</ets>.]</ety> <def>To impart metallic properties to; to impregnate with a metal.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metallochrome</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tal"lo*chrome</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Metallochromy</er>.]</ety> <def>A coloring produced by the deposition of some metallic compound; specifically, the prismatic tints produced by depositing a film of peroxide of lead on polished steel by electricity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metallochromy</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tal"lo*chro`my</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>metallum</ets> metal + Gr. <?/ color.]</ety> <def>The art or process of coloring metals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metallograph</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tal"lo*graph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>metallum</ets> metal + <ets>-graph</ets>.]</ety> <def>A print made by metallography.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metallographic</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tal`lo*graph"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to, or by means of, metallography.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metallographist</ent><br/
<hw>Met`al*log"ra*phist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who writes on the subject of metals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metallography</ent><br/
<hw>Met`al*log"ra*phy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>metallum</ets> metal + <ets>-graphy</ets>: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/tallographie</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The science or art of metals and metal working; also, a treatise on metals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A method of transferring impressions of the grain of wood to metallic surfaces by chemical action.</def>  <rj><au>Knight.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A substitute for lithography, in which metallic plates are used instead of stone.</def>  <rj><au>Knight.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metalloid</ent><br/
<hw>Met"al*loid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>metallum</ets> metal + <ets>-oid</ets>: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/tallo<ium/de</ets>.]</ety> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Formerly, the metallic base of a fixed alkali, or alkaline earth; -- applied by <person>Sir Humphrey Davy</person> to sodium, potassium, and some other metallic substances whose metallic character was supposed to be not well defined.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Now, one of several elementary substances which in the free state are unlike metals, and whose compounds possess or produce acid, rather than basic, properties; a nonmetal; <as>as, boron, carbon, phosphorus, nitrogen, oxygen, sulphur, chlorine, bromine, etc.</as>, are <xex>metalloids</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metalloid</ent><br/
<hw>Met"al*loid</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having the appearance of a metal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Having the properties of a nonmetal; nonmetallic; acid; negative.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metalloidal</ent><br/
<hw>Met`al*loid"al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Metalloid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metallophone</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tal"lo*phone</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>metallum</ets> metal + Gr. <?/ sound.]</ety> <fld>(Music)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>An instrument like a pianoforte, but having metal bars instead of strings.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>An instrument like the xylophone, but having metallic instead of wooden bars.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metallorganic</ent><br/
<hw>Met`al*lor*gan"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Metalorganic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metallotherapy</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tal`lo*ther"a*py</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>metallum</ets> metal + E. <ets>therapy</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Treatment of disease by applying metallic plates to the surface of the body.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metallurgical</ent><br/
<ent>Metallurgic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Met`al*lur"gic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Met`al*lur"gic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/tallurgique</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to metallurgy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metallurgist</ent><br/
<hw>Met"al*lur`gist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/tallurgiste</ets>.]</ety> <def>One who works in metals, or prepares them for use; one who is skilled in metallurgy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metallurgy</ent><br/
<hw>Met"al*lur`gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/tallurgie</ets>, fr. L. <ets>metallum</ets> metal, Gr. <?/ a mine + the root of <?/ work. See <er>Metal</er>, and <er>Work</er>.]</ety> <def>The art of working metals, comprehending the whole process of separating them from other matters in the ore, smelting, refining, and parting them; sometimes, in a narrower sense, only the process of extracting metals from their ores.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metalman</ent><br/
<hw>Met"al*man</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Metalmen</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>A worker in metals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metalogical</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*log"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Beyond the scope or province of logic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>metalorganic</ent><br/
<hw>met`al*or*gan"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Metal</ets>, L. <ets>metallum</ets> + E. <ets>organic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or denoting, any one of a series of compounds of certain metallic elements with organic radicals; as, zinc methyl, sodium ethyl, etc.; now usually <altname>organometallic</altname>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>metallorganic</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metamer</ent><br/
<hw>Met"a*mer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Metamere</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Any one of several metameric forms of the same substance, or of different substances having the same composition; <as>as, xylene has three <ex>metamers</ex>, viz., orthoxylene, metaxylene, and paraxylene</as>; an isomer.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metamere</ent><br/
<hw>Met"a*mere</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>meta-</ets> + <ets>-mere</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>One of successive or homodynamous parts in animals and plants; one of a series of similar parts that follow one another in a vertebrate or articulate animal, as in an earthworm; a segment; a somite. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Loeven's larva</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metameric</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*mer"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>meta-</ets> + Gr. <?/ part.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Having the same molecular formula, but possessing a different bonding structure and different properties; <as>as, methyl ether and ethyl alcohol are <ex>metameric</ex> compounds</as>.  See <er>Isomeric</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The existence of metameric compounds is due to different arrangements of the same atoms in the molecule.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to a metamere or its formation; <as>as, <ex>metameric</ex> segmentation</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metamerically</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*mer"ic*al*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a metameric manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metamerism</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tam"er*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The symmetry of a metameric structure; serial symmetry; the state of being made up of metameres.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>The state or quality of being metameric; isomerism due to different bonding patterns in two substances having the same molecular formula.  Contrasted with <contr>steroisomerism</contr> or <contr>optical isomerism</contr>.  Also, the relation or condition of metameric compounds.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metamorphic</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*mor"phic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Metamorphosis</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Subject to change; changeable; variable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Causing a change of structure.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, produced by, or exhibiting, certain changes which minerals or rocks may have undergone since their original deposition; -- especially applied to the recrystallization which sedimentary rocks have undergone through the influence of heat and pressure, after which they are called <xex>metamorphic</xex> rocks.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metamorphism</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*mor"phism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>The state or quality of being metamorphic; the process by which the material of rock masses has been more or less recrystallized by heat, pressure, etc., as in the change of sedimentary limestone to marble.</def>  <rj><au>Murchison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metamorphist</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*mor"phist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>One who believes that the body of Christ was merged into the Deity when he ascended.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metamorphize</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*mor"phize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To metamorphose.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metamorphose</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*mor"phose</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Metamorphosed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Metamorphosing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/tamorphoser</ets>.]</ety> <def>To change into a different form; to transform; to transmute.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And earth was <qex>metamorphosed</qex> into man.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metamorphose</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*mor"phose</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/tamorphose</ets>. See <er>Metamorphosis</er>.]</ety> <def>Same as <er>Metamorphosis</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metamorphoser</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*mor"pho*ser</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who metamorphoses.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Gascoigne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metamorphosic</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*mor"pho*sic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Changing the form; transforming.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Pownall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metamorphosis</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*mor"pho*sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Metamorphoses</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ to be transformed; <grk>meta`</grk> beyond, over + <grk>morfh`</grk> form.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Change of form, or structure; transformation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>A change in the form or function of a living organism, by a natural process of growth or development; <as>as, the <ex>metamorphosis</ex> of the yolk into the embryo, of a tadpole into a frog, or of a bud into a blossom</as>. Especially, that form of sexual reproduction in which an embryo undergoes a series of marked changes of external form, as the chrysalis stage, pupa stage, etc., in insects.  In these intermediate stages sexual reproduction is usually impossible, but they ultimately pass into final and sexually developed forms, from the union of which organisms are produced which pass through the same cycle of changes. See <er>Transformation</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>The change of material of one kind into another through the agency of the living organism; metabolism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Vegetable metamorphosis</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the doctrine that flowers are homologous with leaf buds, and that the floral organs are transformed leaves.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metanauplius</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Met`a*nau"pli*us</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Meta-</er>, and <er>Nauplius</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A larval crustacean in a stage following the nauplius, and having about seven pairs of appendages.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metanephritic</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*ne*phrit"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the metanephros.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metanephros</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Met`a*neph"ros</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ behind + <?/ kidney.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The most posterior of the three pairs of embryonic renal organs developed in many vertebrates.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metanotum</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Met`a*no"tum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ behind + <?/ back.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The dorsal portion of the metaphorax of insects.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metantimonate</ent><br/
<hw>Met`an*ti*mo"nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of metantimonic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metantimonic</ent><br/
<hw>Met`an*ti*mon"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>met-</ets> + <ets>antimonic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Pertaining to, or designating, an acid (formerly called <altname>antimonic acid</altname>) analogous to metaphosphoric acid, and obtained as a white amorphous insoluble substance, (<chform>HSbO3</chform>).</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Formerly, designating an acid, which is now properly called <altname>pyroantimonic acid</altname>, and analogous to <contr>pyrophosphoric acid</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metapectic</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*pec"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>meta-</ets> + <ets>pectic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or designating, a supposed acid obtained from pectin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metapectin</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*pec"tin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A substance obtained from, and resembling, pectin, and occurring in overripe fruits.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metapeptone</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*pep"tone</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>meta-</ets> + <ets>peptone</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol. Chem.)</fld> <def>An intermediate product formed in the gastric digestion of albuminous matter.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>metaphor</ent><br/
<hw>met"a*phor`</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/t"<adot/*f<ocir/r` <it>or</it> m<ecr/t"<adot/*f<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/taphore</ets>, L. <ets>metaphora</ets>, fr. Gr. <grk>metafora`</grk>, fr. <grk>metafe`rein</grk> to carry over, transfer; <grk>meta`</grk> beyond, over + <grk>fe`rein</grk> to bring, bear.]</ety> <fld>(Rhet.)</fld> <def>The transference of the relation between one set of objects to another set for the purpose of brief explanation; a compressed simile; <it>e. g.</it>, the ship plows the sea.</def> <au>Abbott & Seeley.</au> <ldquo/All the world's a stage.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The statement, <ldquo/that man is a fox,<rdquo/ is a metaphor; but <ldquo/that man is like a fox,<rdquo/ is a simile, similitude, or comparison.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metaphorical</ent><br/
<ent>Metaphoric</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Met`a*phor"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Met`a*phor"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/taphorique</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to metaphor; comprising a metaphor; not literal; figurative; tropical; <as>as, a <ex>metaphorical</ex> expression; a <ex>metaphorical</ex> sense.</as></def> -- <wordforms><wf>Met`a*phor"ic*al*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Met`a*phor"ic*al*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metaphorist</ent><br/
<hw>Met"a*phor*ist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who makes metaphors.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metaphosphate</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*phos"phate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of metaphosphoric acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>metaphosphoric</ent><br/
<hw>met`a*phos*phor"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>meta-</ets> + <ets>phosphoric</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or designating, a monobasic acid, <chform>HPO3</chform>, analogous to nitric acid, and, by heating phosphoric acid, obtained as a crystalline substance, commonly called <altname>glacial phosphoric acid</altname>.  Compare the tribasic <contr>orthophosphoric acid</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metaphrase</ent><br/
<hw>Met"a*phrase</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/t"<adot/*fr<amac/z)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>meta`frasis</grk>, from <grk>metafra`zein</grk> to paraphrase; <grk>meta`</grk> beyond, over + <grk>fra`zein</grk> to speak: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/taphrase</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A verbal translation; a version or translation from one language into another, word for word; a literal translation; -- opposed to <contr>paraphrase</contr>.</def>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An answering phrase; repartee.</def>  <rj><au>Mrs. Browning.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 918 --></p>

<p><ent>metaphrased</ent><br/
<hw>met"a*phrased</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/t"<adot/*fr<amac/zd)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Translated literally.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metaphrasis</ent><br/
<hw>Me*taph"ra*sis</hw> <pr>(m<esl/*t<acr/f"r<adot/*s<icr/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Metaphrase</er>.]</ety> <def>Metaphrase.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metaphrast</ent><br/
<hw>Met"a*phrast</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/taphraste</ets>.]</ety> <def>A literal translator.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metaphrastical</ent><br/
<ent>Metaphrastic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Met`a*phras"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Met`a*phras"tic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/.]</ety> <def>Close, or literal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metaphysic</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*phys"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/taphysique</ets>.]</ety> <def>See <er>Metaphysics</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metaphysic</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*phys"ic</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Metaphysical.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metaphysical</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*phys"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/taphysique</ets>. See <er>Metaphysics</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to metaphysics.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>According to rules or principles of metaphysics; <as>as, <ex>metaphysical</ex> reasoning</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Preternatural or supernatural.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The golden round<br/
Which fate and metaphysical aid doth seem<br/
To have thee crowned withal.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metaphysically</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*phys"ic*al*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In the manner of metaphysical science, or of a metaphysician.</def>  <rj><au>South.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metaphysician</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*phy*si"cian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/taphysicien</ets>.]</ety> <def>One who is versed in metaphysics.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metaphysics</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*phys"ics</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ <?/ <?/ after those things which relate to external nature, after physics, fr. <?/ beyond, after + <?/ relating to external nature, natural, physical, fr. <?/ nature: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/taphysique</ets>. See <er>Physics</er>. The term was first used by the followers of Aristotle as a name for that part of his writings which came <ets>after</ets>, or followed, the part which treated of <ets>physics</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The science of real as distinguished from phenomenal being; ontology; also, the science of being, with reference to its abstract and universal conditions, as distinguished from the science of determined or concrete being; the science of the conceptions and relations which are necessarily implied as true of every kind of being; philosophy in general; first principles, or the science of first principles.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Metaphysics</xex> is distinguished as <xex>general</xex> and <xex>special</xex>. <stype>General metaphysics</stype> is the science of all being as being. <stype>Special metaphysics</stype> is the science of one kind of being; as, the <xex>metaphysics</xex> of chemistry, of morals, or of politics.  According to Kant, a systematic exposition of those notions and truths, the knowledge of which is altogether independent of experience, would constitute the science of metaphysics.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Commonly, in the schools, called <qex>metaphysics</qex>, as being part of the philosophy of Aristotle, which hath that for title; but it is in another sense: for there it signifieth as much as <ldquo/books written or placed after his natural philosophy.<rdquo/  But the schools take them for <ldquo/books of supernatural philosophy;<rdquo/ for the word <qex>metaphysic</qex> will bear both these senses.</q> <rj><qau>Hobbes.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now the science conversant about all such inferences of unknown being from its known manifestations, is called ontology, or <qex>metaphysics</qex> proper.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Hamilton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Metaphysics</qex> are [is] the science which determines what can and what can not be known of being, and the laws of being, a priori.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>The scientific knowledge of mental phenomena; mental philosophy; psychology.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Metaphysics</qex>, in whatever latitude the term be taken, is a science or complement of sciences exclusively occupied with mind.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Hamilton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whether, after all,<br/
A larger <qex>metaphysics</qex> might not help<br/
Our physics.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs. Browning.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metaphysis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*taph"y*sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ after + <?/ nature.]</ety> <def>Change of form; transformation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metaplasm</ent><br/
<hw>Met"a*plasm</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>metaplasmus</ets>, Gr. <?/; <?/ beyond, over + <?/ to mold: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/taplasme</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>A change in the letters or syllables of a word.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metaplast</ent><br/
<hw>Met"a*plast</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Metaplasm</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>A word having more than one form of the root.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metapode</ent><br/
<hw>Met"a*pode</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. <ets>metapodium</ets>, from Gr. <?/ behind + <?/, dim. of <grk>poy`s</grk>, <grk>podo`s</grk>, foot.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The posterior division of the foot in the Gastropoda and Pteropoda.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metapodial</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*po"di*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the metapodialia, or to the parts of the limbs to which they belong.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metapodiale</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Met`a*po`di*a"le</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Metapodialia</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL. See <er>Metapode</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>One of the bones of either the metacarpus or metatarsus.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metapodium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Met`a*po"di*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Metapodia</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Metapode</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metapophysis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Met`a*poph"y*sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Metapophyses</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL. See <er>Meta-</er>, and <er>Apophysis</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A tubercle projecting from the anterior articular processes of some vertebrae; a mammillary process.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metapterygium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*tap`te*ryg"i*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ after + <?/ fin.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The posterior of the three principal basal cartilages in the fins of fishes.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Me*tap`ter*yg"i*al</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metasilicate</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*sil"i*cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of metasilicic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metasilicic</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*si*lic"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>meta-</ets> + <ets>silicic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Designating an acid derived from silicic acid by the removal of water; of or pertaining to such an acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The salts of metasilicic acid are often called <xex>bisilicates</xex>, in mineralogy, as Wollastonite (<chform>CaSiO3</chform>).</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Metasilicic acid</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>a gelatinous substance, or white amorphous powder, analogous to carbonic acid, and forming many stable salts.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metasomatism</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*so"ma*tism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>meta-</ets> + Gr. <?/, <?/, body.]</ety> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>An alteration in a mineral or rock mass when involving a chemical change of the substance, as of chrysolite to serpentine; -- opposed to ordinary <xex>metamorphism</xex>, as implying simply a recrystallization.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Met`a*so*mat"ic</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metasome</ent><br/
<hw>Met"a*some</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>meta-</ets> + <ets>-some</ets> body.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the component segments of the body of an animal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metastannate</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*stan"nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of metastannic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metastannic</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*stan"nic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or designating, a compound of tin (metastannic acid), obtained, as an isomeric modification of stannic acid, in the form of a white amorphous substance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metastasis</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tas"ta*sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Metastases</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., transition, fr. Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ to place in another way; <?/ after + <?/ to place.]</ety>  <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Theol.)</fld> <def>A spiritual change, as during baptism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A change in the location of a disease, as from one part to another.</def>  <rj><au>Dunglison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Especially:</specif> <def>The migration of cancerous or malignant cells from the site of their origin to other parts of the body.  Such cells may migrate to multiple new locations, making therapy more difficult and often leading to death.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>The act or process by which matter is taken up by cells or tissues and is transformed into other matter; in plants, the act or process by which are produced all of those chemical changes in the constituents of the plant which are not accompanied by a production of organic matter; metabolism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>metastasize</ent><br/
<hw>metastasize</hw> <pos>v.</pos> <def>to spread from one part of the body to other parts, and grow there; to spread by metastasis{3}; -- said of cancer cells.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metastatic</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*stat"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of, pertaining to, or caused by, metastasis; <as>as, a <ex>metastatic</ex> abscess; the <ex>metastatic</ex> processes of growth; a <ex>metastatic</ex> tumor.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metasternal</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*ster"nal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the metasternum.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metasternum</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Met`a*ster"num</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>meta-</ets> + <ets>sternum</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The most posterior element of the sternum; the ensiform process; xiphisternum.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The ventral plate of the third or last segment of the thorax of insects.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metastome</ent><br/
<ent>Metastoma</ent><br/
<mhw>{ \'d8<hw>Me*tas"to*ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Met"a*stome</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. <ets>metastoma</ets>, from Gr. <grk>meta`</grk> behind + <grk>sto`ma</grk> mouth.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A median elevation behind the mouth in the arthropods.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metatarsal</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*tar"sal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the metatarsus.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A metatarsal bone.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metatarse</ent><br/
<hw>Met"a*tarse</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Metatarsus.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metatarsus</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*tar"sus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Metatarsi</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL. See <er>Meta-</er>, and <er>Tarsus</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>That part of the skeleton of the hind or lower limb between the tarsus and phalanges; metatarse. It consists, in the human foot, of five bones. See <xex>Illustration</xex> in Appendix.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>metate</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>me*ta"te</hw> <pr>(m<asl/*t<aum/"t<asl/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp., fr. Mex. <ets>metlatl</ets>.]</ety> <def>A flat or somewhat hollowed stone upon which grain or other food is ground, by means of a smaller stone or pestle.</def> <mark>[Southwestern U. S. & Sp. Amer.]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metatheria</ent><br/
<hw>Metatheria</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A subclass of pouched animals.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> subclass <subclass>Metatheria</subclass>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>metatherian</ent><br/
<hw>metatherian</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Any of a group of primitive pouched mammals found mainly in Australia and the Americas.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metathesis</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tath"e*sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Metatheses</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <grk>meta`qesis</grk>, fr. <grk>metatiqe`nai</grk> to place differently, to transpose; <grk>meta`</grk> beyond, over + <grk>tiqe`nai</grk> to place, set. See <er>Thesis</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>Transposition, as of the letters or syllables of a word; <as>as, <xex>pistris</xex> for <xex>pristis</xex>; <xex>meagre</xex> for <xex>meager</xex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A mere change in place of a morbid substance, without removal from the body.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>The act, process, or result of exchange, substitution, or replacement of atoms and radicals; <as>thus, by <ex>metathesis</ex> an acid gives up all or part of its hydrogen, takes on an equivalent amount of a metal or base, and forms a salt</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metathetical</ent><br/
<ent>Metathetic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Met`a*thet"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Met`a*thet"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to metathesis.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metathoracic</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*tho*rac"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the metathorax.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metathorax</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*tho"rax</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL.: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/tathorax</ets>. See <er>Meta-</er>, and <er>Thorax</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The last or posterior segment of the thorax in insects. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Coleoptera</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metatitanic</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*ti*tan"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>meta-</ets> + <ets>titanic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or designating, an acid of titanium analogous to metasilicic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metatungstate</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*tung"state</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of metatungstic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metatungstic</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*tung"stic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>meta-</ets> + <ets>tungstic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or designating, an acid known only in its salts (the <xex>metatungstates</xex>) and properly called <xex>polytungstic</xex>, or <xex>pyrotungstic</xex>, acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metavanadate</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*van"a*date</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of metavanadic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metavanadic</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*va*nad"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>meta-</ets> + <ets>vanadic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or designating, a vanadic acid analogous to metaphosphoric acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metaxylene</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*xy"lene</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>meta-</ets> + <ets>xylene</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>That variety of xylene, or dimethyl benzene, in which the two methyl groups occupy the meta position with reference to each other. It is a colorless inflammable liquid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metayage</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>M<eacute/`ta`yage"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. See <er>M<eacute/tayer</er>.]</ety> <def>A system of farming on halves.</def> <mark>[France & Italy]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metayer</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>M<eacute/`ta`yer"</hw> <pr>(F. ?; E. ?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. LL. <ets>medietarius</ets>, fr. L. <ets>medius</ets> middle, half. See <er>Mid</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>One who cultivates land for a share (usually one half) of its yield, receiving stock, tools, and seed from the landlord; a type of <isa>sharecropper</isa>.</def> <mark>[France & Italy]</mark>  <rj><au>Milman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metazoa</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Met`a*zo"a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ after + <grk>zw^,on</grk> an animal.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Those animals in which the protoplasmic mass, constituting the egg, is converted into a multitude of cells, which are metamorphosed into the tissues of the body.  A central cavity is commonly developed, and the cells around it are at first arranged in two layers, -- the <xex>ectoderm</xex> and <xex>endoderm</xex>.  The group comprises nearly all animals except the Protozoa.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metazoan</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*zo"an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Metazoans</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the Metazoa.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metazoic</ent><br/
<hw>Met`a*zo"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the Metazoa.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metazoon</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Met`a*zo"on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the Metazoa.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mete</ent><br/
<hw>Mete</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Meat.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mete</ent><br/
<hw>Mete</hw>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To meet.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mete</ent><br/
<hw>Mete</hw>, <pos>v. i. & t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Mette</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Met</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<?/tan</ets>.]</ety> <def>To dream; also impersonally; <as>as, <ex>me mette</ex>, I dreamed</as>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/I <xex>mette</xex> of him all night.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mete</ent><br/
<hw>Mete</hw> <pr>(m<emac/t)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Meted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Meting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>metan</ets>; akin to D. <ets>meten</ets>, G. <ets>messen</ets>, OHG. <ets>mezzan</ets>, Icel. <ets>meta</ets>, Sw. <ets>m<aum/ta</ets>, Goth. <ets>mitan</ets>, L. <ets>modus</ets> measure, moderation, <ets>modius</ets> a corn measure, Gr. <?/ to rule, <?/ a corn measure, and ultimately from the same root as E. <ets>measure</ets>, L. <ets>metiri</ets> to measure; cf. Skr. <ets>m<amac/</ets> to measure. <root/99.  Cf. <er>Measure</er>, <er>Meet</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, <er>Mode</er>.]</ety> <def>To find the quantity, dimensions, or capacity of, by any rule or standard; to measure.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mete</ent><br/
<hw>Mete</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To measure.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Mark iv. 24.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mete</ent><br/
<hw>Mete</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>met</ets>. See <er>Mete</er> to measure.]</ety> <def>Measure; limit; boundary; -- used chiefly in the plural, and in the phrase <xex>metes and bounds</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metecorn</ent><br/
<hw>Mete"corn`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A quantity of corn formerly given by the lord to his customary tenants, as an encouragement to, or reward for, labor and faithful service.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metely</ent><br/
<hw>Mete"ly</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>According to measure or proportion; proportionable; proportionate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metempirical</ent><br/
<ent>Metempiric</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Met`em*pir"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Met`em*pir"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>met-</ets> + <ets>empiric</ets>, <ets>-ical</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Metaph.)</fld> <def>Related, or belonging, to the objects of knowledge within the province of metempirics.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If then the empirical designates the province we include within the range of science, the province we exclude may be fitly styled the <qex>metempirical</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>G. H. Lewes.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metempiricism</ent><br/
<hw>Met*em*pir"i*cism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The science that is concerned with metempirics.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metempirics</ent><br/
<hw>Met`em*pir"ics</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The concepts and relations which are conceived as beyond, and yet as related to, the knowledge gained by experience.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metempsychose</ent><br/
<hw>Me*temp"sy*chose</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Metempsychosed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Metempsychosing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Metempsychosis</er>.]</ety> <def>To translate or transfer, as the soul, from one body to another.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Peacham.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metempsychosis</ent><br/
<hw>Me*temp`sy*cho"sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/; <?/ beyond, over + <?/ to animate; <?/ in + <?/ soul. See <er>Psychology</er>.]</ety> <def>The passage of the soul, as an immortal essence, at the death of the animal body it had inhabited, into another living body, whether of a brute or a human being; transmigration of souls.</def>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metemptosis</ent><br/
<hw>Met`emp*to"sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., from Gr. <?/ beyond, after + <?/ a falling upon, fr. <?/ to fall in or upon; <?/ in + <?/ to fall.]</ety> <fld>(Chron.)</fld> <def>The suppression of a day in the calendar to prevent the date of the new moon being set a day too late, or the suppression of the bissextile day once in 134 years.  The opposite to this is the <xex>proemptosis</xex>, or the addition of a day every 330 years, and another every 2,400 years.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metencephalon</ent><br/
<hw>Met`en*ceph"a*lon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Met-</ets> + <ets>encephalon</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The posterior part of the brain, including the medulla; the afterbrain. Sometimes abbreviated to <xex>meten</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metensomatosis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Met`en*so`ma*to"sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., a change of body (by the soul), fr. Gr. <?/.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The assimilation by one body or organism of the elements of another.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meteor</ent><br/
<hw>Me"te*or</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/t<eacute/ore</ets>, Gr. <?/, pl. <?/ things in the air, fr. <?/ high in air, raised off the ground; <?/ beyond + <?/, <?/, a suspension or hovering in the air, fr. <?/ to lift, raise up.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Any phenomenon or appearance in the atmosphere, as clouds, rain, hail, snow, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hail, an ordinary <qex>meteor</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Hall.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Specif.: A transient luminous body or appearance seen in the atmosphere, or in a more elevated region.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The vaulty top of heaven<br/
Figured quite o'er with burning <qex>meteors</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A mass of stone or other substance which sometimes falls to the earth from space beyond the moon, burning up from atomospheric friction and creating a brilliant but usually very brief trail of light in the atmosphere; also called a <altname>shooting star</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The term is especially applied to fireballs, and the masses of stone or other substances which sometimes fall to the earth; also to shooting stars and to ignes fatui. Meteors are often classed as: <xex>aerial meteors</xex>, winds, tornadoes, etc.; <xex>aqueous meteors</xex>, rain, hail, snow, dew, etc.; <xex>luminous meteors</xex>, rainbows, halos, etc.; and <xex>igneous meteors</xex>, lightning, shooting stars, and the like.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meteoric</ent><br/
<hw>Me`te*or"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/t<eacute/orique</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a meteor, or to meteors; atmospheric, <as>as, <ex>meteoric</ex> phenomena; <ex>meteoric</ex> stones.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Influenced by the weather; <as>as, <ex>meteoric</ex> conditions</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Flashing; transient and brilliant, like a meteor{3}; <as>as, <ex>meteoric</ex> fame</as>.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Meteoric</xex> politician.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Craik.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Meteoric iron</b></col>, <col><b>Meteoric stone</b></col></mcol>. <fld>(Min.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Meteorite</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Meteoric paper</b></col>, <cd>a substance of confervoid origin found floating in the air, and resembling bits of coarse paper; -- so called because formerly supposed to fall from meteors.</cd> -- <col><b>Meteoric showers</b></col>, <cd>periodical exhibitions of shooting stars, occuring about the 9th or 10th of August and 13th of November, more rarely in April and December, and also at some other periods.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meteorical</ent><br/
<hw>Me`te*or"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Meteoric.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meteorism</ent><br/
<hw>Me"te*or*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Flatulent distention of the abdomen; tympanites.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meteorite</ent><br/
<hw>Me"te*or*ite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/t<eacute/orite</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A mass of stone or iron which has fallen to the earth from space; an aerolite.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Meteorites usually show a pitted surface with a fused crust, caused by the heat developed in their rapid passage through the earth's atmosphere. A meteorite may consist: <bold>1</bold>. Of metallic iron, alloyed with a small percentage of nickel (<xex>meteoric iron</xex>, <xex>holosiderite</xex>). When etched this usually exhibits peculiar crystalline figures, called <xex>Widmanst<aum/tten figures</xex>. <bold>2</bold>. Of a cellular mass of iron with imbedded silicates (<xex>mesosiderite</xex> or <xex>siderolite</xex>). <bold>3</bold>. Of a stony mass of silicates with little iron (<xex>meteoric stone</xex>, <xex>sporadosiderite</xex>). <bold>4</bold>. Of a mass without iron (<xex>asiderite</xex>).</note>
<-- Comm: carbonaceous? Add mark for composition? --><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meteorize</ent><br/
<hw>Me"te*or*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ to raise to a height.]</ety> <def>To ascend in vapors; to take the form of a meteor.</def>  <rj><au>Evelyn.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meteorograph</ent><br/
<hw>Me`te*or"o*graph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meteor</ets> + <ets>-graph</ets>.]</ety> <def>An instrument which registers meteorologic phases or conditions.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meteorographic</ent><br/
<hw>Me`te*or`o*graph"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to meteorography.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meteorography</ent><br/
<hw>Me`te*or*og"ra*phy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meteor</ets> + <ets>-graphy</ets>.]</ety> <def>The registration of meteorological phenomena.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 919 --></p>

<p><ent>Meteoroid</ent><br/
<hw>Me"te*or*oid</hw> <pr>(m<emac/"t<esl/*<etil/r*oid)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meteor</ets> + <ets>-oid</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>A small body moving through space, or revolving about the sun, which on entering the earth's atmosphere would be deflagrated and appear as a meteor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These bodies [small, solid bodies] before they come into the air, I call <qex>meteoroids</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>H. A. Newton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meteoroidal</ent><br/
<hw>Me`te*or*oid"al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to a meteoroid or to meteoroids.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meteorolite</ent><br/
<hw>Me`te*or"o*lite</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meteor</ets> + <ets>-lite</ets> : cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/t<eacute/orolithe</ets>.]</ety> <def>A meteoric stone; an aerolite; a meteorite.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meteorological</ent><br/
<ent>Meteorologic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Me`te*or`o*log"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Me`te*or`o*log"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/t<eacute/orologique</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to the atmosphere and its phenomena, or to meteorology.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Meteorological table</b></col>, <col><b>Meteorological register</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a table or register exhibiting the state of the air and its temperature, weight, dryness, moisture, motion, etc.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meteorologist</ent><br/
<hw>Me`te*or*ol"o*gist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/t<eacute/orologiste</ets>.]</ety> <def>A person skilled in meteorology.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meteorology</ent><br/
<hw>Me`te*or*ol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/; <?/ + <grk>lo`gos</grk> discourse: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/t<eacute/orologie</ets>. See <er>Meteor</er>.]</ety> <def>The science which treats of the atmosphere and its phenomena, particularly of its variations of heat and moisture, of its winds, storms, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meteoromancy</ent><br/
<hw>Me`te*or"o*man`cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meteor</ets> + <ets>-mancy</ets> : cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/t<eacute/oromancie</ets>.]</ety> <def>A species of divination by atmospheric phenomena, chiefly by thunder and lightning, which was held in high estimation by the Romans.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meteorometer</ent><br/
<hw>Me`te*or*om"e*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meteor</ets> + <ets>-meter</ets>.]</ety> <def>An apparatus which transmits automatically to a central station atmospheric conditions as marked by the anemometer, barometer, thermometer, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meteoroscope</ent><br/
<hw>Me`te*or"o*scope</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ observing the heavenly bodies; <?/ + <?/ to view: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/t<eacute/oroscope</ets>. See <er>Meteor</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>An astrolabe; a planisphere.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>An instrument for measuring the position, length, and direction, of the apparent path of a shooting star.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meteorous</ent><br/
<hw>Me*te"o*rous</hw> <pr>(? <or/ ?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Meteor</er>.]</ety> <def>Of the nature or appearance of a meteor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>-meter</ent><br/
<hw>-me"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[L. <ets>metrum</ets> measure, or the allied Gr. <?/. See <er>Meter</er> rhythm.]</ety> <def>A suffix denoting <xex>that by which anything is measured</xex>; <as>as, baro<ex>meter</ex>, chrono<ex>meter</ex>, dynamo<ex>meter</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meter</ent><br/
<hw>Me"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mete</er> to measure.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, metes or measures. See <er>Coal-meter</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An instrument for measuring, and usually for recording automatically, the quantity measured.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Dry meter</b></col>, <cd>a gas meter having measuring chambers, with flexible walls, which expand and contract like bellows and measure the gas by filling and emptying.</cd> -- <col><b>Wet meter</b></col>, <cd>a gas meter in which the revolution of a chambered drum in water measures the gas passing through it.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meter</ent><br/
<hw>Me"ter</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A line above or below a hanging net, to which the net is attached in order to strengthen it.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metre</ent><br/
<ent>Meter</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Me"ter</hw>, <hw>Me"tre</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>metre</ets>, F. <ets>m<egrave/tre</ets>, L. <ets>metrum</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/; akin to Skr. <ets>m<amac/</ets> to measure. See <er>Mete</er> to measure.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Rhythmical arrangement of syllables or words into verses, stanzas, strophes, etc.; poetical measure, depending on number, quantity, and accent of syllables; rhythm; measure; verse; also, any specific rhythmical arrangements; <as>as, the Horatian <ex>meters</ex>; a dactylic <ex>meter</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The only strict antithesis to prose is <qex>meter</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A poem.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Robynson (More's Utopia).</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A measure of length, equal to 39.37 English inches, the standard of linear measure in the metric system of weights and measures. It was intended to be, and is very nearly, the ten millionth part of the distance from the equator to the north pole, as ascertained by actual measurement of an arc of a meridian. See <cref>Metric system</cref>, under <er>Metric</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Common meter</b></col> <fld>(Hymnol.)</fld>, <cd>four iambic verses, or lines, making a stanza, the first and third having each four feet, and the second and fourth each three feet; -- usually indicated by the initials C. M.</cd> -- <col><b>Long meter</b></col> <fld>(Hymnol.)</fld>, <cd>iambic verses or lines of four feet each, four verses usually making a stanza; -- commonly indicated by the initials L. M.</cd> -- <col><b>Short meter</b></col> <fld>(Hymnol.)</fld>, <cd>iambic verses or lines, the first, second, and fourth having each three feet, and the third four feet.  The stanza usually consists of four lines, but is sometimes doubled.  <xex>Short meter</xex> is indicated by the initials S. M.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meterage</ent><br/
<hw>Me"ter*age</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See 1st <er>Meter</er>.]</ety> <def>The act of measuring, or the cost of measuring.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metergram</ent><br/
<hw>Me"ter*gram`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>A measure of energy or work done; the power exerted in raising one gram through the distance of one meter against gravitation; 100 gram-centimeters.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metewand</ent><br/
<hw>Mete"wand`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mete</ets> to measure + <ets>wand</ets>.]</ety> <def>A measuring rod.</def>  <rj><au>Ascham.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meteyard</ent><br/
<hw>Mete"yard`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>metgeard</ets>. See <er>Mete</er> to measure, and <er>Yard</er> stick.]</ety> <def>A yard, staff, or rod, used as a measure.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meth</ent><br/
<hw>Meth</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Meathe</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methaemoglobin</ent><br/
<hw>Met`haem*o*glo"bin</hw> <pr>(? <or/ ?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>met-</ets> + <ets>haemoglobin</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol. Chem.)</fld> <def>A stable crystalline compound obtained by the decomposition of hemoglobin.  It is found in old blood stains.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>methadone</ent><br/
<ent>methadon</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>methadon</hw>, <hw>methadone</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a narcotic drug similar to morphine but less habit-forming; used in treating heroin addiction.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> methadone hydrochloride.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methal</ent><br/
<hw>Meth"al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>M</ets>yristic + <ets>eth</ets>er + <ets>al</ets>cohol.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A white waxy substance, found in small quantities in spermaceti as an ethereal salt of several fatty acids, and regarded as an alcohol of the methane series.</def><-- cetyl alcohol?? = ethal --><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>methanal</ent><br/
<hw>methanal</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>formaldehyde</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methane</ent><br/
<hw>Meth"ane</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Methal</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A light, colorless, gaseous, inflammable hydrocarbon, <chform>CH4</chform>; marsh gas.  It is the simplest of the aliphatic hydrocarbons.  See <cref>Marsh gas</cref>, under <er>Gas</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Methane series</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>a series of saturated hydrocarbons, of which methane is the first member and type, and (because of their general chemical inertness and indifference) called also the <altname>paraffin (little affinity) series</altname>. The lightest members are gases, as methane, ethane; intermediate members are liquids, as hexane, heptane, etc. (found in benzine, kerosene, etc.); while the highest members are white, waxy, or fatty solids, as paraffin proper.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>methanogen</ent><br/
<hw>methanogen</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A type of archaebacteria found in anaerobic environments such as animal intestinal tracts or sediments or sewage, and capable of producing <prod>methane</prod>; a source of natural gas.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>methanol</ent><br/
<hw>methanol</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>The simplest alcohol of the paraffin series, <chform>CH3.OH</chform>; methyl alcohol.  Called also <altname>wood alcohol</altname>.  It is used as an antifreeze solvent, as a fuel, and as a denaturant for ethyl alcohol.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> methyl alcohol, wood alcohol, wood spirit.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methanometer</ent><br/
<hw>Meth`a*nom"e*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>  <ety>[<ets>Methane</ets> + <ets>-meter</ets>.]</ety> <def>An instrument, resembling a eudiometer, to detect the presence and amount of methane, as in coal mines.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metheglin</ent><br/
<hw>Me*theg"lin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[W. <ets>meddyglyn</ets>; <ets>medd</ets> mead + <ets>llyn</ets> liquor, juice. See <er>Mead</er> a drink.]</ety> <def>A fermented beverage made of honey and water; mead.</def>  <rj><au>Gay.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methene</ent><br/
<hw>Meth"ene</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meth</ets>yl + ethyl<ets>ene</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>See <er>Methylene</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methenyl</ent><br/
<hw>Meth"e*nyl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Methene</ets> + <ets>-yl</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>The hypothetical hydrocarbon radical <chform>CH</chform>, regarded as an essential residue of certain organic compounds.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methide</ent><br/
<hw>Meth"ide</hw> <pr>(? <or/ ?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Methyl</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A binary compound of methyl with some element; <as>as, aluminium <ex>methide</ex>, <chform>Al2(CH3)6</chform></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methinks</ent><br/
<hw>Me*thinks"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. impers.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Methought</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets><thorn/yncan</ets> to seem, <ets>m<emac/ <thorn/ynce<edh/</ets>, <ets>m<emac/ <thorn/<umac/hte</ets>, OE. <ets>me thinketh</ets>, <ets>me thoughte</ets>; akin to G. <ets>d<uum/nken</ets> to seem, <ets>denken</ets> to think, and E. <ets>think</ets>. See <er>Me</er>, and <er>Think</er>.]</ety> <def>It seems to me; I think. See <er>Me</er>.</def> <mark>[R., except in poetry.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In all ages poets have been had in special reputation, and, <qex>methinks</qex>, not without great cause.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methionate</ent><br/
<hw>Me*thi"on*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of methionic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methionic</ent><br/
<hw>Meth`i*on"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Me</ets>thyl + <ets>thionic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or designating, a sulphonic (<it>thionic</it>) acid derivative of methane, obtained as a stable white crystalline substance, <chform>CH2.(SO3H)2</chform>, which forms well defined salts.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Method</ent><br/
<hw>Meth"od</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/thode</ets>, L. <ets>methodus</ets>, fr. Gr. <grk>meqodos</grk> method, investigation following after; <grk>meta`</grk> after + <grk>"odo`s</grk> way.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An orderly procedure or process; regular manner of doing anything; hence, manner; way; mode; <as>as, a <ex>method</ex> of teaching languages; a <ex>method</ex> of improving the mind.</as></def>  <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Orderly arrangement, elucidation, development, or classification; clear and lucid exhibition; systematic arrangement peculiar to an individual.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though this be madness, yet there's <qex>method</qex> in it.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All <qex>method</qex> is a rational progress, a progress toward an end.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Hamilton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Nat. Hist.)</fld> <def>Classification; a mode or system of classifying natural objects according to certain common characteristics; <as>as, the <ex>method</ex> of Theophrastus; the <ex>method</ex> of Ray; the Linnaean <ex>method</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A technique used in acting in which the actor tries to identify with the individual personality of the specific character being portrayed, so as to provide a realistic rendering of the character's role.  Also called <altname>the Method</altname>, <altname>method acting</altname>, the <ecol><b>Stanislavsky Method</b></ecol> or <altname>Stanislavsky System</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Order; system; rule; regularity; way; manner; mode; course; process; means.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Method</er>, <er>Mode</er>, <er>Manner</er>. <xex>Method</xex> implies arrangement; <xex>mode</xex>, mere action or existence. <xex>Method</xex> is a way of reaching a given end by a <xex>series</xex> of acts which tend to secure it; <xex>mode</xex> relates to a single action, or to the form which a series of acts, viewed as a whole, exhibits. <xex>Manner</xex> is literally the <xex>handling</xex> of a thing, and has a wider sense, embracing both <xex>method</xex> and <xex>mode</xex>. An instructor may adopt a good <xex>method</xex> of teaching to write; the scholar may acquire a bad <xex>mode</xex> of holding his pen; the <xex>manner</xex> in which he is corrected will greatly affect his success or failure.</usage><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methodical</ent><br/
<ent>Methodic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Me*thod"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Me*thod"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>methodicus</ets>, Gr. <?/: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/thodique</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Arranged with regard to method; disposed in a suitable manner, or in a manner to illustrate a subject, or to facilitate practical observation; well-ordered; <as>as, the <ex>methodical</ex> arrangement of arguments; a <ex>methodical</ex> treatise.</as></def>  <wns>[wns=2]</wns> <ldquo/<xex>Methodical</xex> regularity.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Proceeding with regard to method; characterized by method or orderliness; systematic; <as>as, a <ex>methodical</ex> investigation</as>.</def> <wns>[wns=1]</wns> <ldquo/Aristotle, strict, <xex>methodic</xex>, and orderly.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Harris.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the ancient school of physicians called methodists.</def>  <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Me*thod"ic*al*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Me*thod"ic*al*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methodios</ent><br/
<hw>Me*thod"ios</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The art and principles of method.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methodism</ent><br/
<hw>Meth"o*dism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>The system of doctrines, polity, and worship, of the sect called Methodists.</def>  <rj><au>Bp. Warburton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methodist</ent><br/
<hw>Meth"o*dist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/thodiste</ets>. See <er>Method</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who observes method.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One of an ancient school of physicians who rejected observation and founded their practice on reasoning and theory.</def>  <rj><au>Sir W. Hamilton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Theol.)</fld> <def>One of a sect of Christians, the outgrowth of a small association called the <ldquo/Holy Club,<rdquo/ formed at Oxford University, <sc>a. d.</sc> 1729, of which the most conspicuous members were <person>John Wesley</person> and his brother <person>Charles Wesley</person>; -- originally so called from the methodical strictness of members of the club in all religious duties.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A person of strict piety; one who lives in the exact observance of religious duties; -- sometimes so called in contempt or ridicule.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methodist</ent><br/
<hw>Meth"o*dist</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the sect of Methodists; <as>as, <ex>Methodist</ex> hymns; a <ex>Methodist</ex> elder.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methodistical</ent><br/
<ent>Methodistic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Meth`o*dis"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Meth`o*dis"tic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to methodists, or to the Methodists.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Meth`o*dis"tic*al*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methodization</ent><br/
<hw>Meth`od*i*za"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act or process of methodizing, or the state of being methodized.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methodize</ent><br/
<hw>Meth"od*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Methodized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Methodizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To reduce to method; to dispose in due order; to arrange in a convenient manner; <as>as, to <ex>methodize</ex> one's work or thoughts</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Spectator.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methodizer</ent><br/
<hw>Meth"od*i`zer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who methodizes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methodological</ent><br/
<hw>Meth`od*o*log"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to methodology.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methodology</ent><br/
<hw>Meth`od*ol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ method + <ets>-logy</ets>.]</ety> <def>The science of method or arrangement; a treatise on method.</def>  <rj><au>Coleridge.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methol</ent><br/
<hw>Meth"ol</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ wine + <ets>-ol</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>An earlier  technical name of methyl alcohol or wood spirit, now called <altname>methanol</altname>; also, by extension, the class name of any of the series of alcohols of the methane series of which <xex>methol</xex> proper is the type. See <cref>Methyl alcohol</cref>, under <er>Methyl</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methought</ent><br/
<hw>Me*thought"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <def><pos>imp.</pos> of <er>Methinks</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methoxyl</ent><br/
<hw>Meth*ox"yl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Meth</ets>yl + hydr<ets>oxyl</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A hypothetical radical, <chform>CH3O</chform>, analogous to hydroxyl.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methyl</ent><br/
<hw>Meth"yl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Methylene</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A univalent hydrocarbon radical, <chform>CH3-</chform>, not existing alone but regarded as an essential residue of methane, and appearing as a component part of many derivatives; <as>as, <ex>methyl</ex> alcohol, <ex>methyl</ex> ether, <ex>methyl</ex> amine, etc.</as></def> <altsp>[Formerly written also <asp>methule</asp>, <asp>methyle</asp>, etc.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Methyl alcohol</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>a light, volatile, inflammable liquid, <chform>CH3.OH</chform>, obtained by the distillation of wood, and hence called <altname>wood alcohol</altname> or <altname>wood spirit</altname>; tecnically referred to as <altname>methanol</altname>; -- called also <altname>methol</altname>, <altname>carbinol</altname>, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Methyl amine</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>a colorless, inflammable, alkaline gas, <chform>CH3.NH2</chform>, having an ammoniacal, fishy odor.  It is produced artificially, and also occurs naturally in herring brine and other fishy products.  It is regarded as ammonia in which a third of its hydrogen is replaced by methyl, and is a type of the class of <isa>substituted ammonias</isa>.</cd> -- <col><b>Methyl ether</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>a light, volatile ether <chform>CH3.O.CH3</chform>, obtained by the etherification of methyl alcohol; -- called also <altname>methyl oxide</altname> or <altname>dimethyl ether</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Methyl green</b></col>. <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Green</er>, <pos>n.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>Methyl orange</b></col>. <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Helianthin</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Methyl violet</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>an artificial dye, consisting of certain methyl halogen derivatives of rosaniline.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methylal</ent><br/
<hw>Meth"yl*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Methyl</ets>ene + <ets>al</ets>cohol.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A light, volatile liquid, <chform>H2C(OCH3)2</chform>, regarded as a complex ether, and having a pleasant ethereal odor. It is obtained by the partial oxidation of methyl alcohol.  Called also <altname>formal</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methylamine</ent><br/
<hw>Meth`yl*am"ine</hw> <pr>(? <or/ ?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>See <cref>Methyl amine</cref>, under <er>Methyl</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methylate</ent><br/
<hw>Meth"yl*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Methyl</ets> + alcohol<ets>ate</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>An alcoholate of methyl alcohol in which the hydroxyl hydrogen is replaced by a metal, after the analogy of a hydrate; <as>as, sodium <ex>methylate</ex>, <chform>CH3ONa</chform></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methylate</ent><br/
<hw>Meth"yl*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To impregnate or mix with methyl or methyl alcohol.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methylated</ent><br/
<hw>Meth"yl*a`ted</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Impregnated with, or containing, methyl alcohol or wood spirit; <as>as, <ex>methylated</ex> spirits</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methylene</ent><br/
<hw>Meth"yl*ene</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/thyl<egrave/ne</ets>, from Gr. <?/ wine + <?/ wood; -- a word coined to correspond to the name <ets>wood spirit</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A divalent hydrocarbon radical, <chform>-CH2-</chform>, not known in the free state, but regarded as an essential residue and component of certain derivatives of methane; <as>as, <ex>methylene</ex> bromide, <chform>CH2Br2</chform></as>; -- formerly called also <altname>methene</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Methylene blue</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>an artificial dyestuff consisting of a complex sulphur derivative of diphenyl amine; -- called also <altname>pure blue</altname>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>methylenedioxymethamphetamine</ent><br/
<hw>methylenedioxymethamphetamine</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a drug designed to have the effects of amphetamines but to avoid the drug laws, but now a controlled substance.  Called also <altname>MDMA</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> MDMA, Adam, ecstasy.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methylic</ent><br/
<hw>Me*thyl"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, derived from, or containing, methyl; specifically, designating methyl alcohol. See under <er>Methyl</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methysticin</ent><br/
<hw>Me*thys"ti*cin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A white, silky, crystalline substance extracted from the thick rootstock of a species of pepper (<spn>Piper methysticum</spn>) of the South Sea Islands; -- called also <altname>kanakin</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metic</ent><br/
<hw>Met"ic</hw> <pr>(? <or/ ?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/, prop., changing one's abode; <?/, indicating change + <?/ house, abode: cf. L. <ets>metoecus</ets>, F. <ets>m<eacute/t<egrave/que</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Gr. Antiq.)</fld> <def>A sojourner; an immigrant; an alien resident in a Grecian city, but not a citizen.</def>  <rj><au>Mitford.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The whole force of Athens, <qex>metics</qex> as well as citizens, and all the strangers who were then in the city.</q> <rj><qau>Jowett (Thucyd. ).</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>meticulosity</ent><br/
<hw>meticulosity</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>strict attention to minute details; the quality of being meticulous.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> meticulousness, punctiliousness, scrupulousness.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meticulous</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tic"u*lous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>meticulosus</ets>, fr. <ets>metus</ets> fear: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/ticuleux</ets>.]</ety> <def>Timid; fearful.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark> <br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Taking great care to get every detail correct; working thoroughly and with precision; <as>as, <ex>meticulous</ex> workmanship</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Me*tic"u*lous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metier</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>M<eacute/`tier"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Calling; vocation; business; trade.</def></p>

<p><q>Not only is it the business of no one to preach the truth but it is the <qex>m<eacute/tier</qex> of many to conceal it.</q>  <rj><qau>A. R. Colquhoun.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>the field or activity at which one excels; one's forte.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metive</ent><br/
<ent>Metif</ent><br/
<mhw>{ \'d8<hw>M<eacute/`tif"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. m.</pos> \'d8<hw>M<eacute/`tive"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. f.</pos> }</mhw><ety>[F.]</ety> <def>See <er>M<eacute/tis</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metisse</ent><br/
<ent>Metis</ent><br/
<mhw>{ \'d8<hw>M<eacute/`tis"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. m.</pos> \'d8<hw>M<eacute/`tisse"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. f.</pos> }</mhw><ety>[F.; akin to Sp. <ets>mestizo</ets>. See <er>Mestizo</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The offspring of a white person and an American Indian.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The offspring of a white person and a quadroon; an octoroon.</def> <mark>[Local, U. S.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bartlett.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metoche</ent><br/
<hw>Met"o*che</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ a sharing, fr. <?/ to share in; <?/ with + <?/ to have.]</ety> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The space between two dentils.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The space between two triglyphs.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metol</ent><br/
<hw>Me"tol</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G.; trade name, fr. <ets>meta-</ets> + kre<ets>sol</ets> cresol.]</ety> <def>A whitish soluble powder used as a developer in photography.  Chemically, it is the sulphate of <chname>methyl-<it>p</it>-amino-<it>m</it>-cresol</chname>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metonic</ent><br/
<hw>Me*ton"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/tonique</ets>.]</ety> <def>Pertaining to, or discovered by, <persfn><etsep>Meton</etsep></persfn>, the Athenian.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Metonic year</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Metonic cycle</b></col></mcol>. <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Cycle</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metonymical</ent><br/
<ent>Metonymic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Met`o*nym"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Met`o*nym"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Metonymy</er>.]</ety> <def>Used by way of metonymy; using the name of one thing for that of another with which it is closely associated.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Met`o*nym"ic*al*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metonymy</ent><br/
<hw>Me*ton"y*my</hw> <pr>(m<esl/*t<ocr/n"<icr/*m<ycr/; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>metonymia</ets>, Gr. <grk>metwnymi`a</grk>; <grk>meta`</grk>, indicating change + <grk>'o`nyma</grk> , for <grk>'o`noma</grk> a name: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/tonymie</ets>. See <er>Name</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Rhet.)</fld> <def>A trope in which one word is put for another that suggests it; <as>as, we say, a man keeps a good <examp>table</examp> instead of good <ex>provisions</ex>; we read <examp>Virgil</examp>, that is, his <ex>poems</ex>; a man has a warm <examp>heart</examp>, that is, warm <ex>affections</ex>; a city dweller has no <examp>wheels</examp>, that is, no automobile.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metope</ent><br/
<hw>Met"o*pe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/; <grk>meta`</grk> with, between + <?/ opening, hole, the hole in the frieze between the beam ends.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>The space between two triglyphs of the Doric frieze, which, among the ancients, was often adorned with carved work. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Entablature</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The face of a crab.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ In the Parthenon, groups of centaurs and heroes in high relief occupy the metopes.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metopic</ent><br/
<hw>Me*top"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ the forehead.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the forehead or frontal bones; frontal; <as>as, the <ex>metopic</ex> suture</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metopomancy</ent><br/
<hw>Met"o*po*man`cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ the forehead + <ets>-mancy</ets>.]</ety> <def>Fortune telling by physiognomy.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Urquhart.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metoposcopical</ent><br/
<ent>Metoposcopic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Met`o*po*scop"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Met`o*po*scop"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or relating to metoposcopy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metoposcopist</ent><br/
<hw>Met`o*pos"co*pist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One versed in metoposcopy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metoposcopy</ent><br/
<hw>Met`o*pos"co*py</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ observing the forehead; <?/ the forehead + <?/ to view: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/toposcopie</ets>.]</ety> <def>The study of physiognomy; the art of discovering the character of persons by their features, or the lines of the face.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metosteon</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*tos"te*on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ after + <?/ bone.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The postero-lateral ossification in the sternum of birds; also, the part resulting from such ossification.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 920 --></p>

<p><ent>Metre</ent><br/
<hw>Me"tre</hw> <pr>(m<emac/"t<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Meter</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metric</ent><br/
<hw>Met"ric</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/t"r<icr/k)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>metricus</ets>, Gr. <?/: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/trique</ets>. See <er>Meter</er> rhythm.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Relating to measurement; involving, or proceeding by, measurement.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the meter as a standard of measurement; of or pertaining to the decimal system of measurement of which a meter is the unit; <as>as, the <ex>metric</ex> system; a <ex>metric</ex> measurement.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Metric analysis</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>analysis by volume; volumetric analysis.</cd> -- <col><b>Metric system</b></col>, <cd>See <er>metric system</er> in the vocabulary.</cd></cs>
<-- nano-, pico-, femto-, atto-; giga-, tera, etc. --><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metrical</ent><br/
<hw>Met"ric*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the meter; arranged in meter; consisting of verses; <as>as, <ex>metrical</ex> compositions</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to measurement; <as>as, the inch, foot, yard, etc.</as>, are <xex>metrical</xex> terms; esp., of or pertaining to the metric system.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metrically</ent><br/
<hw>Met"ric*al*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a metrical manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>metrication</ent><br/
<hw>met`ri*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/t`r<icr/*k<amac/"sh<ucr/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act or process of converting the standard system of units of a country to those of the <er>metric system</er>; metrification; <as>as, Great Britain has completed its <ex>metrification</ex>, but the United States still resists complete change</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metrician</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tri"cian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/tricien</ets>. See <er>Meter</er> rhythm.]</ety> <def>A composer of verses.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metric system</ent><br/
<hw>Met"ric sys"tem</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A system of weights and measures originating in France, the use of which is required by law in many countries, and permitted in many others, including the United States; the system is also called by its French name, <altname>Le Syst<egrave/me International de Unit<eacute/s</altname> (abbreviated <abbr>SI</abbr>).  The principal unit of length is the <xex>meter</xex> (see <er>Meter</er>).  From this are formed the <xex>are</xex>, the <xex>liter</xex>, the <xex>stere</xex>, the <xex>gram</xex>, etc. These units, and others derived from them, are divided decimally, and larger units are formed from multiples by 10, 100, 1,000, and 10,000.  The successive multiplies are designated by the prefixes, <xex>deka-</xex> (formerly <xex>deca-</xex>), <xex>hecto-</xex>, <xex>kilo-</xex>, and <xex>myria-</xex> (seldom used); successive parts by <xex>deci-</xex>, <xex>centi-</xex>, and <xex>milli-</xex>.  The prefixes <xex>mega-</xex> and <xex>micro-</xex> are used to denote a multiple by one million, and the millionth part, respectively; <xex>giga-</xex> and <xex>nano-</xex> denote multiples of one billion (1,000,000,000) and one billionth, respectively.  The prefix for one trillion (10<sup>12</sup>) is <xex>tera</xex>, and for one trillionth (10<sup>-12</sup>) is <xex>pico</xex>;  for one quintillion (10<sup>15</sup>) <xex>peta</xex>, and for (10<sup>-15</sup>) (one quintillionth) <xex>femto</xex>;  for (10<sup>-18</sup>) <xex>atto</xex>.  See the words formed with these prefixes in the Vocabulary. For <xex>metric tables</xex>, see p. 1682.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metric ton</ent><br/
<hw>Met"ric ton</hw>. <def>A weight of 1,000 kilograms, or 2,204.6 pounds avoirdupois.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metrification</ent><br/
<hw>Met`ri*fi*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>  <def>Composition in metrical form; versification.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act or process of converting the standard system of units of a country to those of the metric system; metrication.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metrify</ent><br/
<hw>Met"ri*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>metrum</ets> meter + <ets>-fy</ets>: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/trifier</ets>.]</ety> <def>To make verse.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Skelton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metrist</ent><br/
<hw>Me"trist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A maker of verses.</def>  <rj><au>Bale.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Spenser was no mere <qex>metrist</qex>, but a great composer.</q> <rj><qau>Lowell.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metritis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me*tri"tis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ womb + <ets>-tis</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Inflammation of the womb.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metrochrome</ent><br/
<hw>Met"ro*chrome</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ + <?/ color.]</ety> <def>An instrument for measuring colors.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metrograph</ent><br/
<hw>Met"ro*graph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ measure + <ets>-graph</ets>.]</ety> <def>An instrument attached to a locomotive for recording its speed and the number and duration of its stops.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metrological</ent><br/
<hw>Met`ro*log"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/trologique</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to metrology.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metrology</ent><br/
<hw>Me*trol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ measure + <ets>-m<eacute/trologie</ets>.]</ety> <def>The science of, or a system of, weights and measures; also, a treatise on the subject.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metromania</ent><br/
<hw>Met`ro*ma"ni*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ measure + E. <ets>mania</ets>.]</ety> <def>A mania for writing verses.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metromaniac</ent><br/
<hw>Met`ro*ma"ni*ac</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who has metromania.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metrometer</ent><br/
<hw>Me*trom"e*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ womb + <ets>-meter</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>An instrument for measuring the size of the womb.</def>  <rj><au>Knight.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metronome</ent><br/
<hw>Met"ro*nome</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ measure + <?/ distribute, assign: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/tronome</ets>, It. <ets>metronomo</ets>.]</ety> <def>An instrument consisting of a short pendulum with a sliding weight.  It is set in motion by clockwork, and serves to measure time in music.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metronomy</ent><br/
<hw>Me*tron"o*my</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Metronome</er>.]</ety> <def>Measurement of time by an instrument.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metronymic</ent><br/
<hw>Met`ro*nym"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/; <?/ mother + <?/, for <?/ name.]</ety> <def>Derived from the name of one's mother, or other female ancestor; <as>as, a <ex>metronymic</ex> name or appellation</as>.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A metronymic appellation.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metropole</ent><br/
<hw>Met"ro*pole</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/tropole</ets>. See <er>Metropolis</er>.]</ety> <def>A metropolis.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Holinshed.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metropolis</ent><br/
<hw>Me*trop"o*lis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>metropolis</ets>, Gr. <?/, prop., the mother city (in relation to colonies); <?/ mother + <?/ city. See <er>Mother</er>, and <er>Police</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The mother city; the chief city of a kingdom, state, or country.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Edinburgh] gray <qex>metropolis</qex> of the North.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>The seat, or see, of the metropolitan, or highest church dignitary.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The great <qex>metropolis</qex> and see of Rome.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Any large city.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metropolitan</ent><br/
<hw>Met`ro*pol"i*tan</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>metropolitanus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/tropolitain</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the capital or principal city of a country; <as>as, <ex>metropolitan</ex> luxury</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or designating, a metropolitan or the presiding bishop of a country or province, his office, or his dignity; <as>as, <ex>metropolitan</ex> authority</as>.</def> <ldquo/Bishops <xex>metropolitan</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Sir T. More.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metropolitan</ent><br/
<hw>Met`ro*pol"i*tan</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>metropolitanus</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The superior or presiding bishop of a country or province.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Lat. Church.)</fld> <def>An archbishop.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Gr. Church)</fld> <def>A bishop whose see is a civil metropolis.  His rank is intermediate between that of an archbishop and a patriarch; <as>as, the <ex>metropolitan</ex> of Constantinople</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Hook.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metropolitanate</ent><br/
<hw>Met`ro*pol"i*tan*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The see of a metropolitan bishop.</def>  <rj><au>Milman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metropolite</ent><br/
<hw>Me*trop"o*lite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>metropolita</ets>, Gr. <?/.]</ety> <def>A metropolitan.</def>  <rj><au>Barrow.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metropolitical</ent><br/
<hw>Met`ro*po*lit"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to a metropolis; being a metropolis; metropolitan; <as>as, the <ex>metropolitical</ex> chair</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metrorrhagia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Met`ror*rha"gi*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ womb + <?/ to break.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Profuse bleeding from the womb, esp. such as does not occur at the menstrual period.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metroscope</ent><br/
<hw>Met"ro*scope</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ womb + <ets>-scope</ets>.]</ety> <def>A modification of the stethoscope, for directly auscultating the uterus from the vagina.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metrosideros</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Met`ro*si*de"ros</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ heart of a tree + <?/ iron.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A myrtaceous genus of trees or shrubs, found in Australia and the South Sea Islands, and having very hard wood.  <spn>Metrosideros vera</spn> is the true ironwood.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metrotome</ent><br/
<hw>Met"ro*tome</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Metrotomy</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Surg.)</fld> <def>An instrument for cutting or scarifying the uterus or the neck of the uterus.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metrotomy</ent><br/
<hw>Me*trot"o*my</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ womb + <?/ to cut: cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/trotomie</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Surg.)</fld> <def>The operation of cutting into the uterus; hysterotomy; the Caesarean section.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>-metry</ent><br/
<hw>-me*try</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[See <er>-meter</er>.]</ety> <def>A suffix denoting the <xex>art</xex>, <xex>process</xex>, or <xex>science</xex>, <xex>of measuring</xex>; <as>as, acidi<ex>metry</ex>, bathy<ex>metry</ex>, chloro<ex>metry</ex>, chrono<ex>metry</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mette</ent><br/
<hw>Mette</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <mark>obs.</mark> <def><pos>imp.</pos> of <er>Mete</er>, to dream.</def> <au>Chaucer.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mettle</ent><br/
<hw>Met"tle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[E. <ets>metal</ets>, used in a tropical sense in allusion to the temper of the metal of a sword blade. See <er>Metal</er>.]</ety> <def>Substance or quality of temperament; spirit, esp. as regards honor, courage, fortitude, ardor, etc.; disposition; -- usually in a good sense; <as>as, to test a person's <ex>mettle</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A certain critical hour which shall . . . try what <qex>mettle</qex> his heart is made of.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Gentlemen of brave <qex>mettle</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The winged courser, like a generous horse,<br/
Shows most true <qex>mettle</qex> when you check his course.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To put one one's mettle</b></col>, <cd>to cause or incite one to use one's best efforts.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mettled</ent><br/
<hw>Met"tled</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having mettle; high-spirited; ardent; full of fire.</def>  <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mettlesome</ent><br/
<hw>Met"tle*some</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Full of spirit; possessing constitutional ardor; fiery; <as>as, a <ex>mettlesome</ex> horse</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Met"tle*some*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Met"tle*some*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meum</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Me"um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., neut. of <ets>meus</ets> mine.]</ety> <def>Lit., mine; that which is mine; -- used in the phrase <xex>meum et tuum</xex>, or <xex>meum and tuum</xex>; <as>as, to confound <ex>meum and tuum</ex>, to fail to distinguish one's own property from that of others</as>; to be dishonest.</def></p>

<p><q>Ancestors . . . generally esteemed more renowned for ancient family and high courage than for accurately regarding the trifling distinction of <qex>meum and tuum</qex>.</q>  <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meuse</ent><br/
<hw>Meuse</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A European river, flowing into the North Sea.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Meuse River.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An American operation in World War I (1918); American troops under Pershing drove back the German armies which were saved only by the Armistice on November 11.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Meuse River, Argonne, Argonne Forest, Meuse-Argonne, Meuse-Argonne operation.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meuse-Argonne</ent><br/
<hw>Meuse-Argonne</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>an American operation in World War I (1918); American troops under Pershing drove back the German armies which were saved only by the Armistice on November 11.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Meuse, Meuse River, Argonne, Argonne Forest, Meuse-Argonne operation.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meute</ent><br/
<hw>Meute</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A cage for hawks; a mew. See 4th <er>Mew</er>, 1.</def>  <rj><au>Milman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meve</ent><br/
<hw>Meve</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To move.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mew</ent><br/
<hw>Mew</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<?/w</ets>, akin to D. <ets>meeuw</ets>, G. <ets>m<oum/we</ets>, OHG. <ets>m<?/h</ets>, Icel. <ets>m<amac/r</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A gull, esp. the common British species (<spn>Larus canus</spn>); called also <altname>sea mew</altname>, <altname>maa</altname>, <altname>mar</altname>, <altname>mow</altname>, and <altname>cobb</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mew</ent><br/
<hw>Mew</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mewed</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mewing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>muen</ets>, F. <ets>muer</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mutare</ets> to change, fr. <ets>movere</ets> to move. See <er>Move</er>, and cf. <er>Mew</er> a cage, <er>Molt</er>.]</ety> <def>To shed or cast; to change; to molt; <as>as, the hawk <ex>mewed</ex> his feathers</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nine times the moon had <qex>mewed</qex> her horns.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mew</ent><br/
<hw>Mew</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To cast the feathers; to molt; hence, to change; to put on a new appearance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now everything doth <qex>mew</qex>,<br/
And shifts his rustic winter robe.</q> <rj><qau>Turbervile.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mew</ent><br/
<hw>Mew</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mue</ets>, F. <ets>mue</ets> change of feathers, scales, skin, the time or place when the change occurs, fr. <ets>muer</ets> to molt, mew, L. <ets>mutare</ets> to change. See 2d <er>Mew</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A cage for hawks while mewing; a coop for fattening fowls; hence, any inclosure; a place of confinement or shelter; -- in the latter sense usually in the plural.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Full many a fat partrich had he in <qex>mewe</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Forthcoming from her darksome <qex>mew</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Violets in their secret <qex>mews</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A stable or range of stables for horses; -- compound used in the plural, and so called from the royal stables in London, built on the site of the king's mews for hawks.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mew</ent><br/
<hw>Mew</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mew</er> a cage.]</ety> <def>To shut up; to inclose; to confine, as in a cage or other inclosure.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>More pity that the eagle should be <qex>mewed</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Close <qex>mewed</qex> in their sedans, for fear of air.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mew</ent><br/
<hw>Mew</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Of imitative origin; cf. G. <ets>miauen</ets>.]</ety> <def>To cry as a cat.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>meaw</asp>, <asp>meow</asp>.]</altsp>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mew</ent><br/
<hw>Mew</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The common cry of a cat.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mewl</ent><br/
<hw>Mewl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mewled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mewling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>miauler</ets> to mew, E. <ets>mew</ets> to cry as a cat.  Cf. <er>Miaul</er>.]</ety> <def>To cry, as a young child; to squall.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>meawl</asp>.]</altsp>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mewler</ent><br/
<hw>Mewl"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One that mewls.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mews</ent><br/
<hw>Mews</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. sing. & pl.</pos> <ety>[Prop. pl. of <ets>mew</ets>. See <er>Mew</er> a cage.]</ety> <def>An alley where there are stables; a narrow passage; a confined place.</def> <mark>[Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mr. Turveydrop's great room . . . was built out into a <qex>mews</qex> at the back.</q> <rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mexical</ent><br/
<ent>Mexal</ent><br/
<mhw>\'d8<hw>Mex*al"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mex"i*cal</hw> <pr>(#)</pr></mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>mexcal</ets>.]</ety> <def>See <er>Mescal</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mexican</ent><br/
<hw>Mex"i*can</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to Mexico or its people.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A native or inhabitant of Mexico.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mexican poppy</b></col> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a tropical American herb of the Poppy family (<spn>Argemone Mexicana</spn>) with much the look of a thistle, but having large yellow or white blossoms.</cd> -- <col><b>Mexican tea</b></col> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>an aromatic kind of pigweed from tropical America (<spn>Chenopodium ambrosioides</spn>).</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mexicanize</ent><br/
<hw>Mex"i*can*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. v. t.</pos> <def>To cause to be like the Mexicans, or their country.</def>  <note>At one time this word referred to frequent revolutions of government, considered characteristic of Mexican politics.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mexicanize</ent><br/
<hw>Mex"i*can*ize</hw>, <pos>prop. v. i.</pos> <def>To become like the Mexicans, or their country or government.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meyne</ent><br/
<hw>Meyn"e</hw> <pr>(m<ecr/n"<esl/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <def>Same as <er>Meine</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mezcal</ent><br/
<hw>Mez*cal"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Mescal</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mezereon</ent><br/
<hw>Me*ze"re*on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/z<eacute/r<eacute/on</ets>, Per. <ets>m<amac/zriy<umac/n</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A small European shrub (<spn>Daphne Mezereum</spn>), whose acrid bark is used in medicine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mezquita</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mez*qui"ta</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp.]</ety> <def>A mosque.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mezuzoth</ent><br/
<ent>Mezuzah</ent><br/
<ent>Mezuza</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Me*zu"za</hw>, <hw>Me*zu"zah</hw>, <hw>Mez"u*zoth</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Heb. <ets>m<ecr/z<umac/z<omac/th</ets>, pl. of <ets>m<ecr/z<umac/z<amac/h</ets> doorpost.]</ety> <def>A piece of parchment bearing the Decalogue and attached to the doorpost; -- in use among orthodox Hebrews.  The term is also used to refer to the small case containing this scroll, together with the biblical inscription inside.  The text is usually taken from Deuteronomy 6:4-9 and 11:13-21.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mezza majolica</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mez"za ma*jol"i*ca</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[It. See <er>Mezzo</er>; <er>Majolica</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Ceramics)</fld> <def>Italian pottery of the epoch and general character of majolica, but less brilliantly decorated, esp. such pottery without tin enamel, but painted and glazed.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mezzanine</ent><br/
<hw>Mez"za*nine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mezzanine</ets>, It. <ets>mezzanino</ets>, fr. <ets>mezzano</ets> middle, fr. <ets>mezzo</ets> middle, half. See <er>Mezzo</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Same as <er>Entresol</er>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A partial story which is not on the same level with the story of the main part of the edifice, as of a back building, where the floors are on a level with landings of the staircase of the main house.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A flooring laid over a floor to bring it up to some height or level.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn>  Also <col><b>mezzanine floor</b></col>. <fld>(Theat.)</fld> <def>A floor under the stage, from which various contrivances, as traps, are worked.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The lowest balcony in a theater, or the forward part of the first balcony.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mezza voce</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mez"za vo"ce</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[It., fr. <ets>mezzo</ets>, fem. <ets>mezza</ets> middle, half + <ets>voce</ets> voice, L. <ets>vox</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>With a medium fullness of sound.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mezzo</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mez"zo</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[It., from L. <ets>medius</ets> middle, half. See <er>Mid</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Mean; not extreme.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mezzo-relievo</ent><br/
<hw>Mez"zo-re*lie"vo</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mezzo-rilievo.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mezzo-rilievo</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mez"zo-ri*lie"vo</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It.]</ety> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A middle degree of relief in figures, between high and low relief.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Sculpture in this kind of relief. See under <er>Alto-rilievo</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mezzo-soprano</ent><br/
<hw>Mez"zo-so*pra"no</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Having a medium compass between the soprano and contralto; -- said of the voice of a female singer.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A mezzo-soprano voice.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A person having such a voice.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mezzotint</ent><br/
<hw>Mez"zo*tint</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mezzo-tinto</ets>.]</ety> <def>A manner of engraving on copper or steel by drawing upon a surface previously roughened, and then removing the roughness in places by scraping, burnishing, etc., so as to produce the requisite light and shade. Also, an engraving so produced.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mezzotint</ent><br/
<hw>Mez"zo*tint</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To engrave in mezzotint.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mezzotinter</ent><br/
<hw>Mez"zo*tint`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who engraves in mezzotint.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mezzotinto</ent><br/
<hw>Mez`zo*tin"to</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It. <ets>mezzo</ets> half + <ets>tinto</ets> tinted, p. p. of <ets>tingere</ets> to dye, color, tinge, L. <ets>tingere</ets>. See <er>Mezzo</er>.]</ety> <def>Mezzotint.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mezzotinto</ent><br/
<hw>Mez`zo*tin"to</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mezzotintoed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mezzotintoing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To engrave in mezzotint; to represent by mezzotint.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mho</ent><br/
<hw>Mho</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Anagram of <ets>ohm</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>A unit of conductivity, being the reciprocal of the ohm.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mhometer</ent><br/
<hw>Mhom"e*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>  <ety>[<ets>Mho</ets>  + <ets>-meter</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>An instrument for measuring conductivity.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mhorr</ent><br/
<hw>Mhorr</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Mohr</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mi</ent><br/
<hw>Mi</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A syllable applied to the third tone of the scale of C, <it>i. e.</it>, to E, in European solmization, but to the third tone of any scale in the American system.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miamis</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*a"mis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos>; <sing>sing. <singw>Miami</singw> <pr>(<?/)</pr></sing>. <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>A tribe of Indians that formerly occupied the country between the Wabash and Maumee rivers.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miargyrite</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*ar"gy*rite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ less + <?/ silver. So called because it contains less silver than some kindred ore.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A mineral of an iron-black color, and very sectile, consisting principally of sulphur, antimony, and silver.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mias</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"as</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Malayan.]</ety> <def>The orang-outang.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miascite</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*asc"ite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Named from <ets>Miask</ets>, in the Ural Mountains.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A granitoid rock containing feldspar, biotite, elaeolite, and sodalite.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miasm</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"asm</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>miasme</ets>.]</ety> <def>Miasma.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miasma</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*as"ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Miasmata</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ defilement, fr. <?/ to pollute.]</ety> <def>Infectious particles or germs floating in the air; air made noxious by the presence of such particles or germs; noxious effluvia; malaria.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miasmal</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*as"mal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Containing miasma; miasmatic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miasmatical</ent><br/
<ent>Miasmatic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mi`as*mat"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mi`as*mat"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>miasmatique</ets>.]</ety> <def>Containing, or relating to, miasma; caused by miasma; <as>as, <ex>miasmatic</ex> diseases</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miasmatist</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*as"ma*tist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who has made a special study of miasma.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miasmology</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`as*mol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Miasma</ets> + <ets>-logy</ets>.]</ety> <def>That department of medical science which treats of miasma.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miaul</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*aul"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Miauled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Miauling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>miauler</ets>, of imitative origin, and E. <ets>mew</ets>.  Cf. <er>Mewl</er>.]</ety> <def>To cry as a cat; to mew; to caterwaul.</def>  <rj><au>Sir W. Scott.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miaul</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*aul"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The crying of a cat.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mica</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"ca</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mica</ets> crumb, grain, particle; cf. F. <ets>mica</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>The name of a group of minerals characterized by highly perfect cleavage, so that they readily separate into very thin leaves, more or less elastic.  They differ widely in composition, and vary in color from pale brown or yellow to green or black.  The transparent forms are used in lanterns, the doors of stoves, etc., being popularly called <altname>isinglass</altname>.  Formerly called also <altname>cat-silver</altname>, and <altname>glimmer</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The important species of the <xex>mica group</xex> are: <stype>muscovite</stype>, common or potash mica, pale brown or green, often silvery, including <stype>damourite</stype> (also called <altname>hydromica</altname> and <altname>muscovy glass</altname>); <stype>biotite</stype>, iron-magnesia mica, dark brown, green, or black; <stype>lepidomelane</stype>, iron, mica, black; <stype>phlogopite</stype>, magnesia mica, colorless, yellow, brown; <stype>lepidolite</stype>, lithia mica, rose-red, lilac.<br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>    <ex>Mica</ex> (usually muscovite, also biotite) is an essential constituent of granite, gneiss, and mica slate; <stype>biotite</stype> is common in many eruptive rocks; <stype>phlogopite</stype> in crystalline limestone and serpentine.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mica diorite</b></col> <fld>(Min.)</fld>, <cd>an eruptive rock allied to diorite but containing mica (biotite) instead of hornblende.</cd> -- <col><b>Mica powder</b></col>, <cd>a kind of dynamite containing fine scales of mica.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Mica schist</b></col>, <col><b>Mica slate</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Geol.)</fld>, <cd>a schistose rock, consisting of mica and quartz with, usually, some feldspar.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micaceo-calcareous</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*ca`ce*o-cal*ca"re*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>Partaking of the nature of, or consisting of, mica and lime; -- applied to a mica schist containing carbonate of lime.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micaceous</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*ca"ceous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>micac<eacute/</ets>.]</ety> <def>Pertaining to, or containing, mica; splitting into laminae or leaves like mica.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mice</ent><br/
<hw>mice</hw> <pr>(m<imac/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>, <def><pos>pl.</pos> of <er>Mouse</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micella</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mi*cel"la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Micellae</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL., dim. of L. <ets>mica</ets> a morsel, grain.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>A theoretical aggregation of molecules constituting a structural particle of protoplasm, capable of increase or diminution without change in chemical nature.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miche</ent><br/
<ent>Mich</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mich</hw>, <hw>Miche</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>michen</ets>; cf. OE. <ets>muchier</ets>, <ets>mucier</ets>, to conceal, F. <ets>musser</ets>, and OHG. <ets>m<umac/hhen</ets> to waylay.  Cf. <er>Micher</er>, <er>Curmudgeon</er>, <er>Muset</er>.]</ety> <def>To lie hid; to skulk; to act, or carry one's self, sneakingly.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Colloq.]</mark> <altsp>[Written also <asp>meach</asp> and <asp>meech</asp>.]</altsp>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Michaelmas</ent><br/
<hw>Mich"ael*mas</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Michael</ets> + <ets>mass</ets> religious service; OE. <ets>Mighelmesse</ets>.]</ety> <def>The feast of the archangel Michael, a church festival, celebrated on the  29th of September. Hence, colloquially, autumn.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Michaelmas daisy</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Daisy</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Michelangelesque</ent><br/
<hw>Michelangelesque</hw> <pos>prop. adj.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to Michelangelo.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Michelangelo</ent><br/
<hw>Michelangelo</hw> <pr>(m<imac/`k<ecr/l*<acr/n"j<esl/*l<osl/; It. pron. m<esl/`k<ecr/l*<aum/n"j<esl/*l<osl/)</pr> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>Michelangelo Buonarroti, renowned Italian painter, sculptor and architect; 1475-1564.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><bio> Born <person><b>Michelagnolo Buonarroti</b></person> at Caprese, March 6, 1475: died at Rome, Feb. 18, 1564.  A famous Italian sculptor, painter, architect, and poet.  He came of an ancient but poor Florentine family.  He was apprenticed to the painter <persfn>Ghirlandajo</persfn> April 1, 1488, and with other boys from the atelier began soon after to study the antique marbles collected by <person>Lorenzo de' Medici</person> in the garden of San Marco.  Lorenzo discovered him there, and in 1489 took him into his palace, where he had every opportunity for improvement and study.  The Centaur relief in the Casa Buonarroti was made at this time, at the suggestion of <person>Angelo Poliziano</person>.  In 1491 he came under the influence of <persfn>Savonarola</persfn>, whom he always held in great reverence. In 1492 <persfn>Lorenzo</persfn> died, and Michelangelo's intimate relations with the Medici family terminated. In 1493 he made a large wooden crucifix for the prior of S. Spirito, and with the assistance of the prior began the profound study of anatomy in which he delighted.  Before the expulsion of the Medici he fled to Bologna, where he was soon engaged upon the Arca di San Domenico begun by <person>Niccolo Pisano</person> in 1265, to which he added the well-known kneeling angel of Bologna.  He was probably much influenced by the reliefs of <person>Della Quercia</person> about the door of San Petronio: two of these he afterward imitated in the Sistine chapel.  In 1495 he returned to Florence, when he is supposed to have made the San Giovannino in the Berlin Museum.  From 1496 to 1501 he lived in Rome.  To this period are attributed the Bacchus of the Bargello and the Cupid of the South Kensington Museum.  The most important work of this time is the Piet<agrave/ di San Pietro (1408).  In 1501 he returned to <city>Florence</city>, and Sept. 18 began the great David of the Signoria, made from a block of marble abandoned by <person>Agostino di Duccio</person>, which was placed in position May 18, 1504.  The two roundels of the Madonna and Child in Burlington House and the Bargello were probably made then, and also the picture of the Holy Family in the Uffizi.  In 1503 <person>Piero Soderini</person>, gonfaloniere, projected two frescos for the Sala Grande of the Palazzo Vecchio.  The commission for one was given to <person>Leonardo da Vinci</person>, that for the other to <persfn>Michelangelo</persfn> in 1504.  For it he prepared the great cartoon of the Battle of Cascina, an incident in the war with Pisa when, July 28, 1364, a band of 400 Florentines were attacked while bathing by <person>Sir John Hawkwood's</person> English troopers.  This cartoon contained 288 square feet of surface, and was crowded with nude figures in every position.  It had, probably, more influence upon the art of the Renaissance than any other single work.  To about this time may be attributed the beginning of his poetic creations, of the multitude of which undoubtedly written a few only have come down to us.  In Nov., 1505, he was called to Rome by <person>Pope Julius II.</person> to design his mausoleum, the history of which runs through the entire life of the master.  Repeated designs and repeated attempts to carry them out were made, only to be frustrated by the successors of the great Pope.  The matter finally ended in the reign of <person>Paul III.</person> by the placing in San Pietro in Vincoli of the statue of <persfn>Moses</persfn> surrounded by mediocre works finished by <person>Raffaello da Montelupo</person> and others.  The Two Captives of the Louvre are part of the work as originally designed.  In the spring of 1506 he assisted in the discovery of the Laocoon in the palace of Titus.  His favorite antique was the Belvedere Torso, supposed to be a copy of the Hercules Epitrapezius of Lysippus.  In April, 1506, probably as a result of the intrigues of <persfn>Bramante</persfn>, he was forced to abandon <city>Rome</city> for <city>Florence</city>.  In the autumn he joined the Pope at <city>Bologna</city>, and made (1506-07) the bronze statue of <persfn>Julius</persfn> which stood over the door of San Petronio and was destroyed in 1511.  The ceiling of the Sistine Chapel was begun early in 1508, and finished in Oct., 1512.  <person>Julius II.</person> died Feb. 21, 1513, and was succeeded by <person>Cardinal Giovanni de' Medici</person>, son of the great <persfn>Lorenzo</persfn>, as <person>Leo X,</person>  <persfn>Michelangelo</persfn> was diverted from the tomb of <persfn>Julius</persfn> by <persfn>Leo</persfn>, and employed from 1517 to 1520 in an abortive attempt to build the fa<cced/ade of San Lorenzo in <city>Florence</city>, and in developing the quarries of Carrara and Seravezza. In 1520 he began, by order of <person>Cardinal Giulio de' Medici</person>, the sacristy of San Lorenzo and the tombs of <persfn>Giuliano</persfn> and <person>Lorenzo de' Medici</person> with the famous reclining figures on the sarcophagi, perhaps the most thoroughly characteristic of all his works.  <person>Leo X.</person> was succeeded by <person>Adrian VI.</person> in 1521, and he in turn by <person>Giulio de' Medici</person> as <person>Clement VII.</person> in 1523.  On April 6, 1529, <persfn>Michelangelo</persfn> was appointed "governor and procurator-general over the construction and fortification of the city walls" in <city>Florence</city>.  On Sept. 21, 1529, occurred his unexplained flight to <city>Venice</city>.  He returned Nov. 20 of the same year, and was engaged in the defense of the city until its capitulation, Aug. 12, 1530.  Before the end of the year 1534 he left <city>Florence</city>, never to return.  The statues of the sacristy, including the Madonna and Child, were arranged after his departure.  <person>Alessandro Farnese</person> succeeded <person>Clement VII.</person> as <person>Paul III.</person>, Oct., 1534.  The Last Judgment was begun about Sept. 1, 1535, and finished before Christmas, 1541.  Michelangelo's friendship for <person>Vittoria Colonna</person> began about 1538. (See Colonna, Vittoria.)  The frescos of the Pauline Chapel were painted between 1542 and 1549.  They represent the conversion of <person>St. Paul</person> and the martyrdom of <person>St. Peter</person>.  He succeeded <person>Antonio da Sangallo</person> in 1546 in the offices which he held, and became architect of St Peter's Jan. 1, 1547.  From this time until his death he worked on the church without compensation.  The dome alone was completed with any regard to his plans.</bio><br/
[<source>Century Dict. 1906</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micher</ent><br/
<hw>Mich"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>michare</ets>, <ets>muchare</ets>. See <er>Mich</er>.]</ety> <def>One who skulks, or keeps out of sight; hence, a truant; an idler; a thief, etc.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Michery</ent><br/
<hw>Mich"er*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>Theft; cheating.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Gower.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Michigander</ent><br/
<hw>Michigander</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A resident of Michigan.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miching</ent><br/
<hw>Mich"ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Hiding; skulking; cowardly.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <altsp>[Written also <asp>meaching</asp> and <asp>meeching</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mickey</ent><br/
<ent>Mick</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Mick</hw>, <hw>Mickey</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a person of Irish descent; -- an ethnic slur, offensive and disparaging.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Paddy.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 921 --></p>

<p><ent>Mickle</ent><br/
<hw>Mic"kle</hw> <pr>(m<icr/k"k'l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mikel</ets>, <ets>muchel</ets>, <ets>mochel</ets>, <ets>mukel</ets>, AS. <ets>micel</ets>, <ets>mycel</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>mikil</ets>, OHG. <ets>mihil</ets>, <ets>mihhil</ets>, Icel. <ets>mikill</ets>, <ets>mykill</ets>, Goth. <ets>mikils</ets>, L. <ets>magnus</ets>, Gr. <grk>me`gas</grk>, gen. <grk>mega`loy</grk>; cf. Skr. <ets>mahat</ets>. <root/103.  Cf. <er>Much</er>, <er>Muckle</er>, <er>Magnitude</er>.]</ety> <def>Much; great.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>muckle</asp> and <asp>mockle</asp>.]</altsp> <mark>[Old Eng. & Scot.]</mark> <ldquo/A man of <xex>mickle</xex> might.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micmacs</ent><br/
<hw>Mic"macs</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos>; <sing>sing. <singw>Micmac</singw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</sing> <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>A tribe of Indians inhabiting Nova Scotia and New Brunswick.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>Mikmaks</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mico</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"co</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. or Pg. <ets>mico</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A small South American monkey (<spn>Mico melanurus</spn>), allied to the marmoset. The name was originally applied to an albino variety.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micracoustic</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cra*cous"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Microustic</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micraster</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mi*cras"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mikro`s</grk> small + <?/ star.]</ety> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>A genus of sea urchins, similar to Spatangus, abounding in the chalk formation; -- from the starlike disposal of the ambulacral furrows.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micrencephalous</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cren*ceph"a*lous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <ety>[<ets>Micr-</ets> + Gr. <?/ brain.]</ety> <def>Having a small brain.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micr-</ent><br/
<ent>Micro-</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mi"cro-</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mi"cr-</hw>  }</mhw>. <ety>[Gr. <grk>mikro`s</grk> small.]</ety> <def>A combining form</def> signifying: <sd>(a)</sd> <def><sig>Small</sig>, <sig>little</sig>, <sig>trivial</sig>, <sig>slight</sig>; <as>as, <ex>micro</ex>cosm, <ex>micro</ex>scope</as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Metric System, Elec., Mech., etc.)</fld> <def><sig>A millionth part of</sig>; <as>as, <ex>micro</ex>farad, <ex>micro</ex>ohm, <ex>micro</ex>meter</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microampere</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*am`p<egrave/re"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micr-</ets> + <ets>amp<egrave/re</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>One of the smaller measures of electrical currents; the millionth part of one amp<egrave/re.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microanalysis</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*a*nal"y*sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>  <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>analysis</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Analysis of the structure of materials from careful observation of photomicrographs.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Chemical analysis of very small quantities of substances, requiring special apparatus to handle and weigh small amounts of materials.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microbacteria</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mi`cro*bac*te"ri*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Micro-</er>, and <er>Bacterium</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>In the classification of <persfn>Cohn</persfn>, one of the four tribes of Bacteria.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ In this classification bacteria are divided into four tribes: 1. <fam>Spherobacteria</fam>, or spherical bacteria, as the genus <gen>Micrococcus</gen>. 2. <fam>Microbacteria</fam>, or bacteria in the form of short rods, including the genus <gen>Bacterium</gen>. 3. <fam>Desmobacteria</fam>, or bacteria in straight filaments, of which the genus <gen>Bacillus</gen> is a type. 4. <fam>Spirobacteria</fam>, or bacteria in spiral filaments, as the genus <gen>Vibrio</gen>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microbarograph</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*bar"o*graph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>  <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>barograph</ets>.]</ety> <def>An instrument for recording minor fluctuations of atmospheric pressure, as opposed to general barometric surges.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microbion</ent><br/
<ent>Microbe</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mi"crobe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, \'d8<hw>Mi*cro"bi*on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. <ets>microbion</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/ little + <?/ life.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>A microscopic organism; a microorganism; -- particularly applied to bacteria and especially to pathogenic forms; <as>as, the <ex>microbe</ex> of fowl cholera</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>microbian</ent><br/
<ent>microbial</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mi*cro"bi*al</hw>, <hw>mi*cro"bi*an</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or caused by, microbes; <as>as, <ex>microbial</ex> growth; the <ex>microbian</ex> theory; a <ex>microbian</ex> disease.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microbic</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*crob"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to a microbe.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microbicide</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*crob"i*cide</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Microbe</ets> + L. <ets>caedere</ets> to kill.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Any agent detrimental to, or destructive of, the life of microbes or bacterial organisms.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microbiology</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*bi*ol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Microbe</er>; <er>-logy</er>.]</ety> <def>The branch of biology studying minute organisms, or microbes, such as the bacteria, fungi, viruses, and protozoa.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mi`cro*bi`o*log"ic*al</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> -- <wf>Mi`cro*bi*ol"o*gist</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microcephalous</ent><br/
<ent>Microcephalic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mi`cro*ce*phal"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mi`cro*ceph"a*lous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>cephalic</ets>, <ets>cephalous</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Having a small head; having the cranial cavity small; -- opposed to <ant>megacephalic</ant>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>micro-chemical</ent><br/
<ent>microchemical</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mi`cro*chem"ic*al</hw>, <hw>mi`cro-chem"ic*al</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to microchemistry; <as>as, a <ex>micro-chemical</ex> test</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>micro-chemistry</ent><br/
<ent>microchemistry</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mi`cro*chem"is*try</hw>, <hw>mi`cro-chem"is*try</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>chemistry</ets>.]</ety> <def>The application of chemical tests to minute objects or portions of matter, usually assisted by sensitive instruments; -- distinguished from <xex>macro-chemistry</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microchronometer</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*chro*nom"e*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A chronoscope.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microcline</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"cro*cline</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + Gr. <?/ to incline.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A mineral of the feldspar group, like orthoclase or common feldspar in composition, but triclinic in form.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micrococcal</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*coc"cal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to micrococci; caused by micrococci.</def>  <rj><au>Nature.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micrococcus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mi`cro*coc"cus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Micrococci</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL. See <er>Micro-</er>, and <er>Coccus</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>A genus of <fam>Spherobacteria</fam>, in the form of very small globular or oval cells, forming, by transverse division, filaments, or chains of cells, or in some cases single organisms shaped like dumb-bells (<gen>Diplococcus</gen>), all without the power of motion. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Ascoccus</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Physiologically, micrococci are divided into three groups; <xex>chromogenic</xex>, characterized by their power of forming pigment; <xex>zymogenic</xex>, including those associated with definite chemical processes; and <xex>pathogenic</xex>, those connected with disease.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>microcomputer</ent><br/
<hw>microcomputer</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A small computer based on a microprocessor; in practise, at any given time in the technology of computer development, a <ex>microcomputer</ex> will be one that is less powerful than a <contr>minicomputer</contr>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> personal computer, PC.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microcosm</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"cro*cosm</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>microcosme</ets>, L. <ets>microcosmus</ets>, fr. Gr. <grk>mikro`s</grk> small + <grk>ko`smos</grk> the world.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A little world; a miniature universe.  Hence (so called by Paracelsus), a man, as a supposed epitome of the exterior universe or great world.  Opposed to <contr>macrocosm</contr>.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A relatively small object or system considered as representative of a larger system of which it is part, exhibiting many features of the complete system.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microcosmical</ent><br/
<ent>Microcosmic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mi`cro*cos"mic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mi`cro*cos"mic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>microcosmique</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to the microcosm.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Microcosmic salt</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>a white crystalline substance obtained by mixing solutions of sodium phosphate and ammonium phosphate, and also called <altname>hydric-sodic-ammonic-phosphate</altname>.  It is a powerful flux, and is used as a substitute for borax as a blowpipe reagent in testing for the metallic oxides.  Originally obtained by the alchemists from human urine, and called <altname>sal microcosmicum</altname>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microcosmography</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*cos*mog"ra*phy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Microcosm</ets> + <ets>-graphy</ets>.]</ety> <def>Description of man as a microcosm.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microcoulomb</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*cou`lomb"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>coulomb</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>A measure of electrical quantity; the millionth part of one coulomb.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microcoustic</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*cous"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>acoustic</ets>: cf. F. <ets>microcoustique</ets>, <ets>micracoustique</ets>.]</ety> <def>Pertaining, or suited, to the audition of small sounds; fitted to assist hearing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microcoustic</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*cous"tic</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An instrument for making faint sounds audible, as to a partially deaf person.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microcrith</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*crith"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>crith</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>The weight of the half hydrogen molecule, or of the hydrogen atom, at one time taken as the standard in comparing the atomic weights of the elements; <as>thus, an atom of oxygen weighs sixteen <ex>microcriths</ex>.  This unit is no longer used, and has been replaced by the <altname>Dalton</altname>, which is of approximately the same value.  See <er>molecular weight</er> and <er>Crith</er></as>.</def>  <rj><au>J. P. Cooke.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microcrystalline</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*crys"tal*line</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>crystalline</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Crystallog.)</fld> <def>Crystalline on a fine, or microscopic, scale; consisting of fine crystals; <as>as, the ground mass of certain porphyrics is <ex>microcrystalline</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microcyte</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"cro*cyte</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + Gr. <?/ a hollow vessel.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>One of the elementary granules found in blood.  They are much smaller than an ordinary corpuscle, and are particularly noticeable in disease, as in anaemia.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microdont</ent><br/
<hw>Mic"ro*dont</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micr-</ets> + Gr. <grk>'odoy`s</grk>, <grk>'odo`ntos</grk>, a tooth.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Having small teeth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microfarad</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*far"ad</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>farad</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>The millionth part of a farad.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microfilm</ent><br/
<hw>Mic"ro*film</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>film</ets>.]</ety> <def>a photographic film with one or more very small images of printed or other graphic matter.  Numerous images, corresponding to the contents of a book, newspaper, or journal, are typically produced on one long roll of film, and may be viewed for reading in a special apparatus called a <usedby>microfilm reader</usedby>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microfilm</ent><br/
<hw>Mic"ro*film</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>to photograph and produce images of on microfilm.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microform</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"cro*form</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>form</ets>, n.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>A microscopic form of life; an animal or vegetable organism of microscopic size.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micro-geological</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro-ge`o*log"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to micro-geology.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micro-geology</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro-ge*ol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>geology</ets>.]</ety> <def>The part of geology relating to structure and organisms which require to be studied with a microscope.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micrograph</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"cro*graph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Micrography</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An instrument for executing minute writing or engraving.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>a graphic image, such as a photograph or drawing, representing an object as seen with a microscope, usually much enlarged as compared with the original object.  A photograph of a microscopic image is also called a <altname>photomicrograph</altname> or <altname>microphotograph</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micrographic</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*graph"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to micrography.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micrography</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*crog"ra*phy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>-graphy</ets>: cf. F. <ets>micrographie</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The description of microscopic objects.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Examination or study by means of the microscope, as of an etched surface of metal to determine its structure.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microhm</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*crohm"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micr-</ets> + <ets>ohm</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>The millionth part of an ohm.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microlepidoptera</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mi`cro*lep`i*dop"te*ra</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Micro-</er>, and <er>Lepidoptera</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A tribe of <ord>Lepidoptera</ord>, including a vast number of minute species, as the plume moth, clothes moth, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microlestes</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mi`cro*les"tes</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., from Gr. <grk>mikro`s</grk> small + <?/ a robber.]</ety> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>An extinct genus of small Triassic mammals, the oldest yet found in European strata.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microlite</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"cro*lite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>-lite</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A rare mineral of resinous luster and high specific gravity. It is a tantalate of calcium, and occurs in octahedral crystals usually very minute.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A minute inclosed crystal, often observed when minerals or rocks are examined in thin sections under the microscope.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microlith</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"cro*lith</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>lith</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Microlite</er>, 2.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microlithic</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*lith"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Formed of small stones.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micrological</ent><br/
<ent>Micrologic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mi`cro*log"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mi`cro*log"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to micrology; very minute; <as>as, <ex>micrologic</ex> examination</as>.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mi`cro*log"ic*al*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><-- pref. = microscopic --><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micrology</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*crol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>-logy</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That part of science which treats of microscopic objects, or depends on microscopic observation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Attention to petty items or differences.</def>  <rj><au>W. Taylor.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>micromercurialism</ent><br/
<hw>micromercurialism</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>micro</ets> + <ets>mercurialism</ets>.  Coined by the chemist <person>A. Stock</person> in 1926.  See <er>mercurialism</er>.]</ety> <fu>(1926)</fu>  <def>A form of mercury poisoning resulting from long term exposure to low doses of mercury.  The syndrome of micromercurialism involves complex symptoms of stress, fatigue, memory loss, fine tremors, muscular and reflex insufficiency and low blood pressure, caused by accumulation of mercury in the system.  A condition of hyperthermia is accompanied by a series of functional changes under the effects of mercury.  The combined simultaneous effect of toxic action, temperature and galvanic response infers a cycle of disintegration and change.</def>  <au>Work With Mercury (1972)</au> <note>As proposed by Stock, the syndrome was considered as the union of pathological changes in human body caused by means of low concentrations (as low as 0.01 mg per cubic meter) of mercury vapor over long exposure times (up to 10 years).</note><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micromere</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"cro*mere</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>-mere</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>One of the smaller cells, or blastomeres, resulting from the complete segmentation of a telolecithal ovum.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>micrometeorite</ent><br/
<hw>micrometeorite</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A meteorite so small that it drifts down to Earth without becoming intensely heated in the earth's atmosphere.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>micrometeoritic</ent><br/
<hw>micrometeoritic</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>of or relating to a micrometeorite.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micrometer</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*crom"e*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>-meter</ets>: cf. F. <ets>microm<egrave/tre</ets>.]</ety> <def>An instrument, used with a telescope or microscope, for measuring minute distances, or the apparent diameters of objects which subtend minute angles.  The measurement given directly is that of the image of the object formed at the focus of the object glass.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Circular micrometer</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Ring micrometer</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a metallic ring fixed in the focus of the object glass of a telescope, and used to determine differences of right ascension and declination between stars by observations of the times at which the stars cross the inner or outer periphery of the ring.</cd> -- <col><b>Double image micrometer</b></col>, <cd>a micrometer in which two images of an object are formed in the field, usually by the two halves of a bisected lens which are movable along their line of section by a screw, and distances are determined by the number of screw revolutions necessary to bring the points to be measured into optical coincidence. When the two images are formed by a bisected object glass, it is called a <xex>divided-object-glass micrometer</xex>, and when the instrument is large and equatorially mounted, it is known as a <xex>heliometer</xex>.</cd> -- <col><b>Double refraction micrometer</b></col>, <cd>a species of double image micrometer, in which the two images are formed by the double refraction of rock crystal.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Filar micrometer</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Bifilar micrometer</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See under <er>Bifilar</er>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Micrometer caliper</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Micrometer gauge</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Mech.)</fld>, <cd>a caliper or gauge with a micrometer screw, for measuring dimensions with great accuracy.</cd> -- <col><b>Micrometer head</b></col>, <cd>the head of a micrometer screw.</cd> -- <col><b>Micrometer microscope</b></col>, <cd>a compound microscope combined with a filar micrometer, used chiefly for reading and subdividing the divisions of large astronomical and geodetical instruments.</cd> -- <col><b>Micrometer screw</b></col>, <cd>a screw with a graduated head used in some forms of micrometers; turning the head one full revolution advances the position of the tip of the screw only by a little.</cd> -- <col><b>Position micrometer</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Position</er>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Scale micrometer</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Linear micrometer</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a minute and very delicately graduated scale of equal parts used in the field of a telescope or microscope, for measuring distances by direct comparison.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micrometrical</ent><br/
<ent>Micrometric</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mi`cro*met"ric</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mi`cro*met"ric*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>microm<eacute/trique</ets>.]</ety> <def>Belonging to micrometry; made by the micrometer.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mi`cro*met"ric*al*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micrometry</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*crom"e*try</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The art of measuring with a micrometer.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micromillimeter</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*mil"li*me`ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>millimeter</ets>.]</ety> <def>The millionth part of a meter.</def> <note>The millionth part of a meter is now termed a <altname>micron</altname>, and the word <ex>micromillimeter</ex> does not conform to the IS use of the prefix <er>micro-</er>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micromyx</ent><br/
<hw>Micromyx</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of Old World harvest mice.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Micromyx</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>micron</ent><br/
<hw>mic"ron</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mikro`s</grk> small.]</ety> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>A measure of length; the thousandth part of one millimeter; the millionth part of a meter.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micronesian</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"cro*ne"sian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <ets>Micronesia</ets>, fr. Gr. <grk>mikro`s</grk> small + <grk>nh^sos</grk> an island.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to Micronesia, a collective designation of the islands in the western part of the Pacific Ocean, embracing the Marshall and Gilbert groups, the Ladrones, the Carolines, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micronesians</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*ne"sians</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos>; <sing>sing. <singw>Micronesian</singw></sing>. <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>A dark race inhabiting the Micronesian Islands. They are supposed to be a mixed race, derived from Polynesians and Papuans.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micronometer</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*nom"e*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + chro<ets>nometer</ets>.]</ety> <def>An instrument for noting minute portions of time.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microorganism</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*or"gan*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>organism</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Any microscopic form of life; a form of life too small to be seen by the naked eye; -- particularly applied to bacteria, protozoa, yeasts, and similar organisms, esp. such are supposed to cause infectious diseases.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micropantograph</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*pan"to*graph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>pantograph</ets>.]</ety> <def>A kind of pantograph which produces copies microscopically minute.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microparasite</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*par"a*site</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A parasitic microorganism.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mi`cro*par`a*sit"ic</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micropegmatite</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*peg"ma*tite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>pegmatite</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A rock showing under the microscope the structure of a graphic granite (pegmatite).</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mi`cro*peg`ma*tit"ic</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>microphone</ent><br/
<hw>mi"cro*phone</hw> <pr>(m<imac/"kr<osl/*f<omac/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + Gr. <grk>fwnh`</grk> sound, voice: cf. F. <ets>microphone</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>An instrument for converting sounds into electrical signals, for the purpose of recording or amplifying the sounds.  It produces its effects in various ways, as for example by the changes of intensity in an electric current, occasioned by the variations in the contact resistance of conducting bodies, especially of imperfect conductors, under the action of acoustic vibrations.  Other forms of microphone may use changes in capacitance or other phenomena to transduce the sounds into electrical signals.</def>  <note>The electrical signals produced in a microphone may be transmitted to recording or amplifying equipment through a conducting wire, or by transmission as radio waves.  The latter method is popular for use in small mobile microphones used by performers in plays and other entertainment events, at public meetings, and by broadcast personnel.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>microphonic</ent><br/
<hw>mi`cro*phon"ic</hw> <pr>(m<imac/`kr<osl/*f<ocr/n"<icr/k)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to a microphone; serving to intensify weak sounds.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>microphonics</ent><br/
<hw>mi`cro*phon"ics</hw> <pr>(m<imac/`kr<osl/*f<ocr/n"<icr/ks)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Microphone</er>.]</ety> <def>The science which treats of the means of increasing the intensity of low or weak sounds, or of the microphone.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>microphonous</ent><br/
<hw>mi*croph"o*nous</hw> <pr>(m<isl/*kr<ocr/f"<osl/*n<ucr/s or m<icr/*kr<ocr/f"<osl/*n<ucr/s)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Serving to augment the intensity of weak sounds; microcoustic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>microphotograph</ent><br/
<hw>mi`cro*pho"to*graph</hw> <pr>(m<imac/`kr<osl/*f<omac/"t<osl/*gr<adot/f or m<icr/k`r<osl/*f<omac/"t<osl/*gr<adot/f)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>photograph</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A microscopically small photograph of a picture, writing, printed page, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An enlarged representation of a microscopic object, produced by throwing upon a sensitive plate the magnified image of an object formed by a microscope or other suitable combination of lenses.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ A picture of this kind is preferably called a <xex>photomicrograph</xex>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microphotography</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*pho*tog"ra*phy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The art of making microphotographs.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microphthalmy</ent><br/
<ent>Microphthalmia</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mi`croph*thal"mi*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mi`croph*thal"my</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + Gr. <grk>'ofqalmo`s</grk> eye.]</ety> <def>An unnatural smallness of the eyes, occurring as the result of disease or of imperfect development.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microphyllous</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*croph"yl*lous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + Gr. <grk>fy`llon</grk> leaf.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Small-leaved.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microphytal</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*croph"y*tal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or of the nature of, microphytes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microphyte</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"cro*phyte</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + Gr. <?/ a plant: cf. F. <ets>microphyte</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A very minute plant, one of certain unicellular algae, such as the germs of various infectious diseases are believed to be.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micropyle</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"cro*pyle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + Gr. <?/ gate, orifice: cf. F. <ets>micropyle</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>An opening in the membranes surrounding the ovum, by which nutrition is assisted and the entrance of the spermatozoa permitted.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>An opening in the outer coat of a seed, through which the fecundating pollen enters the ovule.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mi*crop"y*lar</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microscopal</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*cros"co*pal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to microscopy, or to the use of the microscope.</def>  <rj><au>Huxley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microscope</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"cro*scope</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>-scope</ets>.]</ety> <def>An optical instrument, consisting of a lens, or combination of lenses, for making an enlarged image of an object which is too minute to be viewed by the <cref>naked eye</cref>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Compound microscope</b></col>, <cd>an instrument consisting of a combination of lenses such that the image formed by the lens or set of lenses nearest the object (called the <xex>objective</xex>) is magnified by another lens called the <xex>ocular</xex> or <xex>eyepiece</xex>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Oxyhydrogen microscope</b></col>, and <col><b>Solar microscope</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See under <er>Oxyhydrogen</er>, and <er>Solar</er>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Simple microscope</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Single microscope</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a single convex lens used to magnify objects placed in its focus.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microscopial</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*sco"pi*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Microscopic.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Berkeley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microscopical</ent><br/
<ent>Microscopic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mi`cro*scop"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mi`cro*scop"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>microscopique</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the microscope or to microscopy; made with a microscope; <as>as, <ex>microscopic</ex> observation</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Able to see extremely minute objects.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Why has not man a <qex>microscopic</qex> eye?</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Very small.</def> <specif>Specifically,</specif> <def>visible only by the aid of a microscope; <as>as, a <ex>microscopic</ex> insect</as>; also used figuratively; <as>as, a <ex>microscopic</ex> advantage</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microscopically</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*scop"ic*al*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>By the microscope; with minute inspection; in a microscopic manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microscopist</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*cros"co*pist</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One skilled in, or given to, microscopy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microscopy</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*cros"co*py</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The use of the microscope; investigation with the microscope.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microseism</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"cro*seism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>  <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + Gr. <?/ an earthquake, fr. <?/ to shake.]</ety> <def>A feeble earth tremor not directly perceptible, but detected only by means of specially constructed apparatus.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mi`cro*seis"mic</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <wf>Mi`cro*seis"mic*al</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microseismograph</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*seis"mo*graph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>  <ety>[<ets>Microseiem</ets> + <ets>-graph</ets>.]</ety> <def>A microseismometer; specif., a microseismometer producing a graphic record.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microseismology</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*seis*mol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>  <ety>[<ets>Microseiem</ets> + <ets>-logy</ets>.]</ety> <def>Science or study of microseisms.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microseismometer</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*seis*mom"e*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>  <ety>[<ets>Microseism</ets> + <ets>-meter</ets>.]</ety> <def>A seismometer for measuring amplitudes or periods, or both, of microseisms.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mi`cro*seis*mom"e*try</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microseme</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"cro*seme</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + Gr. <?/ sign, mark: cf. F. <ets>micros<egrave/me</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Having the orbital index relatively small; having the orbits broad transversely; -- opposed to <ant>megaseme</ant>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>microsome</ent><br/
<hw>microsome</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Cell biology)</fld> <def>a tiny granule in the cytoplasm of a cell; it consists of ribosomes bound to fragments of the endoplasmic reticulum and mitochondria.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microsorium</ent><br/
<hw>Microsorium</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of tropical usually epiphytic ferns, found from Africa to Asia, and from Polynesia to Australia.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Microsorium</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 922 --></p>

<p><ent>Microspectroscope</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*spec"tro*scope</hw> <pr>(m<imac/`kr<osl/*sp<ecr/k"tr<osl/*sk<omac/p <it>or</it> m<icr/`kr<osl/*sp<ecr/k"tr<osl/*sk<omac/p)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>spectroscope</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>A spectroscope arranged for attachment to a microscope, for observation of the spectrum of light from minute portions of any substance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microsporangium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mi`cro*spo*ran"gi*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Micro-</er>, and <er>Sporangium</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A sporangium or conceptacle containing only very minute spores.  Cf. <er>Macrosporangium</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microspore</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"cro*spore</hw> <pr>(m<imac/"kr<osl/*sp<omac/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>spore</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>One of the exceedingly minute spores found in certain flowerless plants, as <gen>Selaginella</gen> and <gen>Isoetes</gen>, which bear two kinds of spores, one very much smaller than the other.  Cf. <er>Macrospore</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microsporic</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*spor"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to microspores.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microsthene</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"cro*sthene</hw> <pr>(m<imac/"kr<osl/*sth<emac/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + Gr. <grk>sqe`nos</grk> might, strength.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of a group of mammals having a small size as a typical characteristic.  It includes the lower orders, as the <ord>Insectivora</ord>, <ord>Cheiroptera</ord>, <ord>Rodentia</ord>, and <ord>Edentata</ord>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microsthenic</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*sthen"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having a typically small size; of or pertaining to the microsthenes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microtasimeter</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*ta*sim"e*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>tasimeter</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>A tasimeter, especially when arranged for measuring very small extensions. See <er>Tasimeter</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microtome</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"cro*tome</hw> <pr>(m<imac/"kr<osl/*t<omac/m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + Gr. <grk>te`mnein</grk> to cut.]</ety> <def>An instrument for making very thin sections for microscopical examination.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microtomical</ent><br/
<ent>Microtomic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mi`cro*tom"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mi`cro*tom"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pert. to the microtome or microtomy; cutting thin slices.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microtomist</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*crot"o*mist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who is skilled in or practices microtomy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microtomy</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*crot"o*my</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The art of using the microtome; investigation carried on with the microtome.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microvolt</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*volt"</hw> <pr>(m<imac/"kr<osl/*v<omac/lt`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>volt</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>A measure of electro-motive force; the millionth part of one volt.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microweber</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*we"ber</hw> <pr>(m<imac/`kr<osl/*v<amac/"b<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>weber</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>The millionth part of one weber.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microzoa</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mi`cro*zo"a</hw> <pr>(m<imac/`kr<osl/*z<omac/"<adot/)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mikro`s</grk> small + <grk>zw^,on</grk> an animal.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The Infusoria.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microzo0spore</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`cro*zo"o*spore</hw> <pr>(m<imac/`kr<osl/*z<omac/"<osl/*sp<omac/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + <ets>zoospore</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A small motile spore furnished with two vibratile cilia, found in certain green algae.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Microzyme</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"cro*zyme</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Micro-</ets> + Gr. <grk>zy`mh</grk> leaven.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>A microorganism which is supposed to act like a ferment in causing or propagating certain infectious or contagious diseases; a pathogenic bacterial organism.</def> <mark>[obsolete]</mark> <br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micruroides</ent><br/
<hw>Micruroides</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of coral snakes.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Micruroides</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micrurus</ent><br/
<hw>Micrurus</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of snakes including certain of the coral snakes, such as the <member>eastern coral snake</member> (<spn>Micrurus fulvius</spn>).</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Micrurus</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>micturate</ent><br/
<hw>micturate</hw> <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>to pass urine through the ureter; to urinate.</def> <mark>[Medical]</mark><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> urinate, piddle, puddle, piss, pee, pee-pee, make water, relieve oneself, take a leak, spend a penny, wee, wee-wee, make, pass water.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Micturition</ent><br/
<hw>Mic`tu*ri"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>micturire</ets> to desire to make water, v. desid. fr. <ets>mingere</ets>, <ets>mictum</ets>, to make water.]</ety> <def>The act of voiding urine; urination; also, a morbidly frequent passing of the urine, in consequence of disease.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mid</ent><br/
<hw>Mid</hw> <pr>(m<icr/d)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <it>wanting</it>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Midmost</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>midd</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>middi</ets>, D. <ets>mid</ets> (in comp.), OHG. <ets>mitti</ets>, Icel. <ets>mi<edh/r</ets>, Goth. <ets>midjis</ets>, L. <ets>medius</ets>, Gr. <grk>me`sos</grk>, Skr. <ets>madhya</ets>. <root/271.  Cf. <er>Amid</er>, <er>Middle</er>, <er>Midst</er>, <er>Mean</er>, <er>Mediate</er>, <er>Meridian</er>, <er>Mizzen</er>, <er>Moiety</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Denoting the middle part; <as>as, in <ex>mid</ex> ocean</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No more the mounting larks, while Daphne sings,<br/
Shall list'ning in <qex>mid</qex> air suspend their wings.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Occupying a middle position; middle; <as>as, the <ex>mid</ex> finger; the <ex>mid</ex> hour of night.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Phon.)</fld> <def>Made with a somewhat elevated position of some certain part of the tongue, in relation to the palate; midway between the <xex>high</xex> and the <xex>low</xex>; -- said of certain vowel sounds; <as>as, <amac/ (<amac/le), <ecr/ (<ecr/ll), <omac/ (<omac/ld)</as>. See <xex>Guide to Pronunciation</xex>, <sect/<sect/ 10, 11.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Mid</xex> is much used as a prefix, or combining form, denoting the <xex>middle</xex> or <xex>middle part</xex> of a thing; as, <xex>mid</xex>-air, <xex>mid</xex>-channel, <xex>mid</xex>-age, <xex>mid</xex>day, <xex>mid</xex>land, etc. Also, specifically, in geometry, to denote a circle inscribed in a triangle (a <xex>mid</xex>circle), or relation to such a circle; as, <xex>mid</xex>-center, <xex>mid</xex>radius.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mid</ent><br/
<hw>Mid</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Middle.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>About the <qex>mid</qex> of night come to my tent.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mid</ent><br/
<hw>Mid</hw>, <pos>prep.</pos> <def>See <er>Amid</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mida</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"da</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ a destructive insect in pulse.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The larva of the bean fly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>midair</ent><br/
<hw>mid*air"</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>some point in the air; above ground level; <as>as, the planes collided in <ex>midair</ex></as>; also used attributively; <as>as, a <ex>midair</ex> collision</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midas</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"das</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[So called from L. <ets>Midas</ets>, a man fabled to have had ass's ears.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of longeared South American monkeys, including numerous species of marmosets. See <er>Marmoset</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midas's ear</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"das's ear"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[See <er>Midas</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A pulmonate mollusk (<spn>Auricula aurismidae</spn> or <spn>Ellobium aurismidae</spn>); -- so called from resemblance to a human ear.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midbrain</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"brain`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mid</ets>, a. + <ets>brain</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The middle segment of the brain; the mesencephalon. See <er>Brain</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midday</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"day`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>middaeg</ets>. See <er>Mid</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and <er>Day</er>.]</ety> <def>The middle part of the day; noon.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midday</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"day`</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to noon; meridional; <as>as, the <ex>midday</ex> sun</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midden</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"den</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <altsp>[Also <asp>midding</asp>.]</altsp> <ety>[Cf. Dan. <ets>m<oum/gdynge</ets>, E. <ets>muck</ets>, and <ets>dung</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A dunghill.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An accumulation of refuse about a dwelling place; especially, an accumulation of shells or of cinders, bones, and other refuse on the supposed site of the dwelling places of prehistoric tribes, -- as on the shores of the Baltic Sea and in many other places. See <er>Kitchen middens</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midden crow</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"den crow"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The common European crow.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Middest</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"dest</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>; <pos>superl.</pos> of <er>Mid</er>. <ety>[See <er>Midst</er>.]</ety> <def>Situated most nearly in the middle; middlemost; midmost.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/ 'Mongst the <xex>middest</xex> crowd.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Middest</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"dest</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Midst; middle.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midding</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"ding</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Midden</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Middle</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"dle</hw> <pr>(m<icr/d"d'l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>middel</ets>, AS. <ets>middel</ets>; akin to D. <ets>middel</ets>, OHG. <ets>muttil</ets>, G. <ets>mittel</ets>.  <root/271. See <er>Mid</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Equally distant from the extreme either of a number of things or of one thing; mean; medial; <as>as, the <ex>middle</ex> house in a row; a <ex>middle</ex> rank or station in life; flowers of <ex>middle</ex> summer; men of <ex>middle</ex> age.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Intermediate; intervening.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Will, seeking good, finds many <qex>middle</qex> ends.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J. Davies.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Middle</xex> is sometimes used in the formation of self-explaining compounds; as, <xex>middle</xex>-sized, <xex>middle</xex>-witted.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Middle Ages</b></col>, <cd>the period of time intervening between the decline of the Roman Empire and the revival of letters.  <persfn>Hallam</persfn> regards it as beginning with the sixth and ending with the fifteenth century.</cd> -- <col><b>Middle class</b></col>, <cd>in England, people who have an intermediate position between the aristocracy and the artisan class. It includes professional men, bankers, merchants, and small landed proprietors</cd><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>middle-class</qex> electorate of Great Britain.</q> <rj><qau>M. Arnold.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <col><b>Middle distance</b></col>. <fld>(Paint.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Middle-ground</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Middle English</b></col>. <cd>See <er>English</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 2.</cd> -- <col><b>Middle Kingdom</b></col>, <cd>China.</cd> -- <col><b>Middle oil</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>that part of the distillate obtained from coal tar which passes over between 170<deg/ and 230<deg/ Centigrade; -- distinguished from the <contr>light oil</contr>, and the <contr>heavy oil</contr> or <contr>dead oil</contr>.</cd> -- <col><b>Middle passage</b></col>, <cd>in the slave trade, that part of the Atlantic Ocean between Africa and the West Indies.</cd> -- <col><b>Middle post</b></col>. <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <cd>Same as <er>King-post</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Middle States</b></col>, <cd>New York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, and Delaware; which, at the time of the formation of the Union, occupied a middle position between the Eastern States (or New England) and the Southern States.</cd> <mark>[U.S.]</mark> -- <col><b>Middle term</b></col> <fld>(Logic)</fld>, <cd>that term of a syllogism with which the two extremes are separately compared, and by means of which they are brought together in the conclusion.</cd> <au>Brande.</au> -- <col><b>Middle tint</b></col> <fld>(Paint.)</fld>, <cd>a subdued or neutral tint.</cd> <au>Fairholt.</au> -- <col><b>Middle voice</b></col>. <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Voice</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Middle watch</b></col>, <cd>the period from midnight to four <sc>a. m.</sc></cd>; <specif>also,</specif> <cd>the men on watch during that time.</cd> <au>Ham. Nav. Encyc.</au> -- <col><b>Middle weight</b></col>, <cd>a pugilist, boxer, or wrestler classed as of medium weight, <it>i. e.</it>, over 140 and not over 160 lbs., in distinction from those classed as <contr>light weights</contr>, <contr>heavy weights</contr>, etc.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Middle</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"dle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>middel</ets>. See <er>Middle</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>The point or part equally distant from the extremities or exterior limits, as of a line, a surface, or a solid; an intervening point or part in space, time, or order of series; the midst; central portion</def>; <specif>specif.,</specif> <def>the waist.</def> <au>Chaucer.</au> <ldquo/The <xex>middle</xex> of the land.<rdquo/ <au>Judg. ix. 37.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In this, as in most questions of state, there is a <qex>middle</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Midst</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Middle-age</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"dle-age`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <ety>[<ets>Middle</ets> + <ets>age</ets>.  Cf. <er>Mediaeval</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to the Middle Ages; mediaeval.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Middle-aged</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"dle-aged`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Being about the middle of the ordinary age of man; early in the century, it was considered  between 30 and 50 years old, but by the end of the 19th centruy it was considered as 40 to 60.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Middle-earth</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"dle-earth`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The world, considered as lying between heaven and hell.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><-- a land in Tolkien's "Hobbit" and "Ring" books -->  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Middle-ground</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"dle-ground`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Paint.)</fld> <def>That part of a picture between the foreground and the background.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>middle-level</ent><br/
<hw>middle-level</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>intermediate in rank or position; <as>as, <ex>middle-level</ex> management</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Middleman</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"dle*man</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Middlemen</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>An agent between two parties; a broker; a go-between; any dealer between the producer and the consumer; in Ireland, one who takes land of the proprietors in large tracts, and then rents it out in small portions to the peasantry.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A person of intermediate rank; a commoner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>The man who occupies a central position in a file of soldiers.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Middlemost</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"dle*most`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Midmost</er>.]</ety> <def>Being in the middle, or nearest the middle; midmost.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>middle-of-the-road</ent><br/
<hw>middle-of-the-road</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>  <def>supporting or pursuing a course of action that is neither liberal nor conservative.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> centrist, moderate.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>not extreme, especially in political views.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p> -- <wordforms><wf>middle-of-the-roader</wf>, <pos>n.</pos> -- <wf>middle-of-the-roadism</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms></p>

<p><ent>Middler</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"dler</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One of a middle or intermediate class in some schools and seminaries.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Middling</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"dling</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of middle rank, state, size, or quality; about equally distant from the extremes; medium; moderate; mediocre; ordinary.</def> <ldquo/A town of but <xex>middling</xex> size.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Hallam.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Plainly furnished, as beseemed the <qex>middling</qex> circumstances of its inhabitants.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Mid"dling*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mid"dling*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Middlings</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"dlings</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A combination of the coarser parts of ground wheat the finest bran, separated from the fine flour and coarse bran in bolting; -- formerly regarded as valuable only for feed; but now, after separation of the bran, used for making the best quality of flour. <xex>Middlings</xex> contain a large proportion of gluten.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In the southern and western parts of the United States, the portion of the hog between the ham and the shoulder; bacon; -- called also <altname>middles</altname>.</def>  <rj><au>Bartlett.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Middy</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"dy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Middies</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>A colloquial abbreviation of <altname>midshipman</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mid-eighties</ent><br/
<hw>mid-eighties</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the time of life between 80 and 90.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> eighties.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midfeather</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"feath`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Steam Boilers)</fld> <def>A vertical water space in a fire box or combustion chamber.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>A support for the center of a tunnel.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mid-February</ent><br/
<hw>mid-February</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the middle part of February.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>midfield</ent><br/
<hw>midfield</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(sport)</fld> <def>the middle part of a playing field (as in football or lacrosse); <as>as, he ran the kickoff back to <ex>midfield</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mid-fifties</ent><br/
<hw>mid-fifties</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the time of life between 50 and 60.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> fifties.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mid-forties</ent><br/
<hw>mid-forties</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the time of life between 40 and 50.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> forties.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mithgarthr</ent><br/
<ent>Midgarth</ent><br/
<ent>Midgard</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mid"gard</hw> <pr>(m<icr/d"g<aum/rd)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> Also <hw>Mid"garth</hw> <pr>(-g<aum/r<th/)</pr>, \'d8<hw>Mith"garthr</hw> <pr>(<it>Icel.</it> m<esl/<th/"g<aum/r<th/r')</pr> }</mhw>. <ety>[Icel. <ets>mi<edh/gar<edh/r</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Teut. Myth.)</fld> <def>The middle space or region between heaven and hell, the abode of human beings; the earth.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midge</ent><br/
<hw>Midge</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>migge</ets>, AS. <ets>mycge</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>muggia</ets>, D. <ets>mug</ets>, G. <ets>m<uum/cke</ets>, OHG. <ets>mucca</ets>, Icel. <ets>m<?/</ets>, Sw. <ets>mygga</ets>, <ets>mygg</ets>, Dan. <ets>myg</ets>; perh. named from its buzzing; cf. Gr. <?/ to low, bellow.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Any one of many small, delicate, long-legged flies of the <gen>Chironomus</gen>, and allied genera, which do not bite.  Their larvae are usually aquatic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A very small fly, abundant in many parts of the United States and Canada, noted for the irritating quality of its bite.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The name is also applied to various other small flies. See <cref>Wheat midge</cref>, under <er>Wheat</er>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midget</ent><br/
<hw>Midg"et</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Dim. of <ets>midge</ets>.]</ety>  <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A minute bloodsucking fly.</def> <mark>[Local, U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A very diminutive person having normal proportions of the body parts; compare <contr>dwarf</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midgut</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"gut`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mid</ets>, a. + <ets>gut</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The middle part of the alimentary canal from the stomach, or entrance of the bile duct, to, or including, the large intestine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midheaven</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"heav`en</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The midst or middle of heaven or the sky.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>The meridian, or middle line of the heavens; the point of the ecliptic on the meridian.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>midiron</ent><br/
<hw>midiron</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Golf)</fld> <def>a long iron{5} with a nearly vertical face.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> two iron.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mid-January</ent><br/
<hw>mid-January</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the middle part of January.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mid-July</ent><br/
<hw>mid-July</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the middle part of July.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mid-June</ent><br/
<hw>mid-June</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the middle part of June.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midland</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"land</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Being in the interior country; distant from the coast or seashore; <as>as, <ex>midland</ex> towns or inhabitants</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Howell.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Surrounded by the land; mediterranean.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And on the <qex>midland</qex> sea the French had awed.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midland</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"land</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The interior or central region of a country; -- usually in the plural.</def>  <rj><au>Drayton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midmain</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"main`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The middle part of the main or sea.</def> <mark>[Poetic]</mark>  <rj><au>Chapman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mid-March</ent><br/
<hw>mid-March</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the middle part of March.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mid-May</ent><br/
<hw>mid-May</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the middle part of May.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midmost</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"most`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>middemiste</ets>.  Cf. <er>Foremost</er>.]</ety> <def>Middle; middlemost.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ere night's <qex>midmost</qex>, stillest hour was past.</q> <rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midnight</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"night`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>midniht</ets>.]</ety> <def>The middle of the night; twelve o'clock at night.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The iron tongue of <qex>midnight</qex> hath told twelve.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midnight</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"night`</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Being in, or characteristic of, the middle of the night; <as>as, <ex>midnight</ex> studies; <ex>midnight</ex> gloom.</as></def> <ldquo/<xex>Midnight</xex> shout and revelry.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midnight sun</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"night` sun</hw>. <def>The sun shining at midnight in the arctic or antarctic summer.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mid-nineties</ent><br/
<hw>mid-nineties</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the time of life between 90 and 100.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> nineties.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mid-November</ent><br/
<hw>mid-November</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the middle part of November.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mid-October</ent><br/
<hw>mid-October</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the middle part of October.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mid-off</ent><br/
<hw>mid-off</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Cricket)</fld> <def>the fielding position in cricket closest to the bowler on the off side.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mid-on</ent><br/
<hw>mid-on</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Cricket)</fld> <def>the fielding position in cricket closest to the bowler on the on side.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midrash</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mid*rash"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Midrashim</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, <plw>Midrashoth</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Heb., explanation.]</ety> <def>A talmudic exposition of the Hebrew law, or of some part of it.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midrib</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"rib`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A continuation of the petiole, extending from the base to the apex of the lamina of a leaf.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midriff</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"riff</hw> <pr>(m<icr/d"r<icr/f)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>midhrif</ets>; <ets>midd</ets> mid, middle + <ets>hrif</ets> bowels, womb; akin to OFries. <ets>midref</ets> midriff, <ets>rif</ets>, <ets>ref</ets>, belly, OHG. <ets>href</ets> body, and to L. <ets>corpus</ets> body. See <er>Corpse</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <sn>1.</sn> <def>See <er>Diaphragm</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 2.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The middle part of the front of the body, from the waist to the chest.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>Smote him into the <qex>midriff</qex> with a stone.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That part of a garment, especially a dress or bodice, that covers the midriff{2}.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mid-sea</ent><br/
<ent>Mid sea</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mid" sea"</hw>, <it>or</it> <hw>Mid"-sea"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The middle part of the sea or ocean.</def>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The Mid-sea</b></col>, <cd>the Mediterranean Sea.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mid-September</ent><br/
<hw>mid-September</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the middle part of September.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mid-seventies</ent><br/
<hw>mid-seventies</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the time of life between 70 and 80.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> seventies.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midship</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"ship`</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to, or being in, the middle of a ship.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Midship beam</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>the beam or timber upon which the broadest part of a vessel is formed.</cd> -- <col><b>Midship bend</b></col>, <cd>the broadest frame in a vessel.</cd> <au>Weale.</au></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midshipman</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"ship`man</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Midshipmen</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Formerly, a kind of naval cadet, in a ship of war, whose business was to carry orders, messages, reports, etc., between the officers of the quarter-deck and those of the forecastle, and render other services as required.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>In the English naval service, the second rank attained by a combatant officer after a term of service as naval cadet. Having served three and a half years in this rank, and passed an examination, he is eligible to promotion to the rank of lieutenant.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>In the United States navy, the lowest grade of officers in line of promotion, being students or graduates of the Naval Academy awaiting promotion to the rank of ensign.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An American marine fish of the genus <gen>Porichthys</gen>, allied to the toadfish; also called <altname>singingfish</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Cadet midshipman</b></col>, <cd>formerly a title distinguishing a cadet line officer from a cadet engineer at the U. S. Naval Academy. See under <er>Cadet</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Cadet midshipman</b></col>, <cd>formerly, a naval cadet who had served his time, passed his examinations, and was awaiting promotion; -- now called, in the United States, <altname>midshipman</altname>; in England, <altname>sublieutenant</altname>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midships</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"ships`</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[For <ets>amidships</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>In the middle of a ship; -- properly <altname>amidships</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midships</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"ships`</hw>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The timbers at the broadest part of the vessel.</def>  <rj><au>R. H. Dana, Jr.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mid-sixties</ent><br/
<hw>mid-sixties</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the time of life between 60 and 70.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> sixties.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midst</ent><br/
<hw>Midst</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <ets>middest</ets>, <ets>in the middest</ets>, for older <ets>in middes</ets>, where <ets>-s</ets> is adverbial (orig. forming a genitive), or still older <ets>a midde</ets>, <ets>a midden</ets>, <ets>on midden</ets>. See <er>Mid</er>, and cf. <er>Amidst</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The interior or central part or place; the middle; -- used chiefly in the objective case after <xex>in</xex>; <as>as, in the <ex>midst</ex> of the forest</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And when the devil had thrown him in the <qex>midst</qex>, he came out of him.</q> <rj><qau>Luke iv. 35.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is nothing . . . in the <qex>midst</qex> [of the play] which might not have been placed in the beginning.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, figuratively, the condition of being surrounded or beset; the press; the burden; <as>as, in the <ex>midst</ex> of official duties; in the <ex>midst</ex> of secular affairs.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The expressions <xex>in our midst</xex>, <xex>in their midst</xex>, etc., are avoided by some good writers, the forms <xex>in the midst of us</xex>, <xex>in the midst of them</xex>, etc., being preferred.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Midst</er>, <er>Middle</er>.</syn> <usage> <xex>Midst</xex> in present usage commonly denotes a part or place surrounded on enveloped by or among other parts or objects (see <er>Amidst</er>); while <xex>middle</xex> is used of the center of length, or surface, or of a solid, etc. We say in the <xex>midst</xex> of a thicket; in the <xex>middle</xex> of a line, or the <xex>middle</xex> of a room; in the <xex>midst</xex> of darkness; in the <xex>middle</xex> of the night.</usage><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midst</ent><br/
<hw>Midst</hw>, <pos>prep.</pos> <def>In the midst of; amidst.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midst</ent><br/
<hw>Midst</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In the middle.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>midstream</ent><br/
<hw>midstream</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the middle of a stream; <as>as, don't change horses in <ex>midstream</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midsummer</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"sum`mer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>midsumor</ets>.]</ety> <def>The middle of summer.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Midsummer daisy</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the oxeye daisy.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>midsummer-men</ent><br/
<hw>midsummer-men</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A Eurasian mountain plant (<spn>Sedum rosea</spn>) with fleshy pink-tipped leaves and a cluster of yellow flowers.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> rose-root, <spn>Sedum rosea</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>midterm</ent><br/
<hw>midterm</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>the middle of the gestation period.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The middle of an academic term or a political term in office.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An examination given in the middle of an academic term; a midterm examination.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> midterm examination, midterm exam, midterm.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mid-thirties</ent><br/
<hw>mid-thirties</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the time of life between 30 and 40.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> thirties, thirty-something.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mid-twenties</ent><br/
<hw>mid-twenties</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the time of life between 20 and 30.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> twenties.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midward</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"ward</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Situated in the middle.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midward</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"ward</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In or toward the midst.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midway</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"way`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The middle of the way or distance; a middle way or course.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Paths indirect, or in the <qex>midway</qex> faint.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midway</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"way`</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Being in the middle of the way or distance; <as>as, the <ex>midway</ex> air</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midway</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"way`</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In the middle of the way or distance; half way.</def> <ldquo/She met his glance <xex>midway</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midweek</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"week`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The middle of the week. Also used adjectively.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>midweekly</ent><br/
<hw>midweekly</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>occurring during the middle of the week; <as>as, a <ex>midweekly</ex> prayer meeting</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> midweek.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midwest</ent><br/
<hw>Midwest</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The north central region of the U. S.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Middle West.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>midwestern</ent><br/
<hw>midwestern</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the Midwest  region of the U. S., generally including Ohio; Indiana; Illinois; Iowa; Missouri; Kansas; Nebraska; and sometimes Michigan; Wisconsin; Minnesota; <as>as, a <ex>midwestern</ex> city; <ex>midwestern</ex> accent</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midwife</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"wife`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Midwives</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>midwif</ets>, fr. AS. <ets>mid</ets> with (akin to Gr. <?/) + <?/ woman, wife. Properly, the woman or wife who is attendant upon a woman in childbirth. See <er>Meta-</er>, and <er>Wife</er>.]</ety> <def>A woman who assists other women in childbirth; a female practitioner of the obstetric art.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midwife</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"wife`</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To assist in childbirth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midwife</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"wife`</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To perform the office of midwife.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midwifery</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"wife`ry</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The art or practice of assisting women in childbirth; obstetrics.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Assistance at childbirth; help or cooperation in production.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Midwinter</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"win`ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>midwinter</ets>.]</ety> <def>The middle of winter.</def>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 923 --></p>

<p><ent>Midwive</ent><br/
<hw>Mid"wive`</hw> <pr>(m<icr/d"w<imac/v`)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To midwife.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mien</ent><br/
<hw>Mien</hw> <pr>(m<emac/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mine</ets>; perh. from sane source as <ets>mener</ets> to lead; cf. E. <ets>demean</ets>, <ets>menace</ets>, <ets>mine</ets>, n.]</ety> <def>Aspect; air; manner; demeanor; carriage; bearing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Vice is a monster of so frightful <qex>mien</qex>,<br/
As, to be hated, needs but to be seen.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mierkat</ent><br/
<hw>mierkat</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A South African mongooselike viverrine (<spn>Suricata suricata</spn>) having a lemurlike face and only four toes; called also <altname>suricate</altname>.</def> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>meerkat</asp>.]</altsp><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> meerkat.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miff</ent><br/
<hw>Miff</hw> <pr>(m<icr/f)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Prov. G. <ets>muff</ets> sullenness, sulkiness, <ets>muffen</ets> to be silky, <ets>muff<ium/g</ets> sullen, pouting.]</ety> <def>A petty falling out; a tiff; a quarrel; offense.</def>  <rj><au>Fielding.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miff</ent><br/
<hw>Miff</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To offend slightly.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Might</ent><br/
<hw>Might</hw> <pr>(m<imac/t)</pr>, <def><pos>imp.</pos> of <er>May</er>.</def> <ety>[AS. <ets>meahte</ets>, <ets>mihte</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Might</ent><br/
<hw>Might</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>meaht</ets>, <ets>miht</ets>, from the root of <ets>magan</ets> to be able, E. <ets>may</ets>; akin to D. <ets>magt</ets>, OS. <ets>maht</ets>, G. <ets>macht</ets>, Icel. <ets>m<amac/ttr</ets>, Goth. <ets>mahts</ets>. <root/103.  See <er>May</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <def>Force or power of any kind, whether of body or mind; energy or intensity of purpose, feeling, or action; means or resources to effect an object; strength; force; power; ability; capacity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What so strong,<br/
But wanting rest, will also want of <qex>might</qex>?</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou shalt love the Lord thy God with all thine heart, and with all thy soul, and with all thy <qex>might</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Deut. vi. 5.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>With might and main</b></col>. <cd>See under 2d <er>Main</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mightful</ent><br/
<hw>Might"ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Mighty.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mightily</ent><br/
<hw>Might"i*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mighty</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>In a mighty manner; with might; with great earnestness; vigorously; powerfully.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whereunto I also labor, striving according to his working, which worketh in me <qex>mightily</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Col. i. 29.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To a great degree; very much.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Practical jokes amused us <qex>mightily</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mightiness</ent><br/
<hw>Might"i*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality of being mighty; possession of might; power; greatness; high dignity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How soon this <qex>mightiness</qex> meets misery.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Highness; excellency; -- with a possessive pronoun, a title of dignity; <as>as, their high <ex>mightinesses</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mightless</ent><br/
<hw>Might"less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Without; weak.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mighty</ent><br/
<hw>Might"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Mightier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Mightiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>meahtig</ets>, <ets>mihtig</ets>; akin to G. <ets>m<aum/chtig</ets>, Goth. <ets>mahteigs</ets>. See <er>Might</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Possessing might; having great power or authority.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wise in heart, and <qex>mighty</qex> in strength.</q> <rj><qau>Job ix. 4.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Accomplished by might; hence, extraordinary; wonderful.</def> <ldquo/His <xex>mighty</xex> works.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Matt. xi. 20.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Denoting an extraordinary degree or quality in respect of size, character, importance, consequences, etc.</def>  <ldquo/A <xex>mighty</xex> famine.<rdquo/ <au>Luke xv. 14.</au> <ldquo/Giants of <xex>mighty</xex> bone.<rdquo/ <au>Milton.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mighty</qex> was their fuss about little matters.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mighty</ent><br/
<hw>Might"y</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mighties</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <def>A warrior of great force and courage.</def> <mark>[R. & Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>1 Chron. xi. 12.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mighty</ent><br/
<hw>Might"y</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a great degree; very.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <ldquo/He was <xex>mighty</xex> methodical.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Jeffrey.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We have a <qex>mighty</qex> pleasant garden.</q> <rj><qau>Doddridge.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Migniard</ent><br/
<hw>Mign"iard</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mignard</ets>, akin to <ets>mignon</ets>. See <er>Minion</er>.]</ety> <def>Soft; dainty.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Migniardise</ent><br/
<hw>Mign"iard*ise</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mignardise</ets>.]</ety> <def>Delicate fondling.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mignon</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"gnon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>See 3d <er>Minion</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mignon</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"gnon</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To flatter.</def> <mark>[R. & Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Danie<?/.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mignonette</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`gnon*ette"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mignonnette</ets>, dim. of <ets>mignon</ets> darling. See 2d <er>Minion</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A plant (<spn>Reseda odorata</spn>) having greenish flowers with orange-colored stamens, and exhaling a delicious fragrance.  In Africa it is a low shrub, but further north it is usually an annual herb.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mignonette pepper</b></col>, <cd>coarse pepper.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>migraine</ent><br/
<hw>mi*graine"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>migraine</ets>, LL. <ets>hemigrania</ets>, L. <ets>hemicrania</ets>, <ets>hemicranium</ets>, Gr. <grk>"hmikrani`a</grk>; <grk>"hmi-</grk> half + <grk>krani`on</grk> skull.  See <er>Hemi-</er> and <er>Cranium</er>, and cf. <er>Hemicrania</er>, <er>Migraine</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A kind of intense sick or nervous headache, usually periodical and confined to one side of the head; called also <altname>migraine headache</altname>.  Same as <er>megrim</er>.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mi*grain"ous</wf>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Migrant</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"grant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>migrans</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>migrare</ets>. See <er>Migrate</er>.]</ety> <def>Migratory.</def> <au>Sir T. Browne.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Migrant</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"grant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A migratory bird, person, or other animal.</def></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A person who changes residence frequently in search of employment, especially farm labor, such as harvesting crops seasonally; also called <altname>migrant laborer</altname> or <altname>migrant worker</altname>.  Sometimes the migrant worker is not a resident of the country in which the work is performed.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Migrate</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"grate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Migrated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Migrating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>migratus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>migrare</ets> to migrate, transfer.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To remove from one country or region to another, with a view to residence; to change one's place of residence; to remove; <as>as, the Moors who <ex>migrated</ex> from Africa into Spain; to <ex>migrate</ex> to the West.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To pass periodically from one region or climate to another for feeding or breeding; -- said of certain birds, fishes, and quadrupeds.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Migration</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*gra"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>migratio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>migration</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act of migrating.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Migratory</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"gra*to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>migratoire</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Removing regularly or occasionally from one region or climate to another; <as>as, <ex>migratory</ex> birds</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, roving; wandering; nomad; <as>as, <ex>migratory</ex> habits; a <ex>migratory</ex> life.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Migratory locust</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Locust</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Migratory thrush</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the American robin. See <er>Robin</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mikado</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*ka"do</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Jap.]</ety> <def>The popular designation of the hereditary sovereign of Japan; the emperor of Japan.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mike</ent><br/
<hw>mike</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[shortened from <ets>microphone</ets>.]</ety> <def>A <er>microphone</er>, the device for converting sound waves into electrical energy.</def> <mark>[informal]</mark> <br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> microphone.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mikmaks</ent><br/
<hw>Mik"maks</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Micmacs</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mil</ent><br/
<hw>mil</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>an obsolete monetary unit of Cyprus equal in value to <frac1x1000/ of a pound.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>a unit of length equal to <frac1x1000/ inch, used especially in measuring the thickness of sheets of materials.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>one milliliter; -- used mostly in informal speech.</def> <mark>[laboratory slang]</mark><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> milliliter, millilitre, ml, cubic centimeter, cubic centimetre, cc.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>a unit of angular size equal to <frac1x6400/ of 360 degrees; -- it is used especially in artillery ranging.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mil.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mil</ent><br/
<hw>mil</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[by contraction from <ets>million</ets>.]</ety> <def>One million dollars; <as>as, his new house cost over a <ex>mil</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[slang]</mark><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milady</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*la"dy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. English.]</ety> <def>Lit., my lady; hence (as used on the Continent), an English noblewoman or gentlewoman.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milage</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"age</hw> <pr>(?; 48)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Mileage</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milanese</ent><br/
<hw>Mil`an*ese"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to Milan in Italy, or to its inhabitants.</def> -- <def2><pos>n. sing. & pl.</pos> <def>A native or inhabitant of Milan; people of Milan.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milch</ent><br/
<hw>Milch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>milche</ets>; akin to G. <ets>melk</ets>, Icel. <ets>milkr</ets>, <ets>mj<omac/lkr</ets>, and to E. <ets>milk</ets>. See <er>Milk</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Giving milk; -- now applied only to beasts.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Milch</xex> camels.<rdquo/ <au>Gen. xxxii.</au> <ldquo/<xex>Milch</xex> kine.<rdquo/ <au>Shak.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Tender; pitiful; weeping.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mild</ent><br/
<hw>Mild</hw> <pr>(m<imac/ld)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Milder</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Mildest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>milde</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>mildi</ets>, D. & G. <ets>mild</ets>, OHG. <ets>milti</ets>, Icel. <ets>mildr</ets>, Sw. & Dan. <ets>mild</ets>, Goth. <ets>milds</ets>; cf. Lith. <ets>melas</ets> dear, Gr. <?/ gladdening gifts.]</ety> <def>Gentle; pleasant; kind; soft; bland; clement; hence, moderate in degree or quality; -- the opposite of <xex>harsh</xex>, <xex>severe</xex>, <xex>irritating</xex>, <xex>violent</xex>, <xex>disagreeable</xex>, etc.; -- applied to persons and things; <as>as, a <ex>mild</ex> disposition; a <ex>mild</ex> eye; a <ex>mild</ex> air; a <ex>mild</ex> medicine; a <ex>mild</ex> insanity.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The rosy morn resigns her light<br/
And <qex>milder</qex> glory to the noon.</q> <rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Adore him as a <qex>mild</qex> and merciful Being.</q> <rj><qau>Rogers.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Mild steel</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Low steel</b></col></mcol>, <cd>steel that has but little carbon in it and is not readily hardened.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Soft; gentle; bland; calm; tranquil; soothing; pleasant; placid; meek; kind; tender; indulgent; clement; mollifying; lenitive; assuasive. See <er>Gentle</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milden</ent><br/
<hw>Mild"en</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make mild, or milder.</def>  <rj><au>Lowell.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mildew</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"dew</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>melede<aacute/w</ets>; akin to OHG. <ets>militou</ets>, G. <ets>mehlthau</ets>, <ets>mehltau</ets>; prob. orig. meaning, honeydew; cf. Goth. <ets>milip</ets> honey. See <er>Mellifluous</er>, and <er>Dew</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A growth of minute powdery or webby fungi, whitish or of different colors, found on various diseased or decaying substances.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>powdery mildew</b></col> <cd>a fungal disease of plants caused by an ascomycete of the order <ord>Erysiphales</ord>, characterized by a powdery white film on the surface of the affected plants.  It is damaging to, e.g., roses and lilacs.  Also, a fungus that causes such a disease.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mildew</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"dew</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mildewed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mildewing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To taint with mildew; <as>as, <ex>mildewed</ex> clothing</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He . . . <qex>mildews</qex> the white wheat.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mildew</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"dew</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become tainted with mildew.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mildly</ent><br/
<hw>Mild"ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a mild manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mildness</ent><br/
<hw>Mild"ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being mild; <as>as, <ex>mildness</ex> of temper; the <ex>mildness</ex> of the winter.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mile</ent><br/
<hw>Mile</hw> <pr>(m<imac/l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<imac/l</ets>, fr. L. <ets>millia</ets>, <ets>milia</ets>; pl. of <ets>mille</ets> a thousand, i. e., <ets>milia passuum</ets> a thousand paces.  Cf. <er>Mill</er> the tenth of a cent, <er>Million</er>.]</ety> <def>A certain measure of distance, being equivalent in England and the United States to 320 poles or rods, or 5,280 feet.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The distance called a <xex>mile</xex> varies greatly in different countries.  Its length in yards is, in Norway, 12,182; in Brunswick, 11,816; in Sweden, 11,660; in Hungary, 9,139; in Switzerland, 8,548; in Austria, 8,297; in Prussia, 8,238; in Poland, 8,100; in Italy, 2,025; in England and the United States, 1,760; in Spain, 1,552; in the Netherlands, 1,094.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Geographical mile</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Nautical mile</b></col></mcol>, <cd>one sixtieth of a degree of a great circle of the earth, or 6080.27 feet.</cd> -- <col><b>Mile run</b></col>. <cd>Same as <cref>Train mile</cref>. See under <er>Train</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Roman mile</b></col>, <cd>a thousand paces, equal to 1,614 yards English measure.</cd> -- <col><b>Statute mile</b></col>, <cd>a mile conforming to statute, that is, in England and the United States, a mile of 5,280 feet, as distinguished from any other mile.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mileage</ent><br/
<hw>Mile"age</hw> <pr>(m<imac/l"<asl/j; 48)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An allowance for traveling expenses at a certain rate per mile.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Aggregate length or distance in miles; esp., the sum of lengths of tracks or wires of a railroad company, telegraph company, etc.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>milage</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The number of miles that a vehicle can travel after consuming a certain quantity of fuel; in the United States, usually expressed in units of <unit>miles per gallon</unit>; <as>as, smaller cars tend to get better <ex>mileage</ex></as>.  It is sometimes used as a nmeasure of the energy efficiency of a vehicle.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Use, profit or advantage; <as>as, he got a lot of <ex>mileage</ex> out of one hit record</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Constructive mileage</b></col>, <cd>a mileage allowed for journeys supposed to be made, but not actually made.</cd>  <rj><au>Bartlett.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mileometer</ent><br/
<hw>mileometer</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a meter that shows mileage traversed.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> odometer, hodometer, milometer.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milepost</ent><br/
<hw>Mile"post`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A post, or one of a series of posts, set up to indicate spaces of a mile each or the distance in miles from a given place.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An event or accomplishment marking a significant advance in an endeavor; a notable achievment; <as>as, putting a man in orbit was a big <ex>milepost</ex> on the way to the moon</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> milestone.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milesian</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*le"sian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>Milesius</ets>, Gr. <?/.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anc. Geog.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to Miletus, a city of Asia Minor, or to its inhabitants.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Irish Legendary Hist.)</fld> <def>Descended from King Milesius of Spain, whose two sons are said to have conquered Ireland about 1300 <sc>b. c.</sc>; or pertaining to the descendants of King Milesius; hence, Irish.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milesian</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*le"sian</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A native or inhabitant of Miletus.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A native or inhabitant of Ireland.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milestone</ent><br/
<hw>Mile"stone`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A stone serving the same purpose as a milepost.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An event or accomplishment marking a significant advance in an endeavor; a notable achievment; <as>as, putting a man in orbit was a major <ex>milestone</ex> on the way to the moon</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> milepost.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milfoil</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"foil</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mille-feuille</ets>, L. <ets>millefolium</ets>; <ets>mille</ets> thousand + <ets>folium</ets> leaf. See <er>Foil</er> a leaf.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A common composite herb (<spn>Achillea Millefolium</spn>) with white flowers and finely dissected leaves; yarrow.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Water milfoil</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>an aquatic herb with dissected leaves (<spn>Myriophyllum</spn>).</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miliaria</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mil`i*a"ri*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Miliary</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A fever accompanied by an eruption of small, isolated, red pimples, resembling a millet seed in form or size; miliary fever.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miliary</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"ia*ry</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>miliarius</ets>, fr. <ets>milium</ets> millet: cf. F. <ets>miliaire</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Like millet seeds; <as>as, a <ex>miliary</ex> eruption</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Accompanied with an eruption like millet seeds; <as>as, a <ex>miliary</ex> fever</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Small and numerous; <as>as, the <ex>miliary</ex> tubercles of Echini</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miliary</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"ia*ry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the small tubercles of Echini.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milice</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mi`lice"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>Militia.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milieu</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mi`lieu"</hw> <pr>(m<esl/*ly<etil/")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>mi</ets> middle (L. <ets>medius</ets>) + <ets>lieu</ets> place. See <er>Demi-</er>, <er>Lieu</er>.]</ety> <def>Environment.</def></p>

<p><q>The intellectual and moral <qex>milieu</qex> created by multitudes of self-centered, cultivated personalities.</q>  <rj><qau>J. A. Symonds.</qau></rj></p>

<p><q>It is one of the great outstanding facts of his progressive relation to the elements of his social <qex>milieu</qex>.</q>  <rj><qau>J. M. Baldwin.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miliola</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mil"i*o`la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., dim. of L. <ets>milium</ets> millet. So named from its resemblance to millet seed.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of <ord>Foraminifera</ord>, having a porcelanous shell with several longitudinal chambers.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miliolite</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"i*o*lite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>A fossil shell of, or similar to, the genus <gen>Miliola</gen>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miliolite</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"i*o*lite</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>The same <er>Miliolitic</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Miliolite limestone</b></col> <fld>(Geol.)</fld>, <cd>a building stone, one of the group of the Paris basin, almost entirely made up of many-chambered microscopic shells.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miliolitic</ent><br/
<hw>Mil`i*o*lit"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the genus <gen>Miliola</gen>; containing miliolites.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Militancy</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"i*tan*cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Militant</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The state of being militant; warfare.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A military spirit or system; militarism.</def>  <rj><au>H. Spencer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Militant</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"i*tant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>militans</ets>, <ets>-antis</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>militare</ets> to be soldier: cf. F. <ets>militant</ets>. See <er>Militate</er>.]</ety> <def>Engaged in warfare; fighting; combating; serving as a soldier.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mil"i*tant*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At which command the powers <qex>militant</qex> . . .<br/
Moved on in silence.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Church militant</b></col>, <cd>the Christian church on earth, which is supposed to be engaged in a constant warfare against its enemies, and is thus distinguished from the <xex>church triumphant</xex>, in heaven.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Militar</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"i*tar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Military.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Militarily</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"i*ta*ri*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a military manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>militarisation</ent><br/
<hw>militarisation</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>militarization.</def> <mark>[mostly Brit.]</mark> <br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mobilization, mobilisation, militarization.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Militarism</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"i*ta*rism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>militarisme</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A military state or condition; a military system; reliance on military force in administering government.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The spirit and traditions of military life.</def>  <rj><au>H. Spencer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The view that military strength, efficiency and values should dominate the country's public policy choices and take precedence over other interests.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The policy of maintaining a large military force, even in peacetime; -- a term usually used by opponents of such a policy on the assumption that such a large force is unnecessary for national defense.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Militarist</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"i*ta*rist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A military man.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A person having a strong spirit of militarism, in senses 3 or 4.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>militaristic</ent><br/
<hw>militaristic</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>imbued with militarism, in senses 3 or 4.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>militarization</ent><br/
<hw>militarization</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>act of assembling and putting into readiness the military forces for war or other emergency.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mobilization, mobilisation, militarisation.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>militarize</ent><br/
<hw>militarize</hw> <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>to lend a military character to (a country), as by building up a military force.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> make military.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>militarized</ent><br/
<hw>militarized</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Equipped with weapons; armed; -- used of persons, regions, or the military.  Contrasted to <ant>unarmed</ant> and <contr>demilitarized</contr>; <as>as, if that's a demilitarized zone, I wonder what a <ex>militarized</ex> zone would look like</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Military</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"i*ta*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>militaris</ets>, <ets>militarius</ets>, from <ets>miles</ets>, <ets>militis</ets>, soldier: cf. F. <ets>militaire</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to soldiers, to arms, or to war; belonging to, engaged in, or appropriate to, the affairs of war; <as>as, a <ex>military</ex> parade; <ex>military</ex> discipline; <ex>military</ex> bravery; <ex>military</ex> conduct; <ex>military</ex> renown.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor do I, as an enemy to peace,<br/
Troop in the throngs of <qex>military</qex> men.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Performed or made by soldiers; <as>as, a <ex>military</ex> election; a <ex>military</ex> expedition.</as></def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Military law</b></col>. <cd>See <cref>Martial law</cref>, under <er>Martial</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Military order</b></col>. <fld>(a)</fld> <cd>A command proceeding from a military superior.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>An association of military persons under a bond of certain peculiar rules; especially, such an association of knights in the Middle Ages, or a body in modern times taking a similar form, membership of which confers some distinction.</cd> -- <col><b>Military tenure</b></col>, <cd>tenure of land, on condition of performing military service.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Military</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"i*ta*ry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>militaire</ets>.]</ety> <def>The whole body of soldiers; soldiery; militia; troops; the army.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Militate</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"i*tate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Militated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Militating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>militare</ets>, <ets>militatum</ets>, to be a soldier, fr. <ets>miles</ets>, <ets>militis</ets>, soldier.]</ety> <def>To make war; to fight; to contend; -- usually followed by <xex>against</xex> and <xex>with</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These are great questions, where great names <qex>militate</qex> against each other.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The invisible powers of heaven seemed to <qex>militate</qex> on the side of the pious emperor.</q> <rj><qau>Gibbon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>militate against</ent><br/
<hw>mil"i*tate a*gainst"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To argue against; to cast doubt on; -- used in reference to facts which tend to disprove a hypothesis; <as>as, the absence of a correlation of budget deficits with inflation <ex>militates against</ex> any causal relation between the two</as>.  Opposite of <contr>support</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Militia</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*li"tia</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., military service, soldiery, fr. <ets>miles</ets>, <ets>militis</ets>, soldier: cf. F. <ets>milice</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>In the widest sense, the whole military force of a nation, including both those engaged in military service as a business, and those competent and available for such service; specifically, the body of citizens enrolled for military instruction and discipline, but not subject to be called into actual service except in emergencies.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The king's captains and soldiers fight his battles, and yet . . . the power of the <qex>militia</qex> is he.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Military service; warfare.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Baxter.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Militiaman</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*li"tia*man</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Militiamen</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>One who belongs to the militia.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Militiate</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*li"ti*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To carry on, or prepare for, war.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Walpole.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milk</ent><br/
<hw>Milk</hw> <pr>(m<icr/lk)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>meoluc</ets>, <ets>meoloc</ets>, <ets>meolc</ets>, <ets>milc</ets>; akin to OFries. <ets>meloc</ets>, D. <ets>melk</ets>, G. <ets>milch</ets>, OHG. <ets>miluh</ets>, Icel. <ets>mj<omac/lk</ets>, Sw. <ets>mj<oum/lk</ets>, Dan. <ets>melk</ets>, Goth. <ets>miluks</ets>, G. <ets>melken</ets> to milk, OHG. <ets>melchan</ets>, Lith. <ets>milszti</ets>, L. <ets>mulgere</ets>, Gr. <grk>'ame`lgein</grk>. <root/107.  Cf. <er>Milch</er>, <er>Emulsion</er>, <er>Milt</er> soft roe of fishes.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>A white fluid secreted by the mammary glands of female mammals for the nourishment of their young, consisting of minute globules of fat suspended in a solution of casein, albumin, milk sugar, and inorganic salts.</def> <ldquo/White as morne <xex>milk</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A kind of juice or sap, usually white in color, found in certain plants; latex. See <er>Latex</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An emulsion made by bruising seeds; <as>as, the <ex>milk</ex> of almonds, produced by pounding almonds with sugar and water</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The ripe, undischarged spat of an oyster.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Condensed milk</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Condense</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>Milk crust</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>vesicular eczema occurring on the face and scalp of nursing infants. See <er>Eczema</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Milk fever</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <cd>A fever which accompanies or precedes the first lactation</cd>. It is usually transitory. <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Vet. Surg.)</fld> <cd>A form puerperal peritonitis in cattle; also, a variety of meningitis occurring in cows after calving.</cd> -- <col><b>Milk glass</b></col>, <cd>glass having a milky appearance.</cd> -- <col><b>Milk knot</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>a hard lump forming in the breast of a nursing woman, due to obstruction to the flow of milk and congestion of the mammary glands.</cd> -- <col><b>Milk leg</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>a swollen condition of the leg, usually in puerperal women, caused by an inflammation of veins, and characterized by a white appearance occasioned by an accumulation of serum and sometimes of pus in the cellular tissue.</cd> -- <col><b>Milk meats</b></col>, <cd>food made from milk, as butter and cheese.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Bailey.</au> -- <col><b>Milk mirror</b></col>. <cd>Same as <er>Escutcheon</er>, 2.</cd> -- <col><b>Milk molar</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>one of the deciduous molar teeth which are shed and replaced by the premolars.</cd> -- <col><b>Milk of lime</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>a watery emulsion of calcium hydrate, produced by macerating quicklime in water.</cd> -- <col><b>Milk parsley</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>an umbelliferous plant (<spn>Peucedanum palustre</spn>) of Europe and Asia, having a milky juice.</cd> -- <col><b>Milk pea</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a genus (<gen>Galactia</gen>) of leguminous and, usually, twining plants.</cd> -- <col><b>Milk sickness</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>See <er>milk sickness</er> in the vocabulary.</cd> -- <col><b>Milk snake</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a harmless American snake (<spn>Ophibolus triangulus</spn>, or <spn>Ophibolus eximius</spn>). It is variously marked with white, gray, and red.  Called also <altname>milk adder</altname>, <altname>chicken snake</altname>, <altname>house snake</altname>, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Milk sugar</b></col>. <fld>(Physiol. Chem.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Lactose</er>, and <cref>Sugar of milk</cref> (below).</cd> -- <col><b>Milk thistle</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>an esculent European thistle (<spn>Silybum marianum</spn>), having the veins of its leaves of a milky whiteness.</cd> -- <col><b>Milk thrush</b></col>. <fld>(Med.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Thrush</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Milk tooth</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>one of the temporary first set of teeth in young mammals; in man there are twenty.</cd> -- <col><b>Milk tree</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a tree yielding a milky juice, as the cow tree of South America (<spn>Brosimum Galactodendron</spn>), and the <spn>Euphorbia balsamifera</spn> of the Canaries, the milk of both of which is wholesome food.</cd> -- <col><b>Milk vessel</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a special cell in the inner bark of a plant, or a series of cells, in which the milky juice is contained. See <er>Latex</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Rock milk</b></col>. <cd>See <cref>Agaric mineral</cref>, under <er>Agaric</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Sugar of milk</b></col>. <cd>The sugar characteristic of milk; a hard white crystalline slightly sweet substance obtained by evaporation of the whey of milk.  It is used in pellets and powder as a vehicle for homeopathic medicines, and as an article of diet. See <er>Lactose</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 924 --></p>

<p><ent>Milk</ent><br/
<hw>Milk</hw> <pr>(m<icr/lk)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Milked</conjf> <pr>(m<icr/lkt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Milking</conjf>.]</vmorph><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To draw or press milk from the breasts or udder of, by the hand or mouth; to withdraw the milk of.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Milking</xex> the kine.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Gay.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have given suck, and know<br/
How tender 't is to love the babe that <qex>milks</qex> me.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To draw from the breasts or udder; to extract, as milk; <as>as, to <ex>milk</ex> wholesome milk from healthy cows</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To draw anything from, as if by milking; to compel to yield profit or advantage; to plunder.</def>  <rj><au>Tyndale.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They [the lawyers] <qex>milk</qex> an unfortunate estate as regularly as a dairyman does his stock.</q> <rj><qau>London Spectator.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To milk the street</b></col>, <cd>to squeeze the smaller operators in stocks and extract a profit from them, by alternately raising and depressing prices within a short range; -- said of the large dealers.</cd> <mark>[Cant]</mark> -- <col><b>To milk a telegram</b></col>, <cd>to use for one's own advantage the contents of a telegram belonging to another person.</cd> <mark>[Cant]</mark></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milk</ent><br/
<hw>Milk</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To draw or to yield milk.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>To give off small gas bubbles during the final part of the charging operation; -- said of a storage battery.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>milkcap</ent><br/
<hw>milkcap</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A type of edible mushroom (<spn>Lactarius delicioso</spn>).</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> <spn>Lactarius delicioso</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milken</ent><br/
<hw>Milk"en</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Consisting of milk.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milker</ent><br/
<hw>Milk"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who milks; also, a mechanical apparatus for milking cows.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A cow or other animal that gives milk.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milkful</ent><br/
<hw>Milk"ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Full of milk; abounding with food.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <ldquo/<xex>Milkful</xex> vales.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Sylvester.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milkily</ent><br/
<hw>Milk"i*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a milky manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milkiness</ent><br/
<hw>Milk"i*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>State or quality of being milky.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milk-livered</ent><br/
<hw>Milk"-liv`ered</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>White-livered; cowardly; timorous.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milkmaid</ent><br/
<hw>Milk"maid`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A woman who milks cows or is employed in the dairy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milkman</ent><br/
<hw>Milk"man</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Milkmen</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>A man who sells milk or delivers it to customers.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>milk shake</ent><br/
<ent>milkshake</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>milk"shake`</hw>, <hw>milk" shake`</hw></mhw> <pr>(m<icr/lk" sh<amac/k`)</pr> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A frothy drink of milk and flavoring and sometimes fruit or ice cream, shaken together or blended in  a blender.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> milk shake, shake.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milk sickness</ent><br/
<hw>Milk sickness</hw>. <fld>(Veter., Med.)</fld> <def>A peculiar malignant disease, occurring in parts of the western United States, and affecting certain kinds of farm stock (esp. cows), and persons using the meat or dairy products of infected cattle. Its chief symptoms in man are uncontrollable vomiting, obstinate constipation, pain, and muscular tremors. Its origin in cattle has been variously ascribed to the presence of certain plants in their food, and to polluted water.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milksop</ent><br/
<hw>Milk"sop`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A piece of bread sopped in milk; figuratively, an effeminate or weak-minded person.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To wed a <qex>milksop</qex> or a coward ape.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milk vetch</ent><br/
<hw>Milk" vetch`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A leguminous herb (<spn>Astragalus glycyphyllos</spn>) of Europe and Asia, supposed to increase the secretion of milk in goats.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The name is sometimes taken for the whole genus <gen>Astragalus</gen>, of which there are about two hundred species in North America, and even more elsewhere.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>milkwagon</ent><br/
<hw>milkwagon</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a wagon for delivering milk.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milkweed</ent><br/
<hw>Milk"weed`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Any plant of the genera <gen>Asclepias</gen> and <gen>Acerates</gen>, abounding in a milky juice, and having its seed attached to a long silky down; silkweed.  The name is also applied to several other plants with a milky juice, as to several kinds of spurge.  Its leaves are a favorite food source for the larvae of the monarch butterfly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milkwort</ent><br/
<hw>Milk"wort`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of plants (<gen>Polygala</gen>) of many species.  The common European <spn>Polygala vulgaris</spn> was supposed to have the power of producing a flow of milk in nurses.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The species of <gen>Campanula</gen>, or bellflower, are sometimes called <xex>milkwort</xex>, from their juice.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milky</ent><br/
<hw>Milk"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Consisting of, or containing, milk.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Pails high foaming with a <qex>milky</qex> flood.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Like, or somewhat like, milk; whitish and turbid; <as>as, the water is <ex>milky</ex>. <ldquo/<ex>Milky</ex> juice.<rdquo/</as></def>  <rj><au>Arbuthnot.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Yielding milk.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Milky</xex> mothers.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Roscommon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Mild; tame; spiritless.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Has friendship such a faint and <qex>milky</qex> heart?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Milky Way</b></col>. <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Galaxy</er>, 1.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mill</ent><br/
<hw>Mill</hw> <pr>(m<icr/l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mille</ets> a thousand.  Cf. <er>Mile</er>.]</ety> <def>A money of account of the United States, having the value of the tenth of a cent, or the thousandth of a dollar.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mill</ent><br/
<hw>Mill</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mille</ets>, <ets>melle</ets>, <ets>mulle</ets>, <ets>milne</ets>, AS. <ets>myln</ets>, <ets>mylen</ets>; akin to D. <ets>molen</ets>, G. <ets>m<uum/hle</ets>, OHG. <ets>mul<imac/</ets>, <ets>mul<imac/n</ets>, Icel. <ets>mylna</ets>; all prob. from L. <ets>molina</ets>, fr. <ets>mola</ets> millstone; prop., that which grinds, akin to <ets>molere</ets> to grind, Goth. <ets>malan</ets>, G. <ets>mahlen</ets>, and to E. <ets>meal</ets>. <root/108. See <ets>Meal</ets> flour, and cf. <er>Moline</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A machine for grinding or comminuting any substance, as grain, by rubbing and crushing it between two hard, rough, or indented surfaces; <as>as, a grist<ex>mill</ex>, a coffee <ex>mill</ex>; a bone <ex>mill</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A machine used for expelling the juice, sap, etc., from vegetable tissues by pressure, or by pressure in combination with a grinding, or cutting process; <as>as, a cider <ex>mill</ex>; a cane <ex>mill</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A machine for grinding and polishing; <as>as, a lapidary <ex>mill</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A common name for various machines which produce a manufactured product, or change the form of a raw material by the continuous repetition of some simple action; <as>as, a saw<ex>mill</ex>; a stamping <ex>mill</ex>, etc.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A building or collection of buildings with machinery by which the processes of manufacturing are carried on; <as>as, a cotton <ex>mill</ex>; a powder <ex>mill</ex>; a rolling <ex>mill</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Die Sinking)</fld> <def>A hardened steel roller having a design in relief, used for imprinting a reversed copy of the design in a softer metal, as copper.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>An excavation in rock, transverse to the workings, from which material for filling is obtained.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A passage underground through which ore is shot.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A milling cutter. See <xex>Illust.</xex> under <er>Milling</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>A pugilistic encounter.</def> <mark>[Cant]</mark>  <rj><au>R. D. Blackmore.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>Short for <er>Treadmill</er>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn>  <def>The raised or ridged edge or surface made in milling anything, as a coin or screw.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>A building or complex of buildings containing a mill{1} or other machinery to grind grains into flour.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Edge mill</b></col>, <col><b>Flint mill</b></col></mcol>, <cd>etc. See under <er>Edge</er>, <er>Flint</er>, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Mill bar</b></col> <fld>(Iron Works)</fld>, <cd>a rough bar rolled or drawn directly from a bloom or puddle bar for conversion into merchant iron in the mill.</cd> -- <col><b>Mill cinder</b></col>, <cd>slag from a puddling furnace.</cd> -- <col><b>Mill head</b></col>, <cd>the head of water employed to turn the wheel of a mill.</cd> -- <col><b>Mill pick</b></col>, <cd>a pick for dressing millstones.</cd> -- <col><b>Mill pond</b></col>, <cd>a pond that supplies the water for a mill.</cd> -- <col><b>Mill race</b></col>, <cd>the canal in which water is conveyed to a mill wheel, or the current of water which drives the wheel.</cd> -- <col><b>Mill tail</b></col>, <cd>the water which flows from a mill wheel after turning it, or the channel in which the water flows.</cd> -- <col><b>Mill tooth</b></col>, <cd>a grinder or molar tooth.</cd> -- <col><b>Mill wheel</b></col>, <cd>the water wheel that drives the machinery of a mill.</cd> -- <col><b>Gin mill</b></col>, <cd>a tavern; a bar; a saloon; especially, a cheap or seedy establishment that serves liquor by the drink.</cd> -- <col><b>Roller mill</b></col>, <cd>a mill in which flour or meal is made by crushing grain between rollers.</cd> -- <col><b>Stamp mill</b></col> <fld>(Mining)</fld>, <cd>a mill in which ore is crushed by stamps.</cd> -- <col><b>To go through the mill</b></col>, <cd>to experience the suffering or discipline necessary to bring one to a certain degree of knowledge or skill, or to a certain mental state.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mill</ent><br/
<hw>Mill</hw> <pr>(m<icr/l)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Milled</conjf> <pr>(m<icr/ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Milling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Mill</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, and cf. <er>Muller</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To reduce to fine particles, or to small pieces, in a mill; to grind; to comminute.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To shape, finish, or transform by passing through a machine; specifically, to shape or dress, as metal, by means of a rotary cutter.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make a raised border around the edges of, or to cut fine grooves or indentations across the edges of, as of a coin, or a screw head; also, to stamp in a coining press; to coin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To pass through a fulling mill; to full, as cloth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To beat with the fists.</def> <mark>[Cant]</mark>  <rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To roll into bars, as steel.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To mill chocolate</b></col>, <cd>to make it frothy, as by churning.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mill</ent><br/
<hw>Mill</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>To swim under water; -- said of air-breathing creatures.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To undergo hulling, as maize.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn>  <def>To move in a circle, as cattle upon a plain; to move around aimlessly; -- usually used with <ptcl>around</ptcl>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><q>The deer and the pig and the nilghar were <qex>milling</qex> round and round in a circle of eight or ten miles radius.</q>  <rj><qau>Kipling.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn>  <def>To swim suddenly in a new direction; -- said of whales.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn>  <def>To take part in a mill; to box.</def> <mark>[Cant]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mill</ent><br/
<hw>Mill</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>To fill (a winze or interior incline) with broken ore, to be drawn out at the bottom.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>To cause to mill, or circle round, as cattle.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millboard</ent><br/
<hw>Mill"board`</hw> <pr>(m<icr/l"b<omac/rd`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A kind of stout pasteboard.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mill-cake</ent><br/
<hw>Mill"-cake`</hw> <pr>(m<icr/l"k<amac/k`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The incorporated materials for gunpowder, in the form of a dense mass or cake, ready to be subjected to the process of granulation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milldam</ent><br/
<hw>Mill"dam`</hw> <pr>(m<icr/l"d<acr/m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A dam or mound to obstruct a water course, and raise the water to a height sufficient to turn a mill wheel.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milled</ent><br/
<hw>Milled</hw> <pr>(m<icr/ld)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having been subjected to some process of milling.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <def>Having multiple fine grooves on the rim, in the direction from obverse to reverse; -- of coins.  Coins of silver and gold were <ex>milled</ex> to make it impossible for uncrupulous persons to shave small pieces from the edge without detection.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Milled cloth</b></col>, <cd>cloth that has been beaten in a fulling mill.</cd> -- <col><b>Milled lead</b></col>, <cd>lead rolled into sheets.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millefiore glass</ent><br/
<hw>Mil`le*fi*o"re glass`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[It. <ets>mille</ets> thousand + <ets>fiore</ets> flower.]</ety> <def>Slender rods or tubes of colored glass fused together and embedded in clear glass; -- used for paperweights and other small articles.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millenarian</ent><br/
<hw>Mil`le*na"ri*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Millenary</er>.]</ety> <def>Consisting of a thousand years; of or pertaining to the millennium, or to the Millenarians.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millenarian</ent><br/
<hw>Mil`le*na"ri*an</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who believes that Christ will personally reign on earth a thousand years; a Chiliast.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millenarism</ent><br/
<ent>Millenarianism</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mil`le*na"ri*an*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mil"le*na*rism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The doctrine of Millenarians.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millenary</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"le*na*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>millenarius</ets>, fr. <ets>milleni</ets> a thousand each, fr. <ets>mille</ets> a thousand: cf. F. <ets>mill<eacute/naire</ets>. See <er>Mile</er>.]</ety> <def>Consisting of a thousand; millennial.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millenary</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"le*na*ry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The space of a thousand years; a millennium; also, a <er>Millenarian</er>.</def><ldquo/During that <xex>millenary</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Hare.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millennial</ent><br/
<hw>Mil*len"ni*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the millennium, or to a thousand years; <as>as, a <ex>millennial</ex> period; <ex>millennial</ex> happiness.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millennialist</ent><br/
<hw>Mil*len"ni*al*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who believes that Christ will reign personally on earth a thousand years; a Chiliast; also, a believer in the universal prevalence of Christianity for a long period.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millenniarism</ent><br/
<ent>Millennianism</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mil*len"ni*an*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mil*len"ni*a*rism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Belief in, or expectation of, the millennium{2}; millenarianism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millennist</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"len*nist</hw> <pr>(m<icr/l"l<ecr/n*n<icr/st)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who believes in the millennium{2}.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millennium</ent><br/
<hw>Mil*len"ni*um</hw> <pr>(m<icr/l*l<ecr/n"n<icr/*<ucr/m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL., fr. L. <ets>mille</ets> a thousand + <ets>annus</ets> a year. See <er>Mile</er>, and <er>Annual</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A period of one thousand years.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <def>The period of a thousand years mentioned in the twentieth chapter of Revelation, during which holiness is to be triumphant throughout the world.  Some believe that, during this period, Christ will reign on earth in person with his saints.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>A long period of happiness, righteousness, and prosperity, usually considered as being in the indefinite future.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A thousandth anniversary;</def> <specif>especially,</specif> <def>Each first day of January falling in a year which is a multiple of one thousand, such as in 1000 <sc>a. d.</sc> or 2000 <sc>a. d.</sc>; <as>as, the second <ex>millenium</ex> will be celebrated on January 1, 2000; also used attributively, as a <ex>millenium</ex> celebration</as>.</def>  <note>Technically, if the calendar of the Common Era (Anno Domini) is considered as beginning on January 1, 1 <sc>a. d.</sc>, then the <ex>millenium</ex> will fall in each year ending in <it>001</it>, as in 1001 <sc>a. d.</sc> or January 1, 2001 <sc>a. d.</sc>.  However in the common culture, the change of the first digit of the year from 1 to 2, as from 1999 to 2000 is considered as the more symbolic event, especially since the dating of the beginning of the Christian era is somewhat arbitrary, having been an attempt to fix the date of the birth of Christ, and being considered by scholars as being in error by as much as five years.</note><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>millennium bug</ent><br/
<hw>mil*len"ni*um bug`</hw> <pr>(m<icr/l*l<ecr/n"n<icr/*<ucr/m b<ucr/g`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Computers)</fld> <def>An error in the coding of certain computer programs which store the year component of the date as two digits, assuming that the first two digits are <it>19</it>, rather than as a complete number of four digits; when such programs are used after January 1, 2000, the date may be misinterpreted, causing serious errors or total failure of the program; -- called also <altname>year 2000 bug</altname>, <altname>year 2000 problem</altname> and <altname>Y2K bug</altname>.</def>  <note>In the several years leading up to the year 2000, large corporations and other users of computers in total spent many billions of dollars correcting this error in the programs they use.</note><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milleped</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"le*ped</hw> <pr>(m<icr/l"l<esl/*p<ecr/d<icr/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>millepeda</ets>; <ets>mille</ets> a thousand + <ets>pes</ets>, <ets>pedis</ets>, foot: cf. F. <ets>mille-pieds</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A myriapod with many legs, esp. a chilognath, as the galleyworm.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>millipede</asp> and <asp>milliped</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millepora</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mil*le*po"ra</hw> <pr>(m<icr/l*l<esl/*p<omac/"r<adot/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of Hydrocorallia, which includes the millipores.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millepore</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"le*pore</hw> <pr>(m<icr/l"l<esl/*p<omac/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mille</ets> thousand + <ets>porus</ets> pore: cf. F. <ets>mill<eacute/pore</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any coral of the genus Millepora, having the surface nearly smooth, and perforated with very minute unequal pores, or cells. The animals are hydroids, not Anthozoa. See <er>Hydrocorallia</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milleporite</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"le*po*rite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>A fossil millepore.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miller</ent><br/
<hw>Mill"er</hw> <pr>(m<icr/l"<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who keeps or attends a flour mill or gristmill.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A milling machine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A moth or lepidopterous insect; -- so called because the wings appear as if covered with white dust or powder, like a miller's clothes. Called also <altname>moth miller</altname>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The eagle ray.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The hen harrier.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Miller's thumb</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A small fresh-water fish of the genus <gen>Uranidea</gen> (formerly <gen>Cottus</gen>), as the European species (<spn>Uranidea gobio</spn>), and the American (<spn>Uranidea gracilis</spn>); -- called also <altname>bullhead</altname>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A small bird, as the gold-crest, chiff-chaff, and long-tailed tit.</cd> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millerite</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"ler*ite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A believer in the doctrine of <person>William <etsep>Miller</etsep></person> (d. 1849), who taught that the end of the world and the second coming of Christ were at hand.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millerite</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"ler*ite</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <person>W. H. <etsep>Miller</etsep></person>, of Cambridge, Eng.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A sulphide of nickel, commonly occurring in delicate capillary crystals, also in incrustations of a bronze yellow; -- sometimes called <altname>hair pyrites</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millesimal</ent><br/
<hw>Mil*les"i*mal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>millesimus</ets>, fr. <ets>mille</ets> a thousand.]</ety> <def>Thousandth; consisting of thousandth parts; <as>as, <ex>millesimal</ex> fractions</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>millet</ent><br/
<hw>mil"let</hw> <pr>(m<icr/l"l<ecr/t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., dim. of <ets>mil</ets>, L. <ets>milium</ets>; akin to Gr. <grk>meli`nh</grk>, AS. <ets>mil</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The name of several cereal and forage grasses which bear an abundance of small roundish grains. The common millets of Germany and Southern Europe are <spn>Panicum miliaceum</spn>, and <spn>Setaria Italica</spn>.</def></p>

<p><-- all species in this note are subtypes -->
<note><hand/ <col><b>Arabian millet</b></col> is <spn>Sorghum Halepense</spn>. -- <col><b>Egyptian millet</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>East Indian millet</b></col> is <spn>Penicillaria spicata</spn>. -- <col><b>Indian millet</b></col> is <spn>Sorghum vulgare</spn>. (See under <er>Indian</er>.) -- <col><b>Italian millet</b></col> is <spn>Setaria Italica</spn>, a coarse, rank-growing annual grass, valuable for fodder when cut young, and bearing nutritive seeds; -- called also <altname>Hungarian grass</altname>. -- <col><b>Texas millet</b></col> is <spn>Panicum Texanum</spn>. -- <col><b>Wild millet</b></col>, <xex>or</xex> <col><b>Millet grass</b></col>, is <spn>Milium effusum</spn>, a tall grass growing in woods.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mill-girl</ent><br/
<hw>mill-girl</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a girl who works in a mill.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milli-</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"li-</hw> <pr>(m<icr/l"l<icr/-)</pr>. <ety>[From L. <ets>mille</ets> a thousand.]</ety> <fld>(Metric System, Elec., Mech., etc.)</fld> <def>A prefix denoting a <sig>thousandth part of</sig>; <as>as, <ex>milli</ex>meter, <ex>milli</ex>gram, <ex>milli</ex>amp<egrave/re</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>milliammeter</ent><br/
<hw>milliammeter</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a sensitive ammeter for detecting small currents, graduated in milliamperes.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milliampere</ent><br/
<hw>Mil`li*am`p<egrave/re"</hw> <pr>(m<icr/l"l<icr/*<aum/N`p<acir/r")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Milli-</ets> + <ets>amp<egrave/re</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>The thousandth part of one ampere.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milliard</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mil`liard"</hw> <pr>(F. m<esl/l`y<adot/r"; E. m<icr/l"l<icr/*<aum/rd)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., from <ets>mille</ets>, <ets>mil</ets>, thousand, L. <ets>mille</ets>.]</ety> <def>A thousand millions; -- usually called <altname>billion</altname> in the United States.   See <er>Billion</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milliary</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"li*a*ry</hw> <pr>(m<icr/l"l<icr/*<asl/*r<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>milliarius</ets> containing a thousand, fr. <ets>mille</ets> thousand: cf. F. <ets>milliaire</ets> milliary.  See <er>Mile</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to a mile, or to distance by miles; denoting a mile or miles.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>milliary</qex> column, from which they used to compute the distance of all the cities and places of note.</q> <rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milliary</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"li*a*ry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Milliaries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>milliarium</ets>. See <er>Milliary</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>A milestone.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millier</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mil`lier"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>mille</ets> thousand.]</ety> <def>A weight of the metric system, being one million grams; a metric ton.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millifold</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"li*fold`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mille</ets> thousand + E. <ets>fold</ets> times.]</ety> <def>Thousandfold.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Davies (Holy Roode).</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milligramme</ent><br/
<ent>Milligram</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mil"li*gram</hw>, <hw>Mil"li*gramme</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>milligramme</ets>; <ets>milli-</ets> milli- + <ets>gramme</ets>. See 3d <er>Gram</er>.]</ety> <def>A measure of mass and weight, in the metric system, being the thousandth part of a gram, very nearly equal to the weight of a cubic millimeter of water, or .01543 of a grain avoirdupois.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millilitre</ent><br/
<ent>Milliliter</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mil"li*li`ter</hw>, <hw>Mil"li*li`tre</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>millilitre</ets>; <ets>milli-</ets> milli- + <ets>litre</ets>. See <er>Liter</er>.]</ety> <def>A measure of capacity in the metric system, containing the thousandth part of a liter.  It is very nearly equal to a cubic centimeter, and is equal to .061025 of an English cubic inch, or to .033815 of an American fluid ounce.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millimetre</ent><br/
<ent>Millimeter</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mil"li*me`ter</hw>, <hw>Mil"li*me`tre</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>millim<egrave/tre</ets>; <ets>milli-</ets> milli- + <ets>m<egrave/tre</ets>. See 3d <er>Meter</er>.]</ety> <def>A lineal measure in the metric system, containing the thousandth part of a meter; equal to .03937 of an inch. See 3d <er>Meter</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millimicron</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"li*mi`cron</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>  <ety>[<ets>Milli-</ets> + <ets>micron</ets>.]</ety> <def>The thousandth part of a micron or the millionth part of a millimeter; one nanometer; -- a unit of length sometimes used in measuring light waves, etc.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>milline</ent><br/
<hw>milline</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>an advertising measure; one agate line appearing in one million copies of a publication.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milliner</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"li*ner</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <ets>Milaner</ets> an inhabitant of <ets>Milan</ets>, in Italy; hence, a man from <ets>Milan</ets> who imported women's finery.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Formerly, a man who imported and dealt in small articles of a miscellaneous kind, especially such as please the fancy of women.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No <qex>milliner</qex> can so fit his customers with gloves.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A person who designs, makes, trims, or deals in hats, bonnets, headdresses, etc., for women.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Man milliner</b></col>, <cd>a man who makes or deals in millinery, that occupation having been at one time predominantly performed by women; hence, contemptuously, a man who is busied with trifling occupations or embellishments.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millinery</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"li*ner*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The articles made or sold by milliners, as headdresses, hats or bonnets, laces, ribbons, and the like.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The business of work of a milliner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millinet</ent><br/
<hw>Mil`li*net"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A stiff cotton fabric used by milliners for lining bonnets.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milling</ent><br/
<hw>Mill"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act or employment of grinding or passing through a mill; the process of fulling; the process of making a raised or intented edge upon coin, etc.; the process of dressing surfaces of various shapes with rotary cutters. See <er>Mill</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>High milling</b></col>, <cd>milling in which grain is reduced to flour by a succession of crackings, or of slight and partial crushings, alternately with sifting and sorting the product.</cd> -- <col><b>Low milling</b></col>, <cd>milling in which the reduction is effected in a single crushing or grinding.</cd> -- <col><b>Milling cutter</b></col>, <cd>a fluted, sharp-edged rotary cutter for dressing surfaces, as of metal, of various shapes.</cd> -- <col><b>Milling machine</b></col>, <cd>a machine tool for dressing surfaces by rotary cutters.</cd> -- <col><b>Milling tool</b></col>, <cd>a roller with indented edge or surface, for producing like indentations in metal by rolling pressure, as in turning; a knurling tool; a milling cutter.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Million</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"lion</hw> <pr>(m<icr/l"y<ucr/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., from LL. <ets>millio</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mille</ets> a thousand. See <er>Mile</er>.]</ety>  <sn>1.</sn> <def>The number of ten hundred thousand, or a thousand thousand, -- written 1,000,000. See the Note under <er>Hundred</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A very great number; an indefinitely large number.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Millions</qex> of truths that a man is not concerned to know.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The mass of common people; -- with the article <xex>the</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For the play, I remember, pleased not the <qex>million</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millionaire</ent><br/
<hw>Mil`lion*aire"</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>millionnaire</ets>.]</ety> <def>One whose wealth is counted by millions of francs, dollars, or pounds; a very rich person; a person worth a million or more.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>millionnaire</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millionairess</ent><br/
<hw>Mil`lion*air"ess</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A woman who is a millionaire, or the wife of a millionaire.</def> <mark>[Humorous]</mark>  <rj><au>Holmes.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millionary</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"lion*a*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to millions; consisting of millions; <as>as, the <ex>millionary</ex> chronology of the pundits</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Pinkerton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millioned</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"lioned</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Multiplied by millions; innumerable.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millionnaire</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mil`lion`naire"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>Millionaire.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millionth</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"lionth</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Being the last one of a million of units or objects counted in regular order from the first of a series or succession; being one of a million.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millionth</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"lionth</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quotient of a unit divided by one million; one of a million equal parts.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milliped</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"li*ped</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The same <er>Milleped</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millistere</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"li*stere</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>millist<egrave/re</ets>, from <ets>milli-</ets> milli- + <ets>st<egrave/re</ets>.]</ety> <def>A liter, or cubic decimeter.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milliweber</ent><br/
<hw>Mil`li*we"ber</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Milli-</ets> + <ets>weber</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>The thousandth part of one weber.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>millpond</ent><br/
<hw>millpond</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a pond formed by damming a stream to provide a head of water to turn a mill wheel.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>millrace</ent><br/
<hw>millrace</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a channel from a millpond to a millwheel, to provide the water current that turns the millwheel.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> millrun.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 925 --></p>

<p><ent>Millreis</ent><br/
<ent>Millree</ent><br/
<ent>Millrea</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mill"rea`</hw> <pr>(m<icr/l"r<emac/`)</pr>, <hw>Mill"ree`</hw>, <hw>Mill"reis`</hw> <pr>(m<icr/l"r<emac/s`)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Milreis</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millrynd</ent><br/
<ent>Millrind</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mill"rind`</hw> <pr>(m<icr/l"r<imac/nd`)</pr>, <hw>Mill"rynd`</hw> <pr>(m<icr/l"r<imac/nd`)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mill</ets> + <ets>rynd</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>A figure supposed to represent the iron which holds a millstone by being set into its center.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>millrun</ent><br/
<hw>millrun</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a <er>millrace</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> millrace.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mill-sixpence</ent><br/
<hw>Mill"-sixpence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A milled sixpence; -- the sixpence being one of the first English coins milled (1561).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millstone</ent><br/
<hw>Mill"stone`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One of two circular stones used for grinding grain or other substance in a mill{1}.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No man shall take the nether or the upper <qex>millstone</qex> to pledge.</q> <rj><qau>Deut. xxiv. 6.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The cellular siliceous rock called buhrstone is usually employed for millstones; also, some kinds of lava, as that Niedermendig, or other firm rock with rough texture. The surface of a millstone has usually a series of radial grooves in which the powdered material collects.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Millstone girt</b></col> <fld>(Geol.)</fld>, <cd>a hard and coarse, gritty sandstone, dividing the Carboniferous from the Subcarboniferous strata. See <cref>Farewell rock</cref>, under <er>Farewell</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and <xex>Chart</xex> of <er>Geology</er>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>To see into a millstone</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To see through a millstone</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to see into or through a difficult matter.</cd> <mark>(Colloq.)</mark></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>millwheel</ent><br/
<hw>millwheel</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a waterwheel that is used to drive machinery in a mill.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millwork</ent><br/
<hw>Mill"work`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The shafting, gearing, and other driving machinery of mills.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The business of setting up or of operating mill machinery.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Millwright</ent><br/
<hw>Mill"wright`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mechanic whose occupation is to build mills, or to set up their machinery.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>milometer</ent><br/
<hw>milometer</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a meter that shows mileage traversed.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> odometer, hodometer, mileometer.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milord</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*lord"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. (also It., Sp., Russ.), fr. E. <ets>my lord</ets>.]</ety> <def>Lit., my lord; hence (as used on the Continent), an English nobleman or gentleman.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milquetoast</ent><br/
<hw>Milquetoast</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From Caspar Milquetoast, a character in a cartoon strip by H. T. Webster, <publ>The Timid Soul</publ> (1935).]</ety>  <def>a timid, unassertive man or boy fearful of confrontation and easily manipulated and dominated.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> sissy, pantywaist, pansy, milksop.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milreis</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"reis`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pg. <ets>mil reis</ets>, i. e., one thousand reis; <ets>mil</ets> a thousand + <ets>reis</ets>, pl. of <ets>real</ets> a rei.]</ety> <def>A Portuguese money of account rated in the treasury department of the United States at one dollar and eight cents; also, a Brazilian money of account rated at fifty-four cents and six mills (1913).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milt</ent><br/
<hw>Milt</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>milte</ets>; akin to D. <ets>milt</ets>, G. <ets>milz</ets>, OHG. <ets>milzi</ets>, Icel. <ets>milti</ets>, Dan. <ets>milt</ets>, Sw. <ets>mj<aum/lte</ets>, and prob. to E. <ets>malt</ets>, <ets>melt</ets>. <root/108. See <er>Malt</er> the grain.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The spleen.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milt</ent><br/
<hw>Milt</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Akin to Dan. <ets>melk</ets>, Sw. <ets>mj<oum/lke</ets>, G. <ets>milch</ets>, and E. <ets>milk</ets>. See <er>Milk</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The spermatic fluid of fishes.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The testes, or spermaries, of fishes when filled with spermatozoa.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milt</ent><br/
<hw>Milt</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To impregnate (the roe of a fish) with milt.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milter</ent><br/
<hw>Milt"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. D. <ets>milter</ets>, G. <ets>milcher</ets>, <ets>milchner</ets>. See 2d <er>Milt</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A male fish.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miltonian</ent><br/
<hw>Mil*to"ni*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <def>Miltonic.</def>  <rj><au>Lowell.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miltonic</ent><br/
<hw>Mil*ton"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <def>Of, pertaining to, or resembling, <persfn>Milton</persfn>, or his writings; <as>as, <ex>Miltonic</ex> prose</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miltwaste</ent><br/
<hw>Milt"waste`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <ety>[1st <ets>milt</ets> + <ets>waste</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A small European fern (<spn>Asplenium Ceterach</spn>) formerly used in medicine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milvine</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"vine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>milvus</ets> kite.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or resembling birds of the kite kind.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milvine</ent><br/
<hw>Mil"vine</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A bird related to the kite.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Milvus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mil"vus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., a kite.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of raptorial birds, including the European kite.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mime</ent><br/
<hw>Mime</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mimus</ets>, Gr. <?/, akin to <?/ to imitate, to mimic: cf. F. <ets>mime</ets>.  Cf. <er>Mimosa</er>.]</ety>  <sn>1.</sn> <def>A kind of drama in which real persons and events were generally represented in a ridiculous manner; an ancient Greek or Roman form of farce.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An actor in such representations.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The art of representing actions, events, situations, or stories solely by gestures and body movements, without speaking; pantomime{3}.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An actor who performs or specializes in mime{3}; an actor who communicates entirely by gesture and facial expression; a pantomime{2}; a pantomimist; a mimer.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mummer, pantomimer, pantomimist.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A mimic.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mime</ent><br/
<hw>Mime</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To mimic.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> -- <wordforms><wf>Mim"er</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mimeo</ent><br/
<hw>mimeo</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[by shortening.]</ety> <def>A mimeograph.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mimeograph, mimeograph machine, Roneo.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mimeo</ent><br/
<hw>mimeo</hw> <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>to make copies of using a mimeograph.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mimeograph.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mimeograph</ent><br/
<hw>Mim"e*o*graph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ to imitate + <ets>-graph</ets>.]</ety> <def>A copying device that uses a stencil through which ink is pressed; it was invented by <persfn>Edison</persfn>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mimeo, mimeograph machine, Roneo.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mimeograph</ent><br/
<hw>mimeograph</hw> <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>to make copies of using a mimeograph; <as>as, She <ex>mimeographed</ex> the syllabus</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mimeo.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mimer</ent><br/
<hw>mim"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A person who performs in a mime.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mime, mummer, pantomimer, pantomimist.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A mimic.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mimesis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mi*me"sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ imitation.]</ety> <fld>(Rhet. & Biol.)</fld> <def>Imitation; mimicry.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mimetene</ent><br/
<hw>Mim"e*tene</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>See <er>Mimetite</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mimetical</ent><br/
<ent>Mimetic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mi*met"ic</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <hw>Mi*met"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw><ety>[Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ to imitate.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Apt to imitate; given to mimicry; imitative.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Characterized by mimicry; -- applied to animals and plants; <as>as, <ex>mimetic</ex> species; <ex>mimetic</ex> organisms. See <er>Mimicry</er>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mimetism</ent><br/
<hw>Mim"e*tism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From Gr. <?/ to mimic.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Mimicry</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mimetite</ent><br/
<hw>Mim"e*tite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ an imitator. So called because it resembles pyromorphite.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A mineral occurring in pale yellow or brownish hexagonal crystals. It is an arseniate of lead.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mimical</ent><br/
<ent>Mimic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mim"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mim"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mimicus</ets>, Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ mime: cf. F. <ets>mimique</ets>. See <er>Mime</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Imitative; mimetic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Oft, in her absence, <qex>mimic</qex> fancy wakes<br/
To imitate her.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Man is, of all creatures, the most <qex>mimical</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>W. Wotton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Consisting of, or formed by, imitation; imitated; <as>as, <ex>mimic</ex> gestures</as>.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Mimic</xex> hootings.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Wordsworth.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Imitative; characterized by resemblance to other forms; -- applied to crystals which by twinning resemble simple forms of a higher grade of symmetry.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Mimic</xex> often implies something droll or ludicrous, and is less dignified than <xex>imitative</xex>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mimic beetle</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a beetle that feigns death when disturbed, esp. the species of <gen>Hister</gen> and allied genera.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mimic</ent><br/
<hw>Mim"ic</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who imitates or mimics, especially one who does so for sport; a copyist; a buffoon.</def>  <rj><au>Burke.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mimic</ent><br/
<hw>Mim"ic</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mimicked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mimicking</conjf>.]</vmorph><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To imitate or ape for sport; to ridicule by imitation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The walk, the words, the gesture, could supply,<br/
The habit <qex>mimic</qex>, and the mien belie.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>To assume a resemblance to (some other organism of a totally different nature, or some surrounding object), as a means of protection or advantage.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To ape; imitate; counterfeit; mock.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mimically</ent><br/
<hw>Mim"ic*al*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In an imitative manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mimicker</ent><br/
<hw>Mim"ick*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who mimics; a mimic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An animal which imitates something else, in form or habits.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mimicry</ent><br/
<hw>Mim"ic*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or practice of one who mimics; ludicrous imitation for sport or ridicule.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Protective resemblance; the resemblance which certain animals and plants exhibit to other animals and plants or to the natural objects among which they live, -- a characteristic which serves as their chief means of protection against enemies; imitation; mimesis; mimetism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mimir</ent><br/
<hw>Mimir</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Norse mythology)</fld> <def>A giant who guarded the well of wisdom.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mimographer</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*mog"ra*pher</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mimographus</ets>, Gr. <?/; <?/ a mime + <?/ to write: cf. F. <ets>mimographe</ets>.]</ety> <def>A writer of mimes.</def>  <rj><au>Sir T. Herbert.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mimosa</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mi*mo"sa</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ imitator.  Cf. <er>Mime</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of leguminous plants, containing many species, and including the sensitive plants (<spn>Mimosa sensitiva</spn>, and <spn>Mimosa pudica</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The term <ex>mimosa</ex> is also applied in commerce to several kinds bark imported from Australia, and used in tanning; -- called also <altname>wattle bark</altname>.</note>  <rj><au>Tomlinson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mimosaceae</ent><br/
<hw>Mimosaceae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of spiny woody plants (usually shrubs or small trees) whose leaves mimic animals in sensitivity to touch; commonly included in the family <fam>Leguminosae</fam>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Mimosaceae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mimosoideae</ent><br/
<hw>Mimosoideae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>An alternative name used in some classification systems for the family <altname>Mimosaceae</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> subfamily <subfam>Mimosoideae</subfam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mimotannic</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`mo*tan"nic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mimo</ets>sa + <ets>tannic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or designating, a variety of tannin or tannic acid found in Acacia, Mimosa, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mimus</ent><br/
<hw>Mimus</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The type genus of the family <fam>Mimidae</fam>, comprising certain of the mockingbirds.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus Mimus.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>min.</ent><br/
<hw>min.</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>An abbreviation for <abbr>minute</abbr>, a unit of time equal to 60 seconds or 1/60th of an hour.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> minute, min.[abbrev.].</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Min</ent><br/
<hw>Min</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>a dialect of Chinese.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Min dialect, Fukkianese, Hokkianese, Amoy, Taiwanese.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>an Egyptian god of procreation.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mina</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>mi"na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> L. <plw>Minae</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, E. <plw>Minas</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/.]</ety> <def>An ancient weight or denomination of money, of varying value.  The Attic mina was valued at a hundred drachmas.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mina</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Myna</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minable</ent><br/
<hw>Min"a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Such as can be mined; <as>as, <ex>minable</ex> earth</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Sir T. North.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minacious</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*na"cious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>minax</ets>, <ets>-acis</ets>. See <er>Menace</er>.]</ety> <def>Threatening; menacing.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minacity</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*nac"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Disposition to threaten.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minaret</ent><br/
<hw>Min"a*ret</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>minarete</ets>, Ar. <ets>man<amac/rat</ets> lamp, lantern, lighthouse, turret, fr. <ets>n<amac/r</ets> to shine.]</ety> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A slender, lofty tower attached to a mosque and surrounded by one or more projecting balconies, from which the summon to prayer is cried by the muezzin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minargent</ent><br/
<hw>Min*ar"gent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. contr. from alu<ets>min</ets>ium + L. <ets>argent</ets>um silver.]</ety> <def>An alloy consisting of copper, nickel, tungsten, and aluminium; -- used by jewelers.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minatorily</ent><br/
<ent>Minatorially</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Min`a*to"ri*al*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Min"a*to*ri*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a minatory manner; with threats.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minatory</ent><br/
<hw>Min"a*to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>minatorius</ets>, fr. <ets>minari</ets> to threaten. See <er>Menace</er>.]</ety> <def>Threatening; menacing.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minaul</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*naul"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Manul</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mince</ent><br/
<hw>Mince</hw> <pr>(m<icr/ns)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Minced</conjf> <pr>(m<icr/nst)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Minging</conjf> <pr>(m<icr/n"s<icr/ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>minsian</ets> to grow less, dwindle, fr. <ets>min</ets> small; akin to G. <ets>minder</ets> less, Goth. <ets>minniza</ets> less, <ets>mins</ets> less, adv., L. <ets>minor</ets>, adj. (cf. <er>Minor</er>); or more likely fr. F. <ets>mincer</ets> to mince, prob. from (assumed) LL. <ets>minutiare</ets>. <root/101. See <er>Minish</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To cut into very small pieces; to chop fine; to hash; <as>as, to <ex>mince</ex> meat</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To suppress or weaken the force of; to extenuate; to palliate; to tell by degrees, instead of directly and frankly; to clip, as words or expressions; to utter half and keep back half of; <as>as, he doesn't <ex>mince</ex> words</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I know no ways to <qex>mince</qex> it in love, but directly to say -- <ldquo/I love you.<rdquo/</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Siren, now <qex>mince</qex> the sin,<br/
And mollify damnation with a phrase.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If, to <qex>mince</qex> his meaning, I had either omitted some part of what he said, or taken from the strength of his expression, I certainly had wronged him.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To affect; to make a parade of.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mince</ent><br/
<hw>Mince</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To walk with short steps; to walk in a prim, affected manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The daughters of Zion are haughty, and walk with stretched forth necks and wanton eyes, . . . <qex>mincing</qex> as they go.</q> <rj><qau>Is. iii. 16.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I 'll . . . turn two <qex>mincing</qex> steps<br/
Into a manly stride.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To act or talk with affected nicety; to affect delicacy in manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mince</ent><br/
<hw>Mince</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A short, precise step; an affected manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mince-meat</ent><br/
<hw>Mince"-meat`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Minced meat; meat chopped very fine; a mixture of boiled meat, suet, apples, etc., chopped very fine, to which spices and raisins are added; -- used in making mince pie.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mince pie</ent><br/
<hw>Mince" pie`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <def>A pie made of mince-meat.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mincer</ent><br/
<hw>Min"cer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who minces.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mincing</ent><br/
<hw>Min"cing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>That minces; characterized by primness or affected nicety.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mincingly</ent><br/
<hw>Min"cing*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a mincing manner; not fully; with affected nicety.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mind</ent><br/
<hw>Mind</hw> <pr>(m<imac/nd)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>mynd</ets>, <ets>gemynd</ets>; akin to OHG. <ets>minna</ets> memory, love, G. <ets>minne</ets> love, Dan. <ets>minde</ets> mind, memory, remembrance, consent, vote, Sw. <ets>minne</ets> memory, Icel. <ets>minni</ets>, Goth. <ets>gamunds</ets>, L. <ets>mens</ets>, <ets>mentis</ets>, mind, Gr. <grk>me`nos</grk>, Skr. <ets>manas</ets> mind, <ets>man</ets> to think. <root/104, 278.  Cf. <er>Comment</er>, <er>Man</er>, <er>Mean</er>, <pos>v.</pos>, 3d <er>Mental</er>, <er>Mignonette</er>, <er>Minion</er>, <er>Mnemonic</er>, <er>Money</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The intellectual or rational faculty in man; the understanding; the intellect; the power that conceives, judges, or reasons; also, the entire spiritual nature; the soul; -- often in distinction from the <contr>body</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By the <qex>mind</qex> of man we understand that in him which thinks, remembers, reasons, wills.</q> <rj><qau>Reid.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What we mean by <qex>mind</qex> is simply that which perceives, thinks, feels, wills, and desires.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Hamilton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let every man be fully persuaded in his own <qex>mind</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Rom. xiv. 5.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>mind</qex> shall banquet, though the body pine.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state, at any given time, of the faculties of thinking, willing, choosing, and the like; psychical activity or state;</def> <specif>as:</specif> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Opinion; judgment; belief.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A fool uttereth all his <qex>mind</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Prov. xxix. 11.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Being so hard to me that brought your <qex>mind</qex>, I fear she'll prove as hard to you in telling her <qex>mind</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>Choice; inclination; liking; intent; will.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If it be your <qex>minds</qex>, then let none go forth.</q> <rj><qau>2 Kings ix. 15.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>Courage; spirit.</def>  <rj><au>Chapman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Memory; remembrance; recollection; <as>as, to have or keep in <ex>mind</ex>, to call to <ex>mind</ex>, to put in <ex>mind</ex>, etc.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To have a mind</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To have a great mind</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to be inclined or strongly inclined in purpose; -- used with an infinitive.</cd> <ldquo/Sir Roger de Coverly . . . told me that he <xex>had a great mind</xex> to see the new tragedy with me.<rdquo/ <au>Addison.</au> -- <col><b>To lose one's mind</b></col>, <cd>to become insane, or imbecile.</cd> -- <col><b>To make up one's mind</b></col>, <cd>to come to an opinion or decision; to determine.</cd> -- <col><b>To put in mind</b></col>, <cd>to remind.</cd> <ldquo/Regard us simply as <xex>putting you in mind</xex> of what you already know to be good policy.<rdquo/ <au>Jowett (Thucyd. ).</au></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mind</ent><br/
<hw>Mind</hw> <pr>(m<imac/nd)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Minded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Minding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>myndian</ets>, <ets>gemynd<imac/an</ets> to remember. See <er>Mind</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>  <sn>1.</sn> <def>To fix the mind or thoughts on; to regard with attention; to treat as of consequence; to consider; to heed; to mark; to note.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Mind</xex> not high things, but condescend to men of low estate.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Rom. xii. 16.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My lord, you nod: you do not <qex>mind</qex> the play.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To occupy one's self with; to employ one's self about; to attend to; <as>as, to <ex>mind</ex> one's business</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bidding him be a good child, and <qex>mind</qex> his book.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To obey; <as>as, to <ex>mind</ex> parents; the dog <ex>minds</ex> his master.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To have in mind; to purpose.</def>  <rj><au>Beaconsfield.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>mind</qex> to tell him plainly what I think.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To put in mind; to remind.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>  <rj><au>M. Arnold.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>minded</qex> them of the mutability of all earthly things.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I do thee wrong to <qex>mind</qex> thee of it.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Never mind</b></col>, <cd>do not regard it; it is of no consequence; no matter.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To notice; mark; regard; obey. See <er>Attend</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mind</ent><br/
<hw>Mind</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To give attention or heed; to obey; <as>as, the dog <ex>minds</ex> well</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mind-altering</ent><br/
<hw>mind-altering</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>producing mood changes or distorted perception; -- used mostly of psychoactive substances; <as>as, hallucinogenic drugs are <ex>mind-altering</ex> substances</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mind-bending</ent><br/
<hw>mind-bending</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>intensely affecting the mind, especially in producing hallucinations; -- usually of chemical substances.</def> <mark>[informal]</mark><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mind-blowing.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mind-blowing</ent><br/
<hw>mind-blowing</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>  <def>mind-bending.</def> <mark>[informal]</mark><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> .</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>intensely affecting the mind or emotions; astonishing; -- usually referring to extraordinary experiences; <as>as, spending a week in the jungle was a <ex>mind-blowing</ex> experience; a <ex>mind-blowing</ex> horror story</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mind-boggling</ent><br/
<hw>mind-boggling</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>intellectually or emotionally overwhelming; straining one's capacity to comprehend or cope; <as>as, a <ex>mind-boggling</ex> display; a <ex>mind-boggling</ex> puzzle</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minded</ent><br/
<hw>Mind"ed</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Disposed; inclined; having a mind.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Joseph . . . was <qex>minded</qex> to put her away privily.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. i. 19.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If men were <qex>minded</qex> to live virtuously.</q> <rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Minded</xex> is much used in composition; as, high-<xex>minded</xex>, feeble-<xex>minded</xex>, bloody-<xex>minded</xex>, sober-<xex>minded</xex>, double-<xex>minded</xex>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minden</ent><br/
<hw>Minden</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A battle in the Seven Years' War (1759) in which the Anglo-Allied forces under duke <person>Ferdinand of Brunswick</person> defeated the French under <person>Marshal Contades</person>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> battle of Minden.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minder</ent><br/
<hw>Mind"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who minds, tends, or watches something, as a child, a machine, or cattle; <as>as, a <ex>minder</ex> of a loom</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One to be attended; specif., a pauper child intrusted to the care of a private person.</def> <mark>[Eng.]</mark>  <rj><au>Dickens.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mindful</ent><br/
<hw>Mind"ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Bearing in mind; regardful; attentive; heedful; observant.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What is man, that thou art <qex>mindful</qex> of him?</q> <rj><qau>Ps. viii. 4.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I promise you to be <qex>mindful</qex> of your admonitions.</q> <rj><qau>Hammond.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Mind"ful*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mind"ful*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minding</ent><br/
<hw>Mind"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Regard; mindfulness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mindless</ent><br/
<hw>Mind"less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Not indued with mind or intellectual powers; stupid; unthinking.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Unmindful; inattentive; heedless; careless.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cursed Athens, <qex>mindless</qex> of thy worth.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mine</ent><br/
<hw>Mine</hw> <pr>(m<emac/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>See <er>Mien</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mine</ent><br/
<hw>Mine</hw> <pr>(m<imac/n)</pr>, <pos>pron. & a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>min</ets>, fr. AS. <ets>m<imac/n</ets>; akin to D. <ets>mijn</ets>, OS., OFries., & OHG. <ets>m<imac/n</ets>, G. <ets>mein</ets>, Sw. & Dan. <ets>min</ets>, Icel. <ets>minn</ets>, Goth. <ets>meins</ets> my, mine, <ets>meina</ets> of me, and E. <ets>me</ets>. <root/187. See <er>Me</er>, and cf. <er>My</er>.]</ety> <def>Belonging to me; my. Used as a pronominal to me; my. Used as a pronominal adjective in the predicate; <as>as, <ldquo/Vengeance is <ex>mine</ex>; I will repay.<rdquo/ <au>Rom. xii. 19</au></as>. Also, in the old style, used attributively, instead of <xex>my</xex>, before a noun beginning with a vowel.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I kept myself from <qex>mine</qex> iniquity.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. xviii. 23.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Mine</xex> is often used absolutely, the thing possessed being understood; as, his son is in the army, <xex>mine</xex> in the navy.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When a man deceives me once, says the Italian proverb, it is his fault; when twice, it is <qex>mine</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Horne.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This title honors me and <qex>mine</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She shall have me and <qex>mine</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mine</ent><br/
<hw>Mine</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>miner</ets>, L. <ets>minare</ets> to drive animals, in LL. also, to lead, conduct, dig a mine (cf. E. <ets>lode</ets>, and <ets>lead</ets> to conduct), akin to L. <ets>minari</ets> to threaten; cf. Sp. <ets>mina</ets> mine, conduit, subterraneous canal, a spring or source of water, It. <ets>mina</ets>. See <er>Menace</er>, and cf. <er>Mien</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To dig a mine or pit in the earth; to get ore, metals, coal, or precious stones, out of the earth; to dig in the earth for minerals; to dig a passage or cavity under anything in order to overthrow it by explosives or otherwise.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To form subterraneous tunnel or hole; to form a burrow or lodge in the earth; <as>as, the <ex>mining</ex> cony</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mine</ent><br/
<hw>Mine</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mined</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mining</conjf>.]</vmorph><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To dig away, or otherwise remove, the substratum or foundation of; to lay a mine under; to sap; to undermine; hence, to ruin or destroy by slow degrees or secret means.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>mined</qex> the walls.</q> <rj><qau>Hayward.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Too lazy to cut down these immense trees, the spoilers . . . had <qex>mined</qex> them, and placed a quantity of gunpowder in the cavity.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To dig into, for ore or metal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lead veins have been traced . . . but they have not been <qex>mined</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ure.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To get, as metals, out of the earth by digging.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The principal ore <qex>mined</qex> there is the bituminous cinnabar.</q> <rj><qau>Ure.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mine</ent><br/
<hw>Mine</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. LL. <ets>mina</ets>. See <er>Mine</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A subterranean cavity or passage</def>; <specif>especially:</specif> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A pit or excavation in the earth, from which metallic ores, precious stones, coal, or other mineral substances are taken by digging; -- distinguished from the pits from which stones for architectural purposes are taken, and which are called <xex>quarries</xex>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A cavity or tunnel made under a fortification or other work, for the purpose of blowing up the superstructure with some explosive agent.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 926 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any place where ore, metals, or precious stones are got by digging or washing the soil; <as>as, a placer <ex>mine</ex></as>.</def><-- esp. in <cref>gold mine</cref> --><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <mark>(Fig.)</mark>: <def>A rich source of wealth or other good.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>An explosive device placed concealed in a location, on land or at sea, where an enemy vehicle or enemy personnel may pass through, having a triggering mechanism which detects people or vehicles, and which will explode and kill or maim personnel or destroy or damage vehicles.  A mine placed at sea (formerly called a <altname>torpedo</altname>, see <er>torpedo</er>{2} <sd>(a)</sd>) is also called an <ecol><b>marine mine</b></ecol> and <ecol><b>underwater mine</b></ecol> and sometimes called a <styp><ecol><b>floating mine</b></ecol></styp>, even though it may be anchored to the floor of the sea and not actually float freely.  A mine placed on land (formerly called a <altname>torpedo</altname>, see <er>torpedo</er>{3}), usually buried, is called a <ecol><b>land mine</b></ecol>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mine dial</b></col>, <cd>a form of magnetic compass used by miners.</cd> -- <col><b>Mine pig</b></col>, <cd>pig iron made wholly from ore; in distinction from <contr>cinder pig</contr>, which is made from ore mixed with forge or mill cinder.</cd> -- <col><b>gold mine</b></col> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>a mine where gold is obtained.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <mark>(Fig.)</mark> <cd>a rich source of wealth or other good; same as <er>Mine</er> 3.</cd></cs>  <rj><au>Raymond.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mined</ent><br/
<hw>mined</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>extracted from a source of supply as of minerals from the earth.</def> [Narrower terms: <stype>deep-mined</stype>; <stype>exploited</stype>; <stype>strip-mined</stype>]<br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>minefield</ent><br/
<hw>minefield</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>a region in which explosive mines{4} have been placed, especially a region on land.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <mark>(Fig.)</mark> <def>A situation in which a simple mistake can have disastrous consequences; a touchy or dangerous situation requiring great caution; <as>as, the candidate threaded his way skillfully through a <ex>minefield</ex> of loaded questions from the audience</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>minelayer</ent><br/
<hw>minelayer</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a ship equipped for laying underwater mines.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>minelaying</ent><br/
<hw>minelaying</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act or process of laying explosive mines in concealed places to destroy enemy personnel and equipment.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mining.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miner</ent><br/
<hw>Min"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mineur</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>One who mines; a digger for metals, etc.; one engaged in the business of getting ore, coal, or precious stones, out of the earth; one who digs military mines; <as>as, armies have sappers and <ex>miners</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Any of numerous insects which, in the larval state, excavate galleries in the parenchyma of leaves.  They are mostly minute moths and dipterous flies.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The chattering, or garrulous, honey eater of Australia (<spn>Myzantha garrula</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Miner's elbow</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>a swelling on the black of the elbow due to inflammation of the bursa over the olecranon; -- so called because of frequent occurrence in miners.</cd> -- <col><b>Miner's inch</b></col>, <cd>in hydraulic mining, the amount of water flowing under a given pressure in a given time through a hole one inch in diameter. It is a unit for measuring the quantity of water supplied.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mineral</ent><br/
<hw>Min"er*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>min<eacute/ral</ets>, LL. <ets>minerale</ets>, fr. <ets>minera</ets> mine. See <er>Mine</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>An inorganic species or substance occurring in nature, having a definite chemical composition and usually a distinct crystalline form.  Rocks, except certain glassy igneous forms, are either simple minerals or aggregates of minerals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A mine.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Anything which is neither animal nor vegetable, as in the most general classification of things into three kingdoms (animal, vegetable, and mineral).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mineral</ent><br/
<hw>Min"er*al</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to minerals; consisting of a mineral or of minerals; <as>as, a <ex>mineral</ex> substance</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Impregnated with minerals; <as>as, <ex>mineral</ex> waters</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mineral acids</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>inorganic acids, as sulphuric, nitric, phosphoric, hydrochloric, acids, etc., as distinguished from the <contr>organic acids</contr>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mineral blue</b></col>, <cd>the name usually given to azurite, when reduced to an impalpable powder for coloring purposes.</cd> -- <col><b>Mineral candle</b></col>, <cd>a candle made of paraffin.</cd> -- <col><b>Mineral caoutchouc</b></col>, <cd>an elastic mineral pitch, a variety of bitumen, resembling caoutchouc in elasticity and softness. See <er>Caoutchouc</er>, and <er>Elaterite</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mineral chameleon</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <cd>See <cref>Chameleon mineral</cref>, under <er>Chameleon</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mineral charcoal</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Charcoal</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mineral cotton</b></col>. <cd>See <cref>Mineral wool</cref> (below).</cd> -- <col><b>Mineral green</b></col>, <cd>a green carbonate of copper; malachite.</cd> -- <col><b>Mineral kingdom</b></col> <fld>(Nat. Sci.)</fld>, <cd>that one of the three grand divisions of nature which embraces all inorganic objects, as distinguished from plants or animals.</cd> -- <col><b>Mineral oil</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Naphtha</er>, and <er>Petroleum</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mineral paint</b></col>, <cd>a pigment made chiefly of some natural mineral substance, as red or yellow iron ocher.</cd> -- <col><b>Mineral patch</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Bitumen</er>, and <er>Asphalt</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mineral right</b></col>, <cd>the right of taking minerals from land.</cd> -- <col><b>Mineral salt</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>a salt of a mineral acid.</cd> -- <col><b>Mineral tallow</b></col>, <cd>a familiar name for <altname>hatchettite</altname>, from its fatty or spermaceti-like appearance.</cd> -- <col><b>Mineral water</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Water</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mineral wax</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Ozocerite</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mineral wool</b></col>, <cd>a fibrous wool-like material, made by blowing a powerful jet of air or steam through melted slag. It is a poor conductor of heat.</cd></cs><-- = glass wool? Also used in filters and sound insulation. --><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mineralist</ent><br/
<hw>Min"er*al*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>min<eacute/raliste</ets>.]</ety> <def>One versed in minerals; mineralogist.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mineralization</ent><br/
<hw>Min`er*al*i*za"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>min<eacute/ralisation</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The process of mineralizing, or forming a mineral by combination of a metal with another element; also, the process of converting into a mineral, as a bone or a plant.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of impregnating with a mineral, as water.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The conversion of a cell wall into a material of a stony nature.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mineralize</ent><br/
<hw>Min"er*al*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mineralized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mineralizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>min<eacute/raliser</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To transform into a mineral.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In these caverns the bones are not <qex>mineralized</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Buckland.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To impregnate with a mineral; <as>as, <ex>mineralized</ex> water</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To charge or impregnate with ore.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mineralize</ent><br/
<hw>Min"er*al*ize</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To go on an excursion for observing and collecting minerals; to mineralogize.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mineralized</ent><br/
<hw>mineralized</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>containing or impregnated with minerals; <as>as, <ex>mineralized</ex> water; red stains that signify <ex>mineralized</ex> land</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>converted into a mineral.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> petrified.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mineralizer</ent><br/
<hw>Min"er*al*i`zer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An element which is combined with a metal, thus forming an ore.  <as>Thus, in galena, or lead ore, sulphur is a <ex>mineralizer</ex>; in hematite, oxygen is a <ex>mineralizer</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mineralogical</ent><br/
<hw>Min`er*al*og"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>min<eacute/ralogique</ets>. See <er>Mineralogy</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to mineralogy; <as>as, a <ex>mineralogical</ex> table</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mineralogically</ent><br/
<hw>Min`er*al*og"ic*al*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>According to the principles of, or with reference to, mineralogy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mineralogist</ent><br/
<hw>Min`er*al"o*gist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>min<eacute/ralogiste</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>One versed in mineralogy; one devoted to the study of minerals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A carrier shell (<spn>Phorus</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mineralogize</ent><br/
<hw>Min`er*al"o*gize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To study mineralogy by collecting and examining minerals.</def>  <rj><au>Miss Edgeworth.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mineralogy</ent><br/
<hw>Min`er*al"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mineralogies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[<ets>Mineral</ets> + <ets>-logy</ets>: cf. F. <ets>min<eacute/ralogie</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The science which treats of minerals, and teaches how to describe, distinguish, and classify them.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A treatise or book on this science.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- minerology, minerological = misspelling for mineralogy, mineralogical --><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minerva</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*ner"va</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.]</ety> <fld>(Rom. Myth.)</fld> <def>The goddess of wisdom, of war, of the arts and sciences, of poetry, and of spinning and weaving; -- identified with the Grecian <altname>Pallas Athene</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>minesweeper</ent><br/
<hw>minesweeper</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A boat designed for the purpose of detecting and disposing of marine mines.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>minesweeping</ent><br/
<hw>minesweeping</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>the activity of detecting and disposing of marine mines.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minette</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*nette"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The smallest of regular sizes of portrait photographs.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minever</ent><br/
<hw>Min"e*ver</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Miniver</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minge</ent><br/
<hw>Minge</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>myngian</ets>; akin to E. <ets>mind</ets>.]</ety> <def>To mingle; to mix.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minge</ent><br/
<hw>Minge</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. corrupt. fr. <ets>midge</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A small biting fly; a midge.</def> <mark>[Local, U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>minginess</ent><br/
<hw>minginess</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>an extreme stinginess.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> meanness, niggardliness, niggardness, parsimony, parsimoniousness, tightfistedness.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mingle</ent><br/
<hw>Min"gle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mingled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mingling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From OE. <ets>mengen</ets>, AS. <ets>mengan</ets>; akin to D. & G. <ets>mengen</ets>, Icel. <ets>menga</ets>, also to E. <ets>among</ets>, and possibly to <ets>mix</ets>.  Cf. <er>Among</er>, <er>Mongrel</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To mix; intermix; to combine or join, as an individual or part, with other parts, but commonly so as to be distinguishable in the product; to confuse; to confound.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There was . . . fire <qex>mingled</qex> with the hail.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. ix. 24.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To associate or unite in society or by ties of relationship; to cause or allow to intermarry; to intermarry.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The holy seed have <qex>mingled</qex> themselves with the people of those lands.</q> <rj><qau>Ezra ix. 2.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To deprive of purity by mixture; to contaminate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>mingled</qex>, imperfect virtue.</q> <rj><qau>Rogers.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To put together; to join.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To make or prepare by mixing the ingredients of.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[He] proceeded to <qex>mingle</qex> another draught.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mingle</ent><br/
<hw>Min"gle</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become mixed or blended.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To associate (with certain people); <as>as, he's too highfalutin to <ex>mingle</ex> with working stiffs</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To move (among other people); -- of people; <as>as, the president left his car to <ex>mingle</ex> with the crowd; a host at a a party should <ex>mingle</ex> with his guests</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mingle</ent><br/
<hw>Min"gle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mixture.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mingleable</ent><br/
<hw>Min"gle*a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>That can be mingled.</def>  <rj><au>Boyle.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mingledly</ent><br/
<hw>Min"gled*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Confusedly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mingle-mangle</ent><br/
<hw>Min"gle-man`gle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Reduplicated fr. <ets>mingle</ets>.]</ety> <def>To mix in a disorderly way; to make a mess of.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Udall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mingle-mangle</ent><br/
<hw>Min"gle-man`gle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A hotchpotch.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Latimer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minglement</ent><br/
<hw>Min"gle*ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of mingling, or the state of being mixed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mingler</ent><br/
<hw>Min"gler</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who mingles.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minglingly</ent><br/
<hw>Min"gling*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a mingling manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minaceous</ent><br/
<hw>Min`*a"ceous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of the color of minium or red lead; miniate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miniard</ent><br/
<hw>Min"iard</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Migniard.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miniardize</ent><br/
<hw>Min"iard*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To render delicate or dainty.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Howell.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miniate</ent><br/
<hw>Min"i*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Miniated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Miniating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>miniatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>miniare</ets>. See <er>Minium</er>.]</ety> <def>To paint or tinge with red lead or vermilion; also, to decorate with letters, or the like, painted red, as the page of a manuscript.</def>  <rj><au>T. Wharton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miniate</ent><br/
<hw>Min"i*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the color of red lead or vermilion; painted with vermilion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miniature</ent><br/
<hw>Min"i*a*ture</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It. <ets>miniatura</ets>, fr. L. <ets>miniare</ets>. See <er>Miniate</er>, <pos>v.</pos>,<er>Minium</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Originally, a painting in colors such as those in mediaeval manuscripts; in modern times, any very small painting, especially a portrait.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Greatly diminished size or form; reduced scale.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Lettering in red; rubric distinction.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A particular feature or trait.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Massinger.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miniature</ent><br/
<hw>Min"i*a*ture</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Being on a small scale; much reduced from the reality; <as>as, a <ex>miniature</ex> copy</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miniature</ent><br/
<hw>Min"i*a*ture</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To represent or depict in a small compass, or on a small scale.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>miniaturisation</ent><br/
<hw>miniaturisation</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>miniaturization.</def> <mark>[Chiefly Brit.]</mark><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>miniaturise</ent><br/
<hw>miniaturise</hw> <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>miniaturize.</def> <mark>[Chiefly Brit.]</mark><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miniaturist</ent><br/
<hw>Min"i*a*tur`ist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A painter of miniatures.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>miniaturization</ent><br/
<hw>miniaturization</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act or process of making on a greatly reduced scale.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> miniaturisation.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>miniaturize</ent><br/
<hw>miniaturize</hw> <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To design or construct on a smaller scale.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> miniaturise.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minibus</ent><br/
<hw>Min"i*bus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>minor</ets> less + <ets>-bus</ets>, as in <ets>omnibus</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A kind of light passenger vehicle, carrying four persons.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark> <br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A type of bus (omnibus) similar in general appearnace to a standard-sized bus, but smaller and having a smaller passenger capacity, typically about 15 persons.  It is usually used for transportation over relatively short distances.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>minicomputer</ent><br/
<hw>minicomputer</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Computers)</fld> <def>a mid-sized digital computer; at any given point in the development of computer technology, a <ex>minicomputer</ex> will be faster and have greater capacity than a <contr>microcomputer</contr>, but will be slower and have less capacity than a <contr>mainframe computer</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minie ball</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ie ball`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[From the inventor, Captain <ets>Mini<eacute/</ets>, of France.]</ety> <def>A conical rifle bullet, with a cavity in its base plugged with a piece of iron, which, by the explosion of the charge, is driven farther in, expanding the sides to fit closely the grooves of the barrel.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minie rifle</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ie ri"fle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <def>A rifle adapted to minie balls.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minify</ent><br/
<hw>Min"i*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Minified</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Minifying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>minor</ets> less + <ets>-fly</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To make small, or smaller; to diminish the apparent dimensions of; to lessen.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To degrade by speech or action.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minikin</ent><br/
<hw>Min"i*kin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OD. <ets>minneken</ets> a darling, dim. of <ets>minne</ets> love; akin to G. <ets>minne</ets>, and to E. <ets>mind</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A little darling; a favorite; a minion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Florio.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A little pin.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minikin</ent><br/
<hw>Min"i*kin</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Small; diminutive.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minim</ent><br/
<hw>Min"im</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>minime</ets>, L. <ets>minimus</ets> the least, smallest, a superl. of <ets>minor</ets>: cf. It. <ets>minima</ets> a note in music. See <er>Minor</er>, and cf. <ets>Minimum</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Anything very minute; <as>as, the <ex>minims</ex> of existence</as>; -- applied to animalcula; and the like.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The smallest liquid measure, equal to about one drop; the sixtieth part of a fluid drachm, equal to one four-hundred-eightieth of a fluid ounce, or 0.06161 milliliter (U. S. measure) or 0.05919 milliliters (British measure).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A small fish; a minnow.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A little man or being; a dwarf.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>One of an austere order of mendicant hermits or friars founded in the 15th century by <person>St. Francis of Paola</person>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A time note, formerly the shortest in use; a half note, equal to half a semibreve, or two quarter notes or crotchets.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A short poetical encomium.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minim</ent><br/
<hw>Min"im</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Minute.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Minim</xex> forms.<rdquo/  <rj><au>J. R. Drake.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minimal</ent><br/
<hw>Min"i*mal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of, pertaining to, or having a character of, a minim or minimum; least; smallest; <as>as, a <ex>minimal</ex> amount or value</as>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miniment</ent><br/
<hw>Min"i*ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. corrupt. of <ets>moniment</ets>.]</ety> <def>A trifle; a trinket; a token.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>minimisation</ent><br/
<hw>minimisation</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>minimization.</def> <mark>[Chiefly Brit.]</mark><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minimization</ent><br/
<hw>Min`i*mi*za"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act or process of minimizing.</def>  <rj><au>Bentham.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>minimize</ent><br/
<hw>min"i*mize</hw> <pr>(m<icr/n"<icr/*m<imac/z)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>minimized</conjf> <pr>(m<icr/n"<icr/*m<imac/zd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>minimizing</conjf> <pr>(m<icr/n"<icr/*m<imac/*z<icr/ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To reduce to the smallest part or proportion possible; to reduce to a minimum.</def>  <rj><au>Bentham.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To represent, to oneself or others, as of no importance or minimal importance or effect; to belittle or disarage.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>minimized</ent><br/
<hw>minimized</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Reduced to the smallest possible size or amount or degree.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minimum</ent><br/
<hw>Min"i*mum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Minima</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., fr. <ets>minimus</ets>. See <er>Minim</er>.]</ety> <def>The least quantity assignable, admissible, or possible, in a given case; hence, a thing of small consequence; -- opposed to <ant>maximum</ant>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Minimum thermometer</b></col>, <cd>a thermometer for recording the lowest temperature since its last adjustment.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minimus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Min"i*mus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Minimi</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. See <er>Minim</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A being of the smallest size.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The little finger; the fifth digit, or that corresponding to it, in either the manus or pes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>de minimis</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>de minimus</b></col></mcol> <pos>a.</pos><cd>of trifling consequence or importance; too insignificant to be worthy of concern; -- a reference to the phrase <cref>de minimis non curat lex</cref>.</cd> -- <col><b>de minimis non curat lex</b></col> <ety>[Latin]</ety> <cd>The law does not concern itself with trifles; -- a principle of law, that even if a technical violation of a law appears to exist according to the letter of the law, if the effect is too small to be of consequence, the violation of the law will not be considered as a sufficient cause of action, whether in civil or criminal proceedings.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mining</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mine</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <def>The act or business of making mines or of working them.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mining</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to mines; <as>as, <ex>mining</ex> engineer; <ex>mining</ex> machinery; a <ex>mining</ex> region.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mining engineering</b></col>. <cd>See the Note under <er>Engineering</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minion</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Minimum.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Burton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minion</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ion</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mignon</ets>, fr. OHG. <ets>minni</ets> love, G. <ets>minne</ets>; akin to E. <ets>mind</ets>. See <er>Mind</er>, and cf. <er>Mignonette</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A loved one; one highly esteemed and favored; -- in a good sense.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God's disciple and his dearest <qex>minion</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sylvester.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Is this the Athenian <qex>minion</qex> whom the world<br/
Voiced so regardfully?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An obsequious or servile dependent or agent of another; a fawning favorite.</def>  <rj><au>Sir J. Davies.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Go, rate thy <qex>minions</qex>, proud, insulting boy!</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>A small kind of type, in size between brevier and nonpareil.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><hand/ <miniontype>This line is printed in <it>minion</it> type.</miniontype><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An ancient form of ordnance, the caliber of which was about three inches.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minion</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ion</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See 2d <er>Minion</er>.]</ety> <def>Fine; trim; dainty.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/Their . . . <xex>minion</xex> dancing.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Fryth.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minionette</ent><br/
<hw>Min`ion*ette"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Small; delicate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/His <xex>minionette</xex> face.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Walpole.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minionette</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ion*ette</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>A size of type between nonpareil and minion; -- used in ornamental borders, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minioning</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ion*ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Kind treatment.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minionize</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ion*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To flavor.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minionly</ent><br/
<ent>Minionlike</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Min"ion*like`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Min"ion*ly</hw>, }</mhw> <pos>a. & adv.</pos> <def>Like a minion; daintily.</def>  <rj><au>Camden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minionship</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ion*ship</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>State of being a minion.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minious</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>minium</ets> red lead.]</ety> <def>Of the color of red or vermilion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minish</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ish</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>menusen</ets>, F. <ets>menuiser</ets> to make small, cut small, fr. (assumed) LL. <ets>minutiare</ets>, for <ets>minutare</ets>, fr. L. <ets>minutus</ets> small. See <er>Minute</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and cf. <er>Diminish</er>, <er>Minge</er>.]</ety> <def>To diminish; to lessen.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The living of poor men thereby <qex>minished</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Latimer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minishment</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ish*ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of diminishing, or the state of being diminished; diminution.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minister</ent><br/
<hw>Min"is*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>ministre</ets>, F. <ets>ministre</ets>, fr. L. <ets>minister</ets>, orig. a double comparative from the root of <ets>minor</ets> less, and hence meaning, an inferior, a servant. See 1st <er>Minor</er>, and cf. <er>Master</er>, <er>Minstrel</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A servant; a subordinate; an officer or assistant of inferior rank; hence, an agent, an instrument.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Moses rose up, and his <qex>minister</qex> Joshua.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xxiv. 13.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I chose<br/
Camillo for the <qex>minister</qex>, to poison<br/
My friend Polixenes.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An officer of justice.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I cry out the on the <qex>ministres</qex>, quod he,<br/
That shoulde keep and rule this cit<eacute/.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One to whom the sovereign or executive head of a government intrusts the management of affairs of state, or some department of such affairs.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Ministers</qex> to kings, whose eyes, ears, and hands they are, must be answerable to God and man.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A representative of a government, sent to the court, or seat of government, of a foreign nation to transact diplomatic business.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Ambassadors are classed (in the diplomatic sense) in the first rank of public ministers, ministers plenipotentiary in the second. <ldquo/The United States diplomatic service employs two classes of ministers, -- ministers plenipotentiary and ministers resident.<rdquo/</note>  <rj><au>Abbott.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>One who serves at the altar; one who performs sacerdotal duties; the pastor of a church duly authorized or licensed to preach the gospel and administer the sacraments.</def>  <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Delegate; official; ambassador; clergyman; parson; priest.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minister</ent><br/
<hw>Min"is*ter</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Ministered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Ministering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>ministren</ets>, OF. <ets>ministrer</ets>, fr. L. <ets>ministrare</ets>. See <er>Minister</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To furnish or apply; to afford; to supply; to administer.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He that <qex>ministereth</qex> seed to the sower.</q> <rj><qau>2 Cor. ix. 10.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We <qex>minister</qex> to God reason to suspect us.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minister</ent><br/
<hw>Min"is*ter</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To act as a servant, attendant, or agent; to attend and serve; to perform service in any office, sacred or secular.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Son of man came not to be <qex>ministered</qex> unto, but to <qex>minister</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. xx. 28.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To supply or to things needful; esp., to supply consolation or remedies; <as>as, to <ex>minister</ex> to the sick</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Matt. xxv. 44.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Canst thou not <qex>minister</qex> to a mind diseased?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ministerial</ent><br/
<hw>Min`is*te"ri*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>ministerialis</ets>: cf. F. <ets>minist<eacute/riel</ets>. See <er>Minister</er>, and cf. <er>Minstrel</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to ministry or service; serving; attendant.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Enlightening spirits and <qex>ministerial</qex> flames.</q> <rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the office of a minister or to the ministry as a body, whether civil or sacerdotal.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Ministerial</xex> offices.<rdquo/ <au>Bacon.</au> <ldquo/A <xex>ministerial</xex> measure.<rdquo/ <au>Junius.</au> <ldquo/<xex>Ministerial</xex> garments.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Tending to advance or promote; contributive.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Ministerial</xex> to intellectual culture.<rdquo/  <rj><au>De Quincey.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The ministerial benches</b></col>, <cd>the benches in the House of Commons occupied by members of the cabinet and their supporters; -- also, the persons occupying them.</cd> <ldquo/Very solid and very brilliant talents distinguish <xex>the ministerial benches</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Burke.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Official; priestly; sacerdotal; ecclesiastical.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ministerialist</ent><br/
<hw>Min`is*te"ri*al*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A supporter of the ministers, or the party in power.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ministerially</ent><br/
<hw>Min`is*te"ri*al*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a ministerial manner; in the character or capacity of a minister.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ministery</ent><br/
<hw>Min"is*ter*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Ministry</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ministracy</ent><br/
<hw>Min"is*tra*cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Ministration.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ministral</ent><br/
<hw>Min"is*tral</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Ministerial.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 927 --></p>

<p><ent>Ministrant</ent><br/
<hw>Min"is*trant</hw> <pr>(m<icr/n"<icr/s*tr<ait/nt)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>ministrans</ets>, <ets>-antis</ets>, of <ets>ministrare</ets> to minister.]</ety> <def>Performing service as a minister; attendant on service; acting under command; subordinate.</def> <ldquo/Princedoms and dominations <xex>ministrant</xex>.<rdquo/ <au>Milton.</au> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>One who ministers.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ministration</ent><br/
<hw>Min`is*tra"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>ministratio</ets>, fr. <ets>ministrare</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act of ministering; service; ministry.</def> <ldquo/The days of his <xex>ministration</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Luke i. 23.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ministrative</ent><br/
<hw>Min"is*tra*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Serving to aid; ministering.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ministress</ent><br/
<hw>Min"is*tress</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. L. <ets>ministrix</ets>.]</ety> <def>A woman who ministers.</def>  <rj><au>Akenside.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ministry</ent><br/
<hw>Min"is*try</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> Ministries <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>ministerium</ets>. See <er>Minister</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, and cf. <er>Mystery</er> a trade.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of ministering; ministration; service.</def> <ldquo/With tender <xex>ministry</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Thomson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>Agency; instrumentality.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The ordinary <qex>ministry</qex> of second causes.</q> <rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wicked <qex>ministry</qex> of arms.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The office, duties, or functions of a minister, servant, or agent; ecclesiastical, executive, or ambassadorial function or profession.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The body of ministers of state; also, the clergy, as a body.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Administration; rule; term in power; <as>as, the <ex>ministry</ex> of Pitt</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ministryship</ent><br/
<hw>Min"is*try*ship</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The office of a minister.</def>  <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>minium</ent><br/
<hw>min"i*um</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>minium</ets>, an Iberian word, the Romans getting all their cinnabar from Spain; cf. Basque <ets>armine<aacute/</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A heavy, brilliant red pigment, consisting of an oxide of lead, <chform>Pb3O4</chform>, obtained by exposing lead or massicot to a gentle and continued heat in the air.  It is used as a cement, as a paint, and in the manufacture of flint glass.  Called also <altname>red lead</altname>, <altname>lead tetroxide</altname>, <altname>lead orthoplumbate</altname>, <altname>mineral orange</altname>, <altname>mineral red</altname>, <altname>Paris red</altname>, <altname>Saturn red</altname>, and less definitively, <altname>lead oxide</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miniver</ent><br/
<hw>Min"i*ver</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Meniver</er>.]</ety> <def>A fur esteemed in the Middle Ages as a part of costume.  It is uncertain whether it was the fur of one animal only or of different animals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minivet</ent><br/
<hw>Min"i*vet</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A singing bird of India of the family <fam>Campephagidae</fam>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mink</ent><br/
<hw>Mink</hw> <pr>(m<icr/<nsm/k)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. 2d <er>Minx</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A carnivorous mammal of the genus <gen>Mustela</gen> (foremrly <gen>Putorius</gen>), allied to the weasel.  The European mink is <spn>Mustela lutreola</spn>.  The common American mink (<spn>Mustela vison</spn>) varies from yellowish brown to black.  Its fur is highly valued.  Called also <altname>minx</altname>, <altname>nurik</altname>, and <altname>vison</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The fur of the mink{1}.    Together with sable, it is one of the most expensive furs not taken from endangerd species.  When the fur is taken from animals grown on a farm, it called <stype>ranch mink</stype>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minnesinger</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ne*sing`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G., fr. <ets>minne</ets> love + <ets>singen</ets> to sing.]</ety> <def>A love-singer; specifically, one of a class of German poets and musicians who flourished from about the middle of the twelfth to the middle of the fourteenth century.  They were chiefly of noble birth, and made love and beauty the subjects of their verses.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minnesotan</ent><br/
<hw>Minnesotan</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A resident of Minnesota.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>minniebush</ent><br/
<hw>minniebush</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A low shrub (<spn>Menziesia pilosa</spn>) of the eastern U. S. with downy twigs.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> minnie bush, <spn>Menziesia pilosa</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minnow</ent><br/
<hw>Min"now</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>menow</ets>, cf. AS. <ets>myne</ets>; also OE. <ets>menuse</ets>, OF. <ets>menuise</ets> small fish; akin to E. <ets>minish</ets>, <ets>minute</ets>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also <asp>minow</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A small European fresh-water cyprinoid fish (<spn>Phoxinus laevis</spn>, formerly <spn>Leuciscus phoxinus</spn>); sometimes applied also to the young of larger kinds; -- called also <altname>minim</altname> and <altname>minny</altname>. The name is also applied to several allied American species, of the genera <gen>Phoxinus</gen>, <gen>Notropis</gen>, or <gen>Minnilus</gen>, and <gen>Rhinichthys</gen>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any of numerous small American cyprinodont fishes of the genus <gen>Fundulus</gen>, and related genera. They live both in fresh and in salt water. Called also <altname>killifish</altname>, <altname>minny</altname>, and <altname>mummichog</altname>.</def><-- see <er>mummichog</er> --><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minny</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ny</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A minnow.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mino bird</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"no bird"</hw> <pr>(m<imac/"n<osl/ b<etil/rd)</pr>. <ety>[Hind. <ets>main<amac/</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An Asiatic bird (<spn>Gracula musica</spn>), allied to the starlings.  It is black, with a white spot on the wings, and a pair of flat yellow wattles on the head.  It is often tamed and taught to pronounce words.  It is one of the birds called <isa>mynah bird</isa>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>minor</ent><br/
<hw>mi"nor</hw> <pr>(m<imac/"n<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L., a comparative with no positive; akin to AS. <ets>min</ets> small, G. <ets>minder</ets> less, OHG. <ets>minniro</ets>, a., <ets>min</ets>, adv., Icel. <ets>minni</ets>, a., <ets>minnr</ets>, adv., Goth. <ets>minniza</ets>, a., <ets>mins</ets>, adv., Ir. & Gael. <ets>min</ets> small, tender, L. <ets>minuere</ets> to lessen, Gr. <grk>miny`qein</grk>, Skr. <ets>mi</ets> to damage.  Cf. <er>Minish</er>, <er>Minister</er>, <er>Minus</er>, <er>Minute</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Inferior in bulk, degree, importance, etc.; less; smaller; of little account; <as>as, <ex>minor</ex> divisions of a body</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Less by a semitone in interval or difference of pitch; <as>as, a <ex>minor</ex> third</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Asia Minor</b></col> <fld>(Geog.)</fld>, <cd>the Lesser Asia; that part of Asia which lies between the Euxine, or Black Sea, on the north, and the Mediterranean on the south.</cd> -- <col><b>Minor mode</b></col> <fld>(Mus.)</fld>, <cd>that mode, or scale, in which the third and sixth are minor, -- much used for mournful and solemn subjects.</cd> -- <col><b>Minor orders</b></col> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld>, <cd>the rank of persons employed in ecclesiastical offices who are not in holy orders, as doorkeepers, acolytes, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Minor scale</b></col> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <cd>The form of the minor scale is various.  The strictly correct form has the third and sixth minor, with a semitone between the seventh and eighth, which involves an augmented second interval, or three semitones, between the sixth and seventh, as, <supr>6/F</supr>, <supr>7/G<sharp/</supr>, <supr>8/A</supr>.  But, for melodic purposes, both the sixth and the seventh are sometimes made major in the ascending, and minor in the descending, scale, thus: --<br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><illust><-- Comm: an illustration of a bar with ascending and descending notes on a minor scale --></illust><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>See <er>Major</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Minor term of a syllogism</b></col> <fld>(Logic)</fld>, <cd>the subject of the conclusion.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minor</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"nor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A person of either sex who has not attained the age at which full civil rights are accorded; an infant; in England and the United States, one under twenty-one years of age.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ In hereditary monarchies, the minority of a sovereign ends at an earlier age than of a subject.  The minority of a sovereign of Great Britain ends upon the completion of the eighteenth year of his age.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Logic)</fld> <def>The minor term, that is, the subject of the conclusion; also, the minor premise, that is, that premise which contains the minor term; in hypothetical syllogisms, the categorical premise.  It is the second proposition of a regular syllogism, as in the following: Every act of injustice partakes of meanness; to take money from another by gaming is an act of injustice; therefore, the taking of money from another by gaming partakes of meanness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A Minorite; a Franciscan friar.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minorat</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mi`no*rat"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G. Cf. <er>Minor</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A custom or right, analogous to borough-English in England, formerly existing in various parts of Europe, and surviving in parts of Germany and Austria, by which certain entailed estates, as a homestead and adjacent land, descend to the youngest male heir.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minorate</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"nor*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>minoratus</ets>; p. p. of <ets>minorare</ets> to diminish, fr. <ets>minor</ets>, a. See 1st <er>Minor</er>.]</ety> <def>To diminish.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minoration</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`nor*a"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>minoratio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>minoration</ets>.]</ety> <def>A diminution.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minoress</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"nor*ess</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <cref>Franciscan Nuns</cref>, under <er>Franciscan</er>, <pos>a.</pos></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minorite</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"nor*ite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>minor</ets> less.  Cf. 2d <er>Minor</er>, 3.]</ety> <def>A Franciscan friar.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minority</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*nor"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Minorities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>minorit<eacute/</ets>. See <er>Minor</er>, <pos>a. & n.</pos>]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The state of being a minor, or under age.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>State of being less or small.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The smaller number; -- opposed to <ant>majority</ant>; <as>as, the <ex>minority</ex> must be ruled by the majority</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Those members of a legislature that belong to the political party which is in the minority in that institution; <as>as, the bill will pass even if the <ex>minority</ex> are strongly opposed</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>minor league</ent><br/
<hw>minor league</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>Sport)</fld> <def>A league of professional sports teams less proficient than a <contr>major leagues</contr>.  Players in the minor leagues generally are paid less than those in the major leagues, and their games attract less atention.</def>  <note>Certain minor league sports teams are often owned by those owning a major league club, and the minor league clubs are used to provide practise and opportunity for evaluation for candidates who wish to play in the major leagues.</note><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> minor league.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>minor-league</ent><br/
<hw>minor-league</hw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to a minor league.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of mediocre talent or poor accomplishment; unimportant; -- of people; <as>as, a <ex>minor-league</ex> physicist</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>minors</ent><br/
<hw>minors</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The <er>minor leagues</er>, those leagues of professional sports teams less proficient than the <contr>majors</contr>, or <contr>major leagues</contr>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> minor league.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minos</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"nos</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/.]</ety> <fld>(Class. Myth.)</fld> <def>A king and lawgiver of Crete, fabled to be the son of <persfn>Jupiter</persfn> and <persfn>Europa</persfn>.  After death he was made a judge in the Lower Regions.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minotaur</ent><br/
<hw>Min"o*taur</hw> <pr>(m<icr/n"<osl/*t<add/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>Minotaurus</ets>, Gr. <grk>Minw`tayros</grk>; <grk>Mi`nos</grk>, the husband of <persfn>Pasiphae</persfn> + <grk>tay^ros</grk> a bull, the <persfn>Minotaur</persfn> being the offspring of <persfn>Pasiphae</persfn> and a bull: cf. F. <ets>minotaure</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Class. Myth.)</fld> <def>A fabled monster, half man and half bull, confined in the labyrinth constructed by <persfn>Daedalus</persfn> in Crete.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minow</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ow</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Minnow</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minster</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ster</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>mynster</ets>, fr. L. <ets>monasterium</ets>. See <er>Monastery</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A church of a monastery.  The name is often retained and applied to the church after the monastery has ceased to exist (<as>as Beverly <ex>Minster</ex>, Southwell <ex>Minster</ex>, etc.</as>), and is also improperly used for any large church.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Minster house</b></col>, <cd>the official house in which the canons of a cathedral live in common or in rotation.</cd>  <rj><au>Shipley.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minstrel</ent><br/
<hw>Min"strel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>minstrel</ets>, <ets>menestral</ets>, OF. <ets>menestrel</ets>, fr. LL. <ets>ministerialis</ets> servant, workman (cf. <ets>ministrellus</ets> harpist), fr. L. <ets>ministerium</ets> service. See <er>Ministry</er>, and cf. <er>Ministerial</er>.]</ety> <def>In the Middle Ages, one of an order of men who subsisted by the arts of poetry and music, and sang verses to the accompaniment of a harp or other instrument; in modern times, a poet; a bard; a singer and harper; a musician.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minstrelsy</ent><br/
<hw>Min"strel*sy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The arts and occupation of minstrels; the singing and playing of a minstrel.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Musical instruments.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A collective body of minstrels, or musicians; also, a collective body of minstrels' songs.</def> <au>Chaucer.</au> <ldquo/The <xex>minstrelsy</xex> of heaven.<rdquo/ <au>Milton.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mint</ent><br/
<hw>Mint</hw> <pr>(m<icr/nt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>minte</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mentha</ets>, Gr. <grk>mi`nqa</grk>, <grk>mi`nqh</grk>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The name of several aromatic labiate plants, mostly of the genus <gen>Mentha</gen>, yielding odoriferous essential oils by distillation. See <er>Mentha</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <styp><col><b>Corn mint</b></col></styp> is <spn>Mentha arvensis</spn>. -- <styp><col><b>Horsemint</b></col></styp> is <spn>Mentha sylvestris</spn>, and in the United States <spn>Monarda punctata</spn>, which differs from the true mints in several respects. -- <styp><col><b>Mountain mint</b></col></styp> is any species of the related genus <gen>Pycnanthemum</gen>, common in North America. -- <styp><col><b>Peppermint</b></col></styp> is <spn>Mentha piperita</spn>. -- <styp><col><b>Spearmint</b></col></styp> is <spn>Mentha viridis</spn>. -- <styp><col><b>Water mint</b></col></styp> is <spn>Mentha aquatica</spn>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mint camphor</b></col>. <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Menthol</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mint julep</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Julep</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mint sauce</b></col>, <cd>a sauce flavored with spearmint, for meats.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mint</ent><br/
<hw>Mint</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>mynet</ets> money, coin, fr. L. <ets>moneta</ets> the mint, coined money, fr. <ets>Moneta</ets>, a surname of Juno, in whose at Rome money was coined; akin to <ets>monere</ets> to warn, admonish, AS. <ets>manian</ets>, and to E. <ets>mind</ets>. See <er>Mind</er>, and cf. <er>Money</er>, <er>Monition</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A place where money is coined by public authority.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>Any place regarded as a source of unlimited supply; the supply itself.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>mint</qex> of phrases in his brain.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <def>A large quantity of money; <as>as, to make a <ex>mint</ex> in stock trading</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mint</ent><br/
<hw>Mint</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Minted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Minting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>mynetian</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To make by stamping, as money; to coin; to make and stamp into money.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To invent; to forge; to fabricate; to fashion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Titles . . . of such natures as may be easily <qex>minted</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Minting mill</b></col>, <cd>a coining press.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mint</ent><br/
<hw>mint</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Like new; in brand-new condition; unworn, as a coin recently made at a mint{1}; <as>as, he had a '53 Cadillac in <ex>mint</ex> condition</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <fld>(Numismatics)</fld> <def>Uncirculated; in the same condition as when it was freshly coined at the mint{1}.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mintage</ent><br/
<hw>Mint"age</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The coin, or other production, made in a mint.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Stamped in clay, a heavenly <qex>mintage</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sterling.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The duty paid to the mint for coining.  At one time people could bring precious metals, as gold or silver, to a mint and receive in return coins of the same value, minus the commision charged by the mint, which was the <ex>mintage</ex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The act or process of minting{1}; <as>as, a coin of recent <ex>mintage</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The quantity of coins of a specific type made by the mint; <as>as, coins of low <ex>mintage</ex> tend to be more valuable as collectors' items</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minter</ent><br/
<hw>Mint"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who mints.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mintman</ent><br/
<hw>Mint"man</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mintmen</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>One skilled in coining, or in coins; a coiner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mint-master</ent><br/
<hw>Mint"-mas`ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The master or superintendent of a mint. Also used figuratively.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mint sauce</ent><br/
<hw>Mint sauce</hw>. <sn>1.</sn> <def>A sauce of vinegar and sugar flavored with spearmint leaves.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>Money.</def> <mark>[Slang, Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mint state</ent><br/
<hw>mint state</hw>. <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Numismatics)</fld> <def>A numerical grade indicating the degree of perfection of the condition of a coin which is classified as uncirculated, ranging from 70 for a coin in perfect condition to 60 for a coin which is uncirculated but may have a weak strike, or numerous small scratches from being handled in mint bags; usually used as the abbreviation <abbr>MS</abbr>; <as>as, an <ex>MS</ex>-67 Morgan Dollar</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>minuend</ent><br/
<hw>min"u*end</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>minuendus</ets> to be diminished, fr. <ets>minuere</ets> to lessen, diminish. See <er>Minish</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Arith.)</fld> <def>In the process of subtraction{2}, the number from which another number (the <corr>subtrahend</corr>) is to be subtracted, to find the <corr>difference</corr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minuet</ent><br/
<hw>Min"u*et</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>menu</ets> small, L. <ets>minutus</ets> small. So called on account of the short steps of the dance. See 4th <er>Minute</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A slow graceful dance consisting of a coupee, a high step, and a balance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A tune or air to regulate the movements of the dance so called; a movement in suites, sonatas, symphonies, etc., having the dance form, and commonly in 3-4, sometimes 3-8, measure.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minum</ent><br/
<hw>Min"um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See 2d <er>Minion</er>, <er>Minum</er>, 6.]</ety> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A small kind of printing type; minion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A minim.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minus</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"nus</hw> <pr>(m<imac/"n<ucr/s)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. See <er>Minor</er>, and cf. <er>Mis-</er> pref. from the French.]</ety> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>Less; requiring to be subtracted; negative; <as>as, a <ex>minus</ex> quantity</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Minus sign</b></col> <fld>(Math.)</fld>, <cd>the sign [-] denoting <xex>minus</xex>, or <xex>less</xex>, prefixed to negative quantities, or quantities to be subtracted. See <cref>Negative sign</cref>, under <er>Negative</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>minus</ent><br/
<hw>mi"nus</hw> <pr>(m<imac/"n<ucr/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>minuses</plw> <pr>(m<imac/"n<ucr/s*<esl/z)</pr>.</plu> <def>A factor counted as a disadvantage; a loss or potential loss in a situation or plan; <as>as, he added up all the pluses and <ex>minuses</ex> and decided not to do it; as, the lack of money is a big <ex>minus</ex> in an election campaign</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>minuscular</ent><br/
<hw>minuscular</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>of or relating to minuscule script, a small cursive script developed from uncial, and used in the 7th to 9th centuries.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> minuscule.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minuscule</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*nus"cule</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>minusculus</ets> rather small, fr. <ets>minus</ets> less: cf. F. <ets>minuscule</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Any very small, minute object.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small Roman letter which is neither capital nor uncial; a manuscript written in such letters.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>minuscule</ent><br/
<hw>minuscule</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or relating to a minuscule{2} or of a script written in minuscules{2}; of the size and style of minuscules{2}; written in minuscules{2}; minuscular.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><q>These <qex>minuscule</qex> letters are cursive forms of the earlier uncials.</q> <rj><qau>I. Taylor (The Alphabet).</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minutary</ent><br/
<hw>Min"u*ta*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to, or consisting of, minutes.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minute</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ute</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>minuta</ets> a small portion, small coin, fr. L. <ets>minutus</ets> small: cf. F. <ets>minute</ets>. See 4th <er>Minute</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The sixtieth part of an hour; sixty seconds. (Abbrev. <abbr>m.</abbr> or <abbr>min.</abbr>; <as>as, 4 h. 30 <ex>m.</ex></as>)</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Four <qex>minutes</qex>, that is to say, <qex>minutes</qex> of an hour.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The sixtieth part of a degree; sixty seconds (Marked thus (<prime/); <as>as, 10<deg/ 20<prime/</as>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A nautical or a geographic mile.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A coin; a half farthing.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Wyclif (Mark xii. 42)</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A very small part of anything, or anything very small; a jot; a tittle.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Minutes</qex> and circumstances of his passion.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A point of time; a moment.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I go this <qex>minute</qex> to attend the king.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>The memorandum; a record; a note to preserve the memory of anything; <as>as, to take <ex>minutes</ex> of a contract; to take <ex>minutes</ex> of a conversation or debate; to read the <ex>minutes</ex> of the last meeting.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A fixed part of a module. See <er>Module</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Different writers take as the minute one twelfth, one eighteenth, one thirtieth, or one sixtieth part of the module.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minute</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ute</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to a minute or minutes; occurring at or marking successive minutes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Minute bell</b></col>, <cd>a bell tolled at intervals of a minute, as to give notice of a death or a funeral.</cd> -- <col><b>Minute book</b></col>, <cd>a book in which written minutes are entered.</cd> -- <col><b>Minute glass</b></col>, <cd>a glass measuring a minute or minutes by the running of sand.</cd> -- <col><b>Minute gun</b></col>, <cd>a discharge of a cannon repeated every minute as a sign of distress or mourning.</cd> -- <col><b>Minute hand</b></col>, <cd>the long hand of a watch or clock, which makes the circuit of the dial in an hour, and marks the minutes.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minute</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ute</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <er>Minuted</er>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <er>Minuting</er>.]</ety> <def>To set down a short sketch or note of; to jot down; to make a minute or a brief summary of.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Empress of Russia, with her own hand, <qex>minuted</qex> an edict for universal tolerance.</q> <rj><qau>Bancroft.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minute</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*nute"</hw> <pr>(m<imac/*n<umac/t" <it>or</it> m<icr/*n<umac/t")</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>minutus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>minuere</ets> to lessen. See <er>Minish</er>, <er>Minor</er>, and cf. <er>Menu</er>, <er>Minuet</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Very small; little; tiny; fine; slight; slender; inconsiderable; <as>as, <ex>minute</ex> details</as>.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Minute</xex> drops.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Attentive to small things; paying attention to details; critical; particular; precise; <as>as, a <ex>minute</ex> observer; <ex>minute</ex> observation.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Little; diminutive; fine; critical; exact; circumstantial; particular; detailed.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Minute</er>, <er>Circumstantial</er>, <er>Particular</er>.  A <xex>circumstantial</xex> account embraces all the leading events; a <xex>particular</xex> account includes each event and movement, though of but little importance; a <xex>minute</xex> account goes further still, and omits nothing as to person, time, place, adjuncts, etc.</usage><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minute-jack</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*nute"-jack`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A figure which strikes the hour on the bell of some fanciful clocks; -- called also <altname>jack of the clock house</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A timeserver; an inconstant person.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minutely</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*nute"ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[From 4th <er>Minute</er>.]</ety> <def>In a minute manner; with minuteness; exactly; nicely.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minutely</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ute*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From 1st <er>Minute</er>.]</ety> <def>Happening every minute; continuing; unceasing.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Throwing themselves absolutely upon God's <qex>minutely</qex> providence.</q> <rj><qau>Hammond.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minutely</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ute*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>At intervals of a minute; very often and regularly.</def>  <rj><au>J. Philips.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Minutely</qex> proclaimed in thunder from heaven.</q> <rj><qau>Hammond.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minuteman</ent><br/
<hw>Min"ute*man</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Minutemen</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>A militiaman who was to be ready to march at a moment's notice; -- a term used in the American Revolution.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minuteness</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*nute"ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality of being minute.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minutia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mi*nu"ti*a</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Minutiae</plw> <pr>(-<emac/)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., fr. <ets>minutus</ets> small, minute. See 4th <er>Minute</er>.]</ety> <def>A minute particular; a small or minor detail; -- used chiefly in the plural.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minx</ent><br/
<hw>Minx</hw> <pr>(m<icr/<nsm/ks)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. of Low German origin; cf. LG. <ets>minsk</ets> wench, jade, hussy, D. <ets>mensch</ets>; prop. the same word as D. & G. <ets>mensch</ets> man, human being, OHG. <ets>mennisco</ets>, AS. <ets>mennisc</ets>, fr. <ets>man</ets>. See <er>Man</er>.]</ety>  <sn>1.</sn> <def>A pert or a wanton girl.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A she puppy; a pet dog.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Udall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minx</ent><br/
<hw>Minx</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mink</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The mink; -- called also <cref>minx otter</cref>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 928 --></p>

<p><ent>Miny</ent><br/
<hw>Min"y</hw> <pr>(m<imac/n"<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Abounding with mines; like a mine.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Miny</xex> caverns.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Thomson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minyan</ent><br/
<hw>Min*yan"</hw> <pr>(m<esl/n*y<aum/n")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Jewish Relig.)</fld> <def>A quorum, or number necessary, for conducting public worship.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miocene</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"o*cene</hw> <pr>(m<imac/"<osl/*s<emac/n)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mei`wn</grk> less + <grk>kaino`s</grk> new, fresh, recent.]</ety> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the middle division of the Tertiary.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>The Miocene period. See <cref>Chart</cref> of <er>Geology</er>.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miohippus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mi`o*hip"pus</hw> <pr>(m<imac/`<osl/*h<icr/p"p<ucr/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mei`wn</grk> less + <grk>"ippo`s</grk> horse.]</ety> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>An extinct Miocene mammal of the Horse family, closely related to the genus <gen>Anhithecrium</gen>, and having three usable hoofs on each foot.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miquelet</ent><br/
<hw>Miq"ue*let</hw> <pr>(m<icr/k"w<esl/*l<ecr/t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>miquelete</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>An irregular or partisan soldier; a bandit.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mir</ent><br/
<hw>Mir</hw> <pr>(m<emac/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Russ. <ets>mir'</ets>.]</ety> <def>A Russian village community.</def>  <rj><au>D. M. Wallace.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mir</ent><br/
<hw>Mir</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Per. <ets>m<imac/r</ets>.]</ety> <def>Same as <er>Emir</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mira</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mi"ra</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., from L. <ets>mirus</ets> wonderful.]</ety> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>A remarkable variable star in the constellation Cetus (<altname><omicron/ Ceti</altname>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mirabilary</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*rab"i*la*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mirabilaries</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>One who, or a work which, narrates wonderful things; one who writes of wonders.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mirabile dictu</ent><br/
<hw>mi*ra"bi*le dic"tu</hw> <pr>(m<esl/*r<aum/"b<icr/*l<asl/ d<icr/k"t<oomac/)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[Latin.]</ety> <def>Remarkably; strange to say; marvelous to relate.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mirabilis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mi*rab"i*lis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[L., wonderful.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of plants. See <er>Four-o'clock</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mirabilite</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*rab"i*lite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Native sodium sulphate; Glauber's salt.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mirable</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"ra*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mirabilis</ets>, fr. <ets>mirari</ets> to wonder: cf. OF. <ets>mirable</ets>. See <er>Marvel</er>.]</ety> <def>Wonderful; admirable.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miracle</ent><br/
<hw>Mir"a*cle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>miraculum</ets>, fr. <ets>mirari</ets> to wonder. See <er>Marvel</er>, and cf. <er>Mirror</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A wonder or wonderful thing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That <qex>miracle</qex> and queen of genus.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <def>An event or effect contrary to the established constitution and course of things, or a deviation from the known laws of nature; a supernatural event, or one transcending the ordinary laws by which the universe is governed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They considered not the <qex>miracle</qex> of the loaves.</q> <rj><qau>Mark vi. 52.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A miracle play.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A story or legend abounding in miracles.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When said was all this <qex>miracle</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Miracle monger</b></col>, <cd>an impostor who pretends to work miracles.</cd> -- <col><b>Miracle play</b></col>, <cd>one of the old dramatic entertainments founded on legends of saints and martyrs or (see 2d <er>Mystery</er>, 2) on events related in the Bible.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miracle</ent><br/
<hw>Mir"a*cle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make wonderful.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miraculize</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*rac"u*lize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cause to seem to be a miracle.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shaftesbury.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miraculous</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*rac"u*lous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>miraculeux</ets>. See <er>Miracle</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Of the nature of a miracle; performed by supernatural power; effected by the direct agency of almighty power, and not by natural causes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Supernatural; wonderful.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Wonder-working.</def> <ldquo/The <xex>miraculous</xex> harp.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Mi*rac"u*lous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mi*rac"u*lous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mirador</ent><br/
<hw>Mir`a*dor"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp., fr. <ets>mirar</ets> to behold, view. See <er>Mirror</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Belvedere</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mirage</ent><br/
<hw>Mi`rage"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>mirer</ets> to look at carefully, to aim, <ets>se mirer</ets> to look at one's self in a glass, to reflect, to be reflected, LL. <ets>mirare</ets> to look at. See <er>Mirror</er>.]</ety> <def>An optical effect, sometimes seen on the ocean, but more frequently in deserts, due to total reflection of light at the surface common to two strata of air differently heated.  The reflected image is seen, commonly in an inverted position, while the real object may or may not be in sight.  When the surface is horizontal, and below the eye, the appearance is that of a sheet of water in which the object is seen reflected; when the reflecting surface is above the eye, the image is seen projected against the sky.  The <stype>fata Morgana</stype> and <stype>looming</stype> are species of <ex>mirage</ex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By the <qex>mirage</qex> uplifted the land floats vague in the ether,<br/
Ships and the shadows of ships hang in the motionless air.</q> <rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mirbane</ent><br/
<hw>Mir"bane</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Nitrobenzene</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mire</ent><br/
<hw>Mire</hw> <pr>(m<imac/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<imac/re</ets>, <ets>m<ymac/re</ets>; akin to D. <ets>mier</ets>, Icel. <ets>maurr</ets>, Dan. <ets>myre</ets>, Sw. <ets>myra</ets>; cf. also Ir. <ets>moirbh</ets>, Gr. <grk>my`rmhx</grk>.]</ety> <def>An ant.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <see>See <er>Pismire</er>.</see><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mire</ent><br/
<hw>Mire</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mire</ets>, <ets>myre</ets>; akin to Icel. <ets>m<?/rr</ets> swamp, Sw. <ets>myra</ets> marshy ground, and perh. to E. <ets>moss</ets>.]</ety> <def>Deep mud; wet, spongy earth.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He his rider from the lofty steed<br/
Would have cast down and trod in dirty <qex>mire</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mire crow</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the pewit, or laughing gull.</cd> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> -- <col><b>Mire drum</b></col>, <cd>the European bittern.</cd> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mire</ent><br/
<hw>Mire</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mired</conjf> <pr>(m<imac/rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Miring</conjf>.]</vmorph><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause or permit to stick fast in mire; to plunge or fix in mud; <as>as, to <ex>mire</ex> a horse or wagon</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>To stick or entangle; to involve in difficulties; -- often used in the passive or predicate form; <as>as, we got <ex>mired</ex> in bureaucratic red tape and it took years longer than planned</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To soil with mud or foul matter.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Smirched thus and <qex>mired</qex> with infamy.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mire</ent><br/
<hw>Mire</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To stick in mire.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mirifical</ent><br/
<ent>Mirific</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mi*rif"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mi*rif"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mirificus</ets>; <ets>mirus</ets> wonderful + <ets>-ficare</ets> (in comp.) to make. See <er>-fy</er>.]</ety> <def>Working wonders; wonderful.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mirificent</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*rif"i*cent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Wonderful.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miriness</ent><br/
<hw>Mir"i*ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality of being miry.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mirk</ent><br/
<hw>Mirk</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Murky</er>.]</ety> <def>Dark; gloomy; murky.</def>  <rj><au>Spenser. Mrs. Browning.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mirk</ent><br/
<hw>Mirk</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Darkness; gloom; murk.</def> <ldquo/In <xex>mirk</xex> and mire.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Longfellow.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mirksome</ent><br/
<hw>Mirk"some</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Dark; gloomy; murky.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark> <au>Spenser.</au> -- <wordforms><wf>Mirk"some*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos> <mark>[Archaic]</mark></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mirky</ent><br/
<hw>Mirk"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Dark; gloomy. See <er>Murky</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mirliton</ent><br/
<hw>Mir"li*ton</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A kind of musical toy into which one sings, hums, or speaks, producing a coarse, reedy sound.  It is also called a <altname>kazoo</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>Trilby singing <ldquo/Ben Bolt<rdquo/ into a <qex>mirliton</qex> was a thing to be remembered, whether one would or no!</q>  <rj><qau>Du Maurier.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>same as <er>chayote{2}</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mirounga</ent><br/
<hw>Mirounga</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus comprising the elephant seals.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Mirounga</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mirror</ent><br/
<hw>Mir"ror</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mirour</ets>, F. <ets>miroir</ets>, OF. also <ets>mireor</ets>, fr. (assumed) LL. <ets>miratorium</ets>, fr. <ets>mirare</ets> to look at, L. <ets>mirari</ets> to wonder. See <er>Marvel</er>, and cf. <er>Miracle</er>, <er>Mirador</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A looking-glass or a speculum; any glass or polished substance that forms images by the reflection of rays of light.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And in her hand she held a <qex>mirror</qex> bright,<br/
Wherein her face she often view<egrave/d fair.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which gives a true representation, or in which a true image may be seen; hence, a pattern; an exemplar.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She is <qex>mirour</qex> of all courtesy.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O goddess, heavenly bright,<br/
<qex>Mirror</qex> of grace and majesty divine.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Speculum</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mirror carp</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a domesticated variety of the carp, having only three or fur rows of very large scales side.</cd> -- <col><b>Mirror plate</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A flat glass mirror without a frame</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Flat glass used for making mirrors.</cd> -- <col><b>Mirror writing</b></col>, <cd>a manner or form of backward writing, making manuscript resembling in slant and order of letters the reflection of ordinary writing in a mirror. The substitution of this manner of writing for the common manner is a symptom of some kinds of nervous disease.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mirror</ent><br/
<hw>Mir"ror</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mirrored</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mirroring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To reflect, as in a mirror.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To copy or duplicate; to mimic or imitate; <as>as, the files at <org>Project Gutenberg</org> were <ex>mirrored</ex> on several other ftp sites around the world</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To have a close resemblance to; <as>as, his opinions often <ex>mirrored</ex> those of his wife</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mirrored</ent><br/
<hw>mirrored</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Reflected in or as if in a mirror.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mirrorlike</ent><br/
<hw>mirrorlike</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>capable of reflecting light like a mirror; flat and reflective; <as>as, the <ex>mirrorlike</ex> surface of the lake</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> specular.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mirrorscope</ent><br/
<hw>Mir"ror*scope</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>  <ety>[<ets>Mirror</ets> + <ets>-scope</ets>.]</ety> <def>See <er>Projector</er>, below.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mirth</ent><br/
<hw>Mirth</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mirthe</ets>, <ets>murthe</ets>, <ets>merthe</ets>, AS. <ets>myr<edh/</ets>, <ets>myrg<edh/</ets>, <ets>merh<edh/</ets>, <ets>mirh<edh/</ets>. See <er>Merry</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Merriment; gayety accompanied with laughter; jollity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then will I cause to cease . . . from the streets of Jerusalem, the voice of <qex>mirth</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. vii. 34.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which causes merriment.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Merriment; joyousness; gladness; fun; frolic; glee; hilarity; festivity; jollity. See <er>Gladness</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mirthful</ent><br/
<hw>Mirth"ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Full of mirth or merriment; merry; <as>as, <ex>mirthful</ex> children</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Indicating or inspiring mirth; <as>as, a <ex>mirthful</ex> face</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mirthful</qex>, comic shows.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Mirth"ful*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mirth"ful*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mirthless</ent><br/
<hw>Mirth"less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Without mirth.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mirth"less*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miry</ent><br/
<hw>Mir"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From 2d <er>Mire</er>.]</ety> <def>Abounding with deep mud; full of mire; muddy; <as>as, a <ex>miry</ex> road</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miryachit</ent><br/
<hw>Mir"ya*chit`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <altsp>[Written also <asp>myriachit</asp>.]</altsp> <ety>[Yakoot <ets>merj<aum/k</ets> epileptic, fr. <ets>imerek</ets> jerk, rage.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A nervous disease in which the patient involuntarily imitates the words or action of another.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mirza</ent><br/
<hw>Mir"za</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Per. <ets>m<imac/rz<amac/</ets>, abbrev. fr. <ets>m<imac/rz<amac/deh</ets> son of the prince; <ets>m<imac/r</ets> prince (Ar. <ets>am<imac/r</ets>, <ets>em<imac/r</ets>) + <ets>z<amac/deh</ets> son.]</ety> <def>The common title of honor in Persia, prefixed to the surname of an individual.  When appended to the surname, it signifies <sig>Prince</sig>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mis-</ent><br/
<hw>Mis-</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s-)</pr>. <ety>[In words of Teutonic origin, fr. AS. <ets>mis-</ets>; akin to D. <ets>mis-</ets>, G. <ets>miss-</ets>, OHG. <ets>missa-</ets>, <ets>missi-</ets>, Icel. & Dan. <ets>mis-</ets>, Sw. <ets>miss-</ets>, Goth. <ets>missa-</ets>; orig., a p. p. from the root of G. <ets>meiden</ets> to shun, OHG. <ets>m<imac/dan</ets>, AS. <ets>m<imac/<edh/an</ets> (<root/100.  Cf. <er>Miss</er> to fail of). In words from the French, fr. OF. <ets>mes-</ets>, F. <ets>m<eacute/-</ets>, <ets>mes-</ets>, fr. L. <ets>minus</ets> less (see <er>Minus</er>). In present usage these two prefixes are commonly confounded.]</ety> <def>A prefix used adjectively and adverbially in the sense of <sig>amiss</sig>, <sig>wrong</sig>, <sig>ill</sig>, <sig>wrongly</sig>, <sig>unsuitably</sig>; <as>as, <ex>mis</ex>deed, <ex>mis</ex>lead, <ex>mis</ex>chief, <ex>mis</ex>creant</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mis</ent><br/
<hw>Mis</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s)</pr>, <pos>a. & adv.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Amiss</er>.]</ety> <def>Wrong; amiss.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/To correcten that [which] is <xex>mis</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misacceptation</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*ac`cep*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong acceptation; understanding in a wrong sense.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misaccompt</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ac*compt"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To account or reckon wrongly.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misadjust</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ad*just"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To adjust wrongly of unsuitably; to throw out of adjustment.</def>  <rj><au>I. Taylor.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misadjustment</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ad*just"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong adjustment; unsuitable arrangement.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misadventure</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ad*ven"ture</hw> <pr>(?; 135)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mesaventure</ets>, F. <ets>m<eacute/saventure</ets>.]</ety> <def>Mischance; misfortune; ill luck; unlucky accident; ill adventure.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Homicide by misadventure</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>homicide which occurs when a man, doing a lawful act, without any intention of injury, unfortunately kills another; -- called also <altname>excusable homicide</altname>. See <er>Homicide</er>.</cd>  <rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Mischance; mishap; misfortune; disaster; calamity.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misadventured</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ad*ven"tured</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Unfortunate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misadventurous</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ad*ven"tur*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Unfortunate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misadvertence</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ad*vert"ence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Inadvertence.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misadvice</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ad*vice"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Bad advice.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misadvise</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ad*vise"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To give bad counsel to.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misadvised</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ad*vised"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Ill advised.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mis`ad*vis"ed*ly</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>misaffect</ent><br/
<hw>mis`af*fect"</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s`<acr/f*f<ecr/kt")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To dislike.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>misaffected</ent><br/
<hw>mis`af*fect"ed</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Ill disposed.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>misaffection</ent><br/
<hw>mis`af*fec"tion</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s`<acr/f*f<ecr/k"sh<ucr/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An evil or wrong affection; the state of being ill affected.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>misaffirm</ent><br/
<hw>mis`af*firm"</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s`<acr/f*f<etil/rm")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To affirm incorrectly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>misaimed</ent><br/
<hw>mis*aimed"</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s*<amac/md")</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Not rightly aimed.</def>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>misaligned</ent><br/
<hw>mis`a*ligned"</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s`<adot/*l<imac/nd")</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Aligned improperly; not correctly aligned.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>misalignment</ent><br/
<hw>mis`align"ment</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s`<adot/*l<imac/n"m<eit/nt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of aligning improperly or state of being improperly aligned.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>misallegation</ent><br/
<hw>mis*al`le*ga"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A erroneous statement or allegation.</def>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>misallege</ent><br/
<hw>mis`al*lege"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To state erroneously.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misalliance</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`al*li"ance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/salliance</ets>.]</ety> <def>A marriage with a person of inferior rank or social station; an improper alliance; a mesalliance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A Leigh had made a <qex>misalliance</qex>, and blushed<br/
A Howard should know it.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs. Browning.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misallied</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`al*lied"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Wrongly allied or associated.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misallotment</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`al*lot"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A wrong allotment.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misalter</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*al"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To alter wrongly; esp., to alter for the worse.</def>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>misandrist</ent><br/
<hw>mis"an*drist</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s"<acr/n*dr<icr/st)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>one who hates men.  Contrast <contr><er>misogynist</er></contr> and cf. <er>misandry</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> man-hater.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>misandry</ent><br/
<hw>mis"an*dry</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s"<acr/n*dr<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>misei^n</grk> to hate  + <grk>'andh`r</grk> a man.]</ety> <def>Hatred of men.  Contrast <contr><er>misogyny</er></contr> and cf. <er>misandrist</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> man-hating.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>misanthrope</ent><br/
<hw>mis"an*thrope</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s"<acr/n*thr<omac/p)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>misa`nqrwpos</grk>; <grk>misei^n</grk> to hate + <grk>'a`nqrwpos</grk> a man; cf. F. <ets>misanthrope</ets>.  Cf. <er>Miser</er>.]</ety> <def>A hater of mankind; a misanthropist.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misanthropical</ent><br/
<ent>Misanthropic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mis`an*throp"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mis`an*throp"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>misanthropique</ets>.]</ety> <def>Hating or disliking mankind.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misanthropist</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*an"thro*pist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A misanthrope.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misanthropos</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*an"thro*pos</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Misanthrope</er>.]</ety> <def>A misanthrope.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misanthropy</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*an"thro*py</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/: cf. F. <ets>misanthropie</ets>.]</ety> <def>Hatred of, or dislike to, mankind; -- opposed to <ant>philanthropy</ant>.</def>  <rj><au>Orrery.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misapplication</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*ap`pli*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A wrong application.</def>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misapply</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ap*ply"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Misapplied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Misapplying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To apply wrongly; to use for a wrong purpose; <as>as, to <ex>misapply</ex> a name or title; to <ex>misapply</ex> public money.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misappreciated</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ap*pre"ci*a`ted</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Improperly appreciated.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misapprehend</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*ap`pre*hend"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To take in a wrong sense; to misunderstand.</def>  <rj><au>Locke.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misapprehension</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*ap`pre*hen"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mistaking or mistake; wrong apprehension of one's meaning of a fact; misconception; misunderstanding.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misapprehensively</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*ap`pre*hen"sive*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>By, or with, misapprehension.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misappropriate</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ap*pro"pri*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To appropriate wrongly; to use for a wrong purpose.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>misappropriated</ent><br/
<hw>mis`ap*pro"pri*a*ted</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>taken for one's own use in violation of a trust.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> embezzled.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misappropriation</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ap*pro`pri*a"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong appropriation; wrongful use.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misarrange</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ar*range"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Misarranged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Misarranging</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To place in a wrong order, or improper manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misarrangement</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ar*range"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong arrangement.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misarcribe</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ar*cribe"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To ascribe wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misassay</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`as*say"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To assay, or attempt, improperly or unsuccessfully.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>W. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misassign</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`as*sign"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To assign wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misattend</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`at*tend"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To misunderstand; to disregard.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misaventure</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`a*ven"ture</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Misadventure.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misavize</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`a*vize"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To misadvise.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misbear</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*bear"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To carry improperly; to carry (one's self) wrongly; to misbehave.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misbecome</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`be*come"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>Not to become; to suit ill; not to befit or be adapted to.</def>  <rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy father will not act what <qex>misbecomes</qex> him.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misbecoming</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`be*com"ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Unbecoming.</def> <au>Milton.</au> -- <wordforms><wf>Mis`be*com"ing*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mis`be*com"ing*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>  <rj><au>Boyle.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misbede</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*bede"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Misbode</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Misboden</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>mis-be<ocir/dan</ets>.]</ety> <def>To wrong; to do injury to.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who hath you <qex>misboden</qex> or offended?</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misbefitting</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`be*fit"ting</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Not befitting.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misbegotten</ent><br/
<ent>Misbegot</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mis`be*got"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mis`be*got"ten</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>p. a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Unlawfully or irregularly begotten; of bad or disreputable origin; pernicious.</def> <ldquo/Valor <xex>misbegot</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Poorly designed or planned; badly carried out; ill-conceived.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misbehave</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`be*have"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Misbehaved</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Misbehaving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To behave ill; to conduct one's self improperly; -- often used with a reciprocal pronoun.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misbehaved</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`be*haved"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Guilty of ill behavior; illbred; rude.</def> <ldquo/A <xex>misbehaved</xex> and sullen wench.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misbehavior</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`be*hav"ior</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Improper, rude, or uncivil behavior; ill conduct.</def>  <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misbelief</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`be*lief"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Erroneous or false belief.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misbelieve</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`be*lieve"</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To believe erroneously, or in a false religion.</def> <ldquo/That <xex>misbelieving</xex> Moor.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misbeliever</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`be*liev"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who believes wrongly; one who holds a false religion.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misbeseem</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`be*seem"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To suit ill.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misbestow</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`be*stow"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To bestow improperly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misbestowal</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`be*stow"al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of misbestowing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misbileve</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`bi*leve"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Misbelief; unbelief; suspicion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misbode</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*bode"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <def><pos>imp.</pos> of <er>Misbede</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misboden</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*bo"den</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <def><pos>p. p.</pos> of <er>Misbede</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misborn</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"born`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Born to misfortune.</def>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscalculate</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*cal"cu*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To calculate erroneously.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To judge wrongly, especially about the effects of action or the likely course of events.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>miscalculation</ent><br/
<hw>mis*cal`cu*la"tion</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>a mistake in calculating.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> misreckoning, misestimation.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An error in judgment, especially about the effects of action or the likely course of events; <as>as, IBM's <ex>miscalculation</ex> about the impact of microcomputers cost them many billions in lost opportunities; Sadam's invasion of Kuwait was only his worst, but not his last, <ex>miscalculation</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscall</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*call"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To call by a wrong name; to name improperly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To call by a bad name; to abuse.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscarriage</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*car"riage</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Unfortunate event or issue of an undertaking; failure to attain a proper or desired result or reach a destination; <as>as, a serious <ex>miscarriage</ex> of justice</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When a counselor, to save himself,<br/
Would lay <qex>miscarriages</qex> upon his prince.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Ill conduct; evil or improper behavior; <as>as, the failings and <ex>miscarriages</ex> of the righteous</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Rogers.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The act of bringing forth a child before the time it is viable; a premature birth, resulting in death of the fetus; spontaneous abortion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscarriageable</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*car"riage*a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Capable of miscarrying; liable to fail.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscarry</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*car"ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Miscarried</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Miscarrying</conjf>.]</vmorph><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To carry, or go, wrong; to fail of reaching a destination, or fail of the intended effect; to be unsuccessful; to suffer defeat.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My ships have all <qex>miscarried</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The cardinal's letters to the pope <qex>miscarried</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To bring forth young before the time they are viable; to have a spontaneous abortion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscast</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*cast"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cast or reckon wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscast</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*cast"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An erroneous cast or reckoning.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>miscegenate</ent><br/
<hw>miscegenate</hw> <pos>v.</pos> <def>to marry or cohabit with a person of another race.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscegenation</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ce*ge*na"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>miscere</ets> to mix + the root of <ets>genus</ets> race.]</ety> <def>A mixing of races; amalgamation, as by intermarriage of black and white.</def>  <note>Until the late twentieth century, <ex>misceganation</ex> was a crime in some states of the Southern United States.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscellanarian</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`cel*la*na"ri*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Miscellany</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to miscellanies.</def> <au>Shaftesbury.</au> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A writer of miscellanies.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscellane</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"cel*lane</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Miscellaneous</er>, and cf. <er>Maslin</er>.]</ety> <def>A mixture of two or more sorts of grain; -- now called <altname>maslin</altname> and <altname>meslin</altname>.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscellanea</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mis"cel*la"ne*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[L. See <er>Miscellany</er>.]</ety> <def>A collection of miscellaneous matters; matters of various kinds.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscellaneous</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`cel*la"ne*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>miscellaneus</ets> mixed, miscellaneous, fr. <ets>miscellus</ets> mixed, fr. <ets>miscere</ets> to mix. See <er>Mix</er>, and cf. <er>Miscellany</er>.]</ety> <def>Mixed; mingled; consisting of several things; of diverse sorts; promiscuous; heterogeneous; <as>as, a <ex>miscellaneous</ex> collection</as>.</def> <ldquo/A <xex>miscellaneous</xex> rabble.<rdquo/ <au>Milton.</au> -- <wordforms><wf>Mis`cel*la"ne*ous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mis`cel*la"ne*ous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscellanist</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"cel*la*nist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A writer of miscellanies; miscellanarian.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscellany</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"cel*la*ny</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Miscellanies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>miscellanea</ets>, neut. pl. of. <ets>miscellaneus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>miscellan<eacute/e</ets>, pl. <ets>miscellan<eacute/es</ets>. See <er>Miscellaneous</er>.]</ety> <def>A mass or mixture of various things; a medley; esp., a collection of compositions on various subjects.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>'T is but a bundle or <qex>miscellany</qex> of sin; sins original, and sins actual.</q> <rj><qau>Hewyt.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Miscellany madam</b></col>, <cd>a woman who dealt in various fineries; a milliner.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 929 --></p>

<p><ent>Miscellany</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"cel*la*ny</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s"s<ecr/l*l<asl/*n<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Miscellaneous; heterogeneous.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscensure</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*cen"sure</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To misjudge.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Daniel.</au> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>Erroneous judgment.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Sylvester.</au></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mischance</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*chance"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>meschance</ets>, OF. <ets>mescheance</ets>.]</ety> <def>Ill luck; ill fortune; mishap.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Never come <qex>mischance</qex> between us twain.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Calamity; misfortune; misadventure; mishap; infelicity; disaster. See <er>Calamity</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mischance</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*chance"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To happen by mischance.</def>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mischanceful</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*chance"ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Unlucky.</def>  <rj><au>R. Browning.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mischaracterize</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*char"ac*ter*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To characterize falsely or erroneously; to give a wrong character to.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They totally <qex>mischaracterize</qex> the action.</q> <rj><qau>Eton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mischarge</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*charge"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To charge erroneously, as in an account.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A mistake in charging.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mischief</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"chief</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s"ch<icr/f)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>meschef</ets> bad result, OF. <ets>meschief</ets>; pref. <ets>mes-</ets> (L. <ets>minus</ets> less) + <ets>chief</ets> end, head, F. <ets>chef</ets> chief. See <er>Minus</er>, and <er>Chief</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Harm; damage; esp., disarrangement of order; trouble or vexation caused by human agency or by some living being, intentionally or not; often, calamity, mishap; trivial evil caused by thoughtlessness, or in sport.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy tongue deviseth <qex>mischiefs</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. lii. 2.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The practice whereof shall, I hope, secure me from many <qex>mischiefs</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Cause of trouble or vexation; trouble.</def>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>mischief</qex> was, these allies would never allow that the common enemy was subdued.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To be in mischief</b></col>, <cd>to be doing harm or causing annoyance.</cd> -- <col><b>To make mischief</b></col>, <cd>to do mischief, especially by exciting quarrels.</cd> -- <col><b>To play the mischief</b></col>, <cd>to cause great harm; to throw into confusion.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Damage; harm; hurt; injury; detriment; evil; ill.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Mischief</er>, <er>Damage</er>, <er>Harm</er>. <xex>Damage</xex> is an injury which diminishes the value of a thing; <xex>harm</xex> is an injury which causes trouble or inconvenience; <xex>mischief</xex> is an injury which disturbs the order and consistency of things.  We often suffer <xex>damage</xex> or <xex>harm</xex> from accident, but <xex>mischief</xex> always springs from perversity or folly.</usage><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mischief</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"chief</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To do harm to.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mischiefable</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"chief*a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Mischievous.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Lydgate.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mischiefful</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"chief*ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Mischievous.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Foote.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mischief-maker</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"chief-mak`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who makes mischief; one who excites or instigates quarrels or enmity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mischief-making</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"chief-mak`ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Causing harm; exciting enmity or quarrels.</def> <au>Rowe.</au> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>The act or practice of making mischief, inciting quarrels, etc.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mischievous</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"chie*vous</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s"ch<esl/*v<ucr/s)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Causing mischief; harmful; hurtful; -- now often applied where the evil is done carelessly or in sport; <as>as, a <ex>mischievous</ex> child</as>.</def> <ldquo/Most <xex>mischievous</xex> foul sin.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This false, wily, doubling disposition is intolerably <qex>mischievous</qex> to society.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Harmful; hurtful; detrimental; noxious; pernicious; destructive.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Mis"chie*vous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mis"chie*vous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mischna</ent><br/
<hw>Misch"na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mishna</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mischnic</ent><br/
<hw>Misch"nic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>See <er>Mishnic</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mischoose</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*choose"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Mischose</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mischosen</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mischoosing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To choose wrongly.</def>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mischoose</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*choose"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make a wrong choice.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mischristen</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*chris"ten</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To christen wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscibility</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ci*bil"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>miscibilit<eacute/</ets>.]</ety> <def>Capability of being mixed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscible</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"ci*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>miscible</ets>, fr. L. <ets>miscere</ets> to mix.]</ety> <def>Capable of being mixed; mixable.</def>  <rj><au>Burke.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Mixable in all proportions; forming a single phase when mixed in any proportion; -- of liquids; <as>as, water and alcohol are <ex>miscible</ex> in all proportions; water and gasoline are not <ex>miscible</ex>; benzene and ethyl alcohol are <ex>miscible</ex>, and ethyl alcohol is <ex>miscible</ex> with water, but water is not <ex>miscible</ex> with benzene.</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscitation</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ci*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Erroneous citation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscite</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*cite"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cite erroneously.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misclaim</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*claim"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mistaken claim.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscognizant</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*cog"ni*zant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Not cognizant; ignorant; not knowing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscognize</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*cog"nize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To fail to apprehend; to misunderstand.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Holland.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscollocation</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*col`lo*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong collocation.</def>  <rj><au>De Quincey.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscolor</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*col"or</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To give a wrong color to.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <mark>[figuratively]</mark> <def>To set forth erroneously or unfairly; to misrepresent; <as>as, to <ex>miscolor</ex> facts</as>.</def>  <rj><au>C. Kingsley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscomfort</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*com"fort</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Discomfort.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscomprehend</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*com`pre*hend"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To get a wrong idea of or about; to misunderstand.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscomputation</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*com`pu*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Erroneous computation; false reckoning.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscompute</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`com*pute"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Miscount</er>.]</ety> <def>To compute erroneously.</def>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misconceit</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`con*ceit"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Misconception.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misconceive</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`con*ceive"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Misconceived</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Misconceiving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To conceive wrongly; to interpret incorrectly; to receive a false notion of; to misunderstand; to misjudge; to misapprehend.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those things which, for want of due consideration heretofore, they have <qex>misconceived</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To misapprehend; misunderstand; mistake.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misconceiver</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`con*ceiv"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who misconceives.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misconception</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`con*cep"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Erroneous conception; false opinion; wrong understanding.</def>  <rj><au>Harvey.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misconclusion</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`con*clu"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An erroneous inference or conclusion.</def>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misconduct</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*con"duct</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Wrong conduct; bad behavior; mismanagement.</def>  <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Unlawful or unethical conduct by a person holding a public office or having a position of responsibility in the administration of justice; malfeasance; <as>as, discussing the case out of court during a trial is <ex>misconduct</ex> by a juror</as>;</def> <specif>especially,</specif> <def>misuse of office by an elected or appointed government official, also called <altname>misconduct in office</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Misbehavior; misdemeanor; mismanagement; misdeed; delinquency; offense.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misconduct</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`con*duct"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To conduct amiss; to mismanage.</def>  <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To misconduct one's self</b></col>, <cd>to behave improperly.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misconduct</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`con*duct"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To behave amiss.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misconfident</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*con"fi*dent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having a mistaken confidence; wrongly trusting.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misconjecture</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`con*jec"ture</hw> <pr>(?; 135)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A wrong conjecture or guess.</def>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misconjecture</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`con*jec"ture</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To conjecture wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misconsecrate</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*con"se*crate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To consecrate amiss.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Misconsecrated</xex> flags.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misconsecration</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*con`se*cra"tion</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong consecration.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misconsequence</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*con"se*quence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A wrong consequence; a false deduction.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misconstruable</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*con"stru*a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Such as can be misconstrued, as language or conduct.</def>  <rj><au>R. North.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misconstruct</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`con*struct"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To construct wrongly; to construe or interpret erroneously.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misconstruction</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`con*struc"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Erroneous construction; wrong interpretation.</def>  <rj><au>Bp. Stillingfleet.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misconstrue</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*con"strue</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Misconstrued</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Misconstruing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To construe wrongly; to interpret erroneously.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Do not, great sir, <qex>misconstrue</qex> his intent.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Much afflicted to find his actions <qex>misconstrued</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misconstruer</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*con"stru*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who misconstrues.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscontent</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`con*tent"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Discontent.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscontinuance</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`con*tin"u*ance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Discontinuance; also, continuance by undue process.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscopy</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*copy"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To copy amiss.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscopy</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*copy"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mistake in copying.</def>  <rj><au>North Am. Rev.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscorrect</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`cor*rect"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To fail or err in attempting to correct.</def> <ldquo/Scaliger <xex>miscorrects</xex> his author.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscounsel</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*coun"sel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To counsel or advise wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscount</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*count"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>mesconter</ets>, F. <ets>m<eacute/compter</ets>.  Cf. <er>Miscompute</er>.]</ety> <def>To count erroneously.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscount</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*count"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/compte</ets> error, OF. <ets>mesconte</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An erroneous counting.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <def>An erroneous count of ballots cast in an election.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscovet</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*cov"et</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To covet wrongfully.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscreancy</ent><br/
<ent>Miscreance</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mis"cre*ance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mis"cre*an*cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>mescreance</ets>, F. <ets>m<eacute/cr<eacute/ance</ets> incredulity.]</ety> <def>The quality of being miscreant; adherence to a false religion; false faith.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Ayliffe.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscreant</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"cre*ant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>mescreant</ets>, F. <ets>m<eacute/cr<eacute/ant</ets>; pref. <ets>mes-</ets> (L. <ets>minus</ets> less) + p. pr. fr. L. <ets>credere</ets> to believe. See <er>Creed</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>One who holds a false religious faith; a misbeliever.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser. De Quincey.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou oughtest not to be slothful to the destruction of the <qex>miscreants</qex>, but to constrain them to obey our Lord God.</q> <rj><qau>Rivers.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One not restrained by Christian principles; an unscrupulous villain; a depraved person; a vile wretch.</def>  <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj></p>

<p><ent>Miscreant</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"cre*ant</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Holding a false religious faith.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Destitute of conscience; unscrupulous; villainous; base; depraved.</def>  <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscreate</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`cre*ate"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Miscreated; illegitimate; forged; <as>as, <ex>miscreate</ex> titles</as>.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Poet.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscreate</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`cre*ate"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To create badly or amiss.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscreated</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`cre*at"ed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Formed unnaturally or illegitimately; deformed.</def>  <rj><au>Spenser. Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscreative</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`cre*a"tive</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Creating amiss.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscredent</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*cre"dent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>mis-</ets> + <ets>credent</ets>.  Cf. <er>Miscreant</er>.]</ety> <def>A miscreant, or believer in a false religious doctrine.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Holinshed.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscredulity</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`cre*du"li*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong credulity or belief; misbelief.</def>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miscue</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*cue"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Billiards)</fld> <def>A false stroke with a billiard cue, the cue slipping from the ball struck without impelling it as desired.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>To make a mistake;</def> <specif>especially</specif> <def>to fail to execute a necessary or expected action at the proper time, such as making a play in sports, or saying one's line in a drama.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdate</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*date"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Misdated</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Misdating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To put a false or erroneous date on (a document).</def>  <rj><au>Young.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To assign an incorrect date to; <as>as, the fall of Troy was <ex>misdated</ex> by medieval writers</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>misdating</ent><br/
<hw>misdating</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The assignment of a date to something at a time when it could not have existed or occurred.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> anachronism, mistiming.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdeal</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*deal"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Misdealt</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Misdealing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To deal or distribute wrongly, as cards; to make a wrong distribution.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdeal</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*deal"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of misdealing; a wrong distribution of cards to the players.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdeed</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*deed"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>misd<aemac/d</ets>. See <er>Deed</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>An evil deed; a wicked action.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Evils which our own <qex>misdeeds</qex> have wrought.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Misconduct; misdemeanor; fault; offense; trespass; transgression; crime.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdeem</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*deem"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To misjudge.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdemean</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`de*mean"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To behave ill; -- with a reflexive pronoun; <as>as, to <ex>misdemean</ex> one's self</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdemeanant</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`de*mean"ant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One guilty of a misdemeanor.</def>  <rj><au>Sydney Smith.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdemeanor</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`de*mean"or</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Ill behavior; evil conduct; fault.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A crime less than a felony.</def>  <rj><au>Wharton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ As a rule, in the old English law, offenses capitally punishable were felonies; all other indictable offenses were misdemeanors. In common usage, the word <xex>crime</xex> is employed to denote the offenses of a deeper and more atrocious dye, while small faults and omissions of less consequence are comprised under the gentler name of <xex>misdemeanors</xex>.  <rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj><br/
<br/
   The distinction, however, between felonies and misdemeanors is purely arbitrary, and is in most jurisdictions either abrogated or so far reduced as to be without practical value.  Cf. <er>Felony</er>.  <rj><au>Wharton.</au></rj></note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Misdeed; misconduct; misbehavior; fault; trespass; transgression.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdempt</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*dempt"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <mark>obs.</mark> <def><pos>p. p.</pos> of <er>Misdeem</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdepart</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`de*part"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To distribute wrongly.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>misdeparteth</qex> riches temporal.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misderive</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`de*rive"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To turn or divert improperly; to misdirect.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To derive erroneously.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdescribe</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`de*scribe"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To describe wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdesert</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`de*sert"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Ill desert.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdevotion</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`de*vo"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mistaken devotion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdiet</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*di"et</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Improper diet.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdiet</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*di"et</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To diet improperly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdight</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*dight"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Arrayed, prepared, or furnished, unsuitably.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdirect</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`di*rect"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To give a wrong direction to; <as>as, to <ex>misdirect</ex> a passenger, or a letter; to <ex>misdirect</ex> one's energies.</as></def>  <rj><au>Shenstone.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdirection</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`di*rec"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of directing wrongly, or the state of being so directed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>An error of a judge in charging the jury on a matter of law.</def>  <rj><au>Mozley & W.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The direction of another's attention to an unimportant place or matter, for the purpose of being able to perform an action undetected; <as>as, <ex>misdirection</ex> is an important part of a magician's art</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdisposition</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*dis`po*si"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Erroneous disposal or application.</def>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdistinguish</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`dis*tin"guish</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make wrong distinctions in or concerning.</def>  <rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdivide</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`di*vide"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To divide wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdivision</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`di*vi"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong division.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdo</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*do"</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s*d<oomac/")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Misdid</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Misdone</conjf> <pr>(m<icr/s*d<ucr/n")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Misdoing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>misd<omac/n</ets>. See <er>Do</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To do wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Afford me place to show what recompense<br/
Towards thee I intend for what I have <qex>misdone</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To do wrong to; to illtreat.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdo</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*do"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To do wrong; to commit a fault.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have <qex>misdone</qex>, and I endure the smart.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdoer</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*do"er</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A wrongdoer.</def>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdoing</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*do"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A wrong done; a fault or crime; an offense; <as>as, it was my <ex>misdoing</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdoubt</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*doubt"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To be suspicious of; to have suspicion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I do not <qex>misdoubt</qex> my wife.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdoubt</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*doubt"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Suspicion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Irresolution; hesitation.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdoubtful</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*doubt"ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a</pos> <def>Misgiving; hesitating.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/Her <xex>misdoubtful</xex> mind.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misdread</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*dread"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Dread of evil.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mise</ent><br/
<hw>Mise</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mise</ets> a putting, setting, expense, fr. <ets>mis</ets>, <ets>mise</ets>, p. p. of <ets>mettre</ets> to put, lay, fr. LL. <ets>mittere</ets> to send.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The issue in a writ of right.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Expense; cost; disbursement.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A tax or tallage; in Wales, an honorary gift of the people to a new king or prince of Wales; also, a tribute paid, in the country palatine of Chester, England, at the change of the owner of the earldom.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misease</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*ease"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mesaise</ets>, OF. <ets>mesaise</ets>.]</ety> <def>Want of ease; discomfort; misery.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miseased</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*eased"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having discomfort or misery; troubled.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miseasy</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*eas"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Not easy; painful.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misedition</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`e*di"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An incorrect or spurious edition.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miseducate</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*ed"u*cate</hw> <pr>(?; 135)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To educate in a wrong manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misemploy</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`em*ploy"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To employ amiss; <as>as, to <ex>misemploy</ex> time, advantages, talents, etc.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their frugal father's gains they <qex>misemploy</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misemployment</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`em*ploy"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong or mistaken employment.</def>  <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misenter</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*en"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To enter or insert wrongly, as a charge in an account.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misentreat</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`en*treat"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To treat wrongfully.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Grafton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misentry</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*en"try</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An erroneous entry or charge, as of an account.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miser</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"ser</hw> <pr>(m<imac/"z<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>miser</ets> wretched, miserable; cf. Gr. <grk>mi^sos</grk> hate, <grk>misei^n</grk> to hate: cf. It. & Sp. <ets>misero</ets> wretched, avaricious.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A wretched person; a person afflicted by any great misfortune.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The woeful words of a <qex>miser</qex> now despairing.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P. Sidney.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A despicable person; a wretch.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A covetous, grasping, mean person; esp., one having wealth, who lives miserably for the sake of saving and increasing his hoard.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As some lone <qex>miser</qex>, visiting his store,<br/
Bends at his treasure, counts, recounts it o'er.</q> <rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A stingy person; one very reluctant to spend money.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A kind of large earth auger.</def>  <rj><au>Knight.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miserable</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"er*a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mis<eacute/rable</ets>, L. <ets>miserabilis</ets>, fr. <ets>miserari</ets> to lament, pity, fr. <ets>miser</ets> wretched. See <er>Miser</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Very unhappy; wretched; living in misery.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What hopes delude thee, <qex>miserable</qex> man?</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Causing unhappiness or misery.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What 's more <qex>miserable</qex> than discontent?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Worthless; mean; despicable; <as>as, a <ex>miserable</ex> fellow; a <ex>miserable</ex> dinner.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Miserable</qex> comforters are ye all.</q> <rj><qau>Job xvi. 2.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Avaricious; niggardly; miserly.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Abject; forlorn; pitiable; wretched.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miserable</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"er*a*ble</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A miserable person.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sterne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miserableness</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"er*a*ble*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state or quality of being miserable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miserably</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"er*a*bly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a miserable; unhappily; calamitously; wretchedly; meanly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They were <qex>miserably</qex> entertained.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P. Sidney.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The fifth was <qex>miserably</qex> stabbed to death.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miseration</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`er*a"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Commiseration.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miserere</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mis`e*re"re</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., have mercy, fr. <ets>misereri</ets> to have mercy, fr. <ets>miser</ets>. See <er>Miser</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld> <def>The psalm usually appointed for penitential acts, being the 50th psalm in the Latin version.  It commences with the word <xex>miserere</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A musical composition adapted to the 50th psalm.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where only the wind signs <qex>miserere</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Lowell.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A small projecting boss or bracket, on the under side of the hinged seat of a church stall (see <er>Stall</er>).  It was intended, the seat being turned up, to give some support to a worshiper when standing.  Called also <xex>misericordia</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Ileus</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misericorde</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"er*i*corde"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mis<eacute/ricorde</ets>. See <er>Misericordia</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Compassion; pity; mercy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Anc. Armor.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Misericordia</er>, 2.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misericordia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mis`e*ri*cor"di*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., mercy, compassion; <ets>miser</ets> wretched + <ets>cor</ets>, <ets>cordis</ets>, heart.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(O. Law)</fld> <def>An amercement.</def>  <rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Anc. Armor.)</fld> <def>A thin-bladed dagger; so called, in the Middle Ages, because used to give the death wound or <ldquo/mercy<rdquo/ stroke to a fallen adversary.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>An indulgence as to food or dress granted to a member of a religious order.</def>  <rj><au>Shipley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 930 --></p>

<p><ent>Miserly</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"ser*ly</hw> <pr>(m<imac/"z<etil/r*l<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Miser</er>.]</ety> <def>Like a miser; very covetous; avaricious; stingy; sordid; niggardly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Avaricious; niggardly; sordid; parsimonious; avaricious; penurious; covetous; stingy; mean. See <er>Avaricious</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misery</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"ser*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Miseries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>miserie</ets>, L. <ets>miseria</ets>, fr. <ets>miser</ets> wretched: cf. F. <ets>mis<egrave/re</ets>, OF. also, <ets>miserie</ets>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Great unhappiness; extreme pain of body or mind; wretchedness; distress; woe.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Destruction and <qex>misery</qex> are in their ways.</q> <rj><qau>Rom. iii. 16.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Cause of misery; calamity; misfortune.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When we our betters see bearing our woes,<br/
We scarcely think our <qex>miseries</qex> our foes.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Covetousness; niggardliness; avarice.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Wretchedness; torture; agony; torment; anguish; distress; calamity; misfortune.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misesteem</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`es*teem"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/sestime</ets>.]</ety> <def>Want of esteem; disrespect.</def>  <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misestimate</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*es"ti*mate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To estimate erroneously.</def>  <rj><au>J. S. Mill.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misexplanation</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*ex`pla*na"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An erroneous explanation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misexplication</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*ex`pli*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong explication.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misexposition</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*ex`po*si"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong exposition.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misexpound</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ex*pound"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To expound erroneously.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misexpression</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ex*pres"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong expression.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misfaith</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*faith"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Want of faith; distrust.</def> <ldquo/[Anger] born of your <xex>misfaith</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misfall</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*fall"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Misfell</conjf>; <pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Misfallen</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Misfalling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To befall, as ill luck; to happen to unluckily.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misfare</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*fare"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>misfaran</ets>.]</ety> <def>To fare ill.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>Misfortune.</def></def2> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misfashion</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*fash"ion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To form wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misfeasance</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*fea"sance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. pref. <ets>mes-</ets> wrong (L. <ets>minus</ets> less) + <ets>faisance</ets> doing, fr. <ets>faire</ets> to do, L. <ets>facere</ets>.  Cf. <er>Malfeasance</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A trespass; a wrong arising from an overt act; the improper doing of an act which a person might lawfully do.</def>  <rj><au>Bouvier.</au>  <au>Wharton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misfeature</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*fea"ture</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Ill feature.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Keats.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misfeeling</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*feel"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Insensate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Wyclif.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misfeign</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*feign"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To feign with an evil design.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misfit</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*fit"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or the state of fitting badly; <as>as, a <ex>misfit</ex> in making a coat; a ludicrous <ex>misfit</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Something that fits badly, as a garment.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I saw an uneasy change in Mr. Micawber, which sat tightly on him, as if his new duties were a <qex>misfit</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A person who does not fit in comfortably with the surrounding situation or society; one who cannot conform or adjust to the circumstances in which he lives.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misform</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*form"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Misformed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Misforming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To make in an ill form.</def>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misformation</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`for*ma"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Malformation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misfortunate</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*for"tu*nate</hw> <pr>(?; 135)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Producing misfortune.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misfortune</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*for"tune</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Bad fortune or luck; calamity; an evil accident; disaster; mishap; mischance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Consider why the change was wrought,<br/
You 'll find his <qex>misfortune</qex>, not his fault.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Calamity; mishap; mischance; misadventure; ill; harm; disaster. See <er>Calamity</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misfortune</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*for"tune</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To happen unluckily or unfortunately; to miscarry; to fail.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Stow.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misfortuned</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*for"tuned</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Unfortunate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misframe</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*frame"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To frame wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misget</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*get"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To get wrongfully.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misgie</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*gie"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>See <er>Misgye</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misgive</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*give"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Misgave</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Misgiven</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Misgiving</conjf>.]</vmorph><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To give or grant amiss.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Laud.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Specifically: To give doubt and apprehension to, instead of confidence and courage; to impart fear to; to make irresolute; -- usually said of the mind or heart, and followed by the objective personal pronoun.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So doth my heart <qex>misgive</qex> me in these conflicts<br/
What may befall him, to his harm and ours.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such whose consciences <qex>misgave</qex> them, how ill they had deserved.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To suspect; to dread.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misgive</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*give"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To give out doubt and apprehension; to be fearful or irresolute.</def> <ldquo/My mind <xex>misgives</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>misgiving</ent><br/
<hw>mis*giv"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Evil premonition; doubt; distrust; a feeling of apprehension; -- used commonly in the plural.</def> <ldquo/Suspicious and <xex>misgivings</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>South.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misgo</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*go"</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s*g<omac/")</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To go astray.</def>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misgotten</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*got"ten</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s*g<ocr/t"t'n)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Unjustly gotten.</def>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misgovern</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*gov"ern</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To govern badly; <as>as, to <ex>misgovern</ex> a country</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Knolles.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misgovernance</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*gov"ern*ance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Misgovernment; misconduct; misbehavior.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer. Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misgoverned</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*gov"erned</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Ill governed, as a people; ill directed.</def> <ldquo/Rude, <xex>misgoverned</xex> hands.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misgovernment</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*gov"ern*ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Bad government; want of government.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misgracious</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*gra"cious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Not gracious.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misgraff</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*graff"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To misgraft.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misgraft</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*graft"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To graft wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misground</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*ground"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To found erroneously.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Misgrounded</xex> conceit.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misgrowth</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*growth"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Bad growth; an unnatural or abnormal growth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misguess</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*guess"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To guess wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misguidance</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*guid"ance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong guidance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misguide</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*guide"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To guide wrongly; to lead astray; <as>as, to <ex>misguide</ex> the understanding</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misguide</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*guide"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Misguidance; error.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misguiding</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*guid"ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Misleading.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mis*guid"ing*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misgye</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*gye"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To misguide.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mishandle</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*han"dle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To handle ill or wrongly; to maltreat.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mishap</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*hap"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Evil accident; ill luck; misfortune; mischance.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Secure from worldly chances and <qex>mishaps</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mishap</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*hap"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To happen unluckily; -- used impersonally.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/If that me <xex>mishap</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mishappen</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*hap"pen</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To happen ill or unluckily.</def>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mishappy</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*hap"py</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Unhappy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mishcup</ent><br/
<hw>Mish*cup"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Scup</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The scup.</def> <mark>[Local, U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mishear</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*hear"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To hear incorrectly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mishmash</ent><br/
<hw>Mish"mash`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. G. <ets>mish-mash</ets>, fr. <ets>mischen</ets> to mix.]</ety> <def>A hodgepodge or hotchpotch; a confused jumble.</def>  <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>mishmosh</asp>.]</altsp> <rj><au>Sir T. Herbert.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mishna</ent><br/
<hw>Mish"na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NHeb. <ets>mishn<amac/h</ets>, i. e., repetition, doubling, explanation (of the divine law), fr. Heb. <ets>sh<amac/n<amac/h</ets> to change, to repeat.]</ety> <def>A collection or digest of Jewish traditions and explanations of Scripture, forming the text of the Talmud.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>Mischna</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mishnic</ent><br/
<hw>Mish"nic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the Mishna.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misimagination</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`im*ag`i*na"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong imagination; delusion.</def>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misimprove</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`im*prove"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To use for a bad purpose; to abuse; to misuse; <as>as, to <ex>misimprove</ex> time, talents, advantages, etc.</as></def>  <rj><au>South.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misimprovement</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`im*prove"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Ill use or employment; use for a bad purpose.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misincline</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"in*cline"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cause to have a wrong inclination or tendency; to affect wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misinfer</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`in*fer"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To infer incorrectly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misinform</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`in*form"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To give untrue information to; to inform wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misinform</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`in*form"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To give untrue information; (with <xex>against</xex>) to calumniate.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bp. Montagu.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misinformant</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`in*form"ant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A misinformer.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misinformation</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*in`for*ma"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Untrue or incorrect information.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misinformer</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`in*form"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who gives untrue or incorrect information.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misinstruct</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`in*struct"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To instruct amiss.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misinstruction</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`in*struc"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong or improper instruction.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misintelligence</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`in*tel"li*gence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Wrong information; misinformation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Disagreement; misunderstanding.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misintend</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`in*tend"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To aim amiss.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misinterpret</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`in*ter"pret</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To interpret erroneously; to understand or to explain in a wrong sense.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misinterpretable</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`in*ter"pret*a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Capable of being misinterpreted; liable to be misunderstood.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misinterpretation</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`in*ter"pre*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of interpreting erroneously; a mistaken interpretation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misinterpreter</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`in*ter"pret*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who interprets erroneously.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misjoin</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*join"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To join unfitly or improperly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misjoinder</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*join"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>An incorrect union of parties or of causes of action in a procedure, criminal or civil.</def>  <rj><au>Wharton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misjudge</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*judge"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To judge erroneously or unjustly; to err in judgment; to misconstrue.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misjudgment</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*judg"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Written also <ets>misjudgement</ets>.]</ety> <def>A wrong or unjust judgment.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miskeep</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*keep"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To keep wrongly.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misken</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*ken"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>Not to know.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miskin</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"kin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. for <ets>music + -kin</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A little bagpipe.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Drayton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miskindle</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*kin"dle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To kindle amiss; to inflame to a bad purpose; to excite wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misknow</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*know"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To have a mistaken notion of or about.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mislactation</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`lac*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Defective flow or vitiated condition of the milk.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mislay</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*lay"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mislaid</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mislaying</conjf>.]</vmorph><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To lay in a wrong place; to ascribe to a wrong source.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The fault is generally <qex>mislaid</qex> upon nature.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To lay in a place not recollected; to misplace; to lose.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>The . . . charter, indeed, was unfortunately <qex>mislaid</qex>: and the prayer of their petition was to obtain one of like import in its stead.</q> <rj><qau>Hallam.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mislayer</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*lay"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who mislays.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misle</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"sle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Misled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Misling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Prop. <ets>mistle</ets>, fr. <ets>mist</ets>.  Cf. <er>Mistle</er>, <er>Mizzle</er>.]</ety> <def>To rain in very fine drops, like a thick mist; to mizzle; to drizzle.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark> <br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misle</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"sle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A fine rain; a thick mist; a mizzle; a drizzle.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mislead</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*lead"</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s*l<emac/d")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Misled</conjf> <pr>(m<icr/s*l<ecr/d")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Misleading</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>misl<aemac/dan</ets>. See <er>Mis-</er>, and <er>Lead</er> to conduct.]</ety> <def>To lead into a wrong way or path; to lead astray; to guide into error; to cause to mistake; to deceive.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Trust not servants who <qex>mislead</qex> or misinform you.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To give due light<br/
To the <qex>mislead</qex> and lonely traveler.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To delude; deceive. See <er>Deceive</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misleader</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*lead"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who leads into error.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misleading</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*lead"ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Leading astray; delusive.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mislearn</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*learn"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To learn wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misled</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*led"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <def><pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> of <er>Mislead</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mislen</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"len</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Maslin</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misletoe</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"le*toe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mistletoe</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mislight</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*light"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To deceive or lead astray with a false light.</def>  <rj><au>Herrick.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mislike</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*like"</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s*l<imac/k")</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Misliked</conjf> <pr>(m<icr/s*l<imac/kt")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Misliking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>misl<imac/cian</ets> to displease. See <er>Like</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <def>To dislike; to disapprove of; to have aversion to; <as>as, to <ex>mislike</ex> a man</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who may like or <qex>mislike</qex> what he says.</q> <rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mislike</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*like"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Dislike; disapprobation; aversion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misliker</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*lik"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who dislikes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misliking</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*lik"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Dislike; aversion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mislin</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"lin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. & a.</pos> <def>See <er>Maslin</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mislive</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*live"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To live amiss.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mislodge</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*lodge"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To lodge amiss.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misluck</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*luck"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Ill luck; misfortune.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misly</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Raining in very small drops; drizzling.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark> <br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mismake</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*make"</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s*m<amac/k")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make or form amiss; to spoil in making.</def> <ldquo/Limping possibilities of <xex>mismade</xex> human nature.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Mrs. Browning.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mismanage</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*man"age</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To manage ill or improperly; <as>as, to <ex>mismanage</ex> public affairs</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mismanagement</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*man"age*ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong or bad management; <as>as, he failed through <ex>mismagement</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mismanager</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*man"a*ger</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who manages ill.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mismark</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*mark"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To mark wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mismatch</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*match"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To match unsuitably.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mismatched</ent><br/
<hw>mis*matched"</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Matched unsuitably; grouped into pairs or sets with incompatible characteristics.</def> [Narrower terms: <stype>ill-sorted, incompatible, mismated, unsuited</stype>; <stype>odd, unmatched, unmated, unpaired </stype>] <see>Also See: <er>incompatible</er>.</see>  Antonym: <ant>matched</ant>.<br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of very unequal ability; -- of contestants in a contest.  The less able contestant is said to be <contr>overmatched</contr> or <contr>outclassed</contr>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> uneven, not fairly matched.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mismate</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*mate"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To mate wrongly or unsuitably; to mismatch; <as>as, to <ex>mismate</ex> gloves or shoes; a <ex>mismated</ex> couple.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mismeasure</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*meas"ure</hw> <pr>(?; 135)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To measure or estimate incorrectly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mismeasurement</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*meas"ure*ment</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong measurement.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mismeter</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*me"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To give the wrong meter to, as to a line of verse.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misname</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*name"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To call by the wrong name; to give a wrong or inappropriate name to.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misnomer</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*no"mer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. pref. <ets>mes-</ets> amiss, wrong (L. <ets>minus</ets> less) + F. <ets>nommer</ets> to name, L. <ets>nominare</ets>, fr. <ets>nomen</ets> name. See <er>Name</er>.]</ety> <def>The misnaming of a person in a legal instrument, as in a complaint or indictment; any misnaming of a person or thing; a wrong or inapplicable name or title.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Many of the changes, by a great <qex>misnomer</qex>, called parliamentary <ldquo/reforms<rdquo/.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The word <ldquo/synonym<rdquo/ is fact a <qex>misnomer</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Whately.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misnomer</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*no"mer</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To misname.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misnumber</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*num"ber</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To number wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misnurture</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*nur"ture</hw> <pr>(?; 135)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To nurture or train wrongly; <as>as, to <ex>misnurture</ex> children</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misobedience</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`o*be"di*ence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mistaken obedience; disobedience.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misobserve</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ob*serve"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To observe inaccurately; to mistake in observing.</def>  <rj><au>Locke.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misobserver</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`ob*serv"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who misobserves; one who fails to observe properly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misogamist</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*sog"a*mist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>misei^n</grk> to hate + <?/ marriage.]</ety> <def>A hater of marriage.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misogamy</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*sog"a*my</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>misogamie</ets>.]</ety> <def>Hatred of marriage.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>misogynic</ent><br/
<hw>misogynic</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>misogynous.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>misogynism</ent><br/
<hw>misogynism</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>misogyny.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misogynist</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*sog"y*nist</hw> <pr>(m<icr/*s<ocr/j"<icr/*n<icr/st)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>misogy`nhs</grk>, <grk>misogy`naios</grk>; <grk>misei^n</grk> to hate + <grk>gynh`</grk> woman: cf. F. <ets>misogyne</ets>.]</ety> <def>A woman hater.  Contrast <contr>misandrist</contr>.</def>  <rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misogynous</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*sog"y*nous</hw> <pr>(m<icr/*s<ocr/j"<icr/*n<ucr/s)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Hating women; having deep-seated distrust of women; -- used of men.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misogyny</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*sog"y*ny</hw> <pr>(m<icr/*s<ocr/j"<icr/*n<ycr/; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>misogyni`a</grk>: cf. F. <ets>misogynie</ets>.]</ety> <def>Hatred of women.  Contrast <contr>misandry</contr>.</def>  <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misology</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*sol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(m<icr/*s<ocr/l"<osl/*j<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>misologi`a</grk>; <grk>misei^n</grk> to hate + <grk>lo`gos</grk> discourse.]</ety> <def>Hatred of argument or discussion; hatred of enlightenment.</def>  <rj><au>G. H. Lewes.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misopinion</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`o*pin"ion</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong opinion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misorder</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*or"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To order ill; to manage erroneously; to conduct badly.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misorder</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*or"der</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Irregularity; disorder.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Camden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misorderly</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*or"der*ly</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Irregular; disorderly.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misordination</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*or`di*na"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong ordination.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misotheism</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"o*the`ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>misei^n</grk> to hate + <grk>qeo`s</grk> god.]</ety> <def>Hatred of God.</def>  <rj><au>De Quincey.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mispaint</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*paint"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To paint ill, or wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mispassion</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*pas"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong passion or feeling.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mispay</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*pay"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Appay</er>.]</ety> <def>To dissatisfy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mispend</ent><br/
<ent>Mispell</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Mis*pell"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, <hw>Mis*pend"</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, etc.</mhw> <def>See <er>Misspell</er>, <er>Misspend</er>, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mispense</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*pense"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Misspense</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misperception</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`per*cep"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Erroneous perception.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mispersuade</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`per*suade"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To persuade amiss.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mispersuasion</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`per*sua"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A false persuasion; wrong notion or opinion.</def>  <rj><au>Dr. H. More.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mispickel</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*pick"el</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Arsenical iron pyrites; arsenopyrite.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misplace</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*place"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Misplaced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Misplacing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To put in a wrong place; to set or place on an improper or unworthy object; <as>as, he <ex>misplaced</ex> his confidence</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To place in a location that one does not recall; to  mislay; to lose.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misplacement</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*place"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of misplacing, or the state of being misplaced.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misplead</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*plead"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To err in pleading.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mispleading</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*plead"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>An error in pleading.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mispoint</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*point"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To point improperly; to punctuate wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mispolicy</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*pol"i*cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong policy; impolicy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mispractice</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*prac"tice</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong practice.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mispraise</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*praise"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To praise amiss.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misprint</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*print"</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s*pr<icr/nt")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To print wrongly; to make a mistake in printing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>misprint</ent><br/
<hw>mis"print</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s"pr<icr/nt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mistake in printing; a deviation from the copy; <as>as, a book full of <ex>misprints</ex></as>.  Misprints are sometimes noted and corrected in a list of <partof>corrigenda</partof> distributed with a book.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misprise</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*prise"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>See <er>Misprize</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misprise</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*prise"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>mesprise</ets> mistake, F. <ets>m<eacute/prise</ets>, fr. <ets>mespris</ets>, masc., <ets>mesprise</ets>, fem., p. p. of <ets>mesprendre</ets> to mistake; F. <ets>m<eacute/prendre</ets>; pref. <ets>mes-</ets> amiss + <ets>prendre</ets> to take, L. <ets>prehendere</ets>.]</ety> <def>To mistake.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misprision</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*pri"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>misprisio</ets>, or OF. <ets>mesprison</ets>, prop., a mistaking, but confused with OF. <ets>mespris</ets> contempt, F. <ets>m<eacute/pris</ets>. See 2d <er>Misprise</er>, <er>Misprize</er>, <er>Prison</er>.]</ety><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of misprising; misapprehension; misconception; mistake.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>  <rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>misprision</qex> of this passage has aided in fostering the delusive notion.</q> <rj><qau>Hare.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Neglect; undervaluing; contempt.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A neglect, negligence, or contempt.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ In its larger and older sense it was used to signify <ldquo/every considerable misdemeanor which has not a certain name given to it in the law.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Russell.</au></rj><br/
<br/
  In a more modern sense it is applied exclusively to two offenses: --<br/
  <b>1.</b> <col><b>Misprision of treason</b></col>, which is omission to notify the authorities of an act of treason by a person cognizant thereof. <au>Stephen.</au><br/
  <b>2.</b> <col><b>Misprision of felony</b></col>, which is a concealment of a felony by a person cognizant thereof.  <rj><au>Stephen.</au></rj></note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 931 --></p>

<p><ent>Misprize</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*prize"</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s*pr<imac/z")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>mesprisier</ets> to deprise, F. <ets>m<eacute/priser</ets>; pref. amiss, wrong (L. <ets>minus</ets> less + LL. <ets>pretium</ets> price. See <er>price</er>, <er>Prize</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <def>To slight or undervalue.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O, for those vanished hours, so much <qex>misprized</qex>!</q> <rj><qau>Hillhouse.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I do not blame them, madam, nor <qex>misprize</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs. Browning.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misproceeding</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`pro*ceed"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong or irregular proceding.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misprofess</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`pro*fess"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make a false profession; to make pretensions to skill which is not possessed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misprofess</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`pro*fess"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make a false profession of.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mispronounce</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`pro*nounce"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mispronounced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mispronouncing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To pronounce incorrectly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mispronunciation</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`pro*nun`ci*a"tion</hw> <pr>(? <or/ ?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong or improper pronunciation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misproportion</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`pro*por"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To give wrong or unesthetic proportions to; to join without due proportion; <as>as, the legs were <ex>misrpoportioned</ex> to the body</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>misproportion</ent><br/
<hw>mis`pro*por"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An improper or unesthetic proportion.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misproud</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*proud"</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Viciously proud.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mispunctuate</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*punc"tu*ate</hw> <pr>(?; 135)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To punctuate wrongly or incorrectly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misquotation</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`quo*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Erroneous or inaccurate quotation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misquote</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*quote"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To quote erroneously or incorrectly.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misraise</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*raise"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To raise or excite unreasonable.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Misraised</xex> fury.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misrate</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*rate"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To rate erroneously.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misread</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*read"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Misread</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Misreading</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To read amiss; to misunderstand in reading.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misreceive</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`re*ceive"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To receive wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misrecital</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`re*cit"al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An inaccurate recital.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misrecite</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`re*cite"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To recite erroneously.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misreckon</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*reck"on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To reckon wrongly; to miscalculate.</def>  <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misreckoning</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*reck"on*ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An erroneous computation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misrecollect</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*rec`ol*lect"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To have an erroneous remembrance of; to suppose erroneously that one recollects.</def>  <rj><au>Hitchcock.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misrecollection</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*rec`ol*lec"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Erroneous or inaccurate recollection.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misreform</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`re*form"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To reform wrongly or imperfectly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misregard</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`re*gard"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong understanding; misconstruction.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misregulate</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*reg"u*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To regulate wrongly or imperfectly; to fail to regulate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misrehearse</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`re*hearse"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To rehearse or quote incorrectly.</def>  <rj><au>Sir T. More.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misrelate</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`re*late"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To relate inaccurately.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misrelation</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`re*la"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Erroneous relation or narration.</def>  <rj><au>Abp. Bramhall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misreligion</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`re*li"gion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>False religion.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misremember</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`re*mem"ber</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To mistake in remembering; not to remember correctly.</def>  <rj><au>Sir T. More.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misrender</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*ren"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To render wrongly; to translate or recite wrongly.</def>  <rj><au>Boyle.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misrepeat</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`re*peat"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To repeat wrongly; to give a wrong version of.</def>  <rj><au>Gov. Winthrop.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misreport</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`re*port"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To report erroneously; to give an incorrect account of.</def>  <rj><au>Locke.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misreport</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`re*port"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An erroneous report; a false or incorrect account given.</def>  <rj><au>Denham. South.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misrepresent</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*rep`re*sent"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To represent incorrectly (almost always, unfavorably); to give a false or erroneous representation of, either maliciously, ignorantly, or carelessly.</def>  <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misrepresent</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*rep`re*sent"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make an incorrect or untrue representation.</def>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misrepresentation</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*rep`re*sen*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Untrue representation; false or incorrect statement or account; -- usually unfavorable to the thing represented; <as>as, a <ex>misrepresentation</ex> of a person's motives</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Sydney Smith.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ In popular use, this word often conveys the idea of intentional untruth.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misrepresentative</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*rep`re*sent"a*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Tending to convey a wrong impression; misrepresenting.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misrepresenter</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*rep`re*sent"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who misrepresents.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misrepute</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`re*pute"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To have in wrong estimation; to repute or estimate erroneously.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misrule</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*rule"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To rule badly; to misgovern.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misrule</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*rule"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act, or the result, of misruling.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Disorder; confusion; tumult from insubordination.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Enormous riot and <qex>misrule</qex> surveyed.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Abbot of Misrule</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Lord of Misrule</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See under <er>Abbot</er>, and <er>Lord</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misruly</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*rul"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Unruly.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miss</ent><br/
<hw>Miss</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Misses</plw> <pr>(m<icr/s"s<ecr/z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Contr. fr. <ets>mistress</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A title of courtesy prefixed to the name of a girl or a woman who has not been married. See <er>Mistress</er>, 5.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ There is diversity of usage in the application of this title to two or more persons of the same name. We may write either <xex>the Miss Browns</xex> or <xex>the Misses Brown</xex>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A young unmarried woman or a girl; <as>as, she is a <ex>miss</ex> of sixteen</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Gay vanity, with smiles and kisses,<br/
Was busy 'mongst the maids and misses.</q> <rj><qau>Cawthorn.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A kept mistress. See <er>Mistress</er>, 4.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Evelyn.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Card Playing)</fld> <def>In the game of three-card loo, an extra hand, dealt on the table, which may be substituted for the hand dealt to a player.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miss</ent><br/
<hw>Miss</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Missed</conjf> <pr>(m<icr/st)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Missing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>missan</ets>; akin to D. & G. <ets>missen</ets>, OHG. <ets>missan</ets>, Icel. <ets>missa</ets>, Sw. <ets>mista</ets>, Dan. <ets>miste</ets>. <root/100. See <er>Mis-</er>, pref.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To fail of hitting, reaching, getting, finding, seeing, hearing, etc.; <as>as, to <ex>miss</ex> the mark one shoots at; to <ex>miss</ex> the train by being late; to <ex>miss</ex> opportunites of getting knowledge; to <ex>miss</ex> the point or meaning of something said.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When a man <qex>misses</qex> his great end, happiness, he will acknowledge he judged not right.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To omit; to fail to have or to do; to get without; to dispense with; -- now seldom applied to persons.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She would never <qex>miss</qex>, one day,<br/
A walk so fine, a sight so gay.</q> <rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We cannot <qex>miss</qex> him; he does make our fire,<br/
Fetch in our wood.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To discover the absence or omission of; to feel the want of; to mourn the loss of; to want; <as>as, to <ex>miss</ex> an absent loved one</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Neither <qex>missed</qex> we anything . . . Nothing was <qex>missed</qex> of all that pertained unto him.</q> <rj><qau>1 Sam. xxv. 15, 21.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What by me thou hast lost, thou least shalt <qex>miss</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To miss stays</b></col>. <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Stay</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miss</ent><br/
<hw>Miss</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To fail to hit; to fly wide; to deviate from the true direction.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men observe when things hit, and not when they <qex>miss</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Flying bullets now,<br/
To execute his rage, appear too slow;<br/
They <qex>miss</qex>, or sweep but common souls away.</q> <rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To fail to obtain, learn, or find; -- with <xex>of</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Upon the least reflection, we can not <qex>miss</qex> of them.</q> <rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To go wrong; to err.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Amongst the angels, a whole legion<br/
Of wicked sprites did fall from happy bliss;<br/
What wonder then if one, of women all, did <qex>miss</qex>?</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To be absent, deficient, or wanting.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <see>See <er>Missing</er>, <pos>a.</pos></see><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What here shall <qex>miss</qex>, our toil shall strive to mend.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miss</ent><br/
<hw>Miss</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of missing; failure to hit, reach, find, obtain, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Loss; want; felt absence.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There will be no great <qex>miss</qex> of those which are lost.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Mistake; error; fault.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He did without any great <qex>miss</qex> in the hardest points of grammar.</q> <rj><qau>Ascham.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Harm from mistake.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missa</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mis"sa</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Missae</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[LL. See 1st <er>Mass</er>.]</ety> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld> <def>The service or sacrifice of the Mass.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missal</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"sal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>missale</ets>, liber <ets>missalis</ets>, from <ets>missa</ets> mass: cf. F. <ets>missel</ets>. See 1st <er>Mass</er>.]</ety> <def>The book containing the service of the Mass for the entire year; a Mass book.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missal</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"sal</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the Mass, or to a missal or Mass book.</def>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missay</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*say"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To say wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To speak evil of; to slander.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missay</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*say"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To speak ill.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misseek</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*seek"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To seek for wrongly.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misseem</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*seem"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make a false appearance.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To misbecome; to be misbecoming.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missel</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"sel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mistletoe.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Missel bird</b></col>, <col><b>Missel thrush</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a large European thrush (<spn>Turdus viscivorus</spn>) which feeds on the berries of the mistletoe; -- called also <altname>mistletoe thrush</altname> and <altname>missel</altname>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misseldine</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"sel*dine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mistletoe</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also <asp>misselden</asp>.]</altsp> <def>The mistletoe.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Baret.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misseltoe</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"sel*toe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mistletoe</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missemblance</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*sem"blance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>False resemblance or semblance.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missend</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*send"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To send amiss or incorrectly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misserve</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*serve"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To serve unfaithfully.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misset</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*set"</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s*s<ecr/t")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To set or place wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misshape</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*shape"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To shape ill; to give an ill or unnatural from to; to deform.</def> <ldquo/Figures monstrous and <xex>misshaped</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misshapen</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*shap"en</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having a bad or ugly form.</def> <ldquo/The mountains are <xex>misshapen</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Bentley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Mis*shap"en*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mis*shap"en*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missheathed</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*sheathed"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Sheathed by mistake; wrongly sheathed; sheathed in a wrong place.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missificate</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*sif"i*cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>missa</ets> Mass + <ets>-ficare</ets> (in comp.) to make. See <er>fy-</er>.]</ety> <def>To perform Mass.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missile</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"sile</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>missils</ets>, fr. <ets>mittere</ets>, <ets>missum</ets>, to cause to go, to send, to throw; cf. Lith. <ets>mesti</ets> to throw: cf. F. <ets>missile</ets>.  Cf. <er>Admit</er>, <er>Dismiss</er>, <er>Mass</er> the religious service, <er>Message</er>, <er>Mission</er>.]</ety> <def>Capable of being thrown; adapted for hurling or to be projected from the hand, or from any instrument or engine{2}, so as to strike an object at a distance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We bend the bow, or wing the <qex>missile</qex> dart.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missile</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"sile</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>missile</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A weapon thrown or projected or intended to be projected, as a lance, an arrow, or a bullet.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A rocket-propelled device designed to fly through the air and deliver a warhead of explosive materials to a target.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note>Numerous types of rocket-propelled missile{2} are now used in modern warfare.  Some types with names indicating their range or function are: <stype>antiaircraft missile</stype>; <stype>ballistic missile</stype>; <stype>cruise missile</stype>; <stype>antiballistic missile missile</stype>; <stype>air-to-air missile</stype>; <stype>air-to-ground missile</stype>; <stype>guided missile</stype>; <stype>intercontinental ballistic missile</stype> (<abbr>IBM</abbr>); <stype>intermediate range ballistic missile</stype> (<abbr>IRBM</abbr>); <stype>surface-to-air missile</stype>.</note></p>

<p><ent>Missing</ent><br/
<hw>Miss"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Miss</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <def>Absent from the place where it was expected to be found; lost; lacking; wanting; not present when called or looked for.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Neither was there aught <qex>missing</qex> unto them.</q> <rj><qau>1 Sam. xxv. 7.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For a time caught up to God, as once<br/
Moses was in the mount, and <qex>missing</qex> long.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missingly</ent><br/
<hw>Miss"ing*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>With a sense of loss.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mission</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>missio</ets>, fr. <ets>mittere</ets>, <ets>missum</ets>, to send: cf. F. <ets>mission</ets>. See <er>Missile</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of sending, or the state of being sent; a being sent or delegated by authority, with certain powers for transacting business; comission.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whose glorious deeds, but in these fields of late,<br/
Made emulous <qex>missions</qex> 'mongst the gods themselves.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That with which a messenger or agent is charged; an errand; business or duty on which one is sent; a commission.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How to begin, how to accomplish best<br/
His end of being on earth, and <qex>mission</qex> high.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Persons sent; any number of persons appointed to perform any service; a delegation; an embassy; <as>as, the Russian <ex>mission</ex> to the United Nations</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>In these ships there should be a <qex>mission</qex> of three of the fellows or brethren of Solomon's house.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An assotiation or organization of missionaries; a station or residence of missionaries.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>An organization for worship and work, dependent on one or more churches.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A course of extraordinary sermons and services at a particular place and time for the special purpose of quickening the faith and zeal participants, and of converting unbelievers.</def>  <rj><au>Addis & Arnold.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Dismission; discharge from service.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mission school</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A school connected with a mission and conducted by missionaries</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A school for the religious instruction of children not having regular church privileges.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Message; errand; commission; deputation.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mission</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To send on a mission.</def> <mark>[Mostly used in the form of the past participle.]</mark>  <rj><au>Keats.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missionary</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"sion*ary</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Missionaries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>missionnaire</ets>. See <er>Mission</er>, <pos>n</pos>.]</ety> <def>One who is sent on a mission; especially, one sent to propagate religion.</def>  <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Missionary apostolic</b></col>, <cd>a Roman Catholic missionary sent by commission from the pope.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missionary</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"sion*a*ry</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to missions; <as>as, a <ex>missionary</ex> meeting; a <ex>missionary</ex> fund.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missioner</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"sion*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A missionary; an envoy; one who conducts a mission. See <er>Mission</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 6.</def> <ldquo/Like mighty <xex>missioner</xex> you come.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missis</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mistress; a wife; -- so used by the illiterate.</def>  <rj><au>G. Eliot.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missish</ent><br/
<hw>Miss"ish</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Like a miss; prim; affected; sentimental.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Miss"ish*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mississippian</ent><br/
<hw>Mississippian</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A geological period extending from from 310 million to 345 million years ago; it was associated with an increase of land areas, the presence of primitive ammonites, and emergence of winged insects; called also <altname>Missippian period</altname> and <altname>Lower Carboniferous period</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Missippian period, Lower Carboniferous, Lower Carboniferous period.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A resident of Mississippi.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missit</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*sit"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To sit badly or imperfectly upon; to misbecome.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missive</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"sive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Missive</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Specially sent; intended or prepared to be sent; <as>as, a letter <ex>missive</ex></as>.</def>  <rj><au>Ayliffe.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Missile.</def> <ldquo/The <xex>missive</xex> weapons fly.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Letters missive</b></col>, <cd>letters conveying the permission, comand, or advice of a superior authority, as a sovereign. They are addressed and sent to some certain person or persons, and are distinguished from <xex>letters patent</xex>, which are addressed to the public.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missive</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"sive</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. lettre <ets>missive</ets>. See <er>Mission</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is sent; a writing containing a message.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who is sent; a messenger.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missound</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*sound"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To sound wrongly; to utter or pronounce incorrectly.</def>  <rj><au>E,Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missourian</ent><br/
<hw>Missourian</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A resident of Missouri.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misspeak</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*speak"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To err in speaking.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misspeak</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*speak"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To utter wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misspeech</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*speech"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong speech.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misspell</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*spell"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Misspelled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>, or <conjf>Misspelt</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Misspelling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To spell incorrectly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misspelling</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*spell"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A wrong spelling.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misspend</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*spend"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Misspent</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Misspending</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To spend amiss or for wrong purposes; to squander; to waste; <as>as, to <ex>misspend</ex> time or money</as>.</def>  <rj><au>J. Philips.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misspender</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*spend"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who misspends.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>misspense</ent><br/
<hw>mis*spense"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A spending improperly; a wasting.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Barrow.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misspent</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*spent"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <def><pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> of <er>Misspend</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misstate</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*state"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To state wrongly; <as>as, to <ex>misstate</ex> a question in debate</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Bp. Sanderson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misstatement</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*state"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An incorrect statement.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misstayed</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*stayed"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>Having missed stays; -- said of a ship.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misstep</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*step"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A wrong step; an error of conduct.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misstep</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*step"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To take a wrong step; to go astray.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missuccess</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`suc*cess"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Failure.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missuggestion</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`sug*ges"tion</hw> <pr>(? <or/ ?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong or evil suggestion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missummation</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`sum*ma"tion</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong summation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misswear</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*swear"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To swear falsely.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missy</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"sy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>See <er>Misy</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Missy</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"sy</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An affectionate, or contemptuous, form of <xex>miss</xex>; a young girl; a miss.</def> -- <def2><pos>a.</pos> <def>Like a miss, or girl.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mist</ent><br/
<hw>mist</hw> <pr>(m<icr/st)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>mist</ets>; akin to D. & Sw. <ets>mist</ets>, Icel. <ets>mistr</ets>, G. <ets>mist</ets> dung, Goth. <ets>ma<iacute/hstus</ets>, AS. <ets>m<imac/gan</ets> to make water, Icel. <ets>m<imac/ga</ets>, Lith. <ets>migla</ets> mist, Russ. <ets>mgla</ets>, L. <ets>mingere</ets>, <ets>meiere</ets>, to make water, Gr. <grk>'omichei^n</grk> to make water, <grk>'omi`chlh</grk> mist, Skr. <ets>mih</ets> to make water, n., a mist <ets>m<emac/gha</ets> cloud.  <root/102.  Cf. <er>Misle</er>, <er>Mizzle</er>, <er>Mixen</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Visible watery vapor suspended in the atmosphere, at or near the surface of the earth; fog.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Coarse, watery vapor, floating or falling in visible particles, approaching the form of rain; <as>as, Scotch <ex>mist</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence, anything which dims or darkens, and obscures or intercepts vision.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His passion cast a <qex>mist</qex> before his sense.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mist flower</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a composite plant (<spn>Eupatorium coelestinum</spn>), having heart-shaped leaves, and corymbs of lavender-blue flowers.  It is found in the Western and Southern United States.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mist</ent><br/
<hw>Mist</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Misted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Misting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To cloud; to cover with mist; to dim.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mist</ent><br/
<hw>Mist</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To rain in very fine drops; <as>as, it <ex>mists</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistakable</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*tak"a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Liable to be mistaken; capable of being misconceived.</def>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistake</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*take"</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s*t<amac/k")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & obs. p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mistook</conjf> <pr>(m<icr/s*t<oocr/k")</pr>; <pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mistaken</conjf> <pr>(m<icr/s*t<amac/k"'n)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mistaking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Pref. <ets>mis-</ets> + <ets>take</ets>: cf. Icel. <ets>mistaka</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To take or choose wrongly.</def> <mark>[Obs. or R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To take in a wrong sense; to misunderstand misapprehend, or misconceive; <as>as, to <ex>mistake</ex> a remark; to <ex>mistake</ex> one's meaning.</as></def>  <rj><au>Locke.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My father's purposes have been <qex>mistook</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To substitute in thought or perception; <as>as, to <ex>mistake</ex> one person for another</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A man may <qex>mistake</qex> the love of virtue for the practice of it.</q> <rj><qau>Johnson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To have a wrong idea of in respect of character, qualities, etc.; to misjudge.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mistake</qex> me not so much,<br/
To think my poverty is treacherous.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistake</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*take"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To err in knowledge, perception, opinion, or judgment; to commit an unintentional error.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Servants <qex>mistake</qex>, and sometimes occasion misunderstanding among friends.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 932 --></p>

<p><ent>Mistake</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*take"</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s*t<amac/k")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An apprehending wrongly; a misconception; a misunderstanding; a fault in opinion or judgment; an unintentional error of conduct.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Infallibility is an absolute security of the understanding from all possibility of <qex>mistake</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Misconception, error, which when non-negligent may be ground for rescinding a contract, or for refusing to perform it.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>No mistake</b></col>, <cd>surely; without fail; <as>as, it will happen at the appointed time, and <ex>no mistake</ex></as>.</cd> <mark>[Low]</mark></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Blunder; error; bull. See <er>Blunder</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistaken</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*tak"en</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>p.a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Being in error; judging wrongly; having a wrong opinion or a misconception; <as>as, a <ex>mistaken</ex> man; he is <ex>mistaken</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Erroneous; wrong; <as>as, a <ex>mistaken</ex> notion</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistakenly</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*tak"en*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>By mistake.</def>  <rj><au>Goldsmith.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistakenness</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*tak"en*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Erroneousness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistaker</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*tak"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who mistakes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Well meaning ignorance of some <qex>mistakers</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Hall.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistaking</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*tak"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An error; a mistake.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistakingly</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*tak"ing*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Erroneously.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistaught</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*taught"</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s*t<add/t")</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Misteach</er>.]</ety> <def>Wrongly taught; <as>as, a <ex>mistaught</ex> youth</as>.</def>  <rj><au>L'Estrange.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misteach</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*teach"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mistaught</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Misteaching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>mist<aemac/can</ets>.]</ety> <def>To teach wrongly; to instruct erroneously.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistell</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*tell"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mistold</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mistelling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To tell erroneously.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistemper</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*tem"per</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To temper ill; to disorder; <as>as, to <ex>mistemper</ex> one's head</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Warner.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This inundation of <qex>mistempered</qex> humor.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mister</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Master</er>, and cf. <er>Mistress</er>.]</ety> <def>A title of courtesy prefixed to the name of a man or youth. It is usually written in the abbreviated form <abbr>Mr.</abbr></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To call your name, inquire your where,<br/
Or what you think of <qex>Mister</qex> Some-one's book,<br/
Or <qex>Mister</qex> Other's marriage or decease.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs. Browning.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mister</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"ter</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To address or mention by the title Mr.; <as>as, he <ex>mistered</ex> me in a formal way</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mister</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"ter</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>mistier</ets> trade, office, ministry, need, F. <ets>m<eacute/tier</ets> trade, fr. L. <ets>ministerium</ets> service, office, ministry. See <er>Ministry</er>, <er>Mystery</er> trade.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mester</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A trade, art, or occupation.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In youth he learned had a good <qex>mester</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Manner; kind; sort.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But telleth me what <qex>mester</qex> men ye be.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Need; necessity.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Rom. of R.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mister</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"ter</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be needful or of use.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As for my name, it <qex>mistereth</qex> not to tell.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misterm</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*term"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To call by a wrong name; to miscall.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistery</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"ter*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mystery</er>, a trade.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistful</ent><br/
<hw>Mist"ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Clouded with, or as with, mist.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misthink</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*think"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Think</er>.]</ety> <def>To think wrongly.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/Adam <xex>misthought</xex> of her.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misthink</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*think"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To have erroneous thoughts or judgment of; to think ill of.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misthought</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*thought"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Erroneous thought; mistaken opinion; error.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misthrive</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*thrive"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To thrive poorly; to be not thrifty or prosperous.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misthrow</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*throw"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To throw wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistico</ent><br/
<ent>Mistic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mis"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mis"ti*co</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>m<iacute/stico</ets>.]</ety> <def>A kind of small sailing vessel used in the Mediterranean.  It is rigged partly like a xebec, and partly like a felucca.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistide</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*tide"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>mist<imac/dan</ets>. See <er>Tide</er>.]</ety> <def>To happen or come to pass unfortunately; also, to suffer evil fortune.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistigri</ent><br/
<ent>Mistigris</ent><br/
<mhw>{ \'d8<hw>Mis`ti`gris"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, \'d8<hw>Mis`ti`gri"</hw>  }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mistigri</ets>.]</ety> <def>A variety of the game of poker in which the joker is used, and called <xex>mistigris</xex> or <xex>mistigri</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistihead</ent><br/
<hw>Mist"i*head</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mistiness.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistily</ent><br/
<hw>Mist"i*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>With mist; darkly; obscurely.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistime</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*time"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>mist<imac/main</ets> to turn out ill.]</ety> <def>To time wrongly; not to adapt to the time.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mistiming</ent><br/
<hw>mistiming</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act or process of assigning something to a time when it could not have existed or occurred.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> anachronism, misdating.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistiness</ent><br/
<hw>Mist"i*ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>State of being misty.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistion</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mistio</ets>, <ets>mixtio</ets>. See <er>Mix</er>, and cf. <er>Mixtion</er>.]</ety> <def>Mixture.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistitle</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*ti"tle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To call by a wrong title.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistle</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"tle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Eng. <ets>mist</ets>. See <er>Misle</er>, and <er>Mizzle</er>.]</ety> <def>To fall in very fine drops, as rain; to drizzle.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistletoe</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"tle*toe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>mistelt<amac/n</ets>; <ets>mistel</ets> mistletoe + <ets>t<amac/n</ets> twig. AS. <ets>mistel</ets> is akin of D., G., Dan. & Sw. <ets>mistel</ets>, OHG. <ets>mistil</ets>, Icel. <ets>mistil</ets>teinn; and AS. <ets>t<amac/n</ets> to D. <ets>teen</ets>, OHG. <ets>zein</ets>, Icel. <ets>teinn</ets>, Goth. <ets>tains</ets>.  Cf. <er>Missel</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A parasitic evergreen plant of Europe (<spn>Viscum album</spn>), bearing a glutinous fruit.  When found upon the oak, where it is rare, it was an object of superstitious regard among the Druids.  A bird lime is prepared from its fruit.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>misletoe</asp>, <asp>misseltoe</asp>, and <asp>mistleto</asp>.]</altsp>  <rj><au>Lindley.</au>  <au>Loudon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The mistletoe of the United States is <spn>Phoradendron serotinum</spn> (syn. <spn>Phoradendron flavescens</spn>), having broader leaves than the European kind.  In different regions various similar plants are called by this name.  The mistletoe is used as a decoration at Christmas time, and it is a tradition that two persons of the oposite sex finding each other under a mistletoe sprig should kiss.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistonusk</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mis"to*nusk</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From the Indian name.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The American badger.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistook</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*took"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <def><pos>imp. & obs. p. p.</pos> of <er>Mistake</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistradition</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`tra*di"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A wrong tradition.</def> <ldquo/Monsters of <xex>mistradition</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistrain</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*train"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To train amiss.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistral</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"tral</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. Proven<cced/al.]</ety> <def>A violent and cold northwest wind experienced in the Mediterranean provinces of France, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistranslate</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`trans*late"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To translate erroneously.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistranslation</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`trans*la"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong translation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistransport</ent><br/
<hw>Mis`trans*port"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To carry away or mislead wrongfully, as by passion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistreading</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*tread"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Misstep; misbehavior.</def> <ldquo/To punish my <xex>mistreadings</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistreat</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*treat"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To treat amiss; to abuse.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mistreated</ent><br/
<hw>mistreated</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>physically abused.</def> [Narrower terms: <stype>assaulted, molested, raped</stype>; <stype>battered, beaten</stype>; <stype>misunderstood </stype>]<br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> abused, ill-treated, maltreated.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistreatment</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*treat"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong treatment.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistress</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"tress</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>maistress</ets>, OF. <ets>maistresse</ets>, F. <ets>ma<icir/tresse</ets>, LL. <ets>magistrissa</ets>, for L. <ets>magistra</ets>, fem. of <ets>magister</ets>. See <er>Master</er>, <er>Mister</er>, and cf. <er>Miss</er> a young woman.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A woman having power, authority, or ownership; a woman who exercises authority, is chief, etc.; the female head of a family, a school, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The late queen's gentlewoman! a knight's daughter!<br/
To be her <qex>mistress</qex>' <qex>mistress</qex>!</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A woman well skilled in anything, or having the mastery over it.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A letter desires all young wives to make themselves <qex>mistresses</qex> of Wingate's Arithmetic.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A woman regarded with love and devotion; she who has command over one's heart; a beloved object; a sweetheart.</def> <mark>[Poetic]</mark>  <rj><au>Clarendon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A woman filling the place, but without the rights, of a wife; a woman having an ongoing usually exclusive sexual relationship with a man, who may provide her with financial support in return; a concubine; a loose woman with whom one consorts habitually; <as>as, both his wife and his <ex>mistress</ex> attended his funeral</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Spectator.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A title of courtesy formerly prefixed to the name of a woman, married or unmarried, but now superseded by the contracted forms, <abbr>Mrs.</abbr>, for a married, and <abbr>Miss</abbr>, for an unmarried, woman.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now <qex>Mistress</qex> Gilpin (careful soul).</q> <rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A married woman; a wife.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Several of the neighboring <qex>mistresses</qex> had assembled to witness the event of this memorable evening.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>The old name of the jack at bowls.</def>  <rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To be one's own mistress</b></col>, <cd>to be exempt from control by another person.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistress</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"tress</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To wait upon a mistress; to be courting.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Donne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistressship</ent><br/
<hw>Mis"tress*ship</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Female rule or dominion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Ladyship, a style of address; -- with the personal pronoun.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Massinger.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistrial</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*tri"al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A false or erroneous trial; a trial which has no result; a trial which comes to no conclusion, such as a criminal trial which does not produce a unanimous verdict of the jurors.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistrist</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*trist"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To mistrust.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistrow</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*trow"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To think wrongly.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistrust</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*trust"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Want of confidence or trust; suspicion; distrust.</def>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistrust</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*trust"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To regard with jealousy or suspicion; to suspect; to doubt the integrity of; to distrust.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will never <qex>mistrust</qex> my wife again.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To forebode as near, or likely to occur; to surmise.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By a divine instinct, men's minds <qex>mistrust</qex><br/
Ensuing dangers.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistruster</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*trust"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who mistrusts.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistrustful</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*trust"ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having or causing mistrust, suspicions, or forebodings.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their light blown out in some <qex>mistrustful</qex> wood.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Mis*trust"ful*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mis*trust"ful*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistrustingly</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*trust"ing*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>With distrust or suspicion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistrustless</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*trust"less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having no mistrust or suspicion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The swain <qex>mistrustless</qex> of his smutted face.</q> <rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistune</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*tune"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To tune wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistura</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mis*tu"ra</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. See <er>Mixture</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A mingled compound in which different ingredients are contained in a liquid state; a mixture. See <er>Mixture</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 4.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Sometimes, a liquid medicine containing very active substances, and which can only be administered by drops.</def>  <rj><au>Dunglison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misturn</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*turn"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To turn amiss; to pervert.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistutor</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*tu"tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To instruct amiss.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misty</ent><br/
<hw>Mist"y</hw> <pr>(m<icr/st"<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Mistier</adjf> <pr>(m<icr/st"<icr/*<etil/r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Mistiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>mistig</ets>. See <er>Mist</er>. In some senses <ets>misty</ets> has been confused with <ets>mystic</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Accompanied with mist; characterized by the presence of mist; obscured by, or overspread with, mist; <as>as, a <ex>misty</ex> morning; <ex>misty</ex> weather; <ex>misty</ex> mountains; a <ex>misty</ex> atmosphere.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Obscured as if by mist; dim; obscure; clouded; <as>as, <ex>misty</ex> sight; to peer into the <ex>misty</ex> future</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The more I muse therein [theology],<br/
The <qex>mistier</qex> it seemeth.</q> <rj><qau>Piers Plowman.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misunderstand</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*un`der*stand"</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s*<ucr/n`d<etil/r*st<acr/nd")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Misunderstood</conjf> <pr>(m<icr/s*<ucr/n`d<etil/r*st<oocr/d")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Misunderstanding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To misconceive; to mistake; to miscomprehend; to take in a wrong sense.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misunderstander</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*un`der*stand"er</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s*<ucr/n`d<etil/r*st<acr/nd"<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who misunderstands.</def>  <rj><au>Sir T. More.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misunderstanding</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*un`der*stand"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Mistake of the meaning; error; misconception.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Disagreement; difference of opinion; dissension; quarrel.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Misunderstandings</xex> among friends.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misurato</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mi`su*ra"to</hw> <pr>(m<emac/`s<oomac/*r<aum/"t<osl/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[It.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Measured; -- a direction to perform a passage in strict or measured time.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misusage</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*us"age</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s*<umac/z"<asl/j)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>m<eacute/susage</ets>.]</ety> <def>Bad treatment; abuse.</def>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misuse</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*use"</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s*<umac/z")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/suser</ets>. See <er>Mis-</er>, prefix from French, and <er>Use</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To treat or use improperly; to use to a bad purpose; to misapply; <as>as, to <ex>misuse</ex> one's talents</as>.</def>  <rj><au>South.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sweet poison of <qex>misused</qex> wine.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To abuse; to treat ill.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O, she <qex>misused</qex> me past the endurance of a block.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To maltreat; abuse; misemploy; misapply.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misuse</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*use"</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s*<umac/s")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Wrong use; misapplication; erroneous or improper use.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Words little suspected for any such <qex>misuse</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Violence, or its effects.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misusement</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*use"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Misuse.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misuser</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*us"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who misuses.</def> <ldquo/Wretched <xex>misusers</xex> of language.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Coleridge.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Unlawful use of a right; use in excess of, or varying from, one's right.</def>  <rj><au>Bouvier.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misvalue</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*val"ue</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To value wrongly or too little; to undervalue.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But for I am so young, I dread my work<br/
Wot be <qex>misvalued</qex> both of old and young.</q> <rj><qau>W. Browne.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misvouch</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*vouch"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To vouch falsely.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miswander</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*wan"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To wander in a wrong path; to stray; to go astray.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misway</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*way"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A wrong way.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miswear</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*wear"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To wear ill.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miswed</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*wed"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To wed improperly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misween</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*ween"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To ween amiss; to misjudge; to distrust; to be mistaken.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miswend</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*wend"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To go wrong; to go astray.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/The world is <xex>miswent</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Gower.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misword</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*word"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To word wrongly; <as>as, to <ex>misword</ex> a message, or a sentence</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misword</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*word"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A word wrongly spoken; a cross word.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sylvester.</au>  <au>Breton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misworship</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*wor"ship</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Wrong or false worship; mistaken practices in religion.</def>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such hideous jungle of <qex>misworships</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Carlyle.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misworship</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*wor"ship</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To worship wrongly.</def>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misworshiper</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*wor"ship*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who worships wrongly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miswrite</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*write"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To write incorrectly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miswrought</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*wrought"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Badly wrought.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misy</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"sy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. L. <ets>misy</ets> a mineral, perh. copperas, Gr. <?/.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>An impure yellow sulphate of iron; yellow copperas or copiapite.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misyoke</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*yoke"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To yoke improperly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miszealous</ent><br/
<hw>Mis*zeal"ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Mistakenly zealous.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mite</ent><br/
<hw>Mite</hw> <pr>(m<imac/t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<imac/te</ets> mite (in sense 1); akin to LG. <ets>mite</ets>, D. <ets>mijt</ets>, G. <ets>miete</ets>, OHG. <ets>m<imac/za</ets>; cf. Goth. <ets>maitan</ets> to cut.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A minute arachnid, of the order <ord>Acarina</ord>, of which there are many species; <as>as, the <styp>dust <ex>mite</ex></styp>, <styp>cheese <ex>mite</ex></styp>, <styp>sugar <ex>mite</ex></styp>, <styp>harvest <ex>mite</ex></styp>, <styp>three-toed spider <ex>mite</ex></styp>, etc.</as> See <er>Acarina</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[D. <ets>mijt</ets>; prob. the same word.]</ety> <def>A small coin formerly circulated in England, rated at about a third of a farthing.  The name is also applied to a small coin used in Palestine in the time of Christ.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Two <qex>mites</qex>, which make a farthing.</q> <rj><qau>Mark xii. 49.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A small weight; one twentieth of a grain.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Anything very small; a minute object; a very little quantity or particle.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For in effect they be not worth a <qex>myte</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitella</ent><br/
<hw>Mitella</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of low slender herbs of North America and Northeast Asia having flowers with trifid or pinnatifid petals.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Mitella</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitre</ent><br/
<ent>Miter</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mi"ter</hw>, <hw>Mi"tre</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mitre</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mitra</ets> headband, turban, Gr. <?/.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A covering for the head, worn on solemn occasions by bishops and other church dignitaries.  It has been made in many forms, the present form being a lofty cap with two points or peaks.</def>  <rj><au>Fairholt.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The surface forming the beveled end or edge of a piece where a miter joint is made; also, a joint formed or a junction effected by two beveled ends or edges; a miter joint.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Numis.)</fld> <def>A sort of base money or coin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Miter box</b></col> <fld>(Carp. & Print.)</fld>, <cd>an apparatus for guiding a handsaw at the proper angle in making a miter joint; esp., a wooden or metal trough with vertical kerfs in its upright sides, for guides.</cd> -- <col><b>Miter dovetail</b></col> <fld>(Carp.)</fld>, <cd>a kind of dovetail for a miter joint in which there is only one joint line visible, and that at the angle.</cd> -- <col><b>Miter gauge</b></col> <fld>(Carp.)</fld>, <cd>a gauge for determining the angle of a miter.</cd> -- <col><b>Miter joint</b></col>, <cd>a joint formed by pieces matched and united upon a line bisecting the angle of junction, as by the beveled ends of two pieces of molding or brass rule, etc.  The term is used especially when the pieces form a right angle, such as the edges of a window frame, and the edge of each piece at the point of junction is cut at a 45<deg/ angle to its long direction.  See <er>Miter</er>, 2.</cd> -- <col><b>Miter shell</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one of numerous species of marine univalve shells of the genus <gen>Mitra</gen>.</cd> -- <col><b>Miter square</b></col> <fld>(Carp.)</fld>, <cd>a bevel with an immovable arm at an angle of 45<deg/, for striking lines on stuff to be mitered; also, a square with an arm adjustable to any angle.</cd> -- <col><b>Miter wheels</b></col>, <cd>a pair of bevel gears, of equal diameter, adapted for working together, usually with their axes at right angles.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitre</ent><br/
<ent>Miter</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mi"ter</hw>, <hw>Mi"tre</hw>  }</mhw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mitered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or <conjf>Mitred</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mitering</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or <conjf>Mitring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To place a miter upon; to adorn with a miter.</def> <wns>[wns=2]</wns>  <ldquo/<xex>Mitered</xex> locks.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To match together, as two pieces of molding or brass rule on a line bisecting the angle of junction; to fit together in a miter joint.</def> <wns>[wns=3]</wns><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To bevel the ends or edges of, for the purpose of matching together at an angle.</def> <wns>[wns=1]</wns><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitre</ent><br/
<ent>Miter</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mi"ter</hw>, <hw>Mi"tre</hw>  }</mhw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To meet and match together, as two pieces of molding, on a line bisecting the angle of junction.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miterwort</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"ter*wort`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Any plant of the genus <gen>Mitella</gen>, -- slender, perennial herbs with a pod slightly resembling a bishop's miter; bishop's cap.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>False miterwort</b></col>, <cd>a white-flowered perennial herb of the United States (<spn>Tiarella cardifolia</spn>).</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mithic</ent><br/
<hw>Mith"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>See <er>Mythic</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mithras</ent><br/
<ent>Mithra</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Mi"thra</hw>, <hw>Mi"thras</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[L., from Gr. <?/.]</ety> <def>The sun god of the ancient Persians; the god of light and truth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mithraistic</ent><br/
<ent>mithraic</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mithraic</hw> <hw>mithraistic</hw></mhw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to Mithraism.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mithraicism</ent><br/
<hw>Mithraicism</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>Mithraism.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> .</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mithraism</ent><br/
<hw>Mithraism</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The ancient Persian religion which worshiped <persfn>Mithra</persfn>; it was popular among Romans during first three centuries <sc>a. d.</sc></def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Mithraicism.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mithraist</ent><br/
<hw>Mithraist</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>An adherent of Mithraism.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mithridate</ent><br/
<hw>Mith"ri*date</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>An antidote against poison, or a composition in form of an electuary, supposed to serve either as a remedy or a preservative against poison; an alexipharmic; -- so called from <person>King <etsep>Mithridates</etsep></person>, its reputed inventor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Love is] a drop of the true elixir; no <qex>mithridate</qex> so effectual against the infection of vice.</q> <rj><qau>Southey.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 933 --></p>

<p><ent>Mithridatic</ent><br/
<hw>Mith`ri*dat"ic</hw> <pr>(m<icr/th`r<icr/*d<acr/t"<icr/k)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to King Mithridates, or to a mithridate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitigable</ent><br/
<hw>Mit"i*ga*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Admitting of mitigation; that may be mitigated.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitigant</ent><br/
<hw>Mit"i*gant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mitigans</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>mitigare</ets>. See <er>Mitigate</er>.]</ety> <def>Tending to mitigate; mitigating; lenitive.</def>  <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitigate</ent><br/
<hw>Mit"i*gate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mitigated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mitigating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>mitigatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>mitigare</ets> to soften, mitigate; <ets>mitis</ets> mild, soft + the root of <ets>agere</ets> to do, drive.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make less severe, intense, harsh, rigorous, painful, etc.; to soften; to meliorate; to alleviate; to diminish; to lessen; <as>as, to <ex>mitigate</ex> heat or cold; to <ex>mitigate</ex> grief.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make mild and accessible; to mollify; -- applied to persons.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This opinion . . . <qex>mitigated</qex> kings into companions.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To alleviate; assuage; allay. See <er>Alleviate</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mitigated</ent><br/
<hw>mitigated</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>made less severe or intense.</def> <ant>unmitigated</ant><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mitigating</ent><br/
<hw>mitigating</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>serving to reduce blame; -- of situations; <as>as, <ex>mitigating</ex> factors; <ex>mitigating</ex> circumstances</as>.  Opposite of <ant>aggravating</ant>.</def> [Narrower terms: <stype>exculpatory</stype>]<br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> extenuating.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitigation</ent><br/
<hw>Mit`i*ga"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mitigacioun</ets>, F. <ets>mitigation</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mitigatio</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act of mitigating, or the state of being mitigated; abatement or diminution of anything painful, harsh, severe, afflictive, or calamitous; <as>as, the <ex>mitigation</ex> of pain, grief, rigor, severity, punishment, or penalty</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Alleviation; abatement; relief.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitigative</ent><br/
<hw>Mit"i*ga*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mitigativus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mitigatif</ets>.]</ety> <def>Tending to mitigate; alleviating.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitigator</ent><br/
<hw>Mit"i*ga`tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who, or that which, mitigates.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitigatory</ent><br/
<hw>Mit"i*ga*to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Tending to mitigate or alleviate; mitigative.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miting</ent><br/
<hw>Mit"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mite</er>.]</ety> <def>A little one; -- used as a term of endearment.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Skelton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitis casting</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"tis cast`ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[Perh. fr. L. <ets>mitis</ets> mild.]</ety> <def>A process, invented by <person>P. Ostberg</person>, for producing malleable iron castings by melting wrought iron, to which from 0.05 to 0.1 per cent of aluminum is added to lower the melting point, usually in a petroleum furnace, keeping the molten metal at the bubbling point until it becomes quiet, and then pouring the molten metal into a mold lined with a special mixture consisting essentially of molasses and ground burnt fire clay; also, a casting made by this process; -- called also <altname>wrought-iron casting</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitis metal</ent><br/
<hw>Mitis metal</hw>. <def>The malleable iron produced by mitis casting; -- called also simply <altname>mitis</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitome</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"tome</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ a thread.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The denser part of the protoplasm of a cell.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark> <br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitosis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mi*to"sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ a thread.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>See <er>Karyokinesis</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitotic</ent><br/
<hw>Mi*tot"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to mitosis; karyokinetic; <as>as, <ex>mitotic</ex> cell division</as>; -- opposed to <ant>amitotic</ant>.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mi*tot"ic*al*ly</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitraille</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mi`traille"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. See <er>Mitrailleur</er>.]</ety> <def>Shot or bits of iron used sometimes in loading cannon.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitrailleur</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mi`tra`illeur"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>One who serves a mitrailleuse.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A mitralleuse.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitrailleuse</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mi`tra`illeuse"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>mitrailler</ets> to fire grapeshot, fr. <ets>mitraille</ets> old iron, grapeshot, dim. of OF. <ets>mite</ets> a mite.]</ety> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A breech-loading machine gun consisting of a number of barrels fitted together, so arranged that the barrels can be fired simultaneously, or successively, and rapidly.</def> <mark>[obsolescent]</mark> <br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitral</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"tral</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mitral</ets>. See <er>Miter</er>.]</ety> <def>Pertaining to a miter; resembling a miter; <as>as, the <ex>mitral</ex> valve between the left auricle and left ventricle of the heart</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitre</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"tre</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. & v.</pos> <def>See <er>Miter</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mitrewort</ent><br/
<hw>mitrewort</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Any of various rhizomatous perennial herbs of the genus <gen>Mitella</gen> having a capsule resembling a bishop's miter.</def> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>miterwort</asp>.]</altsp><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> miterwort, bishop's cap.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitriform</ent><br/
<hw>Mit"ri*form</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Miter</ets> + <ets>-form</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mitriforme</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having the form of a miter, or a peaked cap; <as>as, a <ex>mitriform</ex> calyptra</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Gray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitt</ent><br/
<hw>Mitt</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Abbrev. fr. <ets>mitten</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A mitten; also, a covering for the wrist and hand and not for the fingers, usually worn by women.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Baseball)</fld> <def>A large glove, usually made of leather or similar material, with differing degrees of padding and usually some form of webbing in the large space between the thumb insert and the insert for the index finger; a baseball glove.  It is used to assist in catching the baseball.  The <styp>catcher's <ex>mitt</ex></styp> has more padding and less webbing.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A hand; -- used mostly in slang expressions; <as>as, keep your <ex>mitts</ex> off my box of chocolates!</as></def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitten</ent><br/
<hw>Mit"ten</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mitaine</ets>, <ets>meteyn</ets>, F. <ets>mitaine</ets>, perh. of Celtic origin; cf. Ir. <ets>miotog</ets>, Gael. <ets>miotag</ets>, Ir. & Gael. <ets>mutan</ets> a muff, a thick glove.  Cf. <er>Mitt</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A covering for the hand, worn to defend it from cold or injury.  It differs from a glove in not having a separate sheath for each finger.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A cover for the wrist and forearm.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To give the mitten to</b></col>, <cd>to dismiss as a lover; to reject the suit of.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> -- <col><b>To handle without mittens</b></col>, <cd>to treat roughly; to handle without gloves.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mittened</ent><br/
<hw>Mit"tened</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Covered with a mitten or mittens.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Mittened</xex> hands.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Whittier.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mittent</ent><br/
<hw>Mit"tent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mittens</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>mittere</ets> to send.]</ety> <def>Sending forth; emitting.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Wiseman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mittimus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mit"ti*mus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., we send, fr. <ets>mittere</ets> to send.]</ety> <fld>(Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A precept or warrant granted by a justice for committing to prison a party charged with crime; a warrant of commitment to prison.</def> <au>Burrill.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A writ for removing records from one court to another.</def>  <au>Brande & C.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mittler's green</ent><br/
<hw>Mit"tler's green`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A pigment of a green color, the chief constituent of which is oxide of chromium.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitty</ent><br/
<hw>Mit"ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The stormy petrel.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mitu</ent><br/
<hw>Mi"tu</hw> <pr>(m<imac/"t<usl/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Braz. <ets>mitu poranga</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A South American curassow of the genus <gen>Mitua</gen>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mity</ent><br/
<hw>Mit"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mite</er>.]</ety> <def>Having, or abounding with, mites.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mix</ent><br/
<hw>Mix</hw> <pr>(m<icr/ks)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mixed</conjf> <pr>(m<icr/kst)</pr> (less properly <conjf>Mixt</conjf>); <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mixing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>miscan</ets>; akin to OHG. <ets>misken</ets>, G. <ets>mischen</ets>, Russ. <ets>mieshate</ets>, W. <ets>mysgu</ets>, Gael. <ets>measg</ets>, L. <ets>miscere</ets>, <ets>mixtum</ets>, Gr. <grk>mi`sgein</grk>, <grk>migny`nai</grk>, Skr. <ets>mi<cced/ra</ets> mixed.  The English word has been influenced by L. <ets>miscere</ets>, <ets>mixtum</ets> (cf. <er>Mixture</er>), and even the AS. <ets>miscan</ets> may have been borrowed fr. L. <ets>miscere</ets>.  Cf. <er>Admix</er>, <er>Mash</er> to bruise, <er>Meddle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause a promiscuous interpenetration of the parts of, as of two or more substances with each other, or of one substance with others; to unite or blend into one mass or compound, as by stirring together; to mingle; to blend; <as>as, to <ex>mix</ex> flour and salt; to <ex>mix</ex> wines.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fair persuasions <qex>mixed</qex> with sugared words.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To unite with in company; to join; to associate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ephraim, he hath <qex>mixed</qex> himself among the people.</q> <rj><qau>Hos. vii. 8.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To form by mingling; to produce by the stirring together of ingredients; to compound of different parts.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hast thou no poison <qex>mixed</qex>?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have chosen an argument <qex>mixed</qex> of religious and civil considerations.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To combine (two or more activities) within a specified or implied time frame; <as>as, to <ex>mix</ex> studying and partying while at college</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mix</ent><br/
<hw>Mix</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become united into a compound; to be blended promiscuously together.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To associate; to mingle; <as>as, Democrats and Republicans <ex>mixed</ex> freely at the party</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>He had <qex>mixed</qex><br/
Again in fancied safety with his kind.</q> <rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mixable</ent><br/
<hw>Mix"a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Capable of being mixed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mixed</ent><br/
<hw>Mixed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Formed by mixing; united; mingled; blended. See <er>Mix</er>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mixed action</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>a suit combining the properties of a real and a personal action.</cd> -- <col><b>Mixed angle</b></col>, <cd>a mixtilineal angle.</cd> -- <col><b>Mixed fabric</b></col>, <cd>a textile fabric composed of two or more kinds of fiber, as a poplin.</cd> -- <col><b>Mixed marriage</b></col>, <cd>a marriage between persons of different races or religions; specifically, one between a Roman Catholic and a Protestant.</cd> -- <col><b>Mixed number</b></col>, <cd>a whole number and a fraction taken together.</cd> -- <col><b>Mixed train</b></col>, <cd>a railway train containing both passenger and freight cars.</cd> -- <col><b>Mixed voices</b></col> <fld>(Mus.)</fld>, <cd>voices of both males and females united in the same performance.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mixedly</ent><br/
<hw>Mix"ed*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a mixed or mingled manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mixen</ent><br/
<hw>Mix"en</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>mixen</ets>, <ets>myxen</ets>, fr. <ets>meohx</ets>, <ets>meox</ets>, dung, filth; akin to E. <ets>mist</ets>. See <er>Mist</er>.]</ety> <def>A compost heap; a dunghill.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer. Tennyson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mixer</ent><br/
<hw>Mix"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, mixes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A person who has social intercourse with others of many sorts; a person viewed as to his casual sociability; -- commonly used with some characterizing adjective; <as>as, a good <ex>mixer</ex>; a bad <ex>mixer</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq. or Slang, U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>a social gathering, game, or dance organized to provide an opportunity for people to meet each other; <as>as, on the first night of the conference they had a wine-and-cheese <ex>mixer</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>a nonalcoholic beverage (such as fruit juice, club soda or ginger ale) added to an alcoholic beverage to produce a mixed drink.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>any device used for mixing.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>an electronic device for blending or manipulating sounds from different sources to produce a composite soundtrack, for an audio recording, video recording, or a movie.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>The technician who operates a <er>mixer{6}</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mixogamous</ent><br/
<hw>Mix*og"a*mous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ a mixing + <?/ marriage.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Pairing with several males; -- said of certain fishes of which several males accompany each female during spawning.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mixolydian mode</ent><br/
<hw>Mix`o*lyd"i*an mode`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[Gr. <?/ a mixing + E. <ets>Lydian</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>The seventh ecclesiastical mode, whose scale commences on G.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mixtilinear</ent><br/
<ent>Mixtilineal</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mix`ti*lin"e*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mix`ti*lin"e*ar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mixtus</ets> mixed (p. p. of <ets>miscere</ets> to mix) + E. <ets>lineal</ets>, <ets>linear</ets>.]</ety> <def>Containing, or consisting of, lines of different kinds, as straight, curved, and the like; <as>as, a <ex>mixtilinear</ex> angle, that is, an angle contained by a straight line and a curve</as>.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mixtion</ent><br/
<hw>Mix"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mixtio</ets>, <ets>mistio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mixtion</ets>. See <er>Mistion</er>, <er>Mix</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Mixture.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A kind of cement made of mastic, amber, etc., used as a mordant for gold leaf.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mixtly</ent><br/
<hw>Mixt"ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>With mixture; in a mixed manner; mixedly.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mixture</ent><br/
<hw>Mix"ture</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mixtura</ets>, fr. <ets>miscere</ets>, <ets>mixtum</ets>, to mix: cf. F. <ets>mixture</ets>. See <er>Mix</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of mixing, or the state of being mixed; <as>as, made by a <ex>mixture</ex> of ingredients</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which results from mixing different ingredients together; a compound; <as>as, to drink a <ex>mixture</ex> of molasses and water</as>; -- also, a medley.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is also a <qex>mixture</qex> of good and evil wisely distributed by God, to serve the ends of his providence.</q> <rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An ingredient entering into a mixed mass; an additional ingredient.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cicero doubts whether it were possible for a community to exist that had not a prevailing <qex>mixture</qex> of piety in its constitution.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A kind of liquid medicine made up of many ingredients; esp., as opposed to <contr>solution</contr>, a liquid preparation in which the solid ingredients are not completely dissolved.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Physics & Chem.)</fld> <def>A mass of two or more ingredients, the particles of which are separable, independent, and uncompounded with each other, no matter how thoroughly and finely commingled; -- contrasted with a <contr>compound</contr> and <contr>solution</contr>; <as>thus, gunpowder is a mechanical <ex>mixture</ex> of carbon, sulphur, and niter</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>An organ stop, comprising from two to five ranges of pipes, used only in combination with the foundation and compound stops; -- called also <altname>furniture stop</altname>. It consists of high harmonics, or overtones, of the ground tone.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Union; admixture; intermixture; medley.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mix up</ent><br/
<hw>mix up</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To confuse the identities of (two or more objects); to mistake (one object for another); <as>as, at the family gathering he <ex>mixed up</ex> his two nieces, to their great amusement</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To mix together; -- usually implying a mistake, whether done intentionally or unintentionally; <as>as, the <ex>mixed up</ex> this year's receipts with last year's, and it took hours to find the right ones</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mix-up</ent><br/
<hw>mix-up</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a mistake that results from taking one thing to be another.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> confusion, confounding.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mizenmast</ent><br/
<hw>mizenmast</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>mizzenmast.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mizzen, mizen.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mizmaze</ent><br/
<hw>Miz"maze`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A maze or labyrinth.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mizzen</ent><br/
<hw>Miz"zen</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[It. <ets>mezzana</ets>, fr. <ets>mezzano</ets> middle, fr. <ets>mezzo</ets> middle, half: cf. F. <ets>misaine</ets> foresail. See <er>Mezzo</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>Hindmost; nearest the stern; <as>as, the <ex>mizzen</ex> shrouds, sails, etc.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mizzen</ent><br/
<hw>Miz"zen</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The hindmost of the fore and aft sails of a three-masted vessel; also, the spanker.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mizzenmast</ent><br/
<hw>Miz"zen*mast</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>the third mast from the bow in a vessel having three or more masts; the after and shorter mast of a yawl, ketch, or dandy.</def>  <note>The definition varies slightly with the dictionary; in some dictionaries it is the last mast of a three-masted vessel; in others, it is the mast after the mainmast  of a vessel of three or more masts. PJC.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mizzle</ent><br/
<hw>Miz"zle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mizzled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mizzling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Misle</er>, and cf. <er>Mistle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To rain in very fine drops; to drizzle.</def>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To take one's self off; to go.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As long as George the Fourth could reign, he reigned,<br/
And then he <qex>mizzled</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Epigram, quoted by Wright.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mizzle</ent><br/
<hw>Miz"zle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mist; fine rain.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mizzy</ent><br/
<hw>Miz"zy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>moisi</ets> moldy, musty, p. p. of <ets>moisir</ets> to mold, fr. L. <ets>mucere</ets> to be moldy.]</ety> <def>A bog or quagmire.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Ainsworth.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>ml</ent><br/
<hw>ml</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>milliliter; -- the IS standard abbreviation.</def> <mark>[abbreviation]</mark><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mm</ent><br/
<hw>mm</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>millimeter; -- the IS standard abbreviation.</def> <mark>[abbreviation]</mark><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mM</ent><br/
<hw>mM</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>Chem.)</fld> <def>millimolar; -- the IS standard abbreviation.</def> <mark>[abbreviation]</mark><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mn</ent><br/
<hw>Mn</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>The chemical symbol for <altname>manganese</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>M'-Naught</ent><br/
<hw>M'-Naught"</hw> <pr>(m<ait/k*n<add/t")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <fld>(Steam Engines)</fld> <def>To increase the power of (a single-cylinder beam engine) by adding a small high-pressure cylinder with a piston acting on the beam between the center and the flywheel end, using high-pressure steam and working as a compound engine, -- a plan introduced by <persfn>M'Naught</persfn>, a Scottish engineer, in 1845.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mnemonical</ent><br/
<ent>Mnemonic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mne*mon"ic</hw> <pr>(n<esl/*m<ocr/n"<icr/k)</pr>, <hw>Mne*mon"ic*al</hw> <pr>(n<esl/*m<ocr/n"<icr/*k<ait/l)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mnhmoniko`s</grk>, fr. <grk>mnh`mwn</grk> mindful, remembering, <grk>mnh`mh</grk> memory, <grk>mna^sqai</grk> to think on, remember; akin to E. <ets>mind</ets>.]</ety> <def>Assisting in memory; helping to remember; <as>as, a <ex>mnemonic</ex> device</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mnemonic</ent><br/
<hw>mnemonic</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Something used to assist the memory, as an easily remembered acronym or verse.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An abbreviated word that resembles the full word, used so as to be easily recognized; <as>as, the CIDE uses <it>...</it> tags as <ex>mnemnonics</ex> for an italicised word or field</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note> In basic organic chemistry class, one may learn the <ex>mnenomic</ex> <ldquo/Oh my, such good apple pie<rdquo/ to help remember the names of the dicarboxylic acids in increasing order of length, namely: oxalic, malonic, succinic, glutaric, adipic, and pimelic acids. (From L. Fieser's Organic Chemistry text).</note></p>

<p><ent>Mnemonician</ent><br/
<hw>Mne`mo*ni"cian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who instructs in the art of improving or using the memory.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mnemonics</ent><br/
<hw>Mne*mon"ics</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>ta~ mnhmonika`</grk>: cf. F. <ets>mn<eacute/monique</ets>.]</ety> <def>The art of memory; a method for improving the memory; a system of precepts and rules intended to assist the memory; artificial memory.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mnemosyne</ent><br/
<hw>Mne*mos"y*ne</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <grk>mnhmosy`nh</grk> remembrance, memory, and the goddess of memory. See <er>Mnemonic</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Class Myth.)</fld> <def>The goddess of memory and the mother of the Muses.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mnemotechnical</ent><br/
<hw>mnemotechnical</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>  <def>same as <er>mnemonic</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mnemonic, mnemotechnic.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mnemotechny</ent><br/
<hw>Mne"mo*tech`ny</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ memory + <?/ art: cf. F. <ets>mn<eacute/motechnie</ets>.]</ety> <def>Mnemonics.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mniaceae</ent><br/
<hw>Mniaceae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of erect mosses with club-shaped paraphyses andgonal cells of the upper leaf surface; sometimes treated as a subfamily of <fam>Bryaceae</fam>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Mniaceae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mnium</ent><br/
<hw>Mnium</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of mosses similar to those of genus <gen>Bryum</gen> but larger.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Mnium</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mo</ent><br/
<hw>Mo</hw> <pr>(m<omac/)</pr>, <pos>a., adv., & n.</pos> <altsp>[Written also <asp>moe</asp>.]</altsp> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<amac/</ets>. See <er>More</er>.]</ety> <def>More; -- usually, more in number.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An hundred thousand <qex>mo</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Likely to find <qex>mo</qex> to commend than to imitate it.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mo</ent><br/
<hw>Mo</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>chemical symbol for the element <er>molybdenum</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>MO</ent><br/
<hw>MO</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <def>abbreviation for <er>modus operandi</er>, manner of operating; -- often used to refer to the method an habitual criminal uses to perpetrate his crime.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>-mo</ent><br/
<hw>-mo</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <def>A suffix added to the names of certain numerals or to the numerals themselves, to indicate the number of leaves made by folding a sheet of paper; <as>as, sixteen<ex>mo</ex> or 16<ex>mo</ex>; eighteen<xex>mo</xex> or 18<xex>mo</xex></as>.  It is taken from the Latin forms similarly used; <as>as, <xex>duodecimo</xex>, <xex>sextodecimo</xex>, etc.</as>  A small circle, placed after the number and near its top, is often used for <xex>-mo</xex>; as, 16<deg/, 18<deg/, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moa</ent><br/
<hw>mo"a</hw> <pr>(m<omac/"<adot/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Native name.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of several very large extinct species of wingless birds belonging to <gen>Dinornis</gen>, and other related genera, of the suborder <ord>Dinornithes</ord>, found in <country>New Zealand</country>.  They are allied to the apteryx and the ostrich.  They were probably exterminated by the natives before <country>New Zealand</country> was discovered by Europeans.  Some species were much larger than the ostrich.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moabite</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ab*ite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One of the posterity of Moab, the son of Lot. (<au>Gen. xix. 37.</au>)  Also used adjectively.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moabitess</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ab*i`tess</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A female Moabite.</def>  <rj><au>Ruth i. 22.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moabite stone</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ab*ite stone</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Archaeol.)</fld> <def>A block of black basalt, found at Dibon in Moab by <person>Rev. F. A. Klein</person>, Aug. 19, 1868, which bears an inscription of thirty-four lines, dating from the 9th century <sc>b. c.</sc>, and written in the Moabite alphabet, the oldest Phoenician type of the Semitic alphabet.  It records the victories of <persfn>Mesha</persfn>, king of <xex>Moab</xex>, esp. those over Israel (<au>2 Kings iii. 4, 5, 27</au>).</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moabitish</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ab*i`tish</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Moabite.</def>  <rj><au>Ruth ii. 6.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moan</ent><br/
<hw>Moan</hw> <pr>(m<omac/n)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Moaned</conjf> <pr>(m<omac/nd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Moaning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<aemac/nan</ets> to moan, also, to mean; but in the latter sense perh. a different word.  Cf. <er>Mean</er> to intend.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make a low prolonged sound of grief or pain, whether articulate or not; to groan softly and continuously.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Unpitied and unheard, where misery <qex>moans</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let there bechance him pitiful mischances,<br/
To make him <qex>moan</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To emit a sound like moan; -- said of things inanimate; <as>as, the wind <ex>moans</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moan</ent><br/
<hw>Moan</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To bewail audibly; to lament.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye floods, ye woods, ye echoes, <qex>moan</qex><br/
My dear Columbo, dead and gone.</q> <rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To afflict; to distress.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Which infinitely <qex>moans</qex> me.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moan</ent><br/
<hw>Moan</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mone</ets>. See <er>Moan</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A low prolonged sound, articulate or not, indicative of pain or of grief; a low groan.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sullen <qex>moans</qex>, hollow groans.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A low mournful or murmuring sound; -- of things.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Rippling waters made a pleasant <qex>moan</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moanful</ent><br/
<hw>Moan"ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Full of moaning; expressing sorrow.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Moan"ful*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moat</ent><br/
<hw>Moat</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>mote</ets> hill, dike, bank, F. <ets>motte</ets> clod, turf: cf. Sp. & Pg. <ets>mota</ets> bank or mound of earth, It. <ets>motta</ets> clod, LL. <ets>mota</ets>, <ets>motta</ets>, a hill on which a fort is built, an eminence, a dike, Prov. G. <ets>mott</ets> bog earth heaped up; or perh. F. <ets>motte</ets>, and OF. <ets>mote</ets>, are from a LL. p. p. of L. <ets>movere</ets> to move (see <er>Move</er>). The name of <ets>moat</ets>, properly meaning, bank or mound, was transferred to the ditch adjoining: cf. F. <ets>dike</ets> and <ets>ditch</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Fort.)</fld> <def>A deep trench around the rampart of a castle or other fortified place, sometimes filled with water; a ditch.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moat</ent><br/
<hw>Moat</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To surround with a moat.</def>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moate</ent><br/
<hw>Moate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mute</er> to molt.]</ety> <def>To void the excrement, as a bird; to mute.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mob</ent><br/
<hw>Mob</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mobcap</er>.]</ety> <def>A mobcap.</def>  <rj><au>Goldsmith.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mob</ent><br/
<hw>Mob</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To wrap up in, or cover with, a cowl.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mob</ent><br/
<hw>Mob</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mobile vulgus</ets>, the movable common people. See <er>Mobile</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The lower classes of a community; the populace, or the lowest part of it.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A cluster of <qex>mob</qex> were making themselves merry with their betters.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>A throng; a rabble; esp., an unlawful or riotous assembly; a disorderly crowd.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>mob</qex> of gentlemen who wrote with ease.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Had every Athenian citizen been a Socrates, every Athenian assembly would still have been a <qex>mob</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Madison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Confused by brainless <qex>mobs</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A criminal organization or organized criminal gangs, collectively; the Mafia; the syndicate; <as>as, he was a lawyer for the <ex>mob</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mob law</b></col>, <cd>law administered by the mob; lynch law.</cd> -- <col><b>Swell mob</b></col>, <cd>well dressed thieves and swindlers, regarded collectively.</cd> <mark>[Slang]</mark> <au>Dickens.</au></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mob</ent><br/
<hw>Mob</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mobbed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mobbing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To crowd about, as a mob, and attack or annoy; <as>as, to <ex>mob</ex> a house or a person</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mobbish</ent><br/
<hw>Mob"bish</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Like a mob; tumultuous; lawless; <as>as, a <ex>mobbish</ex> act</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Bp. Kent.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mobcap</ent><br/
<hw>Mob"cap`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[D. <ets>mop-muts</ets>; OD. <ets>mop</ets> a woman's coif + D. <ets>muts</ets> cap.]</ety> <def>A plain cap or headdress for women or girls; especially, one tying under the chin by a very broad band, generally of the same material as the cap itself.</def>  <rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mobile</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"bile</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mobilis</ets>, for <ets>movibilis</ets>, fr. <ets>movere</ets> to move: cf. F. <ets>mobile</ets>. See <er>Move</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Capable of being moved; not fixed in place or condition; movable.</def> <ldquo/Fixed or else <xex>mobile</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Skelton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Characterized by an extreme degree of fluidity; moving or flowing with great freedom; <as>as, benzine and mercury are <ex>mobile</ex> liquids; -- opposed to <ex>viscous</ex>, <ex>viscoidal</ex>, or <ex>oily</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Easily moved in feeling, purpose, or direction; excitable; changeable; fickle.</def>  <rj><au>Testament of Love.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The quick and <qex>mobile</qex> curiosity of her disposition.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Changing in appearance and expression under the influence of the mind; <as>as, <ex>mobile</ex> features</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>Capable of being moved, aroused, or excited; capable of spontaneous movement.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Capable of moving readily, or moving frequenty from place to place; <as>as, a <ex>mobile</ex> work force</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Having motor vehicles to permit movement from place to place; <as>as, a <ex>mobile</ex> library; a <ex>mobile</ex> hospital</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mobile</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"bile</hw> <pr>(m<omac/"b<icr/l; L. m<ocr/b"<icr/*l<emac/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mobile vulgus</ets>. See <er>Mobile</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and cf. 3d <er>Mob</er>.]</ety> <def>The mob; the populace.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/The unthinking <xex>mobile</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>South.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mobile</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"bile</hw> <pr>(m<omac/"b<emac/l`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>a form of sculpture having several sheets or rods of a stiff material attached to each other by thin wire or twine in a balanced and artfully arranged tree configuration, with the topmost member suspended in air from a support so that the parts may move independently when set in motion by a current of air.</def> <br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mobilise</ent><br/
<hw>mobilise</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Mobilize.</def> <mark>[Chiefly Brit.]</mark> <br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mobilisation</ent><br/
<hw>mobilisation</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mobilization.</def> <mark>[Chiefly Brit.]</mark> <br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 934 --></p>

<p><ent>Mobility</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*bil"i*ty</hw> <pr>(m<osl/*b<icr/l"<icr/*t<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mobilitas</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mobilit<eacute/</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality or state of being mobile; <as>as, the <ex>mobility</ex> of a liquid, of an army, of the populace, of features, of a muscle</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The mob; the lower classes.</def> <mark>[Humorous]</mark>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mobilization</ent><br/
<hw>Mob`i*li*za"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mobilization</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act of mobilizing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mobilize</ent><br/
<hw>Mob"i*lize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mobilized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mobilizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>mobiliser</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To assemble and organize and make ready for use or action; <as>as, to <ex>mobilize</ex> volunteers for the election campaign</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mobilise, marshal.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <def>To put in a state of readiness for active service in war, as an army corps; <as>as, to <ex>mobilize</ex> the National Guard</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mobilise, militarize, militarise.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mobius strip</ent><br/
<ent>Moebius strip</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Mo"bi*us strip`</hw>, <hw>M<oum/"bi*us strip`</hw>, <hw>Moe"bi*us strip`</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <person>August F. <etsep>M<oum/bius</etsep></person>, a German mathematician.]</ety> <def>A mathematical object, or a physical representation of it, which is a two-dimensional sheet with only one surface.  It is constructed or visualized as a rectangle, one end of which is held fixed while the opposite end is twisted through a 180 degree angle and joined to the fixed end.  It is a two-dimensional object that can only exist in a three-dimensional space.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note>The moebius strip was the subject of a famous woodcut by <person>M. Escher</person>, published in 1963.  See <a href="images/mobius.jpg">Moebius Strip II</a>.</note><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moble</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mob</er> to wrap up.]</ety> <def>To wrap the head of in a hood.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mobles</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"bles</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <def>See <er>Moebles</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mobocracy</ent><br/
<hw>Mob*oc"ra*cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mob</ets> rabble + <ets>-cracy</ets>, as in <ets>democracy</ets>.]</ety> <def>A condition in which the lower classes of a nation control public affairs without respect to law, precedents, or vested rights.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is good name that Dr. Stevens has given to our present situation (for one can not call it a government), a <qex>mobocracy</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Walpole.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mobocrat</ent><br/
<hw>Mob"o*crat</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who favors a form of government in which the unintelligent populace rules without restraint.</def>  <rj><au>Bayne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mobocratic</ent><br/
<hw>Mob`o*crat"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of, or relating to, a mobocracy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mocassin</ent><br/
<hw>mocassin</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Variant spelling of <er>moccasin</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> moccasin, moccasins.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moccasin</ent><br/
<hw>moc"ca*sin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[An Indian word. Algonquin <ets>makisin</ets>.]</ety> <altsp>[Sometimes written <asp>moccason</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A shoe made of deerskin, or other soft leather, the sole and upper part being one piece.  It is the customary shoe worn by the American Indians.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A poisonous snake of the Southern United States.  The water moccasin (<spn>Ancistrodon piscivorus</spn> syn. <spn>Agkistrodon piscivorus</spn>, also called <altname>cottonmouth</altname> and <altname>cottonmouth water moccasin</altname>) is usually found in or near water.  Above, it is olive brown, barred with black; beneath, it is brownish yellow, mottled with darker.  The upland moccasin is <spn>Ancistrodon atrofuscus</spn>.  They resemble rattlesnakes, but are without rattles.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Moccasin flower</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a species of lady's slipper (<spn>Cypripedium acaule</spn>) found in North America.  The lower petal is two inches long, and forms a rose-colored moccasin-shaped pouch.  It grows in rich woods under coniferous trees.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moccasined</ent><br/
<hw>Moc"ca*sined</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Covered with, or wearing, a moccasin or moccasins.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Moccasined</xex> feet.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Harper's Mag.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mocha</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"cha</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A seaport town of Yemen, on the Red Sea, also spelled <asp>Mukha</asp>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A variety of coffee originally brought from Mocha.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An Abyssinian weight, equivalent to a Troy grain.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A flavoring made from an infusion of coffee or of a combination of coffee with chocolate or cocoa.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A color of a deep chocolate brown.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mocha stone</b></col> <fld>(Min.)</fld>, <cd>moss agate.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moche</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Moche</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>A bale of raw silk.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moche</ent><br/
<hw>Moche</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Much.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mochel</ent><br/
<hw>Moch"el</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a. & adv.</pos> <def>Much.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mochila</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo*chi"la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp.]</ety> <def>A large leather flap which covers the saddletree.</def> <mark>[Western U.S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mock</ent><br/
<hw>Mock</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mocked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mocking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>moquer</ets>, of uncertain origin; cf. OD. <ets>mocken</ets> to mumble, G. <ets>mucken</ets>, OSw. <ets>mucka</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To imitate; to mimic; esp., to mimic in sport, contempt, or derision; to deride by mimicry.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To see the life as lively <qex>mocked</qex> as ever<br/
Still sleep <qex>mocked</qex> death.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mocking</qex> marriage with a dame of France.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To treat with scorn or contempt; to deride.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Elijah <qex>mocked</qex> them, and said, Cry aloud.</q> <rj><qau>1 Kings xviii. 27.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let not ambition <qex>mock</qex> their useful toil.</q> <rj><qau>Gray.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To disappoint the hopes of; to deceive; to tantalize; <as>as, to <ex>mock</ex> expectation</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou hast <qex>mocked</qex> me, and told me lies.</q> <rj><qau>Judg. xvi. 13.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He will not . . . <br/
<qex>Mock</qex> us with his blest sight, then snatch him hence.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To deride; ridicule; taunt; jeer; tantalize; disappoint. See <er>Deride</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mock</ent><br/
<hw>Mock</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make sport in contempt or in jest; to speak in a scornful or jeering manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When thou <qex>mockest</qex>, shall no man make thee ashamed?</q> <rj><qau>Job xi. 3.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She had <qex>mocked</qex> at his proposal.</q> <rj><qau>Froude.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mock</ent><br/
<hw>Mock</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An act of ridicule or derision; a scornful or contemptuous act or speech; a sneer; a jibe; a jeer.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fools make a <qex>mock</qex> at sin.</q> <rj><qau>Prov. xiv. 9.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Imitation; mimicry.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Crashaw.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mock</ent><br/
<hw>Mock</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Imitating reality, but not real; false; counterfeit; assumed; sham.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That superior greatness and <qex>mock</qex> majesty.</q> <rj><qau>Spectator.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mock bishop's weed</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a genus of slender umbelliferous herbs (<gen>Discopleura</gen>) growing in wet places.</cd> -- <col><b>Mock heroic</b></col>, <cd>burlesquing the heroic; <as>as, a <ex>mock heroic</ex> poem</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mock lead</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Blende</er> (<sd>a</sd>).</cd> -- <col><b>Mock nightingale</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the European blackcap.</cd> -- <col><b>Mock orange</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a genus of American and Asiatic shrubs (<gen>Philadelphus</gen>), with showy white flowers in panicled cymes.  <spn>Philadelphus coronarius</spn>, from Asia, has fragrant flowers; the American kinds are nearly scentless.</cd> -- <col><b>Mock sun</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Parhelion</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mock turtle soup</b></col>, <cd>a soup made of calf's head, veal, or other meat, and condiments, in imitation of green turtle soup.</cd> -- <col><b>Mock velvet</b></col>, <cd>a fabric made in imitation of velvet. See <er>Mockado</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mockable</ent><br/
<hw>Mock"a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Such as can be mocked.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mockado</ent><br/
<hw>Mock"a*do</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A stuff made in imitation of velvet; -- probably the same as <altname>mock velvet</altname>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our rich <qex>mockado</qex> doublet.</q> <rj><qau>Ford.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mockadour</ent><br/
<hw>Mock"a*dour</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mokadour</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mockage</ent><br/
<hw>Mock"age</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mockery.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mockbird</ent><br/
<hw>Mock"bird`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The European sedge warbler (<spn>Acrocephalus phragmitis</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mocker</ent><br/
<hw>Mock"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, mocks; a scorner; a scoffer; a derider.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A deceiver; an impostor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A mocking bird.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mocker nut</ent><br/
<ent>mockernut</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mockernut</hw>, <hw>mocker nut</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos>  <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <def>A smooth-barked North American hickory (<spn>Carya tomentosa</spn>) with 7 to 9 leaflets bearing a hard-shelled edible nut, which is far inferior to the true shagbark hickory nut.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mockernut hickory, black hickory, white-heart hickory, big-bud hickory, <spn>Carya tomentosa</spn> .</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The fruit of the mockernut{1}.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mockery</ent><br/
<hw>Mock"er*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mockeries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F. <ets>moquerie</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of mocking, deriding, and exposing to contempt, by mimicry, by insincere imitation, or by a false show of earnestness; a counterfeit appearance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is, as the air, invulnerable,<br/
And our vain blows malicious <qex>mockery</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Grace at meals is now generally so performed as to look more like a <qex>mockery</qex> upon devotion than any solemn application of the mind to God.</q> <rj><qau>Law.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And bear about the <qex>mockery</qex> of woe.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Insulting or contemptuous action or speech; contemptuous merriment; derision; ridicule.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The laughingstock of fortune's <qex>mockeries</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Subject of laughter, derision, or sport.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The cruel handling of the city whereof they made a <qex>mockery</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>2 Macc. viii. 17.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mocking</ent><br/
<hw>Mock"ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Imitating, esp. in derision, or so as to cause derision; mimicking; derisive.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mocking thrush</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any species of the genus <gen>Harporhynchus</gen>, as the brown thrush (<spn>Harporhynchus rufus</spn>).</cd> -- <col><b>Mocking wren</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any American wren of the genus <gen>Thryothorus</gen>, esp. <spn>Thryothorus Ludovicianus</spn>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mocking bird</ent><br/
<ent>mockingbird</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mockingbird</hw>, <hw>mocking bird</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <def>A long-tailed gray-and-white songbird of North America (<spn>Mimus polyglottos</spn>), remarkable for its exact imitations of the notes of other birds. Its back is gray; the tail and wings are blackish, with a white patch on each wing; the outer tail feathers are partly white.  Originally its range was confined mostly to the southern states, but by late 19th century it had migrated as far north as New York.  The name is also applied to other members of thee same and related genera, found in Mexico, Central America, and the West Indies, such as the <ecol><b>blue mockingbird</b></ecol> of Mexico, <spn>Melanotis caerulescens</spn>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mocker, <spn>Mimus polyglottos</spn> .</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mockingly</ent><br/
<hw>Mock"ing*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>By way of derision; in a contemptuous or mocking manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mockingstock</ent><br/
<hw>Mock"ing*stock`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A butt of sport; an object of derision.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mockish</ent><br/
<hw>Mock"ish</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Mock; counterfeit; sham.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mockle</ent><br/
<hw>Moc"kle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>See <er>Mickle</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moco</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"co</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A South American rodent (<spn>Cavia rupestris</spn>), allied to the Guinea pig, but larger; -- called also <altname>rock cavy</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modal</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"dal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>modal</ets>. See <er>Mode</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a mode or mood; consisting in mode or form only; relating to form; having the form without the essence or reality.</def>  <rj><au>Glanvill.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Logic & Metaph.)</fld> <def>Indicating, or pertaining to, some mode of conceiving existence, or of expressing thought, such as the modes of possibility or obligation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to or denoting mood.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modal</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"dal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> <fld>(Gram.)</fld>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A modal auxiliary.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>modal auxiliary</ent><br/
<hw>mo"dal aux*il"iar*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> <fld>(Gram.)</fld>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Any one of the auxiliary verbs of English, such as <examp>can</examp>, <examp>may</examp>, <examp>will</examp>, <examp>shall</examp>, <examp>must</examp>, <examp>might</examp>, <examp>could</examp>, <examp>would</examp>, or <examp>should</examp>, which are used together with the infinitive form of another verb to express distinctions of mood{2}, such as uncertainty, possibility, command, emphasis, and obligation.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modalist</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"dal*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Theol.)</fld> <def>One who regards Father, Son, and Spirit as modes of being, and not as persons, thus denying personal distinction in the Trinity.</def>  <rj><au>Eadie.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modality</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*dal"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>modalit<eacute/</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality or state of being modal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Logic & Metaph.)</fld> <def>A modal relation or quality; a mode or point of view under which an object presents itself to the mind.  According to Kant, the quality of propositions, as assertory, problematical, or apodeictic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>modal logic</ent><br/
<hw>mo"dal log"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A system of logic which studies how to combine propositions which include the concepts of necessity, possibility, and obligation.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modally</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"dal*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a modal manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A compound proposition, the parts of which are united <qex>modally</qex> . . . by the particles  <ldquo/as<rdquo/ and <ldquo/so.<rdquo/</q> <rj><qau>Gibbs.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mode</ent><br/
<hw>Mode</hw> <pr>(m<omac/d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>modus</ets> a measure, due or proper measure, bound, manner, form; akin to E. <ets>mete</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mode</ets>. See <er>Mete</er>, and cf. <er>Commodious</er>, <er>Mood</er> in grammar, <er>Modus</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Manner of doing or being; method; form; fashion; custom; way; style; <as>as, the <ex>mode</ex> of speaking; the <ex>mode</ex> of dressing.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The duty of itself being resolved on, the <qex>mode</qex> of doing it may easily be found.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A table richly spread in regal <qex>mode</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Prevailing popular custom; fashion, especially in the phrase <xex>the mode</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The easy, apathetic graces of a man of the <qex>mode</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Variety; gradation; degree.</def>  <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Metaph.)</fld> <def>Any combination of qualities or relations, considered apart from the substance to which they belong, and treated as entities; more generally, condition, or state of being; manner or form of arrangement or manifestation; form, as opposed to <contr>matter</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Modes</qex> I call such complex ideas, which, however compounded, contain not in them the supposition of subsisting by themselves, but are considered as dependencies on, or affections of, substances.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Logic)</fld> <def>The form in which the proposition connects the predicate and subject, whether by simple, contingent, or necessary assertion; the form of the syllogism, as determined by the quantity and quality of the constituent proposition; mood.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Mood</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>The scale as affected by the various positions in it of the minor intervals; <as>as, the Dorian <ex>mode</ex>, the Ionic <ex>mode</ex>, etc.</as>, of ancient Greek music.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ In modern music, only the major and the minor mode, of whatever key, are recognized.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A kind of silk. See <er>Alamode</er>, <pos>n.</pos></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>the value of the variable in a frequency distribution or probability distribution, at which the probability or frequency has a maximum.  The maximum may be local or global.  Distributions with only one such maximum are called <er>unimodal</er>; with two maxima, <er>bimodal</er>, and with more than two, <er>multimodal</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Method; manner. See <er>Method</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- ##??mode of action (Biochem) --><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Model</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"el</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mod<egrave/le</ets>, It. <ets>modello</ets>, fr. (assumed) L. <ets>modellus</ets>, fr. <ets>modulus</ets> a small measure, dim. of <ets>modus</ets>. See <er>Mode</er>, and cf. <er>Module</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A miniature representation of a thing, with the several parts in due proportion; sometimes, a facsimile of the same size; <as>as, a <frac1x100/ scale <ex>model</ex> of the B-52 bomber</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In charts, in maps, and eke in <qex>models</qex> made.</q> <rj><qau>Gascoigne.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I had my father's signet in my purse,<br/
Which was the <qex>model</qex> of that Danish seal.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You have the <qex>models</qex> of several ancient temples, though the temples and the gods are perished.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Something intended to serve, or that may serve, as a pattern of something to be made; a material representation or embodiment of an ideal; sometimes, a drawing; a plan; <as>as, the clay <ex>model</ex> of a sculpture; the inventor's <ex>model</ex> of a machine.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[The application for a patent] must be accompanied by a full description of the invention, with drawings and a <qex>model</qex> where the case admits of it.</q> <rj><qau>Am. Cyc.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When we mean to build<br/
We first survey the plot, then draw the <qex>model</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Anything which serves, or may serve, as an example for imitation; <as>as, a government formed on the <ex>model</ex> of the American constitution; a <ex>model</ex> of eloquence, virtue, or behavior.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That by which a thing is to be measured; standard.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He that despairs measures Providence by his own little, contracted <qex>model</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Any copy, or resemblance, more or less exact.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou seest thy wretched brother die,<br/
Who was the <qex>model</qex> of thy father's life.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A person who poses as a pattern for an artist; <as>as, the artist used his daughter as a <ex>model</ex> for an Indian maiden</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A person who is employed to wear clothing for the purpose of advertising or display, or who poses with a product for the same purpose; a mannequin{1}; <as>as, a fashion <ex>model</ex></as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mannequin{1}.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>A professional <qex>model</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>H. James.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A particular version or design of an object that is made in multiple versions; <as>as, the 1993 <ex>model</ex> of the Honda Accord; the latest <ex>model</ex> of the HP laserjet printer</as>.  For many manufactured products, the <ex>model</ex> name is encoded as part of the <col><b>model number</b></col>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> modification{2}.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>An abstract and often simplified conceptual representation of the workings of a system of objects in the real world, which often includes mathematical or logical objects and relations representing the objects and relations in the real-world system, and constructed for the purpose of explaining the workings of the system or predicting its behavior under hypothetical conditions; <as>as, the administration's <ex>model</ex> of the United States economy predicts budget surpluses for the next fifteen years; different <ex>models</ex> of the universe assume different values for the cosmological constant; <ex>models</ex> of proton structure have grown progressively more complex in the past century</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Working model</b></col>, <cd>a model of a machine which can do on a small scale the work which the machine itself does, or is expected to do.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Model</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"el</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Suitable to be taken as a model or pattern; <as>as, a <ex>model</ex> house; a <ex>model</ex> husband.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Model</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"el</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Modeled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or <conjf>Modelled</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Modeling</conjf> or <conjf>Modelling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>modeler</ets>, It. <ets>modellare</ets>.]</ety> <def>To plan or form after a pattern; to form in model; to form a model or pattern for; to shape; to mold; to fashion; <as>as, to <ex>model</ex> a house or a government; to <ex>model</ex> an edifice according to the plan delineated.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Model</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"el</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <fld>(Fine Arts)</fld> <def>To make a copy or a pattern; to design or imitate forms; <as>as, to <ex>model</ex> in wax</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>modeled</ent><br/
<hw>modeled</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>resembling sculpture; <as>as, her finely <ex>modeled</ex> features</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> sculptural, sculptured, sculpturesque.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modeler</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"el*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who models; hence, a worker in plastic art.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>modeller</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modeling</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"el*ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Fine Arts)</fld> <def>The act or art of making a model from which a work of art is to be executed; the formation of a work of art from some plastic material. Also, in painting, drawing, etc., the expression or indication of solid form.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>modelling</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Modeling plane</b></col>, <cd>a small plane for planing rounded objects.</cd> -- <col><b>Modeling wax</b></col>, <cd>beeswax melted with a little Venice turpentine, or other resinous material, and tinted with coloring matter, usually red, -- used in modeling.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modelize</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"el*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To model.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>modem</ent><br/
<hw>mo"dem</hw> <pr>(m<omac/"d<ecr/m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[by shortening from <ets>mo</ets>dulator-<ets>dem</ets>odulator.]</ety> <def>An electronic device that converts electronic signals into sound waves, and sound waves into electronic signals, used to transmit information between computers by the use of ordinary telephone lines; also called <altname>modulator-demodulator</altname>; <as>as, the latest <ex>modems</ex> can transmit data at 56,000 baud over a clear telephone line</as>.  The speed of transmission of information by a modem is usually measured in units of <er>baud</er>, equivalent to bits per second.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modena</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mod"e*na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <ets>Modena</ets>, in Italy.]</ety> <def>A certain crimsonlike color.</def>  <rj><au>Good.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modenese</ent><br/
<hw>Mod`e*nese"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to Modena or its inhabitants.</def> -- <def2><pos>n. sing. & pl.</pos> <def>A native or inhabitant of Modena; the people of Modena.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moder</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. See <er>Mother</er> female parent.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A mother.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The principal piece of an astrolabe, into which the others are fixed.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moder</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To moderate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moderable</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"er*a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>moderabilis</ets>.]</ety> <def>Moderate; temperate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moderance</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"er*ance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Moderation.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Caxton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moderate</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"er*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>moderatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>moderate</ets>, <ets>moderati</ets>, to moderate, regulate, control, fr. <ets>modus</ets> measure. See <er>Mode</er>.]</ety> <def>Kept within due bounds; observing reasonable limits; not excessive, extreme, violent, or rigorous; limited; restrained</def>; as: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Limited in quantity; sparing; temperate; frugal; <as>as, <ex>moderate</ex> in eating or drinking; a <ex>moderate</ex> table</as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Limited in degree of activity, energy, or excitement; reasonable; calm; slow; <as>as, <ex>moderate</ex> language; <ex>moderate</ex> endeavors.</as></def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>Not extreme in opinion, in partisanship, and the like; <as>as, a <ex>moderate</ex> Calvinist; a <ex>moderate</ex> Republican</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A number of <qex>moderate</qex> members managed . . . to obtain a majority in a thin house.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <def>Not violent or rigorous; temperate; mild; gentle; <as>as, a <ex>moderate</ex> winter</as>.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Moderate</xex> showers.<rdquo/ <au>Walter.</au> <sd>(e)</sd> <def>Limited as to degree of progress; <as>as, to travel at <ex>moderate</ex> speed</as>.</def> <sd>(f)</sd> <def>Limited as to the degree in which a quality, principle, or faculty appears; <as>as, an infusion of <ex>moderate</ex> strength; a man of <ex>moderate</ex> abilities</as>.</def> <sd>(g)</sd> <def>Limited in scope or effects; <as>as, a reformation of a <ex>moderate</ex> kind</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moderate</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"er*ate</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>One of a party in the Church of Scotland in the 18th century, and part of the 19th, professing moderation in matters of church government, in discipline, and in doctrine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moderate</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"er*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Moderated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Moderating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To restrain from excess of any kind; to reduce from a state of violence, intensity, or excess; to keep within bounds; to make temperate; to lessen; to allay; to repress; to temper; to qualify; <as>as, to <ex>moderate</ex> rage, action, desires, etc.; to <ex>moderate</ex> heat or wind.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By its astringent quality, it <qex>moderates</qex> the relaxing quality of warm water.</q> <rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>moderate</qex> stiff minds disposed to strive.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To preside over, direct, or regulate, as a public meeting or a discussion; <as>as, to <ex>moderate</ex> a synod; to <ex>moderate</ex> a debate</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moderate</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"er*ate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become less violent, severe, rigorous, or intense; <as>as, the wind has <ex>moderated</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To preside as a moderator.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Dr. Barlow [was] engaged . . . to <qex>moderate</qex> for him in the divinity disputation.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Barlow's Remains (1693).</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moderated</ent><br/
<hw>moderated</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>having elements or qualities mixed in proper or suitable proportions; especially, made less severe.  Contrasted with <ant>harsh</ant>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> qualified, tempered.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moderately</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"er*ate*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a moderate manner or degree; to a moderate extent.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Each nymph but <qex>moderately</qex> fair.</q> <rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moderateness</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"er*ate*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being moderate; temperateness; moderation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moderating</ent><br/
<hw>moderating</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>lessening in intensity or strength.  Opposite of <ant>intensifying</ant>.</def> [Narrower terms: <stype>tempering</stype>; <stype>weakening</stype>]<br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moderation</ent><br/
<hw>Mod`er*a"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>moderatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mod<eacute/ration</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of moderating, or of imposing due restraint.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state or quality of being mmoderate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In <qex>moderation</qex> placing all my glory,<br/
While Tories call me Whig, and Whigs a Tory.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Calmness of mind; equanimity; <as>as, to bear adversity with <ex>moderation</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The calm and judicious <qex>moderation</qex> of Orange.</q> <rj><qau>Motley.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>The first public examinations for degrees at the University of Oxford; -- usually contracted to <altname>mods</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 935 --></p>

<p><ent>Moderatism</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"er*a*tism</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/d"<etil/r*<asl/*t<icr/z'm)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Moderation in doctrines or opinion, especially in politics or religion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moderato</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mod`e*ra"to</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a. & adv.</pos> <ety>[It. See <er>Moderate</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>With a moderate degree of quickness; moderately.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Allegro moderato</b></col>, <cd>a little slower than allegro.</cd> -- <col><b>Andante moderato</b></col>, <cd>a little faster than andante.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moderator</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"er*a`tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.: cf. F. <ets>mod<eacute/rateur</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, moderates, restrains, or pacifies.</def>  <rj><au>Sir W. Raleigh.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Angling was . . . a <qex>moderator</qex> of passions.</q> <rj><qau>Walton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The officer who presides over an assembly or discussion to preserve order, propose questions, regulate the proceedings, and declare the votes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>In the University of Oxford, an examiner for moderations; at Cambridge, the superintendant of examinations for degrees; at Dublin, either the first (senior) or second (junior) in rank in an examination for the degree of Bachelor of Arts.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A mechanical arrangement for regulating motion in a machine, or producing equality of effect.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moderatorship</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"er*a`tor*ship</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The office of a moderator.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moderatress</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"er*a`tress</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A female moderator.</def>  <rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moderatrix</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"er*a`trix</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.]</ety> <def>A female moderator.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modern</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"ern</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>moderne</ets>, L. <ets>modernus</ets>; akin to <ets>modo</ets> just now, orig. abl. of <ets>modus</ets> measure; hence, by measure, just now. See <er>Mode</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the present time, or time not long past; late; not ancient or remote in past time; of recent period; <as>as, <ex>modern</ex> days, ages, or time; <ex>modern</ex> authors; <ex>modern</ex> fashions; <ex>modern</ex> taste; <ex>modern</ex> practice.</as></def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>New and common; trite; commonplace.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We have our philosophical persons, to make <qex>modern</qex> and familiar, things supernatural and causeless.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Modern English</b></col>. <cd>See the Note under <er>English</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modern</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"ern</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A person of modern times; -- opposed to <ant>ancient</ant>.</def>  <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>modernisation</ent><br/
<hw>modernisation</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Modernization.</def>  <mark>[Chiefly Brit.]</mark> <br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> modernizing.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modernism</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"ern*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Modern practice; a thing of recent date; esp., a modern usage or mode of expression.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Certain methods and tendencies which, in Biblical questions, apologetics, and the theory of dogma, in the endeavor to reconcile the doctrines of the Roman Catholic Church with the conclusions of modern science, replace the authority of the church by purely subjective criteria; -- so called officially by Pope Pius X.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modernist</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"ern*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>moderniste</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who admires the moderns, or their ways and fashions.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An advocate of the teaching of modern subjects, as modern languages, in preference to the ancient classics.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>modernistic</ent><br/
<hw>modernistic</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Conspicuously (sometimes outrageously) modern in style or appearance; <as>as, shiny tables in <ex>modernistic</ex> design</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modernity</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*der"ni*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Modernness; something modern.</def>  <rj><au>Walpole.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modernization</ent><br/
<hw>Mod`ern*i*za"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of rendering modern in style; the act or process of causing to conform to modern of thinking or acting.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modernize</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"ern*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Modernized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Modernizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>moderniser</ets>.]</ety> <def>To render modern; to adapt to modern person or things; to cause to conform to recent or present usage or taste.</def>  <rj><au>Percy.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modernizer</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"ern*i`zer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who modernizes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modernly</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"ern*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In modern times.</def>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modernness</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"ern*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being modern; recentness; novelty.</def>  <rj><au>M. Arnold.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modest</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"est</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>modeste</ets>, L. <ets>modestus</ets>, fr. <ets>modus</ets> measure. See <er>Mode</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Restraining within due limits of propriety; not forward, bold, boastful, or presumptious; rather retiring than pushing one's self forward; not obstructive; <as>as, a <ex>modest</ex> youth; a <ex>modest</ex> man.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Observing the proprieties of the sex; not unwomanly in act or bearing; free from undue familiarity, indecency, or lewdness; decent in speech and demeanor; -- said of a woman.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mrs. Ford, the honest woman, the <qex>modest</qex> wife.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The blushing beauties of a <qex>modest</qex> maid.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Evincing modestly in the actor, author, or speaker; not showing presumption; not excessive or extreme; moderate; <as>as, a <ex>modest</ex> request; <ex>modest</ex> joy.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Reserved; unobtrusive; diffident; bashful; coy; shy; decent; becoming; chaste; virtuous.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modestly</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"est*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a modest manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modesty</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"es*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>modestia</ets>: cf. F. <ets>modestie</ets>. See <er>Modest</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality or state of being modest; that lowly temper which accompanies a moderate estimate of one's own worth and importance; absence of self-assertion, arrogance, and presumption; humility respecting one's own merit.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Natural delicacy or shame regarding personal charms and the sexual relation; purity of thought and manners; due regard for propriety in speech or action.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her blush is guiltiness, not <qex>modesty</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Modesty piece</b></col>, <cd>a narrow piece of lace worn by women over the bosom.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Bashfulness; humility; diffidence; shyness. See <er>Bashfulness</er>, and <er>Humility</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modicity</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*dic"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>modicitas</ets>; cf. F. <ets>modicit<eacute/</ets>.]</ety> <def>Moderateness; smallness; meanness.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modicum</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"i*cum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. <ets>modicus</ets> moderate, fr. <ets>modus</ets>. See <er>Mode</er>.]</ety> <def>A little; a small quantity; a measured supply.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Modicums</xex> of wit.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her usual <qex>modicum</qex> of beer and punch.</q> <rj><qau>Thackeray.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modifiability</ent><br/
<hw>Mod`i*fi`a*bil"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Capability of being modified; state or quality of being modifiable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modifiable</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"i*fi`a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Modify</er>.]</ety> <def>Capable of being modified; liable to modification.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modificable</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*dif"i*ca*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Modifiable.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modificate</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"i*fi*cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Modify</er>.]</ety> <def>To qualify.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bp. Pearson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modification</ent><br/
<hw>Mod`i*fi*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>modificatio</ets> a measuring: cf. F. <ets>modification</ets>. See <er>Modify</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of modifying, or the state of being modified; a change; <as>as, the <ex>modification</ex> of an opinion, or of a machine.</as></def>  <rj><au>Bentley.</au></rj><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> change, alteration, adjustment.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Something which has been modified; a modified form or condition; state as modified; <as>as, the various <ex>modifications</ex> of light; the latest <ex>modification</ex> of the operating system crashes less frequently</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> model{8}.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>The alteration of the meaning of a word or phrase by another word or phrase; -- usually a restriction of the scope of the word modified; <as>as, in the phrase <ldquo/a billion dollars is a <examp>relatively</examp> small sum to spend on cancer research<rdquo/ the <ex>modification</ex> of <it>small</it> by <examp>relatively</examp> is needed to make the sentence accurate, rather than ludicrous</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modificative</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"i*fi*ca*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>That which modifies or qualifies, as a word or clause.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modificatory</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"i*fi*ca`to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Tending or serving to modify; modifying.</def>  <rj><au>Max M<uum/ller.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modifier</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"i*fi`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, modifies.</def>  <rj><au>Hume.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>A word or phrase that modifies another word, phrase, or sentence, usually by limiting the scope or restricting the meaning of the sentence element modified.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modify</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"i*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Modified</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Modifying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>modifier</ets>, L. <ets>modificare</ets>, <ets>modificari</ets>; <ets>modus</ets> limit + <ets>-ficare</ets> (in comp.) to make. See <er>Mode</er>, and <er>-fy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To change somewhat the form or qualities of; to change a part of something while leaving most parts unchanged; to alter somewhat; <as>as, to <ex>modify</ex> a contrivance adapted to some mechanical purpose; to <ex>modify</ex> the terms of a contract.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To limit or reduce in extent or degree; to moderate; to qualify; to lower.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of his grace<br/
He <qex>modifies</qex> his first severe decree.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modillion</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*dil"lion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>modillon</ets>, It. <ets>modiglione</ets>.  Cf. <er>Module</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>The enriched block or horizontal bracket generally found under the cornice of the Corinthian and Composite entablature, and sometimes, less ornamented, in the Ionic and other orders; -- so called because of its arrangement at regulated distances.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modiolar</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*di"o*lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>modiolus</ets>, dim. of <ets>modius</ets> the Roman corn measure.]</ety> <def>Shaped like a bushel measure.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modiolus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo*di"o*lus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Modioli</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., a small measure.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The central column in the osseous cochlea of the ear.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modish</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"ish</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>According to the mode, or customary manner; conformed to the fashion; fashionable; hence, conventional; <as>as, a <ex>modish</ex> dress; a <ex>modish</ex> feast.</as></def> <au>Dryden.</au> <ldquo/<xex>Modish</xex> forms of address.<rdquo/ <au>Barrow.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Mod"ish*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mod"ish*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modist</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"ist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who follows the fashion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modiste</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo`diste"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. See <er>Mode</er>; cf. <er>Modist</er>.]</ety> <def>One, esp. a woman, who makes, or deals in, articles of fashion, esp. of the fashionable dress of ladies; a dress-maker or milliner.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modius</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo"di*us</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Modii</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L.]</ety> <fld>(Rom. Antiq.)</fld> <def>A dry measure, containing about a peck.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modocs</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"docs</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos>; <sing>sing. <singw>Modoc</singw> <pr>(<?/)</pr></sing>. <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>A tribe of warlike Indians formerly inhabiting Northern California. They are nearly extinct.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modular</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"u*lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to mode, modulation, module, or modius; <as>as, <ex>modular</ex> arrangement; <ex>modular</ex> accent; <ex>modular</ex> measure.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modulate</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"u*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Modulated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Modulating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>modulatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>modulari</ets> to measure, to modulate, fr. <ets>modulus</ets> a small measure, meter, melody, dim. of <ets>modus</ets>. See <er>Mode</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To form, as sound, to a certain key, or to a certain portion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To vary or inflect in a natural, customary, or musical manner; <as>as, the organs of speech <ex>modulate</ex> the voice in reading or speaking</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Could any person so <qex>modulate</qex> her voice as to deceive so many?</q> <rj><qau>Broome.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Electronics)</fld> <def>To alter the amplitude, frequency, phase, or intensity of (the carrier wave of a radio signal) at intervals, so as to represent information to be conveyed by the signal; -- a technique used to convey information by means of radio waves transmitted by one electronic device and received by another.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modulate</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"u*late</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>To pass from one key into another.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>modulated</ent><br/
<hw>modulated</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <fld>(Electronics)</fld> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having either amplitude, intensity, frequency, or phase altered at intervals to represent information to be transmitted; -- of the carrier wave of a radio signal transmitted from one device to another for the purpose of conveying information.  Opposite of <ant>unmodulated</ant>.</def> [Narrower terms: <stype>frequency modulated</stype>; <stype>amplitude modulated</stype>]<br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>altered in volume as well as tone or pitch.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modulation</ent><br/
<hw>Mod`u*la"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>modulatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>modulation</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of modulating, or the state of being modulated; <as>as, the <ex>modulation</ex> of the voice</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Sound modulated; melody.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Thomson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A change of key, whether transient, or until the music becomes established in the new key; a shifting of the tonality of a piece, so that the harmonies all center upon a new keynote or tonic; the art of transition out of the original key into one nearly related, and so on, it may be, by successive changes, into a key quite remote. There are also sudden and unprepared modulations.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Electronics)</fld> <def>The alteration of hte amplitude, intensity, frequency, or phase (of the carrier wave of a radio signal) at intervals, so as to represent information to be transmitted.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modulator</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"u*la`tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.]</ety> <def>One who, or that which, modulates.</def>  <rj><au>Denham.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>modulator-demodulator</ent><br/
<hw>mod"u*la`tor-de`mod"u*la`tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An electronic device that converts electronic signals into sound waves, and sound waves into electronic signals, used to transmit information between computers by the use of ordinary telephone lines; usually called a <altname>modem</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Module</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"ule</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>modulus</ets> a small measure, dim. of <ets>modus</ets>. See <er>Mode</er>, and cf. <er>Model</er>, <er>Modulus</er>, <er>Mold</er> a matrix.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A model or measure.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>The size of some one part, as the diameter of semi-diameter of the base of a shaft, taken as a unit of measure by which the proportions of the other parts of the composition are regulated. Generally, for columns, the semi-diameter is taken, and divided into a certain number of parts, called <xex>minutes</xex> (see <er>Minute</er>), though often the diameter is taken, and any dimension is said to be so many <xex>modules</xex> and <xex>minutes</xex> in height, breadth, or projection.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Module</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"ule</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See <er>module</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, <er>Modulate</er>.]</ety> <def>To model; also, to modulate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sandys.</au>  <au>Drayton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modulus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mod"u*lus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Moduli</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., a small measure. See <er>Module</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <fld>(Math., Mech., & Physics)</fld> <def>A quantity or coefficient, or constant, which expresses the measure of some specified force, property, or quality, as of elasticity, strength, efficiency, etc.; a parameter.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Modulus of a machine</b></col>, <cd>a formula expressing the work which a given machine can perform under the conditions involved in its construction; the relation between the work done upon a machine by the moving power, and that yielded at the working points, either constantly, if its motion be uniform, or in the interval of time which it occupies in passing from any given velocity to the same velocity again, if its motion be variable; -- called also the <xex>efficiency</xex> of the machine.</cd> <au>Mosley.</au> <au>Rankine.</au> -- <col><b>Modulus of a system of logarithms</b></col> <fld>(Math.)</fld>, <cd>a number by which all the Napierian logarithms must be multiplied to obtain the logarithms in another system.</cd> -- <col><b>Modulus of elasticity</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The measure of the elastic force of any substance, expressed by the ratio of a stress on a given unit of the substance to the accompanying distortion, or strain</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>An expression of the force (usually in terms of the height in feet or weight in pounds of a column of the same body) which would be necessary to elongate a prismatic body of a transverse section equal to a given unit, as a square inch or foot, to double, or to compress it to half, its original length, were that degree of elongation or compression possible, or within the limits of elasticity; -- called also <altname>Young's modulus</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Modulus of rupture</b></col>, <cd>the measure of the force necessary to break a given substance across, as a beam, expressed by eighteen times the load which is required to break a bar of one inch square, supported flatwise at two points one foot apart, and loaded in the middle between the points of support.</cd> <au>Rankine.</au></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo"dus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Modi</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. See <er>Mode</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Old Law)</fld> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The arrangement of, or mode of expressing, the terms of a contract or conveyance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A qualification involving the idea of variation or departure from some general rule or form, in the way of either restriction or enlargement, according to the circumstances of the case, as in the will of a donor, an agreement between parties, and the like.</def>  <rj><au>Bracton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A fixed compensation or equivalent given instead of payment of tithes in kind, expressed in full by the phrase <altname>modus decimandi</altname>.</def>  <rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They, from time immemorial, had paid a <qex>modus</qex>, or composition.</q> <rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modus operandi</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo"dus op`er*an"di</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr> <ety>[L.]</ety>, <def>manner of operating. Often abbreviated to <altname>MO</altname></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Modus vivendi</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo"dus vi*ven"di</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[L.]</ety> <def>Mode, or manner, of living; hence, a temporary arrangement of affairs until disputed matters can be settled.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mody</ent><br/
<hw>Mod"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mode</er>.]</ety> <def>Fashionable.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moe</ent><br/
<hw>Moe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A wry face or mouth; a mow.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moe</ent><br/
<hw>Moe</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make faces; to mow.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moe</ent><br/
<hw>Moe</hw>, <pos>a., adv., & n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<amac/</ets> See <er>More</er>.]</ety> <def>More. See <er>Mo</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/Sing no more ditties, sing no <xex>moe</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moebles</ent><br/
<hw>Moe"bles</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[OE., fr. OF. <ets>moeble</ets>, <ets>mueble</ets>, movable, from L. <ets>mobilis</ets>.]</ety> <def>Movables; furniture; -- also used in the singular (<singw><it>moeble</it></singw>).</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<-- here we mark both the singular word and the written font -->  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moelline</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"el*line</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>moelle</ets>, fr. L. <ets>medulla</ets> marrow.]</ety> <def>An unguent for the hair.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moellon</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"el*lon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>Rubble masonry.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moesogothic</ent><br/
<hw>Moe`so*goth"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Belonging to the Moesogoths, a branch of the Goths who settled in Moesia.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moesogothic</ent><br/
<hw>Moe`so*goth"ic</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The language of the Moesogoths; -- also called <altname>Gothic</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moeve</ent><br/
<hw>Moeve</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To move.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moff</ent><br/
<hw>Moff</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A thin silk stuff made in Caucasia.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mog</ent><br/
<hw>Mog</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>  <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mogged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mogging</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Etym. unknown.]</ety> <def>To move away; to go off.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng. or Local, U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mogen David</ent><br/
<hw>Mogen David</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Hebrew, shield of David.]</ety> <def>A hexagram{1a}, when used as the symbol of Judaism; called also <altname>Magen David</altname> and <altname>Star of David</altname>.  It is included on the flag of the state of Israel</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Star of David, Magen David.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moggan</ent><br/
<hw>Mog"gan</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A closely fitting knit sleeve; also, a legging of knitted material.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moghul</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*ghul"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>an alternate from of <er>mogul</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mogul</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*gul"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From the Mongolian.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A person of the Mongolian race.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <def>Any of the Mongolian peoples who conquered parts of India and established an empire lasting from 1526 to 1857.  Also, any of their descendents.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Railroad)</fld> <def>A heavy locomotive for freight traffic, having three pairs of connected driving wheels and a two-wheeled truck.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A great personage; magnate; autocrat; <as>as, an industrial <ex>mogul</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Great Mogul</b></col>, <it>or</it>  <col><b>Grand Mogul</b></col></mcol>, <cd>the sovereign of the empire founded in Hindustan by the Mongols under <persfn>Baber</persfn> in the sixteenth century.  Hence, a very important personage; a lord; -- sometimes only <altname>mogul</altname> or <altname>Moghul</altname>.</cd></cs>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mogul</ent><br/
<ent>Moghul</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Mo*ghul"</hw>, <hw>Mo*gul"</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mogul</er>, <pos>n.</pos>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to the Moguls{2}; <as>as, The Taj Mahal, the most beautiful piece of <ex>Mogul</ex> architecture, was built by the <ex>Mogul</ex> emperor <person>Shah Jehan</person> as a mausoleum for his favorite wife</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mogul empire</ent><br/
<ent>Moghul empire</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Mo*ghul" empire</hw>, <hw>Mo*gul" empire</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mogul</er>, <pos>n.</pos>.]</ety> <def>The empire created in <country>India</country> by invading Mongolians (Tatars), established under <persfn>Baber</persfn>, who conquered Hindustan in 1526.  The established religion of the empire was Islam.  After the death of the Great Mogul <persfn>Aurung-Zeb</persfn> in 1707, power passed to the Mahrattas and the British.  The empire existed only nominally in the early 1800's, and was finally abolished in 1857 by the deposing of the last emperor.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moha</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ha</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A kind of millet (<spn>Setaria Italica</spn>); German millet.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mohair</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"hair`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>moire</ets>, perh. from Ar. <ets>mukhayyar</ets> a kind of coarse camelot or haircloth; but prob. fr. L. <ets>marmoreus</ets> of marble, resembling marble.  Cf. <er>Moire</er>, <er>Marble</er>.]</ety> <def>The long silky hair or wool of the Angora goat of Asia Minor; also, a fabric made from this material, or an imitation of such fabric.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mohammed</ent><br/
<hw>Mohammed</hw> <pr>(m<omac/*h<acr/m"m<ecr/d)</pr> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>['The praised one'.]</ety> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>Mahomed</asp>, <asp>Mahomet</asp>, <asp>Muhammad</asp> (the Arabic form), <asp>Mahmoud</asp>, <asp>Mehemet</asp>, etc.]</altsp> <def>The prophet who founded Islam (570-632).</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Muhammad, Mahomet, Mahmoud.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><bio> Mohammed (or Mahomet <pr>(ma*hom"et)</pr>) was born at Mecca, Arabia, about 570: died at Medina, Arabia, June 8, 632.  He was the founder of Islam ('surrender,' namely, to God), formerly also called Mohammedanism.  He was the posthumous son of Abdallah by his wife Amina, of the family of Hashim, the noblest among the Koreish, and was brought up in the desert among the Banu Saad by a Bedouin woman named <persfn>Halima</persfn>.  At the age of six he lost his mother, and at eight his grandfather, when he was cared for by his uncle <persfn>Abu-Talib</persfn>.  When about twelve years old (582) he accompanied a caravan to Syria, and may on this occasion have come for the first time in contact with Jews and Christians.  A few years later he took part in the "sacrilegious war" (so called because carried on during the sacred months, when fighting was forbidden) which raged between the Koreish and the Banu Hawazin 580-590.  He attended sundry preachings and recitations at Okatz, which may have awakened his poetical and rhetorical powers and his religious feelings; and for some time was occupied as a shepherd, to which he later refers as being in accordance with his career as a prophet, even as it was with that of Moses and David.  When twenty-five years old he entered the service of the widow <persfn>Khadijah</persfn>, and made a second journey to Syria, on which he again had an opportunity to come in frequent contact with Jews and Christians, and to acquire some knowledge of their religious teachings.  He soon married <persfn>Khadijah</persfn>, who was fifteen years his senior.  Of the six children which she bore him, <persfn>Fatima</persfn> became the most famous.  In 605 he attained some influence in <city>Mecca</city> by settling a dispute about the rebuilding of the Kaaba.  The impressions which he had gathered from his contact with Judaism and Christianity, and from Arabic lore, began now strongly to engage his mind.  He frequently retired to solitary places, especially to the cave of Mount Hira, north of Mecca.  He passed at that time (he was then about forty years old) through great mental struggles, and repeatedly meditated suicide.  It must have been during these lonely contemplations that the yearnings for a messenger from God for his people, and the thought that he himself might be destined for this mission, were born in his ardent mind.  During one of his reveries, in the month of Ramadan, 610, he beheld in sleep the angel <persfn>Gabriel</persfn>, who ordered him to read from a scroll which he held before him the words which begin the 96th sura (chapter) of the Koran.  After the lapse of some time, a second vision came, and then the revelations began to follow one another frequently.  His own belief in his mission as apostle and prophet of God was now firmly established.  The first convert was his wife <persfn>Khadijah</persfn>, then followed his cousin and adopted son <persfn>Ali</persfn>, his other adopted son <persfn>Zeid</persfn>, and <persfn>Abu-Bekr</persfn>, afterward his father-in-law and first successor (calif).  Gradually about 60 adherents rallied about him.  But after three years' preaching the mass of the Meccans rose against him, so that part of his followers had to resort to Abyssinia for safety in 614.  This is termed the first hejira.  Mohammed in the meanwhile continued his meetings in the house of one of his disciples, Arqaan, in front of the Kaaba, which later became known as the "House of Islam."  At one time he offered the Koreish a compromise, admitting their gods into his system as intercessors with the Supreme Being, but, becoming conscience-stricken, took back his words.  The conversion of <persfn>Hamza</persfn> and <persfn>Omar</persfn> and 39 others in 615-616 strengthened his cause.  The Koreish excommunicated Mohammed and his followers, who were forced to live in retirement.  In 620, at the pilgrimage, he won over to his teachings a small party from <city>Medina</city>.  In <city>Medina</city>, whither a teacher was deputed, the new religion spread rapidly.  To this period belongs the vision or dream of the miraculous ride, on the winged horse Borak, to Jerusalem, where he was received by the prophets, and thence ascended to heaven.  In 622 more than 70 persons from Medina bound themselves to stand by Mohammed.  The Meccans proposed to kill him, and he fled on the 20th of June, 622, to Medina.  This is known as the hejira ('the flight'), and marks the beginning of the Muslim era.  This event formed a turning-point in the activity of Mohammed.  He was thus far a religious preacher and persuader; he became in his Medinian period a legislator and warrior.  He built there in 623 the first mosque, and married <persfn>Ayesha</persfn>.  In 624 the first battle for the faith took place between Mohammed and the Meccans in the plain of Bedr, in which the latter were defeated.  At this time, also, <persfn>Mohammed</persfn> began bitterly to inveigh against the Jews, who did not recognize his claims to be the "greater prophet" promised by <persfn>Moses</persfn>.  He changed the attitude of prayer (kibla) from the direction of Jerusalem to that of the Kaaba in <city>Mecca</city>, appointed Friday as the day for public worship, and instituted the fast of Ramadan and the tithe or poor-rate.  The Jewish tribe of the Banu Kainuka, settled at <city>Medina</city>, was driven out; while of another Jewish tribe, the Banu Kuraiza, all the men, 700 in number, were massacred.  In 625 Mohammed and his followers were defeated by the Meccans in the battle of Ohud.  The following years were filled out with expeditions.  One tribe after another submitted to <persfn>Mohammed</persfn>, until in 631 something like a definite Muslim empire was established.  In 632 the prophet made his last pilgrimage to <city>Mecca</city>, known as the "farewell pilgrimage," or the pilgrimage of the "announcement" or of "Islam."  In the same year he died while planning an expedition against the frontier of the Byzantine empire.  <city>Mohammed</city> was a little above the middle height, of a commanding figure, and is described as being of a modest, tender, and generous disposition.  His manner of life was very simple and frugal.  He mended his own clothes, and his common diet was barley-bread and water.   But he enjoyed perfumes and the charms of women.  His character appears composed of the strongest inconsistencies.  He could be tender, kind, and liberal, but on occasions indulged in cruel and perfidious assassinations.  With regard to his prophetic claims, it is as difficult to assume that he was sincere throughout, or self-deceived, as that he was throughout an impostor.  In his doctrines there is practically nothing original.  The legends of the Koran are chiefly drawn from the Old Testament and the rabbinical literature, which <persfn>Mohammed</persfn> must have learned from a Jew near <city>Mecca</city>, though he presents them as original revelations by the angel <persfn>Gabriel</persfn>, See <er>Koran</er>.</bio><br/
[<source>Century Dict. 1906</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mohammedan</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*ham"med*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <ets>Mohammed</ets>, fr. Ar. <ets>muh<aacute/mmad</ets> praiseworthy, highly praised.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to Mohammed, or to Islam, the religion and institutions founded by Mohammed; in the latter sense, synonymous with <altname>Islamic</altname>, the term preferred by Moslems.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>Mahometan</asp>, <asp>Mahomedan</asp>, <asp>Muhammadan</asp>, etc.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mohammedan</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*ham"med*an</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A follower of Mohammed, the founder of Islam (also called Islamism or Mohammedanism); an adherent of Islam; one who professes Islam; a Muslim; a Moslem; a Musselman; -- this term is used mostly by non-Moslems, and some Moslems find it offensive.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>Muhammadan</asp>, <asp>Mahometan</asp>, <asp>Mahomedan</asp>, etc.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mohammedan calendar</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*ham"med*an cal"en*dar</hw>. <def>The Muslim calendar, a lunar calendar reckoning from the year of the hegira (hejira), 622 <sc>a. d.</sc> Thirty of its years constitute a cycle, of which the 2d, 5th, 7th, 10th, 13th, 16th, 18th, 21st, 24th, 26th, and 29th are leap years, having 355 days; the others are common, having 354 days.</def> <note>By the following tables any Mohammedan date may be changed into the Christian date, or vice versa, for the years 1900-1935 <sc>a. d.</sc><br/
