   The following general rule for finding the date of commencement of any Mohammedan year has a maximum error of a day: Multiply 970,224 by the Mohammedan year, point off six decimal places, and add 621.5774. The whole number will be the year <sc>a. d.</sc>, and the decimal multiplied by 365 will give the day of the year.</note><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><note> The Mohammedan calendar is one of the most primitive. It is strictly a Lunar calendar, the year consisting of twelve lunar months, which retrograde through the seasons in about 321/2 years.  To reconcile the lunar cycle to a given number of complete days, a leap year is introduced on the 2nd, 5th, 7th, 10th, 13th, 16th, 18th, 21st, 24th, 26th and 29th years of a thirty year cycle, making these years consist of 355 days instead of 354.  The names of the months and the number of days are: 1, Muharram (30); 2, Saphar (29); 3, Rabia I (30); 4, Rabia II (29); 5, Jomada I (30); 6, Jomada II (29); 7, Rajah (30); 8, Shaaban (29); 9, Ramadan (30); 10, Shawaal (29); 11, Dulkasda (30); and 12, Dulheggia (29 or 30).  The years are calculated from July 16, 622 A.D., the day following the Hegira, the flight of Mohammed from Mecca to Medina after an attempted assassination.  The beginning of the 46th cycle, with the first day of Muharram, in the year 1351, compares to May 7, 1932 of the Gregorian calendar; continuing: 1365 Dec. 6, 1945 1366 Nov. 25, 1946 1367 Nov. 15, 1947 1368 Nov. 3, 1948 1369 Oct. 24, 1949 1370 Oct. 13, 1950 1371 Oct. 2, 1951 1372 Sept. 21, 1952 1373 Sept. 10, 1953 1374 Aug. 30, 1954 To find the Gregorian equivalent to any Mohammedan date multiply 970,224 by the Mohammedan year, point off six decimal places and add 621.5774. The whole number will be the year A.D., and the decimal multiplied by 365 will be the day of the year. </note> <au>http://www.arsakeio.gr/universe/timeref1.htm</au><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mohammedan Era</ent><br/
<hw>Mohammedan Era</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The era in use in Moslem countries. See <er>Mohammedan year</er>, below.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mohammedism</ent><br/
<ent>Mohammedanism</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mo*ham"med*an*ism</hw>, <hw>Mo*ham"med*ism</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The religion, or doctrines and precepts, of <persfn>Mohammed</persfn>, contained in the <book>Koran</book>; Islamism; Islam.  The term <altname>Islam</altname> is preferred by most Moslems, and some find the term <ex>Mohammedanism</ex> to be offensive, as they worship <persfn>Allah</persfn>, not <persfn>Mohammed</persfn>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mohammedize</ent><br/
<ent>Mohammedanize</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mo*ham"med*an*ize</hw>, <hw>Mo*ham"med*ize</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. v. t.</pos> <def>To make conformable to the principles, or customs and rites, of Islam.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>Mahometanize</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mohammedan year</ent><br/
<hw>Mohammedan year</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The year used by Muslims, consisting of twelve lunar months without intercalation, so that they retrograde through all the seasons in about 32<frac12/ years.  The Mohammedan era begins with the year 622 <sc>a. d.</sc>, the first day of the Mohammedan year 1332 being Nov. 30, 1913, according to the Gregorian calendar.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mohawk</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"hawk</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>One of a tribe of Indians who formed part of the Five Nations.  They formerly inhabited the valley of the Mohawk River.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One of certain ruffians who infested the streets of London in the time of Addison, and took the name from the Mohawk Indians.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark>  <rj><au>Spectator. Macaulay.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mohicans</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*hi"cans</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n. pl.</pos>; <sing>sing. <singw>Mohican</singw> <pr>(<?/)</pr></sing>. <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>A tribe of Lenni-Lenape Indians who formerly inhabited Western Connecticut and Eastern New York.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>Mohegans</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moho</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo"ho</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Native name.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A gallinule (<spn>Notornis Mantelli</spn>) formerly inhabiting New Zealand, but now supposed to be extinct.  It was incapable of flight. See <er>Notornis</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moho</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ho</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Short for <ets>Mohorovicic discontinuity</ets>, from <person>Andrija <etsep>Mohorovi<ccar/i<cacute/</etsep></person>, a Yugoslavian geologist.]</ety> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>The boundary between the earth's crust and the semiliquid mantle beneath.  It varies in depth from 3 miles beneath the surface at certain points in the ocean to over 25 miles under certain parts of continents.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mohock</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"hock</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mohawk</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moholi</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo*ho"li</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Maholi</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mohorovicic discontinuity</ent><br/
<hw>Mohorovicic discontinuity</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>same as 2nd <er>Moho</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mohr</ent><br/
<hw>Mohr</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A West African gazelle (<spn>Gazella mohr</spn>), having horns on which are eleven or twelve very prominent rings. It is one of the species which produce bezoar.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mhorr</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mohur</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"hur</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Hind., fr. Per. <ets>muhur</ets>, <ets>muhr</ets>, a gold coin, a seal, seal ring.]</ety> <def>A British Indian gold coin, of the value of fifteen silver rupees, or $7.21 (in 1913).</def>  <rj><au>Malcom.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muharram</ent><br/
<ent>Mohurrum</ent><br/
<mhw>{ \'d8<hw>Mo*hur"rum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, \'d8<hw>Mu*har"ram</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Ar. <ets>muharram</ets>, prop., sacred, forbidden, n., the first month of the Mohammedan lunar year.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The first month of the Mohammedan year.</def>  <rj><au>Whitworth.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A festival of the Shiah sect of the Muslims held during the first ten days of the month Mohurrum.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moider</ent><br/
<hw>Moi"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To toil.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng. & Scot.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moidore</ent><br/
<hw>Moi"dore</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pg. <ets>moeda d'ouro</ets>, lit., coin of gold.  Cf. <er>Money</er>, and <er>Aureate</er>.]</ety> <def>A gold coin of Portugal, valued at about 27s. sterling.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 936 --></p>

<p><ent>Moiety</ent><br/
<hw>Moi"e*ty</hw> <pr>(moi"<esl/*t<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Moieties</plw> <pr>(moi"<esl/*t<icr/z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F. <ets>moiti<eacute/</ets>, L. <ets>medietas</ets>, fr. <ets>medius</ets> middle, half. See <er>Mid</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and cf. <er>Mediate</er>, <er>Mediety</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One of two equal parts; a half; <as>as, a <ex>moiety</ex> of an estate, of goods, or of profits; the <ex>moiety</ex> of a jury, or of a nation.</as></def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The more beautiful <qex>moiety</qex> of his majesty's subject.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An indefinite part; a small part.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moil</ent><br/
<hw>Moil</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Moiled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Moiling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>moillen</ets> to wet, OF. <ets>moillier</ets>, <ets>muillier</ets>, F. <ets>mouller</ets>, fr. (assumed) LL. <ets>molliare</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mollis</ets> soft. See <er>Mollify</er>.]</ety> <def>To daub; to make dirty; to soil; to defile.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou . . . doest thy mind in dirty pleasures <qex>moil</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moil</ent><br/
<hw>Moil</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Moil</er> to daub; prob. from the idea of struggling through the wet.]</ety> <def>To soil one's self with severe labor; to work with painful effort; to labor; to toil; to drudge.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Moil</qex> not too much under ground.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now he must <qex>moil</qex> and drudge for one he loathes.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moil</ent><br/
<hw>Moil</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A spot; a defilement.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>moil</qex> of death upon them.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs. Browning.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moile</ent><br/
<hw>Moile</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mule</ets> a slipper.]</ety> <def>A kind of high shoe anciently worn.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>moyle</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moineau</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Moi"neau</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <fld>(Fort.)</fld> <def>A small flat bastion, raised in the middle of an overlong curtain.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moira</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Moi"ra</hw> <pr>(moi"r<adot/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>Moi^ra</grk>.]</ety> <fld>(Greek Myth.)</fld> <def>The deity who assigns to every man his lot.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moire</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Moire</hw> <pr>(mw<aum/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.  Cf. <er>Mohair</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Originally, a fine textile fabric made of the hair of an Asiatic goat; afterwards, any textile fabric to which a watered appearance is given in the process of calendering.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A watered, clouded, or frosted appearance produced upon either textile fabrics or metallic surfaces; moi`r<eacute/.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moire</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Moi`r<eacute/"</hw> <pr>(mw<aum/`r<amac/"; m<omac/"r<amac/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A watered, clouded, or frosted appearance on textile fabrics or metallic surfaces.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>Erroneously, moire, the fabric.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn>  <def>A wavy pattern of lines produced by the superposition of two patterns having closely spaced, often curved, lines, so that the lines of the two patterns intersect at an acute angle.  When the superposing patterns are moved relative to the observer or relative to each other, a shimmering effect is produced in which the apparent pattern changes, often producing a pleasing artistic effect.  The effect may be seen, for example, when the superposed folds of a sheer fabric, such as a window curtain, are observed with transmitted light.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> moire pattern.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn>  <fld>(Printing)</fld> <def>An interference pattern produced by the dots of a color printing process.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Moire antique</b></col>, <cd>a superior kind of thick moire.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moire</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Moi`r<eacute/"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F., p.p. of <ets>moirer</ets> to water (silk, etc.). See <er>Moire</er>.]</ety> <def>Watered; having a watered or clouded appearance; -- as of silk or metals.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moire</ent><br/
<hw>Moi*r<eacute/"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>  <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Moir<eacute/ed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Moir<eacute/eing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> Also <hw>Moire</hw>. <ety>[F. <ets>moir<eacute/</ets>.]</ety> <def>To give a watered or clouded appearance to (a surface).</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moire metallique</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Moi`r<eacute/" m<eacute/`tal`lique"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>A crystalline or frosted appearance produced by some acids on tin plate; also, the tin plate thus treated.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moist</ent><br/
<hw>Moist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>moiste</ets>, OF. <ets>moiste</ets>, F. <ets>moite</ets>, fr. L. <ets>muccidus</ets>, for <ets>mucidus</ets>, moldy, musty.  Cf. <er>Mucus</er>, <er>Mucid</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Moderately wet; damp; humid; not dry; <as>as, a <ex>moist</ex> atmosphere or air</as>.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Moist</xex> eyes.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fresh, or new.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/Shoes full <xex>moist</xex> and new.<rdquo/ <ldquo/A draught of <xex>moist</xex> and corny ale.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moist</ent><br/
<hw>Moist</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To moisten.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moisten</ent><br/
<hw>Mois"ten</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Moistened</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Moistening</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make damp; to wet in a small degree.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A pipe a little <qex>moistened</qex> on the inside.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To soften by making moist; to make tender.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It <qex>moistened</qex> not his executioner's heart with any pity.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moistener</ent><br/
<hw>Mois"ten*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who, or that which, moistens.</def>  <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moistful</ent><br/
<hw>Moist"ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Full of moisture.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moistless</ent><br/
<hw>Moist"less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Without moisture; dry.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moistness</ent><br/
<hw>Moist"ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being moist.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moisture</ent><br/
<hw>Mois"ture</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>moistour</ets>, F. <ets>moiteur</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A moderate degree of wetness.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which moistens or makes damp or wet; exuding fluid; liquid in small quantity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All my body's <qex>moisture</qex><br/
Scarce serves to quench my furnace-burning heat.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moistureless</ent><br/
<hw>Mois"ture*less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Without moisture.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moisty</ent><br/
<hw>Moist"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Moist.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moither</ent><br/
<hw>Moi"ther</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Etymol. uncertain.]</ety> <def>To perplex; to confuse.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>  <rj><au>Lamb.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moither</ent><br/
<hw>Moi"ther</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To toil; to labor.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mojarra</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*jar"ra</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp.]</ety> <def>Any of certain basslike marine fishes (mostly of tropical seas, and having a deep, compressed body, protracile mouth, and large silvery scales) constituting the family <fam>Gerridae</fam>, as <spn>Gerres plumieri</spn>, found from Florida to Brazil and used as food.  Also, any of numerous other fishes of similar appearance but belonging to other families.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mokadour</ent><br/
<hw>Mok"a*dour</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>mocador</ets> handkerchief.]</ety> <def>A handkerchief.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moke</ent><br/
<hw>Moke</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A stupid person; a dolt.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A donkey.</def> <mark>[Cant]</mark>  <rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn>  <def>A negro.</def> <mark>[U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn>  <fld>(Theat. Slang)</fld> <ety>[More fully <ets>musical moke</ets>.]</ety> <def>A performer, as a minstrel, who plays on several instruments.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moke</ent><br/
<hw>Moke</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mesh of a net, or of anything resembling a net.</def>  <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moky</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ky</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Icel. <ets>m<oum/kkvi</ets> cloud, mist, <ets>m<oum/kkr</ets> a dense cloud, W. <ets>mwg</ets> smoke, and E. <ets>muggy</ets>, <ets>muck</ets>.]</ety> <def>Misty; dark; murky; muggy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mol</ent><br/
<hw>mol</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A quantity of a substance equal to the molecular weight of a substance expressed in grams; a gram molecule; the basic unit of amount of substance adopted under the System International d'Unites; <as>as, he added two <ex>mols</ex> of dextrose to the medium</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> gram molecule, mole.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mola</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Sunfish</er>, 1.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>molal</ent><br/
<hw>molal</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Being at a concentration with the designated number of moles (of solute) per 1000 grams of solvent; <as>as, an 0.5 <ex>molal</ex> solution of glycerol in water</as>.  Compare <er>molar</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>molality</ent><br/
<hw>molality</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A measure of concentaration of substances in mixtures, 1 molal being the concentration of a solution containing 1 mole of solute per 1000 grams of solvent.  Compare <er>molar</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>molar</ent><br/
<hw>mo"lar</hw> <pr>(m<omac/"l<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>moles</ets> mass.]</ety> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to a mass of matter; -- said of the properties or motions of masses, as distinguished from those of molecules or atoms.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>molar</ent><br/
<hw>mo"lar</hw> <pr>(m<omac/"l<etil/r <it>or</it>  m<omac/"l<aum/r)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>moles</ets> mass.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Being at a concentration having the designated number of moles (of solute) per liter of solvent; <as>as, an 0.2 <ex>molar</ex> solution of sodium chloride in water is close to isotonic</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molar</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"lar</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>molaris</ets>, fr. <ets>mola</ets> mill, fr. <ets>molere</ets> to grind in a mill. See <er>Mill</er> the machine.]</ety> <def>Having power to grind; grinding; <as>as, the <ex>molar</ex> teeth</as>; also, of or pertaining to the molar teeth.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molar</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"lar</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Any one of the teeth back of the incisors and canines.  The molars which replace the deciduous or milk teeth are designated as <stype>premolars</stype>, and those which are not preceded by deciduous teeth are sometimes called <stype>true molars</stype>. See <er>Tooth</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molary</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"la*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Same as 2d <er>Molar</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molasse</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*lasse"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>molasse</ets>, prob. fr. <ets>mollasse</ets> flabby, flimsy, fr. L. <ets>mollis</ets> soft.]</ety> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>A soft Tertiary sandstone; -- applied to a rock occurring in Switzerland. See <xex>Chart</xex> of <er>Geology</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molasses</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*las"ses</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<eacute/lasse</ets>, cf. Sp. <ets>melaza</ets>, Pg. <ets>mela<cced/o</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mellaceus</ets> honeylike, honey-sweet, <ets>mel</ets>, <ets>mellis</ets>, honey. See <er>Mellifluous</er>, and cf. <er>Melasses</er>.]</ety> <def>The thick, brown or dark colored, viscid, uncrystallizable sirup which drains from sugar, in the process of manufacture; any thick, viscid, sweet sirup made from vegetable juice or sap, as of the sorghum or maple. See <er>Treacle</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mold</ent><br/
<hw>Mold</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mole</er> a spot.]</ety> <def>A spot; a blemish; a mole.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mould</ent><br/
<ent>Mold</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mold</hw>, <hw>Mould</hw>}</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>molde</ets>, AS. <ets>molde</ets>; akin to D. <ets>mul</ets>, G. <ets>mull</ets>, <ets>mulm</ets>, OHG. <ets>molt</ets>, <ets>molta</ets>, Icel. <ets>mold</ets>, Dan. <ets>muld</ets>, Sw. <ets>mull</ets>, Goth. <ets>mulda</ets>, and E. <ets>meal</ets> flour. See <er>Meal</er>, and cf. <er>Mole</er> an animal, <er>Mull</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <altsp>[The prevalent spelling is, perhaps, <asp>mould</asp>; but as the <it>u</it> has not been inserted in the other words of this class, as <it>bold</it>, <it>gold</it>, <it>old</it>, <it>cold</it>, etc., it seems desirable to complete the analogy by dropping it from this word, thus spelling it as Spenser, South, and many others did. The omission of the <it>u</it> is now very common in America.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Crumbling, soft, friable earth; esp., earth containing the remains or constituents of organic matter, and suited to the growth of plants; soil.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Earthy material; the matter of which anything is formed; composing substance; material.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The etherial <qex>mold</qex>,<br/
Incapable of stain.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nature formed me of her softest <qex>mold</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mould</ent><br/
<ent>Mold</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mold</hw>, <hw>Mould</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Molded</conjf> or <conjf>Moulded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Molding</conjf> or <conjf>Moulding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To cover with mold or soil.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mould</ent><br/
<ent>Mold</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mold</hw>, <hw>Mould</hw>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From the p. p. of OE. <ets>moulen</ets> to become moldy, to rot, prob. fr. Icel. <ets>mygla</ets> to grow musty, <ets>mugga</ets> mugginess; cf. Sw. <ets>m<oum/gla</ets> to grow moldy. See <er>Muggy</er>, and cf. <er>Moldy</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A growth of minute fungi of various kinds, esp. those of the great groups <fam>Hyphomycetes</fam>, and <fam>Physomycetes</fam>, forming on damp or decaying organic matter.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The common blue mold of cheese, the brick-red cheese mold, and the scarlet or orange strata which grow on tubers or roots stored up for use, when commencing to decay, are familiar examples.  <rj><au>M. J. Berkley.</au></rj></note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mould</ent><br/
<ent>Mold</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mold</hw>, <hw>Mould</hw>, }</mhw> <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cause to become moldy; to cause mold to grow upon.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mould</ent><br/
<ent>Mold</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mold</hw>, <hw>Mould</hw>, }</mhw> <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become moldy; to be covered or filled, in whole or in part, with a mold.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mould</ent><br/
<ent>Mold</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mold</hw>, <hw>Mould</hw>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>molde</ets>, OF. <ets>mole</ets>, F. <ets>moule</ets>, fr. L. <ets>modulus</ets>. See <er>Model</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[For spelling, see 2d <er>Mold</er>, above.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The matrix, or cavity, in which anything is shaped, and from which it takes its form; also, the body or mass containing the cavity; <as>as, a sand <ex>mold</ex>; a jelly <ex>mold</ex>.</as></def>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That on which, or in accordance with which, anything is modeled or formed; anything which serves to regulate the size, form, etc., as the pattern or templet used by a shipbuilder, carpenter, or mason.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The glass of fashion and the <qex>mold</qex> of form.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Cast; form; shape; character.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Crowned with an architrave of antique <qex>mold</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A group of moldings; <as>as, the arch <ex>mold</ex> of a porch or doorway; the pier <ex>mold</ex> of a Gothic pier, meaning the whole profile, section, or combination of parts.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A fontanel.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Paper Making)</fld> <def>A frame with a wire cloth bottom, on which the pump is drained to form a sheet, in making paper by hand.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mould</ent><br/
<ent>Mold</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mold</hw>, <hw>Mould</hw>, }</mhw> <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mouler</ets>, OF. <ets>moler</ets>, <ets>moller</ets>. See <er>Mold</er> the matrix.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To form into a particular shape; to shape; to model; to fashion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He forgeth and <qex>moldeth</qex> metals.</q> <rj><qau>Sir M. Hale.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Did I request thee, Maker, from my clay<br/
To <qex>mold</qex> me man?</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To ornament by molding or carving the material of; <as>as, a <ex>molded</ex> window jamb</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To knead; <as>as, to <ex>mold</ex> dough or bread</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Founding)</fld> <def>To form a mold of, as in sand, in which a casting may be made.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouldable</ent><br/
<ent>Moldable</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mold"a*ble</hw>, <hw>Mould"a*ble</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Capable of being molded or formed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouldboard</ent><br/
<ent>Moldboard</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mold"board`</hw>, <hw>Mould"board`</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A curved plate of iron (originally of wood) back of the share of a plow, which turns over the earth in plowing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Founding)</fld> <def>A follow board.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moulder</ent><br/
<ent>Molder</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mold"er</hw>, <hw>Mould"er</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who, or that which, molds or forms into shape; specifically <fld>(Founding)</fld>, one skilled in the art of making molds for castings.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moulder</ent><br/
<ent>Molder</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mold"er</hw>, <hw>Mould"er</hw>, }</mhw> <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Moldered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or <conjf>Mouldered</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Moldering</conjf> or <conjf>Mouldering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From <er>Mold</er> fine soft earth: cf. Prov. G. <ets>multern</ets>.]</ety> <def>To crumble into small particles; to turn to dust by natural decay; to lose form, or waste away, by a gradual separation of the component particles, without the presence of water; to crumble away.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>moldering</qex> of earth in frosts and sun.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When statues <qex>molder</qex>, and when arches fall.</q> <rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If he had sat still, the enemy's army would have <qex>moldered</qex> to nothing.</q> <rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moulder</ent><br/
<ent>Molder</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mold"er</hw>, <hw>Mould"er</hw>, }</mhw> <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To turn to dust; to cause to crumble; to cause to waste away.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Time's] gradual touch<br/
Has <qex>moldered</qex> into beauty many a tower.</q> <rj><qau>Mason.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouldery</ent><br/
<ent>Moldery</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mold"er*y</hw>, <hw>Mould"er*y</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Covered or filled with mold; consisting of, or resembling, mold.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouldiness</ent><br/
<ent>Moldiness</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mold"i*ness</hw>, <hw>Mould"i*ness</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Moldy</er>.]</ety> <def>The state of being moldy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moulding</ent><br/
<ent>Molding</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mold"ing</hw>, <hw>Mould"ing</hw>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or process of shaping in or on a mold, or of making molds; the art or occupation of a molder.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything cast in a mold, or which appears to be so, as grooved or ornamental bars of wood or metal, or sculptures.</def> <wns>[wns=1]</wns><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mold, mould, molding, modeling, clay sculpture.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A plane, or curved, narrow surface, either sunk or projecting, used for decoration by means of the lights and shades upon its surface.  Moldings vary greatly in pattern, and are generally used in groups, the different members of each group projecting or retreating, one beyond another. See <er>Cable</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 3, and <cref>Crenelated molding</cref>, under <er>Crenelate</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos></def> <wns>[wns=2]</wns><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <specif>Especially:</specif> <def>a decorative strip used for ornamentation or finishing.</def> <wns>[wns=3]</wns><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> moolding.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>a preliminary sculpture in wax or clay from which a finished work can be copied.</def> <wns>[wns=5]</wns><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> modeling, moulding.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moulding</ent><br/
<ent>Molding</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mold"ing</hw>, <hw>Mould"ing</hw>, }</mhw> <pos>p. a.</pos> <def>Used in making a mold or moldings; used in shaping anything according to a pattern.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Molding board</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Moulding board</b></col></mcol>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>See <cref>Follow board</cref>, under <er>Follow</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos></cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A board on which bread or pastry is kneaded and shaped.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Molding machine</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Moulding machine</b></col></mcol>. <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Woodworking)</fld> <cd>A planing machine for making moldings</cd>. (<sd>b</sd>) <fld>(Founding)</fld> <cd>A machine to assist in making molds for castings.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Molding mill</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Moulding mill</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a mill for shaping timber.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Molding sand</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Moulding sand</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Founding)</fld>, <cd>a kind of sand containing clay, used in making molds.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouldwarp</ent><br/
<ent>Moldwarp</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mold"warp</hw>, <hw>Mould"warp</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>moldwerp</ets>: AS. <ets>molde</ets> soil + <ets>weorpan</ets> to throw up; cf. OD. <ets>molworp</ets>, G. <ets>maulwurf</ets>, Icel. <ets>moldvarpa</ets>, Dan. <ets>muldvarp</ets>. See <er>Mold</er> soil, <er>Warp</er>, and cf. <er>Mole</er> the animal.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Mole</er> the animal.</def>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouldy</ent><br/
<ent>Moldy</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mold"y</hw>, <hw>Mould"y</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Moldier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or <adjf>Mouldier</adjf>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Moldiest</adjf> or <adjf>Mouldiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[From <er>Mold</er> the growth of fungi.]</ety> <def>Overgrown with, or containing, mold; smelling of mold; <as>as, <ex>moldy</ex> cheese or bread</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mole</ent><br/
<hw>Mole</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<amac/l</ets>; akin to OHG. <ets>meil</ets>, Goth. <ets>mail</ets> Cf. <er>Mail</er> a spot.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A spot; a stain; a mark which discolors or disfigures.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Piers Plowman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A spot, mark, or small permanent protuberance on the human body; esp., a spot which is dark-colored, from which commonly issue one or more hairs.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mole</ent><br/
<hw>Mole</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mola</ets>.]</ety> <def>A mass of fleshy or other more or less solid matter generated in the uterus.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mole</ent><br/
<hw>Mole</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<ocir/le</ets>, L. <ets>moles</ets>.  Cf. <er>Demolish</er>, <er>Emolument</er>, <er>Molest</er>.]</ety> <def>A mound or massive work formed of masonry or large stones, etc., laid in the sea, often extended either in a right line or an arc of a circle before a port which it serves to defend from the violence of the waves, thus protecting ships in a harbor; also, sometimes, the harbor itself.</def>  <rj><au>Brande & C.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mole</ent><br/
<hw>Mole</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>molle</ets>, either shortened fr. <ets>moldwerp</ets>, or from the root of E. <ets>mold</ets> soil: cf. D. <ets>mol</ets>, OD. <ets>molworp</ets>. See <er>Moldwarp</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any insectivore of the family <fam>Talpidae</fam>.  They have minute eyes and ears, soft fur, and very large and strong fore feet.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The common European mole, or moldwarp (<spn>Talpa Europaea</spn>), is noted for its extensive burrows.  The common American mole, or shrew mole (<spn>Scalops aquaticus</spn>), and star-nosed mole (<spn>Condylura cristata</spn>) have similar habits.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ In the Scriptures, the name is applied to two unindentified animals, perhaps the chameleon and mole rat.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A plow of peculiar construction, for forming underground drains.</def> <mark>[U.S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <mark>(fig.)</mark><def>A spy who lives for years an apparently normal life (to establish a cover) before beginning his spying activities.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Duck mole</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Duck</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Golden mole</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Chrysochlore</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mole cricket</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>an orthopterous insect of the genus <gen>Gryllotalpa</gen>, which excavates subterranean galleries, and throws up mounds of earth resembling those of the mole.  It is said to do damage by injuring the roots of plants.  The common European species (<spn>Gryllotalpa vulgaris</spn>), and the American (<spn>Gryllotalpa borealis</spn>), are the best known.</cd> -- <col><b>Mole rat</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one of several species of Old World rodents of the genera <gen>Spalax</gen>, <gen>Georychus</gen>, and several allied genera.  They are molelike in appearance and habits, and their eyes are small or rudimentary.</cd> -- <col><b>Mole shrew</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one of several species of short-tailed American shrews of the genus <gen>Blarina</gen>, esp. <spn>Blarina brevicauda</spn>.</cd> -- <col><b>Water mole</b></col>, <cd>the duck mole.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mole</ent><br/
<hw>mole</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A quantity of a substance equal to the molecular weight of a substance expressed in grams; a gram molecule; the basic unit of amount of substance adopted under the System International d'Unites; <as>as, he added two <ex>moles</ex> of sodium chloride to the medium</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> gram molecule, mol.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mole</ent><br/
<hw>Mole</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Moled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Moling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To form holes in, as a mole; to burrow; to excavate; <as>as, to <ex>mole</ex> the earth</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To clear of molehills.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>  <rj><au>Pegge.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molebut</ent><br/
<hw>Mole"but</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The sunfish (<gen>Orthagoriscus</gen>, or <gen>Mola</gen>).</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>molebat</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molecast</ent><br/
<hw>Mole"cast`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A little elevation of earth made by a mole; a molehill.</def>  <rj><au>Mortimer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molech</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"lech</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[Heb. <ets>molek</ets> king.]</ety> <fld>(Script.)</fld> <def>The fire god of the Ammonites, to whom human sacrifices were offered; Moloch.</def>  <rj><au>Lev. xviii. 21.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molecular</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*lec"u*lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mol<eacute/culare</ets>. See <er>Molecule</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Phys. & Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, connected with, produced by, or consisting of, molecules; <as>as, <ex>molecular</ex> forces; <ex>molecular</ex> groups of atoms, etc.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Molecular attraction</b></col> <fld>(Phys.)</fld>, <cd>attraction acting between the molecules of bodies, and at insensible distances.</cd> -- <col><b>Molecular weight</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>the weight of a molecule of any gas or vapor as compared with the hydrogen atom having weight of 1 as a standard; the sum of the atomic weights of the constituents of a molecule; <as>thus, the <ex>molecular weight</ex> of water (<chform>H2O</chform>) is 18</as>.  For more precise measurements, the weight of the carbon isotope carbon-12 is used as the standard, that isotope having the value of 12.000.  In this systen, now used almost universally, the hydrogen atom has a weight of 1.0079.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>molecular formula</ent><br/
<hw>mo*lec"u*lar form"u*la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>An expression representing the composition of elements in a chemical substance, commonly consisting of a series of letters and numbers comprising the atomic symbols of each element present in a compound followed by the number of atoms of that element present in one molecule of the substance.  Thus the <ex>molecular formula</ex> for common alcohol (ethyl alcohol) is <chform>C2H6O</chform>, meaning that each molecule contains two carbon atoms, six hydrogen atoms, and one oxygen atom.  The <ex>molecular formula</ex> may be written to provide some indication of the actual structure of the molecule, in which case structural units may be written separately.  Thus, ethyl alcohol can also be written as <chform>CH3.CH2.OH</chform> or <chform>CH3-CH2-OH</chform>, in which the period or dash between functional groups indicates a single bond between the principle atoms of each group.  This formula shows that in ethyl alcohol, the carbon of a methyl group (<chform>CH3-</chform>) is attached to the carbon of a methylene group (<chform>-CH2-</chform>), which is attached to the oxygen of a hydroxyl group (<chform>-OH</chform>).  A <contr>structural formula</contr> is a graphical depiction of the relative positions of atoms in a molecule, and may be very complicated.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molecularity</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*lec`u*lar"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Phys. & Chem.)</fld> <def>The state of consisting of molecules; the state or quality of being molecular.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molecularly</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*lec"u*lar*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <fld>(Phys. & Chem.)</fld> <def>With molecules; in the manner of molecules.</def>  <rj><au>W. R. Grove.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molecule</ent><br/
<hw>Mol"e*cule</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Dim. fr. L. <ets>moles</ets> a mass: cf. F. <ets>mol<eacute/cule</ets>. See 3d <er>Mole</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One of the very small invisible particles of which all ordinary matter is supposed to consist.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>The smallest part of any substance which possesses the characteristic properties and qualities of that substance, and which can exist alone in a free state.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A group of atoms so united and combined by chemical affinity that they form a complete, integrated whole, being the smallest portion of any particular compound that can exist in a free state; <as>as, a <ex>molecule</ex> of water consists of two atoms of hydrogen and one of oxygen</as>.  Cf. <er>Atom</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mole-eyed</ent><br/
<hw>Mole"-eyed`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having eyes like those of the mole; having imperfect sight.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molehill</ent><br/
<hw>Mole"hill`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A little hillock of earth thrown up by moles working under ground; hence, a very small hill, or an insignificant obstacle or difficulty; <as>as, to make a mountain out of a <ex>molehill</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Having leapt over such mountains, lie down before a <qex>molehill</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 937 --></p>

<p><ent>molendinarious</ent><br/
<ent>mMolendinaceous</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>mMo*len`di*na"ceous</hw> <pr>(m<osl/*l<ecr/n`d<icr/*n<amac/"sh<ucr/s)</pr>, <hw>mo*len`di*na"ri*ous</hw> <pr>(m<osl/*l<ecr/n`d<icr/*n<amac/"r<icr/*<ucr/s)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>molendinarius</ets>, fr. <ets>molendinum</ets> a mill, fr. <ets>molere</ets> to grind.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Resembling the sails of a windmill.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moleskin</ent><br/
<hw>mole"skin`</hw> <pr>(m<omac/l"sk<icr/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Any fabric having a thick soft shag, like the fur of a mole; esp., a kind of strong twilled fustian.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A soft fabric having an adhesive backing, applied to the skin at points susceptible to abrasion, as on the feet, to prevent irritation or blistering during exercise, such as hiking.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molest</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*lest"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Molested</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Molesting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>molester</ets>, L. <ets>molestare</ets>, fr. <ets>molestus</ets> troublesome, fr. <ets>moles</ets> a heavy mass, load, burden. See 3d <er>Mole</er>.]</ety> <def>To trouble; to disturb; to render uneasy; to interfere with; to vex.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They have <qex>molested</qex> the church with needless opposition.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To trouble; disturb; incommode; inconvenience; annoy; vex; tease.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molest</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*lest"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Molestation.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molestation</ent><br/
<hw>Mol`es*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>molestation</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act of molesting, or the state of being molested; disturbance; annoyance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>molested</ent><br/
<hw>molested</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>sexually abused.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> assaulted, raped, fondled.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molester</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*lest"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who molests.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molestful</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*lest"ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Troublesome; vexatious.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molesty</ent><br/
<ent>Molestie</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mo*les"tie</hw>, <hw>Mo*les"ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>molestia</ets>.]</ety> <def>Molestation.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molewarp</ent><br/
<hw>Mole"warp`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Moldwarp</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moliminous</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*lim"i*nous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>molimen</ets> a great exertion; <ets>moles</ets> a heavy mass.]</ety> <def>Of great bulk or consequence; very important.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Dr. H. More.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moline</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"line</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>molina</ets> mill, fr. <ets>molere</ets> to grind. See <er>Mill</er>.]</ety> <def>The crossed iron that supports the upper millstone by resting on the spindle; a millrind.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Cross moline</b></col> <fld>(Her.)</fld>, <cd>a cross each arm of which is divided at the end into two rounded branches or divisions.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molinism</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"lin*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>The doctrines of the <org>Molinists</org>, somewhat resembling the tenets of the <org>Arminians</org>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molinist</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"lin*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>A follower of the opinions of <persfn>Molina</persfn>, a Spanish Jesuit (in respect to grace); an opposer of the Jansenists.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moll</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Moll</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[G., fr. L. <ets>mollis</ets> soft, tender, elegiac.  Cf. <er>Molle</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Minor; in the minor mode; <as>as, A <ex>moll</ex>, that is, A minor</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mollah</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mol"lah</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Ar. <ets>maul<amac/</ets>, commonly <ets>moll<amac/</ets>in Turkey.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One of the higher order of Turkish; also, a Turkish title of respect for a religious and learned man.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mullah</asp> and <asp>moolah</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A title of respect used in Islamic countries for one who is learned in Islamic law; a teacher or expounder of Islamic law.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molle</ent><br/
<hw>Mol"le</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Moll</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Lower by a semitone; flat; <as>as, E <ex>molle</ex>, that is, E flat</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mollebart</ent><br/
<hw>Mol"le*bart</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An agricultural implement used in Flanders, consisting of a kind of large shovel drawn by a horse and guided by a man.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mollebaert</asp> and <asp>mouldebaert</asp>.]</altsp>  <rj><au>Simmonds.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mollemoke</ent><br/
<hw>Mol"le*moke`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sw. <ets>mallemucke</ets> the stormy petrel.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of several species of large pelagic petrels and fulmars, as <spn>Fulmarus glacialis</spn>, of the North Atlantic, and several species of <gen>Aestrelata</gen>, of the Southern Ocean. See <er>Fulmar</er>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mollymawk</asp>, <asp>malmock</asp>, <asp>mollemock</asp>, <asp>mallemocke</asp>, etc.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mollient</ent><br/
<hw>Mol"lient</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>molliens</ets>, p. p. of <ets>mollire</ets> to soften, fr. <ets>mollis</ets> soft.]</ety> <def>Serving to soften; assuaging; emollient.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molliently</ent><br/
<hw>Mol"lient*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Assuagingly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mollifiable</ent><br/
<hw>Mol"li*fi`a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Capable of being mollified.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mollification</ent><br/
<hw>Mol`li*fi*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>mollificatio</ets>; cf. F. <ets>mollification</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act of mollifying, or the state of being mollified; a softening.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mollifier</ent><br/
<hw>Mol"li*fi`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who, or that which, mollifies.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mollify</ent><br/
<hw>Mol"li*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mollified</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mollifying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>mollifier</ets>, L. <ets>mollificare</ets>; <ets>mollis</ets> soft + <ets>-ficare</ets> (in comp.) to make. See <er>Enmollient</er>, <er>Moil</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, and <er>-fy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To soften; to make tender; to reduce the hardness, harshness, or asperity of; to qualify; <as>as, to <ex>mollify</ex> the ground</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With sweet science <qex>mollified</qex> their stubborn hearts.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To assuage, as pain or irritation, to appease, as excited feeling or passion; to pacify; to calm.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mollinet</ent><br/
<hw>Mol"li*net</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Moline</er>.]</ety> <def>A little mill.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mollipilose</ent><br/
<hw>Mol`li*pi*lose"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mollis</ets> soft + <ets>pilosus</ets> hairy.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having soft hairs; downy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mollities</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mol*li"ti*es</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., softness.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Unnatural softness of any organ or part.</def>  <rj><au>Dunglison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mollitude</ent><br/
<hw>Mol"li*tude</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mollitudo</ets>, fr. <ets>mollis</ets> soft.]</ety> <def>Softness; effeminacy; weakness.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mollusc</ent><br/
<hw>Mol"lusc</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Mollusk</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mollusca</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mol*lus"ca</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Mollusk</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the grand divisions of the animal kingdom, a phylum including the classes <class>Cephalopoda</class>, <class>Gastropoda</class>, <class>Pteropoda</class>, <class>Scaphopoda</class>, and <class>Pelecyopoda</class> (syn. <class>Bivalvia</class>, formerly called <class>Lamellibranchiata</class>, or <class>Conchifera</class>).  These animals have an unsegmented bilateral body, with most of the organs and parts paired, but not repeated longitudinally.  Most of them develop a mantle, which incloses either a branchial or a pulmonary cavity.  They are generally more or less covered and protected by a calcareous shell, which may be univalve, bivalve, or multivalve.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Formerly the Brachiopoda, Bryzoa, and Tunicata were united with the Lamellibranchiata in an artificial group called Acephala, which was also included under Mollusca. See <er>Molluscoidea</er>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molluscan</ent><br/
<hw>Mol*lus"can</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to mollusks.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A mollusk; one of the Mollusca.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molluscoid</ent><br/
<hw>Mol*lus"coid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mollusca</ets> + <ets>-oid</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Resembling the true mollusks; belonging to the Molluscoidea.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>One of the Molluscoidea.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molluscoidal</ent><br/
<hw>Mol`lus*coid"al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Molluscoid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molluscoidea</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mol`lus*coi"de*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Mollusk</er>, and <er>-oid</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A division of Invertebrata which includes the classes <class>Brachiopoda</class> and <class>Bryozoa</class>; -- called also <altname>Anthoid Mollusca</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Originally the Tunicata were included under Molluscoidea, from which they are known to differ widely in structure and embryology. Molluscoidea were formerly considered a subdivision of Mollusca, but they are now known to have more relationship with Annelida than with Mollusca.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molluscous</ent><br/
<hw>Mol*lus"cous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Molluscan.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molluscum</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mol*lus"cum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Mollusk</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A cutaneous disease characterized by numerous tumors, of various forms, filled with a thick matter; -- so called from the resemblance of the tumors to some molluscous animals.</def>  <rj><au>Dunglison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mollusk</ent><br/
<hw>Mol"lusk</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mollusque</ets>, L. <ets>mollusca</ets> a kind of soft nut with a thin shell, fr. <ets>molluscus</ets> soft, <ets>mollis</ets> soft. See <er>Mollify</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the <phylum>Mollusca</phylum>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mollusc</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molly</ent><br/
<hw>Mol"ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Mollemoke</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molly</ent><br/
<hw>Mol"ly</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A pet or colloquial name for <xex>Mary</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Molly cottontail</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Cottontail</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Molly Maguire</b></col> <pr>(m<adot/*gw<imac/r")</pr>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <er>Molly Maguires</er> <pr>(-gw<imac/rz)</pr>.</plu> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A member of a secret association formed among the tenantry in Ireland about 1843, principally for the purpose of intimidating law officers and preventing the service of legal writs.  Its members disguised themselves in the dress of women.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A member of a similar association of Irishmen organized in the anthracite coal region of Pennsylvania, about 1854, for the purpose of intimidating employers and officers of the law, and for avenging themselves by murder on persons obnoxious to them.  The society was broken up by criminal prosecutions in 1876.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mollycoddle</ent><br/
<hw>mollycoddle</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a pampered darling; an effeminate man; a milksop.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mollycoddle</ent><br/
<hw>mollycoddle</hw> <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To pamper or coddle.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molly-mawk</ent><br/
<hw>Mol"ly-mawk`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Mollemoke</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moloch</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"loch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[Heb. <ets>molek</ets> king.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Script.)</fld> <def>The fire god of the Ammonites in Canaan, to whom human sacrifices were offered; Molech.  Also applied figuratively.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A spiny Australian lizard (<spn>Moloch horridus</spn>). The horns on the head and numerous spines on the body give it a most formidable appearance.</def>
<-- illustr. of Moloch. --><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molokany</ent><br/
<ent>Molokane</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mol`o*ka"ne</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mol`o*ka"ny</hw>  }</mhw>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[Russ. <ets>molokane</ets>.]</ety> <def>See <er>Raskolnik</er>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molosse</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*losse"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Molossus</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molosses</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*los"ses</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Molasses.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molossine</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*los"sine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A bat of the genus <gen>Molossus</gen>, as the monk bat.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molossus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo*los"sus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/, prop., Molossian, belonging to the Molossians, a people in the eastern part of Epirus.]</ety> <fld>(Gr. & Lat. Pros.)</fld> <def>A foot of three long syllables.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>molosse</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molotov</ent><br/
<hw>Molotov</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a city in the European part of Soviet Russia.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Perm.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molotov cocktail</ent><br/
<hw>Molotov cocktail</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A home-made incendiary device consisting of a bottle filled with gasoline, and a cloth wick.  The wick is lighted, and the bottle thrown at a target, such as a vehicle, where it may shatter and spread intense flames over the vehicle, destroying or damaging it.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molt</ent><br/
<hw>Molt</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <mark>obs.</mark> <def><pos>imp.</pos> of <er>Melt</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au>  <au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moult</ent><br/
<ent>Molt</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Molt</hw>, <hw>Moult</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Molted</conjf> or <conjf>Moulted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Molting</conjf> or <conjf>Moulting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>mouten</ets>, L. <ets>mutare</ets>. See <er>Mew</er> to molt, and cf. <er>Mute</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <altsp>[The prevalent spelling is, perhaps, <asp>moult</asp>; but as the <asp>u</asp> has not been inserted in the otherwords of this class, <as>as, <ex>bolt</ex>, <ex>colt</ex>, <ex>dolt</ex>, etc.</as>, it is desirable to complete the analogy by the spelling <asp>molt</asp>.]</altsp> <def>To shed or cast the hair, feathers, skin, horns, or the like, as an animal or a bird.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moult</ent><br/
<ent>Molt</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Molt</hw>, <hw>Moult</hw>, }</mhw> <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cast, as the hair, skin, feathers, or the like; to shed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moult</ent><br/
<ent>Molt</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Molt</hw>, <hw>Moult</hw>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act or process of changing the feathers, hair, skin, etc.; molting.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moltable</ent><br/
<hw>Molt"a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Capable of assuming a molten state; meltable; fusible.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molten</ent><br/
<hw>Mol"ten</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Melt</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Melted; being in a state of fusion, esp. when the liquid state is produced by a high degree of heat; <as>as, <ex>molten</ex> iron</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Made by melting and casting the substance or metal of which the thing is formed; <as>as, a <ex>molten</ex> image</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>molting</ent><br/
<hw>molting</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act or process by which an animal molts; especially, the periodic shedding of the cuticle in arthropods or the outer skin in reptiles, or feathers in birds.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> molt, moult, moulting, ecdysis.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molto</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mol"to</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[It.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Much; very; <as>as, <ex>molto</ex> adagio, very slow</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moly</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A fabulous herb of occult power, having a black root and white blossoms, said by <persfn>Homer</persfn> to have been given by <persfn>Hermes</persfn> to <persfn>Ulysses</persfn> to counteract the spells of <persfn>Circe</persfn>.</def>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A kind of garlic (<spn>Allium Moly</spn>) with large yellow flowers; -- called also <altname>golden garlic</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molybdate</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*lyb"date</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of molybdic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molybdena</ent><br/
<hw>Mol`yb*de"na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>molybdaena</ets> galena, Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ lead.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>See <er>Molybdenite</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molybdenite</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*lyb"de*nite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>molybd<eacute/nite</ets>. See <er>Molybdena</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A mineral occurring in soft, lead-gray, foliated masses or scales, resembling graphite; sulphide of molybdenum.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molybdenous</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*lyb"de*nous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>See <er>Molybdous</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molybdenum</ent><br/
<hw>Mol`yb*de"num</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL.: cf. F. <ets>molybd<egrave/ne</ets>. See <er>Molybdena</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A rare element of the chromium group, occurring in nature in the minerals molybdenite and wulfenite, and when reduced obtained as a hard, silver-white, difficulty fusible metal.  Symbol Mo.  Atomic number 42. Atomic weight 95.94.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molybdic</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*lyb"dic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>molybdique</ets>. See <er>molybdena</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or containing, molybdenum; specif., designating those compounds in which the element has a higher valence, as contrasted with <contr>molybdous</contr> compounds; <as>as, <ex>molybdic</ex> oxide</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molybdite</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*lyb"dite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Molybdic ocher.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molybdous</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*lyb"dous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Molybdena</er>.]</ety> <def>Of, pertaining to, or containing, molybdenum; specif., designating those compounds in which molybdenum has a lower valence as contrasted with <contr>molybdic</contr> compounds.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mome</ent><br/
<hw>Mome</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Mumm</er>, <er>Momus</er>.]</ety> <def>A dull, silent person; a blockhead.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moment</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>moment</ets>, L. <ets>momentum</ets>, for <ets>movimentum</ets> movement, motion, moment, fr. <ets>movere</ets> to move. See <er>Move</er>, and cf. <er>Momentum</er>, <er>Movement</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A minute portion of time; a point of time; an instant; <as>as, at that very <ex>moment</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In a <qex>moment</qex>, in the twinkling of an eye.</q> <rj><qau>1 Cor. xv. 52.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Impulsive power; force; momentum.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>moments</qex> or quantities of motion in bodies.</q> <rj><qau>Berkley.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Touch, with lightest <qex>moment</qex> of impulse,<br/
His free will.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Importance, as in influence or effect; consequence; weight or value; consideration.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Matters of great <qex>moment</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is an abstruse speculation, but also of far less <qex>moment</qex> and consequence of us than the others.</q> <rj><qau>Bentley.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An essential element; a deciding point, fact, or consideration; an essential or influential circumstance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>An infinitesimal change in a varying quantity; an increment or decrement.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>Tendency, or measure of tendency, to produce motion, esp. motion about a fixed point or axis.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Moment of a couple</b></col> <fld>(Mech.)</fld>, <cd>the product of either of its forces into the perpendicular distance between them.</cd> -- <col><b>Moment of a force</b></col>. <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <mark>With respect to a point</mark>, <cd>the product of the intensity of the force into the perpendicular distance from the point to the line of direction of the force</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <mark>With respect to a line</mark>, <cd>the product of that component of the force which is perpendicular to the plane passing through the line and the point of application of the force, into the shortest distance between the line and this point</cd>. <sd>(c)</sd> <mark>With respect to a plane that is parallel to the force</mark>, <cd>the product of the force into the perpendicular distance of its point of application from the plane.</cd> -- <col><b>Moment of inertia</b></col>, <cd>of a rotating body, the sum of the mass of each particle of matter of the body into the square of its distance from the axis of rotation; -- called also <altname>moment of rotation</altname> and <altname>moment of the mass</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Statical moment</b></col>, <cd>the product of a force into its leverage; the same as <altname>moment of a force</altname> with respect to a point, line, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Virtual moment</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Virtual</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Instant; twinkling; consequence; weight; force; value; consideration; signification; avail.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Momental</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*men"tal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>momental</ets>.]</ety> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Lasting but a moment; brief.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not one <qex>momental</qex> minute doth she swerve.</q> <rj><qau>Breton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Important; momentous.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to moment or momentum.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Momentally</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*men"tal*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>For a moment.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Momentany</ent><br/
<ent>Momentaneous</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mo`men*ta"ne*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mo"men*ta*ny</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>momentaneus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>momentan<eacute/</ets>.]</ety> <def>Momentary.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Hooker.</au> <ldquo/<xex>Momentany</xex> as a sound.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Momentarily</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"men*ta*ri*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Every moment; from moment to moment.</def> <rj><au>Shenstone.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In a moment; in the immediate future.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Momentariness</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"men*ta*ri*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state or quality of being momentary; shortness of duration.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Momentary</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"men*ta*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>momentarius</ets>. See <er>Moment</er>.]</ety> <def>Done in a moment; continuing only a moment; lasting a very short time; <as>as, a <ex>momentary</ex> pang</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>momentary</qex> joy breeds months of pain.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Momently</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ment*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>For a moment.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In a moment; every moment; momentarily.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Momentous</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*men"tous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. L. <ets>momentosus</ets> rapid, momentary.]</ety> <def>Of moment or consequence; very important; weighty; <as>as, a <ex>momentous</ex> decision; <ex>momentous</ex> affairs.</as></def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mo*men"tous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mo*men"tous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>momentousness</ent><br/
<hw>mo*men"tous*ness</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>utmost importance.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Momentum</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*men"tum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> L. <plw>Momenta</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, F. <plw>Momentums</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. See <er>Moment</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>The quantity of motion in a moving body, being always proportioned to the quantity of matter multiplied by the velocity; impetus.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Essential element, or constituent element.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I shall state the several <qex>momenta</qex> of the distinction in separate propositions.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Hamilton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A property of an activity or course of events, viewed as analogous to forward motion or to physical momentum (def. 1), such that the activity is believed to be able to continue moving forward without further application of force or effort; -- often used to describe an increase in the acquisition of public support for a purpose; <as>as, as, the petition drive gained <ex>momentum</ex> when it was mentioned in the newspapers</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Momier</ent><br/
<hw>Mom"i*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>m<ocir/mier</ets>, fr. OF. <ets>momer</ets>, <ets>mommer</ets>, to mumm, to mask one's self.]</ety> <def>A name given in contempt to strict Calvinists in Switzerland, France, and some parts of Germany, in the early part of the 19th century.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mommery</ent><br/
<hw>Mom"mer*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mummery</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Rowe.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Momordica</ent><br/
<hw>Momordica</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of Old World tropical vine.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Momordica</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Momos</ent><br/
<hw>Momos</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos>  <fld>(Gr. Myth.)</fld> <def>The god of blame and mockery; Momus.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Momot</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"mot</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Momot</ets> and <ets>motmot</ets>, the native American name.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Motmot</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Momotus</ent><br/
<hw>Momotus</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The type genus of the <fam>Momotidae</fam>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Momotus</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Momus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo"mus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ blame, ridicule, Momus.]</ety> <fld>(Gr. Myth.)</fld> <def>The god of mockery and censure.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mon</ent><br/
<hw>Mon</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Jap., usually translated as <ets>crest</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Japan)</fld> <def>The badge of a family, esp. of a family of the ancient feudal nobility.  The most frequent form of the mon is circular, and it commonly consists of conventionalized forms from nature, flowers, birds, insects, the lightnings, the waves of the sea, or of geometrical symbolic figures; color is only a secondary character.  It appears on lacquer and pottery, and embroidered on, or woven in, fabrics.  The imperial chrysanthemum, the mon of the reigning family, is used as a national emblem.  Formerly the mon of the shoguns of the Tokugawa family was so used.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mon-</ent><br/
<hw>Mon-</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <def>Same as <er>Mono-</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mona</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo"na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[CF. Sp. & Pg. <ets>mona</ets>, fem. of <ets>mono</ets> a monkey, ape.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A small, handsome, long-tailed West American monkey (<spn>Cercopithecus mona</spn>). The body is dark olive, with a spot of white on the haunches.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monachal</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"a*chal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>monachus</ets> a monk: cf. F. <ets>monacal</ets>. See <er>Monk</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to monks or a monastic life; monastic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monachism</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"a*chism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>monachisme</ets>.]</ety> <def>The system and influences of a monastic life; monasticism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monacid</ent><br/
<hw>mon*ac"id</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mon-</ets> + <ets>acid</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Having one hydrogen atom replaceable by an acidic atom or radical.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> monoacid, monoacidic, monacidic.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Capable of neutralizing one equivalent of a monobasic acid; -- said of bases, and of certain metals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monacid</ent><br/
<hw>mon*ac"id</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>  <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>An acid having one replaceable hydrogen atom.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> monoacid.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monad</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ad</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>monas</ets>, <ets>-adis</ets>, a unit, Gr. <?/, <?/, fr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> alone.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An ultimate atom, or simple, unextended point; something ultimate and indivisible.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Philos. of Leibnitz)</fld> <def>The elementary and indestructible units which were conceived of as endowed with the power to produce all the changes they undergo, and thus determine all physical and spiritual phenomena.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the smallest flagellate Infusoria; esp., the species of the genus <gen>Monas</gen>, and allied genera.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>A simple, minute organism; a primary cell, germ, or plastid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>An atom or radical whose valence is one, or which can combine with, be replaced by, or exchanged for, one atom of hydrogen.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Monad deme</b></col> <fld>(Biol.)</fld>, <cd>in tectology, a unit of the first order of individuality.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 938 --></p>

<p><ent>Monadaria</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mon`a*da"ri*a</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/n`<adot/*d<amac/"r<icr/*<adot/)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Monad</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The Infusoria.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monadelphia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mon`a*del"phi*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., from Gr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> alone + <grk>'adelfo`s</grk> brother.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A Linnaean class of plants having the stamens united into a tube, or ring, by the filaments, as in the Mallow family.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monadelphous</ent><br/
<ent>Monadelphian</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mon`a*del"phi*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mon`a*del"phous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>monadelphie</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the Monadelphia; having the stamens united in one body by the filaments.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monadical</ent><br/
<ent>Monadic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mo*nad"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mo*nad"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of, pertaining to, or like, a monad, in any of its senses. See <er>Monad</er>, <pos>n.</pos></def>  <rj><au>Dr. H. More.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monadiform</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nad"i*form</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Monad</ets> + <ets>-form</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Having the form of a monad; resembling a monad in having one or more filaments of vibratile protoplasm; <as>as, <ex>monadiform</ex> young</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monadology</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`ad*ol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Monad</ets> + <ets>-logy</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Philos.)</fld> <def>The doctrine or theory of monads.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monal</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nal"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any Asiatic pheasant of the genus <gen>Lophophorus</gen>, as the Impeyan pheasant.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monamide</ent><br/
<hw>Mon*am"ide</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mon-</ets> + <ets>amide</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>An amido compound with only one amido group; a monoamide.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monamine</ent><br/
<hw>Mon*am"ine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mon-</ets> + <ets>amine</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A basic compound containing one amido group; a monoamine; <as>as, methyl amine is a <ex>monamine</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monander</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nan"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>One of the Monandria.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monandria</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo*nan"dri*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., from Gr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> alone + <grk>'anh`r</grk>, <grk>'andro`s</grk>, a man.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A Linnaean class of plants embracing those having but a single stamen.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monandrian</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nan"dri*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>; <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Monandrous</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monandric</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nan"dric</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to monandry; practicing monandry as a system of marriage.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monandrous</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nan"drous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the monandria; having but one stamen.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monandry</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nan"dry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Monandria</er>.]</ety> <def>The possession by a woman of only one husband at the same time; -- contrasted with <xex>polyandry</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monanthous</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nan"thous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mon-</ets> + Gr. <grk>'a`nqos</grk> flower.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having but one flower; one-flowered.</def>  <rj><au>Gray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monarch</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"arch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>monarque</ets>, L. <ets>monarcha</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/, <?/; <grk>mo`nos</grk> alone + <?/ to be first, rule, govern. See <er>Archi-</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A sole or supreme ruler; a sovereign; the highest ruler; an emperor, king, queen, prince, or chief.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He who reigns<br/
<qex>Monarch</qex> in heaven, . . . upheld by old repute.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One superior to all others of the same kind; <as>as, an oak is called the <ex>monarch</ex> of the forest</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A patron deity or presiding genius.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Come, thou, <qex>monarch</qex> of the vine,<br/
Plumpy Bacchus.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A very large red and black butterfly (<spn>Danais Plexippus</spn>); -- called also <altname>milkweed butterfly</altname> and <altname>monarch butterfly</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monarch</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"arch</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Superior to others; preeminent; supreme; ruling.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Monarch</xex> savage.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monarchal</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nar"chal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to a monarch; suiting a monarch; sovereign; regal; imperial.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Satan, whom now transcendent glory raised<br/
Above his fellows, with <qex>monarchal</qex> pride.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monarch butterfly</ent><br/
<hw>mon"arch but"ter*fly</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A very large red and black butterfly (<spn>Danais Plexippus</spn>) having striking orange-brown wings with black veins in a reticulated pattern; -- called also <altname>milkweed butterfly</altname> and <altname>monarch</altname>.  Its larvae feed on the leaves of the milkweed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monarchess</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"arch*ess</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A female monarch.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monarchial</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nar"chi*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Monarchic.</def>  <rj><au>Burke.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monarchian</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nar"chi*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>One of a sect in the early Christian church which rejected the doctrine of the Trinity; -- called also <altname>patripassian</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monarchical</ent><br/
<ent>Monarchic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mo*nar"chic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mo*nar"chic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>monarchique</ets>, Gr. <?/.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to a monarch, or to monarchy.</def> <au>Burke.</au> -- <wordforms><wf>Mo*nar"chic*al*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monarchism</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"arch*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The principles of, or preference for, monarchy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monarchist</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"arch*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>monarchiste</ets>.]</ety> <def>An advocate of, or believer in, monarchy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monarchize</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"arch*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Monarchized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Monarchizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To play the sovereign; to act the monarch.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monarchize</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"arch*ize</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To rule; to govern.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monarchizer</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"arch*i`zer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who monarchizes; also, a monarchist.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monarcho</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nar"cho</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The nickname of a crackbrained Italian who fancied himself an emperor.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monarchy</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"arch*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Monarchies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F. <ets>monarchie</ets>, L. <ets>monarchia</ets>, Gr. <?/. See <er>Monarch</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A state or government in which the supreme power is lodged in the hands of a monarch.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A system of government in which the chief ruler is a monarch.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In those days he had affected zeal for <qex>monarchy</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The territory ruled over by a monarch; a kingdom.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What scourage for perjury<br/
Can this dark <qex>monarchy</qex> afford false Clarence.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fifth monarchy</b></col>, <cd>a universal monarchy, supposed to be the subject of prophecy in Daniel ii.; the four preceding monarchies being Assyrian, Persian, Grecian, and Roman. See <cref>Fifth Monarchy men</cref>, under <er>Fifth</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monarda</ent><br/
<hw>monarda</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Any of various aromatic herbs of the genus <gen>Monarda</gen>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> wild bergamot.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monas</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo"nas</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Monad</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of minute flagellate Infusoria of which there are many species, both free and attached. See <xex>Illust.</xex> under <er>Monad</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monasterial</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`as*te"ri*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>monasterials</ets>, fr. <ets>monasterium</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to monastery, or to monastic life.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mon`as*te"ri*al*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monastery</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"as*te*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Monasteries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>monasterium</ets>, Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ a solitary, a monk, fr. <?/ to be alone, live in solitude, fr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> alone.  Cf. <er>Minister</er>.]</ety> <def>A house of religious retirement, or of secusion from ordinary temporal concerns, especially for monks; -- more rarely applied to such a house for females.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Convent; abbey; priory. See <er>Cloister</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monastic</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nas"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A monk.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monastical</ent><br/
<ent>Monastic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mo*nas"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mo*nas"tic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ monk: cf. F. <ets>monastique</ets>. See <er>Monastery</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to monasteries, or to their occupants, rules, etc., <as>as, <ex>monastic</ex> institutions or rules</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Secluded from temporal concerns and devoted to religion; recluse.</def> <ldquo/A life <xex>monastic</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Denham.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monastically</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nas"tic*al*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a monastic manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monasticism</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nas"ti*cism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The monastic life, system, or condition.</def>  <rj><au>Milman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monasticon</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nas"ti*con</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Monastic</er>.]</ety> <def>A book giving an account of monasteries.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monatomic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`a*tom"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mon-</ets> + <ets>atomic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Consisting of, or containing, one atom; <as>as, the molecule of mercury is <ex>monatomic</ex></as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Having the equivalence or replacing power of an atom of hydrogen; univalent; <as>as, the methyl radical is <ex>monatomic</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monaural</ent><br/
<hw>mon*au"ral</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/n*<ocir/r"<ait/l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having or hearing with only one ear.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Same as <er>monophonic</er>{2}.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monaxial</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nax"i*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mon-</ets> + <ets>axial</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Having only one axis; developing along a single line or plane; <as>as, <ex>monaxial</ex> development</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monazite</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"a*zite</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/n"<adot/*z<imac/t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From Gr. <grk>mona`zein</grk> to be solitary, in allusion to its isolated crystals.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A mineral occurring usually in small isolated crystals, -- a phosphate of the cerium metals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monday</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"day</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/n"d<asl/; 48)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>moneday</ets>, <ets>monenday</ets>, AS. <ets>m<omac/nandaeg</ets>, i.e., day of the moon, day sacred to the moon; akin to D. <ets>maandag</ets>, G. <ets>montag</ets>, OHG. <ets>m<amac/natag</ets>, Icel. <ets>m<amac/nadagr</ets>, Dan. <ets>mandag</ets>, Sw. <ets>m<aring/ndag</ets>. See <er>Moon</er>, and <er>Day</er>.]</ety> <def>The second day of the week; the day following Sunday.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monday's Child</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"day's Child</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/n"d<amac/z ch<imac/ld`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A child who is fair of face; -- a reference to a nineteenth century poem.  See below.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>Monday's child is fair of face,<br/
Tuesday's child is full of grace,<br/
Wednesday's child is full of woe,<br/
Thursday's child has far to go,<br/
Friday's child is loving and giving,<br/
Saturday's child works hard for a living,<br/
But the child who is born on the Sabbath day,<br/
Is lucky and happy and good and gay.</q><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monde</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Monde</hw> <pr>(m<ocir/Nd)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. See <er>Mundane</er>.]</ety> <def>The world; a globe as an ensign of royalty.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>A. Drummond.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Le beau monde</b></col> <ety>[F.]</ety>, <cd>fashionable society. See <er>Beau monde</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Demi monde</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Demimonde</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mone</ent><br/
<hw>Mone</hw> <pr>(m<omac/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The moon.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mone</ent><br/
<hw>Mone</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A moan.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monecious</ent><br/
<ent>Monecian</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mo*ne"cian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mo*ne"cious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>See <er>Monoecian</er>, and <er>Monoecious</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monembryony</ent><br/
<hw>Mon*em"bry*o*ny</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mono-</er>, and <er>Embryo</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The condition of an ovule having but a single embryo.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mon*em`bry*on"ic</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moner</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ner</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the Monera.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monera</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo*ne"ra</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> single.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The lowest division of rhizopods, including those which resemble the amoebas, but are destitute of a nucleus.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark> <br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>One of the five kingdoms of living organisms in the five-kingdom classification, consisting of microscopic usually monocellular prokaryotic organisms that mostly reproduce by asexual fission, sporulation, or budding; it includes the bacteria and cyanophytes (blue-green algae), as well as certain primitive pathogenic microbes, such as the Rickettsias.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moneral</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*ne"ral</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the Monera.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moneran</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*ne"ran</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the Monera.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>One of the Monera.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moneron</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo*ne"ron</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> L. <plw>Monera</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>; E. <plw>Monerons</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the Monera.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monerula</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo*ner"u*la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., dim. of <ets>moner</ets>. See <er>Monera</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>A germ in that stage of development in which its form is simply that of a non-nucleated mass of protoplasm.  It precedes the one-celled germ.  So called from its likeness to a moner.</def>  <rj><au>Haeckel.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monesia</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*ne"sia</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Pharm.)</fld> <def>The bark, or a vegetable extract brought in solid cakes from South America and believed to be derived from the bark, of the tree <spn>Chrysophyllum glycyphloeum</spn>.  It is used as an alterative and astringent.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monesin</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*ne"sin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The acrid principle of Monesia, sometimes used as a medicine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monest</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nest"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Admonish</er>.]</ety> <def>To warn; to admonish; to advise.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Wyclif (2 Cor. v. 20).</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monestrous</ent><br/
<hw>mon*es"trous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having only one estrus period per breeding cycle or per year; -- of certain mammals.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monetarism</ent><br/
<hw>mon"e*tar*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An economic theory holding that the rate of growth of the money supply is the priunciple cause of changes in inflation, economic growth, and unemployment.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monetarist</ent><br/
<hw>mon"e*tar*ist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who adheres to the theory of monetarism.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monetary</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"e*ta*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>monetarius</ets> belonging to a mint. See <er>Money</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to money, or consisting of money; pecuniary.</def> <ldquo/The <xex>monetary</xex> relations of Europe.<rdquo/  <rj><au>E. Everett.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Monetary unit</b></col>, <cd>the standard of a national currency, as the dollar in the United States, the pound in England, the peso in Mexico, the ruble in Russia, the franc in France, the mark in Germany.  Also, the standard of an international currency, such as the euro used in the European union.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moneth</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"eth</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A month.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monetisation</ent><br/
<hw>monetisation</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>monetization.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monetization</ent><br/
<hw>mon`e*ti*za"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act or process of converting into money, or of establishing something (e.g. gold or silver) as the legal tender of a country; <as>as, the <ex>monetization</ex> of silver</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monetize</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"e*tize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To convert into money; to adopt as current money; <as>as, to <ex>monetize</ex> silver</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Money</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ey</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Moneys</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>moneie</ets>, OF. <ets>moneie</ets>, F. <ets>monnaie</ets>, fr. L. <ets>moneta</ets>. See <er>Mint</er> place where coin is made, <er>Mind</er>, and cf. <er>Moidore</er>, <er>Monetary</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A piece of metal, as gold, silver, copper, etc., coined, or stamped, and issued by the sovereign authority as a medium of exchange in financial transactions between citizens and with government; also, any number of such pieces; coin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To prevent such abuses, . . . it has been found necessary . . . to affix a public stamp upon certain quantities of such particular metals, as were in those countries commonly made use of to purchase goods.  Hence the origin of coined <qex>money</qex>, and of those public offices called mints.</q> <rj><qau>A. Smith.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any written or stamped promise, certificate, or order, as a government note, a bank note, a certificate of deposit, etc., which is payable in standard coined money and is lawfully current in lieu of it; in a comprehensive sense, any currency usually and lawfully employed in buying and selling.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Any article used as a medium of payment in financial transactions, such as checks drawn on checking accounts.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Economics)</fld> <def>Any form of wealth which affects a person's propensity to spend, such as checking accounts or time deposits in banks, credit accounts, letters of credit, etc.  Various aggregates of money in different forms are given different names, such as <stype>M-1</stype>, the total sum of all currency in circulation plus all money in demand deposit accounts (checking accounts).</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Whatever, among barbarous nations, is used as a medium of effecting exchanges of property, and in the terms of which values are reckoned, as sheep, wampum, copper rings, quills of salt or of gold dust, shovel blades, etc., is, in common language, called their <xex>money</xex>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>In general, wealth; property; <as>as, he has much <ex>money</ex> in land, or in stocks; to make, or lose, <ex>money</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The love of <qex>money</qex> is a root of all kinds of evil.</q> <rj><qau>1 Tim vi. 10 (Rev. Ver. ).</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Money bill</b></col> <fld>(Legislation)</fld>, <cd>a bill for raising revenue.</cd> -- <col><b>Money broker</b></col>, <cd>a broker who deals in different kinds of money; one who buys and sells bills of exchange; -- called also <altname>money changer</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Money cowrie</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one of several species of <gen>Cypraea</gen> (esp. <spn>Cypraea moneta</spn>) formerly much used as money by savage tribes. See <er>Cowrie</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Money of account</b></col>, <cd>a denomination of value used in keeping accounts, for which there may, or may not, be an equivalent coin; <it>e. g.</it>, the mill is a <xex>money of account</xex> in the United States, but not a coin.</cd> -- <col><b>Money order</b></col>, <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>an order for the payment of money; specifically, a government order for the payment of money, issued at one post office as payable at another; -- called also <altname>postal money order</altname>.</cd> -- <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>a similar order issued by a bank or other financial institution.</cd> -- <col><b>Money scrivener</b></col>, <cd>a person who procures the loan of money to others.</cd> <mark>[Eng.]</mark> -- <mcol><col><b>Money spider</b></col>, <col><b>Money spinner</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a small spider; -- so called as being popularly supposed to indicate that the person upon whom it crawls will be fortunate in money matters.</cd> -- <col><b>Money's worth</b></col>, <cd>a fair or full equivalent for the money which is paid.</cd> -- <col><b>A piece of money</b></col>, <cd>a single coin.</cd> -- <col><b>Ready money</b></col>, <cd>money held ready for payment, or actually paid, at the time of a transaction; cash.</cd> -- <col><b>plastic money</b></col>, <cd>credit cards, usually made out of plastic; also called <altname>plastic</altname>; <as>as, put it on the <ex>plastic</ex></as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To make money</b></col>, <cd>to gain or acquire money or property; to make a profit in dealings.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Money</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ey</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To supply with money.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moneyage</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ey*age</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>monnayage</ets> coinage.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A tax paid to the first two Norman kings of England to prevent them from debashing the coin.</def>  <rj><au>Hume.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Mintage; coinage.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moneybag</ent><br/
<hw>moneybag</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a drawstring bag for holding money.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moneyed</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"eyed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Supplied with money; having money; wealthy; <as>as, <ex>moneyed</ex> men</as>.</def>  <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>monied</asp>.]</altsp> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Converted into money; coined.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If exportation will not balance importation, away must your silver go again, whether <qex>moneyed</qex> or not <qex>moneyed</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Consisting in, or composed of, money.</def>  <rj><au>A. Hamilton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moneyer</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ey*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Money</er>; cf. OF. <ets>monoier</ets>, F. <ets>monnoayeur</ets>, L. <ets>monetarius</ets> a master of the mint.  Cf. <er>Monetary</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A person who deals in money; banker or broker.</def> <mark>[Obs. or R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An authorized coiner of money.</def>  <rj><au>Sir M. Hale.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The Company of Moneyers</b></col>, <cd>the officials who formerly coined the money of Great Britain, and who claimed certain prescriptive rights and privileges.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moneylender</ent><br/
<hw>moneylender</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>someone who lends money at excessive rates of interest.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> usurer, loan shark, shark, money-lender.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moneyless</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ey*less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Destitute of money; penniless; impecunious.</def>  <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Money-maker</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ey-mak`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who coins or prints money; also, a counterfeiter of money.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who accumulates money or wealth; specifically, one who makes money-getting his governing motive.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Money-making</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ey-mak`ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act or process of making money; the acquisition and accumulation of wealth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Obstinacy in <qex>money-making</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milman.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Money-making</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ey-mak`ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Affording profitable returns; lucrative; <as>as, a <ex>money-making</ex> business</as>.  Opposite of <contr>unprofitable</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Successful in gaining money, and devoted to that aim; <as>as, a <ex>money-making</ex> man</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moneyman</ent><br/
<hw>moneyman</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a person skilled in large scale financial transactions.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> financier.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>money-spinner</ent><br/
<hw>money-spinner</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a project that generates a continuous flow of money.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> moneymaker, cash cow.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><-- ##??Money supply;  --></p>

<p><ent>Moneywort</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ey*wort`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A trailing plant (<spn>Lysimachia Nummularia</spn>), with rounded opposite leaves and solitary yellow flowers in their axils.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mongcorn</ent><br/
<hw>Mong"corn`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mangcorn</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monger</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ger</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>mangere</ets>, fr. <ets>mangian</ets> to trade; akin to Icel. <ets>manga</ets> to trade, <ets>mangari</ets> a trader, OHG. <ets>mangari</ets>, <ets>mengari</ets>; cf. L. <ets>mango</ets> a dealer in slaves.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A trader; a dealer; -- now used chiefly in composition; <as>as, fish<ex>monger</ex>, iron<ex>monger</ex>, news<ex>monger</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small merchant vessel.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Blount.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monger</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ger</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To deal in; to make merchandise of; to traffic in; -- used chiefly of discreditable traffic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mongol</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"gol</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One of the Mongols.</def> -- <def2><pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to Mongolia or the Mongols.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mongolian</ent><br/
<hw>Mon*go"li*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to Mongolia or the Mongols.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>One of the Mongols.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mongolic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon*gol"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>See <er>Mongolian</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mongoloid</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"go*loid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mongol</ets> + <ets>-oid</ets>.]</ety> <def>Resembling a Mongol or the Mongols; having race characteristics, such as color, hair, and features, like those of the Mongols.</def>  <rj><au>Huxley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of, related to, or affected with, <er>Down syndrome</er>; -- not a technical term.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mongoloid</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"go*loid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A person affected with <er>Down syndrome</er>; -- not a technical term.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mongolians</ent><br/
<ent>Mongols</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mon"gols</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mon*go"li*ans</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>One of the great races of man, including the greater part of the inhabitants of China, Japan, and the interior of Asia, with branches in Northern Europe and other parts of the world.  By some American Indians are considered a branch of the Mongols.  In a more restricted sense, the inhabitants of Mongolia and adjacent countries, including the Burats and the Kalmuks.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mongoos</ent><br/
<ent>Mongoose</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mon"goose</hw>, <hw>Mon"goos</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu>pl. <plw>Mongooses</plw> <pr>(#)</pr></plu> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A species of ichneumon (<spn>Herpestes griseus</spn>), native of India.  Applied also to other allied species, as the African banded mongoose (<spn>Crossarchus fasciatus</spn>).</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mungoose</asp>, <asp>mungoos</asp>, <asp>mungous</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[Tamil <ets>manegos</ets>.]</ety> <def>A Madagascan lemur (<spn>Lemur mongos</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mongrel</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"grel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. shortened fr. <ets>mongrel</ets>, and akin to AS. <ets>mengan</ets> to mix, and E. <ets>mingle</ets>. See <er>Mingle</er>.]</ety> <def>The progeny resulting from a cross between two breeds, as of domestic animals; anything of mixed breed.</def>  <rj><au>Drayton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mongrel</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"grel</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Not of a pure breed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of mixed kinds; <as>as, <ex>mongrel</ex> language</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mongrelize</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"grel*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To cause to be mongrel; to cross breeds, so as to produce mongrels.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>'Mongst</ent><br/
<hw>'Mongst</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prep.</pos> <def>See <er>Amongst</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moniker</ent><br/
<ent>monicker</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>monicker</hw>, <hw>moniker</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The name of a person, especially an alias or a nickname.</def> <mark>[slang]</mark> <br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> nickname, alias, sobriquet, cognomen.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monied</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ied</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>See <er>Moneyed</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monifier</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nif"i*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. L. <ets>monile</ets> necklace + <ets>ferre</ets> to bear.]</ety> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>A fossil fish.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moniliales</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo*nil`i*a"les</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. L. <ets>monile</ets> necklace, -- because the conidia are produced in chains.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The largest of the three orders into which the Fungi Imperfecti are divided, including various forms.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moniliasis</ent><br/
<hw>moniliasis</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>An infectious disease caused by fungi of the genera <causedby><gen>Monilia</gen></causedby> or <causedby><gen>Candida</gen></causedby> especially <causedby><spn>Candida albicans</spn></causedby>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> candidiasis, monilia disease.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moniliform</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nil"i*form</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>monile</ets> necklace + <ets>-form</ets>: cf. F. <ets>moniliforme</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Joined or constricted, at regular intervals, so as to resemble a string of beads; <as>as, a <ex>moniliform</ex> root; a <ex>moniliform</ex> antenna</as>.  See <ex>Illust</ex>. of <er>Antenna</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moniment</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"i*ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>monimentum</ets>, <ets>monumentum</ets>. See <er>Monument</er>.]</ety> <def>Something to preserve memory; a reminder; a monument; hence, a mark; an image; a superscription; a record.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monish</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ish</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>monesten</ets>. See <er>Admonish</er>, <er>Monition</er>.]</ety> <def>To admonish; to warn. See <er>Admonish</er>.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>  <rj><au>Ascham.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monisher</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ish*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who monishes; an admonisher.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monishment</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ish*ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Admonition.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 939 --></p>

<p><ent>Monism</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ism</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/n"<icr/z'm <it>or</it> m<omac/"n<icr/z'm)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From Gr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> single.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Metaph.)</fld> <def>That doctrine which refers all phenomena to a single ultimate constituent or agent; -- the opposite of <contr>dualism</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The doctrine has been held in three generic forms: matter and its phenomena have been explained as a modification of mind, involving an idealistic <xex>monism</xex>; or mind has been explained by and resolved into matter, giving a materialistic <xex>monism</xex>; or, thirdly, matter, mind, and their phenomena have been held to be manifestations or modifications of some one substance, like the substance of Spinoza, or a supposed unknown something of some evolutionists, which is capable of an objective and subjective aspect.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>See <er>Monogenesis</er>, 1.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The doctrine that the universe is an organized unitary being or total self-inclusive structure.</def></p>

<p><q><qex>Monism</qex> means that the whole of reality, i.e., everything that is, constitutes one inseparable and indivisible entirety. <qex>Monism</qex> accordingly is a unitary conception of the world. It always bears in mind that our words are abstracts representing parts or features of the One and All, and not separate existences.  Not only are matter and mind, soul and body, abstracts, but also such scientific terms as atoms and molecules, and also religious terms such as God and world.</q>  <rj><qau>Paul Carus.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monist</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A believer in monism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monistic</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nis"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of, pertaining to, or involving, monism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monition</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*ni"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>monitio</ets>, from <ets>monere</ets> to warn, bring to mind; akin to E. <ets>mind</ets>. See <er>Mind</er>, and cf. <er>Admonish</er>, <er>Money</er>, <er>Monster</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Instruction or advice given by way of caution; an admonition; a warning; a caution.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sage <qex>monitions</qex> from his friends.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Information; indication; notice; advice.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We have no visible <qex>monition</qex> of . . . other periods, such as we have of the day by successive light and darkness.</q> <rj><qau>Holder.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Admiralty Practice)</fld> <def>A process in the nature of a summons to appear and answer.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Eccl. Law)</fld> <def>An order monishing a party complained against to obey under pain of the law.</def>  <rj><au>Shipley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monitive</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"i*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Conveying admonition; admonitory.</def>  <rj><au>Barrow.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monitor</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"i*tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. <ets>monere</ets>. See <er>Monition</er>, and cf. <er>Mentor</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who admonishes; one who warns of faults, informs of duty, or gives advice and instruction by way of reproof or caution.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You need not be a <qex>monitor</qex> to the king.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, specifically, a pupil selected to look to the school in the absence of the instructor, to notice the absence or faults of the scholars, or to instruct a division or class.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any large Old World lizard of the genus <gen>Varanus</gen>; esp., the Egyptian species (<spn>Varanus Niloticus</spn>), which is useful because it devours the eggs and young of the crocodile.  It is sometimes five or six feet long.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <ety>[So called from the name given by <person>Captain Ericson</person>, its designer, to the first ship of the kind.]</ety> <def>An ironclad war vessel, very low in the water, and having one or more heavily-armored revolving turrets, carrying heavy guns.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>A tool holder, as for a lathe, shaped like a low turret, and capable of being revolved on a vertical pivot so as to bring successively the several tools in holds into proper position for cutting.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A monitor nozzle.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Monitor top</b></col>, <cd>the raised central portion, or clearstory, of a car roof, having low windows along its sides.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monitorial</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`i*to"ri*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a monitor or monitors.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Done or performed by a monitor; <as>as, <ex>monitorial</ex> work</as>; conducted or taught by monitors; <as>as, a <ex>monitorial</ex> school; <ex>monitorial</ex> instruction.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monitorially</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`i*to"ri*al*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a monitorial manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monitor nozzle</ent><br/
<hw>Monitor nozzle</hw>. <def>A nozzle capable of turning completely round in a horizontal plane and having a limited play in a vertical plane, used in hydraulic mining, fire-extinguishing apparatus, etc.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monitorship</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"i*tor*ship</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The post or office of a monitor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monitory</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"i*to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>monitorius</ets>.]</ety> <def>Giving admonition; instructing by way of caution; warning.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Losses, miscarriages, and disappointments, are <qex>monitory</qex> and instructive.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monitory</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"i*to*ry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Admonition; warning; especially, a monition proceeding from an ecclesiastical court, but not addressed to any one person.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monitrix</ent><br/
<ent>Monitress</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mon"i*tress</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mon"i*trix</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A female monitor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monk</ent><br/
<hw>Monk</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>munuc</ets>, <ets>munec</ets>, <ets>munc</ets>, L. <ets>monachus</ets>, Gr. <?/, fr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> alone.  Cf. <er>Monachism</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A man who retires from the ordinary temporal concerns of the world, and devotes himself to religion; one of a religious community of men inhabiting a monastery, and bound by vows to a life of chastity, obedience, and poverty.</def> <ldquo/A <xex>monk</xex> out of his cloister.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Monks</qex> in some respects agree with regulars, as in the substantial vows of religion; but in other respects <qex>monks</qex> and regulars differ; for that regulars, vows excepted, are not tied up to so strict a rule of life as <qex>monks</qex> are.</q> <rj><qau>Ayliffe.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>A blotch or spot of ink on a printed page, caused by the ink not being properly distributed. It is distinguished from a <xex>friar</xex>, or white spot caused by a deficiency of ink.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A piece of tinder made of agaric, used in firing the powder hose or train of a mine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A South American monkey (<spn>Pithecia monachus</spn>); also applied to other species, as <spn>Cebus xanthocephalus</spn>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The European bullfinch.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Monk bat</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a South American and West Indian bat (<spn>Molossus nasutus</spn>); -- so called because the males live in communities by themselves.</cd> -- <col><b>Monk bird</b></col><fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the friar bird.</cd> -- <col><b>Monk seal</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a species of seal (<spn>Monachus albiventer</spn>) inhabiting the Black Sea, the Mediterranean Sea, and the adjacent parts of the Atlantic.</cd> -- <col><b>Monk's rhubarb</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a kind of dock; -- also called <altname>patience</altname> (<spn>Rumex Patientia</spn>).</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monkery</ent><br/
<hw>Monk"er*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Monkeries</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The life of monks; monastic life; monastic usage or customs; -- now usually applied by way of reproach.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Miters, and wretched dead mediaeval <qex>monkeries</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Carlyle.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A collective body of monks.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though he have a whole <qex>monkery</qex> to sing for him.</q> <rj><qau>Latimer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monkey</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"key</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Monkeys</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Cf. OIt. <ets>monicchio</ets>, It. <ets>monnino</ets>, dim. of <ets>monna</ets> an ape, also dame, mistress, contr. fr. <ets>madonna</ets>. See <er>Madonna</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>In the most general sense, any one of the Quadrumana, including apes, baboons, and lemurs.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Any species of Quadrumana, except the lemurs.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>Any one of numerous species of Quadrumana (esp. such as have a long tail and prehensile feet) exclusive of apes and baboons.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The monkeys are often divided into three groups: (<stype>a</stype>) <stype>Catarrhines</stype>, or <fam>Simidae</fam>. These have an oblong head, with the oblique flat nostrils near together. Some have no tail, as the apes.  All these are natives of the Old World. (<stype>b</stype>) <stype>Platyrhines</stype>, or <fam>Cebidae</fam>. These have a round head, with a broad nasal septum, so that the nostrils are wide apart and directed downward.  The tail is often prehensile, and the thumb is short and not opposable.  These are natives of the New World. (<stype>c</stype>) <stype>Strepsorhines</stype>, or <fam>Lemuroidea</fam>. These have a pointed head with curved nostrils.  They are natives of Southern Asia, Africa, and Madagascar.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A term of disapproval, ridicule, or contempt, as for a mischievous child.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This is the <qex>monkey's</qex> own giving out; she is persuaded I will marry her.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The weight or hammer of a pile driver, that is, a very heavy mass of iron, which, being raised on high, falls on the head of the pile, and drives it into the earth; the falling weight of a drop hammer used in forging.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A small trading vessel of the sixteenth century.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Monkey boat</b></col>. <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A small boat used in docks</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A half-decked boat used on the River Thames.</cd> -- <col><b>Monkey block</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a small single block strapped with a swivel.</cd> <au>R. H. Dana, Jr.</au> -- <col><b>Monkey flower</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a plant of the genus <gen>Mimulus</gen>; -- so called from the appearance of its gaping corolla.</cd> <au>Gray.</au> -- <col><b>Monkey gaff</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a light gaff attached to the topmast for the better display of signals at sea.</cd> -- <col><b>Monkey jacket</b></col>, <cd>a short closely fitting jacket, worn by sailors.</cd> -- <col><b>Monkey rail</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a second and lighter rail raised about six inches above the quarter rail of a ship.</cd> -- <col><b>Monkey shine</b></col>, <cd>monkey trick.</cd> <mark>[Slang, U.S.]</mark> -- <col><b>Monkey trick</b></col>, <cd>a mischievous prank.</cd> <au>Saintsbury.</au> -- <col><b>Monkey wheel</b></col>. <cd>See <cref>Gin block</cref>, under 5th <er>Gin</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monkey</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"key</hw>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To act or treat as a monkey does; to ape; to act in a grotesque or meddlesome manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To monkey with</b></col>, <col><b>To monkey around with</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to handle in a meddlesome manner.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monkey-bread</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"key-bread`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The fruit of the <spn>Adansonia digitata</spn>; also, the tree. See <er>Adansonia</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monkey-cup</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"key-cup`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>See <er>Nepenthes</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monkey pod</ent><br/
<ent>monkeypod</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>monkeypod</hw>, <hw>monkey pod</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>large ornamental tropical American tree (<spn>Albizia saman</spn>) with bipinnate leaves and globose clusters of flowers with crimson stamens and sweet-pulp seed pods eaten by cattle.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> rain tree, saman, zaman, zamang, <spn>Albizia saman</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monkey-pot</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"key-pot`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The fruit of two South American trees (<spn>Lecythis Ollaria</spn>, and <spn>Lecythis Zabucajo</spn>), which have for their fruit large, pot-shaped, woody capsules containing delicious nuts, and opening almost explosively by a circular lid at the top.  Vases and pots are made of this capsule.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monkey's puzzle</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"key's puz"zle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A lofty coniferous Chilian tree (<spn>Araucaria araucana</spn>, formerly <spn>Araucaria imbricata</spn>), the branches of which are so crowded and intertwisted <ldquo/as to puzzle a monkey to climb.<rdquo/  It is also called <altname>monkey puzzle</altname> and <altname>monkey puzzle tree</altname>.  The edible nuts are over an inch long, and are called <xex>pi<ntil/on</xex> by the Chilians.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monkeytail</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"key*tail`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A short, round iron bar or lever used in naval gunnery.</def>  <rj><au>Totten.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monkey wrench</ent><br/
<ent>monkeywrench</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>monkeywrench</hw>, <hw>monkey wrench</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A wrench or spanner which has one fixed and one adjustable jaw.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> monkey wrench.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monkfish</ent><br/
<hw>Monk"fish</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The angel fish (<gen>Squatina</gen>).</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The angler (<gen>Lophius</gen>), esp. the goosefishes <spn>Lophius Americanus</spn> in America and <spn>Lophius piscatorius</spn> in Europe, used for food.</def> <au>[MW10]</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monkflower</ent><br/
<hw>Monk"flow`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A name of certain curious orchids which bear three kinds of flowers formerly referred to three genera, but now ascertained to be sexually different forms of the same genus (<spn>Catasetum tridentatum</spn>, etc.).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monkhood</ent><br/
<hw>Monk"hood</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Monk</ets> + <ets>-hood</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The character or condition of a monk.</def>  <rj><au>Atterbury.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Monks, regarded collectively.</def>  <rj><au>Longfellow.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monking</ent><br/
<hw>Monk"ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Monkish.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Coleridge.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monkish</ent><br/
<hw>Monk"ish</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Like a monk, or pertaining to monks; monastic; <as>as, <ex>monkish</ex> manners; <ex>monkish</ex> dress; <ex>monkish</ex> solitude.</as></def> -- <wordforms><wf>Monk"ish*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monkly</ent><br/
<hw>Monk"ly</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Like, or suitable to, a monk.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monkshood</ent><br/
<hw>Monks"hood`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A plant of the genus <gen>Aconitum</gen>; aconite. See <er>Aconite</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monk's seam</ent><br/
<hw>Monk's" seam`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>An extra middle seam made at the junction of two breadths of canvas, ordinarily joined by only two rows of stitches.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mon-</ent><br/
<ent>Mono-</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mon"o-</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mon-</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>. <ety>[Gr. <?/.]</ety> <def>A prefix signifying <sig>one</sig>, <sig>single</sig>, <sig>alone</sig>; <as>as, <ex>mono</ex>carp, <ex>mono</ex>poly</as>; <fld>(Chem.)</fld> indicating that a compound contains <sig>one atom</sig>, <sig>one radical</sig>, or <sig>one group</sig> of that to the name of which it is united; <as>as, <ex>mon</ex>oxide, <ex>mono</ex>sulphide, <ex>mon</ex>atomic, etc.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mono</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo"no</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The <altname>black howler</altname> (<spn>Mycetes villosus</spn>), a monkey of Central America.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monobasic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*ba"sic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>basic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Capable of being neutralized by a univalent base or basic radical; having but one acid hydrogen atom to be replaced; -- said of acids; <as>as, acetic, nitric, and hydrochloric acids are <ex>monobasic</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monocarboxylic</ent><br/
<ent>monocarbonic</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mon`o*car*bon"ic</hw>, <hw>mon`o*car*box*yl"ic</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>carbonic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Containing one carboxyl group; <as>as, acetic acid is a <ex>monocarbonic</ex> acid</as>.  The more common term is <altname>monocarboxylic</altname>.  Contrasted with <contr>dicarboxylic</contr>, <contr>tricarboxylic</contr>, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monocardian</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*car"di*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <?/ heart.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having a single heart, as fishes and amphibians.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>An animal having a single heart.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monocarp</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*carp</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A monocarpic plant.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monocarpellary</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*car"pel*la*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>carpellary</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Consisting of a single carpel, as the fruit of the pea, cherry, and almond.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monocarpous</ent><br/
<ent>Monocarpic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mon`o*car"pic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mon`o*car"pous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <?/ fruit: cf. F. <ets>monocarpe</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Bearing fruit but once, and dying after fructification, as beans, maize, mustard, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Annual and biennual herbs are monocarpic, so also some plants of longer duration, as the century plant.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monocephalous</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*ceph"a*lous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <grk>kefalh`</grk> head.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having a solitary head; -- said of unbranched composite plants.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monoceros</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo*noc"e*ros</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/; <grk>mo`nos</grk> alone, single + <grk>ke`ras</grk> horn.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A one-horned creature; a unicorn; a sea monster with one horn.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mighty <qex>monoceroses</qex> with immeasured tails.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>The Unicorn, a constellation situated to the east Orion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monochlamydeous</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*chla*myd"e*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <?/, <?/, cloak: cf. F. <ets>monochlamyd<eacute/</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having a single floral envelope, that is, a calyx without a corolla, or, possibly, in rare cases, a corolla without a calyx.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monochord</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*chord</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>monochordon</ets>, Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ with but one string; <?/ only, single + <?/ string: cf. F. <ets>monocorde</ets>. See <er>Chord</er>, and cf. <er>Mainchord</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>An instrument for experimenting upon the mathematical relations of musical sounds. It consists of a single string stretched between two bridges, one or both of which are movable, and which stand upon a graduated rule for the purpose of readily changing and measuring the length of the part of the string between them.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monochromatic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*chro*mat"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>monochromatique</ets>. See <er>Monochrome</er>.]</ety> <def>Consisting of one color, or presenting rays of light of one color only.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Monochromatic lamp</b></col> <fld>(Opt.)</fld>,<cd>a lamp whose flame yields rays of some one homogenous light. It is of great importance in optical experiments.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monochrome</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*chrome</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ of one color; <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <?/ color: cf. F. <ets>monochrome</ets>.]</ety> <def>A painting or drawing in a single color; a picture made with a single color.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monochromic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*chro"mic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Made, or done, with a single color; <as>as, a <ex>monochromic</ex> picture</as>.  Called also, <altname>monochromatic</altname> and <altname>monochrome</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monochromy</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*chro`my</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The art of painting or drawing in monochrome.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monochronic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*chron"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <?/ time.]</ety> <def>Existing at the same time; contemporaneous.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monociliated</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*cil"i*a`ted</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>ciliated</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Having but one cilium.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monocle</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*cle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. See <er>Monocular</er>.]</ety> <def>An eyeglass for one eye.</def>  <rj><au>Simmonds.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monoclinal</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*cli"nal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Monoclinic</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>Having one oblique inclination; -- applied to strata that dip in only one direction from the axis of elevation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monocline</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*cline</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>A monoclinal fold.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monoclinic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*clin"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <?/ to incline.]</ety> <fld>(Crystallog.)</fld> <def>Having one oblique intersection; -- said of that system of crystallization in which the vertical axis is inclined to one, but at right angles to the other, lateral axis. See <er>Crystallization</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monoclinous</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*noc"li*nous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <?/ couch, fr. <?/ to lie down: cf. F. <ets>monocline</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Hermaphrodite, or having both stamens and pistils in every flower.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monocondyla</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mon`o*con"dy*la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Mono-</er>, and <er>Condyle</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A group of vertebrates, including the birds and reptiles, or those that have only one occipital condyle; the Sauropsida.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monocotyl</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*co*tyl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Any monocotyledonous plant.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monocotyle</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*co*tyle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>monocotyle</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Monocotyledonous.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monocotyledon</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*cot`y*le"don</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>cotyledon</ets>: cf. F. <ets>monocotyl<eacute/done</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A plant with only one cotyledon, or seed lobe; a member of the <class>Monocotyledonae</class>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The plural, <xex>monocotyledons</xex>, is used as the name of a large class of plants (the <class>Monocotyledones</class>, or <class>Monocotyledonae</class>), and is generally understood to be equivalent to the term <xex>endogens</xex>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monocotyledones</ent><br/
<ent>Monocotyledonae</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Monocotyledonae</hw>, <hw>Monocotyledones</hw></mhw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A class of plants comprising seed plants that produce an embryo with a single cotyledon and parallel-veined leaves: grasses; lilies; palms; and orchids.  It is divided into four subclasses or superorders: Alismatidae; Arecidae; Commelinidae; and Liliidae.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> class <class>Monocotyledones</class>, <class>Monocotyledonae</class>, class <class>Monocotyledonae</class>, <class>Liliopsida</class>, class <class>Liliopsida</class>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monocotyledonous</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*cot`y*le"don*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>monocotyl<eacute/don<eacute/</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having only one cotyledon, seed lobe, or seminal leaf.</def>  <rj><au>Lindley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monocracy</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*noc"ra*cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>-cracy</ets>, as in <ets>democracy</ets>.]</ety> <def>Government by a single person; undivided rule.</def>  <rj><au>Sydney Smith.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monocrat</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*crat</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Gr. <?/ ruling alone.]</ety> <def>One who governs alone.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monocrotic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*crot"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or showing, monocrotism; <as>as, a <ex>monocrotic</ex> pulse; a pulse of the <ex>monocrotic</ex> type.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monocrotism</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*noc"ro*tism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> alone + <?/ a beating.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>That condition of the pulse in which the pulse curve or sphygmogram shows but a single crest, the dicrotic elevation entirely disappearing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monocular</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*noc"u*lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>monoculus</ets>; Gr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + L. <ets>oculus</ets> eye: cf. F. <ets>monoculaire</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having only one eye; with one eye only; <as>as, <ex>monocular</ex> vision</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Adapted to be used with only one eye at a time; <as>as, a <ex>monocular</ex> microscope</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 940 --></p>

<p><ent>monocule</ent><br/
<hw>mon"o*cule</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/n"<osl/*k<umac/l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Monocular</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A small crustacean with one median eye.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monoculous</ent><br/
<hw>mo*noc"u*lous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Monocular.</def>  <rj><au>Glanvill.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monocystic</ent><br/
<hw>mon`o*cys"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mono-</er>, and <er>Cyst</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to a division (<fam>Monocystidea</fam>) of the protozoan order  <ord>Gregarinida</ord>, in which the body consists of one sac.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monodactylous</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*dac"tyl*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>monoda`ktylos</grk>; <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <grk>da`ktylos</grk> finger: cf. F. <ets>monodactyle</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having but one finger or claw.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monodelphian</ent><br/
<ent>Monodelph</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mon"o*delph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mon`o*del"phi*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the Monodelphia.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monodelphia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mon`o*del"phi*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <grk>delfy`s</grk> the womb.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The group that includes all ordinary or placental mammals; the Placentalia. See <er>Mammalia</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monodelphous</ent><br/
<ent>Monodelphic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mon`o*del"phic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mon`o*del"phous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the Monodelphia.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monodical</ent><br/
<ent>Monodic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mo*nod"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mo*nod"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Belonging to a monody.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>For one voice; monophonic.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Homophonic; -- applied to music in which the melody is confined to one part, instead of being shared by all the parts as in the style called <contr>polyphonic</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monodimetric</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*di*met"ric</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>dimetric</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Crystallog.)</fld> <def>Dimetric.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monodist</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*dist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A writer of a monody.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monodrame</ent><br/
<ent>Monodrama</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mon"o*dra`ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mon"o*drame</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <?/ drama.]</ety> <def>A drama acted, or intended to be acted, by a single person.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monodramatic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*dra*mat"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to a monodrama.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monody</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*dy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Monodies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>monodia</ets>, Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ singing alone; <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <?/ song: cf. F. <ets>monodie</ets>. See <er>Ode</er>.]</ety> <def>A species of poem of a mournful character, in which a single mourner expresses lamentation; a song for one voice.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monodynamic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*dy*nam"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>dynamic</ets>.]</ety> <def>Possessing but one capacity or power.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Monodynamic</xex> men.<rdquo/  <rj><au>De Quincey.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monodynamism</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*dy"na*mism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The theory that the various forms of activity in nature are manifestations of the same force.</def>  <rj><au>G. H. Lewes.</au></rj> <note>A philosophical form of the grand unified theory?</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monoecia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo*noe"ci*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <?/ house.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A Linnaean class of plants, whose stamens and pistils are in distinct flowers in the same plant.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monoecian</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*noe"cian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the Monoecia; monoecious.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>One of the Monoecia.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A monoecious animal, as certain mollusks.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monoecious</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*noe"cious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Having the sexes united in one individual, as when male and female flowers grow upon the same individual plant; hermaphrodite; -- opposed to <ant>dioecious</ant>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monoecism</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*noe"cism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The state or condition of being monoecious.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogam</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*gam</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>One of the Monogamia.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogamia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mon`o*ga"mi*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Monogamous</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A Linnaean order of plants, having solitary flowers with united anthers, as in the genus <gen>Lobelia</gen>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogamic</ent><br/
<ent>Monogamian</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mon`o*ga"mi*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mon`o*gam"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Monogamous</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Pertaining to, or involving, monogamy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the <ord>Monogamia</ord>; having a simple flower with united anthers.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogamist</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nog"a*mist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who practices or upholds monogamy.</def>  <rj><au>Goldsmith.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogamous</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nog"a*mous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>monogamus</ets> having but one wife, Gr. <?/; <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <?/ marriage.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Upholding, or practicing, monogamy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Monogamian</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Mating with but one of the opposite sex; -- said of birds and mammals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monogamousness</ent><br/
<hw>monogamousness</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state of being monogamous; having one wife at a time.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> monogamy, monogyny.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogamy</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nog"a*my</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>monogamia</ets>, Gr. <?/: cf. F. <ets>monogamie</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Single marriage; marriage with but one person, husband or wife, at the same time; -- opposed to <contr>polygamy</contr>. Also, one marriage only during life; -- opposed to <contr>deuterogamy</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>State of being paired with a single mate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogastric</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*gas"tric</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <?/ belly.]</ety> <def>Having but a single stomach.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogenesis</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*gen"e*sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>genesis</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Oneness of origin; esp. <fld>(Biol.)</fld>, development of all beings in the universe from a single cell; -- opposed to <contr>polygenesis</contr>. Called also <altname>monism</altname>.</def>  <rj><au>Dana.</au>  <au>Haeckel.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>That form of reproduction which requires but one parent, as in reproduction by fission or in the formation of buds, etc., which drop off and form new individuals; asexual reproduction.</def>  <rj><au>Haeckel.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The direct development of an embryo, without metamorphosis, into an organism similar to the parent organism; -- opposed to <contr>metagenesis</contr>.</def>  <rj><au>E. van Beneden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogenetic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*ge*net"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Monogenesis</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>One in genesis; resulting from one process of formation; -- used of a mountain range.</def>  <rj><au>Dana.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Relating to, or involving, monogenesis; <as>as, the <ex>monogenetic</ex> school of physiologists, who admit but one cell as the source of all beings</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogenic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*gen"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to monogenesis.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Producing only one kind of germs, or young; developing only in one way.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogenism</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nog"e*nism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Anthropol.)</fld> <def>The theory or doctrine that the human races have a common origin, or constitute a single species.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogenist</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nog"e*nist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Anthropol.)</fld> <def>One who maintains that the human races are all of one species; -- opposed to <contr>polygenist</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogenistic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*ge*nis"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Monogenic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogenous</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nog"e*nous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to monogenesis; <as>as, <ex>monogenous</ex>, or asexual, reproduction</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogeny</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nog"e*ny</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Monogenesis.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Anthropol.)</fld> <def>The doctrine that the members of the human race have all a common origin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogoneutic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*go*neu"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <?/ offspring.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having but one brood in a season.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogram</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*gram</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>monogramma</ets>; Gr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <grk>gra`mma</grk> letter, fr. <grk>gra`fein</grk> to write: cf. F. <ets>monogramme</ets>. See <er>Graphic</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A character or cipher composed of two or more letters interwoven or combined so as to represent a name, or a part of it (usually the initials).  Monograms are often used on seals, ornamental pins, rings, buttons, and by painters, engravers, etc., to distinguish their works.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><illust>Monogram.</illust><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The monogram above, combining the letters of the name <er>Karolvs</er>, was used by Charlemagne.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A picture in lines; a sketch.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An arbitrary sign for a word.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monogram</ent><br/
<hw>mon"o*gram</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To inscribe or ornament with a monogram.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogrammal</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*gram`mal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>See <er>Monogrammic</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogrammatic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*gram*mat"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Monogrammic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogrammic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*gram"mic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of, pertaining to, or resembling, a monogram.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogrammous</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*gram`mous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Monogrammic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monograph</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*graph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>-graph</ets>.]</ety> <def>A written account or description of a single thing, or class of things; a special treatise on a particular subject of limited range.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monographer</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nog"ra*pher</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A writer of a monograph.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monographical</ent><br/
<ent>Monographic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mon`o*graph"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mon`o*graph"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>monographique</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to a monograph, or to a monography; <as>as, a <ex>monographic</ex> writing; a <ex>monographic</ex> picture.</as></def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mon`o*graph"ic*al*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monographist</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nog"ra*phist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who writes a monograph.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monographous</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nog"ra*phous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Monographic.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monography</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nog"ra*phy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>-graphy</ets>: cf. F. <ets>monographie</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Representation by lines without color; an outline drawing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A monograph.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogyn</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*gyn</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>One of the Monogynia.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogynia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mon`o*gyn"i*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <?/ woman, female.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A Linnaean order of plants, including those which have only one style or stigma.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogynian</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*gyn"i*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to the <ord>Monogynia</ord>; monogynous.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>One of the <ord>Monogynia</ord>.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogynous</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nog"y*nous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>monogyne</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to <ord>Monogynia</ord>; having only one style or stigma.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monogyny</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nog"y*ny</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Monogynia</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Marriage with the one woman only.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The state or condition of being monogynous.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monohemerous</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*hem"er*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <?/ day.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Lasting but one day.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monoicous</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*noi"cous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Monoecious.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monolatry</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nol"a*try</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <?/ worship.]</ety> <def>Worship of a single deity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monolingual</ent><br/
<hw>mon`o*lin"gual</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Using or knowing only one language; <as>as, <ex>monolingual</ex> speakers; a <ex>monolingual</ex> dictionary</as>.  Opposite of <ant>multilingual</ant>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monolith</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*lith</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>monolithe</ets>, L. <ets>monolithus</ets> consisting of a single stone, Gr. <?/; <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <grk>li`qos</grk> stone.]</ety> <def>A single stone, especially one of large size, shaped into a pillar, statue, or monument.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monolithal</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*lith`al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Monolithic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monolithic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*lith"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to a monolith; consisting of a single stone.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monologist</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nol"o*gist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Monologue</er>.]</ety> <def>One who soliloquizes; esp., one who monopolizes conversation in company.</def>  <rj><au>De Quincey.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monologue</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*logue</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>monologue</ets>, Gr. <?/ speaking alone; <grk>mo`nos</grk> alone, single, sole + <grk>lo`gos</grk> speech, discourse, <grk>le`gein</grk> to speak. See <er>Legend</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A speech uttered by a person alone; soliloquy; also, talk or discourse in company, in the strain of a soliloquy; <as>as, an account in <ex>monologue</ex></as>.</def>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A dramatic composition for a single performer.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monology</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/.]</ety> <def>The habit of soliloquizing, or of monopolizing conversation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was not by an insolent usurpation that Coleridge persisted in <qex>monology</qex> through his whole life.</q> <rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monomachy</ent><br/
<ent>Monomachia</ent><br/
<mhw>{ \'d8<hw>Mon`o*ma"chi*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mo*nom"a*chy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>monomachia</ets>, Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ fighting in single combat; <grk>mo`nos</grk> single, alone + <?/ to fight.]</ety> <def>A duel; single combat.</def> <ldquo/The duello or <xex>monomachia</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Sir W. Scott.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monomachist</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nom"a*chist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who fights in single combat; a duelist.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monomane</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*mane</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A monomaniac.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monomania</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*ma"ni*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>mania</ets>.]</ety> <def>Derangement of the mind in regard of a single subject only; also, such a concentration of interest upon one particular subject or train of ideas to show mental derangement.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Insanity; madness; alienation; aberration; derangement; mania. See <er>Insanity</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monomaniac</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`oma"ni*ac</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A person affected by monomania.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monomaniacal</ent><br/
<ent>Monomaniac</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mon`oma"ni*ac</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mon`oma"ni*a*cal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>monomaniaque</ets>.]</ety> <def>Affected with monomania, or partial derangement of intellect; caused by, or resulting from, monomania; <as>as, a <ex>monomaniacal</ex> delusion</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monome</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ome</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. Gr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <ets>-nome</ets> as in <ets>binome</ets>. See <er>Binomial</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>A monomial.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monomer</ent><br/
<hw>mon"o*mer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>The basic conceptual building unit of a polymer; a molecule of low molecular weight which may combine with other molecules to form a molecule in a chain or branched form having high molecular weight; <as>as, amino acids are the <ex>monomer</ex> units which are combined to form proteins; vinylic plastics are formed from <ex>monomers</ex> having a vinyl group</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monomeric</ent><br/
<hw>mon`o*mer"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Not linked to other molecules of the same kind; having the property of a monomer.  Opposed to <ant>polymeric</ant>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monomerous</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nom"er*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr.  single; <grk>mo`nos</grk> alone + <?/ part.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Composed of solitary parts, as a flower with one sepal, one petal, one stamen, and one pistil.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having but one joint; -- said of the foot of certain insects.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monometallic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*me*tal"lic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Consisting of one metal; of or pertaining to monometallism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monometallism</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*met"al*lism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>metal</ets>.]</ety> <def>The legalized use of one metal only, as gold, or silver, in the standard currency of a country, or as a standard of money values. See <er>Bimetallism</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monometallist</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*met"al*list</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who believes in monometallism as opposed to bimetallism, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monometer</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nom"e*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ of one meter; <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <?/ measure.]</ety> <def>A rhythmic series, consisting of a single meter.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monometric</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*met"ric</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>monom<eacute/trique</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Crystallog.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Isometric</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monomial</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*no"mi*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Monome</er>, <er>Binomial</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Alg.)</fld> <def>A single algebraic expression; that is, an expression unconnected with any other by the sign of addition, substraction, equality, or inequality.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monomial</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*no"mi*al</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Alg.)</fld> <def>Consisting of but a single term or expression.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monomorphous</ent><br/
<ent>Monomorphic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mon`o*mor"phic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mon`o*mor"phous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <grk>morfh`</grk> form.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Having but a single form; retaining the same form throughout the various stages of development; of the same or of an essentially similar type of structure; -- opposed to <contr>dimorphic</contr>, <contr>trimorphic</contr>, and <contr>polymorphic</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monomphalus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo*nom"pha*lus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> alone + <?/ the navel.]</ety> <def>A form of double monster, in which two individuals are united by a common umbilicus.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monomyaria</ent><br/
<ent>Monomya</ent><br/
<mhw>{ \'d8<hw>Mo*no"my*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, \'d8<hw>Mon`o*my*a"ri*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <?/, <?/, muscle.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An order of lamellibranchs having but one muscle for closing the shell, as the oyster.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monomyary</ent><br/
<ent>Monomyarian</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mon`o*my"a*ri*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mon`o*my"a*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the <ord>Monomya</ord>.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>One of the <ord>Monomya</ord>.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mononomial</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*no"mi*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. & a.</pos> <def>Monomyal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monoousious</ent><br/
<ent>Monoousian</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mon`o*ou"si*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mon`o*ou"si*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <?/ being, substance, essence.]</ety> <fld>(Theil.)</fld> <def>Having but one and the same nature or essence.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monopathy</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nop"a*thy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/; <grk>mo`nos</grk> alone + <?/, <?/, to suffer.]</ety> <def>Suffering or sensibility in a single organ or function.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mon`o*path"ic</wf>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monopersonal</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*per"son*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>personal</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having but one person, or form of existence.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monopetalous</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*pet"al*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>petal</ets>: cf. F. <ets>monop<eacute/tale</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having only one petal, or the corolla in one piece, or composed of petals cohering so as to form a tube or bowl; gamopetalous.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The most recent authors restrict this form to flowers having a solitary petal, as in species of <gen>Amorpha</gen>, and use <contr>gamopetalous</contr> for a corolla of several petals combined into one piece. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Gamopetalous</er>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monophanous</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*noph"a*nous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <?/ to show.]</ety> <def>Having one and the same appearance; having a mutual resemblance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monophonic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*phon"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <?/ a voice.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Single-voiced; having but one part; <as>as, a <ex>monophonic</ex> composition</as>; -- opposed to <ant>polyphonic</ant>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or relating to a system for recording and reproducing sound, which has only one sound channel; also called <altname>monaural</altname> or <altname>mono</altname>.  It contrasts with <contr>stereophonic</contr> (or <contr>stereo</contr>), <contr>quadraphonic</contr>, or <contr>surround-sound</contr>, which have two or more channels, and can thus reproduce the effect of the sound coming from more than one direction.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monophthong</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"oph*thong</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ with one sound; <grk>mo`nos</grk> alone + <?/ sound, voice.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A single uncompounded vowel sound.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A combination of two written vowels pronounced as one; a digraph.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monophthongal</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`oph*thon"gal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Consisting of, or pertaining to, a monophthong.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monophyletic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*phy*let"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ of one tribe, fr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <?/ clan.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to a single family or stock, or to development from a single common parent form; -- opposed to <ant>polyphyletic</ant>; <as>as, <ex>monophyletic</ex> origin</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monophyllous</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*noph"yl*lous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mono`fyllos</grk>; <grk>mo`nos</grk> alone + <grk>fy`llon</grk> leaf: cf. F. <ets>monophylle</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>One-leaved; composed of a single leaf; <as>as, a <ex>monophyllous</ex> involucre or calyx</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monophyodont</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*phy"o*dont</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> single (<grk>mo`nos</grk> alone + <?/ to produce) + <grk>'odoy`s</grk>, <grk>'odo`ntos</grk>, a tooth.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Having but one set of teeth; -- opposed to <contr>diphyodont</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monophysite</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*noph"y*site</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/; <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <?/ nature: cf. F. <ets>monophysite</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>One of a sect, in the ancient church, who maintained that the human and divine in Jesus Christ constituted but one composite nature. Also used adjectively.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monophysitical</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*phy*sit"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to Monophysites, or their doctrines.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monoplast</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*plast</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>-plast</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>A monoplastic element.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monoplastic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*plas"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>-plastic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>That has one form, or retains its primary form, <as>as, a <ex>monoplastic</ex> element</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monoplegia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mon`ople"gi*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <?/ a stroke.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Paralysis affecting a single limb.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monopneumona</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mon`op*neu"mo*na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Mono-</er>, and <er>Pneumonia</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A suborder of Dipnoi, including the Ceratodus.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>monopneumonia</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monopode</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*pode</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One of a fabulous tribe or race of Ethiopians having but one leg and foot.</def>  <rj><au>Sir J. Mandeville.</au>  <au>Lowell.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A monopodium.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monopodial</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*po"di*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having a monopodium or a single and continuous axis, as a birchen twig or a cornstalk.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monopodium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mon`o*po"di*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> L. <plw>Monopodia</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, E. <plw>-ums</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. See <er>Monopody</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A single and continuous vegetable axis; -- opposed to <contr>sympodium</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monopody</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nop"o*dy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <grk>poy`s</grk>, <grk>podo`s</grk>, foot: cf. <?/, <?/, one-footed.]</ety> <fld>(Pros.)</fld> <def>A measure of but a single foot.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monopoler</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nop"o*ler</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A monopolist.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 941 --></p>

<p><ent>Monopolist</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nop"o*list</hw> <pr>(m<osl/*n<ocr/p"<osl/*l<icr/st)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who monopolizes; one who has a monopoly; one who favors monopoly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monopolistic</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nop`o*lis"tic</hw> <pr>(m<osl/*n<ocr/p`<osl/*l<icr/s"t<icr/k)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to a monopolist.</def>  <rj><au>North Am. Rev.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monopolite</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nop"o*lite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A monopolist.</def>  <rj><au>Sylvester.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monopolize</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nop"o*lize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Monopolized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Monopolizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From <er>Monopoly</er>.]</ety> <def>To acquire a monopoly of; to have or get the exclusive privilege or means of dealing in, or the exclusive possession of; to engross the whole of; <as>as, to <ex>monopolize</ex> the coffee trade; to <ex>monopolize</ex> land.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monopolizer</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nop"o*li`zer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who monopolizes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monopoly</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nop"o*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Monopolies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>monopolium</ets>, Gr. <?/, <?/; <grk>mo`nos</grk> alone + <?/ to sell.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The exclusive power, or privilege of selling a commodity; the exclusive power, right, or privilege of dealing in some article, or of trading in some market; sole command of the traffic in anything, however obtained; <as>as, the proprietor of a patented article is given a <ex>monopoly</ex> of its sale for a limited time; chartered trading companies have sometimes had a <ex>monopoly</ex> of trade with remote regions; a combination of traders may get a <ex>monopoly</ex> of a particular product.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Raleigh held a <qex>monopoly</qex> of cards, Essex a <qex>monopoly</qex> of sweet wines.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Exclusive possession; <as>as, a <ex>monopoly</ex> of land</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If I had a <qex>monopoly</qex> out, they would have part on 't.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The commodity or other material thing to which the monopoly relates; <as>as, tobacco is a <ex>monopoly</ex> in France</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monopolylogue</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*pol"y*logue</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <grk>poly`s</grk> many + <grk>lo`gos</grk> speech.]</ety> <def>An exhibition in which an actor sustains many characters.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monopsychism</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*psy"chism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <?/ soul.]</ety> <def>The doctrine that there is but one immortal soul or intellect with which all men are endowed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monopteral</ent><br/
<hw>mo*nop"ter*al</hw> <pr>(m<osl/*n<ocr/p"t<etil/r*<ait/l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mono`pteros</grk> with a row of pillars only; <grk>mo`nos</grk> alone, only + <grk>ptero`n</grk> feather, wing, also, a row of pillars: cf. F. <ets>monopt<egrave/re</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>Round and without a cella; consisting of a single ring of columns supporting a roof; -- said esp. of a temple.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monopteron</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo*nop"ter*on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Monoptera</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL. See <er>Monopteral</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A circular temple consisting of a roof supported on columns, without a cella.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monoptote</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"op*tote</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>monoptotum</ets>, Gr. <grk>mono`ptwtos</grk>; <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <?/ apt to fall, fallen, fr. <?/ to fall; cf. <?/ case.]</ety> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A noun having only one case.</def>  <rj><au>Andrews.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A noun having only one ending for the oblique cases.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monopyrenous</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*py*re"nous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>pyrene</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having but a single stone or kernel.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monorganic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`or*gan"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mon-</ets> + <ets>organic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol. & Med.)</fld> <def>Belonging to, or affecting, a single organ, or set of organs.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monorhina</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mon`o*rhi"na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <?/, <?/, nose.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The Marsipobranchiata.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monorhyme</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*rhyme</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>rhyme</ets>: cf. F. <ets>monorime</ets>.]</ety> <def>A composition in verse, in which all the lines end with the same rhyme.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>-rid</ent><br/
<ent>Monosaccharide</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mon`o*sac"cha*ride</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> Also <hw>-rid</hw>  }</mhw>. <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>saccharide</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A simple sugar; any of a number of sugars (including the trioses, tetroses, pentoses, hexoses, etc.), not decomposable into simpler sugars by hydrolysis. Specif., as used by some, a hexose.  The monosaccharides are all open-chain compounds containing hydroxyl groups and either an aldehyde group or a ketone group.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monosepalous</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*sep"al*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>sepal</ets>: cf. F. <ets>monos<eacute/pale</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having only one sepal, or the calyx in one piece or composed of the sepals united into one piece; gamosepalous.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The most recent writers restrict this term to flowers having a solarity sepal, and use <contr>gamosepalous</contr> for a calyx formed by several sepals combined into one piece.  Cf. <er>Monopetalous</er>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monosodium glutamate</ent><br/
<hw>monosodium glutamate</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The monosodium salt of the natural amino acid L-glutamine (<chform>C5H8NNaO4</chform>), used as a food additive to enhance flavor; abbreviated <abbr>MSG</abbr>.  It is usually marketed as the monhydrate (<chform>C5H8NNaO4.H2O</chform>). It is commmonly used in Chinese-American restaurants, and has been identified as a main cause of <causes>Chinese restaurant syndrome</causes>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monosperm</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*sperm</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A monospermous plant.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monospermous</ent><br/
<ent>Monospermal</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mon`o*sper"mal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mon`o*sper"mous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <grk>spe`rma</grk> seed: cf. F. <ets>monosperme</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having only one seed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monospherical</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*spher"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>spherical</ets>.]</ety> <def>Consisting of one sphere only.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monostich</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*stich</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/, from <?/ consisting of one verse; <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <grk>sti`chos</grk> line, verse.]</ety> <def>A composition consisting of one verse only.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monostichous</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nos"ti*chous</hw> <pr>(m<osl/*n<ocr/s"t<icr/*k<ucr/s)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Monostich</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Arranged in a single row on one side of an axis, as the flowers in grasses of the tribe <fam>Chloridae</fam>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monostrophe</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nos"tro*phe</hw> <pr>(m<osl/*n<ocr/s"tr<osl/*f<esl/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mono`strofos</grk> monostrophic.]</ety> <def>A metrical composition consisting of a single strophe.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monostrophic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*stroph"ic</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/n`<osl/*str<ocr/f"<icr/k)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>monostrofiko`s</grk>; <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <grk>strofh`</grk> strophe.]</ety> <fld>(Pros.)</fld> <def>Having one strophe only; not varied in measure; written in unvaried measure.</def>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monosulphide</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*sul"phide</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>sulphide</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A sulphide containing one atom of sulphur, and analogous to a monoxide; -- contrasted with a <ant>polysulphide</ant>; <as>as, galena is a <ex>monosulphide</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monosulphuret</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*sul"phu*ret</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>sulphuret</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>See <er>Monosulphide</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monosyllabic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*syl*lab"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>monosyllabique</ets>.]</ety> <def>Being a monosyllable, or composed of monosyllables; <as>as, a <ex>monosyllabic</ex> word; a <ex>monosyllabic</ex> language.</as></def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mon`o*syl*lab"ic*al*ly</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monosyllabism</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*syl"la*bism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state of consisting of monosyllables, or having a monosyllabic form; frequent occurrence of monosyllables.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monosyllable</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*syl`la*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>monosyllabus</ets> of one syllable, Gr. <?/: cf. F. <ets>monosyllabe</ets>. See <er>Mono-</er>, <er>Syllable</er>.]</ety> <def>A word of one syllable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monosyllabled</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*syl`la*bled</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Formed into, or consisting of, monosyllables.</def>  <rj><au>Cleveland.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monosymmetrical</ent><br/
<ent>Monosymmetric</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mon`o*sym*met"ric</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mon`o*sym*met"ric*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>symmetric</ets>, <ets>-ical</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Crystallog.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Monoclinic</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monotessaron</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*tes"sa*ron</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <?/ four.]</ety> <def>A single narrative framed from the statements of the four evangelists; a gospel harmony.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monothalama</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mon`o*thal"a*ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <grk>qa`lamos</grk> a chamber.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A division of Foraminifera including those that have only one chamber.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monothalaman</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*thal"a*man</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Monothalamous</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A foraminifer having but one chamber.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monothalamous</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*thal"a*mous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <grk>qa`lamos</grk> chamber: cf. F. <ets>monothalame</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One-chambered.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monothalmic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*thal"mic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Monothalamous</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Formed from one pistil; -- said of fruits.</def>  <rj><au>R. Brown.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monothecal</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*the"cal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Br. <?/ box.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having a single loculament.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monotheism</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*the*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <?/ god: cf. F. <ets>monoth<eacute/isme</ets>.]</ety> <def>The doctrine or belief that there is but one God.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monotheist</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*the*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>monoth<eacute/iste</ets>.]</ety> <def>One who believes that there is but one God.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monotheistic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*the*is"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to monotheism.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monothelitism</ent><br/
<ent>Monothelism</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mo*noth"e*lism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mo*noth"e*li*tism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>monoth<eacute/lisme</ets>, <ets>monoth<eacute/litisme</ets>.]</ety> <def>The doctrine of the Monothelites.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monothelite</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*noth"e*lite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/; <grk>mo`nos</grk> alone, only + <?/, <?/, to will, be willing: cf. F. <ets>monoth<eacute/lite</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>One of an ancient sect who held that Christ had but one will as he had but one nature.  Cf. <er>Monophysite</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Gibbon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monothelitic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*the*lit"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the <org>Monothelites</org>, or their doctrine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monotocous</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*not"o*cous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <?/ birth, offspring.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Bearing fruit but once; monocarpic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Uniparous; laying a single egg.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monotomous</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*not"o*mous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + Gr. <?/ cutting, fr. <?/ to cut.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Having a distinct cleavage in a single direction only.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monotone</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*tone</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Monotonous</er>, <er>Monotony</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A single unvaried tone or sound.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Rhet.)</fld> <def>The utterance of successive syllables, words, or sentences, on one unvaried key or line of pitch.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monotonical</ent><br/
<ent>Monotonic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mon`o*ton"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mon`o*ton"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of, pertaining to, or uttered in, a monotone; monotonous.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Monotonical</xex> declamation.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Chesterfield.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>Always increasing or always decreasing, as the value of the independent variable increases; -- of a function.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monotonist</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*not"o*nist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who talks in the same strain or on the same subject until weariness is produced.</def>  <rj><au>Richardson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monotonous</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*not"o*nous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/; <grk>mo`nos</grk> alone, single + <?/ tone. See <er>Tone</er>.]</ety> <def>Uttered in one unvarying tone; continued with dull uniformity; characterized by monotony; without change or variety; wearisome.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mo*not"o*nous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mo*not"o*nous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monotony</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*not"o*ny</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/: cf. F. <ets>monotonie</ets>. See <er>Monotonius</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A frequent recurrence of the same tone or sound, producing a dull uniformity; absence of variety, as in speaking or singing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any irksome sameness, or want of variety.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At sea, everything that breaks the <qex>monotony</qex> of the surrounding expanse attracts attention.</q> <rj><qau>W. Irving.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monotremata</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mon`o*trem"a*ta</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <?/ hole.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A subclass of Mammalia, having a cloaca in which the ducts of the urinary, genital, and alimentary systems terminate, as in birds.  The female lays eggs like a bird. See <cref>Duck mole</cref>, under <er>Duck</er>, and <er>Echidna</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monotrematous</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*trem"a*tous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the Monotremata.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monotreme</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*treme</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>monotr<egrave/me</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the <subclass>Monotremata</subclass>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monotriglyph</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`o*tri"glyph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>triglyph</ets>: cf. F. <ets>monotriglyphe</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A kind of intercolumniation in an entablature, in which only one triglyph and two metopes are introduced.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monotropa</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo*not"ro*pa</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <?/ turn, from <?/ to turn.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of parasitic or saprophytic plants including the Indian pipe and pine sap. The name alludes to the dropping end of the stem.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monotropaceae</ent><br/
<hw>Monotropaceae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of plants, used in some classifications for saprophytic herbs; it is sometimes included in the family <fam>Pyrolaceae</fam>, and contains the genera <gen>Monotropa</gen> and <gen>Sarcodes</gen>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Monotropaceae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monotypic</ent><br/
<ent>Monotype</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mon"o*type</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mon`o*typ"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>-type</ets>: cf. F. <ets>monotype</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Having but one type; containing but one representative; <as>as, a <ex>monotypic</ex> genus, which contains but one species</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monotype</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"o*type</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <sn>1.</sn> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + <ets>-type</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The only representative of its group, as a single species constituting a genus.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>A print (but one impression can be taken) made by painting on metal and then transferring the painting to paper by pressure; also, the process of making such prints.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn>  <def>A kind of keyboard-operated typesetting and casting machine that makes and sets separate characters.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monovalent</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nov"a*lent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mono-</ets> + L. <ets>valens</ets>, p. pr. See <er>Valence</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Having a valence of one; univalent. See <er>Univalent</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monovular</ent><br/
<hw>monovular</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <fld>(Biol.)</fld>  <def>derived from a single egg or ovum; -- of twins; <as>as, identical twins are <ex>monovular</ex></as>.  Contrasted with <ant>fraternal</ant>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> identical.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monoxide</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nox"ide</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mon-</ets> + <ets>oxide</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>An oxide containing one atom of oxygen in each molecule; <as>as, barium <ex>monoxide</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monoxylon</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo*nox"y*lon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., from Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ made from one piece of wood; <grk>mo`nos</grk> alone + <?/ wood.]</ety> <def>A canoe or boat made from one piece of timber.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monoxylous</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*nox"y*lous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Monoxylon</er>.]</ety> <def>Made of one piece of wood.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monozoa</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mon`o*zo"a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., from Gr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> single + <grk>zw^,on</grk> an animal.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A division of Radiolaria; -- called also <altname>Monocyttaria</altname>.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mon`o*zo"ic</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monroe doctrine</ent><br/
<hw>Mon*roe" doc"trine</hw>. <def>See under <er>Doctrine</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monseigneur</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mon`sei`gneur"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Messeigneurs</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>mon</ets> my + <ets>seigneur</ets> lord, L. <ets>senior</ets> older. See <er>Senior</er>, and cf. <er>Monsieur</er>.]</ety> <def>My lord; -- a title in France of a person of high birth or rank; <as>as, <ex>Monseigneur</ex> the Prince, or <ex>Monseigneur</ex> the Archibishop</as>.  It was given, specifically, to the dauphin, before the Revolution of 1789. (Abbrev. <abbr>Mgr.</abbr>)</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monsel's salt</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"sel's salt`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A basic sulphate of iron; -- so named from <etsep>Monsel</etsep>, a Frenchman.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monsel's solution</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"sel's so*lu"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[See <er>Monsel's salt</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>An aqueous solution of Monsel's salt, having valuable styptic properties.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monsieur</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mon*sieur"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Messieurs</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>mon</ets> my + <ets>Sieur</ets>, abbrev. of <ets>seigneur</ets> lord. See <er>Monseigneur</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The common title of civility in France in speaking to, or of, a man; Mr. or Sir.</def> <altsp>[Represented by the abbreviation <abbr>M.</abbr> or <abbr>Mons.</abbr> in the singular, and by <plw><abbr>MM.</abbr></plw> or <plw><abbr>Messrs.</abbr></plw> in the plural.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The oldest brother of the king of France.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A Frenchman.</def> <mark>[Contemptuous]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monsignore</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mon`si*gno"re</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Monsignors</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[It., my lord.  Cf. <er>Monseigneur</er>.]</ety> <def>My lord; -- an ecclesiastical dignity bestowed by the pope, entitling the bearer to social and domestic rank at the papal court. (Abbrev. <abbr>Mgr.</abbr>)</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monsoon</ent><br/
<hw>mon*soon"</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/n*s<oomac/n")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Malay <ets>m<umac/sim</ets>, fr. Ar. <ets>mausim</ets> a time, season: cf. F. <ets>monson</ets>, <ets>mousson</ets>, Sr. <ets>monzon</ets>, Pg. <ets>mon<cced/<atil/o</ets>, It. <ets>monsone</ets>.]</ety> <def>A wind blowing part of the year from one direction, alternating with a wind from the opposite direction; -- a term applied particularly to periodical winds of the Indian Ocean, which blow from the southwest from the latter part of May to the middle of September, and from the northeast from about the middle of October to the middle of December.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A heavy rainfall in India associated with the southwest monsoon{1}.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The season in which the monsoon{2} occurs.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monster</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ster</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/n*st<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>monstre</ets>, F. <ets>monstre</ets>, fr. L. <ets>monstrum</ets>, orig., a divine omen, indicating misfortune; akin of <ets>monstrare</ets> to show, point out, indicate, and <ets>monere</ets> to warn. See <er>Monition</er>, and cf. <er>Demonstrate</er>, <er>Muster</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Something of unnatural size, shape, or quality; a prodigy; an enormity; a marvel.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>monster</qex> or marvel.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Specifically , an animal or plant departing greatly from the usual type, as by having too many limbs.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Any thing or person of unnatural or excessive ugliness, deformity, wickedness, or cruelty.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monster</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ster</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Monstrous in size.</def>  <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Enormous or very powerful; <as>as, he drove a <ex>monster</ex> Harley</as>.</def> <mark>[informal]</mark><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monster</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ster</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make monstrous.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monstera</ent><br/
<hw>monstera</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>any plant of the genus <gen>Monstera</gen>; they are often grown as houseplants.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A tropical cylindrical pineconelike fruit with pineapple-banana flavor.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> ceriman.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>monstrance</ent><br/
<hw>mon"strance</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/n*str<ait/ns)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>monstrantia</ets>, fr. L. <ets>monstrare</ets> to show: cf. OF. <ets>monstrance</ets>. See <er>Monster</er>.]</ety> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld> <def>A transparent pyx, in which the consecrated host is exposed to view.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monstration</ent><br/
<hw>Mon*stra"tion</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/n*str<amac/"sh<ucr/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>monstratio</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act of demonstrating; proof.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A certain <qex>monstration</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Grafton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monstrosity</ent><br/
<hw>Mon*stros"i*ty</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/n*str<ocr/s"<icr/*t<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Monstrosities</plw> <pr>(m<ocr/n*str<ocr/s"<icr/*t<icr/z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>monstruosit<eacute/</ets>. See <er>Monstrous</er>.]</ety> <def>The state of being monstrous, or out of the common order of nature; that which is monstrous; a monster.</def>  <rj><au>South.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>monstrosity</qex> never changes the name or affects the immutability of a species.</q> <rj><qau>Adanson (Trans.).</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monstrous</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"strous</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/n"str<ucr/s)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>monstruous</ets>, F. <ets>monstrueux</ets>, fr. L. <ets>monstruosus</ets>, fr. <ets>monstrum</ets>. See <er>Monster</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Marvelous; strange.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Having the qualities of a monster; deviating greatly from the natural form or character; abnormal; <as>as, a <ex>monstrous</ex> birth</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Locke.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He, therefore, that refuses to do good to them whom he is bound to love . . . is unnatural and <qex>monstrous</qex> in his affections.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Extraordinary in a way to excite wonder, dislike, apprehension, etc.; -- said of size, appearance, color, sound, etc.; <as>as, a <ex>monstrous</ex> height; a <ex>monstrous</ex> ox; a <ex>monstrous</ex> story.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Extraordinary on account of ugliness, viciousness, or wickedness; hateful; horrible; dreadful.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So bad a death argues a <qex>monstrous</qex> life.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Abounding in monsters.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where thou, perhaps, under the whelming tide<br/
Visitest the bottom of the <qex>monstrous</qex> world.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monstrous</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"strous</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Exceedingly; very; very much.</def> <ldquo/A <xex>monstrous</xex> thick oil on the top.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And will be <qex>monstrous</qex> witty on the poor.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monstrously</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"strous*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a monstrous manner; unnaturally; extraordinarily; <as>as, <ex>monstrously</ex> wicked</as>.</def> <ldquo/Who with his wife is <xex>monstrously</xex> in love.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monstrousness</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"strous*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state or quality of being monstrous, unusual, extraordinary.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monstruosity</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`stru*os"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Monstrosity.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monstruous</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"stru*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Monstrous.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mont</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mont</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. See <er>Mount</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>Mountain.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Montaigne</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"taigne</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mountain.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Montanic</ent><br/
<hw>Mon*tan"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>montanus</ets>, fr. <ets>mons</ets>, <ets>montis</ets>, mountain. See <er>Mount</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to mountains; consisting of mountains.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Montanist</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ta*nist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>A follower of <persfn>Mintanus</persfn>, a Phrygian enthusiast of the second century, who claimed that the Holy Spirit, the Paraclete, dwelt in him, and employed him as an instrument for purifying and guiding men in the Christian life.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mon`ta*nis"tic</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <wf>Mon`ta*nis"tic*al</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Montant</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"tant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.,prop., mounting, fr. <ets>monter</ets> to mount, fr. L. <ets>mons</ets>, <ets>montis</ets>, mountain. See <er>Mount</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Fencing)</fld> <def>An upward thrust or blow.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>An upright piece in any framework; a mullion or muntin; a stile.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <see>See <er>Stile</er>.</see><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mont de piete</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mont" de pi`<eacute/`t<eacute/"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[F., fr. It. <ets>monte di piet<agrave/</ets> mount of piety.]</ety> <def>One of certain public pawnbroking establishments which originated in Italy in the 15th century, the object of which was to lend money at a low rate of interest to poor people in need; -- called also <altname>mount of piety</altname>.  The institution has been adopted in other countries, as in Spain and France. See <er>Lombard-house</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 942 --></p>

<p><ent>Monte</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mon"te</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/n"t<asl/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp., lit., mountain, hence, the stock of cards remaining after laying out a certain number, fr. L. <ets>mons</ets>, <ets>montis</ets>, mountain.]</ety> <def>A favorite gambling game among Spaniards, played with dice or cards.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>three-card monte</b></col> <cd>a gambling game using playing cards, in which a dealer shows a bettor three cards face up and specifies one to be identified, and after the cards are turned face down and moved around quickly, the bettor must identify which of the three cards is the specified card.  It is sometimes engaged in by dealers on the streets of a city, with bets made by passers-by.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monte</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mon"te</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>In Spanish America, a wood; forest; timber land; esp., in parts of South America, a comparatively wooden region.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monte-acid</ent><br/
<hw>Monte`-ac"id</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>monter</ets> to raise + <ets>acide</ets> acid.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>An acid elevator, as a tube through which acid is forced to some height in a sulphuric acid manufactory.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monteith</ent><br/
<hw>Mon*teith"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Monteth</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monteith</ent><br/
<hw>Mon*teith"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A kind of cotton handkerchief having a uniform colored ground with a regular pattern of white spots produced by discharging the color; -- so called from the Glasgow manufactures.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monte-jus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Monte"-jus"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>monter</ets> to bring up + <ets>jus</ets> juice.]</ety> <def>An apparatus for raising a liquid by pressure of air or steam in a reservoir containing the liquid.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Montem</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"tem</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>ad montem</ets> to the hillock. See <er>Mount</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>A custom, formerly practiced by the scholars at Eton school, England, of going every third year, on Whittuesday, to a hillock near the Bath road, and exacting money from all passers-by, to support at the university the senior scholar of the school.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Montero</ent><br/
<hw>Mon*te"ro</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>montera</ets> a hunting cap, fr. <ets>montero</ets> a huntsman, <ets>monte</ets> a mountain, forest, L. <ets>mons</ets>, <ets>montis</ets>, mountain. See <er>Mount</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>An ancient kind of cap worn by horsemen or huntsmen.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Montessori Method</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`tes*so"ri Meth"od</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Pedagogy)</fld> <def>A system of training and instruction, primarily for use with normal children aged from three to six years, devised by <person>Dr. Maria <etsep>Montessori</etsep></person> while teaching in the <ldquo/Houses of Childhood<rdquo/ (schools in the poorest tenement districts of Rome, Italy), and first fully described by her in 1909.  The fundamental aim is to create self-motivation for education, and the leading features are freedom for physical activity (no stationary desks and chairs), informal and individual instruction, the very early development of reading and writing skills, and an extended sensory and motor training (with special emphasis on vision, touch, perception of movement, and their interconnections), mediated by a patented, standardized system of <ldquo/didactic apparatus,<rdquo/ which is declared to be <ldquo/auto-regulative.<rdquo/  Most of the chief features of the method are borrowed from current methods used in many institutions for training feeble-minded children, and dating back especially to the work of the French-American physician <person>Edouard O. Seguin</person> (1812-80).</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monteith</ent><br/
<ent>Monteth</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mon*teth"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mon*teith"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A vessel in which glasses are washed; -- so called from the name of the inventor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>New things produce new words, and thus <qex>Monteth</qex><br/
Has by one vessel saved his name from death.</q> <rj><qau>King.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Montgolfier</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mont`gol"fier</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A balloon which ascends by the buoyancy of air heated by a fire; a fire balloon; -- so called from two brothers, Stephen and <person>Joseph <etsep>Montgolfier</etsep></person>, of France, who first constructed and sent up a fire balloon.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Month</ent><br/
<hw>Month</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/nth)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>month</ets>, <ets>moneth</ets>, AS. <ets>m<omac/n<edh/</ets>, <ets>m<omac/na<edh/</ets>; akin to <ets>m<omac/na</ets> moon, and to D. <ets>maand</ets> month, G. <ets>monat</ets>, OHG. <ets>m<amac/n<omac/d</ets>, Icel. <ets>m<amac/nu<edh/r</ets>, <ets>m<amac/na<edh/r</ets>, Goth. <ets>m<emac/n<omac/<thorn/s</ets>. <root/272.  See <er>Moon</er>.]</ety> <def>One of the twelve portions into which the year is divided; the twelfth part of a year, corresponding nearly to the length of a synodic revolution of the moon, -- whence the name.  In popular use, a period of four weeks is often called a <ex>month</ex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ In the common law, a <xex>month</xex> is a lunar month, or twenty-eight days, unless otherwise expressed. <au>Blackstone.</au> In the United States the rule of the common law is generally changed, and a <xex>month</xex> is declared to mean a calendar month. <au>Cooley's Blackstone.</au></note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>A month mind</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A strong or abnormal desire</cd>. <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Shak.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A celebration made in remembrance of a deceased person a month after death.</cd> <au>Strype.</au> -- <col><b>Calendar months</b></col>, <cd>the months as adjusted in the common or Gregorian calendar; April, June, September, and November, containing 30 days, and the rest 31, except February, which, in common years, has 28, and in leap years 29.</cd> -- <col><b>Lunar month</b></col>, <cd>the period of one revolution of the moon, particularly a synodical revolution; but several kinds are distinguished, as the <stype>synodical month</stype>, or period from one new moon to the next, in mean length 29 d. 12 h. 44 m. 2.87 s.; the <stype>nodical month</stype>, or time of revolution from one node to the same again, in length 27 d. 5 h. 5 m. 36 s.; the <stype>sidereal</stype>, or time of revolution from a star to the same again, equal to 27 d. 7 h. 43 m. 11.5 s.; the <stype>anomalistic</stype>, or time of revolution from perigee to perigee again, in length 27 d. 13 h. 18 m. 37.4 s.; and the <stype>tropical</stype>, or time of passing from any point of the ecliptic to the same again, equal to 27 d. 7 h. 43 m. 4.7 s.</cd> -- <col><b>Solar month</b></col>, <cd>the time in which the sun passes through one sign of the zodiac, in mean length 30 d. 10 h. 29 m. 4.1 s.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monthling</ent><br/
<hw>Month"ling</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>That which is a month old, or which lives for a month.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Wordsworth.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monthly</ent><br/
<hw>Month"ly</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Continued a month, or a performed in a month; <as>as, the <ex>monthly</ex> revolution of the moon</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Done, happening, payable, published, etc., once a month, or every month; <as>as, a <ex>monthly</ex> visit; <ex>monthly</ex> charges; a <ex>monthly</ex> installment; a <ex>monthly</ex> magazine.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Monthly nurse</b></col>, <cd>a nurse who serves for a month or some short time, esp. one which attends women after childbirth.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monthly</ent><br/
<hw>Month"ly</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Monthlies</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>A publication which appears regularly once a month.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monthly</ent><br/
<hw>Month"ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Once a month; in every month; <as>as, the moon changes <ex>monthly</ex></as>.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>As if under the influence of the moon; in the manner of a lunatic.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Middleton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monticle</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ti*cle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>monticulus</ets>, dim. of <ets>mons</ets>, <ets>montis</ets>, mountain: cf. F. <ets>monticule</ets>. See <er>Mount</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>A little mount; a hillock; a small elevation or prominence.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>monticule</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monticulate</ent><br/
<hw>Mon*tic"u*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Furnished with monticles or little elevations.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monticule</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ti*cule</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Monticle</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monticulous</ent><br/
<hw>Mon*tic"u*lous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Monticulate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Montiform</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ti*form</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mons</ets>, <ets>montis</ets>, mountain + <ets>-form</ets>.]</ety> <def>Resembling a mountain in form.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Montigenous</ent><br/
<hw>Mon*tig"e*nous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>montigena</ets>; <ets>mons</ets>, <ets>montis</ets>, mountain + the root of <ets>gignere</ets> to beget.]</ety> <def>Produced on a mountain.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Montoir</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mon`toir"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>monter</ets> to mount. See <er>Montant</er>.]</ety> <def>A stone used in mounting a horse; a horse block.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monton</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"ton</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp.]</ety> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>A heap of ore; a mass undergoing the process of amalgamation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Montre</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"tre</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., show, show case, organ case.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Organ Building)</fld> <def>A stop, usually the open diapason, having its pipes <ldquo/shown<rdquo/ as part of the organ case, or otherwise specially mounted.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>A hole in the wall of a pottery kiln, by which the state of the pieces within can be judged.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Montross</ent><br/
<hw>Mon*tross"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Matross</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Montrue</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"true</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>monter</ets> to mount. See <er>Montoir</er>.]</ety> <def>That on which anything is mounted; a setting; hence, a saddle horse.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monument</ent><br/
<hw>Mon"u*ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>monumentum</ets>, fr. <ets>monere</ets> to remind, admonish. See <er>Monition</er>, and cf. <er>Moniment</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Something which stands, or remains, to keep in remembrance what is past; a memorial.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of ancient British art<br/
A pleasing <qex>monument</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Philips.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our bruised arms hung up for <qex>monuments</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A building, pillar, stone, or the like, erected to preserve the remembrance of a person, event, action, etc.; <as>as, the Washington <ex>monument</ex>; the Bunker Hill <ex>monument</ex></as>. Also, a tomb, with memorial inscriptions.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On your family's old <qex>monument</qex><br/
Hang mournful epitaphs, and do all rites<br/
That appertain unto a burial.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A stone or other permanent object, serving to indicate a limit or to mark a boundary.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A saying, deed, or example, worthy of record.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Acts and <qex>Monuments</qex> of these latter and perilous days.</q> <rj><qau>Foxe.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Memorial; remembrance; tomb; cenotaph.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monumental</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`u*men"tal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>monumentalis</ets>: cf. F. <ets>monumental</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of, pertaining to, or suitable for, a monument; <as>as, a <ex>monumental</ex> inscription</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Serving as a monument; memorial; preserving memory.</def> <ldquo/Of pine, or <xex>monumental</xex> oak.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A work outlasting <qex>monumental</qex> brass.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Of lasting significance; <as>as, a <ex>monumental</ex> work of literature; a <ex>monumental</ex> accomplishment</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Exceptionally large in quantity, quality, or degree; <as>as, a <ex>monumental</ex> amount of work to be done</as></def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monumentally</ent><br/
<hw>Mon`u*men"tal*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>By way of memorial.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>By means of monuments.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monureid</ent><br/
<hw>Mon*u"re*id</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mon-</ets> + <ets>ureid</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Any one of a series of complex nitrogenous substances regarded as derived from one molecule of urea; <as>as, alloxan is a <ex>monureid</ex></as>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>monureide</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moo</ent><br/
<hw>Moo</hw> <pr>(m<omac/)</pr>, <pos>a., adv., & n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mo</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moo</ent><br/
<hw>Moo</hw> <pr>(m<oomac/)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mooed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mooing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Of imitative origin.]</ety> <def>To make the noise of a cow; to low; -- a child's word.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moo</ent><br/
<hw>Moo</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The lowing of a cow.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mooch</ent><br/
<hw>mooch</hw> <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>to ask for and get free; to borrow without intending to repay; to sponge; -- usually with objects of small value; <as>as, he <ex>mooched</ex> a few cigarettes from me</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> bum, cadge, grub, sponge.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To beg for.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moo-cow</ent><br/
<hw>moo-cow</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a cow{1}; -- a child's word.  See 1st <er>cow</er>{1}, <pos>n.</pos></def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mood</ent><br/
<hw>Mood</hw> <pr>(m<oomac/d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[The same word as <ets>mode</ets>, perh. influenced by <ets>mood</ets> temper. See <er>Mode</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Manner; style; mode; logical form; musical style; manner of action or being. See <er>Mode</er> which is the preferable form).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>Manner of conceiving and expressing action or being, as positive, possible, conditional, hypothetical, obligatory, imperitive, etc., without regard to other accidents, such as time, person, number, etc.; <as>as, the indicative <ex>mood</ex>; the imperitive <ex>mood</ex>; the infinitive <ex>mood</ex>; the subjunctive <ex>mood</ex>. Same as <er>Mode</er>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mood</ent><br/
<hw>Mood</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mood</ets>, <ets>mod</ets>, AS. <ets>m<omac/d</ets>mind, feeling, heart, courage; akin to OS. & OFries. <ets>m<omac/d</ets>, D. <ets>moed</ets>, OHG. <ets>muot</ets>, G. <ets>muth</ets>, <ets>mut</ets>, courage, Dan. & Sw. <ets>mod</ets>, Icel. <ets>m<omac/<edh/r</ets> wrath, Goth. <ets>m<omac/ds</ets>.]</ety> <def>Temper of mind; temporary state of the mind in regard to passion or feeling; humor; <as>as, a melancholy <ex>mood</ex>; a suppliant <ex>mood</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Till at the last aslaked was his <qex>mood</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fortune is merry,<br/
And in this <qex>mood</qex> will give us anything.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The desperate recklessness of her <qex>mood</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mooder</ent><br/
<hw>Moo"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mother.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moodily</ent><br/
<hw>Mood"i*ly</hw> <pr>(m<oomac/d"<icr/*l<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a moody manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moodiness</ent><br/
<hw>Mood"i*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being moody; specifically, liability to strange or violent moods.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moodir</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Moo"dir</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Ar. <ets>mud<imac/r</ets>.]</ety> <def>The governor of a province in Egypt, etc.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mudir</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moodish</ent><br/
<hw>Mood"ish</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Moody.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moodishly</ent><br/
<hw>Mood"ish*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Moodily.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moody</ent><br/
<hw>Mood"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Moodier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Moodiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<omac/dig</ets> courageous.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Subject to varying moods, especially to states of mind which are unamiable or depressed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence: Out of humor; peevish; angry; fretful; also, abstracted and pensive; sad; gloomy; melancholy.</def> <ldquo/Every peevish, <xex>moody</xex> malcontent.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Rowe.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Arouse thee from thy <qex>moody</qex> dream!</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Gloomy; pensive; sad; fretful; capricious.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moollah</ent><br/
<ent>Moolah</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Moo"lah</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mool"lah</hw>  }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mollah</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moolley</ent><br/
<hw>Mool"ley</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Mulley</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moolah</ent><br/
<ent>moola</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>moo"la</hw>, <hw>moo"lah</hw></mhw> <pr>(m<oomac/"l<adot/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>money.</def> <mark>[slang]</mark><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moon</ent><br/
<hw>Moon</hw> <pr>(m<oomac/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mone</ets>, AS. <ets>m<omac/na</ets>; akin to D. <ets>maan</ets>, OS. & OHG. <ets>m<amac/no</ets>, G. <ets>mond</ets>, Icel. <ets>m<amac/ni</ets>, Dan. <ets>maane</ets>, Sw. <ets>m<aring/ne</ets>, Goth. <ets>m<emac/na</ets>, Lith. <ets>men<uring/</ets>, L. <ets>mensis</ets> month, Gr. <grk>mh`nh</grk> moon, <grk>mh`n</grk> month, Skr. <ets>m<amac/s</ets> moon, month; prob. from a root meaning to measure (cf. Skr. <ets>m<amac/</ets> to measure), from its serving to measure the time. <root/271.  Cf. <er>Mete</er> to measure, <er>Menses</er>, <er>Monday</er>, <er>Month</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The celestial orb which revolves round the earth; the satellite of the earth; a secondary planet, whose light, borrowed from the sun, is reflected to the earth, and serves to dispel the darkness of night.  The diameter of the moon is 2,160 miles, its mean distance from the earth is 240,000 miles, and its mass is one eightieth that of the earth. See <cref>Lunar month</cref>, under <er>Month</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The crescent <qex>moon</qex>, the diadem of night.</q> <rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A secondary planet, or satellite, revolving about any member of the solar system; <as>as, the <ex>moons</ex> of Jupiter or Saturn</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The time occupied by the moon in making one revolution in her orbit; a month; <as>as, it's been many <ex>moons</ex> since I last visited Washington</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Fort.)</fld> <def>A crescentlike outwork. See <er>Half-moon</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The deliberately exposed naked buttocks.</def> <mark>[slang]</mark><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Moon blindness</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Far.)</fld> <cd>A kind of ophthalmia liable to recur at intervals of three or four weeks</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <cd>Hemeralopia.</cd> -- <col><b>Moon dial</b></col>, <cd>a dial used to indicate time by moonlight.</cd> -- <col><b>Moon face</b></col>, <cd>a round face like a full moon.</cd> -- <col><b>Moon madness</b></col>, <cd>lunacy.</cd> <mark>[Poetic]</mark> -- <col><b>Moon month</b></col>, <cd>a lunar month.</cd> -- <col><b>Moon trefoil</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a shrubby species of medic (<spn>Medicago arborea</spn>). See <er>Medic</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Moon year</b></col>, <cd>a lunar year, consisting of lunar months, being sometimes twelve and sometimes thirteen.</cd> -- <col><b>blue moon</b></col>, <cd>see <er>blue moon</er> in the vocabulary.</cd> -- <col><b>many moons</b></col>, <cd>a long time.</cd> </cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moon</ent><br/
<hw>Moon</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mooned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mooning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To expose to the rays of the moon.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If they have it to be exceeding white indeed, they seethe it yet once more, after it hath been thus sunned and <qex>mooned</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Holland.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To expose one's naked buttocks to (a person); -- a vulgar sign of contempt or disrespect, sometimes done as a prank.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moon</ent><br/
<hw>Moon</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To act if moonstruck; to wander or gaze about in an abstracted manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Elsley was <qex>mooning</qex> down the river by himself.</q> <rj><qau>C. Kingsley.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonbeam</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"beam`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A ray of light from the moon.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonblind</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"blind`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Dim-sighted; purblind.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonblink</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"blink`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A temporary blindness, or impairment of sight, said to be caused by sleeping in the moonlight; -- sometimes called <altname>nyctalopia</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mooncalf</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"calf`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A monster; a false conception; a mass of fleshy matter, generated in the uterus.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A dolt; a stupid fellow.</def>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moon-culminating</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"-cul"mi*na`ting</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Culminating, or coming to the meredian, at or about the same time with the moon; -- said of a star or stars, esp. of certain stars selected beforehand, and named in an ephemeris (as the Nautical Almanac), as suitable to be observed in connection with the moon at culmination, for determining terrestrial longitude.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mooned</ent><br/
<hw>Mooned</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or resembling the moon; symbolized by the moon.</def> <ldquo/Sharpening in <xex>mooned</xex> horns.<rdquo/ <ldquo/<xex>Mooned</xex> Ashtaroth.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mooner</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who abstractedly wanders or gazes about, as if moonstruck.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Dickens.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonery</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"er*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Conduct of one who moons.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonet</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"et</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A little moon.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moon-eye</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"-eye`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A eye affected by the moon; also, a disease in the eye of a horse.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Any species of American fresh-water fishes of the genus <gen>Hyodon</gen>, esp. <spn>Hyodon tergisus</spn> of the Great Lakes and adjacent waters.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The cisco.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moon-eyed</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"-eyed`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having eyes affected by the moon; moonblind; dim-eyed; purblind.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moon-faced</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"-faced`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having a round, full face.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonfish</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"fish`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>An American marine fish (<spn>Vomer setipennis</spn>); -- called also <altname>bluntnosed shiner</altname>, <altname>horsefish</altname>, and <altname>sunfish</altname>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A broad, thin, silvery marine fish (<spn>Selene vomer</spn>); -- called also <altname>lookdown</altname>, and <altname>silver moonfish</altname>.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The mola. See <er>Sunfish</er>, 1.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonflower</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"flow`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The oxeye daisy; -- called also <altname>moon daisy</altname>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A kind of morning glory (<spn>Ipomoea Bona-nox</spn>) with large white flowers opening at night.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moong</ent><br/
<hw>Moong</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Mung</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonglade</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"glade`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The bright reflection of the moon's light on an expanse of water.</def> <mark>[Poetic]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moonie</ent><br/
<hw>moo"nie</hw> <pr>(m<oomac/"n<emac/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The European goldcrest.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonie</ent><br/
<hw>Moo"nie</hw> <pr>(m<oomac/"n<emac/)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[from <person>Sun Myun <etsep>Moon</etsep></person>, Korean evangelist and founder.]</ety> <def>A member of the <org>Unification Church</org>, founded by <person>Sun Myun <etsep>Moon</etsep></person>.</def> <mark>[informal & contemptuous.]</mark><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonish</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"ish</hw> <pr>(m<oomac/n"<icr/sh)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Like the moon; variable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Being but a <qex>moonish</qex> youth.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonless</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Being without a moon or moonlight.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonlight</ent><br/
<hw>Moon`light`</hw> <pr>(m<oomac/n"l<imac/t`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The light of the moon.</def> -- <def2><pos>a.</pos> <def>Occurring during or by moonlight; characterized by moonlight.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonlight</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"light`</hw> <pr>(m<oomac/n"l<imac/t`)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To work at a second job in addition to one's main occupation; -- often done at night, hence the word.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonlighter</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"light`er</hw> <pr>(m<oomac/n"l<imac/t`<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who follows an occupation or pastime by moonlight;</def> as: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A moonshiner.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>In Ireland, one of a band that engaged in agrarian outrages by night.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>A serenader by moonlight.</def> <mark>[Local, U. S.]</mark> <sd>(d)</sd> <def>One who works at a second job in addition to his main occupation.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonling</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"ling</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A simpleton; a lunatic.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonlit</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"lit`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Illumined by the moon.</def> <ldquo/The <xex>moonlit</xex> sea.<rdquo/ <au>Moore.</au> <ldquo/<xex>Moonlit</xex> dells.<rdquo/ <au>Lowell.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonraker</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"rak`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Moonsail</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonrise</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"rise`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The rising of the moon above the horizon; also, the time of its rising.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moon-round</ent><br/
<hw>moon-round</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>resembling the moon in shape.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> moonlike.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonsail</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"sail`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A sail sometimes carried in light winds, above a skysail.</def>  <rj><au>R. H. Dana, Jr.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonseed</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"seed`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A climbing plant of the genus <gen>Menispermum</gen>; -- so called from the crescentlike form of the seeds.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonset</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"set`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The descent of the moon below the horizon; also, the time when the moon sets.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonshee</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Moon"shee</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Hind. <ets>munish<imac/</ets>, fr. Ar. <ets>munish<imac/</ets> a writer, author, secretary, tutor.]</ety> <def>A Muslim professor or teacher of language.</def> <mark>[India]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonshine</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"shine`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The light of the moon.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, show without substance or reality.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A month.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A preparation of eggs for food.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Liquor smuggled or illicitly distilled, especially liquor distilled illegally in rural parts of the southern U. S.</def> <mark>[Dial. Eng., & Colloq. or Slang, U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonshine</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"shine`</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Moonlight.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Clarendon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Empty; trivial; idle.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn>  <def>Designating, or pertaining to, illicit liquor; <as>as, <ex>moonshine</ex> whisky</as>.</def> <mark>[Dial. Eng., & Colloq. or Slang, U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonshiner</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"shin`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A person engaged in illicit distilling; -- so called because the work is largely done at night.</def> <mark>[Cant, U.S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonshining</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"shin`ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Illicit distilling.</def> <mark>[Slang or Colloq., U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonshiny</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"shin`y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Moonlight.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I went to see them in a <qex>moonshiny</qex> night.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moon shot</ent><br/
<hw>Moon" shot`</hw> <pr>(m<oomac/n" sh<ocr/t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The action or event of sending a spacecraft to the moon; -- used of manned or unmanned missions.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moon-splashed</ent><br/
<hw>moon-splashed</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>splashed or covered patchily with moonlight; <as>as, the <ex>moon-splashed</ex> world</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> moon splashed.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonstone</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"stone`</hw> <pr>(m<oomac/n"st<omac/n`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A nearly pellucid variety of feldspar, showing pearly or opaline reflections from within.  It is used as a gem.  The best specimens come from Ceylon.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonstricken</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"strick`en</hw> <pr>(m<oomac/n"str<icr/k`'n)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>See <er>Moonstruck</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonstruck</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"struck`</hw> <pr>(m<oomac/n"str<ucr/k`)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Mentally affected or deranged by the supposed influence of the moon; lunatic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Produced by the supposed influence of the moon.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Moonstruck</xex> madness.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Made sick by the supposed influence of the moon, as a human being; made unsuitable for food, as fishes, by such supposed influence.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moonwalk</ent><br/
<hw>moonwalk</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>a kind of dance step in which the dancer seems to be sliding backward on the spot; <as>as, <person>Michael Jackson</person> perfected the <ex>moonwalk</ex> in the 1980s</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>an exploratory walk by an astronaut on the surface of Earth's moon.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moonwort</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"wort`</hw> <pr>(m<oomac/n"w<ucir/rt`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The herb lunary or honesty. See <er>Honesty</er>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Any fern of the genus <gen>Botrychium</gen>, esp. <spn>Botrychium Lunaria</spn>; -- so named from the crescent-shaped segments of its frond.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moony</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the moon.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Soft and pale as the <qex>moony</qex> beam.</q> <rj><qau>J. R. Drake.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Furnished with a moon; bearing a crescent.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But soon the miscreant <qex>moony</qex> host<br/
Before the victor cross shall fly.</q> <rj><qau>Fenton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Silly; weakly sentimental.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>  <rj><au>G. Eliot.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moony</ent><br/
<hw>Moon"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A follower of the <person>Rev. Sun Myun <etsep>Moon</etsep></person>; a member of the <membof>Unification Church</membof>; -- often considered disparaging.</def> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>Moonie</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moor</ent><br/
<hw>Moor</hw> <pr>(m<oomac/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>More</ets>, <ets>Maure</ets>, L. <ets>Maurus</ets> a Moor, a Mauritanian, an inhabitant of Mauritania, Gr. <grk>May^ros</grk>; cf. <grk>may^ros</grk> black, dark.  Cf. <er>Morris</er> a dance, <er>Morocco</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One of a mixed race inhabiting Morocco, Algeria, Tunis, and Tripoli, chiefly along the coast and in towns.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Hist.)</fld> <def>Any individual of the swarthy races of Africa or Asia which have adopted the Muslim religion.</def> <ldquo/In Spanish history the terms <xex>Moors</xex>, Saracens, and Arabs are synonymous.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Internat. Cyc.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moor</ent><br/
<hw>Moor</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mor</ets>, AS. <ets>m<omac/r</ets> moor, morass; akin to D. <ets>moer</ets> moor, G. <ets>moor</ets>, and prob. to Goth. <ets>marei</ets> sea, E. <ets>mere</ets>. See <er>Mere</er> a lake.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An extensive waste covered with patches of heath, and having a poor, light soil, but sometimes marshy, and abounding in peat; a heath.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In her girlish age she kept sheep on the <qex>moor</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Carew.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A game preserve consisting of moorland.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Moor buzzard</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the marsh harrier.</cd> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> -- <col><b>Moor coal</b></col> <fld>(Geol.)</fld>, <cd>a friable variety of lignite.</cd> -- <col><b>Moor cock</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the male of the <er>moor fowl</er> or red grouse of Europe.</cd> -- <col><b>Moor coot</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Gallinule</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Moor game</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>Same as <er>Moor fowl</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Moor grass</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a tufted perennial grass (<spn>Sesleria caerulea</spn>), found in mountain pastures of Europe.</cd> -- <col><b>Moor hawk</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the marsh harrier.</cd> -- <col><b>Moor hen</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The female of the <er>moor fowl</er>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A gallinule, esp. the European species. See <er>Gallinule</er>.</cd> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>An Australian rail (<spn>Tribonyx ventralis</spn>).</cd> -- <col><b>Moor monkey</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the black macaque of Borneo (<spn>Macacus maurus</spn>).</cd> -- <col><b>Moor titling</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the European stonechat (<spn>Pratinocola rubicola</spn>).</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 943 --></p>

<p><ent>Moor</ent><br/
<hw>Moor</hw> <pr>(m<oomac/r)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Moored</conjf> <pr>(m<oomac/rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mooring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Prob. fr. D. <ets>marren</ets> to tie, fasten, or moor a ship. See <er>Mar</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To fix or secure, as a vessel, in a particular place by casting anchor, or by fastening with cables or chains; <as>as, the vessel was <ex>moored</ex> in the stream; they <ex>moored</ex> the boat to the wharf.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: To secure, or fix firmly.</def>  <rj><au>Brougham.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moor</ent><br/
<hw>Moor</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To cast anchor; to become fast.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On oozy ground his galleys <qex>moor</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moorage</ent><br/
<hw>Moor"age</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A place for mooring.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moorball</ent><br/
<hw>Moor"ball`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A fresh-water alga (<spn>Cladophora Aegagropila</spn>) which forms a globular mass.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moorband</ent><br/
<hw>Moor"band`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Moorpan</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mooress</ent><br/
<hw>Moor"ess</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A female Moor; a Moorish woman.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moor fowl</ent><br/
<ent>moorfowl</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>moorfowl</hw>, <hw>moor fowl</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>  <sn>1.</sn>  <def>A reddish-brown grouse (<spn>Lagopus Scoticus</spn>) of upland moors of Great Britain; the European ptarmigan, or <altname>red grouse</altname>, also called the <altname>moorgame</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> red grouse, moorbird, moorgame, <spn>Lagopus scoticus</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The European heath grouse. See under <er>Heath</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moorgame</ent><br/
<hw>moorgame</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The <er>moorfowl</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> red grouse, , moorbird, <spn>Lagopus scoticus</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moorhen</ent><br/
<hw>moorhen</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A black gallinule (<spn>Gallinula chloropus</spn>) that inhabits ponds and lakes.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> <spn>Gallinula chloropus</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The female of the <er>moor fowl</er>; the <altname>moor hen</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mooring</ent><br/
<hw>Moor"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of confining a ship to a particular place, by means of anchors or fastenings.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which serves to confine a ship to a place, as anchors, cables, bridles, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>The place or condition of a ship thus confined.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And the tossed bark in <qex>moorings</qex> swings.</q> <rj><qau>Moore.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mooring block</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a heavy block of cast iron sometimes used as an anchor for mooring vessels.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moorish</ent><br/
<hw>Moor"ish</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From 2d <er>Moor</er>.]</ety> <def>Having the characteristics of a moor or heath.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Moorish</xex> fens.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Thomson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moorish</ent><br/
<hw>Moor"ish</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See 1st <er>Moor</er>, and cf. <er>Morris</er>, <er>Moresque</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to Morocco or the Moors; in the style of the Moors.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Moorish architecture</b></col>, <cd>the style developed by the Moors in the later Middle Ages, esp. in Spain, in which the arch had the form of a horseshoe, and the ornamentation admitted no representation of animal life.  It has many points of resemblance to the Arabian and Persian styles, but should be distinguished from them. See <xex>Illust.</xex> under <er>Moresque</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moorland</ent><br/
<hw>Moor"land</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<omac/rland</ets>.]</ety> <def>Land consisting of a moor or moors.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moorpan</ent><br/
<hw>Moor"pan`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <ets>Hard pan</ets>, under <er>Hard</er>.]</ety> <def>A clayey layer or pan underlying some moors, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moorstone</ent><br/
<hw>Moor"stone`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A species of English granite, used as a building stone.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mooruk</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Moo"ruk</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Native name.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A species of cassowary (<spn>Casuarius Bennetti</spn>) found in New Britain, and noted for its agility in running and leaping.  It is smaller and has stouter legs than the common cassowary.  Its crest is bilobed; the neck and breast are black; the back, rufous mixed with black; and the naked skin of the neck, blue.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moory</ent><br/
<hw>Moor"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to moors; marshy; fenny; boggy; moorish.</def>  <rj><au>Mortimer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As when thick mists arise from <qex>moory</qex> vales.</q> <rj><qau>Fairfax.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moory</ent><br/
<hw>Moor"y</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A kind of blue cloth made in India.</def>  <rj><au>Balfour (Cyc of India).</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moose</ent><br/
<hw>moose</hw> <pr>(m<oomac/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[A native name; Knisteneaux <ets>mouswah</ets>; Algonquin <ets>monse</ets>. <ets>Mackenzie</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A large cervine mammal (<spn>Alces alces</spn> syn. <spn>Alces machlis</spn>, syn <spn>Alces Americanus</spn>), native of the Northern United States and Canada. The adult male is about as large as a horse, and has very large, palmate antlers. It closely resembles the European elk, and by many Zoologists is considered the same species. See <er>Elk</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A member of the Progressive Party; a Bull Moose.</def> <mark>[Obsolescent. Cant, from the early 1900's.]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <mark>[capitalized]</mark> <def>A member of the fraternal organization named <membof>Loyal Order of Moose</membof>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Moose bird</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the Canada jayor whisky jack. See <er>Whisky jack</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Moose deer</b></col>. <cd>Same as <er>Moose</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Moose yard</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a locality where moose, in winter, herd together in a forest to feed and for mutual protection.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moosewood</ent><br/
<hw>Moose"wood`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The striped maple (<spn>Acer Pennsylvanicum</spn>).</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Leatherwood.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moot</ent><br/
<hw>moot</hw> <pr>(m<omac/t)</pr>, <pos>v.</pos> <def>See 1st <er>Mot</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moot</ent><br/
<hw>moot</hw> <pr>(m<oomac/t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Shipbuilding)</fld> <def>A ring for gauging wooden pins.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moot</ent><br/
<hw>Moot</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mooted</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mooting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>moten</ets>, <ets>motien</ets>, AS. <ets>m<omac/tan</ets> to meet or assemble for conversation, to discuss, dispute, fr. <ets>m<omac/t</ets>, <ets>gem<omac/t</ets>, a meeting, an assembly; akin to Icel. <ets>m<omac/t</ets>, MHG. <ets>muoz</ets>.  Cf. <er>Meet</er> to come together.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To argue for and against; to debate; to discuss; to propose for discussion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A problem which hardly has been mentioned, much less <qex>mooted</qex>, in this country.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Hamilton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Specifically: To discuss by way of exercise; to argue for practice; to propound and discuss in a mock court.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>First a case is appointed to be <qex>mooted</qex> by certain young men, containing some doubtful controversy.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. Elyot.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To render inconsequential, as having no effect on the practical outcome; to render academic; <as>as, the ruling that the law was invalid <ex>mooted</ex> the question of whether he actually violated it</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moot</ent><br/
<hw>Moot</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To argue or plead in a supposed case.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is a difference between <qex>mooting</qex> and pleading; between fencing and fighting.</q> <rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moot</ent><br/
<hw>Moot</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<omac/t</ets>, <ets>gem<omac/t</ets>, a meeting; -- usually in comp.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mote</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A meeting for discussion and deliberation; esp., a meeting of the people of a village or district, in Anglo-Saxon times, for the discussion and settlement of matters of common interest; -- usually in composition; <as>as, folk-<ex>moot</ex></as>.</def>  <rj><au>J. R. Green.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[From <er>Moot</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <def>A discussion or debate; especially, a discussion of fictitious causes by way of practice.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The pleading used in courts and chancery called <qex>moots</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. Elyot.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Moot case</b></col>, <cd>a case or question to be mooted; a disputable case; an unsettled question.</cd> <au>Dryden.</au> -- <col><b>Moot court</b></col>, <cd>a mock court, such as is held by students of law for practicing the conduct of law cases.</cd> -- <col><b>Moot point</b></col>, <cd>a point or question to be debated; a doubtful question.</cd> -- <col><b>to make moot</b></col> <pos>v. t.</pos> <cd>to render moot{2}; to moot{3}.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moot</ent><br/
<hw>Moot</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Subject, or open, to argument or discussion; undecided; debatable; mooted.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of purely theoretical or academic interest; having no practical consequence; <as>as, the team won in spite of the bad call, and whether the ruling was correct is a <ex>moot</ex> question</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mootable</ent><br/
<hw>Moot"a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Capable of being mooted.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mooter</ent><br/
<hw>Moot"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A disputer of a mooted case.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moot-house</ent><br/
<ent>Moot-hall</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Moot"-hall`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Moot"-house`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<omac/th<?/s</ets>.]</ety> <def>A hall for public meetings; a hall of judgment.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/The <xex>moot-hall</xex> of Herod.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Wyclif.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moot-hill</ent><br/
<hw>Moot"-hill`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(O. Eng. Law)</fld> <def>A hill of meeting or council; an elevated place in the open air where public assemblies or courts were held by the Saxons; -- called, in Scotland, <altname>mute-hill</altname>.</def>  <rj><au>J. R. Green.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mootman</ent><br/
<hw>Moot"man</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mootmen</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <fld>(O. Eng. Law)</fld> <def>One who argued moot cases in the inns of court.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mop</ent><br/
<hw>Mop</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mope</er>.]</ety> <def>A made-up face; a grimace.</def> <ldquo/What <xex>mops</xex> and mowes it makes!<rdquo/  <rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mop</ent><br/
<hw>Mop</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make a wry mouth.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mop</ent><br/
<hw>Mop</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[CF. W. <ets>mop</ets>, <ets>mopa</ets>, Ir. <ets>moipal</ets>, Gael. <ets>moibeal</ets>, <ets>moibean</ets>; or OF. <ets>mappe</ets> a napkin (see <er>Map</er>, <er>Napkin</er>).]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An implement for washing floors, or the like, made of a piece of cloth, or a collection of thrums, or coarse yarn, fastened to a handle.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A fair where servants are hired.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The young of any animal; also, a young girl; a moppet.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>  <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mop head</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The end of a mop, to which the thrums or rags are fastened</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A clamp for holding the thrums or rags of a mop.</cd> <mark>[U.S.]</mark></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mop</ent><br/
<hw>Mop</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mopped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mopping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To rub or wipe with a mop, or as with a mop; <as>as, to <ex>mop</ex> a floor; to <ex>mop</ex> one's face with a handkerchief.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mopboard</ent><br/
<hw>Mop"board`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Carp.)</fld> <def>A narrow board nailed against the wall of a room next to the floor; skirting board; baseboard. See <er>Baseboard</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mope</ent><br/
<hw>Mope</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Moped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Moping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. D. <ets>moppen</ets> to pout, Prov. G. <ets>muffen</ets> to sulk.]</ety> <def>To be dull and spiritless; to spend time doing little; <as>as, to <ex>mope</ex> around the house</as>.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Moping</xex> melancholy.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A sickly part of one true sense<br/
Could not so <qex>mope</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mope</ent><br/
<hw>Mope</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make spiritless and stupid.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mope</ent><br/
<hw>Mope</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A dull, spiritless person.</def>  <rj><au>Burton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mope-eyed</ent><br/
<hw>Mope"-eyed`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Shortsighted; purblind.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mopeful</ent><br/
<hw>Mope"ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Mopish.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mop-headed</ent><br/
<hw>mop-headed</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>having a bushy top without a leader; -- of trees; <as>as, <ex>mop-headed</ex> cabbage palms</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mopheaded.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mopish</ent><br/
<hw>Mop"ish</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Dull; spiritless; dejected.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mop"ish*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mop"ish*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moplah</ent><br/
<hw>Mop"lah</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Malayalam <ets>m<amac/pplia</ets>.]</ety> <def>One of a class of Muslims in Malabar.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moppet</ent><br/
<hw>Mop"pet</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From 3d <er>Mop</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A rag baby; a puppet made of cloth; hence, also, in fondness, a little girl, or a woman.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A long-haired pet dog.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mopsy</ent><br/
<ent>Mopsey</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mop"sey</hw>, <hw>Mop"sy</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A moppet.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A slatternly, untidy woman.</def>  <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mopsical</ent><br/
<hw>Mop"si*cal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Shortsighted; mope-eyed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mopstick</ent><br/
<hw>Mop"stick`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The long handle of a mop.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mopus</ent><br/
<hw>mo"pus</hw> <pr>(m<omac/"p<ucr/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mope; a drone.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moquette</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo*quette"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>A kind of carpet having a short velvety pile.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mora</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mor"a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It.]</ety> <def>A game of guessing the number of fingers extended in a quick movement of the hand, -- much played by Italians of the lower classes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mora</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ra</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A leguminous tree of Guiana and Trinidad (<spn>Dimorphandra excelsa</spn>); also, its timber, used in shipbuilding and making furniture.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mora</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo"ra</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.]</ety> <fld>(Rom. & Civil Law)</fld> <def>Delay; esp., culpable delay; postponement.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moraine</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*raine"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.  Cf. Prov. G. <ets>mur</ets> stones broken off, It. <ets>mora</ets> a heap of stones, hillock, G. <ets>m<uum/rbe</ets> soft, broken up, OHG. <ets>muruwi</ets>, AS. <ets>mearu</ets> tender, Gr. <?/ to cause to wither, Skr. <ets>ml<amac/</ets> to relax.]</ety> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>An accumulation of earth and stones carried forward and deposited by a glacier.</def>  <rj><au>Lyell.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ If the moraine is at the extremity of the glacier it is a <xex>terminal moraine</xex>; if at the side, a <xex>lateral moraine</xex>; if parallel to the side on the central portion of the glacier, a <xex>medial moraine</xex>.  See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Glacier</er>.  In the last case it is formed by the union of the lateral moraines of the branches of the glacier.  A <xex>ground moraine</xex> is one beneath the mass of ice.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morainic</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*rain"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to a moranie.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moral</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. It. <ets>moralis</ets>, fr. <ets>mos</ets>, <ets>moris</ets>, manner, custom, habit, way of life, conduct.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Relating to duty or obligation; pertaining to those intentions and actions of which right and wrong, virtue and vice, are predicated, or to the rules by which such intentions and actions ought to be directed; relating to the practice, manners, or conduct of men as social beings in relation to each other, as respects right and wrong, so far as they are properly subject to rules.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Keep at the least within the compass of <qex>moral</qex> actions, which have in them vice or virtue.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mankind is broken loose from <qex>moral</qex> bands.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She had wandered without rule or guidance in a <qex>moral</qex> wilderness.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Conformed to accepted rules of right; acting in conformity with such rules; virtuous; just; <as>as, a <ex>moral</ex> man</as>.  Used sometimes in distinction from <xex>religious</xex>; <as>as, a <ex>moral</ex> rather than a religious life</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wiser and more <qex>moral</qex> part of mankind.</q> <rj><qau>Sir M. Hale.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Capable of right and wrong action or of being governed by a sense of right; subject to the law of duty.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>moral</qex> agent is a being capable of those actions that have a <qex>moral</qex> quality, and which can properly be denominated good or evil in a <qex>moral</qex> sense.</q> <rj><qau>J. Edwards.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Acting upon or through one's moral nature or sense of right, or suited to act in such a manner; <as>as, a <ex>moral</ex> arguments; <ex>moral</ex> considerations</as>.  Sometimes opposed to <contr>material</contr> and <contr>physical</contr>; <as>as, <ex>moral</ex> pressure or support</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Supported by reason or probability; practically sufficient; -- opposed to <contr>legal</contr> or <contr>demonstrable</contr>; <as>as, a <ex>moral</ex> evidence; a <ex>moral</ex> certainty.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Serving to teach or convey a moral; <as>as, a <ex>moral</ex> lesson; <ex>moral</ex> tales.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Moral agent</b></col>, <cd>a being who is capable of acting with reference to right and wrong.</cd> -- <col><b>Moral certainty</b></col>, <cd>a very high degree or probability, although not demonstrable as a certainty; a probability of so high a degree that it can be confidently acted upon in the affairs of life; <as>as, there is a <ex>moral certainty</ex> of his guilt</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>Moral insanity</b></col>, <cd>insanity, so called, of the moral system; badness alleged to be irresponsible.</cd> -- <col><b>Moral philosophy</b></col>, <cd>the science of duty; the science which treats of the nature and condition of man as a moral being, of the duties which result from his moral relations, and the reasons on which they are founded.</cd> -- <col><b>Moral play</b></col>, <cd>an allegorical play; a morality.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> -- <col><b>Moral sense</b></col>, <cd>the power of moral judgment and feeling; the capacity to perceive what is right or wrong in moral conduct, and to approve or disapprove, independently of education or the knowledge of any positive rule or law.</cd> -- <col><b>Moral theology</b></col>, <cd>theology applied to morals; practical theology; casuistry.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moral</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The doctrine or practice of the duties of life; manner of living as regards right and wrong; conduct; behavior; -- usually in the plural.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Corrupt in their <qex>morals</qex> as vice could make them.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The inner meaning or significance of a fable, a narrative, an occurrence, an experience, etc.; the practical lesson which anything is designed or fitted to teach; the doctrine meant to be inculcated by a fiction; a maxim.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus may we gather honey from the weed,<br/
And make a <qex>moral</qex> of the devil himself.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To point a <qex>moral</qex>, or adorn a tale.</q> <rj><qau>Johnson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We protest against the principle that the world of pure comedy is one into which no <qex>moral</qex> enters.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A morality play. See <er>Morality</er>, 5.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moral</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"al</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To moralize.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morale</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo`rale"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. See <er>Moral</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>The moral condition, or the condition in other respects, so far as it is affected by, or dependent upon, moral considerations, such as zeal, spirit, hope, and confidence; mental state, as of a body of men, an army, and the like.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moraler</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"al*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A moralizer.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moralism</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"al*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A maxim or saying embodying a moral truth.</def>  <rj><au>Farrar.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moralise</ent><br/
<hw>moralise</hw> <pos>v.</pos> <def>moralize.</def> <mark>[Chiefly Brit.]</mark> <br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moralist</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"al*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>moraliste</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who moralizes; one who teaches or animadverts upon the duties of life; a writer of essays intended to correct vice and inculcate moral duties.</def>  <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who practices moral duties; a person who lives in conformity with moral rules; one of correct deportment and dealings with his fellow-creatures; -- sometimes used in contradistinction to one whose life is controlled by religious motives.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The love (in the <qex>moralist</qex> of virtue, but in the Christian) of God himself.</q> <rj><qau>Hammond.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moralistic</ent><br/
<hw>moralistic</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>narrowly and conventionally moral; -- of people.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>disposed to moralize{2}; -- of people.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> moralizing.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morality</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*ral"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Moralities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>moralitas</ets>: cf. F. <ets>moralit<eacute/</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The relation of conformity or nonconformity to the moral standard or rule; quality of an intention, a character, an action, a principle, or a sentiment, when tried by the standard of right.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>morality</qex> of an action is founded in the freedom of that principle, by virtue of which it is in the agent's power, having all things ready and requisite to the performance of an action, either to perform or not perform it.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The quality of an action which renders it good; the conformity of an act to the accepted standard of right.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of <qex>moralitee</qex> he was the flower.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am bold to think that <qex>morality</qex> is capable of demonstration.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The doctrines or rules of moral duties, or the duties of men in their social character; ethics.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The end of <qex>morality</qex> is to procure the affections to obey reason, and not to invade it.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The system of <qex>morality</qex> to be gathered out of . . . ancient sages falls very short of that delivered in the gospel.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The practice of the moral duties; rectitude of life; conformity to the standard of right; virtue; <as>as, we often admire the politeness of men whose <ex>morality</ex> we question</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A kind of allegorical play, so termed because it consisted of discourses in praise of morality between actors representing such characters as Charity, Faith, Death, Vice, etc. Such plays were occasionally exhibited as late as the reign of <person>Henry VIII.</person></def>  <rj><au>Strutt.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Intent; meaning; moral.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Taketh the <qex>morality</qex> thereof, good men.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moralization</ent><br/
<hw>Mor`al*i*za"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>moralisation</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of moralizing; moral reflections or discourse.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Explanation in a moral sense.</def>  <rj><au>T. Warton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 944 --></p>

<p><ent>Moralize</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"al*ize</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/r"<ait/l*<imac/z)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Moralized</conjf> <pr>(m<ocr/r"<ait/l*<imac/zd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Moralizing</conjf> <pr>(m<ocr/r"<ait/l*<imac/*z<icr/ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>moraliser</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To apply to a moral purpose; to explain in a moral sense; to draw a moral from.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This fable is <qex>moralized</qex> in a common proverb.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Did he not <qex>moralize</qex> this spectacle?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To furnish with moral lessons, teachings, or examples; to lend a moral to.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>While chastening thoughts of sweetest use, bestowed<br/
By Wisdom, <qex>moralize</qex> his pensive road.</q> <rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To render moral; to correct the morals of.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It had a large share in <qex>moralizing</qex> the poor white people of the country.</q> <rj><qau>D. Ramsay.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To give a moral quality to; to affect the moral quality of, either for better or worse.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Good and bad stars <qex>moralize</qex> not our actions.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. Browne.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moralize</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"al*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make moral reflections; to regard acts and events as involving a moral.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>to lecture to a person in a manner asserting moral principles.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> sermonize, preachify, moralise.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moralizer</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"al*i`zer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who moralizes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morally</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"al*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>In a moral or ethical sense; according to the rules of morality.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By good, good <qex>morally</qex> so called, <ldquo/bonum honestum<rdquo/ ought chiefly to be understood.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>According to moral rules; virtuously.</def> <ldquo/To live <xex>morally</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>In moral qualities; in disposition and character; <as>as, one who physically and <ex>morally</ex> endures hardships</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>In a manner calculated to serve as the basis of action; according to the usual course of things and human judgment; according to reason and probability.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is <qex>morally</qex> impossible for an hypocrite to keep himself long upon his guard.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>morals</ent><br/
<hw>morals</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>motivation based on ideas of right and wrong.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> ethical motive, ethics, morality.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morass</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*rass"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>marras</ets>, <ets>mareis</ets> (perh. through D. <ets>moeras</ets>), fr. F. <ets>marais</ets>, prob. from L. <ets>mare</ets> sea, in LL., any body of water; but perh. influenced by some German word. See <er>Mere</er> a lake, and cf. <er>Marsh</er>.]</ety> <def>A tract of soft, wet ground; a marsh; a fen.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Morass ore</b></col>. <fld>(Min.)</fld> <cd>See <cref>Bog ore</cref>, under <er>Bog</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>morassy</ent><br/
<hw>mo*rass"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Marshy; fenny.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Pennant.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morate</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"rate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of moric acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moration</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*ra"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>moratio</ets>.]</ety> <def>A delaying tarrying; delay.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moratorium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mor`a*to"ri*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Moratory</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A period during which an obligor has a legal right to delay meeting an obligation, esp. such a period granted, as to a bank, by a moratory law.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>a suspension of an activity.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>an officially authorized period of delay or waiting; <as>as, a <ex>moratorium</ex> on putting a law into effect</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moratory</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"a*to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>moratorius</ets> delaying, fr. <ets>morari</ets> to delay.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to delay; esp., designating a law passed, as in a time of financial panic, to postpone or delay for a period the time at which notes, bills of exchange, and other obligations, shall mature or become due.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moravian</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*ra"vi*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to Moravia, or to the United Brethren. See <er>Moravian</er>, <pos>n.</pos></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moravian</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*ra"vi*an</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>One of a religious sect called the <membof>United Brethren</membof> (an offshoot of the Hussites in Bohemia), which formed a separate church of Moravia, a northern district of Austria, about the middle of the 15th century.  After being nearly extirpated by persecution, the society, under the name of <membof>The Renewed Church of the United Brethren</membof>, was reestablished in 1722-35 on the estates of <person>Count Zinzendorf</person> in Saxony.  Called also <altname>Herrnhuter</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moravianism</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*ra"vi*an*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The religious system of the Moravians.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moray</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"ay</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A muraena.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morbid</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"bid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>morbidus</ets>, fr. <ets>morbus</ets> disease; prob. akin to <ets>mori</ets> to die: cf. F. <ets>morbide</ets>, It. <ets>morbido</ets>. See <er>Mortal</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Not sound and healthful; induced by a diseased or abnormal condition; diseased; sickly; <as>as, a <ex>morbid</ex> condition; a <ex>morbid</ex> constitution; a <ex>morbid</ex> state of the juices of a plant.</as></def> <ldquo/Her sick and <xex>morbid</xex> heart.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Hawthorne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to disease or diseased parts; <as>as, <ex>morbid</ex> anatomy</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Indicating an unhealthy mental attitude or disposition; especially, abnormally gloomy, to an extent not justified by the situation; preoccupied with death, disease, or fear of death; <as>as, a <ex>morbid</ex> interest in details of a disaster</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Gruesome; <as>as, a <ex>morbid</ex> topic</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Diseased; sickly; sick.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Morbid</er>, <er>Diseased</er>. <xex>Morbid</xex> is sometimes used interchangeably with <xex>diseased</xex>, but is commonly applied, in a somewhat technical sense, to cases of a prolonged nature; <as>as, a <ex>morbid</ex> condition of the nervous system</as>; a <xex>morbid</xex> sensibility, etc.</usage><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morbidezza</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mor`bi*dez"za</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It., softness, delicacy. See <er>Morbid</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Fine Arts)</fld> <def>Delicacy or softness in the representation of flesh.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A term used as a direction in execution, signifying, with extreme delicacy.</def>  <rj><au>Ludden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morbidity</ent><br/
<hw>Mor*bid"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality or state of being morbid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Morbid quality; disease; sickness.</def>  <rj><au>C. Kingsley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Amount of disease; rate of sickness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morbidly</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"bid*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a morbid manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morbidness</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"bid*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being morbid; morbidity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morbifical</ent><br/
<ent>Morbific</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mor*bif"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mor*bif"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>morbus</ets> disease + <ets>-ficare</ets> (in comp.) to make: cf. F. <ets>morbifique</ets>. See <er>-fy</er>.]</ety> <def>Causing disease; generating a sickly state; <as>as, a <ex>morbific</ex> matter</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morbillous</ent><br/
<hw>Mor*bil"lous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>morbilli</ets> measles, dim. of L. <ets>morbus</ets> disease: cf. F. <ets>morbilleux</ets>.]</ety> <def>Pertaining to the measles; partaking of the nature of measels, or resembling the eruptions of that disease; measly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morbose</ent><br/
<hw>Mor*bose"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>morbosus</ets>, fr. <ets>morbus</ets> disease.]</ety> <def>Proceeding from disease; morbid; unhealthy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Morbose</qex> tumors and excrescences of plants.</q> <rj><qau>Ray.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morbosity</ent><br/
<hw>Mor*bos"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>morbositas</ets>.]</ety> <def>A diseased state; unhealthiness.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morceau</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mor`ceau"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>A bit; a morsel.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mordacious</ent><br/
<hw>Mor*da"cious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mordax</ets>, <ets>-acis</ets>, fr. <ets>mordere</ets>, <ets>morsum</ets>, to bite. See <er>Morsel</er>.]</ety> <def>Biting; given to biting; hence, figuratively, sarcastic; severe; scathing.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mor*da"cious*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mordacity</ent><br/
<hw>Mor*dac"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mordacitas</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mordacit<eacute/</ets>. See <er>Mordacious</er>.]</ety> <def>The quality of being mordacious; biting severity, or sarcastic quality.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mordant</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"dant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F., p. pr. of <ets>mordere</ets> to bite; L. <ets>mordere</ets>. See <er>Morsel</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Biting; caustic; sarcastic; keen; severe.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Dyeing & Calico Printing)</fld> <def>Serving to fix colors.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mordant</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"dant</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., originally, biting.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Any corroding substance used in etching.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Dyeing & Calico Printing)</fld> <def>Any substance, as alum or copperas, which, having a twofold attraction for organic fibers and coloring matter, serves as a bond of union, and thus gives fixity to, or <xex>bites in</xex>, the dyes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Gilding)</fld> <def>Any sticky matter by which the gold leaf is made to adhere.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mordant</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"dant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mordanted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mordanting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To subject to the action of, or imbue with, a mordant; <as>as, to <ex>mordant</ex> goods for dyeing</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mordantly</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"dant*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In the manner of a mordant.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mordente</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mor*den"te</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>An embellishment resembling a trill.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mordicancy</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"di*can*cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A biting quality; corrosiveness.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Evelyn.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mordicant</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"di*cant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mordicans</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>mordicare</ets> to bite, fr. <ets>mordere</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mordicant</ets>.]</ety> <def>Biting; acrid; <as>as, the <ex>mordicant</ex> quality of a body</as>.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Boyle.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mordication</ent><br/
<hw>Mor`di*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mordicatio</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act of biting or corroding; corrosion.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mordicative</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"di*ca*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mordicativus</ets>.]</ety> <def>Biting; corrosive.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Holland.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>More</ent><br/
<hw>More</hw> <pr>(m<omac/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<omac/r</ets>. See <er>Moor</er> a waste.]</ety> <def>A hill.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>  <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>More</ent><br/
<hw>More</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>more</ets>, <ets>moru</ets>; akin to G. <ets>m<oum/hre</ets> carrot, OHG. <ets>moraha</ets>, <ets>morha</ets>.]</ety> <def>A root.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>More</ent><br/
<hw>More</hw>, <pos>a., compar.</pos> <amorph>[<it>Positive wanting</it>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Most</adjf> <pr>(m<omac/st)</pr>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>more</ets>, <ets>mare</ets>, and (orig. neut. and adv.) <ets>mo</ets>, <ets>ma</ets>, AS. <ets>m<amac/ra</ets>, and (as neut. and adv.) <ets>m<amac/</ets>; akin to D. <ets>meer</ets>, OS. <ets>m<emac/r</ets>, G. <ets>mehr</ets>, OHG. <ets>m<emac/ro</ets>, <ets>m<emac/r</ets>, Icel. <ets>meiri</ets>, <ets>meirr</ets>, Dan. <ets>meere</ets>, <ets>meer</ets>, Sw. <ets>mera</ets>, <ets>mer</ets>, Goth. <ets>maiza</ets>, a., <ets>mais</ets>, adv., and perh. to L. <ets>major</ets> greater, compar. of <ets>magnus</ets> great, and <ets>magis</ets>, adv., more. <root/103.  Cf. <er>Most</er>, <er>uch</er>, <er>Major</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Greater; superior; increased;</def> <specif>as:</specif> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Greater in quality, amount, degree, quality, and the like; with the singular.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He gat <qex>more</qex> money.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If we procure not to ourselves <qex>more</qex> woe.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>More</xex>, in this sense, was formerly used in connection with some other qualifying word, -- <xex>a</xex>, <xex>the</xex>, <xex>this</xex>, <xex>their</xex>, etc., -- which now requires the substitution of <xex>greater</xex>, <xex>further</xex>, or the like, for <xex>more</xex>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whilst sisters nine, which dwell on Parnasse height,<br/
Do make them music for their <qex>more</qex> delight.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>more</qex> part knew not wherefore they were come together.</q> <rj><qau>Acts xix. 32.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wrong not that wrong with a <qex>more</qex> contempt.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>Greater in number; exceeding in numbers; -- with the plural.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The people of the children of Israel are <qex>more</qex> and mightier than we.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. i. 9.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Additional; other; <as>as, he wept because there were no <ex>more</ex> worlds to conquer</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With open arms received one poet <qex>more</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>More</ent><br/
<hw>More</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A greater quantity, amount, or number; that which exceeds or surpasses in any way what it is compared with.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And the children of Israel did so, and gathered, some <qex>more</qex>, some less.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xvi. 17.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is in addition; something other and further; an additional or greater amount.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They that would have <qex>more</qex> and <qex>more</qex> can never have enough.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O! That pang where <qex>more</qex> than madness lies.</q> <rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Any more</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>Anything or something additional or further; <as>as, I do not need <ex>any more</ex></as>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <mark>Adverbially:</mark> <cd>Further; beyond a certain time; <as>as, do not think <ex>any more</ex> about it</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>No more</b></col>, <cd>not anything more; nothing in addition.</cd> -- <col><b>The more and less</b></col>, <cd>the high and low.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Shak.</au> <ldquo/All cried, both <xex>less and more</xex>.<rdquo/ <au>Chaucer.</au></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>More</ent><br/
<hw>More</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>In a greater quantity; in or to a greater extent or degree.</def> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>With a verb or participle.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Admiring <qex>more</qex><br/
The riches of Heaven's pavement.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>With an adjective or adverb (instead of the suffix <xex>-er</xex>) to form the comparative degree; <as>as, <ex>more</ex> durable; <ex>more</ex> active; <ex>more</ex> sweetly</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Happy here, and <qex>more</qex> happy hereafter.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Double comparatives were common among writers of the Elizabeth period, and for some time later; as, <xex>more</xex> brighter; <xex>more</xex> dearer.<br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The duke of Milan<br/
And his <qex>more</qex> braver daughter.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>
</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In addition; further; besides; again.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yet once <qex>more</qex>, O ye laurels, and once <qex>more</qex>,<br/
Ye myrtles brown, with ivy never sere,<br/
I come to pluck your berries harsh and crude.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>More and more</b></col>, <cd>with continual increase.</cd> <ldquo/Amon trespassed <xex>more and more</xex>.<rdquo/ <au>2 Chron. xxxiii. 23.</au> -- <col><b>The more</b></col>, <cd>to a greater degree; by an added quantity; for a reason already specified.</cd> -- <col><b>The more -- the more</b></col>, <cd>by how much more -- by so much more.</cd> <ldquo/<xex>The more</xex> he praised it in himself, <xex>the more</xex> he seems to suspect that in very deed it was not in him.<rdquo/ <au>Milton.</au> -- <col><b>To be no more</b></col>, <cd>to have ceased to be; <as>as, Cassius <ex>is no more</ex>; Troy <ex>is no more</ex></as>.</cd><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those oracles which set the world in flames,<br/
Nor ceased to burn till kingdoms were <qex>no more</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>
</cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>More</ent><br/
<hw>More</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make more; to increase.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Gower.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moreen</ent><br/
<hw>mo*reen"</hw> <pr>(m<osl/*r<emac/n")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Mohair</er>.]</ety> <def>A thick woolen fabric, watered or with embossed figures; -- used in upholstery, for curtains, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>morel</ent><br/
<hw>mor"el</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/r"<ecr/l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>moril</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>An edible fungus (<spn>Morchella esculenta</spn>), the upper part of which is covered with a reticulated and pitted hymenium.  It is used as food, and for flavoring sauces.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>moril</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>morel</ent><br/
<hw>mor"el</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>morelle</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Nightshade; -- so called from its blackish purple berries.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>morelle</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A kind of cherry. See <er>Morello</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Great morel</b></col>, <cd>the deadly nightshade.</cd> -- <col><b>Petty morel</b></col>, <cd>the black nightshade. See <er>Nightshade</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moreland</ent><br/
<hw>more"land</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/r"l<acr/nd)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Moorland.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morelle</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*relle"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., orig. fem. of <ets>moreau</ets> black, OF. <ets>morel</ets>, fr. LL. <ets>morellus</ets>.  Cf. <er>Morello</er>, <er>Murrey</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Nightshade. See 2d <er>Morel</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morello</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*rel"lo</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. It. <ets>morello</ets> blackish, OF. <ets>morel</ets>.  Cf. <er>Morelle</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A kind of nearly black cherry with dark red flesh and juice, -- used chiefly for preserving.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morendo</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo*ren"do</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a. & n.</pos> <ety>[It.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Dying; a gradual decrescendo at the end of a strain or cadence.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moreness</ent><br/
<hw>More"ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Greatness.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Wyclif.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moreover</ent><br/
<hw>More*o"ver</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[<ets>More</ets> + <ets>over</ets>.]</ety> <def>Beyond what has been said; further; besides; in addition; furthermore; also; likewise.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Moreover</qex>, he hath left you all his walks.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Besides</er>, <er>Moreover</er>.</syn> <usage> Of the two words, <xex>moreover</xex> is the stronger and is properly used in solemn discourse, or when what is added is important to be considered. See <er>Besides</er>.</usage><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morepork</ent><br/
<hw>More"pork`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[So named from its cry.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The Australian crested goatsucker (<spn>Aegotheles Novae-Hollandiae</spn>).  Also applied to other allied birds, as <spn>Podargus Cuveiri</spn>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mores</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo"res</hw> <pr>(m<omac/"r<emac/z)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos>; <sing><it>sing.</it> <singw>Mos</singw> <pr>(m<omac/s)</pr></sing>. <ety>[L.]</ety> <def>Customs; habits; esp., moral customs conformity to which is more or less obligatory; customary law.</def> <mark>[singular is rarely used]</mark> <br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moresk</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*resk"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a. & n.</pos> <def>Moresque.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moresque</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*resque"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. It. <ets>moresco</ets>, or Sp. <ets>morisco</ets>. See <er>Morris</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to, or in the manner or style of, the Moors; Moorish.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>The Moresque style of architecture or decoration. See <cref>Moorish architecture</cref>, under <er>Moorish</er>.</def></def2> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mauresque</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morgan</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"gan</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of a celebrated breed of small compact American saddle and trotting horses; -- so called from the name of the stud (Justin Morgan) from which the breed originated in Vermont.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morgan</ent><br/
<hw>Morgan</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def><person>John Pierpont Morgan</person>, a noted American financier and philanthropist; 1837-1913.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> <person>J. P. Morgan</person>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morganatic</ent><br/
<hw>Mor`ga*nat"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>matrimonium ad morganaticam</ets>, fr. <ets>morganatica</ets> a morning gift, a kind of dowry paid on the morning before or after the marriage, fr. OHG. <ets>morgan</ets> morning, in <ets>morgangeba</ets> morning gift, G. <ets>morgengabe</ets>. See <er>Morn</er>.]</ety> <def>Pertaining to, in the manner of, or designating, a kind of marriage, called also <altname>left-handed marriage</altname>, between a man of superior rank and a woman of inferior, in which it is stipulated that neither the latter nor her children shall enjoy the rank or inherit the possessions of her husband.</def> <au>Brande & C.</au> -- <wordforms><wf>Mor`ga*nat"ic*al*ly</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morgay</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"gay</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[W. <ets>morgi</ets> dogfish, shark; <ets>mor</ets> sea + <ets>ci</ets> dog.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The European small-spotted dogfish, or houndfish. See the Note under <er>Houndfish</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morglay</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"glay</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Claymore</er>.]</ety> <def>A sword.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morgue</ent><br/
<hw>Morgue</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A place where the bodies of dead persons are kept, until they are identified, or claimed by their friends; a deadhouse.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Newspapers)</fld> <def>A room containing reference files of older material in a newspaper office; also, the material contained in such a room.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moria</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo"ri*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ folly.]</ety> <def>Idiocy; imbecility; fatuity; foolishness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morian</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ri*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>A Moor.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In vain the Turks and <qex>Morians</qex> armed be.</q> <rj><qau>Fairfax.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moribund</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"i*bund</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>moribundus</ets>, from <ets>moriri</ets> to die. See <er>Mortal</er>.]</ety> <def>In a dying state; dying; at the point of death.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The patient was comatose and <qex>moribund</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Copland.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moribund</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"i*bund</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A dying person.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moric</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ric</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to, or derived from, fustic (see <er>Morin</er>); <as>as, <ex>moric</ex> acid</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morice</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"ice</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Morisco</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morigerate</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*rig"er*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>morigeratus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>morigerari</ets> to comply with. See <er>Morigerous</er>.]</ety> <def>Obedient.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morigeration</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*rig`er*a"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>morigeratio</ets>.]</ety> <def>Obsequiousness; obedience.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Evelyn.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morigerous</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*rig"er*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>morigerus</ets>; <ets>mos</ets>, <ets>moris</ets>, custom, manner + <ets>gerere</ets> to bear, conduct.]</ety> <def>Obedient; obsequious.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Brathwait.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moril</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"il</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>morille</ets>; cf. OHG. <ets>morhila</ets>, G. <ets>morchel</ets>, OHG. <ets>morha</ets> carrot. See <er>More</er> a root.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>An edible fungus. Same as 1st <er>Morel</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morin</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"rin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A yellow crystalline substance (<chform>C15H10O7</chform>) of acid properties extracted from <prodby>fustic</prodby> (<spn>Chlorophora tinctoria</spn> syn. <spn>Maclura tinctoria</spn>, formerly called <altname>Morus tinctoria</altname>); -- called also <altname>moric acid</altname> and <altname>natural yellow 8</altname>.  It is used as a dye for wool, giving a color from lemon yellow through olive to olive brown, depending on the metal with which it is mordanted.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morinda</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*rin"da</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of rubiaceous trees and shrubs, mostly East Indian, many species of which yield valuable red and yellow dyes. The wood is hard and beautiful, and used for gunstocks.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>morindin</ent><br/
<hw>mo*rin"din</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A yellow dyestuff (<chform>C27H30O14</chform>) extracted from the root bark of an East Indian plant (<spn>Morinda citrifolia</spn>) or from the bark of <spn>Coprosma australis</spn>.  The substance is also found in the fruit of the <spn>Morinda citrifolia</spn>, called <prodby>noni</prodby>, which is touted by some merchants to have a stimulatory effect on the immune system.  It is a disaccharide derivative of anthracenedione.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morinel</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"i*nel`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>morinelle</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The dotterel.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moringa</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*rin"ga</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[Malayam <ets>murunggi</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of trees of Southern India and Northern Africa.  One species (<spn>Moringa pterygosperma</spn>) is the horse-radish tree, and its seeds, as well as those of <spn>Moringa aptera</spn>, are known in commerce as <prod>ben</prod> or <prod>ben nuts</prod>, and yield the oil called <prod>oil of ben</prod>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moringic</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*rin"gic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Designating an organic acid obtained from oil of ben. See <er>Moringa</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morintannic</ent><br/
<hw>Mo`rin*tan"nic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[NL. <ets>Morus</ets> fustic + E. <ets>tannic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or designating, a variety of tannic acid extracted from fustic (<spn>Chlorophora tinctoria</spn>,  formerly <spn>Maclura tinctoria</spn> and <spn>Morus tinctoria</spn>) as a yellow crystalline substance; -- called also <altname>maclurin</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morion</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ri*on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>morion</ets>, Sp. <ets>morrion</ets>; cf. Sp. <ets>morra</ets> the upper part of the head, <ets>morro</ets> anything that is round.]</ety> <def>A kind of open helmet, without visor or beaver, and somewhat resembling a hat.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A battered <qex>morion</qex> on his brow.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morion</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ri*on</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A dark variety of smoky quartz.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morioplasty</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ri*o*plas`ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ piece (dim. of <?/ a part + <ets>-plasty</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Surg.)</fld> <def>The restoration of lost parts of the body.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 945 --></p>

<p><ent>Morisco</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*ris"co</hw> <pr>(m<osl/*r<icr/s"k<osl/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Sp. See <er>Morris</er> the dance.]</ety> <def>Moresque.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morisco</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*ris"co</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>morisco</ets> Moorish.]</ety> <def>A thing of Moorish origin;</def> as: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The Moorish language.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A Moorish dance, now called <altname>morris dance</altname>.</def> <au>Marston</au>. <sd>(c)</sd> <def>One who dances the Moorish dance.</def> <au>Shak</au>. <sd>(d)</sd> <def>Moresque decoration or architecture.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morisk</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"risk</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Morisco</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morkin</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"kin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Akin to Sw. <ets>murken</ets> putrefied, Icel. <ets>morkinn</ets> putrid.]</ety> <def>A beast that has died of disease or by mischance.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morland</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"land</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Moorland.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morling</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"ling</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mort</ets> dead, L. <ets>mortuus</ets>, fr. <ets>moriri</ets> to die.]</ety> <def>Mortling.</def> <mark>[Eng.]</mark>  <rj><au>Ainsworth.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mormal</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"mal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mort-mai</ets> a deadly evil. <ets>Nares</ets>.]</ety> <def>A bad sore; a gangrene; a cancer.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <altsp>[Written also <asp>morrimal</asp> and <asp>mortmal</asp>.]</altsp>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mormo</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"mo</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mormw`</grk> a hideous she-monster, a bugbear.]</ety> <def>A bugbear; false terror.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Jonhson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mormon</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mor"mon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mormw`n</grk> monster, bugbear.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A genus of sea birds, having a large, thick bill; the puffin.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The mandrill.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mormon</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"mon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>One of a Christian denomination (<membof>The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints</membof>) in the United States, followers of <person>Joseph Smith</person>, who professed to have found an addition to the Bible, engraved on golden plates, called the <col><it>Book of Mormon</it></col>, first published in 1830.  The Mormons believe in polygamy, and their hierarchy of apostles, etc., has control of civil and religious matters.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The Mormons call their religious organization <membof>The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints</membof>. Its head claims to receive revelations of God's will, and to have certain supernatural powers.  The church headquarters are in <city>Salt Lake City</city>, Utah.  They form a substantial fraction of the population of Utah, and at the end of the 20th centrury their numbers were increasing due to active proselytization.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mormon</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"mon</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>A member of a sect, called the <membof>Reorganized Church of Jesus of Latterday Saints</membof>, which has always rejected polygamy.  It was organized in 1852, and is represented in about forty States and Territories of the United States.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mormon</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"mon</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the Mormons; <as>as, the <ex>Mormon</ex> religion; <ex>Mormon</ex> practices.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mormondom</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"mon*dom</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The country inhabited by the Mormons; the Mormon people.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mormonism</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"mon*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The doctrine, system, and practices of the Mormons.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mormonite</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"mon*ite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A Mormon.</def> -- <def2><pos>a.</pos> <def>Mormon.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Mormonite</xex> religion.<rdquo/</def2>  <rj><au>F. W. Newman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morn</ent><br/
<hw>Morn</hw> <pr>(m<ocir/rn)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>morwen</ets>, <ets>morgen</ets>, AS. <ets>morgen</ets>; akin to D. <ets>morgen</ets>, OS. <ets>morgan</ets>, G. <ets>morgen</ets>, Icel. <ets>morginn</ets>, <ets>morgunn</ets>, Sw. <ets>morgon</ets>, Dan. <ets>morgen</ets>, Goth. <ets>ma<uacute/rgins</ets>.  Cf. <er>Morrow</er>, <er>Morning</er>.]</ety> <def>The first part of the day; the morning; -- used chiefly in poetry.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From <qex>morn</qex><br/
To noon he fell, from noon to dewy eve.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morne</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"ne</hw> <pr>(m<ocir/r"n<eit/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the morn; morning.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/White as <xex>morne</xex> milk.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morne</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Morne</hw> <pr>(m<ocir/rn)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>morne</ets> sad, sorrowful. See <er>Mourn</er>.]</ety> <def>A ring fitted upon the head of a lance to prevent wounding an adversary in tilting.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morne</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mor`n<eacute/"</hw> <pr>(m<ocir/r`n<asl/")</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>morne</ets> a morne.]</ety> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>Without teeth, tongue, or claws; -- said of a lion represented heraldically.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morning</ent><br/
<hw>Morn"ing</hw> <pr>(m<ocir/rn"<icr/ng)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>morning</ets>, <ets>morwening</ets>. See <er>Morn</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The first or early part of the day, variously understood as the earliest hours of light, the time near sunrise; the time from midnight to noon, from rising to noon, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The first or early part; <as>as, the <ex>morning</ex> of life</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The goddess Aurora.</def> <mark>[Poetic]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morning</ent><br/
<hw>Morn"ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to the first part or early part of the day; being in the early part of the day; <as>as, <ex>morning</ex> dew; <ex>morning</ex> light; <ex>morning</ex> service.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She looks as clear<br/
As <qex>morning</qex> roses newly washed with dew.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Morning gown</b></col>, <cd>a gown worn in the morning before one is dressed for the day.</cd> -- <col><b>Morning gun</b></col>, <cd>a gun fired at the first stroke of reveille at military posts.</cd> -- <col><b>Morning sickness</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>nausea and vomiting, usually occurring in the morning; -- a common sign of pregnancy.</cd> -- <col><b>Morning star</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>Any one of the planets (Venus, Jupiter, Mars, or Saturn) when it precedes the sun in rising, esp. Venus.  Cf. <cref>Evening star</cref>, <er>Evening</er>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Satan. See <er>Lucifer</er>.</cd><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Since he miscalled the <qex>morning star</qex>,<br/
Nor man nor fiend hath fallen so far.</q> <rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <cd>A weapon consisting of a heavy ball set with spikes, either attached to a staff or suspended from one by a chain.</cd> -- <col><b>Morning watch</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>the watch between four <sc>a. m.</sc> and eight <sc>a. m.</sc>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morning-glory</ent><br/
<ent>Morning glory</ent><br/
<hw>Morn"ing-glo`ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A climbing plant (<spn>Ipomoea purpurea</spn>) having handsome, funnel-shaped flowers, usually red, pink, purple, white, or variegated, sometimes pale blue. See <er>Dextrorsal</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morningtide</ent><br/
<hw>Morn"ing*tide`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Morning time.</def> <mark>[Poetic]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mornward</ent><br/
<hw>Morn"ward</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Towards the morn.</def> <mark>[Poetic]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>mornward</qex> now the starry hands move on.</q> <rj><qau>Lowell.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moro</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ro</hw> <pr>(m<omac/"r<osl/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. It. <ets>mora</ets> mulberry, L. <ets>morum</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A small abscess or tumor having a resemblance to a mulberry.</def>  <rj><au>Dunglison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moro</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ro</hw> <pr>(m<omac/"r<osl/)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Moros</plw> <pr>(m<omac/"r<osl/s)</pr></plu>. <ety>[Sp., moor.  See <er>moor</er>, <pos>n.</pos> and <er>Moros</er>.]</ety>  <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>A member of any of the <er>Moros</er>, a group one of various tribes of the southern Phillippine Islands, mostly Malays adhering to Islam.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Linguistics)</fld> <def>Any of the languages of the Moro people, of the Austronesian language family.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moroccan</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*roc"can</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to Morocco, or its inhabitants.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morocco</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*roc"co</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Named from <ets>Morocco</ets>, the country.  Cf. <er>Morris</er> the dance.]</ety> <def>A fine kind of leather, prepared commonly from goatskin (though an inferior kind is made of sheepskin), and tanned with sumac and dyed of various colors; -- said to have been first made by the Moors.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morology</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*rol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mwrologi`a</grk> foolish talk, <grk>mw^ros</grk> foolish + <grk>lo`gos</grk> discourse.]</ety> <def>Foolish talk; nonsense; folly.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moron</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ron</hw> <pr>(m<omac/"r<ocr/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mw^ros</grk> foolish, stupid.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Pedagogy)</fld> <def>A mentally retarded person whose intellectual development proceeds normally up to about the eighth year of age and is then arrested so that there is little or no further development; an adult having the mental development of an 8-to-12-year old.  A <ex>moron</ex> is considered capable of doing routine work under supervision.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, a very stupid person.</def> <mark>[informal, derogatory]</mark> <br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>mo*ron"ic</wf> <pos>adj.</pos> -- <wf>mo*ron"ic*al*ly</wf> <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>mo"ron*ism</wf> <pos>n.</pos> -- <wf>mo*ron"i*ty</wf> <pos>n.</pos></wordforms></p>

<p><ent>Moron</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*ron"</hw> <pr>(m<osl/*r<omac/n")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>Sp. pl.</it> <plw>Morones</plw> <pr>(#)</pr></plu>. <ety>[Sp.]</ety> <def>An inferior olive size having a woody pulp and a large clingstone pit, growing in the mountainous and high-valley districts around the city of <etsep>Moron</etsep>, in Spain.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morone</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*rone"</hw> <pr>(m<osl/*r<omac/n")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Maroon; the color of an unripe black mulberry.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moronic</ent><br/
<hw>moronic</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>having a mental age of between eight and twelve years; also used as a derogatory term.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moros</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ros</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos>; <sing><it>sing.</it> <singw>Moro</singw> <pr>(<?/)</pr></sing>. <ety>[Sp., pl. of <ets>Moro</ets> Moor.]</ety> <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>The Muslim tribes of the southern Philippine Islands, said to have formerly migrated from Borneo.  Some of them are warlike and addicted to piracy.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morosaurus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo`ro*sau"rus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., from Gr. <grk>mw^ros</grk> stupid + <grk>sau^ros</grk> lizard.]</ety> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>An extinct genus of large herbivorous dinosaurs, found in Jurassic strata in America.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morose</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*rose"</hw> <pr>(m<osl/*r<omac/s")</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>morosus</ets>, prop., excessively addicted to any particular way or habit, fr. <ets>mos</ets>, <ets>moris</ets>, manner, habit, way of life: cf. F. <ets>morose</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of a sour temper; sullen and austere; ill-humored; severe.</def> <ldquo/A <xex>morose</xex> and affected taciturnity.<rdquo/  <rj><au>I. Watts.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Lascivious; brooding over evil thoughts.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Sullen; gruff; severe; austere; gloomy; crabbed; crusty; churlish; surly; ill-humored.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morosely</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*rose"ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Sourly; with sullen austerity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moroseness</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*rose"ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Sourness of temper; sulenness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Learn good humor, never to oppose without just reason; abate some degrees of pride and <qex>moroseness</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>I. Watts.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Moroseness</xex> is not precisely <xex>peevishness</xex> or <xex>fretfulness</xex>, though often accompanied with it. It denotes more of silence and severity, or ill-humor, than the irritability or irritation which characterizes <xex>peevishness</xex>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morosis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo*ro"sis</hw> <pr>(m<osl/*r<omac/"s<icr/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mw`rwsis</grk>, fr. <grk>mw^ros</grk> silly, foolish.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Idiocy; fatuity; stupidity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morosity</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*ros"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>morositas</ets>: cf. F. <ets>morosit<eacute/</ets>.]</ety> <def>Moroseness.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Jer. Taylor.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morosoph</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ro*soph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>mwro`s</grk> foolish + <grk>sofo`s</grk> wise.  See also <er>sophomore</er>.]</ety> <def>A philosophical or learned fool.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morosous</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*ro"sous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Morose.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sheldon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moroxite</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*rox"ite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Gr. <?/, <?/, a sort of pipe clay.]</ety> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A variety of apatite of a greenish blue color.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moroxylate</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*rox"y*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A morate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moroxylic</ent><br/
<hw>Mor`ox*yl"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>morus</ets> a mulberry tree + Gr. <?/ wood.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or derived from, the mulberry; moric.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morphean</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"phe*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or relating to <persfn>Morpheus</persfn>, to dreams, or to sleep.</def>  <rj><au>Keats.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>morph</ent><br/
<hw>morph</hw> <pr>(m<ocir/rf)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Linguistics)</fld> <def>A sequence of phonemes, often a word fragment, which constitutes the minimum unit of meaning or syntax within a given word.  A morph may be one of several variants of a morpheme, depending for its individal form on the context in which it occurs.  Thus the <ex>morphs</ex> <examp>-s</examp> and <examp>-es</examp> are variants of the morpheme by which the plural form of an English noun is expressed.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>morph</ent><br/
<hw>morph</hw> <pr>(m<ocir/rf)</pr>, <pos>v. i. & t.</pos> <def>To transform smoothly in imperceptible steps from one image to another, on a computer screen.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>morpheme</ent><br/
<hw>mor"pheme</hw> <pr>(m<ocir/r"f<emac/m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Linguistics)</fld> <def>The smallest unit of meaning of a language, which cannot be divided into smaller parts carrying meaning; it is usually smaller than a single wordform, such as the <examp>-ed</examp> morpheme of verbs in the past tense or the <examp>-s</examp> morpheme of nouns in the plural form.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>morphemic</ent><br/
<hw>mor*phem"ic</hw> <pr>(m<ocir/r*f<emac/m"<icr/k)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Linguistics)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to a morpheme.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>mor*phem"ic*al*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms></p>

<p><ent>morphemics</ent><br/
<hw>mor*phem"ics</hw> <pr>(m<ocir/r*f<emac/m"<icr/ks)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Linguistics)</fld> <def>The study of the types and functions of morphemes; morphology{4}.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morpheus</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"pheus</hw> <pr>(m<ocir/r"f<umac/s <it>or</it> m<ocir/r"f<esl/*<ucr/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <grk>Morfey`s</grk> prop., the fashioner or molder, because of the shapes he calls up before the sleeper, fr. <grk>morfh`</grk> form, shape.]</ety> <fld>(Class. Myth.)</fld> <def>The god of dreams.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morphew</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"phew</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>morphe<eacute/</ets>, LL. <ets>morphea</ets>; cf. It. <ets>morfea</ets>.]</ety> <def>A scurfy eruption.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Drayton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morphew</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"phew</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cover with a morphew.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morphia</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"phi*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Morphine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morphine</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"phine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From Morpheus: cf. F. <ets>morphine</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A bitter white crystalline alkaloid found in opium, possessing strong narcotic properties, and much used as an anodyne; -- called also <altname>morphia</altname>, and <altname>morphina</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>morphing</ent><br/
<hw>morph"ing</hw> <pr>(m<ocir/rf"<icr/ng)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Computers)</fld> <def>The smooth transformation of one shape or image into another, displayed on the computer screen as a series of images that appear to be continuous, as if in a movie.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>morphinism</ent><br/
<hw>mor"phin*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A morbid condition produced by the excessive or prolonged use of morphine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>morpho</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>mor"pho</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/, an epithet of Venus.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of numerous species of large, handsome, tropical American butterflies, of the genus <gen>Morpho</gen>. They are noted for the very brilliant metallic luster and bright colors (often blue) of the upper surface of the wings.  The lower surface is usually brown or gray, with eyelike spots.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>morphogenesis</ent><br/
<hw>mor`pho*gen"e*sis</hw> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The development of the tissues and organs of an organism; the formation of structural features of an organism.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>morphogenetic</ent><br/
<hw>mor`pho*ge*net"ic</hw> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to morphogenesis; concerned with the process of development of the normal features of an organism.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morphogeny</ent><br/
<hw>Mor*phog"e*ny</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>form</ets> + root of <grk>gi`gnesqai</grk> to be born.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>History of the evolution of forms; that part of ontogeny that deals with the germ history of forms; -- distinguished from <contr>physiogeny</contr>.</def>  <rj><au>Haeckel.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morphological</ent><br/
<ent>Morphologic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mor`pho*log"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mor`pho*log"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>morphologique</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or according to, the principles of morphology.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mor`pho*log"ic*al*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morphologist</ent><br/
<hw>Mor*phol"o*gist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>One who is versed in the science of morphology.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morphology</ent><br/
<hw>Mor*phol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>morfh`</grk> form + <ets>-logy</ets>: cf. F. <ets>morphologie</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>That branch of biology which deals with the structure of animals and plants, treating of the forms of organs and describing their varieties, homologies, and metamorphoses. See <er>Tectology</er>, and <er>Promorphology</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The form and structure of an organism.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Linguistics)</fld> <def>The branch of linguistics which studies the patterns by which words are formed from other words, including inflection, compounding, and derivation.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <def>The study of the patterns of inflection of words or word classes in any given language; the study of the patterns in which morphemes combine to form words, and the rules for combination; morphemics; <as>as, the <ex>morphology</ex> of Spanish verbs</as>; also, the inflection patterns themselves.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morphon</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"phon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/, p. pr. of <?/ to form.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>A morphological individual, characterized by definiteness of form, in distinction from <contr>bion</contr>, a physiological individual. See <er>Tectology</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Haeckel.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Of morphons there are six orders or categories: 1. <stype>Plastids</stype> or elementary organisms. 2. <stype>Organs</stype>, homoplastic or heteroplastic. 3. <stype>Antimeres</stype> (opposite or symmetrical or homotypic parts). 4. <stype>Metameres</stype> (successive or homodynamous parts). 5. <stype>Personae</stype> (shoots or buds of plants, individuals in the narrowest sense among the higher animals). 6. <stype>Corms</stype> (stocks or colonies). For orders 2, 3, and 4 the term <xex>idorgan</xex> has been recently substituted. See <er>Idorgan</er>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morphonomy</ent><br/
<hw>Mor*phon"o*my</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>morfh`</grk> form + <?/ a law.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The laws of organic formation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morphophyly</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"pho*phy`ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>morfh`</grk> form + <?/ a clan.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The tribal history of forms; that part of phylogeny which treats of the tribal history of forms, in distinction from the tribal history of functions.</def>  <rj><au>Haeckel.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morphosis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mor*pho"sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mo`rfwsis</grk> form, fr. <grk>morfh`</grk> form.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The order or mode of development of an organ or part.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morphotic</ent><br/
<hw>Mor*phot"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ fit for forming.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>Connected with, or becoming an integral part of, a living unit or of the morphological framework; <as>as, <ex>morphotic</ex>, or tissue, proteids</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Foster.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>-morphous</ent><br/
<hw>-mor"phous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[Gr. <grk>morfh`</grk> form.]</ety> <def>A combining form denoting <sig>form</sig>, <sig>shape</sig>; <as>as, iso<ex>morphous</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morpion</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"pi*on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>mordre</ets> to bite + L. <ets>pedis</ets> louse.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A louse.</def>  <rj><au>Hudibras.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morrice</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"rice</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as 1st <er>Morris</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morrice</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"rice</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Dancing the morrice; dancing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In shoals and bands, a <qex>morrice</qex> train.</q> <rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morricer</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"ri*cer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A morris dancer.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morrimal</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"ri*mal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. & a.</pos> <def>See <er>Mormal</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morris</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"ris</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>morisco</ets> Moorish, fr. <ets>Moro</ets> a Moor: cf. F. <ets>moresque</ets>, It. <ets>moresca</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A Moorish dance, usually performed by a single dancer, who accompanies the dance with castanets.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A dance formerly common in England, often performed in pagenats, processions, and May games. The dancers, grotesquely dressed and ornamented, took the parts of Robin Hood, Maidmarian, and other fictitious characters.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An old game played with counters, or men, which are placed at the angles of a figure drawn on a board or on the ground; also, the board or ground on which the game is played.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The nine-men's <qex>morris</qex> is filled up with mud.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The figure consists of three concentric squares, with lines from the angles of the outer one to those of the inner, and from the middle of each side of the outer square to that of the inner.  The game is played by two persons with nine or twelve pieces each (hence called <xex>nine-men's morris</xex> or <xex>twelve-men's morris</xex>).  The pieces are placed alternately, and each player endeavors to prevent his opponent from making a straight row of three. Should either succeed in making a row, he may take up one of his opponent's pieces, and he who takes off all of his opponent's pieces wins the game.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morris</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"ris</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[So called from its discoverer.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A marine fish having a very slender, flat, transparent body.  It is now generally believed to be the young of the conger eel or some allied fish.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morris-chair</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"ris-chair`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. fr. the proper name <ets>Morris</ets>.]</ety> <def>A kind of easy-chair with a back which may be lowered or raised.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morris-pike</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"ris-pike`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A Moorish pike.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morro</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mor"ro</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp., any spherical object.]</ety> <def>A round hill or point of land; hence, <col><b>Morro castle</b></col>, a castle on a hill.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morrot</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"rot</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Marrot</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morrow</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"row</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>morwe</ets>, <ets>morwen</ets>, AS. <ets>morgen</ets>. See <er>Morn</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Morning.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/White as <xex>morrow's</xex> milk.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We loved he by the <qex>morwe</qex> a sop in wine.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The next following day; the day subsequent to any day specified or understood.</def>  <rj><au>Lev. vii. 16.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Till this stormy night is gone,<br/
And the eternal <qex>morrow</qex> dawn.</q> <rj><qau>Crashaw.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The day following the present; to-morrow.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Good morrow</b></col>, <cd>good morning; -- a form of salutation.</cd> -- <col><b>To morrow</b></col>. <cd>See <er>To-morrow</er> in the Vocabulary.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morse</ent><br/
<hw>Morse</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>morse</ets>, Russ. <ets>morj'</ets>; perh. akin to E. <ets>mere</ets> lake; cf. Russ. <ets>more</ets> sea.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The walrus. See <er>Walrus</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morse</ent><br/
<hw>Morse</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>morsus</ets> a biting, a clasp, fr. <ets>mordere</ets> to bite.]</ety> <def>A clasp for fastening garments in front.</def>  <rj><au>Fairholt.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morse alphabet</ent><br/
<hw>Morse" al"pha*bet</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <def>same as <er>Morse code</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morse code</ent><br/
<hw>Morse" code"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Teleg.)</fld> <def>a telegraphic code, in which dots, dashes, and spaces represent letters, numbers, and other elements of text.  The original code was invented by <person>Samuel B. <etsep>Morse</etsep></person>. The code now mostly used is the <stype>International Morse code</stype>, also referred to simply as the <ex>Morse code</ex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note>The present International Morse Code is given in the table below.  There are no spaces in the <stype>International Morse Code</stype>.<br/
<br/
<pre><tt><er>Alphabet</er><br/
----------------------------------------------------------<br/
A .-          H ....       O ---          V ...-<br/
B -...        I ..         P .--.         W .--<br/
C _._.        J .---       Q --.-         X -..-<br/
D -..         K -.-        R .-.          Y -.--<br/
E .           L .-..       S ...          Z --..<br/
F ..-.        M --         T -<br/
G --.         N -.         U ..-<br/
<br/
<er>Numerals</er><br/
<br/
1 .----       4 ....-          7 --...<br/
2 ..---       5 .....          8 ---..<br/
3 ...--       6 -....          9 ----.<br/
0 -----      
<br/
<er>Punctuation</er><br/
<br/
 . (Period)            .-.-.-    , (Comma)             --..--<br/
 ? (Question Mark)     ..--..    ; (Semicolon)         -.-.-.
 : (Colon)             ---...    ' (apostrophe)        .----.
 - (hyphen)            -....-    / (forward slash)     -..-.
 ( (left parenthesis)  -.--.     ) (right parenthesis) -.--.-
----------------------------------------------------------------<br/
</tt></pre></p>

<p>The Alphabetic code which was originally in use in North America is given in the table below.  In length, or duration, one dash is theoretically equal to three dots; the space between the elements of a letter is equal to one dot; the interval in spaced letters, as O . ., is equal to three dots. There are no spaces in any letter composed wholly or in part of dashes.</p>

<p><pre><tt><er>Alphabet</er><br/
<br/
A .-          H ....       O . .          V ...-<br/
B - . . .     I ..         P .....        W .--<br/
C .. .        J -.-.       Q ..-.         X .-..<br/
D -..         K -.-        R . ..         Y .. ..<br/
E .           L <mdash/    S ...          Z ... .<br/
F .-.         M --         T --           & . ...<br/
G --.         N -.         U ..-<br/
<br/
<er>Numerals</er><br/
<br/
1 .--.        4 . . . .-          7 --..<br/
2 ..-..       5 ---               8 - . . . .<br/
3 . . . -.    6 . . . . . .       9 -..-<br/
0 ----     Period ..--..   Comma .-.-<br/
</tt></pre></p>

<p>The Morse code was used chiefly with the electric telegraph, but is also employed in signalling with flags, lights, etc.</note><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morsel</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"sel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>morsel</ets>, F. <ets>morceau</ets>, LL. <ets>morsellus</ets>, a dim. fr. L. <ets>morsus</ets> a biting, bite, fr. <ets>mordere</ets> to bite; prob. akin to E. <ets>smart</ets>. See <er>Smart</er>, and cf. <er>Morceau</er>, <er>Mordant</er>, <er>Muse</er>, <pos>v.</pos>, <er>Muzzle</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A little bite or bit of food.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every <qex>morsel</qex> to a satisfied hunger is only a new labor to a tired digestion.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small quantity; a little piece; a fragment.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morsing horn</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"sing horn`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <def>A horn or flask for holding powder, as for priming.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir W. Scott.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morsitation</ent><br/
<hw>Mor`si*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of biting or gnawing.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morsure</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"sure</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>mordere</ets>, <ets>morsum</ets>, to bite.]</ety> <def>The act of biting.</def>  <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mort</ent><br/
<hw>Mort</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Icel. <ets>margt</ets>, neut. of <ets>margr</ets> many.]</ety> <def>A great quantity or number.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There was a <qex>mort</qex> of merrymaking.</q> <rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mort</ent><br/
<hw>Mort</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Etym. uncert.]</ety> <def>A woman; a female.</def> <mark>[Cant, archaic]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Male gypsies all, not a <qex>mort</qex> among them.</q> <rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mort</ent><br/
<hw>Mort</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Etymol. uncertain.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A salmon in its third year.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mort</ent><br/
<hw>Mort</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., death, fr. L. <ets>mors</ets>, <ets>mortis</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Death; esp., the death of game in the chase.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A note or series of notes sounded on a horn at the death of game.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sportsman then sounded a treble <qex>mort</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The skin of a sheep or lamb that has died of disease.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng. & Scot.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mort cloth</b></col>, <cd>the pall spread over a coffin; black cloth indicative or mourning; funeral hangings.</cd> <au>Carlyle.</au> -- <col><b>Mort stone</b></col>, <cd>a large stone by the wayside on which the bearers rest a coffin.</cd> <mark>[Eng.]</mark> <au>H. Taylor.</au></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mort</ent><br/
<hw>Mort</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mort</ets> dummy, lit., dead.]</ety> <def>A variety of dummy whist for three players; also, the exposed or dummy hand in this game.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortal</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"tal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mortel</ets>, L. <ets>mortalis</ets>, from <ets>mors</ets>, <ets>mortis</ets>, death, fr. <ets>moriri</ets> 8die; akin to E. <ets>murder</ets>. See <er>Murder</er>, and cf. <er>Filemot</er>, <er>Mere</er> a lake, <er>Mortgage</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Subject to death; destined to die; <as>as, man is <ex>mortal</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Destructive to life; causing or occasioning death; terminating life; exposing to or deserving death; deadly; <as>as, a <ex>mortal</ex> wound; a <ex>mortal</ex> sin.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Fatally vulnerable; vital.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Last of all, against himself he turns his sword, but missing the <qex>mortal</qex> place, with his poniard finishes the work.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the time of death.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Safe in the hand of one disposing Power,<br/
Or in the natal or the <qex>mortal</qex> hour.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Affecting as if with power to kill; deathly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The nymph grew pale, and in a <qex>mortal</qex> fright.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Human; belonging to man, who is mortal; <as>as, <ex>mortal</ex> wit or knowledge; <ex>mortal</ex> power</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The voice of God<br/
To <qex>mortal</qex> ear is dreadful.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Very painful or tedious; wearisome; <as>as, a sermon lasting two <ex>mortal</ex> hours</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir W. Scott.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Mortal foe</b></col>, <col><b>Mortal enemy</b></col></mcol>, <cd>an inveterate, desperate, or implacable enemy; a foe bent on one's destruction.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortal</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"tal</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A being subject to death; a human being; man.</def> <ldquo/Warn poor <xex>mortals</xex> left behind.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Tickell.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortality</ent><br/
<hw>Mor*tal"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mortalitas</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mortalit<eacute/</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The condition or quality of being mortal; subjection to death or to the necessity of dying.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When I saw her die,<br/
I then did think on your <qex>mortality</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Carew.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 946 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Human life; the life of a mortal being.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From this instant<br/
There 's nothing serious in <qex>mortality</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Those who are, or that which is, mortal; the human race; humanity; human nature.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Take these tears, <qex>mortality's</qex> relief.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Death; destruction.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The whole sum or number of deaths in a given time or a given community; also, the proportion of deaths to population, or to a specific number of the population; death rate; <as>as, a time of great, or low, <ex>mortality</ex>; the <ex>mortality</ex> among the settlers was alarming.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Bill of mortality</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Bill</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Law of mortality</b></col>, <cd>a mathematical relation between the numbers living at different ages, so that from a given large number of persons alive at one age, it can be computed what number are likely to survive a given number of years.</cd> -- <col><b>Table of mortality</b></col>, <cd>a table exhibiting the average relative number of persons who survive, or who have died, at the end of each year of life, out of a given number supposed to have been born at the same time.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortalize</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"tal*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mortalized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mortalizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To make mortal.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortally</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"tal*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>In a mortal manner; so as to cause death; <as>as, <ex>mortally</ex> wounded</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In the manner of a mortal or of mortal beings.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I was <qex>mortally</qex> brought forth.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>In an extreme degree; to the point of dying or causing death; desperately; <as>as, <ex>mortally</ex> jealous</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Adrian <qex>mortally</qex> envied poets, painters, and artificers, in works wherein he had a vein to excel.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortalness</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"tal*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Quality of being mortal; mortality.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortar</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"tar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>morter</ets>, AS. <ets>mort<emac/re</ets>, L. <ets>mortarium</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mortier</ets> mortar.  Cf. sense 2 (below), also 2d <er>Mortar</er>, <er>Martel</er>, <er>Morter</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A strong vessel, commonly in form of an inverted bell, in which substances are pounded or rubbed with a pestle.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[F. <ets>mortier</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mortarium</ets> mortar (for trituarating).]</ety> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A short piece of ordnance, used for throwing bombs, carcasses, shells, etc., at high angles of elevation, as 45<deg/, and even higher; -- so named from its resemblance in shape to the utensil above described.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mortar bed</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>a framework of wood and iron, suitably hollowed out to receive the breech and trunnions of a mortar.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Mortar boat</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Mortar vessel</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a boat strongly built and adapted to carrying a mortar or mortars for bombarding; a bomb ketch.</cd> -- <col><b>Mortar piece</b></col>, <cd>a mortar.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Shak.</au></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortar</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"tar</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mortier</ets>, F. <ets>mortier</ets>, L. <ets>mortarium</ets> mortar, a large basin or trough in which mortar is made, a mortar (in sense 1, above). See 1st <er>Mortar</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A building material made by mixing lime, cement, or plaster of Paris, with sand, water, and sometimes other materials; -- used in masonry for joining stones, bricks, etc., also for plastering, and in other ways.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mortar bed</b></col>, <cd>a shallow box or receptacle in which mortar is mixed.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortar</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"tar</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To plaster or make fast with mortar.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortar</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"tar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mortier</ets>. See <er>Mortar</er> a vessel.]</ety> <def>A chamber lamp or light.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mortar board</ent><br/
<ent>mortarboard</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mortarboard</hw>, <hw>mortar board</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A small square board with a handle beneath, for holding mortar; a hawk; used by masons to hold or carry mortar.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An academic cap topped by broad, projecting, stiff and flat square top, with a tassel attached to the top and hanging down.  It was once worn by students in some colleges, but is now worn usually only at graduation ceremonies.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortgage</ent><br/
<hw>Mort"gage</hw> <pr>(m<ocir/r"g<asl/j; 48)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mort-gage</ets>; <ets>mort</ets> dead (L. <ets>mortuus</ets>) + <ets>gage</ets> pledge. See <er>Mortal</er>, and <er>Gage</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A conveyance of property, upon condition, as security for the payment of a debt or the preformance of a duty, and to become void upon payment or performance according to the stipulated terms; also, the written instrument by which the conveyance is made.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ It was called a <xex>mortgage</xex> (or <xex>dead pledge</xex>) because, whatever profit it might yield, it did not thereby redeem itself, but became lost or <xex>dead</xex> to the mortgager upon breach of the condition.  But in equity a <xex>right of redemption</xex> is an inseparable incident of a mortgage until the mortgager is debarred by his own laches, or by judicial decree.</note>  <rj><au>Cowell.</au> <au>Kent.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>State of being pledged; <as>as, lands given in <ex>mortgage</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Chattel mortgage</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Chattel</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To foreclose a mortgage</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Foreclose</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mortgage deed</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>a deed given by way of mortgage.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortgage</ent><br/
<hw>Mort"gage</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mortgaged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mortgaging</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To grant or convey, as property, for the security of a debt, or other engagement, upon a condition that if the debt or engagement shall be discharged according to the contract, the conveyance shall be void, otherwise to become absolute, subject, however, to the right of redemption.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence: To pledge, either literally or figuratively; to make subject to a claim or obligation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mortgaging</qex> their lives to covetise.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I myself an <qex>mortgaged</qex> to thy will.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mortgaged</ent><br/
<hw>mortgaged</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>burdened with legal or financial obligations; <as>as, His house was <ex>mortgaged</ex> to the hilt</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortgagee</ent><br/
<hw>Mort`ga*gee"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The person to whom property is mortgaged, or to whom a mortgage is made or given.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortgagor</ent><br/
<ent>Mortgageor</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mort"gage*or</hw>, <hw>Mort"ga*gor</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>One who gives a mortgage.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The letter <xex>e</xex> is required analogically after the second <xex>g</xex> in order to soften it; but the spelling <xex>mortgagor</xex> is in fact the prevailing form. When the word is contradistinguished from <xex>mortgagee</xex> it is accented on the last syllable <pr>(-j<ocir/r")</pr>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortgager</ent><br/
<hw>Mort"ga*ger</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>One who gives a mortgage.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortiferous</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"tif"er*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mortifier</ets>; <ets>mors</ets>, <ets>mortis</ets>, death + <ets>ferre</ets> to bring: cf. F. <ets>mortif<egrave/re</ets>.]</ety> <def>Bringing or producing death; deadly; destructive; <as>as, a <ex>mortiferous</ex> herb</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Gov. of Tongue.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortification</ent><br/
<hw>Mor`ti*fi*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>mortificatio</ets> a killing. See <er>Mortify</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of mortifying, or the condition of being mortified</def>; especially: <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>The death of one part of an animal body, while the rest continues to live; loss of vitality in some part of a living animal; gangrene.</def> <au>Dunglison.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Alchem. & Old Chem.)</fld> <def>Destruction of active qualities; neutralization.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Bacon.</au> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>Subjection of the passions and appetites, by penance, abstinence, or painful severities inflicted on the body.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>mortification</qex> of our lusts has something in it that is troublesome, yet nothing that is unreasonable.</q> <rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Deep humiliation or shame, from a loss of pride; painful embarassment, usually arising from exposure of a mistake; chagrin; vexation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which mortifies; the cause of humiliation, chagrin, or vexation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is one of the vexatious <qex>mortifications</qex> of a studious man to have his thoughts discovered by a tedious visit.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Scots Law)</fld> <def>A gift to some charitable or religious institution; -- nearly synonymous with <altname>mortmain</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Chagrin; vexation; shame. See <er>Chagrin</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortified</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"ti*fied</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <def><pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> of <er>Mortify</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mortified</ent><br/
<hw>mor"ti*fied</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Deeply embarrased; painfully humiliated.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortifiedness</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"ti*fied*ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state of being mortified; humiliation; subjection of the passions.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortifier</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"ti*fi`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who, or that which, mortifies.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortify</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"ti*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mortified</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mortifying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>mortifien</ets>, F. <ets>mortifier</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mortificare</ets>; L. <ets>mors</ets>, <ets>mortis</ets>, death + <ets>-ficare</ets> (in comp.) to make. See <er>Mortal</er>, and <er>-fy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To destroy the organic texture and vital functions of; to produce gangrene in.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To destroy the active powers or essential qualities of; to change by chemical action.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Quicksilver is <qex>mortified</qex> with turpentine.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>mortified</qex> pearls in vinegar.</q> <rj><qau>Hakewill.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To deaden by religious or other discipline, as the carnal affections, bodily appetites, or worldly desires; to bring into subjection; to abase; to humble; <as>as, to <ex>mortify</ex> the flesh</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With fasting <qex>mortified</qex>, worn out with tears.</q> <rj><qau>Harte.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mortify</qex> thy learned lust.</q> <rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mortify</qex>, therefore, your members which are upon the earth.</q> <rj><qau>Col. iii. 5.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To affect with vexation, chagrin; to depress.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The news of the fatal battle of Worcester, which exceedingly <qex>mortified</qex> our expectations.</q> <rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How often is the ambitious man <qex>mortified</qex> with the very praises he receives, if they do not rise so high as he thinks they ought!</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To humiliate deeply, especially by injuring the pride of; to embarrass painfully; to humble; <as>as, the team was <ex>mortified</ex> to lose by 45 to 0</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortify</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"ti*fy</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To lose vitality and organic structure, as flesh of a living body; to gangrene.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To practice penance from religious motives; to deaden desires by religious discipline.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This makes him . . . give alms of all that he hath, watch, fast, and <qex>mortify</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Law.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be subdued; to decay, as appetites, desires, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortifying</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"ti*fy`ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Tending to mortify; affected by, or having symptoms of, mortification; <as>as, a <ex>mortifying</ex> wound; <ex>mortifying</ex> flesh.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Subduing the appetites, desires, etc.; <as>as, <ex>mortifying</ex> penances</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Tending to humble or abase; humiliating; <as>as, a <ex>mortifying</ex> repulse</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortifyingly</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"ti*fy`ing*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a mortifying manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortise</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"tise</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mortaise</ets>; cf. Sp. <ets>mortaja</ets>, Ar. <ets>murtazz</ets> fixed, or W. <ets>mortais</ets>, Ir. <ets>mortis</ets>, <ets>moirtis</ets>, Gael. <ets>moirteis</ets>.]</ety> <def>A cavity cut into a piece of timber, or other material, to receive something (as the end of another piece) made to fit it, and called a <inv>tenon</inv>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mortise and tenon</b></col> <fld>(Carp.)</fld>, <cd>made with a mortise and tenon; joined or united by means of a mortise and tenon; -- used adjectively.</cd> -- <col><b>Mortise joint</b></col>, <cd>a joint made by a mortise and tenon.</cd> -- <col><b>Mortise lock</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Lock</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mortise wheel</b></col>, <cd>a cast-iron wheel, with wooden clogs inserted in mortises on its face or edge; -- also called <altname>mortise gear</altname>, and <altname>core gear</altname>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortise</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"tise</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mortised</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mortising</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cut or make a mortise in.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To join or fasten by a tenon and mortise; <as>as, to <ex>mortise</ex> a beam into a post, or a joist into a girder</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortling</ent><br/
<hw>Mort"ling</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Morling</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An animal, as a sheep, dead of disease or privation; a morling.</def> <mark>[Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Wool plucked from a dead sheep; morling.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortmain</ent><br/
<hw>Mort"main`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mort</ets>, <ets>morte</ets>, dead + <ets>main</ets> hand; F. <ets>main-morte</ets>. See <er>Mortal</er>, and <er>Manual</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Possession of lands or tenements in, or conveyance to, dead hands, or hands that cannot alienate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The term was originally applied to conveyance of land made to ecclesiastical bodies; afterward to conveyance made to <xex>any</xex> corporate body.</note>  <rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortmal</ent><br/
<hw>Mort"mal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mormal</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortpay</ent><br/
<hw>Mort"pay`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mort</ets> dead + E. <ets>pay</ets>.]</ety> <def>Dead pay; the crime of taking pay for the service of dead soldiers, or for services not actually rendered by soldiers.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortrew</ent><br/
<ent>Mortress</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mor"tress</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mor"trew</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mortar</er>.]</ety> <def>A dish of meats and other ingredients, cooked together; an ollapodrida.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au>  <au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortuary</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"tu*a*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mortuaries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[LL. <ets>mortuarium</ets>. See <er>Mortuary</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A sort of ecclesiastical heriot, a customary gift claimed by, and due to, the minister of a parish on the death of a parishioner. It seems to have been originally a voluntary bequest or donation, intended to make amends for any failure in the payment of tithes of which the deceased had been guilty.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A burial place; a place for the dead.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A place for the reception of the dead before burial; a deadhouse; a morgue.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A <er>funeral home</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortuary</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"tu*a*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mortuarius</ets>, fr. <ets>mortuus</ets> dead: cf. F. <ets>mortuaire</ets>. See <er>Mortal</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to the dead; <as>as, <ex>mortuary</ex> monuments</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mortuary urn</b></col>, <cd>an urn for holding the ashes of a dead person after cremation.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morula</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mor"u*la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Morulae</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL., dim. of L. <ets>morum</ets> a mulberry.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The sphere or globular mass of cells (<parts>blastomeres</parts>), formed by the clevage of the ovum or egg in the first stages of its development; -- called also <altname>mulberry mass</altname>, <altname>segmentation sphere</altname>, and <altname>blastosphere</altname>. See <er>Segmentation</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morulation</ent><br/
<hw>Mor`u*la"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The process of cleavage, or segmentation, of the ovum, by which a morula is formed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo"rus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., mulberry tree. See <er>Mulberry</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of trees, some species of which produce edible fruit; the mulberry. See <er>Mulberry</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <col><b>Morus alba</b></col> is the white mulberry, a native of India or China, the leaves of which are extensively used for feeding silkworms, for which it furnishes the chief food. -- <col><b>Morus multicaulis</b></col>, the many-stemmed or Chinese mulberry, is only a form of white mulberry, preferred on account of its more abundant leaves. -- <col><b>Morus nigra</b></col>, the black mulberry, produces a dark-colored fruit, of an agreeable flavor.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morwe</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"we</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Morrow</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morwening</ent><br/
<hw>Mor"wen*ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Morning.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mos</ent><br/
<hw>Mos</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>, <def><pos>sing.</pos> of <er>Mores</er>.</def> <mark>[Rare]</mark> <br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mosaic</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*sa"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mosa<ium/que</ets>; cf. Pr. <ets>mozaic</ets>, <ets>musec</ets>, Sp. & Pg. <ets>mosaico</ets>, It. <ets>mosaico</ets>, <ets>musaico</ets>, LGr. <?/, <?/, L. <ets>musivum</ets>; all fr. Gr. <?/ belonging to the Muses. See <er>Muse</er> the goddess.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Fine Arts)</fld> <def>A surface decoration made by inlaying in patterns small pieces of variously colored glass, stone, or other material; -- called also <altname>mosaic work</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A picture or design made in mosaic; an article decorated in mosaic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Something resembling a mosaic{1}; something made up of different pieces, fitted together by design to form a unified composition.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>aerial mosaic</b></col> <cd>An aerial photograph of a large area, made by carefully fitting together aerial photographs of smaller areas so that the edges match in location, and the whole provides a continuous image of the larger area.  Called also <col><b>mosaic map</b></col> and <altname>photomosaic</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>mosaic virus</b></col> <cd>A type of plant virus that causes green and yellow mottling of leaves of a plant.  A much-studied type is the <stype>tobacco mosaic virus</stype>, affecting the tobacco plant.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mosaic</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*sa"ic</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the style of work called mosaic; formed by uniting pieces of different colors; variegated; tessellated; also, composed of various materials or ingredients.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A very beautiful <qex>mosaic</qex> pavement.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Florentine mosaic</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Florentine</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mosaic gold</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>See <er>Ormolu</er>.</cd>  <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Stannic sulphide, <chform>SnS2</chform>, obtained as a yellow scaly crystalline powder, and used as a pigment in bronzing and gilding wood and metal work. It was called by the alchemists <altname>aurum musivum</altname>, or <altname>aurum mosaicum</altname>. Called also <altname>bronze powder</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mosaic work</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Mosaic</er>, <pos>n.</pos></cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mosaic</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*sa"ic</hw>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <ety>[From <etsep>Moses</etsep>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to <persfn>Moses</persfn>, the leader of the <grp>Israelites</grp>, or established through his agency; <as>as, the <ex>Mosaic</ex> law, rites, or institutions</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mosaical</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*sa"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Mosaic (in either sense).</def> <ldquo/A <xex>mosaical</xex> floor.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Sir P. Sidney.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mosaically</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*sa"ic*al*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In the manner of a mosaic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mosaism</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"sa*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Attachment to the system or doctrines of Moses; that which is peculiar to the Mosaic system or doctrines.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mosasaurian</ent><br/
<ent>Mosasaur</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mos"a*saur</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mos`a*sau"ri*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>One of an extinct order of reptiles, including <gen>Mosasaurus</gen> and allied genera. See <er>Mosasauria</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mosasauria</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mos`a*sau"ri*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Mosasaurus</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>An order of large, extinct, marine reptiles, found in the Cretaceous rocks, especially in America.  They were serpentlike in form and in having loosely articulated and dilatable jaws, with large recurved teeth, but they had paddlelike feet. Some of them were over fifty feet long. They are, essentially, fossil sea serpents with paddles. Called also <altname>Pythonomarpha</altname>, and <altname>Mosasauria</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mosasaurus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mos`a*sau"rus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. L. <ets>Mosa</ets> the River Meuse (on which Meastricht is situated) + Gr. <?/ a lizard.]</ety> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>A genus of extinct marine reptiles allied to the lizards, but having the body much elongated, and the limbs in the form of paddles.  The first known species, nearly fifty feet in length, was discovered in Cretaceous beds near <city>Maestricht</city>, in the Netherlands.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>Mososaurus</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moschatel</ent><br/
<hw>Mos"cha*tel`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ musk: cf. F. <ets>moscatelline</ets>. See <er>Muscadel</er>, <er>Musk</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A plant of the genus <gen>Adoxa</gen> (<spn>Adoxa moschatellina</spn>), the flowers of which are pale green, and have a faint musky smell.  It is found in woods in all parts of Europe, and is called also <altname>hollow root</altname> and <altname>musk crowfoot</altname>.</def>  <rj><au>Loudon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moschine</ent><br/
<hw>Mos"chine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to <gen>Moschus</gen>, a genus including the musk deer.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mosel</ent><br/
<hw>Mos"el</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. & v.</pos> <def>See <er>Muzzle</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moselle</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*selle"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A light wine, usually white, produced in the vicinity of the river Moselle.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moses</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ses</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A large flatboat, used in the West Indies for taking freight from shore to ship.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mosey</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"sey</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Perh. fr. <er>Vamose</er>.]</ety> <def>To go, or move (in a certain manner); -- usually with <ptcl>out</ptcl>, <ptcl>off</ptcl>, <ptcl>along</ptcl>, etc.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>  <rj><au>E. N. Wescott.</au></rj><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mosk</ent><br/
<hw>Mosk</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mosque</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moslem</ent><br/
<hw>Mos"lem</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/z"l<ecr/m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Moslems</plw> <pr>(m<ocr/z"l<ecr/mz)</pr>, <xex>or collectively</xex> <plw>Moslem</plw>.</plu> <ety>[Ar. <ets>muslim</ets> a true believer in the Muslim faith, fr. <ets>salama</ets> to submit to God, to resign one's self to the divine will.  Cf. <er>Islam</er>, <er>Mussulman</er>.]</ety> <def>An adherent of Islam; a Mussulman; an orthodox Muslim.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>muslim</asp>.]</altsp> <ldquo/Heaps of slaughtered <xex>Moslem</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They piled the ground with <qex>Moslem</qex> slain.</q> <rj><qau>Halleck.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 947 --></p>

<p><ent>Moslem</ent><br/
<hw>Mos"lem</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/z"l<ecr/m)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the Muslims; Islamic; <as>as, <ex>Moslem</ex> lands; the <ex>Moslem</ex> faith.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moslings</ent><br/
<hw>Mos"lings</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <def>Thin shreds of leather shaved off in dressing skins.</def>  <rj><au>Simmonds.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mososaurus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mos`o*sau"rus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL.]</ety> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Mosasaurus</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mosque</ent><br/
<hw>Mosque</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/sk)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mosqu<eacute/e</ets>, Sp. <ets>mezquita</ets>, Ar. <ets>masjid</ets>, from <ets>sajada</ets> to bend, adore.]</ety> <def>A Muslim church or place of religious worship.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mosk</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mosquito</ent><br/
<hw>Mos*qui"to</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/s*k<emac/*t<osl/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mosquitoes</plw> <pr>(m<ocr/s*k<emac/*t<omac/z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Sp. <ets>mosquito</ets>, fr. <ets>mosca</ets>fly, L. <ets>musca</ets>.  Cf. <er>Musket</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of various species of gnats of the genus <gen>Culex</gen> and allied genera.  The females have a proboscis containing, within the sheathlike labium, six fine, sharp, needlelike organs with which they puncture the skin of man and animals to suck the blood.  These bites, when numerous, cause, in many persons, considerable irritation and swelling, with some pain.  The larvae and pupae, called <stage>wigglers</stage>, are aquatic.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>musquito</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Mosquito bar</b></col>, <col><b>Mosquito net</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a net or curtain for excluding mosquitoes, -- used for beds and windows.</cd> -- <col><b>Mosquito fleet</b></col>, <cd>a fleet of small vessels.</cd> -- <col><b>Mosquito hawk</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a dragon fly; -- so called because it captures and feeds upon mosquitoes.</cd> -- <col><b>Mosquito netting</b></col>, <cd>a loosely-woven gauzelike fabric for making mosquito bars.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mosquitofish</ent><br/
<hw>mosquitofish</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A silvery topminnow (<spn>Gambusia affinis</spn>) with rows of black spots of tropical North America and West Indies; important in mosquito control.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> <spn>Gambusia affinis</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moss</ent><br/
<hw>Moss</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/s; 115)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mos</ets>; akin to AS. <ets>me<oacute/s</ets>, D. <ets>mos</ets>, G. <ets>moos</ets>, OHG. <ets>mos</ets>, <ets>mios</ets>, Icel. <ets>mosi</ets>, Dan. <ets>mos</ets>, Sw. <ets>mossa</ets>, Russ. <ets>mokh'</ets>, L. <ets>muscus</ets>.  Cf. <er>Muscoid</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A cryptogamous plant of a cellular structure, with distinct stem and simple leaves.  The fruit is a small capsule usually opening by an apical lid, and so discharging the spores.  There are many species, collectively termed <xex>Musci</xex>, growing on the earth, on rocks, and trunks of trees, etc., and a few in running water.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The term <xex>moss</xex> is also popularly applied to many other small cryptogamic plants, particularly <xex>lichens</xex>, species of which are called <xex>tree moss</xex>, <xex>rock moss</xex>, <xex>coral moss</xex>, etc. <xex>Fir moss</xex> and <xex>club moss</xex> are of the genus <gen>Lycopodium</gen>. See <cref>Club moss</cref>, under <er>Club</er>, and <er>Lycopodium</er>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A bog; a morass; a place containing peat; <as>as, the <ex>mosses</ex> of the Scottish border</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Moss</xex> is used with participles in the composition of words which need no special explanation; as, <xex>moss</xex>-capped, <xex>moss</xex>-clad, <xex>moss</xex>-covered, <xex>moss</xex>-grown, etc.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Black moss</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Black</er>, and <er>Tillandsia</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Bog moss</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Sphagnum</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Feather moss</b></col>, <cd>any moss branched in a feathery manner, esp. several species of the genus <gen>Hypnum</gen>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Florida moss</b></col>, <col><b>Long moss</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Spanish moss</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See <er>Tillandsia</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Iceland moss</b></col>, <cd>a lichen. See <er>Iceland Moss</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Irish moss</b></col>, <cd>a seaweed. See <er>Carrageen</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Moss agate</b></col> <fld>(Min.)</fld>, <cd>a variety of agate, containing brown, black, or green mosslike or dendritic markings, due in part to oxide of manganese. Called also <altname>Mocha stone</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Moss animal</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a bryozoan.</cd> -- <col><b>Moss berry</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the small cranberry (<spn>Vaccinium Oxycoccus</spn>).</cd> -- <col><b>Moss campion</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a kind of mosslike catchfly (<spn>Silene acaulis</spn>), with mostly purplish flowers, found on the highest mountains of Europe and America, and within the Arctic circle.</cd> -- <col><b>Moss land</b></col>, <cd>land produced accumulation of aquatic plants, forming peat bogs of more or less consistency, as the water is grained off or retained in its pores.</cd> -- <col><b>Moss pink</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a plant of the genus <gen>Phlox</gen> (<spn>Phlox subulata</spn>), growing in patches on dry rocky hills in the Middle United States, and often cultivated for its handsome flowers.</cd> <au>Gray.</au> -- <col><b>Moss rose</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a variety of rose having a mosslike growth on the stalk and calyx.  It is said to be derived from the Provence rose.</cd> -- <col><b>Moss rush</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a rush of the genus <gen>Juncus</gen> (<spn>Juncus squarrosus</spn>).</cd> -- <col><b>Scale moss</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Hepatica</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moss</ent><br/
<hw>Moss</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mossed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mossing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To cover or overgrow with moss.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An oak whose boughs were <qex>mossed</qex> with age.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mossback</ent><br/
<hw>Moss"back`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A veteran partisan; one who is so conservative in opinion that he may be likened to a stone or old tree covered with moss.</def> <mark>[Political Slang, U.S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mossbunker</ent><br/
<ent>Mossbanker</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Moss"bank`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Moss"bunk`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The menhaded.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mossgrown</ent><br/
<ent>moss-grown</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>moss"-grown`</hw>, <hw>moss"grown`</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Overgrown with moss; mossy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mossiness</ent><br/
<hw>Moss"i*ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state of being mossy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mosstrooper</ent><br/
<hw>Moss"troop`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Moss</ets> + <ets>trooper</ets>.]</ety> <def>One of a class of marauders or bandits that formerly infested the border country between England and Scotland; -- so called in allusion to the <xex>mossy</xex> or boggy character of much of the border country.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mossy</ent><br/
<hw>Moss"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Mossier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Mossiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Overgrown with moss; abounding with or edged with moss; <as>as, <ex>mossy</ex> trees; <ex>mossy</ex> streams.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Old trees are more <qex>mossy</qex> far than young.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Resembling moss; <as>as, <ex>mossy</ex> green</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Most</ent><br/
<hw>Most</hw> <pr>(m<omac/st)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>, <pos>superl.</pos> of <er>More</er>. <ety>[OE. <ets>most</ets>, <ets>mast</ets>, <ets>mest</ets>, AS. <ets>m<aemac/st</ets>; akin to D. <ets>meest</ets>, OS. <ets>m<emac/st</ets>, G. <ets>meist</ets>, Icel. <ets>mestr</ets>, Goth. <ets>maists</ets>; a superl. corresponding to E. <ets>more</ets>.  <root/103. See <er>More</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Consisting of the greatest number or quantity; greater in number or quantity than all the rest; nearly all.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Most</xex> men will proclaim every one his own goodness.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Prov. xx. 6.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The cities wherein <qex>most</qex> of his mighty works were done.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. xi. 20.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Greatest in degree; <as>as, he has the <ex>most</ex> need of it</as>.</def> <ldquo/In the <xex>moste</xex> pride.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Highest in rank; greatest.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Most</xex> is used as a noun, the words <xex>part</xex>, <xex>portion</xex>, <xex>quantity</xex>, etc., being omitted, and has the following meanings: <b>1.</b> The greatest value, number, or part; preponderating portion; highest or chief part. <b>2.</b> The utmost; greatest possible amount, degree, or result; especially in the phrases <xex>to make the most of</xex>, <xex>at the most</xex>, <xex>at most</xex>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A quarter of a year or some months <qex>at the most</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A covetous man <qex>makes the most of</qex> what he has.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>For the most part</b></col>, <cd>in reference to the larger part of a thing, or to the majority of the persons, instances, or things referred to; as, human beings, <xex>for the most part</xex>, are superstitious; the view, <xex>for the most part</xex>, was pleasing.</cd> -- <col><b>Most an end</b></col>, <cd>generally. See <cref>An end</cref>, under <er>End</er>, <pos>n.</pos></cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/She sleeps <xex>most an end</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Massinger.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Most</ent><br/
<hw>Most</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<aemac/st</ets>. See <er>Most</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>In the greatest or highest degree.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those nearest to this king, and <qex>most</qex> his favorites, were courtiers and prelates.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Placed before an adjective or adverb, <xex>most</xex> is used to form the superlative degree, being equivalent to the termination <xex>-est</xex>; as, <xex>most</xex> vile, <xex>most</xex> wicked; <xex>most</xex> illustrious; <xex>most</xex> rapidly.  Formerly, and until after the Elizabethan period of our literature, the use of the double superlative was common.  See <er>More</er>, <pos>adv.</pos></note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>most unkindest</qex> cut of all.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>most straitest</qex> sect of our religion.</q> <rj><qau>Acts xxvi. 5.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mostahiba</ent><br/
<hw>Mos`ta*hi"ba</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mustaiba</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moste</ent><br/
<hw>Mos"te</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <mark>obs.</mark> <def><pos>imp.</pos> of <er>Mote</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Most-favored-nation clause</ent><br/
<hw>Most-favored-nation clause</hw> <fld>(Diplomacy)</fld>,  <def>A clause, often inserted in treaties, by which each of the contracting nations binds itself to grant to the other in certain stipulated matters the same terms as are then, or may be thereafter, granted to the nation which receives from it the most favorable terms in respect of those matters.  It is used most frequently in treaties regarding the terms of trade between countries, as regarding tariffs and non-tariff barriers to trade.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>There was a <ldquo/<qex>most-favored-nation</qex><rdquo/ <qex>clause</qex> with provisions for the good treatment of strangers entering the Republic.</q>  <rj><qau>James Bryce.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><q>Steam navigation was secured by the Japanese as far as Chungking, and under the <qex>most-favored-nation clause</qex> the right accrued to us.</q>  <rj><qau>A. R. Colquhoun.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mostick</ent><br/
<ent>Mostic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mos"tic</hw>, <hw>Mos"tick</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Maul-stick</er>.]</ety> <def>A painter's maul-stick.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mostly</ent><br/
<hw>Most"ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>For the greatest part; for the most part; chiefly; in the main.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mostra</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mos"tra</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>See <er>Direct</er>, <pos>n.</pos></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mostwhat</ent><br/
<hw>Most"what`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>For the most part.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/All the rest do <xex>mostwhat</xex> far amiss.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mot</ent><br/
<hw>Mot</hw> <pr>(m<omac/t)</pr>, <pos>v.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>Sing. pres. ind.</pos> <conjf>Mot</conjf>, <conjf>Mote</conjf>, <conjf>Moot</conjf> <pr>(m<omac/t)</pr>, <pos>pl.</pos> <conjf>Mot</conjf>, <conjf>Mote</conjf>, <conjf>Moote</conjf>, <pos>pres. subj.</pos> <conjf>Mote</conjf>; <pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Moste</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Must</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <def>May; must; might.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>moot</qex> as well say one word as another</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wordes <qex>mote</qex> be cousin to the deed.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men <qex>moot</qex> [i.e., one only] give silver to the poore freres.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>So mote it be</b></col>, <cd>so be it; amen; -- a phrase in some rituals, as that of the Freemasons.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mot</ent><br/
<hw>Mot</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/t; m<osl/, def. 2)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. See <er>Motto</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A word; hence, a motto; a device.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tarquin's eye may read the <qex>mot</qex> afar.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A pithy or witty saying; a witticism.</def> <mark>[A Gallicism]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here and there turns up a . . . savage <qex>mot</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>N. Brit. Rev.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A note or brief strain on a bugle.</def>  <rj><au>Sir W. Scott.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motacil</ent><br/
<hw>Mot"a*cil</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>motacille</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any singing bird of the genus <gen>Motacilla</gen>; a wagtail.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motation</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>motare</ets>, <ets>motatum</ets>, to keep moving.]</ety> <def>The act of moving; motion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mote</ent><br/
<hw>Mote</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v.</pos> <def>See 1st <er>Mot</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mote</ent><br/
<hw>Mote</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Moot</er>, a meeting.]</ety> <mark>[Obs., except in a few combinations or phrases.]</mark> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A meeting of persons for discussion; <as>as, a ward<ex>mote</ex> in the city of London</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A body of persons who meet for discussion, esp. about the management of affairs; <as>as, a folk<ex>mote</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A place of meeting for discussion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mote bell</b></col>, <cd>the bell rung to summon to a <ex>mote</ex>.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mote</ent><br/
<hw>Mote</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The flourish sounded on a horn by a huntsman. See <er>Mot</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 3, and <er>Mort</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mote</ent><br/
<hw>Mote</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mot</ets>, AS. <ets>mot</ets>.]</ety> <def>A small particle, as of floating dust; anything proverbially small; a speck.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The little <qex>motes</qex> in the sun do ever stir, though there be no wind.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We are <qex>motes</qex> in the midst of generations.</q> <rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moted</ent><br/
<hw>Mot"ed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Filled with motes, or fine floating dust; <as>as, the air</as>.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Moted</xex> sunbeams.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motet</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*tet"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., a dim. of <ets>mot</ets> word; cf. It. <ets>mottetto</ets>, dim. of <ets>motto</ets> word, device. See <er>Mot</er>, <er>Motto</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A composition adapted to sacred words in the elaborate polyphonic church style; an anthem.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moth</ent><br/
<hw>Moth</hw> <pr>(m<ocr/th)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mote.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moth</ent><br/
<hw>Moth</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Moths</plw> <pr>(m<ocr/thz)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>mothe</ets>, AS. <ets>mo<edh/<edh/e</ets>; akin to D. <ets>mot</ets>, G. <ets>motte</ets>, Icel. <ets>motti</ets>, and prob. to E. <ets>mad</ets> an earthworm.  Cf. <er>Mad</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, <er>Mawk</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any nocturnal lepidopterous insect, or any not included among the butterflies; <as>as, the luna <ex>moth</ex>; Io <ex>moth</ex>; hawk <ex>moth</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any lepidopterous insect that feeds upon garments, grain, etc.; <as>as, the clothes <ex>moth</ex>; grain <ex>moth</ex>; bee <ex>moth</ex></as>. See these terms under <er>Clothes</er>, <er>Grain</er>, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of various other insects that destroy woolen and fur goods, etc., esp. the larvae of several species of beetles of the genera <gen>Dermestes</gen> and <gen>Anthrenus</gen>.  Carpet moths are often the larvae of <gen>Anthrenus</gen>.  See <cref>Carpet beetle</cref>, under <er>Carpet</er>, <er>Dermestes</er>, <er>Anthrenus</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Anything which gradually and silently eats, consumes, or wastes any other thing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Moth blight</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any plant louse of the genus <gen>Aleurodes</gen>, and related genera. They are injurious to various plants.</cd> -- <col><b>Moth gnat</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a dipterous insect of the genus <gen>Bychoda</gen>, having fringed wings.</cd> -- <col><b>Moth hunter</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the goatsucker.</cd> -- <col><b>Moth miller</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a clothes moth. See <er>Miller</er>, 3, <sd>(a)</sd>.</cd> -- <col><b>Moth mullein</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a common herb of the genus <gen>Verbascum</gen> (<spn>Verbascum Blattaria</spn>), having large wheel-shaped yellow or whitish flowers.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mothball</ent><br/
<hw>moth"ball`</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A small sphere of camphor or naphthalene used to keep moths away from stored clothing.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> camphor ball.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mothball</ent><br/
<hw>moth"ball`</hw> <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To put into long-term storage; <as>as, to <ex>mothball</ex> the battleships not needed after the war</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moth-eat</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"-eat`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To eat or prey upon, as a moth eats a garment.</def> <mark>[Rarely used except in the form <it>moth-eaten</it>, p. p. or a.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ruin and neglect have so <qex>moth-eaten</qex> her.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. Herbert.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moth-eaten</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"-eat`en</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>having holes due to eating by moths or moth larvae; -- of cloth or clothing.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mothen</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"en</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Full of moths.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Fulke.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mother</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"er</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/<th/"<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>moder</ets>, AS. <ets>m<omac/dor</ets>; akin to D. <ets>moeder</ets>, OS. <ets>m<omac/dar</ets>, G. <ets>mutter</ets>, OHG. <ets>muotar</ets>, Icel. <ets>m<omac/<edh/ir</ets>, Dan. & Sw. <ets>moder</ets>, OSlav. <ets>mati</ets>, Russ. <ets>mate</ets>, Ir. & Gael. <ets>mathair</ets>, L. <ets>mater</ets>, Gr. <grk>mh`thr</grk>, Skr. <ets>m<amac/t<rsdot/</ets>; cf. Skr. <ets>m<amac/</ets> to measure. <root/268.  Cf. <er>Material</er>, <er>Matrix</er>, <er>Metropolis</er>, <er>Father</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A female parent; especially, one of the human race; a woman who has borne a child.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which has produced or nurtured anything; source of birth or origin; generatrix.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Alas! poor country! . . . it can not<br/
Be called our <qex>mother</qex>, but our grave.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I behold . . . the solitary majesty of Crete, <qex>mother</qex> of a religion, it is said, that lived two thousand years.</q> <rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An old woman or matron.</def> <mark>[Familiar]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The female superior or head of a religious house, as an abbess, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Hysterical passion; hysteria.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mother Carey's chicken</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one of several species of small petrels, as the stormy petrel (<spn>Procellaria pelagica</spn>), and Leach's petrel (<spn>Oceanodroma leucorhoa</spn>), both of the Atlantic, and <spn>Oceanodroma furcata</spn> of the North Pacific.</cd> -- <col><b>Mother Carey's goose</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the giant fulmar of the Pacific.  See <er>Fulmar</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mother's mark</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>a congenital mark upon the body; a birthmark; a naevus.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mother</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"er</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Received by birth or from ancestors; native, natural; <as>as, <ex>mother</ex> language</as>; also acting the part, or having the place of a mother; producing others; originating.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is the <qex>mother</qex> falsehood from which all idolatry is derived.</q> <rj><qau>T. Arnold.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mother cell</b></col> <fld>(Biol.)</fld>, <cd>a cell which, by endogenous divisions, gives rise to other cells (daughter cells); a parent cell.</cd> -- <col><b>Mother church</b></col>, <cd>the original church; a church from which other churches have sprung; <as>as, the <ex>mother church</ex> of a diocese</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mother country</b></col>, <cd>the country of one's parents or ancestors; the country from which the people of a colony derive their origin.</cd> -- <col><b>Mother liquor</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>the impure or complex residual solution which remains after the salts readily or regularly crystallizing have been removed.</cd> -- <col><b>Mother queen</b></col>, <cd>the mother of a reigning sovereign; a queen mother.</cd> -- <col><b>Mother tongue</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A language from which another language has had its origin</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>The language of one's native land; native tongue.</cd> -- <col><b>Mother water</b></col>. <cd>See <cref>Mother liquor</cref> (above).</cd> -- <col><b>Mother wit</b></col>, <cd>natural or native wit or intelligence.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mother</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"er</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mothered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mothering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To adopt as a son or daughter; to perform the duties of a mother to.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The queen, to have put lady Elizabeth besides the crown, would have <qex>mothered</qex> another body's child.</q> <rj><qau>Howell.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mother</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"er</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Akin to D. <ets>modder</ets> mud, G. <ets>moder</ets> mold, mud, Dan. <ets>mudder</ets> mud, and to E. <ets>mud</ets>. See <er>Mud</er>.]</ety> <def>A film or membrane which is developed on the surface of fermented alcoholic liquids, such as vinegar, wine, etc., and acts as a means of conveying the oxygen of the air to the alcohol and other combustible principles of the liquid, thus leading to their oxidation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The film is composed of a mass of rapidly developing microorganisms of the genus <gen>Mycoderma</gen>, and in the <cref>mother of vinegar</cref> the microorganisms (<spn>Mycoderma aceti</spn>) composing the film are the active agents in the Conversion of the alcohol into vinegar. When thickened by growth, the film may settle to the bottom of the fluid. See <cref>Acetous fermentation</cref>, under <er>Fermentation</er>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mother</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"er</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become like, or full of, mother, or thick matter, as vinegar.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mother</ent><br/
<hw>moth"er</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/<th/"<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Shortened from <ets>motherfucker</ets> as a euphemism.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Same as <er>motherfucker</er>.</def> <mark>[Vulgar slang]</mark><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A person or thing with some exceptional quality, as great size or power; <as>as, a grizzly stuck his nose in my tent and I grabbed my pistol and shot the <ex>mother</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark> <br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>motherboard</ent><br/
<hw>moth"er*board`</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Electronics)</fld> <def>The board containing the main circuits of an electronic device, especially computers.  The term is used primarily in microcomputer literature, where it designates the board containing the main <part>expansion bus</part>, and usually also the <part>cpu</part>.   On motherboards designed with an expansion bus, often all of the circuits not contained on an expansion card are on the <ex>motherboard</ex>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mothered</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"ered</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Thick, like mother; viscid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They oint their naked limbs with <qex>mothered</qex> oil.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>motherfucker</ent><br/
<hw>moth"er*fuck`er</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A person who is deemed to be worthless or despicable; -- obscene and highly offensive.</def> <mark>[vulgar slang]</mark><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> rotter, rat, skunk, stinker, bum, crumb, lowlife, scum bag, cocksucker, mother.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any object viewed as annoying or frustrating; -- usually used as an expression of anger.</def> <mark>[vulgar slang]</mark><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mother Goose</ent><br/
<hw>Mother Goose</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The supposed author of a book of nursery rhymes first published as <ldquo/Mother Goose's Melodies,<rdquo/ and usually called simply <ldquo/Mother Goose.<rdquo/  The first English edition is said to have been printed in 1719 in London.  The actual persons who composed the rhymes is unknown, and earlier similar rhymes in French are a likely source for some of them.  <ex>Mother Goose</ex> is also used as the title of a book of Mother Goose rhymes.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motherhood</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"er*hood</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state of being a mother; the character or office of a mother.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mothering</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"er*ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A rural custom in England, of visiting one's parents on Midlent Sunday, -- supposed to have been originally visiting the mother church to make offerings at the high altar.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mother-in-law</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"er-in-law`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The mother of one's husband or wife.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motherland</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"er*land`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The country of one's ancestors; -- same as <altname>fatherland</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motherless</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"er*less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<omac/dorle<aacute/s</ets>.]</ety> <def>Destitute of a mother; having lost a mother; <as>as, <ex>motherless</ex> children</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>motherlike</ent><br/
<hw>motherlike</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>suggestive of or acting like a mother; motherly; maternal.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motherliness</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"er*li*ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state or quality of being motherly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motherly</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"er*ly</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<omac/dorlic</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to a mother; like, or suitable for, a mother; tender; maternal; <as>as, <ex>motherly</ex> authority, love, or care</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Maternal; paternal.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Motherly</er>, <er>Maternal</er>. <xex>Motherly</xex>, being Anglo-Saxon, is the most familiar word of the two when both have the same meaning.  Besides this, <xex>maternal</xex> is confined to the feelings of a mother toward her <xex>own</xex> children, whereas <xex>motherly</xex> has a secondary sense, denoting a care <xex>like</xex> that of a mother for her offspring.  There is, perhaps, a growing tendency thus to separate the two, confining <xex>motherly</xex> to the latter signification.  <ldquo/They termed her the great mother, for her <xex>motherly</xex> care in cherishing her brethren whilst young.<rdquo/ <au>Sir W. Raleigh.</au></usage><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motherly</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"er*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a manner of a mother.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mother-naked</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"er-na`ked</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Naked as when born; completely naked.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> naked as the day one was born, in one's birthday suit.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mother-of-pearl</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"er-of-pearl`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The hard, iridescent, pearly internal layer of several kinds of shells, esp. of pearl oysters, river mussels, and the abalone shells; nacre. See <er>Pearl</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mother-of-thousands</ent><br/
<hw>mother-of-thousands</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>An East Asiatic saxifrage (<spn>Saxifraga stolonifera</spn>) with racemes of small red-and-white flowers; spreads by numerous creeping stolons; called also <altname>strawberry geranium</altname> and <altname>strawberry saxifrage</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> strawberry geranium, strawberry saxifrage, <spn>Saxifraga stolonifera</spn>, Saxifraga sarmentosam.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mother-of-thyme</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"er-of-thyme`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>An aromatic plant (<spn>Thymus Serphyllum</spn>); -- called also <altname>wild thyme</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mother's Day</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"er's Day</hw>. <def>A day appointed for the honor and uplift of motherhood by the loving remembrance of each person of his mother through the performance of some act of kindness, visit, tribute, or letter. The founder of the day is <person>Anna Jarvis</person>, of <city>Philadelphia</city>, who designated the second Sunday in May, or for schools the second Friday, as the time, and a white carnation as the badge.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motherwort</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"er*wort`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A labiate herb (<spn>Leonurus Cardiaca</spn>), of a bitter taste, used popularly in medicine; lion's tail.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The mugwort. See <er>Mugwort</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 948 --></p>

<p><ent>Mothery</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"er*y</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/<th/"<etil/r*<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Consisting of, containing, or resembling, mother (in vinegar).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mothy</ent><br/
<hw>Moth"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Infested with moths; moth-eaten.</def> <ldquo/An old <xex>mothy</xex> saddle.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motif</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"tif</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>Motive.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark> <br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In literature and the fine arts, a salient feature or element of a composition or work; esp., the theme, or central or dominant feature;</def> <specif>specif.</specif> <fld>(Music)</fld>, <def>a motive{3}.  See also <er>leitmotif</er>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>motif</qex>, of old things lost, is a favorite one for the serious ballade.</q>  <rj><qau>R. M. Alden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><q>The design . . . is . . . based on the peacock -- a <qex>motif</qex> favored by decorative artists of all ages.</q>  <rj><qau>R. D. Benn.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn>  <fld>(Dressmaking)</fld> <def>A decorative appliqu<eacute/ design or figure, as of lace or velvet, used in trimming; also, a repeated design.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motific</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*tif"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>motus</ets> motion (fr. <ets>movere</ets> to move) + <ets>facere</ets> to make.]</ety> <def>Producing motion.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motile</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"tile</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Motive</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Exhibiting, or capable of, spontaneous movement; <as>as, <ex>motile</ex> bacteria, <ex>motile</ex> protozoa, <ex>motile</ex> cilia, <ex>motile</ex> spores, etc.</as></def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>Producing motion; <as>as, <ex>motile</ex> powers</as>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motile</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"tile</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Psychol.)</fld> <def>A person whose prevailing mental imagery takes the form of inner feelings of action, such as incipient pronunciation of words, muscular innervations, etc.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motility</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*til"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>motilit<eacute/</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>Capability of motion; contractility.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motion</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>motio</ets>, fr. <ets>movere</ets>, <ets>motum</ets>, to move. See <er>Move</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act, process, or state of changing place or position; movement; the passing of a body from one place or position to another, whether voluntary or involuntary; -- opposed to <contr>rest</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Speaking or mute, all comeliness and grace<br/
attends thee, and each word, each <qex>motion</qex>, forms.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Power of, or capacity for, motion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Devoid of sense and <qex>motion</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Direction of movement; course; tendency; <as>as, the <ex>motion</ex> of the planets is from west to east</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In our proper <qex>motion</qex> we ascend.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Change in the relative position of the parts of anything; action of a machine with respect to the relative movement of its parts.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This is the great wheel to which the clock owes its <qex>motion</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Dr. H. More.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Movement of the mind, desires, or passions; mental act, or impulse to any action; internal activity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let a good man obey every good <qex>motion</qex> rising in his heart, knowing that every such <qex>motion</qex> proceeds from God.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A proposal or suggestion looking to action or progress; esp., a formal proposal made in a deliberative assembly; <as>as, a <ex>motion</ex> to adjourn</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yes, I agree, and thank you for your <qex>motion</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>An application made to a court or judge orally in open court.  Its object is to obtain an order or rule directing some act to be done in favor of the applicant.</def>  <rj><au>Mozley & W.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Change of pitch in successive sounds, whether in the same part or in groups of parts.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The independent <qex>motions</qex> of different parts sounding together constitute counterpoint.</q> <rj><qau>Grove.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Conjunct motion</xex> is that by single degrees of the scale. <xex>Contrary motion</xex> is that when parts move in opposite directions. <xex>Disjunct motion</xex> is motion by skips. <xex>Oblique motion</xex> is that when one part is stationary while another moves. <xex>Similar</xex> or <xex>direct motion</xex> is that when parts move in the same direction.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>A puppet show or puppet.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What <qex>motion</qex>'s this? the model of Nineveh?</q> <rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Motion, in mechanics, may be simple or compound. <col><b>Simple motions</b></col> are: (<stype>a</stype>) <xex>straight translation</xex>, which, if of indefinite duration, must be reciprocating. (<stype>b</stype>) <xex>Simple rotation</xex>, which may be either continuous or reciprocating, and when reciprocating is called <xex>oscillating</xex>. (<stype>c</stype>) <xex>Helical</xex>, which, if of indefinite duration, must be reciprocating. <col><b>Compound motion</b></col> consists of combinations of any of the simple motions.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Center of motion</b></col>, <col><b>Harmonic motion</b></col></mcol>, <cd>etc. See under <er>Center</er>, <er>Harmonic</er>, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Motion block</b></col> <fld>(Steam Engine)</fld>, <cd>a crosshead.</cd> -- <col><b>Perpetual motion</b></col> <fld>(Mech.)</fld>, <cd>an incessant motion conceived to be attainable by a machine supplying its own motive forces independently of any action from without.  According to the law of conservation of energy, such perpetual motion is impossible, and no device has yet been built that is capable of perpetual motion.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Movement</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motion</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"tion</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Motioned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Motioning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make a significant movement or gesture, as with the hand; <as>as, to <ex>motion</ex> to one to take a seat</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make proposal; to offer plans.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motion</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"tion</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To direct or invite by a motion, as of the hand or head; <as>as, to <ex>motion</ex> one to a seat</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To propose; to move.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I want friends to <qex>motion</qex> such a matter.</q> <rj><qau>Burton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>motional</ent><br/
<hw>motional</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>of or pertaining to motion.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motioner</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"tion*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who makes a motion; a mover.</def>  <rj><au>Udall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motionist</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"tion*ist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mover.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motionless</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"tion*less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Without motion; being at rest.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motion picture</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"tion pic"ture</hw>. <sn>1.</sn> <def>A series of pictures on a strip of film, taken at regular intervals in rapid succession (now usually 24 frames per second for ordinary work) by a special camera, intended to capture the image of objects in motion.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>the display of the images captured on a <er>motion picture</er>{1}, presented to the eye in very rapid succession by projection from a special apparatus (a <usedby><er>movie projector</er></usedby>), with shows some or all of the objects in the picture represented in changing positions, producing, by persistence of vision, the optical effect of a continuous picture in which the objects appear to move as they did in the original scene.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> movie, moving picture, flick.</syn>
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>  <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The conceptual or informational content of a <er>motion picture</er>{1}; the actions or events represented in a <er>motion picture</er>{1}; the story line of a movie.</def>  <ldquo/One of the great punch lines in <xex>motion picture</xex> history is <lsquo/Round up the usual suspects.' from <lsquo/Casablanca'.<rdquo/ 
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motivate</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ti*vate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>  <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>-vated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>-vating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From <er>Motive</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To provide with a motive; to move; impel; induce; incite.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mo`ti*va"tion</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>  <rj><au>William James.</au></rj><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> move, prompt, incite, induce impel, drive.</syn><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>motivated</ent><br/
<hw>motivated</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Having a strong motive; -- of people.  Opposite of <ant>unmotivated</ant>.</def> [Narrower terms: <stype>driven, impelled</stype>]<br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>motivative</ent><br/
<ent>motivating</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>motivating</hw> <hw>motivative</hw></mhw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>causing motion or impelling to action; providing a motive{2}; <as>as, <ex>motivating</ex> arguments</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> motive(prenominal).</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><q>It may well be that ethical language has primarily a <qex>motivative</qex> function</q> <qau>Arthur Pap</qau></p>

<p><ent>motivation</ent><br/
<hw>motivation</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or process of motivating.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The mental process that arouses an organism to action; <as>as, a large part of a teacher's job is to give students the <ex>motivation</ex> to learn on their own</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> motive, need.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The goal or mental image of a goal that creates a motivation{2}; <as>as, the image of a peaceful world is a powerful <ex>motivation</ex> for only a rare few individuals</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motive</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>motif</ets>, LL. <ets>motivum</ets>, from <ets>motivus</ets> moving, fr. L. <ets>movere</ets>, <ets>motum</ets>, to move. See <er>Move</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which moves; a mover.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which incites to action; anything prompting or exciting to choise, or moving the will; cause; reason; inducement; object; motivation{2}.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By <qex>motive</qex>, I mean the whole of that which <qex>moves</qex>, excites, or invites the mind to volition, whether that be one thing singly, or many things conjunctively.</q> <rj><qau>J. Edwards.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>The theme or subject; a leading phrase or passage which is reproduced and varied through the course of a comor a movement; a short figure, or melodic germ, out of which a whole movement is develpoed. See also <cref>Leading motive</cref>, under <er>Leading</er>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>motivo</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Fine Arts)</fld> <def>That which produces conception, invention, or creation in the mind of the artist in undertaking his subject; the guiding or controlling idea manifested in a work of art, or any part of one.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Incentive; incitement; inducement; reason; spur; stimulus; cause.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Motive</er>, <er>Inducement</er>, <er>Reason</er>. <xex>Motive</xex> is the word originally used in speaking of that which determines the choice.  We call it an <xex>inducement</xex> when it is attractive in its nature.  We call it a <xex>reason</xex> when it is more immediately addressed to the intellect in the form of argument.</usage><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motive</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"tive</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Causing motion; having power to move, or tending to move; <as>as, a <ex>motive</ex> argument; <ex>motive</ex> power</as>.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Motive</xex> faculty.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Bp. Wilkins.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Motive power</b></col> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>a natural agent, as water, steam, wind, electricity, etc., used to impart motion to machinery; a motor; a mover.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motive</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To prompt or incite by a motive or motives; to move.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motiveless</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"tive*less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Destitute of a motive; not incited by a motive.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mo"tive*less*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>  <rj><au>G. Eliot.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motivity</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*tiv"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Motive</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The power of moving or producing motion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The quality of being influenced by motives.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motivo</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo*ti"vo</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It. See <er>Motive</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>See <er>Motive</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 3, 4.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motley</ent><br/
<hw>Mot"ley</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mottelee</ets>, <ets>motle</ets>; cf. OF. <ets>mattel<eacute/</ets> clotted, curdled, OF, ciel <ets>mattonn<eacute/</ets> a mottled sky, <ets>mate</ets>, <ets>maton</ets>, curdled milk, Prov. G. <ets>matte</ets> curd.  Cf. <er>Mottle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Variegated in color; consisting of different colors; dappled; party-colored; <as>as, a <ex>motley</ex> coat</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Wearing motley or party-colored clothing. See <er>Motley</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 1.</def> <ldquo/A <xex>motley</xex> fool.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Composed of different or various parts; heterogeneously made or mixed up; discordantly composite; <as>as, <ex>motley</ex> style</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Byron.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motley</ent><br/
<hw>Mot"ley</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A combination of distinct colors; esp., the party-colored cloth, or clothing, worn by the professional fool.</def> <au>Chaucer.</au> <ldquo/<xex>Motley</xex> 's the only wear.<rdquo/ <au>Shak.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, a jester, a fool.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Man of motley</b></col>, <cd>a fool.</cd> </cs><mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <au>Beau. & Fl.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>motley collection</ent><br/
<hw>mot"ley col*lec"tion</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A collection of objects of various kinds; a hodgepodge; a medley; a confused mixture; an omnium gatherum.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motley-minded</ent><br/
<hw>Mot"ley-mind`ed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having a mind of a jester; foolish.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motmot</ent><br/
<hw>Mot"mot</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Momot</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of several species of long-tailed, passerine birds of the genus <gen>Momotus</gen>, having a strong serrated beak.  In most of the species the two long middle tail feathers are racket-shaped at the tip, when mature.  The bird itself is said by some writers to trim them into this shape.  They feed on insects, reptiles, and fruit, and are found from Mexico to Brazil.  The name is derived from its note.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>momot</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moto</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mo"to</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Movement; manner of movement; particularly, movement with increased rapidity; -- used especially in the phrase <xex>con moto</xex>, directing to a somewhat quicker movement; <as>as, <ex>andante con moto</ex>, a little more rapidly than <ex>andante</ex>, etc.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motograph</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"to*graph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>movere</ets>, <ets>motum</ets>, to move + <ets>-graph</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>A device utilized in the making of a loud-speaking telephone, depending on the fact that the friction between a metallic point and a moving cylinder of moistened chalk, or a moving slip of paper, on which it rests is diminished by the passage of a current between the point and the moving surface.</def> <mark>[obsolescent]</mark> -- <wordforms><wf>Mo`to*graph"ic</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moton</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"ton</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Etymol. uncertain.]</ety> <fld>(Anc. Armor)</fld> <def>A small plate covering the armpit in armor of the 14th century and later.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motor</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. <ets>movere</ets>, <ets>motum</ets>, to move.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, imparts motion; a source of mechanical power.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>A prime mover; a machine by means of which a source of power, as steam, moving water, electricity, etc., is made available for doing mechanical work.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn>  <def>A motor car; an automobile.</def> <mark>[archiac Colloq.]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motorial</ent><br/
<ent>Motory</ent><br/
<ent>Motor</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mo"tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mo"to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mo*to"ri*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>motorius</ets> that has motion. See <er>Motor</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>Causing or setting up motion; pertaining to organs of motion; -- applied especially in physiology to those nerves or nerve fibers which only convey impressions from a nerve center to muscles, thereby causing motion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>motorboat</ent><br/
<hw>motorboat</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a boat propelled by an internal-combustion engine driving propellers immersed in the water.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> powerboat.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>motorbus</ent><br/
<hw>motorbus</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a road vehicle carrying many passengers; used for public transport; an omnibus.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> bus, autobus, coach, charabanc, double-decker, jitney, motorcoach, omnibus.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>motorcade</ent><br/
<hw>motorcade</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a procession of people traveling in motor cars.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motorcar</ent><br/
<ent>Motor car</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Motor car</hw>, <it>or</it> <hw>Mo"tor*car`</hw> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An automobile, locomobile, or locomotive designed to run and be steered on a street or roadway; esp., an automobile specially designed for passengers and propelled by an internal combustion engine.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> car, auto, automobile, machine.</syn><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <fld>(Elec. Railroads)</fld> <def>Any car containing motors for propulsion.</def> <mark>[U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motorbike</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"tor*bike`</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>a light two-wheeled vehicle containing a motor for propulsion.  It is lighter in construction and has a lower speed than a <er>motorcycle</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <def>a small motorcycle with a low frame and small weels and elevated handlebars.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> minibike.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <def>a bicyle with a motor attached for propulsion.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>motorcoach</ent><br/
<hw>motorcoach</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a <er>motorbus</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> bus, autobus, coach, charabanc, double-decker, jitney, motorbus, omnibus.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>motor cycle</ent><br/
<ent>motorcycle</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>mo"tor*cy`cle</hw>, <it>or</it>  <hw>mo"tor cy`cle</hw> }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A two-wheeled vehicle having a motor attached so as to be self-propelled.  In common usage, a <ex>motorcycle</ex> is of heavier construction with larger wheels, a more powerful motor, and a higher maximum speed than a <er>motorbike</er>.</def> <note>A motorcycle may have a small appended compartment called a <part>sidecar</part>, supported by a third wheel, which can carry a passenger.</note><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><note>In Great Britain as of 1913 the term <xex>motor cycle</xex> was treated by statute (<au>3 Ed VII. c. 36</au>) as limited to motor cars (self-propelled vehicles) designed to travel on not more than three wheels, and weighing unladen (that is, without water, fuel, or accumulators necessary for propulsion) not more than three hundred weight (336 lbs.).</note><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>motorcycle</ent><br/
<hw>motorcycle</hw> <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>to ride a motorcycle.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> cycle.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>motorcycling</ent><br/
<hw>motorcycling</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The process of riding a motocycle.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>travel on a motorcycle.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>motorcyclist</ent><br/
<hw>mo"tor*cyc`list</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A person who rides a motorcycle.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> biker, cyclist.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>motor-driven</ent><br/
<hw>mo`tor-driv`en</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>Driven or actuated by a motor, esp. by an individual electric motor. An electric motor forms an integral part of many machine tools in numerous modern machine shops.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>motored</ent><br/
<hw>motored</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>equipped with a motor or motors; motorized.  Opposite of <ant>unmotorized</ant>.</def> [Narrower terms: <stype>bimotored</stype>; <stype>trimotored </stype>]<br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motor generator</ent><br/
<hw>Motor generator</hw>. <def>The combination consisting of a generator and a driving motor mechanically connected, usually on a common bedplate and with the two shafts directly coupled or combined into a single shaft.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motoring</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"tor*ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>the act or recreation of riding in or driving a motor car or automobile.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motoring</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"tor*ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to motor cars or automobiles, or to the technology of such; addicted to riding in or driving automobiles; <as>as, <ex>motoring</ex> parlance; my <ex>motoring</ex> friend</as>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>motorisation</ent><br/
<hw>motorisation</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>motorization.</def> <mark>[Chiefly Brit.]</mark> <br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motorise</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"tor*ise</hw> <pr>(m<omac/"t<etil/r*<imac/z)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>same as <er>motorize</er>.</def> <mark>[Brit.]</mark><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>motorization</ent><br/
<hw>motorization</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the act of motorizing (equiping with motors or with motor vehicles).</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> motorisation.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motorize</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"tor*ize</hw> <pr>(m<omac/"t<etil/r*<imac/z)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>  <ety>[<ets>Motor</ets> + <ets>-ize</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To substitute motor-driven vehicles, or automobiles, for the horses and horse-drawn vehicles of (a fire department, city, etc.).</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark> -- <wordforms><wf>Mo`tor*i*za"tion</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>to equip (a piece of machinery) with a motor.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>to provide with automobiles or other motor vehicles; <as>as, a <ex>motorized</ex> army division</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mechanize.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>motorized</ent><br/
<hw>motorized</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>same as <er>motored</er>; <as>as, a <ex>motorized</ex> wheelchair</as>.  Opposite of <ant>unmotorized</ant>.</def> [Narrower terms: <stype>bimotored </stype>; <stype>trimotored </stype>]<br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> motored.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>Equipped with vehicles to permit rapid movement from place to place.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mechanized.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>motorless</ent><br/
<hw>motorless</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>having no motor.  Opposite of <ant>motorized</ant>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> unmotorized.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motorman</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"tor*man</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A man who controls a motor.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>an operator of a motor vehicle, especially of a streetcar or subway train.</def> <br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motormouth</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"tor*mouth</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>a person who talks excessively.</def> <mark>[derogatory]</mark> <br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motorpathic</ent><br/
<hw>Mo`tor*path"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to motorpathy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motorpathy</ent><br/
<hw>Mo*tor"pa*thy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>motor</ets> a mover + Gr. <?/, <?/, to suffer.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>same as <er>Kinesiatrics</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motte</ent><br/
<hw>Motte</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>motte</ets> a clod, clump, or hillock.]</ety> <def>A clump of trees in a prairie.</def> <mark>[Local, U.S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mottle</ent><br/
<hw>Mot"tle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mottled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mottling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From <er>Mottled</er>.]</ety> <def>To mark with spots of different color, or shades of color, as if stained; to spot; to maculate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mottle</ent><br/
<hw>Mot"tle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mottled appearance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mottled</ent><br/
<hw>Mot"tled</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Motley</er>.]</ety> <def>Marked with spots of different colors; variegated; spotted; <as>as, <ex>mottled</ex> wood</as>.</def> <ldquo/The <xex>mottled</xex> meadows.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Drayton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mottling</ent><br/
<hw>mottling</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>the act of coloring with areas of different shades.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A mottled pattern.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motto</ent><br/
<hw>Mot"to</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mottoes</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[It. <ets>motto</ets> a word, a saying, L. <ets>muttum</ets> a mutter, a grunt, cf. <ets>muttire</ets>, <ets>mutire</ets>, to mutter, mumble; prob. of imitative origin.  Cf. <er>Mot</er> a word.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>A sentence, phrase, or word, forming part of an heraldic achievment.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A sentence, phrase, or word, prefixed to an essay, discourse, chapter, canto, or the like, suggestive of its subject matter; a short, suggestive expression of a guiding principle; a maxim.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was the <qex>motto</qex> of a bishop eminent for his piety and good works, . . . <ldquo/Serve God, and be cheerful.<rdquo/</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mottoed</ent><br/
<hw>Mot"toed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Bearing or having a motto; <as>as, a <ex>mottoed</ex> coat or device</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motty</ent><br/
<hw>Mot"ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Full of, or consisting of, motes.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mottie</asp>.]</altsp> <mark>[Scot.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>motty</qex> dust reek raised by the workmen.</q> <rj><qau>H. Miller.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouchoir</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mou`choir"</hw> <pr>(m<oomac/`shw<aum/r")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>A handkerchief.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouezzin</ent><br/
<hw>Mou*ez"zin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>See <er>Muezzin</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouflon</ent><br/
<hw>Mouf"lon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mouflon</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A wild sheep (<spn>Ovis musimon</spn>), inhabiting the mountains of Sardinia, Corsica, etc.  Its horns are very large, with a triangular base and rounded angles.  It is supposed by some to be the original of the domestic sheep.  Called also <altname>musimon</altname> or <altname>musmon</altname>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>moufflon</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mought</ent><br/
<hw>Mought</hw> <pr>(mout)</pr>, <mark>obs.</mark> <pos>imp.</pos> <mord>of <er>May</er>.</mord> <def>Might.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouillation</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mouil*la"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mouill<eacute/</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Phon.)</fld> <def>The act of uttering the sound of a mouill<eacute/ letter.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouille</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mouil`l<eacute/"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F., lit., wet.]</ety> <fld>(Phon.)</fld> <def>Applied to certain consonants having a <ldquo/liquid<rdquo/ or softened sound; <it>e. g.</it>, in French, <it>l</it> or <it>ll</it> and <it>gn</it> (like the <it>lli</it> in <xex>million</xex> and <it>ni</it> in <xex>minion</xex>); in Italian, <it>gl</it> and <it>gn</it>; in Spanish, <it>ll</it> and <it><ntil/</it>; in Portuguese, <it>lh</it> and <it>nh.</it></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouldy</ent><br/
<ent>Moulder</ent><br/
<ent>Mould</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mould</hw> <pr>(m<omac/lt)</pr>, <hw>Mould"er</hw> <pr>(m<omac/ld"<etil/r)</pr>, <hw>Mould"y</hw> <pr>(m<omac/ld"<ycr/)</pr>, etc. }</mhw> <def>See <er>Mold</er>, <er>Molder</er>, <er>Moldy</er>, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moulding</ent><br/
<hw>moulding</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>a sculpture produced by molding.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mold, mould, molding, modeling, clay sculpture.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>a decorative recessed or relieved surface.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> molding, border.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>a decorative strip used for ornamentation or finishing.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> molding.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>a preliminary sculpture in wax or clay from which a finished work can be copied.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> modeling, molding.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moule</ent><br/
<hw>Moule</hw> <pr>(m<omac/l)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>moulen</ets>. See <er>Mold</er>.]</ety> <def>To contract mold; to grow moldy; to mold.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let us not <qex>moulen</qex> thus in idleness.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moulinet</ent><br/
<ent>Mouline</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mou*line"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mou"li*net</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>moulinet</ets>, orig., a little mill, dim. of <ets>moulin</ets> mill. See <er>Mill</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The drum upon which the rope is wound in a capstan, crane, or the like.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A machine formerly used for bending a crossbow by winding it up.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>In sword and saber exercises, a circular swing of the weapon.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moult</ent><br/
<hw>Moult</hw> <pr>(m<omac/lt)</pr>, <pos>v. & n.</pos> <def>See <er>Molt</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moulten</ent><br/
<hw>Moult"en</hw> <pr>(m<omac/lt'n)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having molted.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/A <xex>moulten</xex> raven.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moun</ent><br/
<hw>Moun</hw> <pr>(moun)</pr>, <pos>v.</pos>, <def><pos>pl.</pos> of <er>Mow</er>, may.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Wyclif.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mounch</ent><br/
<hw>Mounch</hw> <pr>(mounch)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To munch.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mound</ent><br/
<hw>Mound</hw> <pr>(mound)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>monde</ets> the world, L. <ets>mundus</ets>. See <er>Mundane</er>.]</ety> <def>A ball or globe forming part of the regalia of an emperor or other sovereign.  It is encircled with bands, enriched with precious stones, and surmounted with a cross; -- called also <altname>globe</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mound</ent><br/
<hw>Mound</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mound</ets>, <ets>mund</ets>, protection, AS. <ets>mund</ets> protection, hand; akin to OHG. <ets>munt</ets>, Icel. <ets>mund</ets> hand, and prob. to L. <ets>manus</ets>. See <er>Manual</er>.]</ety> <def>An artificial hill or elevation of earth; a raised bank; an embarkment thrown up for defense; a bulwark; a rampart; also, a natural elevation appearing as if thrown up artificially; a regular and isolated hill, hillock, or knoll.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To thrid the thickets or to leap the <qex>mounds</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mound bird</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See <er>moundbird</er> in the vocabulary.</cd> -- <col><b>Mound builders</b></col> <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld>, <cd>the tribe, or tribes, of North American aborigines who built, in former times, extensive mounds of earth, esp. in the valleys of the Mississippi and Ohio Rivers.  Formerly they were supposed to have preceded the Indians, but later investigations go to show that they were, in general, identical with the tribes that occupied the country when discovered by Europeans.</cd> -- <col><b>Mound maker</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one of the <er>megapodes</er>.  See also <er>moundbird</er> in the vocabulary.</cd> -- <col><b>Shell mound</b></col>, <cd>a mound of refuse shells, collected by aborigines who subsisted largely on shellfish. See <er>Midden</er>, and <er>Kitchen middens</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mound</ent><br/
<hw>Mound</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mounded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mounding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To fortify or inclose with a mound.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mound bird</ent><br/
<ent>moundbird</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>moundbird</hw>, <hw>mound bird</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any of several large-footed short-winged birds of Australasia, which build mounds of decaying vegetation to incubate eggs.  Called also <altname>mound builder</altname>, <altname>mound maker</altname>, <altname>megapode</altname>, <altname>brush turkey</altname>, and <altname>scrub fowl</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> megapode, mound builder, scrub fowl, brush turkey.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mount</ent><br/
<hw>Mount</hw> <pr>(mount)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>munt</ets>, <ets>mont</ets>, <ets>mount</ets>, AS. <ets>munt</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mons</ets>, <ets>montis</ets>; cf. L. <ets>minae</ets> protections, E. <ets>eminent</ets>, <ets>menace</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mont</ets>.  Cf. <er>Mount</er>, <pos>v.</pos>, <er>Mountain</er>, <er>Mont</er>, <er>Monte</er>, <er>Montem</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A mass of earth, or earth and rock, rising considerably above the common surface of the surrounding land; a mountain; a high hill; -- used always instead of <xex>mountain</xex>, when put before a proper name; <as>as, <ex>Mount</ex> Washington</as>; otherwise, chiefly in poetry.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A bulwark for offense or defense; a mound.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hew ye down trees, and cast a <qex>mount</qex> against Jerusalem.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. vi. 6.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <ety>[See <er>Mont de pi<eacute/t<eacute/</er>.]</ety> <def>A bank; a fund.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Palmistry)</fld> <def>Any one of seven fleshy prominences in the palm of the hand which are taken as significant of the influence of <ldquo/planets,<rdquo/ and called the <xex>mounts</xex> of Jupiter, Mars, Mercury, the Moon, Saturn, the Sun or Apollo, and Venus.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mount of piety</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Mont de pi<eacute/t<eacute/</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mount</ent><br/
<hw>Mount</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mounted</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mounting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>mounten</ets>, <ets>monten</ets>, F. <ets>monter</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mons</ets>, <ets>montis</ets>, mountain. See <er>Mount</er>, <pos>n.</pos> (above).]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To rise on high; to go up; to be upraised or uplifted; to tower aloft; to ascend; -- often with <xex>up</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though Babylon should <qex>mount</qex> up to heaven.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. li. 53.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The fire of trees and houses <qex>mounts</qex> on high.</q> <rj><qau>Cowley.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To get up on anything, as a platform or scaffold; especially, to seat one's self on a horse for riding.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To attain in value; to amount.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bring then these blessings to a strict account,<br/
Make fair deductions, see to what they <qex>mount</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mount</ent><br/
<hw>Mount</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To get upon; to ascend; to climb; <as>as, to <ex>mount</ex> the pulpit and deliver a sermon</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Shall we <qex>mount</qex> again the rural throne?</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To place one's self on, as a horse or other animal, or anything that one sits upon; to bestride.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to mount; to put on horseback; to furnish with animals for riding; to furnish with horses.</def> <ldquo/To <xex>mount</xex> the Trojan troop.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Hence: To put upon anything that sustains and fits for use, as a gun on a carriage, a map or picture on cloth or paper; to prepare for being worn or otherwise used, as a diamond by setting, or a sword blade by adding the hilt, scabbard, etc.; <as>as, to <ex>mount</ex> a picture or diploma in  a frame</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To raise aloft; to lift on high.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What power is it which <qex>mounts</qex> my love so high?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ A fort or ship is said to <xex>mount</xex> cannon, when it has them arranged for use in or about it.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To mount guard</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>to go on guard; to march on guard; to do duty as a guard.</cd> -- <col><b>To mount a play</b></col>, <cd>to prepare and arrange the scenery, furniture, etc., used in the play.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mount</ent><br/
<hw>Mount</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mount</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <def>That upon which a person or thing is mounted</def>, <specif>especially:</specif> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A horse.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She had so good a seat and hand, she might be trusted with any <qex>mount</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>G. Eliot.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>The cardboard or cloth on which a drawing, photograph, or the like is mounted; a mounting.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mountable</ent><br/
<hw>Mount"a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Such as can be mounted.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mountain</ent><br/
<hw>Moun"tain</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mountaine</ets>, <ets>montaine</ets>, F. <ets>montagne</ets>, LL. <ets>montanea</ets>, <ets>montania</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mons</ets>, <ets>montis</ets>, a mountain; cf. <ets>montanus</ets> belonging to a mountain. See 1st <er>Mount</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A large mass of earth and rock, rising above the common level of the earth or adjacent land; earth and rock forming an isolated peak or a ridge; an eminence higher than a hill; a mount.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>A range, chain, or group of such elevations; <as>as, the White <ex>Mountains</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A mountainlike mass; something of great bulk; a large quantity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I should have been a <qex>mountain</qex> of mummy.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The Mountain</b></col> (<au>La montagne</au>) <fld>(French Hist.)</fld>, <cd>a popular name given in 1793 to a party of extreme Jacobins in the National Convention, who occupied the highest rows of seats.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 949 --></p>

<p><ent>Mountain</ent><br/
<hw>Moun"tain</hw> <pr>(moun"t<icr/n)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a mountain or mountains; growing or living on a mountain; found on or peculiar to mountains; among mountains; <as>as, a <ex>mountain</ex> torrent; <ex>mountain</ex> pines; <ex>mountain</ex> goats; <ex>mountain</ex> air; <ex>mountain</ex> howitzer.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Like a mountain; mountainous; vast; very great.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The high, the <qex>mountain</qex> majesty of worth.</q> <rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mountain antelope</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the goral.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain ash</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>an ornamental tree, the <spn>Pyrus Americana</spn> (or <spn>Sorbus Americana</spn>), producing beautiful bunches of red berries. Its leaves are pinnate, and its flowers white, growing in fragrant clusters. The European species is the <spn>Pyrus aucuparia</spn>, or rowan tree.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain barometer</b></col>, <cd>a portable barometer, adapted for safe transportation, used in measuring the heights of mountains.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain beaver</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the sewellel.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain blue</b></col> <fld>(Min.)</fld>, <cd>blue carbonate of copper; azurite.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain cat</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the catamount. See <er>Catamount</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain chain</b></col>, <cd>a series of contiguous mountain ranges, generally in parallel or consecutive lines or curves.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain cock</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>capercailzie. See <er>Capercailzie</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain cork</b></col> <fld>(Min.)</fld>, <cd>a variety of asbestus, resembling cork in its texture.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain crystal</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Crystal</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain damson</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a large tree of the genus <gen>Simaruba</gen> (<spn>Simaruba amarga</spn>) growing in the West Indies, which affords a bitter tonic and astringent, sometimes used in medicine.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain dew</b></col>, <cd>Scotch whisky, so called because often illicitly distilled among the mountains.</cd> <mark>[Humorous]</mark> -- <col><b>Mountain ebony</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a small leguminous tree (<spn>Bauhinia variegata</spn>) of the East and West Indies; -- so called because of its dark wood. The bark is used medicinally and in tanning.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain flax</b></col> <fld>(Min.)</fld>, <cd>a variety of asbestus, having very fine fibers; amianthus. See <er>Amianthus</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain fringe</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>climbing fumitory. See under <er>Fumitory</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain goat</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Mazama</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain green</b></col>. <fld>(Min.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>Green malachite, or carbonate of copper</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>See <cref>Green earth</cref>, under <er>Green</er>, <pos>a.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>Mountain holly</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a branching shrub (<spn>Nemopanthes Canadensis</spn>), having smooth oblong leaves and red berries.  It is found in the Northern United States.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain laurel</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>an American shrub (<spn>Kalmia latifolia</spn>) with glossy evergreen leaves and showy clusters of rose-colored or white flowers.  The foliage is poisonous.  Called also <altname>American laurel</altname>, <altname>ivy bush</altname>, and <altname>calico bush</altname>.  See <er>Kalmia</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain leather</b></col> <fld>(Min.)</fld>, <cd>a variety of asbestus, resembling leather in its texture.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain licorice</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a plant of the genus <gen>Trifolium</gen> (<spn>Trifolium Alpinum</spn>).</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain limestone</b></col> <fld>(Geol.)</fld>, <cd>a series of marine limestone strata below the coal measures, and above the old red standstone of Great Britain.  See <xex>Chart</xex> of <er>Geology</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain linnet</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the twite.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain magpie</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The yaffle, or green woodpecker</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>The European gray shrike.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain mahogany</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Mahogany</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain meal</b></col> <fld>(Min.)</fld>, <cd>a light powdery variety of calcite, occurring as an efflorescence.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain milk</b></col> <fld>(Min.)</fld>, <cd>a soft spongy variety of carbonate of lime.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain mint</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Mint</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain ousel</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the ring ousel; -- called also <altname>mountain thrush</altname> and <altname>mountain colley</altname>.  See <er>Ousel</er>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Mountain pride</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Mountain green</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a tree of Jamaica (<spn>Spathelia simplex</spn>), which has an unbranched palmlike stem, and a terminal cluster of large, pinnate leaves.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain quail</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the plumed partridge (<spn>Oreortyx pictus</spn>) of California.  It has two long, slender, plumelike feathers on the head.  The throat and sides are chestnut; the belly is brown with transverse bars of black and white; the neck and breast are dark gray.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain range</b></col>, <cd>a series of mountains closely related in position and direction.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain rice</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>An upland variety of rice, grown without irrigation, in some parts of Asia, Europe, and the United States</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>An American genus of grasses (<gen>Oryzopsis</gen>).</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain rose</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a species of rose with solitary flowers, growing in the mountains of Europe (<spn>Rosa alpina</spn>).</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain soap</b></col> <fld>(Min.)</fld>, <cd>a soft earthy mineral, of a brownish color, used in crayon painting; saxonite.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain sorrel</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a low perennial plant (<spn>Oxyria digyna</spn> with rounded kidney-form leaves, and small greenish flowers, found in the White Mountains of New Hampshire, and in high northern latitudes.</cd> <au>Gray.</au> -- <col><b>Mountain sparrow</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the European tree sparrow.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain spinach</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Orach</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain tobacco</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a composite plant (<spn>Arnica montana</spn>) of Europe; called also <altname>leopard's bane</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mountain witch</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a ground pigeon of Jamaica, of the genus <gen>Geotrygon</gen>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mountaineer</ent><br/
<hw>Moun`tain*eer"</hw> <pr>(moun`t<icr/n*<emac/r")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>montanier</ets>, LL. <ets>montanarius</ets>. See <er>Mountain</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An inhabitant of a mountain; one who lives among mountains.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A rude, fierce person.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No savage fierce, bandit, or <qex>mountaineer</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A person who climbs mountains for sport.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mountaineer</ent><br/
<hw>moun`tain*eer"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To live or act as a mountaineer; to climb mountains.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You can't go <qex>mountaineering</qex> in a flat country.</q> <rj><qau>H. James.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mountaineering</ent><br/
<hw>moun`tain*eer"ing</hw> <pr>(moun`t<icr/n*<emac/r"<icr/ng)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Climbing mountains as a sport.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mountainer</ent><br/
<hw>Moun"tain*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mountaineer.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mountainet</ent><br/
<hw>Moun"tain*et</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A small mountain.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mountainous</ent><br/
<hw>Moun"tain*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>montagneux</ets>, L. <ets>montaniosus</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Full of, or containing, mountains; <as>as, the <ex>mountainous</ex> country of the Swiss</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Inhabiting mountains.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Large as, or resembling, a mountain; huge; of great bulk; <as>as, a <ex>mountainous</ex> heap</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Prior.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mountainousness</ent><br/
<hw>Moun"tain*ous*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state or quality of being mountainous.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mountance</ent><br/
<hw>Mount"ance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>montance</ets>.]</ety> <def>Amount; sum; quantity; extent.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mountain specter</ent><br/
<hw>Moun"tain spec"ter</hw>. <def>An optical phenomenon sometimes seen on the summit of mountains (as on the Brocken) when the observer is between the sun and a mass of cloud.  The figures of the observer and surrounding objects are seen projected on the cloud, greatly enlarged and often encircled by rainbow colors.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mountain State</ent><br/
<hw>Moun"tain State</hw>. <def>Montana; -- a nickname.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mountant</ent><br/
<hw>Mount"ant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>montant</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>monter</ets>. See <er>Mount</er>, and cf. <er>Montant</er>.]</ety> <def>Raised; high.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mountebank</ent><br/
<hw>Mount"e*bank</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It. <ets>montimbanco</ets>, <ets>montambanco</ets>; <ets>montare</ets> to mount + <ets>in</ets> in, upon + <ets>banco</ets> bench. See <er>Mount</er>, and 4th <er>Bank</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who mounts a bench or stage in the market or other public place, boasts of his skill in curing diseases, and vends medicines which he pretends are infallible remedies; a quack doctor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such is the weakness and easy credulity of men, that a <qex>mountebank</qex> . . . is preferred before an able physician.</q> <rj><qau>Whitlock.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any boastful or false pretender; a charlatan; a quack.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nothing so impossible in nature but <qex>mountebanks</qex> will undertake.</q> <rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mountebank</ent><br/
<hw>Mount"e*bank</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cheat by boasting and false pretenses; to gull.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mountebank</ent><br/
<hw>Mount"e*bank</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To play the mountebank.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mountebankery</ent><br/
<hw>Mount"e*bank`er*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The practices of a mountebank; quackery; boastful and vain pretenses.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mountebankish</ent><br/
<hw>Mount"e*bank`ish</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Like a mountebank or his quackery.</def>  <rj><au>Howell.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mountebankism</ent><br/
<hw>Mount"e*bank*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The practices of a mountebank; mountebankery.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mounted</ent><br/
<hw>Mount"ed</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Seated or serving on horseback or similarly; <as>as, <ex>mounted</ex> police; <ex>mounted</ex> infantry.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Placed on a suitable support, or fixed in a setting; <as>as, a <ex>mounted</ex> gun; a <ex>mounted</ex> map; a <ex>mounted</ex> gem.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mountenaunce</ent><br/
<hw>Mount"e*naunce</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mountance.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mounter</ent><br/
<hw>Mount"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who mounts.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An animal mounted; a monture.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mounting</ent><br/
<hw>Mount"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of one that mounts.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That by which anything is prepared for use, or set off to advantage; equipment; embellishment; setting; <as>as, the <ex>mounting</ex> of a sword or diamond</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Aeronautics)</fld> <def>same as  <er>Carriage</er>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mountingly</ent><br/
<hw>Mount"ing*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In an ascending manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mountlet</ent><br/
<hw>Mount"let</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A small or low mountain.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mounty</ent><br/
<hw>Mount"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mont<eacute/e</ets>, fr. <ets>monter</ets>. See <er>Mount</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <def>The rise of a hawk after prey.</def>  <rj><au>Sir P. Sidney.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mourn</ent><br/
<hw>Mourn</hw> <pr>(m<omac/rn)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mourned</conjf> <pr>(m<omac/rnd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mourning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>murnan</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>mornian</ets>, OHG. <ets>mornen</ets>, Goth. <ets>ma<uacute/rnan</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To express or to feel grief or sorrow; to grieve; to be sorrowful; to lament; to be in a state of grief or sadness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Abraham came to <qex>mourn</qex> for Sarah, and to weep for her.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. xxiii. 2.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To wear the customary garb of a mourner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We <qex>mourn</qex> in black; why <qex>mourn</qex> we not in blood?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Grieve for an hour, perhaps, then <qex>mourn</qex> a year.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mourn</ent><br/
<hw>Mourn</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To grieve for; to lament; to deplore; to bemoan; to bewail.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As if he <qex>mourned</qex> his rival's ill success.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And looking over the hills, I <qex>mourn</qex><br/
The darling who shall not return.</q> <rj><qau>Emerson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To utter in a mournful manner or voice.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The lovelorn nightingale<br/
Nightly to thee her sad song <qex>mourneth</qex> well.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Deplore</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mourne</ent><br/
<hw>Mourne</hw> <pr>(m<omac/rn)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See 2d <er>Morne</er>.]</ety> <def>The armed or feruled end of a staff; in a sheephook, the end of the staff to which the hook is attached.</def>  <rj><au>Sir P. Sidney.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mourner</ent><br/
<hw>Mourn"er</hw> <pr>(m<omac/rn"<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who mourns or is grieved at any misfortune, as the death of a friend.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His <qex>mourners</qex> were two hosts, his friends and foes.</q> <rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who attends a funeral as a hired mourner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mourners</qex> were provided to attend the funeral.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mournful</ent><br/
<hw>Mourn"ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Full of sorrow; expressing, or intended to express, sorrow; mourning; grieving; sad; also, causing sorrow; saddening; grievous; <as>as, a <ex>mournful</ex> person; <ex>mournful</ex> looks, tones, loss.</as></def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mourn"ful*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mourn"ful*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Sorrowful; lugubrious; sad; doleful; heavy; afflictive; grievous; calamitous.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mourning</ent><br/
<hw>Mourn"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>murnung</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of sorrowing or expressing grief; lamentation; sorrow.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Garb, drapery, or emblems indicative of grief, esp. clothing or a badge of somber black.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The houses to their tops with black were spread,<br/
And ev'n the pavements were with <qex>mourning</qex> hid.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Deep mourning</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Deep</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mourning</ent><br/
<hw>Mourn"ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Grieving; sorrowing; lamenting.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Employed to express sorrow or grief; worn or used as appropriate to the condition of one bereaved or sorrowing; <as>as, <ex>mourning</ex> garments; a <ex>mourning</ex> ring; a <ex>mourning</ex> pin, and the like.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mourning bride</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a garden flower (<spn>Scabiosa atropurpurea</spn>) with dark purple or crimson flowers in flattened heads.</cd> -- <col><b>Mourning dove</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a wild dove (<spn>Zenaidura macroura</spn>) found throughout the United States; -- so named from its plaintive note. Called also <altname>Carolina dove</altname>. See <xex>Illust.</xex> under <er>Dove</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mourning warbler</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>an American ground warbler (<spn>Geothlypis Philadelphia</spn>).  The male has the head, neck, and chest, deep ash-gray, mixed with black on the throat and chest; other lower parts are pure yellow.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mourningly</ent><br/
<hw>Mourn"ing*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a mourning manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mournival</ent><br/
<hw>Mour"ni*val</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Murnival</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouse</ent><br/
<hw>Mouse</hw> <pr>(mous)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mice</plw> <pr>(m<imac/s)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>mous</ets>, <ets>mus</ets>, AS. <ets>m<umac/s</ets>, pl. <ets>m<ymac/s</ets>; akin to D. <ets>muis</ets>, G. <ets>maus</ets>, OHG. & Icel. <ets>m<umac/s</ets>, Dan. <ets>muus</ets>, Sw. <ets>mus</ets>, Russ. <ets>muishe</ets>, L. <ets>mus</ets>, Gr. <grk>my^s</grk>, Skr. <ets>m<umac/sh</ets> mouse, <ets>mush</ets> to steal. <root/277.  Cf. <er>Muscle</er>, <er>Musk</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of numerous species of small rodents belonging to the genus <gen>Mus</gen> and various related genera of the family <fam>Muridae</fam>.  The common house mouse (<spn>Mus musculus</spn>) is found in nearly all countries.  The American <stype>white-footed mouse</stype>, or <stype>deer mouse</stype> (<spn>Peromyscus leucopus</spn>, formerly <spn>Hesperomys leucopus</spn>) sometimes lives in houses.  See <er>Dormouse</er>, <cref>Meadow mouse</cref>, under <er>Meadow</er>, and <cref>Harvest mouse</cref>, under <er>Harvest</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A knob made on a rope with spun yarn or parceling to prevent a running eye from slipping.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Same as 2d <er>Mousing</er>, 2.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A familiar term of endearment.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A dark-colored swelling caused by a blow.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A match used in firing guns or blasting.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Field mouse</b></col>, <col><b>Flying mouse</b></col></mcol>, etc. <cd>See under <er>Field</er>, <er>Flying</er>, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Mouse bird</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a coly.</cd> -- <col><b>Mouse deer</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a chevrotain, as the kanchil.</cd> -- <col><b>Mouse galago</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a very small West American galago (<spn>Galago murinus</spn>). In color and size it resembles a mouse. It has a bushy tail like that of a squirrel.</cd> -- <col><b>Mouse hawk</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A hawk that devours mice</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>The hawk owl; -- called also <altname>mouse owl</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mouse lemur</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one of several species of very small lemurs of the genus <gen>Chirogaleus</gen>, found in Madagascar.</cd> -- <col><b>Mouse piece</b></col> <fld>(Cookery)</fld>, <cd>the piece of beef cut from the part next below the round or from the lower part of the latter; -- called also <altname>mouse buttock</altname>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouse</ent><br/
<hw>Mouse</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Moused</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mousing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To watch for and catch mice.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To watch for or pursue anything in a sly manner; to pry about, on the lookout for something.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouse</ent><br/
<hw>Mouse</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To tear, as a cat devours a mouse.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/[Death] <xex>mousing</xex> the flesh of men.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To furnish with a mouse; to secure by means of a mousing. See <er>Mouse</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 2.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouse-ear</ent><br/
<hw>Mouse"-ear`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The forget-me-not (<spn>Myosotis palustris</spn>) and other species of the same genus.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A European species of hawkweed (<spn>Hieracium Pilosella</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mouse-ear chickweed</b></col>, <cd>a name of two common species of chickweed (<spn>Cerastium vulgarium</spn>, and <spn>Cerastium viscosum</spn>).</cd> -- <col><b>Mouse-ear cress</b></col>, <cd>a low cruciferous herb (<spn>Sisymbrium Thaliana</spn>). All these are low herbs with soft, oval, or obovate leaves, whence the name.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mousefish</ent><br/
<hw>Mouse"fish`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Frogfish</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mousehole</ent><br/
<hw>Mouse"hole`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A hole made by a mouse, for passage or abode, as in a wall; hence, a very small hole like that gnawed by a mouse.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mousekin</ent><br/
<hw>mouse"kin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A little mouse.</def>  <rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mouseketeer</ent><br/
<hw>mouse"ke*teer`</hw> <pr>(mous"k<ecr/*t<emac/r`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One of a group of children appearing on the television program <membof>The Mickey Mouse Club</membof> in the 1950's.</def> <mark>[U. S.]</mark> <br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouser</ent><br/
<hw>Mous"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A cat that catches mice; <as>as, a good <ex>mouser</ex> is better than a dozen mousetraps</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who pries about on the lookout for something.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mousetail</ent><br/
<hw>Mouse"tail`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of ranunculaceous plants (<gen>Myosurus</gen>), in which the prolonged receptacle is covered with imbricating achenes, and so resembles the tail of a mouse.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mouse trap</ent><br/
<ent>mousetrap</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mouse"trap`</hw>, <hw>mouse" trap`</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Any device that catches, and usually kills, mice.  They are of various designs, the most common being a stiff loop of wire mounted on a small wooden platform base and attached to a strong spring, which holds the loop firmly against the base.  To activate the trap, the loop is pulled through a 180<deg/ arc against the tension of the spring and held against the base by a delicate metal catch, which can keep the loop from moving, though in a state of high tension.  The metal catch is moved when a mouse tries to take a piece of bait attached to it, releasing the loop which forcefully moves though an arc, usually killing the mouse.  A larger version of the same device is used as a <contr>rat trap</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mousie</ent><br/
<hw>Mous"ie</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Diminutive for <er>Mouse</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Burns.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mousing</ent><br/
<hw>Mous"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Impertinently inquisitive; prying; meddlesome.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Mousing</xex> saints.<rdquo/  <rj><au>L'Estrange.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mousing</ent><br/
<hw>Mous"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of hunting mice.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A turn or lashing of spun yarn or small stuff, or a metallic clasp or fastening, uniting the point and shank of a hook to prevent its unhooking or straighening out.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A ratchet movement in a loom.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mousing hook</b></col>, <cd>a hook with an attachment which prevents its unhooking.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mousle</ent><br/
<hw>Mou"sle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To sport with roughly; to rumple.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mouzle</asp>.]</altsp> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Wycherley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mousquetaire</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mous`que*taire"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A musketeer, esp. one of the French royal musketeers of the 17th and 18th centuries, conspicuous both for their daring and their fine dress.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>A mosquetaire cuff or glove, or other article of dress fancied to resemble those worn by the French mosquetaires.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mousquetaire cuff</ent><br/
<hw>Mousquetaire cuff</hw>. <def>A deep flaring cuff.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mousquetaire glove</ent><br/
<hw>Mousquetaire glove</hw>. <def>A woman's glove with a long, loosely fitting wrist.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mousse</ent><br/
<hw>Mousse</hw> <pr>(m<oomac/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Cookery)</fld> <def>A frozen dessert of a frothy texture, made of sweetened and flavored whipped cream, sometimes with the addition of egg yolks and gelatin.  Mousse differs from ice cream in being beaten before -- not during -- the freezing process.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any of a variety of foods whipped to a light texture; <as>as, a salmon <ex>mousse</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A foam containing special chemicals, used for styling hair.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mousseline</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mousse`line"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>Muslin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mousseline de laine</b></col> <pr>(<?/)</pr>. <ety>[F., muslin of wool.]</ety> <cd>Muslin delaine. See under <er>Muslin</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mousseline glass</b></col>, <cd>a kind of thin blown glassware, such as wineglasses, etc.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mousseline de soie</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mousse`line de soie"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>A soft thin silk fabric with a weave like that of muslin.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moustache</ent><br/
<hw>Mous`tache"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>Mustache.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moustachio</ent><br/
<hw>moustachio</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A large bushy moustache.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mustachio, handle-bars.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mousy</ent><br/
<hw>Mous"y</hw> <pr>(mouz"<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Infested with mice; smelling of mice.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moutan</ent><br/
<hw>Mou"tan</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The Chinese tree peony (<spn>Paeonia Mountan</spn>), a shrub with large flowers of various colors.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouth</ent><br/
<hw>Mouth</hw> <pr>(mouth)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mouths</plw> <pr>(mou<th/z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>mouth</ets>, <ets>mu<thorn/</ets>, AS. <ets>m<umac/<edh/</ets>; akin to D. <ets>mond</ets>, OS. <ets>m<umac/<edh/</ets>, G. <ets>mund</ets>, Icel. <ets>mu<edh/r</ets>, <ets>munnr</ets>, Sw. <ets>mun</ets>, Dan. <ets>mund</ets>, Goth. <ets>mun<thorn/s</ets>, and possibly L. <ets>mentum</ets> chin; or cf. D. <ets>muil</ets> mouth, muzzle, G. <ets>maul</ets>, OHG. <ets>m<umac/la</ets>, Icel. <ets>m<umac/li</ets>, and Skr. <ets>mukha</ets> mouth.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The opening through which an animal receives food; the aperture between the jaws or between the lips; also, the cavity, containing the <contains>tongue</contains> and <contains>teeth</contains>, between the lips and the pharynx; the buccal cavity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>An opening affording entrance or exit; orifice; aperture;</def> as: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The opening of a vessel by which it is filled or emptied, charged or discharged; <as>as, the <ex>mouth</ex> of a jar or pitcher; the <ex>mouth</ex> of the lacteal vessels, etc.</as></def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The opening or entrance of any cavity, as a cave, pit, well, or den.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The opening of a piece of ordnance, through which it is discharged.</def> <sd>(d)</sd> <def>The opening through which the waters of a river or any stream are discharged.</def> <sd>(e)</sd> <def>The entrance into a harbor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Saddlery)</fld> <def>The crosspiece of a bridle bit, which enters the mouth of an animal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A principal speaker; one who utters the common opinion; a mouthpiece.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every coffeehouse has some particular statesman belonging to it, who is the <qex>mouth</qex> of the street where he lives.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Cry; voice.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Speech; language; testimony.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That in the <qex>mouth</qex> of two or three witnesses every word may be established.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. xviii. 16.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A wry face; a grimace; a mow.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Counterfeit sad looks,<br/
Make <qex>mouths</qex> upon me when I turn my back.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Down at the mouth</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Down in the mouth</b></col></mcol>, <cd>chapfallen; of dejected countenance; depressed; discouraged.</cd> <mark>[Obs. or Colloq.]</mark> -- <col><b>Mouth friend</b></col>, <cd>one who professes friendship insincerely.</cd> <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>Mouth glass</b></col>, <cd>a small mirror for inspecting the mouth or teeth.</cd> -- <col><b>Mouth honor</b></col>, <cd>honor given in words, but not felt.</cd> <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>Mouth organ</b></col>. <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>Pan's pipes</cd>. See <er>Pandean</er>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>An harmonicon.</cd> -- <col><b>Mouth pipe</b></col>, <cd>an organ pipe with a lip or plate to cut the escaping air and make a sound.</cd> -- <col><b>To stop the mouth</b></col>, <cd>to silence or be silent; to put to shame; to confound.</cd> -- <col><b>To put one's foot in one's mouth</b></col>, <cd>to say something which causes one embarrassment.</cd> -- <col><b>To run off at the mouth</b></col>, <cd>to speak excessively.</cd> -- <col><b>To talk out of both sides of one's mouth</b></col>, <cd>to say things which are contradictory.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>The mouth</qex> of them that speak lies shall be <qex>stopped</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. lxiii. 11.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whose <qex>mouths</qex> must be <qex>stopped</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Titus i. 11.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 950 --></p>

<p><ent>Mouth</ent><br/
<hw>Mouth</hw> <pr>(mou<th/)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mouthed</conjf> <pr>(mou<th/d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mouthing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To take into the mouth; to seize or grind with the mouth or teeth; to chew; to devour.</def>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To utter with a voice affectedly big or swelling; to speak in a strained or unnaturally sonorous manner; <as>as, <ex>mouthing</ex> platitudes</as>.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Mouthing</xex> big phrases.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Hare.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mouthing</qex> out his hollow oes and aes.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To form or cleanse with the mouth; to lick, as a bear her cub.</def>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To make mouths at.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>R. Blair.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouth</ent><br/
<hw>Mouth</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To speak with a full, round, or loud, affected voice; to vociferate; to rant.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I'll bellow out for Rome, and for my country,<br/
And <qex>mouth</qex> at Caesar, till I shake the senate.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To put mouth to mouth; to kiss.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make grimaces, esp. in ridicule or contempt.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Well I know, when I am gone,<br/
How she <qex>mouths</qex> behind my back.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouthed</ent><br/
<hw>Mouthed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Furnished with a mouth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Having a mouth of a particular kind; using the mouth, speech, or voice in a particular way; -- used only in composition; <as>as, wide-<ex>mouthed</ex>; hard-<ex>mouthed</ex>; foul-<ex>mouthed</ex>; mealy-<ex>mouthed</ex>.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouther</ent><br/
<hw>Mouth"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who mouths; an affected speaker.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouth-footed</ent><br/
<hw>Mouth"-foot`ed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having the basal joints of the legs converted into jaws.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouthful</ent><br/
<hw>Mouth"ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mouthfuls</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <sn>1.</sn> <def>As much as is usually put into the mouth at one time.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, a small quantity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A statement that has a profound truth in it; <as>as, you said a <ex>mouthful</ex>!</as></def> <mark>[informal]</mark> <br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouthless</ent><br/
<hw>Mouth"less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m<umac/<edh/le<aacute/s</ets>.]</ety> <def>Destitute of a mouth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouth-made</ent><br/
<hw>Mouth"-made`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Spoken without sincerity; not heartfelt.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Mouth-made</xex> vows.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouthpiece</ent><br/
<hw>Mouth"piece`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The part of a musical or other instrument to which the mouth is applied in using it; <as>as, the <ex>mouthpiece</ex> of a bugle, or of a tobacco pipe</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An appendage to an inlet or outlet opening of a pipe or vessel, to direct or facilitate the inflow or outflow of a fluid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One who delivers the opinion of others or of another; a spokesman; <as>as, the <ex>mouthpiece</ex> of his party</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Egmont was imprudent enough to make himself the <qex>mouthpiece</qex> of their remonstrance.</q> <rj><qau>Motley.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>A person's lawyer.</def> <mark>[slang]</mark>  <note>This is a term that was used sometimes in old movies.  When a tough bad guy was arrested he might say <ldquo/I ain't sayin' nothin' without my <ex>mouthpiece</ex>!<rdquo/</note><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mouthwash</ent><br/
<hw>mouthwash</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a medicated solution used for gargling and rinsing the mouth.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> gargle.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mouton</ent><br/
<hw>mouton</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>meat from a mature sheep.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mutton.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Movability</ent><br/
<hw>Mov`a*bil"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Movableness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Movable</ent><br/
<hw>Mov"a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>movable</ets>. See <er>Move</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Capable of being moved, lifted, carried, drawn, turned, or conveyed, or in any way made to change place or posture; susceptible of motion; not fixed or stationary; <as>as, a <ex>movable</ex> steam engine</as>.</def> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>moveable</asp>.]</altsp><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> transferable, transferrable, transportable.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Changing from one time to another; <as>as, <ex>movable</ex> feasts, <it>i. e.</it>, church festivals, the date of which varies from year to year</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Movable letter</b></col> <fld>(Heb. Gram.)</fld>, <cd>a letter that is pronounced, as opposed to one that is quiescent.</cd> -- <col><b>Movable feast</b></col> <fld>(Ecclesiastical)</fld>, <cd>a holy day that changes date, depending on the lunar cycle.  An example of such a day is <stype>Easter</stype>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Movable</ent><br/
<hw>Mov"a*ble</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Movables</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An article of wares or goods; a commodity; a piece of property not fixed, or not a part of real estate; generally, in the plural, goods; wares; furniture.</def> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>moveable</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Furnished with the most rich and princely <qex>movables</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Rom. Law)</fld> <def>Property not attached to the soil.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The word is not convertible with <xex>personal property</xex>, since rents and similar incidents of the soil which are personal property by our law are immovables by the Roman law.</note>  <rj><au>Wharton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Movableness</ent><br/
<hw>Mov"a*ble*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being movable; mobility; susceptibility of motion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Movably</ent><br/
<hw>Mov"a*bly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a movable manner or condition.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Move</ent><br/
<hw>Move</hw> <pr>(m<oomac/v)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Moved</conjf> <pr>(m<oomac/vd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Moving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>moven</ets>, OF. <ets>moveir</ets>, F. <ets>mouvoir</ets>, L. <ets>movere</ets>; cf. Gr. <grk>'amei`bein</grk> to change, exchange, go in or out, quit, Skr. <ets>m<imac/v</ets>, p. p. <ets>m<umac/ta</ets>, to move, push.  Cf. <er>Emotion</er>, <er>Mew</er> to molt, <er>Mob</er>, <er>Mutable</er>, <er>Mutiny</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to change place or posture in any manner; to set in motion; to carry, convey, draw, or push from one place to another; to impel; to stir; <as>as, the wind <ex>moves</ex> a vessel; the horse <ex>moves</ex> a carriage.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chess, Checkers, etc.)</fld> <def>To transfer (a piece or man) from one space or position to another on a playing board, according to the rules of the game; <as>as, to <ex>move</ex> a king</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To excite to action by the presentation of motives; to rouse by representation, persuasion, or appeal; to influence.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Minds desirous of revenge were not <qex>moved</qex> with gold.</q> <rj><qau>Knolles.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No female arts his mind could <qex>move</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To arouse the feelings or passions of; especially, to excite to tenderness or compassion; to touch pathetically; to excite, as an emotion.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When he saw the multitudes, he was <qex>moved</qex> with compassion on them.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. ix. 36.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[The use of images] in orations and poetry is to <qex>move</qex> pity or terror.</q> <rj><qau>Felton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To propose; to recommend; specifically, to propose formally for consideration and determination, in a deliberative assembly; to submit, as a resolution to be adopted; <as>as, to <ex>move</ex> to adjourn</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let me but <qex>move</qex> one question to your daughter.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They are to be blamed alike who <qex>move</qex> and who decline war upon particular respects.</q> <rj><qau>Hayward.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To apply to, as for aid.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To stir; agitate; trouble; affect; persuade; influence; actuate; impel; rouse; prompt; instigate; incite; induce; incline; propose; offer.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Move</ent><br/
<hw>Move</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To change place or posture; to stir; to go, in any manner, from one place or position to another; <as>as, a ship <ex>moves</ex> rapidly</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The foundations also of the hills <qex>moved</qex> and were shaken, because he was wroth.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. xviii. 7.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On the green bank I sat and listened long, . . . <br/
Nor till her lay was ended could I <qex>move</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To act; to take action; to stir; to begin to act; <as>as, to <ex>move</ex> in a matter</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To change residence; to remove, as from one house, town, or state, to another.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Chess, Checkers, etc.)</fld> <def>To change the place of a piece in accordance with the rules of the game.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Move</ent><br/
<hw>Move</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of moving; a movement.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chess, Checkers, etc.)</fld> <def>The act of moving one of the pieces, from one position to another, in the progress of the game; also, the opportunity or obligation to so move a piece; one's turn; <as>as, you can only borrow from the bank in Monopoly when it's your <ex>move</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An act for the attainment of an object; a step in the execution of a plan or purpose.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To make a move</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To take some action toward a goal, usually one involving interaction with other people.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To move a piece, as in a game.</cd> -- <col><b>To be on the move</b></col>, <cd>to bustle or stir about.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moveable</ent><br/
<hw>moveable</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>movable.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> , transferable, transferrable, transportable.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moved</ent><br/
<hw>moved</hw> <pos>pred. adj.</pos> <def>affected emotionally.  Opposite of <ant>unmoved</ant>.</def> <see>Also See <er>affected</er>, <er>emotional</er>.</see> <br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moveless</ent><br/
<hw>Move`less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Motionless; fixed.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Moveless</xex> as a tower.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Movement</ent><br/
<hw>Move"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mouvement</ets>. See <er>Move</er>, and cf. <er>Moment</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of moving in space; change of place or posture; motion; <as>as, the <ex>movement</ex> of an army in marching or maneuvering; the <ex>movement</ex> of a wheel or a machine</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Manner or style of moving; <as>as, a slow, or quick, or sudden, <ex>movement</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Transference, by any means, from one situation to another; a change of situation; progress toward a goal; advancement; <as>as, after months of fruitless discussion there was finally some <ex>movement</ex> toward an agreement</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Motion of the mind or feelings; emotion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The rhythmical progression, pace, and tempo of a piece.</def> <ldquo/Any change of time is a change of <xex>movement</xex>.<rdquo/ <au>Busby.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>One of the several strains or pieces, each complete in itself, with its own time and rhythm, which make up a larger work; <as>as, the several <ex>movements</ex> of a suite or a symphony</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>A system of mechanism for transmitting motion of a definite character, or for transforming motion; as, the wheelwork of a watch; <as>as, a seventeen jewel <ex>movement</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A more or less organized effort by many people to achieve some goal, especially a social or artistic goal; <as>as, the women's liberation <ex>movement</ex>; the progressive <ex>movement</ex> in architecture</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Febrile movement</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>an elevation of the body temperature; a fever.</cd> -- <col><b>Movement cure</b></col>. <fld>(Med.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Kinesiatrics</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Movement of the bowels</b></col>, <cd>an evacuation or stool; a passage or discharge.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Motion.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Movement</er>, <er>Motion</er>. <xex>Motion</xex> expresses a general idea of not being at rest; <xex>movement</xex> is oftener used to express a definite, regulated motion, esp. a progress.</usage><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Movent</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"vent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>movens</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>movere</ets>. See <er>Move</er>.]</ety> <def>Moving.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Grew.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Movent</ent><br/
<hw>Mo"vent</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>That which moves anything.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mover</ent><br/
<hw>Mov"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A person or thing that moves, stirs, or changes place.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A person or thing that imparts motion, or causes change of place; a motor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, excites, instigates, or causes movement, change, etc.; <as>as, <ex>movers</ex> of sedition</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These most poisonous compounds,<br/
Which are the <qex>movers</qex> of a languishing death.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A proposer; one who offers a proposition, or recommends anything for consideration or adoption; <as>as, the <ex>mover</ex> of a resolution in a legislative body</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Movie</ent><br/
<hw>Mov"ie</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A motion picture.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> film, picture, moving picture, motion picture, picture show, flick.</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A motion picture show; the event of showing a motion picture.  In the <pluf>pl.</pluf>, the event of showing a motion picture at a movie theater; <as>as, to go to the <ex>movies</ex>; to spend an evening at the <ex>movies</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>The motion picture industry or medium, generally.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moving</ent><br/
<hw>Mov"ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Changing place or posture; causing motion or action; <as>as, a <ex>moving</ex> car, or power</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Exciting movement of the mind or feelings; adapted to move the sympathies, passions, or affections; touching; pathetic; <as>as, a <ex>moving</ex> appeal</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I sang an old <qex>moving</qex> story.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Moving force</b></col> <fld>(Mech.)</fld>, <cd>a force that accelerates, retards, or deflects the motion of a body.</cd> -- <col><b>Moving plant</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a leguminous plant (<spn>Desmodium gyrans</spn>); -- so called because its leaflets have a distinct automatic motion.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moving</ent><br/
<hw>Mov"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of changing place or posture; esp., the act of changing one's dwelling place or place of business.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Moving day</b></col>, <cd>a day when one moves; esp., a day when a large number of tenants change their dwelling place.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Movingly</ent><br/
<hw>Mov"ing*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a moving manner.</def>  <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Movingness</ent><br/
<hw>Mov"ing*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The power of moving.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moving picture</ent><br/
<hw>Moving picture</hw>. <def>same as <er>motion picture</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mow</ent><br/
<hw>Mow</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <altsp>[Written also <asp>moe</asp> and <asp>mowe</asp>.]</altsp> <ety>[F. <ets>moue</ets> pouting, a wry face; cf. OD. <ets>mouwe</ets> the protruded lip.]</ety> <def>A wry face.</def> <ldquo/Make <xex>mows</xex> at him.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mow</ent><br/
<hw>Mow</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make mouths.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nodding, becking, and <qex>mowing</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Tyndale.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mow</ent><br/
<hw>Mow</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Mew</er>, a gull.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mow</ent><br/
<hw>Mow</hw>, <pos>v.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>pres. sing.</pos> <conjf>Mow</conjf>, <pos>pl.</pos> <conjf>Mowe</conjf>, <conjf>Mowen</conjf>, <conjf>Moun</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>magan</ets>. See <er>May</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <def>May; can.</def> <ldquo/Thou <xex>mow</xex> now escapen.<rdquo/ <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our walles <qex>mowe</qex> not make hem resistence.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mow</ent><br/
<hw>Mow</hw> <pr>(m<omac/)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Mowed</conjf> <pr>(m<omac/d)</pr>; <pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mowed</conjf> or <conjf>Mown</conjf> <pr>(m<omac/n)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mowing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>mowen</ets>, <ets>mawen</ets>, AS. <ets>m<amac/wan</ets>; akin to D. <ets>maaijen</ets>, G. <ets>m<aum/hen</ets>, OHG. <ets>m<amac/jan</ets>, Dan. <ets>meie</ets>, L. <ets>metere</ets> to reap, mow, Gr. <grk>'ama^n</grk>.  Cf. <er>Math</er>, <er>Mead</er> a meadow, <er>Meadow</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cut down, as grass, with a scythe or machine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cut the grass from; <as>as, to <ex>mow</ex> a meadow</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cut down; to cause to fall in rows or masses, as in mowing grass; -- with <xex>down</xex>; <as>as, a discharge of grapeshot <ex>mows</ex> down whole ranks of men</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mow</ent><br/
<hw>Mow</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To cut grass, etc., with a scythe, or with a machine; to cut grass for hay.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mow</ent><br/
<hw>Mow</hw> <pr>(mou)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mowe</ets>, AS. <ets>m<umac/ga</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A heap or mass of hay or of sheaves of grain stowed in a barn.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The place in a barn where hay or grain in the sheaf is stowed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mow</ent><br/
<hw>Mow</hw> <pr>(mou)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To lay, as hay or sheaves of grain, in a heap or mass in a barn; to pile and stow away.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mowburn</ent><br/
<hw>Mow"burn`</hw> <pr>(mou"b<ucir/rn`)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To heat and ferment in the mow, as hay when housed too green.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mowe</ent><br/
<hw>Mowe</hw> <pr>(mou)</pr>, <pos>v.</pos> <def>See 4th <er>Mow</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mowe</ent><br/
<hw>Mowe</hw>, <pos>n. & v.</pos> <def>See 1st & 2d <er>Mow</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mower</ent><br/
<hw>Mow"er</hw> <pr>(m<omac/"<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who, or that which, mows; a mowing machine; <as>as, a lawn <ex>mower</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mowing</ent><br/
<hw>Mow"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of one who, or the operation of that which, mows.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Land from which grass is cut; meadow land.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mowing machine</b></col>, <cd>an agricultural machine armed with knives or blades for cutting standing grass, etc.  It may be drawn by a horse or horses, or propelled by a powered engine.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mown</ent><br/
<hw>Mown</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>p. p. & a.</pos> <def>Cut down by mowing, as grass; deprived of grass by mowing; <as>as, a <ex>mown</ex> field</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mowyer</ent><br/
<hw>Mow"yer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mower.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moxa</ent><br/
<hw>Mox"a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[A corruption of Japan. <ets>mogusa</ets> (pronounced <ets>mongsa</ets>), an escharotic made from the plant <ets>yomigi</ets>: cf. F. <ets>moxa</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A soft woolly mass prepared from the young leaves of <spn>Artemisia Chinensis</spn>, and used as a cautery by burning it on the skin; hence, any substance used in a like manner, as cotton impregnated with niter, amadou.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A plant from which this substance is obtained, esp.  <spn>Artemisia Chinensis</spn>, and <spn>Artemisia moxa</spn>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moxie</ent><br/
<hw>Mox"ie</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[fr. Moxie, a trade name for a beverage.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>energy; pep.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>courage, determination.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Know-how, expertise.</def>  <rj><au>MW10.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moya</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Moy"a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mud poured out from volcanoes during eruptions; -- so called in South America.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moyle</ent><br/
<hw>Moyle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. & v.</pos> <def>See <er>Moil</er>, and <er>Moile</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mozarabic</ent><br/
<ent>Mozarab</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Moz"a*rab</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Moz`a*rab"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>. <def>Same as <er>Muzarab</er>, <er>Muzarabic</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mozzetta</ent><br/
<ent>Mozetta</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mo*zet"ta</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Moz*zet"ta</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It. <ets>mozzetta</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mosette</ets>.  Cf. <er>Amice</er> a hood or cape.]</ety> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>A cape, with a small hood; -- worn by the pope and other dignitaries of the Roman Catholic Church.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mr.</ent><br/
<hw>Mr.</hw>. <pr>(<?/)</pr>. <def>The customary abbreviation of <sig>Mister</sig> in writing and printing. See <er>Master</er>, 4.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mrs.</ent><br/
<hw>Mrs.</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>. <def>The customary abbreviation of <sig>Mistress</sig> or <sig>Missess</sig> when used as a title of courtesy, in writing and printing; <as>as, <ex>Mrs.</ex> Clinton is commonly called by her full name, <person>Hillary Rodham Clinton</person></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>msasa</ent><br/
<hw>msasa</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Amall shrubby African tree (<spn>Brachystegia speciformis</spn>) having compound leaves and racemes of small fragrant green flowers.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> <spn>Brachystegia speciformis</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>MSB</ent><br/
<hw>MSB</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>mutual savings bank</er>.</def> <mark>[abbr.]</mark> <br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>MSG</ent><br/
<hw>MSG</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>monosodium glutamate</er>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> monosodium glutamate.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>MST</ent><br/
<hw>MST</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mountain Standard Time, the time of the 105th meridian, used in the mountain states of the U.S.</def> <mark>[abbr.]</mark> <br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Mountain Time, Mountain Standard Time.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>MT</ent><br/
<hw>MT</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A <altname>metric ton</altname>, a unit of weight equivalent to 1000 kilograms.</def> <mark>[abbr.]</mark> <br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> metric ton, tonne, t.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mu</ent><br/
<hw>mu</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <pr>(m<umac/)</pr> <def>The 12th letter of the Greek alphabet (<mu/, <MU/).</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mu'adhdhin</ent><br/
<hw>mu'adhdhin</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>muezzin</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>muazzin</ent><br/
<hw>muazzin</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>muezzin</er>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucamide</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*cam"ide</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Muc</ets>ic + <ets>amide</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>The acid amide of mucic acid, obtained as a white crystalline substance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucate</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of mucic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muce</ent><br/
<hw>Muce</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Muse</er>, and <er>Muset</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucedin</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*ce"din</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mucus</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot. Chem.)</fld> <def>A yellowish white, amorphous, nitrogenous substance found in wheat, rye, etc., and resembling gluten; -- formerly called also <altname>mucin</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Much</ent><br/
<hw>Much</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/ch)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar. & superl.</pos> wanting, but supplied by <adjf>More</adjf> <pr>(m<omac/r)</pr>, and <adjf>Most</adjf> <pr>(m<omac/st)</pr>, from another root.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>moche</ets>, <ets>muche</ets>, <ets>miche</ets>, prob. the same as <ets>mochel</ets>, <ets>muchel</ets>, <ets>michel</ets>, <ets>mikel</ets>, fr. AS. <ets>micel</ets>, <ets>mycel</ets>; cf. Gr. <grk>me`gas</grk>, fem. <grk>mega`lh</grk>, great, and Icel. <ets>mj<oum/k</ets>, adv., much. <root/103. See <er>Mickle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Great in quantity; long in duration; <as>as, <ex>much</ex> rain has fallen; <ex>much</ex> time.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou shalt carry <qex>much</qex> seed out into the field, and shalt gather but little in.</q> <rj><qau>Deut. xxviii. 38.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Many in number.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Edom came out against him with <qex>much</qex> people.</q> <rj><qau>Num. xx. 20.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>High in rank or position.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Much</ent><br/
<hw>Much</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A great quantity; a great deal; also, an indefinite quantity; <as>as, you have as <ex>much</ex> as I</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He that gathered <qex>much</qex> had nothing over.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xvi. 18.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Much</xex>in this sense can be regarded as an adjective qualifying a word unexpressed, and may, therefore, be modified by <xex>as</xex>, <xex>so</xex>, <xex>too</xex>, <xex>very</xex>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A thing uncommon, wonderful, or noticeable; something considerable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And [he] thought not <qex>much</qex> to clothe his enemies.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To make much of</b></col>, <cd>to treat as something of especial value or worth.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Much</ent><br/
<hw>Much</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Icel. <ets>mj<oum/k</ets>. See <er>Much</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>To a great degree or extent; greatly; abundantly; far; nearly.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Much</xex> suffering heroes.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou art <qex>much</qex> mightier than we.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. xxvi. 16.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Excellent speech becometh not a fool, <qex>much</qex> less do lying lips a prince.</q> <rj><qau>Prov. xvii. 7.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Henceforth I fly not death, nor would prolong<br/
Life <qex>much</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All left the world <qex>much</qex> as they found it.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Temple.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muchel</ent><br/
<hw>Much"el</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<root/103. See <er>Mickle</er>.]</ety> <def>Much.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muchness</ent><br/
<hw>Much"ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Greatness; extent.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Colloq.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The quantity and <qex>muchness</qex> of time which it filcheth.</q> <rj><qau>W. Whately.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Much of a muchness</b></col>, <cd>much the same.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <ldquo/Men's men; gentle or simple, they're <xex>much of a muchness</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>G. Eliot.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muchwhat</ent><br/
<hw>Much"what`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Nearly; almost; much.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <ldquo/<xex>Muchwhat</xex> after the same manner.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Glanvill.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucic</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"cic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mucus</ets> mucus: cf. F. <ets>mucique</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or derived from, gums and micilaginous substances; specif., denoting an acid obtained by the oxidation of gums, dulcite, etc., as a white crystalline substance isomeric with saccharic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucid</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"cid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mucidus</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mucus</ets> mucus. See <er>Mucus</er>, and cf. <er>Moist</er>.]</ety> <def>Musty; moldy; slimy; mucous.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mu"cid*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucific</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*cif"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mucus</ets> + L. <ets>-ficare</ets> (in comp.) to make. See  <er>-fy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Inducing or stimulating the secretion of mucus; blennogenous.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>Secreting mucus.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muciform</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ci*form</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mucus</ets> + <ets>-form</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>Resembling mucus; having the character or appearance of mucus.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucigen</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ci*gen</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Muc</ets>in + <ets>-gen</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>A substance which is formed in mucous epithelial cells, and gives rise to mucin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucigenous</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*cig"e*nous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>Connected with the formation of mucin; resembling mucin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>mucigenous</qex> basis is manufactured at the expense of the ordinary protoplasm of the cell.</q> <rj><qau>Foster.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucilage</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ci*lage</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., from L. <ets>mucilago</ets> a musty juice, fr. <ets>mucus</ets> mucus, slime. See <er>Mucus</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot. Chem.)</fld> <def>A gummy or gelatinous substance produced in certain plants by the action of water on the cell wall, as in the seeds of quinces, of flax, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An aqueous solution of gum, or of substances allied to it; a glue; a liquid adhesive; <as>as, medicinal <ex>mucilage</ex>; <ex>mucilage</ex> for fastening envelopes.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucilaginous</ent><br/
<hw>Mu`ci*lag"i*nous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mucilagineux</ets>. See <er>Mucilage</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Partaking of the nature of, or resembling, mucilage; moist, soft, and viscid; slimy; ropy; <as>as, a <ex>mucilaginous</ex> liquid</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of, pertaining to, or secreting, mucilage; <as>as, the <ex>mucilaginous</ex> glands</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Soluble in water, but not in alcohol; yielding mucilage; <as>as, <ex>mucilaginous</ex> gums or plants</as>.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mu`ci*lag"i*nous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 951 --></p>

<p><ent>Mucin</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"cin</hw> <pr>(m<umac/"s<icr/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mucus</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot. Chem.)</fld> <def>See <er>Mucedin</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Physiol. Chem.)</fld> <def>Any of a class of high molecular weight glycoproteins which are contained in mucus, and give to the latter secretion its peculiar ropy character.  They are found in all the secretions from mucous glands, and also between the fibers of connective tissue, as in tendons. They form viscous solutions and serve to provide lubrication for movement within body cavities, and some protection of surfaces. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Demilune</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucinogen</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*cin"o*gen</hw> <pr>(m<usl/*s<icr/n"<osl/*j<ecr/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mucin</ets> + <ets>-gen</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Mucigen</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muciparous</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*cip"a*rous</hw> <pr>(m<usl/*s<icr/"p<adot/*r<ucr/s)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mucus</ets> + L. <ets>parere</ets> to produce.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>Secreting, or producing, mucus or mucin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucivore</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ci*vore</hw> <pr>(m<umac/"s<icr/*v<omac/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mucus</ets> slime, mucus + <ets>vorare</ets> to devour.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An insect which feeds on mucus, or the sap of plants, as certain Diptera, of the tribe <fam>Mucivora</fam>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muck</ent><br/
<hw>Muck</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/k)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Abbreviation of <xex>Amuck</xex>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To run a muck</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Amuck</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muck</ent><br/
<hw>Muck</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Icel. <ets>myki</ets>; akin to D. <ets>m<oum/g</ets>.  Cf. <er>Midden</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Dung in a moist state; manure.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Vegetable mold mixed with earth, as found in low, damp places and swamps.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Anything filthy or vile.</def>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Money; -- in contempt.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The fatal <qex>muck</qex> we quarreled for.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>The unwanted material, especially  rock or soil, that must be excavated in order to reach the valuable ore; also, the unwanted material after being excavated or crushed by blasting, or after being removed to a waste pile.  In the latter sense, also called a <er>muck pile</er>.</def><br/
[<source>RDH</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Muck bar</b></col>, <cd>bar iron which has been through the rolls only once.</cd> -- <col><b>Muck iron</b></col>, <cd>crude puddled iron ready for the squeezer or rollers.</cd> <au>Knight.</au>  <col>muck pile</col> <cd>see <er>muck pile</er> in the vocabulary.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+RH</source>]</p>

<p><ent>muck</ent><br/
<hw>muck</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Like muck; mucky; also, used in collecting or distributing muck; <as>as, a <ex>muck</ex> fork</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>muck</ent><br/
<hw>muck</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To manure with muck.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>muck</ent><br/
<hw>muck</hw>, <pos>v. i. & t.</pos> <def>To excavate and remove muck{5}.  Often used with <ptcl>out</ptcl>, <as>as, to <ex>muck</ex> out a round</as>.</def><br/
[<source>RDH</source>]</p>

<p><q> . . . <company>Inco</company> is still much more advanced than other mining companies.  He says that the LKAB mine in <country>Sweden</country> is the closest rival.  He predicts that, by 2008, <company>Inco</company> can reach a new productivity plateau, doubling the current mining productivity from 3,350 tonnes to 6,350 tonnes per person per year. Another aim is to triple the mine cycle rate (the time to drill, blast and <qex>muck</qex> a round) from one cycle to three complete cycles per 24 hours.</q> <qau>http://www.canadianminingjournal.com/issues/apr00/page10.asp</qau><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>


<p><ent>Muckender</ent><br/
<hw>Muck"en*der</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/k"<ecr/n*d<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>mocador</ets>.  Cf. <er>Mokadour</er>.]</ety> <def>A handkerchief.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <altsp>[Written also <asp>muckinder</asp>, <asp>muckiter</asp>, <asp>mockadour</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucker</ent><br/
<hw>Muck"er</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/k"<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A term of reproach for a low or vulgar labor person.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mucker</ent><br/
<hw>muck"er</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/k"<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Construction)</fld> <def>An excavating machine designed to remove particulate material from within a confined area, as in a tunnel or mine.</def><br/
[<source>RDH</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucker</ent><br/
<hw>Muck"er</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To scrape together, as money, by mean labor or shifts.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Udall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muckerer</ent><br/
<hw>Muck"er*er</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/k"<etil/r*<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A miser; a niggard.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muckiness</ent><br/
<hw>Muck"i*ness</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/k"<esl/*n<ecr/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality of being mucky.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muckle</ent><br/
<hw>Muc"kle</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/k"k'l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mickle</er>.]</ety> <def>Much.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muckmidden</ent><br/
<hw>Muck"mid`den</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/k"m<icr/d`d'n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A dunghill.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>muck pile</ent><br/
<hw>muck" pile`</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/k" p<imac/l`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Construction)</fld> <def>The broken material at the face of a tunnel being bored, after being crushed by blasting.</def><br/
[<source>RDH</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>Muck{5} that has been placed in a spoil area.</def><br/
[<source>RDH</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muck rake</ent><br/
<hw>Muck" rake`</hw>. <def>A rake for scraping up muck or dung. See <er>Muckrake</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>, below.</def> <mark>[obs.]</mark> <br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>muckrake</ent><br/
<hw>muck"rake`</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/k"r<amac/k`)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>  <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>-raked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>-raking</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To seek for, expose, or charge, especially habitually, corruption, real or alleged, on the part of public men and corporations.</def>  <note>On April 14, 1906, President Roosevelt delivered a speech on <ldquo/The Man with the Muck Rake,<rdquo/ in which he deprecated sweeping and unjust charges of corruption against public men and corporations.  The phrase was taken up by the press, and the verb to <er>muckrake</er>, in the above sense, and the noun <it>muckraker</it>, to designate one so engaged, were speedily coined and obtained wide currency.  The original allusion was to a character in Bunyan's <ldquo/Pilgrim's Progress<rdquo/ so intent on raking up muck that he could not see a celestial crown held above him.</note><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>muckraker</ent><br/
<hw>muck"rak`er</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/k"r<amac/k`<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>  <def>A person who habitually muckrakes.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucksy</ent><br/
<hw>Muck"sy</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/k"s<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Somewhat mucky; soft, sticky, and dirty; muxy.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>  <rj><au>R. D. Blackmore.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muckworm</ent><br/
<hw>Muck"worm`</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/k"w<ucir/rm`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A larva or grub that lives in muck or manure; -- applied to the larvae of the tumbledung and allied beetles.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who scrapes together money by mean labor and devices; a miser.</def> <ldquo/Misers are <xex>muckworms</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucky</ent><br/
<hw>Muck"y</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/k"<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Filthy with muck; miry; <as>as, a <ex>mucky</ex> road</as>.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Mucky</xex> filth.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Vile, in a moral sense; sordid.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mucky</qex> money and false felicity.</q> <rj><qau>Latimer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucocele</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"co*cele</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mucus</ets> + Gr. <grk>kh`lh</grk> tumor.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>An enlargement or protrusion of the mucous membrane of the lachrymal passages, or dropsy of the lachrymal sac, dependent upon catarrhal inflammation of the latter.</def>  <rj><au>Dunglison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucoid</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"coid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mucus</ets> + <ets>-oid</ets>.]</ety> <def>Resembling mucus.</def>  <rj><au>Dunglison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mucoid degeneration</b></col>, <cd>a form of degeneration in which the tissues are transformed into a semisolid substance resembling mucus.</cd>  <rj><au>Quain.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucoid</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"coid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>  <ety>[<ets>Muc</ets>in + <ets>-oid</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol. Chem.)</fld> <def>One of a class of mucinlike substances yielding on decomposition a reducing carbohydrate together with some form of proteinaceous matter.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muconate</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"co*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of muconic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muconic</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*con"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mu</ets>cic + ita<ets>conic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or designating, an organic acid (<chform>C6H6O4</chform>, <chname>2-4-hexadienedoic acid</chname>), obtained indirectly from mucic acid, and somewhat resembling itaconic acid.  Various other means of synthesis have been reported.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucopurulent</ent><br/
<hw>Mu`co*pu"ru*lent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mucus</ets> + <ets>purulent</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Having the character or appearance of both mucus and pus.</def>  <rj><au>Dunglison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucor</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mu"cor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. <ets>mucere</ets> to be moldy or musty.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of minute fungi.  The plants consist of slender threads with terminal globular sporangia; mold.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucorales</ent><br/
<hw>Mucorales</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>An order of mostly saprophytic fungi.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> order <ord>Mucorales</ord>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mucosa</ent><br/
<hw>mucosa</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The mucus-secreting membrane lining all body cavities or passages that communicate with the exterior; called also <altname>mucous membrane</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mucous membrane.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucosity</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*cos"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being mucous or slimy; mucousness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucous</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"cous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mucosus</ets>, fr. <ets>mucus</ets> mucus.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of, pertaining to, or resembling, mucus; slimy, ropy, or stringy, and lubricous; <as>as, a <ex>mucous</ex> substance</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Secreting a slimy or mucigenous substance; <as>as, the <ex>mucous</ex> membrane</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mucous membrane</b></col>. <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Membrane</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mucous patches</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>elevated patches found in the mucous membranes of the mouth and anus, usually due to syphilis.</cd> -- <col><b>Mucous tissue</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>a form of connective tissue in an early stage of development, found in the umbilical cord and in the embryo, and also in certain tumors called <partof>myxomata</partof>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucousness</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"cous*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being mucous; sliminess.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucro</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mu"cro</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.]</ety> <fld>(Bot. & Zool.)</fld> <def>A minute abrupt point, as of a leaf; any small, sharp point or process, terminating a larger part or organ.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucronated</ent><br/
<ent>Mucronate</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mu"cro*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mu"cro*na`ted</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mucronatus</ets>, fr. <ets>mucro</ets> a sharp point: cf. F. <ets>mucron<eacute/</ets>.]</ety> <def>Ending abruptly in a sharp point; abruptly tipped with a short and sharp point; <as>as, a <ex>mucronate</ex> leaf</as>.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mu"cro*nate*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucronulate</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*cron"u*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having, or tipped with, a small point or points.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muculent</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"cu*lent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>muculentus</ets>, fr. <ets>mucus</ets>.]</ety> <def>Slimy; moist, and moderately viscous.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucus</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"cus</hw> <pr>(m<umac/"k<ucr/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mucus</ets>, <ets>muccus</ets>; cf. <ets>mucere</ets> to be moldy or musty, Gr. <grk>my`xa</grk> mucus, and Skr. <ets>muc</ets> to release.  Cf. <er>Match</er> for striking fire, <er>Moist</er>, <er>Mucilage</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>A viscid fluid secreted by mucous membranes, which it serves to moisten and protect. It covers the lining membranes of all the cavities which open externally, such as those of the mouth, nose, lungs, intestinal canal, urinary passages, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>Any other animal fluid of a viscid quality, as the synovial fluid, which lubricates the cavities of the joints; -- improperly so used.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A gelatinous or slimy substance found in certain algae and other plants.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mucusin</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"cus*in</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Physiol. Chem.)</fld> <def>Mucin.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mud</ent><br/
<hw>Mud</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Akin to LG. <ets>mudde</ets>, D. <ets>modder</ets>, G. <ets>moder</ets> mold, OSw. <ets>modd</ets> mud, Sw. <ets>modder</ets> mother, Dan. <ets>mudder</ets> mud.  Cf. <er>Mother</er> a scum on liquors.]</ety> <def>Earth and water mixed so as to be soft and adhesive.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mud bass</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a fresh-water fish (<spn>Acantharchum pomotis</spn> or <spn>Acantharchus pomotis</spn>) of the Eastern United States. It produces a deep grunting note.</cd> -- <col><b>Mud bath</b></col>, <cd>an immersion of the body, or some part of it, in mud charged with medicinal agents, as a remedy for disease.</cd> -- <col><b>Mud boat</b></col>, <cd>a large flatboat used in dredging.</cd> -- <col><b>Mud cat</b></col>. <cd>See <er>mud cat</er> in the vocabulary.</cd> -- <col><b>Mud crab</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one of several American marine crabs of the genus <gen>Panopeus</gen>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mud dab</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the winter flounder. See <er>Flounder</er>, and <er>Dab</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mud dauber</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a mud wasp; the <er>mud-dauber</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mud devil</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the fellbender.</cd> -- <col><b>Mud drum</b></col> <fld>(Steam Boilers)</fld>, <cd>a drum beneath a boiler, into which sediment and mud in the water can settle for removal.</cd> -- <col><b>Mud eel</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a long, slender, aquatic amphibian (<spn>Siren lacertina</spn>), found in the Southern United States.  It has persistent external gills and only the anterior pair of legs.  See <er>Siren</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mud frog</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a European frog (<spn>Pelobates fuscus</spn>).</cd> -- <col><b>Mud hen</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The American coot (<spn>Fulica Americana</spn>)</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>The clapper rail.</cd> -- <col><b>Mud lark</b></col>, <cd>a person who cleans sewers, or delves in mud.</cd> <mark>[Slang]</mark> -- <col><b>Mud minnow</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any small American fresh-water fish of the genus <gen>Umbra</gen>, as <spn>Umbra limi</spn>.  The genus is allied to the pickerels.</cd> -- <col><b>Mud plug</b></col>, <cd>a plug for stopping the mudhole of a boiler.</cd> -- <col><b>Mud puppy</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the menobranchus.</cd> -- <col><b>Mud scow</b></col>, <cd>a heavy scow, used in dredging; a mud boat.</cd> <mark>[U.S.]</mark> -- <mcol><col><b>Mud turtle</b></col>, <col><b>Mud tortoise</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one of numerous species of fresh-water tortoises of the United States.</cd> -- <col><b>Mud wasp</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one of numerous species of hymenopterous insects belonging to <gen>Pepaeus</gen>, and allied genera, which construct groups of mud cells, attached, side by side, to stones or to the woodwork of buildings, etc.  The female places an egg in each cell, together with spiders or other insects, paralyzed by a sting, to serve as food for the larva.  Called also <altname>mud dauber</altname>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mud</ent><br/
<hw>Mud</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To bury in mud.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make muddy or turbid.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mudar</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mu"dar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Hind. <ets>mad<amac/r</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Either one of two asclepiadaceous shrubs (<spn>Calotropis gigantea</spn>, and <spn>Calotropis procera</spn>), which furnish a strong and valuable fiber.  The acrid milky juice is used medicinally.</def> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>madar</asp> and <asp>muddar</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mudarin</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"da*rin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A brown, amorphous, bitter substance having a strong emetic action, extracted from the root of the mudar.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mud cat</ent><br/
<ent>mudcat</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mudcat</hw>, <hw>mud cat</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A large catfish (<spn>Pylodictus olivaris</spn>, formerly <spn>Leptops olivaris</spn>) of the central U. S. having a flattened head and projecting jaw.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> flathead catfish, goujon, shovelnose catfish, spoonbill catfish, <spn>Pylodictus olivaris</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mud dauber</ent><br/
<ent>mud-dauber</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mud"-daub`er</hw>, <hw>mud" daub`er</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A wasp of the family <fam>Sphegidae</fam> (<fam>Sphecidae</fam>) which builds a nest of mud and stores insects and spiders in it; a digger-wasp.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mud crab</ent><br/
<ent>mud-crab</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mud"-crab`</hw>, <hw>mud" crab`</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A crab of the genus <gen>Panop<oe/us</gen> (also written <gen>Panopeus</gen>).</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muddily</ent><br/
<hw>Mud"di*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a muddy manner; turbidly; without mixture; cloudily; obscurely; confusedly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mudder</ent><br/
<hw>Mud"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>a racehorse that exhibits a better than usual performance when the racetrack is wet or muddy.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An athlete who performs better than his/her average under muddy conditions.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muddiness</ent><br/
<hw>Mud"di*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The condition or quality of being muddy; turbidness; foulness caused by mud, dirt, or sediment; <as>as, the <ex>muddiness</ex> of a stream</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Obscurity or confusion, as in treatment of a subject; intellectual dullness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muddle</ent><br/
<hw>Mud"dle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Muddled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Muddling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From <er>Mud</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make turbid, or muddy, as water.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He did ill to <qex>muddle</qex> the water.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cloud or stupefy; to render stupid with liquor; to intoxicate partially.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Epicurus seems to have had brains so <qex>muddled</qex> and confounded, that he scarce ever kept in the right way.</q> <rj><qau>Bentley.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Often drunk, always <qex>muddled</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To waste or misuse, as one does who is stupid or intoxicated.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>muddle</qex> it [money] away without method or object, and without having anything to show for it.</q> <rj><qau>Hazlitt.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To mix confusedly; to confuse; to make a mess of; <as>as, to <ex>muddle</ex> matters</as>; also, to perplex; to mystify.</def>  <rj><au>F. W. Newman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muddle</ent><br/
<hw>Mud"dle</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To dabble in mud.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To think and act in a confused, aimless way.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muddle</ent><br/
<hw>Mud"dle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A state of being turbid or confused; hence, intellectual cloudiness or dullness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We both grub on in a <qex>muddle</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muddlehead</ent><br/
<hw>Mud"dle*head`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A stupid person; a blunderer.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <au>C. Reade.</au> -- <wordforms><wf>Mud"dle-head`ed</wf>, <pos>a.</pos> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <au>Dickens.</au></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muddler</ent><br/
<hw>Mud"dler</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who, or that which, muddles.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muddy</ent><br/
<hw>Mud"dy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Muddier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Muddiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Abounding in mud; besmeared or dashed with mud; <as>as, a <ex>muddy</ex> road or path; <ex>muddy</ex> boots.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Turbid with mud; <as>as, <ex>muddy</ex> water</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Consisting of mud or earth; gross; impure.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>muddy</qex> vesture of decay.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Confused, as if turbid with mud; cloudy in mind; dull; stupid; also, immethodical; incoherent; vague.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cold hearts and <qex>muddy</qex> understandings.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Dost think I am so <qex>muddy</qex>, so unsettled.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Not clear or bright.</def>  <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muddy</ent><br/
<hw>Mud"dy</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Muddied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Muddying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To soil with mud; to dirty; to render turbid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <mark>(Fig.)</mark>: <def>To cloud; to make dull or heavy; to confuse.</def>  <rj><au>Grew.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muddy-headed</ent><br/
<hw>Mud"dy-head`ed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Dull; stupid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muddy-mettled</ent><br/
<hw>Mud"dy-met`tled</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Dull-spirited.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mudfish</ent><br/
<hw>Mud"fish`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The European loach.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The bowfin (<spn>Amia calva</spn>).</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The South American lipedosiren, and the allied African species (<spn>Protopterus annectens</spn>). See <er>Lipedosiren</er>.</def> <sd>(d)</sd> <def>The mud minnow, a fish of the genus <gen>Umbra</gen> or family <fam>Umbridae</fam>.</def> <sd>(e)</sd> <cd>any fish which lives in muddy waters, such as the <er>mummichog</er>, a killifish.</cd><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mudhole</ent><br/
<hw>Mud"hole`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A hole, or hollow place, containing mud, as in a road.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Steam Boilers)</fld> <def>A hole near the bottom, through which the sediment is withdrawn.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mudir</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"dir</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Moodir</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mudsill</ent><br/
<hw>Mud"sill`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The lowest sill of a structure, usually embedded in the soil; the lowest timber of a house; also, that sill or timber of a bridge which is laid at the bottom of the water. See <er>Sill</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: A person of the lowest stratum of society; -- a term of opprobrium or contempt.</def> <mark>[Southern U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mudsucker</ent><br/
<hw>Mud"suck`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A woodcock.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mudwall</ent><br/
<hw>Mud"wall`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The European bee-eater. See <er>Bee-eater</er>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>modwall</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mudwort</ent><br/
<hw>Mud"wort`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A small herbaceous plant growing on muddy shores (<spn>Limosella aquatica</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mue</ent><br/
<hw>Mue</hw> <pr>(m<umac/)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To mew; to molt.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Quarles.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>muesli</ent><br/
<hw>mues"li</hw> <pr>(m<umac/s"l<esl/ <it>or</it> m<umac/z"l<esl/)</pr>  <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mixture of untoasted dry cereals, nuts, and fruits, eaten mostly as a breakfast cereal; -- of Swiss origin.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>muezzin</ent><br/
<hw>mu*ez"zin</hw> <pr>(m<usl/*<ecr/z"z<icr/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Ar.]</ety> <def>A Muslim crier of the hour of prayer; the Moslem official of a mosque who summons the faithful to prayer from a minaret five times a day.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mouezzin</asp>, <asp>mueddin</asp>, <asp>muazzin</asp>, <asp>mu'adhdhin</asp>, and <asp>muwazzin</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muff</ent><br/
<hw>Muff</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/f)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. LG. <ets>muff</ets>, D. <ets>mof</ets>, G., Dan., & Sw. <ets>muff</ets>, F. <ets>moufle</ets> mitten, LL. <ets>muffula</ets>, MHG. <ets>mouwe</ets> sleeve, D. <ets>mouw</ets>, and E. <ets>muffle</ets>, v.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A soft cover of cylindrical form, usually of fur, worn by women to shield the hands from cold.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>A short hollow cylinder surrounding an object, as a pipe.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Glass Manuf.)</fld> <def>A blown cylinder of glass which is afterward flattened out to make a sheet.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <ety>[Perhaps a different word; cf. Prov. E. <ets>maffle</ets> to slammer.]</ety> <def>A stupid fellow; a poor-spirited person.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <ldquo/A <xex>muff</xex> of a curate.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <ety>[See 4.]</ety> <fld>(Baseball)</fld> <def>A failure to hold a ball when once in the hands.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The whitethroat.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muff</ent><br/
<hw>Muff</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Muffed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Muffing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To handle awkwardly; to fumble; to fail to hold, as a ball, in catching it.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muffetee</ent><br/
<hw>Muf`fe*tee"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A small muff worn over the wrist.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>  <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muffin</ent><br/
<hw>Muf"fin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Muff</er>.]</ety> <def>A light, spongy, cylindrical cake, used for breakfast and tea.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muffineer</ent><br/
<hw>Muf`fin*eer"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A dish for keeping muffins hot.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muffish</ent><br/
<hw>Muff"ish</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Muff</er>, 4 & 5.]</ety> <def>Stupid; awkward.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muffle</ent><br/
<hw>Muf"fle</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/f"f'l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The bare end of the nose between the nostrils; -- used esp. of ruminants.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muffle</ent><br/
<hw>Muf"fle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Muffled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Muffling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>moufle</ets> a mitten, LL. <ets>muffula</ets>, OD. <ets>moffel</ets> a muff. See <er>Muff</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To wrap up in something that conceals or protects; to wrap, as the face and neck, in thick and disguising folds; hence, to conceal or cover the face of; to envelop; to inclose; -- often with <xex>up</xex>.</def>  <rj><au>South.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The face lies <qex>muffled</qex> up within the garment.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>muffled</qex> with a cloud his mournful eyes.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Muffled</qex> up in darkness and superstition.</q> <rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To prevent seeing, or hearing, or speaking, by wraps bound about the head; to blindfold; to deafen.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To wrap or fit with something that dulls or deadens the sound of; <as>as, to <ex>muffle</ex> the strings of a drum, or that part of an oar which rests in the rowlock; to <ex>muffle</ex> the exhaust of a motor vehicle</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muffle</ent><br/
<hw>Muf"fle</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>maffle</ets>, <ets>mumble</ets>, D. <ets>moffelen</ets>.]</ety> <def>To speak indistinctly, or without clear articulation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muffle</ent><br/
<hw>Muf"fle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>moufle</ets>, prop., a mitten, from the resemblance in shape. See <er>Muffle</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, <er>Muff</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Anything with which another thing, as an oar or drum, is muffled; also, a boxing glove; a muff.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Metal.)</fld> <def>An earthenware compartment or oven, often shaped like a half cylinder, used in furnaces to protect objects heated from the direct action of the fire, as in scorification of ores, cupellation of ore buttons, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Ceramics)</fld> <def>A small oven for baking and fixing the colors of painted or printed pottery, without exposing the pottery to the flames of the furnace or kiln.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A pulley block containing several sheaves.</def>  <rj><au>Knight.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>muffled</ent><br/
<hw>muffled</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>  <def>same as <er>muted</er>; <as>as, <ex>muffled</ex> drums; the <ex>muffled</ex> noises of the street</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> dull, muted, softened.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Wrapped up especially for protection or secrecy; <as>as, children <ex>muffled</ex> almost to the eyebrows</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muffler</ent><br/
<hw>Muf"fler</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Anything used in muffling; esp., a scarf for protecting the head and neck in cold weather; a tippet.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fortune is painted blind, with a <qex>muffler</qex> above her eyes.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A cushion for terminating or softening a note made by a stringed instrument with a keyboard.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A kind of mitten or boxing glove, esp. when stuffed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>One who muffles.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>Any of various devices to deaden the noise of escaping gases or vapors, as a tube filled with obstructions, through which the exhaust gases of an internal-combustion engine, as on an automobile, are passed (called also <altname>silencer</altname>).</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muflon</ent><br/
<hw>Muf"lon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Mouflon</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mufti</ent><br/
<hw>Muf"ti</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Muftis</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Ar. <ets>mufti</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An official expounder of Muslim law.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One of the chief legal advisers to the Sultan of the Ottoman Empire.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mufti</ent><br/
<hw>muf"ti</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Ordinary civilian dress when worn by persons who serve in a uniformed service, such as the military or police.  It originally was used in reference to British naval or military officers, and originated with the British service in India.</def> <mark>[Colloq. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mug</ent><br/
<hw>Mug</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/g)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Ir. <ets>mugam</ets> a mug, <ets>mucog</ets> a cup.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A kind of ceramic or metal drinking cup, with a handle, -- usually cylindrical and without a lip.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The face or mouth; <as>as, I don't want to see your ugly <ex>mug</ex> again</as>; -- often used contemptuously.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark>  <rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mug</ent><br/
<hw>mug</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/g)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To take property from (a person) in a public place by threatening or committing violence on the person who is robbed; to rob, especially to rob by use of a weapon such as a knife or gun.</def>  <note>To rob a person or a business indoors is not usually referred to as to <ex>mug</ex>, but to <contr>stick up</contr> or <contr>hold up</contr>.</note><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> rob, stick up</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mugful</ent><br/
<hw>mugful</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>the quantity that can be held in a mug.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mug.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muggard</ent><br/
<hw>Mug"gard</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. G. <ets>mucker</ets> a sulky person, <ets>muckish</ets> sullen, peevish, <ets>mucken</ets> to mutter, grumble.]</ety> <def>Sullen; displeased.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muggur</ent><br/
<ent>Muggar</ent><br/
<ent>Mugger</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mug"ger</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> Also <hw>Mug"gar</hw>, <hw>Mug"gur</hw> }</mhw>. <ety>[Hind. <ets>magar</ets>, fr. Skr. <ets>makara</ets> sea monster.]</ety> <def>The common crocodile (<spn>Crocodilus palustris</spn>) of India, the East Indies, etc. It becomes twelve feet or more long.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mugger</ent><br/
<hw>mugger</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A thief who takes property by threatening (or performing) violence on the person who is robbed; a person who commits a mugging; one who mugs.  See <er>mug</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos></def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> robber</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mugget</ent><br/
<hw>Mug"get</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The small entrails of a calf or a hog.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mugginess</ent><br/
<hw>Mug"gi*ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The condition or quality of being muggy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mugging</ent><br/
<hw>Mug"ging</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> from <er>mug</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <def>A robbery; a taking of property by threatening (or performing) violence on the person who is robbed.  See <er>mug</er>, <pos>v.</pos></def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> robbery, holdup, stickup</syn><br/
[<source>PJC</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muggins</ent><br/
<hw>Mug"gins</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Etym. unknown.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A game of dominoes in which the object is to make the sum of the two ends of the line some multiple of five.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>A game at cards which depends upon building in suits or matching exposed cards, the object being to get rid of one's cards.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muggins</ent><br/
<hw>Mug"gins</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>In certain games, to score against, or take an advantage over (an opponent), as for an error, announcing the act by saying <ldquo/muggins.<rdquo/</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muggish</ent><br/
<hw>Mug"gish</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>See <er>Muggy</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muggletonian</ent><br/
<hw>Mug`gle*to"ni*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>One of an extinct sect, named after <person>Ludovic <etsep>Muggleton</etsep></person>, an English journeyman tailor, who (about 1657) claimed to be inspired.</def>  <rj><au>Eadie.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muggy</ent><br/
<hw>Mug"gy</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/g"g<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Muggier</adjf> <pr>(m<ucr/g"g<icr/*<etil/r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Muggiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[Cf. Icel. <ets>mugga</ets> mist, mugginess.  Cf. 4th <er>Mold</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Moist; damp; moldy; <as>as, <ex>muggy</ex> straw</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Warm, damp, and windless; uncomfortably hot and humid; sultry; <as>as, <ex>muggy</ex> air, weather</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 952 --></p>

<p><ent>Mughouse</ent><br/
<hw>Mug"house`</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/g"hous`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An alehouse; a pothouse.</def>  <rj><au>Tickel.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mugiency</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"gi*en*cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A bellowing.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mugient</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"gi*ent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mugiens</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>mugire</ets> to bellow.]</ety> <def>Lowing; bellowing.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mugil</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mu"gil</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[L., a sort of fish.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of fishes including the gray mullets. See <er>Mullet</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mugilidae</ent><br/
<hw>Mugilidae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of fish including the gray mullets.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Mugilidae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mugiloidea</ent><br/
<hw>Mugiloidea</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A suborder of fishes distinguished by abdominal pelvic fins, including the families <fam>Mugilidae</fam>; <fam>Atherinidae</fam>; and <fam>Sphyraenidae</fam>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> suborder <subord>Mugiloidea</subord>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mugiloid</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"gi*loid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Like or pertaining to the genus <gen>Mugil</gen>, or family <fam>Mugilidae</fam>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mugweed</ent><br/
<hw>Mug"weed`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A slender European weed (<spn>Galium Cruciata</spn>); -- called also <altname>crossweed</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mugwort</ent><br/
<hw>Mug"wort`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>mucgwyrt</ets>.  Cf. <er>Midge</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A somewhat aromatic composite weed (<spn>Artemisia vulgaris</spn>), at one time used medicinally; -- called also <altname>motherwort</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mugwump</ent><br/
<hw>mug"wump`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Algonquin <ets>mugquomp</ets> a chief.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A bolter from the Republican party in the national election of 1884; an Independent.</def> <mark>[Political Cant, U.S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A person who is undecided about an issue, especially a political one; a person who takes a neutral stance on an issue; a fence-sitter.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mugwumpism</ent><br/
<ent>Mugwumpery</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mug"wump`er*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mug"wump*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The acts and views of the mugwumps.</def> <mark>[Political Cant, U.S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muhammedan</ent><br/
<ent>Muhammadan</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mu*ham"mad*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mu*ham"med*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Islamic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muhammedan</ent><br/
<ent>Muhammadan</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mu*ham"mad*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mu*ham"med*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A Muslim.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muhammadanism</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*ham"mad*an*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Mohammedanism; Islam.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muharram</ent><br/
<hw>Muharram</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The first month of the Islamic calendar.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>muishond</ent><br/
<hw>muishond</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A southern African weasel.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mujik</ent><br/
<hw>mujik</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A Russian peasant (especially prior to 1917).</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> muzhik, moujik, muzjik.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulada</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mu*la"da</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A moor.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark>  <rj><au>Lockhart.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulada</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mu*la"da</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. Amer., fr. Sp. <ets>mulo</ets>, <ets>mula</ets>, a mule.]</ety> <def>A drove of mules.</def> <mark>[Southwest. U.S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulatto</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*lat"to</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mulattoes</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Sp. & Pg. <ets>mulato</ets>, masc., <ets>mulata</ets>, fem., of a mixed breed, fr. <ets>mulo</ets> mule, L. <ets>mulus</ets>. See <er>Mule</er>.]</ety> <def>The offspring of a negress by a white man, or of a white woman by a negro, -- usually of a brownish yellow complexion.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulattress</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*lat"tress</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A female mulatto.</def>  <rj><au>G. W. Gable.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulberry</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ber*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mulberries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>moolbery</ets>, <ets>murberie</ets>, AS. <ets>murberie</ets>, where the first part is fr. L. <ets>morum</ets> mulberry; cf. Gr. <?/, <?/.  Cf. <er>Murrey</er>, <er>Sycamore</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The berry or fruit of any tree of the genus <gen>Morus</gen>; also, the tree itself. See <er>Morus</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A dark pure color, like the hue of a black mulberry.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mulberry mass</b></col>. <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Morula</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Paper mulberry</b></col>, <cd>a tree (<spn>Broussonetia papyrifera</spn>), related to the true mulberry, used in Polynesia for making tapa cloth by macerating and pounding the inner bark, and in China and Japan for the manufacture of paper.  It is seen as a shade tree in America.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulberry-faced</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ber*ry-faced`</hw> <pr>(-f<amac/st`)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having a face of a mulberry color, or blotched as if with mulberry stains.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulch</ent><br/
<hw>Mulch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <ets>mull</ets> dirt, also Prov. G. <ets>mulsch</ets>, <ets>molsch</ets>, rotten, soft, mellow, as fruit.]</ety> <def>Half-rotten straw, or any similar light, porous, organic substance strewn on the ground, as over the roots of plants, to protect from heat, drought, etc., and to hinder weed growth and preserve moisture.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulch</ent><br/
<hw>Mulch</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mulched</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mulching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To cover or dress with mulch.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulct</ent><br/
<hw>Mulct</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mulcta</ets>, <ets>multa</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A fine or penalty, esp. a pecuniary punishment or penalty.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A blemish or defect.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Amercement; forfeit; forfeiture; penalty.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulct</ent><br/
<hw>Mulct</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mulcted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mulcting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>mulctare</ets>, <ets>multare</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To punish for an offense or misdemeanor by imposing a fine or forfeiture, esp. a pecuniary fine; to fine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, to deprive of; to withhold by way of punishment or discipline.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulctuary</ent><br/
<ent>Mulctary</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mulc"ta*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mulc"tu*a*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Imposing a pecuniary penalty; consisting of, or paid as, a fine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fines, or some known <qex>mulctuary</qex> punishments.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Temple.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mule</ent><br/
<hw>Mule</hw> <pr>(m<umac/l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., a she-mule, L. <ets>mula</ets>, fem. of <ets>mulus</ets>; cf. Gr. <grk>my`klos</grk>, <grk>mychlo`s</grk>.  Cf. AS. <ets>m<umac/l</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mulus</ets>.  Cf. <er>Mulatto</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A hybrid animal; specifically, one generated between an ass and a mare.  Sometimes the term is applied to the offspring of a horse and a she-ass, but that hybrid is more properly termed a <contr>hinny</contr>.  See <er>Hinny</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Mules are much used as draught animals.  They are hardy, and proverbial for stubbornness.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A plant or vegetable produced by impregnating the pistil of one species with the pollen or fecundating dust of another; -- called also <altname>hybrid</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A very stubborn person.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A machine, used in factories, for spinning cotton, wool, etc., into yarn or thread and winding it into cops; -- called also <altname>jenny</altname> and <altname>mule-jenny</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A slipper that has no fitting around the heel.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mules, scuff, scuffs.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mule armadillo</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a long-eared armadillo <fld>(Tatusia hybrida)</fld>, native of Buenos Ayres; -- called also <altname>mulita</altname>. See <xex>Illust.</xex> under <er>Armadillo</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mule deer</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a large deer (<spn>Cervus macrotis</spn> syn. <spn>Cariacus macrotis</spn>) of the Western United States.  The name refers to its long ears.</cd> -- <col><b>Mule pulley</b></col> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>an idle pulley for guiding a belt which transmits motion between shafts that are not parallel.</cd> -- <col><b>Mule twist</b></col>, <cd>cotton yarn in cops, as spun on a mule; -- in distinction from yarn spun on a throstle frame.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mule-jenny</ent><br/
<hw>Mule"-jen`ny</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mule</er>, 4.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mule killer</ent><br/
<hw>Mule killer</hw>. <def>Any of several arthropods erroneously supposed to kill live stock, in the southern United States, by stinging or by being swallowed;</def> as: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A whip scorpion.</def> <mark>[Florida]</mark> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A walking-stick insect.</def> <mark>[Texas]</mark> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>A mantis.</def> <sd>(d)</sd> <def>A wheel bug.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muleteer</ent><br/
<hw>Mu`le*teer"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>muletier</ets>, fr. <ets>mulet</ets> a mule, dim. fr. L. <ets>mulus</ets>.]</ety> <def>One who drives mules.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulewort</ent><br/
<hw>Mule"wort`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A fern of the genus <gen>Hemionitis</gen>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muley</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ley</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Sawmills)</fld> <def>A stiff, long saw, guided at the ends but not stretched in a gate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Muley axle</b></col> <fld>(Railroad)</fld>, <cd>a car axle without collars at the outer ends of the journals.</cd>  <rj><au>Forney.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muley</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ey</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mulley</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muliebrity</ent><br/
<hw>Mu`li*eb"ri*ty</hw> <pr>(m<umac/`l<icr/*<ecr/b"r<icr/*t<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>muliebritas</ets>, fr. <ets>muliebris</ets> belonging to a woman, fr. <ets>mulier</ets> a woman.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The state of being a woman or of possessing full womanly powers; womanhood; -- correlate of <contr>virility</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>Effeminancy; softness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulier</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mu"li*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., a woman.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A woman.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Lawful issue born in wedlock, in distinction from an elder brother born of the same parents before their marriage; a lawful son.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Civ. Law)</fld> <def>A woman; a wife; a mother.</def>  <rj><au>Blount.</au>  <au>Cowell.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulierly</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"li*er*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In the manner or condition of a mulier; in wedlock; legitimately.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulierose</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"li*er*ose`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mulierosus</ets>.]</ety> <def>Fond of woman.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Charles Reade.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulierosity</ent><br/
<hw>Mu`li*er*os"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mulierositas</ets>.]</ety> <def>A fondness for women.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Dr. H. More.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulierty</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"li*er*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Condition of being a mulier; position of one born in lawful wedlock.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulish</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ish</hw> <pr>(m<umac/l"<icr/sh)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Like a mule; sullen; stubborn.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mul"ish*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mul"ish*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mull</ent><br/
<hw>Mull</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Perh. contr. fr. <ets>mossul</ets>. See <er>Muslin</er>.]</ety> <def>A thin, soft kind of muslin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mull</ent><br/
<hw>Mull</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Icel. <ets>m<umac/li</ets> a snout, muzzle, projecting crag; or cf. Ir. & Gael. <ets>meall</ets> a heap of earth, a mound, a hill or eminence, W. <ets>moel</ets>.  Cf. <er>Mouth</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A promontory; <as>as, the <ex>Mull</ex> of Cantyre</as>.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A snuffbox made of the small end of a horn.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mull</ent><br/
<hw>Mull</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. akin to <ets>mold</ets>. <root/108. See <er>Mold</er>.]</ety> <def>Dirt; rubbish.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Gower.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mull</ent><br/
<hw>Mull</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mullen</ets>. See 2d <er>Muller</er>.]</ety> <def>To powder; to pulverize.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mull</ent><br/
<hw>Mull</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To work (over) mentally; to cogitate; to ruminate; -- usually with <ptcl>over</ptcl>; <as>as, to <ex>mull</ex> over a thought or a problem</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq. U.S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mull</ent><br/
<hw>Mull</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An inferior kind of madder prepared from the smaller roots or the peelings and refuse of the larger.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mull</ent><br/
<hw>Mull</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mulled</conjf> <pr>(m<ucr/ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mulling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From <ets>mulled</ets>, for <ets>mold</ets>, taken as a p. p.; OE. <ets>mold</ets>-ale funeral ale or banquet. See <er>Mold</er> soil.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To heat, sweeten, and enrich with spices; <as>as, to <ex>mull</ex> wine</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>New cider, <qex>mulled</qex> with ginger warm.</q> <rj><qau>Gay.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To dispirit or deaden; to dull or blunt.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mullah</ent><br/
<ent>Mulla</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Mul"la</hw>, <hw>Mul"lah</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Mollah</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mullagatawny</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`la*ga*taw"ny</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Tamil <ets>milagu-tann<imac/r</ets> pepper water.]</ety> <def>An East Indian curry soup.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mullah</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"lah</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mollah</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mullar</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A die, cut in intaglio, for stamping an ornament in relief, as upon metal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mullein</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"lein</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>moleyn</ets>, AS. <ets>molegn</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Any plant of the genus <gen>Verbascum</gen>.  They are tall herbs having coarse leaves, and large flowers in dense spikes.  The common species, with densely woolly leaves, is <spn>Verbascum Thapsus</spn>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Moth mullein</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Moth</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mullein foxglove</b></col>, <cd>an American herb (<spn>Seymeria macrophylla</spn>) with coarse leaves and yellow tubular flowers with a spreading border.</cd> -- <col><b>Petty mullein</b></col>, <cd>the cowslip.</cd> <au>Dr. Prior.</au></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mullen</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"len</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>See <er>Mullein</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muller</ent><br/
<hw>Mull"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, mulls.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A vessel in which wine, etc., is mulled over a fire.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muller</ent><br/
<hw>Mull"er</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mullen</ets> to pulverize, bruise; cf. Icel. <ets>mylja</ets>; prob. akin to E. <ets>mold</ets> soil. See <er>Mold</er> soil, and cf. <er>Mull</er> dirt.]</ety> <def>A stone or thick lump of glass, or kind of pestle, flat at the bottom, used for grinding pigments or drugs, etc., upon a slab of similar material.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muellerian</ent><br/
<ent>Mullerian</ent><br/
<hw>M<uum/l*le"ri*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <fld>(Anat., Med.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or discovered by, <person>Johannes <etsep>M<uum/ller</etsep></person>; <as>as, Mullerian duct; Muellerian tumor; M<uum/llerian capsule</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>M<uum/llerian ducts</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>a pair of embryonic ducts which give rise to the genital passages in the female, but disappear in the male.</cd> -- <col><b>M<uum/llerian fibers</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>the sustentacular or connective-tissue fibers which form the framework of the retina.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mullet</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"let</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>molet</ets>, <ets>mulet</ets>, F. <ets>mulet</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mullus</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of numerous fishes of the genus Mugil; -- called also <altname>gray mullets</altname>. They are found on the coasts of both continents, and are highly esteemed as food. Among the most valuable species are <styp><spn>Mugil capito</spn></styp> of Europe, and <styp><spn>Mugil cephalus</spn></styp> which occurs both on the European and American coasts.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any species of the genus <gen>Mullus</gen>, or family <fam>Mullidae</fam>; called also <altname>red mullet</altname>, and <altname>surmullet</altname>, esp. the plain surmullet (<spn>Mullus barbatus</spn>), and the striped surmullet (<spn>Mullus surmulletus</spn>) of Southern Europe.  The former is the mullet of the Romans. It is noted for the brilliancy of its colors. See <er>Surmullet</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>French mullet</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Ladyfish</er> <sd>(a)</sd>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mullet</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"let</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>molette</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>A star, usually five pointed and pierced; -- when used as a difference it indicates the third son.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mullet</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"let</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>molet</ets> a sort of pinchers.]</ety> <def>Small pinchers for curling the hair.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moolley</ent><br/
<ent>Mulley</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mul"ley</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mool"ley</hw>  }</mhw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[CF. Gael. <ets>maolag</ets> a hornless cow, <ets>maol</ets> bald, hornless, blunt.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A mulley or polled animal.</def> <mark>[U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A cow.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.; U.S., a child's word.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Leave milking and dry up old <qex>mulley</qex>, thy cow.</q> <rj><qau>Tusser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moolley</ent><br/
<ent>Mulley</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mul"ley</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mool"ley</hw>  }</mhw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Destitute of horns, although belonging to a species of animals most of which have horns; hornless; polled; <as>as, <ex>mulley</ex> cattle; a <ex>mulley</ex> (or <ex>moolley</ex>) cow.</as></def> <mark>[U. S.]</mark> <altsp>[Written also <asp>muley</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mulligan stew</ent><br/
<ent>mulligan</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mulligan</hw>, <hw>mulligan stew</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A stew made typically of meat, vegetables, and any conveniently available ingredients; also, an Irish version of burgoo.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Irish burgoo.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Golf)</fld> <def>In informal and friendly games of golf, a permission to take another stroke without counting the previous stroke against the score, when a stroke was poorly played; a free stroke; <as>as, to take a <ex>mulligan</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulligatawny</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`li*ga*taw"ny</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mullagatawny</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulligrubs</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"li*grubs</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Prov. E. <ets>mull</ets> to squeeze, pull about, <ets>mulling</ets> numb or dull.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A griping of the intestines; colic.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whose dog lies sick of the <qex>mulligrubs</qex>?</q> <rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, sullenness; the sulks.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mullingong</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"lin*gong</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <cref>Duck mole</cref>, under <er>Duck</er>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mollingong</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mullion</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"lion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[A corruption of <ets>munnion</ets>, F. <ets>moignon</ets> stump of an amputated limb, stump, OF. <ets>moing</ets> mutilated; cf. Armor. <ets>mo<ntil/</ets>, <ets>mou<ntil/</ets>, <ets>mank</ets>, <ets>monk</ets>, and also L. <ets>mancus</ets> maimed.]</ety> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A slender bar or pier which forms the division between the lights of windows, screens, etc.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>An upright member of a framing. See <er>Stile</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mullion</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"lion</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To furnish with mullions; to divide by mullions.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mullock</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"lock</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mull</er> dirt: cf. Scot. <ets>mulloch</ets>, <ets>mulock</ets>, crumb. <root/108.]</ety> <def>Rubbish; refuse; dirt.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All this <qex>mullok</qex> [was] in a sieve ythrowe.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulloid</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"loid</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/l"loid)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[NL. <ets>Mullus</ets>, generic name (fr. L. <ets>mullus</ets> surmullet) + <ets>-oid</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Like or pertaining to the genus <gen>Mullus</gen>, which includes the surmullet, or red mullet.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mull over</ent><br/
<hw>mull over</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To think about; to consider; to ruminate about; <as>as, <ex>mull</ex> it <ex>over</ex> and decide in the morning</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq. U.S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulmul</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"mul</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A fine, soft muslin; mull.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulse</ent><br/
<hw>Mulse</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/ls)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mulsum</ets> (sc. <ets>vinum</ets>), fr. <ets>mulsus</ets> mixed with honey, honey-sweet, p. p. of <ets>mulcere</ets> to sweeten, soften.]</ety> <def>Wine boiled and mingled with honey.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mult-</ent><br/
<hw>Mult-</hw>. <def>See <er>Multi-</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multangular</ent><br/
<hw>Mul*tan"gu*lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multangulus</ets>; <ets>multus</ets> much, many + <ets>angulus</ets> angle: cf. F. <ets>multangulaire</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having many angles.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mul*tan"gu*lar*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mul*tan"gu*lar*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multanimous</ent><br/
<hw>Mul*tan"i*mous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mult-</ets> + L. <ets>animus</ets> mind.]</ety> <def>Many-minded; many-sided.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>multanimous</qex> nature of the poet.</q> <rj><qau>J. R. Lowell.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multarticulate</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`tar*tic"u*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mult-</ets> + <ets>articulate</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having many articulations or joints.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multeity</ent><br/
<hw>Mul*te"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multus</ets> much, many.]</ety> <def>Multiplicity.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Coleridge.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mult-</ent><br/
<ent>Multi-</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mul"ti-</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mult-</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>. <ety>[L. <ets>multus</ets> much.]</ety> <def>A prefix signifying <sig>much</sig> or <sig>many</sig>; <sig>several</sig>; <sig>more than one</sig>; <as>as, <ex>multi</ex>axial, <ex>mult</ex>ocular</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiaxial</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*ax"i*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>axial</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Having more than one axis; developing in more than a single line or plain; -- opposed to <ant>monoaxial</ant>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multicapsular</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*cap"su*lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>capsular</ets>: cf. F. <ets>multicapsulaire</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having many, or several, capsules.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multicarinate</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*car"i*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>carinate</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Many-keeled.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multicavous</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*ca"vous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multicavus</ets>; <ets>multus</ets> much, many + <ets>cavum</ets>, <ets>cavus</ets>, a cavity, hole, fr. <ets>cavus</ets> hollow.]</ety> <def>Having many cavities.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multicellular</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*cel"lu*lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Consisting of, or having, many cells or more than one cell.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multicentral</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*cen"tral</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>central</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having many, or several, centers; <as>as, a <ex>multicentral</ex> cell</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Multicentral development</b></col> <fld>(Biol.)</fld>, <cd>growth, or development, from several centers. According as the insubordination to a single center is more or less pronounced, the resultant organism will be more or less irregular in form and may even become discontinuous.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multicipital</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*cip"i*tal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + L. <ets>caput</ets> head.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having many heads or many stems from one crown or root.</def>  <rj><au>Gray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multicolor</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*col`or</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Multi-</er>, and <er>Color</er>.]</ety> <def>Having many, or several, colors.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multicostate</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*cos"tate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>costate</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having numerous ribs, or costae, as the leaf of a plant, or as certain shells and corals.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multicuspid</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*cus"pid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <ets>Multi-</ets>, and <ets>Cuspid</ets>.]</ety> <def>Multicuspidate; -- said of teeth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multicuspidate</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*cus"pi*date</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>cuspidate</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having many cusps or points.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multidentate</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*den"tate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>dentate</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having many teeth, or toothlike processes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multidigitate</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*dig"i*tate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>digitate</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having many fingers, or fingerlike processes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multifaced</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*faced`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>face</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having many faces.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multifarious</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*fa"ri*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multifarius</ets>; <ets>multus</ets> much, many.  Cf. <er>Bifarious</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having multiplicity; having great diversity or variety; of various kinds; diversified; made up of many differing parts; manifold.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is a <qex>multifarious</qex> artifice in the structure of the meanest animal.</q> <rj><qau>Dr. H. More.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having parts, as leaves, arranged in many vertical rows.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multifariously</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*fa"ri*ous*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>With great multiplicity and diversity; with variety of modes and relations.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multifariousness</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*fa"ri*ous*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Multiplied diversity.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The fault of improperly uniting in one bill distinct and independent matters, and thereby confounding them.</def>  <rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiferous</ent><br/
<hw>Mul*tif"er*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multifer</ets>; <ets>multus</ets> much, many + <ets>ferre</ets> to bear.]</ety> <def>Bearing or producing much or many.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multifid</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*fid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multifidus</ets>; <ets>multus</ets> much, many + <ets>findere</ets> to split: cf. F. <ets>multifide</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having many segments; cleft into several parts by linear sinuses; <as>as, a <ex>multifid</ex> leaf or corolla</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiflorous</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*flo"rous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multiflorus</ets>; <ets>multus</ets> much, many + <ets>flos</ets>, <ets>floris</ets>, flower: cf. F. <ets>multiflore</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having many flowers.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 953 --></p>

<p><ent>Multiflue</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*flue</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/l"t<icr/*fl<umac/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>flue</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having many flues; <as>as, a <ex>multiflue</ex> boiler</as>. See <er>Boiler</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multifoil</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*foil</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/l"t<icr/*foil)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>foil</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>An ornamental foliation consisting of more than five divisions or foils.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <see>See <er>Foil</er>.</see><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multifoil</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*foil</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having more than five divisions or foils.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multifold</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*fold</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/l"t<icr/*f<omac/ld)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>fold</ets>.]</ety> <def>Many times doubled; manifold; numerous.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiform</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*form</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/l"t<icr/*f<ocir/rm)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multiformis</ets>; <ets>multus</ets> much, many + <ets>forma</ets> shape: cf. F. <ets>multiforme</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having many forms, shapes, or appearances.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A plastic and <qex>multiform</qex> unit.</q> <rj><qau>Hare.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiformity</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*form"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multiformitas</ets>.]</ety> <def>The quality of being multiform; diversity of forms; variety of appearances in the same thing.</def>  <rj><au>Purchas.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiformous</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*form"ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Multiform.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multigenerous</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*gen"er*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multigenerus</ets>; <ets>multus</ets> + <ets>genus</ets>, <ets>generis</ets>, kind.]</ety> <def>Having many kinds.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multigranulate</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*gran"u*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>granulate</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having, or consisting of, many grains.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multigraph</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*graph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>  <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>-graph</ets>.]</ety> <def>A combined rotary type-setting and printing machine for office use.  The type is transferred semi-automatically by means of keys from a type-supply drum to a printing drum.  The printing may be done by means of an inked ribbon to print <ldquo/typewritten<rdquo/ letters, or directly from inked type or a stereotype plate, as in a printing press.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multijugate</ent><br/
<hw>Mul*tij"u*gate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having many pairs of leaflets.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multijugous</ent><br/
<hw>Mul*tij"u*gous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multijugus</ets>; <ets>multus</ets> + <ets>jugum</ets> yoke.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Consisting of many parts.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Multijugate</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multilateral</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*lat"er*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>lateral</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having many sides; many-sided.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multilineal</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*lin"e*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>lineal</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having many lines.</def>  <rj><au>Steevens.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multilobar</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*lo"bar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>lobar</ets>.]</ety> <def>Consisting of, or having, many lobes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multilocular</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*loc"u*lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>locular</ets>: cf. F. <ets>multiloculaire</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having many or several cells or compartments; <as>as, a <ex>multilocular</ex> shell or capsule</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiloquence</ent><br/
<hw>Mul*til"o*quence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Quality of being multiloquent; use of many words; talkativeness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiloquous</ent><br/
<ent>Multiloquent</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mul*til"o*quent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mul*til"o*quous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multiloquus</ets>; <ets>multus</ets> much, many + <ets>loqui</ets> to speak.]</ety> <def>Speaking much; very talkative; loquacious.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiloquy</ent><br/
<hw>Mul*til"o*quy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multiloquium</ets>.]</ety> <def>Excess of words or talk.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multinodate</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*no"date</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>nodate</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having many knots or nodes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multinodous</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*no"dous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multinodus</ets>.]</ety> <def>Same as <er>Multinodate</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multinomial</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*no"mi*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. & a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>-nomial</ets>, as in binomial. See <er>Binomial</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Alg.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Polynomial</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multinominous</ent><br/
<ent>Multinominal</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mul`ti*nom"i*nal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mul`ti*nom"i*nous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multinominis</ets>; <ets>multus</ets> many + <ets>nomen nominis</ets> name.]</ety> <def>Having many names or terms.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>multinominal</ent><br/
<hw>mul`ti*nom"i*nal</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>Polynomial.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multinuclear</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*nu"cle*ar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>nuclear</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Containing many nuclei; <as>as, <ex>multinuclear</ex> cells</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multinucleated</ent><br/
<ent>Multinucleate</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mul`ti*nu"cle*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mul`ti*nu"cle*a`ted</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Multinuclear.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiparous</ent><br/
<hw>Mul*tip"a*rous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + L. <ets>parere</ets> to produce: cf. F. <ets>multipare</ets>.]</ety> <def>Producing many, or more than one, at a birth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multipartite</ent><br/
<hw>Mul*tip"ar*tite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multipartitus multus</ets> much, many <ets>partitus</ets> divided, p. p.: cf. F. <ets>multipartite</ets>. See <er>Partite</er>.]</ety> <def>Divided into many parts; having several parts.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiped</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*ped</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multipes</ets>, <ets>multipeda</ets>; <ets>multus</ets> much, many + <ets>pes</ets>, <ets>pedis</ets>, foot: cf. F. <ets>multip<egrave/de</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An insect having many feet, as a myriapod.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiped</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*ped</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having many feet.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiphase</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*phase</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>  <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>phase</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having many phases;</def> <specif>specif.</specif> <fld>(Elec.)</fld>, <def>pertaining to, or designating, a generator producing, or any system conveying or utilizing, two or more waves of pressure, or electromotive force, not in phase with each other; polyphase.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiplane</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*plane</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having several or many planes or plane surfaces; <as>as, a <ex>multiplane</ex> kite</as>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiplane</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*plane</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>  <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>plane</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Aeronautics)</fld> <def>An airplane with three or more superposed main wings, such as a <stype>triplane</stype>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiple</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*ple</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>multiple</ets>, and E. <ets>quadruple</ets>, and <ets>multiply</ets>.]</ety> <def>Containing more than once, or more than one; consisting of more than one; manifold; repeated many times; having several, or many, parts.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Law of multiple proportion</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>the generalization that when the same elements unite in more than one proportion, forming two or more different compounds, the higher proportions of the elements in such compounds are simple multiples of the lowest proportion, or the proportions are connected by some simple common factor; thus, iron and oxygen unite in the proportions <chform>FeO</chform>, <chform>Fe2O3</chform>, <chform>Fe3O4</chform>, in which compounds, considering the oxygen, 3 and 4 are simple multiplies of 1.  Called also the <altname>Law of Dalton</altname> or <altname>Dalton's Law</altname>, from its discoverer.</cd> -- <col><b>Multiple algebra</b></col>, <cd>a branch of advanced mathematics that treats of operations upon units compounded of two or more unlike units.</cd> -- <col><b>Multiple conjugation</b></col> <fld>(Biol.)</fld>, <cd>a coalescence of many cells (as where an indefinite number of amoeboid cells flow together into a single mass) from which conjugation proper and even fertilization may have been evolved.</cd> -- <col><b>Multiple fruits</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>See <cref>Collective fruit</cref>, under <er>Collective</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Multiple star</b></col> <fld>(Astron.)</fld>, <cd>several stars in close proximity, which appear to form a single system.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiple</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*ple</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>A quantity containing another quantity an integral number of times without a remainder.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ A <col><b>common multiple</b></col> of two or more numbers contains each of them a number of times exactly; thus, 24 is a <ex>common multiple</ex> of 3 and 4. The <col><b>least common multiple</b></col> is the smallest number that will do this; thus, 12 is the <ex>least common multiple</ex> of 3 and 4 (abbreviated <abbr>LCM</abbr>).</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiplex</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*plex</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multiplex</ets>, <ets>-plicis</ets>. See <er>Multiply</er>.]</ety> <def>Manifold; multiple.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multipliable</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*pli`a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>multipliable</ets>.]</ety> <def>Capable of being multiplied.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mul"ti*pli`a*ble*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiplicable</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*pli*ca*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multiplicabilis</ets>.]</ety> <def>Capable of being multiplied; multipliable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiplicand</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*pli*cand`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multiplicandus</ets> to be multiplied: cf. F. <ets>multiplicande</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>The number which is to be multiplied by another number called the <corr>multiplier</corr>. See Note under <er>Multiplication</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiplicate</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*pli*cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multiplicatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>multiplicare</ets>. See <er>Multiply</er>.]</ety> <def>Consisting of many, or of more than one; multiple; multifold.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Multiplicate flower</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a flower that is double, or has an unusual number of petals in consequence of the abnormal multiplication of the parts of the floral whorls.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiplication</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*pli*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multiplicatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>multiplication</ets>. See <er>Multiply</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or process of multiplying, or of increasing in number; the state of being multiplied; <as>as, the <ex>multiplication</ex> of the human species by natural generation</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The increase and <qex>multiplication</qex> of the world.</q> <rj><qau>Thackeray.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>The process of repeating, or adding to itself, any given number or quantity a certain number of times; commonly, the process of ascertaining by a briefer computation the result of such repeated additions; also, the rule by which the operation is performed; -- the reverse of <inv>division</inv>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The word <xex>multiplication</xex> is sometimes used in mathematics, particularly in multiple algebra, to denote any distributive operation expressed by one symbol upon any quantity or any thing expressed by another symbol.  Corresponding extensions of meaning are given to the words <xex>multiply</xex>, <xex>multiplier</xex>, <xex>multiplicand</xex>, and <xex>product</xex>. Thus, since <mathex><phi/(<it>x + y</it>) = <phi/<it>x</it> + <phi/<it>y</it></mathex> (see under <er>Distributive</er>), where <phi/(<it>x + y</it>), <phi/<it>x</it>, and <phi/<it>y</it> indicate the results of any distributive operation represented by the symbol <phi/ upon <it>x + y</it>, <it>x</it>, and <it>y</it>, severally, then because of many very useful analogies <phi/(<it>x + y</it>) is called the <xex>product</xex> of <phi/ and <it>x + y</it>, and the operation indicated by <phi/ is called <xex>multiplication</xex>.  Cf. <er>Facient</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 2.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>An increase above the normal number of parts, especially of petals; augmentation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The art of increasing gold or silver by magic, -- attributed formerly to the alchemists.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Multiplication table</b></col>, <cd>a table giving the product of a set of numbers multiplied in some regular way; commonly, a table giving the products of the first ten or twelve numbers multiplied successively by 1, 2, 3, etc., up to 10 or 12.  Called also a <altname>times table</altname>, used by students in elementary school prior to memorization of the table.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiplicative</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*pli*ca*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>multiplicatif</ets>.]</ety> <def>Tending to multiply; having the power to multiply, or incease numbers.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiplicatively</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*pli*ca*tive*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>So as to multiply.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiplicator</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*pli*ca`tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.: cf. F. <ets>multiplicateur</ets>.  Cf. <er>Multiplier</er>.]</ety> <def>The number by which another number is multiplied; a multiplier.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiplicious</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*pli"cious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Multiplex</er>.]</ety> <def>Manifold.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiplicity</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*plic"ity</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>multiplicit<eacute/</ets>.]</ety> <def>The quality of being multiple, manifold, or various; a state of being many; a multitude; <as>as, a <ex>multiplicity</ex> of thoughts or objects</as>.</def> <ldquo/A <xex>multiplicity</xex> of goods.<rdquo/  <rj><au>South.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiplier</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*pli`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>multiplier</ets>.  Cf. <er>Multiplicator</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, multiplies or increases number.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>The number by which another number (the <corr>multiplicand</corr>) is multiplied.  See the Note under <er>Multiplication</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>An instrument for multiplying or increasing by repetition or accumulation the intensity of a force or action, as heat or electricity.  It is particularly used to render such a force or action appreciable or measurable when feeble.  See <er>Thermomultiplier</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiply</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*ply</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Multiplied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Multiplying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>multiplier</ets>, L. <ets>multiplicare</ets>, fr. <ets>multiplex</ets> manifold. See <er>Multitude</er>, <er>Complex</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To increase in number; to make more numerous; to add quantity to.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Impunity will <qex>multiply</qex> motives to disobedience.</q> <rj><qau>Ames.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>To add (any given number or quantity) to itself a certain number of times; to find the product of by multiplication; <as>thus 7 <ex>multiplied</ex> by 8 produces the number 56; to <ex>multiply</ex> two numbers</as>. See the Note under <er>Multiplication</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To increase (the amount of gold or silver) by the arts of alchemy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Multiplying gear</b></col> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>gear for increasing speed.</cd> -- <col><b>Multiplying lens</b></col>. <fld>(Opt.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Lens</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiply</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*ply</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become greater in number; to become numerous.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When men began to <qex>multiply</qex> on the face of the earth, and daughters were born unto them.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. vi. 1.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To increase in extent and influence; to spread.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The word of God grew and <qex>multiplied</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Acts xii. 24.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To increase amount of gold or silver by the arts of alchemy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multipolar</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*po"lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>  <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>polar</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having many poles; in <fld>Anat.</fld>, designating specif. a nerve cell which has several dendrites.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>Having, or pertaining to, many poles, as a field magnet or armature of a dynamo, or a dynamo having such a field magnet or (sometimes) armature.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multipotent</ent><br/
<hw>Mul*tip"o*tent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multipotens</ets>; <ets>multus</ets> much + <ets>potens</ets> powerful. See <er>Potent</er>.]</ety> <def>Having manifold power, or power to do many things.</def> <ldquo/Jove <xex>multipotent</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multipresence</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*pres"ence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state or power of being multipresent.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>multipresence</qex> of Christ's body.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Hall.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multipresent</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*pres"ent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>present</ets>, a.]</ety> <def>Being, or having the power to be, present in two or more places at once.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiradiate</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*ra"di*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>radiate</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having many rays.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiramified</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*ram"i*fied</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + p. p. of <ets>ramify</ets>.]</ety> <def>Divided into many branches.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiramose</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*ra*mose"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>ramose</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having many branches.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiscious</ent><br/
<hw>Mul*tis"cious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multiscius</ets>; <ets>multus</ets> much + <ets>scius</ets> knowing, fr. <ets>scire</ets> to know.]</ety> <def>Having much or varied knowledge.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multisect</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*sect</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + L. <ets>sectus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>secare</ets> to cut.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Divided into many similar segments; -- said of an insect or myriapod.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiseptate</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*sep"tate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>septate</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Divided into many chambers by partitions, as the pith of the pokeweed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiserial</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*se"ri*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>serial</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Arranged in many rows, or series, as the scales of a pine cone, or the leaves of the houseleek.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multisiliquous</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*sil"i*quous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>siliquious</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having many pods or seed vessels.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multisonous</ent><br/
<hw>Mul*tis"o*nous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multisonus</ets>; <ets>multus</ets> much, many + <ets>sonus</ets> sound.]</ety> <def>Having many sounds, or sounding much.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multispiral</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*spi"ral</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>spiral</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having numerous spiral coils round a center or nucleus; -- said of the opercula of certain shells.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multistriate</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*stri"ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>striate</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having many streaks.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multisulcate</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*sul"cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>sulcate</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having many furrows.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multisyllable</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*syl`la*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>syllable</ets>.]</ety> <def>A word of many syllables; a polysyllable.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> -- <wordforms><wf>Mul`ti*syl*lab"ic</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multititular</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*tit"u*lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>titular</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having many titles.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multitubular</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*tu"bu*lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>tubular</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having many tubes; <as>as, a <ex>multitubular</ex> boiler</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multitude</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*tude</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>multitude</ets>, L. <ets>multitudo</ets>, <ets>multitudinis</ets>, fr. <ets>multus</ets> much, many; of unknown origin.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A great number of persons collected together; a numerous collection of persons; a crowd; an assembly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But when he saw the <qex>multitudes</qex>, he was moved with compassion on them.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. ix. 36.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A great number of persons or things, regarded collectively; <as>as, the book will be read by a <ex>multitude</ex> of people; the <ex>multitude</ex> of stars; a <ex>multitude</ex> of cares.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is a fault in a <qex>multitude</qex> of preachers, that they utterly neglect method in their harangues.</q> <rj><qau>I. Watts.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>multitude</qex> of flowers<br/
As countless as the stars on high.</q> <rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The state of being many; numerousness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They came as grasshoppers for <qex>multitude</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Judg. vi. 5.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The multitude</b></col>, <cd>the populace; the mass of men.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Throng; crowd; assembly; assemblage; commonalty; swarm; populace; vulgar. See <er>Throng</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multitudinary</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*tu"di*na*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Multitudinous.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multitudinous</ent><br/
<hw>Mul`ti*tu"di*nous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Consisting of a multitude; manifold in number or condition; <as>as, <ex>multitudinous</ex> waves</as>.</def> <ldquo/The <xex>multitudinous</xex> seas.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A renewed jingling of <qex>multitudinous</qex> chains.</q> <rj><qau>G. Kennan.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a multitude.</def> <ldquo/The <xex>multitudinous</xex> tongue.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Mul`ti*tu"di*nous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mul`ti*tu"di*nous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multivagous</ent><br/
<ent>Multivagant</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mul*tiv"a*gant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mul*tiv"a*gous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multivagus</ets>; <ets>multus</ets> much + <ets>vagus</ets> wandering; cf. <ets>vagans</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>vagari</ets>. See <er>Vagary</er>.]</ety> <def>Wandering much.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multivalence</ent><br/
<hw>Mul*tiv"a*lence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Quality, state, or degree, of a multivalent element, atom, or radical.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multivalent</ent><br/
<hw>Mul*tiv"a*lent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + L. <ets>valens</ets>, p. pr. See <er>Valence</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Having a valence greater than one, as silicon.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Having more than one degree of valence, as sulphur.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Immunology)</fld> <def>Having multiple antigen-binding sites; -- of antibody molecules.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Immunology)</fld> <def>Containing several types of antibody, to protect against more than one disease; polyvalent; -- of vaccines.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multivalve</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ti*valve</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>multivalve</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any mollusk which has a shell composed of more than two pieces.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multivalvular</ent><br/
<ent>Multivalve</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mul"ti*valve</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mul`ti*val"vu*lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>valve</ets>, <ets>valvular</ets>: cf. F. <ets>multivalve</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having many valves.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Many-valved; having more than two valves; -- said of certain shells, as the chitons.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multiversant</ent><br/
<hw>Mul*tiv"er*sant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + L. <ets>versans</ets>, p. pr. See <er>Versant</er>.]</ety> <def>Turning into many shapes; assuming many forms; protean.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multivious</ent><br/
<hw>Mul*tiv"i*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a. & adv.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>multivius</ets>; <ets>multus</ets> many + <ets>via</ets> way.]</ety> <def>Having many ways or roads; by many ways.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multivocal</ent><br/
<hw>Mul*tiv"o*cal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>vocal</ets>.]</ety> <def>Signifying many different things; of manifold meaning; equivocal.</def> <ldquo/An ambiguous <xex>multivocal</xex> word.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Coleridge.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A multivocal word.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <au>Fitzed. Hall.</au></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multocular</ent><br/
<hw>Mul*toc"u*lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + L. <ets>oculus</ets> eye.]</ety> <def>Having many eyes, or more than two.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multum</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"tum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An extract of quassia licorice, fraudulently used by brewers in order to economize malt and hops.</def>  <rj><au>Craig.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hard multum</b></col>, <cd>a preparation made from <spn>Cocculus Indicus</spn>, etc., used to impart an intoxicating quality to beer.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multungulate</ent><br/
<hw>Mul*tun"gu*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Multi-</ets> + <ets>ungulate</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having many hoofs.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Multure</ent><br/
<hw>Mul"ture</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>multure</ets>, <ets>moulture</ets>, F. <ets>mouture</ets>, fr. L. <ets>molitura</ets> a grinding, <ets>molere</ets> to grind. See <er>Mill</er> the machine.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Scots Law)</fld> <def>The toll for grinding grain.</def>  <rj><au>Erskine.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A grist or grinding; the grain ground.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mum</ent><br/
<hw>Mum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Of imitative origin.  Cf. <er>Mumble</er>.]</ety> <def>Silent; not speaking; <as>as, to keep <ex>mum</ex></as>.</def>  <rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The citizens are <qex>mum</qex>, and speak not a word.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>mum's the word</b></col> <cd>keep this a secret; don't tell anybody.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mum</ent><br/
<hw>Mum</hw>, <pos>interj.</pos> <def>Be silent! Hush!</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mum</qex>, then, and no more.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mum</ent><br/
<hw>Mum</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Silence.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Hudibras.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mum</ent><br/
<hw>Mum</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G. <ets>mummere</ets>, fr. Christian <ets>Mumme</ets>, who first brewed it in 1492.]</ety> <def>A sort of strong beer, originally made in Brunswick, Germany.</def>  <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The clamorous crowd is hushed with mugs of <qex>mum</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mumble</ent><br/
<hw>Mum"ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mumbled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mumbling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>momelen</ets>; cf. D. <ets>mompelen</ets>, <ets>mommelen</ets>, G. <ets>mummelen</ets>, Sw. <ets>mumla</ets>, Dan. <ets>mumle</ets>.  Cf. <er>Mum</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, <er>Mumm</er>, <er>Mump</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To speak with the lips partly closed, so as to render the sounds inarticulate and imperfect; to utter words in a grumbling indistinct manner, indicating discontent or displeasure; to mutter.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Peace, you <qex>mumbling</qex> fool.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A wrinkled hag, with age grown double,<br/
Picking dry sticks, and <qex>mumbling</qex> to herself.</q> <rj><qau>Otway.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To chew something gently with closed lips.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 954 --></p>

<p><ent>Mumble</ent><br/
<hw>Mum"ble</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/m"b'l)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To utter with a low, inarticulate voice.</def>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To chew or bite gently, as one without teeth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Gums unarmed, to <qex>mumble</qex> meat in vain.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To suppress, or utter imperfectly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mumblety peg</ent><br/
<ent>Mumbledy peg</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Mum"ble*dy peg`</hw>, <hw>Mum"ble*ty peg`</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A game played with a pocketknife, the object of which is to throw the knife in any of a vairety of ways (such as over the back), or from various positions, and have it stick in the ground or another surface.  Also called <altname>mumble-the-peg</altname> and <altname>mumble peg</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mumblenews</ent><br/
<hw>Mum"ble*news`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A talebearer.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mumbler</ent><br/
<hw>Mum"bler</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who mumbles.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mumbling</ent><br/
<hw>Mum"bling</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Low; indistinct; inarticulate.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mum"bling*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mumbo Jumbo</ent><br/
<hw>Mum"bo Jum"bo</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Perh. fr. the native name of an African god.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Among the Mandingos of the western Sudan, a bugbear by means of which the women are terrified and disciplined by societies of the men, one of whom assumes a masquerade for the purpose; hence, loosely, any Negro idol, fetish, or bugaboo.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><q>The miserable <qex>Mumbo Jumbo</qex> they paraded.</q> <rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An object of superstitious homage and fear.</def>  <rj><au>Carlyle.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Incomprehensible or senseless language, usually intended to avoid answering plainly, confuse a listener, or obscure an issue.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Language so arcane or obscure as to be unintelligible to the listener.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mum-chance</ent><br/
<hw>Mum"-chance`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A game of hazard played with cards in silence.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng.]</mark>  <rj><au>Decker.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A silent, stupid person.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>  <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mum-chance</ent><br/
<hw>Mum"-chance`</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Silent and idle.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Boys can't sit <qex>mum-chance</qex> always.</q> <rj><qau>J. H. Ewing.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mu meson</ent><br/
<ent>mu-meson</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>mu-meson</hw>, <hw>mu meson</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>an elementary particle with a negative charge and a half-life of 2 microseconds; the muon.  It is a <isa>lepton</isa>, not a true meson, and decays to an electron and neutrino and antineutrino.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> muon, negative muon.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mumm</ent><br/
<hw>Mumm</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mummed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mumming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[D. <ets>mimmen</ets> to mask, <ets>mom</ets> a mask; akin to G. <ets>mumme</ets> disguise; prob. of imitative origin, and akin to E. <ets>mum</ets>, <ets>mumble</ets>, in allusion to the indistinctness of speech occasioned by talking from behind a mask.  Cf. <er>Mumble</er>, <er>Mummery</er>.]</ety> <def>To sport or make diversion in a mask or disguise; to mask.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With <qex>mumming</qex> and with masking all around.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mummer</ent><br/
<hw>Mumm"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>mommeur</ets>. See <er>Mumm</er>, and cf. <er>Momier</er>.]</ety> <def>One who mumms, or makes diversion in disguise; a masker; a buffon.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Jugglers and dancers, antics, <qex>mummers</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mummery</ent><br/
<hw>Mum"mer*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mummeries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F. <ets>momerie</ets>, of Dutch or German origin. See <er>Mumm</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Masking; frolic in disguise; buffoonery.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>mummery</qex> of foreign strollers.</q> <rj><qau>Fenton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Farcical show; hypocritical disguise and parade or ceremonies.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mummichog</ent><br/
<hw>Mum"mi*chog</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Amer. Indian name.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of several species of small American cyprinodont fishes of the genus <gen>Fundulus</gen>, and of allied genera; the killifishes; -- called also <altname>minnow</altname>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mummychog</asp>, <asp>mummachog</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mummification</ent><br/
<hw>Mum`mi*fi*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mummify</er>.]</ety> <def>The act of making a mummy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mummified</ent><br/
<hw>Mum"mi*fied</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Converted into a mummy or a mummylike substance; having the appearance of a mummy; withered.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mummiform</ent><br/
<hw>Mum"mi*form</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mummy</ets> + <ets>-form</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having some resemblance to a mummy; -- in Zoology, said of the pupae of certain insects.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mummify</ent><br/
<hw>Mum"mi*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mummified</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mummifying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[<ets>Mummy</ets> + <ets>-fy</ets>: cf. F. <ets>momifier</ets>.]</ety> <def>To embalm and dry as a mummy; to make into, or like, a mummy.</def>  <rj><au>Hall (1646).</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mummify</ent><br/
<hw>mum"mi*fy</hw> <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To turn into a mummy-like corpse; to dry up with unusually little decomposition; -- said of dead animals; <as>as, A <ex>mummified</ex> body was found in the attic</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mummy</ent><br/
<hw>Mum"my</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/m"m<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mummies</plw> <pr>(m<ucr/m"m<icr/z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F. <ets>momie</ets>; cf. Sp. & Pg. <ets>momia</ets>, It. <ets>mummia</ets>; all fr. Per. <ets>m<umac/miy<amac/</ets>, fr. <ets>m<umac/m</ets> wax.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A dead body embalmed and dried after the manner of the ancient Egyptians; also, a body preserved, by any means, in a dry state, from the process of putrefaction.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Dried flesh of a mummy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Sir. J. Hill.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A gummy liquor that exudes from embalmed flesh when heated; -- formerly supposed to have magical and medicinal properties.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au>  <au>Sir T. Herbert.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A brown color obtained from bitumen. See <cref>Mummy brown</cref> (below).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Gardening)</fld> <def>A sort of wax used in grafting, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>One whose affections and energies are withered.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mummy brown</b></col>, <cd>a brown color, nearly intermediate in tint between burnt umber and raw umber.  A pigment of this color is prepared from bitumen, etc., obtained from Egyptian tombs.</cd> -- <col><b>Mummy wheat</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>wheat found in the ancient mummy cases of Egypt.  No botanist now believes that genuine mummy wheat has been made to germinate in modern times.</cd> -- <col><b>To beat to a mummy</b></col>, <cd>to beat to a senseless mass; to beat soundly.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mummy</ent><br/
<hw>Mum"my</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mummied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mummying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To embalm; to mummify.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mummychog</ent><br/
<hw>Mum"my*chog</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Mummichog</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mump</ent><br/
<hw>Mump</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Akin to <ets>mumble</ets>; cf. D. <ets>mompen</ets> to cheat; perh. orig., to whine like a beggar, D. <ets>mompelen</ets> to mumble. See <er>Mumble</er>, <er>Mum</er>, and cf. <er>Mumps</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To move the lips with the mouth closed; to mumble, as in sulkiness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>mumps</qex>, and lovers, and hangs the lip.</q> <rj><qau>Taylor, 1630.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To talk imperfectly, brokenly, or feebly; to chatter unintelligibly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cheat; to deceive; to play the beggar.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And then when <qex>mumping</qex> with a sore leg, . . . canting and whining.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To be sullen or sulky.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mump</ent><br/
<hw>Mump</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mumped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mumping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To utter imperfectly, brokenly, or feebly.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Old men who <qex>mump</qex> their passion.</q> <rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To work over with the mouth; to mumble; <as>as, to <ex>mump</ex> food</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To deprive of (something) by cheating; to impose upon.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mumper</ent><br/
<hw>Mump"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A beggar; a begging impostor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Deceived by the tales of a Lincoln's Inn <qex>mumper</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mumpish</ent><br/
<hw>Mump"ish</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Sullen, sulky.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mump"ish*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mump"ish*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mumps</ent><br/
<hw>Mumps</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prov. E. <ets>mump</ets> to be sulky.  Cf. <er>Mump</er>, <er>Mumble</er>, and <er>Mum</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Sullenness; silent displeasure; the sulks.</def>  <rj><au>Skinner.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[Prob. so called from the patient's appearance.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A specific infectious febrile disorder characterized by a nonsuppurative inflammation of the parotid glands, and sometimes causing inflammation of the testes or ovaries; also called <altname>epidemic parotitis</altname> or <altname>infectious parotitis</altname>.  It is caused by infection with a <causes>paramyxovirus</causes>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mun</ent><br/
<hw>Mun</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mouth</er>.]</ety> <def>The mouth.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One a penny, two a penny, hot cross buns,<br/
Butter them and sugar them and put them in your <qex>muns</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Old Rhyme.</qau>  <qau>Halliwell.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Munch</ent><br/
<hw>Munch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Munched</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Munching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Prob. akin to <ets>mumble</ets>: cf. also F. <ets>manger</ets> to eat (cf. <er>Mange</er>), and <ets>m<acir/cher</ets> to cher (cf. <er>Masticate</er>). See <er>Mumble</er>.]</ety> <def>To chew with a grinding, crunching sound, as a beast chews provender; to chew deliberately or in large mouthfuls.</def> <altsp>[Formerly written also <asp>maunch</asp> and <asp>mounch</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I could <qex>munch</qex> your good dry oats.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Munchausenism</ent><br/
<hw>Mun*chau"sen*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[So called in allusion to <person>Baron <ets>Munchausen's</ets></person> extravagant tales of travel.]</ety> <def>An extravagant fiction embodying an account of some marvelous exploit or adventure.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muncher</ent><br/
<hw>Munch"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who munches.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mund</ent><br/
<hw>Mund</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mun</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mundane</ent><br/
<hw>Mun"dane</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mundanus</ets>, fr. <ets>mundus</ets> the world, an implement, toilet adornments, or dress; cf. <ets>mundus</ets>, a., clean, neat, Skr. <ets>ma<nsdot/<dsdot/</ets> to adorn, dress, <ets>ma<nsdot/<dsdot/a</ets> adornment.  Cf. <er>Monde</er>, <er>Mound</er> in heraldry.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the world; worldly, as contrasted with <contr>heavenly</contr>; earthly; terrestrial; <as>as, the <ex>mundane</ex> sphere; <ex>mundane</ex> concerns</as>.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mun"dane*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The defilement of <qex>mundane</qex> passions.</q> <rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Commonplace; ordinary; banal.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mundanity</ent><br/
<hw>Mun*dan"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Worldliness.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mundation</ent><br/
<hw>Mun*da"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mundatio</ets>, fr. <ets>mundare</ets> to make clean.]</ety> <def>The act of cleansing.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mundatory</ent><br/
<hw>Mun"da*to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mundatorius</ets>.]</ety> <def>Cleansing; having power to cleanse.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mundic</ent><br/
<hw>Mun"dic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Iron pyrites, or arsenical pyrites; -- so called by the Cornish miners.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mundificant</ent><br/
<hw>Mun*dif"i*cant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mundificans</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>mundificare</ets> to make clean, fr. <ets>mundus</ets> clean + <ets>-ficare</ets> (in comp.) to make. See <er>-fy</er>.]</ety> <def>Serving to cleanse and heal.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A mundificant ointment or plaster.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mundification</ent><br/
<hw>Mun`di*fi*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act or operation of cleansing.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mundificative</ent><br/
<hw>Mun*dif"i*ca*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Cleansing.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A detergent medicine or preparation.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mundify</ent><br/
<hw>Mun"di*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mondifier</ets>, L. <ets>mundificare</ets>. See <er>Mundificant</er>.]</ety> <def>To cleanse.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mundil</ent><br/
<hw>Mun"dil</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A turban ornamented with an imitation of gold or silver embroidery.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mundivagant</ent><br/
<hw>Mun*div"a*gant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mundus</ets> the world + <ets>vagans</ets> wandering, p. pr. of <ets>vagari</ets>. See <er>Vagary</er>.]</ety> <def>Wandering over the world.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mundungus</ent><br/
<hw>Mun*dun"gus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Sp. <ets>mondongo</ets> paunch, tripe, black pudding.]</ety> <def>A stinking tobacco.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Munerary</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ner*a*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>munerarius</ets>, from <ets>munus</ets> a gift.]</ety> <def>Having the nature of a gift.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Munerate</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ner*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>muneratus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>munerare</ets> to give, bestow, fr. <ets>munus</ets> a gift.]</ety> <def>To remunerate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muneration</ent><br/
<hw>Mu`ner*a"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>muneratio</ets>.]</ety> <def>Remuneration.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mung</ent><br/
<hw>Mung</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/ng)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Hind. <ets>m<umac/ng</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Green gram, a kind of legume (pulse) (<spn>Vigna radiata</spn> syn. <spn>Phaseolus aureus</spn>, syn. <spn>Phaseolus Mungo</spn>), grown for food in British India; called also <altname>gram</altname>, <altname>mung bean</altname>, <altname>Chinese mung bean</altname>, and <altname>green-seeded mung bean</altname>.  It is an erect, bushy annual producing edible green or yellow seeds, and edible pods and young sprouts.</def>  <rj><au>Balfour (Cyc. of India).</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mung bean</ent><br/
<hw>Mung" bean`</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/ng" b<emac/n`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>  <def>The <er>mung</er> (<spn>Vigna radiata</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The bean produced by the <er>mung</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Munga</ent><br/
<hw>Mun"ga</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <cref>Bonnet monkey</cref>, under <er>Bonnet</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mungcorn</ent><br/
<hw>Mung"corn`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Mangcorn</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mungo</ent><br/
<hw>Mun"go</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A material of short fiber and inferior quality obtained by deviling woolen rags or the remnants of woolen goods, specif. those of felted, milled, or hard-spun woolen cloth, as distinguished from <contr>shoddy</contr>, or the deviled product of loose-textured woolen goods or worsted, -- a distinction often disregarded.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Mungo</xex> properly signifies the disintegrated rags of woolen cloth, as distinguished from those of worsted, which form <contr>shoddy</contr>.  The distinction is very commonly disregarded.</note>  <rj><au>Beck (Draper's Dict.).</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mungoos</ent><br/
<ent>Mungoose</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mun"goose</hw>, <hw>Mun"goos</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Mongoose</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mungrel</ent><br/
<hw>Mun"grel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. & a.</pos> <def>See <er>Mongrel</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Municipal</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*nic"i*pal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>municipalis</ets>, fr. <ets>municipium</ets> a town, particularly in Italy, which possessed the right of Roman citizenship, but was governed by its own laws, a free town, fr. <ets>municeps</ets> an inhabitant of a free town, a free citizen; <ets>munia</ets> official duties, functions + <ets>capere</ets> to take: cf. F. <ets>municipal</ets>.  Cf. <er>Immunity</er>, and <er>Capacoius</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a city or a corporation having the right of administering local government; <as>as, <ex>municipal</ex> rights; <ex>municipal</ex> officers.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a state, kingdom, or nation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Municipal</qex> law is properly defined to be a rule of civil conduct prescribed by the supreme power in a state.</q> <rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Municipalism</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*nic"i*pal*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Municipal condition.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Municipality</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*nic`i*pal"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Municipalities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>municipalit<eacute/</ets>.]</ety> <def>A municipal district; a borough, city, or incorporated town or village.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Municipalize</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*nic"i*pal*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>  <ety>[<ets>Municipal</ets> + <ets>-ize</ets>.]</ety> <def>To bring under municipal oversight or control; <as>as, a <ex>municipalized</ex> industry</as>.</def></p>

<p><q>London people are now determined to centralize and to <qex>municipalize</qex> such services.</q>  <rj><qau>The Century.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Municipally</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*nic"i*pal*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a municipal relation or condition.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Munific</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*nif"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Munificent</er>.]</ety> <def>Munificent; liberal.</def> <mark>[Obs. or R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Munificate</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*nif"i*cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>munificatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>munificare</ets> to present with a thing, fr. <ets>munificus</ets>. See <er>Munificent</er>.]</ety> <def>To enrich.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Munificence</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*nif"i*cence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. L. <ets>munire</ets> to fortify.]</ety> <def>Means of defense; fortification.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Munificence</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*nif"i*cence</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>munificentia</ets>: cf. F. <ets>munificence</ets>.]</ety> <def>The quality or state of being munificent; a giving or bestowing with extraordinary liberality; generous bounty; lavish generosity.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Benevolence; beneficence; liberality; generosity; bounty; bounteousness. See <er>Benevolence</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The virtues of liberality and <qex>munificence</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Munificent</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*nif"i*cent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>munificus</ets>; <ets>munus</ets> service, gift + <ets>-ficare</ets> (in comp.) to make.  Cf. <er>Immunity</er>, <er>-fy</er>.]</ety> <def>Very liberal in giving or bestowing; lavish; <as>as, a <ex>munificent</ex> benefactor</as>.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mu*nif"i*cent*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
<syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Bounteous; bountiful; liberal; generous.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Munify</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ni*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Munificate</er>.]</ety> <def>To prepare for defense; to fortify.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muniment</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ni*ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>munimentum</ets>, fr. <ets>munire</ets> to fortify. See <er>Munition</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of supporting or defending.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which supports or defends; stronghold; place or means of defense; munition; assistance.</def> <ldquo/Other <xex>muniments</xex> and petty helps.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A record; the evidences or writings whereby a man is enabled to defend the title to his estate; title deeds and papers.</def>  <rj><au>Blount.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Muniment room</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Muniment house</b></col></mcol>, <cd>that room in a cathedral, castle, or other public building, which is used for keeping the records, charters, seals, deeds, and the like.</cd>  <au>Gwilt.</au></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Munite</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*nite"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>munitus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>munire</ets> to wall, fortify.]</ety> <def>To fortify; to strengthen.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Munition</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*ni"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., munition of war, L. <ets>munitio</ets> a fortifying, fortification, fr. <ets>munire</ets> to fortify, defend with a wall; cf. <ets>moenia</ets> walls, <ets>murus</ets> (for <ets>moirus</ets>) a wall, and Skr. <ets>mi</ets> to fix, make firm.  Cf. <er>Ammunition</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Fortification; stronghold.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His place of defense shall be the <qex>munitions</qex> of rocks.</q> <rj><qau>Is. xxxiii. 16.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Whatever materials are used in war for defense or for annoying an enemy; ammunition; also, stores and provisions; military stores of all kinds.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The bodies of men, <qex>munition</qex>, and money, may justly be called the sinews of war.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Raleigh.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Munity</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ni*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Immunity</er>.]</ety> <def>Freedom; security; immunity.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>W. Montagu.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>munja</ent><br/
<ent>munj</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>munj</hw>, <hw>munja</hw></mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A tough Asiatic grass (<spn>Saccharum bengalense</spn> syn. <spn>Saccharum munja</spn>) whose culms are used for ropes and baskets.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> munj, <spn>Saccharum bengalense</spn>, <spn>Saccharum munja</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Munjeet</ent><br/
<hw>Mun*jeet"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Hind. <ets>maj<imac/<tsdot/h</ets> a drug used for dyeing red.]</ety> <def>See <cref>Indian madder</cref>, under <er>Madder</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Munjistin</ent><br/
<hw>Mun"jis*tin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>An orange-red coloring substance resembling alizarin, found in the root of an East Indian species of madder (<spn>Rubia munjista</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Munnion</ent><br/
<hw>Mun"nion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mullion</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Munting</ent><br/
<ent>Muntin</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mun"tin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mun"ting</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[CF. <er>Montant</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Mullion</er>; -- especially used in joiner's work.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muntjac</ent><br/
<hw>Munt"jac</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of several species of small Asiatic deer of the genus <gen>Cervulus</gen>, esp. <spn>Cervulus muntjac</spn>, which occurs both in India and on the East Indian Islands.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>muntjak</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muntz metal</ent><br/
<hw>Muntz" met`al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <def>See under <er>Metal</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muraena</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mu*rae"na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of large eels of the family <fam>Muraenidae</fam>. They differ from the common eel in lacking pectoral fins and in having the dorsal and anal fins continuous.  The murry (<spn>Muraena Helenae</spn>) of Southern Europe was the muraena of the Romans.  It is highly valued as a food fish.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murenoid</ent><br/
<ent>Muraenoid</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mu*rae"noid</hw>, <hw>Mu*re"noid</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[NL. <ets>Muraena</ets>, the generic name + <ets>-oid</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Like or pertaining to the genus <gen>Muraena</gen>, or family <fam>Muraenidae</fam>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murage</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"rage</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>murer</ets> to wall, fr. <ets>mur</ets> wall, L. <ets>murus</ets>. See <er>Mure</er> a wall.]</ety> <def>A tax or toll paid for building or repairing the walls of a fortified town.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mural</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ral</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>muralis</ets>, fr. <ets>murus</ets> wall. See <er>Mure</er> a wall.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a wall; being on, or in, a wall; growing on, or against, a wall; <as>as, a <ex>mural</ex> quadrant</as>.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Mural</xex> breach.<rdquo/ <au>Milton.</au> <ldquo/<xex>Mural</xex> fruit.<rdquo/ <au>Evelyn.</au><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Resembling a wall; perpendicular or steep; <as>as, a <ex>mural</ex> precipice</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mural circle</b></col> <fld>(Astron.)</fld>, <cd>a graduated circle, in the plane of the meridian, attached permanently to a perpendicular wall; -- used for measuring arcs of the meridian. See <er>Circle</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 3.</cd> -- <col><b>Mural crown</b></col> <fld>(Rom. Antiq.)</fld>, <cd>a golden crown, or circle of gold indented so as to resemble a battlement, bestowed on him who first mounted the wall of a besieged place, and there lodged a standard.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murder</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"der</hw> <pr>(m<ucir/r"d<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>morder</ets>, <ets>morther</ets>, AS. <ets>mor<edh/or</ets>, fr. <ets>mor<edh/</ets> murder; akin to D. <ets>moord</ets>, OS. <ets>mor<edh/</ets>, G., Dan., & Sw. <ets>mord</ets>, Icel. <ets>mor<edh/</ets>, Goth. <ets>ma<uacute/r<thorn/r</ets>, OSlav. <ets>mr<emac/ti</ets> to die, Lith. <ets>mirti</ets>, W. <ets>marw</ets> dead, L. <ets>mors</ets>, <ets>mortis</ets>, death, <ets>mori</ets>, <ets>moriri</ets>, to die, Gr. <grk>broto`s</grk> (for <grk>mroto`s</grk>) mortal, <grk>'a`mbrotos</grk> immortal, Skr. <ets>m<rsdot/</ets> to die, <ets>m<rsdot/ta</ets> death.  <root/105.  Cf. <er>Amaranth</er>, <er>Ambrosia</er>, <er>Mortal</er>.]</ety> <def>The offense of killing a human being with malice prepense or aforethought, express or implied; intentional and unlawful homicide.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Mordre</xex> will out.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The killing of their children had, in the account of God, the guilt of <qex>murder</qex>, as the offering them to idols had the guilt of idolatry.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Slaughter grows <qex>murder</qex> when it goes too far.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ <xex>Murder in the second degree</xex>, in most jurisdictions, is a malicious homicide committed without a specific intention to take life.</note>  <rj><au>Wharton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murder</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"der</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Murdered</conjf> <pr>(m<ucir/r"d<etil/rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Murdering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>mortheren</ets>, <ets>murtheren</ets>, AS. <ets>myr<edh/rian</ets>; akin to OHG. <ets>murdiren</ets>, Goth. <ets>ma<uacute/r<thorn/rjan</ets>. See <er>Murder</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To kill with premediated malice; to kill (a human being) willfully, deliberately, and unlawfully. See <er>Murder</er>, <pos>n.</pos></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To destroy; to put an end to.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Canst thou] <qex>murder</qex> thy breath in middle of a word?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To mutilate, spoil, or deform, as if with malice or cruelty; to mangle; <as>as, to <ex>murder</ex> the king's English</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To kill; assassinate; slay. See <er>Kill</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>murdered</ent><br/
<hw>murdered</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>killed unlawfully; <as>as, the <ex>murdered</ex> woman</as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 955 --></p>

<p><ent>Murderer</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"der*er</hw> <pr>(m<ucir/r"d<etil/r*<etil/r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One guilty of murder; a person who, in possession of his reason, unlawfully kills a human being with premeditated malice.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small cannon, formerly used for clearing a ship's decks of boarders; -- called also <altname>murdering piece</altname>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murderess</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"der*ess</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A woman who commits murder.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murderment</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"der*ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Murder.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Farfax.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murderous</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"der*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to murder; characterized by, or causing, murder or bloodshed; having the purpose or quality of murder; bloody; sanguinary; <as>as, the <ex>murderous</ex> king; <ex>murderous</ex> rapine; <ex>murderous</ex> intent; a <ex>murderous</ex> assault.</as></def> <ldquo/<xex>Murderous</xex> coward.<rdquo/ <au>Shak.</au> -- <wordforms><wf>Mur"der*ous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Bloody; sanguinary; bloodguilty; bloodthirsty; fell; savage; cruel.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murdress</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"dress</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A battlement in ancient fortifications with interstices for firing through.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mure</ent><br/
<hw>Mure</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>murus</ets>; or F. <ets>mur</ets>, fr. L. <ets>murus</ets>.  Cf. <er>Munition</er>.]</ety> <def>A wall.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mure</ent><br/
<hw>Mure</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mured</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>murer</ets>, L. <ets>murare</ets>. See <er>Mure</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To inclose in walls; to wall; to immure; to shut up.</def>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The five kings are <qex>mured</qex> in a cave.</q> <rj><qau>John. x. (Heading).</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murenger</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ren*ger</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who had charge of the wall of a town, or its repairs.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murex</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mu"rex</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Murices</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., the purple fish.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of marine gastropods, having rough, and frequently spinose, shells, which are often highly colored inside; the rock shells.  They abound in tropical seas.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murexan</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*rex"an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Murexide</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A complex nitrogenous substance obtained from murexide, alloxantin, and other ureids, as a white, or yellowish, crystalline which turns red on exposure to the air; -- called also <altname>uramil</altname>, <altname>dialuramide</altname>, and formerly <altname>purpuric acid</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murexide</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*rex"ide</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>murex</ets> the purple fish, purple.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A crystalline nitrogenous substance (<chform>C8H8N6O6</chform>, <chname>5-5'-nitrilodibarbituric acid monoammonium salt</chname>) having a splendid dichroism, being green by reflected light and garnet-red by transmitted light.  It was formerly used in dyeing calico, and was obtained in a large quantities from guano.  It is now synthesized from alloxan.  Formerly called also <altname>ammonium purpurate</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murexoin</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*rex"o*<ium/n</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A complex nitrogenous compound obtained as a scarlet crystalline substance, and regarded as related to murexide.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muriate</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ri*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Muriatic</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of muriatic hydrochloric acid; a chloride; <as>as, <ex>muriate</ex> of ammonia</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ This term, as also the word <xex>muriatic</xex>, was formerly applied to the chlorides before their true composition was understood, and while they were erroneously supposed to be compounds of an acid with an oxide.  <xex>Muriate</xex> and <xex>muriatic</xex> are still occasionally used as commercial terms, but are obsolete in scientific language.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muriated</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ri*a`ted</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Put in brine.</def>  <rj><au>Evelyn.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Combined or impregnated with muriatic or hydrochloric acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Photog.)</fld> <def>Prepared with chloride of silver through the agency of common salt.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muriatic</ent><br/
<hw>Mu`ri*at"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>muriaticus</ets> pickled, from <ets>muria</ets> brine: cf. F. <ets>muriatique</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or obtained from, sea salt, or from chlorine, one of the constituents of sea salt; hydrochloric.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Muriatic acid</b></col>, <cd>hydrochloric acid, <chform>HCl</chform>; -- formerly called also <altname>marine acid</altname>, and <altname>spirit of salt</altname>. See <er>hydrochloric</er>, and the Note under <er>Muriate</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muriatiferous</ent><br/
<hw>Mu`ri*a*tif"er*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Muriat</ets>ic + <ets>-ferous</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Old Chem.)</fld> <def>Producing muriatic substances or salt.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muricated</ent><br/
<ent>Muricate</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mu"ri*cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mu"ri*ca`ted</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>muricatus</ets>, fr. <ets>murex</ets> a pointed rock or stone.]</ety> <def>Formed with sharp points; full of sharp points or of pickles; covered, or roughened, as a surface, with sharp points or excrescences.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muricoid</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ri*coid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mur</ets>ex + <ets>-oid</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Like, or pertaining to, the genus Murex, or family <fam>Muricidae</fam>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muriculate</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*ric"u*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Minutely muricate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muride</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ride</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>muria</ets> brine.]</ety> <fld>(Old Chem.)</fld> <def>Bromine; -- formerly so called from its being obtained from sea water.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muriform</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ri*form</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>murus</ets> a wall + <ets>-form</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Resembling courses of bricks or stones in squareness and regular arrangement; <as>as, a <ex>muriform</ex> variety of cellular tissue</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murine</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"rine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>murinus</ets>, from <ets>mus</ets>, <ets>muris</ets>, mouse: cf. F. <ets>murin</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to a family of rodents (<fam>Muridae</fam>), of which the mouse is the type.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murine</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"rine</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of a tribe of rodents, of which the mouse is the type.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muringer</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"rin*ger</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Murenger</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Jacob.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murk</ent><br/
<hw>Murk</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Murky</er>.]</ety> <def>Dark; murky.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He can not see through the mantle <qex>murk</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>J. R. Drake.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murk</ent><br/
<hw>Murk</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Darkness; mirk.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murk</ent><br/
<hw>Murk</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The refuse of fruit, after the juice has been expressed; marc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murkily</ent><br/
<hw>Murk"i*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Darkly; gloomily.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murkiness</ent><br/
<hw>Murk"i*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state of being murky.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murky</ent><br/
<hw>Murk"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Murkier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Murkiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>mirke</ets>, <ets>merke</ets>, AS. <ets>myrce</ets>, <ets>mirce</ets>; akin to Icel. <ets>myrkr</ets>, Dan. & Sw. <ets>m<oum/rk</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Dark; gloomy.</def> <ldquo/The <xex>murkiest</xex> den.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>murky</qex> deep lowering o'er our heads.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Obscured by haze or mist; clouded; turbid; <as>as, poor visibility in the <ex>murky</ex> water</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murlins</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"lins</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A seaweed. See <er>Baddrelocks</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murmur</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"mur</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>murmure</ets>: cf. L. <ets>murmur</ets>.  CF. <er>Murmur</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A low, confused, and indistinct sound, like that of running water.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A complaint half suppressed, or uttered in a low, muttering voice.</def>  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some discontents there are, some idle <qex>murmurs</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murmur</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"mur</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Murmured</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Murmuring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>murmurer</ets>, L. <ets>murmurare</ets>, <ets>murmurari</ets>, fr. <ets>murmur</ets> murmur; cf. Gr. <?/ to roar and boil, said of water, Skr. <ets>marmara</ets> a rustling sound; prob. of imitative origin.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make a low continued noise, like the hum of bees, a stream of water, distant waves, or the wind in a forest.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>murmured</qex> as doth a swarm of bees.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To utter complaints in a low, half-articulated voice; to feel or express dissatisfaction or discontent; to grumble; -- often with <xex>at</xex> or <xex>against</xex>.</def> <ldquo/His disciples <xex>murmured</xex> at it.<rdquo/  <rj><au>John vi. 61.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And all the children of Israel <qex>murmured</qex> against Moses and against Aaron.</q> <rj><qau>Num. xiv. 2.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Neither <qex>murmur</qex> ye, as some of them also <qex>murmured</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>1 Cor. x. 10.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murmur</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"mur</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To utter or give forth in low or indistinct words or sounds; <as>as, to <ex>murmur</ex> tales</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The people <qex>murmured</qex> such things concerning him.</q> <rj><qau>John vii. 32.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murmuration</ent><br/
<hw>Mur`mur*a"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>murmuratio</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act of murmuring; a murmur.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Skelton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murmurer</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"mur*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who murmurs.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murmuring</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"mur*ing</hw>, <pos>a. & n.</pos> <def>Uttering murmurs; making low sounds; complaining.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Mur"mur*ing*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murmurous</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"mur*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. L. <ets>murmuriosus</ets>, OF. <ets>murmuros</ets>.]</ety> <def>Attended with murmurs; exciting murmurs or complaint; murmuring.</def> <mark>[Archaic or Poetic]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The lime, a summer home of <qex>murmurous</qex> wings.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murnival</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"ni*val</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Perh. fr. F. <ets>mornifle</ets> a game at cards.]</ety> <def>In the game of gleek, four cards of the same value, as four aces or four kings; hence, four of anything.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mournival</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murphy</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"phy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A potato.</def> <mark>[Humorous]</mark>  <rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murr</ent><br/
<hw>Murr</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. abbrev. from <ets>murrain</ets>.]</ety> <def>A catarrh.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Gascoigne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murrain</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"rain</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>moreine</ets>, OF. <ets>morine</ets>, fr. OF. <ets>morir</ets>, <ets>murir</ets>, 8die, L. <ets>mori</ets>, <ets>moriri</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Far.)</fld> <def>An infectious and fatal disease among cattle.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>A murrain on you</b></col>, <cd>may you be afflicted with a pestilent disease.</cd> <au>Shak.</au></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murrain</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"rain</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having, or afflicted with, murrain.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murrayin</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"ray*in</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A glucoside found in the flowers of a plant (<spn>Murraya exotica</spn>) of South Asia, and extracted as a white amorphous slightly bitter substance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murre</ent><br/
<hw>Murre</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of several species of sea birds of the genus <gen>Uria</gen>, or <gen>Catarractes</gen>; a guillemot.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The murres are allied to the auks, and are abundant on the northern coasts of Europe and America.  They often breed in large communities on the projecting ledges of precipituous cliffs, laying one or two large eggs on the bare rocks.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murrelet</ent><br/
<hw>Murre"let</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Murre</ets> + <ets>-let</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of several species of sea birds of the genera <gen>Synthliboramphus</gen> and <gen>Brachyramphus</gen>, inhabiting the North Pacific.  They are closely related to the murres.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murrey</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"rey</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>mor<eacute/e</ets> a dark red color, <ets>mor</ets> blackish brown, fr. L. <ets>morum</ets> mulberry, blackberry, or fr. <ets>Maurus</ets> a Moor.  Cf. <er>Mulberry</er>, <er>Moor</er>, <er>Morelle</er>.]</ety> <def>A dark red color.</def> -- <def2><pos>a.</pos> <def>Of a dark red color.</def></def2>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murrhine</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"rhine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>murrhinus</ets>, fr. <ets>murrha</ets>: cf. F. <ets>murrhin</ets>.]</ety> <def>Made of the stone or material called by the Romans <xex>murrha</xex>; -- applied to certain costly vases of great beauty and delicacy used by the luxurious in Rome as wine cups; <as>as, <ex>murrhine</ex> vases, cups, vessels</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Murrhine glass</b></col>, <cd>glassware made in imitation of murrhine vases and cups.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murrion</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"ri*on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Murrain</er>.]</ety> <def>Infected with or killed by murrain.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murrion</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"ri*on</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A morion. See <er>Morion</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murry</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Muraena</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murth</ent><br/
<hw>Murth</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Etymol. uncertain.]</ety> <def>Plenty; abundance.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murther</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"ther</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. & v.</pos> <def>Murder, <pos>n.</pos> & <pos>v.</pos></def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov.]</mark> <ldquo/The treason of the <xex>murthering</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murtherer</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"ther*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A murderer.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murza</ent><br/
<hw>Mur"za</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One of the hereditary nobility among the Tatars, esp. one of the second class.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ This word must not be confounded with the Persian <xex>Mirza</xex>, though perhaps of the same origin.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mures</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., a mouse.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of small rodents, including the common mouse and rat.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musa</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mu"sa</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Musae</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL., fr. Ar. <ets>mauz</ets>, <ets>mauza</ets>, banana.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of perennial, herbaceous, endogenous plants of great size, including the banana (<spn>Musa sapientum</spn>), the plantain (<spn>Musa paradisiaca</spn> of Linnaeus, but probably not a distinct species), the Abyssinian (<spn>Musa Ensete</spn>), the Philippine Island (<spn>Musa textilis</spn>, which yields Manila hemp), and about eighteen other species. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Banana</er> and <er>Plantain</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musaceae</ent><br/
<hw>Musaceae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of treelike tropical Asian herbs including the banana tree.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Musaceae</fam>, banana family.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musaceous</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*sa"ceous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of, pertaining to, or resembling, plants of the genus <gen>Musa</gen>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musal</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the Muses, or to Poetry.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musales</ent><br/
<hw>Musales</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>An order of tropical plants.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> order <ord>Musales</ord>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musang</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*sang"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A small animal of Java (<spn>Paradoxirus fasciatus</spn>), allied to the civets. It swallows, but does not digest, large quantities of ripe coffee berries, thus serving to disseminate the coffee plant; hence it is called also <altname>coffee rat</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musar</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"sar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An itinerant player on the musette, an instrument formerly common in Europe.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musard</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"sard</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>muser</ets> to loiter, trifle. See <er>Muse</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <def>A dreamer; an absent-minded person.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Rom. of R.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musca</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mus"ca</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Muscae</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., a fly.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of dipterous insects, including the common house fly, and numerous allied species.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Formerly, a large part of the Diptera were included under the genus <gen>Musca</gen>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>A small constellation situated between the Southern Cross and the Pole.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Muscae volitantes</b></col> <pr>(<?/)</pr>. <ety>[L., flying flies.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <cd>Specks or filaments apparently seen moving or gliding about in the field of vision.  Their appearance is often a symptom of disease of the eye, or of disorder of the nervous system.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>muscadelle</ent><br/
<ent>Muscadel</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>Mus"ca*del`</hw>, <hw>mus"ca*delle</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It. <ets>moscadello</ets>, <ets>moscatello</ets>, LL. <ets>muscatellum</ets> or <ets>muscadellum</ets> (sc. <ets>vinum</ets>), fr. <ets>muscatellus</ets> nutmeglike, dim. of <ets>muscatus</ets> smelling like musk, <ets>muscatum</ets> and <ets>muscata</ets> (sc. <ets>nux</ets>) nutmeg: cf. F. <ets>muscadelle</ets>, fr. Italian. See <er>Musk</er> and cf. <er>Moschatel</er>, <er>Muscardin</er>, <er>Muscat</er>, <er>Nutmeg</er>.]</ety> <def>See <er>Muscatel</er>, <pos>n.</pos></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Quaffed off the <qex>muscadel</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscadet</ent><br/
<hw>Muscadet</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A white grape grown esp. in the Loire Valley in France.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A dry white wine from the Loire Valley in France.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscadine</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"ca*dine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Muscadel</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A name given to several very different kinds of grapes, but in America used chiefly for the scuppernong, or southern fox grape, which is said to be the parent stock of the Catawba.  See <er>Grapevine</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A fragrant and delicious pear.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Muscardin</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Northern muscadine</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a derivative of the northern fox grape, and scarcely an improvement upon it.</cd> -- <col><b>Royal muscadine</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a European grape of great value.  Its berries are large, round, and of a pale amber color.  Called also <altname>golden chasselas</altname>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscales</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mus*ca"les</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. L. <ets>muscus</ets> moss.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>An old name for mosses in the widest sense, including the true mosses and also hepaticae and sphagna.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscallonge</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"cal*longe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Muskellunge</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscardin</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"car*din</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. <ets>muscadin</ets> a musk-scented lozenge, fr. <ets>muscade</ets> nutmeg, fr. L. <ets>muscus</ets> musk. See <er>Muscadel</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The common European dormouse; -- so named from its odor.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>muscadine</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscardine</ent><br/
<hw>Mus`car*dine"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>A disease which is very destructive to silkworms, and which sometimes extends to other insects.  It is attended by the development of a fungus (provisionally called <spn>Botrytis bassiana</spn>).  Also, the fungus itself.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscariform</ent><br/
<hw>Mus*car"i*form</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>muscarium</ets> fly brush + <ets>-form</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having the form of a brush.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscarin</ent><br/
<hw>Mus*ca"rin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Physiol. Chem.)</fld> <def>A solid crystalline substance, <chform>C5H13NO2</chform>, found in the toadstool (<spn>Agaricus muscarius</spn>), and in putrid fish. It is a typical ptomaine, and a violent poison.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscat</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"cat</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. See <er>Muscadel</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A name given to several varieties of Old World grapes, differing in color, size, etc., but all having a somewhat musky flavor. The muscat of Alexandria is a large oval grape of a pale amber color.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>muskat</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscatel</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"ca*tel`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of, pertaining to, or designating, or derived from, a muscat grapes or similar grapes; <as>as, <ex>muscatel</ex> grapes; <ex>muscatel</ex> wine, etc.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscatel</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"ca*tel`</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A common name for several varieties of rich sweet wine, made in Italy, Spain, and France.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Finest raisins, dried on the vine; <ldquo/sun raisins.<rdquo/</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><altsp>[Variously written <asp>moscatel</asp>, <asp>muscadel</asp>, etc.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muschelkalk</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Musch"el*kalk`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G., from <ets>muschel</ets> shell + <ets>kalk</ets> limestone.]</ety> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>A kind of shell limestone, whose strata form the middle one of the three divisions of the Triassic formation in Germany. See <xex>Chart</xex>, under <er>Geology</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musci</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mus"ci</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>muscus</ets> moss.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>An order or subclass of cryptogamous plants; the mosses. See <er>Moss</er>, and <er>Cryptogamia</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscicapidae</ent><br/
<hw>Muscicapidae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of Old World (true) flycatchers.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Muscicapidae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscicapine</ent><br/
<hw>Mus*cic"a*pine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>musca</ets> a fly + <ets>capere</ets> to catch.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the <fam>Muscicapidae</fam>, a family of birds that includes the true flycatchers.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscid</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"cid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Any fly of the genus Musca, or family <fam>Muscidae</fam>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscidae</ent><br/
<hw>Muscidae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of two-winged flies esp. the housefly.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Muscidae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musciform</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"ci*form</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Musca</ets> + <ets>-form</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having the form or structure of flies of the genus <gen>Musca</gen>, or family <fam>Muscidae</fam>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musciform</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"ci*form</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Muscus</ets> + <ets>-form</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having the appearance or form of a moss.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscivora-forficata</ent><br/
<hw>Muscivora-forficata</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A gray flycatcher of Southwestern U. S. and Mexico and Central America having a long forked tail and white breast and salmon and scarlet markings; the scissortailed flycatcher.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> scissortail, scissortailed flycatcher.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscle</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"cle</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/s"'l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>musculus</ets> a muscle, a little mouse, dim. of <ets>mus</ets> a mouse. See <er>Mouse</er>, and cf. sense 3 (below).]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>An organ which, by its contraction, produces motion.</def> See <xex>Illust.</xex> of Muscles of the Human Body, in Appendix. <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The contractile tissue of which muscles are largely made up.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Muscles are of two kinds, <xex>striated</xex> and <xex>nonstriated</xex>.  The striated muscles, which, in most of the higher animals, constitute the principal part of the flesh, exclusive of the fat, are mostly under the control of the will, or <xex>voluntary</xex>, and are made up of great numbers of elongated fibres bound together into bundles and inclosed in a sheath of connective tissue, the <part>perimysium</part>.  Each fiber is inclosed in a delicate membrane (the <part>sarcolemma</part>), is made up of alternate segments of lighter and darker material which give it a transversely striated appearance, and contains, scattered through its substance, protoplasmic nuclei, the so-called <parts>muscle corpuscles</parts>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>   The nonstriated muscles are <xex>involuntary</xex>. They constitute a large part of the walls of the alimentary canal, blood vessels, uterus, and bladder, and are found also in the iris, skin, etc. They are made up of greatly elongated cells, usually grouped in bundles or sheets.<br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Muscular strength or development; <as>as, to show one's <ex>muscle</ex> by lifting a heavy weight</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <ety>[AS. <ets>muscle</ets>, L. <ets>musculus</ets> a muscle, mussel. See above.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Mussel</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An essential part of something; <as>as, budget cuts have gone beyond the fat and are cutting into the <ex>muscle</ex> of the government</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Bodyguards or other persons hired to provide protection or commit violence; <as>as, he doesn't go out without his <ex>muscle</ex> along</as>.</def> <mark>[slang]</mark> <br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Muscle curve</b></col> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld>, <cd>contraction curve of a muscle; a myogram; the curve inscribed, upon a prepared surface, by means of a myograph when acted upon by a contracting muscle. The character of the curve represents the extent of the contraction.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>muscle</ent><br/
<hw>mus"cle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To compel by threat of force; <as>as, they <ex>muscled</ex> the shopkeeper into paying protection money</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To moved by human force; <as>as, to <ex>muscle</ex> the piano onto the truck</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>musclebuilder</ent><br/
<hw>musclebuilder</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>someone who does special exercises to develop the musculature; a bodybuilder.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>musclebuilding</ent><br/
<hw>musclebuilding</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>exercise that builds muscles through tension; bodybuilding.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> bodybuilding, anaerobic exercise.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 956 --></p>

<p><ent>Muscled</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"cled</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/s"l'd)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Furnished with muscles; having muscles; <as>as, things well <ex>muscled</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>muscleman</ent><br/
<hw>muscleman</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a bully employed by a gangster.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscle reading</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"cle read`ing</hw>. <def>The art of making discriminations between objects of choice, of discovering the whereabouts of hidden objects, etc., by inference from the involuntary movements of one whose hand the reader holds or with whom he is otherwise in muscular contact.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscling</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"cling</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Fine Arts)</fld> <def>Exhibition or representation of the muscles.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A good piece, the painters say, must have good <qex>muscling</qex>, as well as coloring and drapery.</q> <rj><qau>Shaftesbury.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscogees</ent><br/
<hw>Mus*co"gees</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <def>See <er>Muskogees</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscoid</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"coid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Muscus</ets> + <ets>-oid</ets>: cf. F. <ets>muscoide</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Mosslike; resembling moss.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscoid</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"coid</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A term formerly applied to any mosslike flowerless plant, with a distinct stem, and often with leaves, but without any vascular system.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscoidea</ent><br/
<hw>Muscoidea</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A superfamily of two-winged flies esp. the families: <fam>Muscidae</fam>; <fam>Gasterophilidae</fam>; <fam>Calliphoridae</fam>; and <fam>Tachinidae</fam>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> superfamily <fam>Muscoidea</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscology</ent><br/
<hw>Mus*col"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Muscus</ets> + <ets>-logy</ets>.]</ety> <def>Bryology.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscosity</ent><br/
<hw>Mus*cos"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>muscosus</ets> mossy, fr. <ets>muscus</ets> moss.]</ety> <def>Mossiness.</def>  <rj><au>Jonhson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscovado</ent><br/
<hw>Mus`co*va"do</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Corrupted fr. Sp. <ets>mascabado</ets>; cf. Pg. <ets>mascavado</ets>, F. <ets>moscouade</ets>, n., formerly also <ets>mascovade</ets>, It. <ets>mascavato</ets>.]</ety> <def>Pertaining to, or of the nature of, unrefined or raw sugar, obtained from the juice of the sugar cane by evaporating and draining off the molasses.  Muscovado sugar contains impurities which render it dark colored and moist.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscovado</ent><br/
<hw>Mus`co*va"do</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Unrefined or raw sugar.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscovite</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"co*vite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Muscovy glass</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A native or inhabitant of Muscovy or ancient Russia; hence, a Russian.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An inhabitant of Moscow.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Common potash mica, essentially <chform>KAl3Si3O10(OH)2</chform>. It is used as an electrical insulator.  See <er>Mica</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscovy duck</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"co*vy duck`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[A corruption of <ets>musk</ets> duck.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A duck (<spn>Cairina moschata</spn>), larger than the common duck, often raised in poultry yards. Called also <altname>musk duck</altname>.  It is native of tropical America, from Mexico to Southern Brazil.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscovy glass</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"co*vy glass`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[From <ets>Muscovy</ets>, the old name of Russia: cf. F. verre de <ets>Moscovie</ets>.]</ety> <def>Mica; muscovite. See <er>Mica</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscular</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"cu*lar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>musculaire</ets>. See <er>Muscle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a muscle, or to a system of muscles; consisting of, or constituting, a muscle or muscles; <as>as, <ex>muscular</ex> fiber</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Great <qex>muscular</qex> strength, accompanied by much awkwardness.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Performed by, or dependent on, a muscle or the muscles.</def> <ldquo/The <xex>muscular</xex> motion.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Arbuthnot.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Well furnished with muscles; having well-developed muscles; brawny; hence, strong; powerful; vigorous; <as>as, a <ex>muscular</ex> body or arm</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Muscular Christian</b></col>, <cd>one who believes in a part of religious duty to maintain a healthful and vigorous physical state.</cd> <au>T. Hughes.</au> -- <col><b>Muscular Christianity</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The practice and opinion of those Christians who believe that it is a part of religious duty to maintain a vigorous condition of the body, and who therefore approve of athletic sports and exercises as conductive to good health, good morals, and right feelings in religious matters.</cd> <au>T. Hughes.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>An active, robust, and cheerful Christian life, as opposed to a meditative and gloomy one.</cd> <au>C. Kingsley.</au> -- <col><b>Muscular excitability</b></col> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld>, <cd>that property in virtue of which a muscle shortens, when it is stimulated; irritability; contractility.</cd> -- <col><b>Muscular sense</b></col> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld>, <cd>muscular sensibility; the sense by which we obtain knowledge of the condition of our muscles and to what extent they are contracted, also of the position of the various parts of our bodies and the resistance offering by external objects.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscularity</ent><br/
<hw>Mus`cu*lar"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state or quality of being muscular.</def>  <rj><au>Grew.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscularize</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"cu*lar*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make muscular.</def>  <rj><au>Lowell.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscularly</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"cu*lar*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a muscular manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musculation</ent><br/
<hw>Mus`cu*la"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Musculature.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musculature</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"cu*la*ture</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>musculature</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The muscular system of an animal, or of any of its parts; musculation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muscule</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"cule</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>musculus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>muscule</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A long movable shed used by besiegers in ancient times in attacking the walls of a fortified town.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musculin</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"cu*lin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>musculus</ets> a muscle.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol. Chem.)</fld> <def>See <er>Syntonin</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musculocutaneous</ent><br/
<hw>Mus`cu*lo*cu*ta"ne*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>musculus</ets> + E. <ets>cutaneous</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Pertaining both to muscles and skin; <as>as, the <ex>musculocutaneous</ex> nerve</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musculophrenic</ent><br/
<hw>Mus`cu*lo*phren"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>musculus</ets> muscle + E. <ets>phrenic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to the muscles and the diaphragm; <as>as, the <ex>musculophrenic</ex> artery</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musculosity</ent><br/
<hw>Mus`cu*los"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being musculous; muscularity.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musculospiral</ent><br/
<hw>Mus`cu*lo*spi"ral</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>musculus</ets> muscle + E. <ets>spiral</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the muscles, and taking a spiral course; -- applied esp. to a large nerve of the arm.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musculous</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"cu*lous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>musculosus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>musculeux</ets>.]</ety> <def>Muscular.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Jonhson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muse</ent><br/
<hw>Muse</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From F. <ets>musse</ets>. See <er>Muset</er>.]</ety> <def>A gap or hole in a hedge, hence, wall, or the like, through which a wild animal is accustomed to pass; a muset.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Find a hare without a <qex>muse</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Old Prov.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muse</ent><br/
<hw>Muse</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>Muse</ets>, L. <ets>Musa</ets>, Gr. <?/.  Cf. <er>Mosaic</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, <er>Music</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Class. Myth.)</fld> <def>One of the nine goddesses, daughters of Zeus and Mnemosyne, who presided over song and the different kinds of poetry, and also the arts and sciences; -- often used in the plural.  At one time certain other goddesses were considered as muses.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Granville commands; your aid, O Muses, bring:<br/
What <qex>Muse</qex> for Granville can refuse to sing?</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The names of the Muses and the arts they presided over were: <examp>Calliope</examp> (Epic poetry), <examp>Clio</examp> (History), <examp>Erato</examp> (Lyric poetry), <examp>Euterpe</examp> (music), <examp>Melpomene</examp> (Tragedy), <examp>Polymnia</examp> or <examp>Polyhymnia</examp> (religious music), <examp>Terpsichore</examp> (dance), <examp>Thalia</examp> (comedy), and <examp>Urania</examp> (astronomy).</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A particular power and practice of poetry; the inspirational genius of a poet.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A poet; a bard.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muse</ent><br/
<hw>Muse</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mused</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Musing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>muser</ets> to loiter or trifle, orig., to stand with open mouth, fr. LL. <ets>musus</ets>, <ets>morsus</ets>, muzzle, snout, fr. L. <ets>morsus</ets> a biting, bite, fr. <ets>mordere</ets> to bite. See <er>Morsel</er>, and cf. <er>Amuse</er>, <er>Muzzle</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To think closely; to study in silence; to meditate.</def> <ldquo/Thereon <xex>mused</xex> he.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>mused</qex> upon some dangerous plot.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P. Sidney.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be absent in mind; to be so occupied in study or contemplation as not to observe passing scenes or things present; to be in a brown study.</def>  <rj><au>Daniel.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To wonder.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au>  <au>B. Jonson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To consider; meditate; ruminate. See <er>Ponder</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muse</ent><br/
<hw>Muse</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To think on; to meditate on.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Come, then, expressive Silence, <qex>muse</qex> his praise.</q> <rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To wonder at.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muse</ent><br/
<hw>Muse</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Contemplation which abstracts the mind from passing scenes; absorbing thought; hence, absence of mind; a brown study.</def>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Wonder, or admiration.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Museful</ent><br/
<hw>Muse"ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Meditative; thoughtfully silent.</def> <ldquo/<xex>Museful</xex> mopings.<rdquo/ <au>Dryden.</au> -- <wordforms><wf>Muse"ful*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Museless</ent><br/
<hw>Muse"less</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Unregardful of the Muses; disregarding the power of poetry; unpoetical.</def>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muser</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who muses.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muset</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"set</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>mussette</ets>, dim. of <ets>musse</ets>, <ets>muce</ets>, a hiding place, fr. F. <ets>musser</ets>, OF. <ets>mucier</ets>, <ets>muchier</ets>, to conceal, hide.  Cf. <er>Micher</er>.]</ety> <def>A small hole or gap through which a wild animal passes; a muse.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musette</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*sette"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., dim. of OF. <ets>muse</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A small bagpipe formerly in use, having a soft and sweet tone.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An air adapted to this instrument; also, a kind of rustic dance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Museum</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*se"um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., a temple of the Muses, hence, a place of study, fr. Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ a Muse.]</ety> <def>A repository or a collection of natural, scientific, or literary curiosities, or of works of art.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Museum beetle</b></col>, <col><b>Museum pest</b></col></mcol>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Anthrenus</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mush</ent><br/
<hw>Mush</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Gael. <ets>mus</ets>, <ets>muss</ets>, pap, porridge, any thick preparation of fruit, OHG. <ets>muos</ets>; akin to AS. & OS. <ets>m<omac/s</ets> food, and prob, to E. <ets>meat</ets>. See <er>Meat</er>.]</ety> <def>Meal (esp. Indian meal) boiled in water; hasty pudding; supawn.</def> <mark>[U.S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mush</ent><br/
<hw>Mush</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>moucheter</ets> to cut with small cuts.]</ety> <def>To notch, cut, or indent, as cloth, with a stamp.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mush</ent><br/
<hw>Mush</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Perh. short for <ets>mush on</ets>, a corrupt of E. <ets>marchons</ets>, the cry of the voyageurs and coureurs de bois to their dogs.]</ety> <def>A march on foot, esp. across the snow with dogs; <as>as, he had a long <ex>mush</ex> before him</as>; -- also used attributively.</def> <mark>[Colloq., Alaska & Northwestern U. S.]</mark><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mush</ent><br/
<hw>Mush</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos>  <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mushed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mushing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To travel on foot, esp. across the snow with dogs.</def> -- <def2><pos>v. t. </pos> <def>To cause to travel or journey.</def> <mark>[Rare]</mark> <mark>[Colloq., Alaska & Northwestern U. S.]</mark></def2><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mushroom</ent><br/
<hw>Mush"room</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>muscheron</ets>, OF. <ets>mouscheron</ets>, F. <ets>mousseron</ets>; perhaps fr. <ets>mousse</ets> moss, of German origin. See <er>Moss</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>An edible fungus (<spn>Agaricus campestris</spn>), having a white stalk which bears a convex or oven flattish expanded portion called the <part>pileus</part>.  This is whitish and silky or somewhat scaly above, and bears on the under side radiating gills which are at first flesh-colored, but gradually become brown.  The plant grows in rich pastures and is proverbial for rapidity of growth and shortness of duration.  It has a pleasant smell, and is largely used as food. It is also cultivated from spawn.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Any large fungus developing a visible fruiting body with a stem and cap, usu. of the basidiomycetes;</def> <specif>especially</specif> <def>one of the genus <gen>Agaricus</gen>; a toadstool. Several species are edible; but many are very poisonous.  The term <ex>mushroom</ex> is used most often for edible varieties, the poisonous ones being termed <contr>toadstools</contr> or other names.  But this distinction is often ignored.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who rises suddenly from a low condition in life; an upstart.</def>  <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mushroom</ent><br/
<hw>Mush"room</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to mushrooms; <as>as, <ex>mushroom</ex> catchup</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Resembling mushrooms in rapidity of growth and shortness of duration; short-lived; ephemerial; <as>as, <ex>mushroom</ex> cities</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mushroom anchor</b></col>, <cd>an anchor shaped like a mushroom, capable of grasping the ground in whatever way it falls.</cd> -- <col><b>Mushroom coral</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any coral of the genus <gen>Fungia</gen>. See <er>Fungia</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mushroom spawn</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the mycelium, or primary filamentous growth, of the mushroom; also, cakes of earth and manure containing this growth, which are used for propagation of the mushroom.</cd> -- <col><b>mushroom cloud</b></col>, <cd>a cloud of smoke rising and then spreading laterally to take on the shape of a mushroom -- caused by large fires or explosions, esp. nuclear explosions.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mushroom</ent><br/
<hw>mush"room</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>to grow or expand rapidly.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>to grow so much and so rapidly as to change qualitatively; used with <ptcl>into</ptcl>; <as>as, a minor border skirmish <ex>mushroomed into</ex> a full-blown war</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mushroom-headed</ent><br/
<hw>Mush"room-head`ed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having a cylindrical body with a convex head of larger diameter; having a head like that of a mushroom.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mushy</ent><br/
<hw>Mush"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Soft like mush; figuratively, good-naturedly weak and effusive; weakly sentimental.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She 's not <qex>mushy</qex>, but her heart is tender.</q> <rj><qau>G. Eliot.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Music</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"sic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>musique</ets>, fr. L. <ets>musica</ets>, Gr. <?/ (sc. <?/), any art over which the Muses presided, especially music, lyric poetry set and sung to music, fr. <?/ belonging to Muses or fine arts, fr. <?/ Muse.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The science and the art of tones, or musical sounds, <it>i. e.</it>, sounds of higher or lower pitch, begotten of uniform and synchronous vibrations, as of a string at various degrees of tension; the science of harmonical tones which treats of the principles of harmony, or the properties, dependences, and relations of tones to each other; the art of combining tones in a manner to please the ear.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Not all <xex>sounds</xex> are <xex>tones</xex>. Sounds may be unmusical and yet please the ear. <xex>Music</xex> deals with <xex>tones</xex>, and with no other sounds. See <er>Tone</er>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Melody; a rhythmical and otherwise agreeable succession of tones.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Harmony; an accordant combination of simultaneous tones.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The written and printed notation of a musical composition; the score.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Love of music; capacity of enjoying music.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The man that hath no <qex>music</qex> in himself<br/
Nor is not moved with concord of sweet sounds,<br/
Is fit for treasons, stratagems, and spoils.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A more or less musical sound made by many of the lower animals. See <er>Stridulation</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Magic music</b></col>, <cd>a game in which a person is guided in finding a hidden article, or in doing a specific act required, by music which is made more loud or rapid as he approaches success, and slower as he recedes.  It is similar to the game of <er>hot and cold</er>, but using music as the clue.</cd> <au>Tennyson.</au> -- <col><b>Music box</b></col>. <cd>See <cref>Musical box</cref>, under <er>Musical</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Music hall</b></col>, <cd>a place for public musical entertainments.</cd> -- <col><b>Music loft</b></col>, <cd>a gallery for musicians, as in a dancing room or a church.</cd> -- <col><b>Music of the spheres</b></col>, <cd>the harmony supposed to be produced by the accordant movement of the celestial spheres.</cd> -- <col><b>Music paper</b></col>, <cd>paper ruled with the musical staff, for the use of composers and copyists.</cd> -- <col><b>Music pen</b></col>, <cd>a pen for ruling at one time the five lines of the musical staff.</cd> -- <col><b>Music shell</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a handsomely colored marine gastropod shell (<spn>Voluta musica</spn>) found in the East Indies; -- so called because the color markings often resemble printed music. Sometimes applied to other shells similarly marked.</cd> -- <col><b>To face the music</b></col>, <cd>to meet any disagreeable necessity, such as a reprimand for an error or misdeed, without flinching.</cd> <mark>[Colloq. or Slang]</mark></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musical</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"sic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>musical</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to music; having the qualities of music; or the power of producing music; devoted to music; melodious; harmonious; <as>as, <ex>musical</ex> proportion; a <ex>musical</ex> voice; <ex>musical</ex> instruments; a <ex>musical</ex> sentence; <ex>musical</ex> persons.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Musical box</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Music box</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a box or case containing apparatus moved by clockwork so as to play certain tunes automatically.  The apparatus may be driven by a wind-up spring mechanism or by batteries.</cd> -- <col><b>Musical fish</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any fish which utters sounds under water, as the drumfish, grunt, gizzard shad, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Musical glasses</b></col>, <cd>glass goblets or bowls so tuned and arranged that when struck, or rubbed, they produce musical notes.  Cf. <er>Harmonica</er>, 1.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musical</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"sic*al</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Music.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To fetch home May with their <qex>musical</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A social entertainment of which music is the leading feature; a musical party.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A drama in which music and song are prominent features; a musical drama or musical play; <as>as, Oklahoma! was a breakthrough in the form and popularity of the <ex>musical</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musicale</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mu`si`cale"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.  Cf. <ets>Soir<eacute/e musicale</ets>.]</ety> <def>A social musical party.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musically</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"sic*al*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a musical manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musicalness</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"sic*al*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality of being musical.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Music drama</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"sic dra`ma</hw>. <def>An opera in which the text and action are not interrupted by set arias, duets, etc., the music being determined throughout by dramatic appropriateness; musical drama of this character, in general.  It involves the use of a kind of melodious declamation, the development of leitmotif, great orchestral elaboration, and a fusion of poetry, music, action, and scene into an organic whole.  The term is applied esp. to the later works of Wagner: <ldquo/Tristan und Isolde,<rdquo/ <ldquo/Die Meistersinger,<rdquo/ <ldquo/Rheingold,<rdquo/ <ldquo/Walk<uum/re,<rdquo/ <ldquo/Siegfried,<rdquo/ <ldquo/G<oum/tterd<aum/mmerung,<rdquo/ and <ldquo/Parsifal.<rdquo/</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Music hall</ent><br/
<hw>Music hall</hw>. <def>A place for public musical entertainments; specif. (<mark>Eng.</mark>), esp. a public hall for vaudeville performances, in which smoking and drinking are usually allowed in the auditorium.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musician</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*si"cian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>musicien</ets>.]</ety> <def>One skilled in the art or science of music; esp., a skilled singer, or performer on a musical instrument.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musicomania</ent><br/
<hw>Mu`si*co*ma"ni*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Music</ets> + <ets>mania</ets>: cf. F. <ets>musicomanie</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A kind of monomania in which the passion for music becomes so strong as to derange the intellectual faculties.</def>  <rj><au>Dunglison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musimon</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"i*mon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Musmon</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Mouflon</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>musing</ent><br/
<hw>musing</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>Thinking long and intensely.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> brooding, broody, contemplative, meditative, pensive, pondering, reflective, ruminative.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musingly</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"ing*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a musing manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musit</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"sit</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Muset</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musk</ent><br/
<hw>Musk</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/sk)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>musc</ets>, L. <ets>muscus</ets>, Per. <ets>musk</ets>, fr. Skr. <ets>mushka</ets> testicle, orig., a little mouse. See <er>Mouse</er>, and cd. <er>Abelmosk</er>, <er>Muscadel</er>, <er>Muscovy duck</er>, <er>Nutmeg</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A substance of a reddish brown color, and when fresh of the consistency of honey, obtained from a bag being behind the navel of the male musk deer.  It has a slightly bitter taste, but is specially remarkable for its powerful and enduring odor.  It is used in medicine as a stimulant antispasmodic.  The term is also applied to secretions of various other animals, having a similar odor.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The musk deer. See <cref>Musk deer</cref> (below).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The perfume emitted by musk, or any perfume somewhat similar.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The musk plant (<spn>Mimulus moschatus</spn>).</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A plant of the genus <gen>Erodium</gen> (<spn>Erodium moschatum</spn>); -- called also <altname>musky heron's-bill</altname>.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>A plant of the genus <gen>Muscari</gen>; grape hyacinth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Musk beaver</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>muskrat (1).</cd> -- <col><b>Musk beetle</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a European longicorn beetle (<spn>Aromia moschata</spn>), having an agreeable odor resembling that of attar of roses.</cd> -- <col><b>Musk cat</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Bondar</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Musk cattle</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>musk oxen. See <cref>Musk ox</cref> (below).</cd> -- <col><b>Musk deer</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a small hornless deer (<spn>Moschus moschiferus</spn>), which inhabits the elevated parts of Central Asia.  The upper canine teeth of the male are developed into sharp tusks, curved downward.  The male has scent bags on the belly, from which the musk of commerce is derived.  The deer is yellow or red-brown above, whitish below.  The pygmy musk deer are chevrotains, as the kanchil and napu.</cd> -- <col><b>Musk duck</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The Muscovy duck</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>An Australian duck (<spn>Biziura lobata</spn>).</cd> -- <col><b>Musk lorikeet</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the Pacific lorikeet (<spn>Glossopsitta australis</spn>) of Australia.</cd> -- <col><b>Musk mallow</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a name of two malvaceous plants</cd>: <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A species of mallow (<spn>Malva moschata</spn>), the foliage of which has a faint musky smell</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>An Asiatic shrub. See <er>Abelmosk</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Musk orchis</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a European plant of the Orchis family (<spn>Herminium Minorchis</spn>); -- so called from its peculiar scent.</cd> -- <col><b>Musk ox</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>an Arctic hollow-horned ruminant (<spn>Ovibos moschatus</spn>), now existing only in America, but found fossil in Europe and Asia.  It is covered with a thick coat of fine yellowish wool, and with long dark hair, which is abundant and shaggy on the neck and shoulders.  The full-grown male weighs over four hundred pounds.</cd> -- <col><b>Musk parakeet</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>Same as <cref>Musk lorikeet</cref> (above).</cd> -- <col><b>Musk pear</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a fragrant kind of pear much resembling the Seckel pear.</cd> -- <col><b>Musk plant</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the <spn>Mimulus moschatus</spn>, a plant found in Western North America, often cultivated, and having a strong musky odor.</cd> -- <col><b>Musk root</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the name of several roots with a strong odor, as that of the nard (<spn>Nardostachys Jatamansi</spn>) and of a species of <gen>Angelica</gen>.</cd> -- <col><b>Musk rose</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a species of rose (<spn>Rosa moschata</spn>), having peculiarly fragrant white blossoms.</cd> -- <col><b>Musk seed</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the seed of a plant of the Mallow family (<spn>Hibiscus moschatus</spn>), used in perfumery and in flavoring. See <er>Abelmosk</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Musk sheep</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the musk ox.</cd> -- <col><b>Musk shrew</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a shrew (<spn>Sorex murinus</spn>), found in India.  It has a powerful odor of musk.  Called also <altname>sondeli</altname>, and <altname>mondjourou</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Musk thistle</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a species of thistle (<spn>Carduus nutans</spn>), having fine large flowers, and leaves smelling strongly of musk.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Musk tortoise</b></col>, <col><b>Musk turtle</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a small American fresh-water tortoise (<spn>Armochelys odorata</spn> syn. <spn>Ozotheca odorata</spn>), which has a distinct odor of musk; -- called also <altname>stinkpot</altname>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 957 --></p>

<p><ent>Musk</ent><br/
<hw>Musk</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/sk)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To perfume with musk.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muskadel</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"ka*del`</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/s"k<adot/*d<ecr/l`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Muscadel</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muskat</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"kat</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/s"k<acr/t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Muscat</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muskellunge</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"kel*lunge</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From the Amer. Indian name.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A large American pike (<spn>Esox masquinongy</spn> formerly <spn>Esox nobilior</spn>) found in the Great Lakes, and other Northern lakes, and in the St. Lawrence River. It is valued as a food fish.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>maskallonge</asp>, <asp>maskalonge</asp>, <asp>maskinonge</asp>, <asp>muskallonge</asp>, <asp>muskellonge</asp>, and <asp>muskelunjeh</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musket</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"ket</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mousquet</ets>, It. <ets>moschetto</ets>, formerly, a kind of hawk; cf. OF. <ets>mousket</ets>, <ets>moschet</ets>, a kind of hawk falcon, F. <ets>mouchet</ets>, prop., a little fly (the hawk prob. being named from its size), fr. L. <ets>musca</ets> a fly.  Cf. <er>Mosquito</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Sometimes written also <asp>musquet</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The male of the sparrow hawk.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A species of firearm formerly carried by the infantry of an army.  It was originally fired by means of a match, or matchlock, for which several mechanical appliances (including the flintlock, and finally the percussion lock) were successively substituted.  This arm has been completely superseded by the rifle, and is now only of historical interest.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musketeer</ent><br/
<hw>Mus`ket*eer"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mousquetaire</ets>; cf. It. <ets>moschettiere</ets>.]</ety> <def>A soldier armed with a musket.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musketo</ent><br/
<hw>Mus*ke"to</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mosquito</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musketoon</ent><br/
<hw>Mus`ket*oon"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mousqueton</ets>; cf. It. <ets>moschettone</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A short musket.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who is armed with such a musket.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musketry</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"ket*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mousqueterie</ets>; cf. It. <ets>moschetteria</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Muskets, collectively.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The fire of muskets.</def>  <rj><au>Motley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muskiness</ent><br/
<hw>Musk"i*ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being musky; the scent of musk.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muskmelon</ent><br/
<hw>Musk"mel`on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Musk</ets> + <ets>melon</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The fruit of a cucurbitaceous plant (<spn>Cucumis Melo</spn>) of the gourd family, having a peculiar aromatic flavor, and cultivated in many varieties, the principal sorts being the cantaloupe, of oval form and yellowish flesh, and the smaller nutmeg melon with greenish flesh.  See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Melon</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muskogees</ent><br/
<hw>Mus*ko"gees</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos>; <sing>sing. <singw>Muskogee</singw> <pr>(<?/)</pr></sing>. <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>A powerful tribe of North American Indians that formerly occupied the region of Georgia, Florida, and Alabama.  They constituted a large part of the Creek confederacy.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>Muscogees</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muskrat</ent><br/
<hw>Musk"rat`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A North American aquatic fur-bearing rodent (<spn>Ondatra zibethica</spn> formerly <spn>Fiber zibethicus</spn>).  It resembles a rat in color and having a long scaly tail, but the tail is compressed, the hind feet are webbed, and the ears are concealed in the fur.  It has scent glands which secrete a substance having a strong odor of musk.  Called also <altname>musquash</altname>, <altname>musk beaver</altname>, <altname>ondatra</altname>, and sometimes <altname>water rat</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The musk shrew.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The desman.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muskwood</ent><br/
<hw>Musk"wood`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[So called from its fragrance.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The wood of a West Indian tree of the Mahogany family (<spn>Moschoxylum Swartzii</spn>).</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The wood of an Australian tree (<spn>Eurybia argophylla</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musky</ent><br/
<hw>Musk"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having an odor of musk, or somewhat the like.</def>  <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>musky</ent><br/
<hw>musk"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The <er>muskellunge</er>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muslim</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"lim</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. & a.</pos> <def>See <er>Moslem</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muslin</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"lin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mousseline</ets>; cf. It. <ets>mussolino</ets>, <ets>mussolo</ets>, Sp. <ets>muselina</ets>; all from <ets>Mussoul</ets> a city of Mesopotamia, Ar. <ets>Mausil</ets>, Syr. <ets>Mauzol</ets>, <ets>Muzol</ets>, <ets>Mosul</ets>, where it was first manufactured.  Cf. <er>Mull</er> a kind of cloth.]</ety> <def>A thin cotton, white, dyed, or printed.  The name is also applied to coarser and heavier cotton goods; <as>as, shirting and sheeting <ex>muslins</ex></as>.  In sheeting, <ex>muslin</ex> is not as finely woven as <contr>percale</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Muslin cambric</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Cambric</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Muslin delaine</b></col>, <cd>a light woolen fabric for women's dresses. See <er>Delaine</er>.</cd> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mousseline de laine</asp>.]</altsp></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muslinet</ent><br/
<hw>Mus`lin*et"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mousselinette</ets>.]</ety> <def>A sort of coarse or light cotton cloth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musmon</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"mon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>musmo</ets>, <ets>musimo</ets>, a Sardinian animal; cf. Gr. <grk>moy`smwn</grk>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Mouflon</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musomania</ent><br/
<hw>Mu`so*ma"ni*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Musicomania</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musquash</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"quash</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[American Indian name.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Muskrat</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Musquash root</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>an umbelliferous plant (<spn>Cicuta maculata</spn>), having a poisonous root. See <er>Water hemlock</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musquaw</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Mus"quaw</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[American Indian name.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The American black bear. See <er>Bear</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musquet</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"quet</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Musket</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musquito</ent><br/
<hw>Mus*qui"to</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Mosquito</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musrol</ent><br/
<ent>Musrole</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mus"role</hw>, <hw>Mus"rol</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>muserolle</ets>, fr. <ets>muserau</ets> a muzzle, OF. <ets>musel</ets>. See <er>Muzzle</er>.]</ety> <def>The nose band of a horse's bridle.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muss</ent><br/
<hw>Muss</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>mousche</ets> a fly, also, the play called <ets>muss</ets>, fr. L. <ets>musca</ets> a fly.]</ety> <def>A scramble, as when small objects are thrown down, to be taken by those who can seize them; a confused struggle.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muss</ent><br/
<hw>Muss</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A state of confusion or disorder; -- prob. variant of <xex>mess</xex>, but influenced by <xex>muss</xex>, a scramble.</def> <mark>[Colloq. U.S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muss</ent><br/
<hw>Muss</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mussed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mussing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To disarrange, as clothing; to rumple; -- often used with <ptcl>up</ptcl>; <as>as, the wind <ex>mussed</ex> up my hair</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq. U.S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muss</ent><br/
<hw>Muss</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OE. <ets>mus</ets> a mouse. See <er>Mouse</er>.]</ety> <def>A term of endearment.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <see>See <er>Mouse</er>.</see>  <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mussel</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"sel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Muscle</er>, 3.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of many species of marine bivalve shells of the genus <gen>Mytilus</gen>, and related genera, of the family <fam>Mytidae</fam>.  The common mussel (<spn>Mytilus edulis</spn>; see <xex>Illust.</xex> under <er>Byssus</er>), and the larger, or horse, mussel (<spn>Modiola modiolus</spn>), inhabiting the shores both of Europe and America, are edible. The former is extensively used as food in Europe.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of numerous species of <gen>Unio</gen>, and related fresh-water genera; -- called also <altname>river mussel</altname>. See <er>Naiad</er>, and <er>Unio</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mussel digger</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the grayback whale. See <cref>Gray whale</cref>, under <er>Gray</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mussitation</ent><br/
<hw>Mus`si*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mussitatio</ets> suppression of the voice, fr. <ets>mussitare</ets> to be silent, to murmur.]</ety> <def>A speaking in a low tone; mumbling.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mussite</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"site</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A variety of pyroxene, from the Mussa Alp in Piedmont; diopside.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mussulman</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"sul*man</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mussulmans</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Ar. <ets>muslim<imac/n</ets>, pl. of <ets>muslim</ets>: cf. F. & Sp. <ets>musulman</ets>. See <er>Moslem</er>.]</ety> <def>A Muslim; a Moslem.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mussulmanic</ent><br/
<hw>Mus`sul*man"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of, pertaining to, or like, the Muslims (Mussulmans), or their customs: Islamic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mussulmanish</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"sul*man*ish</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Islamic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mussulmanism</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"sul*man*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Islam.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mussulmanly</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"sul*man*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In the manner of Moslems.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mussy</ent><br/
<hw>Muss"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From 2d <er>Muss</er>.]</ety> <def>Disarranged; rumpled.</def> <mark>[Colloq. U.S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Must</ent><br/
<hw>Must</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/st)</pr>, <pos>v. i. <or/ auxiliary</pos>. <ety>[OE. <ets>moste</ets>, a pret. generally meaning, could, was free to, pres. <ets>mot</ets>, <ets>moot</ets>, AS. <ets>m<omac/ste</ets>, pret. <ets>m<omac/t</ets>, pres.; akin to D. <ets>moetan</ets> to be obliged, OS. <ets>m<omac/tan</ets> to be free, to be obliged, OHG. <ets>muozan</ets>, G. <ets>m<uum/ssen</ets> to be obliged, Sw. <ets>m<aring/ste</ets> must, Goth. <ets>gam<omac/tan</ets> to have place, have room, to able; of unknown origin.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be obliged; to be necessitated; -- expressing either physical or moral necessity; <as>as, a man <ex>must</ex> eat for nourishment; we <ex>must</ex> submit to the laws.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be morally required; to be necessary or essential to a certain quality, character, end, or result; <as>as, he <ex>must</ex> reconsider the matter; he <ex>must</ex> have been insane.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Likewise <qex>must</qex> the deacons be grave.</q> <rj><qau>1 Tim. iii. 8.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Morover, he [a bishop] <qex>must</qex> have a good report of them which are without.</q> <rj><qau>1 Tim. iii. 7.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The principal verb, if easily supplied by the mind, was formerly often omitted when <xex>must</xex> was used; <as>as, I <ex>must</ex> away</as>. <ldquo/I <xex>must</xex> to Coventry.<rdquo/ <au>Shak.</au></note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Must</ent><br/
<hw>Must</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>must</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mustum</ets> (sc. <ets>vinum</ets>), from <ets>mustus</ets> young, new, fresh.  Cf. <er>Mustard</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The expressed juice of the grape, or other fruit, before fermentation.</def> <ldquo/These men ben full of <xex>must</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Wyclif (Acts ii. 13.).</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No fermenting <qex>must</qex> fills . . . the deep vats.</q> <rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[Cf. <er>Musty</er>.]</ety> <def>Mustiness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Must</ent><br/
<hw>Must</hw>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <def>To make musty; to become musty.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>musth</ent><br/
<ent>must</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>must</hw>, <hw>musth</hw></mhw> <pr>(m<ucr/st)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Hind. <ets>mast</ets> intoxicated, ruttish, fr. Skr. <ets>matta</ets>, p.p. of <ets>mad</ets> to rejoice, intoxicate.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Being in a condition of dangerous frenzy, usually connected with sexual excitement; -- said of adult male elephants which become so at irregular intervals, typicaly due to increased testosterone levels.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos>  <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The condition of frenzy.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>An elephant in must.</def></def2><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mustac</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"tac</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>moustac</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A small tufted monkey.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mustache</ent><br/
<hw>Mus*tache"</hw> <pr>(m<ucr/s*t<adot/sh"; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mustaches</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <altsp>[Written also <asp>moustache</asp>.]</altsp> <ety>[F. <ets>moustache</ets>, It. <ets>mostaccio</ets> visage, <ets>mostacchio</ets> mustache, fr. Gr. <grk>my`stax</grk> upper lip and the beard upon it; cf. <grk>ma`stax</grk> mouth: cf. Sp. <ets>mostacho</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That part of the beard which grows on the upper lip; hair left growing above the mouth.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A West African monkey (<spn>Cercopithecus cephus</spn>). It has yellow whiskers, and a triangular blue mark on the nose.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any conspicuous stripe of color on the side of the head, beneath the eye of a bird.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A stain or discoloration on the upper lip of a person; <as>as, wearing a milk <ex>mustache</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[informal]</mark> <br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mustachio</ent><br/
<hw>Mus*ta"chio</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mustachios</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>A mustache.</def>  <rj><au>Longfellow.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mustachioed</ent><br/
<hw>mus*ta"chioed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having a mustache or mustachios.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mustached.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mustahfiz</ent><br/
<hw>Mus`tah"fiz`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Turk. & Ar. <ets>musta<hsdot/fi<zsdot/</ets> who trusts to another's keeping, a soldier of a garrison.]</ety> <def>See <er>Army organization</er>, above.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mustaiba</ent><br/
<hw>Mus`ta*i"ba</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A close-grained, heavy wood of a brownish color, brought from Brazil, and used in turning, for making the handles of tools, and the like.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mostahiba</asp>.]</altsp>  <rj><au>MaElrath.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mustang</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"tang</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>muste<ntil/o</ets> belonging to the graziers, strayed, wild.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The half-wild horse of the plains in Mexico, California, etc.  It is small, hardy, and easily sustained.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mustard grape</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a species of grape (<spn>Vitis candicans</spn>), native in Arkansas and Texas.  The berries are small, light-colored, with an acid skin and a sweet pulp.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mustard</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"tard</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>moustarde</ets>, F. <ets>moutarde</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mustum</ets> must, -- mustard was prepared for use by being mixed with <ets>must</ets>. See <er>Must</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The name of several cruciferous plants of the genus <gen>Brassica</gen> (formerly <gen>Sinapis</gen>), as <stype>white mustard</stype> (<spn>Brassica alba</spn>), <stype>black mustard</stype> (<spn>Brassica Nigra</spn>), <stype>wild mustard</stype> or <stype>charlock</stype> (<spn>Brassica Sinapistrum</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ There are also many herbs of the same family which are called <ex>mustard</ex>, and have more or less of the flavor of the true mustard; as, bowyer's mustard (<spn>Lepidium ruderale</spn>); hedge mustard (<spn>Sisymbrium officinale</spn>); Mithridate mustard (<spn>Thlaspi arvense</spn>); tower mustard (<spn>Arabis perfoliata</spn>); treacle mustard (<spn>Erysimum cheiranthoides</spn>).</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A powder or a paste made from the seeds of black or white mustard, used as a condiment and a rubefacient.  Taken internally it is stimulant and diuretic, and in large doses is emetic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mustard oil</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>a substance obtained from mustard, as a transparent, volatile and intensely pungent oil.  The name is also extended to a number of analogous compounds produced either naturally or artificially.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mustee</ent><br/
<hw>Mus*tee"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mestee</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mustela</ent><br/
<hw>Mustela</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The type genus of the family <fam>Mustelidae:</fam> minks and weasels.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Mustela</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mustelid</ent><br/
<hw>mustelid</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A member of the <fam>Mustelidae</fam>, fissiped fur-bearing carnivorous mammals.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> musteline mammal, musteline.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mustelidae</ent><br/
<hw>Mustelidae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of fissiped fur-bearing carnivorous mammals including the weasels; polecats; ferrets; minks; fishers; otters; badgers; skunks; wolverines; and martens.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Mustelidae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musteline</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"te*line</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mustelinus</ets>, fr. <ets>mustela</ets> weasel.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Like or pertaining to the family <fam>Mustelidae</fam>, or the weasels and martens.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mustelus</ent><br/
<hw>Mustelus</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of sharks including certain of the smooth dogfishes.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus Mustelus.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muster</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>moustre</ets>, OF. <ets>mostre</ets>, <ets>moustre</ets>, F. <ets>montre</ets>, LL. <ets>monstra</ets>. See <er>Muster</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Something shown for imitation; a pattern.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A show; a display.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Piers Plowman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An assembling or review of troops, as for parade, verification of numbers, inspection, exercise, or introduction into service.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The hurried <qex>muster</qex> of the soldiers of liberty.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>See how in warlike <qex>muster</qex> they appear,<br/
In rhombs, and wedges, and half-moons, and wings.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The sum total of an army when assembled for review and inspection; the whole number of effective men in an army.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And the <qex>muster</qex> was thirty thousands of men.</q> <rj><qau>Wyclif.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye publish the <qex>musters</qex> of your own bands, and proclaim them to amount of thousands.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Any assemblage or display; a gathering.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of the temporal grandees of the realm, mentof their wives and daughters, the <qex>muster</qex> was great and splendid.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Muster book</b></col>, <cd>a book in which military forces are registered.</cd> -- <col><b>Muster file</b></col>, <cd>a muster roll.</cd> -- <col><b>Muster master</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>one who takes an account of troops, and of their equipment; a mustering officer; an inspector.</cd> <mark>[Eng.]</mark> -- <col><b>Muster roll</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>a list or register of all the men in a company, troop, or regiment, present or accounted for on the day of muster.</cd> -- <col><b>To pass muster</b></col>, <cd>to pass through a muster or inspection without censure.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such excuses will not <qex>pass muster</qex> with God.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muster</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"ter</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mustered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mustering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>mustren</ets>, prop., to show, OF. <ets>mostrer</ets>, <ets>mustrer</ets>, <ets>moustrer</ets>, <ets>monstrer</ets>, F. <ets>montrer</ets>, fr. L. <ets>monstrare</ets> to show. See <er>Monster</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To collect and display; to assemble, as troops for parade, inspection, exercise, or the like.</def>  <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence: To summon together; to enroll in service; to get together.</def> <ldquo/Mustering <xex>all its force</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the gay feathers he could <qex>muster</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To muster troops into service</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>to inspect and enter troops on the muster roll of the army.</cd> -- <col><b>To muster troops out of service</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>to register them for final payment and discharge.</cd> -- <col><b>To muster up</b></col>, <cd>to gather up; to succeed in obtaining; to obtain with some effort or difficulty.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One of those who can <qex>muster up</qex> sufficient sprightliness to engage in a game of forfeits.</q> <rj><qau>Hazlitt.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muster</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"ter</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be gathered together for parade, inspection, exercise, or the like; to come together as parts of a force or body; <as>as, his supporters <ex>mustered</ex> in force</as>.</def> <ldquo/The <xex>mustering</xex> squadron.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Byron.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mustily</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"ti*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>In a musty state.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mustiness</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"ti*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being musty.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Musty</ent><br/
<hw>Mus"ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Mustier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Mustiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[From L. <ets>mustum</ets> must; or perh. fr. E. <ets>moist</ets>.  Cf. <er>Must</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, <er>Moist</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having the rank, pungent, offensive odor and taste which substances of organic origin acquire during warm, moist weather; foul or sour and fetid; moldy; <as>as, <ex>musty</ex> corn; <ex>musty</ex> books.</as></def>  <rj><au>Harvey.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Spoiled by age; rank; stale.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The proverb is somewhat <qex>musty</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Dull; heavy; spiritless.</def> <ldquo/That he may not grow <xex>musty</xex> and unfit for conversation.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutability</ent><br/
<hw>Mu`ta*bil"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mutabilitas</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mutabilit<eacute/</ets>.]</ety> <def>The quality of being mutable, or subject to change or alteration, either in form, state, or essential character; susceptibility of change; changeableness; inconstancy; variation.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Plato confessed that the heavens and the frame of the world are corporeal, and therefore subject to <qex>mutability</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Stillingfleet.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutable</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ta*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mutabilis</ets>, fr. <ets>mutare</ets> to change. See <er>Move</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Capable of alteration; subject to change; changeable in form, qualities, or nature.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Things of the most accidental and <qex>mutable</qex> nature.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Changeable; inconstant; unsettled; unstable; fickle.</def> <ldquo/Most <xex>mutable</xex> wishes.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Byron.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Changeable; alterable; unstable; unsteady; unsettled; wavering; inconstant; variable; fickle.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutableness</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ta*ble*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality of being mutable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutably</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ta*bly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Changeably.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutacism</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ta*cism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Mytacism</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutage</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"tage</hw> <pr>(m<umac/"t<asl/j)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>A process for checking the fermentation of the must of grapes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 958 --></p>

<p><ent>mutagen</ent><br/
<hw>mu"ta*gen</hw> <pr>(m<umac/"t<adot/*j<ecr/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A chemical compound or other external influence (such as ionizing radiation) which causes mutations{3}.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mutagenesis</ent><br/
<hw>mu`ta*gen"e*sis</hw> <pr>(m<umac/`t<adot/*j<ecr/n"<esl/*s<icr/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>the causing of a mutation or the occurrence of a mutation{3}.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mutagenicity</ent><br/
<hw>mu`ta*gen*i"ci*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>the degree or measure of the ability to cause mutation{3};  -- said of mutagens.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mutandum</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>mu*tan"dum</hw> <pr>(m<usl/*t<acr/n"d<ucr/m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mutanda</plw> <pr>(m<usl/*t<acr/n"d<adot/)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., fr. <ets>mutare</ets> to change.]</ety> <def>A thing which is to be changed; something which must be altered; -- used chiefly in the plural.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mutation</ent><br/
<hw>mu*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(m<usl/*t<amac/"sh<ucr/n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mutatio</ets>, fr. <ets>mutare</ets> to change: cf. F. <ets>mutation</ets>. See <er>Mutable</er>.]</ety> <def>Change; alteration, either in form or qualities.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The vicissitude or <qex>mutations</qex> in the superior globe are no fit matter for this present argument.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Gradual definitely tending variation, such as may be observed in a group of organisms in the fossils of successive geological levels.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn>  <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>As now employed (first by <person>de Vries</person>), a cellular process resulting in a sudden inheritable variation (the offspring differing from its parents in some well-marked character or characters) as distinguished from a gradual variation in which the new characters become fully developed only in the course of many generations.  The occurrence of mutations, the selection of strains carrying mutations permitting enhanced survival under prevailing conditions, and the mechanism of hereditary of the characters so appearing, are well-established facts; whether and to what extent the mutation process has played the most important part in the evolution of the existing species and other groups of organisms is an unresolved question.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The result of the above process; a suddenly produced variation.</def> <note>Mutations can occur by a change in the fundamental coding sequence of the hereditary material, which in most organisms is DNA, but in some viruses is RNA.  It can also occur by rearrangement of an organism's chromosomes.  Specific mutations due to a change in DNA sequence have been recognized as causing certain specific hereditary diseases.  Certain processes which produce variation in the genotype of an organism, such as sexual mixing of chromosomes in offspring, or artificially induced recombination or introduction of novel genetic material into an organism, are not referred to as <ex>mutation</ex>.</note><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>a variant strain of an organism in which the hereditary variant property is caused by a mutation{3}.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mutative</ent><br/
<hw>mutative</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to or marked by genetic mutation{3}.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutch</ent><br/
<hw>Mutch</hw> <pr>(much)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. D. <ets>mutse</ets> a cap, G. <ets>m<uum/tze</ets>.  Cf. <er>Amice</er> a cape.]</ety> <def>The close linen or muslin cap of an old woman.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng. & Scot.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutchkin</ent><br/
<hw>Mutch"kin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A liquid measure equal to four gills, or an imperial pint.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mute</ent><br/
<hw>Mute</hw> <pr>(m<umac/t)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mutare</ets> to change. See <er>Molt</er>.]</ety> <def>To cast off; to molt.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Have I <qex>muted</qex> all my feathers?</q> <rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mute</ent><br/
<hw>Mute</hw>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mutir</ets>, <ets><eacute/meutir</ets>, OF. <ets>esmeltir</ets>, fr. OD. <ets>smelten</ets>, prop., to melt. See <er>Smelt</er>.]</ety> <def>To eject the contents of the bowels; -- said of birds.</def>  <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mute</ent><br/
<hw>Mute</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The dung of birds.</def>  <rj><au>Hudibras.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mute</ent><br/
<hw>Mute</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mutus</ets>; cf. Gr. <grk>my`ein</grk> to shut, Skr. <ets>m<umac/ta</ets> bound, <ets>m<umac/ka</ets> dumb: cf. OE. <ets>muet</ets>, fr. F. <ets>muet</ets>, a dim. of OF. <ets>mu</ets>, L. <ets>mutus</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Not speaking; uttering no sound; silent.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the heavenly choir stood <qex>mute</qex>,<br/
And silence was in heaven.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ In law a prisoner is said to stand <xex>mute</xex>, when, upon being arranged, he makes no answer, or does not plead directly, or will not put himself on trial.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Incapable of speaking; dumb.</def>  <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Not uttered; unpronounced; silent; also, produced by complete closure of the mouth organs which interrupt the passage of breath; -- said of certain letters. See 5th <er>Mute</er>, 2.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Not giving a ringing sound when struck; -- said of a metal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mute swan</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a European wild white swan (<spn>Cygnus olor</spn> syn. <spn>Cygnus gibbus</spn>), which produces no loud notes, in distinction from the <contr>Trumpeter swan</contr>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Silent; dumb; speechless.</syn>  -- <usage><er>Mute</er>, <er>Silent</er>, <er>Dumb</er>. One is <xex>silent</xex> who <xex>does</xex> not speak; one is <xex>dumb</xex> who <xex>can</xex> not, for want of the proper organs; <as>as, a <ex>dumb</ex> beast, etc.</as>; and hence, figuratively, we speak of a person as struck <xex>dumb</xex> with astonishment, etc.  One is <xex>mute</xex> who is <xex>held back</xex> from speaking by some special cause; <as>as, he was <ex>mute</ex> through fear; <ex>mute</ex> astonishment, etc.</as>  Such is the case with most of those who never speak from childhood; they are not ordinarily <xex>dumb</xex>, but <xex>mute</xex> because they are deaf, and therefore never learn to talk; and hence their more appropriate name is <xex>deaf-mutes</xex>.<br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They spake not a word;<br/
But, like <qex>dumb</qex> statues, or breathing stones,<br/
Gazed each on other.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All sat <qex>mute</qex>,<br/
Pondering the danger with deep thoughts.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>
</usage><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mute</ent><br/
<hw>Mute</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who does not speak, whether from physical inability, unwillingness, or other cause.</def> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>One who, from deafness, either congenital or from early life, is unable to use articulate language; a deaf-mute.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A person employed by undertakers at a funeral.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>A person whose part in a play does not require him to speak.</def> <sd>(d)</sd> <def>Among the Turks, an officer or attendant who is selected for his place because he can not speak.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Phon.)</fld> <def>A letter which represents no sound; a silent letter; also, a close articulation; an element of speech formed by a position of the mouth organs which stops the passage of the breath; <as>as, <stype>p</stype>, <stype>b</stype>, <stype>d</stype>, <stype>k</stype>, <stype>t</stype></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A little utensil made of brass, ivory, or other material, so formed that it can be fixed in an erect position on the bridge of a violin, or similar instrument, in order to deaden or soften the tone.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>muted</ent><br/
<hw>muted</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>  <def>same as <er>quiet</er>; <as>as, the <ex>muted</ex> atmosphere of a church</as>.  Opposite of <ant>noisy</ant>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> hushed.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn>  <def>softened; rendered less loud or harsh; -- of sounds and instruments which produce sounds; <as>as, <ex>muted</ex> trumpets</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> dull, muffled, softened.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mute-hill</ent><br/
<hw>Mute"-hill`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Moot-hill</er>.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutely</ent><br/
<hw>Mute"ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Without uttering words or sounds; in a mute manner; silently.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muteness</ent><br/
<hw>Mute"ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The quality or state of being mute; speechlessness.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutessarif</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*tes`sa*rif"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Turk. & Ar. <ets>mute<cced/arif</ets> freely disposing of anything, master.]</ety> <def>In Turkey prior to the revolution, an administrative authority of any of certain sanjaks.  They were appointed directly by the Sultan.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutessarifat</ent><br/
<hw>Mu*tes`sa*ri*fat"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Turk. & Ar. <ets>mute<cced/arifah</ets> office of a mutessarif.]</ety> <def>In Turkey, a sanjak whose head is a mutessarif.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muticous</ent><br/
<ent>Mutic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mu"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mu"ti*cous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>muticus</ets>, for <ets>mutilus</ets>. See <er>Mutilate</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot. & Zool.)</fld> <def>Without a point or pointed process; blunt.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutilate</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ti*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mutilatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>mutilare</ets> to mutilate, fr. <ets>mutilus</ets> maimed; cf. Gr. <?/, <?/.  Cf. <er>Mutton</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Deprived of, or having lost, an important part; mutilated.</def>  <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having finlike appendages or flukes instead of legs, as a cetacean.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutilate</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ti*late</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A cetacean, or a sirenian.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutilate</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ti*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mutilated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mutilating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cut off or remove a limb or essential part of; to maim; to cripple; to disfigure; to hack; <as>as, to <ex>mutilate</ex> the body, a statue, etc.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To destroy or remove a material part of, so as to render imperfect; <as>as, to <ex>mutilate</ex> the orations of Cicero</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Among the <qex>mutilated</qex> poets of antiquity, there is none whose fragments are so beautiful as those of Sappho.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Mutilated gear</b></col>, <col><b>Mutilated wheel</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>a gear wheel from a portion of whose periphery the cogs are omitted. It is used for giving intermittent movements.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mutilated</ent><br/
<hw>mutilated</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>  <def>badly injured, perhaps with amputation or permanent disfigurement; <as>as, <ex>mutilated</ex> victims of the rocket attack</as>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> maimed.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn>  <def>damaged, often deliberately; -- of compositions; <as>as, a <ex>mutilated</ex> text</as>.  Opposite of <ant>undamaged</ant> or <ant>intact</ant>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mangled, mutilated.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutilation</ent><br/
<hw>Mu`ti*la"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mutilatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mutilation</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act of mutilating, or the state of being mutilated; deprivation of a limb or of an essential part.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutilator</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ti*la"tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mutilateur</ets>.]</ety> <def>One who mutilates.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutilous</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ti*lous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mutilus</ets>. See <er>Mutilate</er>.]</ety> <def>Mutilated; defective; imperfect.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutine</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"tine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mutin</ets>.]</ety> <def>A mutineer.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutine</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"tine</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mutiner</ets>.]</ety> <def>To mutiny.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutineer</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ti*neer`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mutiny</er>.]</ety> <def>One guilty of mutiny.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muting</ent><br/
<hw>Mut"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Dung of birds.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutinous</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ti*nous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mutiny</er>.]</ety> <def>Disposed to mutiny; in a state of mutiny; characterized by mutiny; seditious; insubordinate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The city was becoming <qex>mutinous</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Mu"ti*nous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mu"ti*nous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutiny</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ti*ny</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mutinies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[From <ets>mutine</ets> to mutiny, fr. F. <ets>se mutiner</ets>, fr. F. <ets>mutin</ets> stubborn, mutinous, fr. OF. <ets>meute</ets> riot, LL. <ets>movita</ets>, fr. <ets>movitus</ets>, for L. <ets>motus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>movere</ets> to move. See <er>Move</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Insurrection against constituted authority, particularly military or naval authority; concerted revolt against the rules of discipline or the lawful commands of a superior officer; hence, generally, forcible resistance to rightful authority; insubordination.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In every <qex>mutiny</qex> against the discipline of the college, he was the ringleader.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Violent commotion; tumult; strife.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To raise a <qex>mutiny</qex> betwixt yourselves.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mutiny act</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>an English statute reenacted annually to punish mutiny and desertion.</cd>  <rj><au>Wharton.</au></rj></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Insurrection</er>.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutiny</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"ti*ny</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mutinied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mutinying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To rise against, or refuse to obey, lawful authority in military or naval service; to excite, or to be guilty of, mutiny or mutinous conduct; to revolt against one's superior officer, or any rightful authority.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To fall into strife; to quarrel.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutism</ent><br/
<hw>Mut"ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The condition, state, or habit of being mute, or without speech.</def>  <rj><au>Max M<uum/ller.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutoscope</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"to*scope</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mutare</ets> to change + <ets>-scope</ets>.]</ety> <def>A simple form of moving-picture machine in which the series of views, exhibiting the successive phases of a scene, are printed on paper and mounted around the periphery of a wheel.  The rotation of the wheel brings them rapidly into sight, one after another, and the blended effect gives a semblance of motion.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mutt</ent><br/
<hw>mutt</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>An dog that is of inferior quality or of mixed breed.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> cur, mongrel.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutter</ent><br/
<hw>Mut"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Muttered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Muttering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Prob. of imitative origin; cf. L. <ets>muttire</ets>, <ets>mutire</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To utter words indistinctly or with a low voice and lips partly closed; esp., to utter indistinct complaints or angry expressions; to grumble; to growl.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wizards that peep, and that <qex>mutter</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Is. viii. 19.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Meantime your filthy foreigner will stare,<br/
And <qex>mutter</qex> to himself.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To sound with a low, rumbling noise.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thick lightnings flash, the <qex>muttering</qex> thunder rolls.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutter</ent><br/
<hw>Mut"ter</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To utter with imperfect articulations, or with a low voice; <as>as, to <ex>mutter</ex> threats</as>.</def>  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutter</ent><br/
<hw>Mut"ter</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Repressed or obscure utterance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutterer</ent><br/
<hw>Mut"ter*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who mutters.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutteringly</ent><br/
<hw>Mut"ter*ing*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>With a low voice and indistinct articulation; in a muttering manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutton</ent><br/
<hw>Mut"ton</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>motoun</ets>, OF. <ets>moton</ets>, <ets>molton</ets>, a sheep, wether, F. <ets>mouton</ets>, LL. <ets>multo</ets>, by transposition of <it>l</it> fr. L. <ets>mutilus</ets> mutilated. See <er>Mutilate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A sheep.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chapman.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not so much ground as will feed a <qex>mutton</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir H. Sidney.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Muttons</qex>, beeves, and porkers are good old words for the living quadrupeds.</q> <rj><qau>Hallam.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The flesh of a sheep.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The fat of roasted <qex>mutton</qex> or beef.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A loose woman; a prostitute.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mutton bird</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the Australian short-tailed petrel (<spn>Nectris brevicaudus</spn>).</cd> -- <col><b>Mutton chop</b></col>, <cd>a rib of mutton for broiling, with the end of the bone at the smaller part chopped off.</cd> -- <col><b>Mutton fish</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the American eelpout. See <er>Eelpout</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Mutton fist</b></col>, <cd>a big brawny fist or hand.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <au>Dryden.</au> -- <col><b>Mutton monger</b></col>, <cd>a pimp.</cd> <mark>[Low & Obs.]</mark> <au>Chapman.</au> -- <col><b>To return to one's muttons</b></col>. <ety>[A translation of a phrase from a farce by <person>De Brueys</person>, <ets>revenons <agrave/ nos moutons</ets> let us return to our sheep.]</ety> <cd>To return to one's topic, subject of discussion, etc.</cd> <mark>[Humorous]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I willingly <qex>return to my muttons</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>H. R. Haweis.</qau></rj>
</cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>muttonfish</ent><br/
<hw>muttonfish</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A fish (<spn>Lutjanus analis</spn>) similar to and often marketed as <ldquo/red snapper<rdquo/.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mutton snapper, <spn>Lutjanus analis</spn>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>muttonhead</ent><br/
<hw>muttonhead</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A stupid or foolish person; a dolt; a numbskull; a blockhead; -- disparaging and offensive.  These words are used to express a low opinion of someone's intelligence.</def> <mark>[disparaging]</mark> <br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> dunce, dunderhead, numskull, blockhead, bonehead, lunkhead, hammerhead, knucklehead, loggerhead, shithead, fuckhead.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muttony</ent><br/
<hw>Mut"ton*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Like mutton; having a flavor of mutton.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutual</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"tu*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mutuel</ets>, L. <ets>mutuus</ets>, orig., exchanged, borrowed, lent; akin to <ets>mutare</ets> to change. See <er>Mutable</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Reciprocally acting or related; reciprocally receiving and giving; reciprocally given and received; reciprocal; interchanged; <as>as, a <ex>mutual</ex> love, advantage, assistance, aversion, etc.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Conspiracy and <qex>mutual</qex> promise.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. More.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Happy in our <qex>mutual</qex> help,<br/
And <qex>mutual</qex> love.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A certain shyness on such subjects, which was <qex>mutual</qex> between the sisters.</q> <rj><qau>G. Eliot.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Possessed, experienced, or done by two or more persons or things at the same time; common; joint; <as>as, <ex>mutual</ex> happiness; a <ex>mutual</ex> effort.</as></def>  <rj><au>Burke.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A vast accession of misery and woe from the <qex>mutual</qex> weeping, and wailing, and gnashing of teeth.</q> <rj><qau>Bentley.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/   This use of <xex>mutual</xex> as synonymous with <xex>common</xex> is inconsistent with the idea of interchange, or reciprocal relation, which properly belongs to it; but the word has been so used by many writers of high authority.  The present tendency is toward a careful discrimination.<br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mutual</qex>, as Johnson will tell us, means something reciprocal, a giving and taking.  How could people have <qex>mutual</qex> ancestors?</q> <rj><qau>P. Harrison.</qau></rj>
</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mutual insurance</b></col>, <cd>agreement among a number of persons to insure each other against loss, as by fire, death, or accident.</cd> -- <col><b>Mutual insurance company</b></col>, <cd>one which does a business of insurance on the mutual principle, the policy holders sharing losses and profits <xex>pro rata</xex>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Reciprocal; interchanged; common.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutualism</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"tu*al*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Ethics)</fld> <def>The doctrine of mutual dependence as the condition of individual and social welfare.</def>  <rj><au>F. Harrison.</au>  <au>H. Spencer.</au>  <au>Mallock.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mutualist</ent><br/
<hw>mutualist</hw> <pos>adj.</pos>  <def>One practising or advocating the doctrine of mutualism.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> interdependent, mutually beneficial.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutuality</ent><br/
<hw>Mu`tu*al"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mutualit<eacute/</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality of correlation; reciprocation; interchange; interaction; interdependence.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Reciprocity of consideration.</def>  <rj><au>Wharton.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutually</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"tu*al*ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a mutual manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mutual savings bank</ent><br/
<hw>mutual savings bank</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>a state-chartered savings bank owned by its depositors and managed by a board of trustees.  Abbreviated <altname>MSB</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutuary</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"tu*a*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mutuarius</ets> mutual.See <er>Mutuation</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>One who borrows personal chattels which are to be consumed by him, and which he is to return or repay in kind.</def>  <rj><au>Bouvier.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutuation</ent><br/
<hw>Mu`tu*a"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mutuatio</ets>, fr. <ets>mutuare</ets>, <ets>mutuari</ets>, to borrow, fr. <ets>mutuus</ets>. See <er>Mutual</er>.]</ety> <def>The act of borrowing or exchanging.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mutule</ent><br/
<hw>Mu"tule</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>mutulus</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A projecting block worked under the corona of the Doric corice, in the same situation as the modillion of the Corinthian and Composite orders. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Gutta</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Oxf. Gloss.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mux</ent><br/
<hw>Mux</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Mixen</er>.]</ety> <def>Dirt; filth; muck.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>  <rj><au>ose.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mux</ent><br/
<hw>Mux</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To mix in an untidy and offensive way; to make a mess of.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.; Colloq. U.S.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muxy</ent><br/
<hw>Mux"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Soft; sticky, and dirty.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> <see>See <er>Mucky</er>.</see><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muzarab</ent><br/
<hw>Muz"a*rab</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>mozarabe</ets>, fr. Ar. <ets>mosta'rib</ets>, a name applied to strange tribes living among the Arabs.]</ety> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>One of a denomination of Christians formerly living under the government of the Moors in Spain, and having a liturgy and ritual of their own.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>Mozarab</asp>, <asp>Mostarab</asp>.]</altsp>  <rj><au>Brande & C.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muzarabic</ent><br/
<hw>Muz`a*rab"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to Muzarabs; <as>as, the <ex>Muzarabic</ex> liturgy</as>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>Mozarabic</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>muzjik</ent><br/
<hw>muzjik</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A Russian peasant (especially prior to 1917).</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> muzhik, moujik, mujik.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muzziness</ent><br/
<hw>Muz"zi*ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state or quality of being muzzy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muzzle</ent><br/
<hw>Muz"zle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mosel</ets>, OF. <ets>musel</ets>, F. <ets>museau</ets> muzzle or snout, LL. <ets>musellus</ets>, fr. <ets>musus</ets>, <ets>morsus</ets>. See <er>Muse</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>, and cf. <er>Morsel</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The projecting mouth and nose of a quadruped, as of a horse; a snout.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The mouth of a thing; the end for entrance or discharge; <as>as, the <ex>muzzle</ex> of a gun</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A fastening or covering (as a band or cage) for the mouth of an animal, to prevent eating or vicious biting.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With golden <qex>muzzles</qex> all their mouths were bound</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Muzzle sight</b></col>. <fld>(Gun.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Dispart</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 2.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muzzle</ent><br/
<hw>Muz"zle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Muzzled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Muzzling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>museler</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To bind the mouth of; to fasten the mouth of, so as to prevent biting or eating; hence, figuratively, to bind; to sheathe; to restrain from speech or action; <as>as, the dictator <ex>muzzled</ex> all the newspapers</as>.</def> <ldquo/My dagger <xex>muzzled</xex>.<rdquo/  <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou shalt not <qex>muzzle</qex> the ox when he treadeth out the corn.</q> <rj><qau>Deut. xxv. 4.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To fondle with the closed mouth.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>L'Estrange.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muzzle</ent><br/
<hw>Muz"zle</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To bring the mouth or muzzle near.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The bear <qex>muzzles</qex> and smells to him.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muzzle-loader</ent><br/
<hw>Muz"zle-load`er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A firearm which receives its charge through the muzzle, as distinguished from one which is loaded at the breech.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muzzle-loading</ent><br/
<hw>Muz"zle-load`ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Receiving its charge through the muzzle; <as>as, a <ex>muzzle-loading</ex> rifle</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muzzy</ent><br/
<hw>Muz"zy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>muse</ets>.]</ety> <def>Absent-minded; dazed; muddled; stupid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The whole company stared at me with a whimsical, <qex>muzzy</qex> look, like men whose senses were a little obfuscated by beer rather than wine.</q> <rj><qau>W. Irving.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>MVP</ent><br/
<hw>MVP</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <mark>(acron.)</mark> <def>most valuable player; the player judged to be the most important to the sport, also the name of the award given to that player.</def> <mark>[abbreviation]</mark><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mx</ent><br/
<hw>Mx</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The symbol for the <sig>maxwell</sig>, a cgs unit of magnetic flux.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> maxwell.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>My</ent><br/
<hw>My</hw> <pr>(m<imac/)</pr>, <pos>a. & poss. pron.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mi</ets>, fr. <ets>min</ets>. See <er>Mine</er>, and cf., for loss of <it>n</it>, <er>A</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, <er>An</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>Of or belonging to me; -- used always attributively; <as>as, <ex>my</ex> body; <ex>my</ex> book</as>; -- <xex>mine</xex> is used in the predicate; <as>as, the book is <ex>mine</ex></as>. See <er>Mine</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mya</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My"a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mya</ets> a kind of mussel.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of bivalve mollusks, including the common long, or soft-shelled, clam.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myaceae</ent><br/
<hw>Myaceae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>An order of clams.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> order <ord>Myaceae</ord>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myacidae</ent><br/
<hw>Myacidae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of soft-shell clams.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Myacidae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myadestes</ent><br/
<hw>Myadestes</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of birds including  the solitaires, thrushes noted for their beautiful songs.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myalgia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My*al"gi*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ muscle + <?/ pain.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Pain in the muscles; muscular rheumatism or neuralgia.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myall wood</ent><br/
<hw>My*all" wood`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A durable, fragrant, and dark-colored Australian wood, used by the natives for spears. It is obtained from the small tree <spn>Acacia homolophylla</spn>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myaria</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My*a"ri*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A division of bivalve mollusks of which the common clam (<gen>Mya</gen>) is the type.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mycelium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My*ce"li*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>my`khs</grk> a mushroom.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The white threads or filamentous growth from which a mushroom or fungus is developed; the so-called mushroom spawn.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>My*ce"li*al</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myceloid</ent><br/
<hw>Myc"e*loid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mycel</ets>ium + <ets>-oid</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Resembling mycelium.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mycetes</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My*ce"tes</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>mykhth`s</grk> a bellower, fr. <grk>myka^sqai</grk> to bellow.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of South American monkeys, including the howlers. See <er>Howler</er>, 2, and <xex>Illust.</xex></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mycetoid</ent><br/
<hw>Myc"e*toid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <ety>[Gr. <grk>my`khs</grk>, <grk>my`khtos</grk>, a fungus + <ets>-oid</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Resembling a fungus.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mycetozoa</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My*ce`to*zo"a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL.; Gr. <grk>my`khs</grk>, <grk>my`khtos</grk>, fungus + <?/ pl. of <grk>zw^,on</grk> an animal.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The Myxomycetes; -- so called by those who regard them as a class of animals.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>My*ce`to*zo"an</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mycobacteria</ent><br/
<hw>mycobacteria</hw> <pos>n. pl.</pos> <def>A group of rod-shaped bacteria, some saprophytic or causing diseases.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mycobacterium.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mycobacterium</ent><br/
<hw>mycobacterium</hw> <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>mycobacteria</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <def>Any of various rod-shaped bacteria, some saprophytic or causing diseases.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mycoderma</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>my`co*der"ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., from Gr. <grk>my`khs</grk> a fungus + <grk>de`rma</grk> skin.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>One of the forms in which bacteria group themselves; a more or less thick layer of motionless but living bacteria, formed by the bacteria uniting on the surface of the fluid in which they are developed.  This production differs from the zoogloea stage of bacteria by not having the intermediary mucous substance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <mark>(Capitalized)</mark> <def>A genus of microorganisms of which the acetic ferment (<spn>Mycoderma aceti</spn>), which converts alcoholic fluids into vinegar, is a representative.  Cf. <er>Mother</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mycological</ent><br/
<ent>Mycologic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>My`co*log"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>My`co*log"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or relating to mycology, or the fungi.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mycologist</ent><br/
<hw>My*col"o*gist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who is versed in, or who studies, mycology.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mycology</ent><br/
<hw>My*col"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>my`khs</grk> fungus + <ets>-logy</ets>.]</ety> <def>That branch of botanical science which relates to the mushrooms and other fungi.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mycomelic</ent><br/
<hw>My`co*mel"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. (spurious) <grk>my^kos</grk> mucus (L. <ets>mucus</ets>) + <grk>me`li</grk> honey.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or designating, a complex nitrogenous acid of the alloxan group, obtained as a honey-yellow powder.  Its solutions have a gelatinous consistency.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mycoprotein</ent><br/
<hw>My`co*pro"te*in</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. (spurious) <grk>my^kos</grk> mucus (L. <ets>mucus</ets>) + E. <ets>protein</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The protoplasmic matter of which bacteria are composed.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark> <br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mycose</ent><br/
<hw>My"cose</hw> <pr>(m<imac/"k<omac/s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>my`khs</grk> a mushroom.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A variety of sugar, isomeric with sucrose and obtained from certain lichens and fungi.  Called also <altname>trehalose</altname>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mykose</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 959 --></p>

<p><ent>Mycothrix</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Myc"o*thrix</hw> <pr>(m<imac/k"<osl/*thr<icr/ks)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. (spurious) <grk>my`khs</grk> mucus (L. <ets>mucus</ets>) + <grk>qri`x</grk>, <grk>tricho`s</grk>, hair.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The chain of micrococci formed by the division of the micrococci in multiplication.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mycteria</ent><br/
<hw>Mycteria</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of birds including certain of the wood ibises, including the endangered <spn>Mycteria americana</spn>; it is sometimes assigned to a subfamily <subfam>Mycteriinae</subfam>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Mycteria</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mydaleine</ent><br/
<hw>My*da"le*ine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>myda^n</grk> to be clammy (from decay).]</ety> <fld>(Physiol. Chem.)</fld> <def>A toxic alkaloid (ptomaine) obtained from putrid flesh and from herring brines.  As a poison it is said to execute profuse diarrhoea, vomiting, and intestinal inflammation.</def>  <rj><au>Brieger.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mydatoxin</ent><br/
<hw>Myd`a*tox"in</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>myda^n</grk> to be clammy (from decay) + <ets>tox</ets>ic + <ets>in</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol. Chem.)</fld> <def>A poisonous amido acid, <chform>C6H13NO2</chform>, separated by Brieger from decaying horseflesh. In physiological action, it is similar to curare.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mydaus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Myd"a*us</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>myda^n</grk> to be clammy or damp.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The teledu.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mydriasis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My*dri"a*sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol. & Med.)</fld> <def>A long-continued or excessive dilatation of the pupil of the eye.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mydriatic</ent><br/
<hw>Myd`ri*at"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Causing dilatation of the pupil.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A mydriatic medicine or agent, as belladonna.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myelencephala</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My`e*len*ceph"a*la</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Myelencephalon</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Vertebrata</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myelencephalic</ent><br/
<hw>My`e*len`ce*phal"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the myelencephalon; cerebro-spinal.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myelencephalon</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My`e*len*ceph"a*lon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., from Gr. <grk>myelo`s</grk> marrow + E. <ets>encephalon</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The brain and spinal cord; the cerebro-spinal axis.  Sometimes abbreviated to <altname>myelencephal</altname>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The metencephalon.</def>  <rj><au>Huxley.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myelencephalous</ent><br/
<hw>My`e*len*ceph"a*lous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the Myelencephala.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>myeline</ent><br/
<ent>myelin</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>my"e*lin</hw>, <hw>my"e*line</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>myelo`s</grk> marrow.]</ety>  <fld>(Physiol. Chem.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A soft white substance constituting the medullary sheaths of nerve fibers, and composed mainly of cholesterin, lecithin, cerebrin, protein, and some fat.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>One of a group of phosphorized principles occurring in nerve tissue, both in the brain and nerve fibers.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>myelinic</ent><br/
<hw>myelinic</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to myelin.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myelitis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My`e*li"tis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., from Gr. <grk>myelo`s</grk> marrow + <ets>-itis</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Inflammation of the spinal marrow or its membranes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Inflammation of bone marrow.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myelocoele</ent><br/
<hw>My"e*lo*coele`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>myelo`s</grk> marrow + <grk>koi^los</grk> hollow.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The central canal of the spinal cord.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>myelofibrosis</ent><br/
<hw>myelofibrosis</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Fibrosis of the bone marrow.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myelogenic</ent><br/
<hw>My`e*lo*gen"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>myelo`s</grk> marrow + the root of <grk>gi`gnesqai</grk> to be born.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>Derived from, or pertaining to, the bone marrow.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myeloid</ent><br/
<hw>My"e*loid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>myelo`s</grk> marrow + <ets>-oid</ets>.]</ety> <def>Resembling marrow in appearance or consistency; <as>as, a <ex>myeloid</ex> tumor</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myeloidin</ent><br/
<hw>My`e*loid"in</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Myelin</ets> + <ets>-oid</ets> + <ets>-in</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol. Chem.)</fld> <def>A substance, present in the protoplasm of the retinal epithelium cells, and resembling, if not identical with, the substance (<xex>myelin</xex>) forming the medullary sheaths of nerve fibers.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myelon</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My"e*lon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>myelo`s</grk> marrow.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The spinal cord. (Sometimes abbrev. to <abbr>myel.</abbr>)</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myelonal</ent><br/
<hw>My"e*lo`nal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the myelon; <as>as, the <ex>myelonal</ex>, or spinal, nerves</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myeloneura</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My`e*lo*neu"ra</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>myelo`s</grk> + <grk>ney^ron</grk> a nerve.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The Vertebrata.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myeloplax</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My*el"o*plax</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> E. <plw>Myeloplaxes</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, L. <plw>Myeloplaces</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>myelo`s</grk> marrow + <?/ anything flat and broad.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>One of the huge multinucleated cells found in the marrow of bone and occasionally in other parts; a giant cell. See <er>Osteoclast</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mygale</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Myg"a*le</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[L., a field mouse, Gr. <?/.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of very large hairy spiders of the family <fam>Ctenizidae</fam>, having four lungs and only four spinnerets.  They do not spin webs, but usually construct tubes in the earth, which are often furnished with a trapdoor.  The South American bird spider (<spn>Mygale avicularia</spn>), and the crab spider, or matoutou (<spn>Mygale cancerides</spn>) are among the largest species.  They are also called <altname>trapdoor spiders</altname>.  Some of the species are erroneously called <xex>tarantulas</xex>, as the Texas tarantula (<spn>Mygale Hentzii</spn>).</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mykiss</ent><br/
<hw>My"kiss</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Russ. <ets>muikize</ets>, prob. fr. a native name.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A salmon (<spn>Salmo mykiss</spn>, syn. <spn>Salmo purpuratus</spn>) marked with black spots and a red throat, found in most of the rivers from Alaska to the Colorado River, and in Siberia; -- called also <altname>black-spotted trout</altname>, <altname>cutthroat trout</altname>, and <altname>redthroat trout</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mylitta</ent><br/
<hw>Mylitta</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Babylonian and Assyrian Mythology)</fld>  <def>The goddess of love and fertility and war; also called <altname>Ishtar</altname>; the counterpart of <persfn>Ashtoreth</persfn> and <persfn>Astarte</persfn>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Ishtar.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mylodon</ent><br/
<hw>Myl"o*don</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ a mill + <grk>'odoy`s</grk>, <grk>'odo`ntos</grk>, a tooth.]</ety> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>An extinct genus of large slothlike American edentates, allied to Megatherium.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mylodontidae</ent><br/
<hw>Mylodontidae</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>A natural family of extinct South American edentates.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Mylodontidae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mylohyoid</ent><br/
<hw>My`lo*hy"oid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ the molar teeth + E. <ets>hyoid</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or in the region of, the lower jaw and the hyoid apparatus; <as>as, the <ex>mylohyoid</ex> nerve</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mynah</ent><br/
<ent>myna</ent><br/
<mhw><hw>my"na</hw>, <hw>my"nah</hw></mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mino bird</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of numerous species of Asiatic starlings of the genera <gen>Acridotheres</gen>, <gen>Sturnopastor</gen>, <gen>Sturnia</gen>, <gen>Gracula</gen>, and allied genera.  In habits they resemble the European starlings, and like them are often caged and taught to talk.  See <cref>Hill myna</cref>, under <er>Hill</er>, and <er>Mino bird</er>.</def> <altsp>[Spelt also <asp>mynah</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mynchen</ent><br/
<hw>Myn"chen</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>mynecen</ets>, fr. <ets>munec</ets> monk. See <er>Monk</er>.]</ety> <def>A nun.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mynchery</ent><br/
<hw>Myn"cher*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A nunnery; -- a term still applied to the ruins of certain nunneries in England.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mynheer</ent><br/
<hw>Myn*heer"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[D. <ets>mijnheer</ets>.]</ety> <def>The Dutch equivalent of <sig>Mr.</sig> or <sig>Sir</sig>; hence, a Dutchman.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>myo-</ent><br/
<hw>my"o-</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <def>A combining form of Gr. <?/, <?/, a <xex>muscle</xex>; <as>as, <ex>myo</ex>graph, <ex>myo</ex>chrome</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>myocardial</ent><br/
<hw>myocardial</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the myocardium.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>myocarditis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>my`o*car*di"tis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. see <er>myocardium</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Inflammation of the myocardium.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myocardium</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My`o*car"di*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/, <?/, muscle + <?/ heart.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The main substance of the muscular wall of the heart inclosed between the epicardium and endocardium.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myochrome</ent><br/
<hw>My"o*chrome</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Myo-</ets> + Gr. <?/ color.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>A colored albuminous substance in the serum from red-colored muscles.  It is identical with hemoglobin.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myocomma</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My`o*com"ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> L. <plw>Myocommata</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, E. <plw>Myocommas</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL. See <er>Myo-</er>, and <er>Comma</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A myotome.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myodynamics</ent><br/
<hw>My`o*dy*nam"ics</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Myo-</ets> + <ets>dynamics</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>The department of physiology which deals with the principles of muscular contraction; the exercise of muscular force or contraction.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myodynamiometer</ent><br/
<hw>My`o*dy*na`mi*om"e*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A myodynamometer.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myodynamometer</ent><br/
<hw>My`o*dy`na*mom"e*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Myo-</ets> + E. <ets>dynamometer</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>An instrument for measuring the muscular strength of man or of other animals; a dynamometer.</def>  <rj><au>Dunglison.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myoepithelial</ent><br/
<hw>My`o*ep`i*the"li*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Myo-</ets> + <ets>epithelial</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Derived from epithelial cells and destined to become a part of the muscular system; -- applied to structural elements in certain embryonic forms.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having the characteristics of both muscle and epithelium; <as>as, the <ex>myoepithelial</ex> cells of the hydra</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myogalid</ent><br/
<hw>My*og"a*lid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Myo-</ets> + Gr. <?/ a weasel.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the <fam>Myogalodae</fam>, a family of Insectivora, including the desman, and allied species.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myogram</ent><br/
<hw>My"o*gram</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Myo-</ets> + <ets>-gram</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>See <cref>Muscle curve</cref>, under <er>Muscle</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myograph</ent><br/
<hw>My"o*graph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Myo-</ets> + <ets>-graph</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>An instrument for determining and recording the different phases, as the intensity, velocity, etc., of a muscular contraction.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myographical</ent><br/
<ent>Myographic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>My`o*graph"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>My`o*graph"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to myography.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myography</ent><br/
<hw>My*og"ra*phy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>myographie</ets>.]</ety> <def>The description of muscles, including the study of muscular contraction by the aid of registering apparatus, as by some form of myograph; myology.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myohaematin</ent><br/
<hw>My`o*haem"a*tin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Myo-</ets> + <ets>haematin</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>A red-colored respiratory pigment found associated with hemoglobin in the muscle tissue of a large number of animals, both vertebrate and invertebrate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myoid</ent><br/
<hw>My"oid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Myo-</ets> + <ets>-oid</ets>.]</ety> <def>Composed of, or resembling, muscular fiber.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myolemma</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My`o*lem"ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/, <?/, a muscle + <?/ skin.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Sarcolemma.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myolin</ent><br/
<hw>My"o*lin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/, <?/, muscle.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>The essential material of muscle fibers.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myological</ent><br/
<ent>Myologic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>My`o*log"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>My`o*log"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to myology.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myologist</ent><br/
<hw>My*ol"o*gist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One skilled in myology.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myology</ent><br/
<hw>My*ol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Myo-</ets> + <ets>-logy</ets>: cf. F. <ets>myologie</ets>.]</ety> <def>That part of anatomy which treats of muscles.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myoma</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My*o"ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Myo-</er>, and <er>-oma</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A tumor consisting of muscular tissue.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myomancy</ent><br/
<hw>My"o*man`cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>my^s</grk> mouse + <ets>-mancy</ets>.]</ety> <def>Divination by the movements of mice.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myomorph</ent><br/
<hw>My"o*morph</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One of the Myomorpha.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myomorpha</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My`o*mor"pha</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>my^s</grk>, <grk>myo`s</grk>, a mouse + <grk>morfh`</grk> form.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An extensive group of rodents which includes the rats, mice, jerboas, and many allied forms.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myopathia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My`o*pa*thi"a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/, <?/, a muscle + <?/, <?/, to suffer.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Any affection of the muscles or muscular system.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myopathic</ent><br/
<hw>My`o*path"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to myopathia.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myopathy</ent><br/
<hw>My*op"a*thy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Same as <er>Myopathia</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myope</ent><br/
<hw>My"ope</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. Gr. <?/, <?/; <?/ to close, shut the eyes + <?/, <?/, the eye.]</ety> <def>A person having myopia; a myops.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myophan</ent><br/
<hw>My"o*phan</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Myo-</ets> + Gr. <?/ to show.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A contractile striated layer found in the bodies and stems of certain Infusoria.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myopia</ent><br/
<hw>My*o"pi*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. See <er>Myope</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Nearsightedness; shortsightedness; a condition of the eye in which the rays from distant object are brought to a focus before they reach the retina, and hence form an indistinct image; while the rays from very near objects are normally converged so as to produce a distinct image.  It is corrected by the use of a concave lens.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myopic</ent><br/
<hw>My*op"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to, or affected with, or characterized by, myopia; nearsighted.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Myopic astigmatism</b></col>, <cd>a condition in which the eye is affected with myopia in one meridian only.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myops</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My"ops</hw> <pr>(m<imac/"<ocr/ps)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL.]</ety> <def>See <er>Myope</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myopsis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My*op"sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ fly + <?/ sight.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>The appearance of <cref>muscae volitantes</cref>. See <cref>Muscae volitantes</cref>, under <er>Musca</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myopy</ent><br/
<hw>My"o*py</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>myopie</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Myopia.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myosin</ent><br/
<hw>My"o*sin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>my^s</grk>, <grk>myo`s</grk> a muscle.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol. Chem.)</fld> <def>A protein present in muscle, serving as the principle contractile protein in muscle contraction.</def>  <note>It was earlier considered as being formed in the process of coagulation which takes place in <er>rigor mortis</er>.  See <cref>Muscle plasma</cref>, under <er>Plasma</er>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ Myosin belongs to the group of globulins.  It is insoluble in water, but soluble in dilute solution of salt, and is especially characterized by being completely precipitated by saturation of its solutions with salt.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myosis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My*o"sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ to close the eyes or lips.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Long-continued contraction of the pupil of the eye.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myositic</ent><br/
<hw>My`o*sit"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Myotic.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myositis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My`o*si"tis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/, <?/, muscle + <ets>-itis</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Inflammation of the muscles.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myosotis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My`o*so"tis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[NL.; Gr. <?/, lit., mouse ear.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of plants. See <er>Mouse-ear</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myotic</ent><br/
<hw>My*ot"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Myosis</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Producing myosis, or contraction of the pupil of the eye, as opium, calabar bean, etc.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A myotic agent.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myotome</ent><br/
<hw>My"o*tome</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Myotomy</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A muscular segment; one of the zones into which the muscles of the trunk, especially in fishes, are divided; a myocomma.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>One of the embryonic muscular segments arising from the protovertebrae; also, one of the protovertebrae themselves.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The muscular system of one metamere of an articulate.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myotomic</ent><br/
<hw>My`o*tom"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to a myotome or myotomes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myotomy</ent><br/
<hw>My*ot"o*my</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Myo-</ets> + Gr. <?/ to cut: cf. F. <ets>myotomie</ets>.]</ety> <def>The dissection, or that part of anatomy which treats of the dissection, of muscles.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrcia</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Myr"ci*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A large genus of tropical American trees and shrubs, nearly related to the true myrtles (<gen>Myrtus</gen>), from which they differ in having very few seeds in each berry.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myria-</ent><br/
<hw>Myr"i*a-</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[Gr. <?/ a myriad. See <er>Myriad</er>.]</ety> <def>A prefix, esp. in the metric system, indicating <sig>ten thousand</sig>, <sig>ten thousand times</sig>; <as>as, <ex>myria</ex>meter</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myriacanthous</ent><br/
<hw>Myr`i*a*can"thous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ numberless + <grk>'a`kanqa</grk> a spine.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Having numerous spines, as certain fishes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myriad</ent><br/
<hw>Myr"i*ad</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/, <?/, fr. <?/ numberless, pl. <?/ ten thousand: cf. F. <ets>myriade</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The number of ten thousand; ten thousand persons or things.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An immense number; a very great many; an indefinitely large number.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myriad</ent><br/
<hw>Myr"i*ad</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Consisting of a very great, but indefinite, number; <as>as, <ex>myriad</ex> stars</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myriagramme</ent><br/
<ent>Myriagram</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Myr"i*a*gram</hw>, <hw>Myr"i*a*gramme</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>myriagramme</ets>. See <er>Myria-</er>, and 3d <er>Gram</er>.]</ety> <def>A metric weight, consisting of ten thousand grams or ten kilograms.  It is equal to 22.046 lbs. avoirdupois.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrialitre</ent><br/
<ent>Myrialiter</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Myr"i*a*li`ter</hw>, <hw>Myr"i*a*li`tre</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>myrialitre</ets>. See <er>Myria-</er>, and <er>Liter</er>.]</ety> <def>A metric measure of capacity, containing ten thousand liters.  It is equal to 2641.7 wine gallons.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myriametre</ent><br/
<ent>Myriameter</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Myr"i*a*me`ter</hw>, <hw>Myr"i*a*me`tre</hw>  }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>myriam<egrave/tre</ets>. See <er>Myria-</er>, and <er>Meter</er>.]</ety> <def>A metric measure of length, containing ten thousand meters.  It is equal to 6.2137 miles.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myriapod</ent><br/
<hw>Myr"i*a*pod</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>myriapode</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the <class>Myriapoda</class>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myriapoda</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Myr`i*ap"o*da</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ numberless + <ets>-poda</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A class, or subclass, of arthropods, related to the hexapod insects, from which they differ in having the body made up of numerous similar segments, nearly all of which bear true jointed legs.  They have one pair of antennae, three pairs of mouth organs, and numerous tracheae, similar to those of true insects.  The larvae, when first hatched, often have but three pairs of legs. See <er>Centiped</er>, <er>Galleyworm</er>, <er>Milliped</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The existing Myriapoda are divided into three orders: <ord>Chilopoda</ord>, <ord>Chilognatha</ord> or <ord>Diplopoda</ord>, and <ord>Pauropoda</ord> (see these words in the Vocabulary).  Large fossil species (very different from any living forms) are found in the Carboniferous formation.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myriarch</ent><br/
<hw>Myr"i*arch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/, <?/; <?/ ten thousand + <?/ chief.]</ety> <def>A captain or commander of ten thousand men.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myriare</ent><br/
<hw>Myr"i*are</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. See <er>Myria-</er>, and 2d <er>Are</er>.]</ety> <def>A measure of surface in the metric system containing ten thousand ares, or one million square meters.  It is equal to about 247.1 acres.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrica</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My*ri"ca</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/ tamarisk.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A widely dispersed genus of shrubs and trees, usually with aromatic foliage.  It includes the bayberry or wax myrtle, the sweet gale, and the North American sweet fern, so called.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myricin</ent><br/
<hw>Myr"i*cin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>myricine</ets>. Prob. so called from a fancied resemblance to the wax of the bayberry (<gen>Myrica</gen>).]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A silky, crystalline, waxy substance, forming the less soluble part of beeswax, and regarded as a palmitate of a higher alcohol of the paraffin series; -- called also <altname>myricyl alcohol</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myricyl</ent><br/
<hw>Myr"i*cyl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Myric</ets>in + <ets>-yl</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A hypothetical radical regarded as the essential residue of myricin; -- called also <altname>melissyl</altname>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myriological</ent><br/
<hw>Myr`i*o*log"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or relating to a myriologue.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myriologist</ent><br/
<hw>Myr`i*ol"o*gist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who composes or sings a myriologue.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myriologue</ent><br/
<hw>Myr"i*o*logue</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>myriologue</ets>, <ets>myriologie</ets>, NGr. <?/, <?/, fr. Gr. <grk>Moi^ra</grk> the goddess of fate or death + <grk>lo`gos</grk> speech, discourse.]</ety> <def>An extemporaneous funeral song, composed and sung by a woman on the death of a friend.</def> <mark>[Modern Greece]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myriophyllous</ent><br/
<hw>Myr`i*oph"yl*lous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ numberless + <grk>fy`llon</grk> leaf.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Having an indefinitely great or countless number of leaves.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myriopoda</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Myr`i*op"o*da</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <def>See <er>Myriapoda</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myriorama</ent><br/
<hw>Myr`i*o*ra"ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ numberless + <?/ a sight, fr. <?/ to see.]</ety> <def>A picture made up of several smaller pictures, drawn upon separate pieces in such a manner as to admit of combination in many different ways, thus producing a great variety of scenes or landscapes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrioscope</ent><br/
<hw>Myr"i*o*scope</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ numberless + <ets>-scope</ets>.]</ety> <def>A form of kaleidoscope.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 960 --></p>

<p><ent>Myristate</ent><br/
<hw>My*ris"tate</hw> <pr>(m<icr/*r<icr/s"t<asl/t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A salt of myristic acid.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myristic</ent><br/
<hw>My*ris"tic</hw> <pr>(m<icr/*r<icr/s"t<icr/k)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or derived from, the nutmeg (<gen>Myristica</gen>).  Specifically, designating an acid (<chform>C14H28O2</chform>) found in nutmeg oil and otoba fat, and extracted as a white crystalline waxy substance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myristin</ent><br/
<hw>My*ris"tin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>The myristate of glycerin, -- found as a vegetable fat in nutmeg butter, etc.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myristone</ent><br/
<hw>My*ris"tone</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Myrist</ets>ic + <ets>-one</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>The ketone of myristic acid, obtained as a white crystalline substance.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrmecophaga</ent><br/
<hw>Myrmecophaga</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The type genus of the <fam>Myrmecophagidae</fam>; the South American ant bear.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Myrmecophaga</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrmecophagidae</ent><br/
<hw>Myrmecophagidae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A natural family of New World anteaters.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Myrmecophagidae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>myrmecophagous</ent><br/
<hw>myrmecophagous</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>feeding on ants but usually not living with them.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>myrmecophile</ent><br/
<hw>myrmecophile</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>An organism such as an insect that habitually shares the nest of a species of ant.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>myrmecophilous</ent><br/
<hw>myrmecophilous</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Associated with, or benefitted by ants through sharing their nest.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrmecophyte</ent><br/
<hw>Myr"me*co*phyte`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>my`rmhx</grk>, <grk>my`rmhkos</grk>, ant + <grk>fyto`n</grk> plant.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A plant that affords shelter and food to certain species of ants which live in symbiotic relations with it. Special adaptations for this purpose exist; thus, <spn>Acacia spadicigera</spn> has large hollows thorns, and species of <gen>Cecropia</gen> have stem cavities.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Myr`me*co*phyt"ic</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>myrmecophytic</ent><br/
<hw>myrmecophytic</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to a myrmecophyte.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrmeleon</ent><br/
<hw>Myrmeleon</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The type genus of the <fam>Myrmeleontidae</fam>, including the antlions.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus Myrmeleon.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrmeleontidae</ent><br/
<hw>Myrmeleontidae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of the order <ord>Neuroptera</ord>, including the antlions.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Myrmeleontidae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrmicine</ent><br/
<hw>Myr"mi*cine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to <gen>Myrmica</gen>, a genus of ants including the small house ant (<spn>Myrmica molesta</spn>), and many others.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrmidon</ent><br/
<hw>Myr"mi*don</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>Myrmidones</ets>, Gr. <grk>Myrmido`nes</grk>, pl.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One of a fierce tribe or troop who accompanied <persfn>Achilles</persfn>, their king, to the Trojan war.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A soldier or a subordinate civil officer who executes cruel orders of a superior without protest or pity; -- sometimes applied to bailiffs, constables, etc.</def>  <rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With unabated ardor the vindictive man of law and his <qex>myrmidons</qex> pressed forward.</q> <rj><qau>W. H. Ainsworth.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrmidonian</ent><br/
<hw>Myr`mi*do"ni*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Consisting of, or like, myrmidons.</def>  <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrmotherine</ent><br/
<hw>Myr`mo*the"rine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>my`rmhx</grk> an ant + <grk>qhra^n</grk> to hunt.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Feeding upon ants; -- said of certain birds.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrobolan</ent><br/
<ent>Myrobalan</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>My*rob"a*lan</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>My*rob"o*lan</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>myrobalanum</ets> the fruit of a palm tree from which a balsam was made, Gr. <grk>myroba`lanos</grk>; <grk>my`ron</grk> any sweet juice distilling from plants, any prepared unguent or sweet oil + <grk>ba`lanos</grk> an acorn or any similar fruit: cf. F. <ets>myrobolan</ets>.]</ety> <def>A dried astringent fruit much resembling a prune.  It contains tannin, and was formerly used in medicine, but is now chiefly used in tanning and dyeing.  Myrobolans are produced by various species of <gen>Terminalia</gen> of the East Indies, and of <gen>Spondias</gen> of South America.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myronic</ent><br/
<hw>My*ron"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>my`ron</grk> a sweet-smelling unguent.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or obtained from, mustard; -- used specifically to designate a glucoside called <xex>myronic acid</xex>, found in mustard seed.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myropolist</ent><br/
<hw>My*rop"o*list</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>myropw`lhs</grk>; <grk>my`ron</grk> unguent + <grk>pwlei^n</grk> to sell.]</ety> <def>One who sells unguents or perfumery.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Jonhson.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrosin</ent><br/
<hw>Myr"o*sin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>An enzyme, resembling diastase, found in mustard seeds.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myroxylon</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My*rox"y*lon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>my`ron</grk> a sweet juice distilling from a plant + <grk>xy`lon</grk> wood.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of leguminous trees of tropical America, the different species of which yield balsamic products, among which are balsam of Peru, and balsam of Tolu.  The species were formerly referred to <gen>Myrospermum</gen>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrrh</ent><br/
<hw>Myrrh</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mirre</ets>, OF. <ets>mirre</ets>, F. <ets>myrrhe</ets>, L. <ets>myrrha</ets>, <ets>murra</ets>, Gr. <?/; cf. Ar. <ets>murr</ets> bitter, also myrrh, Heb. <ets>mar</ets> bitter.]</ety> <def>A gum resin, usually of a yellowish brown or amber color, of an aromatic odor, and a bitter, slightly pungent taste.  It is valued for its odor and for its medicinal properties.  It exudes from the bark of a shrub of Abyssinia and Arabia, the <spn>Commiphora Myrrha</spn> (syn. <spn>Balsamodendron Myrrha</spn>) of the family <fam>Burseraceae</fam>, or from the <spn>Commiphora abyssinica</spn>.  The myrrh of the Bible is supposed to have been partly the gum above named, and partly the exudation of species of <gen>Cistus</gen>, or rockrose.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>False myrrh</b></col>. <cd>See the Note under <er>Bdellium</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrrhic</ent><br/
<hw>Myr"rhic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of, pertaining to, or obtained from, myrrh.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrrhine</ent><br/
<hw>Myr"rhine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Murrhine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrtaceae</ent><br/
<hw>Myrtaceae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of trees and shrubs yielding fragrant oils, including the myrtles, eucalyptus, clove, allspice, and guava; the <altname>myrtle family</altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Myrtaceae</fam>, myrtle family.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrtaceous</ent><br/
<hw>Myr*ta"ceous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>myrtaceus</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or resembling, a large and important natural family of trees and shrubs (<fam>Myrtaceae</fam> of the order <ord>Myrtales</ord>), of which the myrtle (<gen>Myrtus</gen>) is the type.  It includes the genera <gen>Eucalyptus</gen>, <gen>Pimenta</gen>, <gen>Lechythis</gen>, and about seventy more.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrtales</ent><br/
<hw>Myrtales</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural order of trees and shrubs including the myrtle family, Myrtaceae; Combretaceae; Elaeagnaceae; Haloragidaceae; Melastomaceae; Lecythidaceae; Lythraceae; Rhizophoraceae; Onagraceae; Lecythidaceae; and Punicaceae.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> order <ord>Myrtales</ord>, <ord>Thymelaeales</ord>, order Thymelaeales.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrtiform</ent><br/
<hw>Myr"ti*form</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>myrtus</ets> myrtle + <ets>-form</ets>: cf. F. <ets>myrtiforme</ets>.]</ety> <def>Resembling myrtle or myrtle berries; having the form of a myrtle leaf.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrtillocactus</ent><br/
<hw>Myrtillocactus</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A small genus of arborescent cacti of Mexico and Central America.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Myrtillocactus</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrtle</ent><br/
<hw>Myr"tle</hw> <pr>(m<etil/r"t'l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>myrtil</ets> bilberry, prop., a little myrtle, from <ets>myrte</ets> myrtle, L. <ets>myrtus</ets>, <ets>murtus</ets>, Gr. <grk>my`rtos</grk>; cf. Per. <ets>m<umac/rd</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A species of the genus <gen>Myrtus</gen>, especially <spn>Myrtus communis</spn>. The common myrtle has a shrubby, upright stem, eight or ten feet high. Its branches form a close, full head, thickly covered with ovate or lanceolate evergreen leaves.  It has solitary axillary white or rosy flowers, followed by black several-seeded berries.  The ancients considered it sacred to Venus.  The flowers, leaves, and berries are used variously in perfumery and as a condiment, and the beautifully mottled wood is used in turning.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note><hand/ The name is also popularly but wrongly applied in America to two creeping plants, the blue-flowered periwinkle and the yellow-flowered moneywort.  In the West Indies several myrtaceous shrubs are called <ex>myrtle</ex>.</note><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Bog myrtle</b></col>, <cd>the sweet gale.</cd> -- <col><b>Crape myrtle</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Crape</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Myrtle warbler</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a North American wood warbler (<spn>Dendroica coronata</spn>); -- called also <altname>myrtle bird</altname>, <altname>yellow-rumped warbler</altname>, and <altname>yellow-crowned warbler</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Myrtle wax</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>See <cref>Bayberry tallow</cref>, under <er>Bayberry</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Sand myrtle</b></col>, <cd>a low, branching evergreen shrub (<spn>Leiophyllum buxifolium</spn>), growing in New Jersey and southward.</cd> -- <col><b>Wax myrtle</b></col> <cd>(<spn>Myrica cerifera</spn>). See <er>Bayberry</er>.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myrtus</ent><br/
<hw>Myrtus</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>The type genus of the <fam>Myrtaceae</fam>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Myrtus</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myself</ent><br/
<hw>My*self"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>pron.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Ourselves</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>I or me in person; -- used for emphasis, my own self or person; as I <xex>myself</xex> will do it; I have done it <xex>myself</xex>; -- used also instead of <xex>me</xex>, as the object of the first person of a reflexive verb, without emphasis; <as>as, I will defend <ex>myself</ex></as>.</def><-- a reflexive pron. --><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myselven</ent><br/
<hw>My*selv"en</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>pron.</pos> <def>Myself.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mysidacea</ent><br/
<hw>Mysidacea</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>An order of crustaceans including the opossum shrimp.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> order <ord>Mysidacea</ord>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mysidae</ent><br/
<hw>Mysidae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A natural family of small shrimplike crustaceans.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Mysidae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mysis</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My"sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ a closing of the lips or eyes.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of small schizopod shrimps found both in fresh and salt water; the opossum shrimps.  One species inhabits the Great Lakes of North America, and is largely eaten by the whitefish.  The marine species form part of the food of right whales.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mystacal</ent><br/
<hw>Mys"ta*cal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>my`stax</grk> mustache.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the upper lip, or mustache.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mystagogical</ent><br/
<ent>Mystagogic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mys`ta*gog"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mys`ta*gog"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to interpretation of mysteries or to mystagogue; of the nature of mystagogy.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mystagogue</ent><br/
<hw>Mys"ta*gogue</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mystagogus</ets>, Gr. <?/; <?/ one initiated in mysteries + <?/ leading, n., a leader, fr. <?/ to lead: cf. F. <ets>mystagogue</ets>. See 1st <er>Mystery</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who interprets mysteries, especially of a religious kind.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who keeps and shows church relics.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mystagogy</ent><br/
<hw>Mys"ta*go`gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The doctrines, principles, or practice of a mystagogue; interpretation of mysteries.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mysterial</ent><br/
<hw>Mys*te"ri*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Mysterious.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mysteriarch</ent><br/
<hw>Mys*te"ri*arch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mysteriarches</ets>, Gr. <?/; <?/ mystery + <?/ chief.]</ety> <def>One presiding over mysteries.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mysterious</ent><br/
<hw>Mys*te"ri*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>myst<egrave/rieux</ets>. See 1st <er>Mystery</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to mystery; containing a mystery; difficult or impossible to understand; inexplicable; obscure; not revealed or explained; enigmatical; incomprehensible.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God at last<br/
To Satan, first in sin, his doom applied,<br/
Thought in <qex>mysterious</qex> terms.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Obscure; secret; occult; dark; mystic; cabalistic; enigmatical; unintelligible; inexplicable; incomprehensible.</syn><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mysteriously</ent><br/
<hw>Mys*te"ri*ous*ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a mysterious manner.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mysteriousness</ent><br/
<hw>Mys*te"ri*ous*ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The state or quality of being mysterious.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Something mysterious; a mystery.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>  <rj><au>Jer. Taylor.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mysterize</ent><br/
<hw>Mys"ter*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mysterized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mysterizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To make mysterious; to make a mystery of.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mystery</ent><br/
<hw>Mys"ter*y</hw> <pr>(m<icr/s"t<etil/r*<ycr/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mysteries</plw> <pr>(m<icr/s"t<etil/r*<icr/z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>mysterium</ets>, Gr. <grk>mysth`rion</grk>, fr. <grk>my`sths</grk> one initiated in mysteries; cf. <grk>myei^n</grk> to initiate into the mysteries, fr. <grk>my`ein</grk> to shut the eyes.  Cf. <er>Mute</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A profound secret; something wholly unknown, or something kept cautiously concealed, and therefore exciting curiosity or wonder; something which has not been or can not be explained; hence, specifically, that which is beyond human comprehension.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We speak the wisdom of God in a <qex>mystery</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>1 Cor. ii. 7.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If God should please to reveal unto us this great <qex>mystery</qex> of the Trinity, or some other <qex>mysteries</qex> in our holy religion, we should not be able to understand them, unless he would bestow on us some new faculties of the mind.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A kind of secret religious celebration, to which none were admitted except those who had been initiated by certain preparatory ceremonies; -- usually plural; <as>as, the Eleusinian <ex>mysteries</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>The consecrated elements in the eucharist.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Anything artfully made difficult; an enigma.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mystery</ent><br/
<hw>Mys"ter*y</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mysteries</plw>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>mistere</ets>, OF. <ets>mestier</ets>, F. <ets>m<eacute/tier</ets>, L. <ets>ministerium</ets>. See <er>Ministry</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A trade; a handicraft; hence, any business with which one is usually occupied.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fie upon him, he will discredit our <qex>mystery</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And that which is the noblest <qex>mystery</qex><br/
Brings to reproach and common infamy.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A dramatic representation of a Scriptural subject, often some event in the life of Christ; a dramatic composition of this character; <as>as, the Chester <ex>Mysteries</ex>, consisting of dramas acted by various craft associations in that city in the early part of the 14th century</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><ldquo/<qex>Mystery</qex> plays,<rdquo/ so called because acted by craftsmen.</q> <rj><qau>Skeat.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mystical</ent><br/
<ent>Mystic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Mys"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Mys"tic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mysticus</ets>, Gr. <?/ belonging to secret rites, from <?/ one initiated: cf. F. <ets>mystique</ets>. See 1st <er>Mystery</er>, <er>Misty</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Remote from or beyond human comprehension; baffling human understanding; unknowable; obscure; mysterious.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Heaven's numerous hierarchy span<br/
The <qex>mystic</qex> gulf from God to man.</q> <rj><qau>Emerson.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God hath revealed a way <qex>mystical</qex> and supernatural.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Importing or implying mysticism; involving some secret meaning; allegorical; emblematical; <as>as, a <ex>mystic</ex> dance; <ex>mystic</ex> Babylon.</as></def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus, then, did the spirit of unity and meekness inspire every joint and sinew of the <qex>mystical</qex> body.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn>  <def>employing mysticism; <as>as, <ex>mystical</ex> intuition; <ex>mystical</ex> explanations</as>; -- contrasted to <contr>logical</contr>, <contr>rational</contr>, <contr>analytical</contr>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Mys"tic*al*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Mys"tic*al*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mystic</ent><br/
<hw>Mys"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One given to mysticism; one who holds mystical views, interpretations, etc.; especially, in ecclesiastical history, one who professed mysticism. See <er>Mysticism</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mysticete</ent><br/
<hw>Mys"ti*cete</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>my`stax</grk> the upper lip, also, the mustache + <grk>kh^tos</grk> a whale.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any right whale, or whalebone whale. See <er>Cetacea</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mysticeti</ent><br/
<hw>Mysticeti</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A suborder including baleen whales: right whales; rorquals; blue whales; and humpbacks.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> suborder <subord>Mysticeti</subord>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mysticism</ent><br/
<hw>Mys"ti*cism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mysticisme</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Obscurity of doctrine.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>The doctrine of the Mystics, who professed a pure, sublime, and wholly disinterested devotion, and maintained that they had direct intercourse with the divine Spirit, and aquired a knowledge of God and of spiritual things unattainable by the natural intellect, and such as can not be analyzed or explained.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Philos.)</fld> <def>The doctrine that the ultimate elements or principles of knowledge or belief are gained by an act or process akin to feeling or faith.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mystification</ent><br/
<hw>Mys`ti*fi*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mystification</ets>.]</ety> <def>The act of mystifying, or the state of being mystied; also, something designed to, or that does, mystify.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The reply of Pope seems very much as though he had been playing off a <qex>mystification</qex> on his Grace.</q> <rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mystificator</ent><br/
<hw>Mys"ti*fi*ca`tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who mystifies.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mystify</ent><br/
<hw>Mys"ti*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mystified</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mystifying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>mystifier</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/ + L. <ets>-ficare</ets> (in comp.) to make. See 1st <er>Mystery</er>, and <er>-fy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To involve in mystery; to make obscure or difficult to understand; <as>as, to <ex>mystify</ex> a passage of Scripture</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To perplex the mind of; to puzzle; to impose upon the credulity of; to baffle; <as>as, to <ex>mystify</ex> an opponent</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He took undue advantage of his credulity and <qex>mystified</qex> him exceedingly.</q> <rj><qau>Ld. Campbell.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mystique</ent><br/
<hw>mystique</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An aura of reverence or mystery stemming from  feelings of high value or interest or meaning surrounding a person or thing; <as>as, the Kennedy <ex>mystique</ex></as>.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The aura of mystery surrounding the esoteric knowledge and skills required in certain occupations, or the power of those possessing those skills; <as>as, the <ex>mystique</ex> of the astrophysicists</as>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mytacism</ent><br/
<hw>My"ta*cism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/.  Cf. <er>Metacism</er>.]</ety> <def>Too frequent use of the letter <it>m</it>, or of the sound represented by it.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myth</ent><br/
<hw>Myth</hw> <pr>(m<icr/th)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <altsp>[Written also <asp>mythe</asp>.]</altsp> <ety>[Gr. <grk>my^qos</grk> myth, fable, tale, talk, speech: cf. F. <ets>mythe</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A story of great but unknown age which originally embodied a belief regarding some fact or phenomenon of experience, and in which often the forces of nature and of the soul are personified; an ancient legend of a god, a hero, the origin of a race, etc.; a wonder story of prehistoric origin; a popular fable which is, or has been, received as historical.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A person or thing existing only in imagination, or whose actual existence is not verifiable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As for Mrs. Primmins's bones, they had been <qex>myths</qex> these twenty years.</q> <rj><qau>Ld. Lytton.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Myth history</b></col>, <cd>history made of, or mixed with, myths.</cd></cs><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mythe</ent><br/
<hw>Mythe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>See <er>Myth</er>.</def>  <rj><au>Grote.</au></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mythical</ent><br/
<ent>Mythic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Myth"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Myth"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mythicus</ets>, Gr. <?/. See <er>Myth</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or relating to myths; described in a myth; of the nature of a myth; fabulous; imaginary; fanciful; mythological.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Myth"ic*al*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>mythic</qex> turf where danced the nymphs.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs. Browning.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hengist and Horsa, Vortigern and Rowena, Arthur and Mordred, are <qex>mythical</qex> persons, whose very existence may be questioned.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mythographer</ent><br/
<hw>My*thog"ra*pher</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>myqogra`fos</grk>; <grk>my^qos</grk> + <grk>gra`fein</grk> to write.]</ety> <def>A composer of fables.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mythologer</ent><br/
<hw>My*thol"o*ger</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mythologist.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mythologian</ent><br/
<hw>Myth`o*lo"gi*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mythologist.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mythological</ent><br/
<ent>Mythologic</ent><br/
<mhw>{ <hw>Myth`o*log"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <hw>Myth`o*log"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mythologicus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>mytholigique</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to mythology or to myths; <as>as, <ex>mythological</ex> creatures</as>.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Myth`o*log"ic*al*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>based on or told of in traditional stories; lacking factual basis or historical validity; mythical; fabulous.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> fabulous, mythic, mythical.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mythologisation</ent><br/
<hw>mythologisation</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>mythologization.</def> <mark>[Chiefly Brit.]</mark> <br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mythologist</ent><br/
<hw>My*thol"o*gist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mythologiste</ets>.]</ety> <def>One versed in, or who writes on, mythology or myths.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mythologization</ent><br/
<hw>mythologization</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>The construction of a myth; the restatement of a message as a myth.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> mythologisation.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mythologize</ent><br/
<hw>My*thol"o*gize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>mythologiser</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To relate, classify, and explain, or attempt to explain, myths; to write upon myths.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To construct and propagate myths.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mythologizer</ent><br/
<hw>My*thol"o*gi`zer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who, or that which, mythologizes.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Imagination has always been, and still is, in a narrower sense, the great <qex>mythologizer</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Lowell.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mythologue</ent><br/
<hw>Myth"o*logue</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Mythology</er>.]</ety> <def>A fabulous narrative; a myth.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>May we not . . . consider his history of the fall as an excellent <qex>mythologue</qex>, to account for the origin of human evil?</q> <rj><qau>Geddes.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mythology</ent><br/
<hw>My*thol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mythologies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F. <ets>mythologie</ets>, L. <ets>mythologia</ets>, Gr. <grk>myqologi`a</grk>; <grk>my^qos</grk>, fable, myth + <grk>lo`gos</grk> speech, discourse.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The science which treats of myths; a treatise on myths.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A body of myths; esp., the collective myths which describe the gods of a heathen people; <as>as, the <ex>mythology</ex> of the Greeks</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mythoplasm</ent><br/
<hw>Myth"o*plasm</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>my^qos</grk> myth + <grk>pla`ssein</grk> to form.]</ety> <def>A narration of mere fable.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mythopoeic</ent><br/
<hw>Myth`o*poe"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>myqopoio`s</grk> making myths; <grk>my^qos</grk> myth + <grk>poiei^n</grk> to make.]</ety> <def>Making or producing myths; giving rise to mythical narratives.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>mythopoeic</qex> fertility of the Greeks.</q> <rj><qau>Grote.</qau></rj><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mythopoetic</ent><br/
<hw>Myth`o*po*et"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>my^qos</grk> myth + <?/ able to make, producing, fr. <grk>poiei^n</grk> to make.]</ety> <def>Making or producing myths or mythical tales.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mytiloid</ent><br/
<hw>Myt"i*loid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mytilus</ets> + <ets>-oid</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Like, or pertaining to, the genus <gen>Mytilus</gen>, or family <fam>Mytilidae</fam>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mytilotoxine</ent><br/
<hw>Myt`i*lo*tox"ine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Mytilus</ets> + <ets>toxic</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol. Chem.)</fld> <def>A poisonous base (leucomaine) found in the common mussel.  It either causes paralysis of the muscles, or gives rise to convulsions, including death by an accumulation of carbonic acid in the blood.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mytilus</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Myt"i*lus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., a sea mussel, Gr. <?/.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of marine bivalve shells, including the common mussel. See <xex>Illust.</xex> under <er>Byssus</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myxa</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Myx"a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., a lamp nozzle, Gr. <?/.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The distal end of the mandibles of a bird.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>myxedema</ent><br/
<hw>myxedema</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A pathological condition due to severe hyperthyroidism, marked by dry skin and swellings around lips and nose as well as mental and physical deterioration.</def> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>myxoedema</asp>.]</altsp><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myxine</ent><br/
<hw>Myx"ine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of marsipobranchs, including the hagfish. See <er>Hag</er>, 4.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myxinoid</ent><br/
<hw>Myx"i*noid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Like, or pertaining to, the genus <gen>Myxine</gen>.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>A hagfish.</def></def2><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myxinoidei</ent><br/
<hw>Myxinoidei</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A suborder of hagfishes as distinguished from lampreys.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Myxiniformes, suborder <subord>Myxiniformes</subord>, Hyperotreta, suborder <subord>Hyperotreta</subord>, Myxinoidea, suborder <subord>Myxinoidei</subord>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myxobacter</ent><br/
<hw>Myxobacter</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Microbiol.)</fld> <def>One genus of <er>myxobacteria</er>.</def><br/
[<source>PJC</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>myxobacterium</ent><br/
<hw>myxobacterium</hw> <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>myxobacteria</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu>  <def>A type of bacteria that form colonies in self-produced slime; they inhabit moist soils or decaying plant matter or animal waste.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> myxobacterium, myxobacter, gliding bacteria, slime bacteria.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myxobacteriaceae</ent><br/
<hw>Myxobacteriaceae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A family of bacteria living mostly in soils and on dung; called also <fam>Polyangiaceae</fam>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> Polyangiaceae, family <fam>Polyangiaceae</fam>, family <fam>Myxobacteriaceae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myxocephalus</ent><br/
<hw>Myxocephalus</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>A genus of fish including the grubb (<spn>Myxocephalus aenaeus</spn>), a type of sculpin.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> genus <gen>Myxocephalus</gen>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myxocystodea</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Myx`o*cys*to"de*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ mucus + <?/ a bladder.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A division of Infusoria including the Noctiluca.  See <er>Noctiluca</er>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myxoedema</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Myx`oe*de"ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL. fr. Gr. <?/ mucus + <ets>oedema</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A disease producing a peculiar cretinoid appearance of the face, slow speech, and dullness of intellect, and due to failure of the functions of the thyroid gland.</def> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>myxedema</asp>.]</altsp>-- <wordforms><wf>Myx`oe*dem"a*tous</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>, <wf>Myx`oe*dem"ic</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myxoma</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Myx*o"ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Myxomata</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ mucus + <ets>-oma</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A tumor made up of a gelatinous tissue resembling that found in the umbilical cord.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>myxomatosis</ent><br/
<hw>myxomatosis</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>a viral disease (usually fatal) of rabbits.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>myxomycete</ent><br/
<hw>myxomycete</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>an organism of the class <class>Myxomycetes</class>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> true slime mold, acellular slime mold, plasmodial slime mold.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myxomycetes</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Myx`o*my*ce"tes</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL.; Gr. <?/ mucus, slime + <ets>myceles</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A class of peculiar organisms, the slime molds, formerly regarded as animals (Mycetozoa), but now generally thought to be plants and often separated as a distinct phylum (Myxophyta); essentially equivalent to the division Myxomycota.  They are found on damp earth and decaying vegetable matter, and consist of naked masses of protoplasm, often of considerable size, which creep very slowly  over the surface and ingest solid food.</def> -- <wordforms><wf>Myx`o*my*ce"tous</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos></wordforms><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> true slime molds, acellular slime molds, plasmodial slime molds.</syn><br/
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myxomycota</ent><br/
<hw>Myxomycota</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The slime molds; organisms having a noncellular and multinucleate creeping vegetative phase and a propagative spore-producing stage: comprises Myxomycetes and Acrasiomycetes and Plasmodiophoromycetes; in some classifications placed in the kingdom Protoctista.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> division Myxomycota, Gymnomycota, division Gymnomycota.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myxophyceae</ent><br/
<hw>Myxophyceae</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>A former term for the natural family <altname><fam>Cyanophyceae</fam></altname>.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> family <fam>Myxophyceae</fam>, Schizophyceae, family <fam>Schizophyceae</fam>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myxophyta</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>Myx*oph"y*ta</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL.; Gr. <?/ mucus, slime + <?/ plant.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A phylum of the vegetable kingdom consisting of the class <class>Myxomycetes</class>.  By some botanists it is not separated from the Thallophyta.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myxopod</ent><br/
<hw>Myx"o*pod</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ mucus, slime + <ets>-pod</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A rhizopod or moneran. Also used adjectively; <as>as, a <ex>myxopod</ex> state</as>.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myxosporidia</ent><br/
<hw>Myxosporidia</hw> <pos>prop. n.</pos> <def>An order of sporozoans.</def><br/
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> order <ord>Myxosporidia</ord>.</syn><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>myxosporidian</ent><br/
<hw>myxosporidian</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <def>An organism of the order <ord>Myxosporidia</ord>, mostly parasitic in fishes and including various serious pathogens.</def><br/
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myzontes</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My*zon"tes</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/ to suck.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The Marsipobranchiata.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Myzostomata</ent><br/
\'d8<hw>My`zo*stom"a*ta</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>my`zein</grk> to suck + <grk>sto`ma</grk>, <grk>-atos</grk>, mouth.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An order of curious parasitic worms found on crinoids. The body is short and disklike, with four pairs of suckers and five pairs of hook-bearing parapodia on the under side.</def><br/
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

